title: Bayonne, New Jersey
complex: Bayonne is a city in Hudson County, New Jersey, United States. <s> Located in the Gateway Region, Bayonne is situated on a peninsula located between Newark Bay to the west, the Kill Van Kull to the south, and New York Bay to the east. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the city's population was 63,024, reflecting an increase of 1,182 (+1.9%) from the 61,842 counted in the 2000 Census, which had in turn increased by 398 (+0.6%) from the 61,444 counted in the 1990 Census. <s> Bayonne is east of Newark, the state's largest city, north of Elizabeth in Union County and west of Brooklyn. <s> It shares a land border with Jersey City to the north and is connected to Staten Island by the Bayonne Bridge.
simple: Bayonne (pronounced "bay-OWN") is a city in Hudson County, New Jersey, United States. <s> As of 2010, the population was 63,024. <s> Bayonne is east of Newark, the state's largest city, north of Elizabeth in Union County and west of Brooklyn.

title: List of political parties in Australia
complex: This article lists political parties in Australia. <s> These are Australian political parties which are no longer registered with any federal, state or territory political bodies, and can thus no longer contest elections. <s> However, they still remain active in electoral politics through running candidates under a local government party, as independents, or as members of an electoral alliance.
simple: This is a list of Australian political parties. <s> These groups are no longer registered and can no longer take part in elections.

title: Botanical name
complex: A botanical name is a formal scientific name conforming to the "International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants" (ICN) and, if it concerns a plant cultigen, the additional cultivar or Group epithets must conform to the "International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants" (ICNCP). <s> The code of nomenclature covers "all organisms traditionally treated as algae, fungi, or plants, whether fossil or non-fossil, including blue-green algae (Cyanobacteria), chytrids, oomycetes, slime moulds and photosynthetic protists with their taxonomically related non-photosynthetic groups (but excluding Microsporidia)." <s> The purpose of a formal name is to have a single name that is accepted and used worldwide for a particular plant or plant group. <s> For example, the botanical name "Bellis perennis" denotes a plant species which is native to most of the countries of Europe and the Middle East, where it has accumulated various names in many languages. <s> Later, the plant was introduced worldwide, bringing it into contact with more languages. <s> English names for this plant species include: daisy, English daisy, and lawn daisy. <s> The cultivar "Bellis perennis" 'Aucubifolia' is a golden-variegated horticultural selection of this species. <s> A botanical name in three parts, i.e., an infraspecific name (a name for a taxon below the rank of species) needs a "connecting term" to indicate rank. <s> In the "Calystegia" example above, this is "subsp.", for subspecies. <s> In botany there are many ranks below that of species (in zoology there is only one such rank, subspecies, so that this "connecting term" is not used in zoology). <s> A name of a "subdivision of a genus" also needs a connecting term (in the "Acacia" example above, this is "subg.", <s> The connecting term is not part of the name itself. <s> For botanical nomenclature, the "ICN" prescribes a two-part name or binary name for any taxon below the rank of genus down to, and including the rank of species. <s> Taxa below the rank of species get a three part (infraspecific name). <s> A binary name consists of the name of a genus and an epithet.
simple: A botanical name is a formal scientific name which follows the "International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants" (ICN). <s> If it concerns a plant cultigen, the additional cultivar term must follow the "International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants". <s> The code of nomenclature covers "all organisms traditionally treated as plants, whether fossil or non-fossil, e.g. blue-green algae (Cyanobacteria); fungi, including chytrids, oomycetes, and slime moulds; photosynthetic protists and taxonomically related non-photosynthetic groups". <s> The purpose of a formal name is to have a single name which is accepted and used worldwide for a particular plant or plant group. <s> For example, the botanical name "Bellis perennis" was given to a plant species which is native to most of the countries of Europe and the Middle East, where it has various names in many languages. <s> Later it has been introduced worldwide, bringing it into contact with more languages. <s> Some English names for this plant species are: daisy, English daisy, lawndaisy. <s> The cultivar "Bellis perennis" 'Aucubifolia' is a golden-variegated horticultural selection of this species. <s> A name in three parts, i.e., an infraspecific name (a name for a taxon below the rank of species), needs a "connecting term" to indicate rank. <s> In the "Calystegia" example above, this is "subsp." (for subspecies). <s> In botany there are many ranks below that of species (in zoology there is only one such rank, subspecies, so that this "connecting term" is unnecessary there). <s> A name of a "subdivision of a genus" also needs a connecting term (in the "Acacia" example above, this is "subg.", <s> The connecting term is not part of the name itself. <s> For botanical nomenclature, the "ICBN" prescribes a two-part name or binary name for any taxon below the rank of genus down to, and including the rank of species. <s> Taxa below the rank of species get a three part name. <s> A binary name consists of the name of a genus and an epithet.

title: Albert Meyong
complex: Albert Meyong Zé (born 19 October 1980), known as Meyong, is a Cameroonian former footballer who played as a striker.
simple: Albert Meyong (born 19 October 1980) is a Cameroonian football player.

title: Adil Khan (footballer)
complex: Adil Ahmed Khan (born 7 July 1988) is an Indian professional footballer who currently plays for the Hyderabad FC as a midfielder or defender. <s> A product of the Sesa Football Academy, Adil Khan started his football career in SESA in 2003 where he played for 5 years before moving to Sporting Clube de Goa in 2008. <s> He would spend 5 years at Sporting, playing for them in various positions, primarily in full back and centre midfield, first in the I-League 2nd Division and later in the I-League for 5 years and scoring 12 goals. <s> Khan made his senior international debut against Azerbaijan for India on 27 February 2012.
simple: Adil Ahmad Khan (born July 7, 1988) is an Indian professional athlete. <s> Khan has been a part of the Sporting Clube de Goa since 2007. <s> Khan played for India against Azerbaijan in 2012.

title: Syunik Province
complex: Syunik ( , ] ) is the southernmost province of Armenia. <s> It is bordered by the Vayots Dzor Province from the north, Azerbaijan's Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic exclave from the west, the "de facto" independent Nagorno-Karabakh Republic from the east, and Iran from the south. <s> Its capital and largest city is the town of Kapan. <s> The National Statistical Service of the Republic of Armenia (ARMSTAT) reported its population was 141,771 in the 2011 census, down from 152,684 at the 2001 census. <s> Historically, Syunik is supposed to be one of the 15 provinces of the ancient Kingdom of Armenia. <s> At various times, the region of present-day Syunik was also known by other names such as "Syunia", "Sisakan" and "Zangezur" (or "Zangadzor"). <s> However, the present-name of the province is derived from the ancient Armenian Siunia dynasty, who were the Nakharar (governors) of the historic province of Syunik since the 1st century. <s> According to the 2011 official census, Syunik has a population of 141,771 (69,836 men and 71,935 women), forming around 4.7% of the entire population of Armenia. <s> The urban population is 95,170 (67.13%) and the rural is 46,601 (32.87%). <s> The province has 7 urban and 102 rural communities. <s> The largest urban community is the provincial center of Kapan, with a population of 43,190. <s> The other urban centres are Goris, Sisian, Kajaran, Meghri, Agarak and Dastakert.
simple: Syunik is the southernmost province of Armenia. <s> It borders Iran to the south. <s> The capital is Kapan. <s> The National Statistical Service of the Republic of Armenia (ARMSTAT) reported its population was 152,900 in 2010. <s> Historically, Syunik was one of the 15 provinces of the Kingdom of Armenia. <s> There are 7 urban communities and 102 rural communities. <s> Other important cities and towns include Goris, Sisian, Meghri, Agarak, and Dastakert.

title: Malanje Province
complex: Malanje is a province of Angola. <s> It has an area of 97,602 km2 and a 2014 census population of 968,135. <s> Malanje is the capital of the province.
simple: Malanje is a province of Angola. <s> Malanje is the capital of the province.

title: Wilhelm Weinberg
complex: Wilhelm Weinberg (Stuttgart, 25 December 1862 – 27 November 1937, Tübingen) was a German obstetrician-gynecologist, practicing in Stuttgart, who in a 1908 paper, published in German in "Jahresheft des Vereins für vaterländische Naturkunde in Württemberg" (The Annals of the Society of National Natural History in Württemberg), expressed the concept that would later come to be known as the Hardy-Weinberg principle. <s> Weinberg is also credited as the first to explain the effect of ascertainment bias on observations in genetics. <s> Weinberg developed the principle of genetic equilibrium independently of British mathematician G.H. Hardy. <s> He delivered an exposition of his ideas in a lecture on January 13, 1908, before the "Verein für vaterländische Naturkunde in Württemberg" (Society for the Natural History of the Fatherland in Württemberg), about six months before Hardy's paper was published in English. <s> His lecture was printed later that year in the society's yearbook. <s> Weinberg's contributions were unrecognized in the English speaking world for more than 35 years. <s> Curt Stern, a German scientist who immigrated to the United States before World War II, pointed out in a brief paper in "Science" that Weinberg's exposition was both earlier and more comprehensive than Hardy's. <s> Before 1943, the concepts in genetic equilibrium that are known today as the Hardy-Weinberg principle had been known as "Hardy's law" or "Hardy's formula" in English-language texts. <s> Weinberg pioneered in studies of twins, developing techniques for analysis of phenotypic variation that partitioned this variance into genetic and environmental components. <s> In the process, he recognized that ascertainment bias was affecting many of his calculations, and he produced methods to correct for it. <s> Weinberg observed that proportions of homozygotes in familial studies of classic autosomal recessive genetic diseases generally exceed the expected Mendelian ratio of 1:4, and he explained how this is the result of ascertainment bias. <s> In his work with albino children, he recognized that in some families where both parents carry a recessive mutation, no disease occurs by chance. <s> He reasoned that many carrier couples were not being counted, and he demonstrated methods for correcting results to produce the expected Mendelian ratios. <s> He discovered the answer to several seeming paradoxes caused by ascertainment bias. <s> For example, he explained that the reason that parents as a whole are more fertile than their children is because children must necessarily come from fertile parents. <s> By the same token, he recognized that ascertainment was responsible for a phenomenon known as anticipation, the tendency for a genetic disease to manifest earlier in life and with increased severity in later generations. <s> Weinberg recognized that this was because those later generations were the offspring of that selected group of earlier carriers that had successfully reproduced. <s> Subsequent researchers have reasoned that such carriers who reproduce might be expected to carry favorable compensatory mutations that allowed them to reproduce successfully in spite of their disease. <s> In a class of autosomal and X-linked dominant diseases known as trinucleotide repeat disorders (for example, Huntington's disease), a molecular mechanism for anticipation has also been demonstrated. <s> It is caused by the instability of repeating nucleotide sequences that tend to undergo expansion, causing disease at an earlier and earlier age as trinucleotide repeats accumulate. <s> Weinberg was born in Stuttgart and studied medicine at Tübingen, Berlin and Munich, receiving an M.D. in 1886. <s> He returned to Stuttgart in 1889, where he remained running a large practice as a gynecologist and obstetrician until he retired to Tübingen a few years before his death in 1937. <s> Much of his academic life he spent studying genetics especially focusing on applying the laws of inheritance to populations. <s> Additional contributions by Weinberg to statistical genetics included the first estimate of the rate of twinning – Realizing that identical twins would have to be same-sex, while dizygotic twins could be either same or opposite sex, Weinberg derived the formula for estimating the frequency of monozygotic and dizygotic twins from the ratio of same sex and opposite twins to the total of maternities. <s> Weinberg also estimated that the heritability of twinning itself was close to zero.
simple: Wilhelm Weinberg (1862 – 1937) was a German Jewish physician who became an important geneticist. <s> He was a obstetrician and gynecologist, practising in Stuttgart. <s> In 1908, he expressed the principle which would later come to be known as the Hardy–Weinberg law. <s> Weinberg is also credited as the first to explain the effect of ascertainment bias on observations in genetics. <s> Weinberg developed the principle of genetic equilibrium independently of British mathematician G.H. Hardy. <s> He delivered an exposition of his ideas in a lecture on 13 January 1908, about six months before Hardy's paper was published in English. <s> His lecture was printed later that year in the society's yearbook. <s> Weinberg's contributions were unrecognized in the English speaking world for more than 35 years. <s> Curt Stern, a German geneticist who emigrated to the United States before World War II, pointed out in a brief paper in "Science" that Weinberg's exposition was both earlier and more comprehensive than Hardy's. <s> Weinberg pioneered studies of twins, and developed techniques to analyse phenotypic variation. <s> His aim was to partition this variance into genetic and environmental components. <s> In the process, he recognized that ascertainment bias was affecting many of his calculations, and he produced methods to correct for it. <s> Weinberg observed that proportions of homozygotes in familial studies of classic recessive genetic diseases generally exceed the expected Mendelian ratio of 1:4, and he explained how this is the result of ascertainment bias. <s> In his work with albino children, he recognized that in some families where both parents carry a recessive mutation, by chance no albino child occurs. <s> He reasoned that many carrier couples were not being counted, and he demonstrated methods for correcting results to produce the expected Mendelian ratios. <s> He discovered the answer to several seeming paradoxes caused by ascertainment bias. <s> For example, he explained that the reason that parents as a whole are more fertile than their children is because children must necessarily come from fertile parents. <s> By the same token, he recognized that ascertainment was responsible for a phenomenon known as "genetic anticipation", the tendency for a genetic disease to manifest earlier in life and with increased severity in later generations. <s> Weinberg recognized that this was because those later generations were the offspring of that selected group of earlier carriers that had successfully reproduced. <s> Weinberg was born in Stuttgart and studied medicine at Tübingen and Munich, receiving an M.D. in 1886. <s> He returned to Stuttgart in 1889, where he remained running a large practice as a gynecologist and obstetrician until he retired to Tübingen a few years before his death in 1937. <s> Much of his academic life was spent studying genetics, especially on applying the laws of inheritance in populations. <s> Additional contributions by Weinberg to statistical genetics included the first estimate of the rate of twinning. <s> Realizing that identical twins would have to be the same sex, while non-identical twins could be either same or opposite sex, Weinberg derived the formula for estimating the frequency of MZ and DZ twins from the ratio of same and opposite sex twins to the total of maternities. <s> Weinberg also estimated that the heritability of twinning itself was close to zero.

title: Lawrence County, Ohio
complex: Lawrence County is the southernmost county located in the U.S. state of Ohio. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 62,450. <s> Its county seat is Ironton. <s> The county was created in 1815 and later organized in 1817.
simple: Lawrence County is a county in the U.S. state of Ohio. <s> In 2010, 62,450 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Ironton.

title: Serbian language
complex: Serbian ( / , ] ) is the standardized variety of the Serbo-Croatian language mainly used by Serbs. <s> It is the official language of Serbia, co-official in the territory of Kosovo, and one of the three official languages of Bosnia and Herzegovina.
simple: Serbian is South Slavic language spoken by Serbs, primarily in Serbia, Kosovo, Montenegro and some parts of neighboring countries.

title: Luís de Camões
complex: Luís Vaz de Camões (] ; sometimes rendered in English as Camoens or Camoëns, e.g. by Byron in "English Bards and Scotch Reviewers", ; c. 1524 or 1525 – 20 June O.S. 10 June 1580 ) is considered Portugal's and the Portuguese language's greatest poet. <s> His mastery of verse has been compared to that of Shakespeare, Vondel, Homer, Virgil and Dante. <s> He wrote a considerable amount of lyrical poetry and drama but is best remembered for his epic work "Os Lusíadas" ("The Lusiads"). <s> His collection of poetry "The Parnasum of Luís de Camões" was lost in his lifetime. <s> The influence of his masterpiece "Os Lusíadas" is so profound that Portuguese is sometimes called the "language of Camões".
simple: Luís Vaz de Camões (c. 1524 – June 10, 1580) was Portugal's greatest poet. <s> He has been compared to Homer, Virgil, Dante, Cervantes or Shakespeare. <s> He wrote lyrical poetry (in Portuguese and in Spanish) and drama but is best remembered for his epic work "Os Lusíadas". <s> (His philosophical work "The Parnasum of Luís Vaz" was lost, stolen with part of "Os Lusíadas" by envious enemies while he was staying at Mozambique.)

title: Tarn (river)
complex: The Tarn ( , , possibly meaning 'rapid' or 'walled in') is a 381 km long river in southern France ("régions" Languedoc-Roussillon and Midi-Pyrénées), right tributary of the Garonne.
simple: The Tarn is a river in southern France, tributary of the Garonne river. <s> The Tarn river has a length of 380.6 km and a drainage basin with an area of 15700 km2.

title: David Usher
complex: David Usher (born April 24, 1966) is a British-born Canadian musician, best-selling author, keynote speaker, and activist best known as the front man for the band Moist. <s> He has also released a number of solo albums. <s> David Usher was born in Oxford, England to Thai Buddhist artist Samphan Usher and a Jewish man from Montreal. <s> He has lived in various places such as Malaysia, New York City, California, and Thailand since early childhood, before his family settled in Kingston, Ontario. <s> He attended high school at Kingston Collegiate and Vocational Institute. <s> Usher attended Simon Fraser University in Burnaby, British Columbia, majoring in political science. <s> While studying in Vancouver, Usher helped form the second incarnation of a band called Moist, composed of Usher on vocals, Mark Makoway on guitars, Jeff Pearce on bass, Kevin Young, who, like Usher, had moved to Vancouver from Kingston, on keyboards, and Paul Wilcox on drums. <s> Usher became the principal songwriter for the band. <s> Usher has been involved in the causes War Child Canada, White Ribbon Campaign, and Amnesty International. <s> He is featured in the 2001 MuchMusic special "Musicians in the WarZone", a humanitarian documentary directed by filmmaker Liz Marshall, in which he journeys to the northern border of Thailand to visit a large Burmese refugee community. <s> Usher is on the advisory board of McGill University’s Institute for the Public Life of Art and Ideas, and is the founding director of Amnesty International’s Artists for Amnesty.
simple: David Usher (born April 24, 1966) is an British-born Canadian rock singer-songwriter. <s> Usher was born in Oxford, England. <s> He lived in many different places such as Malaysia, New York City, California and Thailand before his family decided to finally settle in Kingston, Ontario. <s> Usher attended high school at Kingston Collegiate and Vocational Institute and he attended Simon Fraser University in Burnaby, British Columbia. <s> He majored in political science. <s> While attending Simon Fraser, Usher formed Moist with guitarist Mark Makowy and keyboardist Kevin Young. <s> Usher is also a humanist, and he has been involved in causes like War Child Canada, White Ribbon Campaign and Amnesty International. <s> He was featured in the 2001 MuchMusic special "Musicians in the WarZone", a humanitarian documentary which was produced by War Child Canada and was directed by filmmaker Liz Marshall.

title: Ben Smith (ice hockey, born 1988)
complex: Benjamin Alexander Smith (born July 11, 1988) is an American professional ice hockey player currently playing for Adler Mannheim in the Deutsche Eishockey Liga (DEL). <s> He previously played in the National Hockey League (NHL) for the Chicago Blackhawks, San Jose Sharks, Toronto Maple Leafs and the Colorado Avalanche. <s> Smith graduated from Westminster School in 2006 and played four seasons at Boston College. <s> While playing for Boston College, Smith was drafted by the Chicago Blackhawks 169th overall in the sixth round of the 2008 NHL Entry Draft. <s> On October 29, 2010 the Blackhawks recalled Smith from the AHL's Rockford IceHogs to make his NHL debut in a home game against the Edmonton Oilers. <s> He scored his first NHL goal on April 8, 2011 against Jimmy Howard of the Detroit Red Wings. <s> On April 15, 2011, Smith scored 2 goals against the Vancouver Canucks in a 4–3 loss in only his second NHL playoff game. <s> On Sunday, April 24, 2011, during Game 6 of the Western Conference quarterfinals, Smith scored the overtime goal on a rebound against the Vancouver Canucks' goaltender, Roberto Luongo, to force a Game 7 in Vancouver after the Canucks had previously been leading the series 3–0. <s> The Blackhawks ended up losing Game 7 in overtime. <s> On June 17, 2013, Smith was called up to play his first Stanley Cup Finals game, a 2–0 loss to the Boston Bruins, to fill in over the injured Marián Hossa. <s> The Blackhawks won the Cup on June 24, 2013, when they defeated the Bruins in Game 6. <s> On June 27, 2014, the Blackhawks signed him to a two-year contract extension. <s> In the following season, Smith scored four goals in 19 playoff games to help the Blackhawks advance to the Western Conference finals. <s> On March 2, 2015, Smith was traded by the Blackhawks to the San Jose Sharks in exchange for Andrew Desjardins. <s> He scored his first goal with the Sharks the same day in their shutout game against the Montreal Canadiens, but remained for most of the season with the Sharks' AHL affiliate San Jose Barracuda.
simple: Ben Smith (born July 11, 1988) is an American professional ice hockey right winger. <s> He currently plays for the San Jose Sharks of the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> He has also played for the Chicago Blackhawks. <s> He has also played ice hockey in college at Boston College with the Eagles. <s> He made his NHL debut with the Blackhawks on October 29, 2010 against the Edmonton Oilers. <s> He scored 2 goals on April 15, 2011 against the Vancouver Canucks in his second NHL playoff game. <s> On April 24, 2011, Smith scored the overtime goal on a rebound by Niklas Hjalmarsson against the Vancouver Canucks' goaltender, Roberto Luongo, to force a Game 7 in Vancouver. <s> On June 24, 2013, He won the Stanley Cup with the Blackhawks after they defeated the Boston Bruins 4 games to 2 in the 2013 Stanley Cup Finals. <s> On March 2, 2015, the Blackhawks traded Smith to the San Jose Sharks in exchange for Andrew Desjardins.

title: Champaign County, Illinois
complex: Champaign County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> As of the 2010 census, its population was 201,081, making it the 10th-most populous county in Illinois. <s> Its county seat is Urbana. <s> Champaign County was organized in 1833, having been previously a part of Vermilion County. <s> The county and county seat were named for Champaign County, Ohio and Urbana, Ohio respectively, the homeplace of the Illinois legislator who sponsored the bill to create the county.
simple: Champaign County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 201,081, making it the 10th-most populous county in Illinois. <s> The county seat is Urbana. <s> Champaign County was founded in 1833.

title: Fuzzy Knight
complex: John Forrest "Fuzzy" Knight (May 9, 1901 – February 23, 1976) was an American film and television actor. <s> He was also a singer, especially in his early career. <s> He appeared in more than 180 films between 1928 and 1967, usually as a cowboy hero's comic sidekick. <s> Knight became famous to a new generation when he co-starred as Buster Crabbe's sidekick (using his own name as Private Fuzzy Knight) on the 1955 television series "Captain Gallant of the Foreign Legion". <s> In semi-retirement thereafter, Knight continued to make occasional appearances in films and TV shows through 1967. <s> He died in his sleep at the Motion Picture Country House and Hospital in Woodland Hills, California, and was survived by his wife, actress Patricia Ryan (née Thelma de Long). <s> He was buried in Valhalla Memorial Park Cemetery in Burbank, California.
simple: John Forrest "Fuzzy" Knight (May 9, 1901 – February 23, 1976) was an American actor. <s> He appeared mostly in westerns, usually as the hero's friend. <s> He also appeared in the 1950s television series, "Captain Gallant of the Foreign Legion". <s> He married actress Patricia Ryan (née Thelma de Long).

title: Lonely Hearts (1991 film)
complex: Lonely Hearts is a 1991 American thriller film written and directed by Andrew Lane and starring Eric Roberts and Beverly D'Angelo. <s> A lonely woman who becomes obsessed with a con man. <s> She even poses as his sister to help him trick other women.
simple: Lonely Hearts is a 1991 American drama, romance, mystery & suspense television movie. <s> It was directed by Andrew Lane. <s> Lonely Hearts is about a lonely woman who becomes obsessed with a con man. <s> She even poses as his sister to help him trick other women.

title: Seychelles at the Olympics
complex: Seychelles first participated at the Olympic Games in 1980, and has sent athletes to compete in most Summer Olympic Games since then, missing only the 1988 Games when Seychelles did not respond to the invitation sent by the IOC. <s> The nation has never participated in the Winter Olympic Games. <s> To date, no Seychellois athlete has ever won an Olympic medal. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Seychelles was created in 1979 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee that same year.
simple: Seychelles was first at the Olympic Games in 1980. <s> They have been in most Summer Olympic Games since then, missing only the 1988 Games in support of North Korea. <s> The nation has never been in the Winter Olympic Games. <s> As of 2011, no Seychellois athlete has won an Olympic medal. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Seychelles was created in 1979. <s> They were recognized by the International Olympic Committee that same year.

title: Communications-based train control
complex: Communications-based train control (CBTC) is a railway signaling system that makes use of the telecommunications between the train and track equipment for the traffic management and infrastructure control. <s> By means of the CBTC systems, the exact position of a train is known more accurately than with the traditional signaling systems. <s> This results in a more efficient and safe way to manage the railway traffic. <s> Metros (and other railway systems) are able to improve headways while maintaining or even improving safety.
simple: Communications-based train control (CBTC) is a railway signaling system that makes use of telecommunications between the train and track equipment. <s> By means of a CBTC system, the exact position of a train is known more accurately than with the traditional signaling systems. <s> This results in a more efficient and safe way to manage trains. <s> Metros (and other railway systems) are able to run more frequent trains while maintaining or even improving safety.

title: Keytar
complex: The keytar is a relatively lightweight synthesizer that is supported by a strap around the neck and shoulders, similar to the way a guitar is supported by a strap. <s> Keytars allow players a greater range of movement onstage, compared to conventional keyboards, which are placed on stationary stands or which are part of heavy, floor-mounted structures. <s> The instrument has a musical keyboard for triggering musical notes and sounds. <s> Various controls are placed on the instrument's "neck", including those for pitch bends, vibrato, portamento, and sustain.
simple: Keytars are lightweight keyboards that have a strap that is put around the neck and shoulders. <s> The instrument has a keyboard for playing musical notes and sounds.

title: Presbyterian Church in Canada
complex: The Presbyterian Church in Canada is a Presbyterian denomination, serving in Canada under this name since 1875. <s> The United Church of Canada claimed the right to the name from 1925 to 1939. <s> According to the Canada 2001 Census 409,830 Canadians identify themselves as Presbyterian, that is, 1.4% of the population. <s> The Canadian roots of the Presbyterian Church in Canada can be traced to both Scottish settlers and French Huguenots, and the first Presbyterian churches formed in the late 16th and early 17th centuries, following such European Protestant Reformation theologians as John Calvin and John Knox. <s> Once the largest Christian denomination in English-speaking Canada, in 1925 some 70% of its congregations joined with the Methodist Church, Canada and the Congregationalist Union to form the "United Church of Canada." <s> The terms "Continuing Presbyterians" and "Non-Concurring Presbyterians" were then used by those who did not participate in the merger, until the legal right to use the name "Presbyterian Church in Canada" was regained in 1939. <s> The Supreme Court of Canada ruled that although the institutional Presbyterian Church in Canada may legally have merged with the Methodist Church, the United Church had effectively vacated the name and it remained available to the non-concurring Presbyterians.
simple: The Presbyterian Church in Canada is a Protestant Christian denomination in Canada. <s> The four denominations merged in 1875 as the Presbyterian Church in Canada. <s> Presbyterian churches in Canada were started in the late 16th century by Scottish and French Huguenots immigrants. <s> In 1925, 70% of the Presbyterian congregations merged into the United Church of Canada. <s> The Presbyterians who did not join in the union continued using the name Presbyterian Church in Canada.

title: Hispanidad
complex: ] Hispanidad (] , "Hispanicity") is an expression with several meanings, loosely alluding to the group of people, countries and communities sharing the Spanish language and displaying a Spanish-related culture. <s> The term traces back to the early modern period but was redefined by Spanish philosopher Miguel de Unamuno in 1909.
simple: Hispanidad (literally Hispanicness) is the community formed by all the people and nations that share Spanish language and culture.

title: Epic Movie
complex: Epic Movie is a 2007 American parody comedy film directed and written by Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer and produced by Paul Schiff. <s> It was made in a similar style to "Date Movie", Friedberg and Seltzer's previous film, but as a spoof of the "Epic" style of films, hence the name. <s> The film mostly references "", the "Harry Potter" films, Tim Burton's version of "Charlie and the Chocolate Factory", "Pirates of the Caribbean", and "". <s> The song "Ms. New Booty" by Bubba Sparxxx gained commercial attention for being featured in "Epic Movie". <s> Many have considered this to be one of the worst films of all time. <s> "Epic Movie" debuted at number one at the box office with a gross of $18.6 million over the opening weekend. <s> As of May 8, 2007, the film has grossed $86,865,564, with $39,739,367 of that amount earned domestically, despite negative reviews from critics. <s> The film was an economic success for its producers not least because it had a comparatively low budget, estimated at $20 million (the same as "Date Movie").
simple: Epic Movie is a 2007 American parody movie directed and written by Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer. <s> It was made by Paul Schiff. <s> It was made in a similar style to "Date Movie", Friedberg and Seltzer's movie before they made this one. <s> The movie mostly references "" and Tim Burton's version of "Charlie and the Chocolate Factory". <s> "Epic Movie" started at number 1 at the box office. <s> It made $18.6 million over the first weekend. <s> As of May 8, 2007 the movie made $86,865,564 and received generally negative reviews.

title: Sofia Rotaru
complex: Sofiya Mykhaylivna Yevdokymenko-Rotaru (born 7 August 1947), known as Sofia Rotaru ( ] ; ; Romanian: "Sofia Rotaru"), is a former Soviet and Ukrainian pop singer.
simple: Sofia Mihailovna Evdokimenko-Rotaru (born in Marshintsy, Novoselitskiy Rayon, Chernivtsi Oblast, Ukraine on August 7, 1947), simply known as Sofia Rotaru, is a popular Russian, Ukrainian, Moldavian and formerly Soviet singer, actress and producer.

title: Piet Steenkamp
complex: Petrus Antonius Josephus Maria "Piet" Steenkamp (8 March 1925 – 8 January 2016) was a Dutch politician of the Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA) party. <s> He played an important role in the formation of the party and is therefore referred to as the father of the CDA. <s> He was president of the Dutch Senate from 1983 to 1991. <s> He was succeeded by Herman Tjeenk Willink. <s> He died in Eindhoven, Noord-Brabant on 8 January 2016, 90 years old.
simple: Petrus Antonius Josephus Maria "Piet" Steenkamp (8 March 1925 – 8 January 2016) was a Dutch politician and economist. <s> He was a member of the Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA), which he co-founded. <s> He was President of the Senate from 1983 to 1991. <s> Steenkamp died on 8 January 2016 in Eindhoven, North Brabant, aged 90.

title: Stratford Festival
complex: The Stratford Festival is a theatre festival which runs from April to October in the city of Stratford, Ontario, Canada. <s> Founded by local journalist Tom Patterson in 1952, the festival was formerly known as the Stratford Shakespearean Festival, the Shakespeare Festival and the Stratford Shakespeare Festival.
simple: The Stratford Festival, formerly called the Stratford Shakespeare Festival, is an annual theatre festival held in Stratford, Ontario, Canada. <s> It runs from April to October.

title: Alex (footballer, born 1982)
complex: Alex Rodrigo Dias da Costa, better known as Alex (] ; born 17 June 1982), is a retired Brazilian footballer who played as a central defender. <s> He was known for his physical strength and the power of his shot, which has gained him the nicknames of "The Tank" and "Canhão da Vila" ("Cannon of Vila Belmiro").
simple: Alex Rodrigo Dias da Costa (born 17 June 1982) is a Brazilian football player.

title: Sergio Marchionne
complex: Sergio Marchionne (] ; June 17, 1952 – July 25, 2018) was an Italian-Canadian businessman, widely known for his turnarounds of the automakers Fiat and Chrysler, his business acumen and his outspoken and often frank approach, especially when dealing with unpalatable issues related to his companies and the automotive industry. <s> Marchionne was the chairman of CNH Industrial, the chief executive officer (CEO) of Fiat Chrysler Automobiles, the chairman and CEO of FCA US LLC, the chairman and CEO of Ferrari, and the chairman of Maserati. <s> He was the chairman of Swiss-based SGS and vice chairman of UBS from 2008 to 2010, as well as the chairman of the European Automobile Manufacturers Association for 2012 (first elected in January 2006). <s> He was a member of the Peterson Institute for International Economics, and the chairman of the Italian branch of the Council for the United States and Italy. <s> Following complications from surgery, Marchionne resigned from all of his positions in July 2018 and died a few days later. <s> The American business channel CNBC described Marchionne as a "legend of automotive industry", while the British newspaper "Financial Times" considered him as having been "one of the boldest business leaders of his generation". <s> Marchionne was born in Chieti, Abruzzo, Italy, the son of Concezio Marchionne, from Cugnoli (Abruzzo), and Maria Zuccon from Carnizza (today Krnica, Croatia) near Pula in Istria. <s> His father served as a "Carabiniere" in Istria, where he met his future wife. <s> Marchionne's grandfather, Giacomo Zuccon, was killed in September 1943 by Yugoslav Partisans near Barban in Istria, while his uncle Giuseppe Zuccon was killed by the Nazis the same year. <s> In 1945, when the region was occupied by the Yugoslav army, Marchionne's parents moved to Chieti in Abruzzo, where Sergio was born. <s> He died on July 25, 2018, at age 66, most likely from complications related to underlying cancer. <s> Some reports claimed he had suffered from an invasive shoulder cancer.
simple: Sergio Marchionne (]; June 17, 1952 – July 25, 2018) was an Italian-Canadian businessman. <s> Marchionne was the chairman of CNH Industrial, the chief executive officer (CEO) of Fiat Chrysler Automobiles, the chairman and CEO of FCA US LLC, the chairman and CEO of Ferrari, and the chairman of Maserati. <s> He was the chairman of Swiss-based SGS and vice chairman of UBS from 2008 to 2010, as well as the chairman of the European Automobile Manufacturers Association for 2012 (first elected in January 2006). <s> He was a member of the Peterson Institute for International Economics, and the chairman of the Italian branch of the Council for the United States and Italy. <s> In June 2018, Marchionne underwent shoulder surgery after suffering from pain in that area. <s> He was born in Chieti, Italy and raised in Toronto, Ontario. <s> Following complications from surgery he died on July 25, 2018 in Zurich at the age of 66.

title: Stella Turk
complex: Stella Maris Turk, MBE (1925 – 3 April 2017) was a British zoologist, naturalist, and conservationist. <s> She was known for her activities in marine biology and conservation, particularly as it applies to marine molluscs and mammals. <s> Turk became a Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire in 2002, and was awarded the Stamford Raffles Award by the Zoological Society of London in 1979.
simple: Stella Maris Turk, MBE (1925 – 3 April 2017) was a British zoologist, naturalist, and conservationist. <s> Turk was known for her activities in marine biology and conservation as it applies to marine molluscs and mammals. <s> Turk became a Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire in 2002, and was awarded the Stamford Raffles Award by the Zoological Society of London in 1979.

title: Ambutrix
complex: Ambutrix (pronounced ɑ̃.by.t̪ʁiks) is a French commune in the Ain department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region of eastern France. <s> The inhabitants of the commune are known as "Butrians" or "Butrianes". <s> The commune takes its name from the presence of Celtic people called Ambarri in the region.
simple: Ambutrix is a commune. <s> It is found in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region in the Ain department in the east of France. <s> The inhabitants are the "Butrians". <s> The name of the commune comes from a Celtic tribe which lived in the area called the "Ambarres".

title: Franz Vranitzky
complex: Franz Vranitzky (born 4 October 1937) is an Austrian politician. <s> A member of the Social Democratic Party of Austria (SPÖ), he was Chancellor of Austria from 1986 to 1997. <s> In 1984, Vranitzky joined the SPÖ-Freedom Party (FPÖ) government coalition under Chancellor Fred Sinowatz as minister of finance. <s> He was criticized for receiving multiple compensations from his various functions in government-run businesses. <s> Vranitzky chairs the quarterly "Vranitzky colloquia", organised by the study group WiWiPol, which discusses economic topics and their impact on Austria and Europe. <s> He is a former member of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group.
simple: Franz Vranitzky (born 4 October 1937) is an Austrian politician. <s> He is a member of the Social Democratic Party of Austria (SPÖ), he was Chancellor of Austria from 1986 to 1997. <s> In 1984, Vranitzky joined the SPÖ-Freedom Party (FPÖ) government coalition under Chancellor Fred Sinowatz as minister of finance. <s> He is a former member of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group.

title: Erlenmeyer flask
complex: An Erlenmeyer flask, also known as a conical flask (BrE) or a titration flask, is a type of laboratory flask which features a flat bottom, a conical body, and a cylindrical neck. <s> It is named after the German chemist Emil Erlenmeyer (1825–1909), who created it in 1860. <s> Erlenmeyer flasks are also used in microbiology for the preparation of microbial cultures. <s> Erlenmeyer flasks used in cell culture are sterilized and may feature vented closures to enhance gas exchange during incubation and shaking. <s> The use of minimal liquid volumes, typically no more than one fifth of the total flask volume, and baffles molded into the flask's internal surface both serve to maximize gas transfer and promote chaotic mixing when the flasks are orbitally shaken.
simple: An Erlenmeyer flask or conical flask is a kind of flask with a base in the shape of a cone and a short neck. <s> It was first invented in 1861 by a German chemist named Richard Erlenmeyer. <s> Erlenmeyer Flasks are used in laboratories.

title: Thomas Müller
complex: Thomas Müller (] ; born 13 September 1989) is a German professional footballer who plays for and vice-captains Bayern Munich, and has made 100 appearances for the German national team. <s> A versatile player, Müller plays as a midfielder or forward, and has been deployed in a variety of attacking roles – as an attacking midfielder, second striker, centre forward and on either wing. <s> He has been praised for his positioning, teamwork and stamina, work-rate, and has shown consistency in both scoring and creating goals. <s> Müller's role can be described as an attacking all-rounder, a player able to play in a variety of forward positions.
simple: Thomas Müller (born 13 September 1989) is a German football player. <s> He plays for FC Bayern Munich and Germany national team. <s> Müller can play as both a forward and midfielder. <s> Müller is known for his great positioning, team work and stamina.

title: Alma Adamkienė
complex: Alma Adamkienė (née Nutautaitė; February 10, 1927) is a Lithuanian-American philologist and philanthropist. <s> She is the wife of the former President of Lithuania, Valdas Adamkus, and was First Lady during his two terms (1998–2003 and 2004–2009). <s> She also holds United States citizenship. <s> Adamkienė was born in Šiauliai. <s> Her father, Stasys Nutautas, was a businessman; her mother, Ona Soblytė-Nutautienė, assisted her husband in various commercial activities. <s> In 1944, when the Soviet Army returned to Lithuania, Alma Nutautaitė fled with her family to the West. <s> She finished high school in Germany, and later studied Philology at Erlangen University in Nuremberg. <s> Alma Nutautaitė emigrated to the United States of America in 1949. <s> She first worked as a laboratory assistant at a steel factory. <s> Later, she took a position with an insurance company. <s> She also organized and participated in Lithuanian émigré activities. <s> Alma Nutautaitė married Valdas Adamkus in 1951, and took her husband's surname (she is known as Alma Adamkus in the United States). <s> During the presidential election held in Lithuania in 1997, Valdas Adamkus campaigned for the Presidency and won. <s> After Adamkus became President, Adamkienė became involved in various Lithuanian social programs focusing on the welfare of children. <s> She opened a foundation, the Alma Adamkienė Charity and Support Fund, in 1999.
simple: Alma Adamkienė (née Nutautaitė; February 10, 1928) is a Lithuanian-American philologist, philanthropist and public servant. <s> She is the wife of the former President of Lithuania, Valdas Adamkus since being married in 1951. <s> Adamkienė was First Lady during his two terms (1998–2003 and 2004–2009). <s> She also holds United States citizenship. <s> She was born in Šiauliai, Lithuania. <s> She immigrated to the United States in 1949. <s> She first worked as a laboratory assistant at a steel factory. <s> Later, she took a position with an insurance company. <s> She also organized and participated in Lithuanian émigré activities. <s> During the presidential election held in Lithuania in 1997, her husband Valdas Adamkus campaigned for the Presidency and won. <s> After Adamkus became President, Adamkienė became involved in many Lithuanian social programs focusing on the welfare of children.

title: Ellen DeGeneres
complex: Ellen Lee DeGeneres ( ; born January 26, 1958) is an American comedian, television host, actress, writer, and producer. <s> She starred in the popular sitcom "Ellen" from 1994 to 1998 and has hosted her syndicated TV talk show, "The Ellen DeGeneres Show," since 2003. <s> She starred in two television sitcoms, "Ellen" from 1994 to 1998, and "The Ellen Show" from 2001 to 2002. <s> During the fourth season of "Ellen" in 1997, she came out as a lesbian in an appearance on "The Oprah Winfrey Show". <s> Her character, Ellen Morgan, also came out to a therapist played by Winfrey, and the series went on to explore various LGBT issues, including the coming-out process. <s> In 2008, she married her longtime girlfriend Portia de Rossi. <s> DeGeneres was born and raised in Metairie, Louisiana, to Elizabeth Jane (née Pfeffer, born 1930), a speech therapist, and Elliott Everett DeGeneres (c.1925–2018), an insurance agent. <s> She has one brother, Vance, a musician and producer. <s> She is of French, English, German, and Irish descent. <s> She was raised as a Christian Scientist. <s> In 1973, her parents filed for separation and were divorced the following year. <s> Shortly after, Ellen's mother married Roy Gruessendorf, a salesman. <s> Betty Jane and Ellen moved with Gruessendorf from the New Orleans area to Atlanta, Texas. <s> Vance stayed with his father. <s> On a February 2011 episode of her show, she told her studio audience of a letter from the New England Historic Genealogical Society confirming she is 15th cousin to Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge, via their shared common ancestor Thomas Fairfax. <s> When she was 15 or 16 years old, she was molested by her stepfather. <s> DeGeneres graduated from Atlanta High School in May 1976, after completing her first years of high school at Grace King High School in Metairie, Louisiana. <s> She moved back to New Orleans to attend the University of New Orleans, where she majored in communication studies. <s> After one semester, she left school to do clerical work in a law firm with a cousin, Laura Gillen. <s> Her early jobs included working at J. C. Penney, and being a waitress at TGI Fridays and another restaurant, a house painter, a hostess, and a bartender. <s> She relates much of her childhood and career experiences in her comedic work. <s> A selfie orchestrated by 86th Academy Awards host Ellen DeGeneres during the broadcast is the second-most retweeted tweet ever. <s> DeGeneres said she wanted to homage Meryl Streep's record 17 Oscar nominations by setting a new record with her, and invited other Oscar celebrities to join them. <s> The resulting photo of twelve celebrities broke the previous retweet record within forty minutes and was retweeted over 1.8 million times in the first hour. <s> By the end of the ceremony it had been retweeted over 2 million times, less than 24 hours later, it had been retweeted over 2.8 million times. <s> s of May 2017 , it has been retweeted over 3.4 million times. <s> The group selfie effort was parodied by Lego and Matt Groening with The Simpsons. <s> It beat the previous record, which was held by Barack Obama, following his victory in the 2012 presidential election. <s> She is a fan of the National Football League and has shown particular support for the New Orleans Saints and the Green Bay Packers. <s> In 2011, she attended a Saints practice dressed as Packers Hall of Famer Don Hutson. <s> In 1997, DeGeneres came out as lesbian. <s> The disclosure of her sexual orientation sparked intense interest by American tabloids. <s> The contentiousness of the media coverage stunted DeGeneres' professional career and left her "mired in depression". <s> In her book "Love, Ellen", DeGeneres' mother, Betty DeGeneres describes being initially shocked when her daughter came out, but she has since become one of her strongest supporters; she is also an active member of Parents & Friends of Lesbians and Gays (PFLAG) and spokesperson for the Human Rights Campaign's Coming Out Project. <s> Since 2004, DeGeneres has had a relationship with Portia de Rossi. <s> After the overturn of the same-sex marriage ban in California, DeGeneres and de Rossi were engaged, and married in August 2008, at their home in Beverly Hills, California, where they live with their four dogs and three cats. <s> The passage of Proposition 8 cast doubt on the legal status of their marriage, but a subsequent California Supreme Court judgment validated it because it occurred before November 4, 2008. <s> On August 6, 2010, de Rossi filed a petition to legally change her name to Portia Lee James DeGeneres. <s> The petition was granted on September 23, 2010. <s> In November 2011, Secretary of State Hillary Clinton named her a special envoy for Global AIDS Awareness. <s> On December 3, 2011, DeGeneres opened the show at the David Lynch Foundation's 3rd annual "Change Begins Within" gala at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art to raise funds to bring Transcendental Meditation to at-risk populations suffering from epidemic levels of chronic stress and stress-related disorders.
simple: Ellen DeGeneres (born January 26, 1958) is an American stand-up comedian, television host and actress. <s> She is the host of the talk show "The Ellen DeGeneres Show". <s> She starred in two television sitcoms, "Ellen" from 1994 to 1998 and "The Ellen Show" from 2001 to 2002. <s> DeGeneres was born and raised in Metairie, Louisiana. <s> She is the daughter of Elizabeth Jane "Betty" Pfeffer DeGeneres, a speech therapist, and Elliott Everett DeGeneres, an insurance agent. <s> She has one brother, Vance. <s> Her brother is a musician and producer. <s> She is of French, English, German, and Irish ancestry. <s> She was raised as a Christian Scientist until age 13. <s> In 1973, her parents filed for separation and were divorced the following year. <s> Shortly after, Ellen's mother married Roy Gruessendorf, a salesman. <s> Betty Jane and Ellen moved with Gruessendorf from the New Orleans area to Atlanta, Texas. <s> Vance stayed with his father. <s> On a February 9, 2011, episode of "The Ellen DeGeneres Show", DeGeneres shared a letter from the New England Historic Genealogical Society. <s> It said that she is Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge's 15th cousin via their shared common ancestor Thomas Fairfax. <s> DeGeneres graduated from Atlanta High School in May 1976. <s> Her first years of high school were at Grace King High School in Metairie, Louisiana. <s> She moved back to New Orleans to attend the University of New Orleans, where she majored in communication studies. <s> After one semester, she left school to do clerical work in a law firm with a cousin, Laura Gillen. <s> Her early jobs included working at J. C. Penney, being a waitress at TGI Friday's and another restaurant, a house painter, a hostess, and a bartender. <s> She talks about her experiences as a child and at work in her comedic work. <s> DeGeneres took a selfie at the 86th Academy Awards in 2014 with actors such as Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie, Bradley Cooper, Jared Leto, and Lupita Nyong'o. <s> It became the most retweeted image ever on Twitter, with over 3 million retweets. <s> She is a fan of the National Football League, and has shown particular support for the New Orleans Saints and the Green Bay Packers. <s> In 2011, she attended a Saints practice dressed as Packers Hall of Famer Don Hutson. <s> During the fourth season of "Ellen" in 1997, DeGeneres came out publicly as a lesbian in an appearance on "The Oprah Winfrey Show". <s> Since 2004, DeGeneres has been in a relationship with Australian actress Portia de Rossi. <s> They were married on August 16, 2008. <s> In November 2011, then-Secretary of State Hillary Clinton named her a Special Envoy for Global AIDS Awareness.

title: Uhrichsville, Ohio
complex: Uhrichsville is a city in Tuscarawas County, Ohio, United States. <s> The population was 5,413 at the 2010 census. <s> Claymont City School District is the major education provider for the city of Uhrichsville and for the village of Dennison, Ohio. <s> The Twin cities is a nickname used to describe Uhrichsville and Dennison because they are adjacent and similar. <s> Uhrichsville Water Park opened in June 2008. <s> It is heated and features slides, waterfalls, buckets, and a water jungle-gym.

title: Carlit
complex: Henry Russell is known to have made the first ascent of the Pic Carlit in 1864, where he was fascinated by the beautiful view of the Étang du Lanoux, the biggest lake of the Pyrénées.

title: James Corden
complex: James Kimberley Corden (born 22 August 1978) is an English actor, singer, comedian, and television host. <s> He hosts "The Late Late Show with James Corden", a late-night television talk show on CBS. <s> Along with Welsh actress Ruth Jones, Corden co-created, co-wrote and starred in the critically acclaimed BBC sitcom "Gavin & Stacey" (2007–2010; 2019) for which he won the BAFTA Television Award for Best Comedy Performance.
simple: James Kimberley Corden, OBE (born 22 August 1978) is an English actor, writer, producer, comedian, and television host. <s> He currently hosts the late-night television talk show "The Late Late Show with James Corden" on CBS.

title: Polyhydroxyalkanoates
complex: Polyhydroxyalkanoates or PHAs are polyesters produced in nature by numerous microorganisms, including through bacterial fermentation of sugar or lipids. <s> When produced by bacteria they serve as both a source of energy and as a carbon store.
simple: Polyhydroxyalkanoate (PHA) is a biopolymer that is made by bacteria.

title: Beauvau family
complex: Beauvau was a historic family originating in Anjou. <s> The Beauvau du Rivau branch was rooted in Brittany and produced two bishops of Nantes, whilst the Craon (Prince of Craon) branch was established in Lorraine later enjoying great intimacy with the then reigning ducal family. <s> Of knightly extraction, has proofs of its nobility going back as far as 1265. <s> The title of marquis of Beauvau was granted to the head of the family by Louis XIV in 1664. <s> The family also had rights to the prestigious title of "cousin du Roi", reserved for a few families with an alliance with the royal house. <s> Marc de Beauvau, Prince of Craon (1679–1754) was entitled prince of the Holy Roman Empire in 1722, and it was under this title that the family was admitted to the "honneurs de la Cour" in 1775.
simple: The House of Beauvau was a noble family that originated from Anjou a region of France. <s> The Beauvau du Rivau branch was rooted in Brittany. <s> It produced two bishops of Nantes. <s> The Craon (Prince of Craon) branch was established in Lorraine. <s> This branch was intimate with the then reigning ducal family. <s> Of knightly extraction, it has proofs of its nobility going back as far as 1265. <s> The title of marquis of Beauvau was granted to the head of the family by Louis XIV in 1664. <s> The family also had rights to the prestigious title of "cousin du Roi", reserved for a few families with an alliance with the royal house. <s> Marc de Beauvau, Prince of Craon (1679–1754) was entitled prince of the Holy Roman Empire in 1722, and it was under this title that the family was admitted to the "honneurs de la Cour" in 1775. <s> The princely title of Prince of Craon was a title used by the Beauvau family using their status as Prince of the Holy Roman Empire which was gained in 1722.

title: Thomas County, Nebraska
complex: Thomas County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 647. <s> Its county seat is Thedford. <s> The county was formed in 1887, and was named for General George H. Thomas.

title: Divisor
complex: In mathematics, a divisor of an integer formula_1, also called a factor of formula_1, is an integer formula_3 that may be multiplied by some integer to produce formula_1. <s> In this case, one also says that formula_1 is a multiple of formula_6 An integer formula_1 is divisible by another integer formula_3 if formula_3 is a divisor of formula_1; this implies dividing formula_1 by formula_3 leaves no remainder. <s> Divisors can be negative as well as positive, although sometimes the term is restricted to positive divisors. <s> For example, there are six divisors of 4; they are 1, 2, 4, −1, −2, and −4, but only the positive ones (1, 2, and 4) would usually be mentioned. <s> 1 and −1 divide (are divisors of) every integer. <s> Every integer (and its negation) is a divisor of itself. <s> Integers divisible by 2 are called even, and integers not divisible by 2 are called odd. <s> 1, −1, "n" and −"n" are known as the trivial divisors of "n". <s> A divisor of "n" that is not a trivial divisor is known as a non-trivial divisor ( or strict divisor ) . <s> A non-zero integer with at least one non-trivial divisor is known as a composite number, while the units −1 and 1 and prime numbers have no non-trivial divisors. <s> There are divisibility rules that allow one to recognize certain divisors of a number from the number's digits. <s> The total number of positive divisors of formula_1 is a multiplicative function formula_63, meaning that when two numbers formula_3 and formula_1 are relatively prime, then formula_66. <s> For instance, formula_67; the eight divisors of 42 are 1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 14, 21 and 42. <s> However, the number of positive divisors is not a totally multiplicative function: if the two numbers formula_3 and formula_1 share a common divisor, then it might not be true that formula_66.
simple: In mathematics, a divisor of an integer "n", also called a factor of "n", is an integer which evenly divides "n" without leaving a remainder. <s> Thus, divisors can be negative as well as positive, although often we restrict our attention to positive divisors. <s> (For example, there are six divisors of four, 1, 2, 4, -1, -2, -4, but one would usually mention only the positive ones, 1, 2, and 4.) <s> 1 and -1 divide (are divisors of) every integer, every integer is a divisor of itself, and every integer is a divisor of 0, except by convention 0 itself (see also division by zero). <s> Numbers divisible by 2 are called even and numbers not divisible by 2 are called odd. <s> A divisor of "n" that is not 1, -1, "n" or -"n" is known as a non-trivial divisor; numbers with non-trivial divisors are known as composite numbers, while prime numbers have no non-trivial divisors. <s> There are properties which allow one to recognize certain divisors of a number from the number's digits. <s> For example, 7 is a divisor of 42 because 42÷7 = 6. <s> For example, the positive divisors of 42 are 1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 14, 21, 42.

title: Karni Mata Temple
complex: Karni Mata Temple (Hindi: करणी माता मंदिर) is a Hindu temple dedicated to Karni Mata at Deshnoke, 30 km from Bikaner, in Rajasthan, India. <s> It is also known as the Temple of Rats. <s> The temple is famous for the approximately 25,000 black rats that live, and are revered, in the temple. <s> These holy rats are called kabbas, and many people travel great distances to pay their respects. <s> The temple draws visitors from across the country for blessings, as well as curious tourists from around the world.
simple: Karni Mata Temple (Hindi: करणी माता मंदिर) is a Hindu temple dedicated to Karni Mata at Deshnoke, 30 km from Bikaner, in Rajasthan, India. <s> It is also known as the Temple of Rats. <s> The temple is famous for the approximately 25,000 black rats that live, and are revered in, the temple. <s> These holy rats are called kabbas, and many people travel great distances to pay their respects. <s> The temple draws visitors from across the country for blessings, as well as curious tourists from around the world.
