simple: Facta is an encyclopedia in Finnish. <s> It was published as a series of 11 volumes between 1969 and 1974. <s> It describes subjects from a Finnish point of view.

title: Black Dahlia
complex: Elizabeth Short (July 29, 1924 – January 14 or 15, 1947), known posthumously as the "Black Dahlia", was an American woman who was found murdered in the Leimert Park neighborhood of Los Angeles, California. <s> Her case became highly publicized due to the graphic nature of the crime, which included her corpse having been mutilated and bisected at the waist. <s> Short's unsolved murder and the details surrounding it have had a lasting cultural intrigue, generating various theories and public speculation. <s> Her life and death have been the basis of numerous books and films, and her murder is frequently cited as one of the most famous unsolved murders in American history, as well as one of the oldest unsolved cases in Los Angeles County. <s> It has likewise been credited by historians as one of the first major crimes in post-World War II America to capture national attention. <s> Short's severely mutilated body was completely severed at the waist and drained entirely of blood, leaving her skin a pallid white. <s> Medical examiners determined that she had been dead for around ten hours prior to the discovery, leaving her time of death either sometime during the evening of January 14, or the early morning hours of January 15.
simple: Elizabeth Short (July 29, 1924 – January 14 or 15, 1947), known as "the Black Dahlia", was an American woman who was found murdered in a neighborhood of Los Angeles, California. <s> Her case became highly publicized due to the graphic nature of the crime. <s> Short's unsolved murder and the details surrounding it have had caused many theories and public speculation. <s> It is one of the oldest unsolved cases in Los Angeles County. <s> Her corpse was chopped into pieces and severed at the waist.

title: LG Corporation
complex: LG Corporation (Korean: ), formerly Lucky-Goldstar (Korean: "Leogki Geumseong"; Korean: ), is a South Korean multinational conglomerate corporation. <s> It is the fourth-largest chaebol in South Korea. <s> It is headquartered in the LG Twin Towers building in Yeouido-dong, Yeongdeungpo District, Seoul. <s> LG makes electronics, chemicals, and telecom products and operates subsidiaries such as LG Electronics, Zenith, LG Display, LG Uplus, LG Innotek and LG Chem in over 80 countries. <s> LG Corporation established as Lak Hui Chemical Industrial Corp. in 1947. <s> In 1952, Lak Hui (pronounced "Lucky", currently LG Chem) became the first South Korean company to enter the plastics industry. <s> As the company expanded its plastics business, it established GoldStar Co. Ltd. (currently LG Electronics Inc.) in 1958. <s> Both companies Lucky and GoldStar merged and formed Lucky-Goldstar in 1983. <s> Koo Bon-moo renamed the company to LG in 1995. <s> The company also associates the letters LG with the company's tagline "Life's Good". <s> Since 2009, LG has owned the domain name LG.com.
simple: LG Corp. is the second largest Korean multi-industry company that produces electronics, chemicals, and telecommunications products and operates subsidiaries like LG Electronics, LG Display, LG Telecom, LG Boring, and LG Chem in over 80 countries. <s> LG Corp. established as Lak-Hui Chemical Industrial Corp. in 1947. <s> In 1952, Lak-Hui became the first Korean company to enter the plastics industry. <s> While the company expanded its plastic business, it established GoldStar Co.. <s> (currently LG Electronics Inc.) in 1958. <s> Both companies Lucky and GoldStar merged and formed Lucky Goldstar. <s> In 1995, to compete better in the Western market, the Lucky-Goldstar Corporation was renamed "LG". <s> The company also associates the letters LG with the company's tagline "Life's Good".

title: Offenbach am Main
complex: Offenbach am Main (] ) is a city in Hesse, Germany, on the left bank of the river Main. <s> It borders Frankfurt and is part of the Frankfurt urban area and the larger Frankfurt Rhein-Main urban area. <s> It has a population of 138,335 (december 2018). <s> Until the early 1970s Offenbach was dominated by the machine-building and leather industries. <s> The city hosts the German Association for Electrical, Electronic and Information Technologies to this day. <s> The Deutscher Wetterdienst, commonly abbreviated as DWD, (translated from German as German Meteorological Service), residing in the Westend district.
simple: Offenbach is a city in the German state of Hesse. <s> Until the early 1970s the economy of Offenbach was mainly the machine-building and leather industries. <s> The city is the home of the German Association for Electrical, Electronic and Information Technologies until today. <s> The "Deutscher Wetterdienst" (German weather service) is in Offenbach.

title: Dison
complex: Dison is a Walloon municipality located in the Belgian province of Liège. <s> On January 1, 2006, Dison had a total population of 14,243.
simple: Dison is a municipality in the Belgian province of Liège.

title: Captain (association football)
complex: The team captain of an association football team, sometimes known as the skipper, is a team member chosen to be the on-pitch leader of the team: it is often one of the older/or more experienced members of the squad, or a player that can heavily influence a game or have good leadership qualities. <s> The team captain is usually identified by the wearing of an armband. <s> The only official responsibility of a captain specified by the Laws of the Game is to participate in the coin toss prior to kick-off (for choice of ends) and prior to a penalty shootout. <s> Contrary to what is sometimes said, captains have no special authority under the Laws to challenge a decision by the referee. <s> However, referees may talk to the captain of a side about the side's general behaviour when necessary. <s> At an award-giving ceremony after a fixture like a cup competition final, the captain usually leads the team up to collect their medals. <s> Any trophy won by a team will be received by the captain who will also be the first one to hoist it. <s> The captain also generally leads the teams out of the dressing room at the start of the match.
simple: The team captain of a football team is a team member who is chosen to be the leader during a football match. <s> Mostly a captain is an older or more experienced player. <s> A team captain often wears an armband. <s> The captain has to participate in the coin toss before the match and before a penalty shootout. <s> Referees mostly talk to the captain about the behaviour of him and his team mates. <s> When the team wins a trophy it is given to the captain.

title: Pygmy rabbit
complex: The pygmy rabbit ("Brachylagus idahoensis") is a North American rabbit, and is one of only two rabbit species in America to dig its own burrow. <s> The pygmy rabbit differs significantly from species within either the "Lepus" (hare) or "Sylvilagus" (cottontail) genera and is generally considered to be within the monotypic genus Brachylagus. <s> One isolated population, the Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit, is listed as an endangered species by the U.S. Federal government, though the International Union for Conservation of Nature lists the species as lower risk. <s> The pygmy rabbit is the world's smallest leporid, which means adult weights from 375 to about , and a body length from 23.5 to ; females are slightly larger than males. <s> The pygmy rabbit is distinguishable from other leporids by its small size, short ears, gray color, small hind legs, and lack of white fur on the tail. <s> The last male purebred Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit, found only in the Columbia Basin of Washington State, died March 30, 2006, at the Oregon Zoo in Portland. <s> The last purebred female died in 2008. <s> A crossbreeding program conducted by the Oregon Zoo, Washington State University and Northwest Trek is attempting to preserve the genetic line by breeding surviving females with the Idaho pygmy rabbit. <s> Weasels ("Mustela" spp.) are the principal predators of pygmy rabbits. <s> Coyotes ("Canis latrans"), red foxes ("Vulpes vulpes"), badgers, bobcats ("Felis rufus"), great horned owls ("Bubo virginianus") and northern harriers (Circus hudsonius) also prey on pygmy rabbits.
simple: The pygmy rabbit ("Brachylagus idahoensis") is a North American rabbit. <s> One isolated population, the Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit, is listed as an endangered species by the U.S. Federal government. <s> The International Union for Conservation of Nature lists the species as lower risk. <s> The pygmy rabbit is the world's smallest leporid. <s> An average adult weights about 375 to about. <s> It has a body length of 23.5 to. <s> The female rabbit is slightly larger than the male. <s> The pygmy rabbit is different from other leporids by its small size, short ears, gray color and small hind legs. <s> It also does not have any white fur on its tail. <s> The last male purebred Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit died March 30, 2006, at the Oregon Zoo in Portland. <s> The last purebred female died in 2008. <s> A program by the Oregon Zoo, Washington State University and Northwest Trek is trying to preserve the genes by breeding surviving females with the Idaho pygmy rabbit. <s> Weasels are the main predators of pygmy rabbits. <s> Coyotes, red foxes, badgers, bobcats, owls and hawks also hunt pygmy rabbits.

title: Muhammad Habibur Rahman
complex: Muhammad Habibur Rahman (3 December 1928 – 11 January 2014) was a Chief Justice of Bangladesh Supreme Court in 1995. <s> He was the Chief Adviser of the 1996 caretaker government which oversaw the Seventh parliamentary elections in Bangladesh. <s> A language activist and advocate of the Bengali language, he wrote extensively and published eight books on the subject. <s> He played a significant role to implement Bengali in the Supreme Court of Bangladesh. <s> He wrote "Jathashabdo" (1974), the first thesaurus in the Bengali language. <s> Rahman was awarded Bangla Academy Literary Award in 1984 and Ekushey Padak in 2007 by the Government of Bangladesh. <s> He served as a Fellow of Bangla Academy, Asiatic Society of Bangladesh and Worcester College, Oxford. <s> Rahman began his career as a lecturer in history of Dhaka University in 1952. <s> Later he joined Rajshahi University where he subsequently held the office of Dean of the Faculty of Law (1961) and of Reader in History (1962–64). <s> He changed his profession in 1964 when he took to law and joined the Dhaka High Court Bar. <s> In his legal career, he held the offices of Assistant Advocate General (1969), Vice President of High Court Bar Association (1972) and member of Bangladesh bar council(1972). <s> Rahman was an author of seventy books in Bengali on law, language, literature, poetry and religion and five books in English, including two books of verse. <s> Law of Requisition (1966), Rabindra Prabandhey Sanjna O Parthakya Bichar (1968), Jatha-sabda (1974), Matri-bhashar Sapakshey Rabindranath (1983), Qur'an-sutra (1984), Bachan O Prabachan (1985), Gangariddhi thekey Bangladesh (1985), Rabindra Rachanar Rabindra-byaksha (1986), Rabindra-kabyey Art, Sangeet O Sahitya (1986), Koran-shorif Sorol Banganubad, On Rights and Remedies, Amara ki Jabo-na Tader Kachhey Jara Shudhu Banglai Katha Baley (1996). <s> On 11 January 2014, at the age of 85, Rahman died at United Hospital, Gulshan, Dhaka.
simple: Muhammad Habibur Rahman (December 3, 1928 – January 11, 2014) was a Bangladeshi politician and jurist. <s> Justice Habibur Rahman retired from service as the Chief Justice of Bangladesh in 1995. <s> He was also the first Chief Advisor of the Caretaker Government of Bangladesh for a month in 1996. <s> Justice Rahman was conferred a Bangla Academy award for his contribution to literature in 1984 and the Ekushey Padak in 2007. <s> He is a fellow of the Asiatic Society of Bangladesh; Fellow of the Bangla Academy; Honorary Bencher, Lincoln's Inn. <s> Habibur Rahman began his career as a temporary Lecturer in History of Dhaka University on May 1, 1952. <s> Later he joined Rajshahi University where he subsequently held the office of Dean of the Faculty of Law (1961) and of Reader in History (1962-64). <s> Habibur Rahman changed his profession in 1964 when he took to law and joined the Dhaka High Court Bar. <s> In his legal career he held the offices of Assistant Advocate General (1969), Vice President of High Court Bar Association (1972) (now Supreme Court Bar Association) and member of Bangladesh Bar Council (1972). <s> Some of his literary and other noted publications are as follows: Law of Requisition (1966), রবীন্দ্র প্রবন্ধেসঞ্জনা ও পার্থক্য বিচার (Rabindra Prabandhey Sanjna O Parthakya Bichar) (1968), যথা-শব্দ (Jatha-sabda) (1974), মাতৃভাষার স্বপক্ষেরবীন্দ্রনাথ (Matri-bhashar Sapakshey Rabindranath) (1983), কোরআন সূত্র (Qoran-sutra) (1984), বচন ও প্রবাচন (Bachan O Prabachan) (1985), গঙ্গারিদ্ধী থেকে বাংলাদেশ (Gangariddhi thekey Bangladesh) (1985), রবীন্দ্র রচনার রবীন্দ্র ব্যাখ্যা (Rabindra Rachanar Rabindra-byaksha) (1986), রবীন্দ্র কাব্যে, শীল্পে, সঙ্গীত ও সাহিত্যে(Rabindra- kabyey Art, Sangeet O Sahitya) (1986), On Rights and Remedies, আমরা কি যাবো না তাদের কাছে যারা শুধু বাঙলায় কথা বলে (Amara ki Jabo-na Tader Kachhey Jara Shudhu Banglai Katha Baley) (1996). <s> On 11 January 2014, doctors declared him dead on arrival at United Hospital,Dhaka at the age of 84.

title: Wiedemann–Rautenstrauch syndrome
complex: Wiedemann–Rautenstrauch (WR) syndrome ] , also known as neonatal progeroid syndrome, is a rare autosomal recessive progeroid syndrome. <s> There have been over 30 cases of WR. <s> WR is associated with abnormalities in bone maturation, and lipids and hormone metabolism.
simple: Neonatal Progeroid Syndrome also known as Wiedemann-Rautenstrauch syndrome. <s> It is an autosomal recessive progeroid syndrome. <s> There have been over 51 cases of NPS. <s> NPS is associated with abnormalities in bone maturation, lipid and metabolism.

title: Pyrenees
complex: The Pyrenees ( ; ] ; ] ; ; ] ; ; ] ) is a range of mountains in southwest Europe that forms a natural border between Spain and France. <s> Reaching a height of 3404 m altitude at the peak of Aneto, the range separates the Iberian Peninsula from the rest of continental Europe, and extends for about 491 km from the Bay of Biscay (Cap Higuer) to the Mediterranean Sea (Cap de Creus).
simple: The Pyrenees (; ; ; ; ; ) are a range of mountains in southwest Europe that form a natural border between France and Spain.

title: Thomas L. Kane
complex: Thomas Leiper Kane (January 27, 1822 – December 26, 1883) was an American attorney, abolitionist, philanthropist, and military officer who was influential in the western migration of the Latter-day Saint movement and served as a Union Army colonel and general of volunteers in the American Civil War. <s> He received a brevet promotion to major general for gallantry at the Battle of Gettysburg. <s> Kane came in contact with members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints during a Philadelphia conference in May 1846. <s> Kane offered them his advice and help in their conflicts with the US government and in their efforts to emigrate to western territories. <s> Jesse C. Little, presiding LDS elder in the East, was soliciting support for the Latter-day Saints' westward migration. <s> Politically well-connected through his father, Kane provided letters of recommendation and later joined Little in Washington, D.C. <s> The two called on the secretary of state, secretary of war, and President James K. Polk. <s> As a result of their negotiations, the United States agreed to enlist up to 500 LDS men, in five companies of 75 to 100 men each, as the Mormon Battalion, to serve in the Mexican–American War. <s> With the help of his father, Kane obtained US government permission for the refugee Mormons to occupy Pottawattamie and Omaha Indian lands along the Missouri. <s> After carrying dispatches relating to the land agreements and battalion criteria to Fort Leavenworth, Kane sought out Little in the Latter-day Saint encampments on the Missouri River. <s> On July 17, 1846, a meeting was held with Kane, LDS leaders and Army Captain James Allen to create the Mormon Battalion. <s> Kane met many leaders of the church, and became a popular figure among Mormon emigrants. <s> Miller's Hollow, the principal Iowa settlement of the LDS group at the site of present-day Council Bluffs, was renamed Kanesville in recognition of his service. <s> During this stay, Kane became seriously ill. <s> Although good care from both an army physician from Fort Leavenworth and church members helped him recover, he suffered poor health the rest of his life. <s> Kane became a personal friend of Brigham Young, and stayed in contact with the church leader for many years. <s> Kane visited Utah several times, advising Young on dealing with the federal government.
simple: Thomas L. Kane (January 27, 1822 – December 26, 1883) was an American lawyer. <s> Kane met with members of the LDS Church at a meeting in Philadelphia in May 1846. <s> Kane gave them his advice (told them what he thought they should do) and helped with their conflicts (arguments) with the U.S. government. <s> He also helped them when they tried to emigrate (move) to western areas (places) in the US. <s> , an LDS religious leader in the East, was asking for help with the Latter-day Saints' move to the West. <s> Kane was able to get letters of recommendation (letters that say Kane can be trusted) from people who knew his father. <s> Kane later joined Little in , and they met the secretary of state, secretary of war, and President . <s> After they negotiated (shared and talked about ideas), the United States agreed to send 500 LDS men, in five groups of 75 to 100 men each, called the , to help in the . <s> With his fathers help, Kane got U.S. government permission for the refugee (people who have lost or had to leave their homes) Mormons to occupy Pottawattamie and Omaha Indian lands along the Missouri. <s> Kane carried letters to , and looked for Little in the Latter-day Saint camps on the . <s> On July 17, 1846, Kane met with LDS leaders and Army Captain to make the Mormon Battalion. <s> Kane met many leaders of the Church, and became a popular figure among Mormon emigrants (people who moved). <s> Miller's Hollow, the main Iowa settlement (colony) of the LDS group at what is now , was renamed Kanesville to honor Kane for his help. <s> During this time, Kane became really ill with a fever. <s> Although he got help from both an army physician (doctor) from Fort Leavenworth and church members, his health was not good for the rest of his life. <s> He was friends with Brigham Young, a leader in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, or Mormon church, or LDS Church. <s> Kane helped Brigham Young and the Mormons travel to Utah.

title: Ethel Ennis
complex: Ethel Llewellyn Ennis (November 28, 1932 – February 17, 2019) was an American jazz musician whose career spanned seven decades. <s> Ennis spent the majority of her life in her hometown of Baltimore, Maryland, where she was affectionately known as the "First Lady of Jazz". <s> Ennis was born in a row house on North Calhoun Street in Baltimore, Maryland, and grew up in the Sandtown-Winchester neighborhood. <s> She began performing as a church pianist at a young age. <s> Embarking on a solo singing career, she recorded a number of songs for Atlantic Records before her LP debut, "Lullabies for Losers", was released by Jubilee Records in 1955. <s> In 1957, she moved to Capitol Records for a two-album contract, and released "A Change of Scenery". <s> Soon after the 1958 follow-up LP "Have You Forgotten", Ennis took a six-year hiatus from recording, during which she toured Europe with Benny Goodman. <s> Two of her recordings 'Call Me Young' and 'Sing Me A tune' were used in the UK during Testcard intervals on BBC1 between January 1978 and April 1980. <s> In 1963, she recorded four LPs for RCA Victor. <s> However, disenchanted with the creative direction of the label and artist management, Ennis left that label and took another hiatus. <s> Eight years would pass before she received another recording contract. <s> During this period she sang the title song for the 1967 feature film "Mad Monster Party?" <s> The BASF LP "10 Sides of Ethel Ennis" emerged in 1973; later that year, Ennis, a Democrat, was invited to sing at the re-inauguration of Richard Nixon. <s> Her unusual "a cappella" rendition of the national anthem shocked some, but inspired many others. <s> Ennis died from a stroke on February 17, 2019.
simple: Ethel Llewellyn Ennis (November 28, 1932 – February 17, 2019) was an American jazz singer. <s> She was known as the "First Lady of Jazz". <s> She was born in Baltimore, Maryland. <s> Her debut was with 1955's "Lullabies for Losers" was released by Jubilee Records. <s> In 1957, Ennis moved to the Capitol Records label for a two-album contract, and "A Change of Scenery" was released. <s> She performed the main song for the movie "Mad Monster Party?". <s> Ennis was invited to sing at the second inauguration of Richard Nixon. <s> Ennis died at her home in Baltimore from a stroke on February 17, 2019, aged 86.

title: Joseph Marcell
complex: Joseph Marcell (born 14 August 1948) is a British actor and comedian best known for his role as Geoffrey Butler, the butler on the NBC sitcom "The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air" from September 1990, until it ended in May 1996. <s> Born in Saint Lucia, he moved to the United Kingdom when he was nine years old, and grew up in Peckham, South London.
simple: Joseph Marcell (born 18 August 1948) is a Saint Lucian born British actor. <s> He is best known for his role as Geoffrey the butler on the NBC sitcom "The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air" from September 1990 until it ended in May 1996.

title: Rostrevor
complex: Rostrevor is a village and townland in County Down, Northern Ireland. <s> It lies at the foot of Slieve Martin on the coast of Carlingford Lough, near Warrenpoint. <s> The Kilbroney River flows through the village and Rostrevor Forest is nearby. <s> It is within Newry, Mourne and Down District. <s> Rostrevor had a population of 2,433 in the 2001 Census.
simple: Rostrevor (in Irish: "Ros Treabhair", i.e. Trevor’s Wood, also "Caislean Ruairi", i.e. Rory's Castle) is a village in County Down, Northern Ireland. <s> It is on Carlingford Lough and the hill of Slieve Martin, at the base of the Mourne Mountains and on the Kilbroney River. <s> It is in the Newry and Mourne District Council area. <s> It had a population of 2,444 in the 2001 Census.

title: Bamba (snack)
complex: Bamba is one of the leading snack foods produced and sold in Israel. <s> It has been marketed since 1964 with no decline in sales. <s> Bamba makes up 25% of the Israeli snack market. <s> Similar products from other domestic manufacturers include "Parpar" (Telma, since 2000 a subsidiary of Unilever) and "Shush" (Strauss-Elite).
simple: Bamba is an Israeli corn snack and is considered to be one of the most popular snacks for children. <s> Bamba has been made since 1963 with no decline in sales. <s> Bamba makes up 25% of the Israeli snack market.

title: Olten District
complex: Olten District is one of the ten districts of the canton of Solothurn in Switzerland, situated around the city of Olten. <s> Together with the Gösgen District, it forms the electoral district of Olten-Gösgen.
simple: Olten is one of the 10 districts of the canton of Solothurn in Switzerland, found by the city of Olten.

title: Smedjebacken
complex: Smedjebacken is a locality and the seat of Smedjebacken Municipality, Dalarna County, Sweden, with 5,100 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Smedjebacken is an urban area in the county of Dalarna in Sweden. <s> It is the seat of Smedjebacken Municipality.

title: Intensity of preference
complex: Intensity of preference, also known as intensity preference, is a term popularized by the work of the economist Kenneth Arrow, who was a co-recipient of the 1972 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics. <s> This term is used in reference to models for aggregating ordinal rankings. <s> This term is used in economics, politics, marketing, management science and other areas in which methods to derive the consensus ranking are developed. <s> In an analysis of voting, for example, the intensity of preference is a measure of an individual voter's (or group of voters') willingness to incur the costs or inconvenience of the act of officially registering a preferential choice at the time and place required, not the vote itself. <s> The "intensity" of preference can be a factor in aggregating individual choices into social choices.
simple: Intensity of preference, also known as intensity preference, is a term used to identify and describe what happens in a process which leads to consensus agreement or consensus ranking. <s> In the 20th century, the term intensity of preference was coined by the work of the economist Kenneth Arrow, who was a recipient of the 1972 Nobel Prize in Economics. <s> The term is used in economics, politics, marketing and other areas. <s> For example, the intensity of preference is a one of many factors which are important in voting. <s> The term is a measure of an individual voter's (or group of voters') willingness to do something. <s> Intensity of preference focuses on the inconveniences involved in the act of officially registering a choice at a specific time and place, not the vote itself. <s> Intensity of preference is a factor in an analysis of how individual choices develop into social choices. <s> The "intensity of preference" and the inconvenience of voting were factors in the election of Nelson Mandela.

title: Lead dioxide
complex: Lead(IV) oxide, commonly called lead dioxide, plumbic oxide or anhydrous plumbic acid (sometimes wrongly called lead peroxide ), is a chemical compound with the formula PbO. <s> It is an oxide where lead is in an oxidation state of +4; bond type is predominantly covalent. <s> It is an odorless dark-brown crystalline powder which is nearly insoluble in water. <s> It exists in two crystalline forms.
simple: Lead(IV) oxide, also known as lead dioxide, is a chemical compound. <s> Its chemical formula is PbO. <s> It is composed of lead in its +4 oxidation state. <s> It is a dark brown toxic powder.

title: Kim Wilson
complex: Kim Wilson (born January 6, 1951) is an American blues singer and harmonica player. <s> He is best known as the lead vocalist and frontman for the Fabulous Thunderbirds on two hit songs of the 1980s, "Tuff Enuff" and "Wrap It Up." <s> Wilson wrote "Tuff Enuff," the group's only Top 40 hit. <s> Wilson was born in Detroit, Michigan, in 1951, but he grew up in Goleta, California, where he sometimes went by the stage name of "Goleta Slim." <s> He started with the blues in the late 1960s and was tutored by people like Muddy Waters, Jimmy Rogers, Eddie Taylor, Albert Collins, George "Harmonica" Smith, Luther Tucker and Pee Wee Crayton and was influenced by harmonica players such as Little Walter, James Cotton, Big Walter Horton, Slim Harpo and Lazy Lester. <s> Before he moved to Austin, Texas, in 1974, he was the leader of the band Aces, Straights and Shuffles in Minneapolis, Minnesota; the band released one single. <s> In Austin he formed the Fabulous Thunderbirds with guitarist Jimmie Vaughan. <s> They became the house band at Antone's, a blues club owned by Clifford Antone. <s> Wilson continues to perform up to 300 concert dates per year at blues music festivals and clubs all over the world, both as leader of the Fabulous Thunderbirds and with Kim Wilson's Blues Allstars.
simple: Kim Wilson (born January 6, 1951 in Detroit, Michigan) is an American blues singer and harp player. <s> He is best known as the harp player and singer of The Fabulous Thunderbirds. <s> In the 1980s they had two hits with "Tuff Enuff" and "Wrap It Up." <s> He started with the blues in the late 1960s whenhe was a senior at High school. <s> Wilson was tutored by people like Muddy Waters, Jimmie Rogers, Eddie Taylor, Albert Collins, George "Harmonica" Smith, Luther Tucker and Pee Wee Crayton. <s> He was influenced by harmonica players like Little Walter, James Cotton, Big Walter Horton, Slim Harpo and Lazy Lester. <s> 1974 he went to Austin, Texas where he and the guitarist Jimmie Vaughan formed The Fabulous Thunderbirds. <s> They became the house band at the blues club, Antone's. <s> He is doing more than 200 concerts in a year playing in blues clubs and at Festivals around the world.

title: Stanleycaris
complex: Stanleycaris is an extinct, monotypic genus of anomalocaridid which existed in Canada, during the middle Cambrian (Miaolingian). <s> The type species is "Stanleycaris hirpex". <s> "Stanleycaris" was described from the Stephen Formation near the Stanley Glacier Burgess Shale locality and also informally reported from Odaray Mountain. <s> Putative lobopodian species "Aysheaia prolata" from the Cambrian Wheeler Formation (Utah, United States) was reinterpreted as an isolated frontal appendage of a member of the genus "Stanleycaris" by Pates, Daley & Ortega-Hernández (2017).
simple: Stanleycaris (meaning "crab of Stanley Glacier") is an extinct, monotypic genus of anomalocaridid which existed in Canada, during the middle Cambrian. <s> Its fossils were found in the Burgess Shale in and also informally reported from Mount Odaray. <s> Putative lobopodian species "Aysheaia prolata" from Utah, United States were reinterpreted as an isolated frontal appendage of a member of the genus "Stanleycaris" by Pates, Daley & Ortega-Hernández (2017).

title: Prime Minister of Singapore
complex: The Prime Minister of the Republic of Singapore ( ; ; , "Ciṅkappūr kuṭiyaraciṉ piratamar") is the head of the government of the Republic of Singapore, and the country's most powerful political figure. <s> The President of Singapore appoints as Prime Minister a Member of Parliament (MP) who, in his or her opinion, is most likely to command the confidence of a majority of MPs. <s> In practice, the Prime Minister is usually the leader of the majority party in the legislature. <s> The office of Prime Minister dates back to 1959 and was appointed at first by the Governor of Singapore then the Yang di-Pertuan Negara (vice-regal head of state), when Singapore achieved self-governance as the State of Singapore within the British Empire. <s> The title of Prime Minister remained unchanged after the merger with the Federation of Malaya, Sarawak and North Borneo, while Singapore was a state in the Federation of Malaysia from 1963 to 1965, and after independence in 1965. <s> The late Lee Kuan Yew was the first prime minister of Singapore from 1959 to 1990. <s> Lee was succeeded by Goh Chok Tong and was conferred the title of Senior Minister in the Prime Minister's Office. <s> Goh retired on 12 August 2004 and was succeeded by Lee Kuan Yew's son Lee Hsien Loong. <s> Goh was appointed Senior Minister, and the elder Lee Minister Mentor. <s> Lee and Goh resigned from the Cabinet in 2011 but remained as members of Parliament.
simple: The Prime Minister of the Republic of Singapore is the head of the government of the Republic of Singapore. <s> The President of Singapore chooses as Prime Minister a Member of Parliament (MP) who, he thinks, will have the highest chance of being supported by a majority of MPs. <s> The first time there was a Prime Minister was in 1959 and it was chosen by the Governor of Singapore and later the Yang di-Pertuan Negara (head of state), when Singapore could have the power to govern as the State of Singapore inside the British Empire. <s> The title of Prime Minister did not change after Singapore merged with the Federation of Malaya, Sarawak and British North Borneo, while Singapore was a state in the Federation of Malaysia from 1963 to 1965, and after independence in 1965. <s> Lee Kuan Yew was the first prime minister of Singapore from 1959 to 1990 and retired on 26 November 1990. <s> Goh Chok Tong took over Lee Kuan Yew, while Lee Kuan Yew was given the job of Senior Minister in the Prime Minister's Office. <s> Goh Chok Tong retired on 12 August 2004 and was replaced by Lee Kuan Yew's son Lee Hsien Loong. <s> Goh was given the job of Senior Minister, and the older Lee the job of Minister Mentor.

title: Zail Singh
complex: Zail Singh ( ; born Jarnail Singh, 5 May 1916 – 25 December 1994) was the seventh President of India serving from 1982 to 1987. <s> Prior to his presidency, he was a politician with the Indian National Congress party, and had held several ministerial posts in the Union Cabinet, including that of Home Minister. <s> He also served as the Secretary-General of the Non-Aligned Movement from 1983 to 1986. <s> On 29 November 1994, Zail Singh suffered multiple injuries following a motor accident near Kiratpur Sahib in Ropar district when a truck driving down the wrong side of the road hit the car he was travelling in. <s> Singh died in Chandigarh where he had been undergoing treatment on Christmas Day in 1994, aged 78. <s> The Government of India announced seven days of official mourning following his death.
simple: Gyani Zail Singh (; born Jarnail Singh, 5 May 1916 – 25 December 1994) was an Indian politician. <s> He was the seventh President of India from 1982 to 1987. <s> He was a politician with the Indian National Congress party. <s> Singh was killed in a car crash in Chandigarh, India on 25 December 1994 at the age of 78.

title: Knowledge
complex: Knowledge can refer to a theoretical or practical understanding of a subject. <s> It can be implicit (as with practical skill or expertise) or explicit (as with the theoretical understanding of a subject); it can be more or less formal or systematic. <s> In philosophy, the study of knowledge is called epistemology; the philosopher Plato famously defined knowledge as "justified true belief", though this definition is now thought by some analytic philosophers to be problematic because of the Gettier problems, while others defend the platonic definition. <s> However, several definitions of knowledge and theories to explain it exist. <s> The definition of knowledge is a matter of ongoing debate among philosophers in the field of epistemology. <s> The classical definition, described but not ultimately endorsed by Plato, specifies that a statement must meet three criteria in order to be considered knowledge: it must be justified, true, and believed. <s> Some claim that these conditions are not sufficient, as Gettier case examples allegedly demonstrate. <s> There are a number of alternatives proposed, including Robert Nozick's arguments for a requirement that knowledge 'tracks the truth' and Simon Blackburn's additional requirement that we do not want to say that those who meet any of these conditions 'through a defect, flaw, or failure' have knowledge. <s> Richard Kirkham suggests that our definition of knowledge requires that the evidence for the belief necessitates its truth. <s> In many expressions of Christianity, such as Catholicism and Anglicanism, knowledge is one of the seven gifts of the Holy Spirit. <s> In Islam, knowledge (Arabic: علم, "ʿilm") is given great significance. <s> "The Knowing" ("al-ʿAlīm") is one of the 99 names reflecting distinct attributes of God. <s> The Qur'an asserts that knowledge comes from God and various "hadith" encourage the acquisition of knowledge. <s> Muhammad is reported to have said "Seek knowledge from the cradle to the grave" and "Verily the men of knowledge are the inheritors of the prophets". <s> Islamic scholars, theologians and jurists are often given the title "alim", meaning "knowledgeble".
simple: Knowledge can refer to a theoretical or practical understanding of a subject. <s> It can be implicit (as with practical skill or expertise) or explicit (as with the theoretical understanding of a subject); it can be more or less formal or systematic. <s> In philosophy, the study of knowledge is called epistemology. <s> The philosopher Plato defined knowledge as "justified true belief". <s> In many expressions of Christianity, such as Catholicism and Anglicanism, knowledge is one of the seven gifts of the Holy Spirit. <s> In Islam, knowledge has great significance. <s> "The All-Knowing" ("al-ʿAlīm") is one of the Names of God, reflecting distinct properties of God in Islam. <s> The Qur'an asserts that knowledge comes from God (2:239) and various "hadith" encourage getting knowledge. <s> Muhammad is reported to have said "Seek knowledge from the cradle to the grave" and "Verily the men of knowledge are the inheritors of the prophets". <s> Islamic scholars, theologians and jurists are often given the title "alim", meaning 'knowledgeable'.

title: Mike Embley
complex: Michael Kenneth Embley (born 25 May 1955 in Sutton, Surrey) is an English broadcast journalist, best known as a presenter for BBC World News, an international news and current affairs television channel operated by the BBC. <s> He currently presents overnight Tuesday-Friday on BBC World News, BBC One and the BBC News Channel. <s> Before joining the BBC, Embley began his career training as a newspaper journalist with Thomson daily papers in Wales, on the South Wales Echo and the Western Mail. <s> He began broadcasting in 1983, working for BBC Wales' "Wales Today", followed by the consumer affairs programme "Watchdog" in 1987, and "Public Eye" in 1989. <s> Whilst working on "Public Eye", he was the first British reporter to reach San Francisco to report on the earthquake. <s> Embley later joined ITN's Channel 4 News to work as a producer and reporter, before returning to the BBC as a reporter for the flagship One O'Clock News, Six O'Clock News and Nine O'Clock News bulletins. <s> During this time, Embley also worked as a series presenter for "Nature" on BBC Two and made two films for "Panorama". <s> Embley joined BBC World in 1995, and remained there for two years until he became the main presenter of "Newsroom South East", the BBC's regional news programme for London and the South East of England. <s> After the programme was replaced by two separate regional bulletins ("BBC London" and "South East Today") in 2001, Embley rejoined BBC World as a presenter. <s> Since then, he has also presented on the domestic BBC News Channel and carried out one-on-one interviews for the BBC programme "HARDtalk", as well as reporting several series for the radio station BBC World Service.
simple: Mike Embley (born 1955 in Surrey, England) is a British broadcast journalist, best known as a presenter for BBC World News, an international news and current affairs television channel operated by the BBC. <s> Embley was born in Surrey, England in 1955. <s> Before joining the BBC, Embley began his career training as a newspaper journalist with Thomson daily papers in Wales, on the South Wales Echo and the Western Mail. <s> He began broadcasting in 1983, working for BBC Wales' "Wales Today", followed by the consumer affairs programme "Watchdog" in 1987, and "Public Eye" in 1989. <s> Whilst working on "Public Eye", he was the first news reporter with a foreign crew to reach the San Francisco to report on the earthquake. <s> Embley later joined ITN's Channel Four News to work as a producer and reporter, before returning to the BBC as a reporter for the flagship One O'Clock, Six O'Clock and Nine O'Clock News bulletins. <s> During this time, Embley also worked as a series presenter for "Nature" on BBC Two and made two films for "Panorama". <s> Embley joined BBC World in 1995. <s> After the program was replaced by two separate programs ("BBC London" and "South East Today") in 2001, Embley rejoined BBC World as a presenter. <s> Since then, he has also presented on the domestic BBC News Channel and carried out one-on-one interviews for the BBC programme "HARDtalk", as well as reporting several series for the radio station BBC World Service.

title: Vlissingen
complex: Vlissingen (] ; Zeelandic: "Vlissienge"; historical name in ) is a municipality and a city in the southwestern Netherlands on the former island of Walcheren. <s> With its strategic location between the Scheldt river and the North Sea, Vlissingen has been an important harbour for centuries. <s> It was granted city rights in 1315. <s> In the 17th century Vlissingen was a main harbour for ships of the Dutch East India Company (VOC). <s> It is also known as the birthplace of Admiral Michiel de Ruyter. <s> Vlissingen is mainly noted for the yards on the Scheldt where most of the ships of the Royal Netherlands Navy ("Koninklijke Marine") are built.
simple: Vlissingen, Zeelandic: "Vlissienge", English: "Flushing", is a city, municipality and seaport in the province of Zeeland, the Netherlands. <s> It has been an important harbor for centuries. <s> Most of the Royal Netherlands Navy ships are built in Vlissingen.

title: Jefferson Davis County, Mississippi
complex: Jefferson Davis County is a county located in the U.S. state of Mississippi. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 12,487. <s> Its county seat is Prentiss. <s> The county is named in honor of Mississippi Senator and Confederate President Jefferson Davis. <s> The county was carved out of Covington and Lawrence counties in March 1906. <s> Governor James K. Vardaman signed the bill creating the county on May 9, 1906.
simple: Jefferson Davis County is a county located in the U.S. state of Mississippi. <s> As of the 2010 census, 12,487 people lived there. <s> Its county seat is Prentiss. <s> It is named in honor of Mississippi Senator and Confederate President Jefferson Davis. <s> The county was founded on March 31, 1906.

title: Zoji La
complex: Zoji La is a high mountain pass in the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir, located on National Highway 1 between Srinagar and Leh in the western section of the Himalayan mountain range. <s> It separates Kashmir Valley to its west from Dras Valley to its northeast.
simple: Zoji La is a high mountain pass in India.

title: Bread and salt
complex: Bread and salt is a welcome greeting ceremony in several Slavic and other European cultures and in Middle Eastern cultures. <s> The tradition, known by local Slavic names ( , Belarusian: "Хлеб і соль"; ; ; ; / "Hleb i so"; ; ; ; ; ) was also adopted by three non-Slavic nations — Lithuanians, Latvians (both Baltic) and Romanians (Latin) — all three of which are culturally and historically close to their Slavic neighbours ( . <s> It is also common in Albania , Armenia ( , "agh u hats"), the Jewish diaspora, and the Middle East. <s> This tradition has also been observed in spaceflight. <s> When important, respected, or admired guests arrive, they are presented with a loaf of bread (usually a korovai) placed on a "rushnyk" (embroidered ritual cloth). <s> A salt holder or a salt cellar is placed on top of the bread loaf or secured in a hole on the top of the loaf. <s> On official occasions, the "bread and salt" is usually presented by young women dressed in national costumes (e.g., sarafan and kokoshnik). <s> With the advent of the Soviet space program, this tradition has spread into space, where appropriately small packages of bread and salt are used nowadays.
simple: Bread and salt is a Slavic welcome greeting ceremony. <s> When this tradition is observed in spaceflight, small packages of bread and salt are used. <s> When important, respected, or admired guests arrive, they are given a loaf of bread placed on a "rushnik" (embroidered towel). <s> A salt holder or a salt cellar is placed on top of the bread loaf or secured in a hole on the top of the loaf. <s> In modern Russia, on official occasions, the "bread and salt" is presented by young women dressed in national costumes (e.g., sarafan and kokoshnik).

title: Henry Moore
complex: His forms are usually abstractions of the human figure, typically depicting mother-and-child or reclining figures. <s> Moore's works are usually suggestive of the female body, apart from a phase in the 1950s when he sculpted family groups. <s> His forms are generally pierced or contain hollow spaces. <s> Many interpreters liken the undulating form of his reclining figures to the landscape and hills of his birthplace, Yorkshire. <s> Moore was born in Castleford, the son of a coal miner. <s> He became well known through his carved marble and larger-scale abstract cast bronze sculptures, and was instrumental in introducing a particular form of modernism to the United Kingdom. <s> His ability in later life to fulfil large-scale commissions made him exceptionally wealthy. <s> Despite this, he lived frugally; most of the money he earned went towards endowing the Henry Moore Foundation, which continues to support education and promotion of the arts. <s> Moore produced at least three significant examples of architectural sculpture during his career. <s> In 1928, despite his own self-described "extreme reservations", he accepted his first public commission for "West Wind" for the London Underground Building at 55 Broadway in London, joining the company of Jacob Epstein and Eric Gill. <s> In 1953, he completed a four-part concrete screen for the Time-Life Building in New Bond Street, London, and in 1955 Moore turned to his first and only work in carved brick, "Wall Relief" at the Bouwcentrum in Rotterdam. <s> The brick relief was sculpted with 16,000 bricks by two Dutch bricklayers under Moore's supervision.
simple: His forms are usually abstractions of the human figure, typically mother-and-child or reclining figures. <s> Moore's works usually suggest the female body, apart from a phase in the 1950s when he did family groups. <s> His forms are generally pierced or have hollow spaces. <s> Some think the undulating form of his reclining figures reflect the landscape and hills of his birthplace, Yorkshire. <s> Moore was born in Castleford, the son of a mining engineer. <s> He became known for his larger-scale abstract cast bronze and carved marble sculptures. <s> His large-scale commissions made him exceptionally rich. <s> Yet he lived carefully and most of the money he earned went towards endowing the Henry Moore Foundation. <s> This supports education and promotion of the arts. <s> in 1955 Moore did his only work in carved brick, "Wall Relief" at the Bouwcentrum in Rotterdam. <s> The brick relief was sculpted with 16,000 bricks by two Dutch bricklayers under Moore's supervision.

title: Briord
complex: Briord is a commune in the Ain department in eastern France.

title: Triple DES
complex: In cryptography, Triple DES (3DES or TDES), officially the Triple Data Encryption Algorithm (TDEA or Triple DEA), is a symmetric-key block cipher, which applies the DES cipher algorithm three times to each data block. <s> While the government and industry standards abbreviate the algorithm's name as TDES (Triple DES) and TDEA (Triple Data Encryption Algorithm), RFC 1851 referred to it as 3DES from the time it first promulgated the idea, and this namesake has since come into wide use by most vendors, users, and cryptographers. <s> In general, Triple DES with three independent keys (keying option 1) has a key length of 168 bits (three 56-bit DES keys), but due to the meet-in-the-middle attack, the effective security it provides is only 112 bits. <s> Keying option 2 reduces the effective key size to 112 bits (because the third key is the same as the first). <s> However, this option is susceptible to certain chosen-plaintext or known-plaintext attacks, and thus it is designated by NIST to have only 80 bits of security. <s> This can be considered insecure, and, as consequence Triple DES has been deprecated by NIST in 2017. <s> The electronic payment industry uses Triple DES and continues to develop and promulgate standards based upon it, such as EMV.
simple: In cryptography, Triple DES is a block cipher created from the Data Encryption Standard (DES) cipher by using it three times. <s> Triple DES is also known as TDES or, more standard, TDEA (Triple Data Encryption Algorithm ). <s> In general TDES with three different keys (3-key {k, k, k} TDES) has a key length of 168 bits: three 56-bit DES keys (with parity bits 3-key TDES has the total storage length of 192 bits), but due to the meet-in-the-middle attack the effective security it provides is only 112 bits. <s> However, this mode can be taken advantage of through certain chosen-plaintext or known-plaintext attacks and so TDES is treated by NIST to have only 80 bits of security. <s> One large-scale exception is within the electronic payments industry, which still uses 2TDES extensively and continues to develop and spread standards based upon it (e.g. EMV, the standard for inter-operation of IC cards; also called ""Chip cards"", and IC capable POS terminals and ATM's).

title: Kendall Jenner
complex: Kendall Nicole Jenner (born November 3, 1995) is an American model and media personality. <s> Jenner first appeared in the E! reality television show "Keeping Up with the Kardashians", and is one of the pr "the Instagirl era", where models are chosen for their online presence and social media following. <s> Jenner was born in Los Angeles, California, to retired Olympic decathlete champion Caitlyn Jenner and television personality Kris Jenner. <s> Jenner's middle name was a tribute to her mother's best friend Nicole Brown Simpson, who died just before Jenner was conceived.
simple: Kendall Nicole Jenner (born November 3, 1995) is an American model, television personality and socialite. <s> She is on the reality program "Keeping Up with the Kardashians". <s> She is the daughter of Caitlyn Jenner and Kris Jenner. <s> She was born in Los Angeles, California.

title: Rick Hendrick
complex: Joseph Riddick "Rick" Hendrick III (born July 12, 1949) is the current owner of the American NASCAR team, Hendrick Motorsports, and co owner of JR Motorsports, and founder of the Hendrick Automotive Group and Hendrick Marrow Program. <s> He attended Park View High School in South Hill, Virginia, and began his career in auto racing at age 14.
simple: Joseph Riddick Hendrick III (born July 12, 1949) is the owner of the NASCAR race team Hendrick Motorsports.

title: Lappajärvi
complex: Lappajärvi is a municipality in Finland in Southern Ostrobothnia region. <s> The municipality has a population of and covers an area of km2 of which km2 is water.
simple: Lappajärvi is a municipality in Finland.

title: Ice Road Truckers
complex: Ice Road Truckers (commercially abbreviated IRT) is an American reality television series that premiered on History Channel, on June 17, 2007. <s> It features the activities of drivers who operate trucks on seasonal routes crossing frozen lakes and rivers, in remote Arctic territories in Canada and Alaska. <s> Seasons 3–6 also featured Alaska's improved but still remote Dalton Highway, which is mainly snow-covered solid ground.
simple: Ice Road Truckers is a Canadian-American documentary-style reality television series that first appeared on television on The History Channel on June 17, 2007 (first season). <s> The show follows the activities of truck drivers which operate on routes that contain frozen lakes and rivers in the remote Arctic territories of Canada and Alaska.

title: Monir Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian
complex: Monir Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian ( ; 16 December 1922 – 20 April 2019) was an Iranian artist and a collector of traditional folk art. <s> She is noted for having been one of the most prominent Iranian artists of the contemporary period, and she was the first artist to achieve an artistic practice that weds the geometric patterns and cut-glass mosaic techniques of her Iranian heritage with the rhythms of modern Western geometric abstraction. <s> In 2017, the Monir Museum in Tehran, Iran was opened in her honor. <s> Shahroudy was born on December 18, 1922, to educated parents in the religious town of Qazvin in north-western Iran. <s> Farmanfarmaian acquired artistic skills early on in childhood, receiving drawing lessons from a tutor and studying postcard depictions of western art. <s> After studying at the University of Tehran at the Faculty of Fine Art in 1944, she then moved to New York City via steamboat, when World War II derailed her plans to study art in Paris. <s> In New York, she studied at Cornell University, at Parsons The New School for Design, where she majored in fashion illustration, and at the Art Students League. <s> In 1992, Farmanfarmaian returned to Iran and later, in Tehran in 2004, she reaffirmed her place among Iran's art community, gathering both former and new employees to help create her mosaics. <s> She continued to live and work in Tehran until her death. <s> On 20 April 2019 Farmanfarmaian died at her home at the age of 96. <s> Farmanfarmaian married Iranian artist Manoucher Yektai in 1950.
simple: Monir Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian (‎; 16 December 1922 – 20 April 2019) was an Iranian artist and a collector of folk art. <s> She has been called one of the most important Iranian contemporary artists. <s> She is best known for her mosaics and glass paintings. <s> In 2017, the Monir Museum in Tehran was opened in her honour. <s> Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian was born in Qazvin. <s> She lived and worked in the United States for many years but later came back to Iran. <s> She died of natural causes in Tehran on 20 April 2019.

title: Prince Tomohito of Mikasa
complex: Prince Tomohito of Mikasa (寛仁親王 , Tomohito Shinnō , 5 January 1946 – 6 June 2012) was a member of the Imperial House of Japan and the eldest son of Takahito, Prince Mikasa and Yuriko, Princess Mikasa. <s> He was a first cousin of Emperor Akihito, and was formerly sixth in the line of succession to the Japanese throne and the heir apparent to the princely house of Mikasa-no-miya and the title "Prince Mikasa". <s> Prince Tomohito was the first member of the Imperial House of Japan with a full beard since Emperor Meiji, thus earning him the popular nickname of the "Bearded Prince" (ヒゲの殿下 "Hige no Denka"). <s> He died of cancer on 6 June 2012, aged 66. <s> Prince Tomohito was born in 5 January 1946 at Prince Mikasa's family home, He was graduated from the Department of Political Studies in the Faculty of Law of Gakushuin University in 1968. <s> From 1968 – 1970, he studied at Magdalen College, University of Oxford, in the United Kingdom.
simple: Prince Tomohito of Mikasa (寛仁親王, Tomohito Shinnō, 5 January 1946–6 June 2012) was a member of the Imperial House of Japan. <s> The prince was the eldest son of Prince Mikasa who is the younger brother of former Emperor Shōwa. <s> He was a first cousin of Emperor Akihito. <s> At the time of his death, Prince Tomohito was sixth in the line of succession to the Japanese throne. <s> Tomohito was the first member of the Imperial House of Japan to have a full beard since Emperor Meiji. <s> He was known as "the bearded prince". <s> Prince Tomohito graduated from Gakushuin University. <s> In 1968-1970, Tomohito studied politics at Oxford University.

title: Sebastián Battaglia
complex: Sebastián Alejandro Battaglia (born 8 November 1980) is an Argentine former footballer who played as a midfielder. <s> He spent most of his career with Argentine club Boca Juniors, but also had a brief spell with Spanish side Villarreal. <s> At international level, he made 10 appearances for the Argentina national team between 2003 and 2009.
simple: Sebastián Battaglia (born 8 November 1980) is an Argentine football player. <s> He plays for Boca Juniors and Argentina national team.

title: Calenzano
complex: Calenzano (] ) is a "comune" (municipality) in the Metropolitan City of Florence in the Italian region Tuscany, located about 11 km northwest of Florence. <s> As of 31 December 2004, it had a population of 15,557 and an area of 76.9 km2 . <s> Calenzano borders the following municipalities: Barberino di Mugello, Campi Bisenzio, Prato, San Piero a Sieve, Sesto Fiorentino, Vaglia, Vaiano. <s> Calenzano has a station on the regional railway connecting it to Prato, Florence, Pistoia and Lucca. <s> It can be reached by road from the A1 Motorway. <s> Bus services connect it to Prato, Florence, Campi Bisenzio and Barberino di Mugello.
simple: Calenzano is a "comune" (municipality) in the province of Florence in the Italian region Tuscany. <s> It is about 11 km northwest of Florence. <s> Calenano has an area of 76.9 km2 and a population of 15,557 inhabitants. <s> Calenzano borders the following municipalities: Barberino di Mugello, Campi Bisenzio, Prato, San Piero a Sieve, Sesto Fiorentino, Vaglia, Vaiano. <s> Calenzano has a station on the regional railway connecting it to Prato, Florence, Pistoia and Lucca. <s> It can be reached by road from the highway "A1". <s> Buses connect Calenzano to Prato, Florence, Campi Bisenzio and Barberino di Mugello.

title: Gennevilliers
complex: Gennevilliers (] ) is a commune in the northwestern suburbs of Paris, in the Hauts-de-Seine "département" of France. <s> It is located 9.1 km from the center of Paris. <s> Gennevilliers is served by three stations on Paris Métro Line 13: Les Courtilles, Les Agnettes and Gabriel Péri. <s> All three are at the border with the commune of Asnières-sur-Seine.
simple: Gennevilliers is a town in France near Paris. <s> It is in the region Île-de-France and the department of Hauts-de-Seine. <s> Gennevilliers has 3 stations of the Paris Métro Line 13 : "Gabriel Péri", "Les Agnettes", and "Les Courtilles".

title: Lawrence Gonzi
complex: Lawrence Gonzi, KUOM (born 1 July 1953) is a Maltese politician, retired Nationalist politician and lawyer, who served for twenty-five years in various critical roles in Maltese politics. <s> Gonzi was Prime Minister of Malta from 2004 to 2013, and leader of the Nationalist Party. <s> He also served as speaker of the House from 1988 to 1996, and Minister of Social Policy from 1998 to 2004, as well as Deputy Prime Minister from 1999 to 2004. <s> He served in practically all positions in Parliament, being also Leader of the House, an MP and Leader of the Opposition.
simple: Lawrence Gonzi KUOM (born 1 July 1953) is a Maltese politician. <s> He served for twenty-five years in Maltese politics. <s> Gonzi was Prime Minister of Malta from 2004 to 2013, and leader of the Nationalist Party. <s> He also served as speaker of the House from 1988 to 1996, and Minister of Social Policy from 1998 to 2004, as well as Deputy Prime Minister from 1999 to 2004.

title: Fedio
complex: Fedio (also spelled Fedyo; ) is a Syrian village located in Latakia Governorate. <s> Fedio had a population of 4,065 in the 2004 census.

title: Electronic body music
complex: Electronic body music (EBM) is a genre of electronic music that combines elements of industrial music and synth-punk. <s> It developed in the early 1980s in Germany and Belgium and came to prominence in Belgium at the end of the decade. <s> EBM was generally considered a part of the European new wave and post-punk movement and the first style that blended synthesized sounds with an ecstatic style of dancing (e.g. pogo).
simple: Electronic body music (EBM, also known as aggropop) is a music genre that mixes together parts of industrial music and electronic dance music. <s> It first became popular in Belgium.

title: Uíge Province
complex: Uíge , one of the eighteen Provinces of Angola, is located in the northwestern part of the country. <s> Its capital city is of the same name.
simple: Uíge (pronounced: "Weej"), is one of the eighteen provinces of Angola. <s> It is in the northwestern part of the country.

title: Tripura
complex: Tripura is a state in northeastern India. <s> The third-smallest state in the country, it covers 10491 km2 and is bordered by Bangladesh to the north, south, and west, and the Indian states of Assam and Mizoram to the east. <s> In 2011 the state had 3,671,032 residents, constituting 0.3% of the country's population.
simple: Tripura is a state in eastern India. <s> It covers an area of 4,036 mi2.It is the 3rd smallest state of India.

title: Calymmian
complex: The Calymmian Period (from Greek κάλυμμα "(kálymma)", meaning "cover") is the first geologic period in the Mesoproterozoic Era and lasted from round 5 Mya to round 5 Mya (million years ago). <s> Instead of being based on stratigraphy, these dates are defined chronometrically. <s> The supercontinent Columbia broke up during the Calymmian some 1500 Mya.
simple: The Calymmian is the first geological period in the Mesoproterozoic. <s> The supercontinent Columbia broke up during the Calymmian about 1.5 billion years ago.

title: Caucourt
complex: Caucourt is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Caucourt is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Union County, Ohio
complex: Union County is a county located in the U.S. state of Ohio. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 52,300. <s> Its county seat is Marysville. <s> Its name is reflective of its origins, it being the union of portions of Franklin, Delaware, Madison, and Logan counties.
simple: Union County is a county in the U.S. state of Ohio. <s> In 2010, 52,300 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Marysville.

title: 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 3

title: Serbia at the 2018 Winter Paralympics
complex: Serbia sent competitors to the 2018 Winter Paralympics in Pyeongchang, South Korea. <s> One person on the team is para-Nordic skier Milos Zaric. <s> In addition to para-Nordic skier, Zaric is title: Military base
complex: The name used generally refers to the type of military activity that takes place at the base. <s> An overseas military base is a military base that is geographically located outside of the territory of the country whose armed forces are the principal occupants of the base.
simple: The name used generally refers to the type of military that uses the base. <s> A military base is where a country keeps its armed forces.

title: Taurus Mountains
complex: The Taurus Mountains (Turkish: "Toros Dağları"), are a mountain complex in southern Turkey, separating the Mediterranean coastal region of southern Turkey from the central Anatolian Plateau. <s> The system extends along a curve from Lake Eğirdir in the west to the upper reaches of the Euphrates and Tigris rivers in the east. <s> It is a part of the Alpide belt in Eurasia. <s> A Bronze Age archaeological site, where early evidence of tin mining was found, is at Kestel. <s> The pass known in antiquity as the Cilician Gates crosses the range north of Tarsus. <s> In the Aladaglar and Bolkar mountains, limestone has eroded to form karstic landscapes of waterfalls, underground rivers, and some of the largest caves of Asia. <s> The Manavgat River originates on the southern slopes of the Beydaglari range. <s> West Taurus and Taurus Mountains form an arc around the Gulf of Antalya. <s> The East Taşeli Plateau and Goksu River divide it from the Central Taurus Mountains. <s> It has many peaks rising above 3,000 – . <s> The complex is divided into four ranges: The highest point in the central Tauruses is the summit of Mt. Demirkazık (3,756m).
simple: Taurus Mountains (Turkish: "Toros Dağları") are a mountain range in Turkey, from which the Euphrates (Turkish: Fırat) and Tigris (Turkish: Dicle) descend into Syria and Iraq. <s> This mountain range divides the Mediterranean region of southern Turkey from the central plateau. <s> The mountain range extends along a curve from Lake Eğirdir in the west to the upper reaches of the Euphrates and Tigris in the east. <s> At Kestel is a Bronze Age archaeological site where early evidence of tin mining was found. <s> Limestone has eroded to form karstic landscapes of waterfalls, underground rivers, and the largest caves of Asia. <s> The Manavgat River comes from its southern slopes. <s> It has many peaks rising above 10,000–12,000 ft (3,000–3,700 m), with the Demirkazık summit in the region known as Aladağlar, at 3,756 meters (12,322 ft.) as the highest point.

title: Plumetot
complex: Plumetot is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Plumetot is a commune. <s> It is in the Basse-Normandie region in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Yaroslavl
complex: Yaroslavl (Russian: ) is a city and the administrative center of Yaroslavl Oblast, Russia, located 250 km northeast of Moscow. <s> The historic part of the city, a World Heritage Site, is located at the confluence of the Volga and the Kotorosl Rivers. <s> It is one of the Golden Ring cities, a group of historic cities northeast of Moscow that have played an important role in Russian history. <s> In 2010, the city had a population of 591,486. <s> Preceded by Viking sites such as Timerevo from the 8th or 9th centuries, the city of Yaroslavl is said to have been founded in 1010 as an outpost of the Principality of Rostov Veliky, and was first mentioned in 1071. <s> Capital of an independent Principality of Yaroslavl from 1218, it was incorporated into the Grand Duchy of Moscow in 1463.
simple: Yaroslavl is a Russian city on the Volga River. <s> The city's centre is a World Heritage Site. <s> It is one of the Golden Ring cities, a group of historic cities northeast of Moscow. <s> It was founded in 1010.
