title: Weber–Fechner law
complex: The relationship between stimulus and perception is logarithmic. <s> This logarithmic relationship means that if a stimulus varies as a geometric progression (i.e., multiplied by a fixed factor), the corresponding perception is altered in an arithmetic progression (i.e., in additive constant amounts). <s> For example, if a stimulus is tripled in strength (i.e., 3 × 1 ), the corresponding perception may be two times as strong as its original value (i.e., 1 + 1 ). <s> If the stimulus is again tripled in strength (i.e., 3 × 3 × 1 ), the corresponding perception will be three times as strong as its original value (i.e., 1 + 1 + 1 ). <s> Hence, for multiplications in stimulus strength, the strength of perception only adds. <s> The mathematical derivations of the torques on a simple beam balance produce a description that is strictly compatible with Weber's law. <s> Weber found that the just noticeable difference (JND) between two weights was approximately proportional to the weights. <s> Thus, if the weight of 105 g can (only just) be distinguished from that of 100 g, the JND (or differential threshold) is 5 g. <s> If the mass is doubled, the differential threshold also doubles to 10 g, so that 210 g can be distinguished from 200 g. <s> In this example, a weight (any weight) seems to have to increase by 5% for someone to be able to reliably detect the increase, and this minimum required fractional increase (of 5/100 of the original weight) is referred to as the "Weber fraction" for detecting changes in weight.
simple: The relationship between stimulus and perception is logarithmic. <s> This logarithmic relationship is valid, not just for the sensation of weight, but for other stimuli and our sensory perceptions as well. <s> This logarithmic relationship means that if a stimulus varies as a geometric progression (i.e. multiplied by a fixed factor), the corresponding perception is altered in an arithmetic progression (i.e. in additive constant amounts). <s> For example, if a stimulus is tripled in strength (i.e., 3 x 1), the corresponding perception may be two times as strong as its original value (i.e., 1 + 1). <s> If the stimulus is again tripled in strength (i.e., 3 x 3 x 1), the corresponding perception will be three times as strong as its original value (i.e., 1 + 1 + 1). <s> Hence, for multiplications in stimulus strength, the strength of perception only adds. <s> Weber found that the response was proportional to a relative increase in the weight. <s> If the mass is doubled, the threshold is also doubled.

title: Youcef Yousfi
complex: Youcef Yousfi (born 2 October 1941) is an Algerian politician who has been Minister of Energy and Mines between 2010 and 2015. <s> He briefly served as Acting Prime Minister of Algeria in March–April 2014. <s> Yousfi was Algeria's Permanent Representative to the United Nations from 2006 to 2008.
simple: Youcef Yousfi (born 2 October 1941) is an Algerian politician. <s> He has been Minister of Energy and Mines since 2010. <s> He briefly served as Acting Prime Minister of Algeria in March–April 2014. <s> Yousfi was Algeria's Permanent Representative to the United Nations from 2006 to 2008.

title: Tommy Kono
complex: Tamio "Tommy" Kono (June 27, 1930 – April 24, 2016) was an American weightlifter in the 1950s and 1960s. <s> Kono set world records in four different weight classes: lightweight (149 pounds or 67.5 kilograms), middleweight (165 lb or 75 kg), light-heavyweight (182 lb or 82.5 kg), and middle-heavyweight (198 lb or 90 kg). <s> Along with his weightlifting and bodybuilding titles, Kono was an eight-time Amateur Athletic Union James E. Sullivan Award finalist, an award given annually to the top American amateur athlete. <s> He was also one of the first members of the Hawaii Sports Hall of Fame in 1978. <s> In 1990, Kono received the Association of Oldetime Barbell and Strongmen Highest Achievement Award and was inducted into the United States Olympic Hall of Fame. <s> He was elected to the International Weightlifting Federation Hall of Fame in 1993. <s> In 2005, the International Weightlifting Federation named Kono the ""Lifter of the Century"." <s> Kono died on April 24, 2016 in Honolulu, Hawaii from complications of liver disease, aged 85.
simple: Tamio "Tommy" Kono (June 27, 1930 – April 24, 2016) was an American weightlifter in the 1950s and 1960s. <s> Kono was the only Olympic weightlifter in history to have set world records in four different weight classes: lightweight (149 pounds or 67.5 kilograms), middleweight (165 lb or 75 kg), light-heavyweight (182 lb or 82.5 kg), and middle-heavyweight (198 lb or 90 kg). <s> Kono was also an inductee to the Association of Oldetime Barbell and Strongmen (A.O.B.S.) Hall of Fame. <s> In 1993 Kono was elected to the International Weightlifting Federation Hall of Fame. <s> Kono died on April 24, 2016 in Honolulu, Hawaii from complications of liver disease, aged 85.

title: Aurangzeb
complex: Muhi-ud-Din Muhammad (3 November 16183 March 1707), commonly known by the sobriquet Aurangzeb (Persian: "Ornament of the Throne") or by his regnal title Alamgir (Persian: "Conqueror of the World"), was the sixth Mughal emperor, who ruled over almost the entire South Asia for a period of 49 years. <s> Widely considered to be the last effective major ruler of the Mughal Empire, Aurangzeb compiled the Fatawa-e-Alamgiri, and was among the few monarchs to have fully established Sharia law and Islamic economics throughout the Indian subcontinent. <s> He was an accomplished military leader whose rule has been the subject of praise, though he has also been described as the most controversial ruler in Indian history. <s> He was a notable expansionist; during his reign, the Mughal Empire reached its greatest extent, ruling over nearly all of the Indian subcontinent. <s> During his lifetime, victories in the south expanded the Mughal Empire to 4 million square kilometres, and he ruled over a population estimated to be over 158 million subjects, with an annual revenue of $450 million (more than ten times that of his contemporary Louis XIV of France), or £38,624,680 (2,879,469,894 rupees) in 1690. <s> Under his reign, India surpassed Qing China to become the world's largest economy and biggest manufacturing power, worth nearly a quarter of global GDP and more than the entirety of Western Europe, and its largest and wealthiest subdivision, the Bengal Subah, signaled the proto-industrialization. <s> By 1689, the conquest of Golconda, Mughal victories in the south expanded the Mughal Empire to 4 million square kilometres, with a population estimated to be over 158 million. <s> But this supremacy was short-lived. <s> Jos Gommans, Professor of Colonial and Global History at the University of Leiden, says that "... the highpoint of imperial centralisation under emperor Aurangzeb coincided with the start of the imperial downfall." <s> Many Indian historians consider his death year 1707 as the one which marks the end of Medieval Indian history and the start of Modern Indian history when classifying Indian history. <s> This is because of the start of decline of the Mughal empire and the start of domination of European powers in India.
simple: Muhi-ud-Din Muhammad also known as Aurangzeb or by his title Alamgir was the sixth emperor of the Mughal Empire. <s> His reign lasted for 49 years from 1658 until his death in 1707. <s> He compiled the Fatawa Alamgiri, which served as the Islamic law of India. <s> During this time, Aurangzeb greatly expanded the territory of the Mughal Empire. <s> Victories in the south expanded the Empire to more than 3.2 million square kilometres. <s> His empire was the world's largest economy, valued 25% of world's GDP. <s> After his death, the power of the Mughal Empire declined quickly.

title: Ithaca Tompkins Regional Airport
complex: Ithaca Tompkins Regional Airport is a county-owned airport three miles northeast of Ithaca, the county seat and only city in Tompkins County, New York. <s> The National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems for 2011–2015 categorized it as a "primary commercial service" facility. <s> Federal Aviation Administration records say the airport had 103,501 passenger boardings (enplanements) in 2013. <s> The original Ithaca Municipal Airport was west of downtown Ithaca, near the inlet of Cayuga Lake. <s> Its single short runway, proximity to the Lehigh Valley freight yards on the south side, the Cayuga Lake marshes on the north side, and fog in the lake valley limited its growth. <s> Cornell University opened the existing airport on East Hill in 1948 and transferred its ownership to the County in 1956. <s> The former airport site is now Cass Park, including a hangar which was renovated in 1975 to house the Hangar Theatre. <s> In 1994, a new, 33,000 square foot (3,000 m2), $11-million terminal opened, replacing the cramped original building. <s> Simultaneously, the runway was extended from 5801 ft to its present 6977 ft . <s> Runway 32 has an instrument landing system and a medium intensity approach light system with runway alignment lights. <s> Runway 14 has an instrument approach based on the VOR/DME at the airport. <s> A short turf runway was commissioned parallel to the paved runway, but during the 1980s a north-south turf runway was west of the terminal building, about 1802 ft long and 100 ft wide. <s> Airline traffic peaked in 1990 at 226,813 passengers, but by the end of the decade the small size of the market, proximity to Syracuse Hancock International Airport and other regional airports, and crowded airspace led Trans World Airlines, United Airlines, and finally Continental Airlines to leave. <s> In 2001, the airport renamed itself the Ithaca Tompkins Regional Airport, replacing its former moniker, the Tompkins County Airport. <s> In late 2004, after negotiations with the County, Northwest Airlines agreed to add Northwest Airlink service to Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport, which began May 2, 2005. <s> US Airways nonstops to Pittsburgh, a focus city, resumed on November 9, 2005 but ended on April 1, 2006 due to low yield. <s> Passenger traffic has improved with the additional service; the airport served about 140,000 passengers in 2004, increasing to around 170,000 in 2007. <s> On October 6, 2008, Continental Connection resumed service between Ithaca and Newark Liberty International Airport with four daily flights. <s> In 2011, the airport served 242,493 passengers on three airlines. <s> The airport covers 531 acres (215 ha) at an elevation of 1,099 feet (335 m). <s> It has two runways: 14/32 is 6,977 by 150 feet (2,127 x 46 m) asphalt and 15/33 is 2,018 by 50 feet (615 x 15 m) turf. <s> In 2011 the airport had 41,286 aircraft operations, average 113 per day: 77% general aviation, 23% air taxi, < 1% military, and < 1% airline. <s> 57 aircraft were then based at the airport: 77% single-engine, 9% multi-engine, and 14% jet. <s> For over 60 years, the airport has been home to the East Hill Flying Club. <s> The club offers lessons and the use of nine small planes to its members. <s> It is also the home of Taughannock Aviation which provides business jet charter and management as well as being the fixed-base operator. <s> TCAT Route 32 travels to Cornell University and downtown Ithaca (Ithaca Commons) Monday through Friday. <s> On weekends similar service is on Route 72. <s> Both routes operate hourly, or more frequently, throughout most of the day. <s> Ithaca Dispatch (Cayuga, University, Yellow Cab) operates a taxi stand at the airport, although it may be necessary to call in advance, especially during peak hours. <s> Fares to the airport are standardized. <s> Uber and Lyft also operate in Ithaca.
simple: Ithaca Tompkins Regional Airport is a county-owned public-use airport three miles (5 km) northeast of the central business district of Ithaca, the county seat and largest city in Tompkins County, New York, United States. <s> The original Ithaca Municipal Airport was located west of downtown Ithaca, near the inlet of Cayuga Lake. <s> Its single short runway, proximity to the Lehigh Valley freight yards on the south side, the Cayuga Lake marshes on the north side, and fog in the lake valley limited its growth. <s> Cornell University opened the existing airport on East Hill in 1948 and transferred its ownership to the County in 1956. <s> The former airport site is now Cass Park, including an airplane hangar which was renovated in 1975 to house the Hangar Theatre. <s> In 1994, the runway was extended from 5801 ft in length to its present 6601 ft and an entirely new, 33,000 square foot (3,000 m2) terminal building opened, replacing the cramped, aging original building. <s> The northwest-facing runway 32 has an instrument landing system approach and an associated medium intensity approach light system with runway alignment lights. <s> Runway 14, facing southeast, has an instrument approach based on the VOR/DME located at the airport. <s> A short turf runway was built parallel to the paved runway, but during the 1980s another turf runway oriented north-south was available to the west of the terminal building and was approximately 1802 ft long and 100 ft wide. <s> Commercial traffic peaked in 1990 at 226,813 passengers. <s> The airport was hurt by the small size of the market, relative proximity to Syracuse Hancock International Airport and other regional airports, and crowded conditions in Northeastern airspace. <s> The airport name changed from Tompkins County Airport to its current name on March 20, 2001. <s> In late 2004, after negotiations with the County, Northwest Airlines agreed to add Northwest Airlink service to Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport, which began on May 2, 2005. <s> US Airways nonstop service to Pittsburgh resumed on November 9, 2005 but stopped again on April 1, 2006 due to low use. <s> Passenger traffic improved with the additional service; the airport served about 140,000 passengers in 2004, increasing to around 170,000 in 2007. <s> On October 6, 2008, Continental Connection resumed service between Ithaca and Newark Liberty International Airport with four daily flights. <s> Ithaca Tompkins Regional Airport covers an area of 531 acre which contains two runways: 14/32 with 6,601 x 150 ft (2,012 x 46 m) asphalt pavement and 15/33 with a 2,018 x 50 ft (615 x 15 m) turf surface. <s> At that time there were 62 aircraft based at this airport: 68% single-engine, 15% multi-engine, 16% jet and 2% ultralight. <s> For over 50 years, the East Hill Flying Club has been at the airport. <s> The club offers lessons and the use of seven small planes to its members. <s> Taughannock Aviation which provides business jet charter and management is the fixed base operator for the airport. <s> TCAT Route 32 travels to the Commons and Cornell University Monday through Friday, As of 2010, Route 72 serves the airport on weekends. <s> Ithaca Dispatch (Cayuga, University, Yellow Cab) operates a taxi stand at the airport, although it may be necessary to call in advance, especially during peak hours. <s> Fares to and from the airport are standardized.

title: Balloonfest '86
complex: Balloonfest '86 was a 1986 event in which the United Way of Cleveland in Ohio set a world record by releasing almost one-and-a-half million balloons. <s> The event was intended to be a harmless fundraising publicity stunt, but the balloons drifted back over the city, Lake Erie, and landed in the surrounding area, and caused problems for traffic and a nearby airport. <s> The event also interfered with a United States Coast Guard search for two boaters who were later found drowned. <s> In consequence, the organizers and the city faced lawsuits seeking millions of dollars in damages, and cost overruns put the event at a net loss.
simple: Balloonfest '86 was a 1986 event in Cleveland, Ohio. <s> Almost one and a half million balloons were released into the sky. <s> The balloons flew over Lake Erie and areas near there. <s> Two boaters were found dead from drowning. <s> The city faced lawsuits of millions of dollars in damage.

title: Tak Province
complex: Tak ( , ] ) is one of the western provinces ("changwat") of Thailand. <s> Neighbouring provinces are (from north clockwise) Mae Hong Son, Chiang Mai, Lamphun, Lampang, Sukhothai, Kamphaeng Phet, Nakhon Sawan, Uthai Thani and Kanchanaburi. <s> The western edge of the province has a long boundary with Kayin State of Myanmar (Burma). <s> The province is divided into nine districts ("amphoes"). <s> These are further subdivided into 63 sub-districts ("tambons") and 493 villages ("mubans"). <s> Since 2003, United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in Thailand has tracked progress on human development at sub national level using the Human achievement index (HAI), a composite index covering all the eight key areas of human development.Province Tak, with an HAI value of 0.5650 is "low", occupies 75th place in the ranking and that is the second-last of this rank list.
simple: Tak is one of the northern provinces ("changwat") of Thailand. <s> Tak's neighbouring provinces are (clockwise from north) Mae Hong Son, Chiang Mai, Lamphun, Lampang, Sukhothai, Kamphaeng Phet, Nakhon Sawan, Uthai Thani and Kanchanaburi. <s> The western edge of Tak borders Kayin State of Myanmar. <s> Tak has 9 districts ("amphoe"), 63 subdistricts ("tambon") and 493 villages ("muban").

title: Raghbir Singh Bhola
complex: Raghbir Singh Bhola (21 August 1927 – 21 January 2019) was an Indian Airforce Officer and international hockey player who represented India in the 1956 Melbourne and 1960 Rome Olympics, winning a gold and silver medal respectively for the country. <s> Bhola, was born in a middle-class family in Multan (now Pakistan); his ancestors belonged to Pind Dadan Khan and his grandparents moved to Multan around the end of the 18th Century. <s> He went to the Government Model High School, in Khanewal, Pakistan.
simple: Raghbir Singh Bhola (21 August 1927 – 22 January 2019) was an Indian Airforce Officer and a former India hockey player. <s> He represented India in the 1956 Melbourne and 1960 Rome Olympics, winning a gold and silver medal respectively for the country. <s> He was born in Multan, Pakistan.
