title: Yuri Lyubimov
complex: Yuri Petrovich Lyubimov ( ; 30 September O.S. 17 September 1917 5 October 2014) was a Soviet and Russian stage actor and director associated with the internationally renowned Taganka Theatre, which he founded in 1964. <s> He was one of the leading names in the Russian theatre world. <s> After service in the Red Army during World War II, Lyubimov joined the Vakhtangov Theatre (founded by Yevgeny Vakhtangov). <s> In 1953, he received the USSR State Prize. <s> Lyubimov started teaching in 1963 and formed the Taganka Theatre the following year. <s> His celebrated production of Bertold Brecht's "The Good Person of Setzuan" with Anna Orochko's class at the Schukin Theatre Institute earned him the artistic directorship of the Taganka Theatre. <s> With Meyerhold, Stanislavsky, Vakhtangov and Brecht as his spiritual guides, Lyubimov eschewed Soviet drama for the more imaginative worlds of poetry and narrative fiction, which he dramatized, and the classics, which he broke apart, reconstituted and presented from a pronounced critical perspective. <s> Under Lyubimov, the theatre rose to become the most popular in Moscow, with Vladimir Vysotsky and Alla Demidova as the leading actors. <s> In 1971 Shakespeare's "Hamlet" became one of Lyubimov's highly successful and much acclaimed productions. <s> In 1976 he was awarded by the BITEF First Prize for "Hamlet". <s> After Vysotsky's death in 1980, all of Lyubimov's productions were banned by the Communist authorities. <s> In 1984, he was stripped of Soviet citizenship. <s> Thereupon he worked abroad before returning to the Taganka Theatre in 1989. <s> His staging of "Eugene Onegin" premiered in the Taganka on his 85th birthday to much critical acclaim. <s> While in the West he maintained a busy directing career. <s> In the United States he directed "Crime and Punishment" at Arena Stage and "Lulu" at the Lyric Opera of Chicago. <s> In 1983 he directed Crime and Punishment in London, winning the Evening Standard Award for Best Director, in 1985 he directed St Matthew Passion at La Scala. <s> His effort to re-stage his famous "The Master and Margarita" at the American Repertory Theater failed to materialize because of a disagreement with the management of that company. <s> In 1989, his Russian citizenship was restored. <s> In June 2011, before a performance of Bertolt Brecht's play "The Good Person of Szechwan" in Czech, the actors of Taganka refused to rehearse unless they were paid first. <s> Lyubimov paid the money and left the theatre. <s> "I've had enough of this disgrace, these humiliations, this lack of desire to work, this desire just for money", he said. <s> Lyubimov retired from the theatre the following week. <s> Two leading actors of theatre, Dmitry Mezhevich and Alla Smirdan, as well as some administrative assistants, followed Lyubimov. <s> His dramatization of Dostoyevsky's "Demons" premiered the next year. <s> Lyubimov, a director who dominated Russian theatre for half a century, died at 97, after being admitted to the Botkin Clinic in Moscow with heart failure.
simple: Yuri Petrovich Lyubimov (September 30, 1917 – October 5, 2014) is a Soviet and Russian actor and director, founder of the internationally-renowned Taganka Theatre. <s> He is one of the leading names in the Russian theatre world. <s> After service in the Soviet Army during the World War II, Lyubimov joined the Vakhtangov Theatre. <s> In 1953, he received the "USSR State Prize". <s> Lyubimov started teaching in 1963 and formed the Taganka Theatre the following year. <s> Under Lyubimov, the theatre became the most popular in Moscow, with Vladimir Vysotsky and Alla Demidova as the leading actors. <s> After Vysotsky's death in 1980, all of Lyubimov's productions were banned by the Communist authorities. <s> In 1984, he was stripped of Soviet citizenship. <s> Thereupon Lyubimov worked abroad before returning to the Taganka Theatre in 1989. <s> His staging of "Eugene Onegin" premiered in the Taganka on his 85th birthday to much critical acclaim. <s> While in the West he maintained a busy directing career. <s> In the US he directed "Crime and Punishment" at Arena Stage and "Lulu" at the Lyric Opera of Chicago. <s> In 1983 he directed "Crime and Punishment" in London, winning the Evening Standard Award for Best Director. <s> In June, 2011 Lyubimov left the Taganka theatre. <s> Lyubimov died at 97 after being admitted to the Botkin Clinic in Moscow with heart failure.

title: Ettore Boiardi
complex: Ettore Boiardi (October 22, 1897 – June 21, 1985), better known by an Anglicized version of his name, Hector Boyardee, was an Italian-American chef, famous for his brand of food products, named Chef Boyardee. <s> Boiardi was born in Piacenza, Italy, in 1897, to Giuseppe and Maria Maffi Boiardi. <s> On May 9, 1914, at the age of 16, he arrived at Ellis Island aboard "La Lorraine", a ship of French registration. <s> Boiardi died of natural causes on June 21, 1985, at age 87 in his home of Parma, Ohio, survived by his wife Helen and son Mario. <s> He had two grandchildren.
simple: Ettore "Hector" Boiardi (October 22, 1897 – June 21, 1985) was an Italian-American chef. <s> He was famous for his brand of food products, named "Chef Boyardee". <s> Boiardi was born in Piacenza, Italy. <s> Boiardi was married to Helen Wroblewski from 1923 until his death in 1985. <s> He had a son, Mario Boiardi. <s> Boiardi died on June 21, 1985 in Parma, Ohio from natural causes, aged 87.

title: Forsbacka
complex: Forsbacka is a locality situated in Gävle Municipality, Gävleborg County, Sweden with 1,702 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Forsbacka is a locality in Gävle Municipality in Gävleborg County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 1,702 people lived there.

title: Zomergem
complex: Zomergem (] ) is a former municipality located in the Flanders and in the province of East Flanders, in Belgium. <s> The municipality comprises the towns of Oostwinkel, Ronsele and Zomergem proper.
simple: Zomergem is a municipality in the Belgian province of East Flanders.

title: Chitral District
complex: Chitral District is the largest district in the Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan, covering an area of 14,850 km2. <s> Part of the Malakand Division, it is the northernmost district of Pakistan. <s> It shares a border with Gilgit-Baltistan to the east, with Kunar, Badakshan and Nuristan provinces of Afghanistan to the north and west, and with the Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa districts of Swat and Dir to the south. <s> A narrow strip of Wakhan Corridor separates Chitral from Tajikistan in the north. <s> Chitral is counted amongst the highest regions of the world, sweeping from 1,094 meters at Arandu to 7,726 meters at Tirichmir, and packing over 40 peaks more than 6,100 meters in height. <s> The terrain of Chitral is very mountainous and Tirich Mir (25,289 feet) the highest peak of the Hindu Kush, rises in the north of the district. <s> Around 4.8 per cent of the land is covered by forest and 76 per cent is mountains and glaciers. <s> Chitral is connected to the rest of Pakistan by two major road routes, the Lowari Pass (el. <s> 10,230 ft.) from Dir and Shandur Top (elevation 12,200 ft.) from Gilgit. <s> Both routes are closed in winter. <s> The Lowari Tunnel is being constructed under the Lowari Pass. <s> A number of other high passes, including Darkot Pass, Thoi Pass and Zagaran Pass, provide access on foot to Chitral from Gilgit-Baltistan in Ghizer District. <s> The district has a population of about 414,000. <s> The general population is mainly of the Kho people, who speak the Khowar, which is also spoken in parts of Yasin, Gilgit, Dir and Swat. <s> Chitral is also home to the Kalash tribe, who live in Bumburet and two other remote valleys southwest of Chitral town. <s> The town of Chitral is the main town in the district and serves as its capital. <s> It is situated on the west bank of the Chitral River (also known as the Kunar River) at the foot of Tirich Mir which at 7,708 m (25,289 ft) is the highest peak of the Hindu Kush. <s> Until 1969, it served as the capital of the princely state of Chitral. <s> This district is represented by one elected MNA (Member of National Assembly) in Pakistan National Assembly. <s> Its constituency is NA-32.
simple: Chitral is a district in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan. <s> It is the largest district in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, with an area of 14,850 sq. kilometres. <s> Chitral District is the most northerly district in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province. <s> The terrain of Chitral is quite mountainous, part of the Pamir Mountains are situated here. <s> Tirich Mir which at 25,289 feet (7,708 metres) is the highest peak of the Hindu Kush, rises in the north of the district. <s> Chitral is connected to the rest of Pakistan by only two road routes, the Lowari Pass (el. <s> 10,230 ft.) from Dir and Shandur Top (el. <s> 12,200 ft.) from Gilgit. <s> Both routes are closed in winter. <s> Both are closed in winter. <s> The Lowari Tunnel is being constructed under the Lowari Pass and is opened two times a week when Lowari Top is closed due to snowfall. <s> Two other passes give access on foot to Chitral, the Broghol Pass and the Dorah Pass, both from Afghanistan. <s> The general population is mainly of the Kho people, who speak the Khowar language (or Chitrali), which is also spoken in parts of Yasin, Gilgit and Swat. <s> Chitral is also home to the Kalash tribe who live in three remote valleys southwest of Chitral town. <s> Until 1969, Chitral was a princely state, within the Malakand Agency. <s> This district is represented by one elected MNA (Member of National Assembly) in Pakistan National Assembly. <s> Its constituency is NA-32.

title: Lake Thun
complex: Lake Thun is an Alpine lake in the Bernese Oberland in Switzerland named after the city of Thun, on its northern shore. <s> Lake Thun's approximate 2,500 km2 (970 sq mi) catchment area frequently causes local flooding after heavy rainfalls. <s> This occurs because the river Aare , which drains Lake Thun, has only limited capacity to handle the excess runoff. <s> The lake is fed by water from Lake Brienz to the southeast, which is 6 m higher than Lake Thun, and various streams in the Oberland, including the Kander.
simple: Lake Thun is a Alpine lake in the Bernese Oberland in Switzerland named by the city of Thun. <s> It is on the northern shore. <s> The 2,500 km2 catchment area often causes local flooding after heavy rainfalls. <s> This occurs because the river Aare, which drains Lake Thun, can only hold some of the extra runoff. <s> The lake is fed by water from Lake Brienz to the southeast, which is 6 metres higher than Lake Thun. <s> It is also fed by various streams in the Oberland, including the Kander.

title: Mary Wells Lawrence
complex: Mary Wells Lawrence (born Mary Georgene Berg on May 25, 1928 in Youngstown, Ohio, United States) is a retired American advertising executive. <s> She was the founding president of Wells, Rich, Greene, an advertising agency known for its creative work. <s> Lawrence was the first female CEO of a company listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
simple: Mary Wells Lawrence (born Mary Georgene Berg on May 25, 1928) is a retired American advertising executive. <s> She was the founding president of Wells Rich Greene, an advertising agency. <s> Lawrence was the first female CEO of a company listed on the New York Stock Exchange.

title: Carl Icahn
complex: Carl Celian Icahn ( ; born February 16, 1936) is an American businessman, investor, and philanthropist. <s> He is the founder and controlling shareholder of Icahn Enterprises, a diversified conglomerate holding company based in New York City, formerly known as American Real Estate Partners. <s> He is also Chairman of Federal-Mogul, an American developer, manufacturer and supplier of powertrain components and vehicle safety products. <s> In the 1980s Icahn developed a reputation as a "corporate raider" after profiting from the hostile takeover and asset stripping of the American airline TWA. <s> According to "Forbes" magazine, Icahn had a net worth of $17 billion in 2019, making him the 26th-wealthiest person on the Forbes 400, and the 5th-wealthiest hedge fund manager. <s> Icahn was raised in a Jewish family in the Far Rockaway, Queens neighborhood of New York City, where he attended Far Rockaway High School. <s> His father, Michael Icahn, an atheist, was a cantor, and later a substitute teacher. <s> His mother, Bella (née Schnall) also worked as a schoolteacher. <s> Icahn graduated from Princeton University with a Bachelor of Arts degree in philosophy in 1957 and then entered New York University School of Medicine, but he dropped out after two years to join the army reserves. <s> Icahn endorsed Donald Trump for the 2016 U.S. presidential election. <s> He also announced the formation of a super PAC pledging $150 million to push for corporate tax reform, in particular of inversions, which occur when corporations leave the U.S. to take advantage of lower tax rates elsewhere. <s> Upon becoming the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, Trump announced that he would nominate Icahn for Treasury Secretary. <s> However, this position went to Steve Mnuchin instead. <s> On December 21, 2016, it was announced that Icahn would serve as Special Advisor to the President on Regulatory Reform under President Donald Trump. <s> CNBC reported that Icahn would aid Trump in an "individual capacity" rather than as a federal employee, and that he would not have "specific duties" and therefore would not have to relinquish his business interests while serving as an advisor to Trump. <s> Icahn stepped down from this role on August 18, 2017 citing a desire not to interfere with the work of Neomi Rao as Administrator of the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs. <s> In February 2018, Icahn avoided a $6 million loss by selling down his holdings in a steel-price sensitive stock just days before the Trump administration announced a new 25% tariff to be imposed on steel imports. <s> In 1979, Icahn married Liba Trejbal, a ballerina from the former Czechoslovakia. <s> They separated in 1993 and divorced in 1999 after years of litigation during which Liba sought to invalidate a prenuptial agreement she had signed prior to their marriage, claiming duress as she was pregnant at the time. <s> Liba originally fought Icahn's offer of roughly $1.5 million a year because he was worth billions at the time and eventually settled for an undisclosed amount. <s> They have two children, Brett Icahn and Michelle Celia Icahn Nevin. <s> His nephew is Rick Schnall. <s> In 1999, Icahn married his longtime assistant and former broker, Gail Golden. <s> She has two children from a previous marriage.
simple: Carl Celian Icahn (born February 16, 1936) is an American business magnate, investor, activist shareholder, and philanthropist. <s> He is the founder and majority shareholder of Icahn Enterprises, a diversified conglomerate holding company based in New York City, formerly known as American Real Estate Partners. <s> Icahn is also Chairman of Federal-Mogul, an American developer of vehicle safety products. <s> In the 1980s Icahn became known as a "corporate raider" after profiting from the hostile takeover and asset stripping of the American airline TWA. <s> Icahn was born in a Jewish family in New York City. <s> He studied at Princeton University and at New York University. <s> Icahn endorsed Donald Trump for the 2016 U.S. presidential election. <s> Trump announced in October 2015 that he would nominate Icahn for Treasury Secretary if he were to be elected. <s> However, this position went to Steve Mnuchin instead. <s> On December 21, 2016, it was announced that Icahn would serve as Special Advisor to the President on Regulatory Reform under President Donald Trump. <s> Icahn stepped down from the role in August 2017. <s> From 1979 through 1999, Icahn was married to Liba Trejbal. <s> He has two children including businessman Brett Icahn. <s> In 1999, he married Gail Golden.

title: Guido Cavalcanti
complex: Guido Cavalcanti (between 1250 and 1259 – August 1300) was an Italian poet and troubadour, as well as an intellectual influence on his best friend, Dante Alighieri. <s> Cavalcanti is widely regarded as the first major poet of Italian literature: Dante calls him "mentor". <s> In the Commedia he says through Oderisi da Gubbio that "...ha tolto l'uno a l'altro Guido / la gloria de la lingua" (Purgatory XI, 97-8): the verse of the latter, younger Guido (Cavalcanti) has surpassed that of the former, (Guido) Guinizzelli, the founder of Dolce Stil Novo.
simple: Guido Cavalcanti (1259 – August 1300) was an Italian poet from Florence. <s> He was the best friend of Dante Alighieri as well as an influence on his thinking. <s> Cavalcanti is one of the most important poet of Dolce stil novo, and he is widely regarded as the first major poet of Italian literature.

title: Francis Collins
complex: Francis Sellers Collins (born April 14, 1950) is an American physician-geneticist who discovered the genes associated with a number of diseases and led the Human Genome Project. <s> He is director of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) in Bethesda, Maryland, United States. <s> Before being appointed director of the NIH, Collins led the Human Genome Project and other genomics research initiatives as director of the National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI), one of the 27 institutes and centers at NIH. <s> Before joining NHGRI, he earned a reputation as a gene hunter at the University of Michigan. <s> He has been elected to the Institute of Medicine and the National Academy of Sciences, and has received the Presidential Medal of Freedom and the National Medal of Science.
simple: Francis Sellers Collins (born April 14, 1950) is an American physician-geneticist. <s> He is known for his discoveries of disease genes and his leadership of the Human Genome Project. <s> He is director of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) in Bethesda, Maryland since 2009. <s> Before being appointed director of the NIH, Collins led the Human Genome Project and other genomics research initiatives as director of the National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI), one of the 27 institutes and centers at NIH. <s> Before joining NHGRI, he earned a reputation as a gene hunter at the University of Michigan. <s> He has been elected to the Institute of Medicine and the National Academy of Sciences, and has received the Presidential Medal of Freedom and the National Medal of Science.

title: Dr. Seuss
complex: Theodor Seuss Geisel ( or ; March 2, 1904 – September 24, 1991) was an American children's author, political cartoonist, illustrator, poet, animator, screenwriter, and filmmaker. <s> He is known for his work writing and illustrating more than 60 books under the pen name Doctor Seuss ( or abbreviated Dr. Seuss). <s> His work includes many of the most popular children's books of all time, selling over 600 million copies and being translated into more than 20 languages by the time of his death. <s> Geisel died of oral cancer on September 24, 1991 at his home in La Jolla, California at the age of 87. <s> He was cremated and his ashes were scattered. <s> On December 1, 1995, four years after his death, University of California, San Diego's University Library Building was renamed Geisel Library in honor of Geisel and Audrey for the generous contributions that they made to the library and their devotion to improving literacy. <s> Geisel wrote more than 60 books over the course of his long career. <s> Most were published under his well-known pseudonym Dr. Seuss, though he also authored more than a dozen books as Theo LeSieg and one as Rosetta Stone. <s> His books have topped many bestseller lists, sold over 600 million copies, and been translated into more than 20 languages. <s> In 2000, "Publishers Weekly" compiled a list of the best-selling children's books of all time; of the top 100 hardcover books, 16 were written by Geisel, including "Green Eggs and Ham", at number 4, "The Cat in the Hat", at number 9, and "One Fish, Two Fish, Red Fish, Blue Fish", at number 13. <s> In the years after his death in 1991, two additional books were published based on his sketches and notes: "Hooray for Diffendoofer Day!" <s> "My Many Colored Days" was originally written in 1973 but was posthumously published in 1996. <s> In September 2011, seven stories originally published in magazines during the 1950s were released in a collection titled "The Bippolo Seed and Other Lost Stories".
simple: Theodor Seuss Geisel (; March 2, 1904 – September 24, 1991) was an American writer and cartoonist from Springfield, Massachusetts. <s> Theodor Seuss Geisel is one of the most popular children's authors of all time. <s> He was better known by his pen name, Dr. Seuss. <s> Dr. Seuss died from oral cancer in La Jolla, California, aged 87. <s> In his long life Geisel wrote more than 60 books. <s> Though most of them were published as Dr. Seuss, he also wrote 13 books as Theo. <s> His books have sold over 222 million copies and been translated into more than 15 languages. <s> In the years after his death in 1991, several books have been published based on his sketches and notes; these include "Hooray for Diffendoofer Day!" <s> Though they were all published under the name Dr. Seuss, only "My Many Colored Days", originally written in 1973, was entirely by Geisel.

title: Formosa Province
complex: Formosa Province (] ) is a province in northeastern Argentina, part of the Gran Chaco Region. <s> Its northeast end touches Asunción, Paraguay, and borders the provinces of Chaco and Salta to its south and west, respectively. <s> The capital is Formosa. <s> Formosa's protected areas are the Río Pilcomayo National Park and the Formosa National Reserve.
simple: Formosa Province is a province in northeastern Argentina. <s> Formosa is one of the poorest provinces in Argentina. <s> Its northeast end touches Asunción, Paraguay. <s> The capital is Formosa. <s> Formosa's protected areas are the Río Pilcomayo National Park and the Formosa National Reserve.

title: Uganda at the Olympics
complex: Uganda first participated at the Olympic Games in 1956, and has sent athletes to compete in every Summer Olympic Games since then, except for the boycotted 1976 Summer Olympics. <s> Uganda has never competed at the Winter Olympic Games. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Uganda was created in 1950 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee in 1956.
simple: Uganda was first at the Olympic Games in 1956. <s> They have been in every Summer Olympic Games since then, except for the boycotted 1976 Summer Olympics. <s> Uganda has never been at the Winter Olympic Games. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Uganda was formed in 1950 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee in 1956.

title: Bobby Freeman
complex: Robert Thomas "Bobby" Freeman (June 13, 1940 – January 23, 2017) was an African-American rock, soul and R&B singer, songwriter and record producer from San Francisco, best known for his two Top Ten hits, the first in 1958 on Josie Records called "Do You Want to Dance" and the second in 1964 for Autumn Records, "C'mon and Swim". <s> Freeman was born in the San Francisco Bay Area and spent much of his youth in San Francisco, California. <s> He attended Mission High School. <s> He started singing in a doo-wop group, the Romancers, in his early teens, and first recorded with them for Dootone Records in 1956. <s> Their recordings included "House Cat", included on several later rock and roll compilations. <s> However, the group soon fell apart, and Freeman started a new group, the Vocaleers (not to be confused with an earlier group of the same name who recorded "Is It a Dream"). <s> Freeman died of natural causes on January 23, 2017, aged 76.
simple: Robert Thomas "Bobby" Freeman (June 13, 1940 – January 28, 2017) was an African-American soul and R&B singer-songwriter and record producer. <s> He was best known for his two Top Ten hits, the first in 1958 on Josie Records called "Do You Want to Dance" and the second in 1964 for Autumn Records, "C'mon and Swim". <s> Freeman was born in Alameda County, California. <s> He was raised in San Francisco, California. <s> He studied at Mission High School. <s> Freeman died in San Francisco, California on January 28, 2017, aged 76.

title: Ray Phiri
complex: Raymond Chikapa Enock Phiri (23 March 1947 – 12 July 2017) was a South African jazz, fusion and mbaqanga musician born in Mpumalanga to Thabethe Phiri, a Malawian immigrant worker, and South African guitarist nicknamed "Just Now" Phiri. <s> He collaborated with Paul Simon and Ladysmith Black Mambazo on Simon's Graceland (album) project in 1985, and became founding member of the Cannibals in the 1970s. <s> When the Cannibals disbanded Ray founded Stimela, with whom he conceived gold and platinum-selling albums like "Fire, Passion and Ecstacy " (1982), "Look, Listen and Decide" (1986). <s> Phiri was involved in a series of car accidents which affected his personal life and musical career. <s> Phiri was badly injured in 1987 in a crash that claimed the lives of his band manager and six others. <s> In 2003, his wife was killed in a car accident, with Ray escaping serious injury. <s> Phiri was diagnosed with lung cancer and died at the age of 70 on 12 July 2017 at a Nelspruit hospital. <s> A memorial service for Phiri was held at the Mbombela Stadium in Nelspruit on 20 July, and the funeral service took place at the same venue on 22 July.
simple: Raymond Chikapa Enock Phiri (23 March 1947 – 12 July 2017) was a South African jazz guitarist, singer, fusion and mbaqanga musician. <s> He was born in Mpumalanga to Malawian immigrant worker and South African guitarist nicknamed "Just Now" Phiri. <s> Phiri became founding member of the Cannibals in the 1970s. <s> When the Cannibals disbanded Ray founded Stimela, with whom he conceived gold and platinum-selling albums like "Fire, Passion and Ecstasy" (1991), "Look, Listen and Decide" (1992) as well as the controversial "People Don't Talk So Let's Talk". <s> Phiri died at the age of 70 on 12 July 2017 at a Nelspruit hospital from lung cancer.

title: Noblesville, Indiana
complex: Noblesville is a city in and the county seat of Hamilton County, Indiana, United States, just north of Indianapolis. <s> The population was 51,969 at the 2010 census making it the state's 14th largest city/town, up from 19th in 2007.
simple: Noblesville is a city of Indiana in the United States.

title: List of World Heritage Sites in Greece
complex: There are currently 18 UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Greece. <s> Of these, 16 are inscribed based on "cultural" criteria, while the remaining two (Mount Athos, Meteora) are inscribed for meeting both "cultural" and "natural" criteria. <s> Five of the sites are located on islands, one is distributed between the islands and the mainland, with the remaining 12 exclusively on the mainland. <s> This first site to be inscribed was the Temple of Apollo at Bassae in 1986, the most recent is the Philippi, inscribed in 2016.
simple: There are 17 UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Greece. <s> Five of the places are on islands. <s> One is between the islands and the mainland. <s> The remaining 11 are on the mainland.

title: British Rail Class D3/11
complex: British Rail Class D3/11 was a locomotive commissioned by the Great Western Railway, but delivered to its successor British Rail in England. <s> It was a diesel powered locomotive in the pre-TOPS period.
simple: British Rail Class D3/11 was a locomotive commissioned by the Great Western Railway, but delivered to its successor British Rail in England. <s> It was a diesel powered locomotive in the pre-TOPS period.

title: Nâzım Hikmet
complex: Nâzım Hikmet Ran (15 January 1902 – 3 June 1963), commonly known as Nâzım Hikmet (] ) was a Turkish poet, playwright, novelist, screenwriter, director and memoirist. <s> He was acclaimed for the "lyrical flow of his statements". <s> Described as a "romantic communist" and "romantic revolutionary", he was repeatedly arrested for his political beliefs and spent much of his adult life in prison or in exile. <s> His poetry has been translated into more than fifty languages.
simple: Nâzım Hikmet Ran (15 January 1902 – 3 June 1963), commonly known as Nâzım Hikmet, was a Turkish poet, playwright and novelist. <s> He was well liked for the "lyrical flow of his statements". <s> Hikmet was often arrested for his political beliefs. <s> He spent much of his adult life in prison or in exile. <s> His poetry has been translated into more than fifty languages.

title: M1917 Browning machine gun
complex: The M1917 Browning machine gun is a heavy machine gun used by the United States armed forces in World War I, World War II, Korea; it has also been used by other nations. <s> It was a crew served, belt-fed, water-cooled machine gun that served alongside the much lighter air-cooled Browning M1919.
simple: The M1917 Browning machine gun is a .30-06 Springfield machine gun created by John Browning. <s> It was used in World War I and in World War II.

title: Louis IV of France
complex: Louis IV (September 920 / September 921 – 10 September 954), called d'Outremer or Transmarinus (both meaning "from overseas"), reigned as king of West Francia from 936 to 954. <s> A member of the Carolingian dynasty, he was the only son of king Charles the Simple and his second wife Eadgifu of Wessex, daughter of King Edward the Elder of Wessex. <s> His reign is mostly known thanks to the Annals of Flodoard and the later "Historiae" of Richerus.
simple: Louis IV (920 – September 10, 954), was king of France from 936 to 954. <s> He was a member of the Carolingian dynasty and was son of Charles III and Eadgifu of England.

title: David Choby
complex: David Raymond Choby (January 17, 1947 – June 3, 2017) was an American prelate of the Roman Catholic Church. <s> He was the 11th Bishop of Nashville, having previously served as Diocesan Administrator (2004–2006). <s> Bishop Choby was born in Nashville and baptized in the Cathedral Church of the Incarnation, where he would eventually be consecrated a bishop. <s> Bishop Choby sustained two falls in his later years, the second of which occurred in February 2017. <s> The second fall resulted in a number of serious injuries, and Bishop Choby elected to hand over governance of the diocese to Rev. David Perkin, the vicar general. <s> Bishop Choby died June 3, 2017 from infections that resulted from his injuries.
simple: David Raymond Choby (January 17, 1947 – June 3, 2017) was an American prelate of the Roman Catholic Church. <s> He was the 11th Bishop of Nashville, having served as Diocesan Administrator (2004–2006). <s> He was born in Nashville, Tennessee. <s> Choby died at the age of 70 on June 3, 2017 in Nashville, Tennessee after suffering from an infection caused by a fall.

title: Johns Creek, Georgia
complex: Johns Creek is a city in north Fulton County in the U.S. state of Georgia. <s> According to the 2010 U.S. Census, the population was 76,728. <s> The city is a northeastern suburb of Atlanta. <s> In 2017, Johns Creek ranked third on the "USA TODAY" list of "50 best cities to live in."
simple: Johns Creek is a city in the American state of Georgia. <s> It is a part of Fulton County. <s> Johns Creek is the 10th largest city in Georgia. <s> It is a suburb in the northeast of Atlanta.

title: Carlos Altamirano
complex: Carlos Altamirano Orrego (December 18, 1922 – May 19, 2019) was a Chilean lawyer and socialist politician. <s> He was the general secretary of the Chilean Socialist Party (PS) between 1971 and 1979. <s> Before that, he was deputy from 1961 to 1965 and senator from 1965 to 1973. <s> He escaped after Pinochet's coup d'état on September 11, 1973, and lived as a refugee in Cuba. <s> As a young man he won medals in the high jump event at the 1946 and 1947 South American Championships in Athletics. <s> Altamirano started as professor of financial law and public finances in the University of Chile. <s> In 1973, sectors of the Chilean Navy tried to convince leaders of the far-right paramilitary organization "Patria y Libertad" to assassinate him. <s> The plan, however, was not enacted. <s> After the September 11, 1973 coup, Altamirano fled to Cuba. <s> He wrote "Dialéctica de una Derrota" in 1977 ("Dialectics of a Defeat"). <s> He returned to Chile after the end of Pinochet's dictatorship in 1993.
simple: Carlos Altamirano Orrego (December 18, 1922 – May 19, 2019) was a Chilean lawyer. <s> He was the general secretary of the Chilean Socialist Party (PS). <s> He served from 1971 through 1979. <s> He was deputy from 1961 to 1965 and senator from 1965 to 1973. <s> He escaped after Pinochet's coup d'état on September 11, 1973. <s> He lived as a refugee in Cuba. <s> As a young man he was an athlete, winning medals in the high jump event at the 1946 and 1947 South American Championships in Athletics. <s> He returned to Chile after the end of Pinochet's dictatorship in 1993.

title: Warrel Dane
complex: Warrel Dane (born Warrel G. Baker; March 7, 1961 – December 13, 2017) was an American musician who was the lead singer for the metal bands Sanctuary and Nevermore. <s> He was a natural baritone; though he was known for his high-pitched vocals with Serpent's Knight and on the first two Sanctuary albums, later in his career, Dane became more notable for his distinctively deep, dramatic voice. <s> Dane was trained for five years as an opera singer and utilized a very broad vocal range, spanning from notes as low as the G♯ below low C, or G♯ 1, to notes as high as the B♭ below soprano C, or B♭ 5. <s> While his high head voice style vocals were much more prominent in the older Sanctuary albums, there were instances where he utilized it in Nevermore as well. <s> Sanctuary's 2014 comeback album "The Year the Sun Died" includes these higher passages on three songs. <s> Dane provided the voice of Candynose Twinskins in the musical comedy "Metalocalypse" on Adult Swim. <s> On December 13, 2017, it was reported that Dane had died of a heart attack in São Paulo, Brazil, at the age of 56. <s> It was there that he was working on his second solo album.
simple: Warrel Dane (March 7, 1961 – December 13, 2017) was an American heavy metal singer-songwriter, musician and actor. <s> He was the lead singer for the metal bands Sanctuary and Nevermore. <s> He was a natural baritone, though he was known for his high-pitched vocals with Serpent's Knight and on the first two Sanctuary albums. <s> Dane provided the voice of Candynose Twinskins in the musical comedy "Metalocalypse" on Adult Swim. <s> Dane died of a heart attack on December 13, 2017 in São Paulo, Brazil at the age of 56.

title: Cook County, Minnesota
complex: Cook County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> Around 1.8 million visitors travel to Cook County each year. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 5,176, making it the fifth-least populous county in Minnesota. <s> Its county seat is Grand Marais. <s> The Grand Portage Indian Reservation is entirely within the county.
simple: Cook County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> As of 2010, 5,176 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Grand Marais.

title: Lung tumor
complex: "Lung tumors" are neoplastic lung nodules.
simple: Lung tumors are tumors that grow in the lungs. <s> Some of the tumors are cancer.

title: Bévilard
complex: Bévilard is a municipality in the Jura bernois administrative district in the canton of Bern in Switzerland. <s> It is located in the French-speaking Bernese Jura ("Jura Bernois"). <s> On 1 January 2015 the former municipalities of Bévilard, Malleray and Pontenet merged to form the new municipality of Valbirse.
simple: Bévilard is a municipality in the administrative district of Jura bernois in the canton of Berne in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2015 the former municipalities of Bévilard, Malleray and Pontenet into the new municipality of Valbirse.

title: Euro sign
complex: The euro sign (€) is the currency sign used for the euro, the official currency of the European Union (EU) and some non-EU countries (Kosovo and Montenegro). <s> The design was presented to the public by the European Commission on 12 December 1996.
simple: The euro sign (€) is the currency sign used for the euro. <s> The euro is the official money of the Eurozone in the European Union (EU).

title: Gravitropism
complex: Gravitropism (also known as geotropism) is a coordinated process of differential growth by a plant or fungus in response to gravity pulling on it. <s> Gravity can be either "artificial gravity" or natural gravity. <s> It is a general feature of all higher and many lower plants as well as other organisms. <s> Charles Darwin was one of the first to scientifically document that roots show "positive gravitropism" and stems show "negative gravitropism". <s> That is, roots grow in the direction of gravitational pull (i.e., downward) and stems grow in the opposite direction (i.e., upwards).
simple: Gravitropism (also known as Geotropism) is a turning or growth movement by a plant, fungus, or animal in response to gravity. <s> It is a general feature of all higher and many lower plants and also in other organisms. <s> Charles Darwin was one of the first people to say that roots grow downward and stems grow upward in response to gravity.

title: Cha Du-ri
complex: Cha Du-ri (; ] or ] ] ; born 25 July 1980) is a retired German-born South Korean professional footballer. <s> He played as a right back, right winger, or striker.
simple: Cha Du-Ri (born 25 July 1980) is a South Korean football player.

title: Mitchell County, Kansas
complex: Mitchell County (standard abbreviation: MC) is a county located in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the county population was 6,373. <s> The largest city and county seat is Beloit. <s> In 1854, the Kansas Territory was organized, then in 1861 Kansas became the 34th U.S. state. <s> In 1867, Mitchell County was established. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 719 sqmi , of which 702 sqmi is land and 17 sqmi (2.4%) is water. <s> As of the census of 2010, there were 6,373 people, 2,790 households, and 1,725 families residing in the county. <s> The population density was 8.8 people per square mile (3.4/km2). <s> There were 3,296 housing units at an average density of 4.6 per square mile (1.7/km2). <s> The racial makeup of the county was 97.97% White, 0.20% Black or African American, 0.37% Native American, 0.29% Asian, 0.07% Pacific Islander, 0.26% from other races, and 0.80% from two or more races. <s> 1.14% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race. <s> Prior to 1940, Mitchell County was a swing county, backing the national winner in every presidential election from 1900 to 1936. <s> Since 1940, it has become a Republican stronghold, with only George H. W. Bush in 1992 failing to win a majority in the county due to Ross Perot's strong showing in Kansas.
simple: Mitchell County (standard abbreviation: MC) is a county in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> In 2010, 6,373 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Beloit. <s> Beloit is also the biggest city in Mitchell County. <s> In 1867, Mitchell County was created. <s> The U.S. Census Bureau says that the county has a total area of 719 sqmi. <s> Of that, 702 sqmi is land and 17 sqmi (2.4%) is water. <s> Before 1940, Mitchell County was a swing county. <s> They voted for the national winner in every presidential election from 1900 to 1936. <s> Since 1940, it has become very Republican. <s> Only George H. W. Bush in 1992 failed win a majority in the county due to Ross Perot's strong showing in Kansas.

title: Cumberland, Maine
complex: Cumberland is a town in Cumberland County, Maine, United States. <s> The population was 7,211 at the 2010 census. <s> It is part of the Portland–South Portland–Biddeford, Maine Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> Cumberland is one of the wealthiest municipalities in the state.
simple: Cumberland is a town in Cumberland County, Maine, United States. <s> The population was 7,211 at the 2010 census. <s> It is part of the Portland–South Portland–Biddeford, Maine Metropolitan Statistical Area.

title: City Loop
complex: The City Loop (originally called the Melbourne Underground Rail Loop or MURL) is a mostly-underground, partly surface-level and partly elevated subway and rail system around the central business district of Melbourne, Victoria, Australia. <s> The loop includes the city's two largest (both above-ground) stations: Flinders Street and Southern Cross (formerly Spencer Street); and three underground stations: Flagstaff, Melbourne Central (formerly Museum) and Parliament.
simple: The Melbourne City Loop is where Melbourne, Victoria's railway lines meet. <s> The stations in the loop are Flinders Street Station, Southern Cross Station, Parliament, Melbourne Central and Flagstaff.

title: Kaulaulaokalani
complex: Kaulaulaokalani (also written as Ka-ʻulaʻula-o-kalani; "o ka lani" = "of the sky") was an ancient Hawaiian nobleman ("Aliʻi"), who was the High Chief of Koʻolau on the island called Oahu. <s> Kaulaulaokalani was born on Oʻahu as a son of "Aliʻi" Kawalewaleoku (Ka-walewale-oku) of Koʻolau and his spouse, Unaʻula, and was thus a descendant of the wizard Maweke of Tahiti. <s> Kaulaulaokalani's grandparents were Kua-o-Mua and his wife, Kapua-a-Mua, who were the children of the Chiefess Mualani of Koʻolau and her spouse, Kaomealani I. Kawalewaleoku, being born out of the marriage between full siblings, was considered a deity and was one of the rulers of Koʻolau. <s> After his father’s death, Kaulaulaokalani ruled over Koʻolau. <s> During his time, over other parts of Oʻahu ruled High Chief Lakona and High Chiefess Maelo of Kona. <s> Wife of Kaulaulaokalani was called Kalua-i-Olowalu; her parents are not known today. <s> She and Kaulaulaokalani were the parents of the High Chiefess Kaimihauoku of Koʻolau, who was her father’s successor. <s> Kaimihauoku married a man named Loe, whose genealogy is unknown. <s> Their son was Moku-o-Loe, ruler of Koʻolau.
simple: Kaulaulaokalani (Ka-ʻulaʻula-o-kalani) was a Hawaiian nobleman, who lived on the island of Oahu. <s> He was the High Chief of Koʻolau. <s> Part of his name — "o ka lani" — means "one of the sky". <s> He was a son of the Chief Kawalewaleoku and his wife Unaʻula and he succeeded his father, who was considered a deity. <s> He was a ruler of Koʻolau, while his relatives Lakona and Maelo ruled over other parts of the island. <s> Kaulaulaokalani's wife was called Kalua-i-Olowalu, and they had a daughter, Kaimihauoku, who ruled over Koʻolau after her father's death. <s> A grandson of Kaulaulaokalani's was Moku-o-Loe.

title: Daisuke Tomita
complex: Daisuke Tomita (冨田 大介 , Tomita Daisuke , born April 24, 1977 in Ube, Yamaguchi) is a Japanese footballer.
simple: Daisuke Tomita (born 24 April 1977) is a Japanese football player.

title: Hechtel-Eksel
complex: Hechtel-Eksel is a municipality located in the Belgian province of Limburg. <s> On January 1, 2018, it had a total population of 12,290.
simple: Hechtel-Eksel is a municipality in the Belgian province of Limburg.

title: Sorry I'm Late
complex: Sorry I'm Late is the second studio album by English recording artist Cher Lloyd. <s> It was released on 27 May 2014, by Epic Records, Syco Music, and Mr. Kanani. <s> Lloyd herself co-wrote five songs on the album, working with new producers and songwriters such as Beth Ditto and Tove Lo. <s> It is her last album released through Epic and Syco. <s> On 16 October 2013, Lloyd told "Billboard" that the title of her second studio album is "Sorry I'm Late". <s> She explained, "I think it has two meanings. <s> ... It's been a long time since I've actually done anything new, but for me, it's as a person. <s> I mean, I've spent a whole lot of time trying to figure out who I am, and I think everybody goes through that." <s> In November 2013, during an interview with Larry King, Lloyd confirmed that she had left Syco Music after she and Cowell disagreed about her career path in music. <s> Lloyd also confirmed that "Sorry I'm Late", which was originally due for release in November, was pushed back until early 2014, despite the record being done. <s> She remarked, "My album got pushed back and I'm not happy about it. <s> It's all done, but I am currently in the studio for the rest of this week to try and find some more magic. <s> ... It was meant to be coming out in November. <s> Now I think it's going to be early next year." <s> The explicit version of the album artwork depicts Lloyd smoking while sitting in a bathtub; censored pressings of the record remove the smoke. <s> On 20 May 2014, one week before the release, Lloyd made the album available for online stream on MTV.com.
simple: Sorry I'm Late is the second studio album by English recording artist Cher Lloyd. <s> It was released on 23 May 2014 by Epic Records, Syco Music and Mr. Kanani. <s> Lloyd herself co-wrote five songs on the tracklist, working with new producers and songwriters such as Beth Ditto and Tove Lo. <s> It is her last album released through Epic and Syco. <s> On 16 October 2013, Lloyd told "Billboard" that the title of her second studio album is "Sorry I'm Late". <s> She explained, "I think it has two meanings. <s> ... It's been a long time since I've actually done anything new, but for me, it's as a person. <s> I mean, I've spent a whole lot of time trying to figure out who I am, and I think everybody goes through that." <s> Lloyd confirmed that "Sorry I'm Late", which was originally due for release in November, was pushed back until early 2014, despite the record being done. <s> The explicit version of the album artwork depicts Lloyd smoking while sitting in a bathtub; censored pressings of the record remove the smoke.

title: Baluchistan pygmy jerboa
complex: The Baluchistan pygmy jerboa, or the dwarf three-toed jerboa, ("Salpingotulus michaelis") is a species of rodent in the family Dipodidae. <s> It is the only species in the genus Salpingotulus. <s> Adults average only 4.4 cm in head and body length, with the tail averaging 8 cm . <s> Adult females weigh 3.75 g . <s> It is currently considered to be endemic to Pakistan. <s> In the 1999 Guinness Book of Records, it was listed as tied for the smallest rodent in the world with the African pygmy mouse.
simple: The Baluchistan pygmy jerboa ("Salpingotulus michaelis") is a species of rodent in the Dipodidae family. <s> It is the only species in the genus "Salpingotulus". <s> It is endemic to Pakistan.

title: Schöfflisdorf
complex: Schöfflisdorf is a municipality in the district of Dielsdorf in the canton of Zürich in Switzerland. <s> Situated in the Wehntal, Schöfflisdorf has an area of 4 km2 . <s> Of this area, 43.2% is used for agricultural purposes, while 45.2% is forested.
simple: Schöfflisdorf is a municipality in the district of Dielsdorf in the canton of Zurich in Switzerland. <s> It is situated in the Wehntal.

title: Fred Goldsmith (Australian footballer)
complex: Fred Goldsmith (20 August 1932 – 13 April 2017) was an Australian rules footballer who played with South Melbourne in the Victorian Football League (VFL). <s> He was captain-coach of the Albury Football Club in the Ovens & Murray Football League from 1960 to 1965. <s> In 1966 he played nine games with Port Melbourne Football Club in the Victorian Football Association.
simple: Fred Goldsmith (20 August 1932 – 13 April 2017) was an Australian rules footballer. <s> Goldsmith died on 13 April 2017 in Sydney at the age of 84. <s> He was captain-coach of the Albury Football Club in the Ovens & Murray Football League from 1960 to 1965. <s> In 1966 he played nine games with Port Melbourne Football Club in the Victorian Football Association.

title: Williamsburg, Virginia
complex: Williamsburg is a city in the U.S. state of Virginia. <s> As of the 2010 U.S. Census, the population was 14,068.
simple: Williamsburg is a small city in Virginia in the United States.

title: Temperate climate
complex: In geography, the temperate or tepid climates of Earth occur in the middle latitudes, which span between the tropics and the polar regions of Earth. <s> These zones generally have wider temperature ranges throughout the year and more distinct seasonal changes compared to tropical climates, where such variations are often small. <s> They typically feature four distinct seasons, Summer the warmest, Autumn the transitioning season to Winter, the colder season, and Spring the transitioning season from winter back into summer. <s> In the northern hemisphere, the year starts with winter, transitions in the first halfyear through spring into summer, which is in mid-year, then at the second halfyear through autumn into winter at year-end.
simple: In geography, temperate latitudes of the Earth lie between the subtropics and the polar circles. <s> So, most places with a temperate climate have four seasons: summer, autumn, winter and spring.

title: José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero
complex: José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero (] ; born 4 August 1960) is a Spanish politician and member of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE). <s> He was the Prime Minister of Spain being elected for two terms, in the 2004 and 2008 general elections. <s> On 2 April 2011 he announced he would not stand for re-election in the 2011 general election and left office on 21 December 2011. <s> He studied Law at the University of León, graduating in 1982. <s> His performance as a student was above average before his pre-University year. <s> According to his brother Juan: "He didn't study much but it made no difference, he continued successfully". <s> Rodríguez Zapatero met Sonsoles Espinosa in León in 1981. <s> They married on 27 January 1990 and have two daughters named Laura (b. 1993) and Alba (b. 1995). <s> He left office on 20 December 2011 and left the PSOE's Secretary General chair on 4 February 2012 to Alfredo Pérez Rubalcaba. <s> On 9 February he entered the Spanish Council of State. <s> He was also named President of the Advisory Board of the Institute for Cultural Diplomacy, a Berlin-based organization.
simple: Don José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero (; born 4 August 1960 in Valladolid) is a Spanish politician. <s> His party is the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE). <s> He was elected for two terms as Prime Minister of Spain. <s> This was in the 2004 and 2008 general elections. <s> On 2 April 2011 he said he would not stand for re-election. <s> He studied Law at the University of León, graduating in 1982. <s> Rodríguez Zapatero met Sonsoles Espinosa in León in 1981. <s> They married on 27 January 1990 and have two daughters named Laura (born 1993) and Alba (born 1995). <s> He left the office on 21 December 2011. <s> He left the PSOE's Secretary General chair on 4th February 2012 to Alfredo Pérez Rubalcaba. <s> On 9th February he entered the Spanish Council of State.

title: Clodoaldo
complex: Clodoaldo Tavares de Santana, better known as Clodoaldo (] ; born 25 September 1949 in Aracaju), is a Brazilian former footballer who played as a midfielder.
simple: Clodoaldo (born 26 September, 1949) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Portrait of Jacob de Gheyn III
complex: Portrait of Jacob de Gheyn III is a 1632 oil on canvas portrait by Rembrandt of the engraver Jacob de Gheyn III, now in Dulwich Picture Gallery. <s> It is smaller than most of Rembrandt's works, measuring only 29.9 by 24.9 centimetres (11.8 by 9.8 inches). <s> It has been stolen numerous times and its size is one factor that has contributed to its numerous thefts. <s> The painting has been given the moniker "takeaway Rembrandt" as it has been stolen four times since 1966 – the most recorded of any painting. <s> The other two times, the painting was found once underneath a bench in a graveyard in Streatham, and once on the back of a bicycle. <s> Each time the painting has been returned anonymously with more than one person being charged for its disappearance.
simple: Jacob de Gheyn III is a famous painting. <s> It was painted by Rembrandt in 1632 and is the most stolen painting in the world. <s> Jacob de Gheyn III, also known as Jacob III de Gheyn (1596–1641), was a Dutch Golden Age engraver, son of Jacob de Gheyn II, canon of Utrecht (city), and the subject of a 1632 oil painting by Rembrandt. <s> It has been stolen and recovered from galleries at least four times, making it the world's most stolen painting. <s> Every time the painting has been recovered anonymously and as a consequence nobody was accused of the theft.

title: 274301 Wikipedia
complex: 274301 Wikipedia , provisional designation 2008 QH , is a Vestian asteroid orbiting in the inner region of the asteroid belt, approximately 1 km in diameter. <s> It was discovered on 25 August 2008 by astronomers at the Andrushivka Astronomical Observatory in northern Ukraine. <s> The asteroid was named after the online encyclopedia Wikipedia in January 2013.
simple: 274301 Wikipedia is an asteroid in the asteroid belt. <s> It was discovered by Andrushivka Astronomical Observatory in 2008. <s> It was named "Wikipedia" on January 2013.

title: Ghost in the Shell
complex: Ghost in the Shell, known in Japan as Mobile Armored Riot Police (Japanese: 攻殻機動隊 , Hepburn: Kōkaku Kidōtai ) is a Japanese cyberpunk science fiction media franchise originally published as a seinen manga series of the same name written and illustrated by Masamune Shirow. <s> The manga, first serialized in 1989 under the subtitle of "The Ghost in the Shell", and later published as its own tankōbon volumes by Kodansha, told the story of the fictional counter-cyberterrorist organization Public Security Section 9, led by protagonist Major Motoko Kusanagi, in the mid-21st century of Japan.
simple: Ghost in the Shell (攻殻機動隊, Kōkaku Kidōtai) is a Japanese franchise of different media. <s> It was originally published as a manga series, written and illustrated by Masamune Shirow. <s> It told the story of a fictional counter-cyberterrorist organisation.

title: Ernst Bakker
complex: Ernst Carel Bakker (16 April 1946 – 8 February 2014) was a Dutch politician, alderman and member of the Democrats 66 political party. <s> He served as a member of the House of Representatives from 1981 to 1982. <s> He joined the Amsterdam City Council in 1990 before becoming a city alderman beginning in 1992. <s> Bakker relocated to Hilversum in 1998 to become Mayor, a position he held until his retirement in 2011. <s> Bakker died on 8 February 2014 in Hilversum, at the age of 67.
simple: Ernst Carel Bakker (16 April 1946 in Hellendoorn – 8 February 2014 in Hilversum) was a Dutch politician of Democrats 66 (D66). <s> In between he was for a brief period a member of the House of Representatives, from 1981 to 1982. <s> He served as a councillor of Amsterdam for several years, and was also an alderman from 1992 to 1998. <s> Afterwards he was mayor of Hilversum from 1998 to 2011. <s> Bakker died at the age of 67 in 2014.

title: Ravensburg
complex: Ravensburg is a town in Upper Swabia in Southern Germany, capital of the district of Ravensburg, Baden-Württemberg. <s> Ravensburg was first mentioned in 1088. <s> In the Middle Ages, it was an Imperial Free City and an important trading centre. <s> The "Great Ravensburg Trading Society" ("Große Ravensburger Handelsgesellschaft") owned shops and trading companies all over Europe. <s> The historic town centre is still very much intact, including three town gates and over 10 towers of the medieval fortification. <s> "The all-white Mehlsack (Flour Sacks) is a tower marking the Altstadt’s southern edge. <s> A steep staircase leads up to the Veitsburg, a quaint baroque castle." <s> The town's most popular festival is the "Rutenfest" in mid year.
simple: Ravensburg is a town in Upper Swabia in southern Germany. <s> It is the capital of the district of Ravensburg, Baden-Württemberg. <s> Ravensburg was first mentioned in 1088. <s> In the Middle Ages, it was an Imperial Free City and an important trading centre. <s> The "Great Ravensburg Trading Society" ("Große Ravensburger Handelsgesellschaft") owned shops and trading companies all over Europe. <s> The historic town centre is still very much intact, including three town gates and over 10 towers of the medieval fortification. <s> The town's most popular festival is the "Rutenfest" in mid year.

title: Militia
complex: Beginning in the late 20th century, some militias (in particular officially recognized and sanctioned militias of a government) act as professional forces, while still being "part-time" or "on-call" organizations. <s> For instance, the members of some U.S. Army National Guard units are considered professional soldiers, as they are trained to maintain the same standards as their "full-time" (active duty) counterparts.
simple: At the beginning in the late 20th century, some militias acted as professional forces, while still being "part-time" or "on-call" organizations.

title: Premier of Tasmania
complex: The Premier of Tasmania is the head of the executive government in the Australian state of Tasmania. <s> By convention, the leader of the party or political grouping which has majority support in the House of Assembly is invited by the Governor of Tasmania to be Premier and principal adviser. <s> Since the 2014 election, the Premier of Tasmania has been Will Hodgman, leader of the Liberal Party. <s> Hodgman won a second term at the 2018 election, and now holds 13 of the 25 seats in the House of Assembly. <s> Before the 1890s, there was no formal party system in Tasmania. <s> Party labels before that time indicate a general tendency only. <s> The current convention of appointing the Premier from the House of Assembly was not generally applied prior to 1920, with Premiers often appointed from the Legislative Council.
simple: The Premier of Tasmania is the head of the government in the Australian state of Tasmania. <s> The political party which has the most support in the House of Assembly will nominate its leader to be Premier. <s> The leader is then asked by the Governor of Tasmania to act as their principal adviser. <s> The current premier is Will Hodgman of the Liberal Party of Australia, who was sworn in on 31 March 2014. <s> Before the 1890s, there was no political party system in Tasmania. <s> Before 1920 premiers were often appointed from the Legislative Council.

title: Bearded vulture
complex: The bearded vulture ("Gypaetus barbatus"), also known as the lammergeier (or lammergeyer) or ossifrage, is a bird of prey and the only member of the genus "Gypaetus". <s> Traditionally considered an Old World vulture, it actually forms a minor lineage of Accipitridae together with the Egyptian vulture ("Neophron percnopterus"), its closest living relative. <s> It is not much more closely related to the Old World vultures proper than to, for example, hawks, and differs from the former by its feathered neck. <s> Although dissimilar, the Egyptian and bearded vulture each have a lozenge-shaped tail—unusual among birds of prey. <s> The bearded vulture is the only known vertebrate whose diet consists almost exclusively (70 to 90 percent) of bone. <s> It lives and breeds on crags in high mountains in southern Europe, the Caucasus, Africa, the Indian subcontinent, and Tibet, laying one or two eggs in mid-winter that hatch at the beginning of spring.
simple: The bearded vulture ("Gypaetus barbatus"), also known as the lammergeier or lammergeyer, is a bird of prey. <s> It is the only member of the genus Gypaetus. <s> An Old World vulture, it forms a minor line of the Accipitridae with the Egyptian vulture, its closest living relative. <s> They are not much more closely related to the Old World vultures proper than to hawks. <s> They differ from Old World vultures by their feathered neck. <s> It eats mainly carrion and lives and breeds on crags in high mountains in southern Europe, the Caucasus, Africa, the Indian subcontinent, and Tibet. <s> The females lay one or two eggs in mid-winter that hatch at the beginning of spring.

title: Yoram Globus
complex: Yoram Globus (Hebrew: יורם גלובוס ; born 7 September 1943) is an American-Israeli film producer, cinema owner, and distributor. <s> He is most known for his association with The Cannon Group, Inc., an American film production company, which he co-owned with his cousin Menahem Golan.
simple: Yoram Globus (born 21 October 1943), is an Israeli movie producer. <s> He is most famous for his association with Cannon Films Inc., a company he ran with his cousin Menahem Golan.

title: Gesso
complex: Gesso (] ; "chalk", from the , from ) is a white paint mixture consisting of a binder mixed with chalk, gypsum, pigment, or any combination of these. <s> It is used in artwork as a preparation for any number of substrates such as wood panels, canvas and sculpture as a base for paint and other materials that are applied over it. <s> Gesso is used by sculptors to prepare the shape of the final sculpture (fused bronze) or directly as a material for sculpting. <s> Gesso can also be used as a layer between sculpted wood and gold leaf. <s> In this case, a layer of refined and coloured clay, called ‘bole’ is used to cover the gesso before applying the gold. <s> This is usually red in colour. <s> Modern "acrylic gesso" is a widely used ground that is a combination of calcium carbonate with an acrylic polymer, medium latex, a pigment and other chemicals that ensure flexibility, and increase archival life. <s> It is technically not "gesso" at all. <s> "The Painter's Handbook" notes a problem with using oil paints over an acrylic gesso ground instead of a traditional oil ground, citing a mismatch in flexibility over time that could cause the oil paint to delaminate.
simple: It is a white paint mixture. <s> It has a binder mixed with a pigment. <s> Gesso is used in art to prepare a surfaces (wood panels, canvas and sculpture) for painting. <s> Acrylic gesso, a widely used "ground", is a modern version which is cheaper and easier to use than the traditional type of gesso. <s> It is a combination of calcium carbonate with an acrylic polymer medium latex, a pigment and other chemicals to ensure flexibility and increase life. <s> It is technically not "gesso" at all. <s> "The Painter's Handbook" notes a problem with using oil paints over an acrylic gesso ground instead of a traditional oil ground, citing a mismatch in flexibility over time that could cause the oil paint to delaminate (flake off).

title: Trannyshack
complex: Trannyshack is a monthly drag club that takes place at DNA Lounge in San Francisco. <s> It was started by drag queen Heklina in 1996 as an offshoot of Klubstitute, and was a weekly fixture at The Stud bar in San Francisco for 12 years, drawing large crowds on a regular basis. <s> The Tuesday night performances at The Stud ended on 12 August 2008, with Trannyshack resuming as a monthly event at DNA Lounge in March 2010. <s> The Trannyshack stage has hosted celebrities including Lady Gaga, Gwen Stefani, RuPaul, Charo, Michelle Visage, Mary Wilson and many of the contestants from "RuPaul's Drag Race" among others. <s> In the early years of the club, Ana Matronic of the Scissor Sisters lived in San Francisco and performed frequently at Trannyshack before moving to New York in 1999. <s> Trannyshack also holds the annual Trannyshack Reno bus trip.
simple: Trannyshack is a San Francisco drag club started by drag queen Heklina, and takes place at The Stud Bar. <s> This club has hosted many celebrities from Mary Wilson of the Supremes to Charo, RuPaul, Gwen Stefani, Alaska Thunderfuck, Lady Bunny, and more. <s> At one time, Ana Matronic of the Scissor Sisters lived in San Francisco, where she performed at Trannyshack and was the first and only female to reach the finals of the Miss Trannyshack pageant.

title: Wabash Avenue Bridge
complex: The Wabash Avenue Bridge (officially, Irv Kupcinet Bridge) over the Chicago River was built in 1930. <s> Standing west of the Michigan Avenue Bridge and east of Marina City, the bascule bridge connects the Near North Side with "The Loop" area. <s> The single-deck, double-leaf bascule bridge was designed by Thomas Pihlfeldt and built by the Ketler and Elliot Company. <s> The American Institute of Steel Construction awarded it the "Most Beautiful" bridge in 1930.
simple: The Wabash Avenue Bridge (officially, Irv Kupcinet Bridge) over the Chicago River was built in 1930. <s> Standing west of the Michigan Avenue Bridge and southwest of the Trump International Hotel and Tower. <s> The bascule bridge connects the Near North Side with "The Loop" area. <s> The single-deck, double leaf bridge was designed by Thomas Pihlfeldt and built by the Ketler and Elliot Company. <s> The American Institute of Steel Construction awarded it the "Most Beautiful" bridge in 1930.

title: MacBook (2015–2019)
complex: The MacBook (known colloquially as the Retina MacBook or 12-inch MacBook) is a discontinued line of Macintosh portable computers introduced in March 2015 by Apple Inc. <s> The MacBook had a similar appearance to the MacBook Air, but was thinner and lighter, and was available in colors called space gray, silver, gold, and rose gold. <s> It offered a high-resolution Retina Display, a Force Touch trackpad, a redesigned keyboard, and only two ports: a headphone jack and a USB 3.1 Type-C port for charging, data transfer and video output. <s> The MacBook was designed with thinness in mind; the aluminum enclosure was 13.1 mm at its thickest point at the hinge end of the computer. <s> The MacBook includes Intel Core M processors (Kaby Lake architecture) which requires no fans or heat pipe, allowing the logic board to be much smaller than the one in the MacBook Air. <s> The storage cannot be upgraded.
simple: The MacBook Retina is a laptop computer made by Apple Inc.. <s> It was introduced in March 2015. <s> It has one USB "Type C" port, and a headphone jack. <s> The MacBook Retina is designed to be thin. <s> It is 13.1 mm at its thickest point. <s> It has an Intel Core M processor, which is designed for computers like this and does not need a fan or something else to cool it.

title: Electrical substation
complex: A substation is a part of an electrical generation, transmission, and distribution system. <s> Substations transform voltage from high to low, or the reverse, or perform any of several other important functions. <s> Between the generating station and consumer, electric power may flow through several substations at different voltage levels. <s> A substation may include transformers to change voltage levels between high transmission voltages and lower distribution voltages, or at the interconnection of two different transmission voltages.
simple: An electrical substation is a subsidiary station of an electricity generation, transmission and distribution system where voltage is transformed from high to low or the reverse using transformers. <s> Electric power may flow through several substations between generating plant and consumer, and may be changed in voltage in several steps.

title: Hannah (biblical figure)
complex: Hannah ( ; "Ḥannāh" "favor, grace") is one of the wives of Elkanah mentioned in the First Book of Samuel. <s> According to the Hebrew Bible she was the mother of Samuel.
simple: Hannah (meaning "grace of God") is a woman in the Bible, in the book of 1 Samuel chapters 1 and 2. <s> She was the wife of Elkanah and the Mother of Samuel.

title: Falkenberg Municipality
complex: Falkenberg Municipality ("Falkenbergs kommun") is a municipality in Halland County on the Swedish west coast. <s> The town Falkenberg is the municipal seat.
simple: Falkenberg Municipality is a municipality in Halland County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Falkenberg.

title: Gabriel Paletta
complex: Gabriel Alejandro Paletta (] ; born 15 February 1986) is an Argentine footballer who plays as a defender for Chinese club Jiangsu Suning.
simple: Gabriel Paletta (born 15 February 1986) is an Argentine football player.

title: Carob
complex: The carob ("Ceratonia siliqua") is a flowering evergreen tree or shrub in the legume family, Fabaceae. <s> It is widely cultivated for its edible pods, and as an ornamental tree in gardens and landscapes. <s> The carob tree is native to the Mediterranean region and the Middle East. <s> The ripe, dried, and sometimes toasted pod is often ground into "carob powder", which is sometimes used to replace cocoa powder. <s> "Carob bars", an alternative to chocolate bars, as well as carob treats, are often available in health food stores. <s> Carob pods are naturally sweet, not bitter, and contain no theobromine or caffeine. <s> The "carat", a unit of mass for gemstones, and a measurement of purity for gold, takes its name from the Greek word for a carob, "keration" meaning horn, via the Arabic word, "qīrāṭ". <s> The word "carob" comes from Middle French " " (modern French ), which borrowed it from Arabic ("kharrūb", "locust bean pod"), ultimately perhaps from Akkadian language " " or Aramaic "kharubha", related to Hebrew harubh. <s> "Ceratonia siliqua", the scientific name of the carob tree, derives from the Greek "kerátiοn" κεράτιον 'fruit of the carob (from "keras" κέρας 'horn'), and Latin "siliqua" 'pod, carob'. <s> In English, it is also known as "St John's bread", as well as "locust tree", ("not" African locust bean) the designation also applied to several other trees from the same family. <s> The carob tree grows up to 15 m tall. <s> The crown is broad and semispherical, supported by a thick trunk with rough brown bark and sturdy branches. <s> Its leaves are 10 to long, alternate, pinnate, and may or may not have a terminal leaflet. <s> It is frost-tolerant to roughly 20 °F . <s> Most carob trees are dioecious and some are hermaphroditic, so strictly male trees do not produce fruit. <s> When the trees blossom in autumn, the flowers are small and numerous, spirally arranged along the inflorescence axis in catkin-like racemes borne on spurs from old wood and even on the trunk (cauliflory); they are pollinated by both wind and insects. <s> The male flowers smell like human semen, an odor that is caused in part by amines. <s> The fruit is a legume (also known commonly, but less accurately, as a "pod"), that is elongated, compressed, straight, or curved, and thickened at the sutures. <s> The pods take a full year to develop and ripen. <s> When the sweet ripe pods eventually fall to the ground, they are eaten by various mammals, such as swine, thereby dispersing the hard inner seed in the excrement. <s> Carob products consumed by humans come from the dried, sometimes roasted, pod, which has two main parts: the pulp accounts for 90% and the seeds 10% by weight. <s> Carob pulp is sold either as flour or "chunks". <s> The flour of the carob embryo (seed) can also be used for human and animal nutrition, but the seed is often separated before making "carob powder" (see section on "locust bean gum" below). <s> Carob pods are mildly sweet on their own (being roughly 1/3 to 1/2 sugar by dry weight), so they are used in powdered, chip, or syrup form as an ingredient in cakes and cookies, sometimes as a substitute for chocolate in recipes because of the color, texture, and rich taste of carob. <s> In Malta, a traditional sweet eaten during the Christian holidays of Lent and Good Friday is made from carob pods. <s> Also, dried carob fruit is traditionally eaten on the Jewish holiday of "Tu Bishvat". <s> While chocolate contains the chemical compound theobromine in levels that are toxic to some mammals, carob contains none, and it also has no caffeine, so it is sometimes used to make chocolate-like treats for dogs. <s> Carob pod meal is also used as an energy-rich feed for livestock, particularly for ruminants, though its high tannin content may limit this use. <s> Carob pods are about 1/3 to 1/2 sugar by weight, and this sugar can be extracted into a syrup. <s> In Malta, a carob syrup ("ġulepp tal-ħarrub") is made out of the pods. <s> Carob syrup is also used in Crete, and Cyprus exports it. <s> Carob drinks are traditionally imbibed during the Islamic holy month of Ramadan. <s> The crushed pods may be used to make a beverage; carob is used for compote, liqueur, and syrup in Turkey, Malta, Portugal, Spain, and Sicily. <s> In Libya, carob syrup (called "rub") is used as a complement to "asida" (made from wheat flour). <s> The so-called "carob syrup" made in Peru is actually from the fruit of the "Prosopis nigra" tree. <s> Because of its strong taste, carob syrup is sometimes flavored with orange or chocolate. <s> The carob tree is widely cultivated in the horticultural nursery industry as an ornamental plant for Mediterranean climates and other temperate regions around the world, being especially popular in California and Hawaii. <s> The plant develops a sculpted trunk and the form of an ornamental tree after being "limbed up" as it matures, otherwise it is used as a dense and large screening hedge. <s> The plant is very drought tolerant if one does not care about the size of the fruit harvest, and so it is used in xeriscape landscape design for gardens, parks, and public municipal and commercial landscapes.
simple: Carob tree is a species of flowering evergreen tree in the pea family, Fabaceae. <s> It is widely grown for its edible s, and as an ornamental tree in gardens. <s> The carob tree is native to the Cyprus island, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Libya, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Tunisia, Turkey. <s> The ripe, dried pod is often ground to carob powder, which is used to replace cocoa powder. <s> Carob bars, an alternative to chocolate bars, are often available in health-food stores. <s> Carob bars are widely available in health food stores. <s> The carat, a unit of mass for gemstones, and of purity for gold, takes its name, indirectly, from the Greek word for a carob seed, "kerátion". <s> The word carob, used commonly for the fruit, comes from Middle French "carobe" (modern ), which borrowed it from Arabic ("kharrūb", "locust bean pod"). <s> "Ceratonia siliqua", the scientific name of the carob tree given by Carolus Linnaeus to this plant, comes from the Greek "kerátiοn" κεράτιον 'fruit of the carob (from "keras" κέρας 'horn'), and Latin "siliqua" ", carob". <s> The tree is known in English as carob tree, St John's-bread or locust bean (not to be confused with the African locust bean). <s> The carob tree grows up to 15 m tall. <s> The crown (the upper part of tree) is broad and semispherical, supported by a thick trunk with brown rough bark and solid and firm branches. <s> Leaves are 10 to long, alternate and compound. <s> Most carob trees are dioecious (with separate male an female plants) but some are hermaphrodite. <s> The male trees do not produce fruit. <s> The trees blossom in autumn. <s> The flowers are small and in an inflorescence axis in racemes like catkins; the pollination is by both wind and insects. <s> The fruit is a legume (also known as a pod). <s> The pods take a full year to develop and ripen. <s> The sweet ripe pods eventually fall to the ground and are eaten by various mammals (goats, sheep, cows), and so the hard seeds are dispersed. <s> Carob eaten by humans is the dried (and sometimes roasted) pod. <s> Carob is mildly sweet and is used in powdered, chip, or syrup form as an ingredient in cakes and cookies, and as a substitute for chocolate. <s> A traditional sweet, eaten during Lent and Good Friday, is also made from carob pods in Malta. <s> Carob pod meal is used as an energy-rich feed for livestock, particularly for ruminants, though its high tannin content may limit its use. <s> In Malta, a syrup ("ġulepp tal-ħarrub") is made out of carob pods. <s> In Cyprus, carob syrup is known as Cyprus's black gold, and is widely exported. <s> Carob syrup is also used in Crete as a natural sweetener, and is considered a natural source of calcium. <s> Carob juice drinks are traditionally drunk during the Islamic month of Ramadan. <s> Crushed pods may be used to make a beverage; , liqueur, and syrup are made from carob in Turkey, Malta, Portugal, Spain, and Sicily. <s> "C. siliqua" is widely planted in the horticultural as an ornamental plant for planting in Mediterranean climate and other temperate regions around the world, as in California and Hawaii. <s> The plant can be used as a dense and large hedge.

title: Sendurai taluk
complex: Sendurai taluk is a taluk of Ariyalur district of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu. <s> The headquarters of the taluk is the town of Sendurai.Thamilselvan T <s> According to the 2011 census, the taluk of Sendurai had a population of 111,932 with 55,414 males and 56,518 females. <s> There were 1020 women for every 1000 men. <s> The taluk had a literacy rate of 61.6. <s> Child population in the age group below 6 was 6,350 Males and 5,430 Females.
