title: William John Wills
complex: William John Wills (5 January 1834 – 28 June 1861 ) was a British surveyor who also trained as a surgeon. <s> Wills achieved fame as the second-in-command of the ill-fated Burke and Wills expedition, which was the first expedition to cross Australia from south to north, finding a route across the continent from the settled areas of Victoria to the Gulf of Carpentaria. <s> William John Wills was born on 5 January 1834 in Totnes, Devon, England, and he was the second of seven children born to William Wills (died 28 September 1889) and Sarah Mary Elizabeth Wills (née Calley, born 23 December 1800, baptized 12 March 1801 in Totnes, and died 19 February 1880).
simple: William John Wills (1834—1861) was an English surveyor. <s> He became one of the first explorers to cross Australia from the south to the north. <s> The expedition became known as the Burke and Wills expedition. <s> He was born in Totnes, Devon.

title: Citric acid cycle
complex: The citric acid cycle (CAC) – also known as the" TCA cycle (tricarboxylic acid cycle) " or the" Krebs cycle "– is a series of chemical reactions used by all aerobic organisms to release stored energy through the oxidation of acetyl-CoA derived from carbohydrates, fats, and proteins, into adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and carbon dioxide. <s> In addition, the cycle provides precursors of certain amino acids, as well as the reducing agent NADH, that are used in numerous other reactions. <s> Its central importance to many biochemical pathways suggests that it was one of the earliest established components of cellular metabolism and may have originated abiogenically. <s> Even though it is branded as a 'cycle', it is not necessary for metabolites to follow only one specific route; at least three segments of the citric acid cycle have been recognized. <s> Because two acetyl-CoA molecules are produced from each glucose molecule, two cycles are required per glucose molecule. <s> Therefore, at the end of two cycles, the products are: two GTP, six NADH, two QH, and four CO.
simple: Its other names are the citric acidity cycle, and the tricarboxylic acid cycle (TCA cycle). <s> It is the series of chemical reactions used by all aerobic organisms to generate energy. <s> It is important to many biochemical pathways. <s> This suggests that it was one of the earliest parts of cellular metabolism to evolve. <s> Because two acetyl-CoA molecules are produced from each glucose molecule, "two cycles are required per glucose molecule". <s> Therefore, at the end of two cycles, the products are: two ATP, six NADH, two FADH two QH (ubiquinol) and four CO.

title: The Mystery of Al Capone's Vaults
complex: The Mystery of Al Capone's Vaults is a two-hour live American television special that was broadcast in syndication on April 21, 1986. <s> Hosted by Geraldo Rivera, the special centered on the opening of a secret vault in the Lexington Hotel once owned by noted crime lord Al Capone, which turned out to be empty except for debris. <s> "The Mystery of Al Capone's Vaults" is available in its entirety on Geraldo's website.
simple: The Mystery of Al Capone's Vault was a one-time live American television special broadcast in April of 1986. <s> It was hosted by Geraldo Rivera. <s> The program was about the opening of a secret vault once owned by Al Capone.

title: Tetuin
complex: Tetuin is a flavone, a type of flavonoid. <s> It is the 6-O-glucoside of baicalein. <s> It can be isolated from the seeds of "Oroxylum indicum", the Indian trumpetflower, known as टेटु "tetu" in Marathi.
simple: Tetuin is a flavone. <s> It is a type of flavonoid. <s> It is the 6-O-glucoside of baicalein. <s> It can be isolated from the seeds of "Oroxylum indicum", the Indian trumpetflower, known as टेटु "tetu" in Marathi.

title: Danone
complex: Danone S.A. is a French multinational food-products corporation based in Paris and founded in Barcelona, Spain. <s> The company is listed on Euronext Paris where it is a component of the CAC 40 stock market index. <s> Some of the company’s products are branded Dannon in the United States. <s> Danone was present in 130 markets and generated sales of US$25.7 billion in 2016, with more than half in emerging countries. <s> In 2015, fresh dairy products represented 50% of the group's total sales, early life nutrition 22%, water 21% and medical nutrition 7%. <s> In 2017, Franck Riboud became honorary chairman and Faber became chairman as well as retaining his CEO position.
simple: Danone is a French multinational food-products corporation based in Paris and founded in Barcelona, Spain. <s> The company is listed on Euronext Paris where it is a component of the CAC 40 stock market index. <s> Danone is present in over 130 markets and generated sales of €21.9 billion in 2016, with more than half in emerging countries. <s> In 2015, fresh dairy products represented 50% of the group's total sales, early life nutrition 22%, water 21% and medical nutrition 7%.

title: Snape, Suffolk
complex: Snape is a small village in the English county of Suffolk, on the River Alde close to Aldeburgh. <s> It has about 600 inhabitants, measured at 611 at the 2011 Census.
simple: Snape is a village and civil parish in Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England.

title: Ewok
complex: Ewoks are a fictional species of small, mammaloid bipeds that appear in the "Star Wars" universe. <s> They are hunter-gatherers resembling teddy bears that inhabit the forest moon of Endor and live in various arboreal huts and other simple dwellings. <s> They first appeared in the 1983 film "Return of the Jedi" and have since appeared in two made-for-television films, "" (1984) and "" (1985), as well as a short-lived animated series and several books and games.
simple: Ewoks are a fictional race of small, bear-like creatures from George Lucas' "Star Wars" universe. <s> They live on the forests on the moon of the Planet Endor. <s> They first appeared in the film "".

title: Georgi Atanasov (politician)
complex: Georgi Ivanov Atanasov (Bulgarian: Георги Иванов Атанасов) (born 25 July 1933) was a leading member of the Bulgarian Communist Party who served as Prime Minister from 1986-1990. <s> Atanasov supported the move to oust Todor Zhivkov as Chairman of the State Council, joining Petar Mladenov in leading the opposition. <s> In November 1992 he was sentenced to ten years imprisonment for embezzlement, although he was pardoned in 1994.
simple: Georgi Ivanov Atanasov (Bulgarian: Георги Иванов Атанасов) (born 25 July 1933) is a Bulgarian politician and military official. <s> He was a leading member of the Bulgarian Communist Party. <s> He was Prime Minister from 1986 to 1990. <s> Atanasov supported the move to oust Todor Zhivkov as Chairman of the State Council.

title: Albert Ammons
complex: Albert Clifton Ammons (March 1, 1907 – December 2, 1949) was an American pianist and player of boogie-woogie, a bluesy jazz style popular from the late 1930s to the mid-1940s. <s> Ammons was born in Chicago, Illinois. <s> His parents were pianists, and he had learned to play by the age of ten. <s> His interest in boogie-woogie is attributed to his close friendship with Meade Lux Lewis and also his father's interest in the style. <s> Both Albert and Meade would practice together on the piano in the Ammons household. <s> From the age of ten, Ammons learned about chords by marking the depressed keys on the family pianola (player piano) with a pencil and repeated the process until he had mastered it. <s> He also played percussion in a drum and bugle corps as a teenager and was soon performing with bands in clubs in Chicago. <s> After World War I he became interested in the blues, learning by listening to the Chicago pianists Hersal Thomas and the brothers Alonzo and Jimmy Yancey. <s> In the early to mid-1920s Ammons worked as a cab driver for the Silver Taxicab Company. <s> In 1924 he met up with his boyhood friend Meade Lux Lewis, who was also then a taxi driver. <s> Soon the two players began working as a team, performing at club parties. <s> Ammons started his own band at the Club DeLisa in 1934 and remained at the club for the next two years. <s> During that time he played with a five-piece band that included Guy Kelly, Dalbert Bright, Jimmy Hoskins, and Israel Crosby. <s> Ammons also recorded as Albert Ammons's Rhythm Kings for Decca Records in 1936. <s> The Rhythm Kings' version of "Swanee River Boogie" sold a million copies, and their 1936 recording of "Boogie Woogie Stomp" has been described as "the first 12-bar piano based boogie-woogie, which was imitated by many jazz bands." <s> Ammons moved from Chicago to New York City, where he teamed up with another pianist, Pete Johnson. <s> The two performed regularly at the Café Society, occasionally joined by Lewis or by other jazz musicians, including Benny Goodman and Harry James. <s> On December 23, 1938, Ammons appeared at Carnegie Hall with Johnson and Lewis in "From Spirituals to Swing", a concert produced by John H. Hammond, which helped launch the boogie-woogie craze. <s> Two weeks later, the record producer Alfred Lion, who had attended the concert, started Blue Note Records, recording nine Ammons solos, including "The Blues" and "Boogie Woogie Stomp", eight by Lewis and two duets in a one-day session in a rented recording studio. <s> In 1941, Ammons's boogie-woogie music was accompanied by drawn-on-film animation in the short film "Boogie-Doodle", by Norman McLaren. <s> Ammons played himself in the movie "Boogie-Woogie Dream" (1944), with Lena Horne and Johnson. <s> As a sideman with Sippie Wallace in the 1940s Ammons recorded a session with his son, the tenor saxophonist Gene Ammons. <s> Although the boogie-woogie fad began to die down in 1945, Ammons had no difficulty securing work. <s> He continued to tour as a solo artist, and between 1946 and 1949 recorded his last sides, for Mercury Records, with the bassist Israel Crosby, and took on the position of staff pianist with the Lionel Hampton Orchestra. <s> In 1949 he played at the inauguration of President Harry S. Truman. <s> Ammons died of natural causes on December 2, 1949, in Chicago, around three months before his 43rd birthday. <s> He was interred at the Lincoln Cemetery, at Kedzie Avenue in Blue Island, Worth Township, Cook County, Illinois. <s> Ammons has had wide influence on countless pianists, such as Jerry Lee Lewis, Dave Alexander, Dr. John, Hadda Brooks, Johnnie Johnson, Ray Bryant, Erroll Garner, Katie Webster, Axel Zwingenberger, Henri Herbert, and the German pianist, Jörg Hegemann. <s> The latter honoured Ammons, on the occasion of the 100th anniversary of Ammons' birth, with his album, "A Tribute to Albert Ammons".
simple: Albert Ammons (*September 23, 1907 in Chicago, Illinois – †December 2, 1949 in Chicago) was an important American blues - and boogie woogie pianist. <s> Ammons was the son of a couple which both played piano. <s> So he started at the age of ten with piano lessons. <s> After the First World War he became interested in blues. <s> He was influenced by Hersal Thomas and Jimmy Yancey. <s> At the beginning of the 1920s he worked as taxi driver where he met another pianist, Meade Lux Lewis. <s> They formed a team and played at clubs and parties. <s> In 1934 he formed his own band Albert Ammons's Rhythm Kings. <s> Their version of Swanee River Boogie sold over a million copies. <s> Later he went to New York where he teamed with another pianist, Pete Johnson. <s> They often played at the Café Society. <s> But they also played there with famous jazz musicians like Benny Goodman or Harry James. <s> 1938 Ammons, Lewis and Johnson played at the "From Spirituals to Swing concert" on December 23, 1938. <s> One visitor was record producer Alfred Lion who started two weeks later Blue Note Records with recordings of Ammons and Johnson, nine Ammons solos including "The Blues" and "Boogie Woogie Stomp", eight by Lewis and a pair of duets. <s> He went on tours as solo artist. <s> Ammons's played at President Harry S. Truman's inauguration in 1949. <s> He died on December 2, 1949 in Chicago. <s> A lot of pianist like Dave Alexander, Dr. John, Hadda Brooks, Johnnie Johnson, Ray Bryant, Erroll Garner, Katie Webster and Axel Zwingenberger named Ammons as main influence. <s> Axel Zwingenberger recorded a tribute album A Tribute To Albert Ammons celebrating his 100th birthday in 2007.

title: Cape Floristic Region
complex: The Cape Floristic Region is a floristic region located near the southern tip of South Africa. <s> It is the only floristic region of the Cape (South African) Floristic Kingdom, and includes only one floristic province, known as the Cape Floristic Province. <s> The Cape Floristic Region, the smallest of the six recognised floral kingdoms of the world, is an area of extraordinarily high diversity and endemism, and is home to over 9,000 vascular plant species, of which 69 percent are endemic. <s> Much of this diversity is associated with the fynbos biome, a Mediterranean-type, fire-prone shrubland. <s> The economical worth of fynbos biodiversity, based on harvests of fynbos products (e.g. wildflowers) and eco-tourism, is estimated to be in the region of R77 million a year. <s> Thus, it is clear that the Cape Floristic Region has both economic and intrinsic biological value as a biodiversity hotspot.
simple: The Cape flower region is a nature area near the south end of South Africa. <s> Its formal title is the Cape (South Africa) Floristic Region. <s> The region is the smallest of the six "flower kingdoms" of the world, as recognised by Ronald Good. <s> The region has very high diversity. <s> There are more than 9,000 vascular plant species. <s> Much of this diversity is because of the fynbos, a Mediterranean-type shrubland that can easily be destroyed by wildfires. <s> The economic worth of the fynbos area may be about R77 million a year from harvests of products (like wildflowers) and from eco-tourism. <s> The Cape flower region has both economic and biological value.

title: Hungerford Bridge and Golden Jubilee Bridges
complex: The Hungerford Bridge crosses the River Thames in London, and lies between Waterloo Bridge and Westminster Bridge. <s> Owned by Network Rail Infrastructure Ltd (who use its official name of Charing Cross Bridge) it is a steel truss railway bridge flanked by two more recent, cable-stayed, pedestrian bridges that share the railway bridge's foundation piers, and which are named the Golden Jubilee Bridges. <s> The north end of the bridge is Charing Cross railway station, and is near Embankment Pier and the Victoria Embankment. <s> The south end is near Waterloo station, County Hall, the Royal Festival Hall, and the London Eye. <s> Each pedestrian bridge has steps and lift access. <s> The first Hungerford Bridge, designed by Isambard Kingdom Brunel, opened in 1845 as a suspension footbridge. <s> It was named after the then Hungerford Market, because it went from the South Bank to Hungerford Market on the north side of the Thames. <s> The two new 4 m wide footbridges were completed in 2002. <s> They were named the Golden Jubilee Bridges, in honour of the fiftieth anniversary of Queen Elizabeth II's accession, although in practice they are often still referred to as the "Hungerford Footbridges".
simple: Hungerford Bridge, often called Charing Cross Bridge, is a railway bridge.It crosses the River Thames in London from Charing Cross station across to the south, near Waterloo station. <s> The bridge lies between Waterloo Bridge and Westminster Bridge. <s> It is a steel bridge with two more recent pedestrian bridges on either side. <s> The north end of the bridge is Charing Cross station. <s> It is near Embankment Pier and the Victoria Embankment. <s> The south end is near Waterloo station, County Hall, the Royal Festival Hall, and the London Eye. <s> Each footpath has steps and lift access. <s> The first version of the bridge was designed by Isambard Kingdom Brunel, and opened in 1845. <s> These were named the Golden Jubilee Bridges, but are really just footpaths alongside the railway bridge.

title: Decapoda
complex: The Decapoda or decapods (literally "ten-footed") are an order of crustaceans within the class Malacostraca, including many familiar groups, such as crayfish, crabs, lobsters, prawns, and shrimp. <s> Most decapods are scavengers. <s> The order is estimated to contain nearly 15,000 species in around 2,700 genera, with around 3,300 fossil species. <s> Nearly half of these species are crabs, with the shrimp (about 3000 species) and Anomura including hermit crabs, porcelain crabs, squat lobsters (about 2500 species) making up the bulk of the remainder. <s> The earliest fossil decapod is the Devonian "Palaeopalaemon". <s> Decapods can have as many as 38 appendages, arranged in one pair per body segment. <s> As the name Decapoda (from the Greek , " ", "ten", and , "-pod", "foot") implies, ten of these appendages are considered legs. <s> They are the pereiopods, found on the last five thoracic segments. <s> In many decapods, one pair of these "legs" has enlarged pincers, called chelae, with the legs being called chelipeds. <s> In front of the pereiopods are three pairs of maxillipeds which function as feeding appendages. <s> The head has five pairs of appendages, including mouthparts, antennae, and antennules. <s> There are five more pairs of appendages on the abdomen. <s> They are called pleopods. <s> There is one final pair called uropods, which, with the telson, form the tail fan. <s> Classification within the order Decapoda depends on the structure of the gills and legs, and the way in which the larvae develop, giving rise to two suborders: Dendrobranchiata and Pleocyemata. <s> The Dendrobranchiata consist of prawns, including many species colloquially referred to as "shrimp", such as the "white shrimp", "Litopenaeus setiferus". <s> The Pleocyemata include the remaining groups, including "true shrimp". <s> Those groups which usually walk rather than swim (Pleocyemata, excluding Stenopodidea and Caridea) form a clade called Reptantia.
simple: Decapoda is an order of crustaceans in the class Malacostraca. <s> Many familiar groups, such as crayfish, crabs, lobsters, prawns and shrimp are in this order. <s> Many decapods are scavengers - they eat dead plants and animals. <s> As their name suggests, all decapods have ten appendages. <s> In many decapods, the front pair of appendages carry large pinching claws. <s> The claws are called "chelae", so these appendages may be called "chelipeds". <s> The front three pairs of appendages on the thorax are used as jaws, and called "maxillipeds". <s> On the abdomen are swimming appendages called "pleopods", and the body ends in a tail fan. <s> Classification of the order Decapoda depends on the structure of the gills and legs, and the way in which the larvae develop. <s> There are two suborders: Dendrobranchiata and Pleocyemata. <s> Prawns (including many so-called "shrimp", such as the Atlantic white shrimp) make up the Dendrobranchiata. <s> The other groups, including true shrimp, are the Pleocyemata.

title: Treaty of Troyes
complex: The Treaty of Troyes was an agreement that King Henry V of England and his heirs would inherit the French crown upon the death of King Charles VI of France. <s> It was signed in the French city of Troyes on 21 May 1420 in the aftermath of Henry's successful military campaign in France.
simple: The Treaty of Troyes (1420) tried to change the inheritance rule for the kings of France, but did not succeed at doing that. <s> This treaty said that Henry V of England and his sons would become kings of France after the death of Charles VI of France.

title: Mount Thor
complex: Mount Thor, officially gazetted as Thor Peak, is a mountain with an elevation of 1675 m located in Auyuittuq National Park, on Baffin Island, Nunavut, Canada. <s> The mountain is located 46 km northeast of Pangnirtung and features Earth's greatest vertical drop of 1250 m , with the cliff overhanging at an average angle of 15 degrees from vertical.
simple: Mount Thor is a mountain on Baffin Island, Nunavut, Canada.

title: Muiz ud din Qaiqabad
complex: Muiz ud din Qaiqabad (reigned 1287– 1 February 1290) was the tenth sultan of the Mamluk dynasty (Slave dynasty). <s> He was the son of Bughra Khan the Independent sultan of Bengal, as well as grandson of Ghiyas ud din Balban (1266–87).
simple: Muiz ud din Qaiqabad (1269 – 1 February 1290) was the tenth sultan of the Mamluk dynasty (Slave dynasty). <s> He reigned 1287 to 1 February 1290.

title: Cayman Islands
complex: The Cayman Islands ( or ) are an autonomous British Overseas Territory in the western Caribbean Sea. <s> The 264 km2 territory comprises the three islands of Grand Cayman, Cayman Brac and Little Cayman, which are located to the south of Cuba and northeast of Honduras, between Jamaica and Mexico's Yucatán Peninsula. <s> As of spring 2018 , the population of the Cayman Islands was estimated to be 64,420 making it the second-most populated British overseas territory after Bermuda. <s> The capital city is George Town, situated on Grand Cayman, by far the most populous of the three islands. <s> The islands are in the western Caribbean Sea and are the peaks of an undersea mountain range called the Cayman Ridge (or Cayman Rise).
simple: The Cayman Islands are a territory of the United Kingdom in the Caribbean Sea. <s> The three islands are Grand Cayman, Little Cayman, and Cayman Brac. <s> Its capital, George Town, is on the main island (Grand Cayman).

title: Douglas Fielding
complex: Douglas Fielding (6 June 1946 – 26 June 2019) was a British actor of film and television, best known for playing the role of Sergeant Alec Quilley, previously Police Constable, in the police procedural drama "Z-Cars" (1969–1978). <s> He later played the first regular policeman Roy Quick in the BBC soap opera "EastEnders" from 1985 until 1986. <s> Fielding died on 26 June 2019, aged 73.
simple: Douglas Fielding (June 6, 1946 – June 26, 2019) was a British actor. <s> Fielding was best known for playing the role of Sergeant Alec Quilley in the police procedural drama "Z-Cars" (1969–1978). <s> He later played the first regular policeman Roy Quick in the BBC soap opera "EastEnders" from 1985 until 1986. <s> Fielding died on June 26, 2019, aged 73.

title: Kitzbühel
complex: Kitzbühel (] ) is a medieval town situated in the Kitzbühel Alps along the river Kitzbüheler Ache in Tyrol, Austria, about 100 kilometers (62 mi) east of the state capital Innsbruck and is the administrative centre of the Kitzbühel district ("Bezirk"). <s> Kitzbühel is a ski resort of international renown and its ski season lasts from mid October to early May. <s> During winter and early spring it is frequented primarily by upper-class clientele from Austria and from abroad.
simple: Kitzbühel is a small medieval town in Tyrol, Austria. <s> It is the administrative center of the Kitzbühel district ("Bezirk"). <s> It is in the Kitzbühel Alps along the river Kitzbüheler Ache and about 100 km (62 mi) east of the state capital Innsbruck. <s> Kitzbühel is a ski resort of international renown and its ski season lasts from mid October to early May. <s> During winter and early spring it is frequented primarily by upper-class clientele from Austria and from abroad.

title: 1958 FIFA World Cup
complex: The 1958 FIFA World Cup, the sixth staging of the World Cup, was hosted by Sweden from 8 to 29 June. <s> The tournament was won by Brazil, who beat Sweden 5–2 in the final in the Stockholm suburb of Solna for their first title.
simple: The 1958 FIFA World Cup was a football sporting event that was held in Sweden.

title: Christie Brinkley
complex: Christie Brinkley (born Christie Lee Hudson; February 2, 1954) is an American model, actress and entrepreneur. <s> Brinkley gained worldwide fame with her appearances in the late 1970s "Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issues", ultimately appearing on an unprecedented three consecutive covers starting in 1979. <s> She spent twenty-five years as the face of CoverGirl, has appeared on over 500 magazine covers, and has signed contracts with major brands—both fashion and non-fashion. <s> Brinkley has been married four times, most notably between 1985 and 1994 to musician Billy Joel, several of whose music videos she appeared in. <s> Her fourth marriage, to architect Peter Cook, ended in a much-publicized 2008 divorce. <s> Brinkley was born Christie Lee Hudson in Monroe, Michigan on February 2, 1954, the daughter of Marjorie (née Bowling) and Herbert Hudson. <s> Her family moved to Canoga Park, Los Angeles, California, where her mother Marjorie later met and married television writer Donald Brinkley in Bel Air, Los Angeles.
simple: Christie Brinkley (born February 2, 1954) is an American model, actress, writer and designer. <s> She has appeared on magazine covers many times and has a long contract with CoverGirl (the longest of any model in history). <s> Her second marriage was to singer Billy Joel and lasted from 1985-1994. <s> All her four marriages ended in divorce. <s> She was born Christie Lee Hudson in Monroe, Michigan.

title: No Mercy (2001)
complex: No Mercy (2001) was the fourth No Mercy professional wrestling pay-per-view (PPV) event produced by the World Wrestling Federation (WWF). <s> It took place on October 21, 2001, at the Savvis Center in St. Louis, Missouri.
simple: No Mercy (2001) was a professional wrestling pay-per-view show made by World Wrestling Federation (WWF). <s> It was the fourth No Mercy event held by the WWF. <s> It was held on October 21, 2001 at the Savvis Center in St. Louis, Missouri.

title: David Pall
complex: David Boris Pall (2 April 1914 – 21 September 2004), founder of Pall Corporation, was the chemist who invented the Pall filter used in blood transfusions. <s> Born in 1914 in Thunder Bay, Ontario of Russian immigrant parents, he grew up on a farm in Saskatchewan. <s> He attended McGill University, from which he was granted a bachelor's degree in chemistry and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry. <s> He moved to New York City in 1938 and became a part of the Manhattan Project. <s> Pall worked on the design a filter to separate uranium 235 from uranium 238 using sintered stainless steel mesh. <s> In 1946, he established Pall Corporation. <s> The company's initial focus was on the development of filters for use in aircraft hydraulics. <s> However, in 1959, when Dr. Pall's first wife, Josephine, died of aplastic anemia, he began to work on the "Pall filter". <s> Mrs. Pall had undergone multiple blood transfusions in the course of an illness, which were ultimately unsuccessful. <s> His Pall filter was designed to make blood transfusions significantly safer by filtering out white blood cells, thereby reducing the incidence of transfusion reactions and viral infections. <s> Pall expanded the business, adding additional products. <s> Today, Pall Corporation has sales in excess of $2.0 Billion. <s> In his lifetime, Dr. Pall received over 180 patents and in 1990, he received the United States National Medal of Technology from President George H.W. Bush. <s> Pall died of complications of Alzheimer's disease at his last home in Roslyn Estates, New York.
simple: David Boris Pall (2 April 1914 - 21 September 2004), founder of Pall Corporation, was the chemist who invented the Pall filter used in blood transfusions. <s> Born in Thunder Bay, Ontario of Russian immigrant parents, he grew up on a farm in Saskatchewan, and attended McGill University, from which he was granted a bachelor's degree in chemistry and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry. <s> He moved to New York in 1938 and became a part of the Manhattan Project. <s> In 1946, he established Pall Corporation. <s> The company's initial focus was on the development of filters for use in aircraft hydraulics. <s> However, in 1959, when Dr. Pall's first wife, Josephine, died of aplastic anemia, he began to work on the Pall filter. <s> Mrs. Pall had undergone multiple blood transfusions in the course of an illness, which were ultimately unsuccessful. <s> The Pall filter makes blood transfusions significantly safer by filtering out white blood cells, thereby reducing the incidence of transfusion reactions and viral infections. <s> Today, Pall Corporation has sales in excess of $2.0 Billion. <s> In his lifetime, Dr. Pall received over 180 patents and in 1990, he received the United States National Medal of Technology from President George H.W. Bush. <s> Pall, a trustee of the North Shore University Hospital, died of complications of Alzheimer's disease at his last home in Roslyn Estates, New York.

title: Sabu (wrestler)
complex: Terry Michael Brunk (born December 12, 1964) is an American professional wrestler, better known by his ring name Sabu. <s> He currently wrestles on the independent circuit, most recently for Impact Wrestling. <s> He is known for his hardcore wrestling style, which he pioneered in his time with Extreme Championship Wrestling (ECW) from 1995 to 2000. <s> He is also known for his work in World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE) from 2006 to 2007, where he wrestled on the rebooted ECW brand as an "ECW Original". <s> Brunk was trained by his uncle, Ed Farhat (The Sheik), and was initially trained to be a technical wrestler. <s> He began his wrestling career in 1985 in Farhat's promotion, Big Time Wrestling, and was billed as being from Saudi Arabia under the ring names "Sabu the Elephant Boy" (use of "The Elephant Boy" was later dropped) and "Terry S.R." (the "S.R." standing for "Sheik's Revenge").
simple: Terry Michael Brunk (born December 12, 1964) is an American professional wrestler. <s> He is known for competing in hardcore-type matches. <s> He was trained by his uncle, Ed Farhat who was known by his ring name, The Sheik.

title: Pai District
complex: Pai District ( , ] ) is the northeasternmost district ("amphoe") of Mae Hong Son Province, northern Thailand. <s> The district is divided into seven sub-districts ("tambons"), which are further subdivided into 66 villages ("mubans"). <s> Pai itself has township ("thesaban tambon") status and covers parts of "tambon" Wiang Tai.
simple: Amphoe Pai is small district in the northeast of the province of Mae Hongson, Thailand. <s> Amphoe Pai is made up of seven Tambon (local government areas) and 66 villages.

title: Mansfield
complex: Mansfield is a market town in Nottinghamshire, England, the main town in the District of Mansfield and Mansfield Urban Area. <s> Nestling in the Maun Valley surrounded by hills, it lies 12 mi north of Nottingham in a largely urban district, most of whose 106,556 population live in Mansfield (including Mansfield Woodhouse), with Market Warsop a secondary centre.
simple: Mansfield is a town in Nottinghamshire, England.

title: HM Revenue and Customs
complex: Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs (HM Revenue and Customs or HMRC) is a non-ministerial department of the UK Government responsible for the collection of taxes, the payment of some forms of state support and the administration of other regulatory regimes including the national minimum wage. <s> HMRC was formed by the merger of the Inland Revenue and Her Majesty's Customs and Excise, which took effect on 18 April 2005. <s> The department's logo is the St Edward's Crown enclosed within a circle.
simple: Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs (HM Revenue and Customs or HMRC) is a non-ministerial department of the United Kingdom Government. <s> It is responsible for the collection of taxes, the payment of some types of welfare, and the management of other regulations such as the minimum wage. <s> HMRC was formed when the Inland Revenue and Her Majesty's Customs and Excise were combined. <s> This happened on 18 April 2005. <s> The department's logo is the St Edward's Crown enclosed within a circle.

title: Chyna
complex: Chyna (born Joan Marie Laurer; December 27, 1969 – April 20, 2016) was an American professional wrestler, glamour model, pornographic film actress, actress, and bodybuilder. <s> Laurer was born in Rochester, New York, on December 27, 1969. <s> She had two older siblings: Kathy and Sonny. <s> On April 20, 2016, Laurer was found dead at her home in Redondo Beach, California. <s> She was 46 years old.
simple: Chyna (Joan Marie Laurer; December 27, 1970 – April 20, 2016) was an American female wrestler for the World Wrestling Federation. <s> She was also a pornographic actress and television personality. <s> She was born in Rochester, New York. <s> Chyna was found dead at her home in Redondo Beach, California on April 20, 2016, aged 45.

title: Lord Protector
complex: Lord Protector (plural: "Lords Protectors") is a title that has been used in British constitutional law for the head of state. <s> It is also a particular title for the British heads of state in respect to the established church. <s> It is sometimes used to refer to holders of other temporary posts, for example, a regent acting for the absent monarch. <s> The title of "The Lord Protector" was originally used by royal princes or other nobles exercising an individual regency (i.e. not merely as a member of a collegial regency council) while the English monarch was still a minor or otherwise unable to rule. <s> The Lord Protector of the Commonwealth of England, Scotland and Ireland was the title of the head of state during the Commonwealth (or, to monarchists, the Interregnum), following the first period when a Council of State held executive power. <s> The title was held by Oliver Cromwell (December 1653 – September 1658) and subsequently his son and designated successor Richard Cromwell (September 1658 – May 1659) during what is now known as The Protectorate.
simple: A Lord Protector is a British title for heads of state. <s> The title of "Lord Protector" was first used by royal princes or other nobles who ruled while the English monarch was still too young to rule or was not able to rule for some other reason. <s> The Lord Protector of the Commonwealth of England, Scotland and Ireland was the title of the head of state during the Interregnum, following the first period of the Commonwealth under Council of State government. <s> It was held by Oliver Cromwell (December 1653–September 1658) and his son Richard Cromwell (September 1658–May 1659) during what is now known as the Protectorate.

title: First inauguration of George W. Bush
complex: The first inauguration of George W. Bush as the 43rd President of the United States took place on Saturday, January 20, 2001. <s> The inauguration marked the commencement of the first term of George W. Bush as President and Dick Cheney as Vice President. <s> Chief Justice William Rehnquist administered the oath of office at 12:01 p.m. <s> An estimated 300,000 people attended the swearing-in ceremony.
simple: George W. Bush was inaugurated as the 43rd President of the United States on January 20, 2001. <s> This was the beginning of the first term of George W. Bush as President and Dick Cheney as Vice President. <s> Chief Justice William Rehnquist administered the oath of office at 12:01 p.m. <s> An estimated 300,000 people attended the swearing-in ceremony.

title: Riemann sphere
complex: In mathematics, the Riemann sphere, named after Bernhard Riemann, is a model of the extended complex plane, the complex plane plus a point at infinity. <s> This extended plane represents the extended complex numbers, that is, the complex numbers plus a value ∞ for infinity. <s> With the Riemann model, the point "∞" is near to very large numbers, just as the point "0" is near to very small numbers. <s> The extended complex numbers are useful in complex analysis because they allow for division by zero in some circumstances, in a way that makes expressions such as formula_1 well-behaved. <s> For example, any rational function on the complex plane can be extended to a holomorphic function on the Riemann sphere, with the poles of the rational function mapping to infinity. <s> More generally, any meromorphic function can be thought of as a holomorphic function whose codomain is the Riemann sphere. <s> In geometry, the Riemann sphere is the prototypical example of a Riemann surface, and is one of the simplest complex manifolds. <s> In projective geometry, the sphere can be thought of as the complex projective line P(C), the projective space of all complex lines in C.
simple: The Riemann sphere is a mathematical model of the extended complex plane. <s> The model is named after Bernhard Riemann. <s> The extended complex plane is the plane of the complex numbers, plus a point at infinity. <s> With this model, this point at infinity is "close" to very large numbers in the same way zero is "close" to very small ones. <s> The extended complex numbers are useful for Complex analysis: in certain cases, the division by zero is "well-behaved", in the sense that dividing by zero gives this point at infinity. <s> In geometry, the Riemann sphere is a simple example of a Riemann surface. <s> It is also one of the simplest complex manifolds.

title: J. B. S. Haldane
complex: John Burdon Sanderson Haldane ( ; 5 November 18921 December 1964) was a British-Indian scientist known for his work in the study of physiology, genetics, evolutionary biology, and mathematics. <s> He made innovative contributions to the fields of statistics and biostatistics. <s> Between 1919 and 1922 he was a Fellow of New College, Oxford, where he researched physiology and genetics. <s> He then moved to the University of Cambridge, where he accepted a readership in Biochemistry and taught until 1932. <s> From 1927 until 1937 he was also Head of Genetical Research at the John Innes Horticultural Institution. <s> During his nine years at Cambridge, Haldane worked on enzymes and genetics, particularly the mathematical side of genetics. <s> He was the Fullerian Professor of Physiology at the Royal Institution from 1930 to 1932 and in 1933 he became full Professor of Genetics at University College London, where he spent most of his academic career. <s> Four years later he became the first Weldon Professor of Biometry at University College London. <s> In 1956, Haldane left University College London, and joined the Indian Statistical Institute (ISI) in Kolkata, India, where he headed the biometry unit. <s> Officially he stated that he left the UK because of the Suez Crisis, writing: "Finally, I am going to India because I consider that recent acts of the British Government have been violations of international law." <s> He believed that the warm climate would do him good, and that India shared his socialist dreams. <s> The university had sacked his wife Helen for excessive drinking and refusing to pay a fine, triggering Haldane's resignation. <s> He declared he would no longer wear socks, "Sixty years in socks is enough." <s> and always dressed in Indian attire. <s> He was one of the three major figures to develop the mathematical theory of population genetics, along with Ronald Fisher and Sewall Wright. <s> He thus played an important role in the modern evolutionary synthesis of the early 20th century. <s> He re-established natural selection as the central mechanism of evolution by explaining it as a mathematical consequence of Mendelian inheritance.
simple: John Burdon Sanderson Haldane FRS (3 November 1892 – 1 December 1964), known as Jack (but who used 'J.B.S.' in his printed works), was a British geneticist and evolutionary biologist who emigrated to India towards the end of his life. <s> Between 1919 and 1922 he was a Fellow of New College, Oxford University, then moved to Cambridge University, where he accepted a Readership in Biochemistry at Trinity College and taught there until 1932. <s> During his nine years at Cambridge, Haldane worked on enzymes and genetics, particularly the mathematical side of genetics. <s> He then accepted a position as Professor of Genetics and moved to University College London where he spent most of his academic career. <s> Four years later he became the first Weldon Professor of Biometry at University College London. <s> Haldane's move to India, initially to the Indian Statistical Institute (ISI) was influenced by a number of factors. <s> Officially he stated that his chief political reason was in response to the Suez Crisis. <s> He wrote: "Finally, I am going to India because I consider that recent acts of the British Government have been violations of international law." <s> His interest in India was also because of his interest in biological research, belief that the warm climate would do him good and that India offered him freedom and shared socialist dreams. <s> He was one of the founders (along with Ronald Fisher and Sewall Wright) of population genetics. <s> His major professional work was his contribution of mathematical papers on the theory of evolution, which assisted the modern evolutionary synthesis.

title: Taishi Endo
complex: Taishi Endo (遠藤 大志 , Endo Taishi , born March 31, 1980) is a former Japanese football player.
simple: Taishi Endo (born 31 March 1980) is a Japanese football player.

title: Nathaniel Lyon
complex: Nathaniel Lyon (July 14, 1818 – August 10, 1861) was the first Union general to be killed in the American Civil War and is noted for his actions in the state of Missouri at the beginning of the conflict. <s> He fought in the Second Seminole War and the Mexican–American War, before being sent to the divided state of Kansas, where he developed strong pro-Union views. <s> In February 1861, Lyon was made commander of the Union arsenal in St. Louis, Missouri (another divided state), where Lyon forced the surrender of the pro-Confederate militia. <s> This caused a riot by civilians, with Lyon’s troops firing into the crowd (Camp Jackson Affair). <s> Lyon was promoted brigadier-general and given command of Union troops in Missouri. <s> He was killed at the Battle of Wilson’s Creek, while trying to rally his outnumbered soldiers. <s> However, Lyon’s efforts had prevented the State of Missouri from joining the Confederacy. <s> Lyon was born on a farm which was then in Ashford, Connecticut, now in the town of Eastford, the son of Amasa and Kezia Knowlton Lyon and brother of William H. Lyon. <s> As a boy he hated farming. <s> His relatives had fought in the American Revolutionary War and he was determined to follow in their footsteps. <s> In 1837 he applied to the United States Military Academy and graduated eleventh in his class of 52 cadets in 1841. <s> After being reassigned to Fort Riley, Kansas, Lyon became staunchly antislavery. <s> He did not support the radicalism of the abolitionists, and came to support the Republican Party while serving in the border wars known as "Bleeding Kansas." <s> In January 1861, he wrote about the secession crisis, "It is no longer useful to appeal to reason, but to the sword." <s> On May 10 Lyon directed the Missouri volunteer regiments and the 2nd U.S. Infantry to the camp, forcing its surrender. <s> Riots broke out in St. Louis as Lyon marched his prisoners through the city to the St. Louis Arsenal. <s> The event provoked the Camp Jackson Affair of May 10, 1861, in which Lyons' troops opened fire on a crowd of civilians injuring at least 75 and killing 28. <s> Two federals and three militia were also killed and others were wounded. <s> The source of the first shot is disputed, some witnesses claiming it was a drunken rioter, others claiming it was unprovoked. <s> Lyon was nonetheless promoted to brigadier general May 17. <s> and given command over the Union troops in Missouri May 31, 1861 as commander of the Department of the West. <s> The governor fled first to the capitol at Jefferson City (ordering the tracks destroyed behind him), and then retreated with the State Guard to Boonville. <s> Lyon moved up the Missouri River by steamer and occupied Jefferson City without a fight on June 13. <s> Lyon continued the pursuit and on June 17 he defeated a portion of the State Guard at the Battle of Boonville. <s> The governor, his administration, and the Guard retreated to the southwest. <s> Lyon was subsequently supported by the reconvened Missouri State Convention which reconvened on July 22, 1861, declared the office of Governor and other state officials "vacant", and appointed a Unionist provisional state government under former Missouri Chief Justice Hamilton Gamble. <s> Lyon assumed command of the Army of the West on July 2. <s> Lyon reinforced his army before moving southwest in pursuit of Jackson, Price and the State Guard. <s> In the confused aftermath of the Union retreat from Wilson's Creek, Lyon's body was mistakenly left behind on the battlefield and discovered by Confederate forces. <s> It was briefly buried on a Union soldier's farm outside Springfield until it could be returned to Lyon's relatives.
simple: Nathaniel Lyon (July 14, 1818 – August 10, 1861) was the first Union general to be killed in the American Civil War. <s> Lyon fought in the Second Seminole War in Florida and in the Mexican-American War. <s> He died while leading his men at the Battle of Wilson's Creek. <s> Lyon was killed while trying to rally his outnumbered soldiers. <s> However, Lyon’s efforts prevented the State of Missouri from joining the Confederacy. <s> Lyon was born on July 14, 1818, in Ashford, Connecticut. <s> He was the seventh out of nine children born to Amasa and Kezia Knowlton Lyon. <s> Lyon hated farming and wanted to be like his ancestors who fought in the American Revolutionary War. <s> On July 1, 1837, Lyon entered the United States Military Academy at West Point. <s> He graduated in 1841, 11th out of a class of 52. <s> Lyon was next sent to Fort Riley in Kansas. <s> On May 10, 1861, Lyon and his troops surrounded the pro-Confederate Missouri militia and forced them to surrender. <s> While marching his captured prisoners through St. Louis, pro-Confederate citizens began to riot. <s> The incident was called the Camp Jackson Affair. <s> On May 17, Lyon was promoted to brigadier general. <s> He was given command of the Union Army of the West. <s> Lyon moved his army to go after the rebels. <s> When the Union army retreated from Wilson's Creek, Lyon's body was mistakenly left behind on the battlefield.

title: Marie-Antoine Carême
complex: Marie Antoine (Antonin) Carême (] ; 8 June 178412 January 1833) was a French chef and an early practitioner and exponent of the elaborate style of cooking known as "grande cuisine", the "high art" of French cooking: a grandiose style of cookery favoured by both international royalty and by the newly rich of Paris. <s> Carême is often considered one of the first internationally renowned celebrity chefs. <s> Abandoned by his parents in Paris in 1794 at the height of the French Revolution, he worked as a kitchen boy at a cheap Parisian chophouse in exchange for room and board. <s> In 1798, he was formally apprenticed to Sylvain Bailly, a famous "pâtissier" with a shop near the Palais-Royal. <s> The post-revolutionary Palais-Royal was a high profile, fashionable neighborhood filled with vibrant life and bustling crowds. <s> Bailly recognized his talent and ambition. <s> By the time he was prepared to leave Bailly, he could stipulate that he should be free to leave his new employer when a better offer came along. <s> Carême opened his own shop, the "Pâtisserie de la rue de la Paix", which he maintained until 1813. <s> Carême gained fame in Paris for his "pièces montées", elaborate constructions used as centerpieces, which Bailly had displayed in the pâtisserie window. <s> He made these confections, which were sometimes several feet high, entirely out of foodstuffs such as sugar, marzipan, and pastry. <s> He modeled them on temples, pyramids, and ancient ruins, taking ideas from architectural history books which he studied at the nearby Bibliothèque Nationale, thanks to the enlightened attitude of his first employer Bailly. <s> He is credited with the inventions of "gros nougats" and "grosses meringues", "croquantes", made of almonds and honey, and "solilemmes". <s> He did freelance work creating pieces principally for the French diplomat and gourmand Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-Périgord, but also other members of Parisian high society, including Napoleon. <s> While working on his confections at many private kitchens, he quickly extended his culinary skills to main courses. <s> Napoleon was famously indifferent to food, but he understood the importance of social relations in the world of diplomacy. <s> In 1804, he gave money to Talleyrand to purchase Château de Valençay, a large estate outside Paris. <s> The château was intended to act as a kind of diplomatic gathering place. <s> When Talleyrand moved there, he took Carême with him. <s> Carême was set a test by Talleyrand: to create a whole year’s worth of menus, without repetition, and using only seasonal produce. <s> Carême passed the test and completed his training in Talleyrand's kitchens. <s> After the fall of Napoleon, Carême went to London for a time and served as "chef de cuisine" to the Prince Regent, later George IV. <s> Returning to the continent, he accepted the invitation of Tsar Alexander I to come to St. Petersburg, but stayed so briefly that he prepared not even a single meal for the Tsar. <s> Upon returning to Paris, he became chef to banker James Mayer Rothschild. <s> Carême died in his Paris house on the Rue Neuve Saint Roche at the age of 48, due perhaps to many years inhaling the toxic fumes of the coal burning stoves over which he cooked. <s> He is remembered as the founder of the haute cuisine concept and is interred in the Montmartre Cemetery in Paris. <s> In his first major position, Carême worked as "chef de cuisine" to Talleyrand, who actively encouraged Carême in the development of a new refined food style using herbs, fresh vegetables, and simplified sauces with few ingredients. <s> Talleyrand became a famous host during the Congress of Vienna—by the time the congress disbanded, not only the map of Europe but also the culinary tastes of its upper classes had been thoroughly revised. <s> Carême's impact on culinary matters ranged from trivial to theoretical. <s> He is credited with creating the standard chef's hat, the "toque", he designed new sauces and dishes, and he published a classification of all sauces into groups based on four mother sauces. <s> He is also frequently credited with replacing the practice of "service à la française" (serving all dishes at once) with "service à la russe" (serving each dish in the order printed on the menu) after he returned from service in the Russian court, but others say he was a diehard supporter of "service à la française".
simple: Marie Antoine (Antonin) Carême (8 June 1784 – 12 January 1833), was a French chef and author. <s> He is well known for greatly simplifying and writing about the style of cooking known as "haute cuisine", the high art of French cooking. <s> He was known as "chef of kings and king of chefs", because he cooked for royalty, and is often thought of as the first celebrity chef. <s> Carême was born Paris, but was abandoned in 1792 because his parents were very poor. <s> He worked as a kitchen boy at a cheap Paris cafe in exchange for a room and food. <s> In 1798, he was apprenticed to Sylvain Bailly, a famous "pâtissier" (cake baker) with a shop near the Palais-Royal. <s> Carême gained fame in Paris for his cake centrepieces, which Bailly put in the pâtisserie window. <s> The centerpieces were sometimes several feet high, and were only made out of foodstuffs such as sugar, marzipan, and pastry. <s> He modelled them on temples, pyramids, and ancient ruins which he read about in the books he studied at the French national library (Bibliothéque Nationale). <s> Carême also worked for other people, for example the French diplomat and gourmand Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-Périgord, and other members of Parisian high society, including Napoleon. <s> When he worked in the private kitchens he quickly learned about main courses. <s> Napoleon was not interested in having fancy food, but he knew of social contacts that were important for diplomats. <s> In 1804, he gave Talleyrand money to buy Château de Valençay. <s> When Talleyrand moved there, he took Carême with him. <s> Carême was set a test by Talleyrand: he had to create a whole year’s worth of menus, without repeating them, and use only food that was in season. <s> Carême passed the test and finished his training in Talleyrand's kitchens. <s> When Napoléon was defeated Carême went to London for a time and served as "chef de cuisine" to the Prince Regent, later George IV. <s> He returned to Europe to work for Czar Alexander I in St. Petersburg, before returning to Paris, where he was chef to banker James Mayer Rothschild. <s> He died in Paris at the age of 48, and is buried in the Cimetière de Montmartre in Montmartre. <s> Talleyrand encouraged Carême to start a new refined style of eating. <s> Carême's is said to have started "service à la russe" (serving each course in the order printed on the menu) instead of "service à la française" (serving all dishes at once)

title: Soho
complex: Soho is an area of the City of Westminster, part of the West End of London. <s> Originally a fashionable district for the aristocracy, it has been one of the main entertainment districts in the capital since the 19th century. <s> The area was developed from farmland by Henry VIII in 1536, when it became a royal park. <s> It became a parish in its own right in the late 17th century, when buildings started to be developed for the upper class, including the laying out of Soho Square in the 1680s. <s> St Anne's Church was established during the late 17th century, and remains a significant local landmark; other churches are the Church of our Lady of the Assumption and Saint Gregory and St Patrick's Church in Soho Square. <s> The aristocracy had mostly moved away by the mid-19th century, when Soho was particularly badly hit by an outbreak of cholera in 1854. <s> For much of the 20th century Soho had a reputation as a base for the sex industry in addition to its night life and its location for the headquarters of leading film companies. <s> Since the 1980s, the area has undergone considerable gentrification. <s> It is now predominantly a fashionable district of upmarket restaurants and media offices, with only a small remnant of sex industry venues. <s> London's gay community is centred on Old Compton Street in Soho. <s> Soho is about 1 sqmi in area, bounded by Cambridge Circus to the south, Oxford Street to the north, Regent Street to the west, and Charing Cross Road to the east. <s> However, apart from Oxford Street, all of these roads are 19th-century metropolitan improvements, and Soho has never been an administrative unit, with formally defined boundaries. <s> The area to the west is known as Mayfair, to the north Fitzrovia, to the east St Giles and Covent Garden, and to the south St James's. <s> According to the Soho Society, Chinatown, the area between Leicester Square to the south and Shaftesbury Avenue to the north, is part of the area. <s> Soho is part of the West End electoral ward which elects three councillors to Westminster City Council. <s> A significant event in the history of epidemiology and public health was Dr. John Snow's study of an 1854 outbreak of cholera in Soho. <s> He identified the cause of the outbreak as water from the public pump at the junction of Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) and Cambridge Street (now Lexington Street), close to the rear wall of what is today the John Snow public house. <s> Snow mapped the addresses of the sick, and noted that they were mostly people whose nearest access to water was the Broad Street pump. <s> He persuaded the authorities to remove the handle of the pump, thus preventing any more of the infected water from being collected. <s> The spring below the pump was later found to have been contaminated with sewage. <s> This is an early example of epidemiology, public health medicine and the application of science—the germ theory of disease—in a real-life crisis. <s> Science writer Steven Johnson has written about the changes related to the cholera outbreak, and notes that almost every building on the street that existed in 1854 has since been replaced. <s> A replica of the pump, with a memorial plaque and without a handle (to signify Snow's action to halt the outbreak) was erected in 1992 near the location of the original. <s> Soho is near the heart of London's theatre area. <s> It is home to Soho Theatre, built in 2000 to present new plays and comedy. <s> Soho is a centre of the independent film and video industry as well as the television and film post-production industry. <s> Twentieth Century House in Soho Square was built in 1937 for Twentieth Century Fox. <s> The British Board of Film Classification, formerly known as the British Board of Film Censors, has been based in the square since 1950. <s> Soho's key fibre communications network has been managed by Sohonet since 1995, which connects the Soho media and post-production community to British film studios such as Pinewood and Shepperton, along with other locations worldwide include HBO and Warner Brothers. <s> In the 2010s, research commissioned by Westminster City Council showed 23 per cent of the workforce in Soho works in the creative industries.
simple: Soho is an area of the City of Westminster and the West End of London. <s> For much of the 20th century Soho had sex shops, prostitutes, jazz clubs, bars, night clubs, theatres and the movie industry. <s> Since the early 1980s, the area has changed greatly: it has moved upmarket. <s> It now is a fashionable district of expensive restaurants and media offices, with only a few sex industry venues. <s> It is an area of about a square mile, bounded by Oxford Street to the north, Regent Street to the west, Leicester Square to the south and Charing Cross Road to the east. <s> Soho was never an administrative unit with formal boundaries. <s> Apart from Oxford Street, all of these roads are 19th-century metropolitan improvements. <s> The area to the west is known as Mayfair, to the north Fitzrovia, to the east St Giles and Covent Garden, and to the south St James's. <s> According to the Soho Society, Chinatown, the area between Leicester Square to the south and Shaftesbury Avenue to the north, is part of Soho, although some consider it a separate area. <s> A significant event in the history of epidemiology and public health was Dr. John Snow's study of an 1854 outbreak of cholera in Soho. <s> He identified the cause of the outbreak as water from the public water pump located at the junction of Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) and Cambridge Street (now Lexington Street), close to the rear wall of what is today the "John Snow" public house. <s> John Snow mapped the addresses of the sick, and noted that they were mostly people whose nearest access to water was the Broad Street pump. <s> He persuaded the authorities to remove the handle of the pump, thus preventing any more of the infected water from being collected. <s> The spring below the pump was later found to have been contaminated with sewage. <s> This is an early example of epidemiology, public health medicine and the application of science–the germ theory of disease. <s> A replica of the pump, with a memorial plaque and without a handle (to signify John Snow's action to halt the outbreak) was erected near the location of the original pump. <s> Soho is near the heart of London's theatre area, and is a centre of the independent movie and video industry as well as the television and movie 'post-production' industry. <s> It is home to Soho Theatre, built in 2000 for new plays and stand-up comedy. <s> The British Board of Film Classification, formerly known as the British Board of Film Censors, can be found in Soho Square. <s> Soho is criss-crossed by a rooftop telecommunication network, and below ground level with fibre optics making up Sohonet, which connects the Soho media and post-production community to British movie studios such as Pinewood Studios and Shepperton Studios, and to other major production centres (such as Rome, New York City, Los Angeles, Sydney and Wellington, New Zealand.

title: Michael Dukakis
complex: Michael Stanley Dukakis ( ; born November 3, 1933) is a retired American politician who served as the 65th Governor of Massachusetts, from 1975 to 1979 and again from 1983 to 1991. <s> He is the longest-serving governor in Massachusetts history and only the second Greek-American governor in U.S. history, after Spiro Agnew. <s> He was nominated by the Democratic Party for president in the 1988 election, losing to the Republican candidate, Vice President George H. W. Bush. <s> Since leaving office, Dukakis has served on the board of directors for Amtrak and has taught political science at Northeastern University and UCLA. <s> He was mentioned as a potential appointee to the Senate in 2009 to fill the vacancy caused by Ted Kennedy's death, but Governor Deval Patrick chose Paul G. Kirk. <s> In 2012, Dukakis backed the successful Senate campaign of Elizabeth Warren. <s> In 2008, he stated during an interview with Katie Couric that he "owed the American people an apology" because "if I had beaten the old man i.e. George H. W. Bush, we never would have heard of the kid i.e. George W. Bush, and we wouldn't be in this mess." <s> In August 2009, the 75-year-old Dukakis was mentioned as one of two leading candidates as a possible interim successor to Ted Kennedy in the U.S. Senate, after Kennedy's death.
simple: Michael Stanley Dukakis (, born November 3, 1933) served as the 65th and 67th Governor of Massachusetts, from 1975 to 1979 and 1983 to 1991. <s> He is the longest-serving Governor in Massachusetts and only the second Greek-American governor in United States history, after Spiro Agnew. <s> In 1988, he was the Democratic nominee for President, but lost to Republican then–Vice President, George H. W. Bush. <s> Dukakis was mentioned as candidate for Massachusetts Senator for a possible interim successor to Ted Kennedy, after Kennedy's death but Governor Deval Patrick chose Paul G. Kirk, the other candidate and a favorite of the Kennedy Family. <s> In 2008, he talked about his defeat in an interview with Katie Couric, in which he said he "owed the American people an apology" because "if I had beaten the old man, we never would have heard of the kid, and we wouldn't be in this mess."

title: Liga MX
complex: The Liga MX (] ) is the top tier of the Mexican football league system. <s> Currently sponsored by BBVA through its Mexican subsidiary BBVA México, it is officially known as Liga BBVA MX.
simple: Liga MX, known as the Primera División de México before the 2012–13 season, is the top football league in México.

title: Iwashiro Province
complex: Iwashiro Province (岩代国 , Iwashiro-no kuni ) is an old province in the area of Fukushima Prefecture. <s> It was sometimes called Ganshū (岩州 ) .
simple: Iwashiro Province (岩代国, Iwashiro-no kuni) is an old province in the area of Fukushima Prefecture on the island of Honshū. <s> It was sometimes called Ōshū (奥州).

title: Edward Egan
complex: Edward Michael Egan (April 2, 1932 – March 5, 2015) was an American Cardinal of the Roman Catholic Church. <s> He served as Bishop of Bridgeport from 1988 to 2000, and as Archbishop of New York from 2000 to 2009. <s> He was elevated to the cardinalate in 2001. <s> He was the twelfth Bishop, ninth Archbishop, and seventh Cardinal of the See of New York.
simple: Edward Michael Egan (April 2, 1932 – March 5, 2015) was an American Cardinal of the Roman Catholic Church. <s> He served as Bishop of Bridgeport from 1988 to 2000, and as Archbishop of New York from 2000 to 2009. <s> He was elevated to the cardinalate in 2001.

title: Scots language
complex: As there are no universally accepted criteria for distinguishing a language from a dialect, scholars and other interested parties often disagree about the linguistic, historical and social status of Scots and particularly its relationship to English. <s> Although a number of paradigms for distinguishing between languages and dialects exist, they often render contradictory results. <s> Broad Scots is at one end of a bipolar linguistic continuum, with Scottish Standard English at the other. <s> Scots is often regarded as one of the ancient varieties of English, but it has its own distinct dialects. <s> Alternatively, Scots is sometimes treated as a distinct Germanic language, in the way that Norwegian is closely linked to but distinct from Danish. <s> Northumbrian Old English had been established in what is now southeastern Scotland as far as the River Forth by the seventh century, as the region was part of the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Northumbria. <s> Middle Irish was the then language of the Scottish court and the common use of Old English remained largely confined to this area until the thirteenth century. <s> The succeeding variety of Early northern Middle English spoken in southeastern Scotland is also known as Early Scots. <s> It began to further diverge from the Middle English of Northumbria due to twelfth and thirteenth century immigration of Scandinavian-influenced Middle English-speakers from the North and Midlands of England. <s> Later influences on the development of Scots came from the Romance languages via ecclesiastical and legal Latin, Norman French, and later Parisian French, due to the Auld Alliance. <s> Additionally, there were Dutch and Middle Low German influences due to trade with and immigration from the Low Countries. <s> Scots also includes loan words in the legal and administrative fields resulting from contact with Middle Irish, and reflected in early medieval legal documents. <s> Contemporary Scottish Gaelic loans are mainly for geographical and cultural features, such as "ceilidh", "loch" and "clan". <s> From the thirteenth century, the Early Scots language spread further into Scotland via the burghs, which were proto-urban institutions first established by King David I. <s> In the fourteenth century Scotland, the growth in prestige of Early Scots and the complementary decline of French, made Scots the prestige dialect of most of eastern Scotland. <s> By the sixteenth century Middle Scots had established orthographic and literary norms largely independent of those developing in England. <s> From 1610 to the 1690s during the Plantation of Ulster some 200,000 Scots-speaking Lowlanders settled as colonists in Ulster in Ireland. <s> In the core areas of Scots settlement, Scots outnumbered English settlers by five or six to one. <s> The name Modern Scots is used to describe the Scots language after 1700, when southern Modern English was generally adopted as the literary language, though Modern Scots remained the vernacular.
simple: There have been disagreements about the linguistic, historical and social status of Scots. <s> Focused broad Scots is at one end of a scale, with Scottish Standard English at the other. <s> Scots is generally regarded as one of the ancient varieties of English, yet it has its own distinct variations. <s> Northumbrian Old English was established in what is now southeastern Scotland as far as the River Forth by the seventh century. <s> The region was part of the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Northumbria. <s> Early Scots began to diverge from Northumbrian English in the twelfth and thirteenth century. <s> There was immigration of Scandinavian-influenced Middle English-speakers from the North and Midlands of England. <s> Later influences on the development of Scots were from Romance languages via ecclesiastical and legal Latin, Norman and later Parisian French from the Auld Alliance and Dutch and Middle Low German influences by trade and immigration from the Low Countries. <s> Scots also includes loanwords from contact with Gaelic. <s> From the 13th century, Early Scots spread further into Scotland through the burghs established by King David I. <s> The growth in prestige of Early Scots in the 14th century and the decline of French in Scotland made Scots the prestige dialect in most of eastern Scotland. <s> From 1610 to the 1690s, during the Plantation of Ulster, many Scots-speaking Lowlanders, about 200,000, settled there. <s> In the core areas of Scots settlement, there were five or six times as many Scots as Englsih settlers. <s> Southern Modern English was adopted as the literary language after 1700, and "Modern Scots" is sometimes used to describe the spoken language after 1700.

title: J. Jonah Jameson
complex: John Jonah Jameson, Jr. is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics, commonly in association with the superhero Spider-Man. <s> The character was created by writer Stan Lee and artist Steve Ditko, and he first appeared in "The Amazing Spider-Man" #1 (March 1963). <s> He and Peter Parker are related by marriage as a result of his father's wedding to May Parker. <s> Jameson's son John Jameson is the Marvel Universe supporting character who, in addition to his job as a famous astronaut, has become Man-Wolf and Star-God. <s> In the aborted James Cameron script; Jameson is a TV executive instead of editor-in-chief of the "Daily Bugle".
simple: J. Jonah Jameson is a fictional Spider-Man character. <s> He is the father of John Jameson. <s> He is the chief-editor of the "Daily Bugle".

title: Dearham
complex: Dearham is a village and civil parish in the Allerdale district of Cumbria, England. <s> Historically part of Cumberland, it lies about 2 mi east of Maryport and 5 mi west of Cockermouth.
simple: Dearham is a village and civil parish in Allerdale, Cumbria, England.

title: Bradenton, Florida
complex: Bradenton is a city in Manatee County, Florida, United States. <s> The U.S. Census Bureau estimated the city's 2018 population to be 57,644. <s> Bradenton is a principal city of the North Port–Sarasota–Bradenton metropolitan statistical area, which had a 2018 estimated population of 821,573. <s> It is the county seat.
simple: Bradenton is a city of Florida in the United States. <s> It is the county seat of Manatee County.

title: Old Yeller (film)
complex: Old Yeller is a 1957 American drama film produced by Walt Disney. <s> It stars Tommy Kirk, Dorothy McGuire, Fess Parker, and Beverly Washburn. <s> It is about a boy and a stray dog in post-Civil War Texas. <s> The film is based upon the 1956 Newbery Honor-winning book of the same name by Fred Gipson. <s> Gipson also cowrote the screenplay with William Tunberg. <s> The success of the "Old Yeller" film led to a sequel, "Savage Sam", which was also based on a book by Gipson.
simple: Old Yeller is a 1957 Walt Disney movie. <s> It stars Tommy Kirk, Fess Parker, Kevin Corcoran, Dorothy McGuire, and 'Spike'. <s> The movie is about a boy and a stray dog in post-Civil War Texas. <s> It is based on a book by Fred Gipson. <s> A sequel called "Savage Sam" followed in 1958.

title: Austral thrush
complex: The austral thrush ("Turdus falcklandii") is a medium-sized thrush from southern South America. <s> There are two subspecies, the Magellan thrush ("T. f. magellanicus") from south Argentina and south and central Chile, and the Falkland thrush ("T. f. falcklandii") from the Falkland Islands.
simple: Austral thrush ("Turdus falcklandii magellanicus") is a common bird found in southern South America.

title: Sherwood Forest
complex: Sherwood Forest is a royal forest in Nottinghamshire, England, famous by its historic association with the legend of Robin Hood.
simple: Sherwood Forest is an ancient woodland near Nottingham, England. <s> It is famous as the home of the mythical outlaw, Robin Hood and his men (and Maid Marian).

title: Labour and Co-operative
complex: Labour and Co-operative Party (often abbreviated Labour Co-op; ) is a description used by candidates in United Kingdom elections who stand on behalf of both the Labour Party and the Co-operative Party.
simple: Labour Co-operative or Labour and Co-operative is the name used in the United Kingdom to describe politicians who are elected as members of the Co-operative Party.

title: Francisco Pavón
complex: Francisco "Paco" Pavón Barahona (born 9 January 1980) is a Spanish retired footballer who played as a central defender.
simple: Francisco Pavón (born 9 January 1980) is a Spanish football player.

title: Ramón Díaz
complex: Ramón Ángel Díaz (born 29 August 1959) is a former Argentine footballer and manager. <s> He played for River Plate as a striker, and coached it for three tenures, winning eight titles.
simple: Ramón Díaz (born August 29, 1959) is a former Argentine football player.

title: Ivan Grubišić
complex: Ivan Grubišić (20 June 1936 – 19 March 2017) was a Croatian Roman Catholic priest, sociologist, and politician. <s> He served in the Croatian Parliament from 2011 to 2015. <s> Ivan Grubišić was born in Dicmo in a poor family. <s> He had seven brothers and sisters.
simple: Ivan Grubišić (20 June 1936 – 19 March 2017) was a Croatian Roman Catholic priest, sociologist, and independent politician. <s> Grubišić died in Split, Croatia on 19 March 2017, aged 80. <s> He served as a representative in the Croatian Parliament representing the X electoral district from 22 December 2011 through 28 December 2015. <s> Grubišić was born in Dicmo, Kingdom of Yugoslavia.

title: Samuel W. Kinnaird
complex: Samuel W. Kinnaird (May 2, 1840 – April 20, 1923) was a Union Navy sailor in the American Civil War and a recipient of the U.S. military's highest decoration, the Medal of Honor, for his actions at the Battle of Mobile Bay. <s> Born on May 2, 1840, in New York City, Kinnaird was still living in the state of New York when he joined the Navy. <s> He served during the Civil War as a landsman on the . <s> At the Battle of Mobile Bay on August 5, 1864, "Lackawanna" engaged the at close range and Kinnaird displayed "presence of mind and cheerfulness" which helped maintain his shipmates' morale. <s> For this action, he was awarded the Medal of Honor four months later, on December 31, 1864. <s> Kinnaird's official Medal of Honor citation reads: Served as a landsman on board the U.S.S. "Lackawanna" during successful attacks against Fort Morgan, rebel gunboats and the ram "Tennessee" in Mobile Bay, 5 August 1864. <s> Showing a presence of mind and cheerfulness that had much to do with maintaining the crew's morale, Kinnaird served gallantly through the action which resulted in the capture of the prize rebel ram "Tennessee" and in the destruction of batteries at Fort Morgan. <s> Kinnaird died on April 20, 1923, at age 82 and was buried in the New York City neighborhood of Woodside, Queens.
simple: Samuel W. Kinnaird (May 2, 1840 – April 20, 1923) was a Union Navy sailor in the American Civil War. <s> He was a recipient of the U.S. military's highest decoration, the Medal of Honor. <s> He got it for his actions at the Battle of Mobile Bay. <s> He was born on May 2, 1840, in New York City. <s> Kinnaird was still living in the state of New York when he joined the Navy. <s> He served during the Civil War as a landsman on the . <s> At the Battle of Mobile Bay on August 5, 1864, "Lackawanna" engaged the . <s> They fought at close range and Kinnaird displayed "presence of mind and cheerfulness" which helped maintain his shipmates' morale. <s> For this action, he was presented the Medal of Honor four months later on December 31, 1864. <s> Kinnaird's official Medal of Honor citation reads: Served as a landsman on board the U.S.S. "Lackawanna" during successful attacks against Fort Morgan, rebel gunboats and the ram "Tennessee" in Mobile Bay, 5 August 1864. <s> Showing a presence of mind and cheerfulness that had much to do with maintaining the crew's morale, Kinnaird served gallantly through the action which resulted in the capture of the prize rebel ram "Tennessee" and in the destruction of batteries at Fort Morgan. <s> Kinnaird died on April 20, 1923. <s> He was 82 and was buried in the New York City neighborhood of Woodside, Queens.

title: Capparis decidua
complex: Capparis decidua is commonly known as karira, is a useful plant in its marginal habitat. <s> Its spicy fruits are used for preparing vegetables, curry and fine pickles and can attract helpful insectivores; the plant also is used in folk medicine and herbalism. <s> It can be used in landscape gardening, afforestation and reforestation in semidesert and desert areas; it provides assistance against soil erosion. <s> It is a small much branched tree or shrub of arid regions in Africa, Middle East and southern Asia, including the Thar desertears a mass of slender, leafless branches, the small caducous leaves being found only on young shoots. <s> It rarely exceeds a height of 5 meters (15 feet).
simple: Capparis decidua is commonly known as karir, kair, kirir, karril, etc. <s> It is either a small tree with many branches or a shrub of the Thar desert and other hot and dry regions in southern Asia. <s> It has a lot of thin, leafless branches, the small leaves being found only on young shoots. <s> It rarely grows above a height of 5 meters (15 feet).

title: Sobig
complex: The Sobig Worm was a computer worm that infected millions of Internet-connected, Microsoft Windows computers in August 2003. <s> The Sobig.F worm deactivated itself on September 10, 2003. <s> On November 5 the same year, Microsoft announced that they will pay $250,000 for information leading to the arrest of the creator of the Sobig worm.
simple: At the height of the infection, the Sobig worm made up one in seventeen emails sent over the internet. <s> The Sobig worm created over 1 million copies of itself for the rest of 2003. <s> The worm had a shut off date set for September 10, 2003.

title: Bukit Timah Hill
complex: Bukit Timah Hill is a hill located within the planning area of Bukit Panjang in Singapore. <s> The hill stands at an altitude of 163.63 metres (537 ft.) above ground level (approx. 44 storey building) and 182 metres (597 ft.) above sea level, making it the highest natural point in the city-state.
simple: Bukit Timah is an area in Singapore and a hill in that area. <s> The Bukit Timah area is a particularly prominent location with a high land value. <s> Bukit Timah Hill stands at an altitude of 163.63 m and is the highest point in the city-state of Singapore.

title: Keith Birdsong
complex: Keith Birdsong (July 14, 1959 – June 4, 2019) was a Muscogee Creek-Cherokee illustrator, known best for illustrating covers of "Star Trek" novels, usually depicting the various actors of the "Star Trek" television series and movies in a realistic manner. <s> Birdsong died on June 4, 2019, as a result of injuries sustained in a car crash.
simple: Keith Birdsong (July 14, 1959 – June 4, 2019) was a Muscogee Creek-Cherokee illustrator. <s> Birdsong was best known for illustrating covers of "Star Trek" novels. <s> Birdsong was killed in a car crash on June 4, 2019 at the age of 59.

title: Bob Solinger
complex: Robert Edward "Solly" Solinger (December 23, 1925 – December 10, 2014) was a professional ice hockey player who played 99 games in the National Hockey League. <s> Born in Star City, Saskatchewan, he played for the Toronto Maple Leafs and Detroit Red Wings. <s> He was the first winner of the Dudley "Red" Garrett Memorial Award as rookie of the year in the American Hockey League. <s> Solinger won the Calder Cup five times during his playing career to share the record for most Calder Cups won with Les Duff, Fred Glover, and Mike Busniuk. <s> He died on December 10, 2014.
