simple: Robert Edward "Solly" Solinger (December 23, 1925 – December 10, 2014) was a professional Canadian ice hockey player. <s> he played 99 games in the National Hockey League. <s> Solinger was born in Star City, Saskatchewan. <s> He played for the Toronto Maple Leafs and Detroit Red Wings. <s> Solinger died in Edmonton, Alberta, aged 88, on December 10, 2014.

title: Viveca Lärn
complex: Viveca Lärn, earlier Viveca Sundvall, born 6 April 1944 in Örgryte Parish in Gothenburg, Sweden, is a Swedish writer. <s> She is mostly famous for writing the Mimmi and the Eddie children's books series. <s> She has also written books for an adult audience, and many of those books formed the basis for the TV series "Saltön".
simple: Viveca Lärn, earlier Viveca Sundvall, born 6 April 1944 in Örgryte Parish in Gothenburg, Sweden, is a Swedish writer. <s> She is mostly famous for writing the Mimmi and the Eddie children's books series. <s> She has also written books for adults. <s> Her books for adults have led to the TV series "Saltön".

title: Mid-engine design
complex: A mid-engine layout describes the placement of an automobile engine between the rear and front axles and generally behind the passenger compartment.
simple: A mid-engine layout describes the location of an automobile engine between the front and rear axles.

title: Frank Ivancie
complex: Francis James Ivancie (July 19, 1924 – May 2, 2019) was an American businessman and politician who served as mayor of Portland, Oregon, from 1980 to 1985. <s> Prior to his term as mayor, Ivancie served for fourteen years on the Portland City Council. <s> After his retirement from elected office, Ivancie remained active in community affairs, occasionally lending his support to political causes. <s> During his political career, Ivancie was a conservative Democrat.
simple: Francis James "Frank" Ivancie (July 19, 1924 – May 2, 2019) was an American businessman and politician. <s> He served as Mayor of Portland, Oregon, from 1980 to 1985. <s> Before this, Ivancie served for fourteen years on the Portland City Council. <s> During his political career, Ivancie was a conservative Democrat.

title: Northwest Arctic Borough, Alaska
complex: Northwest Arctic Borough is a borough located in the U.S. state of Alaska. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 7,523. <s> The borough seat is Kotzebue. <s> The borough was formed on June 2, 1986.
simple: Northwest Arctic Borough is a borough in the U.S. state of Alaska. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 7,523. <s> The borough seat is Kotzebue. <s> The borough was created on June 2, 1986.

title: Edwin Mosquera
complex: Edwin Orlando Mosquera Roa (26 July 1985 – 2 December 2017) was a Colombian weightlifter who competed in the 69 kg division. <s> He won silver medals at the 2007 Pan American Games and 2016 Pan American Championships, and won the Pan American Championships in 2008 and 2010. <s> He placed 15th at the 2016 Olympics, but had to withdraw from the 2008 Games due to a kneecap injury. <s> Mosquera died on 2 December 2017, after being shot twice.
simple: Edwin Orlando Mosquera Roa (26 July 1985 – 2 December 2017) was a Colombian weightlifter. <s> He competed in the 69 kg weight division. <s> He won a silver medal at the 2007 Pan American Games. <s> He also won two gold medals (2008 and 2010) and a silver medal (2016) at the Pan American Weightlifting Championships. <s> He was at the 2008 and 2016 Summer Olympics. <s> Mosquera died after being shot twice on 2 December 2017 in Palmira, Valle del Cauca.

title: Albert Sabin
complex: Albert Bruce Sabin (born Abram Saperstein; August 26, 1906 – March 3, 1993) was a Polish American medical researcher, best known for developing the oral polio vaccine, which has played a key role in nearly eradicating the disease. <s> Sabin was born in Białystok, Poland, then part of the Russian Empire, to Polish-Jewish parents, Jacob Saperstein and Tillie Krugman. <s> In 1921, he emigrated with his family as "Abram Saperstejn" on the S/S "Lapland" which sailed from Antwerp, Belgium, to the Port of New York. <s> In 1930, he became a naturalized citizen of the United States and changed his name to Sabin, as well as assuming the middle name Bruce. <s> In 1983, Sabin developed calcification of the cervical spine, which caused paralysis and intense pain. <s> Sabin revealed in a television interview that the experience had made him decide to spend the rest of his life working on alleviating pain. <s> This condition was successfully treated by surgery conducted at Johns Hopkins Hospital in 1992 when Sabin was 86. <s> A year later, Sabin died in Washington, D.C., from heart failure.
simple: Albert Bruce Sabin (August 26, 1906 – March 3, 1993) was a Polish-born American medical researcher best known for having developed an oral polio vaccine. <s> Sabin was born Albert Saperstein on August 26, 1906 in Białystok, Russian Empire (now Poland). <s> He became a naturalized citizen of the United States in 1930 and changed his last name to Sabin. <s> Sabin died on March 3, 1993 in his home in Washington, D.C. from heart failure, aged 86.

title: Manganese(II) oxide
complex: Manganese(II) oxide is an inorganic compound with chemical formula MnO. <s> It forms green crystals.
simple: Manganese(II) oxide is a chemical compound. <s> Its chemical formula is MnO. <s> It is made by reduction of manganese(IV) oxide by hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or methane.

title: Astacus astacus
complex: Astacus astacus, the European crayfish, noble crayfish, or broad-fingered crayfish, is the most common species of crayfish in Europe, and a traditional food source. <s> Like other true crayfish, "A. astacus" is restricted to fresh water, living only in unpolluted streams, rivers, and lakes. <s> It is found from France throughout Central Europe, to the Balkan Peninsula, and north as far as parts of the British Isles, Scandinavia, and Eastern Europe. <s> Males may grow up to 16 cm long, and females up to 12 cm. <s> European crayfish are nocturnal and feed on worms, aquatic insects, molluscs, and plants, spending the day resting in a burrow. <s> They become sexually mature after three to four years and a series of moults, and breed in October and November. <s> Fertilised eggs are carried by the female, attached to her pleopods, until the following May, when they hatch and disperse. <s> The main predators of "A. astacus", both as juveniles and adults, are mink, eels, perch, pike, otters, and muskrats. <s> This species was once abundant in Europe, although it was expensive to buy, and is considered to be the finest edible crayfish. <s> It is, however, susceptible to the crayfish plague carried by the invasive North American species signal crayfish ("Pacifastacus leniusculus"), so is listed as a vulnerable species on the IUCN Red List.
simple: The Astacus astacus (or noble crayfish, European crayfish, and broad-fingered crayfish) is a species of crayfish in Europe. <s> Like other crayfish, the Astacus astacus lives in fresh water. <s> The Astacus astacus can be found living in France, Central Europe, Balkan peninsula, the British Isles, Scandinavia, and western parts of the former Soviet Union. <s> Males can reach 16 cm long and females can reach 12 cm. <s> They eat worms, aquatic insects, mollusks, and plants. <s> They spend the day resting in a burrow. <s> They are sexually mature after three to four years. <s> They breed in October and November of every year. <s> The eggs will stay with the female until May. <s> There are many predators that eat the Astacus astacus such as, minks, eels, perch, pike, otters, and muskrats. <s> Because of the crayfish plaque that was brought from the American species the signal crayfish ("Pacifastacus leniusculus"), it is listed as a vulnerable species on the IUCN Red List.

title: Bombyliidae
complex: The Bombyliidae are a family of flies. <s> Their common name are bee flies or humbleflies. <s> Adults generally feed on nectar and pollen, some being important pollinators. <s> Larvae generally are parasitoids of other insects. <s> The Bombyliidae are a large family of flies comprising hundreds of genera, but the lifecycles of most species are known poorly, or not at all. <s> They range in size from very small (2 mm in length) to very large for flies (wingspan of some 40 mm). <s> When at rest, many species hold their wings at a characteristic "swept back" angle. <s> Adults generally feed on nectar and pollen, some being important pollinators, often with spectacularly long probosces adapted to plants such as "Lapeirousia" species with very long, narrow floral tubes. <s> Unlike butterflies, bee flies hold their proboscis straight, and cannot retract it. <s> In parts of East Anglia, locals refer to them as beewhals, thanks to their tusk-like appendages. <s> Many Bombyliidae superficially resemble bees and accordingly the prevalent common name for a member of the family is bee fly. <s> Possibly the resemblance is Batesian mimicry, affording the adults some protection from predators. <s> The larval stages are predators or parasitoids of the eggs and larvae of other insects. <s> The adult females usually deposit eggs in the vicinity of possible hosts, quite often in the burrows of beetles or wasps/solitary bees. <s> Although insect parasitoids usually are fairly host-specific, often highly host-specific, some Bombyliidae are opportunistic and will attack a variety of hosts. <s> The Bombyliidae include at least 4,500 described species, and certainly thousands more remain to be described.
simple: The Bombyliidae are a family of flies. <s> Their common name is bee flies. <s> The Bombyliidae are a large family of flies. <s> It has hundreds of genera, but the life cycles of most species are known poorly, or not at all. <s> The Bombyliidae include a large number of species, but for its size this is one of the least understood families of insects. <s> Some are very small (2 mm in length), but some can be very large for flies (wingspan of some 40 mm). <s> Adults normally feed on nectar and pollen. <s> Those with a spectacularly long proboscis are adapted to plants (such as "Lapeirousia") which have long, narrow floral tubes. <s> The adult flies usually feed on nectar and pollen, and some are important pollinators. <s> Many Bombyliidae look like bees and so a common name for the family is the bee flies. <s> The larval stages are predators or parasitoids of the eggs and larvae of other insects. <s> The adult females usually lay eggs near the nests of possible hosts, often in the burrows of solitary bees, wasps or beetles. <s> Although most bee-flies usually are fairly or highly host-specific, some species do attack a number of hosts.

title: L. L. Zamenhof
complex: Ludwik Lejzer Zamenhof (15 December O.S. 3 December 1859 – 14 April O.S. 1 April 1917 ), often credited as L. L. Zamenhof, was a Polish ophthalmologist and the inventor of the international language Esperanto, the most widely-used constructed international auxiliary language in the world. <s> Zamenhof was born on 15 December O.S. 3 December 1859 , the son of Markus Zamenhof (27 January O.S. 15 January 1837 - 29 November O.S. 16 November 1907 ) and Rozalia Zamenhof (1839 - 1 September O.S. 20 August 1892 ), in the multi-ethnic city of Belostok in Russian Empire (now Białystok in Poland). <s> At that time the city was in the Grodno Governorate of the Russian Empire as a result of the 1807 Treaties of Tilsit. <s> His parents were of Litvak Jewish descent. <s> This group inhabited the former Grand Duchy of Lithuania. <s> He appears to have been natively bilingual in Yiddish and Russian. <s> His father was a teacher of German and French. <s> From him, Zamenhof learned German, French and Hebrew. <s> He also spoke some major language of Białystok: Polish, a Yiddish, Belarusian, and German. <s> Polish became the native language of his children in Warsaw. <s> In school he studied the classical languages Latin, Greek, Hebrew, and Aramaic. <s> He later learned some English, though in his own words not very well. <s> He had an interest in Lithuanian and Italian, and learned Volapük when it came out in 1880. <s> By that point his international language project was already well developed. <s> As a student at secondary school in Warsaw, Zamenhof attempted to create an international language with a grammar that was rich, but complex. <s> When he later studied English, he decided that the international language must have a simpler grammar. <s> Apart from his parents' native languages Russian and Yiddish and his adopted language Polish, his projects were also aided by his mastery of German, a good passive understanding of Latin, Hebrew and French, and a basic knowledge of Greek, English and Italian. <s> Zamenhof's grandson, Louis-Christophe Zaleski-Zamenhof (Adam's son), has lived in France since the 1960s. <s> Zamenhof was nominated 12 times for the Nobel Peace Prize.
simple: Ludwik Lejzer Zamenhof (; , ; 15 December O.S. 3 December 1859 – 14 April O.S. 1 April 1917), credited as L. L. Zamenhof and sometimes as the pseudonymous Dr. Esperanto, was an eye doctor, linguist (who creates a language), and scholar who created the international language Esperanto. <s> Zamenhof was born in 1859 in the town of Białystok, Poland. <s> His parents spoke Russian and Yiddish at home. <s> His father was a German teacher, so Zamenhof learned that language from an early age and spoke the language fluently. <s> Later he learned French, Latin, Greek, Hebrew and English. <s> He also had an interest in Italian, Spanish and Lithuanian. <s> He attempted to create the international language with a grammar that was rich, and complex. <s> Zamenhof decided that the international language must have a simple grammar and be easier to learn than Volapük, an earlier international language. <s> His grandson, Louis-Christophe Zaleski-Zamenhof, has lived in France since the 1960s. <s> He was 14 times nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize between 1907 and 1917.

title: Elena Anaya
complex: Elena Anaya Gutiérrez (born 17 July 1975) is a Spanish actress whose career started in 1995. <s> She starred alongside Antonio Banderas in Pedro Almodóvar's "The Skin I Live In", for which she won the Goya award for Best Actress. <s> She is also known for her roles in "Van Helsing", "Habitación en Roma" "(Room in Rome)" and "Wonder Woman". <s> In November 2016, it was announced that Anaya was expecting her first child with her partner, Tina Afugu Cordero, a costume designer. <s> In February 2017, Anaya gave birth to their son.
simple: Elena Anaya Gutiérrez (born July 17, 1975) is a Spanish actress. <s> Her career dates back to 1995. <s> She starred alongside Antonio Banderas in Pedro Almodóvar's "The Skin I Live In", for which she won the Goya award for Best Actress. <s> She is also known for her roles in "Habitación en Roma" "(Room in Rome)" and "Wonder Woman" as Doctor Poison. <s> In November 2016, it was announced that Anaya was expecting her first child with her partner, Tina Afugu Cordero, a costume designer. <s> In February 2017, Anaya gave birth to their son.

title: Bucegi Mountains
complex: The Bucegi Mountains (Romanian: "Munții Bucegi" ] ; are located in central Romania, south of the city of Brașov. <s> They are part of the Southern Carpathians group of the Carpathian Mountains. <s> At 2505 m , "Omu" is its highest point. <s> To the east, the Bucegi Mountains have a very steep slope towards the popular tourist destination Prahova Valley (a.o. Bușteni and Sinaia). <s> At a higher elevation is the Bucegi Plateau, where wind and rain have turned the rocks into spectacular figures such as the Sphinx and "Babele". <s> The Bucegi is believed to be the Dacian holy mountain "Kogainon", on which the God Zalmoxis resided in a cave.
simple: The Bucegi Mountains are in central Romania to the south of the city Braşov. <s> They are part of the Southern Carpathians group of the Carpathian Mountains of Europe. <s> To the east, the Bucegi Mountains have a very steep slope. <s> This is towards the popular tourist destination Prahova Valley. <s> At a higher elevation is the Bucegi Plateau, where wind and rain have turned the rocks into brilliant figures such as the Sphinx and "Babele". <s> The Bucegi is thought to be the Dacian holy mountain "Kogainon".

title: Grant County, Nebraska
complex: Grant County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 614, making it the fourth-least populous county in Nebraska and the ninth-least populous county in the United States. <s> Its county seat is Hyannis. <s> The county was founded in 1887 and named for Ulysses S. Grant, 18th President of the United States.
simple: Grant County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 census, 614 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Hyannis. <s> It was founded in 1887 and named for Ulysses S. Grant, 18th President of the United States.

title: Paul Okalik
complex: Paul Okalik ( , ] ; born May 26, 1964) is a Canadian politician. <s> He is the first Inuk to have been called to the Nunavut Bar and the first Premier of Nunavut. <s> On November 4, 2010, he was elected Speaker of the Legislative Assembly of Nunavut. <s> Okalik represented the electoral district of Iqaluit West in the Legislative Assembly of Nunavut until April 6, 2011 when he announced he would be resigning in order to run for the Liberal Party of Canada in the riding of Nunavut in the 2011 Canadian federal election. <s> He returned to the Legislative Assembly in 2013 until being defeated in the 2017 general election.
simple: Paul Okalik (, ]; born May 26, 1964) is a Canadian politician. <s> He is the first Inuk member and first first Premier of Nunavut. <s> On November 4, 2010, he was elected Speaker of the Legislative Assembly of Nunavut. <s> Okalik represented the electoral district of Iqaluit West until April 6, 2011. <s> He returned to the Legislative Assembly in 2013 until being defeated in the 2017 general election.

title: Economy of Pakistan
complex: The economy of Pakistan is the 24th largest in the world in terms of purchasing power parity (PPP), and 39th largest in terms of nominal gross domestic product. <s> Pakistan has a population of over 207 million (the world's 6th-largest), giving it a nominal GDP per capita of $1,357 in 2019, which ranks 154th in the world and giving it a PPP GDP per capita of 5,839 in 2019, which ranks 132th in the world for 2019.
simple: It is the 25th largest economy in the world.

simple: Saint-Germain-Langot is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Murray Tyrrell
complex: Sir Murray Louis Tyrrell (1 December 1913 – 13 July 1994) was an Australian public servant, noted as the Official Secretary to the Governor-General of Australia for a record term of 26 years, 1947–73, in which time he served six governors-general. <s> Born in Kilmore, Victoria, Tyrrell was educated at Orbost and Mordialloc and Melbourne Boys' High Schools. <s> He married Ellen (Nell) St Clair Greig on 6 May 1939. <s> They had three children, two daughters born first, Leonie Ellen and Margot Evelyn, and then a son, Michael St Clair. <s> Tyrrell also served Sir William McKell's successors Sir William Slim, Lord Dunrossil, Lord De L'Isle, Lord Casey and Sir Paul Hasluck. <s> The Queen named him a Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (CVO), for his service rendered during the Royal Visit in 1954. <s> He was appointed a Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in 1959. <s> Both of these honours occurred during Sir William Slim's term. <s> Murray Tyrrell was appointed a Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (KCVO) in 1968, during Lord Casey's term. <s> This was awarded for personal service to the Queen, and was not on recommendation from the Prime Minister. <s> He had been attached to the Royal Household at Buckingham Palace from May to August 1962. <s> After his retirement in 1973, which occurred during Sir Paul Hasluck's term, he was succeeded by David Smith. <s> In 1977, he was named the Australian of the Year, jointly with Dame Raigh Roe. <s> Sir Murray lived at 11 Blundell Street, Queanbeyan, New South Wales, in an old heritage cottage still called "Sir Murray Tyrrell's Cottage". <s> He was an Alderman of the Queanbeyan City Council 1976–1980. <s> Tyrrell died on 13 July 1994 in Canberra, at the age of 80.
simple: Sir Murray Louis Tyrrell KCVO CBE (1 December 1913 – 13 July 1994) was an Australian public servant. <s> He was the Official Secretary to the Governor-General of Australia from 1947 to 1973. <s> In his record term of 26 years, served six governors-general. <s> Tyrrell was born in Kilmore, Victoria. <s> He married Ellen St Clair Greig on 6 May 1939. <s> The couple had three children. <s> In 1959, he was made a Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE). <s> In 1977, he was named Australian of the Year with Dame Raigh Roe. <s> He lived in Queanbeyan, New South Wales. <s> Tyrrell died on 13 July 1994 in Canberra of the Australian Capital Territory.

title: Oberallgäu
complex: Oberallgäu is a "Landkreis" (district) in Swabia, Bavaria, Germany. <s> It is bounded by (from the north and clockwise) the districts of Unterallgäu and Ostallgäu, the Austrian states Tyrol and Vorarlberg, the district of Lindau, and the state of Baden-Württemberg (district Ravensburg). <s> The city of Kempten is enclosed by but does not belong to the district.
simple: Oberallgäu is a rural district in Swabia in southwest Bavaria, Germany. <s> To the south of the district are the Austrian states Tyrol and Vorarlberg.

title: Fátima, Portugal
complex: Fátima (] ) is a city in the municipality of Ourém, Beira Litoral Province, in the Central Region and Médio Tejo intermunicipal community of Portugal, with 71.29 km2 of area and 11,788 inhabitants (2011). <s> Its population density is 162.7 hab/km2.
simple: Fátima is a city in Portugal.

title: Reflection (song)
complex: "Reflection" is a song written and produced by Matthew Wilder and David Zippel for the soundtrack of Disney's 1998 animated film "Mulan". <s> In the film, the song is performed by Tony Award winner, Filipina singer and actress Lea Salonga as Fa Mulan. <s> An accompanying music video for "Reflection" was included as a bonus to the "Disney Gold Classic Collection DVD" release of the film in 1998. <s> A single version of the song was recorded by American singer Christina Aguilera and became her debut single. <s> She was 17 at the time it was released. <s> The single's commercial success funded Aguilera's debut album from RCA, in addition to gaining her credibility amongst established writers and producers. <s> Releases of the single were limited, which resulted in the track charting only on the "Billboard" Adult Contemporary chart. <s> An accompanying music video for the song was included on the DVD release of "Mulan". <s> Aguilera has performed the track on four televised performances, including at the "CBS This Morning" show, which saw her gain the attention of songwriter Diane Warren. <s> A later, the remix by Eric Kupper was released. <s> Aguilera approached record label RCA, then having financial difficulties, and was told to contact Disney. <s> After being given the opportunity to record "Reflection", it was reported she had gained a record deal with RCA Records. <s> After she was asked to hit High E above Middle C required for "Reflection", she thought that the song could be the gateway into an album deal. <s> Aguilera spent hours recording a cover of Whitney Houston's "Run to You", which included the note she was asked to hit. <s> After successfully hitting the note, which she called "the note that changed my life", she was given the opportunity to record the song.
simple: "Reflection" is a song that is on the soundtrack of the 1998 animated movie, "Mulan". <s> It was performed in the movie by Lea Salonga. <s> It was the first single by American singer Christina Aguilera. <s> "Reflection" helped fund for Aguilera's debut album. <s> It also gained her popularity among songwriters and music producers. <s> Because the song was not released for commercial audiences, it only charted on the "Billboard" Adult Contemporary chart. <s> The music video was included on the DVD release of "Mulan". <s> Aguilera had performed the track on four televised performances. <s> This includes at the CBS "This Morning" show. <s> This caught the attention of songwriter Diane Warren. <s> Aguilera approached RCA Records. <s> Aguilera recorded herself singing Whitney Houston's song, "Run To You".

title: Jason Elam
complex: Jason Elam (born March 8, 1970) is a former American football placekicker. <s> He was drafted by the Denver Broncos in the third round of the 1993 NFL Draft and played 15 seasons with the Broncos and two with the Atlanta Falcons. <s> A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Elam won two Super Bowl rings with the Broncos and was tied with Tom Dempsey, Sebastian Janikowski and David Akers for the longest field goal in NFL history at 63 yards before it was broken by another Bronco, Matt Prater, on December 8, 2013, with a 64-yard field goal. <s> Elam was drafted by the Broncos in the third round (70th pick overall) of the 1993 NFL Draft.
simple: Jason Elam (born March 8, 1970) is a retired American football placekicker. <s> He was drafted by the Denver Broncos in the third round of the 1993 NFL Draft. <s> He was selected three-times for the Pro Bowl. <s> With the Broncos, Elam won two Super Bowls. <s> He is tied with Tom Dempsey, Sebastian Janikowski, and David Akers for the longest field goal in NFL history at 63 yards.

title: Steve Rowe
complex: Steve Rowe (born 19 January 1965) is the founder, bass guitarist, and vocalist of the Australian Christian death metal band Mortification which was considered to be a major pioneer in the genre. <s> Prior to forming Mortification he was in a traditional heavy metal styled Christian band known as LightForce.
simple: Steve Rowe (born January 1965 in Melbourne) is an Australian bassist. <s> He is the founder of the Christian extreme metal band Mortification.
