title: Muster drill
complex: A muster drill, sometimes referred to as a lifeboat drill or a boat drill, is an exercise that is conducted by the crew of a ship prior to embarking on a voyage. <s> A muster drill prepares passengers for safe evacuation, in the event of an emergency on board the ship, and familiarizes the crew and the passengers with escape routes. <s> In a muster drill, the use of life vests and the escape routes from the ship are explained to the passengers. <s> It is typically conducted approximately 30 minutes prior to the ship's scheduled departure time, and all guests must remain silent during the drill so that everyone will be able to hear the safety announcements from the captain. <s> To alert that the drill is in progress, a general emergency alarm is sounded, and the captain then explains what the passengers need to do. <s> Muster drills are typically not conducted and are usually not required for short trips on the water, such as those taken on ferries, dinner cruises, and riverboats. <s> On ferries, a safety briefing delivered through the PA system alerts passengers to the sound pattern of the emergency alarm and what to do if the signal is heard. <s> The "general emergency alarm" consists of seven or more short blasts followed by one long blast of the ship's horn or whistle (some lines don't sound the signal on the horn or whistle) and by the ship's internal alarm (such as fire alarm bells accompanied with flashing strobe lights in corridors and public areas for hearing impaired) and PA systems with a tone.
simple: A muster drill (sometimes called lifeboat drill) is a practice event which usually takes place on holiday cruise ships. <s> The purpose of a muster drill is to show passengers what to do if there was a real emergency. <s> Muster drills are not required on ferries, but safety announcements are made before the ferry departs. <s> The general emergency alarm is seven short blasts followed by one long blast of the ships horn/whistle and alarms that are built into the ship.

title: Tackle (football move)
complex: Most forms of football have a move known as a tackle. <s> The primary and important purposes of tackling are to dispossess an opponent of the ball, to stop the player from gaining ground towards goal or to stop them from carrying out what they intend. <s> In American football and Canadian football, to tackle is to physically interfere with the forward progress of a player in possession of the ball, such that his forward progress ceases and is not resumed, or such that he is caused to touch some part of his body to the ground other than his feet or hands, or such that he is forced to go out of bounds. <s> In any such case, the ball becomes dead, the down is over, and play ceases until the beginning of the next play. <s> Tackles that involve lunging at an opponent with both legs, regardless of whether the ball is won, are generally considered to constitute serious foul play and hence result in a sending-off. <s> This explicitly includes "scissoring" (tackling with legs apart, so as to trap the opponent's leg or legs in between), which is likely to be punished with a send-off (red card), as it poses a high risk of severe knee injury to the player being tackled. <s> Tackling with "studs up" is considered dangerous. <s> A "studs up tackle" is made when a player lunges into a tackle with a leg or both legs outstretched exposing the soles of their boots. <s> Referees are encouraged to at the very least caution (yellow card) players who commit such challenges.
simple: A tackle in football is a defensive move in various types of football. <s> It aims to stop an opponent who is running with the ball. <s> In American and Canadian football to tackle is to obstruct (physically interfere) the forward progress of a player in possession of the ball. <s> In any such case, the ball becomes dead, the down is over, and play ceases until the beginning of the next play. <s> However, from 2017, tackles from any direction that endanger an opponent's safety may result in the offender being sent-off. <s> This includes "scissoring" which is likely to be punished with a send-off (red card), as it poses a high risk of severe knee injury to the player being tackled. <s> A "studs up" tackle may be dangerous. <s> Referees may caution (yellow card) players who commit such challenges.

title: Elsenham
complex: Elsenham is a village and civil parish in north west Essex in southern England. <s> Its neighbouring towns include Bishop's Stortford, Saffron Walden, and Stansted Mountfitchet.
simple: Elsenham is a village and civil parish in Uttlesford, Essex, England.

title: Separatist movements of Pakistan
complex: Pakistan was established in 1947 as a state for Muslims. <s> The driving force behind the Pakistan Movement were the Muslims in the Muslim minority provinces of United Province and Bombay Presidency rather than the Muslims from the Muslim majority provinces. <s> Its formation was based on the basis of Islamic nationalism. <s> However, rampant corruption within the ranks of the government and bureaucracy, economic inequality between the country's two wings caused mainly by a lack of representative government and the government's indifference to the efforts of fierce ethno-nationalistic politicians like Mujeeb-ur-Rehman from East Pakistan, resulted in civil war in Pakistan and subsequent separation of East Pakistan as the new state of the People's Republic of Bangladesh.
simple: Pakistan was established in 1947 as a state for Muslims of colonial India. <s> The driving force behind the movement for Pakistan was the educated Muslim in the Muslim minority states of United Province and Bombay Presidency, those of the Muslim majority areas such as Punjab region, Sindh or Bengal, parts of which eventually formed Pakistan were less enthusiastic and joined the cause of Pakistan in the last years before independence and partition. <s> Its formation was based on the basis of Islamic nationalism. <s> However, due to rampant corruption within the ranks of the government and bureaucracy, economic inequality between the country's two wings caused mainly by a lack of representative government and the government's indifference to the efforts of fierce ethno-nationalistic politicians like Mujeeb-ur-Rehman, colonial East Bengal (Eastern Pakistan) Civil war of and Partition of Pakistan the Bhola cyclone and the 1970 elections were the major factors, resulting in the formation of a new linguistic state of the People's Republic of Bangladesh.

title: Nawshirwan Mustafa
complex: Nawshirwan Mustafa (22 December 1944 – 19 May 2017) was an Iraqi Kurdish politician who served as the General Coordinator of the Movement for Change and the leader of the opposition in the Kurdistan Region from 1 April 2009 to his death on 19 May 2017. <s> Nawshirwan Mustafa was born on 22 December 1944 in the old quarter of Sulaymaniyah, Iraq, the son of Mustafa Émin Khider. <s> Sulaymaniyah has been home to the Mustafa Émin Khider family since the city was established in 1784. <s> Unlike Kurdistan's other prominent political leaders Masoud Barzani and Jalal Talabani, Mustafa hails from a city, not a village, and is not a member of a tribe. <s> Mustafa died in his hometown of Sulaymaniyah in the early hours of the 19th May 2017 and was buried on 20 May 2017. <s> While it hasn't been confirmed, he is thought to have died of pneumonia.
simple: Nawshirwan Mustafa (22 December 1944 – 19 March 2017) was an Iraqi Kurdish politician. <s> He served as the General Coordinator (رێکخەری گشتی / rêkxerî giştî) of the Movement for Change from 2009 until his death in 2017. <s> He served as the leader of the official opposition in the Kurdistan Region. <s> He was born in Sulaymaniyah, Iraq. <s> Mistafa died in Sulaymaniyah due to lung cancer on 19 May 2017 at the age of 72.

title: John J. Farrell
complex: John J. Farrell (1872 - July 22, 1946) was the Dairy and Food Commissioner of Minnesota in 1917 and president of the National Creamery Buttermakers' Association. <s> By 1921 he was the secretary of National Dairy Products. <s> He was the unsuccessful Democratic candidate in the United States Senate elections of 1924 for senator from Minnesota. <s> He was the Minnesota Democratic state chair in 1931. <s> He was born in 1872 in Ohio to Daniel Farrell and Mary Guyton, both Irish immigrant parents. <s> They migrated to Minnesota in 1886. <s> He married in August 1901 Mabel Sanborn of Faribault, Minnesota, a daughter of W. N. Sanborn. <s> By 1917 he was the Dairy and Food Commissioner of Minnesota and president of the National Creamery Buttermakers' Association. <s> By 1921 he was the secretary of National Dairy Products Committee. <s> In 1924, he was the unsuccessful Democratic candidate for U.S. Senator from Minnesota. <s> He died on July 22, 1946 in South Harbor Township, Mille Lacs County, Minnesota.
simple: John J. Farrell (1872 - July 22, 1946) was the Dairy and Food Commissioner of Minnesota in 1917 and president of the National Creamery Buttermakers' Association. <s> By 1921 he was the secretary of National Dairy Products. <s> He was the unsuccessful Democratic candidate in the United States Senate elections of 1924 for senator from Minnesota. <s> He was the Minnesota Democratic state chair in 1931. <s> Farrell was born in 1872 in Ohio to Daniel Farrell and Mary Guyton, both Irish immigrant parents. <s> They migrated to Minnesota in 1886. <s> He married in August of 1901 Mabel Sanborn of Faribault, Minnesota, a daughter of W. N. Sanborn. <s> By 1917, Farrell was the Dairy and Food Commissioner of Minnesota and president of the National Creamery Buttermakers' Association. <s> By 1921 Farrell was the secretary of National Dairy Products Committee. <s> In 1924, he was the unsuccessful Democratic Candidate for U.S. Senator from Minnesota. <s> Farrell died on July 22, 1946 in South Harbor Township, Mille Lacs County, Minnesota.

title: Glenmore, Wisconsin
complex: Glenmore is a town in Brown County in the U.S. state of Wisconsin. <s> The population was 1,135 at the 2010 census. <s> The unincorporated communities of Glenmore and Shirley are located in the town. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 1,187 people, 375 households, and 322 families residing in the town. <s> The population density was 36.3 people per square mile (14.0/km2).
simple: Glenmore is a town in Brown County of the state of Wisconsin in the United States. <s> Shirley can be found in Glenmore. <s> 1,187 people were living in Glenmore as of 2000.

title: Naucalpan
complex: Naucalpan, officially Naucalpan de Juárez, is a city and municipality located just northwest of Mexico City in the adjoining State of Mexico. <s> The name Naucalpan comes from Nahuatl and means "place of the four neighborhoods" or "four houses." <s> Juárez was added to the official name in 1874 in honor of Benito Juárez.
simple: Naucalpan, officially Naucalpan de Juárez, is a city and municipality in the Mexican state of Mexico. <s> It is just northwest of Mexico City. <s> The name Naucalpan comes from Nahuatl language. <s> It means “place of the four neighborhoods or four houses".

title: Face (professional wrestling)
complex: In professional wrestling, a face (babyface) is a heroic or a "good guy" wrestler, booked (scripted) by the promotion with the aim of being cheered by fans. <s> Traditionally, they wrestle within the rules and avoid cheating (in contrast to the villains who use illegal moves and call in additional wrestlers to do their work for them) while behaving positively towards the referee and the audience.
simple: In professional wrestling, a face is a good guy.

title: Dušan Petković (footballer, born 1974)
complex: Dušan Petković (Serbian Cyrillic: Душан Петковић; born 13 June 1974) is a Serbian former professional footballer who played as a defender. <s> He is the son of Ilija Petković.
simple: Dušan Petković (born 13 June 1974) is a former Serbian football player.

title: The Rescuers Down Under
complex: The Rescuers Down Under is a 1990 American animated adventure film produced by Walt Disney Feature Animation and released by Walt Disney Pictures on November 16, 1990. <s> The 29th Disney animated feature film, the film is the sequel to the 1977 animated film "The Rescuers", which was based on the novels of Margery Sharp. <s> Set in the Australian Outback, the film centers on Bernard and Bianca traveling to Australia to save a boy named Cody from a villainous poacher in pursuit of an endangered bird of prey. <s> "The Rescuers Down Under" features three characters from the first film; Bernard, Bianca and the Chairmouse, all of whom feature the same actors reprising their roles from the original 1977 film. <s> "The Rescuers Down Under" was released in the Walt Disney Classics video series on September 20, 1991, in a pan-and-scan transfer, while "The Rescuers" was released on VHS a year later in September 1992. <s> Unlike the original film, however, "The Rescuers Down Under" was not included in the Walt Disney Masterpiece Collection. <s> Both home video editions went into moratorium on April 30, 1993. <s> Launching in January 2000, Walt Disney Home Video began the Gold Classic Collection, with "The Rescuers Down Under" re-issued on VHS and DVD on August 1, 2000. <s> The DVD contained the film in its 1.66:1 aspect ratio enhanced for television sets and 4.0 surround sound, and was accompanied with special features including a storybook and trivia as well as an "Animals of the Outback" activity booklet. <s> "The Rescuers Down Under" was released alongside "The Rescuers" on Blu-ray in a "2-Movie Collection" on August 21, 2012 to commemorate the first film's 35th anniversary in the United States.
simple: The Rescuers Down Under is a 29th movie and an 1990 American animated adventure movie produced by Walt Disney Feature Animation. <s> It was released by Walt Disney Pictures and Buena Vista Distribution on November 16, 1990. <s> The movie is the sequel to the 1978 movie "The Rescuers", which was based on the novels of Margery Sharp. <s> "The Rescuers Down Under" has three characters from the first movie: Bernard, Bianca, and the Chairmouse. <s> All of them are played by the same actors as in the first movie. <s> "The Rescuers Down Under" was released in the Walt Disney Classics video series on September 20, 1991 with a home video trailer for "The Jungle Book", while "The Rescuers" was released on VHS a year later in September 1992. <s> However, unlike "The Rescuers", "The Rescuers Down Under" did not make it to the "Walt Disney Masterpiece Collection". <s> It was re-released on VHS and DVD on August 1, 2000 as part of the Walt Disney Gold Classic Collection. <s> "The Rescuers Down Under" was released alongside "The Rescuers" on Blu-ray in a "2-Movie Collection" on August 21, 2012 to commemorate the first movie's 35th anniversary.

title: Turriff
complex: Buckley’s in Turriff has been closed since August 25 2019 due to heath and safety issues Turriff is a town and civil parish in Aberdeenshire in Scotland. <s> It lies on the River Deveron, about 166 ft above sea level, and has a population of 5,708. <s> In everyday speech it is often referred to by its Scots name, Turra, which is derived from the Scottish Gaelic pronunciation. <s> The Knights Templar appear to have had a base in the area, and a nearby site is still known as "Temple Brae". <s> Turriff was notable as the scene of the very first engagements of the Wars of the Three Kingdoms (1639–51). <s> Early in 1639, the Marquis of Huntly assembled his forces here, and thereafter went to Kintore in lower Aberdeenshire, eventually marching from there to Aberdeen itself. <s> The Marquis — being informed shortly after his arrival in Aberdeen that a meeting of Covenanters was to be held in Turriff on the fourteenth of February — resolved to disperse them, by occupying the town with 2000 men. <s> The incident was known as the "Raid of Turriff" and was followed a few days later by a minor engagement known as the "Trot of Turriff".
simple: Turriff is a town and parish in Aberdeenshire, Scotland. <s> It is approximately 166 feet above sea level. <s> It is known locally as Turra in the Doric dialect of Scots. <s> The Knights Templar appear to have had a base in the area, and a nearby site is still known as "Temple Brae". <s> Early in 1639, the Marquis of Huntly assembled his forces here, and thereafter went to Kintore in lower Aberdeenshire, eventually marching from there to Aberdeen itself. <s> The Marquis — being informed shortly after his arrival in Aberdeen that a meeting of Covenanters was to be held in Turriff on the fourteenth of February — resolved to disperse them, by occupying the town with 2000 men. <s> The incident was known as the "First raid of Turray".

title: Pavel Nedvěd
complex: Pavel Nedvěd (] ; born 30 August 1972) is a Czech retired footballer who played as a midfielder. <s> Described as one of the best footballers of his generation, he is also regarded as one of the most successful players to emerge from the Czech Republic, winning domestic and European accolades with Italian clubs Lazio, including the last Cup Winners' Cup, and Juventus, whom he led to the 2003 UEFA Champions League Final.
simple: Pavel Nedvěd (born 30 August 1972) is a former Czech football player.

title: Amy Klobuchar
complex: Amy Jean Klobuchar ( ; born May 25, 1960) is an American lawyer and politician serving as the senior United States Senator from Minnesota. <s> A member of the Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party, Minnesota's affiliate of the Democratic Party, she previously served as the Hennepin County Attorney. <s> Born in Plymouth, Minnesota, Klobuchar is a graduate of Yale University and the University of Chicago Law School. <s> She was a partner at two Minneapolis law firms before being elected county attorney for Hennepin County in 1998, making her responsible for all criminal prosecution in Minnesota's most populous county. <s> Klobuchar was first elected to the Senate in 2006, becoming Minnesota's first elected female United States Senator, and reelected in 2012 and 2018. <s> In 2009 and 2010 she was described as a "rising star" in the Democratic Party. <s> She is running for the Democratic nomination for President of the United States in the 2020 election. <s> Born in Plymouth, Minnesota, Klobuchar is the daughter of Rose (née Heuberger), who retired at age 70 from teaching second grade, and Jim Klobuchar, an author and a retired sportswriter and columnist for the "Star Tribune". <s> Klobuchar has one younger sister, Beth. <s> Her father is of Slovene descent; his grandparents were immigrants from Slovenia's White Carniola region, and his father was a miner on the Iron Range; Klobuchar's maternal grandparents were from Switzerland. <s> Her parents divorced when Klobuchar was 15 years old and in high school. <s> The divorce took a serious toll on the family and Amy's relationship with her father was not fully restored until he quit drinking in the 1990s. <s> Klobuchar attended public schools in Plymouth and was valedictorian at Wayzata High School. <s> She received her B.A. degree "magna cum laude" in political science in 1982 from Yale University During her time at Yale, Klobuchar spent time as an intern for then Vice President, and former Minnesota Senator, Walter Mondale. <s> Her senior thesis was "Uncovering the Dome", a 250-page history of the ten years of politics surrounding the building of the Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome in Minneapolis. <s> After Yale, Klobuchar enrolled at the University of Chicago Law School, where she served as an associate editor of the "University of Chicago Law Review" and received her Juris Doctor degree in 1985. <s> Klobuchar was elected Hennepin County attorney in 1998, and reelected in 2002 with no opposition. <s> "Minnesota Lawyer" named her "Attorney of the Year". <s> Klobuchar was President of the Minnesota County Attorneys Association from November 2002 to November 2003. <s> In early 2005 U.S. Senator Mark Dayton announced that he would not seek reelection, and Klobuchar was recognized early as a favorite for the DFL nomination for the 2006 election. <s> EMILY's List endorsed her on September 29, 2005, and Klobuchar won the DFL endorsement on June 9, 2006. <s> She gained the support of the majority of DFL state legislators in Minnesota during the primaries. <s> A poll of DFL state delegates showed Klobuchar beating her then closest opponent, Patty Wetterling, 66% to 15%. <s> In January Wetterling dropped out of the race and endorsed Klobuchar. <s> Former Senate candidate and prominent lawyer Mike Ciresi, who was widely seen as a serious potential DFL candidate, indicated in early February that he would not enter the race; that was viewed as an important boost for Klobuchar. <s> In the general election Klobuchar faced Republican candidate Mark Kennedy, Independence Party candidate Robert Fitzgerald, Constitution candidate Ben Powers, and Green Party candidate Michael Cavlan. <s> Klobuchar led in the polls throughout the campaign, and won with 58% of the vote to Kennedy's 38% and Fitzgerald's 3%, carrying all but eight of Minnesota's 87 counties. <s> She is the first woman to be elected U.S. Senator from Minnesota. <s> (Muriel Humphrey, the state's first female senator and former Second Lady of the United States, was appointed to fill her husband's unexpired term and not elected.) <s> Klobuchar faced State Representative Kurt Bills and won a second term in the U.S. Senate with 65.2% of the vote to Bills's 30.6%, carrying all but two counties. <s> At the end of the 114th Congress in late 2016, Klobuchar had passed more legislation than any other senator. <s> In February 2017 she called for an independent, bipartisan commission to investigate ties between Russia and President Donald Trump and his administration. <s> Concern about Trump's ties to Russia increased after reports that his campaign officials had repeated contact with senior Russian intelligence officials before the 2016 United States elections. <s> Klobuchar had already signaled her interest in U.S.–Russia relations in December 2016 when she joined Republican senators John McCain and Lindsey Graham on a trip to the Baltic states and Ukraine. <s> She maintained high approval ratings throughout 2017, with an April 2017 "Star Tribune" poll placing her approval rating at 72%. <s> In October 2017 Morning Consult listed Klobuchar among the 10 senators with the highest approval ratings, and a November 2017 KSTP-TV poll put her approval rating at 56%. <s> An April 2019 Morning Consult poll found Klobuchar to be the third-most popular sitting senator, with a 58% approval rating and 26% disapproval rating, behind only Vermont Senators Bernie Sanders and Patrick Leahy. <s> On March 30, 2008, Klobuchar announced her endorsement of Senator Barack Obama in the Democratic presidential primary, promising her superdelegate vote to him. <s> She cited Obama's performance in the Minnesota caucuses, where he won with 66% of the popular vote, as well as her own "independent judgment". <s> In 2016 she was an early supporter of Hillary Clinton's second campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination. <s> In 2017 Klobuchar and Bernie Sanders represented the Democratic Party in a televised debate on healthcare policy and the possible repeal of the Affordable Healthcare Act on CNN. <s> On February 10, 2019, Klobuchar announced her candidacy in the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries. <s> She has said that she uses humor as one way to distinguish herself among the many other Democratic candidates in the 2020 campaign. <s> In 1993 Klobuchar married John Bessler, a private practice attorney and a professor at the University of Baltimore School of Law. <s> They have a daughter, Abigail. <s> Klobuchar is a member of the United Church of Christ. <s> Klobuchar has received numerous awards during her career.
simple: Amy Jean Klobuchar (born May 25, 1960) is an American politician and lawyer. <s> She is the senior United States Senator from Minnesota since 2007. <s> She was a lawyer in Minneapolis until being elected county attorney for Hennepin County in 1998, making her responsible for all criminal prosecution in Minnesota's most populous county. <s> Klobuchar was first elected to the Senate in 2006, becoming Minnesota's first elected female United States Senator, and was reelected in 2012 and 2018. <s> In 2009 and 2010, she was called a "rising star" in the Democratic Party. <s> Many believe that she will run for President of the United States in 2020. <s> Klobuchar was born in Plymouth, Minnesota. <s> She is the daughter of Rose Katherine (née Heuberger) and James John "Jim" Klobuchar, a columnist for the "Star Tribune". <s> Klobuchar was a valedictorian at Wayzata High School. <s> She received her B.A. degree in political science in 1982 from Yale University. <s> During her time at Yale, Klobuchar spent time as an intern for Senator Walter Mondale. <s> Klobuchar was elected Hennepin County attorney in 1998, and reelected in 2002. <s> In 2001 "Minnesota Lawyer" named her "Attorney of the Year". <s> Klobuchar was President of the Minnesota County Attorneys Association from November 2002 to November 2003. <s> In early 2005, Senator Mark Dayton announced that he would not seek re-election to the U.S. Senate. <s> In the general election, Klobuchar faced Republican candidate Mark Kennedy. <s> She is the first elected female senator from Minnesota and the second female senator in the state after Muriel Humphrey Brown. <s> Klobuchar faced State Representative Kurt Bills and won a second term in the U.S. Senate in 2012. <s> In late 2016, Klobuchar was known to have passed more legislation than any other senator. <s> In February 2017, she called for an independent, bipartisan commission like the 9/11 Commission to investigate ties between Russia and U.S. President Donald Trump and his administration. <s> She maintained high approval ratings throughout 2017, with the "Star Tribune"'s Minnesota Poll announcing in April 2017 that her approval rating was 72%. <s> In October 2017, Morning Consult listed Klobuchar in the Top 10 of their list of senators with the highest approval rating. <s> On March 30, 2008, Klobuchar announced her endorsement of Senator Barack Obama in the Democratic presidential primary, promising her unpledged superdelegate vote for him. <s> In 2017, Klobuchar and Bernie Sanders represented the Democratic Party in a televised debate on healthcare policy and the possible repeal of the Affordable Healthcare Act on CNN. <s> On February 6, 2019, Klobuchar announced on her Twitter that she will announce her candidacy for President of the United States on February 10 in Minneapolis. <s> On February 10, 2019, Klobuchar announced that she is running for President in the 2020 United States presidential election. <s> In 1993, Klobuchar married John Bessler. <s> They have a daughter. <s> She is a member of the United Church of Christ.

title: Shōtōkai
complex: Shotokai (松濤會 , Shōtōkai ) is the organisation formed originally in 1930 by master Gichin Funakoshi to teach and spread the art of karate-Do. <s> The organization still exists and promotes a style of karate that adheres to Funakoshi's teachings, in particular the notion that competition is contrary to the essence of karate.
simple: Shotokai (松濤會, Shōtōkai) is a martial arts organisation established to teach and spread the art of karate.

title: Pinckney's Treaty
complex: Pinckney's Treaty, also commonly known as the Treaty of San Lorenzo or the Treaty of Madrid, was signed in San Lorenzo de El Escorial on October 27, 1795 and established intentions of friendship between the United States and Spain. <s> It also defined the border between the United States and Spanish Florida, and guaranteed the United States navigation rights on the Mississippi River. <s> With this agreement, the first phase of the ongoing border dispute between the two nations in this region, commonly called the West Florida Controversy, came to a close. <s> The treaty's full title is Treaty of Friendship, Limits, and Navigation Between Spain and the United States. <s> Thomas Pinckney negotiated the treaty for the United States and Don Manuel de Godoy represented Spain. <s> It was presented to the United States Senate on February 26, 1796, and, after debate, was ratified on March 7, 1796. <s> It was ratified by Spain on April 25, 1796 and ratifications were exchanged on that date. <s> The treaty was proclaimed on August 3, 1796.
simple: Pinckney's Treaty is a treaty between Spain and the United States. <s> It is also known as Treaty of San Lorenzo or Treaty of Madrid. <s> It defined the boundaries of the United States with the Spanish colonies and guaranteed the United States navigation rights on the Mississippi River. <s> Among other things, it ended the first phase of the West Florida Controversy, a dispute between the two nations over the boundaries of the Spanish colony of West Florida. <s> The treaty's full title is Treaty of Friendship, Limits, and Navigation Between Spain and the United States. <s> Thomas Pinckney negotiated the treaty for the United States and Don Manuel de Godoy represented Spain. <s> The treaty was presented to the United States Senate on February 26, 1796 and after several weeks of debate was ratified on March 7, 1796. <s> It was ratified by Spain on April 25, 1796 and ratifications were exchanged on that date. <s> The treaty was proclaimed on August 3, 1796.

title: Château d'Usson
complex: The Château d'Usson is one of the so-called Cathar castles in what is now southwestern France. <s> It is located in the "commune" of Rouze, in the Ariège "département". <s> It is sited upstream from Axat, along the Aude River gorge, carved out of the foothills of the Pyrenees.
simple: The Château d'Usson is one of the Cathar castles in southwestern France. <s> It is in the "commune" of Rouze, in the Ariège "département".

title: Mid-Sea Road
complex: The Mid-Sea Road (海中道路 , Kaichū Dōro ) is a road in Uruma, Okinawa, Japan. <s> 4.7 km long, it forms part of Okinawa Prefectural Road No. 10 and runs across the sea.
simple: Mid-Sea Road is a road in Uruma, Okinawa in Japan.

title: Xinyang
complex: Xinyang (; postal: Sinyang) is a prefecture-level city in southeastern Henan province, People's Republic of China, the southernmost administrative division in the province. <s> Its population was 6,109,106 according to the 2010 census, and 1,230,042 of them lived in 2 urban districts, Pingqiao and Shihe. <s> The prefecture-level city of Xinyang has a total land area of 18819 km2 . <s> The city is located in the southernmost part of Henan Province, on the south bank of the Huai River. <s> It borders the cities Zhumadian to the north and Nanyang to the northwest, and the provinces of Anhui and Hubei to the east and south respectively. <s> The region where Xinyang is located is considered a subtropical area and the Dabie Mountains cover most of its territory. <s> The Xinyang City is divided into two districts and eight counties. <s> According to the 2010 Census, the population of Xinyang is of 6,109,106 inhabitants, 6.39% less than the population marked on the last census of 2000, when there were 6,527,368 inhabitants in the city.
simple: Xinyang (信阳) is a prefecture-level city in southern Henan in the People's Republic of China. <s> In 2010, 6,109,106 people lived there. <s> The city is located on the south bank of the Huai River. <s> Xinyang is divided into two districts and eight counties.

title: Catarrh
complex: Catarrh is inflammation of the mucous membranes in one of the airways or cavities of the body, usually with reference to the throat and paranasal sinuses. <s> It can result in a thick exudate of mucus and white blood cells caused by the swelling of the mucous membranes in the head in response to an infection. <s> It is a symptom usually associated with the common cold, pharyngitis, and chesty coughs, but it can also be found in patients with adenoiditis, otitis media, sinusitis or tonsillitis. <s> The phlegm produced by catarrh may either discharge or cause a blockage that may become chronic.
simple: Catarrh is a thick fluid of mucus and white blood cells caused by the swelling of the mucous membranes in the head because of an infection. <s> It is a symptom usually from the common cold and coughs, but can also be found in people with infections of the adenoids, middle ear, sinus or tonsils.

title: Cornish Assembly
complex: A Cornish Assembly is a proposed devolved law-making assembly for Cornwall along the lines of the Scottish Parliament, the National Assembly for Wales and the Northern Ireland Assembly in the United Kingdom.
simple: A Cornish Assembly is a law making parliament that some Cornish people and politicians argue should exist as part of a devolution agreement with the United Kingdom.

title: Division of Warringah
complex: The Division of Warringah is an Australian electoral division in the state of New South Wales. <s> The division is named after the Warringah area of Sydney, which itself is named by an Aboriginal Australian word which translates into English as "rain", "waves" or "sea". <s> The Division was proclaimed at the redistribution of 13 September 1922, and was first contested at the 1922 federal election. <s> Centred on Mosman and the Northern Beaches region of Sydney, it covers most of the land between Middle Harbour and the Tasman Sea. <s> It extends from Port Jackson in the south to the suburb of Dee Why in the north. <s> It includes the suburbs of Allambie, Allambie Heights, Balgowlah, Balgowlah Heights, Balmoral, Beauty Point, Brookvale, Clifton Gardens, Clontarf, Cremorne Point, Curl Curl, Fairlight, Freshwater, Killarney Heights, Kurraba Point, Manly, Manly Vale, Mosman, North Balgowlah, North Curl Curl, North Head, North Manly, Queenscliff, Seaforth, and Wingala; as well as parts of Beacon Hill, Cremorne, Dee Why, Forestville, Frenchs Forest, Narraweena, and Neutral Bay.
simple: The Division of Warringah is a Federal Electoral Division for the Australian House of Representatives in the state of New South Wales. <s> The Division was named after the Warringah area of Sydney. <s> This is an Aboriginal Australian word which means "rain", "waves" or "sea". <s> The Division was created on 13 September 1922, for the 1922 Federal election. <s> It is located in the Northern Beaches region of Sydney. <s> It covers most of the land between Middle Harbour and the Pacific Ocean. <s> It extends from Port Jackson in the south to the suburb of Dee Why in the north. <s> It includes the suburbs of Mosman, Balgowlah, Manly, Brookvale, Beacon Hill and Forestville.

title: Reprise Records
complex: Reprise Records is an American record label founded in 1960 by Frank Sinatra. <s> It is owned by Warner Music Group, and operates through Warner Records, one of its flagship labels. <s> Reprise Records was formed in 1960 by Frank Sinatra in order to allow more artistic freedom for his own recordings. <s> Soon thereafter, he garnered the nickname "The Chairman of the Board".
simple: Reprise Records is an American record label, founded in 1960 by Frank Sinatra, which is owned by Warner Music Group, and operated through Warner Bros. <s> Reprise was formed in 1960 by Frank Sinatra in order to allow more artistic freedom for his own recordings.

title: Montalchez
complex: Montalchez is a former municipality in the district of Boudry in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2018 the former municipalities of Bevaix, Saint-Aubin-Sauges, Gorgier, Vaumarcus, Montalchez and Fresens merged into the new municipality of La Grande-Béroche.
simple: Montalchez is a former municipality in the district of Boudry in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2018 the former municipalities of Bevaix, Saint-Aubin-Sauges, Gorgier, Vaumarcus, Montalchez and Fresens merged into the new municipality of La Grande-Béroche.

title: Mersch (canton)
complex: Mersch is a canton in the centre of Luxembourg. <s> It is the only canton, other than Luxembourg, to be entirely surrounded by other cantons, and therefore not to have an international boundary. <s> The capital is Mersch.
simple: Mersch is a canton in the centre of Luxembourg. <s> It is the only canton, other than Luxembourg, to be entirely surrounded by other cantons, and therefore not to have an international boundary. <s> Its capital is Mersch.

title: Patsy Reddy
complex: Dame Patricia Lee Reddy (born 17 May 1954) is a New Zealand lawyer and businesswoman serving as the 21st and current Governor-General of New Zealand, in office since 2016. <s> She is the third woman to be appointed to the position, after Dame Catherine Tizard and Dame Silvia Cartwright.
simple: Dame Patricia Lee Reddy (born 17 May 1954) is a New Zealand lawyer and businesswoman. <s> She is the 21st and current Governor-General of New Zealand since 2016.

title: Pseudomonas
complex: Pseudomonas is a genus of Gram-negative, Gammaproteobacteria, belonging to the family Pseudomonadaceae and containing 191 validly described species. <s> The members of the genus demonstrate a great deal of metabolic diversity and consequently are able to colonize a wide range of niches.
simple: Pseudomonas is a genus of gammaproteobacteria.

title: Crossgates Commons
complex: Crossgates Commons is a large shopping plaza in Albany, New York. <s> It is owned by The Pyramid Company.
simple: Crossgates Commons is a plaza in Albany, New York near Crossgates Mall.

title: Ghats (mountains)
complex: Ghats refer to two converging mountain ranges in south-eastern India, called the Eastern Ghats and Western Ghats, running along the eastern and western seaboards of the country.
simple: The Ghats are two mountain ranges at the eastern and western edges of the Deccan Plateau in southern India.

title: North Medwyn River
complex: North Medwyn is a river in the Lanarkshire region of Scotland. <s> Along with the confluence of the South Medwyn River it forms the Medwyn water basin. <s> The North Medwyn is a tributary of the River Clyde.
simple: North Medwyn is a river in the Lanarkshire area of Scotland. <s> The North Medwyn is a tributary of the River Clyde.

title: Mariem Hassan
complex: Mariem Hassan ( ‎; May 1958 – 22 August 2015) was a Sahrawi singer and lyricist from Western Sahara. <s> She usually sang in Hassaniyya, an Arabic dialect spoken mostly in Western Sahara and Mauritania, and occasionally in Spanish. <s> Her use of the Spanish language was related to the former status of Western Sahara as a Spanish colony. <s> Hassan died of bone cancer in the Sahrawi refugee camps of Tindouf province, Algeria on 22 August 2015.
simple: Mariem Hassan (‎; 1958 – 22 August 2015), was a Sahrawi singer and lyricist from Western Sahara. <s> She usually sang in Hassaniyya, an Arabic dialect spoken mostly in Western Sahara and Mauritania. <s> Hassan died of bone cancer in a Sahrawi refugee camp in Tindouf, Algeria on 22 August 2015.

title: Breakfast television
complex: Breakfast television (Australia, Ireland, New Zealand and United Kingdom) or morning show (Canada and United States) is a type of infotainment television program, which broadcasts live in the morning (typically scheduled between 6 and 10am, or if it is a local programme, as early as 4am). <s> Often hosted by a small team of hosts, these types of programs are typically targeted at the combined demographic of people getting ready for work and school, and stay-at-home adults and parents. <s> The three breakfast morning shows in the United States ("CBS This Morning", "Today", amd "Good Morning America") air live only in the Eastern Time Zone. <s> (Spanish language shows air live in the Eastern, Central, & Mountain time zones) Stations in the remaining time zones receive these programs on a tape delay (with an updated feed broadcast to viewers in the Pacific Time Zone).
simple: Breakfast television in Australia, Ireland, New Zealand, and United Kingdom or a morning show in Canada and the United States, is a television block after the overnight graveyard slot and before daytime television. <s> Shows include "CBS This Morning" on CBS, "Good Morning America" on ABC, "Today" on NBC, "AMHQ" on The Weather Channel, "BBC Breakfast" on BBC, and "Today" on Nine Network.

title: Jay Roach
complex: Mathew Jay Roach (born June 14, 1957) is an American film director, producer, and screenwriter, best known for directing the "Austin Powers" films and "Meet the Parents". <s> He also directed the comedy film "Dinner for Schmucks" (2010), the HBO political dramas "Recount" (2008), "Game Change" (2012) and "All the Way" (2016), and the political comedy "The Campaign" (2012). <s> His twelfth film, the biographical drama "Trumbo", was released on November 6, 2015. <s> He produced these films under his Everyman Pictures banner.
simple: Matthew Jay Roach (born June 14, 1957) is an American movie director, producer and screenwriter. <s> He is best known for directing the "Austin Powers" movies and "Meet the Parents". <s> He also directed the comedy movie "Dinner for Schmucks" (2010), the HBO political dramas "Recount" (2008) and "Game Change" (2012), and the political comedy "The Campaign" (2012). <s> His twelfth movie, the biographical drama "Trumbo", was released on November 6, 2015 to positive reviews.

title: Alfredo Cristiani
complex: Alfredo Félix Cristiani Burkard, popularly known as Alfredo Cristiani (born November 22, 1947) was President of El Salvador from 1989 to 1994. <s> Born into a wealthy family in San Salvador, his father Felix Cristiani was an Italian immigrant from Bagnaria, Italy and his mother Margoth Burkard de Cristiani was Salvadoran of Swiss descent. <s> He was educated at the 'Escuela Americana' (American School) in San Salvador and Georgetown University in Washington, D.C., where he graduated with a degree in Business Administration.
simple: Alfredo Félix Cristiani Burkard, popularly known as Alfredo Cristiani (born November 22, 1947) is a Peruvian politician. <s> He was the President of El Salvador from 1989 to 1994. <s> Cristiani was born in San Salvador.

title: Butch Hartman
complex: Elmer Earl "Butch" Hartman IV (born January 10, 1965) is an American animator, YouTuber, illustrator, and voice actor, best known for creating the Nicktoons "The Fairly OddParents", "Danny Phantom", "T.U.F.F. Puppy", and "Bunsen Is a Beast". <s> Hartman also owns a production company, Billionfold Inc., which he uses primarily to produce his shows. <s> Hartman was an executive producer on "The Fairly OddParents" for the entirety of its 16-year run. <s> Hartman was born in Highland Park, Michigan. <s> He received the nickname Butch as a young boy and continued to use the name professionally as an adult. <s> Hartman spent his childhood in Roseville, Michigan and his teenage years in New Baltimore, Michigan. <s> He graduated from Anchor Bay High School in New Baltimore in 1983. <s> and subsequently attended the California Institute of the Arts in Valencia, California. <s> While still attending CalArts, Hartman interned as an in-between animator on the Don Bluth film "An American Tail". <s> Shortly after graduating, he was hired as a character designer and storyboard artist for an unidentified "My Little Pony" animated series. <s> As he had no previous experience with storyboards, he was soon fired. <s> Afterwards, he found work with Ruby-Spears, where he worked on "It's Punky Brewster" and "Dink, the Little Dinosaur". <s> He was also a member of the video reference crew for the Disney film "Pocahontas". <s> In the early 1990s he was hired as an artist in the model department at Hanna-Barbera, and was eventually contacted by studio president Fred Seibert to make the shorts "Pfish and Chip" and "Gramps" for the "What a Cartoon! <s> Eventually, he became a writer, director and storyboard artist for several of the early Cartoon Network shows, including "Dexter's Laboratory", "Johnny Bravo", "Cow and Chicken" and "I Am Weasel". <s> After his contract with Hanna-Barbera expired, he went to work with Seibert on the "Oh Yeah! <s> Cartoons" show for Nickelodeon. <s> During his time working at Hanna-Barbera, he became friends with future "Family Guy" creator Seth MacFarlane. <s> The two would later go on to make the short "Zoomates" together for Oh Yeah! <s> The character Dr. Elmer Hartman in "Family Guy" was named after Hartman. <s> He also voiced various characters in the show's first few seasons. <s> His biggest success came in December 1997, when he created "The Fairly OddParents". <s> The series originally started out as a series of shorts on the anthology show, "Oh Yeah! <s> Eventually, Nickelodeon decided to pick the shorts up as a full series. <s> Premiering in 2001, the adapted series ended up becoming a huge hit, second only in the ratings to "SpongeBob SquarePants" (and it briefly even passed "SpongeBob"' s ratings). <s> Following the third "" crossover "The Jimmy-Timmy Power Hour 3: The Jerkinators", the series ceased production in 2006, but it was announced on Hartman's forum on February 2, 2007 that 20 more episodes would be produced; the 6th season of "Fairly OddParents" aired on February 18, 2008, starting with the 1-hour special "Fairly OddBaby". <s> From May 1, 2009 to May 3, 2009, the 3-part special "Wishology" aired; although that too was originally intended as a series finale, the series was renewed for another season. <s> A tenth season was eventually ordered in 2015. <s> "The Fairly OddParents" is Nickelodeon's second longest-running animated show behind "SpongeBob". <s> Due to the success of "The Fairly OddParents", Hartman was asked to create another show for Nickelodeon; Hartman says the President of Nickelodeon asked him if he had an idea, and before he could say the title he was given the greenlight. <s> The show would later become "Danny Phantom". <s> To produce the show, in 2004, Hartman founded Billionfold Inc., which he also used, and still uses today, to produce his other projects. <s> "Danny Phantom" received critical acclaim and is considered Hartman's best show, with Hartman himself acknowledging it as perhaps the best of his programs. <s> "Danny Phantom" ended production in early 2007. <s> Around 2008–2009, Hartman began production his third show for Nickelodeon, "T.U.F.F. Puppy", which premiered in 2010 alongside the "Jimmy Neutron" spin-off "Planet Sheen". <s> The series received mixed to positive reviews and ran for 3 seasons before being cancelled. <s> After Hartman announced that he was leaving Nickelodeon, he said in the same video that he was working new projects to be released in the future. <s> He announced that he is working on a show called "Elf Detective" for his YouTube channel as well as multiple projects with PocketWatch, Inc. <s> On June 18, 2018, he launched a Kickstarter campaign for his own streaming service for family-focused entertainment called OAXIS. <s> It reached its goal of $250,000 on July 18, 2018. <s> His other TV work includes voicing various characters on the animated series "Family Guy" and playing the character Sean Masters on the short-lived series "Generations" in 1991. <s> He also appeared on the NBC soap opera "Days of Our Lives" during the late 1980s. <s> In 2012, it was announced that Hartman was set to serve as the director on the film adaptation of "ALF" for Sony Pictures Animation. <s> Hartman currently lives in Bell Canyon, California, with his wife, Julieann, and daughters, Carly and Sophia Hartman.
simple: Elmer Earl "Butch" Hartman IV (Born January 10, 1965, Highland Park, Michigan) is an American animator, creator of "The Fairly OddParents" and "Danny Phantom". <s> Hartman was born in Highland Park, Michigan to Elmer Earl Hartman III and Carol Davis. <s> He received the nickname "Butch" as a youth and continues to use the name professionally as an adult. <s> Hartman spent his childhood in Roseville, Michigan and his teen years in New Baltimore, Michigan. <s> He graduated from Anchor Bay High School in New Baltimore in 1983. <s> He subsequently attended the California Institute of the Arts in Valencia, California. <s> While still attending the California Institute of the Arts, Hartman received the chance to intern as an in-between animator on the Don Bluth film, "An American Tail". <s> Shortly after graduating for the California Institute of the Arts Hartman was hired as a character designer for the animated series "My Little Pony". <s> Instead, they had him working on storyboards (which he had not done before) and as quickly as he was hired, he was fired. <s> He was also a video reference crew for the Disney movie Pocahontas.Later,he became a writer,television director and storyboard artist for several Hanna-Barbera shows, including "Dexter's Laboratory", "Cow and Chicken", and "Johnny Bravo". <s> After his contract with Hanna-Barbera finished up he went to work with former co-worker Fred Seibert on "Oh,Yeah!Cartoons". <s> MacFarlane also has a character on Family Guy named after Hartman named Dr. Hartman. <s> His biggest success came in 1997, when he created "The Fairly OddParents". <s> It was originally a series of made for TV shorts on the anthology show,"Oh Yeah!Cartoons". <s> In 2001, Nickelodeon picked it up as a full series. <s> "The Fairly OddParents" became a huge hit, second only in the ratings to "SpongeBob SquarePants". <s> "The Fairly OddParents" ceased production in 2006, but it was announced on Hartman's website on February 2, 2007 that 20 more episodes will be produced. <s> Due to the success of "OddParents", Hartman was asked to create another cartoon for Nickelodeon, (Hartman says the President of Nickelodeon asked him if he had an idea, and before he could say the title he was given a contract.) <s> Danny Phantom ended production on August 24, 2007. <s> He also has a brand new cartoon series 'T.U.F.F. PUPPY' set to premiere on Nickelodeon in October, 2010. <s> Hartman is currently working on two new projects for Nickelodeon: one, a live-action series and the other, animated. <s> His other TV work include voice actor|voicing various characters on the animated series "Family Guy" (the series' creator Seth MacFarlane even named the wacky family doctor Hartman after him), and playing the character Sean Masters on the short-lived series "Generations" in 1991. <s> He was also a recurring character on the popular NBC soap opera "Days of Our Lives" (1988 - 1989; see ). <s> Hartman currently lives in Bell Canyon, California, with his wife, Julieann, and daughters, Carly and Sophia.

title: Scion (automobile)
complex: Scion was marketed as a youth brand and was first introduced in March 2002, at the New York Auto Show. <s> There were just two concept vehicles, the bbX (which became the xB), and the ccX (which became the tC).
simple: Scion is marketed to young car buyers.

title: Chemnitzer Land
complex: Chemnitzer Land is a former district in the Free State of Saxony, Germany. <s> It was bounded by (from the north and clockwise) the district of Mittweida, the city of Chemnitz, the districts of Stollberg and Zwickauer Land and the state of Thuringia (district Altenburger Land). <s> The history of the region is largely influenced by the neighbouring cities of Chemnitz and Zwickau. <s> In medieval times the town of Glauchau, today the capital of the district, was the centre of the county of Schönburg-Glauchau. <s> The East German government attempted to turn the region into a huge industrial complex, which is the reason for the dense population. <s> The district was established in 1994 by merging the former districts of Glauchau and Hohenstein-Ernstthal. <s> In August 2008, as a part of the district reform in Saxony, the districts of Zwickauer Land, Chemnitzer Land and the urban district Zwickau were merged into the new district Zwickau.
simple: Chemnitzer Land is a district in the Free State of Saxony, Germany. <s> The district has a very big population because the East German government tried to make the area very industrial. <s> The district was created in 1994 by joining the old districts of Glauchau and Hohenstein-Ernstthal. <s> In 2008, part of city of Zwickau will become part of the district.

title: Plomb du Cantal
complex: The Plomb du Cantal is the highest summit of Mounts of Cantal in the Massif central, France. <s> It's the second highest summit of the Massif central after the mountain of puy de Sancy.
simple: Plomb du Cantal is a French mountain, the highest summit of Mounts of Cantal in the "Massif Central", France. <s> Plomb du Cantal is in the Mounts of Cantal, a chain of volcanic mountains in the Massif Central, in the centre of the Cantal department. <s> It is the highest mountain of the Cantal department and the second highest in the Massif Central, after Puy de Sancy that is 1885 m high.

title: George Clements
complex: George H. Clements is an American Roman Catholic priest who, in 1981, became the first Catholic priest in the Chicago area to adopt a child. <s> Through his founding of several programs, including "one church-one child", "one church-one addict", and "one church-one inmate", he brought greater recognition to social problems and encouraged the adoption of African-American children. <s> In June 1969, Father Clements became the first black pastor of Holy Angels Catholic Church on the South Side of Chicago. <s> He is also well known for his involvement in civil rights activities during a period that extended from the late 1960s to present. <s> In August 2019, Cardinal Blase Cupich asked Clements to step aside from ministry, while the Church investigates allegations that he sexually abused a minor in 1974.
simple: George H. Clements (born January 26, 1932) is an American Roman Catholic priest. <s> In 1981, became the first Catholic priest in the Chicago area to adopt a child. <s> In June 1969, Father Clements became the first black pastor of Holy Angels Catholic Church on the South Side of Chicago. <s> He is also well known for his involvement in civil rights activities since the 1960s.

title: Sandy Ratcliff
complex: Alexandra Ratcliff (2 October 1948 – 7 April 2019), also known as Sandy Ratcliff, was an English actress, model and counsellor. <s> She made an impression as a model and film actress in the 1970s, but she became known for being one of the original cast members of the BBC soap opera "EastEnders" in the 1980s. <s> She portrayed the role of Sue Osman but left the role in 1989. <s> In 2010, she revealed that she had retired from acting to train as a counsellor. <s> Ratcliff died in her sleep and her body was found on 7 April 2019. <s> She was 70 years old.
simple: Alexandra "Sandy" Ratcliff (2 October 1948 – 6 April 2019) was an English actress. <s> She was best known for being one of the original cast members in the BBC soap opera "EastEnders" in the 1980s. <s> She portrayed played Sue Osman but left the role in 1989, after it was revealed that she was addicted to heroin and alcohol. <s> Ratcliff died in her sleep at her home in London on 6 April 2019, aged 70.

title: Supreme Court of Argentina
complex: The Supreme Court of Argentina ( literally Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation) is the highest court of law of the Argentine Republic. <s> It was inaugurated on 15 January 1863. <s> However, during much of the 20th century, the Court and the Argentine judicial system in general, has lacked autonomy from the executive power. <s> The Court has recently been reformed (in 2003) by the decree 222/03. <s> The Supreme Court functions as a last resort tribunal. <s> Its rulings cannot be appealed. <s> It also decides on cases dealing with the interpretation of the constitution (for example, it can overturn a law passed by Congress if it deems it unconstitutional). <s> The members of the Supreme Court are appointed by the President with the agreement of at least two thirds of the present Senate members in a session convened for that purpose, and can only be removed by an impeachment process called "juicio político" ("political trial"), initiated by the Chamber of Deputies and carried out by the Senate, exclusively on grounds of improper behaviour.
simple: The Supreme Court of Argentina is the highest court of law in Argentina. <s> It started on 15 January 1863. <s> The court also decides on cases about the constitution. <s> The members of the Supreme Court are chosen by the President.

title: My Way (Usher song)
complex: "My Way" is a 1998 single from Usher's 1997 album of the same name. <s> It features an uncredited rap and background vocals from Jermaine Dupri. <s> Despite moderate airplay, the single sold well and reached #2 on the U.S. "Billboard" Hot 100. <s> Its rise to #1, however, was halted due to the success of the mega-hit "The Boy Is Mine" by Brandy and Monica, during its 13-week run atop the summit. <s> Due to the disappointment of the "Nice and Slow" single in the U.K., "My Way" was not released as a single there. <s> The song features in the Refrain part of the lyrics and the music of the song by Lil' Troy "Wanna Be a Baller" from his debut album "Sittin' Fat Down South" published officially one month before Usher's song.
simple: "My Way" is a song by American singer Usher. <s> It was released from the album of the name name in 1998. <s> It features Jermaine Dupri as backing vocalist. <s> The song reached number two on the "Billboard" Hot 100 chart. <s> Because "Nice & Slow" was not successful in the UK, "My Way" was not released as a single there.

title: Burt, Iowa
complex: Burt is a city in Kossuth County, Iowa, United States. <s> The population was 533 at the 2010 census.
simple: Burt is a city of Iowa in the United States.

title: Destroyer (Kiss album)
complex: Destroyer is the fourth studio album by American rock band Kiss, released on March 15, 1976 by Casablanca Records in the US. <s> It was the third successive Kiss album to reach the top 40 in the US, as well as the first to chart in Germany and New Zealand.
simple: Destroyer is the fourth studio album and fifth album overall by the American hard rock/heavy metal band Kiss. <s> It was released on March 15, 1976.

title: José Francisco Molina
complex: José Francisco Molina Jiménez (born 8 August 1970) is a Spanish retired footballer who played as a goalkeeper, and is the sporting director of the Royal Spanish Football Federation.
simple: José Francisco Molina (born 8 August 1970) is a former Spanish football player.

title: Saint-Pont
complex: Saint-Pont is a commune in the Allier department in Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes in central France. <s> The poet Alain Borne (1915–1962), winner of the 1954 Prix Antonin-Artaud was born in Saint-Pont.
simple: Saint-Pont is a commune. <s> It is found in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: Chikugo, Fukuoka
complex: Chikugo (筑後市 , Chikugo-shi ) is a city located in Fukuoka Prefecture, Japan. <s> The city was founded on April 1, 1954.
simple: Chikugo (筑後市, Chikugo-shi) is a Japanese city in Fukuoka Prefecture on the island of Kyushu. <s> The city of Chikugo is near Kurume, Fukuoka.

title: Kansas Department of Wildlife, Parks and Tourism
complex: The Kansas Department of Wildlife, Parks, and Tourism (KDWPT) is a state cabinet-level agency led by a Secretary of Wildlife and Parks appointed by the Governor of Kansas. <s> The Office of the Secretary is located in Topeka, the state capital of Kansas. <s> A seven-member, bipartisan commission, also appointed by the Governor, advises the Secretary and approves regulations governing outdoor recreation and fish and wildlife resources in Kansas. <s> KDWPT employs approximately 420 full-time employees in five divisions: Executive Services, Administrative Services, Fisheries and Wildlife, Law Enforcement, and Parks. <s> At full staffing, KDWPT Law Enforcement Division (Kansas Game Wardens) is staffed by 83 positions. <s> Fish and game laws were first organized in the state of Kansas in the form of the Kansas Fish and Game Department in 1905. <s> In 1911, State Fish and Game Department was placed under supervision of the University of Kansas Board of Regents. <s> Another reorganization occurred in 1925 when the Fish and Game Department became the Kansas Forestry, Fish and Game Commission, consisting of three members appointed by the Governor. <s> In 1978, the Forestry part was dropped from the name. <s> The agency became known as the Kansas Fish and Game Commission. <s> Finally in 1987, Governor Mike Hayden signed an executive order merging the State Park and Resources Authority and the Kansas Fish and Game Commission to form the Kansas Department of Wildlife and Parks. <s> On July 1, 2011, the Division of Travel and Tourism was officially transferred from the Department of Commerce to the Kansas Department of Wildlife and Parks. <s> The agency is currently known as the Kansas Department of Wildlife, Parks, and Tourism.
simple: The Kansas Department of Wildlife, Parks, and Tourism (KDWPT) is a state cabinet-level agency. <s> It is led by a Secretary of Wildlife and Parks appointed by the Governor of Kansas. <s> The Office of the Secretary is in Topeka. <s> A seven-member, bipartisan commission, also appointed by the Governor, advises the Secretary and approves regulations about outdoor recreation and fish and wildlife in Kansas. <s> KDWPT has about 420 full-time employees in five divisions: Executive Services, Administrative Services, Fisheries and Wildlife, Law Enforcement, and Parks. <s> At full staffing, KDWPT Law Enforcement Division (Kansas Game Wardens) has 83 positions. <s> Fish and game laws were started in the state of Kansas in the form of the Kansas Fish and Game Department in 1905. <s> On July 1, 2011, the Division of Travel and Tourism was given from the Kansas Department of Commerce to the Kansas Department of Wildlife and Parks. <s> The agency is known as the Kansas Department of Wildlife, Parks, and Tourism.

title: Burdwan division
complex: Burdwan Division is a division in the Indian state of West Bengal.
simple: Burdwan Division is a division in the Indian state of West Bengal.

title: Buffet
complex: A buffet ( , , from French word for "sideboard") is a system of serving meals in which food is placed in a public area where the diners serve themselves. <s> A form of "service à la française", buffets are offered at various places including hotels, restaurants, and many social events. <s> Buffet restaurants normally offer all-you-can-eat food for a set price, but some measure prices by weight or by number of dishes. <s> Buffets usually have some hot dishes, so the term cold buffet (see Smörgåsbord) has been developed to describe formats lacking hot food. <s> Hot or cold buffets usually involve dishware and utensils, but a finger buffet is an array of foods that are designed to be small and easily consumed only by hand, such as cupcakes, slices of pizza, foods on cocktail sticks, etc. <s> The essential feature of the various buffet formats is that the diners can directly view the food and immediately select which dishes they wish to consume, and usually also can decide how much food they take. <s> Buffets are effective for serving large numbers of people at once, and are often seen in institutional settings, business conventions, or large parties. <s> Many boarding schools, colleges, and universities offer optional or mandatory "meal plans", especially in connection with dormitories for students.
simple: A buffet is a serve-yourself food system. <s> Food is placed in a public area where the diners choose what they want. <s> Buffet restaurants usually offer all-you-can-eat food for a set price. <s> Buffets usually have some hot dishes. <s> The term cold buffet (see Smörgåsbord) has been developed to describe buffets lacking hot food. <s> Hot or cold buffets usually involve dishware and utensils, but a finger buffet is designed for small pieces taken by hand, such as cupcakes, slices of pizza, foods on cocktail sticks, etc. <s> The essential feature of the various buffet formats is that the diners can see the food and immediately select which dishes they wish to eat, and usually also can decide how much food they take. <s> Buffets are effective for serving large numbers of people at once, and are often seen in institutional settings, such as business conventions or large parties.

title: 1956 Winter Olympics
complex: The 1956 Winter Olympics, officially known as the VII Olympic Winter Games (French: Les "VII Jeux olympiques d'hiver"; Italian: "VII Giochi olimpici invernali"), was a multi-sport event held in Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy, from 26 January to 5 February 1956. <s> A total of 32 nations sent athletes to Cortina d'Ampezzo. <s> Along with the Soviet Union, Bolivia and Iran competed at the Winter Games for the first time, making Bolivia the first completely Tropical nation to participate in a Winter Olympic. <s> Korea, Liechtenstein, and Turkey returned after having missed the 1952 Winter Olympics, while Argentina, Denmark, New Zealand, and Portugal did not compete at these Games, after having participated in the previous edition. <s> Athletes from West Germany (FRG) and East Germany (GDR) competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would continue for the following two Olympiads. <s> The Cold War began after the allied victory in World War II. <s> Until 1952, many of the Communist countries of Eastern Europe had participated in Worker's Olympics or Spartakiads. <s> The Soviet Union emerged from international isolation by eschewing the Spartakiad and participating in the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki; they made their Winter Olympics debut at the Cortina Games. <s> Soviet general secretary Nikita Khrushchev's aim was to use international sports competitions, such as the Olympics, to demonstrate the superiority of communism, strengthen political ties with other communist countries, and project the Soviet Union as a peace-loving nation actively engaged in the world. <s> The Soviets' participation at the Olympics raised the level of competition as they won the most medals and more gold medals than any other nation. <s> The Cortina Games were held before the Hungarian Revolution and subsequent Soviet invasion, and the Suez War, which occurred in the autumn of 1956; the Winter Games escaped the boycotts that plagued the Melbourne Olympics, which were celebrated in November and December of that year.
simple: The 1956 Winter Olympics, officially known as the VII Olympic Winter Games, were held in 1956 in Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy. <s> A total of 32 nations sent athletes to Cortina d'Ampezzo. <s> Bolivia, Iran, and the USSR competed at the Winter Games for the first time. <s> Korea, Liechtenstein, and Turkey returned after having missed the 1952 Winter Olympics. <s> Argentina, Denmark, New Zealand, and Portugal did not compete at these Games, after participating in 1952. <s> Athletes from West Germany (FRG) and East Germany (GDR) competed together as the United Team of Germany at these Games, an arrangement that would continue for the next two Olympiads. <s> The USSR debuted in these Winter Olympics. <s> They immediately showed their strength by winning more medals than any other nation.

title: Richie Benaud
complex: Richard Benaud ( ; 6 October 1930 – 10 April 2015) was an Australian cricketer who, after his retirement from international cricket in 1964, became a highly regarded commentator on the game. <s> Benaud was a Test cricket all-rounder, blending leg spin bowling with lower-order batting aggression. <s> Along with fellow bowling all-rounder Alan Davidson, he helped restore Australia to the top of world cricket in the late 1950s and early 1960s after a slump in the early 1950s. <s> In 1958 he became Australia's Test captain until his retirement in 1964. <s> He became the first player to reach 200 wickets and 2,000 runs in Test cricket, arriving at that milestone in 1963. <s> Benaud was born in Penrith, New South Wales, in 1930. <s> He came from a cricket family, with his younger brother John Benaud also going on to become an Australian Test cricketer. <s> His father Louis, a third generation Australian of French Huguenot descent, was a leg spinner who played for Penrith District Cricket Club in Sydney Grade Cricket, gaining attention for taking all twenty wickets in a match against St. Marys for 65 runs. <s> Lou later moved to Parramatta region in western Sydney, and played for Cumberland. <s> Benaud also used to live in Coraki, NSW. <s> It was here that Richie Benaud grew up, learning how to bowl leg breaks, googlies and topspinners under his father's watch. <s> Educated at Parramatta High School, Benaud made his first grade debut for Cumberland at age 16, primarily as a batsman. <s> In November 2014, at age 84, Benaud announced that he had been diagnosed with skin cancer. <s> He died in his sleep on 10 April 2015. <s> Prime Minister Tony Abbott offered his family a state funeral but his widow, Daphne, declined, respecting his wishes for a private funeral.
simple: Richard "Richie" Benaud OBE (; 6 October 1930 – 10 April 2015) was an Australian cricketer. <s> After his retirement from international cricket in 1964, he became a well-known commentator on the game. <s> Benaud was a Test cricket all-rounder. <s> Along with fellow bowling all-rounder Alan Davidson, he helped Australia to be at the top of world cricket in the late 1950s and early 1960s after a slump in the early 1950s. <s> In 1958 he became Australia's Test captain until his retirement in 1964. <s> Benaud was born in Penrith, New South Wales. <s> His parents were of French descent. <s> Benaud studied at Parramatta High School. <s> In November 2014, Benaud announced that he was diagnosed with skin cancer, aged 84. <s> He died in his sleep on 10 April 2015 in Sydney. <s> Prime Minister of Australia Tony Abbott offered a state funeral for Benaud, but his family rejected the offer.

title: Kleptomania

title: Jean Stein
complex: Jean Babette Stein (February 9, 1934 – April 30, 2017) was an American author and editor. <s> Stein also worked as a magazine editor. <s> In the late 1950s she was an editor, with Plimpton, at "The Paris Review". <s> From 1990 to 2004, she was editor of the literary/visual arts magazine "Grand Street" with art editor Walter Hopps. <s> The magazine actively sought out international authors, visual artists, composers and scientists to bring to its readership. <s> Stein's first marriage in 1958 was to William vanden Heuvel, a lawyer who served in the U.S. Justice Department under Robert F. Kennedy, and who later also became a diplomat and author. <s> Since 1984, he has been the chairman of the Roosevelt Institute. <s> Their first daughter, Katrina vanden Heuvel, was born in 1959; she is now the editor and publisher of "The Nation" magazine. <s> The couple's second daughter, Wendy vanden Heuvel, was born in 1961, and she is an actress and producer in New York. <s> She is also on the board of the "52nd Street Project", which matches inner-city youth with professional theater artists to create original dramatic works. <s> From 1995 to 2007, Stein was married to Torsten Wiesel, a co-recipient with David H. Hubel of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine. <s> Suffering from depression, Stein apparently committed suicide by jumping from her Manhattan apartment on April 30, 2017.
simple: Jean Stein (February 9, 1934 – April 30, 2017) was an American author and editor. <s> In the late 1950s, she was an editor at "The Paris Review". <s> From 1990 to 2004, she was editor of the literary/visual arts magazine "Grand Street". <s> Stein was married to businessman William vanden Heuvel from 1958 until they divorced in the 1970s. <s> to Nobel Prize-winner Torsten Wiesel from 1995 until they divorced in 2007. <s> Stein committed suicide by jumping off from her apartment building in New York City on April 30, 2017, aged 83.

title: When I'm Sixty-Four
complex: "When I'm Sixty-Four" is a song by the English rock band the Beatles, written by Paul McCartney (credited to Lennon–McCartney) and released on their 1967 album "Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band". <s> The song is sung by a young man to his lover, and is about his plans of their growing old together. <s> Although the theme is ageing, it was one of the first songs McCartney wrote, when he was 16. <s> It was in the Beatles' setlist in their early days as a song to perform when their amplifiers broke down or the electricity went off. <s> Both George Martin and Mark Lewisohn speculated that McCartney may have thought of the song when recording began for "Sgt. Pepper" in December 1966 because his father turned 64 earlier that year. <s> Lennon said of the song, "Paul wrote it in the Cavern days. <s> We just stuck a few more words on it like 'grandchildren on your knee' and 'Vera, Chuck and Dave' ... this was just one that was quite a hit with us." <s> The song was recorded on 6 December 1966, during one of the first sessions for the as-yet-unnamed album that became "Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band". <s> There were multiple overdub sessions, including the lead vocal by McCartney on 8 December and backing vocals by McCartney, Lennon, and George Harrison on 20 December. <s> The clarinets were recorded on 21 December. <s> The song is in the key of D♭ major. <s> Recorded in C major, the master take was sped up to raise the key by one semitone at the insistence of McCartney. <s> Martin remembers that McCartney suggested this change to make his voice sound younger. <s> McCartney says, "I wanted to appear younger, but that was just to make it more rooty-tooty; just lift the key because it was starting to sound turgid." <s> The song was nearly released on a single as the B-side of either "Strawberry Fields Forever" or "Penny Lane". <s> It was instead held over to be included as an album track for "Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band".
simple: "When I'm Sixty-Four" is a love song by The Beatles, written by Paul McCartney (credited to Lennon/McCartney) and released in 1967 on their album "Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band". <s> The song is sung by a young man to his lover, and is about his plans of growing old together with her. <s> Although the theme is aging, it was one of the first songs McCartney wrote, when he was sixteen. <s> The Beatles used it in the early days as a song they could play when the amplifiers broke down or the electricity went off. <s> Both George Martin and Mark Lewisohn thought that McCartney may have thought of the song when recording began for "Sgt. Pepper" in December 1966 because his father turned 64 earlier that year. <s> Lennon said of the song, "Paul wrote it in the Cavern days. <s> We just stuck a few more words on it like 'grandchildren on your knee' and 'Vera, Chuck and Dave' ... this was just one that was quite a hit with us." <s> The song was recorded on 6 December 1966, during one of the first sessions for the as-yet-unnamed album that became "Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band". <s> There were multiple overdub sessions, including the lead vocal by McCartney on 8 December and backing vocals by McCartney, Lennon, and George Harrison on 20 December. <s> The clarinets were recorded on 21 December. <s> The song is in the key of D-flat major. <s> The Beatles recorded the song in C major but the master take was sped up in order to raise the key by one semitone at the insistence of McCartney. <s> Martin remembers that McCartney suggested this change in order to make his voice sound younger. <s> McCartney says, "I wanted to appear younger, but that was just to make it more rooty-tooty; just lift the key because it was starting to sound turgid." <s> The song was nearly released on a single as the B-side with either "Strawberry Fields Forever" or "Penny Lane" as the A-side.

title: Tinikling
complex: Tinikling is a traditional Philippine folk dance which originated during the Spanish colonial era. <s> The dance involves two people beating, tapping, and sliding bamboo poles on the ground and against each other in coordination with one or more dancers who step over and in between the poles in a dance. <s> It is traditionally danced to rondalla music, a sort of serenade played by an ensemble of stringed instruments which originated in Spain during the Middle Ages. <s> The dance originated in Leyte, an island in the Visayas in the central Philippines. <s> It imitates the movement of the "tikling" birds as they walk between grass stems, run over tree branches, or dodge bamboo traps set by rice farmers. <s> Dancers imitate the tikling bird's legendary grace and speed by skillfully maneuvering between large bamboo poles.
simple: Tinikling is a traditional Philippine dance which originated during the Spanish colonial era. <s> Legend has it that tinikling originated during the Spanish rule of the Philippines, when natives worked on large plantations under the control of the King of Spain. <s> The dance involves two people beating, tapping, and sliding bamboo poles on the ground and against each other in coordination with one or more dancers who step over and in between the poles in a dance.The name "tinikling" is a reference to birds close known as "tikling" <s> The dance is made/originated in Leyte, an island in the Visayas in the central Philippines. <s> It follows the movement of the tikling birds as they walk between grass stems, run over tree branches, or dodge bamboo traps set by rice farmers. <s> Dancers follow the tikling bird's legendary grace and speed by skillfully between large bamboo poles.

complex: Athanasios "Sakis" Boulas ( ; 11 March 1954 – 21 February 2014) was a Greek singer, songwriter and actor, born in Kilkis and raised in Piraeus. <s> He made several studio albums and wrote songs for other musicians. <s> He also starred in several television shows and films. <s> He was born in 1954 in Kilkis, Greece and raised in Piraeus, In 1976 He started out his career as the narrator of the documentary film "Arkadi 1866". <s> In 1983 he had a voice role in the film "Dracula of Exarchia", and later that same year did a voice for "Bitter Movie". <s> Boulas died of cancer in an Athens clinic, on 21 February 2014, aged 60.

title: Mukku Raju
complex: Mukku Raju (Sagiraju Rajamraju) was a Tollywood film choreographer and actor. <s> Raju started his career as choreographer in Tamil Cinema / Kollywood, but ended as an actor and has acted in over 1000 films. <s> He also directed and wrote scripts for a few films. <s> He started a dancers associations in Madras, later moved to Hyderabad and co-founded the Telugu Dancers and Directors Association, to support and help the budding directors and dancers. <s> He received the Nandi Award for Best Character Actor in 2008 for his film "1940 Lo Oka Gramam (A Village in 1940)". <s> Raju passed at the age of 83 after a short illness, and his funeral took place at Cherukuvada. <s> He received the Nandi Award for Best Character Actor in 2008 for the film "1940 Lo Oka Gramam".

title: Martin Milner
complex: Martin Sam Milner (December 28, 1931 – September 6, 2015) was an American film, stage, radio, and television actor. <s> Milner is known for his performances on two television series: "Route 66", which aired on CBS from 1960 to 1964, and "Adam-12", which aired on NBC from 1968 to 1975. <s> On September 6, 2015, Milner died of heart failure at his home in Carlsbad, California, at age 83. <s> Milner's remains were cremated by Eternal Hills Memorial Park's mortuary in Oceanside, California..
