title: Windsor, Vermont
complex: Windsor is a town in Windsor County, Vermont, United States. <s> As the "Birthplace of Vermont", the town is where the Constitution of Vermont was adopted in 1777, thus marking the founding of the Vermont Republic—a sovereign state until 1791 when Vermont joined the United States. <s> Over much of its history, Windsor was home to a variety of manufacturing enterprises. <s> The population was 3,553 at the 2010 census. <s> One of the New Hampshire grants, Windsor was chartered as a town on July 6, 1761, by colonial governor Benning Wentworth. <s> It was first settled in August 1764 by Captain Steele Smith and his family from Farmington, Connecticut. <s> In 1777, the signers of the Constitution of the Vermont Republic met at Old Constitution House, a tavern at the time, to declare independence from the British Empire (the Vermont Republic would not become a state until 1791). <s> In 1820, it was the state's largest town, a thriving center for trade and agriculture. <s> In 1835, the first dam was built across Mill Brook to provide water power. <s> Factories made guns, machinery, tinware, furniture and harnesses. <s> The community is named for Windsor, Connecticut. <s> Windsor village began development at the end of the 18th century and achieved importance in Vermont history as the location of the framing of the constitution of Vermont. <s> It is known as the birthplace of Vermont, where the state constitution was signed, and acted as the first capital until 1805 when Montpelier became the official state capital.
simple: Windsor is a town in Windsor County, Vermont, United States. <s> The population was 2,066 at the 2010 census. <s> The first settler in Windsor was Captain Steele Smith who arrived with his family in August 1764. <s> The Constitution of Vermont was written and signed in 1777 at a tavern, now called Old Constitution House. <s> By 1820, Windsor was the largest town in Vermont. <s> A dam built across Mill Brook in 1836 provided water power for these factories. <s> It had factories making guns, machinery, tinware, furniture and harness. <s> It is known as the birthplace of Vermont. <s> It was the first capital until 1805.

title: Axel Lewenhaupt
complex: Count Axel Charles Emil Lewenhaupt (27 May 1917 – 20 November 2018) was a Swedish diplomat and Grand Master of Ceremonies at the Royal Court of Sweden. <s> Lewenhaupt was born in Helsingborg, Sweden and is the son of Colonel, Count Gustaf Lewenhaupt and Baroness Elisabeth Ramel. <s> He passed "studentexamen" in 1936 and his reserve officer exam in 1938 and received a Candidate of Law degree from Uppsala University in 1942 before becoming an attaché at the Ministry for Foreign Affairs in 1943. <s> Lewenhaupt served as an attaché in Rome in 1943. <s> The Swedish legation's duties during World War II in Rome included taking special measures to protect Swedish interests and Swedish nationals (including Elizabeth Hesselblad) who was still in Rome. <s> The focus was to protect the Swedish Institute and the convent church Santa Brigida. <s> After Rome, Lewenhaupt was attaché in Berlin in 1944 and in Helsinki from 1945 to 1947. <s> He was second secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1948 to 1952 and first legation secretary in Madrid from 1952 to 1956. <s> Lewenhaupt was first secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1956 to 1958 and director at the Foreign Ministry from 1958 to 1960. <s> He was embassy counsellor in Washington, D.C. from 1960 to 1962 and ambassador in Leopoldville from 1962 to 1963. <s> Lewenhaupt was acting head of the political department at the Foreign Ministry from 1964 to 1965 and its administrative department from 1965 to 1967. <s> He was ambassador in Bangkok, Rangoon, Kuala Lumpur and Singapore from 1967 to 1970 and ambassador in New Delhi, Colombo and Katmandu from 1970 to 1975. <s> Lewenhaupt was then ambassador in Belgrade and Tirana from 1975 to 1978 and served at the Foreign Ministry from 1978 to 1979.
simple: Count Axel Charles Emil Lewenhaupt (born 27 May 1917) is a former Swedish diplomat and Grand Master of Ceremonies at the Royal Court of Sweden. <s> He was born in Helsingborg, Sweden. <s> He was second secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1948 to 1952 and first legation secretary in Madrid from 1952 to 1956. <s> Lewenhaupt was first secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1956 to 1958 and director at the Foreign Ministry from 1958 to 1960. <s> Lewenhaupt was embassy counsellor in Washington, D.C. from 1960 to 1962 and ambassador in Leopoldville from 1962 to 1963. <s> Lewenhaupt was acting head of the political department at the Foreign Ministry from 1964 to 1965 and its administrative department from 1965 to 1967. <s> He was ambassador in Bangkok, Rangoon, Kuala Lumpur and Singapore.

title: Rockwell B-1 Lancer

simple: The Rockwell B-1 Lancer is a strategic bomber in the service of the US Air Force.

title: Ursula von der Leyen
complex: Ursula Gertrud von der Leyen (] ; ; born 8 October 1958) is a German politician and the President-elect of the European Commission. <s> She served in the federal government of Germany from 2005 to 2019 as the longest-serving member of Angela Merkel's cabinet. <s> She is a member of the centre-right Christian Democratic Union (CDU). <s> In the late 1990s, she became involved in local politics in the Hanover region, and she served as a cabinet minister in the state government of Lower Saxony from 2003 to 2005. <s> In 2005, she joined the federal cabinet, first as Minister of Family Affairs and Youth from 2005 to 2009, then as Minister of Labour and Social Affairs from 2009 to 2013, and finally as Minister of Defence from 2013 to 2019, the first woman to serve as German defence minister. <s> When she left office she was the only minister to have served continuously in Angela Merkel's cabinet since Merkel became Chancellor. <s> She has been deputy leader of the CDU since 2010, and has previously been regarded as a leading contender to succeed Merkel as Chancellor and as the favourite to become Secretary-General of NATO. <s> On 2 July 2019, von der Leyen was proposed by the European Council as the candidate for the office of President of the European Commission. <s> She was elected by the European Parliament on 16 July. <s> She is the first woman to become President of the European Commission.
simple: Ursula Gertrud von der Leyen (; née Albrecht, 8 October 1958) is a German politician. <s> She had served as Minister of Defence of Germany from 2013 to 2019. <s> She is a member of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU). <s> Von der Leyen is the only minister to have been in Angela Merkel's cabinet since she took office in 2005, first as Minister of Family Affairs and Youth from 2005 to 2009, then as Minister of Labour and Social Affairs from 2009 to 2013, before becoming Minister of Defence in 2013. <s> On 2 July 2019, von der Leyen was nominated by the European Council to the position of President of the European Commission. <s> With a close majority, she was elected by the European Parliament on 16 July, making her the first woman to hold the office.

title: Libreville
complex: Libreville is the capital and largest city of Gabon, in western central Africa. <s> The city is a port on the Komo River, near the Gulf of Guinea, and a trade center for a timber region. <s> s of 2013 , its census population was 703,904. <s> The area was inhabited by the Mpongwé tribe long before the French acquired the land in 1839. <s> American missionaries from New England established a mission in Baraka, Gabon, on what is now Libreville, in 1842. <s> In 1846, the Brazilian slave ship "L'Elizia", carrying slaves from the Congo, was captured near Loango by the French navy which was tasked with contributing the British Blockade of Africa. <s> Fifty-two of the freed slaves were resettled on the site of Libreville (French for "Freetown") in 1849. <s> It was the chief port of French Equatorial Africa from 1934 to 1946, and was the central focus of the Battle of Gabon in 1940. <s> Libreville was named in imitation of Freetown, and grew only slowly as a trading post and a minor administrative centre to a population of 32,000 on independence in 1960. <s> It only received its first bank branch when Bank of West Africa (BAO) opened a branch in 1930. <s> Since independence, the city has grown rapidly and now houses nearly half the national population. <s> Libreville International Airport is the largest airport in Gabon and is located around 11 km north of the city. <s> The city is home to a shipbuilding industry, brewing industry, and sawmills. <s> The city exports raw materials such as wood, rubber and cocoa from the city's main port, and the deepwater port at Owendo.
simple: Libreville is the capital city of Gabon. <s> Libreville is a port on the Gabon River, near the Gulf of Guinea. <s> It is a trade center for a timber region. <s> The Mpongwé tribe lived in the area long before the French took control of the land in 1839. <s> It was the chief port of French Equatorial Africa from 1934 to 1946. <s> Libreville was named in after Freetown. <s> It grew slowly as a trading post and a minor administrative centre. <s> It had a population of 31,000 when it became independent in 1960. <s> Since independence, the city has grown more quickly. <s> The Libreville International Airport, the headquarters for Air Gabon, is about 11 km north of the city. <s> The city is home to a shipbuilding industry, brewing industry and sawmills. <s> The city exports raw materials such as wood, rubber and cocoa from the city's main port, and the deepwater port at Owendo.

title: Peter Plympton Smith

title: 2005 FIFA Confederations Cup
complex: The 2005 FIFA Confederations Cup football tournament was the seventh FIFA Confederations Cup. <s> It was held in Germany between 15 June and 29 June 2005, as a prelude to the 2006 FIFA World Cup. <s> The tournament was won by 2002 FIFA World Cup winners Brazil, who defeated Argentina 4–1 in the final at the Waldstadion in Frankfurt. <s> The final was a rematch of the Copa América final also won by Brazil.

title: QVC
complex: QVC (an acronym for "Quality Value Convenience") is an American free-to-air television network, and flagship shopping channel specializing in televised home shopping that is owned by Qurate Retail Group. <s> Founded in 1986 by Joseph Segel in West Chester, Pennsylvania, United States, QVC broadcasts to more than 350 million households in seven countries, including channels in the UK, Germany, Japan, and Italy, along with a joint venture in China with China National Radio called CNR Mall.
simple: The name "QVC" means Quality, Value and Convenience. <s> QVC serves almost 235 million customers in six countries.

title: Reeves County, Texas
complex: Reeves County is a county located in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> As of the 2010 census, its population was 13,783. <s> Its county seat is Pecos. <s> The county was created in 1883 and organized the next year.
simple: Reeves County is a county in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> In 2010, 13,783 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Pecos.

title: Monteille
complex: Monteille is a former commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France. <s> On 1 January 2017, it was merged into the new commune Mézidon Vallée d'Auge.
simple: Monteille is a commune.

title: Dilation and curettage
complex: Dilation (or dilatation) and curettage (D&C) refers to the dilation (widening/opening) of the cervix and surgical removal of part of the lining of the uterus and/or contents of the uterus by scraping and scooping (curettage). <s> It is a therapeutic gynecological procedure as well as the most often used method of first trimester miscarriage or abortion.
simple: Dilation and Curettage (D&C) is a type of surgery used to diagnose and treat problems with woman's uterus.

title: Fokker 100
complex: The Fokker 100 is a medium-sized, twin-turbofan jet airliner from Fokker, the largest such aircraft built by the company before its bankruptcy in 1996. <s> The type possessed low operational costs and initially had scant competition in the 100-seat short-range regional jet class, contributing to strong sales upon introduction in the late 1980s.
simple: Fokker 100 is a narrow-body, twin-engined, medium-range and turbofan regional airliner produced by Fokker as a lengthened and improved version of Fokker F28. <s> It is the largest Fokker manufactured aircraft built.

title: Sondersdorf
complex: Sondersdorf is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France.
simple: Sondersdorf is a commune. <s> It is found in the Haut-Rhin department of eastern France.

title: Floyd County, Texas
complex: Floyd County is a county in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> As of the 2010 census, its population was 6,446. <s> The seat of the county is Floydada. <s> The county was created in 1876 and later organized in 1890.
simple: Floyd County is a county in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> In 2010, 6,446 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Floydada.

title: Assevillers
complex: Assevillers is a commune in the Somme department in Hauts-de-France in northern France.
simple: Assevillers is a commune in the Somme department in Hauts-de-France in northern France.

title: Dawn of the Planet of the Apes
complex: Dawn of the Planet of the Apes is a 2014 American science fiction film directed by Matt Reeves and written by Mark Bomback, Rick Jaffa and Amanda Silver. <s> It stars Andy Serkis, Jason Clarke, Gary Oldman, Keri Russell, Toby Kebbell, and Kodi Smit-McPhee. <s> It is the sequel to the 2011 film "Rise of the Planet of the Apes", which began 20th Century Fox's reboot of the original "Planet of the Apes" series. <s> "Dawn" is set ten years after the events of "Rise", and follows a group of people in San Francisco who struggle to stay alive in the aftermath of a plague that is wiping out humanity, while Caesar tries to maintain dominance over his community of intelligent apes. <s> "Dawn of the Planet of the Apes" was released in the United States on July 11, 2014 and was met with highly positive reviews, with critics praising its visual effects, story, direction, acting, musical score, action sequences and emotional depth. <s> It was also a box office success, grossing over $710 million worldwide, and making it the eighth-highest-grossing film of 2014. <s> The film received an Academy Award nomination for Best Visual Effects. <s> It was also nominated for eight Saturn Awards, including Best Science Fiction Film, Best Director for Reeves, and Best Supporting Actor for Serkis. <s> A third installment, titled "War for the Planet of the Apes", was released on July 14, 2017. <s> The film's score was composed by Michael Giacchino.
simple: Dawn of the Planet of the Apes is an American science-fiction movie directed by Matt Reeves. <s> It stars Andy Serkis, Gary Oldman, Jason Clarke, and Keri Russell. <s> It is the sequel to the 2011 movie "Rise of the Planet of the Apes". <s> It was released on July 11, 2014. <s> A sequel to the film "War of the Plant of the Apes" was released July 14, 2017.

title: Bisma Karisma
complex: Bisma Karisma (born November 27, 1990 in Bandung) Bisma is well known as a member of boy band SM*SH. <s> Before joining SM*SH, was a national Bboy and also a drummer, percussionist and vocalist.
simple: Bisma Karisma (born in Bandung, West Java, Indonesia, November 27, 1990) is an Indonesian singer, dancer and actor. <s> He is a member of the boy band SM*SH.

title: Harold Lederman
complex: Harold Lederman (January 26, 1940 – May 11, 2019) was an American boxing judge and analyst. <s> He began his career as a boxing judge in 1967 and joined the cast of HBO World Championship Boxing in 1986, and was there until HBO dropped boxing in 2018. <s> Lederman was inducted into the International Boxing Hall of Fame in the class of 2016. <s> Lederman died on May 11, 2019 at 79 years of age, from cancer.
simple: Harold Lederman (January 26, 1940 – May 11, 2019) was an American professional boxing judge and analyst. <s> He began his career as a boxing judge in 1967 and joined the cast of "HBO World Championship Boxing" in 1986. <s> He stayed in this role until HBO dropped boxing in 2018. <s> He was added to the International Boxing Hall of Fame in 2016. <s> Lederman died of cancer on May 11, 2019, at the age of 79.

title: Serge Ibaka
complex: Serge Jonas Ibaka Ngobila ( ; born 18 September 1989) is a Congolese-Spanish professional basketball player for the Toronto Raptors of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> Ibaka was drafted by the Oklahoma City Thunder's former incarnation, the Seattle SuperSonics, with the 24th overall pick in the 2008 NBA draft.
simple: Serge Ibaka (born 18 September 1989) is a NBA player born in Republic of the Congo and a naturalized citizen of Spain. <s> Ibaka plays for the Toronto Raptors..

title: Skill
complex: A skill is the ability to carry out a task with determined results often within a given amount of time, energy, or both. <s> Skills can often be divided into domain-general and domain-specific skills.
simple: A skill or technique is a learned ability to do something.

title: Rotselaar
complex: Rotselaar (] ) is a municipality located in the Belgian province of Flemish-Brabant, near the convergence of the Demer and the Dijle. <s> Since January 1, 1977 the municipality comprises the towns of Rotselaar proper, Werchter and Wezemaal.
simple: Rotselaar is a municipality in the Belgian province of Flemish Brabant.

title: Operation Eagle Claw
complex: Operation Eagle Claw, known as Operation Tabas in Iran, was a United States Armed Forces operation ordered by U.S. President Jimmy Carter to attempt to end the Iran hostage crisis by rescuing 52 embassy staff held captive at the Embassy of the United States, Tehran on 24 April 1980. <s> Its failure, and the humiliating public debacle that ensued, damaged U.S. prestige worldwide. <s> Carter blamed his loss in the 1980 U.S. presidential election mainly on his failure to secure the release of the hostages.
simple: Operation Eagle Claw, known as Operation Tabas in Iran, was a United States Armed Forces operation ordered by U.S. President Jimmy Carter to try to end the Iran hostage crisis by rescuing 52 embassy staff held captive at the Embassy of the United States, Tehran on 24 April 1980. <s> Its failure damaged U.S. prestige worldwide. <s> Carter himself blamed his loss in the 1980 U.S. presidential election mainly on his failure to win the release of the hostages.

title: Narita Airport Terminal 1 Station
complex: Narita Airport Terminal 1 (Narita Airport) Station (成田空港駅 , Narita Kūkō eki ) is an underground train station located beneath Terminal 1 of Narita International Airport in Narita, Chiba, Japan. <s> The station is shared between East Japan Railway Company (JR East) and the private railway operator Keisei Electric Railway.
simple: Narita Airport Station (成田空港駅, Narita Kūkō eki) is a train station of East Japan Railway Company(JR East) and Keisei Electric Railway. <s> It is in Narita, Chiba Prefecture, Japan. <s> This station is the main access point of Narita International Airport.

title: Odia language
complex: Odia ( ; formerly romanized as Oriya) is an Indo-Aryan language spoken in the Indian state of Odisha.
simple: Odia (ଓଡ଼ିଆ oṛiā), formerly known as Oriya, is an Indian Dravidian language, mainly spoken in the Indian state of Odisha.

title: Kamenná (Jihlava District)
complex: Kamenná (] ; ) is a village in the Jihlava District, Vysočina Region of the Czech Republic. <s> About 171 people live there and it has 6,33 km2. <s> Kamenná was first documented in 1308.
simple: Kamenná is a village in the Jihlava District, Vysočina Region of the Czech Republic. <s> About 171 people live there. <s> It covers 6,33 km2. <s> Kamenná was first documented in 1308.

title: Études (Chopin)
complex: The Études by Frédéric Chopin are three sets of études (solo studies) for the piano published during the 1830s. <s> There are twenty-seven compositions overall, comprising two separate collections of twelve, numbered Op. 10 and Op. 25, and a set of three without opus number. <s> Chopin's Études formed the foundation for what was then a revolutionary playing style for the piano. <s> They are some of the most challenging and evocative pieces of all the works in concert piano repertoire. <s> Because of this, the music remains popular and often performed in both concert and private stages. <s> Some are so popular they have been given nicknames; arguably the most popular of all is Op. 10, No. 3, sometimes identified by the names ""Tristesse"" ("Sadness") or "Farewell" (""L'Adieu""), as well as the "Revolutionary Étude" (Op. 10, No. 12). <s> No nicknames are of Chopin's original creation. <s> All twenty-seven études were published during Chopin's lifetime; Op. 10, the first group of twelve, were composed between 1829 and 1832, and were published in 1833, in France, Germany, and England. <s> The twelve études of Op. 25 were composed at various times between 1832 and 1836, and were published in the same countries in 1837. <s> The final three, part of a series called compiled by Ignaz Moscheles and François-Joseph Fétis, were composed in 1839, without an assigned opus number. <s> They appeared in Germany and France in November 1840, and England in January 1841. <s> Accompanying copies of these important early editions, there are usually several manuscripts of a single étude in Chopin's own hand, and additional copies made by his close friend, Jules Fontana, along with editions of Karol Mikuli, Chopin's student. <s> The first études of the Opus 10 set were written when Chopin was still in his teens. <s> They rank alongside the early works of Felix Mendelssohn as rare examples of extremely youthful compositions that are regarded as both innovative and worthy of inclusion in the standard canon. <s> Chopin's études elevated the musical form from purely utilitarian exercises to great artistic masterpieces.
simple: The Études by Polish composer Frédéric Chopin are three sets of études for piano. <s> Chopin's "Études" are some of the hardest pieces of all the works in concert piano repertoire. <s> Because of this, the music remain famous and are often played at concerts. <s> Some of them have been given nicknames (but not by Chopin himself) - for example, the last "Étude" from Op. 10 has been called the "Revolutionary" because it was inspired by the November 1830 Uprising, when the Poles were defeated by the Russian Empire. <s> All twenty-seven "Études" were published during Chopin's lifetime; Opus 10, the first group of twelve were written between 1829 and 1832, and were published in 1833, in France, Germany, and England. <s> The twelve "Études" of Opus 25 were composed at various times between 1832 and 1836, and were published in the same countries in 1837. <s> The final three, part of a series called "Méthode des méthodes de piano" compiled by Moscheles and Fétis, were composed in 1839 but with no opus number. <s> The first "Études" of the Opus 10 set were written when Chopin was still in his teens. <s> Chopin's "Études" elevated the musical form from purely utilitarian exercises to great artistic masterpieces.

title: Marietta, Oklahoma
complex: Marietta is a city in and county seat of Love County, Oklahoma, United States. <s> The population was 2,626 at the 2010 census, a 7.4 percent increase from 2,445 at the 2000 census.
simple: Marietta is a city of Oklahoma in the United States. <s> It is the county seat of Love County.

title: Mary T. Clark
complex: Sister Mary Twibill Clark, RSCJ (October 23, 1913 – September 1, 2014) was an American academic and civil rights advocate. <s> She was best known as a scholar of the history of philosophy, and was associated especially with Augustine of Hippo. <s> She served as the President of the American Catholic Philosophical Association in 1977, of the Metaphysical Society of America, and of the Society for Medieval and Renaissance Philosophy. <s> Clark served on the Executive Committee of the Eastern Division of the American Philosophical Association, and towards the end of her life as a visiting academic at Ralston College. <s> Sister Mary Clark died on September 1, 2014, aged 100. <s> She was predeceased by her siblings, Rev. James D. Clark, George A. Clark, and Regina (Mrs. James P.) McGraney.
simple: Sister Mary T. Clark, RSCJ (October 23, 1913 – September 1, 2014) was an Americans educator and civil rights advocate. <s> She was best known as a scholar of the history of philosophy, and was associated especially with Augustine of Hippo. <s> She was formerly the President of the American Catholic Philosophical Association of the Metaphysical Society of America, and of the Society for Medieval and Renaissance Philosophy. <s> She also served on the Executive Committee of the Eastern Division of the American Philosophical Association. <s> She served as a Visitor of Ralston College. <s> Clark died in Savannah, Georgia from natural causes, aged 100.

title: Falkirk
complex: Falkirk ( ; ; ) is a large town in the Central Lowlands of Scotland, historically within the county of Stirlingshire. <s> It lies in the Forth Valley, 23.3 mi north-west of Edinburgh and 20.5 mi north-east of Glasgow.
simple: Falkirk is a town in Scotland.

title: One Fish, Two Fish, Blowfish, Blue Fish
complex: "One Fish, Two Fish, Blowfish, Blue Fish" is the eleventh episode of "The Simpsons" ' second season. <s> It originally aired on Fox network in the United States on January 24, 1991. <s> In the episode, Homer consumes a poisonous fugu fish at a sushi restaurant, and is told that he has only 22 hours left to live. <s> He accepts his fate and makes a list of all the things he wants to do before he dies.
simple: "One Fish, Two Fish, Blowfish, Blue Fish" is the eleventh episode of The Simpsons second season. <s> It first started on the Fox network in the United States on January 24, 1991. <s> In this episode, Homer eats a poisonous fugu fish at a sushi restaurant, and is told that he has only twenty-four hours left to live. <s> He accepts his fate and makes a list of all the things he wants to do before he dies.

title: Aaron Paul
complex: Aaron Paul Sturtevant (born August 27, 1979) is an American actor. <s> He is best known for portraying Jesse Pinkman in the AMC series "Breaking Bad", for which he won several awards, including the Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series (2014), Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actor – Series, Miniseries, or Television Film (2013), and Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series. <s> This made him one of only two actors to win the latter category three times (2010, 2012, 2014), since its separation into comedy and drama. <s> He has also won the Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor on Television three times (2009, 2011, 2013), more than any other actor in that category. <s> Paul began his career with roles in several music videos and guest roles in television, before taking minor roles in films such as "" (2006) and "The Last House on the Left" (2009). <s> In 2007, he had a recurring role as Scott Quittman on the HBO series "Big Love". <s> Following his breakthrough, he began starring in films such as "Need for Speed" (2014), "A Long Way Down" (2014), and "" (2014). <s> Since 2014, he has been the voice of Todd Chavez on the Netflix animated series "BoJack Horseman", on which he is also an executive producer, and portrayed Eddie Lane in the Hulu drama series "The Path" from 2016 to 2018. <s> Aaron Paul Sturtevant was born in Emmett, Idaho, on August 27, 1979, the youngest of four children born to Darla ("née" Haynes) and Robert Sturtevant, a Baptist minister. <s> He was born a month premature in his parents' bathroom.
simple: Aaron Paul Sturtevant (born August 27, 1979) is an American actor. <s> He is best known for his role as Jesse Pinkman on the AMC drama series "Breaking Bad" (2008–2013). <s> The role earned him a Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series in 2010, 2012 and 2014. <s> He has also had roles in movies such as "Need for Speed" (2014), "A Long Way Down" (2014) and "" (2014). <s> He has also voiced Todd Chavez on the Netflix animated series "BoJack Horseman" since 2014. <s> Paul was born in Emmett, Idaho.

title: Arizona
complex: Arizona ( ; ] ; ] ) is a state in the southwestern region of the United States. <s> It is also part of the Western and the Mountain states. <s> It is the sixth largest and the 14th most populous of the 50 states. <s> Its capital and largest city is Phoenix. <s> Arizona shares the Four Corners region with Utah, Colorado, and New Mexico; its other neighboring states are Nevada and California to the west and the Mexican states of Sonora and Baja California to the south and southwest. <s> Southern Arizona is known for its desert climate, with very hot summers and mild winters. <s> Northern Arizona features forests of pine, Douglas fir, and spruce trees; the Colorado Plateau; mountain ranges (such as the San Francisco Mountains); as well as large, deep canyons, with much more moderate summer temperatures and significant winter snowfalls. <s> There are ski resorts in the areas of Flagstaff, Alpine, and Tucson. <s> In addition to the Grand Canyon National Park, there are several national forests, national parks, and national monuments. <s> Arizona became a U.S. state on February 14, 1912. <s> Arizona was the 48th state admitted to the U.S. and the last of the contiguous states to be admitted. <s> Arizona is in the Southwestern United States as one of the Four Corners states. <s> Arizona is the sixth largest state by area, ranked after New Mexico and before Nevada. <s> Of the state's 113998 sqmi , approximately 15% is privately owned. <s> The remaining area is public forest and park land, state trust land and Native American reservations. <s> Arizona is well known for its desert Basin and Range region in the state's southern portions, which is rich in a landscape of xerophyte plants such as the cactus. <s> This region's topography was shaped by prehistoric volcanism, followed by the cooling-off and related subsidence. <s> Its climate has exceptionally hot summers and mild winters. <s> The state is less well known for its pine-covered north-central portion of the high country of the Colorado Plateau (see Arizona Mountains forests). <s> Like other states of the Southwest United States, Arizona has an abundance of mountains and plateaus. <s> Despite the state's aridity, 27% of Arizona is forest, a percentage comparable to modern-day France or Germany . <s> The world's largest stand of ponderosa pine trees is in Arizona. <s> Located in northern Arizona, the Grand Canyon is a colorful, deep, steep-sided gorge, carved by the Colorado River. <s> The canyon is one of the seven natural wonders of the world and is largely contained in the Grand Canyon National Park—one of the first national parks in the United States. <s> President Theodore Roosevelt was a major proponent of designating the Grand Canyon area as a National Park, often visiting to hunt mountain lion and enjoy the scenery. <s> The canyon was created by the Colorado River cutting a channel over millions of years, and is about 277 mi long, ranges in width from 4 to and attains a depth of more than 1 mi . <s> Nearly two billion years of the Earth's history have been exposed as the Colorado River and its tributaries cut through layer after layer of sediment as the Colorado Plateau uplifted. <s> Arizona is home to one of the most well-preserved meteorite impact sites in the world. <s> Created around 50,000 years ago, the Barringer Meteorite Crater (better known simply as "Meteor Crater") is a gigantic hole in the middle of the high plains of the Colorado Plateau, about 25 mi west of Winslow. <s> A rim of smashed and jumbled boulders, some of them the size of small houses, rises 150 ft above the level of the surrounding plain. <s> The crater itself is nearly 1 mi wide, and 570 ft deep. <s> Arizona is one of two U.S. states that do not observe Daylight Saving Time (the other being Hawaii). <s> The exception is within the large Navajo Nation (which observes Daylight Saving Time), in the state's northeastern region. <s> Phoenix, in Maricopa County, is Arizona's capital and largest city. <s> Other prominent cities in the Phoenix metro area include Mesa (Arizona's third largest city), Chandler (Arizona's fourth largest city), Glendale, Peoria, Buckeye, Sun City, Sun City West, Fountain Hills, Surprise, Gilbert, El Mirage, Avondale, Tempe, Tolleson and Scottsdale, with a total metropolitan population of just over 4.7 million. <s> The average high temperature in July, 106 °F , is one of the highest of any metropolitan area in the United States, offset by an average January high temperature of 67 °F , the basis of its winter appeal. <s> The state capital of Arizona is Phoenix. <s> The original Capitol building, with its distinctive copper dome, was dedicated in 1901 (construction was completed for $136,000 in 1900), when the area was a territory. <s> Phoenix became the official state capital with Arizona's admission to the union in 1912. <s> Professional sports teams in Arizona include: State Farm Stadium hosted Super Bowl XLII on February 3, 2008, and Super Bowl XLIX on February 1, 2015. <s> Due to its numerous golf courses, Arizona is home to several stops on the PGA Tour, most notably the Phoenix Open, held at the TPC of Scottsdale, and the WGC-Accenture Match Play Championship at the Ritz-Carlton Golf Club in Marana.
simple: Arizona is a state in the United States of America. <s> The state capital is Phoenix, which also is the largest city in the state. <s> Phoenix is the largest capital city in the US. <s> It is considered part of the Southwestern United States and is bordered by New Mexico to the east, Utah to the north, Nevada to the northwest, California to the west, its northeast corner touches part of Colorado, this area is known as the Four Corners. <s> Arizona's climate can be very hot. <s> Arizona became a state on February 14th, 1912 and became the 48th state accepted into the United States. <s> Arizona is the sixth largest state in area, after New Mexico and before Nevada. <s> Of the state's 113998 sqmi, about 15% is privately owned. <s> The remaining area is public forest and park land, state trust land and Native American reservations. <s> Arizona is best known for its desert landscape. <s> It has plants such as the cactus. <s> It is also known for its climate, which has very hot summers and mild winters. <s> Less well known is the pine-covered high country of the Colorado Plateau in the north-central part of the state. <s> 27% of Arizona is forest. <s> The largest stand of Ponderosa pine trees in the world is in Arizona. <s> The Grand Canyon is a colorful, steep-sided gorge. <s> It is made by the Colorado River in northern Arizona. <s> The canyon is one of the Seven Natural Wonders of the World. <s> Most of the canyon is in the Grand Canyon National Park—one of the first national parks in the United States. <s> Arizona is home to a well-kept meteorite impact site. <s> The Barringer Crater (better known simply as “Meteor Crater”) is a huge hole in the middle of the high plains of the Colorado Plateau. <s> It is about 25 mi west of Winslow. <s> A rim of smashed and jumbled boulders, some of them the size of small houses, rises 150 ft above the level of the surrounding plain. <s> The crater is nearly 1 mile (1.6 km) wide, and 570 ft deep. <s> Arizona is one of two states that does not observe Daylight Saving Time, except in the Navajo Nation in the northeastern part of the state. <s> Professional sports teams in Arizona include: Arizona has many golf courses and is home to several stops on the PGA Tour.

title: Álvaro Recoba
complex: Álvaro Alexánder Recoba Rivero (] ; born 17 March 1976; nickname "El Chino") is a retired Uruguayan footballer who played as a forward or midfielder. <s> Although he began and ended his footballing career in his native country, he also played for several European clubs throughout his career, most notably Italian side Inter Milan, where he spent 11 seasons. <s> Recoba started his career with Uruguay's Danubio. <s> After several years in the Danubio youth teams, he appeared on the first team at age 17 and played for two full seasons, 1994–95 and 1995–96.
simple: Álvaro Recoba (born 17 March 1976) is an Uruguayan football player. <s> He plays for Danubio.

title: Skyland (Washington, D.C.)
complex: Skyland is a neighborhood in Southeast Washington, D.C. <s> It is bounded by Good Hope Road to the northeast, Alabama Avenue to the southeast, and Fort Stanton Park to the south and west. <s> Also see article on Anacostia. <s> The District is in the midst of redeveloping the 18 acre Skyland Shopping Center at Alabama Avenue and Naylor Road, SE in Ward 7 into a mixed-used town center. <s> The District is working with the Rappaport Cos. and the William S. Smith Cos. on a master plan for the site. <s> Initial plans for Skyland Town Center call for more than 320000 sqft of retail space—a combination of high-quality, large format national-brand retailers and neighborhood serving shops and restaurants. <s> The project will also include 420 to 470 units of housing, about 80 percent of the units will be condos and 20 percent will be apartments. <s> The development team expects to have its master plan completed and a Planned Unit Development (PUD) application filed with the Zoning Commission by the spring of 2008. <s> The District and development team are negotiating the business terms of their agreement. <s> The DC Council has already approved a Tax Increment Financing (TIF) package to provide gap financing for the project. <s> Skyland is within the Good Hope neighborhood and borders Hillcrest to the east and Naylor Gardens to the southeast.
simple: Skyland is a neighborhood in Southeast Washington, D.C. <s> It is next to Good Hope Road to the northeast, Alabama Avenue to the southeast, and Fort Stanton Park to the south and west. <s> The District government wants to rebuild the 18 acre Skyland Shopping Center at Alabama Avenue and Naylor Road, SE in Ward 7 into a mixed-used town center. <s> The District is working with the Rappaport Cos. and the William S. Smith Cos. on a new plan for Skyland. <s> They want to build 320000 sqft of retail space. <s> They hope that the new buildings will be filled with high-quality, national stores and locally-owned shops and restaurants. <s> The project will also include 420 to 470 units of housing. <s> About 80 percent of the housing units will be owned by the people who live there and 20 percent will be rented. <s> Rappaport and Smith filed a Planned Unit Development (PUD) application with the Zoning Commission in 2008. <s> The DC Council approved a Tax Increment Financing (TIF) package to loan money for the new buildings. <s> Skyland is a part of the Good Hope neighborhood. <s> Hillcrest to the east and Naylor Gardens to the southeast of the Good Hope neighborhood.

title: Year 2038 problem
complex: The Year 2038 problem relates to representing time in many digital systems as the number of seconds passed since 1 January 1970 and storing it as a signed 32-bit binary integer. <s> Such implementations cannot encode times after 03:14:07 UTC on 19 January 2038. <s> Just like the Y2K problem, the Year 2038 problem is caused by insufficient capacity of the chosen storage unit. <s> Most operating systems designed to run on 64-bit hardware already use signed 64-bit codice_1 integers. <s> Using a signed 64-bit value introduces a new wraparound date that is over twenty times greater than the estimated age of the universe: approximately 292 billion years from now, at 15:30:08 UTC on Sunday, 4 December 292,277,026,596.
simple: The Year 2038 problem could cause problems for computers that use 32 bits of data to store time values, which are represented as the number of seconds since 1st January, 1970, also called the epoch. <s> The problem arises as the biggest number you can store in 32 bits is the equivalent to the 19th January 2038, 03:14:07 UTC. <s> Most 64-bit computers already store the time in a 64-bit number or can be configured to do so.

title: Veal
complex: Veal is the meat of calves, in contrast to the beef from older cattle. <s> Veal can be produced from a calf of either sex and any breed; however, most veal comes from young males of dairy breeds which are not used for breeding. <s> Generally, veal is more expensive than beef from older cattle. <s> Veal production is a way to add value to dairy bull calves and to utilize whey solids, a byproduct from the manufacturing of cheese. <s> Veal has been an important ingredient in Italian, French and other Mediterranean cuisines from ancient times. <s> The veal is often in the form of cutlets, such as the Italian "cotoletta" or the famous Austrian dish Wiener Schnitzel. <s> Some classic French veal dishes include fried "escalopes", fried veal "Grenadines" (small, thick fillet steaks), stuffed "paupiettes", roast joints, and "blanquettes". <s> Because veal is lower in fat than many meats, care must be taken in preparation to ensure that it does not become tough. <s> Veal is often coated in preparation for frying or eaten with a sauce. <s> Veal Parmigiana is a common Italian-American dish made with breaded veal cutlets. <s> Veal production is a controversial topic in animal welfare and some methods are cited as animal cruelty by multiple animal welfare organizations. <s> These organizations and some of their members consider several practices and procedures of veal production to be inhumane. <s> Public efforts by these organizations are placing pressure on the veal industry to change some of its methods. <s> Alternative agricultural uses for male dairy calves include raising bob veal (slaughtered at two or three days old), raising calves as "red veal" without the severe dietary restrictions needed to create pale meat (requiring fewer antibiotic treatments and resulting in lower calf mortality), and as dairy beef. <s> In the US, the use of tethers in veal crates to prevent movement by veal calves was a principal source of controversy in veal farming. <s> Many veal farmers started improving conditions in their veal farms in the 2000s. <s> Veal tethering is criticized because the ability of the calves to move is highly restricted; the crates may have unsuitable flooring; the calves spend their entire lives indoors, experience prolonged sensory, social, and exploratory deprivation; and the calves are more susceptible to high amounts of stress and disease. <s> All milk-fed veal calves in the US are never tethered and are raised in groups by at least 10 weeks of age if not earlier. <s> Veal calf production, as such, is not allowed in many northern European countries, such as in Finland. <s> In Finland, giving feed, drink or other nutrition which is known to be dangerous to an animal which is being cared for is prohibited, as well as failing to give nutrients the lack of which is known to cause the animal to fall ill. <s> The Finnish Animal Welfare Act of 1996 and the Finnish Animal Welfare Decree of 1996 provided general guidelines for the housing and care of animals, and effectively banned veal crates in Finland. <s> Veal crates are not specifically banned in Switzerland, but most calves are raised outdoors. <s> s of 2015 , eight U.S. states ban tethering of calves in veal crates. <s> Nationally, several large veal producers and the American Veal Association are also working to phase out the industry use of tethered veal crates. <s> As of 2017, all American Veal Association members are raising calves in tether free pens and all veal calves are housed in group pens by the time they are 10 weeks of age.
simple: Veal is the meat of young cattle (calves), as opposed to beef from older cattle. <s> Though veal can be made from a calf of either sex and any breed, most veal comes from male calves of dairy cattle breeds. <s> Veal has been an important ingredient in Italian and French cuisine since ancient times. <s> The veal is often in the form of cutlets, such as the Italian cotoletta or the famous Austrian dish Wiener Schnitzel. <s> Some classic French veal dishes include: fried escalopes, fried veal Grenadines (small thick fillet steaks), stuffed paupiettes, roast joints and blanquettes. <s> As veal is lower in fat than many meats, care must be taken in preparation to ensure that it does not become tough. <s> Veal is often coated in preparation for frying or eaten with a sauce. <s> Veal Parmigiana is a common Italian-American dish consisting of breaded veal cutlets. <s> Veal is a controversial issue in terms of animal welfare. <s> Many animal welfare groups, who strongly focus on factory farming, try to educate consumers about several veal production procedures that they consider to be inhumane. <s> This education has been successful in creating pressure on the industry, resulting in recently announced changes in the methods used by the veal industry. <s> Other uses for male dairy calves include raising bob veal (slaughter at 2 or 3 days old), raising calves as "red veal" without the harsh food restrictions needed to create pale meat (resulting in fewer antibiotic treatments and fewer slaughtered calves), and as dairy beef. <s> Many veal farmers listened to the concern of their customers and have started improving conditions in their veal farms. <s> Veal calf production as such is not allowed in many Northern European countries, such as in Finland. <s> In Finland it is illegal to give an animal food the caretaker knows is bad for it, and it is also illegal to not give the animal enough food. <s> Crates are slowly being banned in the United States. <s> As stated above, several large veal producers are working on getting rid of veal crates, as well as the American Veal Association.

title: D. J. Fontana
complex: Dominic Joseph Fontana (March 15, 1931 – June 13, 2018) was an American musician best known as the drummer for Elvis Presley for 14 years. <s> In October 1954 he was hired to play drums for Presley, which marked the beginning of a fifteen-year relationship. <s> He played on over 460 RCA cuts with Elvis. <s> D. J. Fontana was inducted into the Rockabilly Hall of Fame on January 14, 2009, and on April 4, he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, in the "sidemen" category. <s> English musician Wayne Fontana (born Glyn Geoffrey Ellis) took his stage name from the drummer. <s> Fontana died on June 13, 2018 in Nashville at the age of 87. <s> At the time of his death, he was suffering from complications of a broken hip.
simple: Dominic Joseph "D. J." Fontana (March 15, 1931 – June 13, 2018) was an American musician. <s> He was best known as the drummer for Elvis Presley for 14 years. <s> He played on over 460 RCA cuts with Elvis. <s> On April 4, 2009, Fontana was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in Cleveland in the sidemen category. <s> Fontana died on June 13, 2018 in Nashville, Tennessee from complications of a broken hip at the age of 87.

title: Training camp (National Football League)
complex: In the National Football League, training camp refers to the time before the season commences. <s> During this time, teams will sometimes congregate at an outside location, usually a university, to conduct training camp for at least the first few weeks. <s> This is similar to baseball's spring training.
simple: In the National Football League, NFL Training Camp is the time before the season starts. <s> During this time, teams will work hard at an special place, often a university. <s> This is almost the same as baseball's spring training.

title: Crotalus catalinensis
complex: Crotalus catalinensis is a species of venomous pit viper endemic to Isla Santa Catalina in the Gulf of California just off the east coast of the state of Baja California Sur, Mexico. <s> No subspecies are currently recognized. <s> A relatively small and slender species, its most distinctive characteristic is that it lacks a rattle. <s> This snake is found only on Isla Santa Catalina in the Gulf of California off the coast of southern Baja California. <s> This island is also the type locality for the species. <s> While most members of this genus are almost entirely terrestrial due to their heavy body structure, this species' small size makes it a swift and skillful climber. <s> Previous researchers hypothesized that the ability of "C. catalinensis" to climb, combined with its lack of a rattle allowed it to hunt roosting birds, but detailed research into the species’ diet has revealed "C. catalinensis" maintains a mammal-based diet like most rattlesnakes. <s> Further inquiry into the arboreal behavior of this island species has shown individuals actually spend the majority of their time on the ground. <s> Individuals were most likely to be found in low branches of bushes during July, the hottest month on the island. <s> "C. catalinensis" is thought to climb off of the hot ground and into bushes to thermoregulate.
simple: The Santa Catalina Rattlesnake ("Crotalus catalinensis"), also known as the ""Santa Catalina Island Rattlesnake"", is a species of venomous Pit viper found on Santa Catalina Island. <s> There are currently no subspecies recognized. <s> The Santa Catalina Rattlesnake is a small and slender species of rattlesnake. <s> The Santa Catalina Rattlesnake is found on Santa Catalina Island in the Gulf of California. <s> While other rattlesnakes of the genus ""Crotalus"" are mainly terrestrial (live on land), the Santa Catalina Rattlesnake's small size makes it very good climber. <s> In July, the hottest month on Santa Catalina Island, the Santa Catalina Rattlesnake is found on branches of bushes and trees so they can escape the heat on the ground.

title: What Are You Waiting For? (FM Static album)
complex: What Are You Waiting For? <s> is the first album by the pop punk band FM Static. <s> As of the end of 2006, it has sold more than 60,000 copies.
simple: What Are You Waiting For? <s> Although not a bestseller or anything really great, "What Are You Waiting For?" <s> is the debut album from FM Static, a Canadian pop punk band. <s> did manage to sell around 60,000 copies in three and a half years.

title: Joel Hastings Metcalf
complex: Joel Hastings Metcalf (January 4, 1866 – February 23, 1925) was an American astronomer, humanitarian and minister. <s> Reverend Metcalf graduated from Harvard Divinity School in 1892. <s> He served as a Unitarian minister in Burlington, Vermont and in Taunton, Massachusetts, Winchester, Massachusetts and Portland, Maine. <s> He discovered or co-discovered several comets, including 23P/Brorsen-Metcalf and 97P/Metcalf-Brewington, and also 41 asteroids during 1905–1914, as credited by the Minor Planet Center.
simple: Joel Hastings Metcalf (January 4, 1866–February 23, 1925) was an American astronomer. <s> Metcalf graduated from Harvard Divinity School in 1892. <s> He served as a Unitarian minister in Burlington, Vermont and then later in Taunton, Massachusetts, Winchester, Massachusetts and Portland, Maine. <s> He found or co-found many comets, such as 23P/Brorsen-Metcalf and 97P/Metcalf-Brewington; he also found many asteroids.

title: Robert Pires
complex: Robert Emmanuel Pires (born 29 October 1973) is a French football coach and former professional player.
simple: Robert Pirès (born 29 October 1973) is a French football player.

title: Equivalence relation
complex: In mathematics, an equivalence relation is a binary relation that is reflexive, symmetric and transitive. <s> As a consequence of the reflexive, symmetric, and transitive properties, any equivalence relation provides a partition of the underlying set into disjoint equivalence classes. <s> Two elements of the given set are equivalent to each other if and only if they belong to the same equivalence class.
simple: The equivalence relation is a mathematical relation that is symmetric, transitive and reflexive. <s> Using this relation, it is possible to partition a set into (non-empty) subsets, which are called "equivalence classes".

title: Bioleaching
complex: Bioleaching is the extraction of metals from their ores through the use of living organisms. <s> This is much cleaner than the traditional heap leaching using cyanide. <s> Bioleaching is one of several applications within biohydrometallurgy and several methods are used to recover copper, zinc, lead, arsenic, antimony, nickel, molybdenum, gold, silver, and cobalt.
simple: Bioleaching is getting metals from their ores by using living organisms. <s> Bioleaching uses certain types of bacteria to produce a solution called a "leachate". <s> This is much cleaner than the traditional method using cyanide. <s> Bioleaching is one of several methods used to recover copper, zinc, lead, arsenic, antimony, nickel, molybdenum, gold, silver, and cobalt.

title: Kim Yong-il
complex: Kim Yong-il (Korean: , born 2 May 1944) is a North Korean politician. <s> He was the Premier of North Korea from April 2007 to 7 June 2010. <s> He was elected as Premier by the 5th session of the 11th Supreme People's Assembly (SPA) in April 2007, replacing Pak Pong-ju. <s> He was then replaced by Choe Yong-rim after a rare parliamentary session on 7 June 2010.
simple: Kim Yong-il (born 2 May 1944) was the Premier of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea from April 2007 to 7 June 2010. <s> Kim Yong-il was elected Premier of the state at the fifth session of the Workers' Party of Korea National Congress in April 2007 replacing Pak Pong-ju. <s> On June 7 2010 Choe Yong-rim was elected by the National Assembly as his successor.

title: Joseph Engelberger
complex: Engelberger died on December 1, 2015, in Newtown, Connecticut, a little more than four months after celebrating his 90th birthday.
simple: Engelberger died in Newtown, Connecticut from complications following a stroke at the age of 90.

title: Alan Trask
complex: Alan Trask (June 26, 1933 – January 9, 2019) was an American politician in the state of Florida. <s> Trask was born in Bartow, Florida. <s> He attended the University of Florida and Florida Southern College. <s> He was elected to the State Senate for the 27th district in 1968 and served until 1971. <s> He was redistricted to the 13th district in 1973, and served until 1982. <s> He was a former president pro tempore of the senate and was a member of the Democratic Party. <s> In 1981, he and Florida Representative Tom Bush successfully attached an amendment to the state budget that would deny funding to any state university that advocated sexual activity between unmarried adults. <s> Within months, Florida's Supreme Court unanimously ruled the provision an unconstitutional violation of the First Amendment. <s> Shortly thereafter, several ethics allegations were made against Senator Trask, and he resigned from office in July 1982. <s> He later switched to the Republican Party. <s> Trask died on January 9, 2019.
simple: Alan Trask (June 26, 1933 – January 9, 2019) was an American politician. <s> He was born in Bartow, Florida. <s> He was elected to the Florida State Senate for the 27th district in 1968 until 1971. <s> He was redistricted to the 13th district in 1973, and represented it until 1982. <s> He was a former president pro tempore of the senate and was a member of the Democratic Party. <s> He later switched to the Republican Party. <s> Trask died on January 9, 2019 at a hospital in Lakeland, Florida from respiratory failure, aged 85.

title: Bingu wa Mutharika
complex: Bingu wa Mutharika ) (born Brightson Webster Ryson Thom; 24 February 1934 – 5 April 2012) was a Malawian politician and economist who was President of Malawi from May 2004 until his death in April 2012. <s> He was also President of the Democratic Progressive Party, which he founded in February 2005; it obtained a majority in Malawi's parliament in the 2009 general election. <s> During his two terms in office, he was noted for being the Chairperson of the African Union in 2010–2011, as well as for several domestic controversies. <s> In 2009, he purchased a private presidential jet for $13.26 million. <s> This was followed almost immediately by a nationwide fuel shortage which was officially blamed on logistical problems, but was more likely due to the hard currency shortage caused by the freezing of aid by the international community He died of cardiac arrest in Lilongwe while in office on 5 April 2012, at age 78. <s> Mutharika died on 5 April 2012 at the age of 78.
simple: Bingu wa Mutharika (born Brightson Webster Ryson Thom; 24 February 1934 – 5 April 2012) was a Malawian politician and economist. <s> He was President of Malawi from May 2004 until his death in April 2012. <s> He was also President of the Democratic Progressive Party. <s> He was also Chairperson of the African Union in 2010–2011. <s> He died of cardiac arrest in Lilongwe while in office on 5 April 2012, at age 78.

simple: Peray is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Jong Tae-se
complex: Jong Tae-se (romanization used by FIFA, otherwise spelled as Chong Tese (鄭大世; チョン・テセ ) in Japan and Germany; hangul: 정대세, hanja: 鄭大世; (1984--)2 1984 ) is a Japanese-born Korean footballer. <s> He is most remembered for his key performance at 2010 FIFA World Cup representing the North Korea national team.

title: Ronald Buxton (British politician)
complex: Ronald Carlile Buxton (20 August 1923 – 10 January 2017) was a Chartered Structural Engineer, a successful businessman and a Conservative Party politician in the United Kingdom. <s> He married on 20 June 1959, Phyllida, daughter of Captain Henry Roden by Dorothy St John. <s> It was announced on 17 January 2017 that Buxton died on 10 January at the age of 93.
simple: Ronald Carlile Buxton (20 August 1923 – 10 January 2017) was a British politician and civil engineer. <s> He married Phyllida in 1959. <s> Buxton died on 10 January 2017 at the age of 93.

title: MLS Cup 2016
complex: MLS Cup 2016 was the 21st edition of the MLS Cup, the championship game of Major League Soccer (MLS), which took place on December 10, 2016, at BMO Field in Toronto, Ontario, Canada. <s> It was the second final to be hosted in Toronto, after 2010, and the first there since the cup transitioned away from neutral-site venues. <s> The Seattle Sounders won the cup over Toronto FC in a penalty shoot-out that followed a 0–0 draw. <s> Toronto hosted the Philadelphia Union in the single-match knockout round, winning 3–1 and advancing to a series against New York City FC. <s> Toronto won the home leg 2–0, and then proceeded to win 5–0 in New York City, setting a record for largest margin of victory on aggregate. <s> In the Eastern Conference final, Toronto would face their rival Montreal Impact in a bid to be the first Canadian team to play in the MLS Cup.
simple: MLS Cup 2016 was a soccer game played on December 10, 2016. <s> It was the 21st MLS Cup, a special game between the winners of the Eastern and Western Conferences in Major League Soccer. <s> Seattle Sounders FC won the game in a penalty shootout with a score of 5–4 against Toronto FC.. <s> Toronto FC won that game 2–0.

title: Ocean Springs, Mississippi
complex: Ocean Springs is a city in Jackson County, Mississippi, United States, approximately 2 mi east of Biloxi and west of Gautier. <s> It is part of the Pascagoula, Mississippi Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The population was 17,225 at the 2000 U.S. Census. <s> As of the 2010 U.S. Census, the city of Ocean Springs had a population of 17,442.
simple: Ocean Springs is a city in Jackson County, Mississippi, USA, about 2 miles east of Biloxi. <s> It is part of the Pascagoula, Mississippi Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The population was 17,225 at the 2000 census.

complex: Cheyenne is a town in Roger Mills County, Oklahoma, United States. <s> The population was 801 at the 2010 census. <s> It is the county seat of Roger Mills County.

title: Metatarsal bones
complex: The metatarsal bones, or metatarsus are a group of five long bones in the foot, located between the tarsal bones of the hind- and mid-foot and the phalanges of the toes. <s> Lacking individual names, the metatarsal bones are numbered from the medial side (the side of the great toe): the first, second, third, fourth, and fifth metatarsal (often depicted with Roman numerals). <s> The metatarsals are analogous to the metacarpal bones of the hand. <s> The lengths of the metatarsal bones in humans are, in descending order: second, third, fourth, fifth and first. <s> The metatarsal bones are often broken by association football players. <s> These and other recent cases have been attributed to the lightweight design of modern football boots, which provide less protection to the foot. <s> In 2010 some soccer players began testing a new sock that incorporated a rubber silicone pad over the foot to provide protection to the top of the foot. <s> Stress fractures are thought to account for 16% of injuries related to sports participation, and the metatarsals are the bones most often involved.
simple: The metatarsus or metatarsal bones are a group of five long bones in the foot. <s> They are between the tarsal bones of the hind and mid-foot and the phalanges of the toes. <s> The metatarsal bones are numbered from the side of the large toe: the first, second, third, fourth, and fifth metatarsal. <s> They can be numbered with Roman numerals. <s> The metatarsals are like the metacarpal bones of the hand. <s> The metatarsal bones are often broken by soccer players. <s> This may be caused by the lightweight design of modern football boots, which give less protection to the foot. <s> In 2010 some soccer players began testing a new sock that had a rubber silicon pad over the foot to protect the top of the foot.

title: Interstate 68
complex: Interstate 68 (I-68) is a 112.9 mi Interstate Highway in the U.S. states of West Virginia and Maryland, connecting I-79 in Morgantown, West Virginia, to I-70 in Hancock, Maryland. <s> I-68 is also Corridor E of the Appalachian Development Highway System.
simple: Interstate 68 is an Interstate Highway in the United States. <s> It goes from Morgantown, West Virginia east to Hancock, Maryland. <s> The route is 112.9 mi long.

title: Ken Kercheval
complex: Ken Kercheval (July 15, 1935 – April 21, 2019) was an American actor, best known for his role as Cliff Barnes on the television series "Dallas" and its 2012 revival. <s> Kercheval died of pneumonia on April 21, 2019, at the age of 83.
simple: Ken Kercheval (July 15, 1935 – April 21, 2019) was an American actor. <s> He was best known for his role as Cliff Barnes on the 1980s television series "Dallas" and its 2012 revival. <s> Kercheval died of pneumonia in Clinton, Indiana on April 21, 2019 at the age of 83.

title: Tommy Gemmell
complex: Thomas Gemmell (16 October 1943 – 2 March 2017) was a Scottish football player and manager. <s> Although right-footed, he excelled as a left-sided fullback and had powerful shooting ability. <s> Gemmell is best known as one of the Celtic side who won the 1966–67 European Cup; he scored the first Celtic goal in the final. <s> Gemmell played 18 times for Scotland, and also played for Nottingham Forest, Miami Toros and Dundee. <s> After retiring as a player in 1977, Gemmell managed Dundee and Albion Rovers. <s> Gemmell died on 2 March 2017, aged 73, after a long illness. <s> His funeral was held on 10 March with a procession starting from Celtic Park, and was attended by former teammates, serving Celtic manager Brendan Rodgers and Rangers managing director Stewart Robertson.
simple: Thomas "Tommy" Gemmell (16 October 1943 – 2 March 2017) was a Scottish football player and manager. <s> He served as a left-sided fullback and had powerful shooting ability. <s> Gemmell is best known as one of the Celtic side who won the 1966–67 European Cup; he scored the first Celtic goal in the final. <s> Gemmell played 18 times for Scotland, and also played for Nottingham Forest, Miami Toros and Dundee. <s> After retiring as a player in 1977, Gemmell managed Dundee and Albion Rovers. <s> Gemmell died on 2 March 2017, aged 73, after a long illness.

title: Merle Travis
complex: Merle Robert Travis (November 29, 1917 – October 20, 1983) was an American country and western singer, songwriter, and guitarist born in Rosewood, Kentucky. <s> His songs' lyrics often discussed both the lives and the economic exploitation of American coal miners. <s> Among his many well-known songs are "Sixteen Tons," "Re-Enlistment Blues," "I am a Pilgrim," and "Dark as a Dungeon." <s> However, it is his unique guitar style, still called Travis Picking by guitarists, as well as his interpretations of the rich musical traditions of his native Muhlenberg County, Kentucky, for which he is best known today. <s> "Travis Picking" is a syncopated style of guitar fingerpicking rooted in ragtime music in which alternating chords and bass notes are plucked by the thumb while melodies are simultaneously plucked by the index finger. <s> He was inducted into the Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame in 1970 and elected to the Country Music Hall of Fame in 1977.
simple: Merle Robert Travis (November 29, 1917 – October 20, 1983) was an American country singer, songwriter and guitarist. <s> He was born in Rosewood, Kentucky. <s> Travis wrote many well-known songs including: "Sixteen Tons." <s> Travis is best known for his masterful guitar playing style. <s> The style of finger-picking known as "Travis picking" is named after him. <s> He was inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame in 1977.

title: Ronneby
complex: Ronneby is a locality and the seat of Ronneby Municipality in Blekinge County, Sweden with 12,029 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Ronneby is a town in the county of Blekinge in Sweden. <s> It is the seat of Ronneby Municipality.

title: Bee Cave, Texas
complex: Bee Cave is a city located in Travis County, and within the United States state of Texas. <s> The population was estimated at 6,535 as of 2016.
simple: Bee Cave is a city in Travis County, Texas, United States.

title: Fernando Birri
complex: Fernando Birri (March 13, 1925 – December 27, 2017) was an Argentine film maker and theorist. <s> He was considered by many to be the father of the new Latin American cinema. <s> Birri was born in Santa Fe, Argentina. <s> After being involved in theater and poetry, he went to Rome to study film-making at the "Centro Sperimentale di Cinematografia", from 1950 to 1953, and appeared in the 1955 Italian film "Gli Sbandati". <s> In 1956 he returned to Santa Fe, to form the Film Institute at the Universidad Nacional del Litoral university. <s> A year later he started filming scenes of poverty and human misery in lower-class Santa Fe. <s> The project, billed as a "survey film", spanned three years, and filming wrapped up in 1958. <s> Before screening the resulting 33-minute documentary, "Tire dié", Birri debuted with a short film called "La primera fundación de Buenos Aires", which premiered in the 1959 Cannes Film Festival, earning Birri critical acclaim and paving his way for further projects of similar nature, like "Buenos Días, Buenos Aires" (1960) and more famously "Los inundados" (1961), which won the Venice Film Festival award for Best First Film. <s> In 1986 Birri co-founded Escuela Internacional de Cine y Television (The International School of Film and Television), in San Antonio de Los Baños, Cuba. <s> He was the school's first director.
simple: Fernando Birri (March 13, 1925 – December 28, 2017) was an Argentine filmmaker, screenwriter, actor, critic and theorist. <s> He was thought by many to be the father of the new Latin American cinema. <s> He was born in Santa Fe, Argentina. <s> Birri debuted with a short movie called "La primera fundación de Buenos Aires", which premiered in the 1959 Cannes Film Festival. <s> In 1986 Birri co-founded Escuela Internacional de Cine y Television (The International School of Film and Television), in San Antonio de Los Baños, Cuba.

title: Fine-needle aspiration
complex: Fine-needle aspiration (FNA) is a diagnostic procedure used to investigate lumps or masses. <s> In this technique, a thin (23–25 gauge), hollow needle is inserted into the mass for sampling of cells that, after being stained, will be examined under a microscope (biopsy). <s> The sampling and biopsy considered together are called fine-needle aspiration biopsy (FNAB) or fine-needle aspiration cytology (FNAC) (the latter to emphasize that any aspiration biopsy involves cytopathology, not histopathology). <s> Fine-needle aspiration biopsies are very safe minor surgical procedures. <s> Often, a major surgical (excisional or open) biopsy can be avoided by performing a needle aspiration biopsy instead, eliminating the need for hospitalization. <s> In 1981, the first fine-needle aspiration biopsy in the United States was done at Maimonides Medical Center.
simple: Needle aspiration biopsy (NAB), also known as fine needle aspiration cytology (FNAC), fine needle aspiration biopsy (FNAB) and fine needle aspiration (FNA), is a medical procedure performed to diagnose certain kinds of medical conditions, such as lumps in the neck. <s> A thin needle is inserted into a mass or lump to extract cells that will be examined under a microscope. <s> Fine needle aspiration biopsies are very safe, minor surgical procedures. <s> Often, a major surgical (excisional or open) biopsy can be avoided by performing a needle aspiration biopsy instead.

title: United States Secretary of Defense
complex: The secretary of defense (SecDef) is the leader and chief executive officer of the United States Department of Defense, the executive department of the Armed Forces of the U.S. <s> The secretary of defense's position of command and authority over the U.S. military is second only to that of the president. <s> This position corresponds to what is generally known as a defense minister in many other countries. <s> The secretary of defense is appointed by the president with the advice and consent of the Senate, and is by custom a member of the Cabinet and by law a member of the National Security Council. <s> Democratic Republican Political Independent / Unknown <s> The secretary of defense is sixth in the presidential line of succession, following the secretary of the treasury and preceding the attorney general.
simple: The United States Secretary of Defense (SECDEF) is the head of the U.S. Department of Defense (DoD). <s> Democratic Political Independent / Unknown Denotes an "Acting Secretary of Defense" <s> The Secretary of Defense is sixth in line to the United States presidential line of succession.

title: Steve Dubinsky
complex: Steven Dubinsky (born July 9, 1970) is a retired professional ice hockey player who played in the NHL with the Chicago Blackhawks, Calgary Flames, Nashville Predators and St. Louis Blues. <s> He played centre and shot left-handed. <s> Dubinsky was drafted in the 11th round, 226th overall in the 1990 NHL Entry Draft. <s> From there he played for Clarkson University, where he played right wing from 1989-1993 for the Clarkson Golden Knights men's ice hockey team, led the team in scoring his junior year, was named a 1992 Eastern College Athletic Conference (ECAC) All-Star honorable mention, and played with future NHLers Craig Conroy and Todd Marchant. <s> After college Dubinsky reported to the Indianapolis Ice of the IHL where he played the majority of the 1993–1994 season before playing 28 games with the Blackhawks that same season. <s> Dubinsky bounced between the Ice and the Blackhawks before finally earning a full-time roster spot with the Blackhawks for the 1997–98 season. <s> That year he played in all 82 games and scored a career high 18 points. <s> The following season he played one game with the Blackhawks before being traded to the Calgary Flames. <s> He played there for 2 years before rejoining the Blackhawks for the 2000–01 season. <s> The 2001–02 season saw Dubinsky being traded yet again from the Blackhawks, this time to the Nashville Predators.
simple: Steven Dubinsky (born July 9, 1970 in Montreal, Quebec) is a Canadian retired professional ice hockey centre. <s> He played for the Chicago Blackhawks, Calgary Flames, Nashville Predators, and St. Louis Blues <s> He was drafted 226th overall by the Chicago Blackhawks in the 1990 NHL Entry Draft. <s> Before he played in the NHL, Dubinsky played 4 seasons at Clarkson University. <s> From 1993 to 1998, Dubinsky would play for both the Indianapolis Ice of the International Hockey League and the Chicago Blackhawks. <s> He was traded to the Calgary Flames and played 2 seasons with them. <s> He rejoined the Blackhawks in the 2000-01 NHL season and played 2 seasons with them before being traded by the Blackhawks to the Nashville Predators.

title: Annonaceae
complex: The Annonaceae are a family of flowering plants consisting of trees, shrubs, or rarely lianas commonly known as the custard apple family or soursop family. <s> With 108 accepted genera and about 2400 known species, it is the largest family in the Magnoliales. <s> Several genera produce edible fruit, most notably "Annona", "Anonidium", "Asimina", "Rollinia", and "Uvaria". <s> Its type genus is "Annona". <s> The family is concentrated in the tropics, with few species found in temperate regions. <s> About 900 species are Neotropical, 450 are Afrotropical, and the remaining are Indomalayan.
simple: Annonaceae the custard-apple, or annona family, the largest family of the magnolia order. <s> It has 129 genera and 2,220 species. <s> The family consists of trees, shrubs, and woody climbers found mainly in the tropics, with a few species in temperate regions.

title: List of World Heritage Sites in India
complex: The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) World Heritage Sites are important places of cultural or natural heritage as described in the UNESCO World Heritage Convention, established in 1972. <s> Apart from the 38 sites inscribed on the World Heritage List, there is a list of tentative sites for recognition which has been submitted to the UNESCO Committee for evaluation and acceptance. <s> This procedure of prelisting is a prerequisite for the nominations for the World Heritage List to be accepted.
simple: The List of World Heritage Sites in India is a group of places chosen by UNESCO, the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization. <s> There are 48 sites which are on a tentative list.

title: Arrondissement of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne
complex: The arrondissement of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne is an arrondissement of France in the Savoie department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> It has 53 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne is an arrondissement of France. <s> It is part of the Savoie "département", Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> When the Savoie department was created in 1860, the "arrondissement" of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne was part of that original department. <s> The "arrondissement" of Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne is bordered to the north by the "arrondissement" of Albertville, to the east by Italy, to the south by the Hautes-Alpes department, to the west by the Isère department and to the northwest by the "arrondissement" of Chambéry.

title: Henschel Hs 123
complex: The Henschel Hs 123 was a single-seat biplane dive bomber and close-support attack aircraft flown by the German "Luftwaffe" during the Spanish Civil War and the early to midpoint of World War II. <s> It proved to be robust, durable and effective especially in severe conditions.
simple: The Henschel Hs 123 is a biplane built in Nazi Germany as a dive bomber.

title: 4 Strings
complex: 4 Strings are a Dutch vocal trance group. <s> The group was founded by Carlo Resoort and Jan De Vos.
simple: 4 Strings is a Dutch techno music group with a female lead singer.

title: SST Records
complex: SST Records is an American independent record label formed in 1978 in Long Beach, California by musician Greg Ginn. <s> The company was formed in 1966 by Ginn at age 12 as Solid State Tuners, a small business through which he sold electronics equipment. <s> Ginn repurposed the company as a record label to release material by his band Black Flag.
simple: SST Records is an American independent record label formed in 1978 in Long Beach, California by musician Greg Ginn. <s> The company was initially called Solid State Transmitters through which Ginn sold electronics equipment. <s> Ginn repurposed the company as a record label to release material by his band Black Flag.

title: Bud Spencer
complex: Carlo Pedersoli (October 31, 1929 – June 27, 2016), known professionally as Bud Spencer, was an Italian actor, professional swimmer and water polo player. <s> He was known for action-comedy and Spaghetti Western roles with his long-time film partner Terence Hill. <s> The duo "garnered world acclaim and attracted millions to theater seats".
simple: Bud Spencer (born Carlo Pedersoli; 31 October 1929 – 27 June 2016) was an Italian actor, filmmaker and a former professional swimmer. <s> He was known for working on comedy movies with his longtime friend Terence Hill.

complex: This is a list of winners and nominees for the Anthony Asquith Award for Film Music (or BAFTA Award for Best Film Music), which is presented to film composers, given out by the British Academy of Film and Television Arts since 1968. <s> 1980: "The Empire Strikes Back" – John Williams <s> 1981: "The French Lieutenant's Woman" – Carl Davis <s> 1982: "E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial" – John Williams <s> 1983: "Merry Christmas, Mr. Lawrence" – Ryuichi Sakamoto <s> 1984: "Once Upon a Time in America" – Ennio Morricone <s> 1985: "Witness" – Maurice Jarre <s> 1989: "Dead Poets Society" – Maurice Jarre <s> 1990: "Cinema Paradiso (Nuovo Cinema Paradiso)" – Andrea Morricone and Ennio Morricone <s> 1991: "Cyrano de Bergerac" – Jean-Claude Petit <s> 1992: "Strictly Ballroom" – David Hirschfelder <s> 1993: "Schindler's List" – John Williams <s> Anthony Asquith Award for Film Music <s> 1994: "Backbeat" – Don Was <s> 1995: "" - Luis Enríquez Bacalov <s> 1996: "The English Patient" – Gabriel Yared <s> 1997: "Romeo + Juliet" – Nellee Hooper, Craig Armstrong, and Marius de Vries <s> 1998: "Elizabeth" – David Hirschfelder <s> 1999: "American Beauty" – Thomas Newman <s> 2000: "Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon (Wo hu cang long)" – Tan Dun <s> – Craig Armstrong and Marius de Vries <s> 2002: "The Hours" – Philip Glass <s> 2003: "Cold Mountain" – T Bone Burnett and Gabriel Yared <s> 2004: "The Motorcycle Diaries (Diarios de motocicleta)" – Gustavo Santaolalla <s> 2005: "Memoirs of a Geisha" – John Williams <s> 2006: "Babel" – Gustavo Santaolalla <s> 2007: "La Vie en Rose (La môme)" – Christopher Gunning <s> 2008: "Slumdog Millionaire" – A.
