title: Peter Lax
complex: Peter David Lax (born Lax Péter Dávid; 1 May 1926) is a Hungarian-born American mathematician working in the areas of pure and applied mathematics. <s> Lax has made important contributions to integrable systems, fluid dynamics and shock waves, solitonic physics, hyperbolic conservation laws, and mathematical and scientific computing, among other fields. <s> Lax was born in Budapest, Hungary to a Jewish family. <s> Lax began displaying an interest in mathematics at age twelve, and soon his parents hired Rózsa Péter as a tutor for him. <s> His parents Klara Kornfield and Henry Lax were both physicians and his uncle Albert Kornfeld (also known as Albert Korodi) was a mathematician, as well as a friend of Leó Szilárd. <s> Lax is listed as an ISI highly cited researcher. <s> According to György Marx he was one of The Martians.
simple: Peter David Lax (born 1 May 1926) is an American mathematician. <s> He is known for his works in integrable systems, fluid dynamics and shock waves, solitonic physics, hyperbolic conservation laws, and mathematical and scientific computing, among other fields. <s> Lax is of Jewish descent. <s> Lax is listed as an ISI highly cited researcher.

title: List of World Heritage Sites in the Netherlands
complex: This is a list of World Heritage Sites in the Netherlands with properties of cultural and natural heritage in the Netherlands as inscribed in UNESCO's World Heritage List or as on the country's tentative list. <s> The Netherlands, with an extension to Curaçao, accepted the Convention Concerning the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage on 26 August 1992, after which it could nominate properties on their territory to be considered for the World Heritage List. <s> Currently, 10 properties in the Netherlands and Curaçao are inscribed on the World Heritage List. <s> Nine of these are cultural properties and one is a natural property. <s> The first was added to the list in 1995 and the latest in 2014. <s> Eight properties are in the Netherlands, one is in Curaçao, and one is in both the Netherlands and Germany. <s> The tentative list of the Netherlands contains eight properties, all of which were submitted on 17 August 2011.
simple: This is a list of World Heritage Sites in the Netherlands with properties of cultural and natural heritage in the Netherlands that are on UNESCO's World Heritage List. <s> Currently, nine properties in the Netherlands and Curaçao are on the World Heritage List. <s> Eight of these are cultural properties and one is a natural property. <s> The first was added to the list in 1995 and the latest in 2010. <s> Seven properties are in the Netherlands, one is in Curaçao, and one is in both the Netherlands and Germany.

title: 2013 Football League Cup Final
complex: The 2013 Football League Cup Final was a football match between Bradford City and Swansea City, which took place on 24 February 2013 at Wembley Stadium in London. <s> It was the final match of the 2012–13 Football League Cup, the 53rd season of the Football League Cup, a football competition for the 92 teams in the Premier League and the Football League. <s> Swansea won the match 5–0, and qualified for the 2013–14 UEFA Europa League, entering in the third qualifying round. <s> Although based in Wales, their participation in the English football league system means they took one of the English berths in the competition.
simple: The 2013 Football League Cup Final is a football match between Bradford City and Swansea City, which will take place on 24 February 2013 at Wembley Stadium, London. <s> It is the final match of the 2012–13 Football League Cup, the 53rd season of the Football League Cup, a football competition for the 92 teams in the Premier League and the Football League. <s> The winner of the Football League Cup will enter the 2013–14 UEFA Europa League in the third qualifying round.

title: Hippolyta
complex: In Classical Greek mythology, Hippolyta ( ; Greek: "Hippolyte") was the Amazonian queen who possessed a magical girdle (a waist belt that signified her authority as queen of the Amazons) given to her by her father Ares, the god of war. <s> Hippolyta figures prominently in the myths of both Heracles and Theseus.
simple: Hippolyta (, "Hippolyte") was one of the queens of the Amazons in Greek mythology. <s> She was mostly famous for her magical girdle (or war belt in other accounts), given to her by her father, Ares, the god of war.

title: Stress–strain analysis
complex: Stress–strain analysis (or stress analysis) is an engineering discipline that uses many methods to determine the stresses and strains in materials and structures subjected to forces. <s> In continuum mechanics, stress is a physical quantity that expresses the internal forces that neighboring particles of a continuous material exert on each other, while strain is the measure of the deformation of the material. <s> Stress analysis is a primary task for civil, mechanical and aerospace engineers involved in the design of structures of all sizes, such as tunnels, bridges and dams, aircraft and rocket bodies, mechanical parts, and even plastic cutlery and staples. <s> Stress analysis is also used in the maintenance of such structures, and to investigate the causes of structural failures.
simple: Stress analysis is the study of stresses and strains in materials and structures as force is applied against them. <s> Stress analysis is about finding out how much stress causes deformation in a given material. <s> Stress analysis is an important task for civil, mechanical and aerospace engineers. <s> They work on the design of structures of all sizes, such as bridges and dams, machines, and even plastic cutlery and staples. <s> Stress analysis is also used in the maintenance of such structures, and to investigate the causes of structural failures.

title: Aster Berkhof
complex: Lous Paulina Van Den Bergh (born 18 June 1920), known as Lode Van Den Bergh, who uses the pseudonyms Aster Berkhof and Piet Visser, is a Belgian writer. <s> He is married to Nora Steyaert. <s> He was born in Rijkevorsel. <s> He started his career as a monitor at the Catholic University of Leuven, subsequently he worked as a teacher at the Royal Athenaea in Antwerp, Brussels and Koekelberg. <s> Finally he became a professor at the "Saint Ignatius Faculty" in Antwerp.
simple: Lode Van Den Bergh (born 18 June 1920), pseudonym Aster Berkhof and Piet Visser, is a Belgian writer. <s> He is married to Nora Steyaert. <s> He was born in Rijkevorsel. <s> He started his career as a monitor at the Catholic University of Leuven. <s> He also worked as a teacher at the Royal Athenaea in Antwerp, Brussels and Koekelberg. <s> Finally he became a professor at the "Saint Ignatius Faculty" in Antwerp.

title: Paaliaq
complex: Paaliaq is a prograde irregular satellite of Saturn. <s> It was discovered by Brett J. Gladman, John J. Kavelaars, Jean-Marc Petit, Hans Scholl, Matthew J. Holman, Brian G. Marsden, Philip D. Nicholson and Joseph A. Burns in early October 2000, and given the temporary designation S/2000 S 2. <s> It was named in August 2003 after a fictional shaman in the book "The Curse of the Shaman," written by Michael Kusugak, who supplied Kavelaars with the names of giants from Inuit mythology that were used for other Saturnian moons. <s> Paaliaq is thought to be about 22 kilometres in diameter, and orbits Saturn at an average distance of 15.2 million km in 687 days. <s> It is a member of the Inuit group of irregular satellites. <s> It also has a proximity with 9 other moons reaching up to ten miles from each.
simple: Paaliaq is a non-spherical moon of Saturn. <s> It was found by Brett J. Gladman, John J. Kavelaars, Jean-Marc Petit, Hans Scholl, Matthew J. Holman, Brian G. Marsden, Philip D. Nicholson and Joseph A. Burns in early October 2000, and given the designation S/2000 S 2. <s> It was named in August 2003 after a fictional shaman in the book "The Curse of the Shaman," written by Michael Kusugak, who supplied Kavelaars with the names of giants from Inuit mythology that were used for other Saturnian moons. <s> Paaliaq is thought to be about 22 kilometres in diameter, and orbits Saturn at an average distance of 15,200,000 km in 687 days. <s> It is a member of the Inuit group of non-spherical moons.

title: Wood Buffalo National Park
complex: Wood Buffalo National Park is the largest National Park of Canada at 44807 sqkm . <s> It is located in northeastern Alberta and the southern Northwest Territories. <s> Larger in area than Switzerland, it is the second-largest national park in the world. <s> The park was established in 1922 to protect the world's largest herd of free roaming wood bison, currently estimated at more than 5,000. <s> It is one of two known nesting sites of whooping cranes. <s> This area was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 for the biological diversity of the Peace-Athabasca Delta, one of the world's largest freshwater deltas, as well as the population of wild bison. <s> Wood Buffalo National Park contains a large variety of wildlife species, such as moose, bison, great grey owls, black bears, hawks, spotted owls, timber wolves, lynxes, beavers, snowy owls, marmots, bald eagles, martens, wolverines, peregrine falcons, whooping cranes, snowshoe hares, sandhill cranes, ruffed grouses, and the world's northernmost population of red-sided garter snakes, which form communal dens within the park. <s> Wood Buffalo Park contains the only natural nesting habitat for the endangered whooping crane. <s> Known as Whooping Crane Summer Range, it is classified as a Ramsar site.
simple: Wood Buffalo National Park is a national park and the largest one in Canada. <s> The park is located in northeastern Alberta and southern Northwest Territories. <s> It was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 because of it's biological diversity of the Peace-Athabasca Delta, which is one of the world's largest freshwater deltas, as well as the population of wild bison. <s> The park is also populated by moose, wood bison, black bear, wolf, lynx, beaver, brown bear, snowshoe hare, Sandhill Crane, Ruffed Grouse, and the world's northernmost population of Red-sided Garter Snakes. <s> Inside the park is the only natural nesting habitat for the endangered Whooping Crane.

title: Finney County, Kansas
complex: Finney County (county code FI) is a county located in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the county population was 36,776. <s> Its county seat and most populous city is Garden City. <s> Finney County began about 1880 as Buffalo County and Sequoyah County, named after Sequoyah, the Cherokee Indian responsible for the development of the Cherokee alphabet. <s> The two counties were renamed Finney County in honor of then Lieutenant Governor David Wesley Finney. <s> The county grew to the current shape after Garfield County was annexed to it in 1893. <s> The northeast block, separate from the otherwise rectangular area, represents what at one time was Garfield County, which is now occupied partially by the Garfield Township. <s> Charles "Buffalo" Jones, a co-founder of Garden City, was the first member of the Kansas House of Representatives from Finney County. <s> He was known for his efforts to preserve the buffalo from extinction. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 1303 sqmi , of which 1302 sqmi is land and 0.7 sqmi (0.05%) is water. <s> It is the second-largest county in Kansas by area. <s> Finney County is included in the Garden City, KS Micropolitan Statistical Area. <s> As of the 2010 census there were 36,776 people, 12,359 households and 8,903 families residing in the county. <s> The racial makeup of the county was 77.0% White, 2.3% Black or African American, 0.9% Native American, 3.4% Asian, 0.0% Pacific Islander, 13.6% from other races, and 2.9% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino of any race were 46.7% of the population. <s> Finney County has primarily supported Republican presidential candidates throughout its history. <s> In only six elections from 1888 to the present has the county not backed the Republican candidate, the last of these being in 1976 when Jimmy Carter won the county by only 102 votes.
simple: Finney County (county code FI) is a county in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> In 2010, 36,776 people lived there. <s> Its county seat is Garden City. <s> Finney County was created around 1880. <s> It was called Buffalo County and Sequoyah County. <s> They were named after Sequoyah, the Cherokee Indian responsible for the creation of the Cherokee alphabet. <s> The two counties were renamed Finney County. <s> It was named after Lieutenant Governor David Wesley Finney. <s> Charles "Buffalo" Jones was the first member of the Kansas House of Representatives from Finney County. <s> He tried to stop the buffalo from extinction. <s> The U.S. Census Bureau says that the county has a total area of 1303 sqmi. <s> Of that, 1302 sqmi is land and 0.7 sqmi (0.05%) is water. <s> It is the second-largest county in Kansas by area. <s> Finney County is included in the Garden City, KS Micropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The 2010 census says that there were 36,776 people, 12,359 households and 8,903 families living in Finney County. <s> Finney County has often supported Republican presidential candidates. <s> This was when Jimmy Carter won the county by only 102 votes.

title: Requiem shark
complex: Requiem sharks are sharks of the family Carcharhinidae in the order Carcharhiniformes. <s> They are migratory, live-bearing sharks of warm seas (sometimes of brackish or fresh water) such as the spinner shark, the blacknose shark, the blacktip shark, the grey reef shark, the blacktip reef shark, and the Oceanic whitetip shark.
simple: Carcharhinidae, also known as the requiem sharks, is a family of sharks in the order Carcharhiniformes.

title: Katharine, Duchess of Kent
complex: Katharine, Duchess of Kent, (born Katharine Lucy Mary Worsley; 22 February 1933) is a member of the British royal family. <s> Her husband, Prince Edward, Duke of Kent, is a first cousin of Queen Elizabeth II. <s> The Duchess of Kent gained attention for her conversion to Catholicism in 1994; she was the first member of the royal family to convert publicly since the passing of the Act of Settlement 1701. <s> The Duchess of Kent is strongly associated with the world of music and has performed as a member of several choirs.
simple: Katharine, Duchess of Kent, (born Katharine Lucy Mary Worsley; 22 February 1933), is a member of the British Royal Family. <s> Her husband, Prince Edward, Duke of Kent, is a first cousin of Queen Elizabeth II. <s> The Duchess of Kent became famous her conversion to Catholicism in 1994, the first member of the Royal Family to convert publicly since 1701. <s> The Duchess of Kent is strongly associated with the world of music, and has performed as a member of several choirs.

title: Cedar Rapids, Iowa
complex: Cedar Rapids is the second-largest city in Iowa and is the county seat of Linn County. <s> The city lies on both banks of the Cedar River, 20 mi north of Iowa City and 100 mi northeast of Des Moines, the state's capital and largest city.
simple: Cedar Rapids is the second largest city in the U.S. state of Iowa. <s> It is the county seat of Linn County.

title: César Sampaio
complex: Carlos César Sampaio Campos (born 31 March 1968) is a Brazilian former footballer, who played as a midfielder. <s> He is a football analyst for ESPN Brasil.
simple: César Sampaio (born 31 March 1968) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Amicus curiae
complex: An amicus curiae (literally, "friend of the court"; plural, amici curiae) is someone who is not a party to a case and may or may not have been solicited by a party and who assists a court by offering information, expertise, or insight that has a bearing on the issues in the case; and is typically presented in the form of a brief. <s> The decision on whether to consider an amicus brief lies within the discretion of the court. <s> The phrase "amicus curiae" is legal Latin. <s> The "amicus curiae" figure originates in Roman law. <s> Starting in the 9th century, it was incorporated into English law, and it was later extended to most common law systems. <s> Later, it was introduced in international law, in particular concerning human rights. <s> From there, it was integrated in some civil law systems (it has recently been integrated into Argentina's law system and Honduras's 2010 civil procedures code). <s> Today, it is used by the European Court of Human Rights, the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights, the Inter-American Court of Human Rights, the Court of Justice of the European Union and the Special Tribunal for Lebanon. <s> The situation most often noted in the press is when an advocacy group files a brief in a case before an appellate court in which it is not a litigant. <s> Appellate cases are normally limited to the factual record and arguments coming from the lower court case under appeal; attorneys focus on the facts and arguments most favorable to their clients. <s> Where a case may have broader implications, "amicus curiae" briefs are a way to articulate those concerns, so that the possibly broad legal or public policy ramifications of the court's anticipated decisions will not depend solely on the positions and arguments advanced by the parties directly involved in the case. <s> In prominent cases, "amici curiae" are generally organizations with sizable legal budgets. <s> In the United States, for example, non-profit legal advocacy organizations, such as the American Civil Liberties Union, the Landmark Legal Foundation, the Pacific Legal Foundation, the Electronic Frontier Foundation, the American Center for Law and Justice or NORML, frequently submit such briefs to advocate for or against a particular legal change or interpretation. <s> If a decision could affect an entire industry, companies other than the litigants may wish to have their concerns heard. <s> In the United States, federal courts often hear cases involving the constitutionality of state laws. <s> Hence states may file briefs as "amici curiae" when their laws or interests are likely to be affected, as in the Supreme Court case "McDonald v. Chicago," when thirty-two states under the aegis of Texas (and California independently) filed such briefs. <s> "Amici curiae" who do not file briefs often present an academic perspective on the case. <s> For example, if the law gives deference to a history of legislation of a certain topic, a historian may choose to evaluate the claim from specialized expertise. <s> An economist, statistician, or sociologist may choose to do the same. <s> Newspaper editorials, blogs, and other opinion pieces arguably have the capability to influence Supreme Court decisions as "de facto amici curiae". <s> They are not, however, technically considered "amicus curiae," as they do not submit materials to the Court, do not need to ask for leave, and have no guarantee that they will be read. <s> The Supreme Court of the United States has special rules for "amicus curiae" briefs sought to be filed in cases pending before it. <s> Supreme Court Rule 37 states, in part, such a brief should cover "relevant matter" not dealt with by the parties which "may be of considerable help". <s> The cover of an "amicus" brief must identify which party the brief is supporting, or if the brief supports only affirmance or reversal. <s> The Court also requires that, "inter alia", all non-governmental amici identify those providing a monetary contribution to the preparation or submission of the brief. <s> Briefs must be prepared in booklet format, and 40 copies must be served with the Court. <s> In the United States Supreme Court, unless the "amicus" brief is being filed by the federal government (or one of its officers or agents) or a U.S. state, permission of the court (by means of motion for leave) or mutual consent of the parties is generally required. <s> Allowing an "amicus curiae" to present oral argument is considered "extraordinary". <s> The court can also appoint its own "amicus curiae" if neither party supports the decision of the lower court, which it has done at least 44 times. <s> The role of "amicus curiae" briefs in the World Trade Organization (WTO) dispute settlement system is controversial. <s> The controversy arises due to the governmental nature of WTO disputes. <s> As only WTO members have access to the system, any non-members such as non-governmental organizations (NGOs) are excluded and have no right to be heard. <s> Thus the only way for them to contribute to a WTO decision is through "amicus curiae" briefs. <s> To date there is a divergence in approaches in the WTO as to the admissibility of such briefs.

of the parties to assist a court. <s> The decision on whether to admit the information lies at the discretion of the court. <s> The phrase "amicus curiae" is legal Latin. <s> The "amicus curiae" Chicago," when thirty-two states under the aegis of Texas (and California independently) filed such briefs. <s> "Amici curiae" who do not file briefs often present an academic perspective on the case. <s> Newspaper editorials, blogs, and other opinion pieces arguably have the capability to influence Supreme Court decisions as "de facto amici curiae". <s> They are not, however, technically considered "amicus curiae," as they do not submit materials to the Court, do not need to ask for leave, and have no guarantee that they will be read. <s> The Supreme Court of the United States has special rules for "amicus curiae" briefs sought to be filed in cases pending before it. <s> Supreme Court Rule 37 states, in part, such a brief should cover "relevant matter" not dealt with by the parties which "may be of considerable help". <s> The cover of an "amicus" brief must identify which party the brief is supporting, or if the brief supports only affirmance or reversal. <s> The Court also requires that, "inter alia", all non-governmental amici identify those providing a monetary contribution to the preparation or submission of the brief. <s> Briefs must be prepared in booklet format, and 40 copies must be served with the Court. <s> In the United States Supreme Court, unless the "amicus" brief is being filed by the federal government (or one of its officers or agents) or a U.S. state, permission of the court (by means of motion for leave) or mutual consent of the parties is generally required. <s> Allowing an "amicus curiae" to present oral argument is considered "extraordinary". <s> The role of "amicus curiae" briefs in the World Trade Organization (WTO) dispute settlement system is controversial. <s> The controversy arises due to the governmental nature of WTO disputes. <s> As only WTO members have access to the system, any non-members such as non-governmental organizations (NGOs) are excluded and have no right to be heard. <s> Thus the only way for them to contribute to a WTO decision is through "amicus curiae" briefs.

title: Anaïs Mitchell
complex: Anaïs Mitchell ( ; born March 26, 1981) is an American singer-songwriter, musician, and playwright. <s> Mitchell has released seven albums, including "Hadestown" (2010), "Young Man in America" (2012), and "Child Ballads" (2013). <s> Mitchell's father is a novelist and college professor and named her after author Anaïs Nin. <s> She grew up on Treleven farm in Addison County, Vermont, and after traveling to the Middle East, Europe and Latin America as a child, she attended Middlebury College. <s> Having begun writing her first songs at the age of 17, Mitchell won the New Folk award in 2003 at the Kerrville Folk Festival. <s> Her album "Hymns for the Exiled" was released on Chicago's Waterbug Records label in 2004. <s> This recording attracted the attention of singer/songwriter Ani DiFranco, who signed her to the Righteous Babe Records label. <s> In 2006 Mitchell debuted a draft of her "folk opera" "Hadestown", which she wrote in collaboration with arranger Michael Chorney and director Ben T. Matchstick. <s> A revised version of "Hadestown" was staged in 2007. <s> Her third album, "The Brightness," was released that same year on Righteous Babe Records. <s> Mitchell continued quietly working on a stage version of "Hadestown" while also writing and recording new material. <s> In early 2012, she released "Young Man in America" on Wilderland Records. <s> Mitchell opened the North American leg of Bon Iver's autumn 2012 tour, which included two sold-out shows at Radio City Music Hall. <s> The album was largely praised by critics as "genre-defining" and her "second consecutive masterpiece." <s> Mitchell has received favorable reviews on her musical style, sound and performance. <s> An article in "Acoustic Guitar" magazine calls Mitchell "fearlessly emotive" and compares her to Bob Dylan, Leonard Cohen, and Gillian Welch. <s> The UK's "Independent" newspaper called her "the most engaging, and in some ways, most original artist currently working in the field of new American folk music" "The New York Times" noted that "Ms Mitchell's songs address contemporary angst with uncanny vision" and called her "a formidable songwriting talent".
simple: Anaïs Mitchell (; born March 26, 1981) is an American singer, songwriter and guitarist. <s> Anaïs Mitchell is the daughter of a novelist and a college professor. <s> As a child, she grew up on a farm in Addison County, Vermont. <s> She also traveled to the Middle East, Europe and Latin America. <s> She later studied at Middlebury College. <s> In 2003 Mitchell won the "New Folk" award at the Kerrville Folk Festival. <s> Her album, "Hymns for the Exiled", was released on Chicago's Waterbug Records label in 2004. <s> This recording caused her to be noticed by singer/songwriter, Ani DiFranco. <s> DiFranco signed Mitchell to the Righteous Babe Records label. <s> In September that same year Righteous Babe Records released "country e.p." <s> Mitchell released an album called "Young Man in America," on her Wilderland Records label in 2012. <s> Mitchell has gotten good reviews on her musical style and performance. <s> An article in "Acoustic Guitar" magazine compares her to Dylan, Cohen, and Welch.

title: Interstate 890
complex: Interstate 890 (I-890) is a 9.45 mi auxiliary Interstate Highway in the vicinity of Schenectady, New York, in the United States. <s> The highway runs southeast–northwest from an interchange with the New York State Thruway (I-90) northwest of Schenectady to another junction with the Thruway south of the city and passes through Downtown Schenectady along the way. <s> Most of I-890 is six lanes wide, including a section that runs above an industrial section of Schenectady on an elevated highway. <s> I-890 is a local, toll-free alternative to the Thruway, which bypasses the city and its suburbs to the southwest.
simple: Interstate 890 (I-890) is a highway in New York, in the United States. <s> It is 9.45 mi long. <s> Most of I-890 is six lanes wide.

title: Geographical Names Board of New South Wales
complex: The Geographical Names Board of New South Wales, a statutory authority of the Land and Property Information division, Department of Finance and Services in the Government of New South Wales, is the official body for naming and recording details of places and geographical names in the state of New South Wales, Australia. <s> The board was established in 1966 pursuant to the "Geographical Names Act 1966". <s> The "Geographical Names Act, 1966", empowers the board to assign names to places, to investigate and determine the form, spelling, meaning, pronunciation, origin and history of any geographical name and the application of such name with regard to position, extent or otherwise. <s> A place is described in the Act as "any geographical or topographical feature or any district, division, locality, region, city, town, village, settlement or railway station or any other place within the territories and waters of the State of New South Wales but does not include any road, any local government area, urban area, county or district under the Local Government Act, electoral district or subdivision, or any school". <s> The Act also specifies the procedures for formalising names. <s> In recent years the board has been given the power to preserve and promote Aboriginal languages and acknowledge Aboriginal culture through place naming in NSW. <s> The board does this by preferencing traditional Aboriginal place names or names with Aboriginal origin wherever it can. <s> The board is dedicated to restoring traditional Aboriginal names to features with introduced names through its dual naming policy and recognising important traditional Aboriginal placenames alongside longstanding introduced names. <s> The board's policy mirrors the United States Board on Geographic Names in that it seeks to eliminate possessive names from all place names in NSW. <s> Roads called Smith's Road are changed to Smiths Road or Smith Road.
simple: The Geographical Names Board of New South Wales is the officialorganization that records details of places and geographical names in New South Wales, Australia. <s> It was set up in 1966. <s> The "Geographical Names Act, 1966", gives the Board the right to name places, and to find out and decide on the form, spelling, meaning, pronunciation, origin and history of any geographical name. <s> A place is any geographical or topographical feature or any district, division, locality, region, city, town, village, settlement or railway station or any other place within the territories and waters of the State of New South Wales. <s> It does not include roads, any local government areas, urban areas, counties or districts under the Local Government Act, electoral districts, subdivisions, or schools. <s> The Board has the power to keep and promote Aboriginal languages and acknowledge Aboriginal culture through place naming in NSW. <s> The Board does this by using traditional Aboriginal place names or names with Aboriginal origin wherever it can. <s> The Board can give traditional Aboriginal names to features that have been given introduced names through its dual naming policy. <s> The Board's policy is the same as the U.S. Board of Geographical Names, which removes possessive names from all place names in NSW. <s> Roads called Smith's Road are changed to Smiths Road or Smith Road.

title: Martin Luther King Jr. Day
complex: Martin Luther King Jr. <s> Day (officially Birthday of Martin Luther King, Jr., and sometimes referred to as MLK Day) is an American federal holiday marking the birthday of Martin Luther King Jr. <s> It is observed on the third Monday of January each year, which is around King's birthday, January 15. <s> The holiday is similar to holidays set under the Uniform Monday Holiday Act. <s> The earliest Monday for this holiday is January 15 and the latest is January 21. <s> President Ronald Reagan originally opposed the holiday, citing cost concerns. <s> When asked to comment on Helms' accusations that King was a communist, the president said "We'll know in thirty-five years, won't we?", <s> , in reference to the eventual release of FBI surveillance tapes that had previously been sealed. <s> But on November 2, 1983, Reagan signed a bill, proposed by Representative Katie Hall of Indiana, to create a federal holiday honoring King. <s> The bill had passed the Senate by a count of 78 to 22 and the House of Representatives by 338 to 90, veto-proof margins. <s> The holiday was observed for the first time on January 20, 1986. <s> It is observed on the third Monday of January.
simple: Martin Luther King, Jr. <s> It commemorates civil rights activist Martin Luther King, Jr.'s birthday. <s> Day is a US Federal Holiday. <s> It is celebrated on the third Monday in January and is one of only four United States Federal holidays to honor an individual person. <s> President Ronald Reagan signed a bill, proposed by Representative Katie Hall of Indiana, to create a federal holiday honoring King. <s> The holiday was observed for the first time on January 20, 1986. <s> It is observed on the third Monday of January.

title: Toni Braxton (album)
complex: Toni Braxton is the debut studio album by American singer Toni Braxton. <s> It was released on July 13, 1993, by LaFace Records and Arista Records.
simple: Toni Braxton is the self-titled record by the Toni Braxton. <s> It was released in July 1993.

title: Northern giraffe
complex: The northern giraffe ("Giraffa camelopardalis"), also known as three-horned giraffe, is a proposed species of giraffe native to North Africa. <s> In the current IUCN taxonomic scheme there is only one species of giraffe with the name "G. camelopardalis" and nine subspecies. <s> The giraffes have two horn-like protuberances known as ossicones on their foreheads. <s> The northern giraffe's are longer and larger than that of the southern giraffes', though male northern giraffes have a third cylindrical ossicone in the center of the head just above the eyes which are from 3 to 5 inches long. <s> The Northern giraffes live in the savannahs, shrublands and woodlands. <s> After local extinctions in various places, the Northern giraffes are the least numerous species and the most endangered.
simple: A giraffe ("Giraffa camelopardalis") is a mammal which lives in Africa. <s> There are about nine different subspecies of giraffe, with only small differences between them. <s> Both male and female giraffes have small horn-like stumps on their head, which are covered with skin. <s> They live on the savannah, which is the African grassland, or in light woodland. )T

title: Kiruna Church
complex: Kiruna Church is a church building in Kiruna, Sweden, and is one of Sweden's largest wooden buildings. <s> The church exterior is built in a Gothic Revival style, while the altar is in Art Nouveau. <s> The church was built between 1909–1912, and consecrated by Bishop Olof Bergqvist on 8 December 1912. <s> Since 1913, the church is included in the Jukkasjärvi parish in the diocese of Luleå.
simple: Kiruna Church is a church building in the town of Kiruna in Sweden. <s> It was opened on 8 December 1912 by bishop Olof Bergqvist.

title: White Anglo-Saxon Protestant
complex: White Anglo-Saxon Protestants (WASPs) are a social group of white Protestants in the United States, often of British descent, and typically wealthy and well-connected. <s> The group has long dominated American society, culture, and the leadership of major political parties, and had a monopoly on elite society due to intermarriage and nepotism. <s> Although the WASP hegemony on the American establishment has lessened since the World War II era, WASPs continue to be well placed in major financial, business, legal, and academic institutions.
simple: WASP: an acronym for White Anglo-Saxon Protestant. <s> They are a social group of white protestants in the United States. <s> They are often of British descent, and typically wealthy and well-connected. <s> However, WASPs are still well placed in major financial, business and legal firms, and in universities.

title: Péry
complex: Péry is part of the municipality of Péry-La Heutte in the Jura bernois administrative district in the canton of Bern in Switzerland. <s> It is located in the French-speaking Bernese Jura ("Jura Bernois"). <s> On 1 January 2015 the former municipalities of Péry and La Heutte merged to form the new municipality of Péry-La Heutte.
simple: Péry is a former municipality of the administrative district of Jura bernois in the canton of Berne in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2015 the former municipalities of Péry and La Heutte merged into the new municipality of Péry-La Heutte.

title: Clarbec
complex: Clarbec is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Clarbec is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Sakurai, Nara
complex: Sakurai (桜井市 , Sakurai-shi ) is a city located in Nara Prefecture, Japan. <s> Sakurai is home to Ōmiwa Shrine, traditionally considered one of the oldest Shinto shrines in Japan dedicated to the god of sake. <s> Sake dealers across Japan often hang a wooden sugi ball, made at Ōmiwa Shrine, as a talisman to the god of sake. <s> It was featured in Yukio Mishima's novel "Runaway Horses".
simple: Sakurai (桜井市, Sakurai-shi) is a Japanese city in Nara Prefecture on the island of Honshū. <s> Sakurai is home to Ōmiwa Shrine. <s> Sakurai is part of Yukio Mishima's novel, "Runaway Horses".

title: IPass (company)
complex: iPass Inc is an American multinational company headquartered in Redwood Shores, California that provides Internet software and services. <s> The firm was first incorporated in California in July 1996 and later reincorporated in Delaware in June 2000. <s> The company’s stock was added to the NASDAQ on July 24, 2003. <s> iPass was founded in January 1996 by Chris Moore. <s> Moore was replaced by Michael H. Mansouri, who took the position of Chairman, President and CEO in 1999, serving until 2001. <s> Kenneth Denman succeeded Mansouri as President and CEO in 2001, later assuming the position of Chairman in 2003. <s> In July 2003, the firm successfully issued its IPO, raising over $100 million. <s> In 2004, the firm launched a policy orchestration initiative to integrate patch management, assessment and remediation of remote and mobile computers into its connectivity platform. <s> In pursuing this initiative, iPass acquired two companies in 2004: Safe3w, which developed patented dynamic device “fingerprinting” technology, and Mobile Automation, which specialized in mobile device management. <s> Two years later, iPass acquired GoRemote Internet Communications, a former rival in the corporate remote access market. <s> In the midst of these acquisitions, iPass recorded year-end revenue growth, despite declining revenues from the company’s traditional dial-up business. <s> Overall, total revenues grew to $192 million by the end of 2007. <s> In 2008, the company appointed Evan Kaplan as CEO and President to replace Denman. <s> During Kaplan's tenure, the firm began to build a service delivery platform for its new enterprise mobility services. <s> By January 2010, the company delivered the first version of its cloud-based platform, iPass Open Mobile. <s> 2015 ushered in a change in the firm’ executive team, beginning with the appointment of Gary Griffiths to the position of CEO and President. <s> Griffiths and his newly appointed Chief Commercial Officer, Patricia Hume, pursued a new growth strategy for mobile services, launching iPass Unlimited, a per-user, per-month, fixed fee subscription for unlimited Wi-Fi usage. <s> The firm also expanded of its network of global hotspots by 2015 from 18 million to 50 million. <s> The company also undertook enhancements to its products and applications. <s> In November 2015, the firm announced proprietary technology, iPass SmartConnect. <s> iPass is a cloud-based service manager that connects users and devices to the company’s global Wi-Fi footprint. <s> In its simplest form, it is an application, downloaded by service users to laptops, tablets, or smartphones, to identify and connect to the system's hotspots. <s> It is compatible with Automatic Credential Assignment. <s> Derived from the company’s connectivity intellectual property, the app is powered by iPass SmartConnect, iPass’ Wi-Fi service platform, which identifies and rates access points based on factors such as signal strength, speed, bandwidth availability, and connection success rate. <s> The app also incorporates Last Mile VPN security, profile settings, Wi-Fi connectivity, and network curation to expand the network of available hotspots. <s> The platform also includes a proprietary scalable reporting and transaction clearing back-end. <s> The company has a global authentication fabric of integrated servers and software, interconnected with over 160 distinct global Wi-Fi networks. <s> This infrastructure gives the company’s aggregated hotspots the look and feel of iPass hotspots. <s> With the addition of iPass SmartConnect, the architecture now opens avenues for improving connection success, real-time monitoring of network outages, and least-cost network routing . <s> iPass has a Wi-Fi network footprint and supply chain that consists of more than 64 million hotspots in over 160 countries, including major airports, convention centers, planes, trains, train stations, hotels, restaurants, retail, and small business locations. <s> This network footprint includes millions of community and free hotspots.

title: Bouvigny-Boyeffles
complex: Bouvigny-Boyeffles is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region in northern France.
simple: Bouvigny-Boyeffles is a commune.

title: Manicure
complex: A manicure is a cosmetic beauty treatment for the fingernails and hands performed at home or in a nail salon. <s> A manicure consists of filing and shaping the "free edge", pushing and clipping (with a cuticle pusher and cuticle nippers) any nonliving tissue (but limited to the cuticle and hangnails), treatments with various liquids, massage of the hand, and the application of fingernail polish. <s> When the same is applied to the toenails and feet, the treatment is referred to as a pedicure.
simple: A manicure is something a nail technician does to make someone's nails more beautiful. <s> Manicures can be done at home or by a professional in a nail salon. <s> During a manicure, the nail is filed with a nail file; the free edge of the nail is cut, the cuticle is treated, the person's hand is massaged and nail polish is put on.

title: United States Department of Veterans Affairs
complex: The United States Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) is a federal Cabinet-level agency that provides near-comprehensive healthcare services to eligible military veterans at VA medical centers and outpatient clinics located throughout the country; several non-healthcare benefits including disability compensation, vocational rehabilitation, education assistance, home loans, and life insurance; and provides burial and memorial benefits to eligible veterans and family members at 135 national cemeteries. <s> The Department of Veterans Affairs is headed by the Secretary of Veterans Affairs, appointed by the President with the advice and consent of the Senate. <s> The VA, through its Veterans Benefits Administration (VBA), provides a variety of services for veterans including disability compensation, pension, education, home loans, life insurance, vocational, rehabilitation, survivors’ benefits, health care, and burial benefits. <s> In 1978, Congress established the State Cemetery Grants Program (Public Law 95-476). <s> This act is administered by the National Cemetery Administration to aid States and U.S. territories in the establishment, expansion and improvement of veterans cemeteries. <s> The VA was charged with the operation of the NCS, including the marking of graves of all persons in national and State cemeteries (and the graves of veterans in private cemeteries, upon request) as well and administering the State Cemetery Grants Program.
simple: The United States Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) is a government-run military veteran benefit system with Cabinet-level status. <s> The benefits provided include disability compensation, pension, education, home loans, life insurance, vocational rehabilitation, survivors’ benefits, medical benefits and burial benefits. <s> It is administered by the United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs.

title: Boris Spassky
complex: Boris Vasilievich Spassky ( ; born January 30, 1937) is a Russian chess grandmaster. <s> He was the tenth World Chess Champion, holding the title from 1969 to 1972. <s> Spassky played three world championship matches: he lost to Tigran Petrosian in 1966; defeated Petrosian in 1969 to become world champion; then lost to Bobby Fischer in a famous match in 1972. <s> Spassky won the Soviet Chess Championship twice outright (1961, 1973), and twice lost in playoffs (1956, 1963), after tying for first place during the event proper. <s> He was a World Chess Championship candidate on seven occasions (1956, 1965, 1968, 1974, 1977, 1980, and 1985). <s> In addition to his candidates wins in 1965 and 1968, he reached the semi-final stage in 1974 and the final stage in 1977. <s> Spassky emigrated to France in 1976, becoming a French citizen in 1978. <s> He continued to compete in tournaments but was no longer a major contender for the world title. <s> He lost an unofficial rematch against Fischer in 1992. <s> In 2012 he left France and returned to Russia. <s> He is the oldest living former world champion. <s> On October 1, 2006, Spassky suffered a minor stroke during a chess lecture in San Francisco. <s> In his first major post-stroke play, he drew a six-game rapid match with Hungarian Grandmaster Lajos Portisch in April 2007. <s> On September 23, 2010, ChessBase reported that Spassky had suffered a more serious stroke that had left him paralyzed on his left side. <s> After that he returned to France for a long rehabilitation programme. <s> On August 16, 2012, Spassky left France to return to Russia under disputed circumstances and now lives in an apartment in Moscow.
simple: Boris Spassky (born 30 January 1937 in Leningrad), is a Soviet–French chess grandmaster. <s> He was the tenth World Chess Champion, holding the title from late 1969 to 1972. <s> Against Tigran Petrosian in 1966 he lost; against Petrosian again in 1969 (winning), and against Bobby Fischer in 1972 (losing). <s> Spassky won the USSR Chess Championship twice outright (1961, 1973), and twice more lost in playoffs (1956, 1963). <s> He was a World Chess Championship candidate on seven occasions (1956, 1965, 1968, 1974, 1977, 1980, and 1985). <s> Boris won the Candidates match series in 1965 and 1968. <s> On 1 October 2006, Spassky suffered a minor stroke during a chess lecture in San Francisco. <s> On 23 September 2010, ChessBase reported that Spassky had suffered a more serious stroke that had left him paralyzed on his left side. <s> After that he returned to France for a long rehabilitation programme. <s> On 16 August 2012, Spassky left France to return to Russia under disputed circumstances. <s> He now lives in an apartment in Moscow.

title: Bretteville-l'Orgueilleuse
complex: Bretteville-l'Orgueilleuse is a former commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France. <s> On 1 January 2017, it was merged into the new commune Thue et Mue.
simple: Bretteville-l'Orgueilleuse is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Concordia Parish, Louisiana
complex: Concordia Parish borders the Mississippi River in eastern central Louisiana. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 20,822. <s> The parish seat is Vidalia. <s> The parish was formed in 1807.
simple: In the 2010 count, 20,822 people lived in this parish. <s> The parish seat is Vidalia.

title: Giovanni Natoli
complex: Giovanni Forti Natoli or Gianforte Natoli was a Sicilian nobleman, the son of Blasco Natoli Lanza and Domenica Giambruno Perna. <s> He was baron of S. Bartolomeo and Belice. <s> On 20 August 1597 he bought the barony of Sperlinga from Giovanni Ventimiglia, marquis of Gerace, for 30,834 ounces of gold. <s> Natoli was granted a "licentia populandi cum privilegium aedificandi" ("licence to populate and build") by the king of Sicily, Philip II of Spain. <s> In 1627 he was made prince of Sperlinga by Philip IV of Spain. <s> Natoli was married twice: first to Maria Cottone Aragona, daughter of Stefano, count of Bauso; and second, to Melchiora Orioles Moncada, daughter of Orazio, baron of San Pietro di Patti. <s> With the latter he had a son, Francesco Natoli. <s> Giovanni Natoli died on 15 July 1633.

title: Offenburg
complex: Offenburg ("open borough" - coat of arms showing open gates; Fr. <s> "Offenbourg") is a city located in the state of Baden-Württemberg, Germany. <s> With about 57,000 inhabitants (2013), it is the largest city and the administrative capital of the Ortenaukreis. <s> Offenburger FV is a German association football club based in the city of Offenburg, Baden-Württemberg.
simple: Offenburg is a city in the German state of Baden-Württemberg. <s> In 2013 about 57,000 people lived there.

title: Staff (music)
complex: In Western musical notation, the staff (US) or stave (UK) (plural for either: staves) is a set of five horizontal lines and four spaces that each represent a different musical pitch or in the case of a percussion staff, different percussion instruments. <s> Appropriate music symbols, depending on the intended effect, are placed on the staff according to their corresponding pitch or function. <s> Musical notes are placed by pitch, percussion notes are placed by instrument, and rests and other symbols are placed by convention. <s> The vertical position of the notehead on the staff indicates which note to play: higher-pitched notes are marked higher on the staff. <s> The notehead can be placed with its center intersecting a line ("on a line") or in between the lines touching the lines above and below ("in a space"). <s> Notes outside the range of the staff are placed on or between ledger lines—lines the width of the note they need to hold—added above or below the staff. <s> When music on two staves is joined by a brace, or is intended to be played at once by a single performer (usually a keyboard instrument or harp), a grand staff (American English) or great stave (British English) is created. <s> Typically, the upper staff uses a treble clef and the lower staff has a bass clef.
simple: A staff (or stave) is the name given to the five horizontal lines on which we can write music. <s> The higher the pitch of the note the higher it will be on the staff. <s> Musical notes can be placed either on a line (i.e. with a line going through the middle of the note head) or in a space. <s> If two or more staves are being played at the same time the staves are joined on the left by a bracket which is called a brace.

title: Salle Le Peletier
complex: The Salle Le Peletier or Lepeletier (sometimes referred to as the Salle de la rue Le Peletier or the Opéra Le Peletier) was the home of the Paris Opera from 1821 until the building was destroyed by fire in 1873. <s> The theatre was designed and constructed by the architect François Debret on the site of the garden of the Hôtel de Choiseul on the rue Lepeletier. <s> Due to the many changes in government and management during the theatre's existence, it had a number of different official names, the most important of which were: Théâtre de l'Académie Royale de Musique (1821–1848), Opéra-Théâtre de la Nation (1848–1850), Théâtre de l'Académie Nationale de Musique (1850–1852), Théâtre de l'Académie Impériale de Musique (1852–1854), Théâtre Impérial de l'Opéra (1854–1870), and Théâtre National de l'Opéra (1870–1873).
simple: The Salle Le Peletier (sometimes referred to as the Salle de la rue Le Peletier or the Opéra Le Peletier) was the home of the Paris Opera from 1821 until the building was destroyed by fire in 1873. <s> The theatre was designed and constructed by the architect François Debret on the site of the former Hôtel de Choiseul. <s> Due to the many changes in government and management during the theatre's existence, it had a number of different official names, the most important of which were: Théâtre de l'Académie Royale de Musique (1821–1848), Opéra-Théâtre de la Nation (1848–1850), Théâtre de l'Académie Nationale de Musique (1850–1852), Théâtre de l'Académie Impériale de Musique (1852–1854), Théâtre Impérial de l'Opéra (1854–1870), and Théâtre National de l'Opéra (1870–1873).

title: William M. Jennings Trophy
complex: The William M. Jennings Trophy is an annual National Hockey League (NHL) award given to "the goaltender(s) having played a minimum of 25 games for the team with the fewest goals scored against it ... based on regular-season play." <s> From 1946 until 1981, the Vezina Trophy had been awarded under that definition, but it was later changed and replaced by the Jennings Trophy. <s> It is named in honor of William M. Jennings, the longtime governor and president of the New York Rangers. <s> Since its beginnings in 1982, it has been awarded at the end of 32 seasons to 53 different players; mostly in tandems of two goaltenders. <s> The most recent winners are Thomas Greiss and Robin Lehner of the New York Islanders, which had a league-low 191 team goals-against in the 2018–19 NHL season. <s> From 1946 until the 1980–81 season, the Vezina Trophy was awarded to the goaltender(s) of the National Hockey League (NHL) team allowing the fewest goals during the regular season. <s> However, it was recognized that this system often meant the trophy went to the goaltender of the better team rather than the individual and was changed to offer the trophy to the most outstanding goaltender, as voted by the NHL general managers. <s> The William M. Jennings Trophy was created as a replacement and is awarded to the starting goaltender(s) playing for the team with the fewest goals against. <s> The Jennings Trophy was donated by the NHL's board of governors and first presented at the conclusion of the 1981–82 season. <s> It is named in honor of the late William M. Jennings, who was a longtime governor and president of the New York Rangers and a builder of ice hockey in the United States. <s> Normally the minimum number of games a goaltender must play to be eligible for the trophy is 25, but for the lockout shortened 1994–95 season, the required minimum was fourteen games. <s> Seven players have won both the Jennings and Vezina Trophy for the same season: Patrick Roy ( and ), Ed Belfour ( and ), Dominik Hasek ( and ), Martin Brodeur , Miikka Kiprusoff , Tim Thomas , and Carey Price . <s> Roy and Brodeur have won the trophy five times each, the most of any goaltenders. <s> Belfour is third, having won four times. <s> The Montreal Canadiens have the most wins, with six, followed by the New Jersey Devils and the Chicago Blackhawks with five each, and the Buffalo Sabres with three. <s> Bold Player with the fewest goals ever scored against in a season.
simple: The William M. Jennings Trophy is an award in the National Hockey League (NHL) given each year to "to the goalkeeper(s) having played a minimum of 25 games for the team with the fewest goals scored against it. <s> Winners are selected based on regular-season play." <s> Up until 1981, the Vezina Trophy had been awarded under that definition, but it was later changed and replaced by the Jennings Trophy. <s> Since it began in 1982, it has been awarded at the end of 25 seasons to 27 different players. <s> The most recent winners are Corey Crawford of the Chicago Blackhawks and Carey Price of the Montreal Canadiens, who both allowed only 189 team goals against for their teams in the 2014–15 NHL season. <s> Until the 1980–81 season, the Vezina Trophy was awarded to the goaltender(s) of the team allowing the fewest goals during the regular season. <s> However, it was discovered that this often meant the trophy went to the goaltender of the better team rather than the individual, so they changed it to offer the Vezina to the most outstanding goaltender, as voted by the NHL General Managers. <s> The William M. Jennings Trophy was created as a replacement and is given to the goaltender(s) playing for the team with the fewest goals scored against them. <s> The Jennings Trophy was donated by the NHL's board of governors and first handed out at the end of the 1981–82 season. <s> It is named for the late William M. Jennings, who was a governor and president of the New York Rangers and who helped build ice hockey in the United States. <s> Normally the lowest number of games a goaltender must play to be eligible for the trophy is 25, but for the lockout shortened 1994–95 season, the lowest was fourteen games. <s> Five players have won both the Jennings and Vezina Trophy for the same season: Patrick Roy (1988–89 and 1991–92), Ed Belfour (1990–91 and 1992–93), Dominik Hasek (1993–94 and 2000–01), Martin Brodeur (2002–03 and 2003–04) and Miikka Kiprusoff (2005–06). <s> Roy has won the trophy five times, the most of any goaltender. <s> Belfour and Brodeur are tied for second, having each won the trophy four times. <s> It has been won most often by the Montreal Canadiens, on 5 occasions. <s> The New Jersey Devils have won four times, and Buffalo Sabres and Chicago Blackhawks have three wins each. <s> Player is still active in the NHL Player's team won the Stanley Cup Bold Player with the fewest goals ever scored against in a season.

title: Sharon Gless
complex: Sharon Marguerite Gless (born May 31, 1943) is an American actress, who is known for her television roles as Maggie Philbin, the naïve, young receptionist of Frank MacBride and Pete Ryan (played by Eddie Albert and Robert Wagner) on "Switch" (1975–78), Sgt. Christine Cagney in the police procedural drama series "Cagney & Lacey" (1982–88), the title role in "The Trials of Rosie O'Neill" (1990–92), as Debbie Novotny in the Showtime cable television series "Queer as Folk" (2000–2005), and as Madeline Westen on "Burn Notice" (2007–2013). <s> A 10-time Emmy Award nominee and seven-time Golden Globe Award nominee, she won a Golden Globe in 1986 and Emmys in 1986 and 1987 for "Cagney & Lacey", and a second Golden Globe in 1991 for "The Trials of Rosie O'Neill". <s> Gless received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame in 1995.

title: Iris (plant)
complex: Iris is a genus of 260–300 species of flowering plants with showy flowers. <s> It takes its name from the Greek word for a rainbow, which is also the name for the Greek goddess of the rainbow, Iris. <s> Some authors state that the name refers to the wide variety of flower colors found among the many species. <s> As well as being the scientific name, "iris" is also widely used as a common name for all "Iris" species, as well as some belonging to other closely related genera. <s> A common name for some species is 'flags', while the plants of the subgenus "Scorpiris" are widely known as 'junos', particularly in horticulture. <s> It is a popular garden flower. <s> The three, sometimes reduced, petals stand upright, partly behind the sepal bases. <s> They are called "standards". <s> Some smaller iris species have all six lobes pointing straight outwards, but generally limb and standards differ markedly in appearance.
simple: Iris is a genus of 260–300 species of flowering plants with showy flowers. <s> It takes its name from the Greek word for a rainbow. <s> This refers to the wide variety of flower colors found among the many species. <s> The scientific name, "iris" is also very widely used as a common name for all "Iris" species, as well as some belonging to other closely related genera. <s> A common name for some species is 'flags'. <s> Plants of the subgenus "Scorpiris" are widely known as 'junos', particularly in horticulture. <s> It is a member of the Iridaceae family It is a popular garden flower. <s> They have three inner petals called "standards".

title: Canuck
complex: "Canuck" is a slang term for a Canadian. <s> The origins of the word are uncertain. <s> The term "Kanuck" is first recorded in 1835 as an Americanism, originally referring to Dutch Canadians or French Canadians. <s> By the 1850s, the spelling with a "C" became predominant. <s> Today, English Canadians and others use "Canuck" as a mostly affectionate term for any Canadian. <s> English Canadians use "Canuck" as an affectionate or merely descriptive term for their nationality.
simple: "Canuck" is a slang term for Canadian people. <s> The Random House Dictionary says that: "The term Canuck is first recorded about 1835 as an Americanism, originally referring specifically to a French Canadian. <s> This was probably the original meaning, though in Canada and other countries, Canuck now more often refers to any Canadian." <s> When "Canuck" is used by Canadians, the meaning is usually affectionate, friendly or patriotic.

title: Fedor Emelianenko
complex: Fedor Vladimirovich Emelianenko (Russian: , , ] ; born 28 September 1976) is a Russian heavyweight mixed martial artist (MMA), sambist, and judoka, currently competing for Rizin Fighting Federation and Bellator MMA. <s> He has won championships and accolades in multiple sports, most notably in MMA Pride Fighting Championships (heavyweight champion 2003-2007), FIAS World Combat Sambo Championship (Heavyweight Champion 2002, 2005, 2007), and Russian Judo Federation National Championship (Bronze medal 1998, 1999).

title: Make Way for Ducklings
complex: Make Way for Ducklings is a children's picture book written and illustrated by Robert McCloskey. <s> First published in 1941, the book tells the story of a pair of mallards who decide to raise their family on an island in the lagoon in Boston Public Garden, a park in the center of Boston. <s> "Make Way for Ducklings" won the 1942 Caldecott Medal for McCloskey's illustrations, executed in charcoal then lithographed on zinc plates. <s> As of 2003, the book had sold over two million copies. <s> The book's popularity led to the construction of a statue by Nancy Schön in the Public Garden of the mother duck and her eight ducklings, which is a popular destination for children and adults alike. <s> In 1991, Barbara Bush gave a duplicate of this sculpture to Raisa Gorbachev as part of the START Treaty, and the work is displayed in Moscow's Novodevichy Park. <s> The book is the official children's book of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts. <s> Praise for the book is still high over 70 years since its first publication, mainly for the enhancing illustrations and effective pacing. <s> It was criticised for having a loose plot, however. <s> The book is popular worldwide. <s> "Make Way for Ducklings" has been continuously in print since it was first published.
simple: Make Way for Ducklings is a children's picture book written and illustrated by Robert McCloskey. <s> The book is about two mallard ducks who decide to raise their family on an island in the lagoon in Boston Public Garden, a park in the middle of Boston, Massachusetts. <s> "Make Way for Ducklings" won the 1942 Caldecott Medal for McCloskey's pictures, drawn in charcoal, then lithographed on zinc. <s> In 2003, the book had sold more than two million copies. <s> The book was so popular a statue of a mother duck and her eight ducklings were set up in the Public Garden. <s> In 1991, Barbara Bush gave a copy of this statue to Raisa Gorbachev as part of the START Treaty, and the work is in Moscow's Novodevichy Park. <s> The book is the official children's book of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts. <s> The book is still highly praised for over 60 years because of its pictures and pace. <s> However, it was criticised for having a loose plot (story) and weak characters. <s> The book is very popular around the world.

title: Heaton Park
complex: Heaton Park is a municipal park in Manchester, England, covering an area of over 600 acre . <s> The park includes the grounds of a Grade I listed, neoclassical 18th century country house, Heaton Hall.
simple: Heaton Park is the largest municipal park in the Greater Manchester region, and one of the largest in both the United Kingdom and Europe.

title: Ferenc Doór
complex: Ferenc Doór (14 June 1918 – 10 July 2015) was a Hungarian painter and graphic artist, "The lover of the Danube and Szentendre". <s> He was born in Petrilla, Transylvania on 14 June 1918. <s> Between 1938–1941 he studied on the Hungarian University of Fine Arts in Budapest under the István Szőnyi's hands. <s> After the World War II he suffered a captivity of war in Siberia for three years. <s> After his release terminated his study in 1949, as instructor (assistant professor) of Szőnyi involved in the circulation of Hungarian artistic life. <s> In 1957 he became a member of the Art Fund of Fine Arts Association. <s> By the Nagybánya's painting lessons continued painting with natural themes and human figures appear rich color scheme, has joined forces shaping a balanced composition. <s> Oil paintings and water-like substance, were the main elements his expression of color and light. <s> As from his works himself wrote: "I tried my work faithfully follow art my ideas - to capture the potential of everyday life images of beauty - small joys and sorrows, our time and the change of a landscape typical timeless atmosphere of human destinies". <s> He died in his Szentendre home at the age of 97 years on 10 July 2015. <s> He had numerous exhibitions in Hungary and abroad, worked for decades in Szentendre and the creative community of artists houses in Szigliget, Kecskemét, Hódmezővásárhely and Mártély. <s> In the 1950s onward featured in the Hall of Art, Budapest a common ones and in other exhibition spaces in the country. <s> In 2011, he became the "Hungarian Gold Cross of Merit" honors.

title: Jóhanna Sigurðardóttir
complex: Jóhanna Sigurðardóttir (] ; born 4 October 1942) is an Icelandic politician and the former Prime Minister of Iceland. <s> She became active in the trade union movement, serving as an officer. <s> Elected an MP from 1978 to 2013, she was appointed as Iceland's Minister of Social Affairs and Social Security, serving from 1987 to 1994, and from 2007 until 2009. <s> In 1994, when she lost a bid to head the Social Democratic Party, she raised her fist and declared ""Minn tími mun koma!"" <s> ("My time will come!"), <s> , a phrase that became a popular Icelandic expression. <s> She became Prime Minister on 1 February 2009, Iceland's first female Prime Minister and the world's first openly lesbian head of government. <s> "Forbes" listed her among the 100 most powerful women in the world. <s> She has been a member of the Althing (Iceland's parliament) for Reykjavík constituencies since 1978, winning re-election on eight successive occasions. <s> In September 2012, Jóhanna announced she would not seek re-election and retired from politics as Iceland's longest serving member of Parliament.
simple: Jóhanna Sigurðardóttir (pronounced jouːhanːa ˈsɪːɣʏrðartouhtɪr), (born 4 October 1942) is a former Icelandic politician and the former Prime Minister of Iceland. <s> She was Iceland's Minister of Social Affairs and Social Security from 1987–1994 and 2007–2009. <s> In the 1990s, when she lost a bid to head the party, she lifted her fist and declared "Minn tími mun koma!" <s> -- ""My time will come!""— <s> —a phrase that became a popular Icelandic expression. <s> She became Iceland's first female Prime Minister on 1 February 2009, the world's first openly gay head of government of the modern era. <s> She has been a member of the Althing (Iceland's parliament) for Reykjavík constituencies since 1978. <s> She has been re-elected eight times.

title: Schaerbeek
complex: Schaerbeek (obsolete Dutch spelling, retained in French, pronounced ] ) or Schaarbeek (Dutch, ] ) is one of the nineteen municipalities located in the Brussels-Capital Region of Belgium. <s> It is bordered by the City of Brussels, Etterbeek, Evere and Saint-Josse-ten-Noode.
