title: Erriapus
complex: Erriapus ( ; Latin: "Erriapus, Erriappus"), also Saturn XXVIII (28), is a prograde irregular satellite of Saturn. <s> It was discovered by Brett Gladman, John J. Kavelaars and colleagues in 2000, and given the temporary designation S/2000 S 10. <s> It was named Erriapo in August 2003 after Erriapus, a giant in Gaulish mythology; the name was changed from dative "Erriapo" to nominative "Erriapus" per IAU conventions in late 2007. <s> Erriapus is about 10 kilometres in diameter, and orbits Saturn at an average distance of 17,3 Gm in 871 days. <s> As a member of the Gallic group of irregular satellites, which share similar orbital characteristics and a light-red colour, Erriapus is hypothesized to have its origin in the break-up of a common progenitor of the group, or to be a fragment of its largest member, Albiorix.
simple: Erriapus or Saturn XXVIII, is non-spherical moon of Saturn. <s> It was found by Brett Gladman, John J. Kavelaars, et al. in 2000, and given the designation S/2000 S 10. <s> It was named in August 2003 after Erriapo, a giant in Gaulish mythology. <s> Erriapus is about 10 kilometres in diameter, and orbits Saturn at an average distance of 17,300,000 km in 871 days. <s> Erriapus is a member of the Gallic group of non-spherical, sharing a similar orbit and displaying a similar "light-red" colour, Erriapus is thought to have been formed in a break-up of a bigger body.

title: Antiproton
complex: The antiproton, , (pronounced "p-bar") is the antiparticle of the proton. <s> Antiprotons are stable, but they are typically short-lived, since any collision with a proton will cause both particles to be annihilated in a burst of energy. <s> The antiproton was first experimentally confirmed in 1955 at the Bevatron particle accelerator by University of California, Berkeley physicists Emilio Segrè and Owen Chamberlain, for which they were awarded the 1959 Nobel Prize in Physics. <s> In terms of valence quarks, an antiproton consists of two up antiquarks and one down antiquark .
simple: It is the proton’s antiparticle. <s> Antiprotons were first produced and identified in 1955 by Emilio Segrè, Owen Chamberlain (for which they received the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1959), and coworkers by bombarding a copper target with high-energy protons from the proton synchrotron at the University of California at Berkeley.

title: Gonzalo Rodríguez (footballer, born 1984)
complex: Gonzalo Javier Rodríguez Prado (] ; born 10 April 1984), sometimes known as simply Gonzalo, is an Argentine professional footballer who plays as a central defender for San Lorenzo de Almagro.
simple: Gonzalo Javier Rodríguez (born 10 April 1984) is an Argentinae football player.

title: Nashville sound
complex: The Nashville sound originated during the mid 1950s as a subgenre of American country music, replacing the chart dominance of the rough honky tonk music which was most popular in the 1940s and 1950s with "smooth strings and choruses", "sophisticated background vocals" and "smooth tempos". <s> It was an attempt "to revive country sales, which had been devastated by the rise of rock 'n' roll."
simple: It replaced the dominance of honky-tonk (popular during the 1940s and 1950s).

title: Palace of Culture and Science
complex: Palace of Culture and Science ( ; abbreviated PKiN), is a notable high-rise building in central Warsaw, Poland. <s> With a total height of 237 m it is the tallest building in Poland, the 6th-tallest building in the European Union (including spire) and one of the tallest on the European continent.
simple: Palace of Culture and Science is the tallest building in Poland (230 meters). <s> It is in Warsaw.

title: Niederönz
complex: Niederönz is a municipality in the Oberaargau administrative district in the canton of Bern in Switzerland.
simple: Niederönz is a municipality in the administrative district of Oberaargau in the canton of Berne in Switzerland.

title: Platonic realism
complex: Platonic realism is a philosophical term usually used to refer to the idea of realism regarding the existence of universals or abstract objects after the Greek philosopher Plato. <s> As universals were considered by Plato to be ideal forms, this stance is ambiguously also called Platonic idealism.
simple: Platonic realism is the theory of reality developed by Plato, and explained in his theory of Forms. <s> Platonic realism states that the visible world of particular things is a shifting exhibition, like shadows cast on a wall by the activities of their corresponding universal Ideas or Forms.

title: List of historians
complex: This is a list of historians. <s> The names are grouped by order of the historical period in which they were living and producing works, which is not necessarily the same as the period in which they specialize.
simple: This is a list of historians. <s> The names are grouped by order of the historical period in which they were writing, which is not necessarily the same as the period in which they specialised.

title: Frank Ordenewitz
complex: Frank Ordenewitz (born 25 March 1965) is a German former footballer who played as a forward.
simple: Frank Ordenewitz (born March 25, 1965) is a former German football player.

title: Panama City, Florida
complex: Panama City is a city and the county seat of Bay County, Florida, United States. <s> Located along U.S. Route 98, it is the largest city between Tallahassee and Pensacola. <s> It is the more populated of two principal cities of the Panama City-Lynn Haven, Florida Metropolitan Statistical Area.
simple: Panama City is a city in the US state of Florida. <s> It is the county seat of Bay County. <s> It is along U.S. Highway 98 in Bay County.

title: Karl H. Pribram
complex: Karl H. Pribram ( ; ] ; February 25, 1919 – January 19, 2015) was a professor at Georgetown University, in the United States, an emeritus professor of psychology and psychiatry at Stanford University and distinguished professor at Radford University. <s> Board-certified as a neurosurgeon, Pribram did pioneering work on the definition of the limbic system, the relationship of the frontal cortex to the limbic system, the sensory-specific "association" cortex of the parietal and temporal lobes, and the classical motor cortex of the human brain. <s> He worked with Karl Lashley at the Yerkes Primate Center of which he was to become director later. <s> He was professor at Yale University for ten years and at Stanford University for thirty years. <s> In 1999, he was the inaugural winner of the Dagmar and Václav Havel Award for uniting the sciences and the humanities. <s> He died in 2015 in Virginia, aged 95.
simple: Karl H. Pribram (; ]; February 25, 1919 – January 19, 2015) was an Austrian-born American neuroscientist and educator. <s> He taught at Georgetown University, Yale University, Stanford University, and Radford University. <s> He also did a lot of work on the meaning of the limbic system, the relationship of the frontal cortex to the limbic system, cortex discoveries of the parietal and temporal lobes, and the classical motor cortex of the human brain. <s> Pribram died from cancer on January 19, 2015 in Virginia.

title: Finger
complex: A finger is a limb of the human body and a type of digit, an organ of manipulation and found in the hands of humans and other primates. <s> Normally humans have five digits, the bones of which are termed phalanges, on each hand, although some people have more or fewer than five due to congenital disorders such as polydactyly or oligodactyly, or accidental or medical amputations. <s> The first digit is the thumb, followed by index finger, middle finger, ring finger, and little finger or pinkie. <s> According to different definitions, the thumb can be called a finger, or not. <s> The palm has five bones known as metacarpal bones, one to each of the five digits. <s> Human hands contain fourteen digital bones, also called phalanges, or phalanx bones: two in the thumb (the thumb has no middle phalanx) and three in each of the four fingers. <s> These are the distal phalanx, carrying the nail, the middle phalanx, and the proximal phalanx.
simple: A finger is a type of digit attached to the hand. <s> Our type of fingers are similar to those of other primates. <s> Humans have five digits, the bones of which are termed phalanges. <s> The first digit is the thumb, followed by the index finger, middle finger, ring finger, and little finger or 'pinky'. <s> According to different definitions, the thumb can be called a finger, or not. <s> The four fingers have three phalanges each; the thumb has two.

title: Egyptian Armed Forces
complex: The Egyptian Armed Forces are the state military organisation responsible for the defense of Egypt. <s> They consist of the Egyptian Army, Egyptian Navy, Egyptian Air Force and Egyptian Air Defense Forces.
simple: The Egyptian Armed Forces are the military forces of Egypt. <s> It consists of the Egyptian Army, Egyptian Navy, Egyptian Air Force and Egyptian Air Defense Forces.

title: Maumee River
complex: The Maumee River (pronounced ) (Shawnee: "Hotaawathiipi"; Miami-Illinois: "Taawaawa siipiiwi") is a river running from northeastern Indiana into northwestern Ohio and Lake Erie in the United States. <s> It is formed at the confluence of the St. Joseph and St. Marys rivers, where Fort Wayne, Indiana, has developed, and meanders northeastwardly for 137 mi through an agricultural region of glacial moraines before flowing into the Maumee Bay of Lake Erie. <s> The city of Toledo is located at the mouth of the Maumee. <s> The Maumee was designated an Ohio State Scenic River on July 18, 1974. <s> The Maumee watershed is Ohio’s breadbasket; it is two-thirds farmland, mostly corn and soybeans. <s> It is the largest watershed of any of the rivers feeding the Great Lakes, and supplies five percent of Lake Erie’s water.
simple: The Maumee River (pronounced ) (Shawnee: "Hotaawathiipi"; Miami-Illinois: "Taawaawa siipiiwi") is a river running from northeastern Indiana into northwestern Ohio and Lake Erie in the United States. <s> The city of Toledo is located at the mouth of the Maumee. <s> It is the largest watershed of any of the rivers feeding the Great Lakes, and supplies five percent of Lake Erie’s water.

title: Saint John, Barbados
complex: The parish of Saint John (St. John) is a parish of Barbados on the eastern side of the island. <s> It is home to one of its secondary schools, The Lodge School. <s> The parish is the home of many districts such as Ashford and Kendal. <s> It is home to the St. John's Parish Church, which has a scenic view of the Atlantic Ocean from its perch near Hackleton's Cliff, which overlooks the East Coast of the island. <s> In its southeastern corner, the shoreline turns northward, forming the small Conset Bay. <s> Ashford Bird Park is a bird and animal sanctuary of 197 acre .
simple: Saint John ("St. John") is a parish of Barbados. <s> It is on the eastern side of the island. <s> It is home to one of the secondary schools on the island, The Lodge School. <s> In its southeastern corner, the shoreline turns northward instead of southward, forming the small Conset Bay. <s> Ashford Bird Park is a bird and animal sanctuary.

title: Bismuth(III) sulfide
complex: Bismuth(III) sulfide is a chemical compound of bismuth and sulfur. <s> It occurs in nature as the mineral bismuthinite.
simple: Bismuth(III) sulfide, also known as bismuth sulfide, is a chemical compound. <s> It has bismuth and sulfide ions in it. <s> Bismuth(III) sulfide is a brown solid. <s> It is made by reacting hydrogen sulfide with a bismuth compound like bismuth(III) chloride. <s> It is found as the mineral bismuthinite.

title: Adams, Green County, Wisconsin
complex: Adams is a town in Green County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> The population was 464 at the 2000 Census. <s> Willet, now a ghost town, was located in Adams. <s> The earliest settlers were Cornish lead miners; they were followed by settlers from New England, Ireland, Switzerland and Norway. <s> The town has been the home of a Lutheran and a Catholic parish. <s> Saint Francis Catholic Church was formed and built by Catholic immigrants from Ireland, but later merged with Saint Joseph Catholic Church in Argyle, Wisconsin, and the church was eventually torn down; only the cemetery remains. <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the town has a total area of 36.2 square miles (93.7 km2), all of it land. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 464 people, 165 households, and 121 families residing in the town.
simple: Adams is a town in Green County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> There were 464 people living in Adams as of the 2000 Census. <s> The first settlers were Cornish lead miners. <s> They were followed by settlers from New England, Ireland, Switzerland, and Norway. <s> The town has been the home of a Lutheran and a Catholic parish. <s> Saint Francis Catholic Church was made by Catholic immigrants from Ireland. <s> Later, the parish joined with Saint Joseph Catholic Church in Argyle, Wisconsin. <s> The church was later torn down. <s> The town has an area of 36.2 square miles, thanks to the United States Census Bureau.

title: Baltoro Kangri
complex: Baltoro Kangri ( ; also known as the Golden Throne) is a mountain of the Karakoram mountain range in Gilgit-Baltistan, Pakistan. <s> Baltoro Kangri is the 82nd highest mountain in the world with an elevation of 7312 m . <s> It lies to the south of the Gasherbrums and east of Chogolisa Peak (7,665 m). <s> The huge Baltoro Glacier (which is one of the largest glaciers outside polar regions) rises from the foot of Baltoro Kangri. <s> In the north of Baltoro Kangri is the Abruzzi Glacier.
simple: Baltoro Kangri (or Golden Throne) is a mountain in the Karakoram mountain range in the Northern Areas of Pakistan. <s> It lies to the south of the Gasherbrums and east of Chogolisa Peak (7,665 m). <s> The huge Baltoro Glacier, which is one of the largest glaciers outside polar regions, rises from the foot of Baltoro Kangri. <s> In the north of Baltoro Kangri is the Abruzzi Glacier.

title: North American Numbering Plan
complex: The North American Numbering Plan (NANP) is a telephone numbering plan that encompasses twenty-five distinct regions in twenty countries primarily in North America, including the Caribbean. <s> Some North American countries, most notably Mexico, do not participate in the NANP. <s> In the following decades, the system expanded to include all of the United States and its territories, Canada, Bermuda, and seventeen nations of the Caribbean. <s> By 1967, 129 area codes had been assigned.
simple: The North American Numbering Plan (NANP) is a telephone numbering plan. <s> It includes 24 countries and territories, including the United States, Canada, Bermuda, and 17 nations of the Caribbean.

title: Chamely Khatun
complex: Chamely Khatun (born: 11 November 1988, is a Bangladeshi) cricketer who plays for the Bangladesh national women's cricket team. <s> She is a right handed batsman and right-arm slow bowler. <s> Chamely was part of the team that won a silver medal in cricket against the China national women's cricket team at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, China.
simple: Chamely Khatun (born 11 November 1988, is a Bangladeshi) cricketer who plays for the Bangladesh national women's cricket team. <s> She is a right handed batsman and right-arm slow bowler. <s> Chamely was part of the team that won a silver medal in cricket against the China national women's cricket team at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, China.

title: Mayda Insula
complex: Mayda Insula is an island in the Kraken Mare, a body of liquid composed primarily of methane, on Saturn's largest moon Titan. <s> Mayda Insula is the first island (insula) to be named on a planet or moon other than Earth. <s> Mayda Insula was discovered by the "Cassini–Huygens" mission to Saturn. <s> Its name was approved by the International Astronomical Union Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature on April 11, 2008, becoming the first named island on a planetary body other than earth, and the largest. <s> NASA notes, however, that the possibility Mayda Insula is actually peninsular (i.e., connected to the mainland by a strip of land) cannot be conclusively ruled out. <s> All of the insulae on Titan have been named for legendary islands and "Mayda Insula" was derived from the legendary island Mayda which was thought to exist in the northeastern Atlantic Ocean. <s> Its name was approved the same day as the names of Kraken Mare and Ligeia Mare. <s> Mayda Insula lies in the northern end of the Kraken Mare near Titan's north pole. <s> The island has a northernmost latitude of 80.3 degrees north and a southernmost latitude of 77.4 degrees north; it has a westernmost longitude of approximately 321.2 degrees west and an easternmost longitude of 302.7 degrees west. <s> The island is 168 km wide at its widest point. <s> Its dimensions are approximately 90 by , about the same size as the Big Island of Hawaii. <s> Mayda Insula features in Michael Carroll's novel "On the Shores of Titan's Farthest Sea: A Scientific Novel". <s> The 39th chapter of the book is titled "The Hunchback of Mayda Insula".
simple: Mayda Insula is an island in the Kraken Mare. <s> It is a body of liquid composed mostly of methane, on Saturn's largest moon Titan. <s> Mayda Insula is the first island (insula) to be named on a planet or moon other than Earth. <s> Mayda Insula was discovered by the "Cassini–Huygens" mission to Saturn. <s> Its name was approved by the International Astronomical Union Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature on April 11, 2008. <s> It became the first named island anywhere other than earth. <s> However, there is a possibility that Mayda Insula is actually peninsular. <s> All of the island on Titan have been named after legendary islands. <s> "Mayda Insula" was named after a legendary island Mayda which was thought to exist in the northeastern Atlantic Ocean. <s> Its name was approved the same day as the names of Kraken Mare and Ligeia Mare. <s> Mayda Insula was mentioned in Michael Carroll's novel "On the Shores of Titan's Farthest Sea: A Scientific Novel". <s> The 39th chapter of the book is titled "The Hunchback of Mayda Insula".

title: Frank Gore
complex: Franklin Delano "Frank" Gore (born May 14, 1983) is an American football running back for the Buffalo Bills of the National Football League (NFL). <s> He played college football for the University of Miami, and was drafted by the San Francisco 49ers in the third round of the 2005 NFL Draft, playing with them from 2005 to 2014. <s> He is the 49ers all-time leader in rushing yards and rushing touchdowns. <s> Gore was selected in the third round with the 65th overall pick of the 2005 NFL Draft by the San Francisco 49ers. <s> He was the sixth running back to be selected in the 2005 NFL Draft.
simple: Franklin Delano "Frank" Gore (born May 14, 1983) is an American football player. <s> He plays for the San Francisco 49ers. <s> He played football for the University of Miami. <s> He was drafted by the 49ers in the third round of the 2005 NFL Draft.

title: Gilligan's Island
complex: Gilligan's Island is an American sitcom created and produced by Sherwood Schwartz. <s> The show had an ensemble cast that featured Bob Denver, Alan Hale Jr., Jim Backus, Natalie Schafer, Russell Johnson, Tina Louise, and Dawn Wells.
simple: Gilligan's Island is a 1964 American television series.

title: James Turrell
complex: James Turrell (born May 6, 1943) is an American artist primarily concerned with Light and Space. <s> Turrell was a MacArthur Fellow in 1984. <s> Turrell is best known for his work in progress, "Roden Crater", a natural cinder cone crater located outside Flagstaff, Arizona, that he is turning into a massive naked-eye observatory. <s> James Turrell was born in Los Angeles, California. <s> His father, Archibald Milton Turrell, was an aeronautical engineer and educator. <s> His mother, Margaret Hodges Turrell, trained as a medical doctor and later worked in the Peace Corps. <s> His parents were Quakers. <s> Turrell obtained a pilot's license when he was 16 years old. <s> Later, registered as a conscientious objector during the Vietnam War, he ended up flying Buddhist monks out of Chinese-controlled Tibet. <s> Some writers have suggested it was a CIA mission; Turrell called it "a humanitarian mission" — and that he found "some beautiful places to fly". <s> For years he restored antique airplanes to support his "art habit". <s> He received a BA degree from Pomona College in perceptual psychology in 1965 (including the study of the Ganzfeld effect) and also studied mathematics, geology and astronomy there. <s> Turrell enrolled in the graduate Studio Art program at the University of California, Irvine in 1966, where he began making work using light projections. <s> His studies at the University of California, Irvine were interrupted in 1966, when he was arrested for coaching young men to avoid the Vietnam draft. <s> He spent about a year in jail. <s> He later (1973) received an MA degree in art from Claremont Graduate University. <s> In 2004, he was awarded an honorary doctorate by Haverford College. <s> Turrell has received numerous awards in the arts including The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation Fellowship in 1984 and the National Medal of Arts in 2013.
simple: James Turrell (born May 6, 1943) is an American artist. <s> He uses light and space to create his artwork. <s> James Turrell was born in Pasadena, California. <s> His father was Archibald Milton Turrell. <s> He was an aeronautical engineer and teacher. <s> His mother was Margaret Hodges Turrell. <s> She studied medicine and worked in the Peace Corps. <s> Both of his parents were Quakers. <s> Turrell got a pilot's license when he was 16 years old. <s> He earned a BA degree from Pomona College in perceptual psychology in 1965. <s> He studied the Ganzfeld effect and mathematics, geology and astronomy there. <s> Turrell entered the graduate Studio Art program at the University of California, Irvine in 1966. <s> Then he began making work using light projections. <s> In 1966 he was arrested for teaching young men how to avoid getting drafted in the Vietnam War. <s> He spent about a year in jail and left UC Irvine. <s> In 1973, he earned an MA degree in art from Claremont Graduate University. <s> In 2004, he was awarded an honorary doctorate by Haverford College. <s> Turrell has received many awards in the arts including The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation Fellowship in 1984 and the National Medal of Arts in 2013.

title: Zork II
complex: Zork II: The Wizard of Frobozz is an interactive fiction video game published by Infocom in 1981. <s> It was written by Marc Blank, Dave Lebling, Bruce Daniels and Tim Anderson. <s> It was the second game in the popular Zork trilogy and was released for a wide range of computer systems. <s> It begins where "Zork I" left off and leads into "Zork III". <s> It is Infocom's second game. <s> The player begins in the Barrow from "Zork I" armed only with the trusty brass lantern and the elvish sword of great antiquity from before. <s> The objective of the game is not initially clear. <s> The Wizard of Frobozz is soon introduced. <s> The wizard was once a respected enchanter, but when his powers began to fade he was exiled by Lord Dimwit Flathead. <s> Now bordering on senility, the wizard is still a force to be reckoned with. <s> The player's goal in the wizard's realm is to avoid his capricious tricks and to learn to control his magic. <s> Like its predecessor, "Zork II" is essentially a treasure hunt. <s> Unlike the previous game, the ten treasures are tied together by a crude plot. <s> Finding the treasures does not end the game, nor are all the treasures needed to finish the game. <s> Instead, the adventurer must figure out a way to use the treasures in order to reach the game's finale.
simple: Zork II: The Wizard of Frobozz is an interactive fiction video game published by Infocom in 1981. <s> It was written by Marc Blank, Dave Lebling, Bruce Daniels and Tim Anderson. <s> It was the second game in the popular Zork trilogy. <s> It begins where "Zork I" left off and leads into "Zork III". <s> It is Infocom's second game. <s> The player starts in the Barrow from Zork I armed only with the brass lantern and the elvish sword. <s> The purpose of the game is not initially clear. <s> The Wizard of Frobozz is soon introduced. <s> The wizard was once a good sorceror, but when his powers began to go away he was exiled by Lord Dimwit Flathead. <s> Now bordering on insanity, the wizard is a force to be reckoned with. <s> Your goal, as you venture into the wizard's area, is to avoid his tricks and learn to control his magic. <s> Like its predecessor, "Zork II" is essentially a treasure hunt. <s> Unlike the previous game, the ten treasures are tied together by a crude plot. <s> Finding the treasures does not end the game, and finding all the treasures is not needed to finish the game. <s> Instead, the adventurer must figure out a way to use the treasures in order to reach the game's finale.

title: Unicellular organism
complex: A unicellular organism, also known as a single-celled organism, is an organism that consists of only one cell, unlike a multicellular organism that consists of more than one cell. <s> Unicellular organisms fall into two general categories: prokaryotic organisms and eukaryotic organisms. <s> Prokaryotes include bacteria and archaea. <s> Many eukaryotes are multicellular, but the group includes the protozoa, unicellular algae, and unicellular fungi. <s> Unicellular organisms are thought to be the oldest form of life, with early protocells possibly emerging 3.8–4 billion years ago. <s> Some organisms are partially unicellular, like "Dictyostelium discoideum".
simple: Unicellular organisms are organisms that have one cell. <s> Unicellular organisms can be found everywhere. <s> Almost all unicellular organisms are microorganisms but you can observe eukaryotes and many prokaryotes by using a compound microscope. <s> The oldest forms of life existed 3.8 billion years ago, if not longer.

title: Wolfgang Schäuble
complex: Wolfgang Schäuble (] ; born 18 September 1942) is a German lawyer and politician of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party whose political career has spanned more than four decades. <s> He is one of the most experienced and longest serving politicians in German history and since 2017 has been the President of the Bundestag. <s> On 27 September 2017 the CDU/CSU group in the Bundestag announced Schäuble's nomination as President of the Bundestag. <s> He was elected to that position on 24 October 2017.
simple: Wolfgang Schäuble (] born 18 September 1942) is a German lawyer and politician. <s> He is a member of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU). <s> His political career has spanned more than forty years. <s> On 27 September 2017 the CDU/CSU group in the Bundestag announced Schäuble’s nomination as President of the Bundestag and assumed office on 24 October 2017.

title: Frank Sullivan (baseball)
complex: Franklin Leal Sullivan (January 23, 1930 – January 19, 2016), was an American professional baseball right-handed pitcher, who played in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the Boston Red Sox, Philadelphia Phillies, and Minnesota Twins over parts of eleven seasons, spanning –. <s> Sullivan was named to the American League (AL) All-Star team, in and , and was elected to the Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame, in 2008. <s> Sullivan died in Lihue, Hawaii, from pneumonia on January 19, 2016 at the age of 85.
simple: Franklin Leal "Frank" Sullivan (January 23, 1930 – January 19, 2016) was an American right-handed pitcher in Major League Baseball. <s> Sullivan was named to the American League All-Star team in 1955 and 1956, and was elected to the Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame in 2008. <s> Sullivan died in Lihue, Hawaii from pneumonia on January 19, 2016 at the age of 85.

title: Adam Scott (actor)
complex: Adam Paul Scott (born April 3, 1973) is an American actor, comedian, producer, and podcaster. <s> He is known for his role as Ben Wyatt in the NBC sitcom "Parks and Recreation" for which he was nominated for the Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actor in a Comedy Series in 2013. <s> He has also appeared as Derek in the film "Step Brothers", Johnny Meyer in "The Aviator", Henry Pollard in the Starz sitcom "Party Down", Ed Mackenzie in the HBO series "Big Little Lies", Adam Yates, Jr. in "Hot Tub Time Machine 2", and Trevor in the NBC series "The Good Place".
simple: Adam Paul Scott (born April 3, 1973) is an American actor, comedian, director, screenwriter, producer, podcaster, dancer, and poet. <s> He is best known for his role as Ben Wyatt in the NBC sitcom "Parks and Recreation". <s> He has also appeared as Derek in the movie "Step Brothers", and Henry Pollard in the Starz sitcom "Party Down".

title: Slingshot
complex: Slingshots depend on strong elastic materials, typically vulcanized natural rubber or the equivalent, and thus date no earlier than the invention of vulcanized rubber by Charles Goodyear in 1839 (patented in 1844). <s> By 1860, this "new engine" had already established a reputation for juvenile use in vandalism.
simple: How strong and dangerous the slingshot is depends on how it is made and especially the elastic band.

title: Amalgam (chemistry)
complex: An amalgam is an alloy of mercury with another metal, which may be a liquid, a soft paste or a solid, depending upon the proportion of mercury. <s> These alloys are formed through metallic bonding, with the electrostatic attractive force of the conduction electrons working to bind all the positively charged metal ions together into a crystal lattice structure. <s> Almost all metals can form amalgams with mercury, the notable exceptions being iron, platinum, tungsten, and tantalum. <s> Silver-mercury amalgams are important in dentistry, and gold-mercury amalgam is used in the extraction of gold from ore. <s> Dentistry has used alloys of mercury with metals such as silver, copper, indium, tin and zinc. <s> Aluminium can form an amalgam through a reaction with mercury. <s> Aluminium amalgam may be prepared by either grinding aluminium pellets or wire in mercury, or by allowing aluminium wire or foil to react with a solution of mercuric chloride.
simple: An amalgam is a solution of a metal in mercury. <s> Many metals can dissolve in mercury. <s> Platinum and iron cannot form amalgams. <s> Amalgams are used in tooth fillings. <s> Aluminum forms an amalgam which can react with water because the thin oxide coating on the aluminum is dissolved.

title: Klippan, Scania
complex: Klippan (literally "the Cliff") is a locality and the seat of Klippan Municipality, Skåne County, Sweden with 8,116 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: It is the seat of Klippan Municipality.

title: Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement
complex: Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement ( ; , "Chăvash Surăm yal tărăkhĕ") is an administrative and municipal division (a rural settlement) of Alikovsky District of the Chuvash Republic, Russia. <s> It is located in the eastern part of the district. <s> Its administrative center is the rural locality (a "selo") of Chuvashskaya Sorma. <s> Rural settlement's population: 1,758 (2006 est.). <s> Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement comprises sixteen rural localities. <s> The Cheboksary–Yadrin highway crosses the territory of the rural settlement.
simple: Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement or Chuvash-Sorma Rural Settlement (; , "Chăvash Surăm yal tărăkhĕ") is an administrative and municipal division (a rural settlement) of Alikovsky District of the Chuvash Republic, Russia. <s> It is located in the eastern part of the district. <s> Its administrative center is the locality (a "selo") of Chuvashskaya Sorma. <s> Rural settlement's population: 1,758 (2006 est.). <s> Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement comprises sixteen rural localities. <s> The Cheboksary–Yadrin highway crosses the territory of the rural settlement.

title: Ivan Korsak
complex: Ivan Feodosiyovych Korsak ( ; 15 September 1946 – 7 December 2017) was a Ukrainian writer and journalist. <s> Ivan Korsak was born on 15 September 1946 in Zabolottya (in the Ratne district of Volyn region). <s> As an undergraduate in college he studied agronomy and journalism. <s> Korsak worked as an editor of the newspaper "Radyans'ke Polissya" in Kamin-Kashyrsky (1975–90), and also for "Narodna trybuna" in Lutsk (1990–95). <s> In 1996, he became the chief editor of the newspaper "Simya i Dim". <s> Korsak has been a member of the National Union of Writers of Ukraine and an editorial board member of the newspaper "Literary Ukraine" since 2011.
simple: Ivan Feodosiyovych Korsak (; 15 September 1946 – 7 December 2017) was a Ukrainian writer and journalist. <s> Korsak died on 7 December 2017 in Lutsk, Volyn Oblast, at the age of 71. <s> He was born in Zabolottya, Volyn Oblast. <s> He was also worked at newspapers such as "Radyans'ke Polissya", "Narodna trybuna" and "Literary Ukraine". <s> He was best known as chief editor of the newspaper "Simya i Dim".

title: Clare Hollingworth
complex: Clare Hollingworth, OBE (10 October 1911 – 10 January 2017) was an English journalist and author. <s> She was the first war correspondent to report the outbreak of World War II, described as "the scoop of the century". <s> As a reporter for "The Daily Telegraph" in 1939, while travelling from Poland to Germany, she spotted and reported German forces massed on the Polish border; three days later she was the first to report the German invasion of Poland. <s> Hollingworth was appointed OBE by Elizabeth II for "services to journalism" in 1982. <s> She died in 2017 at the age of 105. <s> Hollingworth was born in 1911 in Knighton, a southern suburb of Leicester, the daughter of Daisy and Albert Hollingworth. <s> During World War I, her father took over the running of his father's footwear factory, and the family moved to a farm near Shepshed. <s> She showed an early interest in becoming a writer, against opposition from her mother, and her interest in warfare was stimulated by visits to historical battlefield sites in Britain and France with her father. <s> After leaving school, she attended a domestic science college in Leicester, which she did not enjoy. <s> From 1981, Hollingworth lived in Hong Kong. <s> She was a near-daily visitor to the Foreign Correspondents' Club, where she was an honorary goodwill ambassador.
simple: Clare Hollingworth (10 October 1911 – 10 January 2017) was an English journalist and author. <s> She worked for the newspaper "The Daily Telegraph". <s> She died on 10 January 2017 in Central, Hong Kong at the age of 105. <s> She was born in Knighton, Leicester, England. <s> In World War I, her father took over the running of his father's footwear factory, and they moved to a farm near Shepshed. <s> Hollingworth moved to Hong Kong in the 1980s.

title: José Plácido Caamaño
complex: José María Plácido Caamaño y Gómez-Cornejo (5 October 1837 – December 31, 1900) was President of Ecuador 23 November 1883 to 1 July 1888. <s> Caamaño was born in Guayaquil. <s> He was the grandson of Spanish explorer Jacinto Caamaño. <s> He studied law and theology in the seminary of his native city, and was educated in Quito. <s> Subsequently he was mayor of Guayaquil, and chief of the custom-house service. <s> He was a member of the Progresistas, a liberal Catholic party. <s> An attempt was made to assassinate him in 1886, and he narrowly escaped death by throwing himself into a river. <s> Under his administration telegraphs, railways, an institute of sciences, several Colleges, and many new schools were added to the resources of Ecuador. <s> After his term ended, he served as ambassador to US from 1889 to 1890.
simple: José María Plácido Caamaño y Gómez-Cornejo (5 October 1837 – December 31, 1901) was President of Ecuador from 23 November 1883 to 1 July 1888. <s> Caamaño was born in Guayaquil. <s> He studied law and theology in the seminary of his native city, and was educated in Quito. <s> Subsequently he was mayor of Guayaquil, and chief of the custom-house service. <s> He was a member of the Progresistas, a liberal Catholic party. <s> An attempt was made to assassinate him in 1886, and he narrowly escaped death by throwing himself into a river. <s> Under his administration telegraphs, railways, an institute of sciences, several Colleges, and many new schools were added to the resources of Ecuador. <s> After his term ended, he served as ambassador to US from 1889 to 1890.

title: Nubia
complex: Around AD 350, the area was invaded by the Kingdom of Aksum and the Meroitic kingdom collapsed. <s> Eventually, three smaller Christian kingdoms replaced it: northernmost was Nobatia between the first and second cataract of the Nile River, with its capital at Pachoras (modern-day Faras); in the middle was Makuria, with its capital at Old Dongola; and southernmost was Alodia, with its capital at Soba (near Khartoum).
simple: Their true decline was around 350 AD, when the kingdom of Axum invaded and broke up the culture once again.

title: Lee Teng-hui
complex: Lee Teng-hui (, ] ; born 15 January 1923) is a Taiwanese statesman who was the President of the Republic of China and Chairman of the Kuomintang (KMT) from 1988 to 2000. <s> He was the first president of the Republic of China to be born in Taiwan.
simple: Lee Teng-hui (born 15 January 1923), sometimes called the "father of Taiwan's democracy", is a politician of the Republic of China (commonly known as Taiwan). <s> He was the President of the Republic of China and Chairman of the Kuomintang (KMT) from 1988 to 2000.

title: Aulis Rytkönen
complex: Taavi Aulis Rytkönen (5 January 1929 – 16 April 2014) was a Finnish footballer. <s> He became the country's first professional player when he signed for France's Toulouse FC in 1952. <s> Rytkönen earned 37 caps for the Finnish national team, scoring seven goals. <s> He played for Finland at the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki. <s> He also worked as national coach from 1975 to 1978. <s> He was chosen Finland's Player of the Year in 1949, 1950, and 1952.
simple: Taavi Aulis Rytkönen (5 January 1929 – 16 April 2014) was a Finnish footballer. <s> He became the country's first professional player when he signed for France's Toulouse FC in 1952. <s> He played for Finland at the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki. <s> He also worked as national coach from 1975 to 1978. <s> He was chosen Finland's Player of the Year in 1949, 1950, and 1952.

15, 1982 in the southern village of Kanisah in Lebanon's Tyre District. <s> Abboud's father and mother, named Mounir and Maryam, had three brothers and six sisters between them. <s> As a child Abboud started singing and dancing and was a fan of Egyptian pop singer Amr Diab. <s> Her father encouraged her and bought her a violin while she was six years old. <s> Starting at age 14 she worked as a private tutor for more than 13 students. <s> Abboud studied English literature at the Lebanese University and translation in Beirut Arab University, graduating with a master's degree. <s> She went on to study music at the Lebanese National Higher Conservatory of music for two years. <s> Abboud served as an officer for the Lebanese Police Force, working security for two years in the Beirut–Rafic Hariri International Airport's Inspection Department. <s> Abboud appeared on TV for the first time on the hit show Studio El-Fan as a competitor for its 2001–02 season. <s> She sang at various Beirut cafés and restaurants, eventually networking with musicians like Richard Najm, Tony Abi Karam, and Salim Salameh. <s> Abboud went on to study music under Richard Najm, and in 2006 became a multi-instrumentalist skilled in the oud, organ and guitar. <s> Her first album, "Fi Shouq" ( : "On Longing") was released in late 2007. <s> In an interview with Egyptian media about her penchant to Fakih, in "Design & Brands Event" held at the Four Seasons Hotel of Beirut. <s> Abboud is founder of Amman-based wedding planning company Loulou Secret. <s> She also runs Layal Productions for her music. <s> Sometimes called a seductive artist and femme fatale by Al Akhbar and other critics, Abboud appeared on the program "Bala Teshfir" on the Al Jadeed network in 2015, stating, "Being bold is not seduction". <s> She believes there is a bias against her and said, "I am a normal artist and contemporary with fashion." <s> In 2016 counterfeit images were published attributed to Abboud's likeness. <s> She appointed attorney Haitham Tarshishi to file a lawsuit against "all those involved in the forgery of a picture attributed to her through social media sites, accompanied by words beyond the limits of fitness." <s> In August 2016 the Lebanese Broadcasting Corporation reported that a suspect had been arrested. <s> In April 2017 as a guest on the LBCI satirical program "La-hon Wa-bas" hosted by Hicham Haddad, Abboud condemned an issue of "Nadine Magazine" for its depiction of her chest and face shape with the words, "Bigger than this chest" emblazoned on its cover, based on her quote while she used Arabic word of ṣadr which can be an invocation for conscience and heart. <s> She accused the magazine of trying to increase readership by dumbing down and oversimplifying its content. <s> Earlier in Jun 26, 2017 strongly criticized yellow-pens of Lebanese music journalists. <s> Moved to Beirut in 2009. <s> Abboud cares about her physical health and elegance. <s> In June 2017 she publicly confirmed that she had undergone rhinoplasty, but that the rest of her features were not the result of plastic surgery, stating, "The secret of my beauty is sport". <s> She is an advocate for a public smoking ban for Lebanon, saying, "Smoking and non-smoking areas must be allocated". <s> Having had an interest in sport and horseback riding since childhood, Abboud has four horses, which she keeps in the village of Tanbourit in Lebanon's Sidon District. <s> Their names are Rim, Loulou, Khaybar (named after Khaibar-1 ) and Layal (named after her given name). <s> Abboud is a practising Muslim. <s> She fasts and abstains from performing during Ramadan, and holds the pre-dawn and post-sunset meals of Suhur and Iftar with her family. <s> Involved in philanthropic activities and has described herself as an "abnormal generous person." <s> Abboud married at the age of sixteen in 1998 and gave birth to her only son, Jad, in 2004. <s> She eventually divorced her husband, later describing the marriage as "very formal," adding, "My early marriage was the result of a love story. <s> I am a romantic and dreamy woman." <s> In June 2017 she said, "By respect among us, we divorced and I chose my career in art."

title: Forseti
complex: Forseti (Old Norse "the presiding one," actually "president" in modern Icelandic and Faroese) is the god of justice and reconciliation in Norse mythology. <s> He is generally identified with Fosite, a god of the Frisians. <s> Jacob Grimm noted that if, as Adam of Bremen states, Fosite's sacred island was Heligoland, that would make him an ideal candidate for a deity known to both Frisians and Scandinavians, but that it is surprising he is never mentioned by Saxo Grammaticus. <s> According to Snorri Sturluson in the Prose Edda, Forseti is the son of Baldr and Nanna. <s> His home is Glitnir, its name, meaning "shining," refers to its silver ceiling and golden pillars, which radiated light that could be seen from a great distance.
simple: Forseti is a god of justice and reconciliation in Norse mythology. <s> Forseti's name means "the presiding one" in Old Norse. <s> He is often identified with Fosite, a god in the mythology of the Frisians. <s> Forseti was the son of Nanna and Baldur.

title: Fernando Gago
complex: Fernando Rubén Gago (] ; born 10 April 1986) is an Argentine footballer who last played for Boca Juniors as a defensive midfielder and deep-lying playmaker. <s> He is also a former Argentina national team player.
simple: Fernando Gago (born 10 April 1986) is an Argentine football player. <s> He plays for Real Madrid and Argentina national team.

title: Cachapoal Province
complex: Cachapoal Province is one of three provinces of the central Chilean region of O'Higgins (VI). <s> Its capital is the city of Rancagua (pop. <s> According to the 2002 census by the National Statistics Institute ("INE"), the province spans an area of 7384.2 sqkm and had a population of 542,901 inhabitants (271,226 men and 271,675 women), giving it a population density of 73.5 PD/sqkm . <s> It is the fifth most populated province in the country. <s> Between the 1992 and 2002 censuses, the population grew by 13.8% (65,871 persons). <s> As a province, Cachapoal is a second-level administrative division of Chile, governed by a provincial governor who is appointed by the president.
simple: Cachapoal Province is one of three provinces of the central Chilean region of Libertador General Bernardo O'Higgins (VI). <s> Its capital is the city of Rancagua. <s> s of 2002 (last national census), there were 542,901 people living in the province, giving it a population density of 73.52197936133908 /km2 inhabitants/km2. <s> As a province, Cachapoal is a second-level administrative division, consisting of 17 communes ("comunas"). <s> The province is administered by a governor.

title: Aharon Lichtenstein
complex: Aharon Lichtenstein (May 23, 1933 – April 20, 2015) was a noted Orthodox rabbi and rosh yeshiva. <s> He was an authority in Jewish law ("Halakha"). <s> Rabbi Lichtenstein was born in Paris, France, but grew up in the United States, studied in Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin under Rabbi Yitzchok Hutner. <s> He earned a BA and "semicha" ("rabbinic ordination") at Yeshiva University under Rabbi Joseph B. Soloveitchik, whose daughter, Tovah, he would later marry, and a PhD in English Literature at Harvard University, where he studied under Douglas Bush. <s> In 2005, he and his wife Dr. Tovah (née Soloveitchik) moved to Alon Shvut, where Yeshivat Har Etzion is located. <s> They were married in 1960 and had six children. <s> Lichtenstein was awarded the Israel Prize for Jewish Literature on Israeli Independence Day: May 6, 2014. <s> He died on April 20, 2015. <s> He was a source of inspiration for a wide circle of Jewry, for both his educational attainments and his intellectual and spiritual leadership.
simple: Aharon Lichtenstein (23 May 1933 – 20 April 2015) was a French-born American-Israeli Orthodox rabbi, rosh yeshiva and writer. <s> He was an authority of Jewish law ("Halacha"). <s> Lichtenstein was born in Paris and grew up in New York, United States. <s> He studied at Yeshiva University and Harvard University. <s> He married in 1960 and had six children. <s> He won the Israel Prize in 2014. <s> Lichtenstein died on 20 April 2015 in Jerusalem, aged 81.

title: Francis Dashwood, 11th Baron le Despencer
complex: Francis Dashwood, 11th Baron le Despencer, PC, FRS (December 1708 – 11 December 1781) was an English rake and politician, Chancellor of the Exchequer (1762–1763) and founder of the Hellfire Club. <s> Dashwood was born in Great Marlborough Street, London, in December 1708. <s> He was only son of Sir Francis Dashwood, 1st Baronet (died 1724), and his second wife Mary, eldest daughter of Vere Fane, 4th Earl of Westmorland. <s> Dashwood was educated at Eton College where he became associated with William Pitt the Elder. <s> Upon the death of his father on 4 November 1724, Dashwood, who was only fifteen, inherited his father's estates and the Baronetcy of Dashwood of West Wycombe.
simple: Francis Dashwood, 15th Baron le Despencer (December 1708–11 December 1781) was an English rake and politician. <s> He was Chancellor of the Exchequer (1762-1763) and founder of The Hellfire Club. <s> Dashwood was born in London. <s> He was educated at Eton College where he became associated with William Pitt the Elder.

title: Josefina Villalobos
complex: Josefina Villalobos (born August 5, 1924) is an American-born Colombian-Ecuadorian public servant. <s> She was the First Lady of Ecuador serving from August 10, 1992 through August 10, 1996 when her husband, Sixto Durán Ballén, served as President of Ecuador. <s> Ballén and Villalobos had eight children. <s> After Ballén left office, the two retired and lived in Quito, Ecuador. <s> On November 15, 2016, Ballén died at the age of 95.

title: Taeyeon discography
complex: Kim Tae-yeon, better known by the mononym Taeyeon, is a South Korean singer. <s> Her discography consists of one studio album, four extended plays (EPs), thirty two singles (including six as featured artist), and three promotional singles. <s> She debuted as a member of South Korean girl group Girls' Generation in August 2007 and initially gained some popularity as a singer upon recording soundtrack songs "If" for "Hong Gil Dong" and "Can You Hear Me" for "Beethoven Virus" (2008). <s> She subsequently established herself as one of the most renowned vocalists on the South Korean music scene with further soundtrack recordings, notably "I Love You" for "" (2010), "Missing You like Crazy" for "The King 2 Hearts", "Closer" for "To the Beautiful You" (2012), and "And One" for "That Winter, the Wind Blows" (2013), all of which managed to enter the top ten of South Korea's Gaon Digital Chart. <s> Apart from soundtrack recordings, Taeyeon has also recorded duets with other artists, most notably "Like a Star" with The One and "Different" with Kim Bum-soo, which peaked at numbers one and two on the Gaon Digital Chart, respectively. <s> Her career as a soloist began in 2015 with the release of her debut extended play "I". <s> The EP was a commercial success in South Korea, where it peaked at number two on the country's Gaon Album Chart and has since sold over 150,000 physical copies. <s> The title track of the same name peaked atop the Gaon Digital Chart and has sold over 1.8 million digital units. <s> In February 2016, Taeyeon released "Rain" as the opening single for S.M. Entertainment's digital music project SM Station. <s> The single peaked atop the Gaon Digital Chart and charted at number three on the "Billboard" World Digital Songs. <s> Her second EP "Why" was released in June 2016 to similar success, peaking atop the Gaon Album Chart and having sold over 110,000 physical copies. <s> It produced two Gaon Digital Chart top-ten singles–"Starlight" and "Why". <s> She subsequently released a digital single titled "" in November, which charted at number two on the Gaon Digital Chart. <s> Taeyeon released her first studio album, "My Voice", in February 2017. <s> The album peaked atop the Gaon Album Chart and has sold over 200,000 physical copies in South Korea. <s> It yielded a single titled "Fine", which was a number one on the Gaon Digital Chart and peaked at number seven on the World Digital Songs. <s> It subsequently yielded the single "Make Me Love You" off the deluxe edition, which charted at number four on the Gaon Digital Chart.
simple: Taeyeon's discography consists of a studio album, two EPs, twenty singles and ten soundtracks. <s> The singer debuted in girl group Girls' Generation in August 2007 and then in Girls' Generation-TTS in May 2012. <s> Her solo career began in 2015 with the release of her debut mini-album entitled "I". <s> The EP was a commercial success in South Korea, where it reached number two on Gaon Album Chart and since then has sold more than 140,000 physical copies. <s> The single of the same name managed to position itself in the first position of Gaon Digital Chart and has sold more than 1,8 million digital copies. <s> In February 2016, Taeyeon published "Rain" as the first single from SM Station. <s> The single reached the maximum position in Gaon Digital Chart and was ranked number three in Billboard World Digital Songs. <s> His second EP, Why, was released in June 2016, reaching the top in Gaon Album Chart and managed to sell more than 110,000 physical copies. <s> He produced two singles that were included in the mini album, "Starlight" and "Why". <s> Subsequently, he released a digital single titled "" in November, which was ranked second in Gaon Digital Chart. <s> Taeyeon released her first studio album, "My Voice", in February 2017. <s> The album won first place in Gaon Album Chart and sold more than 109,000 physical copies in its first month of release. <s> He produced the single "Fine", which was number one on Gaon Digital Chart and reached number seven on Billboard World Digital Songs.

title: Bartow, Georgia
complex: Bartow is a town in Jefferson County, Georgia, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 286. <s> Initially the town was known as "Spier's Turnout", but was changed to honor the first Confederate officer to die in battle, Colonel Francis S. Bartow of Savannah, Georgia, who was killed at the Battle of Manassas, Virginia on July 21, 1861.

title: Saint François d'Assise
complex: Saint François d'Assise is an opera in three acts and eight scenes by French composer and librettist Olivier Messiaen, written from 1975 to 1983. <s> It concerns Saint Francis of Assisi, the title character, and displays the composer's devout Catholicism. <s> The world première was given by the Paris Opera at the Palais Garnier on 28 November 1983. <s> For maximum artistic freedom, Messiaen penned both libretto and score. <s> For nearly eight years, the composer consulted Franciscan sources, reading biographies by Thomas of Celano and St. Bonaventure, as well as Francis' own prayers (including "Canticle of the Sun").
simple: Saint François d'Assise is an opera in three acts and eight scenes. <s> The opera was written from 1975 to 1983. <s> The first performance was given by the Paris Opéra at the Palais Garnier on November 28, 1983. <s> The music and libretto were written by Olivier Messiaen.

title: Hämeenlinna
complex: Hämeenlinna ( , Karelian: "Hämienlinna") is a city and municipality of about inhabitants in the heart of the historical province of Häme in the south of Finland. <s> Hämeenlinna is the oldest inland city of Finland and was one of the most important Finnish cities until the 19th century.
simple: Hämeenlinna is a town in Finland.

title: National Portrait Gallery, London
complex: The National Portrait Gallery (NPG) is an art gallery in London housing a collection of portraits of historically important and famous British people. <s> It was the first portrait gallery in the world when it opened in 1856. <s> The gallery moved in 1896 to its current site at St Martin's Place, off Trafalgar Square, and adjoining the National Gallery. <s> It has been expanded twice since then. <s> The National Portrait Gallery also has regional outposts at Beningbrough Hall in Yorkshire and Montacute House in Somerset. <s> It is unconnected to the Scottish National Portrait Gallery in Edinburgh, with which its remit overlaps. <s> The gallery is a non-departmental public body sponsored by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport. <s> The gallery houses portraits of historically important and famous British people, selected on the basis of the significance of the sitter, not that of the artist. <s> The collection includes photographs and caricatures as well as paintings, drawings and sculpture. <s> One of its best-known images is the Chandos portrait, the most famous portrait of William Shakespeare although there is some uncertainty about whether the painting actually is of the playwright. <s> Not all of the portraits are exceptional artistically, although there are self-portraits by William Hogarth, Sir Joshua Reynolds and other British artists of note. <s> Some, such as the group portrait of the participants in the Somerset House Conference of 1604, are important historical documents in their own right. <s> Often, the curiosity value is greater than the artistic worth of a work, as in the case of the anamorphic portrait of Edward VI by William Scrots, Patrick Branwell Brontë's painting of his sisters Charlotte, Emily and Anne, or a sculpture of Queen Victoria and Prince Albert in medieval costume. <s> Portraits of living figures were allowed from 1969. <s> In addition to its permanent galleries of historical portraits, the National Portrait Gallery exhibits a rapidly changing selection of contemporary work, stages exhibitions of portrait art by individual artists and hosts the annual BP Portrait Prize competition. <s> In addition to the busts of the three founders of the gallery over the entrance, the exterior of two of the original 1896 buildings are decorated with stone block busts of eminent portrait artists, biographical writers and historians. <s> These busts, sculpted by Frederick R. Thomas, depict James Granger, William Faithorne, Edmund Lodge, Thomas Fuller, The Earl of Clarendon, Horace Walpole, Hans Holbein the Younger, Sir Anthony van Dyck, Sir Peter Lely, Sir Godfrey Kneller, Louis François Roubiliac, William Hogarth, Sir Joshua Reynolds, Sir Thomas Lawrence and Sir Francis Chantrey.
simple: The National Portrait Gallery (NPG) is an art gallery in London. <s> It holds a collection of portraits of historically important and famous British people. <s> It was the first portrait gallery in the world when it opened in 1856. <s> The gallery moved in 1896 to its current site at St Martin's Place, off Trafalgar Square, next to the National Gallery. <s> It has been expanded twice since then. <s> The National Portrait Gallery also has three regional outposts. <s> It is not connected to the Scottish National Portrait Gallery in Edinburgh. <s> The NPG is a quango sponsored by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport. <s> The gallery houses portraits of historically important and famous British people, selected on the basis of the significance of the sitter, not that of the artist. <s> The collection includes photographs and caricatures as well as paintings, drawings and sculpture. <s> One of its best-known images is the 'Chandos portrait', the most famous portrait of William Shakespeare although there is some uncertainty about whether the painting actually is of the playwright. <s> Not all of the portraits are exceptional artistically, although there are self-portraits by William Hogarth, Sir Joshua Reynolds and other British artists of note. <s> Some, such as the group portrait of the participants in the Somerset House Conference of 1604, are important historical documents in their own right. <s> Often, the curiosity value is greater than the artistic worth of a work, as in the case of the portrait of Edward VI by William Scrots, Patrick Brontë's painting of his sisters Charlotte, Emily and Anne, or a sculpture of Queen Victoria and Prince Albert in medieval costume. <s> Portraits of living figures were allowed from 1969. <s> In addition to its permanent galleries of historical portraits, the National Portrait Gallery exhibits a rapidly changing collection of contemporary work, stages exhibitions of portrait art by individual artists and hosts the annual BP Portrait Prize competition. <s> The Gallery has many portrait busts by sculptors.

title: Trifolium pratense
complex: Trifolium pratense, the red clover, is a herbaceous species of flowering plant in the bean family Fabaceae, native to Europe, Western Asia, and northwest Africa, but planted and naturalised in many other regions. <s> The red clover is native to Europe, Western Asia, and northwest Africa, but it has been naturalized in other continents, like North and South America. <s> Specifically, the red clover was brought to Argentina and Chile over 100 years ago, although it is not clear how exactly it was introduced.
simple: Red Clover ("Trifolium pratense") is a species of plant. <s> It is native to Europe, Africa, and Asia.

title: Nurlan Balgimbayev
complex: Nurlan Utebovich Balgimbayev (, "Nurlan Ótepuly Balǵymbaev"; 20 November 1947 – 14 October 2015) was Prime Minister of Kazakhstan from 10 October 1997 to 1 October 1999. <s> He became President of the Kazakhstan Oil Investment Company in February 2002. <s> On 14 October 2015, Balgimbayev died of cancer in Atyrau at the age of 67.
simple: Nurlan Utebovich Balgimbayev (20 November 1947 – 14 October 2015) served as the Prime Minister of Kazakhstan from 10 October 1997 to 1 October 1999. <s> He was the President of the Kazakhstan Oil Investment Company from February 2002. <s> On 14 October 2015 Balgimbayev died in Atyrau at the age of 68, after a long battle with cancer.

title: Leonhard Nagenrauft
complex: Leonhard Nagenrauft (9 March 1938 in Bischofswiesen – 22 May 2017 in Berchtesgaden) was a West German luger who competed in the late 1960s and early 1970s. <s> He won the silver medal in the men's singles event at the 1971 FIL World Luge Championships in Olang, Italy. <s> Nagenrauft also won two medals in the men's singles event at the FIL European Luge Championships with a gold in 1967 and a bronze in 1972. <s> Nagenrauft also competed in two Winter Olympics, earning his best finish of fifth in the men's singles event at Sapporo in 1972.
simple: Leonhard Nagenrauft (March 9, 1938 in Bischofswiesen – May 22, 2017 in Berchtesgaden) was a West German luger who competed in the late 1960s and early 1970s. <s> Nagenrauft died on May 22, 2017 at the age of 79. <s> He won the silver medal in the men's singles event at the 1971 FIL World Luge Championships in Olang, Italy. <s> Nagenrauft also won two medals in the men's singles event at the FIL European Luge Championships with a gold in 1967 and a bronze in 1972. <s> Nagenrauft also competed in two Winter Olympics, earning his best finish of fifth in the men's singles event at Sapporo in 1972.

title: Liseberg
complex: Liseberg is an amusement park located in Gothenburg, Sweden, that opened in 1923. <s> It is one of the most visited amusement parks in Scandinavia, attracting about three million visitors annually. <s> Among the noteworthy attractions is the wooden roller coaster Balder, twice (2003 and 2005) voted as the "Best Wooden Tracked Roller Coaster" in the world in a major international poll. <s> The park itself has also been chosen as one of the top ten amusement parks in the world (2005) by "Forbes" magazine. <s> In 1923, Gothenburg celebrated its 300-year anniversary with the Gothenburg Exhibition (1923), which included a Leisure Park and the Congress Park; the area was opened on 8 May and included fun slides and the 980 ft long wooden Kanneworffska Funicular, designed by the Danish amusement builder Waldemar Lebech (originally there were 5 trains with 3 cars each that accommodated 10 people in each car, the ride lasted 2 and half minute; the ride was demolished in 1987 after having served over 41 million visitors).
simple: Liseberg is an amusement park in Gothenburg, Sweden. <s> Liseberg opened on 8 May 1923. <s> Liseberg is one of the most visited amusement parks in Scandinavia. <s> Many times it has been voted the world’s best wooden roller coaster. <s> In 2005, Liseberg was chosen as one of the top ten amusement parks in the world by "Forbes Magazine".

title: Mitsuru Komaeda
complex: Mitsuru Komaeda (古前田 充 , Komaeda Mitsuru , born April 14, 1950) is a former Japanese football player and manager. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Mitsuru Komaeda (古前田 充, Komaeda Mitsuru, born April 14, 1950) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: Hyundai Elantra
complex: The Hyundai Elantra , or Hyundai Avante (현대 아반떼) in South Korea, is a compact car produced by the South Korean manufacturer Hyundai since 1990. <s> It was sold in Europe from the spring of 1991. <s> It replaced the somewhat larger on the outside Stellar, although that model had not been offered in many markets.
simple: Hyundai Elantra is a compact car sold by Korean automaker Hyundai. <s> It has been sold since 1990.

title: Uptown Girls
complex: Uptown Girls is a 2003 American comedy-drama film directed by Boaz Yakin, who was working from a screenplay which Julia Dahl, Mo Ogrodnik and Lisa Davidowitz had adapted from the story by Allison Jacobs. <s> It stars Brittany Murphy as a 22-year-old living a charmed life as the daughter of a famous rock and roll musician.
simple: Uptown Girls is a movie starring Brittany Murphy and Dakota Fanning.

title: Bird (1988 film)
complex: Bird is a 1988 American biographical film, produced and directed by Clint Eastwood from a screenplay by Joel Oliansky. <s> The film is a tribute to the life and music of jazz saxophonist Charlie "Bird" Parker. <s> It is constructed as a montage of scenes from Parker's life, from his childhood in Kansas City, through his early death at the age of 34. <s> "Bird" received positive reviews from critics, scoring an 80% "Fresh" rating on Rotten Tomatoes from 20 reviews. <s> Forest Whitaker's performance as Parker received positive notices and several awards, including the Best Actor award at the 1988 Cannes Film Festival and a Golden Globe nomination. <s> Clint Eastwood was awarded the Golden Globe for Best Director.
simple: Bird is a 1988 American biographical movie. <s> It was both directed and produced by Clint Eastwood. <s> "Bird" was released on September 30, 1988. <s> The movie is about the life and music of jazz saxophonist Charlie "Bird" Parker. <s> It has a 78% rating on Rotten Tomatoes. <s> The movie won an Academy Award for Best Sound, a Golden Globe Award for Best Director, and Forest Whitaker won Best Actor at the Cannes Film Festival.

title: Marquesas Islands
complex: The Marquesas Islands ( ; or " " or " "; Marquesan: " " (North Marquesan) and " " (South Marquesan), both meaning "the land of men") are a group of volcanic islands in French Polynesia, an overseas collectivity of France in the southern Pacific Ocean. <s> The Marquesas are located at 9.7812° S, 139.0817° W.
simple: The Marquesas Islands are a group of islands in the pacific ocean. <s> They are a part of French Polynesia.

title: VisualEditor
complex: VisualEditor (VE) is a project to provide a "visual" or "WYSIWYG-like" online rich-text editor as a MediaWiki extension to Wikipedia. <s> It was developed by the Wikimedia Foundation in partnership with Wikia. <s> In July 2013 the beta was enabled by default, with the ability to opt-out, for Mediawiki.org and several of the largest Wikipedias.
simple: It is similar to a WYSIWYG editor, and is available as a MediaWiki extension. <s> VisualEditor (VE) is a project developed by the Wikimedia Foundation together with Wikia. <s> The Beta version of this extension was enabled on Mediawiki.org and other larger Wikipedia in July 2013 by default, but users could decide to opt-out.

title: Molucca Sea
complex: The Moluccan Sea (Indonesian: "Laut Maluku") is located in the western Pacific Ocean, around the vicinity of Indonesia, specifically bordered by the Indonesian Islands of Celebes (Sulawesi) to the west, Halmahera to the east, and the Sula Islands to the south. <s> The Molucca Sea has a total surface area of 77,000 square miles (200,000 square km). <s> The Molucca Sea is rich in coral and has many diving sites due to the deepness of its waters. <s> The deepness of the water explains the reasoning behind dividing the sea into three zones, which functions to transport water from the Pacific Ocean to the shallower seas surrounding it. <s> The deepest hollow in the Molucca Sea is the 15,780-foot (4,810-meter) Batjan (Indonesian: "Bacan") basin. <s> This region is known for its periodic experiences of earthquakes, which stems from the sea itself being a micro plate, in which the Molucca Sea is being subducted in two opposite directions: one in the direction of the Eurasian Plate to the west and the other in the direction of the Philippines Sea Plate to the east. <s> The Molucca Sea borders the Banda Sea to the south and the Celebes Sea to the west. <s> To the north is Philippine Sea and to the east is Halmahera Sea. <s> The islands bordering the Moluccan Sea include Halmahera to the north east, Buru and Ceram in the centre, and Sulawesi to the west. <s> The Talaud Islands to the north are considered to be the northern border the sea, though the Molucca Sea Plate, the tectonic plate named after the sea, extends further north.
simple: The Molucca Sea is in the western Pacific Ocean, within the country of Indonesia. <s> The region is rich in coral and has many diving sites. <s> The Molucca Sea borders the Banda Sea to the south and the Celebes Sea to the north. <s> The islands bordering the Molucca Sea include Halmahera to the north east, Buru and Ceram in the centre, and Sulawesi to the west. <s> The Talaud Islands to the north are the general limit of the sea. <s> The Molucca Sea Plate, the tectonic plate named after the sea, goes further north.

title: Skärblacka
complex: Skärblacka is a locality situated in Norrköping Municipality, Östergötland County, Sweden with 4,059 inhabitants in 2010. <s> In everyday use, the town is known as simply "Blacka".
simple: Skärblacka is a locality in Norrköping Municipality in Östergötland County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 4,059 people lived there. <s> In everyday use, the town is known as simply "Blacka".

title: John Howes
complex: John Forman Howes (June 19, 1924 – February 4, 2017) was a Professor of Asian Studies at the University of British Columbia (UBC) for over three decades. <s> Howes began his studies of the Japanese language in 1944 at the I.T.S. Naval School of Oriental Languages, and served as a translator in the general headquarters of the Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers Occupation of Japan. <s> Returning to the United States, he obtained an undergraduate degree at Oberlin College, and then an MA from Columbia University with a thesis entitled "Uchimura Kanzō; a biographical sketch", followed by a 1965 Ph.D for "Japan's enigma, the young Uchimura Kanzō". <s> Even before completing his doctoral work, in 1961, he joined the Department of Asian Studies at the University of British Columbia, rising to the rank of Professor, and then Emeritus Professor. <s> After retirement from UBC, he taught at Obirin University, near Tokyo. <s> In 2003, Howes was awarded the Order of the Rising Sun by the Emperor of Japan for his contributions to the Canada-Japan community.
simple: John Forman Howes ORS (June 19, 1924 – February 4, 2017) was an American educator. <s> He was the Professor of Asian Studies at the University of British Columbia (UBC) for over 30 years. <s> Howes died on February 4, 2017 in Vancouver, British Columbia, aged 92. <s> After retirement from UBC, he taught at Obirin University, near Tokyo. <s> In 2003, Howes was awarded the Order of the Rising Sun by the Emperor of Japan for his outstanding contributions to the Canada-Japan community.

title: Söderhöjdens BK
complex: Söderhöjdens BK was a sports club in Stockholm, Sweden. <s> is played three seasons in the Swedish women's bandy top division.
simple: Söderhöjdens BK was a sports club in the town of Stockholm in Sweden. <s> The club played three seasons in the Swedish women's bandy top division.

title: Laptev Sea
complex: The Laptev Sea (Russian: , ; ) is a marginal sea of the Arctic Ocean. <s> It is located between the northern coast of Siberia, the Taimyr Peninsula, Severnaya Zemlya and the New Siberian Islands. <s> Its northern boundary passes from the Arctic Cape to a point with co-ordinates of 79°N and 139°E, and ends at the Anisiy Cape. <s> The Kara Sea lies to the west, the East Siberian Sea to the east. <s> The sea is named after the Russian explorers Dmitry Laptev and Khariton Laptev; formerly, it had been known under various names, the last being Nordenskiöld Sea , after explorer Adolf Erik Nordenskiöld. <s> The sea has a severe climate with temperatures below 0 °C (32 °F) over more than nine months per year, low water salinity, scarcity of flora, fauna and human population, and low depths (mostly less than 50 meters). <s> It is frozen most of the time, though generally clear in August and September. <s> The sea shores were inhabited for thousands of years by indigenous tribes of Yukaghirs and then Evens and Evenks, which were engaged in fishing, hunting and reindeer husbandry. <s> They were then settled by Yakuts and later by Russians. <s> Russian explorations of the area started in the 17th century. <s> They came from the south via several large rivers which empty into the sea, such as the prominent Lena River, the Khatanga, the Anabar, the Olenyok, the Omoloy and the Yana. <s> The sea contains several dozen islands, many of which contain well-preserved mammoth remains. <s> The Lena River, with its large delta, is the biggest river flowing into the Laptev Sea, and is the second largest river in the Russian Arctic after Yenisei. <s> Other important rivers include the Khatanga, the Anabar, the Olenyok or Olenek, the Omoloy and the Yana. <s> Both flora and fauna are scarce owing to the harsh climate. <s> Vegetation of the sea is mostly represented by diatoms, with more than 100 species. <s> In comparison, the number of green algae, blue-green algae and flagellate species is about 10 each. <s> The phytoplankton is characteristic of brackish waters and has a total concentration of about 0.2 mg/L. <s> There are about 30 species of zooplankton with the concentration reaching 0.467 mg/L. <s> The coastal flora mainly consists of mosses and lichens and a few flowering plants including Arctic poppy ("Papaver radicatum"), "Saxifraga", "Draba" and small populations of polar ("Salix polaris") and creeping ("Salicaceae") willows. <s> Rare vascular plants include species of "Cerastium" and "Saxifraga". <s> Non-vascular plants include the moss genera "Detrichum", "Dicranum", "Pogonatum", "Sanionia", "Bryum", "Orthothecium" and "Tortura", as well as the lichen genera "Cetraria", "Thamnolia", "Cornicularia", "Lecidea", "Ochrolechia" and "Parmelia". <s> Permanent mammal species include ringed seal ("Phoca hispida"), bearded seal ("Erignathus barbatus"), harp seal ("Pagophilus groenlandicus"), walrus ("Odobenus rosmarus"), collared lemming ("Dicrostonyx torquatus"), Arctic fox ("Alopex lagopus"), reindeer ("Rangifer tarandus") wolf ("Canis lupus"), ermine ("Mustela erminea"), Arctic hare ("Lepus timidus") and polar bear ("Ursus maritimus"), whereas beluga whales ("Delphinapterus leucas") visit the region seasonally. <s> The walrus of the Laptev Sea is sometimes distinguished as a separate subspecies "Odobenus rosmarus laptevi", though this attribution is questioned. <s> There are several dozens species of birds. <s> Some belong to permanent (tundra) species, such as snow bunting ("Plectrophenax nivalis"), purple sandpiper ("Calidris maritima"), snowy owl ("Bubo scandiacus") and brent goose and other make large colonies on the islands and sea shores. <s> The latter include little auk ("Alle alle"), black-legged kittiwake ("Rissa tridactyla"), black guillemot ("Cepphus grylle"), ivory gull ("Pagophila eburnea"), "uria", "charadriiformes" and glaucous gull ("Larus hyperboreus"). <s> Among other bird species are skua, sterna, northern fulmar, ("Fulmarus glacialis"), ivory gull ("Pagophila eburnea"), glaucous gull ("Larus hyperboreus"), Ross's gull ("Rhodostethia rosea"), long-tailed duck ("Clangula hyemalis"), eider, loon and willow grouse ("Lagopus lagopus"). <s> There are 39 fish species, mostly typical of braskish environment; the major ones are grayling and "Coregonus" (whitefishes), such as muksun ("Coregonus muksun"), broad whitefish ("Coregonus nasus") and omul ("Coregonus autumnalis"). <s> Also common are sardine, Arctic cisco, Bering cisco, polar smelt, saffron cod, polar cod, flounder and Arctic char and inconnu. <s> In 1985, the Ust-Lena Nature Reserve was established in the delta (from – "ust", meaning "delta") of the Lena River with an area of 14,300 km. <s> In 1986, New Siberian Islands were included into the reserve. <s> The reserve hosts numerous plants (402 species), fishes (32 species), birds (109 species) and mammals (33 species).
