title: Jack Welch
complex: John Francis "Jack" Welch Jr. (born November 19, 1935) is an American business executive, author, and chemical engineer. <s> He was chairman and CEO of General Electric between 1981 and 2001. <s> During his tenure at GE, the company's value rose 4,000%. <s> In 2006, Welch's net worth was estimated at $720 million. <s> When he retired from GE he received a severance payment of $417 million, the largest such payment in history.
simple: John Francis "Jack" Welch Jr. (born November 19, 1935) is an American retired business executive, author, and chemical engineer. <s> He was chairman and CEO of General Electric between 1981 and 2001. <s> In 2006, Welch's net worth was estimated at $720 million. <s> When he retired from GE he received a severance payment of $417 million, the largest such payment in history.

title: Andelaroche
complex: Andelaroche is a commune in the Allier department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region of central France.
simple: Andelaroche is a French commune. <s> It is in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: Bologna massacre
complex: The Bologna massacre was a terrorist bombing of the Bologna Centrale railway station in Bologna, Italy, on the morning of 2 August 1980 which killed 85 people and wounded over 200. <s> Several members of the neo-fascist terrorist organization Nuclei Armati Rivoluzionari (Armed Revolutionary Nuclei) were sentenced for the bombing, although the group denied involvement.
simple: The Bologna massacre was the bombing of Bologna Centrale railway station in Bologna, Emilia-Romagna, Italy by Nuclei Armati Rivoluzionari. <s> It happened on 2 August 1980. <s> It killed 85 people and injured over 200 others.

title: Ernst Heinrich Meier
complex: Ernst Heinrich Meier (17 May 1813 in Bückeburg 2 March 1866 in Tübingen) was a German orientalist. <s> He published an Indian play, "Sakuntala or the Lost Ring". <s> He also published a collection of German folk songs.
simple: Ernst Heinrich Meier (17 May 1813 in Bückeburg – 2 March 1866 in Tübingen) was a German Orientalist. <s> He published an Indian play, "Sakuntala or the Lost Ring". <s> He also published a collection of German folk songs.

title: Monopoly (game show)
complex: Monopoly is an American television game show based on the board game of the same name. <s> The format was created by Merv Griffin and produced by his production company, Merv Griffin Enterprises. <s> "Monopoly" aired as a summer replacement series on ABC along with "Super Jeopardy!", a special tournament edition of Griffin's quiz show. <s> "Monopoly" premiered on June 16, 1990, and aired following "Super Jeopardy!" for twelve consecutive Saturday nights until September 1, 1990.
simple: Monopoly is an American television game show created by Merv Griffin. <s> It was shown on ABC from June 16, 1990 until September 1, 1990 and had twelve episodes.

title: Lauterpacht Centre for International Law
complex: The Lauterpacht Centre for International Law (LCIL) at the Faculty of Law, Cambridge, England, was founded in 1985 by Sir Elihu Lauterpacht under the name "The Research Centre for International Law". <s> It was renamed in 1997 "to honour the achievements of his father Sir Hersch Lauterpacht and himself". <s> The purpose of the centre is to "promote international law by a combination of individual and group research, whether undertaken privately by scholars or funded externally, and by the publication of monographs and collections of primary materials".
simple: The Lauterpacht Centre for International Law (LCIL) at the Faculty of Law, Cambridge, England, was founded in 1985 by Sir Elihu Lauterpacht under the name The Research Centre for International Law. <s> It was renamed in 1997 “to honour the achievements of his father Sir Hersch Lauterpacht and himself”. <s> The purpose of the centre is to "promote international law by a combination of individual and group research”.

title: Bong
complex: A bong (also water pipe, billy, bing, or moof) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis, tobacco, or other herbal substances. <s> In the bong shown in the photo, the gas flows from the lower port on the left to the upper port on the right.
simple: A bong or a water pipe is a special pipe.

title: Moorhead, Iowa
complex: Moorhead is a city in Monona County, Iowa, United States. <s> Moorhead stands along the Soldier River.
simple: Moorhead is a city of Iowa in the United States.

title: South Magnetic Pole
complex: The South Magnetic Pole is the wandering point on Earth's Southern Hemisphere where the geomagnetic field lines are directed vertically upwards. <s> It should not be confused with the South Geomagnetic Pole described later. <s> The South Magnetic Pole is constantly shifting due to changes in Earth's magnetic field. <s> As of 2005 it was calculated to lie at , placing it off the coast of Antarctica, between Adélie Land and Wilkes Land. <s> In 2015 it lay at (est). <s> That point lies outside the Antarctic Circle. <s> Due to polar drift, the pole is moving northwest by about 10 to per year. <s> Its current distance from the actual Geographic South Pole is approximately 2860 km . <s> The nearest permanent science station is Dumont d'Urville Station. <s> Wilkes Land contains a large gravitational mass concentration.
simple: The South Magnetic Pole is the point on the southern hemisphere where the magnetic lines are directly pointing upward. <s> Because the magnetic field of the Earth changes, the exact location of ths pole does as well., placing it off the coast of Antarctica, between Adelie Land and Wilkes Land. <s> In 2015 it lies at (est). <s> That point lies outside the Antarctic Circle. <s> Due to polar drift, the pole is moving northwest by about 10 to 15 kilometers per year. <s> Its current distance from the actual Geographic South Pole is approximately 2860 km. <s> The nearest permanent science station is Dumont d'Urville Station. <s> Wilkes Land contains a large gravitational mass concentration.

title: First inauguration of Abraham Lincoln
complex: The first inauguration of Abraham Lincoln as the 16th President of the United States was held on Monday, March 4, 1861, on the East Portico of the United States Capitol in Washington, D.C.. <s> The inauguration marked the commencement of the first term of Abraham Lincoln as President and the only term of Hannibal Hamlin as Vice President. <s> The presidential oath of office was administered to Lincoln by Roger B. Taney, Chief Justice of the United States.
simple: The first inauguration of Abraham Lincoln as the 16th President of the United States took place on March 4, 1861. <s> The inauguration was the beginning of the first four-year term of Abraham Lincoln as President and Hannibal Hamlin as Vice President.

title: Floresville, Texas
complex: Floresville is a city in Wilson County, Texas, United States. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the population was estimated at 7,572 in 2017. <s> It is the county seat of Wilson County. <s> The city is also part of the San Antonio Metropolitan Statistical Area.
simple: Floresville is a city in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> It is the county seat of Wilson County.

title: Jim B. Tucker
complex: Jim B. Tucker is a child psychiatrist and Bonner-Lowry Professor of Psychiatry and Neurobehavioral Sciences at the University of Virginia School of Medicine. <s> His main research interests are children who claim to remember previous lives, and natal and prenatal memories. <s> He is the author of "Life Before Life: A Scientific Investigation of Children’s Memories of Previous Lives", which presents an overview of over four decades of reincarnation research at the Division of Perceptual Studies. <s> Tucker worked for several years on this research with Ian Stevenson before taking over upon Stevenson’s retirement in 2002. <s> Since taking over the research into claimed past-life memories from Ian Stevenson in 2002, Tucker has been interviewed about reincarnation in print and broadcast media in the United States, United Kingdom and Canada.
simple: Jim B. Tucker is medical director of the Child and Family Psychiatric Clinic, and associate professor at the Division of Perceptual Studies, at the University of Virginia. <s> His main research interests are reincarnation research, and prenatal and birth memories. <s> Tucker is the author of "Life Before Life: A Scientific Investigation of Children’s Memories of Previous Lives". <s> Tucker, a child psychiatrist, worked for several years on this research with Ian Stevenson before taking over upon Stevenson’s retirement in 2002. <s> He has been interviewed about reincarnation in print and broadcast media in the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada.

title: Basil Yamey
complex: Basil S. Yamey, CBE (born 4 May 1919) is a South African economist. <s> He was born in Cape Town in South Africa, and educated at the University of Cape Town. <s> For many years he was a Professor at the London School of Economics. <s> He was a part-time member of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission from 1966 to 1978, and author of many books and articles, including one on the economics of underdeveloped countries co-authored with Peter Thomas Bauer.

title: Liev Schreiber
complex: Isaac Liev Schreiber ( ; born October 4, 1967) is an American actor, director, screenwriter, and producer. <s> He became known during the late 1990s and early 2000s, having appeared in several independent films, and later mainstream Hollywood films, including the "Scream" trilogy of horror films, "Ransom" (1996), "Phantoms" (1998), "The Sum of All Fears" (2002), "The Omen" (2006), "" (2009), "Taking Woodstock" (2009), "Salt" (2010), "Goon" (2011), "Pawn Sacrifice" (2014), and "Spotlight" (2015). <s> He later became known to a younger generation of audiences for his work in "" (2017), "Isle of Dogs" and "" (2018). <s> Schreiber was born in San Francisco, California, the son of Heather ("née" Milgram) and Tell Carroll Schreiber, a stage actor and director. <s> His father comes from a wealthy Protestant family, and his mother is Jewish.
simple: Liev Isaac Schreiber (; born October 4, 1967) is an American actor, producer, director, and screenwriter. <s> He was known for his role in "Scream", "Phantoms", "The Sum of All Fears", "", "Salt", "Taking Woodstock", and in "The Butler". <s> Schreiber was born on October 4, 1967 in San Francisco, California.

title: Salvatore Garau
complex: Salvatore Garau (born 1953) is an Italian artist from the Mediterranean island of Sardinia. <s> Garau was born in Santa Giusta, in the province of Oristano in the Mediterranean island of Sardinia, Italy. <s> He studied at the Accademia di Belle Arti di Firenze, where he graduated in 1974. <s> In 1977 he became the drummer of the progressive rock group Stormy Six. <s> After the group disbanded he became a visual artist. <s> He had his first solo show in 1984. <s> He participated in the 50th Biennale di Venezia in 2003 and showed work at the European Parliament in Strasbourg in the same year. <s> In 2005 he painted an abstract work on a sheet of PVC, which was then hung to cover the scaffolding on a building in Corso Magenta in Milan. <s> For his installation "Ichthys Sacro Stagno" in Sardinia in 2006 he created large ponds on the floors of three churches in towns in the province of Oristano, which he then populated with fish from nearby ponds. <s> In 2009 he had a solo show at the Musée d'art moderne et contemporain of Saint-Etienne, in France. <s> Garau has work in the collections of several museums including the Museo del Novecento (formerly in the Civico Museo d'Arte Contemporanea), the Museo d’Arte Moderna di Bologna and the Padiglione d'Arte Contemporanea in Milan.

title: Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg
complex: Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg is the second borough of Berlin, formed in 2001 by merging the former East Berlin borough of Friedrichshain and the former West Berlin borough of Kreuzberg. <s> The historic Oberbaum Bridge, formerly a Berlin border crossing for pedestrians, links both districts across the river Spree as the new borough's landmark (as featured in the coat of arms).
simple: Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg is a borough of Berlin. <s> It is a new borough, only made in 2001 by joining the old boroughs of Friedrichshain and Kreuzberg.

title: André Tosel
complex: André Tosel (15 June 1941 – 14 March 2017) was a French Marxist philosopher and academic administrator. <s> He taught Philosophy at the University of Franche-Comté and Pantheon-Sorbonne University until he became a full professor of Philosophy at the University of Nice Sophia Antipolis. <s> He served as its vice president from 1992 to 1998, and as the director of its Center for the History of Ideas from 1998 to 2003. <s> He was the author of several books about Marxism and Marxist theorists. <s> Tosel died on 14 March 2017 in Nice.
simple: André Tosel (15 June 1941 – 14 March 2017) was a French Marxist philosopher and academic administrator. <s> Tosel taught Philosophy at the University of Franche-Comté and Pantheon-Sorbonne University until he became a full professor of Philosophy at the University of Nice Sophia Antipolis. <s> He served as its vice president from 1992 to 1998, and as the director of its Center for the History of Ideas from 1998 to 2003. <s> He was the author of several books about Marxism and Marxist theorists. <s> Tosel died in Nice, France on 14 March 2017 at the age of 75.

title: Black Friday (Lil' Kim mixtape)
complex: Black Friday is the second mixtape by American rapper Lil' Kim, released on February 14, 2011 through PayPal. <s> The title track is a response to Nicki Minaj's song "Roman's Revenge". <s> The mixtape also contains the track "Grindin' Makin' Money", a collaboration which features rappers Birdman and Nicki Minaj, which Kim claims ignited the feud between her and Minaj, as well as another diss song towards Minaj titled "Pissin' on 'Em".
simple: Black Friday is the second mixtape by American rapper Lil' Kim, released on February 14, 2011. <s> The title track also is a diss song aimed at Minaj as Kim imitates Minaj talking about Kim on her song "Roman's Revenge" in an interview.

title: Howard Keel
complex: Harry Clifford Keel (April 13, 1919November 7, 2004), known professionally as Howard Keel, was an American actor and singer with a rich bass-baritone singing voice. <s> He starred in a number of MGM musicals in the 1950s and in the CBS television series "Dallas" from 1981–1991. <s> Keel died at his Palm Desert home on November 7, 2004, six weeks after being diagnosed with colon cancer. <s> He was cremated and his ashes scattered at three favorite places: Mere Golf Club, Cheshire, England; John Lennon Airport, Liverpool, England; and Tuscany, Italy.
simple: Howard Clifford Keel (April 13, 1919 – November 7, 2004) was an American actor and singer. <s> He died of colon cancer in 2004.

title: List of European stadiums by capacity
complex: This is a list of the largest European stadiums. <s> Stadiums with a capacity of 25,000 or more are included. <s> The list includes stadiums in Europe and in countries that normally take part in European sporting competitions. <s> (d) indicates retractable seating deployed, (nd) indicates retractable seating not deployed (m) indicates movable seating deployed (t) indicates capacity with temporary seats to be removed <s> An asterisk - * - indicates that a team does not play all of its home matches at that venue. <s> The "Category" column indicates whether the stadium has been designated by UEFA as capable of hosting Champions League or Europa League matches. <s> The following is a list of European stadiums which are currently under construction and will have a capacity of 25,000 or more.

title: British Rail Class 180
complex: The British Rail Class 180 is class of 14 diesel-hydraulic multiple-unit train built by Alstom at Washwood Heath in 2000/01 for First Great Western (FGW). <s> They are part of the Coradia 1000 family, along with the Class 175.
simple: The Class 180 "Adelante" is a type of British diesel multiple unit built by Alstom between 2000 and 2001 at Washwood Heath in Birmingham.

title: Pontypridd
complex: Pontypridd (] ) is both the county town of Rhondda Cynon Taf in Wales and a community. <s> Often colloquially known as ""Ponty"", it is 12 mi north of Cardiff. <s> The name "Pontypridd" derives from the name "Pont-y-tŷ-pridd", Welsh for "bridge by the earthen house", a reference to a succession of wooden bridges that formerly spanned the River Taff at this point.
simple: Pontypridd is a town in southern Wales. <s> Its name comes from the Welsh "Pont-y-ty-pridd” which means 'bridge by the earthen house'.

title: Alexander I of Scotland
complex: Alexander I (medieval Gaelic: "Alaxandair mac Maíl Coluim"; modern Gaelic: "Alasdair mac Mhaol Chaluim"; c. 1078 – 23 April 1124), posthumously nicknamed The Fierce, was the King of Scotland from 1107 to his death. <s> On the death of Edgar in 1107 he succeeded to the Scottish crown; but, in accordance with Edgar's instructions, their brother David was granted an appanage in southern Scotland.
simple: Alexander I of Scotland (c. 1078 - 23 April 1124) was the son of Malcolm Canmore and Saint Margaret of Scotland. <s> He became the King of Scotland in 1107.

title: Roch Marc Christian Kaboré
complex: Roch Marc Christian Kaboré (born 25 April 1957) is a Burkinabé politician and banker and the President of Burkina Faso, in office since 2015. <s> Previously he served as the Prime Minister of Burkina Faso between 1994 and 1996 and President of the National Assembly of Burkina Faso from 2002 to 2012. <s> He also served as President of the Congress for Democracy and Progress (CDP). <s> In January 2014, he left the ruling CDP and joined a new opposition party, the People's Movement for Progress. <s> He was elected as President of Burkina Faso in the November 2015 general election, winning a majority in the first round of voting. <s> Upon taking office, he became the first non-interim president in 49 years without any past ties to the military. <s> Kaboré was born in Ouagadougou, the capital city of Burkina Faso, then called Upper Volta. <s> He attended school from 1962 to 1968, when he received his CPS (Certificate of Primary School). <s> On completing this basic education certificate, he attended the Collège Saint Jean-Baptiste de la Salle, a selective school in Ouagadougou. <s> He studied there from 1968 to 1975, passing his "BEPC" or General Certificate ('O' Level) in 1972 and his "baccalauréat" ('A' level) in 1975. <s> He went on to study economics at the University of Dijon, majoring in business administration. <s> There, he completed his BA in 1979 and his Master's in 1980.
simple: Roch Marc Christian Kaboré (born 25 April 1957) is a Burkinabé politician. <s> He has been President of Burkina Faso, in office since 2015. <s> Previously, he served as the Prime Minister of Burkina Faso between 1994 and 1996 and President of the National Assembly of Burkina Faso from 2002 to 2012. <s> He also served as President of the Congress for Democracy and Progress (CDP). <s> In January 2014, he left the ruling CDP and founded a new opposition party, the People's Movement for Progress. <s> He was elected as President of Burkina Faso in the November 2015 general election, winning a majority in the first round of voting. <s> He studied economics at the University of Dijon where, in 1979, he obtained a Master's degree in Economics and Management, and in 1980, a DESS in Management which gave him the Certificate of Qualification in Business Administration and Management.

title: Gibbsite
complex: Gibbsite, Al(OH), is one of the mineral forms of aluminium hydroxide. <s> It is often designated as γ-Al(OH) (but sometimes as α-Al(OH).). <s> It is also sometimes called hydrargillite (or hydrargyllite). <s> Gibbsite is an important ore of aluminium in that it is one of three main phases that make up the rock bauxite.
simple: Gibbsite, Al(OH), is one of the mineral forms of aluminium hydroxide. <s> It is often designated as γ-Al(OH) (but sometimes as α-Al(OH)). <s> It is also sometimes called hydrargillite (or hydrargyllite). <s> It is an important ore of aluminium, and one of the main parts of the rock Bauxite.

title: Joe Hayashi
complex: Joe J. Hayashi (August 14, 1920 – April 22, 1945) was a United States Army soldier. <s> He is best known as a recipient of the United States military's highest decoration—the Medal of Honor—for his actions in World War II. <s> Hayashi was born at Salinas, California. <s> He is the son of immigrants who were born in Japan. <s> He is a "Nisei", which means that he is a second generation Japanese-American. <s> Working as a mechanic before the war, Hayashi enlisted in the Army from Los Angeles in May 1941. <s> Hayashi volunteered to be part of the all-"Nisei" 442nd Regimental Combat Team. <s> This army unit was mostly made up of Japanese Americans from Hawaii and the mainland. <s> On April 20, 1945, near Tendola, Italy, Hayashi exposed himself to hostile fire in order to direct mortar fire onto enemy positions. <s> Two days later, he single-handedly silenced three hostile machine guns but was killed while pursuing enemy soldiers. <s> For his actions during the battle, he was awarded the Army's second-highest decoration, the Distinguished Service Cross. <s> A 1990s review of service records for Asian Americans who received the Distinguished Service Cross during World War II led to Hayashi's award being upgraded to the Medal of Honor. <s> In a ceremony at the White House on June 21, 2000, his surviving family was presented with his Medal of Honor by President Bill Clinton. <s> Twenty-one other Asian Americans also received the medal during the ceremony, all but seven of them posthumously. <s> Hayashi's official Medal of Honor citation reads: Private Joe Hayashi distinguished himself by extraordinary heroism in action on 20 and 22 April 1945, near Tendola, Italy. <s> On 20 April 1945, ordered to attack a strongly defended hill that commanded all approaches to the village of Tendola, Private Hayashi skillfully led his men to a point within 75 yards of enemy positions before they were detected and fired upon. <s> After dragging his wounded comrades to safety, he returned alone and exposed himself to small arms fire in order to direct and adjust mortar fire against hostile emplacements. <s> Boldly attacking the hill with the remaining men of his squad, he attained his objective and discovered that the mortars had neutralized three machine guns, killed 27 men, and wounded many others. <s> On 22 April 1945, attacking the village of Tendola, Private Hayashi maneuvered his squad up a steep, terraced hill to within 100 yards of the enemy. <s> Crawling under intense fire to a hostile machine gun position, he threw a grenade, killing one enemy soldier and forcing the other members of the gun crew to surrender. <s> Seeing four enemy machine guns delivering deadly fire upon other elements of his platoon, he threw another grenade, destroying a machine gun nest. <s> He then crawled to the right flank of another machine gun position where he killed four enemy soldiers and forced the others to flee. <s> Attempting to pursue the enemy, he was mortally wounded by a burst of machine pistol fire. <s> The dauntless courage and exemplary leadership of Private Hayashi enabled his company to attain its objective. <s> Private Hayashi's extraordinary heroism and devotion to duty are in keeping with the highest traditions of military service and reflect great credit on him, his unit, and the United States Army.

title: Celeste Yarnall
complex: Celeste Jeanne Yarnall (July 26, 1944 – October 7, 2018) was an American actress primarily of the 1960s and 1970s. <s> She started her career on television before moving to feature film roles. <s> Yarnall died in Westlake Village, California on October 7, 2018, aged 74, from ovarian cancer which she had been diagnosed with in 2014.

title: José Javier Curto Gines
complex: Jose Javier Curto Gines (born December 31, 1964 in Madrid) is a boccia player from Spain. <s> He has a physical disability: He has cerebral palsy and is a BC2 type athlete. <s> He competed at the 2004 Summer Paralympics. <s> He finished first in the one person BC2 boccia game.

title: Caitlin
complex: Caitlin (pronounced ] ) is a female given name of Irish origin. <s> It is the Irish version of the Old French name "Cateline" ] , which comes from Catherine, which in turn comes from the Ancient Greek Αἰκατερίνη (Aikaterine).

title: John H. Gibbons (scientist)
complex: John Howard "Jack" Gibbons (January 15, 1929 – July 17, 2015) was an American scientist, nuclear physicist, and internationally recognized expert in technologies for energy efficiency and energy resource conservation. <s> He served as the Assistant to the President for Science and Technology and Director of the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy under President Bill Clinton from 1993-1998. <s> President Bill Clinton appointed Gibbons to serve as the Assistant to the President for Science and Technology and Director of the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy; his tenure there lasted from February 2, 1993 to April 15, 1998.

title: Icosahedron
complex: There are infinitely many non-similar shapes of icosahedra, some of them being more symmetrical than others. <s> The best known is the (convex, non-stellated) regular icosahedron—one of the Platonic solids—whose faces are 20 equilateral triangles. <s> There are two objects, one convex and one nonconvex, that can both be called regular icosahedra. <s> Each has 30 edges and 20 equilateral triangle faces with five meeting at each of its twelve vertices. <s> Both have icosahedral symmetry. <s> The term "regular icosahedron" generally refers to the convex variety, while the nonconvex form is called a "great icosahedron". <s> The convex regular icosahedron is usually referred to simply as the "regular icosahedron", one of the five regular Platonic solids, and is represented by its Schläfli symbol {3, 5}, containing 20 triangular faces, with 5 faces meeting around each vertex. <s> Its dual polyhedron is the regular dodecahedron {5, 3} having three regular pentagonal faces around each vertex. <s> The great icosahedron is one of the four regular star Kepler-Poinsot polyhedra. <s> Its Schläfli symbol is {3, }. <s> Like the convex form, it also has 20 equilateral triangle faces, but its vertex figure is a pentagram rather than a pentagon, leading to geometrically intersecting faces. <s> The intersections of the triangles do not represent new edges. <s> Its dual polyhedron is the great stellated dodecahedron { , 3}, having three regular star pentagonal faces around each vertex. <s> Stellation is the process of extending the faces or edges of a polyhedron until they meet to form a new polyhedron. <s> It is done symmetrically so that the resulting figure retains the overall symmetry of the parent figure. <s> In their book "The Fifty-Nine Icosahedra", Coxeter et al. enumerated 58 such stellations of the regular icosahedron. <s> Of these, many have a single face in each of the 20 face planes and so are also icosahedra. <s> The great icosahedron is among them. <s> Other stellations have more than one face in each plane or form compounds of simpler polyhedra. <s> These are not strictly icosahedra, although they are often referred to as such.

title: Scientist
complex: A scientist is someone who conducts scientific research to advance knowledge in an area of interest. <s> Some scientists have a desire to apply scientific knowledge for the benefit of people's health, the nations, the world, nature, or industries (academic scientist and industrial scientist). <s> Scientists tend to be less motivated by direct financial reward for their work than other careers.
simple: A scientist is a person who studies or has expertise in science. <s> Scientists who are doing applied science try to use scientific knowledge to improve the world.

title: Shaka Hislop
complex: Neil Shaka Hislop CM (born 22 February 1969) is a retired footballer who played as a goalkeeper. <s> The majority of his career was spent in the top division in England where he was a part of the Newcastle United team which finished second in the Premier League for two successive seasons under Kevin Keegan's first tenure.
simple: Shaka Hislop (born 22 February 1969) is a former Trinidad and Tobago football player.

title: The King of Rome
complex: The King of Rome was a successful racing pigeon, winning a 1001 mi race from Rome, Italy to England, in 1913. <s> It was the subject of a song and book, both by Dave Sudbury, and a radio play. <s> The song's best-known version was recorded by June Tabor. <s> The King of Rome was a racing pigeon that won a 1001 mi race from Rome, Italy to England, in 1913. <s> The bird, a blue cock, ring number NU1907DY168, was owned and bred by Charlie Hudson (born early 1870s, died 13 March 1958 aged 84), of 56 Brook Street, Derby (now demolished, ), who was reported as having started pigeon racing in 1904. <s> At the time of the race, he was president and treasurer of Derby Town Flying Club. <s> He also wrote on pigeon-racing matters for the "Derby Evening Telegraph". <s> On the bird's death he presented its body to Derby Museum and Art Gallery where its taxidermied skin is preserved with accession number DBYMU.1946/48. <s> As of 2011, it is on display, and has previously been exhibited on loan elsewhere, including Walsall Museum and Wollaton Hall in Nottingham. <s> The King of Rome and its owner were the subject of a song and book by Dave Sudbury (born Derby, 1943). <s> title: Yeongam County
complex: Yeongam (] ) is a city and county in South Jeolla Province, South Korea. <s> Bordered with Mokpo and Naju to the north, Jangheung County to the east, and Haenam and Gangjin to the south, Yeongam County comprises two "eups" and nine "myeons", populated with about 57,000 people, and its county hall is seated in Yeongam-eup. <s> The Korean Grand Prix was held along the harbor side, at the Korea International Circuit from 2010 to 2013. <s> The track has been designed by the famous race track designer Hermann Tilke. <s> The circuit is part permanent, part temporary. <s> Construction began in 2007, and was completed in September/October 2010. <s> The circuit had a contract to host the Grand Prix until 2016. <s> After that, a 5-year option would have to be picked up to keep the race until at least 2021. <s> However the race was cancelled after 2013.

title: Highland Football League
complex: The Scottish Highland Football League (commonly known as the Highland League) is a part time, senior professional football league in the north of Scotland. <s> The league, which is the fifth level within Scottish football, is a full member of the Scottish Football Association. <s> It currently consists of 17 teams from the Scottish Highlands as well as the lowlands of Moray and Aberdeenshire. <s> The Highland Football League was formed on 4 August 1893, at the Inverness Workman's Club by employees of the Highland Railway Company who had their Company Headquarters, Locomotive and Carriage & Wagon Workshops (Loch Gorm Works), based in the Highland capital. <s> The original league consisted of seven teams: Inverness Thistle, Caledonian, Clachnacuddin, Forres Mechanics, Inverness Union, Inverness Citadel and Cameron Highlanders. <s> Ross County were an eighth original member, but resigned membership in November 1893. <s> The inaugural champions were Inverness Thistle. <s> Of the original teams, two are still playing in the league today (Clachnacuddin and Forres Mechanics) and two merged to become current Scottish League club Inverness Caledonian Thistle. <s> Many of the member clubs have performed well when competing against SFL clubs in the Scottish Cup. <s> However, from the 1990s onwards, the HFL has been a victim of its own success, with various teams defecting to the Scottish Football League (SFL). <s> It has also had to contend with overexposure of large teams in the area, such as Aberdeen and Inverness Caledonian Thistle, as well as the Old Firm to the South, and to an extent English football. <s> However, the lack of Premier League, and to a lesser extent First Division, teams in the area, has worked in its favour, with some football fans being less willing to travel long distances to games in southern Scotland. <s> The league has been somewhat weakened by the departure of many former members who have subsequently joined the SFL. <s> This happened in 1994 when Caledonian, Inverness Thistle and Ross County left. <s> Until then the HFL had operated with 18 clubs; this was reduced by the departure of the three mentioned clubs, but Wick Academy from the North Caledonian Football League were elected, to create a league of 16 clubs. <s> This was the state of affairs till 2000 when Elgin City and Peterhead were elected into the SFL. <s> In 2002 Inverurie Loco Works were elected into the HFL to give it a membership of 15 clubs. <s> Inverurie Locos are another Highland League football club with its origins in the Scottish railways, having been formed by employees of the Great North of Scotland Railway who had their Locomotive and Carriage and Wagon Workshops in Inverurie, hence the football club's name. <s> In 2008, North Region Junior League sides Formartine United and Turriff United both submitted bids to join the Highland League, following in the footsteps of past Junior League side Inverurie Locos. <s> Banks O' Dee and Strathspey Thistle also applied. <s> On 25 February 2009, Formartine United, Strathspey Thistle and Turriff United were accepted into the league for the following season, with Banks O' Dee being the unsuccessful club.
simple: The Highland Football League (HFL) is a league of football clubs operating not just in the Scottish highlands, as the name may suggest, but also in the north-east lowlands (Moray and Aberdeenshire). <s> The HFL is a full member of the Scottish Football Association. <s> The HFL was formed on 4 August 1893, at the Inverness Workman's Club. <s> The original league consisted of seven teams: Inverness Thistle, Caledonian, Clachnacuddin, Forres Mechanics, Inverness Union, Inverness Citadel and Cameron Highlanders. <s> Ross County were an eighth original member, but resigned membership in November 1893. <s> Of the original teams, two are still playing in the league today (Clachnacuddin and Forres Mechanics), and two merged to become current Scottish Premier League club Inverness Caledonian Thistle. <s> Many of the member clubs have performed well when competing against SFL clubs in the Scottish Cup. <s> However, from the 1990s onwards, the HFL has been a victim of its own success, with various teams defecting to other leagues. <s> Furthermore it has also had to contend with overexposure of large teams in the area, such as Aberdeen and Inverness Caledonian Thistle, as well as the Old Firm to the South, and to an extent English football. <s> However, the lack of Premier League, and to a lesser extent First Division, teams in the area, has worked in its favour, with some football fans being less willing to travel long distances to games in southern Scotland. <s> The league has been somewhat weakened in recent years by the departure of many former members who have subsequently joined the SFL. <s> This happened in 1994 when Caledonian, Inverness Thistle and Ross County left. <s> Until then the HFL had operated with 18 clubs; this was reduced by the departure of the three mentioned clubs, but Wick Academy from the North Caledonian Football League were elected, to create a league of 16 clubs. <s> This was the state of affairs till 2000 when Elgin City and Peterhead were elected into the SFL. <s> In 2002 Inverurie Loco Works were elected into the HFL to give it a membership of 15 clubs, with which it continues to operate. <s> In 2008, North Region Junior League sides Formartine United and Turriff United both submitted bids to join the Highland League, following in the footsteps of past Junior League side Inverurie Locos. <s> However Banks O' Dee and Strathspey Thistle also applied, giving the potential for an 18 team Highland league in 2009-10 if three of these four clubs were elected. <s> On February 25 2009, Formartine United, Turriff United and Strathspey Thistle were accepted into the league for the following season, with Banks O' Dee being the unsuccessful club.

title: Lawrence station (Kansas)
complex: Lawrence is a train station in Lawrence, Kansas, United States, served by Amtrak's "Southwest Chief" train. <s> The Lawrence station was built in 1956 by the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway to replace the Atchison Topeka Santa Fe Station built in 1883 which was damaged by the 1951 flood. <s> The Mid-Century Modern station has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places. <s> In 2011 the station underwent more than $1.5 million in improvements, including the construction of a new 500 ft platform and repairs to the platform canopy, new lighting and improved access for persons with disabilities. <s> A ceremony was held on December 3 to mark the end of the project. <s> The City of Lawrence assumed ownership in 2017, and has been awarded a $1.2 million grant to carry out a complete restoration of the structure. <s> The majority of the restoration is expected to be complete in 2018. <s> The station was added to the Register of Kansas Historic Places on November 18, 2017, and was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2018.

title: Bob Bennett (politician)
complex: Robert Foster "Bob" Bennett (September 18, 1933 – May 4, 2016) was an American politician and businessman. <s> He was a United States Senator from Utah as a member of the Republican Party. <s> Bennett held chairmanships and senior positions on a number of key Senate committees, including the Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs Committee; Appropriations Committee; Rules and Administration Committee; Energy and Natural Resources Committee; and Joint Economic Committee. <s> Bennett was a popular and reliably conservative senator for most of his tenure, earning high ratings from conservative activist groups such as the National Rifle Association, U.S. Chamber of Commerce, and American Conservative Union. <s> However, in 2010 Bennett became one of the most prominent targets of the Tea Party Movement, which criticized his support of the Bush Administration's bank bailout and argued that Bennett was insufficiently conservative. <s> Despite an enthusiastic endorsement from Mitt Romney, Bennett was denied a place on the primary ballot by the 2010 Utah State Republican Convention, placing third behind two Tea-Party-backed candidates. <s> Bennett died on May 4, 2016, aged 82, at his home in Arlington, Virginia after suffering from pancreatic cancer and a stroke.

Bush. <s> Bennett died on May 4, 2016 at his home Arlington, Virginia after suffering from pancreatic cancer and a stroke. <s> He was 82 years old.

title: Ben's Cat
complex: Ben's Cat (April 17, 2006 – July 18, 2017) was an American Thoroughbred racehorse who won 26 stakes races, including six victories in the Mister Diz Stakes and five in the Jim McKay Turf Sprint. <s> He was a four-time Maryland-bred horse of the year and received the 2017 Secretariat Vox Populi Award. <s> He was retired in June 2017 with a record of 32 wins from 63 starts and earnings of over $2.6 million. <s> He died on July 18, 2017 due to complications related to colic surgery and was later buried at Laurel Park. <s> Shortly after his arrival at the farm, Ben's Cat suffered a serious bout of colic. <s> On July 6, 2017, he underwent surgery at the Haygard Equine Medical Institute for an epiploic foramen entrapment, a condition that unlike typical cases of colic is unrelated to changes in diet or routine. <s> He experienced severe post-operative complications and was humanely euthanized on July 18.

title: Milt Pappas
complex: Milton Steven Pappas (May 11, 1939 – April 19, 2016) was a professional baseball pitcher. <s> A 17-year veteran, Pappas, nicknamed "Gimpy", pitched for the Baltimore Orioles (1957 –1965 ), Cincinnati Reds (1966 –1968 ), Atlanta Braves (1968 –1970 ) and Chicago Cubs (1970 –1973 ). <s> Pappas was born to Greek parents, and his birth name was Miltiades Stergios Papastergios. <s> A control specialist, Pappas pitched in 520 games, starting 465, with 209 wins, 164 losses, 43 shutouts, 1,728 strikeouts and a 3.40 ERA in 3,186 innings pitched. <s> Pappas died of natural causes on April 19, 2016.
