title: Lewis Howard Latimer
complex: Lewis Howard Latimer (September 4, 1848 – December 11, 1928) was an American inventor and patent draftsman for the lightbulb and telephone. <s> Lewis Latimer joined the U.S. Navy at the age of 15 on September 16, 1863, and served as a Landsman on the USS "Massasoit". <s> After receiving an honorable discharge from the Navy on July 3, 1865, he gained employment as an office boy with a patent law firm, "Crosby Halstead and Gould", with a $3.00 per week salary. <s> He learned how to use a set square, ruler and other tools. <s> Later, after his boss recognized his talent for sketching patent drawings, Latimer was promoted to the position of head draftsman earning $20.00 a week by 1872. <s> For 25 years, from 1903 until his death in 1928, Lewis Howard Latimer lived with his family in a home on Holly Avenue in what is now known as East Flushing section of Queens, New York. <s> Lewis Howard Latimer died on December 11, 1928, at the age of 80. <s> Approximately sixty years after his death, his home was moved from Holly Avenue to 137th Street in Flushing, Queens, which is about 1.4 miles northwest of its original location. <s> In 1881, Latimer, along with Joseph Nichols, invented a light bulb with a carbon filament, an improvement on Thomas Edison's original paper filament, which would burn out quickly, and sold the patent to the United States Electric Company in 1881. <s> He received a second patent on January 17th 1882 for the "Process of Manufacturing Carbons", an improved method for the production of lightbulb carbon filaments.
simple: Lewis Howard Latimer (September 4, 1848 – December 11, 1928) was an African-American inventor and draftsman. <s> When he was 16 Latimer lied about his age to join the U.S Navy. <s> He learned to draw diagrams. <s> Latimer died on December 11, 1928 in Flushing Queens, New York at the age 80. <s> Latimer also helped Thomas Edison with his patent for the light bulb, and invented a better way to make carbon filaments for light bulbs.

title: Squat (exercise)
complex: A squat is a strength exercise in which the trainee lowers their hips from a standing position and then stands back up. <s> During the descent of a squat, the hip and knee joints flex while the ankle joint dorsiflexes; conversely the hip and knee joints extend and the ankle joint plantarflexes when standing up. <s> Although the squat has long been a basic element of weight training, it has not been without controversy over its safety. <s> Some trainers allege that squats are associated with injuries to the lumbar spine and knees. <s> Others, however, continue to advocate the squat as one of the best exercises for building muscle and strength. <s> Some coaches maintain that incomplete squats (those terminating above parallel) are both less effective and more likely to cause injury than a full squat (terminating with hips at or below knee level).
simple: In powerlifting and bodybuilding, as well as in other sports, squat is an exercise that strengthens the muscles of the thighs, hips and buttocks, as well as the bones, ligaments and insertion of the tendons throughout the lower body. <s> Although the squat is a basic element of weight training, it has been the subject of considerable controversy in recent years. <s> Some trainers allege that squats are associated with injuries to the lumbar spine and knees. <s> As a result, many trainers suggest that the standard barbell squat be modified in various ways. <s> Others, however, reject all suggestions that the exercise be abandoned, continuing to advocate the squat.

title: Anthony Duclair
complex: Anthony Duclair (born August 26, 1995) is a Canadian professional ice hockey forward for the Ottawa Senators of the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> Duclair was selected by the New York Rangers in the third round, 80th overall, of the 2013 NHL Entry Draft, the organization with which he began his NHL career. <s> Duclair has also played in the NHL for the Arizona Coyotes, Chicago Blackhawks and Columbus Blue Jackets. <s> Duclair was born in Laval, Quebec, and grew up in Pointe-Claire, Quebec. <s> He is of Haitian descent. <s> As a youth, he played in the 2008 Quebec International Pee-Wee Hockey Tournament with the Montreal Canadiens minor ice hockey team. <s> His uncle Farell Duclair played in the Canadian Football League. <s> Duclair spent three seasons with the Quebec Remparts of the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League (QMJHL). <s> He scored an impressive 50 goals in 59 games during the 2013–14 season. <s> Duclair was rewarded for his outstanding play being named to the QMJHL First All-Star Team. <s> On January 2, 2014, Duclair signed a three-year, entry-level contract with the New York Rangers. <s> Duclair impressed the Rangers with his performance in the 2014–15 pre-season, leading the team with five points in five games. <s> On October 6, 2014, defenceman Steven Kampfer and centre Andrew Yogan were traded to the Florida Panthers in exchange for forward Joey Crabb, securing an opening-night roster position for Duclair. <s> Duclair scored his first NHL goal on October 27, 2014, against Darcy Kuemper of the Minnesota Wild. <s> On January 6, 2015, Duclair was assigned to the Quebec Remparts for the remainder of the 2014–15 season. <s> On March 1, 2015, while playing with the Remparts, Duclair was traded to the Arizona Coyotes (along with John Moore and two draft picks) in exchange for Keith Yandle and Chris Summers. <s> On October 14, 2015, Duclair scored his first career NHL hat-trick in a 4–0 shut-out win against the Anaheim Ducks. <s> Fellow rookie Max Domi pitched in a goal of his own and an assist on one of Duclair's goals.
simple: Anthony Duclair (born August 26, 1995) is a Canadian ice hockey left winger. <s> He currently plays for the Arizona Coyotes of the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> He has also played for the New York Rangers. <s> He was drafted 80th overall by the New York Rangers in the 2013 NHL Entry Draft. <s> He was born in Montreal, Quebec, and he grew up in Pointe-Claire, Montreal, Quebec. <s> Before playing in the NHL, Duclair played 3 seasons with the Quebec Remparts of the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League (QMJHL). <s> During his time with the Remparts, Duclair was able to score 50 goals in 59 games during the 2013–14 QMJHL season. <s> Due to his impressive feat, he was named to the QMJHL First All-Star Team. <s> On January 2, 2014, he was signed to a three-year entry-level contract as a free agent by the New York Rangers. <s> On October 27, 2014, Duclair scored his first NHL goal against Darcy Kuemper of the Minnesota Wild. <s> On March 1, 2015, the Rangers traded Duclair to the Arizona Coyotes along with John Moore and two draft picks, in exchange for Keith Yandle and Chris Summers. <s> On October 14, 2015, Duclair scored his first NHL career hat-trick in a 4–0 shutout win against the Anaheim Ducks.

title: Endocarditis
complex: Endocarditis is an inflammation of the inner layer of the heart, the endocardium. <s> It usually involves the heart valves. <s> Other structures that may be involved include the interventricular septum, the chordae tendineae, the mural endocardium, or the surfaces of intracardiac devices.
simple: Endocarditis is an inflammation of the inner layer of the heart. <s> Endocarditis most often affects the heart valves.

title: Courthézon
complex: Courthézon is a commune in the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region in southeastern France.
simple: It is in the region Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur in the Vaucluse department in the south of France.

title: Dystopia
complex: Dystopias are often filled with pessimistic views of the ruling class or a government that is brutal or uncaring, ruling with an "iron fist". <s> Dystopian governments are sometimes ruled by a fascist regime or dictator.
simple: A dystopia often has many problems, such as poverty, pollution, or a cruel ruler.

title: Raif Dizdarević
complex: Raif Dizdarević (born 9 December 1926) is a Bosnian politician who served as Yugoslavia's first Bosniak president. <s> Dizdarević participated in the armed resistance as a Yugoslav Partisan during World War II. <s> Dizdarević was born into a Bosnian Muslim family in 1926. <s> His nephew was Srđan Dizdarević, who died in 2016. <s> After the war, as a member of the Communist Party and ally of Josip Broz Tito, he was elevated into high political functions. <s> From 1945 he was a member of the Department of State Security.
simple: Raif Dizdarević (born 9 December 1926) is a Bosniak former politician. <s> During World War II, he fought in the armed resistance in the Partisans. <s> Dizdarević was born in Fojnica. <s> After the war, as a member of the Communist Party and friend of Josip Broz Tito, he became a strong political leader. <s> From 1945 he was a member of the Department of State Security.

title: New Orleans blues
complex: As a style New Orleans blues is primarily driven by piano and horn, enlivened by Caribbean rhythms and Dixieland music. <s> It is generally cheerful in delivery regardless of the subject matter, with a laid back tempo and complex rhythms falling just behind the beat.
simple: New Orleans blues is a mix of Dixieland music and rhythms from Caribbean music.

title: Gernot Jurtin
complex: Gernot Jurtin (9 October 1955 – 5 December 2006) was an Austrian football player, and a legend amongst Sturm Graz fans. <s> Jurtin joined Sturm Graz in the summer of 1974 under coach Karl Schlechta and immediately forced his way into the starting eleven. <s> One of his finest seasons came in 1980/81 when he scored 20 goals in the Bundesliga including five in a 7-0 win against Wiener Sportclub on 5 June 1981. <s> He formed a prolific strike partnership with Bozo Bakota. <s> By the time Jurtin left Sturm Graz in 1987, he had made 373 appearances for them, scoring 119 league goals. <s> The blond-haired number 11 was the first Graz player to break the 100-goal barrier in the league. <s> Between 1979 and 1983, he won 12 caps for Austria, scoring one goal. <s> He made two appearances for them in the 1982 FIFA World Cup, against Chile and Northern Ireland.
simple: Gernot Jurtin (9 October 1955 – 5 December 2006) was an Austrian football striker. <s> Due to his long stay with S.K. Sturm Graz and over 100 goals he is a legend amongst Sturm Graz fans. <s> He started his career with WSV Judenburg and went to SK Sturm Graz in 1974. <s> 1980/81 he was the best scorer of the Austrian Bundesliga. <s> Together with Božo Bakota he formed a dangoures striker duo. <s> In 378 matches he scored 119 goals in the league. <s> Between 1979 and 1983, he played 12 times for Austria, scoring one goal. <s> He made two appearances for them in the 1982 FIFA World Cup, against Chile and Northern Ireland.

title: Peramelemorphia
complex: The order Peramelemorphia includes the bandicoots and bilbies; it equates approximately to the mainstream of marsupial omnivores. <s> All members of the order are endemic to the twin land masses of Australia-New Guinea and most have the characteristic bandicoot shape: a plump, arch-backed body with a long, delicately tapering snout, very large upright ears, relatively long, thin legs, and a thin tail.
simple: The order Peramelemorphia includes the bandicoots and bilbies: it equates approximately to the mainstream of marsupial omnivores.

title: Dietmar Constantini
complex: Dietmar "Didi" Constantini (born 30 May 1955) is a former Austrian football player and now coach. <s> He was appointed as head coach of the Austrian national team in March 2009 and was replaced by Marcel Koller in October 2011.
simple: Dietmar "Didi" Constantini (born 30 May, 1955 in Innsbruck, Austria) is a former Austrian football player and coach. <s> On 4 March 2009, Constantini became coach of the Austrian national football team.

title: Toba Tek Singh District
complex: Toba Tek Singh District is a district in the Punjab province of Pakistan. <s> It is located between 30°33' to 31°2' Degree north latitudes and 72°08' to 72°48' Degree longitudes.
simple: Toba Tek Singh District is a district in the Punjab province of Pakistan. <s> The city of Toba Tek Singh is the capital.

title: 40 BC
complex: Year 40 BC was either a common year starting on Thursday, Friday or Saturday or a leap year starting on Thursday or Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar (the sources differ, see leap year error for further information) and a common year starting on Friday of the Proleptic Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Calvinus and Pollio (or, less frequently, year 714 "Ab urbe condita"). <s> The denomination 40 BC for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: Year 40 BC was either a common year starting on Thursday, Friday or Saturday or a leap year starting on Thursday or Friday of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Calvinus and Pollio.

title: Yvré-le-Pôlin
complex: Yvré-le-Pôlin is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Yvré-le-Pôlin is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Schistosoma mansoni
complex: Schistosoma mansoni is a water-borne parasite of humans, and belongs to the group of blood flukes ("Schistosoma"). <s> The adult lives in the blood vessels (mesenteric veins) near the human intestine.
simple: Schistosoma mansoni is a parasite found in the intestines of humans.

title: Space Ghost Coast to Coast
complex: Space Ghost Coast to Coast is an American adult animated parody talk show, created by Mike Lazzo and hosted by the 1960s Hanna-Barbera cartoon character Space Ghost. <s> Though the original 1960s series aired as a standard Hanna-Barbera Saturday-morning superhero cartoon, "Space Ghost Coast to Coast" was a reboot of the series intended for adults, reinterpreted as a surreal spoof talk show and produced using the original artwork.
simple: Space Ghost Coast to Coast is a parody talk show with characters from the Space Ghost action adventure show from the 1960's.

title: André Ramalho
complex: André Ramalho Silva (born 16 February 1992) is a footballer who plays as a centre-back for Red Bull Salzburg.
simple: André Ramalho Silva (born 16 February 1992) is a football player from Brazil.

title: Fredrik Fasting Torgersen
complex: Fredrik Ludvig Fasting Torgersen (1 October 1934 – 18 June 2015) was a Norwegian man who was convicted of murder in 1958 in a much-debated case, and released from prison in 1974. <s> Serving 16 years in prison before being released, he continuously claimed his innocence. <s> In 2013 Bjørg Njaa, a daughter of a judge in the 1958 trial said that her father was prejudiced against Torgersen even before being assigned to the trial. <s> In 2014 he was denied access to official recordings of then leader of the Norwegian Board of Forensic Medicine, Bjørnar Olaisen, answering to Criminal Cases Review Commission.
simple: Fredrik Ludvig Fasting Torgersen (1 October 1934 – 19 June 2015) was a Norwegian man who was convicted of murder in 1958. <s> Serving 16 years in prison before being released, he has claimed his innocence many times. <s> In 2013 Bjørg Njaa, a daughter of a judge in the 1958 trial said that her father was prejudiced against Torgersen even before being assigned to the trial. <s> In 2014 he was denied access to official recordings of then leader of the Norwegian Board of Forensic Medicine, Bjørnar Olaisen, answering to Criminal Cases Review Commission.

title: WebKit
complex: WebKit is a browser engine used in Apple's Safari browser and other products. <s> WebKit is also the basis for the experimental browser included with the Amazon Kindle e-book reader, and for the default browser in Apple iOS, BlackBerry Browser in OS 6 and above, and Tizen mobile operating systems. <s> WebKit's C++ application programming interface (API) provides a set of classes to display Web content in windows, and implements browser features such as following links when clicked by the user, managing a back-forward list, and managing a history of pages recently visited. <s> WebKit's JavaScriptCore and WebCore components are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License, while the rest of WebKit is available under a BSD-style license.
simple: WebKit is a layout engine made to let web browsers show web pages. <s> WebKit was first made to be used as the layout engine for Safari, and is portable to many other computing platforms. <s> The WebKit engine has a set of classes to display web content in windows, and implements browser features such as following links when clicked by the person using the web browser (the user), managing a back-forward list, and keeping a history of pages recently visited. <s> WebKit's WebCore and JavaScriptCore parts are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License, and the rest of WebKit is available under a BSD-style license.

title: Blest Pair of Sirens
complex: Blest Pair of Sirens is a short work for choir and orchestra by the English composer Hubert Parry, setting John Milton's ode "At a solemn Musick". <s> It was first performed at St James's Hall, London on 17 May 1887, conducted by its dedicatee, Charles Villiers Stanford. <s> The piece is about 11 minutes in duration. <s> Stanford had originally intended to perform an existing work of Parry's, the 1885 cantata "The Glories of our Blood and State". <s> As the concert was to mark the Golden Jubilee of Queen Victoria, it was thought that such lines in the text as "Sceptre and crown must tumble down" made the work unsuitable for the occasion. <s> Asked to write a new piece, Parry turned, at the suggestion of his colleague George Grove, to Milton's ode, which he had been considering setting for many years.
simple: Blest Pair of Sirens is a short work for choir and orchestra by Hubert Parry. <s> It is a setting of an ode called "At a solemn Musick" by John Milton. <s> "Blest Pair of Sirens" was first performed by the Bach Choir conducted by Charles Villiers Stanford. <s> George Grove suggested Milton’s "Ode at a Solemn Music" would be a good poem for Parry to set. <s> The first performance of "Blest Pair of Sirens" at St James’s Hall took place on 17 May 1887. <s> At first Stanford wanted to perform another work by Parry: "The Glories of Our Blood and State". <s> However, the performance was going to be part of Queen Victoria’s Golden Jubilee celebrations.

title: Jegenstorf
complex: Jegenstorf is a municipality in the Bern-Mittelland administrative district in the canton of Bern in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2010 the former municipality of Ballmoos merged into Jegenstorf and on 1 January 2014 Münchringen and Scheunen merged into Jegenstorf.
simple: Jegenstorf (Bernese German: "Jegischtorf") is a municipality in the administrative district of Bern-Mittelland in the canton of Berne in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2010 the former municipality of Ballmoos merged into the municipality of Jegenstorf and on 1 January 2014 the former municipalities of Münchringen and Scheunen merged into the municipality of Jegenstorf.

title: Determinism
complex: Determinism is the philosophical belief that all events are determined completely by previously existing causes. <s> Deterministic theories throughout the history of philosophy have sprung from diverse and sometimes overlapping motives and considerations. <s> The opposite of determinism is some kind of indeterminism (otherwise called nondeterminism) or randomness. <s> Determinism is often contrasted with free will.
simple: In philosophy, determinism is the thesis that there are conditions that make future events happen the way they happen. <s> The opposite position to this idea is called indeterminism.

title: Molson Brewery
complex: The Molson Brewery was formed in 1786 in Montreal by the Molson family. <s> In 2005, Molson merged with US-based Coors to form Molson Coors Brewing Company, the world's seventh-largest brewery at that time.
simple: Molson is a Canadian brewery that was created in 1786 by the founder John Molson.

title: Hikaru Nakamura
complex: Hikaru Nakamura (ヒカル・ナカムラ (in katakana), 中村 光 (in kanji) , Nakamura Hikaru , born December 9, 1987) is a Japanese-born American chess grandmaster. <s> He is a five-time United States Chess Champion, who won the 2011 edition of Tata Steel Group A and represented the United States at five Chess Olympiads, winning a team gold medal and two team bronze medals. <s> He has also written a book about bullet chess called "Bullet Chess: One Minute to Mate". <s> Nakamura was born in Hirakata, Osaka Prefecture, Japan, to an American mother, Carolyn Merrow Nakamura, a classically trained musician and former public school teacher and Japanese father, Shuichi Nakamura. <s> When he was two years of age his family moved to the United States. <s> Nakamura's parents divorced in 1990, when he was 3 years old. <s> He began playing chess at the age of seven and was coached by his Sri Lankan stepfather, FIDE Master and chess author Sunil Weeramantry. <s> From January 14 through January 30, Nakamura competed in the Tata Steel Grandmaster A tournament in Wijk aan Zee among a field of world No. 1 and defending champion Magnus Carlsen, world champion and world No. 2 Viswanathan Anand, world No. 3 and reigning World Blitz champion Levon Aronian, world No. 4 and former world champion Vladimir Kramnik, world No. 7 Alexander Grischuk, former FIDE world champion Ruslan Ponomariov, reigning Russian champion Ian Nepomniachtchi, reigning Chinese champion Wang Hao, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, Alexei Shirov, Anish Giri, Jan Smeets, and Erwin L'Ami. <s> The average rating of the field was 2740, making this thirteen-round event a category 20 tournament.
simple: Hikaru Nakamura (中村光, Nakamura Hikaru) is the leading U.S. chess grandmaster (GM). <s> He has won the U.S. chess championship four times, and represented the United States at five Chess Olympiads. <s> He was born on 9 December 1987 in Japan (Hirakata, Osaka Prefecture). <s> His parents moved to the United States when he was two. <s> In 2011, Nakamura won the Tata Steel Grandmaster A tournament in Wijk aan Zee. <s> His opponents included world #1 and defending champion Magnus Carlsen, former world champion Viswanathan Anand, world #2 Levon Aronian, and former world champion Vladimir Kramnik,

title: Surface wave
complex: In physics, a surface wave is a 90 degree wave that propagates along the interface between differing media. <s> A common example is gravity waves along the surface of liquids, such as ocean waves. <s> Gravity waves can also occur within liquids, at the interface between two fluids with different densities. <s> Elastic surface waves can travel along the surface of solids, such as "Rayleigh" or "Love" waves. <s> Electromagnetic waves can also propagate as "surface waves" in that they can be guided along a refractive index gradient or along an interface between two media having different dielectric constants. <s> In radio transmission, a "ground wave" is a guided wave that propagates close to the surface of the Earth.
simple: In physics, a surface wave can refer to a mechanical wave that propagates along the interface between differing media, usually two fluids with different densities. <s> A surface wave can also be an electromagnetic wave guided by a refractive index gradient. <s> For radio waves, a ground wave is a surface wave that propagates close to the surface of the Earth.

title: River Dart
complex: The River Dart is a river in Devon, England which rises high on Dartmoor, and releases to the sea at Dartmouth. <s> The river's name is presumed to be Brythonic Celtic meaning 'river where oak trees grow' due to the banks of the lower Dart being covered in ancient woods of native oak. <s> The Cornish word for oak is "derow"; alternatively the word for water is "dowr", the probable source of other British hydronyms such as Derwent Water. <s> Bray notes in 1832 that the name was occasionally spelled 'Darant'. <s> The river begins as two separate branches (the East Dart and West Dart), which join at Dartmeet. <s> The paths along these rivers offer very attractive walking, and there are several small waterfalls. <s> The rivers are crossed by a number of clapper bridges, notably at the hamlet of Postbridge. <s> After leaving the moor, the Dart flows southwards past Buckfast Abbey and through the towns of Buckfastleigh, Dartington and Totnes. <s> At Totnes, where there is a seventeenth-century weir (rebuilt in the 1960s), it becomes tidal, and there are no bridges below the town. <s> The Dart estuary is a large ria and is popular for sailing. <s> The village of Kingswear and town of Dartmouth are on the east and west sides of the estuary, and are linked by two vehicle ferries and a passenger ferry. <s> The Kingswear Regatta is held each year. <s> The deep water port of Dartmouth is a sheltered haven. <s> The entrance to the river from the sea is a rocky entrance with cliffs either side. <s> On the East side Kingswear Castle sits very close to the water's edge, and on the west side Dartmouth Castle is built on a rocky promontory at sea level. <s> The castles once operated a defensive chain across the estuary, which was raised at dusk to destroy enemy ships attempting to attack the harbour. <s> The remains of the operating mechanisms for the chain are still visible in Dartmouth castle. <s> The flooded ria that forms the lower reaches of the Dart, with its deep water and steeply sloping valley sides, is a considerable barrier to crossing traffic. <s> There are no bridges below Totnes. <s> The lower section of the River Dart forms Dartmouth Harbour, a deep water natural harbour with a long history of maritime usage. <s> In modern times, the port's commercial activity has declined, but it is still a busy port for local fishing vessels and a wide variety of yachts and other private boats. <s> Several local companies specialise in shipbuilding and repairs to small tonnage craft.
simple: The River Dart is an English river in Devon. <s> It rises on Dartmoor, and reaches the English Channel at Dartmouth. <s> The river's name may be Celtic meaning 'river where oak trees grow'. <s> The banks of the lower Dart are covered in ancient woods of native oak. <s> The Dart begins at Dartmeet where the separate rivers East Dart and West Dart flow into each other. <s> The East and West Dart are crossed by a number of "clapper bridges" which are big slabs of stone laid on the river bed. <s> At Totnes the river becomes tidal, and there are no bridges below the town. <s> The Dart estuary is a large 'ria' (coastel inlet). <s> It is popular for sailing. <s> The entrance to the river from the sea is rocky with cliffs either side. <s> On the East side Kingswear Castle sits very close to the water's edge, and on the west side Dartmouth Castle is built on a rocky promontory at sea level. <s> The castles once operated a defensive chain across the estuary. <s> It was raised at dusk to destroy enemy ships attempting to attack the harbour. <s> The remains of the operating mechanisms for the chain are still visible in Dartmouth castle. <s> The lower section of the River Dart forms Dartmouth Harbour, a deep water natural harbour with a long history. <s> It is still a busy port for local fishing boats and a variety of yachts and other private boats. <s> Several local companies do shipbuilding and repairs to small tonnage craft.

title: National Assembly
complex: Perhaps the best known National Assembly was that established during the French Revolution in 1789, known as the "Assemblée nationale". <s> Consequently, the name is particularly common in Francophone countries.
simple: The best known National Assembly, and the first legislature to be known by this title, was established during the French Revolution in 1789, known as the "Assemblée Nationale".

title: Eagle Pass, Texas
complex: Eagle Pass is a city in and the county seat of Maverick County in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> The population was 26,255 as of the 2010 census (2013 estimate 27,708).
simple: Eagle Pass is a city in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> It is the county seat of Maverick County.

title: Metcard
complex: Metcard was the brand name of an integrated ticketing system used to access public transport in Melbourne, Australia. <s> It was a universal ticket which allowed users to ride on the city's Metlink network, consisting of suburban trains, trams, and buses, including the NightRider network. <s> The Metcard was a credit card-sized ticket made out of cardboard and used a magnetic strip to store fare data. <s> Metcard was operated by "OneLink Transit Systems" under a contract with the Government of Victoria which was managed by the Transport Ticketing Authority. <s> Moves towards automated ticketing were first made in 1992. <s> Tenders were called for the design, supply, installation and on-going maintenance of the system, with the 'OneLink Transit Consortium' becoming the preferred tenderer in September 1993. <s> The contract was signed in May 1994, with the major technology supplier being the ERG Group (now Vix Technology). <s> Testing of prototypes commenced in December 1993, and the roll-out of the system was carried out from August 1996 to April 1998. <s> Public field trials were carried out on buses from 20 August 1996, and on rail services from 18 September 1996. <s> Acceptance occurred in November 1997. <s> The system commenced full revenue service from May 1998 at a cost of $330 million. <s> Contractual issues between OneLink and the Victorian Government were not settled until May 2002 with the payment of up to $65 million in a staged settlement. <s> In 2002, Metcard replaced the functionally identical yet technically simpler punch tickets and scratchie tickets, which were easy to cheat. <s> In 2009, the rollout of a new smartcard ticketing system, Myki, would start the end of Metcard. <s> In 2011, it was announced that the Metcard system would be turned off by 29 December 2012. <s> Controversy surrounded Metcard at its introduction, due to cost over-runs, the abolition of tram conductors and the unreliability of ticket purchasing and validation machines. <s> The ticket vending machines were frequently attacked by vandals (often by pouring liquids into the coin slot), and have undergone several revisions to their design since. <s> An audit released by the Victorian Government in 2001 showed over 1 in 4 (27.2%) of machines at railway stations did not work, and 11.9% of mobile equipment in buses and trams were non-operational. <s> The State Government renegotiated with ticketing network contract operator "OneLink Transit Systems" to improve the service to commuters. <s> Following these improvements, a 2002 audit showed an increase in availability of machines to 92.1% at railway stations, and 98.3% on buses and trams. <s> Usability was also improved, with tram machines able to sell daily tickets. <s> Furthermore, vandalism across the network dropped by 62% between 2001 and 2002. <s> V/Line tickets were aligned with the Metcard system in April 2006, with each V/Line ticket to stations in the Metcard area having the relevant zones printed on them. <s> In March 2007 the Nightrider bus service was also brought under the Metcard system. <s> and zone 3 of the system was abolished, being merged with zone 2. <s> The original Metcard contract with OneLink was to last nine years, expiring in March 2007. <s> In 2005 the contract was amended to permit the system to be extended and modified as work on the replacement myki project progressed, with the contract being able to be terminated on six months notice.
simple: A Metcard is a type of ticket used to use public transport in Melbourne, Australia. <s> Moves towards automated ticketing were first made by the then state Liberal Government in 1992. <s> Tenders were called for the design, supply, installation and on-going maintenance of such a system, with the 'OneLink Transit Consortium' announced as the preferred people to do it in September 1993. <s> The contract was signed in May 1994, with the major technology supplier being the ERG Group. <s> Testing of prototypes commenced in December 1993, and the roll-out of the system was carried out from August 1996 to April 1998, and acceptance occurred in November 1997. <s> Public field trials were carried out on buses from August 20 1996, and on rail services from September 18 1996. <s> The system commenced full revenue service from May 1998 at a cost of $330 million. <s> Contractual issues between OneLink and the Victorian Government were not settled until May 2002 with the payment of up to $65 million in a staged settlement. <s> Metcard replaced a identical yet simpler system of scratchies used on the Melbourne public transport network. <s> Scratchies were easy to cheat and the system was eventually abandoned in 2002, but not before tickets for many years of use were printed. <s> Controversy surrounded Metcard at its introduction, due to it costing to much, the abolition of tram conductors and the unreliability of ticket purchasing and validation machines. <s> The machines were attacked by vandals frequently (often by pouring liquids into the coin slot), and have seen several revisions to their design since. <s> An study released by the State Government in 2001 showed over 1 in 4 (27.2%) of the machines at train stations did not work, and 11.9% of mobile equipment in buses and trams was non-operational. <s> The State Government renegotiated with ticketing network contract operator "OneLink Transit Systems" to improve the service to commuters. <s> Following these improvements, a 2002 audit showed an increase in availability of machines to 92.1% at train stations, and 98.3% on buses and trams. <s> Usability was also improved, with tram machines able to sell daily tickets. <s> Furthermore, vandalism across the network dropped by 62% between 2001 and 2002. <s> V/Line tickets were aligned with the Metcard system in April 2006, with each V/Line ticket to stations in the Metcard area having the relevant zones printed on them. <s> In March 2007 the Nightrider bus service was also brought under the Metcard system. <s> There used to be a Zone 3 , but that has been merged with Zone 2. <s> Zone 3 was removed from the Metcard system (and merged into zone 2) on March 4 2007, due to a State Election promise made by Opposition Leader Ted Ballieu and matched by then Premier Steve Bracks. <s> The original Metcard contract with OneLink was to last nine years, expiring in March 2007. <s> In 2005 the contract was changed to permit the system to be extended and changed as work on the replacement myki project keeps going, with the contract being able to be cancelled on six months notice.

title: Nabi Şensoy
complex: Nabi Sensoy (25 May 1945, Istanbul – 7 February 2018, İzmir, Turkey) was the ambassador of Turkey to the United States. <s> He held that office beginning in January 2006. <s> He was recalled to Turkey in October 2007 after the United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs passed a resolution condemning the Armenian Genocide in the Ottoman Empire. <s> He returned to his position shortly afterwards. <s> He resigned in December of 2009.
simple: Nabi Şensoy (May 25, 1945 – February 7, 2018) was a Turkish politician. <s> He was the Ambassador of Turkey to the United States. <s> Şensoy died on February 7, 2018 in in İzmir, Turkey at the age of 73. <s> Şensoy held that office beginning in January 2006. <s> He was recalled to Turkey in October 2007 after the United States criticized Turkey for the Armenian Genocide in the Ottoman Empire. <s> He returned to his position shortly afterwards. <s> Şensoy resigned in December of 2009.

title: Kantoku
complex: Kantoku (寛徳 ) was a Japanese era name (年号, , "nengō", , lit. <s> "year name") after "Chōkyū" and before "Eishō." <s> This period spanned the years from November 1044 through April 1046. <s> The reigning emperors were Go-Suzaku"-tennō" (後朱雀天皇 ) and Go-Reizei"-tennō" (後冷泉天皇 ) .
simple: Kantoku (寛徳) was a Japanese era name (年号, "nengō", lit. <s> "year name") after "Chōkyū" and before "Eishō." <s> This period started in November 1044 and ended in April 1046. <s> The reigning emperors were Go-Suzaku"-tennō" (後朱雀天皇) and Go-Reizei"-tennō" (後冷泉天皇).

title: Balıkesir
complex: Balıkesir (] ) is a city and the capital city of Balıkesir Province. <s> Balıkesir is in the Marmara region of Turkey and has a population of 331,788 inhabitants. <s> Between 1341–1922, it was the capital of Karasi.
simple: Balıkesir is a city in western Turkey. <s> The city is in the Marmara Region.

title: Composite material
complex: A composite material (also called a composition material or shortened to composite, which is the common name) is a material made from two or more constituent materials with significantly different physical or chemical properties that, when combined, produce a material with characteristics different from the individual components. <s> The individual components remain separate and distinct within the finished structure, differentiating composites from mixtures and solid solutions. <s> Composite materials are generally used for buildings, bridges, and structures such as boat hulls, swimming pool panels, racing car bodies, shower stalls, bathtubs, storage tanks, imitation granite and cultured marble sinks and countertops. <s> The earliest man-made composite materials were straw and mud combined to form bricks for building construction. <s> Ancient brick-making was documented by Egyptian tomb paintings. <s> Wattle and daub is one of the oldest man-made composite materials, at over 6000 years old. <s> Concrete is also a composite material, and is used more than any other man-made material in the world. <s> s of 2006 , about 7.5 billion cubic metres of concrete are made each year—more than one cubic metre for every person on Earth. <s> Fibre-reinforced polymers (FRP)s include carbon-fibre-reinforced polymer (CFRP) and glass-reinforced plastic (GRP). <s> If classified by matrix then there are thermoplastic composites, short fibre thermoplastics, long fibre thermoplastics or long fibre-reinforced thermoplastics. <s> There are numerous thermoset composites, including paper composite panels. <s> Many advanced thermoset polymer matrix systems usually incorporate aramid fibre and carbon fibre in an epoxy resin matrix. <s> Wood is a naturally occurring composite comprising cellulose fibres in a lignin and hemicellulose matrix. <s> Engineered wood includes a wide variety of different products such as wood fibre board, plywood, oriented strand board, wood plastic composite (recycled wood fibre in polyethylene matrix), Pykrete (sawdust in ice matrix), Plastic-impregnated or laminated paper or textiles, Arborite, Formica (plastic) and Micarta.
simple: Composite materials are made from two or more basic material mixed together. <s> Today we use shower stalls and bath tubs made of fiberglass, a type of composite. <s> The earliest man-made composite materials were straw and mud combined to form bricks for building construction. <s> The most primitive composite materials were straw and mud in the form of bricks for building construction. <s> This ancient brick-making process was documented by Egyptian tomb paintings. <s> Concrete itself is a composite material, one of the oldest man-made composites, used more than any other man-made material in the world. <s> Fibre-reinforced polymers are in wide use today, as is glass-reinforced plastic. <s> Wood is a natural composite of cellulose fibres in a matrix of lignin.

title: Comrade
complex: The term comrade is used to mean "mate", "colleague", or "ally", and derives from the Iberian Romance language term "camarada", literally meaning "chamber mate", from Latin "camera" "chamber" or "room". <s> Political use of the term was inspired by the French Revolution, after which it grew into a form of address between socialists and workers.
simple: It literally means "friend", "colleague", but an also mean "ally".

title: Saint-Genis-sur-Menthon
complex: Saint-Genis-sur-Menthon is a commune in the Ain department in eastern France.
simple: Saint-Genis-sur-Menthon is a commune.

title: Patent attorney
complex: A patent attorney is an attorney who has the specialized qualifications necessary for representing clients in obtaining patents and acting in all matters and procedures relating to patent law and practice, such as filing an opposition. <s> The term is used differently in different countries, and thus may or may not require the same legal qualifications as a general legal practitioner. <s> The titles patent agent and patent lawyer are also used in some jurisdictions. <s> In some jurisdictions the terms are interchangeable, while in others the latter is used only if the person qualified as a lawyer. <s> In Europe, requirements for practising as patent attorney before national patent offices should be distinguished from those needed for practising before the European Patent Office (EPO) or the Eurasian Patent Office (EAPO). <s> On the national level, the requirements are not harmonized, although across the 28 Member States of the European Union respective professional qualifications are mutually recognised to some degree. <s> In the United States, a practitioner may either be a patent attorney or patent agent. <s> Both patent attorneys and patent agents have the same license to practice and represent clients before the United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO).
simple: A patent attorney is an attorney who has the specialized skills and training necessary for representing clients in obtaining patents and acting in all matters and procedures relating to patent law and practice. <s> The term is used differently in different countries, and thus may or may not require the same legal qualifications as a general legal practitioner (i.e., a lawyer). <s> The titles patent agent and patent lawyer are also used in some jurisdictions. <s> In some jurisdictions the terms are interchangeable. <s> In other countries, a patent lawyer must also be qualified as a lawyer. <s> In Europe, requirements for practicing as patent attorney before national patent offices differ from those needed for practicing before the European Patent Office (EPO). <s> On the national level, the requirements are not harmonized across the European Union, except that the EU makes sure that respective professional qualifications are mutually recognized to some degree. <s> In the United States, the patent attorney must pass a special examination to test his knowledge of patent office procedures.

title: Ornithocheirus
complex: Ornithocheirus (from Ancient Greek "ὄρνις", meaning "bird", and "χεῖρ", meaning "hand") is a pterosaur genus known from fragmentary fossil remains uncovered from sediments in the UK.
simple: Ornithocheirus was a crested pterosaur that lived during the late Jurassic period.

title: Charter 77
complex: Charter 77 ("Charta 77" in Czech and in Slovak) was an informal civic initiative in the Czechoslovak Socialist Republic from 1976 to 1992, named after the document Charter 77 from January 1977. <s> Founding members and architects were Jiří Němec, Václav Benda, Ladislav Hejdánek, Václav Havel, Jan Patočka, Zdeněk Mlynář, Jiří Hájek, Martin Palouš, Pavel Kohout and Ladislav Lis. <s> Spreading the text of the document was considered a political crime by the communist regime. <s> After the 1989 Velvet Revolution, many of its members played important roles in Czech and Slovak politics.
simple: Charter 77 ("Charta 77" in Czech and in Slovak) was an informal civic initiative in the Czechoslovak Socialist Republic from 1976 to 1992. <s> It is named after the document Charter 77 from January 1977. <s> The founding members and architects were Jiří Němec, Václav Benda, Ladislav Hejdánek, Václav Havel, Jan Patočka, Zdeněk Mlynář, Jiří Hájek, Martin Palouš, Pavel Kohout and Ladislav Lis. <s> The charter was seen as a political crime by the communist regime. <s> After the 1989 Velvet Revolution, many of its members played important roles in Czech and Slovak politics.

title: Akhzivland
complex: Akhzivland is a micronation between Nahariya and the Lebanese border on the Israeli west coast, founded by Eli Avivi in 1971. <s> The micronation is promoted by the Israel Ministry of Tourism even though its legal status remains ambiguous. <s> The micronation is located near the ruins of Achziv, an ancient settlement on the Mediterranean coast in the Western Galilee, about 5 kilometers north of Nahariya. <s> A national park, field school, and the ruins of the Palestinian village of Az-Zeeb, which was captured by the Carmeli Brigade during the 1948 Arab–Israeli War, are located nearby. <s> Eli Avivi died of pneumonia on May 16, 2018. <s> Succeeding Avivi as President on 16 April 2019 was Carl Soderstrom who claimed the vacant seat.
simple: Akhzivland is a micronation between Nahariya and the Lebanese border on the Israeli west coast. <s> The state was founded by Eli Avivi in 1972. <s> The micronation is promoted by the Israel Ministry of Tourism even though its legal status remains debated. <s> The micronation is located near the ruins of Achziv, an ancient settlement on the Mediterranean coast in the Western Galilee, about 5 kilometers north of Nahariya. <s> A national park, field school, and the ruins of the Palestinian village of Az-Zeeb, which was captured by the Carmeli Brigade during the 1948 Arab-Israeli War, are located nearby. <s> Eli Avivi died of pneumonia on May 15, 2018.

title: Philoxenus of Eretria
complex: Philoxenus of Eretria (Greek: ) was a painter from Eretria He was a disciple of Nicomachus of Thebes, whose speed in painting he imitated and even surpassed, having discovered new and rapid methods of coloring. <s> Nevertheless, Pliny states that a picture of his was inferior to none, depicting a battle of Alexander the Great with Darius, which he painted for King Cassander. <s> A similar subject is represented in the celebrated Alexander Mosaic found in the House of the Faun, Pompeii. <s> As a disciple of Nicomachus, who flourished about 360 BC, and as the painter of the battle of Issus (333 BC), Philoxenus must have flourished in the age of Alexander, about 330 BC and onwards.
simple: Philoxenus of Eretria was a painter from Eretria. <s> He was the student of Nicomachus of Thebes. <s> Philoxenus copied his speed in painting. <s> He found new and fast ways of painting. <s> Pliny said a picture Philoxenus painted was the best painting. <s> He painted it for King Cassander. <s> The same subject was used in the Alexander Mosaic in the House of the Faun, in Pompeii.

title: Wikipedia administrators
complex: On Wikipedia, trusted users may be appointed as administrators (also known as admins, sysops, and janitors), following a successful request for adminship. <s> As of 2019, there are administrators on the English Wikipedia. <s> Administrators have additional technical privileges compared with other editors. <s> On Wikipedia, becoming an admin is often referred to as being "given or taking up the mop", a term which has also been used elsewhere. <s> In 2006, "The New York Times" reported that administrators on Wikipedia, of whom there were then about 1,000, were "geographically diverse". <s> In July 2012, it was widely reported that Wikipedia was "running out of administrators", because in 2005 and 2006, 40 to 50 people were often appointed administrators each month, but in the first half of 2012, only nine in total were appointed. <s> However, Jimmy Wales, Wikipedia's co-founder, denied that this was a crisis or that Wikipedia was running out of admins, saying, "The number of admins has been stable for about two years, there's really nothing going on." <s> Wales had previously (in a message sent to the English Wikipedia mailing list on February 11, 2003) stated that being an admin is "not a big deal", and that "It's merely a technical matter that the powers given to sysops are not given out to everyone." <s> In his book "Wikipedia – The Missing Manual", John Broughton states that while many people think of administrators on Wikipedia as judges, that is not the purpose of the role. <s> Instead, he says, admins usually "delete pages" and "protect pages involved in edit wars". <s> While the first Wikipedia administrators were appointed by Jimmy Wales in October 2001, administrator privileges on Wikipedia are now granted through a process known as requests for adminship (RfA). <s> Any registered editor may nominate themselves, or may request another editor to do so. <s> The process has been said to be "akin to putting someone through the Supreme Court" by Andrew Lih, a scientist and professor who is himself an administrator on the English Wikipedia. <s> Lih also said, "It's pretty much a hazing ritual at this point", in contrast to how the process worked early in Wikipedia's history, when all one had to do to become an admin was "prove you weren't a bozo". <s> Candidacy for the role is normally considered only after "extensive work on the wiki". <s> While any editor may vote in an RfA, the outcome is not determined by a majority vote, but rather by whether or not consensus has been reached that the candidate would make a good administrator, a decision which can only be made by a bureaucrat, a Wikipedia editor who is also appointed by the community through a "request" process, though the process is much stricter for them than for administrators. <s> This may have been implemented as a result of RfAs attracting increasing levels of attention: Stvilia et al. quoted that "Prior to mid-2005, RfAs typically did not attract much attention. <s> Since then, it has become quite common for RfAs to attract huge numbers of RfA groupies who all support one another". <s> Once granted administrator privileges, a user has access to additional functions in order to perform certain duties. <s> These include "messy cleanup work", deletion of articles deemed unsuitable, protecting pages (restricting editing privileges to that page), and blocking the accounts of disruptive users. <s> Blocking a user must be done according to Wikipedia's policies and a reason must be stated for the block, which will be permanently logged by the software. <s> Use of this privilege to "gain editing advantages" is considered inappropriate. <s> A scientific paper by researchers from Virginia Tech and Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute found that after editors are promoted to administrator status, they often focus more on articles about controversial topics than they did before. <s> The researchers also proposed an alternative method for choosing administrators, in which more weight is given to the votes of experienced editors. <s> Another paper, presented at the 2008 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems, analyzed data from all 1,551 requests for adminship from January 2006 to October 2007, with the goal of determining which (if any) of the criteria recommended in Wikipedia's "Guide to requests for adminship" page were the best predictors of whether the user in question would actually become an admin. <s> In December 2013, a similar study was published by researchers from the Polish-Japanese Institute of Information Technology in Warsaw which aimed to model the results of requests for adminship on the Polish Wikipedia using a model derived from Wikipedia's edit history. <s> They found that they could "classify the votes in the RfA procedures using this model with an accuracy level that should be sufficient to recommend candidates."
