title: Betoncourt-lès-Brotte
complex: Betoncourt-lès-Brotte is a commune in the Haute-Saône department in the region of Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in eastern France.
simple: Betoncourt-lès-Brotte is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in the Haute-Saône department in the east of France.

title: Fadil Vokrri
complex: Fadil Avdullah Vokrri (23 July 1960 – 9 June 2018) was a football administrator and player. <s> He was president of the Football Federation of Kosovo from 16 February 2008 until his death on 9 June 2018. <s> Vokrri scored a total of 121 goals and had 363 club appearances, he began his career at the age of 16 years old at Llapi. <s> He then moved to Prishtina in 1980 and played there until 1986, scoring 55 goals and making 172 appearances. <s> Vokrri was very successful with Partizan from Belgrade where he scored 18 goals and had 55 appearances. <s> He was key to the team's successful run in the 1988–89 Yugoslav Cup, notably scoring in the final as Partizan won 6–1 against Velež Mostar. <s> On 9 June 2018, Vokrri suffered a heart attack while he was exercising and died on his way to the emergency room. <s> Later that day, the Prishtina City Stadium was renamed to the Fadil Vokrri Stadium in his honour.
simple: Fadil Avdullah Vokrri (23 June 1960 – 9 June 2018) was a Kosovan football administrator and player. <s> He was president of Football Federation of Kosovo from 16 February 2008 until his death on 9 June 2018. <s> Vokrri scored a total of 121 goals and had 363 club appearances. <s> He moved to Pristina in 1980 and played there until 1986 scoring 55 goals and making 172 appearances. <s> On 9 June 2018, Vokrri died of cardiac arrest in Pristina, Kosovo at the age of 57.

title: Valery Bolotov
complex: Valery Dmitrievitch Bolotov (Russian: , ; 13 February 1970 – 27 January 2017) was a Ukrainian militant leader known for his involvement in the Donbass War in eastern Ukraine, and as the leader of the unrecognized Luhansk People's Republic. <s> Bolotov was found dead on 27 January 2017 in his own home in Moscow, Russia. <s> The causes of his death are currently being investigated.
simple: Valery Dmitrievitch Bolotov (, ; 13 February 1970 – 27 January 2017) was a Ukrainian pro-Russian militant leader. <s> He was known for his actions in the Donbass War in eastern Ukraine. <s> Bolotov died on 27 January 2017 in Moscow Oblast at the age of 46.

title: Ronse
complex: Ronse (] ; ) is a Belgian city and a municipality in the Flemish province of East Flanders. <s> The municipality has only the city of Ronse proper.
simple: Ronse is a municipality in the Belgian province of East Flanders.

title: Governor-General of Australia
complex: The Governor-General of the Commonwealth of Australia is the representative of the Australian monarch, currently Queen Elizabeth II. <s> As the Queen is concurrently the monarch of 15 other Commonwealth realms, and resides in the United Kingdom, she, on the advice of her prime minister, appoints a governor-general to carry out constitutional duties within the Commonwealth of Australia. <s> The governor-general has formal presidency over the Federal Executive Council and is commander-in-chief of the Australian Defence Force. <s> The functions of the governor-general include appointing ministers, judges, and ambassadors; giving royal assent to legislation passed by parliament; issuing writs for election; and bestowing Australian honours. <s> A governor-general is not appointed for a specific term, but is generally expected to serve for five years subject to a possible short extension. <s> Since 1 July 2019, the governor-general has been General David Hurley. <s> s of 2019 there are six living former Governors-General of Australia. <s> The most recently deceased governor-general, Sir Ninian Stephen (1982–1989), died on 29 October 2017.
simple: The Governor-General of Australia is the representative in Australia of Australia's head of state, Queen Elizabeth II. <s> The Governor-General of Australia is a powerful person in the country. <s> The Governor-General is leader of the Executive Council and Commander-in-Chief of the Australian Defence Forces. <s> The current Governor-General is David Hurley. <s> s of 2019 there are six living former Governors-General of Australia. <s> The most recently deceased governor-general, Sir Ninian Stephen (1982–1989), died on 29 October 2017.

title: The Heat (film)
complex: The Heat is a 2013 American buddy cop action comedy film directed by Paul Feig and written by Katie Dippold. <s> It stars Sandra Bullock, Melissa McCarthy, Demián Bichir, Marlon Wayans, Michael Rapaport, and Jane Curtin.
simple: The Heat is a 2013 police comedy which stars Sandra Bullock and Melissa McCarthy.

title: Icosagon
complex: In geometry, an icosagon or 20-gon is a twenty-sided polygon. <s> The sum of any icosagon's interior angles is 3240 degrees. <s> The "regular icosagon" has Schläfli symbol {20}, and can also be constructed as a truncated decagon, t{10}, or a twice-truncated pentagon, tt{5}. <s> The area of a regular icosagon with edge length "t" is <s> The Big Wheel on the popular US game show "The Price Is Right" has an icosagonal cross-section. <s> The Globe, the outdoor theater used by William Shakespeare's acting company, was discovered to have been built on an icosagonal foundation when a partial excavation was done in 1989. <s> As a golygonal path, the swastika is considered to be an irregular icosagon. <s> A regular square, pentagon, and icosagon can completely fill a plane vertex. <s> The highest symmetry irregular icosagons are d20, a isogonal icosagon constructed by ten mirrors which can alternate long and short edges, and p20, an isotoxal icosagon, constructed with equal edge lengths, but vertices alternating two different internal angles. <s> These two forms are duals of each other and have half the symmetry order of the regular icosagon. <s> Coxeter states that every zonogon (a 2"m"-gon whose opposite sides are parallel and of equal length) can be dissected into "m"("m"-1)/2 parallelograms. <s> In particular this is true for regular polygons with evenly many sides, in which case the parallelograms are all rhombi. <s> For the icosagon, "m"=10, and it can be divided into 45: 5 squares and 4 sets of 10 rhombs. <s> This decomposition is based on a Petrie polygon projection of a 10-cube, with 45 of 11520 faces. <s> The list OEIS: enumerates the number of solutions as 18,410,581,880, including up to 20-fold rotations and chiral forms in reflection. <s> An icosagram is a 20-sided star polygon, represented by symbol {20/n}.
simple: An icosagon is a shape with 20 sides and 20 corners. <s> The "regular icosagon" has Schläfli symbol {20}, and can also be constructed as a truncated decagon, t{10}, or a twice-truncated pentagon, tt{5}. <s> The amount of space a regular icosagon takes up is <s> The Big Wheel on the popular US game show "The Price Is Right" has an icosagonal cross-section. <s> The Globe, the outdoor theater used by William Shakespeare's acting company, was discovered to have been built on an icosagonal foundation when a partial excavation was done in 1989. <s> As a golygonal path, the swastika is considered to be an irregular icosagon. <s> A regular square, pentagon, and icosagon can completely fill a plane vertex. <s> Coxeter states that every parallel-sided 2"m"-gon can be divided into m(m-1)/2 rhombs. <s> For the icosagon, "m"=10, and it can be divided into 45: 5 squares and 4 sets of 10 rhombs. <s> This decomposition is based on a Petrie polygon projection of a 10-cube, with 45 of 11520 faces. <s> The list A006245 enumerates the number of solutions as 18,410,581,880, including up to 20-fold rotations and chiral forms in reflection.

title: Mary Carlisle
complex: Mary Carlisle (born Gwendolyn Witter; February 3, 1914 – August 1, 2018) was an American actress, singer, and dancer, she was best known for her roles as a wholesome ingénue in numerous 1930s musical-comedy films. <s> Carlisle was born Gwendolyn Witter in Boston, Massachusetts, to Arthur William and Leona Ella (Wotton) Witter. <s> Born into a religious family, she was educated in a convent in Back Bay, Boston, after her family moved to that neighborhood when she was six months old. <s> In 1942, Carlisle married British-born actor James Edward Blakeley (1910–2007), who later became an executive producer at 20th Century Fox. <s> She retired from films shortly after. <s> The couple had one son, James, and two grandchildren during their nearly 65-year marriage. <s> In later life, Carlisle was the manager of the Elizabeth Arden Salon in Beverly Hills, California. <s> After the death of Barbara Kent in 2011, Carlisle became the last surviving WAMPAS Baby Star. <s> She died on August 1, 2018, at the Motion Picture & Television Fund, a retirement community for actors in Woodland Hills, Los Angeles; no cause of death was reported. <s> She was believed to be 104, but never personally confirmed her age or birth date during her life.
simple: Mary Carlisle (born Gwendolyn Witter; February 3, 1914 – August 1, 2018) was a retired American actress, dancer and singer. <s> Carlisle was born on February 3, 1914 in Boston, Massachusetts. <s> She was married to James Blakeley from 1942 until his death in 2007. <s> Carlisle became the last known sole surviving "WAMPAS Baby Star". <s> Carlisle died on August 1, 2018 in Woodland Hills, Los Angeles at the age of 104.

title: Tia Mowry
complex: Tia Dashon Mowry-Hardrict (born July 6, 1978) is an American actress. <s> She first gained recognition for her starring role as Tia Landry in the sitcom "Sister, Sister" (1994–1999), opposite her identical twin sister Tamera Mowry.
simple: Tia Mowry (born July 6 1978 alongside sister Tamera Mowry) is an American actress who, similar to her sister, first became famous as a result of the sitcom "Sister, Sister" in the 1990s.

title: Abid Hamid Mahmud
complex: Lieutenant General Abid Al-Hamid Mahmud al-Tikriti ( ; ) (c. 1957 – June 7, 2012) was an Iraqi military officer under Saddam Hussein's deposed government. <s> On June 7, 2012, he was executed by hanging, according to a spokesman of the Iraqi Ministry of Justice.
simple: Abid Al-Hamid Mahmud al-Tikriti (born c. 1957; died June 7, 2012) was an Iraqi lieutenant general under Saddam Hussein's deposed regime, and he was Saddam's bodyguard. <s> He was executed on June 7, 2012.

title: Intermolecular force
complex: Intermolecular forces (IMF) are the forces which mediate interaction between molecules, including forces of attraction or repulsion which act between molecules and other types of neighboring particles, e.g., atoms or ions. <s> Intermolecular forces are weak relative to intramolecular forces – the forces which hold a molecule together.
simple: In physics, chemistry, and biology, intermolecular forces are forces that act between stable molecules or between functional groups of macromolecules.

title: Fall of a Kingdom
complex: Fall of a Kingdom is the first novel in the "Farsala Trilogy" by American author Hilari Bell. <s> It was previously published under the name "Flame". <s> The series it was in was also referred to as the "Book of Sorahb".
simple: Fall of a Kingdom is the first book in the "Farsala" Trilogy by American author Hilari Bell. <s> It was previously called "Flame!" <s> It is also called "The Book of Sorahb" in the series.

title: Marella Agnelli
complex: Marella Agnelli (] ; born Donna Marella Caracciolo di Castagneto ] ; 4 May 1927 – 23 February 2019) was an Italian noblewoman, art collector, socialite, style icon and widow of Fiat chairman Gianni Agnelli. <s> She often appeared in the fashion magazine "Vogue." <s> She was named to the International Best Dressed List Hall of Fame in 1963.
simple: Marella Agnelli (], born Donna Marella Caracciolo di Castagneto (]); 4 May 1927 – 23 February 2019) was an Italian noblewoman, art collector and socialite. <s> She was the widow Fiat chairman Gianni Agnelli. <s> She often appeared in the fashion magazine "Vogue." <s> She was named to the International Best Dressed List Hall of Fame in 1963.

title: Baltic, South Dakota
complex: Baltic is a city in Minnehaha County, South Dakota, United States. <s> The population was 1,089 at the 2010 census.
simple: Baltic is a city in the eastern part of the U.S. state of South Dakota. <s> It is located in Minnehaha County, and 1,089 people lived there at the 2010 census.

title: María Antonieta de las Nieves
complex: María Antonieta Gómez-Rodríguez (born 22 December 1950), more commonly known by her stage name María Antonieta de las Nieves, is a Mexican actress, comedian, and singer. <s> Her best remembered role is that of La Chilindrina, one of the main characters of the Televisa sitcom "El Chavo del Ocho". <s> De las Nieves became famous as La Chilindrina in the Televisa sitcom "El Chavo del Ocho".
simple: María Antonieta Gómez Rodríguez (born 22 December 1950), more commonly known by her stage name María Antonieta de las Nieves, is a Mexican actress, comedienne, and singer. <s> She is known for her role as La Chilindrina in the Mexican sitcom "El Chavo del Ocho".

title: Michihiro Yasuda
complex: Michihiro Yasuda (安田 理大 , Yasuda Michihiro , born 20 December 1987) is a Japanese footballer.
simple: Michihiro Yasuda (安田 理大, Yasuda Michihiro, born December 20, 1987) is a Japanese football player.

title: Jenna Dewan
complex: Jenna Lee Dewan ( ; born December 3, 1980) is an American actress and dancer. <s> She started her career as a backup dancer for Janet Jackson, and later worked with artists including Pink, Missy Elliott, and Christina Aguilera. <s> She is known for her role as Nora Clark in the 2006 film "Step Up". <s> She has also starred on the short-lived NBC series "The Playboy Club" and had a recurring role on the FX series "". <s> She portrayed Freya Beauchamp on the Lifetime series "Witches of East End" and played Lucy Lane in The CW series "Supergirl". <s> Dewan hosted the NBC reality competition television series "World of Dance".
simple: Jenna Lee Dewan Tatum (born December 3, 1980) is an American actress and dancer. <s> She began her career as a backup dancer for Janet Jackson. <s> Later she worked with artists including Pink, Missy Elliott, and Christina Aguilera. <s> She is known for her role as Nora in the 2006 film "Step Up" for which she won a Teen Choice Award. <s> She has also starred on the short-lived NBC series "The Playboy Club". <s> Tatum had a recurring role on the FX series "". <s> She was Freya Beauchamp on the Lifetime series "Witches of East End".

title: Janet Seidel
complex: Janet Seidel (28 May 1955 – 7 August 2017) was an Australian jazz vocalist and pianist. <s> Seidel's 18 CD albums, recorded with musicians including her brother, bassist David Seidel, have been nominated for prizes such as the ARIA Music Awards. <s> Her album "Moon of Manakoora" won the Bell Award for Best Australian Jazz Vocal Album in 2006. <s> Seidel was described as a "virtual institution" in her country. <s> She was a music teacher at the Sydney Girls High School. <s> Seidel died on 7 August 2017 from ovarian cancer in Sydney at the age of 62. <s> Some newspapers mistakenly reported her death as 8 August.
simple: Janet Seidel (28 May 1955 – 8 August 2017) was an Australian singer, pianist and educator. <s> Her albums, recorded with her brother bassist David Seidel, have been nominated for prizes such as the ARIA Music Awards. <s> Her album "Moon of Manakoora" won the Bell Award for Best Australian Jazz Vocal Album in 2006. <s> She was a music teacher at Sydney Girls High School. <s> Seidel died on 8 August 2017 from ovarian cancer at her home in Sydney, New South Wales at the age of 62.

title: Quranism
complex: Quranism ( ; "al-Qur'āniyya") comprises views that Islamic law and guidance should only be based on the Qur'an, thus opposing the religious authority, reliability, and/or authenticity of hadith literature. <s> Quranists believe that God's message in the Quran is clear and complete as it is, and that it can therefore be fully understood without referencing the Hadith. <s> Quranists affirm that the Hadith literature which exists today is apocryphal, as it had been written three centuries after the death of the Islamic prophet Muhammad; thus, it cannot have the same status as the Quran. <s> Adherents of Quranic Islam are referred to as "Quranists" , or "People of the Quran" . <s> This should not be confused with Ahle-e-Quran, which is an organisation formed by Abdullah Chakralawi.
simple: Quranism (; "al-Qur'āniyya") is the belief that the Quran is the only source for Islam. <s> Quranists reject the Hadiths as they believe that the Hadith literature which exists today is apocryphal, as it had been written three centuries after the death of the Islamic prophet Muhammad; thus, it cannot have the same status as the Quran. <s> Followers of the group are called Quranist Muslims, or Quran alone Muslims or Quraniyoon.

title: Jamal Lewis
complex: Jamal Lewis (born August 26, 1979) is a former American football running back in the National Football League (NFL). <s> He was drafted by the Baltimore Ravens fifth overall in the 2000 NFL Draft. <s> He played college football at Tennessee. <s> After spending his first seven seasons with the Ravens, Lewis signed a free agent contract with the Cleveland Browns prior to the 2007 season and retired after the 2009 season. <s> Lewis is best known for his career as a Raven, where he contributed to the team winning Super Bowl XXXV as a rookie. <s> Lewis is also known for his outstanding 2003 season, where he rushed for 2,066 yards (third-most all-time, behind Eric Dickerson and Adrian Peterson) and was named AP NFL Offensive Player of the Year.
simple: Jamal Lafitte Lewis (born August 26, 1979) is a former American football running back in the National Football League. <s> He was drafted by the Baltimore Ravens fifth overall in the 2000 NFL Draft. <s> He played college football at Tennessee. <s> He also played for the Cleveland Browns from 2007 to 2009. <s> Lewis helped the Ravens win Super Bowl XXXV in his rookie season in 2000.

title: Wilna, New York
complex: Wilna is a town in Jefferson County, New York, United States. <s> The population was 6,427 at the 2010 census. <s> The town is on the eastern side of the county and is east of Watertown.
simple: Wilna is a town in Jefferson County, New York, United States. <s> The population was 6,427 at the 2010 census.

title: Izegem
complex: Izegem is a municipality located in the Belgian province of West Flanders. <s> The municipality comprises the city of Izegem proper and the towns of Emelgem and Kachtem.
simple: Izegem is a municipality in the Belgian province of West Flanders.

title: List of North Carolina hurricanes (1980–1999)
complex: The list of North Carolina hurricanes from 1980 to 1999 encompasses approximately 68 tropical or subtropical cyclones that affected the U.S. state of North Carolina. <s> Collectively, cyclones in North Carolina during the time period resulted in around $10 billion in damage (2007 USD), primarily from hurricanes Fran and Floyd. <s> Additionally, tropical cyclones in North Carolina were responsible for about 56 direct fatalities and at least 47 indirect casualties during the period. <s> Eight cyclones affected the state in the 1985 season, which was the year with the most tropical cyclones impacting the state. <s> Every year included at least one tropical cyclone affecting the state. <s> All but two storms were North Atlantic hurricanes; the exceptions were Eastern Pacific hurricanes Tico in 1983 and Roslyn in 1986. <s> The strongest hurricane to hit the state during the time period was Hurricane Fran in 1996, which struck near Wilmington as a Category 3 hurricane on the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale; Hurricane Emily in 1993 brushed the Outer Banks also as a Category 3 hurricane. <s> The deadliest hurricane during the period was Hurricane Floyd in 1999, which caused 35 fatalities and record-breaking flooding in the eastern portion of the state.
simple: The list of North Carolina hurricanes includes tropical cyclones that affected or struck the U.S. state of North Carolina between 1980 and 1999. <s> Tropical cyclones in North Carolina caused at least $10 billion in damage. <s> Damage is $1 billion in North Carolina. <s> These cyclones killed 56 people directly and at least 47 indirectly. <s> The strongest tropical cyclones to affect North Carolina were Hurricane Emily and Hurricane Fran.

title: Heart arrhythmia
complex: Heart arrhythmia (also known as arrhythmia, dysrhythmia or irregular heartbeat) is a group of conditions in which the heartbeat is irregular, too fast or too slow. <s> A heart rate that is too fast – above 100 beats per minute in adults – is called tachycardia, and a heart rate that is too slow – below 60 beats per minute – is called bradycardia. <s> Many types of arrhythmia have no symptoms.
simple: Cardiac arrhythmia (commonly called irregular heartbeat) is the name for a number of conditions, where the heartbeat is not normal. <s> It may be too fast (tachycardia); too slow (bradycardia); or the heart may not beat in its regular rhythm.

title: Eastern religions
complex: The Eastern religions are the religions that originated in East, South and Southeast Asia and thus have dissimilarities with Western religions. <s> This includes the East Asian religions (Shintoism, Sindoism, Taoism and Confucianism), Indian religions (Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism) as well as animistic indigenous religions.
simple: Eastern religions is the name for a number of religions that had their origins in India, China, Japan and Southeast Asia.

title: David Suzuki: The Autobiography
complex: David Suzuki: The Autobiography is the 2006 autobiography of Canadian science writer and broadcaster David Suzuki. <s> The book focuses mostly on his life since the 1987 publication of his first autobiography, "Metamorphosis: Stages in a Life". <s> It begins with a chronological account of his childhood, academic years, and broadcasting career. <s> In later chapters, Suzuki adopts a memoir style, writing about themes such as his relationship with Australia, his experiences in Brazil and Papua New Guinea, the founding of the David Suzuki Foundation, and his thoughts on climate change, celebrity status, technology, and death. <s> Throughout, Suzuki highlights the continuing impact of events from his childhood. <s> This is Suzuki's forty-third book and, he says, his last. <s> Critics have called the book candid, sincere, and charming, with insightful commentary if occasionally flat stories. <s> Suzuki's scientific background is reflected in the writing's rational and analytic style. <s> Suzuki's autobiography spent four weeks at 1 on the "Maclean's" list of non-fiction best-sellers and six weeks at No. 6 on the "Globe and Mail's" list. <s> The book won two awards in 2007: the Canadian Booksellers' Association's Libris Award for Non-Fiction Book of the Year and the British Columbia Booksellers' Choice Award. <s> The publishers, Greystone Books and Douglas & McIntyre, won the CBA Libris Award for Marketing Achievement of the Year. <s> Later chapters tell of events since "Metamorphosis."
simple: David Suzuki: The Autobiography is the 2006 autobiography of Canadian science writer and broadcaster David Suzuki. <s> The book focuses mostly on his life since the 1987 publication of his first autobiography, "Metamorphosis: Stages in a Life". <s> It begins with a chronological account of his childhood, academic years, and broadcasting career. <s> In later chapters, Suzuki adopts a memoir style, writing about themes such as his relationship with Australia, his experiences in Brazil and Papua New Guinea, the founding of the David Suzuki Foundation, and his thoughts on climate change, celebrity status, technology, and death. <s> Throughout, Suzuki highlights the continuing impact of events from his childhood. <s> This is Suzuki's forty-third book and, he says, his last. <s> Critics have called the book candid, sincere, and charming, with insightful commentary if occasionally flat stories. <s> Suzuki's scientific background is reflected in the writing's rational and analytic style. <s> Suzuki's autobiography spent four weeks at #1 on the "Maclean's" list of non-fiction best-sellers and six weeks at #6 on the "Globe and Mail's" list. <s> The book won two awards in 2007: the Canadian Booksellers' Association's Libris Award for Non-Fiction Book of the Year and the British Columbia Booksellers' Choice Award. <s> The publishers, Greystone Books and Douglas & McIntyre, won the CBA Libris Award for Marketing Achievement of the Year.

title: Tanah Merah MRT station
complex: Tanah Merah MRT station (EW4/CG) is an above-ground Mass Rapid Transit (MRT) interchange station located in Bedok, Singapore. <s> Other than the main service (EW4), Tanah Merah station is also the terminus for the Changi Airport branch line (CG) which is also part of the East West Line. <s> Since 2017, Tanah Merah station is officially assigned the station code "CG", in addition to the station code "EW4" which the station originally had, to differentiate the operations of the main service and the Changi Airport branch line, albeit that it is not displayed on the signage of the station. <s> The station was originally not going to be open with the rest of the East West Line in between 1988 and 1989 as there were only private houses surrounding it, but increasing pressure from Members of Parliament and the public forced SMRT to open this station. <s> When it opened, the demand was extremely stagnant, with only private houses, Bedok South housing estates and Fengshan housing estates to cater to. <s> The demand increased when Singapore Expo and the MRT line to Changi Airport opened. <s> The addition of a new platform was announced by Land Transport Authority on 25 August 2014 to allow trains to arrive and depart at shorter intervals and an improvement in waiting times with the enhancements. <s> On 26 October 2016, the Land Transport Authority awarded the civil contract to Lum Chang Building Contractors Pte. Ltd. to build a new platform at Tanah Merah station and viaducts for a contract sum of S$325 million. <s> In addition to the new platforms, the existing East West Line tracks will be extended to connect the line to the new four-in-one East Coast Integrated Depot at Changi, as well as the new underpass to be constructed, which will be Exit C to Tanah Merah Kechil Avenue and Exit D to The Glades Condominium. <s> In order to facilitate construction, the road at New Upper Changi Road will have to be realigned and the Katong Flower Shop was closed down. <s> When completed in 2024, it will be the second station to have triple island platforms after Jurong East.
simple: Tanah Merah Station (EW4/CG) is an MRT Station in Bedok, Singapore. <s> Tanah Merah MRT is also officially assigned the station code "CG", to differentiate the station's operations on the Main Line and the Changi Airport Branch Line. <s> The station was originally not going to be open with the rest of the East West Line in between 1988 and 1989 as there were only private houses surrounding it, but increasing pressure from Members of Parliament and the public forced SMRT to open this station. <s> When it opened on 4 November 1989, the demand was extremely stagnant, with only private houses, Bedok South housing estates and Fengshan housing estates to cater to. <s> The demand increased when Singapore Expo and the MRT line to Changi Airport opened. <s> The addition of a new platform was announced by Land Transport Authority on 25 August 2014 to allow trains to arrive and depart at shorter intervals and an improvement in waiting times with the enhancements. <s> On 26 October 2016, the Land Transport Authority awarded the civil contract to Lum Chang Building Contractors Pte. Ltd. to build a new platform at Tanah Merah Station and viaducts for a contract sum of S$325 million. <s> In addition to the new platforms, the existing East-West Line tracks will be extended to connect the line to the new four-in-one East Coast Integrated Depot at Changi. <s> When completed in 2024, it will be the second station to have triple island platforms after Jurong East.

title: Veneridae
complex: The Veneridae or venerids, common name: venus clams, are a very large family of minute to large, saltwater clams, marine bivalve molluscs. <s> Over 500 living species of venerid bivalves are known, most of which are edible, and many of which are exploited as food sources.
simple: Veneridae is a family of clams, with over 500 described species, in twelve subfamilies. <s> They are commonly called Venus clams. <s> They are bivalve molluscs. <s> Many are edible and used as seafood.

title: Željko Milinovič
complex: Željko Milinovič (born 12 October 1969 in Ljubljana) is a former Slovenian footballer who has represented his country at the two major tournaments for which they have qualified (Euro 2000 and Football World Cup 2002).
simple: Željko Milinovič (born 12 October 1969) is a former Slovenian football player.

title: Thomas P. Salmon
complex: Thomas Paul Salmon (born August 19, 1932) is a U.S. Democratic Party politician who served as the 75th Governor of Vermont from 1973 to 1977. <s> Governor of Vermont from 1973 to 1977, Salmon chaired the New England Governors' Conference for two years and was a member of the National Governors Association's Executive Committee.
simple: Thomas Paul Salmon (born August 19, 1932) is a U.S. Democratic Party politician. <s> He served as the 75th Governor of Vermont from 1973 to 1977.

title: Mary Ellis (pilot)
complex: Mary Ellis (née Wilkins; 2 February 1917 – 24 July 2018) was a British ferry pilot, and one of the last surviving British women pilots from the Second World War. <s> Mary Wilkins was born on 2 February 1917, in Leafield, Oxfordshire, to a farming family. <s> She developed a fascination with aviation from a young age, as her family home was located near Royal Air Force bases at Bicester Airfield and Port Meadow. <s> At the age of 11 her father paid for her to have a joy ride in a biplane at a flying circus, and she decided she wanted to learn to fly. <s> When she was 16 she started having lessons at a flying club in Witney, successfully gained a private pilot's licence and flew for pleasure until the start of the Second World War in 1939, when all civilian flying was banned. <s> Ellis died at her home in Sandown, Isle of Wight, on 24 July 2018 at the age of 101.
simple: Mary Ellis (née Wilkins; 2 February 1917 – 24 July 2018) was a British ferry pilot. <s> She was one of the last surviving British women pilots from the Second World War. <s> She was born in Leafield, Oxfordshire. <s> Ellis died on 24 July 2018 in Sandown, Isle of Wight, aged 101.

title: Henry Stern
complex: Henry Jordan Stern (May 1, 1935 – March 28, 2019) was a member of the New York City Council from 1974 to 1983 and appointed as the Commissioner of the New York City Department of Parks and Recreation from 1983 to 1990 and again from 1994 to 2000. <s> Stern died on March 28, 2019 at the age of 83 from complications of advanced Parkinson’s disease.
simple: Henry J. Stern (May 1, 1935 – March 28, 2019) was an American politician. <s> He was a member of the New York City Council from 1974 to 1983 and appointed as the Commissioner of the New York City Department of Parks and Recreation from 1983 to 1990 and again from 1994 to 2000. <s> Stern died in New York City on March 28, 2019 from complications of Parkinson's disease at the age of 83.

title: Aneuploidy
complex: Aneuploidy is the presence of an abnormal number of chromosomes in a cell, for example a human cell having 45 or 47 chromosomes instead of the usual 46. <s> It does not include a difference of one or more complete sets of chromosomes. <s> A cell with any number of complete chromosome sets is called a "euploid" cell. <s> An extra or missing chromosome is a common cause of genetic disorders, including some human birth defects. <s> Some cancer cells also have abnormal numbers of chromosomes. <s> Aneuploidy originates during cell division when the chromosomes do not separate properly between the two cells. <s> Most cases of aneuploidy result in miscarriage and the most common extra autosomal chromosomes among live births are 21, 18, and 13. <s> Most embryos cannot survive with a missing or extra autosome (numbered chromosome) and are spontaneously aborted. <s> The most frequent aneuploidy in humans is trisomy 16, although fetuses affected with the full version of this chromosome abnormality do not survive to term (it is possible for surviving individuals to have the mosaic form, where trisomy 16 exists in some cells but not all). <s> The most common aneuploidy that infants can survive with is trisomy 21, which is found in Down syndrome, affecting 1 in 800 births. <s> Trisomy 18 (Edwards syndrome) affects 1 in 6,000 births, and trisomy 13 (Patau syndrome) affects 1 in 10,000 births.
simple: Aneuploidy is a condition where the nucleus of a cell has one or a few chromosomes more or less than the usual number in the species. <s> It is a common cause of genetic disorders. <s> Some cancer cells also have abnormal numbers of chromosomes. <s> Aneuploidy occurs during cell division when the chromosomes do not separate properly between the two cells. <s> Aneuploidy often causes birth defects and miscarriages. <s> Among those who survive birth, Down syndrome is the most common form of aneuploidy.

title: Girl in a Coma
complex: Girl In a Coma was an indie rock band from San Antonio, Texas formerly on Joan Jett's Blackheart Records' label. <s> The band was made up of sisters Nina (vocals/guitar) and Phanie Diaz (drums) and long-time friend, Jenn Alva (bass). <s> The name is a reference to The Smiths' song "Girlfriend in a Coma".
simple: Girl In a Coma is a rock band from San Antonio, Texas on Joan Jett's Blackheart Record's label. <s> The band is made up of sisters Nina(vocals/guitar) and Phanie Diaz (drums) and Jenn Alva (bass).

title: Ike Turner
complex: Izear Luster "Ike" Turner Jr. (November 5, 1931 – December 12, 2007) was an American musician, bandleader, songwriter, arranger, talent scout, and record producer. <s> An early pioneer of fifties rock and roll, he is best known for his work in the 1960s and 1970s with his then-wife Tina Turner in the Ike & Tina Turner Revue. <s> Turner was born in Clarksdale, Mississippi, on November 5, 1931, to Beatrice Cushenberry, a seamstress, and Izear Luster Turner Sr., a Baptist minister. <s> The youngest of their two children, Turner had a sister named Lee Ethel Knight who was "some ten years" his senior.
simple: Ike Turner (November 5, 1931 – December 12, 2007) was an American singer, songwriter and recording artist. <s> He was born in Clarksdale, Mississippi, although he later moved to St. Louis, Missouri then to California.

title: Hearing
complex: Sound may be heard through solid, liquid, or gaseous matter. <s> It is one of the traditional five senses; partial or total inability to hear is called hearing loss. <s> In humans and other vertebrates, hearing is performed primarily by the auditory system: mechanical waves, known as vibrations, are detected by the ear and transduced into nerve impulses that are perceived by the brain (primarily in the temporal lobe). <s> Like touch, audition requires sensitivity to the movement of molecules in the world outside the organism. <s> Both hearing and touch are types of mechanosensation. <s> There are three main components of the human auditory system: the outer ear, the middle ear, and the inner ear.
simple: Hearing is one of the five senses. <s> The ears are used for detecting (listening to) vibrations in the air known as sounds. <s> Most land vertebrates hear through ears. <s> In mammals, sound travels through three main parts of the ear to be heard. <s> These are the outer, middle and inner ear.

title: Krasnoyarsk
complex: Krasnoyarsk ( ; Russian: , ) is a city and the administrative center of Krasnoyarsk Krai, Russia, located on the Yenisei River. <s> It is the third-largest city in Siberia after Novosibirsk and Omsk, with a population of 1,035,528 as of the 2010 Census. <s> Krasnoyarsk is an important junction of the Trans-Siberian Railway and one of Russia's largest producers of aluminium. <s> The city is known for its nature landscapes; author Anton Chekhov judged Krasnoyarsk to be the most beautiful city in Siberia.
simple: Krasnoyarsk is a city and the administrative center of Krasnoyarsk Krai, Russia, located on the Yenisei River. <s> It is the third-largest city in Siberia after Novosibirsk and Omsk. <s> As of 2010, 1,035,528 people lived in the city. <s> Krasnoyarsk is an important junction of the Trans-Siberian Railway and one of Russia's largest producers of aluminum. <s> The city is notable for its nature landscapes; author Anton Chekhov judged Krasnoyarsk to be the most beautiful city in Siberia.

title: Samantha Barks
complex: Samantha Jane Barks (born 2 October 1990) is a Manx actress and singer who has performed on stage and screen as well as television. <s> She rose to fame after coming in third in the BBC talent show-themed television series "I'd Do Anything" in 2008. <s> In 2012, she starred alongside Jonathan Bailey in the Disney Channel series "Groove High", and made her film debut as Éponine in the film version of the musical "Les Misérables".
simple: Samantha Jane Barks (born 2 October 1990) is a Manx singer and actress who first rose to fame after coming third in the BBC talent show–themed television series "I'd Do Anything" in 2008. <s> In 2012, she was cast in her first movie as Éponine in the movie version of the long-running musical "Les Misérables".

title: Andrew Horatio Reeder
complex: Andrew Horatio Reeder (July 12, 1807 – July 5, 1864) was the first governor of the Territory of Kansas. <s> Reeder was born in Easton, Pennsylvania, to Absolom Reeder and Christina (Smith) Reeder. <s> He was educated at an academy in Lawrenceville, New Jersey. <s> He read law in a Pennsylvania law office and was admitted to the bar there in 1828. <s> In 1831, he married Frederika Amalia Hutter. <s> Together they had three sons and seven daughters. <s> Reeder was a loyal member of the Democratic Party and supported the idea of popular sovereignty which dealt with territories' decisions on the issue of slavery. <s> On June 29, 1854, President Franklin Pierce appointed Reeder to the office of the governor of the territory of Kansas and remained in office until August 16, 1855, when he was fired. <s> Reeder took the oath of office on July 7 and arrived in Kansas on October 7. <s> He served until April 17, 1855, when he left the territory, making Daniel Woodson acting territorial governor. <s> Reeder returned to the Kansas Territory on June 23. <s> As governor of the Territory of Kansas, Reeder was a proponent of the controversial Kansas-Nebraska Act. <s> On March 30, 1855, one of the biggest voting frauds took place, when neighboring Missourians came into the Kansas Territory to vote illegally on the issue of Kansas being admitted into the U.S. as a free state or a slave state. <s> The incident caused border violence between Kansas and Missouri, referred to as Bleeding Kansas. <s> Reeder refused to ratify the results, called for a new election to fill the vacancies, and designated the townsite of Pawnee as the meeting place for the first territorial legislature. <s> President Pierce formally dismissed Reeder for his refusal to use his position to aid in making Kansas a slave state. <s> In May 1856, facing indictment for high treason, he left the territory disguised as a wood-chopper. <s> Reeder returned to Pennsylvania, practiced law, and remained active in Republican Party politics. <s> On the first ballot for the vice-presidential nomination taken by delegates to the 1860 Republican National Convention, Reeder received fifty-one votes, which put him in fourth place behind the eventual nominee, Hannibal Hamlin. <s> Andrew Horatio Reeder died in Easton, Pennsylvania, on July 5, 1864, and is buried in Easton Cemetery.
simple: Andrew Horatio Reeder (July 12, 1807 – July 5, 1864) was the first governor of the Territory of Kansas. <s> Reeder was born on July 12, 1807 in Easton, Pennsylvania. <s> He went to school in Lawrenceville, New Jersey. <s> He became a lawyer in 1828 in Pennsylvania. <s> In 1831, he married Frederika Amalia Hutter. <s> They had three sons and seven daughters. <s> Reeder supported the idea of popular sovereignty (where people in a state would decide whether a state becomes free or slave) about slavery. <s> On June 29, 1854, President Franklin Pierce asked Reeder to be the governor of the Kansas Territory. <s> He would stay governor until August 16, 1855. <s> On March 30, 1855, many pro-slavery people from Missouri illegally voted in Kansas. <s> This caused a lot of violence between Missouri and Kansas, known as Bleeding Kansas. <s> Reeder did not approve the results. <s> President Franklin Pierce asked Reeder to quit. <s> This is because Reeder did not let Kansas become a slave state. <s> Reeder came back to Pennsylvania. <s> He stayed in politics and law. <s> He died in Easton, Pennsylvania on July 5, 1864. <s> He is buried in Easton Cemetery.

title: Hachikō
complex: Hachikō (ハチ公 , November 10, 1923 – March 8, 1935) was a Japanese Akita dog remembered for his remarkable loyalty to his owner, Hidesaburō Ueno, for whom he continued to wait for over nine years following Ueno's death. <s> Hachikō was born on November 10, 1923, at a farm near the city of Ōdate, Akita Prefecture. <s> In 1924, Hidesaburō Ueno, a professor at the Tokyo Imperial University, brought him to live in Shibuya, Tokyo, as his pet. <s> Hachikō would meet Ueno at Shibuya Station every day after his commute home. <s> This continued until May 21, 1925, when Ueno died of a cerebral hemorrhage while at work. <s> From then until his death on March 8, 1935, Hachikō would return to Shibuya Station every day to await Ueno's return. <s> Hachiko, a golden brown Akita, was born on November 10, 1923 at a farm located in Ōdate, Akita Prefecture, Japan. <s> In 1924, Hidesaburō Ueno, a professor in the agriculture department at the Tokyo Imperial University, took Hachikō as a pet and brought him to live in Shibuya, Tokyo. <s> Ueno would commute daily to work, and Hachikō would leave the house to greet him at the end of each day at the nearby Shibuya Station. <s> The pair continued the daily routine until May 21, 1925, when Ueno did not return. <s> The professor had suffered a cerebral hemorrhage, while he was giving a lecture, and died without ever returning to the train station in which Hachikō waited. <s> Each day, for the next nine years, nine months and fifteen days, Hachikō awaited Ueno's return, appearing precisely when the train was due at the station. <s> Hachikō attracted the attention of other commuters. <s> Many of the people who frequented the Shibuya train station had seen Hachikō and Professor Ueno together each day. <s> Initial reactions from the people, especially from those working at the station, were not necessarily friendly. <s> However, after the first appearance of the article about him in "Asahi Shimbun" on October 4, 1932, people started to bring Hachikō treats and food to nourish him during his wait. <s> One of Ueno's students, Hirokichi Saito, who developed expertise on the Akita breed, saw the dog at the station and followed him to the Kobayashi home, the home of Ueno's former gardener, Kuzaboro Kobayashi, where he learned the history of Hachikō's life. <s> Shortly after the meeting, the former student published a documented census of Akitas in Japan. <s> His research found only 30 purebred Akitas remaining, including Hachikō from Shibuya Station. <s> He returned frequently to visit Hachikō, and over the years he published several articles about the dog's remarkable loyalty. <s> In 1932, one of his articles, published in "Asahi Shimbun", placed the dog in the national spotlight. <s> Hachikō became a national sensation. <s> His faithfulness to his master's memory impressed the people of Japan as a spirit of family loyalty to which all should strive to achieve. <s> Teachers and parents used Hachikō's vigil as an example for children to follow. <s> A well-known Japanese artist rendered a sculpture of the dog, and throughout the country, a new awareness of the Akita breed grew. <s> Eventually, Hachikō's legendary faithfulness became a national symbol of loyalty, particularly to the person and institution of Emperors. <s> Hachikō died on March 8, 1935 at the age of 11. <s> He was found on a street in Shibuya.
simple: Hachikō (November 10, 1923 – March 8, 1935) was an Akita dog. <s> He is best known for his unusual loyalty. <s> The dog was born on a farm near the city of Ōdate in Akita Prefecture. <s> In
