Shinbun", people started to bring Hachikō treats and food for him to eat while he waited. <s> In 1932 one of Ueno's students Hirokichi Saito (who had learned much about the Akita breed) saw the dog at the station. <s> He followed him to the home of the former gardener of Professor Ueno—Kikuzaboro Kobayashi, where he learned the history of Hachikō's life. <s> Shortly after this meeting, the former student published a census of all the Akitas in Japan. <s> His research found only 30 purebred Akitas still alive, including Hachikō from Shibuya Station. <s> Saito went back many times to visit Hachikō. <s> Over the years he wrote several news stories about the dog's remarkable loyalty. <s> In 1932 one of these stories, published in the Tokyo "Asahi Shinbun", made Hachikō a national sensation. <s> His faithfulness to his master's memory meant a spirit of family loyalty for all Japanese people to achieve. <s> Teachers and parents used Hachikō's devotional watching for his master as an example for children to follow. <s> A well-known Japanese artist made a sculpture of the dog, and in Japan a new awareness of the Akita breed grew. <s> At last, Hachikō's legendary faithfulness became a national symbol of loyalty to the Emperor of Japan himself. <s> Hachikō died on March 8, 1935, and was found on a street in Shibuya.

title: Heinz Hall for the Performing Arts
complex: Heinz Hall is a performing arts center and concert hall located at 600 Penn Avenue in the Cultural District of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. <s> Home to the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra (PSO) and the Pittsburgh Youth Symphony Orchestra, the 2,676 seat hall presents about 200 performances each year. <s> Originally built in 1927 as Loew's Penn Theatre, the former movie palace was renovated and reopened as Heinz Hall in 1971.
simple: Heinz Hall for the Performing Arts is a performing arts center and concert hall located at 600 Penn Avenue in the Cultural District of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. <s> It is home to the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra (PSO) and the Pittsburgh Youth Symphony Orchestra, the 2,676 seat hall presents about 200 performances each year. <s> Originally built in 1927 as Loew's Penn Theatre, the former movie palace was renovated and reopened as Heinz Hall in 1971.

title: Radebeul
complex: Radebeul is a town ("große Kreisstadt") in the Elbe valley in the district of Meißen in Saxony, Germany, a suburb of Dresden. <s> It is well known for its viticulture, a museum dedicated to writer Karl May, and a narrow gauge railway connecting Radebeul with the castle of Moritzburg and the town of Radeburg. <s> The Meißen area, where Radebeul is located, is one of the northeasternmost areas where wine is grown in the 21st century.
simple: Radebeul is a town ("große Kreisstadt") in the district of Meißen in Saxony, Germany, a suburb of Dresden. <s> The Meißen area, where Radebeul is located, is one of the northeasternmost areas where wine is grown today.

title: John Andretti
complex: John Andrew Andretti (born March 12, 1963) is an American race car driver. <s> He is the older brother of racer Adam Andretti, nephew of Indianapolis 500 winner Mario Andretti, and first cousin to IndyCar champion Michael and Jeff Andretti. <s> He is also the first cousin once-removed to IndyCar driver Marco Andretti. <s> His father Aldo Andretti, Mario's twin brother, retired from driving a race car after he nearly died in an accident. <s> He has won in CART, IMSA GTP, Rolex Sports Car Series, and NASCAR. <s> In April 2017, Andretti disclosed that he is battling stage four colon cancer. <s> His cancer battle, originally misdiagnosed as Stage III-A cancer, was widely publicized, with him starting a Twitter hashtag called #CheckIt4Andretti, as far as getting a colonoscopy.
simple: John Andrew Andretti (born March 12, 1963) is an American race car driver. <s> He is the older brother of racer Adam Andretti and the nephew of Indianapolis 500 winner Mario Andretti. <s> He has won in CART, IMSA GTP, Rolex Sports Car Series, and NASCAR. <s> In April 2017, Andretti said that he was diagnosed with stage four colon cancer.

title: Mondeville, Calvados
complex: Mondeville is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy région in northwestern France.
simple: Mondeville, Calvados is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Wild Orchid (film)
complex: Wild Orchid is a 1989 American erotic film directed by Zalman King and starring Mickey Rourke, Carré Otis, Jacqueline Bisset, Bruce Greenwood, and Assumpta Serna. <s> The film was shot in Salvador, Bahia, and Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. <s> King's original version of the film was deemed too sexually graphic for an R-rating and the MPAA threatened to release it with an X-rating, limiting its commercial potential. <s> King reluctantly removed part of a love scene between Otis and Rourke to comply with the R-rating. <s> The scene was widely rumored in the media to have shown the two actors—who had become romantically involved during production of the film—actually having intercourse.
simple: Wild Orchid is an 1989 erotic suspense movie. <s> It was directed by Zalman King. <s> The movie stars Mickey Rourke, Carré Otis, Jacqueline Bisset, Bruce Greenwood, Oleg Vidov and Assumpta Serna. <s> The first version of the movie was too sexual for an R rating. <s> The MPAA threatened give the movie an X rating. <s> King edited the movie down to get the R rating.

title: Jared Martin
complex: Jared Christopher Martin (December 21, 1941 – May 24, 2017) was an American film and television actor. <s> He was best known for his role as Steven "Dusty" Farlow in the 1978 series "Dallas" and for roles on two science fiction TV series, "The Fantastic Journey" and "War of the Worlds". <s> Martin was born in Manhattan to Charles Elmer Martin, a cover artist and cartoonist for "The New Yorker", and his wife, Florence Taylor, an artist and homemaker. <s> He began acting at the age of ten in a local children's theater group. <s> After graduating from the Putney School and Columbia University, where his roommate was Brian De Palma, he spent a summer apprenticing with Joseph Papp's Shakespeare in the Park. <s> After graduating, he worked for a couple of years at "The New York Times" as a copy boy and thumbnail book reviewer for the Sunday edition. <s> Martin died from pancreatic cancer on May 24, 2017 at his home in Philadelphia at age 75.
simple: Jared Christopher Martin (December 21, 1941 – May 24, 2017) was an American movie and television actor. <s> He was best known for his role as Steven "Dusty" Farlow in the 1978 series "Dallas" and for roles on two science fiction TV shows, "The Fantastic Journey" and "War of the Worlds". <s> He was born in Manhattan, New York. <s> Martin died on May 24, 2017 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania from pancreatic cancer at the age of 75.

title: De Wallen
complex: De Wallen (] ) or De Walletjes (] ) is the largest and best known red-light district in Amsterdam. <s> It consists of a network of alleys containing approximately three hundred one-room cabins rented by prostitutes who offer their sexual services from behind a window or glass door, typically illuminated with red lights and blacklight.
simple: De Wallen (""thin walls"") are the biggest and most famous red-light district in Amsterdam.

title: Helix (gastropod)
complex: Helix is a genus of large, air-breathing land snails native to Europe and the Mediterranean region. <s> They are the type genus of the family Helicidae and among the first animal genera described by Carl Linnaeus. <s> Members of the genus first appeared during the Oligocene. <s> Like most land snails, "Helix" species are hermaphroditic, and like other helicids a courting pair will impale each other with hormone-rich love darts prior to exchanging sperm. <s> Well-known species include "Helix pomatia" (Roman snail, Burgundy snail, or edible snail) and "Helix lucorum" (Turkish snail). <s> "Cornu aspersum" (garden snail) – another well-known helicid – was originally described as a member of "Helix" (as ""Helix aspersa""), but the prevailing classification places it in the sister genus "Cornu". <s> "Helix" snails prefer cool, damp environments, as they easily suffer moisture loss. <s> Snails are most active at night and after rainfall. <s> During unfavourable conditions, a snail will remain inside its shell, usually under rocks or other hiding places, to avoid being discovered by predators. <s> In dry climates snails will naturally congregate near water sources, including artificial sources such as waste-water outlets of air conditioners. <s> The common garden snail ("Helix aspersa") is herbivorous. <s> These snails are able to digest most vegetation including carrots and lettuce. <s> They also have a specialized crop of symbiotic bacteria that aid in their digestion, especially with the breakdown of the polysaccharide cellulose into simple sugars. <s> "H. pomatia" and "H. aspersa" are the two edible species that are most used in European cuisine. <s> Spanish cuisine also uses "Otala punctata", "Theba pisana" and "Iberus gualterianus alonensis", amongst others.
simple: Helix is a genus of large air-breathing land snails, terrestrial pulmonate gastropod molluscs. <s> This genus is native to Europe and the regions around the Mediterranean Sea. <s> The genus "Helix" is known from the Oligocene onwards. <s> The best-known species include "Helix aspersa", the common, or brown garden snail, and "Helix pomatia", the Roman snail, Burgundy snail, or edible snail. <s> "Helix" snails prefer cool, damp environments, as they easily get dry. <s> Snails are most active at night and after rainfall. <s> During unfavourable conditions, a snail will remain inside its shell, usually under rocks or other hiding places, to avoid being discovered by predators. <s> In dry climates snails will naturally congregate near water sources, including artificial sources such as waste-water outlets of air conditioners. <s> The common garden snail ("Helix aspersa") is herbivorous. <s> These snails are able to digest most vegetation including carrots and lettuce. <s> They also have a specialized crop of symbiotic bacteria that help their digestion, especially by breaking down the polysaccharide cellulose into simple sugars. <s> "H. pomatia" and some other species are eaten as escargots.

title: Roger Nordström
complex: Roger Ola Nordström (born 27 April 1966 in Malmö, Sweden) is a Swedish former ice hockey goaltender. <s> Playing most seasons for Malmö Redhawks, he then played for German Krefeld Pinguine between 1998-2003. <s> During the 1992 Olympic tournament he was appointed for the Swedish national team.
simple: Roger Nordström, born 27 April 1966 in Malmö, Sweden, is a Swedish former ice hockey goaltender. <s> He played most seasons for Malmö Redhawks. <s> He then played for German club Krefeld Pinguine between 1998-2003. <s> During the 1992 Olympic tournament he was appointed for the Swedish national team.

title: Montréal Mission
complex: The Montréal Mission are a team in the National Ringette League that gathers players from the region of Montreal, Quebec. <s> The Montréal Mission play in the National Ringette League and the team plays its home games at Centre Étienne Desmarteau. <s> The Montréal Mission have played in the National Ringette League since its formation in 2004. <s> For several years, The Montreal Mission have been the best NRL team in the province of Quebec. <s> The team is ranked second in the Eastern Conference of the National Ringette League behind a team from Ontario, the Cambridge Turbos, and it has been in second place for two seasons: 2010-11 and 2009-10. <s> In 2008-09, the Montreal Mission ended its season at the top of the NRL standings for the NRL Eastern Conference with two points more than the Cambridge Turbos. <s> The world championships for ringuette take place once every three years. <s> Several players from the Montréal Mission have been chosen to represent their country. <s> In 2010-11, two players from the Montréal Mission dominated the standings of the league for scores and assists with 141 points for Julie Blanchette in 1st and 132 points for Catherine Cartier in 2nd. <s> In 2009-2010 the two same players dominated the standings with 122 points for (1st) Cartier, 110 points for Blanchette in 2nd and in addition 83 points for Stéphanie Séguin in 4th.
simple: The Montreal Mission is a ringette team at Montreal, Canada. <s> The team plays in the National Ringette League and plays its home games in Centre Étienne Desmarteau. <s> The Montreal Mission have played in the National Ringette League since its formation in 2004. <s> For several years, the best ringette team in Quebec is the Montreal Mission. <s> On the other hand, the team ends in the second rank in the East Conference of the National Ringette League behind a team of the Ontario, the Cambridge Turbos and it since two seasons: 2010-11 and 2009-10. <s> In 2008-09, Montreal Mission ends its season at the top of the classification of the east Conference with two points more than the Cambridge Turbos. <s> The world championships of ringuette occur once in three years. <s> Several players of Montreal Mission were able to represent it their country of origin. <s> In 2010-11, two players of Montreal Mission dominated the classification of the league with 141 points for Julie Blanchette 1st and 132 points for Catherine Cartier 2nd. <s> In 2009-2010 these two same players dominated the classification with 122 points for (1st) Cartier, 110 points for Blanchette 2nd and in addition 83 points for Stéphanie Séguin 4th.

title: Egypt Standard Time
complex: On 21 April 2011, the interim government abolished summer time. <s> The standard time was used the whole year round, with no change in summer.
simple: EET was then used all year, with no summer time change.

title: Fender Stratocaster
complex: The Fender Stratocaster is a model of electric guitar designed from 1952 into 1954 by Leo Fender, Bill Carson, George Fullerton, and completed by Freddie Tavares. <s> The Fender Musical Instruments Corporation has continuously manufactured the Stratocaster from 1954 to the present. <s> It is a double-cutaway guitar, with an extended top "horn" shape for balance like the Precision Bass guitar.
simple: The Fender Stratocaster, also called a Strat, is a type of solidbody electric guitar. <s> The Stratocaster was designed by Leo Fender, Freddie Tavares, and George Fullerton in 1954, and is made by the Fender Musical Instruments Corporation.

title: Ensete
complex: Ensete is a genus of monocarpic flowering plants native to tropical regions of Africa and Asia. <s> It is one of the two genera in the banana family, Musaceae, and includes the false banana or enset ("E. ventricosum"), an economically important food crop in Ethiopia. <s> The genus "Ensete" was first described by Paul Fedorowitsch Horaninow (1796-1865) in his "Prodromus Monographiae Scitaminarum" of 1862 in which he created a single species, "Ensete edule". <s> However, the genus did not receive general recognition until 1947 when it was revived by E. E. Cheesman in the first of a series of papers in the "Kew Bulletin" on the classification of the bananas, with a total of 25 species. <s> Taxonomically, the genus "Ensete" has shrunk since Cheesman revived the taxon. <s> Cheesman acknowledged that field study might reveal synonymy and the most recent review of the genus by Simmonds (1960) listed just six. <s> Recently the number has increased to seven as the Flora of China has, not entirely convincingly, reinstated "Ensete wilsonii". <s> There is one species in Thailand, somewhat resembling "E. superbum", that has not been formally described, and possibly other Asian species. <s> It is possible to separate "Ensete" into its African and Asian species.
simple: Ensete is a genus of flowering plants native to tropical regions of Africa and Asia. <s> It is one of the three genera in the banana family, Musaceae, and includes the false banana or enset ("E. ventricosum"), an economically important foodcrop in Ethiopia. <s> The genus "Ensete" was first described by Paul Fedorowitsch Horaninow (1796-1865) in his "Prodromus Monographiae Scitaminarum" of 1862 in which he created a single species, "Ensete edule". <s> However, the genus did not receive general recognition until 1947 when it was revived by E. E. Cheesman in the first of a series of papers in the "Kew Bulletin" on the classification of the bananas, with a total of 25 species. <s> Taxonomically, the genus "Ensete" has been reduced since Cheesman restore the taxon. <s> Cheesman acknowledged that field study might reveal synonymy and the most recent review of the genus by Simmonds (1960) listed just six. <s> It is possible to separate "Ensete" into its African and Asian species.

title: SEAT León
complex: The SEAT León (] , also spelled Leon outside of Spain) is a hatchback compact car built by the Spanish car manufacturer SEAT since October 1998. <s> The second generation León, "Typ" 1P, was released in 2005, with factory production commencing May 2005. <s> It is based on the Volkswagen Group A5 (PQ35) platform, most notably used by the Volkswagen Golf Mk5.
simple: The SEAT León is a 5-door hatchback automobile produced by SEAT in three generations since 1999. <s> After launching the second generation in 2005, the first generations continues as "León Torro" until 2006.

title: New Bedford, Massachusetts
complex: New Bedford is a city in Bristol County, Massachusetts, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a total population of 95,072 making it the sixth-largest city in Massachusetts. <s> New Bedford is nicknamed "The Whaling City" because during the 19th century, the city was one of the most important whaling ports in the world, along with Nantucket, Massachusetts and New London, Connecticut.
simple: New Bedford is a city in Bristol County, Massachusetts. <s> It is the sixth-largest city in Massachusetts.

title: Juninho Fonseca
complex: Alcides Fonseca Júnior (born August 29, 1958 in Olímpia, São Paulo State), best known as Juninho Fonseca or just Juninho, is a Brazilian former footballer who played as a central defender.
simple: Juninho Fonseca (born 29 August, 1958) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Mona Sahlin
complex: Mona Ingeborg Sahlin (] née Andersson; born 9 March 1957) is a Swedish politician who was leader of the opposition and leader of the Swedish Social Democratic Party from 2007 to 2011. <s> Sahlin was born Mona Ingeborg Andersson in Sollefteå, Västernorrland County, Sweden.
simple: Mona Ingeborg Sahlin (born Andersson on March 9, 1957 in Sollefteå, Sweden) is a former leader for the Swedish Social Democratic Party, when she replaced Göran Persson after his ten years as leader, she was the first woman to do so.

title: Lezhë District
complex: Lezhë District was one of the thirty-six districts of Albania (which were dissolved in 2000) that is now part of Lezhë County. <s> It had a population of 77,184 (2010 estimate), and an area of 479 km2. <s> It is in the north-west of the country, and its capital was Lezhë.
simple: The District of Lezhë is one of the thirty-six districts of Albania. <s> It is part of Lezhë County. <s> There are 77,184 people. <s> The capital is Lezhë.

title: Naughton, Suffolk
complex: Naughton is a village and former civil parish, now in the civil parish of Nedging-with-Naughton, in the Babergh district, in the county of Suffolk, England. <s> It is 10 mi north-west of Ipswich and 7 mi south-west of Stowmarket.
simple: Naughton is a village in Suffolk, England.

title: Beaux Arts Trio
complex: The Beaux Arts Trio was a noted piano trio, celebrated for their vivacity, emotional depth and wide-ranging repertoire. <s> They made their debut on 13 July 1955, at the Berkshire Music Festival, Lenox, Massachusetts, United States, known today as the Tanglewood Music Center. <s> Their final American concert was held at Tanglewood on 21 August 2008. <s> It was webcast live and archived on NPR Music. <s> Their final concert was in Lucerne, Switzerland on 6 September 2008. <s> The Beaux Arts Trio recorded the entire standard piano trio repertoire. <s> In 2005, the trio celebrated its 50th anniversary with two special CD issues, one featuring their most popular releases through their long years of recording (released by Philips Records), and the other an anniversary collection of new music (released by Warner Records). <s> Throughout its existence, the trio was held together by founding pianist Menahem Pressler.
simple: The Beaux Arts Trio was a famous piano trio. <s> The three musicians (a violinist, cellist and pianist first performed together in public on 13 July 1955 at the Berkshire Music Festival, known today as the Tanglewood Music Center. <s> Their last American concert was held at Tanglewood on 21 August 2008. <s> Their last concert was in Lucerne, Switzerland on 6 September 2008. <s> The Beaux Arts Trio made many recordings including all the well-known works for piano, violin and cello. <s> The pianist was Menahem Pressler during its whole existence.

title: Aberdeen, Washington
complex: Aberdeen is a city in Grays Harbor County, Washington, United States. <s> The population was 16,896 at the 2010 census. <s> The city is the economic center of Grays Harbor County, bordering the cities of Hoquiam and Cosmopolis. <s> Aberdeen is occasionally referred to as the "Gateway to the Olympic Peninsula". <s> Aberdeen was founded by Samuel Benn in 1884 and incorporated on May 12, 1890. <s> Although it became the largest and best-known city in Grays Harbor, Aberdeen lagged behind nearby Hoquiam and Cosmopolis in its early years.
simple: Aberdeen is a city in the American state of Washington. <s> Aberdeen is sometimes called the "Gateway to the Olympic Peninsula". <s> Aberdeen was founded by Samuel Benn in 1884.

title: Gonadarche
complex: Gonadarche refers to the earliest gonadal changes of puberty. <s> In response to pituitary gonadotropins, the ovaries in girls and the testes in boys begin to grow and increase the production of the sex steroids, especially estradiol and testosterone.
simple: Gonadarche refers to the first gonadal changes of puberty. <s> The ovaries in girls and the testes in boys begin to grow and increase the production of the sex steroids.

title: Richardson County, Nebraska
complex: Richardson County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 8,363. <s> Its county seat is Falls City. <s> The Nebraska Territory, including this county, was opened for settlement through the Kansas–Nebraska Act on May 30, 1854. <s> Richardson County was created that same year and reorganized in 1855 by the first territorial legislature. <s> It was named after William A. Richardson, a US Representative from the state of Illinois who had sponsored the Kansas-Nebraska Act; subsequently, in 1858, Richardson was appointed governor of the Nebraska Territory.
simple: Richardson County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 census, 8,363 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Falls City. <s> It was founded in 1855.

title: Currawong
complex: Currawongs are three species of medium-sized passerine birds belonging to the genus "Strepera" in the family Artamidae native to Australasia. <s> These are the grey currawong ("Strepera versicolor"), pied currawong ("S. graculina"), and black currawong ("S. fuliginosa").
simple: They form the genus Strepera, which belongs to the Artamidae family of birds. <s> There are three species of currawong.

title: Dress shirt
complex: In the UK, the term "dress shirt" is reserved for a particular type of formal shirt. <s> There are formal day shirts for wearing with morning dress, and the white dress shirts used as eveningwear.
simple: In England, this is a term for a shirt that is worn with a tuxedo.

title: Paul Koslo
complex: Paul Koslo (June 27, 1944 – January 9, 2019) was a German and Canadian actor. <s> Koslo died on January 9, 2019 from pancreatic cancer at the age of 74.
simple: Paul Koslo (June 27, 1944 – January 9, 2019) was a German-Canadian actor. <s> Koslo died on January 9, 2019 from pancreatic cancer at the age of 74.

title: Duke of Noailles
complex: The title of Duke of Noailles was a French peerage created in 1663 for Anne de Noailles, Count of Ayen. <s> Noailles is the name of a prominent French noble family, derived from the castle of Noailles in the territory of Ayen, between Brive and Turenne in Limousin, and claiming to date back to the 11th century. <s> The family did not obtain fame until the 16th century, when its head, Antoine de Noailles (1504–1562), became admiral of France and was ambassador in England during three important years (1553–1556), maintaining a gallant but unsuccessful rivalry with the Spanish ambassador, Simon Renard. <s> Henri de Noailles (1554–1623), son of Antoine, was a commander in the religious wars and was made comte d'Ayen by Henry IV of France in 1593.
simple: The title of Duke of Noailles was a French peerage created in 1663 for Anne de Noailles, Count of Ayen. <s> The title of Duke of Ayen was also given to the family. <s> Noailles is the name of a great French family, derived from the castle of Noailles in the territory of Ayen, between Brive and Turenne in the Limousin, and claiming to date back to the 11th century. <s> It did not obtain fame until the 16th century, when its head, Antoine de Noailles (1504–1562), became admiral of France and was ambassador in England during three important years, 1553–1556, maintaining a gallant but unsuccessful rivalry with the Spanish ambassador, Simon Renard. <s> Henri (1554–1623), son of Antoine, was a commander in the religious wars and was made Count of Ayen by Henry IV of France in 1593.

title: Karl Fritz Lauer
complex: Karl Fritz Lauer (11 April 1938 – 5 June 2018) was a Romanian-German agricultural scientist in phytopathology and herbology. <s> After relocation to West Germany in 1981. <s> He first worked as a scientist at the Botanical Institute of the University of Regensburg before taking over the management of the scientific field research for southern Germany for Rhône-Poulenc from 1983 to 1995.
simple: Karl Fritz Lauer (April 11, 1938 – June 5, 2018) was a Romanian-German Agricultural Scientist in Phytopathology and Herbology. <s> Lauer died in Leonberg, Baden-Württemberg, Germany on June 5, 2018 at the age of 80. <s> After relocation to the German Federal Republic in 1981 he first worked as a scientist at the Botanical Institute of the University of Regensburg before taking over the management of the scientific field research for southern Germany for Rhône-Poulenc from 1983 to 1995.

title: Saint-Nicolas, Pas-de-Calais
complex: Saint-Nicolas or Saint-Nicolas-lez-Arras is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Saint-Nicolas, Pas-de-Calais is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Plum pudding model
complex: The plum pudding model is one of several historical scientific models of the atom. <s> First proposed by J. J. Thomson in 1904 soon after the discovery of the electron, but before the discovery of the atomic nucleus, the model tried to explain two properties of atoms then known: that electrons are negatively-charged particles and that atoms have no net electric charge. <s> The plum pudding model has electrons surrounded by a volume of positive charge, like negatively-charged "plums" embedded in a positively-charged "pudding". <s> The plum pudding model usefully guided his student, Ernest Rutherford, to devise experiments to further explore the composition of atoms. <s> Also, Thomson's model (along with a similar Saturnian ring model for atomic electrons put forward in 1904 by Nagaoka after James Clerk Maxwell's model of Saturn's rings) were useful predecessors of the more correct solar-system-like Bohr model of the atom. <s> In 1909, Hans Geiger and Ernest Marsden conducted experiments with thin sheets of gold. <s> Their professor, Ernest Rutherford, expected to find results consistent with Thomson's atomic model. <s> It was not until 1911 that Rutherford correctly interpreted the experiment's results which implied the presence of a very small nucleus of positive charge at the center of gold atoms. <s> This led to the development of the Rutherford model of the atom.
simple: The plum pudding model was an early (and incorrect) 20th century model of an atom. <s> It was proposed by J.J. Thomson in 1904, after the discovery of the electron, but before the discovery of the atomic nucleus. <s> Basically, in 1909, not long after Thomson's model was proposed, Hans Geiger and Ernest Marsden made an experiment with thin sheets of gold, to test Thomson's model. <s> Their professor, Ernest Rutherford, expected the results to prove Thomson correct, but their results were extremely different to what they were expecting. <s> In 1911, Rutherford discovered that the positive charges come from tiny particles called protons, and that the protons were in a tiny center called the nucleus, and that the electrons were orbiting around the nucleus.

title: Northwest Division (NBA)
complex: The Northwest Division is one of the three divisions in the Western Conference of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> The division consists of five teams: the Denver Nuggets, the Minnesota Timberwolves, the Oklahoma City Thunder, the Portland Trail Blazers and the Utah Jazz.
simple: The Northwest Division is one of three divisions in the Western Conference of the National Basketball Association, along with the Pacific Division and the Southwest Division. <s> The five teams in this division are the Denver Nuggets, Minnesota Timberwolves, Oklahoma City Thunder, Portland Trail Blazers, and the Utah Jazz.

title: Michelangelo Antonioni
complex: Michelangelo Antonioni Cavaliere di Gran Croce OMRI ( , ] ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007), was an Italian film director, screenwriter, editor, and short story author. <s> He is best known for his "trilogy on modernity and its discontents" — "L'Avventura" (1960), "La Notte" (1961), and "L'Eclisse" (1962)—as well as the English-language films "Blowup" (1966) and "The Passenger" (1975). <s> His films have been described as "enigmatic and intricate mood pieces" that rejected action and plot in favor of contemplation, image, and design. <s> According to AllMovie, he "redefined the concept of narrative cinema" and challenged traditional approaches to storytelling, realism, and drama. <s> Antonioni died aged 94 on 30 July 2007 in Rome, the same day that another renowned film director, Ingmar Bergman, also died. <s> Antonioni lay in state at City Hall in Rome where a large screen showed black-and-white footage of him among his film sets and behind-the-scenes.
simple: Michelangelo Antonioni (29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007) was an Italian movie director and screenwriter. <s> His best known movie is "Blowup" made in 1966. <s> He died at the same day as Ingmar Bergman, another famous director.

title: Boydton, Virginia
complex: Boydton is a town in Mecklenburg County, Virginia, United States. <s> The population was 431 at the 2010 census. <s> It is the county seat of Mecklenburg County, and it is near Kerr Lake.
simple: Boydton is a town in the U.S. state of Virginia. <s> It is the county seat of Mecklenburg County.

title: Baroque (band)
complex: Baroque (stylized as BAROQUE and previously as baroque) is a Japanese rock band originally formed in 2001. <s> Originally signed to S'Cube, a sub-division of the independent record label Free-Will, the band later switched to the company's Firewall Division, with distribution handled by Sony Music Entertainment Japan. <s> After releasing two albums, along with a greatest hits compilation, several singles and home video releases, baroque disbanded in 2004. <s> Vocalist ryo and guitarist Kei then reformed their previous band Kannivalism in 2006, while Bansaku and Akira formed boogieman in 2007.
simple: Baroque (written as baroque) is a Japanese visual kei rock band. <s> Members Ryo (Vocals) Kei (Guitar) Bansaku (Bass) Akira(Guitar)

title: Ahmed Fagih
complex: Ahmed Ibrahim al-Fagih (Arabic: أحمد إبراهيم الفقيه "’áħmad 'Ibrāhīm al-faqīh") (December 28, 1942 – April 30, 2019) was a Libyan novelist, playwright, essayist, journalist and diplomat. <s> He began writing short stories at an early age publishing them in Libyan newspapers and magazines. <s> He gained recognition in 1965 when his first collection of short stories "There Is No Water in the Sea" (Arabic: البحر لا ماء فيه) won him the highest award sponsored by the Royal Commission of Fine Arts in Libya. <s> Fagih wrote more many books in of different genres, including short stories, novels, plays, essays, among them "Gazelles" (play), "Evening Visitor" (play), "Gardens of the Night Trilogy" (novels), "The Valley of Ashes" (novel), and his 12-volume epic novel "Maps of the Soul", which had its first three volumes translated into English and published by DARF Publishers in UK in 2014. <s> Fagih held several diplomatic posts representing Libya, in London, Athens, Bucharest and Cairo. <s> He lived and worked between Cairo and Tripoli. <s> Ahmed Fagih was born in 1942 in Mizda, a small oasis town south of Tripoli, where he entered school and studied until his teens before he migrated to Tripoli in 1957 to pursue more higher studies and begin his writing career. <s> Fagih travelled in 1962 to Egypt to study journalism with the help of a UNESCO sponsorship program, returning later to Tripoli to work as a journalist. <s> In 1965 he published his first collection of short stories titled "There Is No Water in the Sea" (Arabic: "البحر لا ماء فيه"), which won him the highest award sponsored by the Royal Commission of Fine Arts in Libya. <s> In the late 1960s he travelled to London to study drama and theatre until 1972. <s> After returning from Britain he was appointed the director of the National Institute of Music and Drama. <s> In 1972 Fagih became the editor of the influential cultural and literary newspaper "The Cultural Weekly" (Arabic: الاسبوع الثقافي "al-Usbūʻ al-thaqāfi"), which featured many new Libyan writers. <s> During this period he founded "The New Theatre "play and drama group through which he directed performed several plays. <s> Fagih became the head of the Department of Arts and Literature at the Libyan Ministry of Information and Culture and in 1978 was one of the founders of the Union of Libyan Writers and was elected as its first Secretary General, later travelling back to London to take a diplomatic position as the press counsellor at the Libyan Embassy in Britain, during his which he established the Arab Cultural Trust, which launched a cultural quarterly magazine named "Azure "becoming its editor-in-chief. <s> In 1983 he was awarded a Doctorate of Philosophy PhD from the Faculty of Arts of The University of Edinburgh submitting a thesis on 'The Libyan short story' He published his three part novel "Garden of The Night "in 1991, which won the best creative work of Beirut Book Fair. <s> In 2000 He edited an English anthology of 13 short stories by Libyan writers.

title: Jeffery Dench
complex: Jeffery Danny Dench (29 April 1928 – 27 March 2014) was an English actor, best known for his work with the Royal Shakespeare Company. <s> He was the older brother of actress Judi Dench. <s> On 27 March 2014 it was announced that Jeffery Dench had died. <s> Writing after his death, Sylvia Morris said: When not playing grotesque old men, he brought humour, warmth and integrity to his parts.
simple: Jeffery Dench (29 April 1928 – 27 March 2014) was an English actor. <s> He is best known for his work with the Royal Shakespeare Company. <s> He was the older brother of actress Judi Dench. <s> Dench died on 27 March 2014, aged 85.

title: Province of Seville
complex: The Province of Seville is a province of southern Spain, in the western part of the autonomous community of Andalusia. <s> It is bordered by the provinces of Málaga, Cádiz in the south, Huelva in the west, Badajoz in the north and Córdoba in the east. <s> Seville is the province's as well as the Andalusian autonomous community's capital. <s> The area of the province is 14,042 km2.
simple: Province of Seville is a province of the Autonomous Community of Andalusia, Spain. <s> Its capital is Seville.

title: Beersel
complex: Beersel (] ) is a municipality located in the Belgian province of Flemish Brabant. <s> The municipality comprises the towns of Alsemberg, Beersel proper, Dworp, Huizingen and Lot.
simple: Beersel is a municipality in the Belgian province of Flemish Brabant.

title: Monchiet
complex: Monchiet is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Monchiet is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Andrew Lang
complex: Andrew Lang (31 March 1844 – 20 July 1912 ) was a Scottish poet, novelist, literary critic, and contributor to the field of anthropology. <s> He is best known as a collector of folk and fairy tales. <s> The Andrew Lang lectures at the University of St Andrews are named after him.
simple: Andrew Lang (31 March 1844 – 20 July 1912) was a Scots poet, novelist, literary critic, and contributor to the field of anthropology. <s> He is best known as a collector of folk and fairy tales. <s> The Andrew Lang lectures at the University of St Andrews are named after him.

title: Chicagoland (TV series)
complex: Chicagoland is a documentary series that debuted its pilot episode at the 2014 Sundance Film Festival on January 19, 2014. <s> It was aired on CNN in eight successive weekly broadcasts beginning March 6, 2014, and ending April 24, 2014. <s> It is executive produced by Robert Redford and Laura Michalchyshyn and created by Mark Benjamin and Marc Levin. <s> During its production, the documentary received assistance from the office of Chicago mayor Rahm Emanuel.
simple: "Chicagoland" is a documentary series based in Chicago, Illinois. <s> Its pilot episode was premiered at the 2014 Sundance Film Festival on January 19. <s> It was aired on CNN on March 6, 2014. <s> The series ended on April 24, 2014. <s> It is produced by Robert Redford.

title: Grant (money)
complex: Grants are non-repayable funds or products disbursed or given by one party (grant makers), often a government department, corporation, foundation or trust, to a recipient, often (but not always) a nonprofit entity, educational institution, business or an individual. <s> In order to receive a grant, some form of "Grant Writing" often referred to as either a proposal or an application is required.
simple: Grants are non-repayable money or products awarded by one party (grant makers) to a recipient. <s> In order to receive a grant, either a proposal or an application is needed.

title: Marga Spiegel
complex: Marga Spiegel (21 June 1912 – 11 March 2014) was a German writer. <s> She was Jewish and survived the Holocaust of World War II. <s> Her story was published into a book in 1969 and a movie, "", released in 2009. <s> She was born in Oberaula, Hesse. <s> Spiegel wrote her most famous book, "Saviors in the Night" in 1960. <s> Unlike other books about the Holocaust, it told about German citizens who saved Spiegel from the concentration camps. <s> Although Spiegel's book became a best-seller, the story was not made into a film until decades later. <s> Spiegel died from natural causes on 11 March 2014 in Münster, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany. <s> She was 101 years old.
simple: Marga Spiegel (21 June 1912 – 11 March 2014) was a German writer. <s> She was Jewish and survived the Holocaust of World War II. <s> Her story was published into a book in 1969 and a movie, "Unter Bauern – Retter in der Nacht", released in 2009. <s> She was born in Oberaula, Hesse, German Empire. <s> Spiegel died from natural causes on 11 March 2014 in Münster, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany. <s> She was 101 years old.

title: Cheri Bustos
complex: Cheryl Lea Bustos (née Callahan; born October 17, 1961) is an American journalist, healthcare executive, and politician who has served as the U.S. Representative for Illinois's 17th congressional district since 2013. <s> A member of the Democratic Party, Bustos is the first woman elected to Congress from her district. <s> In 2019, Bustos assumed a leadership position among House Democrats as chair of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
simple: Cheryl Lea Bustos (née Callahan; born October 17, 1961) is an American journalist, healthcare executive, and politician. <s> Bustos has served as the U.S. Representative for Illinois's 17th congressional district since 2013. <s> She is a member of the Democratic Party. <s> Bustos is the first woman elected to Congress from her district.

title: Koshi Province
complex: Koshi Province (越国 , Koshi no Kuni ) was an ancient province or region of Japan in what is now the Hokuriku region. <s> The region as a whole was sometimes referred to as Esshū (越州 ) . <s> At the end of the 7th century, Koshi was divided into three separate provinces: Echizen, Etchū, and Echigo (as noted in the Taihō Code). <s> The names of these provinces mean 'Upper-Koshi' (Echizen), 'Middle-Koshi' (Etchu), and 'Lower-Koshi' (Echigo), respectively, indicating their relative positions with respect to the capital region (Kinki) at the time the Ritsuryō system was enacted.
simple: Koshi (越) was a very old province of Japan in the area of Niigata, Fukui and Toyama prefectures on the island of Honshū. <s> It was in what is now known as the Hokuriku region. <s> "Koshi" was divided into Echizen, Etchū, and Echigo provinces in the early 8th century.

title: Frigate
complex: A frigate is a type of warship, having various sizes and roles over the last few centuries. <s> The modern French Navy applies the term first-class frigate and second-class frigate to both destroyers and frigates in service. <s> Pennant numbers remain divided between F-series numbers for those ships internationally recognised as frigates and D-series pennant numbers for those more traditionally recognised as destroyers.
simple: A frigate (pronounced ) is a warship. <s> The term has been used for warships of many sizes and roles for a few centuries. <s> In the modern day the term "Frigate" covers a broad range of ships.

title: Dhankuta
complex: Dhankuta is a hill town and the headquarter of Koshi Zone located in Dhankuta District of Eastern Nepal. <s> According to 2011 Nepal census, it has population of 26,440 inhabitants.
simple: Dhankuta is a town in the hills of eastern Nepal.

title: Optare Alero
complex: The Optare Alero is a low-floor integral minibus that was built by Optare between 2001 and 2008. <s> It was built as an alternative to van-derived buses such as the Mercedes-Benz Sprinter. <s> Around 300 were built in the first five years of production. <s> The primary markets for the Alero have been community transport groups and rural demand responsive bus routes.
simple: The Optare Alero was a low-floor minibus that was built by Optare between 2001 and 2008. <s> Around 300 were built in the first five years of being built.

title: Petra Němcová
complex: Petra Němcová (] ; born 24 June 1979) is a Czech model, television host and philanthropist who founded the "Happy Hearts Fund". <s> In 2017, the "Happy Hearts Fund" merged with All Hands Volunteers to create All Hands And Hearts - Smart Response, with Němcová assuming the role of co-founder and vice chair. <s> Němcová was born in Karviná, then Czechoslovakia, now the Czech Republic, and grew up in Karviná in the Moravian-Silesian Region with her sister Olga. <s> In 2017, Petra was appointed by the UNISDR as a Disaster Risk Reduction Champion and Tsunami Awareness Advocate.
simple: Petra Němcová (]; born 24 June 1979) is a Czech model, television host and philanthropist. <s> She founded the "Happy Hearts Fund". <s> In 2017, the "Happy Hearts Fund" merged with All Hands Volunteers to create All Hands And Hearts - Smart Response, with Němcová having the role of co-founder and vice chair. <s> She was born in Karviná, Czechoslovakia. <s> In 2017, Petra was appointed by the UNISDR as a Disaster Risk Reduction Champion and Tsunami Awareness Advocate.

title: Horacio Cartes
complex: Horacio Manuel Cartes Jara OSC (born 5 July 1956) is a Paraguayan businessman and politician. <s> He was the president of Paraguay from 2013 to 2018. <s> He is a member of the Colorado Party. <s> Cartes owns about two dozen businesses in his Grupo Cartes conglomerate including tobacco, soft drinks, meat production, and banking. <s> He was president of Club Libertad football club from 2001 until 2012, and had been the president of the national team department of the Paraguayan Football Association during the 2010 FIFA World Cup qualification. <s> Cartes was the Colorado candidate in the 2013 presidential election. <s> The BBC suggested that his convincing points during his campaign were the promises to raise private capital to upgrade the country's infrastructure, to modernise its public enterprises, to attract international investments, and to create jobs. <s> On 21 April 2013, he was elected President of Paraguay with 45.80% of the vote. <s> When he took office on 15 August, it marked only the second time in the country's 202 years of independence that a ruling party peacefully surrendered power to the opposition.
simple: Horacio Manuel Cartes Jara (born 5 July 1956) is an Paraguayan politician. <s> He serves as President of Paraguay since 2013. <s> Horacio Cartes is the owner of ""Grupo Cartes"", a conglomerate of approximately two dozen of companies. <s> He has also been president of the football club Club Libertad since 2001 <s> Cartes won the 2013 presidential election in Paraguay on 21 April 2013 and took office as President on 15 August 2013.

title: Nufenen
complex: Nufenen (Italian: "Nufena", Romansh: "Nueinas") is a former municipality in the Viamala Region in the Swiss canton of Graubünden. <s> On 1 January 2019 the former municipalities of Hinterrhein, Nufenen and Splügen merged to form the new municipality of Rheinwald. <s> Before 2017, the municipality was located in the Rheinwald sub-district, of the Hinterrhein district, after 2017 it was part of the Viamala Region. <s> It is located on the San Bernardino tunnel road. <s> It consists of the "haufendorf" (an irregular, unplanned and quite closely packed village, built around a central square) of Nufenen.
simple: Nufenen is a former municipality of the district of Hinterrhein in the canton of Graubünden in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2019 the former municipalities of Hinterrhein, Nufenen and Splügen merged to form the new municipality of Rheinwald. <s> It is on the San Bernardino tunnel road.

title: Grigoriy Bronza
complex: Grigoriy Zakharovich Bronza ( ; 30 April 192730 January 2010) was a prominent artist of Transnistria (Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic). <s> He was an art restorer and an honorary member of the Transnistria Union of Artists. <s> Bronza was a designer of postage stamps of Transnistria and Moldova. <s> He also helped create a number of museums in the former Soviet Union. <s> During World War II, Grigoriy Bronza served in the Red Army and was awarded the following Soviet military decorations: Bronza is the author of the first stamps of Moldova issued in June 1991. <s> He designed the first stamps of the Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic issued in December 1993. <s> Bronza designed the third definitive stamp issue of Transnistria (1997). <s> He also created a series of stamps for the 5th anniversary of the events in Bendery (1997), a series of stamps "Historical and modern coats of arms of cities of Transnistria" (1999), the 200th anniversary of Alexander Pushkin issue (1999), etc.
simple: Grigoriy Zakharovich Bronza (30 April 192730 January 2010) was an artist of Transnistria (Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic). <s> He was an art restorer and an honorary member of the Transnistria Union of Artists. <s> Bronza was a designer of postage stamps of Transnistria and Moldova. <s> He also helped create a number of museums in the former Soviet Union. <s> During World War II, Grigoriy Bronza served in the Red Army and was awarded the following Soviet military decorations: Bronza is the author of the first stamps of Moldova issued in June 1991. <s> He designed the first stamps of the Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic issued in December 1993. <s> Bronza designed the third definitive stamp issue of Transnistria (1997). <s> He also created a series of stamps for the 5th anniversary of the events in Bender (1997), a series of stamps "Historical and modern coats of arms of cities of Transnistria" (1999), and the 200th anniversary of Alexander Pushkin issue (1999).

title: Ludwigslust-Parchim
complex: Ludwigslust-Parchim District was established by merging the former districts of Ludwigslust and Parchim as part of the local government reform of September 2011. <s> The name of the district was decided by referendum on 4 September 2011.
simple: Ludwigslust-Parchim Rural District was created by joining the districts of Ludwigslust Rural District and Parchim Rural District on September 4, 2011.

title: Giorgi Margvelashvili
complex: Giorgi Margvelashvili (Georgian: ; born 4 September 1969) is a Georgian academic and politician who was the fourth President of Georgia, in office from 17 November 2013 to 16 December 2018.
simple: Giorgi Margvelashvili (Georgian: ; born 4 September 1969) is a Georgian educator and politician. <s> He served as President of Georgia from 17 November 2013 to 16 December 2018.

title: Wii Party U
complex: Wii Party U (Japanese: Wiiパーティ・U , Hepburn: Wī Pāti Yū ) is a party video game developed and published by Nintendo for the Wii U in 2013. <s> It was announced in a January 2013 Nintendo Direct, and later detailed at E3 2013 and the October 2013 Nintendo Direct. <s> It is the sequel to the 2010 Wii game "Wii Party". <s> "Wii Party U" is a multiplayer video game consisting of a standard board game with mini-games, similar to "Mario Party". <s> Over 80 different new mini-games are available. <s> Multiple people can play mini-games using the Wii U GamePad. <s> Wii Party U also includes a new accessory, a stand for the Wii U GamePad to allow support for the tabletop games.
simple: Wii Party U is a party video game for the Wii U game console. <s> It is the sequel to "Wii Party". <s> "Wii Party U" is a party video game which takes elements from the "Mario Party" series. <s> It has over 80 minigames. <s> Players are able to play minigames with the Wii U GamePad.

title: Bryan Konietzko
complex: Bryan Joseph Konietzko (born June 1, 1975) is an American animation director, writer, producer and musician. <s> He is best known, together with Michael Dante DiMartino, as the co-creator and executive producer of the animated series "" and "The Legend of Korra". <s> Konietzko has worked as a character designer at Film Roman for "Family Guy" and as assistant director for the series "Mission Hill" and "King of the Hill". <s> He was a storyboard artist and art director for the Nickelodeon's animated series "Invader Zim".
simple: Bryan Konietzko (born June 1, 1975) is the co-creator and executive producer of the animated series "". <s> He has also worked as a character designer for the animated series "Family Guy". <s> He was a storyboard artist and art director for the Nickelodeon animated series "Invader Zim".

title: Mińsk Mazowiecki
complex: Mińsk Mazowiecki ""Masovian Minsk"" is a town in central Poland with 40,211 inhabitants (2015). <s> It is situated in the Masovian Voivodeship (since 1999), previously in Siedlce Voivodeship (1975–1998). <s> It is the capital of Mińsk County.
simple: Mińsk Mazowiecki (Minsk, miɲsk mazɔ'vi̯eʦki) is a town in Poland. <s> It is the capital of Mińsk County.

title: Arjun: The Warrior Prince
complex: Arjun: The Warrior Prince is a 2012 Indian animated action film. <s> The film is directed by Arnab Chaudhuri and produced by UTV Motion Pictures and Walt Disney Pictures. <s> The film was released in India on 25 May 2012. <s> Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures held a week-long limited engagement on 1 September 2012 at the El Capitan Theater to qualify for Academy Awards consideration.
simple: Arjun: The Warrior Prince is an Indian animated movie. <s> It is an action movie and was released on 25 May 2012 in India.

title: George H. Heilmeier
complex: George Harry Heilmeier (May 22, 1936 – April 21, 2014) was an American engineer, manager, and a pioneering contributor to liquid crystal displays (LCDs), for which he was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame. <s> Heilmeier's work is an IEEE Milestone. <s> Heilmeier was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, graduated from Abraham Lincoln High School there, received his BS in Electrical Engineering from the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia, and his M.S.E., M.A., and Ph.D. degrees in solid state materials and electronics from Princeton University. <s> Heilmeier had received numerous awards, held 15 patents, and was a member of the National Academy of Engineering, the Defense Science Board, and the National Security Agency Advisory Board. <s> He served on the board of trustees of Fidelity Investments and of Teletech Holdings, and the Board of Overseers of the School of Engineering and Applied Science of the University of Pennsylvania. <s> He died of a stroke in 2014.
simple: George Harry Heilmeier (May 22, 1936 – April 22, 2014) was an American engineer and businessman. <s> He was best known for his work on the liquid crystal displays. <s> He was added in the National Inventors Hall of Fame. <s> He invented the LC-Display and his work is an IEEE Milestone. <s> He was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. <s> Heilmeier died on April 22, 2014 at the age of 77.

title: Arena da Baixada
complex: Arena Joaquim Américo Guimarães is the home stadium of Club Athletico Paranaense. <s> It is located in Curitiba, the state capital of Paraná, Brazil. <s> Known as Arena da Baixada, the football stadium was the first in Brazil to sell its naming rights. <s> It was known as "Kyocera Arena" between 2005 and 1 April 2008. <s> Additionally, the stadium is perhaps best known for being the first retractable roof stadium in South America. <s> With Curitiba selected as one of the host cities of World Cup 2014, the arena between 2012 and 2014 was rebuilt. <s> Its capacity was expanded to 42,372 seats. <s> The stadium was built at the previous location of a Brazilian Army powder depot. <s> In 1934, the stadium was renamed Estádio Joaquim Américo Guimarães. <s> In the 1970s, the original stadium was closed down. <s> After being reopened in 1984 and operating for some years, the old stadium building was demolished on March 26, 1997, right after a construction project of a new arena was announced. <s> In June 1999, the new stadium was built. <s> In 2005, the stadium was renamed "Kyocera Arena", after the Japanese company Kyocera purchased the naming rights. <s> The inaugural match of the old stadium was played on 6 September 1914, when Flamengo beat Internacional 7–1. <s> The first goal of the stadium was scored by Flamengo's Arnaldo. <s> The inaugural match of the new building was played on 24 June 1999, when Athletico Paranaense beat Cerro Porteño of Paraguay 2–1. <s> The first goal of the stadium after its reinauguration was scored by Athletico's Lucas. <s> The stadium's attendance record currently stands at 40.263, set on 12 December 2018 when Athletico defeated Junior Barranquilla on penalties, for the 2018 Sudamericana championship. <s> Although the stadium was not the venue of the 1950 FIFA World Cup, the Estádio Vila Capanema was the venue for Curitiba as a host city of the event. <s> The contract with Kyocera that gave the company naming rights expired in early 2008. <s> It was not renewed, and no new partnership was announced. <s> The stadium went back to its old name, "Arena da Baixada".
simple: It was named Kyocera Arena for a short period of time (beginning 2005 until April 1, 2008). <s> The stadium was built at the previous location of a Brazilian Army powder depot. <s> In 1934, the stadium was renamed Estádio Joaquim Américo Guimarães. <s> In the 1970s, the original stadium was closed down. <s> After being reopened in 1984 and operating for some years, the old stadium building was demolished on March 26, 1997, right after a construction project of a new arena was announced. <s> In June 1999, the new stadium was built. <s> In 2005, the stadium was renamed "Kyocera Arena", after the Japanese company Kyocera purchased the naming rights. <s> The inaugural match of the old stadium was played on September 6, 1914, when Flamengo beat Internacional 7–1. <s> The first goal of the stadium was scored by Flamengo's Arnaldo. <s> The inaugural match of the new building was played on June 24, 1999, when Atlético Paranaense beat Cerro Porteño of Paraguay 2–1. <s> The first goal of the stadium after its reinauguration was scored by Atlético's Lucas. <s> The stadium's attendance record currently stands at 31,740. <s> The contract with Kyocera that gave the company naming rights expired in early 2008. <s> It was not renewed, and no new partnership was announced. <s> The stadium went back to its old name, "Arena da Baixada".

title: Prokopis Pavlopoulos
complex: Prokopios Pavlopoulos ( , ] ; born 10 July 1950), commonly shortened to Prokopis (Προκόπης), is a Greek lawyer, university professor and politician serving as President of the Hellenic Republic since 2015. <s> A member of New Democracy, he previously was Minister of the Interior from 2004 to 2009.
simple: Prokopios Pavlopoulos, (, ], born 10 July 1950), commonly shortened to Prokopis (Προκόπης), is the President of Greece, in office since 2015. <s> Pavlopoulos was a lawyer, university professor and politician, he was Minister for the Interior from 2004 to 2009.

title: Minter City, Mississippi
complex: Minter City is an unincorporated community located in Leflore County and in Tallahatchie County, Mississippi. <s> It is part of the Greenwood, Mississippi micropolitan area, and is within the Mississippi Delta.
simple: Minter City is an unincorporated community located in Leflore County and in Tallahatchie County, Mississippi. <s> It is part of the Greenwood, Mississippi micropolitan area, and is within the Mississippi Delta.

title: Ray Romano
complex: Raymond Albert Romano (born December 21, 1957) is an American stand-up comedian, actor and screenwriter. <s> He is best known for his role on the sitcom "Everybody Loves Raymond", for which he received an Emmy Award, and as the voice of Manny in the "Ice Age" film series. <s> He created and starred in the TNT comedy-drama "Men of a Certain Age" (2009–11).
simple: Ray Romano (born December 21, 1957) is an American stand-up comedian, actor and screenwriter. <s> He is best known as the star of the television series "Everybody Loves Raymond".

title: Zonnebeke
complex: Zonnebeke is a municipality located in the Belgian province of West Flanders. <s> The municipality comprises the villages of , , Passendale, Zandvoorde and Zonnebeke proper.
simple: Zonnebeke is a municipality in the Belgian province of West Flanders.

title: Aten
complex: Aten (also Aton, ) is the disc of the sun in ancient Egyptian mythology, and originally an aspect of the god Ra. <s> The deified Aten is the focus of the monotheistic religion of Atenism established by Amenhotep IV, who later took the name Akhenaten (died ca. 1335 BCE) in worship and recognition of Aten. <s> In his poem "Great Hymn to the Aten", Akhenaten praises Aten as the creator, giver of life, and nurturing spirit of the world. <s> Aten does not have a Creation Myth or family but is mentioned in the Book of the Dead. <s> The worship of Aten was eradicated by Horemheb.
simple: Aten is the disk of the Sun in ancient Egyptian mythology, and an aspect of the Sun-god Ra. <s> The deified Aten is the focus of the monotheistic religion of Atenism established by Amenhotep IV, who later took the name Akhenaten in worship and recognition of the Aten. <s> In his poem "Great Hymn to the Aten", Akhenaten praises Aten as the creator, and giver of life. <s> The worship of Aten was eradicated by Horemheb.

title: Roberts County, South Dakota
complex: Roberts County is a county in the U.S. state of South Dakota. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 10,149. <s> Its county seat is Sisseton. <s> The county was named either for S. G. Roberts of Fargo, North Dakota, or for Solomon Robar, an early local French fur trader. <s> It was created on March 8, 1883, and was fully organized by August 6 of that year. <s> Its boundary was altered one time, in 1885.
simple: Roberts County is a county located in the U.S. state of South Dakota. <s> As of the 2010 census, 10,149 people lived there. <s> Its county seat is Sisseton. <s> It was created in 1883.

title: Armand Gatti
complex: Armand Gatti (] ; 26 January 1924 – 6 April 2017) was a French playwright, poet, journalist, screenwriter, filmmaker and World War II resistance fighter. <s> His debut film "Enclosure" was entered into the 2nd Moscow International Film Festival where he won the Silver Prize for Best Director. <s> Two years later, his film "El Otro Cristóbal" was entered into the 1963 Cannes Film Festival. <s> In 2013 he was awarded the Grand prix du théâtre de l'Académie française. <s> He died on 6 April 2017.
simple: Armand Gatti (]; January 26, 1924 – April 6, 2017) was a Monegasque-born French playwright, poet, journalist, screenwriter, filmmaker and World War II resistance fighter. <s> Gatti's first movie, "Enclosure", was entered into the 2nd Moscow International Film Festival where he won the Silver Prize for Best Director. <s> Two years later, his movie "El Otro Cristóbal" was entered into the 1963 Cannes Film Festival. <s> In 2013 he was awarded the Grand prix du théâtre de l'Académie française. <s> Gatti died on April 6, 2017 in Saint-Mandé, France, aged 93.

title: U-Turn (song)
complex: "U-Turn" is a song by Usher, released as the fourth international single from his 2001 album "8701". <s> The song was a dance track produced by Jermaine Dupri and was a departure from the previous two smooth ballad singles that had been released from the album. <s> The track reached the top 10 in Australia, the top 20 in the UK and Switzerland and was a top 40 hit in the Netherlands. <s> The single was not released in the US. <s> The song was written by Usher, Dupri and Brian Michael Cox who co-wrote four songs on the album including hit single "U Got It Bad". <s> The song also references Michael Jackson and Bobby Brown and also refers to the crunk style of rap making it one of the first mainstream R&B tracks to refer to that style. <s> UK CD "Limited Edition Enhanced 4 Track CD with Poster"
simple: "U-Turn" is a song by American singer Usher. <s> It was released from his album "8701" (2001). <s> It was released as an international single. <s> It was produced by Jermaine Dupri. <s> The song reached the top ten in Australia, top 20 in the UK and Switzerland. <s> It was a top 40 hit in the Netherlands. <s> The song was written by Usher, Dupri, and Brian Michael Cox. <s> Cox had co-wrote four of Usher's songs, including hit single "U Got It Bad". <s> The song mentions Michael Jackson and Bobby Brown. <s> It also talks about crunk. <s> UK CD "Limited Edition Enhanced 4 Track CD with Poster"

title: Sideshow
complex: In North America, a sideshow is an extra, secondary production associated with a circus, carnival, fair, or other such attraction.
simple: A sideshow is an amusement or entertainment usually associated with circus and carnival midways.

title: Division of Cowan
complex: The Division of Cowan is an Australian Electoral Division in Western Australia. <s> The division was created in 1984 and is named for Edith Cowan, the first woman elected to an Australian Parliament. <s> It is located in the northern suburbs of Perth, including the suburbs of Girrawheen, Greenwood, Landsdale and Marangaroo. <s> It is a marginal seat, changing hands between the Australian Labor Party and the Liberal Party.
simple: The Division of Cowan is an Australian Electoral Division in Western Australia. <s> It was created in 1984 and is named for Edith Cowan, the first woman elected to an Australian Parliament. <s> It covers the northern suburbs of Perth, including Girrawheen, Greenwood, Kingsley, Landsdale, Woodvale and Marangaroo.

title: Fontenais
complex: Fontenais is a municipality in the district of Porrentruy in the canton of Jura in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2013 the former municipality of Bressaucourt merged into the municipality of Fontenais.
simple: Fontenais is a municipality of the district of Porrentruy in the canton of Jura in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2013 the former municipality of Bressaucourt merged into the municipality of Fontenais.

title: Strait of Tartary
complex: Strait of Tartary or Gulf of Tartary ( ; ; ; ) is a strait in the Pacific Ocean dividing the Russian island of Sakhalin from mainland Asia (South-East Russia), connecting the Sea of Okhotsk on the north with the Sea of Japan on the south. <s> It is 900 km long, 4–20 m (13-66 ft) deep, and 7.3 km wide at the narrowest point. <s> Since 1973, Vanino-Kholmsk train ferry operates across the strait, connecting the port of Vanino, Khabarovsk Krai on the mainland with Kholmsk on Sakhalin Island.
simple: Strait of Tartary (Gulf of Tartary, Gulf of Tatary, Tatar Strait, Tartar Strait, Strait of Tartar) is a strait in the Pacific Ocean. <s> It divides the Russian island of Sakhalin from mainland Asia. <s> It connects the Sea of Okhotsk on the north with the Sea of Japan on the south. <s> It is 900 km long, 4–20 m deep, and 7.3 km wide at the narrowest point. <s> Since 1973, a rail ferry goes across the strait. <s> It connects the port of Vanino, Khabarovsk Krai on the mainland with Kholmsk on Sakhalin Island.

title: Toni Preckwinkle
complex: Toni Lynn Preckwinkle (née Reed; born March 17, 1947) is an American politician and the current Cook County Board President in Cook County, Illinois, United States. <s> She was first elected in November 2010 as President of the Cook County Board, the executive branch of Cook County government, and became the first woman elected to this position. <s> She was previously a five-term alderman in the Chicago City Council, representing Chicago's 4th ward. <s> In September 2018, Preckwinkle announced her candidacy for Mayor of Chicago to succeed Rahm Emanuel in the 2019 election. <s> She, along with Lori Lightfoot, advanced to the runoff election on April 2. <s> She was defeated in the April 2 election by Lightfoot. <s> Despite this, Preckwinkle will seek re-election as President of the Cook County Board.
simple: Toni Preckwinkle (née Reed; March 17, 1947) is an American politician. <s> She was elected on November 2, 2010, as President of the Cook County Board, the Executive Branch of Cook County government. <s> She is the current Cook County Board President and a former alderman in the Chicago City Council representing Chicago's 4th ward in Cook County, Illinois, United States. <s> On September 20, 2018, Preckwinkle announced her candidacy for Mayor of Chicago in the 2019 election to replace Rahm Emanuel. <s> She advanced to the runoff election on April 2. <s> She was defeated by Lightfoot by nearly 50%.

title: Marugame, Kagawa
complex: Marugame (丸亀市 , Marugame-shi ) is a city located in Kagawa Prefecture, Japan. <s> Since 1947, the city has played host to an annual road running competition: the Marugame Half Marathon. <s> Occurring in early February, the race attracts thousands of runners each year. <s> The Asian record in the half marathon was set on the course by Kayoko Fukushi in 2006. <s> Marugame was founded in April, 1899 during the Meiji era. <s> Marugame was the 53rd city to be given a city code in Japan.
simple: Marugame (丸亀市, Marugame-shi) is a Japanese city in Kagawa Prefecture on the island of Shikoku. <s> Since 1947, the city has hosted to an annual road running competition: the Marugame Half Marathon. <s> The modern city was established in 1899.

title: Trinity County, California
complex: Trinity County is a county in the northwestern part of the state of California. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 13,786, making it the fourth least-populous county in California. <s> The county seat and largest community is Weaverville. <s> The county takes its name from the Trinity River, named in 1845 by Major Pierson B. Reading, who was under the mistaken impression that the river emptied into Trinidad Bay. <s> "Trinity" is the English translation of Trinidad. <s> Trinity County was one of the original counties of California, created in 1850 at the time of statehood. <s> Parts of the county were given to Klamath County in 1852 and to Humboldt County in 1853.
simple: Trinity County is a county in the northwestern part of the U.S. state of California. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 13,786, making it the fourth least-populous county in California. <s> The county seat and largest community is Weaverville. <s> The county takes its name from the Trinity River. <s> Trinity County was founded in 1850.

title: Grunerite
complex: Grunerite is a mineral of the amphibole group of minerals with formula FeSiO(OH). <s> It is the iron endmember of the grunerite-cummingtonite series.
simple: It has the chemical formula FeSiO(OH).

title: Évora
complex: Évora ( , ] ; ) is a city and a municipality in Portugal. <s> The population in 2011 was 56,596, in an area of 1307.08 km2. <s> It is the seat of the Évora District. <s> The present Mayor is Carlos Pinto de Sá of the CDU coalition.
simple: Évora is a city in Portugal. <s> It has 56,596 people. <s> It is the seat of the Évora District.

title: Keble College, Oxford
complex: Keble College is one of the constituent colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> Its main buildings are on Parks Road, opposite the University Museum and the University Parks. <s> The college is bordered to the north by Keble Road, to the south by Museum Road, and to the west by Blackhall Road. <s> Keble was established in 1870, having been built as a monument to John Keble, who had been a leading member of the Oxford Movement which sought to stress the Catholic nature of the Church of England. <s> Consequently, the college's original teaching focus was primarily theological, although the college now offers a broad range of subjects, reflecting the diversity of degrees offered across the wider university. <s> In the period after the Second World War the trends were towards scientific courses (proximity to the university science area east of the University Museum influenced this). <s> As originally constituted, it was for men only and the fellows were mostly bachelors resident in the college. <s> Like many of Oxford's men's colleges, Keble admitted its first mixed-sex cohort in 1979. <s> It remains distinctive for its still-controversial neo-gothic red-brick buildings designed by William Butterfield. <s> The buildings are also notable for breaking from Oxbridge tradition by arranging rooms along corridors rather than around staircases, in order that the scouts could supervise the comings and goings of visitors. <s> (Girton College, Cambridge, similarly breaks this tradition.) <s> Keble is one of the larger colleges of the University of Oxford, with 433 undergraduates and 245 graduate students in 2011/12. <s> Keble's sister college at the University of Cambridge is Selwyn College.
simple: Keble College is one of the colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> Its main buildings are on Parks Road, opposite the University Museum and the University Parks. <s> Keble was founded in 1870, having been built as a monument to John Keble, a leading member of the Oxford Movement. <s> In the period after the second World War the trends were towards scientific courses (the major area devoted to science east of the University Museum influenced this) and eventually co-education for men and women from 1979 onwards. <s> As originally constituted it was for men only and the fellows were mostly bachelors resident in the college. <s> It remains distinctive for its once-controversial neo-gothic red-brick buildings designed by William Butterfield. <s> Keble is one of the larger colleges, with 435 undergraduates and 245 graduate students.

title: Read my lips: no new taxes
complex: "Read my lips: no new taxes" is a phrase spoken by then-American presidential candidate George H. W. Bush at the 1988 Republican National Convention as he accepted the nomination on August 18. <s> Written by speechwriter Peggy Noonan, the line was the most prominent sound bite from the speech. <s> The pledge not to tax the American people further had been a consistent part of Bush's 1988 election platform, and its prominent inclusion in his speech cemented it in the public consciousness. <s> The impact of the election promise was considerable, and many supporters of Bush believe it helped Bush win the 1988 presidential election. <s> The passage was written by leading speechwriter Peggy Noonan, with Jack Kemp having suggested the basic idea.
simple: "Read my lips: no new taxes" is a phrase spoken by then-American presidential candidate George H. W. Bush at the 1988 Republican National Convention as he accepted the nomination on August 18. <s> It was written by speechwriter Peggy Noonan. <s> The statement was a promise not to tax the American people further. <s> The impact of the election promise was considerable, and many supporters of Bush believe it helped him win the 1988 presidential election.

title: Jönköping Concert Hall
complex: The Jönköping Concert Hall is a concert hall in Jönköping, Sweden. <s> It was opened in September 1990. <s> There are two halls, the Hammaskjöld Hall and the Rydberg Hall .
simple: The Jönköping Concert Hall is a concert hall in the town of Jönköping in Sweden. <s> It was opened in September 1990. <s> There are two halls. <s> They are the Hammaskjöld Hall and the Rydberg Hall .

title: Paul Mebus
complex: Paul Mebus (9 June 1920 – 11 December 1993) was a German footballer. <s> He was part of the West German team that won the 1954 FIFA World Cup. <s> He earned six caps for West Germany and played twice for the German 'B-team'. <s> During his club career he played for VfL 06 Benrath and 1.
simple: Paul Mebus (9 June 1920 - 12 December 1993) was a German football player. <s> He played for West Germany national team.

title: Grant County, Arkansas
complex: Grant County is a county in the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> Its population was 17,853 at the 2010 United States Census. <s> The county seat is Sheridan. <s> Formed on February 4, 1869, Grant County is named for former U.S. President Ulysses S. Grant. <s> It is an alcohol prohibition or dry county.
simple: Grant County is a county of the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> 17,853 people lived there at the 2010 census. <s> The county seat is Sheridan. <s> It was founded on February 4, 1869.

title: Grandpa Never Lies
complex: Grandpa Never Lies is a children's book written by Ralph Fletcher and illustrated by Harvey Stevenson. <s> It was first published in 2000. <s> A young girl describes her special relationship with her grandfather over four seasons. <s> The Grandfather tells imaginative tales in response to her questions. <s> Each tale is followed by her refrain of "And Grandpa never lies, so I know it's so". <s> Then Grandma suddenly dies and the little girl and her grandfather mourn together.
simple: Grandpa Never Lies is a children's book written by Ralph Fletcher with pictures drawn by Harvey Stevenson. <s> It was first published in 2000. <s> A young girl describes her special bond with her grandfather over four seasons. <s> The Grandfather tells creative stories in answer to her questions. <s> Each story is followed by her saying "And Grandpa never lies, so I know it's so". <s> Then Grandma suddenly dies and the little girl and her grandfather are sad and comfort each other.

title: Vulvar cancer
complex: Vulvar cancer is a cancer of the vulva, the outer portion of the female genitals. <s> It most commonly affects the outer vaginal lips.
simple: Vulvar cancer is a disease in which cells in the body grow out of control in or on the vulva. <s> The vulva is the outer part of the female genital organs. <s> Vulvar cancer most often occurs on the inner edges of the labia. <s> When vulvar cancers are found early, treatment works best.

title: Family history (medicine)
complex: In medicine, a family history (FH or FHx) consists of information about disorders from which the direct blood relatives of the patient have suffered. <s> Genealogy typically includes very little of the medical history of the family, but the medical history could be considered a specific subset of the total history of a family. <s> Accurate knowledge of a patient's family history may identify a predisposition to developing certain illnesses, which can inform clinical decisions and allow effective management or even prevention of conditions. <s> Although sometimes neglected, many healthcare professionals glean information on family morbidity of particular diseases (e.g. cardiovascular diseases, autoimmune disorders, mental disorders, diabetes, cancer) to assess whether a person is at risk of developing similar problems. <s> Some medical conditions are carried only by the female line such as X-linked conditions and some Mitochondrial diseases. <s> Tracing female ancestors can be difficult in societies that change the woman's family name when she marries.
simple: In medicine, family history means information on medical disorders the direct blood relatives of a patient may have had. <s> Many healthcare professionals look at the information on family medical problems, such as autism, diabetes, mental illness, autoimmune diseases, cancer. <s> Many medical conditions are carried only by the female line, including X-linked conditions. <s> Others are carried by the male line, including Y-linked conditions.

title: Hidden Hills, California
complex: Hidden Hills is a city and gated community in Los Angeles County, California. <s> It is located next to the city of Calabasas and is located in the west San Fernando Valley. <s> It is notable for being home to many actors and celebrities. <s> The 2010 United States Census reported that Hidden Hills had a population of 1,856. <s> The population density was 1,099.1 people per square mile (424.4/km2).
simple: Hidden Hills is a city in Los Angeles County, California, United States, and a gated community. <s> It is in the San Fernando Valley region. <s> The population was 1,856 at the 2010 census.

title: Loki (comics)
