complex: Loki is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. <s> Created by writer Stan Lee, scripter Larry Lieber and penciller Jack Kirby, a version of the character first appeared in "Venus" #6 (August 1949). <s> The modern day incarnation of Loki first appeared in "Journey into Mystery" #85 (October 1962). <s> The character, which is based on the Norse deity of the same name, is the Asgardian god of mischief. <s> He is the adopted brother and often enemy of the superhero Thor, however over the years the character has been depicted as an antihero. <s> In 2009, Loki was ranked as IGN's 8th Greatest Comic Book Villain of All Time and in 2014 was ranked again by IGN, this time as the 4th Greatest Comic Book Villain of All Time. <s> Tom Hiddleston portrays the character in the Marvel Cinematic Universe films "Thor" (2011), "The Avengers" (2012), "" (2013), "" (2017), "" (2018), and "" (2019). <s> Hiddleston will return to portray the role in the Disney+ upcoming series "Loki" (2021).
simple: Loki is a fictional villain who appears in comic books by Marvel Comics. <s> The character first appeared historically in "Venus" No. 6 (August 1949). <s> The character was created by Stan Lee, Larry Lieber and Jack Kirby. <s> He is based on the god Loki from Norse mythology. <s> Loki is the brother and enemy of Thor. <s> In the Marvel Cinematic Universe, Loki is featured in the movies "Thor", "The Avengers" and "". <s> The character Loki is played by Tom Hiddleston.

title: Marco Streller
complex: Marco Streller (born 18 June 1981) is a Swiss former footballer who played as a striker and is best known for his years with FC Basel and the Switzerland national team. <s> He is the sporting director of FC Basel.
simple: Marco Streller (born 18 June 1981) is a Swiss football player. <s> He plays for Basel and Switzerland national team.

title: Carmen Silvera
complex: Carmen Dorothy Blanche Silvera (2 June 1922 – 3 August 2002) was a British comic actress. <s> Born in Canada of Spanish descent, she moved to Coventry, England, with her family when she was a child. <s> She appeared on television regularly in the 1960s, and achieved mainstream fame in the 1980s with her starring role in the British television programme, "'Allo 'Allo!" <s> Silvera first made her name as a television actress in the 1960s British police drama "Z-Cars" in 1962, going on to appear as Camilla Hope in the BBC soap opera "Compact" from 1964 to 1965. <s> She played Mrs Van Schuyler in "Lillie" in 1978, ITV's drama series about the future Edward VII's mistress, Lillie Langtry. <s> In Coventry in 1949, Silvera married John Cunliffe, an actor (not the John Cunliffe who wrote Postman Pat) she had met at repertory theatre in Tonbridge, Kent in 1941. <s> She divorced following a miscarriage and never remarried. <s> A heavy smoker, she died after a battle with lung cancer on 3 August 2002, aged 80, at the Denville Hall retirement home for actors.
simple: Carmen Silvera (3 June 1922 – 3 August 2002) was a Canadian-born British comic actress. <s> She played Camilla Hope in the soap opera "Compact". <s> She also played Mrs. Van Schuyler in Lillie in 1978. <s> She died from lung cancer at age 80 in England.

title: Arlöv
complex: Arlöv (] ) is the seat of Burlöv Municipality, Skåne County, Sweden. <s> It is statistically not defined as a locality of its own, but forms part of the contiguous city of Malmö, 5 km northeast of downtown Malmö.
simple: Arlöv is a place in the county of Skåne in Sweden. <s> It is the seat of Burlöv Municipality.

title: Dax, Landes
complex: Dax (] ; "Dacs" in Occitan) is a commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in southwestern France, sub-prefecture of the Landes department. <s> It is known as a spa, specialising in mud treatment for rheumatism and similar ailments. <s> It was first established by the Romans, and its reputation is supposed to date from a visit by Julia, the daughter of the first Emperor Octavian Augustus. <s> Its Roman name was "Civitas Aquensium". <s> In the Middle Ages, it was administered by viscounts until 1177. <s> With the acquisition of Aquitaine by Henry II Plantagenet, later King of England, Dax remained under English rule until 1451, when it was conquered by French troops before the end of the Hundred Years' War. <s> It successfully withstood a Spanish siege in 1521-1522.
simple: Dax ("Dacs" in Gascon) is a commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in south-western France, sub-prefecture of the Landes department. <s> It is well-known spa town, specialising in mud treatment for rheumatism and similar medical problems. <s> Dax was first established by the Romans, and its name was "Civitas Aquensium". <s> In the Middle Ages, it was administered by viscounts until 1177. <s> when Henry II Plantagenet, later King of England, got the Aquitaine. <s> Dax remained under the English rule until 1451, when it was conquered by the French troops before the end of the Hundred Years' War.

title: Polymorphism (biology)
complex: In biology and zoology, polymorphism is the occurrence of two or more clearly different morphs or forms, also referred to as alternative "phenotypes", in the population of a species. <s> To be classified as such, morphs must occupy the same habitat at the same time and belong to a panmictic population (one with random mating). <s> Put simply, polymorphism is when there are two or more possibilities of a trait on a gene. <s> For example, there is more than one possible trait in terms of a jaguar's skin colouring; they can have light-morph or dark-morph colouring. <s> Due to having more than one possible variation for this gene, it is termed 'polymorphism'. <s> However, if the jaguar has only one possible trait for that gene, it would be termed "monomorphic". <s> For example, if there was only one possible skin colour that a jaguar could have, it would be termed monomorphic. <s> Polymorphism is common in nature; it is related to biodiversity, genetic variation, and adaptation. <s> Polymorphism usually functions to retain variety of form in a population living in a varied environment. <s> The most common example is sexual dimorphism, which occurs in many organisms. <s> Other examples are mimetic forms of butterflies (see mimicry), and human hemoglobin and blood types. <s> The definition has three parts: a) sympatry: one interbreeding population; b) discrete forms; and c) not maintained just by mutation. <s> Genetic polymorphism is actively and steadily maintained in populations by natural selection, in contrast to "transient polymorphisms" where a form is progressively replaced by another. <s> By definition, genetic polymorphism relates to a balance or equilibrium between morphs. <s> The mechanisms that conserve it are types of balancing selection. <s> The mechanism which decides which of several morphs an individual displays is called the "switch". <s> This switch may be genetic, or it may be environmental. <s> Taking sex determination as the example, in humans the determination is genetic, by the XY sex-determination system. <s> In Hymenoptera (ants, bees and wasps), sex determination is by haplo-diploidy: the females are all diploid, the males are haploid. <s> However, in some animals an environmental trigger determines the sex: alligators are a famous case in point. <s> In ants the distinction between workers and guards is environmental, by the feeding of the grubs. <s> Polymorphism with an environmental trigger is called polyphenism. <s> The polyphenic system does have a degree of environmental flexibility not present in the genetic polymorphism. <s> However, such environmental triggers are the less common of the two methods. <s> Sickle-cell anaemia is found mostly in tropical populations in Africa and India. <s> An individual homozygous for the recessive sickle hemoglobin, HgbS, has a short expectancy of life, whereas the life expectancy of the standard hemoglobin (HgbA) homozygote and also the heterozygote is normal (though heterozygote individuals will suffer periodic problems). <s> The sickle-cell variant survives in the population because the heterozygote is resistant to malaria and the malarial parasite kills a huge number of people each year. <s> This is balancing selection or genetic polymorphism, balanced between fierce selection against homozygous sickle-cell sufferers, and selection against the standard HgbA homozygotes by malaria. <s> The heterozygote has a permanent advantage (a higher fitness) so long as malaria exists; and it has existed as a human parasite for a long time. <s> Because the heterozygote survives, so does the HgbS allele survive at a rate much higher than the mutation rate. <s> Ants exhibit a range of polymorphisms. <s> First, there is their characteristic haplodiploid sex determination system, whereby all males are haploid, and all females diploid. <s> Second, there is differentiation between both the females and males based mostly on feeding of larvae, which determines, for example, whether the imago is capable of reproduction. <s> Lastly, there is differentiation of size and 'duties' (particularly of females), which are usually controlled by feeding and/or age, but which may sometimes be genetically controlled. <s> Thus the order exhibits both genetic polymorphism and extensive polyphenism. <s> An example of a botanical genetic polymorphism is heterostyly, in which flowers occur in different forms with different arrangements of the pistils and the stamens. <s> The system is called heteromorphic self-incompatibility, and the general 'strategy' of stamens separated from pistils is known as herkogamy. <s> Pin and thrum heterostyly occurs in dimorphic species of "Primula", such as "P. vulgaris". <s> There are two types of flower. <s> The "pin" flower has a long style bearing the stigma at the mouth and the stamens halfway down; and the "thrum" flower has a short style, so the stigma is halfway up the tube and the stamens are at the mouth. <s> So when an insect in search of nectar inserts its proboscis into a long-style flower, the pollen from the stamens stick to the proboscis in exactly the part that will later touch the stigma of the short-styled flower, and vice versa. <s> Another most important property of the heterostyly system is physiological. <s> If thrum pollen is placed on a thrum stigma, or pin pollen on a pin stigma, the reproductive cells are incompatible and relatively little seed is set. <s> Effectively, this ensures out-crossing, as described by Darwin. <s> Quite a lot is now known about the underlying genetics; the system is controlled by a set of closely linked genes which act as a single unit, a super-gene. <s> All sections of the genus "Primula" have heterostyle species, altogether 354 species out of 419. <s> Since heterostyly is characteristic of nearly all races or species, the system is at least as old as the genus. <s> Between 1861 and 1863, Darwin found the same kind of structure in other groups: flax (and other species of "Linum"); and in purple loosestrife and other species of "Lythrum". <s> Some of the "Lythrum" species are trimorphic, with one style and two stamens in each form. <s> Heterostyly is known in at least 51 genera of 18 families of Angiosperms.
simple: Polymorphism in biology is when two or more clearly different phenotypes exist in the same population of a species. <s> In order to be classified as such, morphs must occupy the same habitat at the same time and belong to a population with random mating. <s> Polymorphism is common in nature. <s> The most common example is sexual dimorphism, which occurs in many organisms. <s> The definition has three parts: a) sympatry: one interbreeding population; b) discrete forms; and c) not maintained just by mutation. <s> Genetic polymorphism is actively and steadily maintained in populations by natural selection. <s> This contrasts with "transient polymorphisms" where a form is progressively replaced by another. <s> By definition, genetic polymorphism relates to a balance or equilibrium between morphs. <s> The mechanisms that conserve it are types of balancing selection. <s> The mechanism which decides which of several morphs an individual displays is called the "switch". <s> This switch may be genetic, or it may be environmental. <s> Taking sex determination as the example, in man the determination is genetic, by the XY sex determination system. <s> In Hymenoptera (ants, bees and wasps), sex determination is by haplo-diploidy: the females are all diploid, the males are haploid. <s> However, in some animals an environmental trigger determines the sex: alligators are a famous case in point. <s> In ants the distinction between workers and guards is environmental, by the feeding of the grubs. <s> Polymorphism with an environmental trigger is called polyphenism. <s> The polyphenic system does have a degree of environmental flexibility not present in the genetic polymorphism. <s> However, such environmental triggers are the less common of the two methods. <s> Such a balance is seen more simply in sickle-cell anaemia, which is found mostly in tropical populations in Africa and India. <s> An individual homozygous for the recessive sickle haemoglobin, HgbS, has a short expectancy of life. <s> The life expectancy of the standard haemoglobin (HgbA) homozygote and also the heterozygote is normal (though heterozygote individuals will suffer periodic problems). <s> The sickle-cell variant survives in the population "because the heterozygote is resistant to malaria" and the malarial parasite kills a huge number of people each year. <s> This is heterozygote advantage, a kind of balance between fierce selection against homozygous sickle-cell sufferers, and selection against the standard HgbA homozygotes by malaria. <s> The heterozygote has a permanent advantage (a higher fitness) so long as malaria exists; and it has existed as a human parasite for a long time. <s> Because the heterozygote survives, so does the HgbS allele survive at a rate much higher than the mutation rate. <s> Ants exhibit a range of polymorphisms. <s> First, there is their characteristic haplodiploid sex determination system, whereby all males are haploid, and all females are diploid. <s> Second, there is differentiation based mostly on feeding of larvae. <s> This determines, for example, whether the adult is capable of reproduction. <s> Lastly, there is differentiation of size and 'duties' (particularly of females), which are usually controlled by feeding and/or age, but which may sometimes be genetically controlled. <s> Thus the order exhibits both genetic polymorphism and extensive polyphenism. <s> An example of a botanical genetic polymorphism is heterostyly, in which flowers occur in different forms with different arrangements of the pistils and the stamens. <s> Pin and thrum heterostyly occurs in dimorphic species of "Primula", such as "P. vulgaris". <s> There are two types of flower. <s> The pin flower has a long style bearing the stigma at the mouth and the stamens half-way down; and the thrum flower has a short style, so the stigma is half-way up the tube and the stamens are at the mouth. <s> So when an insect in search of nectar inserts its proboscis into a long-style flower, the pollen from the stamens stick to the proboscis in exactly the part that will later touch the stigma of the short-styled flower, and vice versa. <s> Another most important property of the heterostyly system is physiological. <s> If thrum pollen is placed on a thrum stigma, or pin pollen on a pin stigma, the reproductive cells are incompatible and relatively little seed is set. <s> Effectively, this ensures outcrossing, as described by Darwin. <s> Quite a lot is now known about the underlying genetics; the system is controlled by a set of closely linked genes; these act as a single unit, a so-called super-gene. <s> All sections of the genus "Primula" have heterostyle species, altogether 354 species out of 419. <s> Since heterostyly is characteristic of nearly all races or species, the system is at least as old as the genus. <s> Between 1861 and 1863, Darwin found the same kind of structure in other groups, such as flax ("Linum") and in Purple Loosestrife and other species of "Lythrum". <s> Heterostyly is known in at least 51 genera of 18 families of Angiosperms.

title: Delta Air Lines Flight 191
complex: Delta Air Lines Flight 191 was a regularly scheduled Delta Air Lines domestic service from Fort Lauderdale, Florida, to Los Angeles with an intermediate stop at Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport (DFW). <s> On August 2, 1985, the Lockheed L-1011 TriStar operating Flight 191 encountered a microburst while on approach to land at DFW. <s> The aircraft struck the ground over a mile short of the runway, struck a car near the airport, and then collided with two water tanks and disintegrated. <s> The crash killed 137 people and injured 28 others. <s> The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) determined that the crash resulted from the flight crew's decision to fly through a thunderstorm, the lack of procedures or training to avoid or escape microbursts, and the lack of hazard information on wind shear. <s> Two of the passengers who initially survived the crash died more than 30 days later.
simple: Delta Air Lines Flight 191 was a regularly scheduled Delta Air Lines domestic service from Fort Lauderdale, Florida to Los Angeles, via Dallas that crashed on August 2, 1985, at 18:05 . <s> The Lockheed L-1011 TriStar operating this flight encountered a microburst while on approach to land on runway 17L (now marked 17C) at Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport (DFW). <s> The flight hit a car driving north of the airport and crashed two water tanks. <s> The crash killed 136 of the 152 passengers and 11 crew on board, and the driver of the car. <s> The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) determined that the crash resulted from the flight crew's decision to fly through a thunderstorm, the lack of procedures and training to avoid or escape microbursts, and the lack of hazard information on wind shear.

title: Quena
complex: The quena (hispanicized spelling of Quechua qina, sometimes also written "kena" in English) is the traditional flute of the Andes. <s> Traditionally made of cane or wood, it has 6 finger holes and one thumb hole, and is open on both ends or the bottom is half-closed (choked). <s> To produce sound, the player closes the top end of the pipe with the flesh between the chin and lower lip, and blows a stream of air downward, along the axis of the pipe, over an elliptical notch cut into the end. <s> It is normally in the key of G, with G4 being the lowest note. <s> It produces a very "textured" and "dark" timbre because of the length-to-bore ratio of about 16 to 20 (subsequently causing difficulty in the upper register), which is very unlike the tone of the Western concert flute with a length-to-bore ratio of about 38 to 20. <s> The quenacho (also "kenacho" in English) is a greater, lower-toned version of the quena and made the same way. <s> It is in the key of D, with D4 being the lowest note, a perfect fourth lower than the quena. <s> It produces a very rich timbre because of the length-to-bore ratio of about 25, paradoxically brighter by comparison to the quena. <s> Quena is mostly used in traditional Andean music. <s> In the 1960s and 1970s the quena was used by several nueva canción musicians. <s> This use was in most cases for particular songs and not as a standard instrument, but some groups such as Illapu and virtuoso player Facio Santillan have used it regularly. <s> In the 1980s and 1990s some post-nueva canción rock groups have also incorporated the quena in some of their songs; notably Soda Stereo in "Cuando Pase el Temblor" and Los Enanitos Verdes in "Lamento Boliviano". <s> The quena is also relatively common in world music. <s> Quenas are usually played in pairs, in harmony. <s> In Peru, one sees white quenas made from the leg-bone of the condor. <s> In most towns in the Andes, "vamos a ir a la quena" (we will go to the quena) was a popular sentence to threaten little children, because according to popular beliefs the instrument was also used to whip.
simple: The quena, also written as "kena" in English, is the traditional flute of Peru and the Andes. <s> Made of bamboo, it has six finger holes and one thumb hole and is open on both ends. <s> To make a sound, the player closes the top end of the pipe with the flesh between the chin and lower lip, and blows a stream of air downward, over a notch cut into the end. <s> It is normally in the key of G major. <s> It produces a very breathy or airy tone. <s> The quenacho (also "kenacho" in English) is a bigger, lower sounding type of quena and made the same way. <s> It is in the key of D major, a fourth lower than the quena. <s> Quena is mostly used in traditional Andean music. <s> In the 1960s and 1970s the quena was used by several Nueva Canción musicians. <s> Some groups such as Illapu have used it regularly. <s> In the 1980s and 1990s some post-Nueva Canción rock groups have also used the quena in some of their songs; notably Soda Stereo in "Cuando Pase el Temblor" and Los Enanitos Verdes in "Lamento Boliviano". <s> The quena is also relatively common in World music. <s> In most of Andes' towns "vamos a ir a la quena" (we will go to the quena) was used to threaten little children, because the quena was made of bamboo, a hard material.

title: Derrick Todd Lee
complex: Derrick Todd Lee (November 5, 1968 – January 21, 2016), also known as the Baton Rouge Serial Killer, was an American serial killer. <s> His killing spree began in 1992 and ended in 2003, and claimed the lives of seven women. <s> Prior to his murder charges, Lee had been arrested for stalking women and watching them in their homes. <s> Despite this, he was initially overlooked by police, because they incorrectly believed the killer was white. <s> Lee was linked by DNA tests to the deaths of seven women in the Baton Rouge and Lafayette areas in Louisiana, and in 2004 was convicted, in separate trials, of the murders of Geralyn DeSoto and Charlotte Murray Pace. <s> The Pace trial resulted in a death sentence. <s> Newspapers suggested Lee was responsible for other unsolved murders in the area, but the police lacked DNA evidence to prove these connections. <s> After Lee's arrest, it was discovered that another serial killer, Sean Vincent Gillis, was operating in the Baton Rouge area during the same time as Lee. <s> Lee died on January 21, 2016, of heart disease at a hospital in Louisiana, where he was transported for treatment from Louisiana State Penitentiary, where he had been awaiting execution.
simple: Derrick Todd Lee (November 5, 1968 – January 21, 2016) was a convicted American serial killer, nicknamed the Baton Rouge Serial Killer. <s> He was linked by DNA to the deaths of seven women in the Baton Rouge and Lafayette areas in Louisiana, and in 2004 was convicted, in separate trials, of the murders of Geralyn DeSoto and Charlotte Murray Pace. <s> The Pace trial resulted in a death sentence. <s> Newspapers have suggested Lee can be linked to other unsolved murders in the area, but the police lacked DNA evidence to prove these connections. <s> Lee died on January 21, 2016 at the age of 47, of an undisclosed medical condition at the Louisiana State Penitentiary in the West Feliciana Parish, while awaiting execution.

title: Vaux-sur-Morges
complex: Vaux-sur-Morges is a municipality in the Swiss canton of Vaud, located in the district of Morges.
simple: Vaux-sur-Morges is a municipality in the canton of Vaud, Switzerland.

title: Painted lady
complex: The Cynthia group of colourful butterflies, commonly called painted ladies, comprises a subgenus of the genus "Vanessa" in the family Nymphalidae. <s> They are well known throughout most of the world. <s> The lifespan of a painted lady butterfly is two to four weeks. <s> The species undergoes complete metamorphosis which has recently been investigated using microtomography. <s> This butterfly is widely distributed all over the Northern hemisphere, and can be seen in all types of habitats except dense forests. <s> Painted ladies lay their eggs on many different plants, and their larvae feed on a wider variety of plants (polyphagus) than most other butterfly species. <s> Even though they are often thought of as the thistle butterfly, and a majority of their eggs are laid on thistles, the larvae feed and can be reared on a varied number of plants and plant types, in several different families.
simple: The painted lady is a butterfly in the Cynthia group of colourful butterflies. <s> The painted lady is a subgenus of the genus "Vanessa" in the family Nymphalidae. <s> They occur in most of the world. <s> The lifespan of a painted lady imago (adult) is only about 2/3 weeks. <s> Their caterpillars feed on many different plants.

title: Megalosauroidea
complex: Megalosauroidea (meaning 'great/big lizard forms') is a superfamily (or clade) of tetanuran theropod dinosaurs that lived from the Middle Jurassic to the Late Cretaceous period. <s> The group is defined as "Megalosaurus bucklandii" and all taxa sharing a more recent common ancestor with it than with "Allosaurus fragilis" or "Passer domesticus". <s> Members of the group include "Spinosaurus", "Megalosaurus", and "Torvosaurus". <s> Carrano, Benson & Sampson (2012) performed much larger phylogenetic analysis of the Tetanurae that includes more taxa. <s> They used the clade name Megalosauria (Bonaparte, 1850) in their analysis and defined it as the node comprising "Megalosaurus", "Spinosaurus", their most recent common ancestor, and all its descendants.
simple: Megalosauroidea is a group of carnivorous theropod dinosaurs. <s> They lived from the Middle Jurassic to the Late Cretaceous period. <s> The definition of the clade Megalosauroidea includes "Megalosaurus bucklandii" and all taxa that share a more recent common ancestor with it than they do with "Allosaurus fragilis" or the House Sparrow. <s> Members of the group include "Spinosaurus", "Megalosaurus", and "Torvosaurus". <s> It is based on a study by Carrano, Benson & Sampson (2012).

title: Jean-Marie Girault
complex: Jean-Marie Girault (9 February 1926 – 1 May 2016) was a French politician and former mayor of Caen.
simple: Jean-Marie Girault (9 February 1926 – 1 May 2016) was a French politician. <s> Girault died in Caen, France on 1 May 2016, aged 90.

title: Elisabeth Moss
complex: Elisabeth Singleton Moss (born July 24, 1982) is an American actor. <s> She is known for her work in several television dramas, earning such accolades as two Primetime Emmy Awards and two Golden Globe Awards, which led "Vulture" to name her the "Queen of Peak TV". <s> Elisabeth Moss was born and raised in Los Angeles, California, the daughter of Ron and Linda Moss, both of whom were musicians. <s> Moss has one younger brother.
simple: Elisabeth Moss (born 24 July 1982) is an American actress. <s> Moss was born in Los Angeles.

title: Calendar (Apple)
complex: Calendar is a personal calendar app made by Apple Inc. that runs on both the macOS desktop operating system and the iOS mobile operating system. <s> It offers online cloud backup of calendars using Apple's iCloud service, or can synchronize with other calendar services, including Google Calendar and Microsoft Exchange Server. <s> The macOS version was known as iCal before the release of OS X Mountain Lion in July 2012. <s> Originally released as a free download for Mac OS X v10.2 on September 10, 2002, it was bundled with the operating system as iCal 1.5 with the release of Mac OS X v10.3. <s> iCal was the first calendar application for Mac OS X to offer support for multiple calendars and the ability to intermittently publish/subscribe to calendars on WebDAV servers. <s> Version 2 of iCal was released as part of Mac OS X v10.4, Version 3 as part of Mac OS X v10.5, Version 4 as part of Mac OS X v10.6, Version 5 as part of Mac OS X v10.7, Version 6 as part of OS X v10.8, Version 7 as part of OS X v10.9, Version 8 as part of OS X v10.10 and OS X v10.11, and version 9 as part of macOS v10.12. <s> Apple licensed the iCal name from Brown Bear Software, who have used it for their iCal application since 1997. <s> iCal's initial development was quite different from other Apple software: it was designed independently by a small French team working "secretly" in Paris, led by Jean-Marie Hullot, a friend of Steve Jobs. <s> iCal's development has since been transferred to Apple US headquarters in Cupertino.
simple: iCal is a personal calendar application made by Apple Inc. that runs on the Mac OS X operating system. <s> Originally released as a free download for Mac OS X v10.2 on September 10 2002, with the release of Mac OS X v10.3 it was bundled with the operating system as iCal 1.5. <s> iCal was the first calendar application for Mac OS X to offer support for multiple calendars and the ability to publish/subscribe calendars to WebDAV server. <s> Version 2 of iCal was released as part of Mac OS X v10.4, Version 3 with Mac OS X v10.5 and Version 4 as part of Mac OS X v10.6. <s> Apple licensed the iCal name from Brown Bear Software, who have used it for their iCal application since 1997. <s> iCal development is quite different from other Apple software because it was designed independently by a small French team working "secretly" in Paris, led by Jean-Marie Hullot, a friend of Steve Jobs. <s> iCal's development has since been transferred to Apple US headquarters in Cupertino.

title: Subotica
complex: Subotica ( ] , ) is a city and the administrative center of the North Bačka District in the autonomous province of Vojvodina, Serbia. <s> Formerly the largest city of Vojvodina region, contemporary Subotica is now the second largest city in the province, following the city of Novi Sad. <s> According to the 2011 census, the city itself has a population of 97,910, while the urban area of Subotica (with adjacent urban settlement of Palić included) has 105,681 inhabitants, and the population of metro area (the administrative area of the city) stands at 141,554 people. <s> Serbian is the most employed language in daily life, but Hungarian is also used by almost one third of the population in their daily conversations. <s> Both languages are also widely employed in commercial and official signage
simple: Subotica ( ] ) is a city in northern Serbia. <s> It is in the Autonomous Province of Vojvodina. <s> The Serbian language is the most employed language in daily life, but Hungarian is also used by almost one third of the population in their daily conversations. <s> Both languages are also widely employed in commercial and official signage

title: Sainte-Foy-de-Montgommery
complex: Sainte-Foy-de-Montgommery is a former commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France. <s> On 1 January 2016, it was merged into the new commune of Val-de-Vie.
simple: Sainte-Foy-de-Montgommery is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Eddie Filgate
complex: Edward "Eddie" Filgate (16 September 1915 – 19 January 2017) was an Irish Fianna Fáil politician who served for five years as Teachta Dála (TD) for the Louth constituency. <s> He became a centenarian in September 2015 and died on 19 January 2017, aged 101.
simple: Edward "Eddie" Filgate (16 September 1915 – 19 January 2017) was an Irish politician. <s> He was a member of Fianna Fáil. <s> He served as Teachta Dála (TD) from 1977 to 1982 for the Louth constituency. <s> Filgate turned 100 in 2015. <s> He died on 19 January 2017 at the age of 101.

title: Form classification
complex: Form classification is the classification of organisms based on their morphology, which does not necessarily reflect their biological relationships. <s> Form classification, generally restricted to palaeontology, reflects uncertainty; the goal of science is to move "form taxa" to biological taxa whose affinity is known.
simple: A form taxon is a group of organisms based on based on what they look like (their morphology). <s> Such a taxon may not reflect their biological relationships.

title: George Gurdjieff
complex: George Ivanovich Gurdjieff ( , ; 31 March 1866/14 January 1872/28 November 1877 – 29 October 1949) was a mystic, philosopher, spiritual teacher, and composer of Armenian and Greek descent, born in Alexandrapol (now Gyumri), Armenia. <s> Gurdjieff taught that most humans do not possess a unified consciousness and thus live their lives in a state of hypnotic "waking sleep", but that it is possible to awaken to a higher state of consciousness and achieve full human potential. <s> Gurdjieff described a method attempting to do so, calling the discipline "The Work" (connoting "work on oneself") or "the System". <s> According to his principles and instructions, Gurdjieff's method for awakening one's consciousness unites the methods of the fakir, monk and yogi, and thus he referred to it as the "Fourth Way". <s> Gurdjieff's teaching addressed the question of humanity's place in the universe and the importance of developing latent potentialities—regarded as our natural endowment as human beings but rarely brought to fruition. <s> He taught that higher levels of consciousness, higher bodies, inner growth and development are real possibilities that nonetheless require conscious work to achieve. <s> The feature film "Meetings with Remarkable Men" (1979), loosely based on Gurdjieff's book by the same name, ends with performances of Gurdjieff's dances taught known simply as the "exercises" but later promoted as "movements". <s> Jeanne de Salzmann and Peter Brook wrote the film, Brook directed, and Dragan Maksimovic and Terence Stamp star, as does South African playwright and actor, Athol Fugard.
simple: George Ivanovich Gurdjieff (13 January 1866 – 29 October 1949), usually called Gurdjieff, was an Armenian guru and writer. <s> Gurdjieff developed a method for working towards a higher state of consciousness and achieving full human potential. <s> He called this "The Work" or "The Method". <s> Gurdjieff's method for awakening one's consciousness is different from that of the fakir, monk or yogi, so his discipline was called originally the "Fourth Way". <s> There is a 1979 British film, "Meetings with Remarkable Men", directed by Peter Brook. <s> It starred Terence Stamp as Prince Lubovedsky, and Dragan Maksimovic as the adult Gurdjieff.

title: Alexander Urbom
complex: Alexander Urbom (born December 20, 1990) is a professional Swedish ice hockey defenceman. <s> He is currently playing with Düsseldorfer EG of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga (DEL). <s> Urbom was drafted by the New Jersey Devils in the third round, 73rd overall, in the 2009 NHL Draft. <s> He previously played for Djurgårdens IF in Elitserien and Brandon Wheat Kings in the WHL.
simple: Alexander Urbom (born December 20, 1990) is a professional Swedish ice hockey defenseman who is currently playing for the Albany Devils. <s> He was drafted by the New Jersey Devils in the third round, 73rd overall, in the 2009 NHL Draft.

title: The History of Rock and Roll
complex: The History of Rock & Roll is a US radio documentary on rock and roll music, originally syndicated in 1969. <s> One of the lengthiest documentaries of any medium (48 hours in the 1969 version, 52 hours each for the 1978 and 1981 versions), "The History of Rock & Roll" is a definitive history of the Rock and Roll genre, stretching from the early 1950s to its day. <s> The "rockumentary," as producers Bill Drake and Gene Chenault called it, features hundreds of interviews and comments from numerous rock artists and people involved with rock and roll. <s> "The History of Rock & Roll" first aired on the weekend of February 21–23, 1969 on 93 KHJ Los Angeles, hosted by Robert W. Morgan. <s> It aired for 48 hours and was later syndicated.
simple: The History of Rock & Roll was a radio documentary on rock and roll music. <s> It was first broadcast in 1969. <s> "The History of Rock & Roll" told the story of Rock and Roll music from the early 1950s to its day. <s> In the fall of 1969 many other stations broadcast this documentary. <s> The 1969 version was 48 hours long. <s> The 1978 version was 52 hours long. <s> Producers Bill Drake and Gene Chenault called this a "rockumentary". <s> Los Angeles radio station KHJ first broadcast this show on February 21-23, 1969.

title: Peter MacGregor-Scott
complex: Peter MacGregor-Scott (December 28, 1947 – October 29, 2017) was a British film producer, production manager and assistant director. <s> He produced the 1997 film "Batman & Robin". <s> He also produced the Cheech & Chong films "Cheech & Chong's The Corsican Brothers", "Still Smokin" and "Born in East L.A.". <s> Others are "The Whoopee Boys" and "Death to Smoochy". <s> Peter MacGregor-Scott was born in Maidenhead, England. <s> His father was J. C. MacGregor Scott, who served as an executive with such British film companies as Columbia Pictures U.K., Warner-Pathe Distributors and Commonwealth United International. <s> He is survived by his two children, Elizabeth Kennedy ("née" MacGregor-Scott), Taylor MacGregor-Scott and his wife, Susan ("née" Brustien) MacGregor-Scott. <s> MacGregor-Scott was involved in a taxi accident in New York City which resulted in complications which would lead to his death on October 25, 2017, aged 69.
simple: Peter MacGregor-Scott (December 28, 1947 – October 25, 2017) was an American movie producer. <s> He produced the 1997 movie, "Batman & Robin". <s> He also produced the Cheech & Chong movie "Cheech & Chong's The Corsican Brothers", "Still Smokin" and "Born in East L.A.". <s> Others are "The Whoopee Boys" and "Death to Smoochy". <s> He was born in Maidenhead, Berkshire, England. <s> MacGregor-Scott was involved in a traffic collision in New York City which would result in his death on October 25, 2017, aged 69.

title: Flag of Panama
complex: The flag of Panama was made by María de la Ossa de Amador and was officially adopted by the "ley 48 de 1925". <s> The Panamanian flag day is celebrated on November 4, one day after Panamanian separation from Colombia, and is one of a series of holidays celebrated in November known as the Fiestas Patrias.
simple: The flag of Panama was created in March 1925.

title: Theobroma cacao
complex: Theobroma cacao, also called the cacao tree and the cocoa tree, is a small (4 - tall) evergreen tree in the family Malvaceae, native to the deep tropical regions of the Americas. <s> Its seeds, cocoa beans, are used to make chocolate liquor, cocoa solids, cocoa butter and chocolate. <s> Cacao beans constituted both a ritual beverage and a major currency system in pre-Columbian Mesoamerican civilizations. <s> At one point, the Aztec empire received a yearly tribute of 980 loads ("xiquipil" in Nahuatl) of cacao, in addition to other goods. <s> Each load represented exactly 8,000 beans. <s> The buying power of quality beans was such that 80–100 beans could buy a new cloth mantle. <s> The use of cacao beans as currency is also known to have spawned counterfeiters during the Aztec empire. <s> In 2016, cocoa beans were cultivated on roughly 10196725 ha worldwide. <s> Cocoa beans are grown by large agroindustrial plantations and small producers, the bulk of production coming from millions of farmers with small plots. <s> A tree begins to bear when it is four or five years old. <s> A mature tree may have 6,000 flowers in a year, yet only about 20 pods. <s> About 1,200 seeds (40 pods) are required to produce 1 kg (2.2 lb) of cocoa paste. <s> Historically, chocolate makers have recognized three main cultivar groups of cacao beans used to make cocoa and chocolate: Forastero, Criollo and Trinitario. <s> The most prized, rare, and expensive is the Criollo group, the cocoa bean used by the Maya. <s> Only 10% of chocolate is made from Criollo, which is arguably less bitter and more aromatic than any other bean. <s> In November 2000, the cacao beans coming from Chuao were awarded an appellation of origin under the title "Cacao de Chuao" (from Spanish-"cacao of Chuao"). <s> The cacao bean in 80% of chocolate is made using beans of the Forastero group, the main and most ubiquitous variety being the Amenolado variety, while the arriba variety (such as the Nacional variety) are less commonly found in Forastero produce. <s> Forastero trees are significantly hardier and more disease-resistant than Criollo trees, resulting in cheaper cacao beans.
simple: The cacao tree is a small tree originally grown in tropical South America. <s> Its seeds are called cocoa and are used to produce cocoa butter, the chocolate drink, as well as chocolate. <s> Cacao beans were commonly used as currency in Pre-Columbian Mesoamerica. <s> A tree begins to bear fruit when it is 4 or 5 years old. <s> In one year, when mature, it may have 6,000 flowers, but only about 20 pods. <s> About 300-600 seeds (10 pods) are required to produce around 1 kg of cocoa paste. <s> There are three main cultivar groups of cacao beans used to make cocoa and chocolate. <s> The most prized, rare, and expensive is the Criollo Group, the cocoa bean used by the Maya. <s> Only 10% of chocolate is made from the Criollo, which is less bitter and more aromatic than any other bean. <s> Trinitario, a hybrid of Criollo and Forastero, is used in about 10% of chocolate. <s> The cacao bean in 80% of chocolate is made using beans of the Forastero Group. <s> Forastero trees are significantly hardier than Criollo trees, resulting in cheaper cacao beans.

title: Rząska
complex: Rząska is a village in the administrative district of Gmina Zabierzów, within Kraków County, Lesser Poland Voivodeship, in southern Poland. <s> It lies approximately 5 km south-east of Zabierzów and 9 km north-west of the regional capital Kraków.
simple: Rząska is a village in the administrative district of Gmina Zabierzów, within Kraków County, Lesser Poland Voivodeship, in southern Poland. <s> It is about 5 km southeast of Zabierzów and 9 km northwest of the city of Kraków.

title: Molly Sandén
complex: Molly My Marianne Sandén (born 3 July 1992) is a Swedish pop singer and voice actress. <s> As a teenager she represented Sweden in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest in 2006, and participated in Melodifestivalen in 2009, and as a young adult in 2012 and 2016. <s> Her sisters Frida and Mimmi are also singers. <s> In 2018 Sandén released her third studio album which was her debut in Swedish, "Större".
simple: Molly Sandén, born July 3, 1992 in Stockholm, Sweden is a Swedish pop and R&B singer, host and voice actress. <s> Her sisters Frida and Mimmi Sandén are also singers.

title: Älghult
complex: Älghult is a locality situated in Uppvidinge Municipality, Kronoberg County, Sweden with 446 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Älghult is a locality in Uppvidinge Municipality in Kronoberg County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 446 people lived there.

title: Diamanda Galás
complex: Diamanda Galás (born August 29, 1955) is a Greek-American soprano sfogato, composer, pianist, organist, performance artist, and painter. <s> She has received international recognition for creating highly original and thought provoking political performance works. <s> Galás was born and raised in San Diego, California, to a Greek mother, Georgiana, and an Egyptian father, James, both of whom were Greek Orthodox Christians. <s> Her father was a gospel choir director who introduced her to classical music. <s> He exposed her to New Orleans jazz and also the classics of their own Greek heritage. <s> Her first album was "The Litanies of Satan", released in 1982. <s> In 2005, Galás was awarded Italy's prestigious Demetrio Stratos International Career Award.
simple: Diamanda Galás (born 1955) is an American avant-garde artist. <s> Galás was born and raised in San Diego, California, to Greek Orthodox parents. <s> In 1982 her first album was released. <s> In 2005 Galás was given the Demetrio Stratos International Career Award.

title: Clubhouse Games
complex: Clubhouse Games, known in parts of Europe as 42 All-Time Classics and in Japan as Daredemo Asobi Taizen (だれでもアソビ大全 , Everyone's Playing Encyclopedia ) , is a compilation video game consisting of card, board, and parlor games developed by Agenda and published by Nintendo for the Nintendo DS handheld video game console. <s> It was first released in Japan on November 3, 2005, in Europe on September 29, 2006, in North America on October 9, 2006, and in Australia on October 26, 2006.
simple: Clubhouse Games is a 2006 video game published by Nintendo and developed by Agenda. <s> It features 42 parlor games. <s> It is for the Nintendo DS game console.

title: Úhořilka
complex: Úhořilka is a small village in the Havlíčkův Brod District, Vysočina Region of the Czech Republic. <s> 51 people live in Úhořilka and it has 2,52 km2. <s> It was first documented in 1454.
simple: Úhořilka is small village in the Havlíčkův Brod District, Vysočina Region of the Czech Republic. <s> 51 people live in Úhořilka. <s> It covers 2,52 km2. <s> It was first documented in 1454.

title: Richard Drew (photographer)
complex: Richard Drew (born 1946) is an Associated Press photo-journalist. <s> In 2001, he took the photo entitled "The Falling Man", which captured the image of a man falling from the World Trade Center towers following the September 11 attacks. <s> A British documentary "The Falling Man" about the photo premiered on the Discovery Times channel on September 10, 2007. <s> Drew was one of four press photographers present at the assassination of Robert F. Kennedy. <s> Drew has been an Associated Press photographer for 40 years, and lives with his wife and two daughters in New York City.
simple: Richard Drew (born 1946) is an Associated Press photo-journalist. <s> He is best known for his photograph "The Falling Man", which shows a man falling from the World Trade Center towers during the September 11 attacks. <s> A British documentary about his photograph, "The Falling Man", aired on Channel 4 on March 16, 2006. <s> Drew was one of the press photographers at the assassination of Robert F. Kennedy. <s> He has worked as an Associated Press photographer for over 40 years.

title: Grumman F6F Hellcat
complex: The Grumman F6F Hellcat is an American carrier-based fighter aircraft of World War II. <s> Designed to replace the earlier F4F Wildcat and to counter the Japanese Mitsubishi A6M Zero, it was the United States Navy's dominant fighter in the second half of the Pacific War.
simple: The F6F Hellcat was a United States Navy fighter aircraft made by Grumman during World War II.

title: ZDF
complex: Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen (] ; ), usually shortened to ZDF (] , stylized as 2DF), is a German public-service television broadcaster based in Mainz, Rhineland-Palatinate. <s> It is run as an independent nonprofit institution, which was founded by all federal states of Germany ("Bundesländer").
simple: Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen is the second public broadcasting coorparation that was founded in Germany.

title: Nairobi National Park
complex: Nairobi National Park is a national park in Kenya. <s> Established in 1946, the national park was Kenya's first.
simple: Nairobi National Park is the smallest park in Kenya.

title: Hitch (film)
complex: Hitch is a 2005 American romantic comedy film directed by Andy Tennant and starring Will Smith, along with Eva Mendes, Kevin James, and Amber Valletta. <s> The film, which was written by Kevin Bisch, features Smith as Alex "Hitch" Hitchens, a professional dating consultant who makes a living teaching men how to woo women. <s> The film was released on February 11, 2005 by Columbia Pictures.
simple: Hitch is a 2005 romantic comedy movie. <s> Will Smith plays Alex. Eva Mendes plays Sara. <s> The movie is about a professional dating consultant who teaches men how to get women to like them. <s> The movie was released on February 11, 2005.

title: Brandon Roy
complex: Brandon Dawayne Roy (born July 23, 1984) is an American basketball coach and a former professional basketball player. <s> Roy played six seasons in the National Basketball Association (NBA) for the Portland Trail Blazers and Minnesota Timberwolves. <s> He was selected sixth in the 2006 NBA draft, having completed four years playing for the Washington Huskies. <s> His nickname was "B-Roy", but he was also referred to as "The Natural" by Trail Blazers announcer Brian Wheeler. <s> On December 10, 2011, Roy announced his retirement from basketball due to a degenerative knee condition, though he returned in 2012 to play five games for the Timberwolves. <s> Born in Seattle, Roy became known for his immediate impact on the Trail Blazers. <s> Zach Randolph, then the team captain, was traded to the New York Knicks at the end of Roy's first season in 2006–07, which cleared the way for Roy to take on a leadership role on the team. <s> That season, Roy won the NBA Rookie of the Year Award in a near-unanimous vote. <s> He was selected as a reserve to the 2008, 2009, and 2010 All-Star games. <s> Roy played the most minutes of any Western Conference player, and tied for the most points in the West in the 2008 season, and he played the most minutes of any player during the 2009 season.
simple: Brandon Roy (born July 23, 1984 in Seattle, Washington) is a retired professional basketball player. <s> He played for the Portland Trail Blazers of the National Basketball Association (NBA) from 2006 to 2011. <s> The Minnesota Timberwolves chose him with the sixth pick in the 2006 NBA Draft, but traded him to the Trail Blazers later that night. <s> On December 9, 2011, Roy said that he would retire from basketball because of knee problems. <s> He won the NBA Rookie of the Year Award in 2007, and was chosen as an All Star in 2008, 2009, and 2010.

title: Goole
complex: Goole is a town, civil parish and inland port located at junction 36 off the M62 via the A614 and approximately 45 mi from the North Sea at the confluence of the rivers Don and Ouse in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England, although historically within the West Riding of Yorkshire. <s> Goole lies 19 mi south of York and 29 mi west of Hull.
simple: Goole is a town and inland port in the East Riding of Yorkshire of England, UK.

title: Sho Naruoka
complex: Sho Naruoka (成岡 翔 , Naruoka Shō , born May 31, 1984 in Shimada, Shizuoka) is a Japanese football player. <s> Naruoka played for Júbilo Iwata from 2003 to 2010 and joined Albirex Niigata in January 2013.
simple: Sho Naruoka (born 31 May 1984) is a Japanese football player. <s> He plays for Júbilo Iwata.

title: Jhang District
complex: Jhang District (Punjabi and ) is a district of the Punjab province of Pakistan. <s> The city of Jhang is the district's capital. <s> In 2009 the tehsil of Chiniot became the separate Chiniot District.
simple: Jhang District is a district in the Punjab province of Pakistan. <s> The city of Jhang is the capital.

title: The Miserable Mill
complex: The Miserable Mill is the fourth novel of the children's novel series "A Series of Unfortunate Events" by Lemony Snicket. <s> In this novel, the Baudelaire orphans live with the owner of Lucky Smells Lumber Mill. <s> The book was published on April 15, 2000, by HarperCollins and illustrated by Brett Helquist. <s> Violet, Klaus and Sunny Baudelaire are traveling on a train heading for Paltryville, the location of the children's new home, the Lucky Smells Lumbermill. <s> Klaus breaks his own glasses when he is purposely tripped by the new foreman, Flacutono, and is sent to see Dr. Orwell. <s> When Klaus returns from the optometrist, hours later, he acts strangely, as if in a trance.
simple: The Miserable Mill is a book by Lemony Snicket. <s> It is the fourth book in a series called "A Series of Unfortunate Events". <s> Violet, Klaus, and Sunny Baudelaire go by train to Paltryville to meet their new guardian at the Lucky Smells Lumbermill. <s> After breaking his glasses, Klaus is sent to the optometrist (eye doctor) Dr. Orwell.

title: A-flat major
complex: A-flat major (or the key of A-flat) is a major scale based on A♭, with the pitches A♭ , B♭, C, D♭, E♭, F, and G. Its key signature has four flats. <s> The relative minor is F minor. <s> Its parallel minor, A-flat minor, is usually replaced by G-sharp minor, since A-flat minor, which would contain seven flats, is not normally used. <s> G-sharp major, its enharmonic, with eight sharps, including the F , has a similar problem, and so A-flat major is often used as the parallel major for G-sharp minor. <s> (The same enharmonic situation occurs with the keys of D-flat major and C-sharp minor.) <s> Beethoven chose A-flat major as the key of the slow movement for most of his C minor works, a practice which Anton Bruckner imitated in his first two C minor symphonies and also Antonín Dvořák in his only C minor symphony. <s> Since A-flat major was not often chosen as the main key for orchestral works of the 18th century, passages or movements in the key often retained the timpani settings of the preceding movement. <s> For example, Beethoven's Symphony No. 5 in C minor has the timpani set to C and G for the first movement. <s> With hand-tuned timpani, there is no time to re-tune the timpani to A-flat and E-flat for the slow second movement in A-flat; accordingly, the timpani in this movement are reserved for the passages in C major. <s> In Bruckner's Symphony No. 1 in C minor, however, the timpani are re-tuned between the first movement in C minor and the following in A-flat major. <s> Charles-Marie Widor considered A-flat major to be the second best key for flute music. <s> A-flat major was the flattest major key to be used as the home key for the keyboard and piano sonatas of Domenico Scarlatti, Joseph Haydn and Ludwig van Beethoven, with each of them using the key for two sonatas: Scarlatti's K. 127 and K. 130, Haydn's Hob XVI 43 and 46, and Beethoven's Op. 26 and Op. 110, while Franz Schubert used it for one piano sonata. <s> It was also the flattest major key to be used for the preludes and fugues in Johann Sebastian Bach's "Well-Tempered Klavier", as flatter major keys were notated as their enharmonic equivalents. <s> Felix Mendelssohn, Johann Nepomuk Hummel, John Field, and Friedrich Kalkbrenner each wrote one piano concerto in A-flat (Mendelssohn's being for two pianos); they had the horns and trumpet tuned to E-flat. <s> Max Bruch's Concerto for Two Pianos in A-flat minor has its last movement in A-flat major, which is the parallel major; this concerto plays with the contrast between the two keys.
simple: A♭ major or A-flat major is a major scale that starts on A-flat. <s> Its relative minor is F minor and its parallel minor is A-flat minor. <s> Beethoven chose A-flat major as the key of the slow movement for most of his C minor works. <s> This was also followed by Antonín Dvořák in his only C minor symphony and Anton Bruckner in his first two C minor symphonies. <s> Since A-flat major was not often chosen as the main key for orchestral music of the 18th century, passages or movements in the key often kept the timpani tuned the same way as they were in the movement before it. <s> For example, Beethoven's Symphony No. 5 in C minor has the timpani set to C and G for the first movement. <s> With hand-tuned timpani, there is no time to retune the timpani to A flat and E flat for the slow second movement in A flat. <s> In Bruckner's Symphony No. 1 in C minor, however, the timpani are retuned between the first movement in C minor and the following in A-flat major. <s> Charles-Marie Widor considered A-flat major to be the second best key for flute music. <s> A-flat major is the major key with the most flats that Domenico Scarlatti used in his keyboard sonatas, though he used it only twice– in K. 127 and K. 130. <s> Felix Mendelssohn and John Field each wrote one piano concerto in A-flat.

title: Vaiśravaṇa
complex: The name is a derivative (used, e.g., for patronymics) of the Sanskrit proper name from the root "hear distinctly", (passive) "become famous". <s> The name is derived from the Sanskrit " " which means "son of Vishrava", a usual epithet of the Hindu god Kubera. <s> is also known as Kubera and Jambhala in Sanskrit and Kuvera in Pāli. <s> The character of is founded upon the Hindu deity Kubera, but although the Buddhist and Hindu deities share some characteristics and epithets, each of them has different functions and associated myths. <s> Although brought into East Asia as a Buddhist deity, has become a character in folk religion and has acquired an identity that is partially independent of the Buddhist tradition (cf. the similar treatment of Guanyin and Yama). <s> He is often portrayed with a yellow face. <s> He carries an umbrella or parasol (chatra) as a symbol of his sovereignty. <s> He is also sometimes displayed with a mongoose, often shown ejecting jewels from its mouth. <s> The mongoose is the enemy of the snake, a symbol of greed or hatred; the ejection of jewels represents generosity. <s> In the Pāli Canon of Theravāda Buddhism, is called . <s> is one of the "Cāturmahārājika deva" or "Four Great Heavenly Kings", each of whom rules over a specific direction. <s> 's realm is the northern quadrant of the world, including the land of Uttarakuru. <s> According to some suttas, he takes his name from a region there called ; he also has a city there called Ālakamandā which is a byword for wealth. <s> governs the yakshas – beings with a nature between 'fairy' and 'ogre'. <s> As with all the Buddhist deities, is properly the name of an office (filled for life) rather than a permanent individual. <s> Each is mortal, and when he dies, he will be replaced by a new . <s> Like other beings of the Cātummahārājika world, his lifespan is 90,000 years (other sources say nine million years). <s> has the authority to grant the yakkhas particular areas (e.g., a lake) to protect, and these are usually assigned at the beginning of a 's reign. <s> When Gautama Buddha was born, became his follower, and eventually attained the stage of sotāpanna, one who has only seven more lives before enlightenment. <s> He often brought the Buddha and his followers messages from the gods and other humans, and protected them. <s> He presented to the Buddha the verses, which Buddhists meditating in the forest could use to ward off the attacks of wild yakkhas or other supernatural beings who do not have faith in the Buddha. <s> These verses are an early form of paritta chanting. <s> In Japan, Bishamonten (毘沙門天), or just Bishamon (毘沙門) is thought of as an armor-clad god of war or warriors and a punisher of evildoers. <s> Bishamon is portrayed holding a spear in one hand and a small pagoda in the other hand, the latter symbolizing the divine treasure house, whose contents he both guards and gives away. <s> In Japanese folklore, he is one of the Seven Lucky Gods. <s> In Tibet, is considered a lokapāla or dharmapāla in the retinue of Ratnasambhava. <s> He is also known as the King of the North. <s> As guardian of the north, he is often depicted on temple murals outside the main door. <s> He is also thought of as a god of wealth. <s> As such, is sometimes portrayed carrying a citron, the fruit of the "jambhara" tree, a pun on another name of his, Jambhala. <s> The fruit helps distinguish him iconically from depictions of Kuvera. <s> He is sometimes represented as corpulent and covered with jewels.
simple: The name Vaiśravaṇa comes from the Sanskrit viśravaṇa which means "Great Fame". <s> Vaiśravaṇa is also known as Kubera in Sanskrit or Kuvera in Pāli. <s> The character of Vaiśravaṇa is set up on the Hindu god Kubera, but although the Buddhist and Hindu deities share some characteristics, both of them have different functions and myths. <s> He is often shown with a yellow face. <s> He carries an umbrella as a sign of his power. <s> He is also sometimes shown with a mongoose, often shown spitting out jewels. <s> The mongoose is the enemy of the snake, which is a symbol of greed or hatred; the spitting out of jewels shows generosity. <s> In the Pāli writings of the Theravāda Buddhist tradition, Vaiśravaṇa is called Vessavaṇa. <s> Vessavaṇa is one of the Four Great Kings, each one of which rules over a direction. <s> Vessavaṇa's direction is the northern quarter of the world. <s> As with all the Buddhist deities, Vessavaṇa is properly the name of a person who has the god inside him rather than a permanent individual. <s> Each Vessavaṇa is a human, and when he dies, he will be replaced by a new Vessavaṇa. <s> Like other beings of the Cātummahārājika world, his lifespan is 90,000 years, but other sources say nine million years. <s> When the Buddha was born, Vessavaṇa became his follower. <s> He often brought the Buddha and his followers messages from the gods and other humans, and protected them. <s> In Japan, Bishamonten (毘沙門天), or just Bishamon (毘沙門) is thought of as a god of war or warriors who wears armor, and a punisher of people who do evil things, a view that is very strange when compared with the more peaceful Buddhist king described above. <s> Bishamon is shown holding a spear in one hand and a small pagoda in the other hand. <s> The Pagoda symbolises the divine treasure house, which holds things that he guards and gives away. <s> In Japanese folklore, he is one of the Japanese Seven Lucky Gods. <s> He is also known as the King of the North. <s> As guardian of the north, he is often shown on temple wall paintings outside the main door. <s> He is also a god of wealth. <s> Vaiśravaṇa is sometimes shown carrying a citron, the fruit of the "jambhara" tree. <s> The fruit helps pick him out from depictions of Kuvera.

title: Jean-Noël Rey
complex: Jean-Noël Rey (23 December 1949 – 16 January 2016) was a Swiss manager and politician of the Social Democratic Party. <s> He was director-general of the Swiss public post and telecommunications service (PTT) from 1990 to 1998, and a member of the National Council of Switzerland from 2003 to 2007. <s> Born in Siders, Valais, Rey graduated with a doctorate in social sciences from the University of Geneva in 1978. <s> He worked as a personal assistant to Federal Councillor Otto Stich and was elected director-general of PTT in 1990. <s> When PTT was split into Swisscom and Swiss Post in 1998, Rey was the subject of allegations of cronyism and resigned as CEO of the new postal service, but was acquitted of criminal charges. <s> Rey was killed in the terror attacks in Burkina Faso in 2016, together with another former Swiss politician, Georgie Lamon. <s> They had been visiting a school built by a Swiss charity founded by Lamon, "Association Yelen", for which Rey had helped raise money.
simple: Jean-Noël Rey (23 December 1949 – 16 January 2016) was a Swiss socialist politician. <s> He was a member of the National Council of Switzerland between 2003 and 2007. <s> He was also the CEO of the national postal service Swiss Post. <s> Rey was shot and killed by terrorists on 16 January 2016 in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso.

title: Sammi Smith
complex: Sammi Smith (August 5, 1943 – February 12, 2005) was an American country music singer and songwriter. <s> Born Jewel Faye Smith, she is best known for her 1971 country-pop crossover hit "Help Me Make It Through the Night", which was written by Kris Kristofferson. <s> She became one of the few women in the outlaw country movement during the 1970s. <s> Sammi Smith was born in Orange County, California, in 1943 but spent her childhood in Oklahoma, Texas, Arizona and Colorado. <s> She dropped out of school at the age of eleven and began to sing professionally in nightclubs.
simple: Jewel Faye Smith (aka Sammi Smith; August 5, 1943 – February 12, 2005) was an American country music singer and songwriter. <s> She had the 1971 hit single "Help Me Make it Through the Night". <s> She was born in Orange County, California.

title: Cuzieu, Ain
complex: Cuzieu is a commune in the Ain department in eastern France.
simple: Cuzieu is a commune.

title: Registan Desert
complex: The Registan Desert (Persian: ), also known as Rigestan Desert, is an extremely arid plateau region located between Helmand and Kandahar provinces in southwestern Afghanistan. <s> It is a sandy desert consisting of small, red sand hills about 50 to 100 ft high, sand-covered plains, and open rocky and clay-covered areas. <s> The underlying base of the hills consists of partly stabilized ancient transverse dunes, reflecting a west-to-east wind and nearly unlimited sand supply. <s> The desert is very sparsely populated by Baluchi and Pashtun nomads. <s> The desert is gradually encroaching on surrounding agricultural areas.
simple: The Registan Desert, also known as Rigestan Desert, is a desert in Afghanistan. <s> It is between Helmand and Kandahar provinces in southwestern Afghanistan. <s> It is a sandy desert with small, red sandhills about 50 to high, plains that are covered with sand, and open rocky and clay areas. <s> There are a few Baluchi and Pashtun nomads there. <s> The desert is starting to go over surrounding agricultural areas.

title: Coroner
complex: A coroner is a government official who is empowered to conduct or order an inquest into the manner or cause of death, and to investigate or confirm the identity of an unknown person who has been found dead within the coroner's jurisdiction.
simple: A coroner is a government official.

title: County Cavan
complex: County Cavan is a county in Ireland. <s> It is in the province of Ulster and is part of the Border Region. <s> It is named after the town of Cavan and is based on the historic Gaelic territory of East Breffny ("Bréifne"). <s> Cavan County Council is the local authority for the county, which had a population of 76,176 at the 2016 census. <s> Cavan borders six counties: Leitrim to the west, Fermanagh and Monaghan to the north, Meath to the south-east, Longford to the south-west and Westmeath to the south. <s> Cavan shares a 70 km border with County Fermanagh in Northern Ireland. <s> Cavan is the 19th largest of the 32 counties in area and the 25th largest by population. <s> The county is characterised by drumlin countryside dotted with many lakes and hills. <s> The north-western area of the county is sparsely populated and mountainous. <s> The Breifne Mountains contain the highest point, Cuilcagh, at 665 m . <s> Cavan is the source of many rivers. <s> Shannon Pot on the slopes of Cuilcagh is the source of the River Shannon, the longest river in Ireland at 386 km . <s> The River Erne is a major river which rises from Beaghy Lough, two miles (3 km) south of Stradone in Cavan and flows for 120 km to Lough Erne. <s> Other rivers in the county include the Blackwater River, which rises near Bailieborough and flows through Lough Ramor, joining the River Boyne at Navan; the Dee which springs near Bailieborough; the River Annalee which flows from Lough Sillan and joins the Erne; and the Cladagh river which rises from Cuilcagh and flows into Fermanagh. <s> The Glyde and the Owenroe also source in Cavan. <s> Cavan is known as 'The Lakeland County' and is reputed to contain 365 lakes. <s> At 18.8 km2 , Lough Sheelin is the county's largest lake; it is situated in the south of the county and forms a three way border on its waters between counties Meath, Westmeath and Cavan. <s> A large complex of lakes form in the north and west of Cavan into designated Specially Protected Areas (SPA); an example is Lough Oughter. <s> Other important wildlife protected lakes such as Lough Gowna and Lough Ramor are in the south and east of the county. <s> Cavan has a mainly hilly (drumlin) landscape and contains just under 7000 ha of forested area, 3.6% of Cavan's total land area. <s> The county contains forests such as Bellamont Forest near Cootehill, Killykeen Forest Park at Lough Oughter (a Coillte state forest concern), Dún na Rí Forest Park and the Burren Forest. <s> In medieval times, the area of Cavan was part of the petty kingdom of East Bréifne or Brefney O'Reilly after its ruling Gaelic family. <s> This in turn was a division of the 11th century Kingdom of Bréifne. <s> For this reason the county is colloquially known as the Breffni County. <s> A high degree of defence was achieved by using the natural landscape of drumlin hills and loughs. <s> The poorly drained heavy clay soils contributed as an obstacle against invasion. <s> Historically, Cavan was part of the western province of Connacht, but was transferred to Ulster in 1584 following the composition of Breifne. <s> In the south, the Lough Sheelin area was part of Leinster until the late 14th century. <s> Parts of Cavan were subjected to Norman influence from the twelfth century and the remains of several motte and bailie fortifications are still visible mainly in the east of the county, as well as the remains of stronger works such as Castlerahan and Clogh Oughter castle. <s> The influence of several monastic orders also owes its origins to around this time with abbey remains existent in locations such as Drumlane and Trinity Island. <s> The Plantation of Ulster from 1610 saw the settlement and origins of several new towns within the county that include Bailieborough, Cootehill, Killeshandra and Virginia. <s> Existing towns such as Cavan and Belturbet became over time more important as trading centres. <s> Wars during the mid-seventeenth century aimed at trying to unsettle the Plantation only led to further plantations of English and Scottish settlers into the county and the beginnings of a thriving flax and linen industry. <s> Agriculture is the largest industry in the county, especially dairy milk processing as well as pig and beef farming. <s> Much of Cavan's land consists of clay soils, which are rich in minerals, but heavy and poorly drained, making pasture farming the dominant farming system in the county. <s> There is a total farmed area of 144269 ha in the county, and there are approximately 219,568 cattle in Cavan. <s> Lakeland Dairies Group, which is based in Killeshandra and has manufacturing sites located throughout Cavan, is Ireland's second largest dairy co-operative with an annual revenue of €545 million. <s> Cavan is one of Ireland's leading counties for pig production, with the county's farms raising a fifth of the national pig herd. <s> Pig farming regulations have put pressure on the industry, which is highly dependent on affordable credit. <s> Traditionally an agricultural economy, Cavan has since expanded in other industries, chiefly quarrying, energy production and manufacturing facilities. <s> As of April 2012, Cavan produces 122.02 megawatts of wind energy. <s> The largest wind farm is at Bindoo, which produces 48 megawatts of energy. <s> Peat cutting exists in the northwest of the county, in the Cuilcagh range. <s> Major industries such as Quinn Quaries and Gypsum Industries are also important employers within the county.
simple: County Cavan (in Gaelic, ) is a county in Ireland. <s> It is part of the Border Region as it is on the border with Northern Ireland. <s> It is part of the province of Ulster. <s> It is named after the town of Cavan. <s> Cavan borders six other counties: Leitrim to the west, Fermanagh and Monaghan to the north, Meath to the south-east, Longford to the south-west and Westmeath to the south. <s> The county has a lot of countryside with many lakes and small hills called drumlins. <s> Not many people live in the north-western area of the county as there are many mountains. <s> The highest point of the county is in the Breifne mountains, mount Cuilcagh at 665 m. <s> Many rivers in Ireland start in County Cavan. <s> The Shannon Pot is the source of the River Shannon, the longest river in Ireland at 386 km. <s> The River Erne is a major river which rises from Beaghy Lough south of Stradone in Cavan and flows for 120 km to Lough Erne. <s> Cavan is known as 'The Lakeland County' and it is said it has 365 lakes, one for every day of the year. <s> At 18.8 km2, Lough Sheelin is the county's largest lake situated in the south of the county. <s> A large area of lakes in the north and west of Cavan are marked as Specially Protected Areas (SPA), example of this being Lough Oughter. <s> Other important wildlife protected lakes such as Lough Gowna and Lough Ramor are in the south and east of the county. <s> The county contains forests such as Bellamont Forest near Cootehill, Killykeen Forest Park at Lough Oughter (a Coillte state forest), Dún na Rí Forest Park and the Burren Forest. <s> In medieval times, the area of Cavan was part of East Bréifne after its ruling Gaelic family. <s> This in was a division of the 11th century Kingdom of Bréifne. <s> For this reason the county is also sometimes known as the Breffni County. <s> The natural landscape of drumlin hills and loughs made a good defence against invaders. <s> Historically, Cavan was part of the western province of Connacht, but was transferred to Ulster in 1584 when Bréifne was shired and became the county of Cavan. <s> In the south, the Lough Sheelin area was part of Leinster until the late 14th century. <s> Parts of Cavan were under Norman influence from the twelfth century. <s> The remains of several buildings from the time can still be seen at Castlerahan and Clogh Oughter castle. <s> There are also some remains of early abbeys in the county, like at Drumlane and Trinity Island. <s> The Plantation of Ulster from 1610 saw the settlement and origins of several new towns within the county like Bailieborough, Cootehill, Killeshandra and Virginia. <s> Existing towns such as Cavan and Belturbet became over time more important as trading centres. <s> Wars aimed at trying to unsettle the Plantation only led to further plantations of English and Scottish settlers into the county and the beginnings of a thriving flax and linen industry. <s> Agriculture is the largest industry in the county, especially dairy milk processing as well as pig and beef farming. <s> Much of Cavan's land is clay soils, which are rich in minerals, but heavy and poorly drained, making pasture farming the dominant farming system in the county. <s> There is a total farmed area of 144269 ha in the county, and there are approximately 219,568 cattle in Cavan. <s> Cavan has expanded in other industries, mainly quarrying, energy production and manufacturing facilities. <s> Peat cutting exists in the northwest of the county, in the Cuilcagh range.

title: Kyriakos Mitsotakis
complex: Kyriakos Mitsotakis ( ; born 4 March 1968) is a Greek politician serving as Prime Minister of Greece since 2019. <s> A member of New Democracy, he has been its president since 2016. <s> Mitsotakis previously was Leader of the Opposition from 2016 to 2019 and Minister of Administrative Reform from 2013 to 2015. <s> He was first elected to the Hellenic Parliament for the Athens B constituency in 2004. <s> After New Democracy suffered two election defeats in 2015, he was elected the party's leader in January 2016. <s> Three years later, on 7 July 2019, he led his party to a majority in the 2019 election, their first since 2007. <s> He is the son of former Prime Minister Konstantinos Mitsotakis. <s> During the 2000 legislative election, Mitsotakis worked for New Democracy's national campaign.
simple: Kyriakos Mitsotakis (; born 4 March 1968) is a Greek politician. <s> He became Prime Minister of Greece on 8 July 2019. <s> He served as Minister of Administrative Reform from 2013 to 2015. <s> Mitsotakis has been a member of the Hellenic Parliament since 2004. <s> He is the son of former Prime Minister Konstantinos Mitsotakis.

title: Murmansk State Technical University
complex: Murmansk State Technical University or MSTU is one of the oldest universities on the Kola peninsula. <s> The university was founded in 1950. <s> Initially it had a name of the High Marine School (HMS).
simple: The Murmansk State Technical University (Russian: Мурманский Государственный Технический Университет, "Murmanskiy Gosudarstvennyy Tekhnicheskiy Universitet"; abbreviated as MSTU in English and МГТУ in Russian) is a public university in Murmansk. <s> It was founded in 1950 as the Murmansk High Marine School (Russian: Мурманское Высшее Мореходное Училище).

title: Drive-through
complex: A drive-through or drive-thru (a sensational spelling of the word "through"), is a type of service provided by a business that allows customers to purchase products without leaving their cars. <s> The format was pioneered in the United States in the 1930s by Jordan Martin, but has since spread to other countries.
simple: A drive-thru (or drive-through) is for quick service, generally at restaurants.

title: Biographical Directory of the United States Congress
complex: The Biographical Directory of the United States Congress is a biographical dictionary of all present and former members of the United States Congress and its predecessor, the Continental Congress. <s> Also included are Delegates from territories and the District of Columbia and Resident Commissioners from the Philippines and Puerto Rico.
simple: The Biographical Directory of the United States Congress is a biographical dictionary of all present and former members of the United States Congress. <s> It also includes all members of the Continental Congress. <s> It also includes delegates from territories and the District of Columbia and Resident Commissioners from the Philippines and Puerto Rico.

title: Pin stripes
complex: Pinstripes are a pattern of very thin stripes of any color running in parallel often found in cloth. <s> The pinstriped suit has become associated with conservative business attire, although many designers now produce the fashionable pinstripe patterns for fashion-conscious consumers. <s> Although found mostly in men's suits, any type of fabric can be pinstriped. <s> The Chicago Cubs' baseball uniforms have had pinstripes since 1907 and they are recognized as the first Major League Baseball team to incorporate pinstriping into a baseball uniform Many other former and current Major League Baseball teams—including the Florida Marlins, Minnesota Twins, Montreal Expos, Colorado Rockies, New York Mets, New York Yankees, Chicago White Sox, and Philadelphia Phillies—later adopted pinstripes on their own uniforms. <s> The Yankees, in particular, are associated with the pattern.
simple: Pin stripes are a pattern of very thin stripes running in parallel found in cloth. <s> Although pin stripes are found in mostly in men's suits, any type of fabric can be pin striped. <s> In baseball, the Chicago Cubs baseball uniforms have had pin stripes since 1907 and they are recognized as the first Major League Baseball team to have pin striping onto a baseball uniform. <s> Many other Major League Baseball teams like the Montreal Expos and New York Yankees later put pin stripes on their own uniforms.

title: Perm Krai
