complex: Perm Krai (Russian: , ) is a federal subject of Russia (a krai) that came into existence on December 1, 2005 as a result of the 2004 referendum on the merger of Perm Oblast and Komi-Permyak Autonomous Okrug. <s> The city of Perm is the administrative center. <s> The population of the krai was 2,635,276 according to the (2010 Census). <s> Perm Krai is located in the east of the East European Plain and the western slope of the Middle Ural Mountains. <s> 99.8% of its area is in Europe, 0.2% in Asia. <s> The krai borders stretch for over 2200 km . <s> The highest point is Mount Tulymsky Kamen at 1496 m . <s> Rivers of Perm Krai belong to the Kama River Basin, the largest tributary of Volga River. <s> There are more than 29,000 rivers in Perm Krai. <s> The total length of all rivers is more than 90000 km . <s> Only two rivers in Perm Krai have lengths exceeding 500 km .
simple: Perm Krai is a "krai" (federal territory) of Russia that came into existence on 1 December 2005 as a result of the 2004 referendum on the merger of Perm Oblast (province) and Komi–Permyak self-governing district. <s> The city of Perm became the administrative center of the new federal subject. <s> Perm Krai is located in the east of the East European Plain and the western slope of the Middle Ural Mountains. <s> The Ural Mountains are in the eastern part of Perm Krai. <s> The highest mountain Tulysmsky Kamen (1496 m) is in the north east of the territory. <s> Rivers of Perm Krai belong to the Kama River Basin, the largest tributary of the Volga River. <s> There are more than 29,000 rivers in Perm Krai. <s> Together they are more than 90000 km long, but only two rivers have lengths exceeding 500 km; the Kama (1120 km) and the Chusovaya (592 km).

title: Marlins Park
complex: Prior to the construction of Marlins Park, the Marlins played home games at what was originally known as Joe Robbie Stadium in Miami Gardens, which was known by a number of different names during the Marlins' tenure there. <s> Joe Robbie Stadium was built in 1987 as home to the Miami Dolphins of the National Football League (NFL), and was designed as a multi-purpose stadium built primarily for football, but its design also accommodated baseball and soccer.
simple: Before Marlins Park opened in 2012, the team, then known as the Florida Marlins, played home games at the venue now known as Hard Rock Stadium.

title: Kerry McCarthy
complex: Kerry Gillian McCarthy (born 26 March 1965) is a British Labour Party politician who has been the Member of Parliament (MP) for Bristol East since 2005 and was the Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs from September 2015 to June 2016. <s> After being re-elected with an increased majority in the 2015 General Election, McCarthy nominated Andy Burnham in that year's Labour leadership campaign.
simple: Kerry Gillian McCarthy (born 26 March 1965) is a British Labour Party politician. <s> She has been the Member of Parliament (MP) for Bristol East since 2005 and was the Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs from September 2015 to June 2016.

title: Litteau
complex: Litteau is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France. <s> The 19th-century poet Hippolyte Guérin was born in Litteau.
simple: Litteau is a commune.

title: Sol Invictus
complex: Sol Invictus ("Unconquered Sun") was the official sun god of the later Roman Empire and a patron of soldiers. <s> On 25 December AD 274, the Roman emperor Aurelian made it an official cult alongside the traditional Roman cults.
simple: Sol Invictus ("the Unconquered Sun") or, more fully, Deus Sol Invictus ("the Unconquered Sun God") was a religious title applied to at least three distinct deities during the later Roman Empire: El Gabal, Mithras, and Sol.

title: Kappa
complex: Kappa (uppercase Κ, lowercase κ or cursive κ; , "káppa") is the 10th letter of the Greek alphabet, used to represent the sound in Ancient and Modern Greek. <s> In the system of Greek numerals, has a value of 20. <s> It was derived from the Phoenician letter kaph . <s> Letters that arose from kappa include the Roman K and Cyrillic К.
simple: Kappa (uppercase/lowercase Κ κ), is the letter of the Greek alphabet, used to represent the "k" sound in Ancient and Modern Greek. <s> The letter κ denotes always the sound "k" in Greek. <s> In the system of Greek numerals, it has a value of 20. <s> Letters that came from it include the Roman K and Cyrillic К.

title: Obstalden
complex: Obstalden is a former municipality in the canton of Glarus in Switzerland. <s> Effective from 1 January 2011, Obstalden is part of the municipality of Glarus Nord.
simple: Obstalden is a former municipality of the canton of Glarus in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2011 the former municipalities of Obstalden, Bilten, Filzbach, Mollis, Mühlehorn, Näfels, Niederurnen and Oberurnen merged into the new municipality of Glarus Nord

title: Ned Zelic
complex: Nedjeljko "Ned" Zelic (] ; born 4 July 1971) is an Australian former footballer. <s> He has played for the Australia youth, Olympic and senior teams, but made himself unavailable in November 1999 after disagreements with coach Frank Farina. <s> Zelic was captain of the Australian team that competed and finished 4th at the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona.
simple: Ned Zelić (born 4 July 1971) is a former Australian football player. <s> He has played for Australia national team.

title: Argis
complex: Argis is a French commune in the Ain department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region of eastern France. <s> The inhabitants of the commune are known as "Argissiens" or "Argissiennes". <s> There was a lordship and a castle in the Middle Ages.
simple: Argis is a commune. <s> It is in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region of the Ain department; in the east of France. <s> The inhabitants are the "Argissiens". <s> In the Middle Ages there was a castle in Argis; but it does not exist anymore.

title: HMS Supply (1759)
complex: Launched in 1759, the third HMS "Supply" was a Royal Navy armed tender that played an important part in the foundation of Australia. <s> The Navy sold her in 1792. <s> She then served commercially until about 1806. <s> She left Spithead on 13 May 1787, and arrived at Botany Bay on 18 January 1788 with the First Fleet under the command of Captain Arthur Phillip (who had transferred from at Cape Town). <s> She was captained by Henry Lidgbird Ball, the master was David Blackburn, and the surgeon was James Callam. <s> "Supply" was the first ship to sail into Port Jackson after the original Botany Bay landing was found unsuitable for settlement. <s> After the establishment of the initial settlement at Port Jackson, "Supply" was the link between the colony and Norfolk Island, making 10 trips. <s> Following the loss of "Sirius" in 1790, she became the colony's only link with the outside world. <s> On 17 April 1790, she was sent to Batavia for supplies, returning on 19 September, her captain having chartered a Dutch vessel, "Waaksamheid", to follow with more stores. <s> "Supply" left Port Jackson on 26 November 1791 and sailed via Cape Horn, reaching Plymouth on 21 April 1792. <s> The Admiralty sold her at auction in July 1792 and her new owners renamed her "Thomas and Nancy". <s> She then carried coal in the Thames area until 1806.
simple: HMS "Supply" was a small ship, an armed tender which sailed with the First Fleet. <s> The ships left England in May 1787 and arrived in Australia in January 1788. <s> After the setting up of the penal colony at Port Jackson, HMS "Supply" made ten trips to Norfolk Island. <s> When HMS "Sirius" was wrecked in 1790, the "Supply" was the new settlement's only ship. <s> In April 1790 she made a trip to Batavia to get more food. <s> She left for England in November 1791 and reached Plymouth on April 21 1792. <s> She was sold at auction in July 1792. <s> Renamed the "Thomas and Nancy" she carried coal on the Thames until 1806.

title: Maurane
complex: Claudine Luypaerts, better known as Maurane (] ; 12 November 1960 – 7 May 2018), was a Belgian singer and actress. <s> Claudine Luypaerts was born on 12 November 1960 in Ixelles, Brussels, to Guy-Philippe Luypaerts, a composer and director of Académie de Musique of Verviers, and Jeannie Patureaux, a piano teacher. <s> When she was a teenager she took part in several musical contests. <s> In 2012, she became a member of the Jury in "Nouvelle Star" broadcast on television station D8. <s> She and singer Pablo Villafranca had a daughter. <s> On 7 May 2018 Maurane was found dead at the age of 57 beside her bathtub at her home in Schaerbeek in the area of Brussels, Belgium.. <s> The following day, the magistrate of the Brussels public prosecutor's office confirms the opening of a judicial inquiry, although the death of the singer is not considered as suspect.
simple: Maurane (born Claudine Luypaerts; 12 November 1960 – 7 May 2018) was a Belgian singer and actress. <s> She was born in Ixelles, Belgium. <s> In 2012, she became a member of the Jury in "Nouvelle Star" broadcast on television station D8. <s> Maurane died in Schaerbeek, Belgian on 7 May 2018 of suspected cardiac arrest at the age of 57.

title: Beaulieu-sur-Oudon
complex: Beaulieu-sur-Oudon is a commune in the Mayenne department in northwestern France.
simple: Beaulieu-sur-Oudon is a commune of 401 people (1999).

title: Academic journal
complex: An academic or scholarly journal is a periodical publication in which scholarship relating to a particular academic discipline is published. <s> Academic journals serve as permanent and transparent forums for the presentation, scrutiny, and discussion of research. <s> They are usually peer-reviewed or refereed. <s> Content typically takes the form of articles presenting original research, review articles, and book reviews. <s> The purpose of an academic journal, according to Henry Oldenburg (the first editor of "Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society"), is to give researchers a venue to "impart their knowledge to one another, and contribute what they can to the Grand design of improving natural knowledge, and perfecting all Philosophical Arts, and Sciences." <s> The term "academic journal" applies to scholarly publications in all fields; this article discusses the aspects common to all academic field journals. <s> Scientific journals and journals of the quantitative social sciences vary in form and function from journals of the humanities and qualitative social sciences; their specific aspects are separately discussed.
simple: An academic or scholarly journal contains articles written by experts in a particular subject. <s> They usually contain articles presenting original research, review articles, and book reviews. <s> The purpose of an academic journal is to give researchers a place to exchange knowledge. <s> The term "academic journal" applies to scholarly publications in all fields. <s> Scientific journals and journals of the social sciences vary in form and function from journals of the humanities.

title: Union County, Arkansas
complex: Union County is a county located on the central southern border of the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 41,639. <s> The county seat is El Dorado. <s> The county was formed on November 2, 1829, and named in recognition of the citizens' petition for a new county, which said that they were petitioning "in the spirit of Union and Unity." <s> The county is directly adjacent to the south to Union Parish in the state of Louisiana.
simple: Union County is a county of the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 41,639. <s> The county seat is El Dorado. <s> It was founded on November 2, 1829.

title: Richard II (play)
complex: The Life and Death of King Richard the Second, commonly called Richard II, is a history play by William Shakespeare believed to have been written in approximately 1595. <s> It is based on the life of King Richard II of England (ruled 1377–1399) and is the first part of a tetralogy, referred to by some scholars as the Henriad, followed by three plays concerning Richard's successors: "Henry IV, Part 1"; "Henry IV, Part 2"; and "Henry V".
simple: Richard II is a play by William Shakespeare. <s> It is a history play. <s> "Richard II" was probably first printed in 1597.

title: Shelby County, Tennessee
complex: Shelby County is a county in the U.S. state of Tennessee. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 927,644.
simple: Shelby County is a county in the U.S. state of Tennessee.

title: Marianne Berglund
complex: Marianne Berglund (born 23 June 1963) is a Swedish former road racing cyclist. <s> On 3 September 1983 she won the women's road race during the UCI Road World Championships in Altenrhein, Switzerland. <s> She also won the Tour of Texas. <s> She rode in the 1984 Summer Olympics and the 1988 Summer Olympics. <s> In 1990, she won the first edition of Tjejtrampet.
simple: Marianne Berglund, born 23 June 1963 in Skellefteå, Sweden is a Swedish former road racing cyclinst. <s> She won the women's road race during the UCI Road World Championships in Altenrhein, Switzerland on 3 September. <s> She has also won the Tour of Texas. <s> She won the first edition of Tjejtrampet in the year of 1990.

title: The Magic Roundabout (film)
complex: The Magic Roundabout (released in France as Pollux - Le manège enchanté and redubbed in the United States as Doogal) is a 2005 French-British computer-animated adventure fantasy film based on the television series "The Magic Roundabout". <s> According to William H. Macy, Harvey Weinstein saw the film and decided to do an American version. <s> On 24 February 2006, the film was released in the United States as Doogal, and was produced by The Weinstein Company. <s> In the United States version, where audiences aren't as familiar with the series, the majority of the British cast's voice work was dubbed by American celebrities such as Chevy Chase (Train), Jimmy Fallon (Dylan), Whoopi Goldberg (Ermintrude), William H. Macy (Brian), Kevin Smith (Moose) and Jon Stewart (Zeebad).
simple: The Magic Roundabout (released in France as Pollux, le manège enchanté and in North America with a shortened form, Doogal) is an Anglo-French animated movie based on the television series of the same name. <s> The movie was released on February 11, 2005 in the United Kingdom and France, and on February 24, 2006 in North America.

title: Hans-Peter Briegel
complex: Hans-Peter Briegel (born 11 October 1955 in Rodenbach, West Germany) is a former German footballer and manager, who played as a defender or as a midfielder.
simple: Hans-Peter Briegel (born 11 October 1955) is a former German football player.

title: Noorderhaaks
complex: Noorderhaaks (] ), also called "Razende Bol" ("Raging Bull" in Dutch), is an uninhabited Dutch island in the North Sea, a few kilometres west of the Marsdiep which separates the island of Texel from the mainland of the Netherlands. <s> The island covers an area of around five km2, although the exact area varies due to tide and the dynamic nature of the area.
simple: Noorderhaaks or "Razende Bol" is an uninhabited small island of the province of North Holland, the Netherlands. <s> It covers an area of 4 km2.

title: Sabeen Mahmud
complex: Sabeen Mahmud (20 June 1974 – 24 April 2015) was a progressive Pakistani human rights activist and social worker who founded the Karachi-based cafe "The Second Floor". <s> She also presided over the Karachi branch of TiE. <s> During the late hours of 24 April 2015, Mahmud, while traveling in her Suzuki Swift (registration Number AWH 541), was fatally shot by gunmen near the DHA library on her way home after hosting a seminar. <s> As her car stopped at a red light less than 500 metres to the north of T2F, Saad Aziz who was riding a motorcycle driven by Aliur Rehman aka Tony rode up alongside it and shot Mahmud, who was in the driving seat, four or five times with a 9mm gun.
simple: Sabeen Mahmud was a Pakistani human rights activist and social NGO worker. <s> She was the founder and director of the Karachi-based cafe The Second Floor (T2F) and president of the Karachi branch of TiE. <s> On 24 April 2015, she was shot dead by unidentified gunmen in Karachi while on her way home after attending a seminar.

title: Haut-Loquin
complex: Haut-Loquin is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Haut-Loquin is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Landsbro
complex: Landsbro (] ) is a locality situated in Vetlanda Municipality, Jönköping County, Sweden with 1,426 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Landsbro is a locality in Vetlanda Municipality in Jönköping County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 1,426 people lived there.

title: Mason, Texas
complex: Mason is a city in, and the county seat of, Mason County, Texas, United States. <s> The city is an agricultural community on Comanche Creek southwest of Mason Mountain, on the Edwards Plateau and part of the Llano Uplift.
simple: Mason is a city in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> It is the county seat of Mason County.

title: Liechtenstein national ice hockey team
complex: The Liechtenstein national ice hockey team is the national ice hockey team of Liechtenstein, and an associate member of the International Ice Hockey Federation. <s> Liechtenstein were first admitted to the International Ice Hockey Federation as an associate member in 2001.
simple: The Liechtenstein national ice hockey team is the national ice hockey team of Liechtenstein. <s> It is a member of the International Ice Hockey Federation.

title: Roger de Montgomery, seigneur of Montgomery
complex: Roger de Montgomery (fl. 1027), seigneur of Montgomery and vicomte of the Hiémois. <s> Roger held the lands of Saint-Germain-de-Montgommery and Sainte-Foy-de-Montgommery, both of which show traces of early castles. <s> He acquired the office of vicomte of the Hiémois probably about the time Robert I became Duke in 1027. <s> In 1031–1032 he witnessed a charter to the abbey of St. Wandrille by Robert I, Duke of Normandy as vicomte. <s> Like Duke Robert, Roger began acquiring church properties, among these, 1025–27 , half the town of Bernay. <s> He took over a wood at 'Crispus Fagidus' which belonged to Jumièges Abbey in the 1030s. <s> He suppressed a market held by the same abbey and transferred it into his own domain. <s> He later returned the market to the abbey and paid restitution for their losses. <s> In 1035 at Robert I's death, his great uncle, Robert Archbishop of Rouen ruled Normandy as regent. <s> Roger seems to have lost favor with the young duke as well as his vicomte office as he signed an early charter of Duke William simply as Roger of Montgomery. <s> At the archbishop’s death in 1037, anarchy broke out in Normandy and among the rebels was Roger de Montgomery, formerly one of Duke Robert's closest companions, who, after being defeated in his own territory, fled to the court of Henry I of France. <s> Roger had been forced into exile by Osbern the Steward who was afterwards killed by William de Montgomery, Roger's son. <s> Roger died on February 7, 1055 in exile in Paris. <s> In 1068 his wife was still holding lands at Bures and Saint-Pair.
simple: Roger I de Montgomery, was the (lord) of Montgomery and vicomte of the Hiesmois in Normandy. <s> Roger held the lands of Saint-Germain-de-Montgommery and Sainte-Foy-de-Montgommery. <s> Both had traces of early castles. <s> He became the Viscount of the Heismois about the same time Robert I of Normandy became Duke in 1027. <s> But as the viscount he witnessed a royal charter to the abbey of St. Wandrille 1031–1032. <s> Like Duke Robert, Roger began taking properties that belonged to the church. <s> These included ( 1025–27) half the town of Bernay. <s> He took over a woodland at 'Crispus Fagidus' which belonged to Jumièges Abbey. <s> He put an end to a market held by the same abbey and took it into his own domain. <s> He returned the market to the abbey and paid restitution for their losses. <s> After 1035 Roger seems to have lost favor with the young duke William. <s> He signed an early charter of Duke William simply as 'Roger of Montgomery'. <s> In 1037 when rebellions broke out, Roger was one of the rebels. <s> When he was defeated he fled to the court of Henry I of France. <s> Roger was forced into exile by Osbern the Steward. <s> Osbern was later killed by William de Montgomery, Roger's son. <s> In 1068 his wife was still holding lands at Bures and Saint-Pair.

title: Promotional recording
complex: A promotional recording, or promo, or plug copy, is an audio or video recording distributed free, usually in order to promote a recording that is or soon will be commercially available. <s> Promos are normally sent directly to broadcasters, such as music radio and television stations, and to tastemakers, such as DJs and music journalists, in advance of the release of commercial editions, in the hope that airplay, reviews, and other forms of exposure will result and stimulate the public's interest in the commercial release. <s> Promos are often distributed in plain packaging, without the text or artwork that appears on the commercial version. <s> Typically a promo is marked with some variation of the following text: "Licensed for promotional use only. <s> It may also state that the promo is still the property of the distributor and is to be "returned upon demand." <s> However, it is not illegal to sell promotional recordings, and recalls of promos are extremely rare and unenforced. <s> Because promos are produced in smaller quantity than releases made available to the general public, they are sometimes considered valuable collectors' items. <s> They are never intended for sale in record stores. <s> In music, a buzz single or advance single is a track or promotional song, released by the label (typically) preceding the album's release. <s> The song(s) are released in order to bring attention to an album's release. <s> Buzz singles are not typically issued to radio as promotional singles, due to the fact that they are only intended to attract minor attention compared to a regular single.
simple: A promotional recording (or promo), is an audio or video recording that is released for free. <s> Promos are sent to broadcasters, such as music radios, television stations, tastemakers, DJs, and music journalists. <s> Promos are often released in plain packaging. <s> Most promos are marked with "Licensed for promotional use only. <s> However, it is not against the law to sell promotional recordings. <s> There has been recalls of promos, but this is rare and not forced by recording labels. <s> Because promos are released in smaller quantities than CD singles, they are sometimes considered a collectors item. <s> They are never released in record stores. <s> They are released to promote a song that will be released through an album.

title: Méré, Yonne
complex: Méré is a commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France.
simple: Méré is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Begoniaceae
complex: Begoniaceae is a family of flowering plants with two genera and about 1825 species occurring in the subtropics and tropics of both the New World and Old World. <s> All but one of the species are in the genus "Begonia". <s> The only other genus in the family, "Hillebrandia", is endemic to the Hawaiian Islands and has a single species. <s> Phylogenetic work supports "Hillebrandia" as the sister taxon to the rest of the family. <s> The genus "Symbegonia" was reduced to a section of "Begonia" in 2003, as molecular phylogenies had shown it to be derived from within that genus. <s> Members of the genus "Begonia" are well-known and popular houseplants.
simple: The Begoniaceae are a family of flowering plants with about 1400-1500 species occurring in the subtropics and tropics of both the New World and Old World. <s> All but one of the species are in the genus "Begonia". <s> The only other genus in the family, "Hillebrandia", is endemic to the Hawaiian Islands and has only one species. <s> has recently been reduced to a section of "Begonia".

title: Coprophagia
complex: Coprophagia or coprophagy is the consumption of feces. <s> The word is derived from the Greek κόπρος " ", "feces" and φαγεῖν " ", "to eat".
simple: Coprophagia is the eating of faeces.

title: Saint-Pantaléon, Vaucluse
complex: Saint-Pantaléon is a commune in the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region in southeastern France.
simple: Saint-Pantaléon, Vaucluse is a commune of 222 people (2015). <s> It is in the region Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur in the Vaucluse department in the south of France.

title: Thanjavur Taluk
complex: Thanjavur is a taluk of Thanjavur district of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu. <s> The headquarters of the taluk is the town of Thanjavur, which is also the seat of the district administration. <s> It has two revenue blocks: Budalur and Thanjavur. <s> According to the 2011 census, the taluk of Thanjavur had a population of 510,411 with 253,723 males and 256,688 females. <s> There were 1012 women for every 1000 men. <s> The taluk had a literacy rate of 78.51%. <s> Of the children less than six years of age, 23,251 were male and 21,749 were female.
simple: Thanjavur Taluk is a tehsil or taluk or administrative division of the Thanjavur district, Tamil Nadu, India. <s> The headquarters of the taluk is the town of Thanjavur, which is also the district headquarters. <s> It itself has been further divided into two revenue blocks: Budalur block and Thanjavur block. <s> According to the 2011 census, the taluk of Thanjavur had a population of 510,411 with 253,723 males and 256,688 females. <s> There were 1012 women for every 1000 men. <s> The taluk had a literacy rate of 78.51%. <s> Of the children less than six years of age, 23,251 were male and 21,749 were female.

title: Burmese language
complex: Below are some of the most commonly used classifiers in Burmese.

title: Mother (Gorky novel)
complex: Mother (Russian: Мать) is a novel written by Maxim Gorky in 1906 about revolutionary factory workers. <s> It was first published, in English, in "Appleton's Magazine" in 1906, then in Russian in 1907. <s> The work was translated into many languages, and was made into a number of films. <s> The German playwright Bertolt Brecht and his collaborators based their 1932 play "The Mother" on this novel.
simple: Mother ("") is a novel written by Maxim Gorky in 1906. <s> It was translated into many languages, many movies are also inspired by it. <s> The play "The Mother" by German playwright Bertolt Brecht is based on this novel.

title: Tim Finn
complex: Brian Timothy "Tim" Finn (born 25 June 1952) is a New Zealand singer and musician. <s> His musical career includes forming 1970s and 1980s New Zealand rock group Split Enz, a number of solo albums, temporary membership in his brother Neil's band Crowded House and joint efforts with Neil Finn as the Finn Brothers. <s> Brian Finn was born in Te Awamutu, New Zealand. <s> He went to Sacred Heart College, Auckland, a Catholic boarding school. <s> In 1971 he started a Bachelor of Arts degree at the University of Auckland. <s> There he jammed in music practice room 129 (later the name of a Split Enz song) with friends and future Split Enz bandmembers Mike Chunn, Robert Gillies, Philip Judd and Noel Crombie. <s> Music soon became more important to him than his studies. <s> In 1972 he quit university. <s> A few months later, Phil and Tim formed the group Split Ends, renamed Split Enz in 1975, shortly before they left New Zealand for Melbourne. <s> Their music moved towards a more mainstream sound in later years, with an eclecticism that incorporated influences from art rock, vaudeville, swing, punk, glam rock, rock and pop. <s> Between 1972 and 1977, Tim and Judd alternated as frontman for the band. <s> When Judd left the band, Tim Finn's younger brother Neil Finn took his place. <s> Finn had his first success away from Split Enz in 1981 when his discarded demo "They Won't Let My Girlfriend Talk to Me" became a top 10 hit for Australian band Jimmy and the Boys. <s> In 1983 Finn recorded his debut solo album, "Escapade", while still a member of Split Enz. <s> This met with major commercial success both in Australia and New Zealand, and yielded hit song "Fraction Too Much Friction", which revealed a more rhythm-based sound than Split Enz had been known for. <s> After contributing four songs to Split Enz album "Conflicting Emotions", Finn left the band permanently in June 1984, to focus on a solo career. <s> The following year he moved to London. <s> 1986 saw the release of his second solo album "Big Canoe". <s> The album utilised a wide variety of instrumentation, including guitars, orchestral backings and traditional Indian instruments - most notably on single "No Thunder, No Fire, No Rain", which was inspired by the Bhopal chemical disaster. <s> Though "Big Canoe" reached number three on the New Zealand charts, it failed to become the international breakthrough that Finn or record company Virgin had hoped. <s> During this time, Finn's focus also turned to soundtrack music, and he landed a few acting roles on-screen. <s> Finn has composed for a number of Australian films and TV productions, including 1981 teen tale "Puberty Blues" and comedy "Les Patterson Saves the World", which yielded Australian hit "You Saved the World". <s> Finn had a small part in Australian film "The Coca-Cola Kid" alongside then-girlfriend Greta Scacchi, and a larger one in her Italian-shot romance "La Donna della Luna" (The Moon Woman). <s> In late 1989, Finn was back living in Melbourne, recording his eponymous third album, "Tim Finn", for Capitol Records. <s> The album would yield strong reviews and New Zealand hit "Parihaka", based on a Maori village known for its campaign of passive resistance to European occupiers. <s> In early 1990, he began playing music with younger brother Neil, for an intended Finn brothers record. <s> After working together on some songs, Neil later proposed incorporating the tracks onto the latest album of Crowded House, the group he had formed after Split Enz dissolved. <s> Tim performed with the band to promote the band's album "Woodface", and co-wrote eight songs, including the hits "Weather with You" and "Four Seasons in One Day". <s> But some time during the tour which followed the album's American release, all concerned realised that the combination was not a good fit. <s> Finn returned to pursue his solo career. <s> Both Tim and Neil were made OBE for services to New Zealand music in the 1993 Queen's Birthday Honours List. <s> The brothers Finn collaborated on another album in 1995, playing most of the instruments themselves. <s> "Finn" was released as the first Finn Brothers release. <s> In support of this album, the brothers toured Europe, Australia and the USA. <s> Also in 1995, Finn formed the band ALT, with Irish musicians Andy White and Liam Ó Maonlaí (from band Hothouse Flowers). <s> ALT's name was formed from the initial letters of their names. <s> They released the album "Altitude" and toured Europe and Australasia. <s> 2000 also saw the release of album "", featuring Finn, and fellow New Zealand singer/songwriters Bic Runga, and Dave Dobbyn. <s> Recorded in August and September 2000 in venues around New Zealand, the album saw the three performers each equitably showcased. <s> Both the concerts and album feature all three performers providing vocal and instrumental backing on each other's songs. <s> The album spent 16 weeks in the New Zealand charts, and was finally released in the UK in May 2007. <s> In 2004, the Finn brothers released their second album, "Everyone Is Here". <s> The album was originally intended to be produced by Tony Visconti but the release has most production credits going to long-time Finn producer Mitchell Froom. <s> A "Mojo" magazine review stated that it contained "some of the most haunting music to bear the Finn imprint". <s> Finn was in a relationship with actress Greta Scacchi from 1983 to 1989. <s> He is currently married to television presenter Marie Azcona, formerly of MTV and TVNZ One's "Music Week". <s> Finn and Azcona have two children; a son, Harper, and a daughter, Elliot. <s> The pair have collaborated on several songs, some of which are featured on "Steel City", the dance show that Finn wrote. <s> Aside from co-writing two tracks with Azcona, Finn collaborated on another with former Split Enz member Mike Chunn. <s> "This discography relates to releases by Tim Finn only. <s> See Finn Brothers' discography, Crowded House discography and Split Enz discography for other related works."
simple: Brian Timothy "Tim" Finn, OBE (born 25 June 1952) is a singer-songwriter born in New Zealand. <s> Finn is most known for his music with his band Split Enz. <s> He has released solo albums, and was member of his brother Neil's band Crowded House. <s> He also released albums with Neil as the Finn Brothers. <s> Tim Finn was born in Te Awamutu, New Zealand. <s> He went to Sacred Heart College, Auckland, a Catholic boarding school. <s> In 1971 he completed a Bachelor of Arts degree at the University of Auckland. <s> It is there that he met Mike Chunn, Robert Gillies, Philip Judd and Noel Crombie. <s> Phil and Tim formed a band called Split Ends, which became Split Enz before they started to tour Australia. <s> Finn recorded his first solo album, "Escapade", in 1983. <s> This album was very successful in Australia and New Zealand. <s> Because of this, he decided to leave Split Enz in 1984. <s> In early 1985, Tim moved to London. <s> His second album "Big Canoe" was not as successful as the first album. <s> He had a bigger role in the movie "La Donna della Luna" (The Moon Woman). <s> In late 1989, he went to live in Melbourne. <s> He recorded his third album, "Tim Finn". <s> In early 1990 he joined Crowded House, the group Neil had formed after Split Enz split up. <s> Because of their success, Tim Finn and Neil Finn were made OBE for services to New Zealand music in the 1993 Queen's Birthday Honours List. <s> The album "Finn" was released in 1995. <s> Also in 1995, Finn worked with singers Andy White and Liam Ó Maonlaí. <s> They formed the band ALT. <s> They released the album "Altitude". <s> In 2000, the album "" was recorded featuring Finn, and New Zealand artists Bic Runga, and Dave Dobbyn. <s> The concerts and album have all three musicians singing and playing on each other's songs. <s> In 2004, the Finn brothers released their second album together, titled, "Everyone Is Here". <s> Finn married the television presenter Marie Azcona, formerly of MTV and TVNZ One's Music Week. <s> Finn and Azcona have two children; a son, Harper, and a daughter, Elliott. <s> They have worked together on several songs, some of which are featured on "Steel City" soundtrack. <s> "This discography relates to releases by Tim Finn only. <s> See Finn Brothers' discography, Crowded House discography and Split Enz discography for other related works."

title: Øivind Holmsen
complex: Øivind Holmsen (28 April 1912 in Oslo – 23 August 1996) was a Norwegian international footballer. <s> He played left back for Lyn and the 1936 Olympic bronze team. <s> He also played in the 1938 FIFA World Cup, and got 36 caps in total.
simple: Øivind Holmsen (28 April 1912 – 23 August 1996) was a Norwegian football player who played for the national team. <s> He was mostly known for winning a bronze medal with his team for placing third at the 1936 Summer Olympics football tournament.

title: Overcoat
complex: An overcoat is a type of long coat intended to be worn as the outermost garment, which usually extends below the knee. <s> Overcoats are most commonly used in winter when warmth is more important. <s> They are sometimes confused with or referred to as topcoats, which are shorter and end at or above the knees. <s> Topcoats and overcoats together are known as outercoats. <s> Unlike overcoats, topcoats are usually made from lighter weight cloth such as gabardine or covert, while overcoats are made from heavier cloth or fur.
simple: An overcoat is a long coat which is worn over other clothes. <s> They go below the knee in length. <s> A coat that is knee length is known as a topcoat.

title: The Trolleybus Museum at Sandtoft
complex: The Trolleybus Museum at Sandtoft is a transport museum which specialises in the preservation of trolleybuses. <s> It is located by the village of Sandtoft, near Belton on the Isle of Axholme in the English county of Lincolnshire.
simple: The Trolleybus Museum at Sandtoft is a transport museum that has old trolleybuses. <s> It is near to the village of Sandtoft, near Belton on the Isle of Axholme in the English county of Lincolnshire.

title: Yaakov Neeman
complex: Yaakov Neeman ( , 16 September 1939 – 1 January 2017) was an Israeli lawyer who also served as Minister of Justice and Minister of Finance. <s> Neeman was born to a religious Zionist family in Tel Aviv during the Mandate era. <s> He was educated at the Midrashiat Noam high-school yeshiva and completed his military service in the Golani Brigade.
simple: Yaakov Neeman (‎ , 16 September 1939 – 1 January 2017) was an Israeli lawyer and academic. <s> He was born in Tel Aviv.

title: Keuruu
complex: Keuruu is a town and municipality of Finland. <s> Neighbouring municipalities are Jämsä, Multia, Mänttä-Vilppula, Petäjävesi, Virrat and Ähtäri. <s> The municipality is unilingually Finnish.
simple: Keuruu is a town and municipality in Central Finland. <s> Keuruu is next to the municipalities of Jämsä, Multia, Mänttä-Vilppula, Petäjävesi, Virrat and Ähtäri.

title: Nando Gazzolo
complex: Ferdinando "Nando" Gazzolo (October 16, 1928 – November 16, 2015) was an Italian actor and voice actor. <s> Born in Savona, the son of the actor and voice actor Lauro Gazzolo and EIAR radio announcer Aida Ottaviani Piccolo, Gazzolo debuted at young age on radio, and in 1948, at twenty years old, he started his acting career entering the stage company led by Antonio Gandusio. <s> He achieved his first personal success in 1951, in the adaptation of "Antonio e Cleopatra" staged by Renzo Ricci. <s> He later worked on stage with Vittorio Gassman and Luigi Squarzina, among others, before focusing in voice acting and dubbing. <s> Gazzolo was also active in films and starred in several TV-series of good success. <s> Gazzolo died on 16 November 2015 in Nepi, aged 87.
simple: Ferdinando "Nando" Gazzolo (16 October 1928 – 16 November 2015) was an Italian actor and voice actor. <s> He was born in Savona, Italy. <s> Gazzolo died in Nepi, Italy from complications of pneumonia at the age of 87.

title: Ramon Menezes
complex: Ramon Menezes Hubner (born 30 June 1972), or simply Ramon, is a Brazilian former footballer who played as an attacking midfielder or forward, and who is a professional football manager.
simple: Ramon Menezes Hubner (born 30 June 1972) is a Brazilian football player.

simple: Karim Haggui (born 20 January 1984) is a Tunisian football player.

title: William Bennett
complex: William John Bennett (born July 31, 1943) is an American conservative pundit, politician, and political theorist, who served as Secretary of Education from 1985 to 1988 under President Ronald Reagan. <s> He also held the post of Director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy under George H. W. Bush. <s> Bennett was born July 31, 1943 in Brooklyn, the son of Nancy ("née" Walsh), a medical secretary, and F. Robert Bennett, a banker. <s> He moved to Washington, D.C., where he attended Gonzaga College High School. <s> He graduated from Williams College, where he was a member of the Kappa Alpha Society, and went on to earn a Ph.D. from the University of Texas at Austin in Political Philosophy. <s> He also has a J.D. from Harvard Law School.
simple: William John "Bill" Bennett (born July 31, 1943) is an American politician. <s> He was the third United States Secretary of Education. <s> He served from February 1985 through September 1988. <s> From 1989 to 1990, he served as the first Director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy. <s> Bennett was born in Brooklyn, New York. <s> He studied at Williams College, at the University of Texas-Austin, and at Harvard Law School.

title: Hyrynsalmi

simple: Hyrynsalmi is a municipality in Kainuu, Finland.

title: Trondheim Region
complex: The Trondheim Region is a statistical metropolitan region in the county of Trøndelag in Norway. <s> It is centered in the city of Trondheim.
simple: The Trondheim Region is a statistical metropolitan area in the counties of Sør-Trøndelag (population: 223,363) and Nord-Trøndelag (23,388) in Norway. <s> It is centered around the city of Trondheim.

title: Schoharie, New York
complex: Schoharie is a town in Schoharie County, New York. <s> The population was 3,299 at the 2000 census. <s> Although the English claimed New York province after taking control from the Dutch, the first European settlements in this area were by Palatine Germans in 1713, after the area was first explored in 1710/11. <s> These Germans were among nearly 3,000 German Protestant refugees who sailed to New York in 1710, on ships arranged by Queen Anne's government. <s> They were refugees from the religious warfare along the border with France, and also had suffered the loss of crops from an extremely harsh winter in 1709, when the Rhine River froze. <s> The English believed the German settlers could help develop the colony and granted them land to the west of English settlements. <s> On October 6, 2018, a limousine crashed in Schoharie, killing 20 people.
simple: Schoharie is a town in Schoharie County, New York. <s> The population was 3,299 at the 2000 census. <s> It was first explored by Germans in the 1710s. <s> On October 6, 2018, a limousine crashed in Schoharie, killing 20 people.

title: Alexander Varshavsky
complex: Alexander Jacob Varshavsky ( ; born 8 November 1946) is a Russian-American biochemist, noted for his discovery of the N-end rule of ubiquitination. <s> A native of Moscow, he is currently researching at Caltech. <s> In 2014 he was awarded the $3 million Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences for his work and also the Albany Medical Center Prize.
simple: Alexander Jacob Varshavsky (; born 8 November 1946) is a Russian-American biochemist, noted for his discovery of the N-end rule of ubiquitination. <s> A native of Moscow, he is currently researching at Caltech. <s> In 2014 he was awarded the $3 million Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences for his work.

title: Marie Severin
complex: Marie Severin ( ; August 21, 1929 – August 29, 2018) was an American comics artist and colorist best known for her work for Marvel Comics and the 1950s' EC Comics. <s> She was inducted into the Will Eisner Comics Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Marie Severin was born in East Rockaway, New York, on Long Island, the second and last child of John Edward Severin, born in Oslo, Norway, who immigrated to the United States at age 3, and a mother, Marguerite (Powers) Severin, from Syracuse, New York, whose heritage was Irish. <s> Her older brother, John Severin, was born in 1922.
simple: Marie Severin (; August 21, 1929 – August 29, 2018) was an American comics artist and colorist. <s> She was best known for her work for Marvel Comics such as on "Spider-Man", "Thor", and "Iron Man" and the 1950s' EC Comics. <s> Severin died in Massapequa, New York on August 29, 2018 from a stroke at the age of 89. <s> Severin was added into the Will Eisner Comics Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Severin was born in East Rockaway, New York.

title: Georgetown, Guyana
complex: Georgetown is a city and the capital of Guyana, located in Region 4, which is also known as the Demerara-Mahaica region. <s> It is the country's largest urban centre. <s> It is situated on the Atlantic Ocean coast at the mouth of the Demerara River and it was nicknamed the 'Garden City of the Caribbean.'
simple: Georgetown is the capital city of Guyana. <s> It is located in the Demerara-Mahaica region. <s> It is the country's largest city.

title: Uli Hoeneß
complex: Ulrich "Uli" Hoeneß (] ; born 5 January 1952), is the president of German football club Bayern Munich and a retired footballer for West Germany who played as a forward for club and country. <s> Hoeneß represented Germany at one World Cup and two European Championships, winning one tournament in each competition.
simple: Uli Hoeneß (born 5 January 1952) is a former German football player.

title: Earthquake simulation
complex: Earthquake simulation applies a real or simulated vibrational input to a structure that possesses the essential features of a real seismic event. <s> Earthquake simulations are generally performed to study the effects of earthquakes on man-made engineered structures, or on natural features which may present a hazard during an earthquake. <s> Studying a building's response to an earthquake is performed by putting a model of the structure on a shake-table that simulates the seismic loading. <s> The earliest such experiments were performed more than a century ago. <s> Another way is to evaluate the earthquake performance analytically. <s> The very first earthquake simulations were performed by statically applying some "horizontal inertia forces", based on scaled peak ground accelerations, to a mathematical model of a building. <s> With the further development of computational technologies, static approaches began to give way to dynamic ones.
simple: Earthquake performance simulation is meant to study effect of earthquakes on building structures and is a practical way of seeing a thing to happen without it actually taking place in the same way. <s> The best way to do it is to put the structure on a shake-table that simulates the seismic loads and watch what may happen next (if you have no time to stand out in the field and wait for a real earthquake to strike, of course). <s> The earliest experiments like this were performed more than a century ago <s> Another way is to evaluate the earthquake performance analytically. <s> The very first earthquake simulations were performed by statically applying some "horizontal inertia forces", based on scaled peak ground accelerations, to a mathematical model of a building. <s> With the further development of computational technologies, statics approaches began to give way to dynamics ones.

title: Condette
complex: Condette is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Condette is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Brot-Dessous
complex: Brot-Dessous is a former municipality in the district of Boudry in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2016 it was absorbed into Rochefort.
simple: Brot-Dessous is a former municipality in the district of Boudry in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2016, it was merged into Rochefort.

title: John Abbot (poet)
complex: John Abbot (1587/1588 – c. 1650) was an English Roman Catholic clergyman and poet. <s> Abbot's birthplace is uncertain, but may have been London or Leicester. <s> He is believed to be the nephew both of George Abbot, the Archbishop of Canterbury and Robert Abbot, the bishop of Salisbury. <s> He was thus from a strongly Protestant family. <s> After being educated at Balliol College, Oxford, he travelled to the continent where he converted to Roman Catholicism. <s> On returning to England he was in Jesuit orders for a while, before working as a secular priest. <s> In 1635 he was imprisoned in the Gatehouse at the Palace of Westminster. <s> He was released within a year, but in 1637 he was again arrested, and seems to have spent the rest of his life in prison. <s> He was, along with other Catholic priests, condemned to death in 1641, but the conviction was never executed, and he appears to have died in prison in 1650. <s> Abbot's best known work is his poem "Devout Rhapsodies" (2 vols., 1647), about the war in heaven and the temptation and fall of man. <s> The work can be seen as a precursor of Milton's "Paradise Lost".
simple: John Abbot (1587/1588 – c. 1650) was an English Roman Catholic priest and poet. <s> Nobody knows where he was born, he might have been from either London or Leicester. <s> Abbot was from a strongly Protestant family because he was the nephew of George Abbot, the Archbishop of Canterbury, but after being educated at Balliol College, Oxford, he travelled to the European continent where he was converted to Roman Catholicism. <s> On returning to England he was in Jesuit orders for a while, before working as a priest. <s> In 1635 he was put in jail. <s> He was released within a year, but in 1637 he was again arrested, and spent the rest of his life in prison. <s> His best known work is his poem "Devout Rhapsodies" (2 vols., 1647), about the war between Good and Evil and the temptation and fall of man.

title: Bichelsee-Balterswil
complex: Bichelsee-Balterswil is a municipality in the district of Münchwilen in the canton of Thurgau in Switzerland. <s> It was formed from the union on January 1, 1996 of Bichelsee and Balterswil. <s> The municipality is located in the Münchwilen district. <s> It consists of the villages of Bichelsee and Balterswil and the hamlets of Höfli, Niederhofen am Bichelsee, Itaslen, Zielwies, Ifwil and Lochwies. <s> The lake Bichelsee is located in the municipality.
simple: Bichelsee-Balterswil is a municipality of the district of Münchwilen in the canton of Thurgau in Switzerland. <s> It was made from the union on January 1, 1996 of Bichelsee and Balterswil. <s> The lake Bichelsee is in the municipality.

title: Irtysh River
complex: The Irtysh River ( , "Erchis mörön", "erchleh", "twirl"; ; , Ertis, ; Chinese: 额尔齐斯河, pinyin: "É'ěrqísī hé", Xiao'erjing: عَعَرٿِسِ حْ; Uyghur: إيرتيش <s> The Irtysh's main tributaries include the Tobol River, Demyanka River and the Ishim River. <s> The Ob-Irtysh system forms a major drainage basin in Asia, encompassing most of Western Siberia and the Altai Mountains.
simple: The Irtysh River (; ; / ; , ""Twirl""; Tatar: , "") is a river in Siberia and Kazakhstan. <s> The main tributary of the Irtysh is the Tobol River. <s> The Ob-Irtysh forms a major drainage basin in Asia, and covers most of Western Siberia and the Altay Mountains.

complex: Jack Hogan (born Richard Roland Benson, Jr.; November 25, 1929) is an American actor. <s> He is most notable for the role of PFC William G. Kirby on the 1960s television show "Combat!"

title: Wolbachia
complex: Wolbachia is a genus of gram-negative bacteria that infects arthropod species, including a high proportion of insects, and also some nematodes. <s> It is one of the most common parasitic microbes and is possibly the most common reproductive parasite in the biosphere. <s> Its interactions with its hosts are often complex, and in some cases have evolved to be mutualistic rather than parasitic.
simple: Wolbachia is a genus of bacteria which infects arthropod species, including a high proportion of insects. <s> It is one of the world's most common parasitic microbes and is possibly the most common reproductive parasite in the biosphere.

title: Noratus cemetery
complex: Noratus cemetery, also spelled Noraduz, is a medieval cemetery with a large number of early khachkars located in the village of Noratus, Gegharkunik marz near Gavar and Lake Sevan, 90 km north of Yerevan. <s> The oldest khachkars in the cemetery date back to the late 10th century. <s> During the revival of the khachkar tradition in the 16-17th centuries many khachkars were built under the yoke of the Safavid Empire when oriental influences seeped into Armenian art. <s> Three master carvers from this period carved khachkars in Noraduz, the most notable of whom was Kiram Kazmogh (1551-1610), his contemporaries were Arakel and Meliset. <s> The cemetery is spread over a seven hectare field containing almost a thousand khachkars each of them depicting unique ornamentation. <s> The majority of the khachkars are covered by moss and lichen. <s> Several tombstones in the cemetery depict carved scenes of weddings and farm life. <s> Adjacent to the old cemetery a new modern cemetery has been built separated by a long fence. <s> Nearby the cemetery in the village there is the Holy Virgin church built in the ninth century. <s> One of the khachkars from the cemetery was donated to the British Museum in 1977 by Catholicos Vazgen I. <s> The front face of the rectangular khachkar has a leaved-cross with two smaller crosses below that are framed with trefoil and bunches of grapes projecting from either side. <s> An inscription on the left side seeks God's mercy for a certain Aputayli. <s> A popular folktale associated with the cemetery concerns the invading army of Tamerlane. <s> According to one story the villagers placed helmets on top of the khachkars and leaned swords against them. <s> From a distance the khachkars looked like armed soldiers holding a defensive position as a result of which Tamerlane’s army retreated.
simple: Noraduz cemetery is a medieval cemetery with many ancient khachkars in the village of Noraduz, Gegharkunik marz near Gavar and Lake Sevan, 90 km north of Yerevan. <s> The oldest khachkars in the cemetery go back to the late 10th century. <s> During the revival of the khachkar tradition in the 16-17th centuries many khachkars were built under the yoke of the Safavid Empire when oriental influences seeped into Armenian art. <s> Three master carvers from this period carved khachkars in Noraduz, the most notable of whom was Kiram Kazmogh (1551-1610), his contemporaries were Arakel and Meliset. <s> Many tombstones in the cemetery show carved scenes of weddings and farm life. <s> A popular folktale involving the cemetery concerns the invading army of Tamerlane. <s> According to one story the villagers placed helmets on top of the khachkars and leaned swords against them. <s> From a distance the khachkars looked like armed soldiers holding a defensive position as a result of which Tamerlane’s army retreated.

title: Italian language in Croatia
complex: As of 2009, the Italian language is officially used in twenty cities and municipalities and ten other settlements in Croatia, according to the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages. <s> It is an officially recognized minority language in Istria County, where it is spoken by 6.83% of the population on the aggregate and closer to 50% of the population in certain subdivisions. <s> The 2011 Census in Croatia reported 17,807 ethnic Italians in the country (some 0.42% of the total population). <s> Ethnologue reported 70,000 persons whose first language is Italian or Venetian in 1998 (referring to Eugen Marinov's 1998 data). <s> This population was composed of 30,000 ethnic Italians and 40,000 ethnic Croats and persons declared regionally ("as Istrians"). <s> Native Italian speakers are largely concentrated along the western coast of peninsula Istria. <s> Because of Croatian trade and tourist relations with Italy, many Croats have some knowledge of the language (mostly in the service and tourist industries). <s> In the past the language had a much larger population than it does now: the Italian (Venetian speaking) population constituted well over half of the population of Istria and (according to the Italian linguist Bartoli) nearly one third of Dalmatians in the second half of the 18th century. <s> In Dalmatia, ethnic Italians underwent significant persecution in the 1800s, whereby, according to the Austrian census it had decreased from 22% in 1816 to 12.5% in 1853, down to a mere 2.9% in 1910. <s> For various reasons—mainly related to nationalism and armed conflict—the numbers of Italian speakers in Croatia declined during the 20th century, especially after the Second World War in a period known as the Istrian exodus, when about 90% Italian-speaking Istrians and Dalmatians left Yugoslav dominated areas in the eastern Adriatic. <s> The 2001 census in Croatia reported 19,636 ethnic Italians in the country. <s> In Istria County, local government services are provided in Croatian and Italian, including the tri-lingual (Croatian, Italian and English) official government website. <s> There are some Italian-language schools in the region of Istria: primary schools in Buje/Buie, Umag/Umago, Novigrad/Cittanova d'Istria, Poreč/Parenzo, and secondary schools in Pula/Pola and Rovinj/Rovigno.
simple: It is an officially recognized minority language in Istria County (where it is spoken by 7.69% of the population). <s> The 2001 census in Croatia reported 19,636 ethnic Italians in the country (some .44% of the total population). <s> Ethnologue reported 70,000 speakers in 1998: 40,000 ethnic Italians and 30,000 ethnic Croats and Istrian people. <s> Native Italian speakers are largely concentrated along the Adriatic coast. <s> In addition, roughly 120,000 Italian tourists visit Croatia each year, so many in the service and tourist industries have some knowledge of the language. <s> Historically, the language had a much larger population than it does now. <s> Government services are provided in Italian and Croatian in Istria County, including the official government website (which is also available in English). <s> There are four Italian-language schools in Istria: primary schools in Buje (Buie) and Novigrad (Cittanova) and secondary schools in Pula (Pola) and Rovinj (Rovigno).

title: Slim Dusty
complex: Slim Dusty, AO MBE (born David Gordon Kirkpatrick; 13 June 1927 – 19 September 2003) was an Australian country music singer-songwriter, guitarist and producer. <s> He was an Australian cultural icon and one of the country's most awarded stars, with a career spanning nearly seven decades and numerous recordings. <s> He was known to record songs in the legacy of Australia, particularly of bush life and renowned Australian bush poets Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson that represented the lifestyle. <s> The music genre was coined the "bush ballad", a style first made popular by Buddy Williams, the first artist to perform the genre in Australia, and also for his many trucking songs. <s> Dusty was the first Australian to have a No. 1 international hit song, with a version of Gordon Parsons' "A Pub with No Beer". <s> He received an unequalled 37 Golden Guitar and two Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) awards and was inducted into the ARIA Hall of Fame and Australian Roll of Renown. <s> At the time of his death, at the age of 76, Dusty had been working on his 106th album for EMI Records. <s> In 2007, his domestic record sales in Australia surpassed seven million. <s> During his lifetime, Dusty was considered an Australian National Treasure. <s> He performed "Waltzing Matilda", a very famous song in Australia, at the closing ceremony of the Sydney 2000 Olympic Games. <s> EMI Records' Australian sales of Dusty's records surpassed seven million in 2007. <s> Slim Dusty was Australia's most successful and prolific musical artist, with more Gold and Platinum albums than any other Australian artist.

title: Sanna Nielsen
complex: Sanna Viktoria Nielsen (born 27 November 1984) is a Swedish singer and television presenter. <s> After her seventh attempt, she won Melodifestivalen in 2014 with the song "Undo" and so represented Sweden in the Eurovision Song Contest 2014 in Copenhagen, Denmark, finishing in 3rd place overall. <s> Sanna was one of the Eurovision Song Contest 2015 commentators for Sweden and hosted Melodifestivalen 2015 along with comedian Robin Paulsson. <s> She was announced as the new presenter for the sing-along show "Allsång på Skansen" for the summer of 2016. <s> She hosted "Eurovision The Party" at the Tele2 Arena for the Eurovision Song Contest 2016. <s> Nielsen was born and grew up in the town of Edenryd in Bromölla Municipality, Skåne. <s> Her paternal grandfather was a Dane from Århus. <s> Nielsen's career started at several talent searches, the first being in 1992 in Olofström. <s> In 1994 she participated in a talent search in Kallinge and won with the song "Can You Feel the Love Tonight". <s> Nielsen performed with the danceband Mats Elmes between 1995 and 1996 at the age of eleven. <s> At the same time she reached the number one spot on the Svensktoppen chart with the song "Till en fågel". <s> Nielsen became the youngest person to reach number one at the chart. <s> In September 1996, Nielsen's debut album "Silvertoner" was released. <s> A reviewer of the album for "Göteborgs-Posten" compared Nielsen to Carola Häggkvist and Sissel Kyrkjebø. <s> During the following years Nielsen released the album "Min önskejul" in 1997 and the single "Time to Say Goodbye" in 1999. <s> During her high school years, she studied the Estetichal programme and music at Helenehoms Gymnastin in Malmö. <s> In December 2001, Nielsen participated in a Christmas tour along with Christer Sjögren, Sten Nilsson and Charlotte Perrelli. <s> In 2002 she toured with Roger Pontare and in December the same year she participated in a Christmas concert with Kalle Moraeus and Tito Beltran in both 2003 and 2004. <s> In February 2006, her second solo music album "Nära mej, nära dej" was released with lyrics and music by Fredrik Kempe and Marcos Ubeda. <s> In July–August 2007 she was on a new music tour called "Sommar, Sommar, Sommar" along with Shirley Clamp and Sonja Aldén. <s> In April 2008 the album "Stronger" was released, an album completely in English language, the first time Nielsen had such an album. <s> The same year the album "Our Christmas" was released, containing Christmas songs along with Shirley Clamp and Sonja Aldén. <s> In 2011, she released the album "I'm In Love". <s> In December 2013 Nielsen released her seventh studio album called "Min jul" with Christmas songs. <s> Nielsen has participated seven times in Melodifestivalen, Sweden's annual music competition and national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest. <s> She made her debut in 2001 performing "I går, i dag", which finished third.

title: Fact
complex: A fact is a thing that is known to be consistent with objective reality and can be proven to be true with evidence. <s> For example, "this sentence contains words" is a linguistic fact, and "the sun is a star" is a cosmological fact. <s> Further, "Abraham Lincoln was the 16th President of the United States" and "Abraham Lincoln was assassinated" are also both facts, of the historical type. <s> All of these statements have the "epistemic quality" of being "ontologically superior" to opinion or interpretation — they are either categorically necessary or supported by adequate historical documentation. <s> The usual test for a statement of fact is verifiability — that is whether it can be demonstrated to correspond to experience. <s> Standard reference works are often used to check facts. <s> Scientific facts are verified by repeatable careful observation or measurement by experiments or other means. <s> The word "fact" derives from the Latin "factum", and was first used in English with the same meaning: "a thing done or performed" a meaning now obsolete. <s> The common usage of "something that has really occurred or is the case" dates from the middle of the sixteenth century. <s> Fact is sometimes used synonymously with "truth", as distinct from opinions, falsehoods, or matters of taste. <s> This use is found in such phrases as, ""It is a fact that the cup is blue"" or ""Matter of fact"", and "... not history, nor fact, but imagination."
simple: A fact is a statement that is real or true, or a thing that can be shown to be real or true. <s> The usual test for a statement of fact is whether it can be seen to be true. <s> Standard reference works are often used to check facts. <s> Scientific facts are verified by careful observation or measurement (by experiments or other means). <s> A fact is something that has really happened or is actually the case. <s> An opinion is different from a fact.

title: North Waziristan
complex: North Waziristan District is a former agency of defunct Federally Administered Tribal Area and now a district in Bannu Division of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province in Pakistan. <s> It is the northern part of Waziristan, a mountainous region of northwest Pakistan, bordering Afghanistan and covering 4,707 km2 . <s> The capital city of North Waziristan is Miramshah. <s> North Waziristan comprises the area west and south-west of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa between the Kurram River (Tochi River) to the north and the Gomal River to the south. <s> Miranshah is district headquarter of North Waziristan. <s> The city of Bannu lies immediately to the east, while the largest town on the Afghan side of the border (Loya Paktia) is Khost.

title: Drug tolerance
complex: Drug tolerance is a pharmacological concept describing subjects' reduced reaction to a drug following its repeated use. <s> Increasing its dosage may re-amplify the drug's effects; however, this may accelerate tolerance, further reducing the drug's effects.
simple: Drug tolerance (or physiological tolerance) is a term used to describe that the organism gets used to a given substance. <s> Drug tolerance also means that over time a drug becomes less effective and larger amounts of the substance are needed to get the same effect.

title: Ocean gyre
complex: In oceanography, a gyre is any large system of circulating ocean currents, particularly those involved with large wind movements. <s> Gyres are caused by the Coriolis effect; planetary vorticity along with horizontal and vertical friction, determine the circulation patterns from the "wind stress curl" (torque). <s> The term "gyre" can be used to refer to any type of vortex in the air or the sea, even one that is man-made, but it is most commonly used in oceanography to refer to the major ocean systems. <s> Tropical gyres are less unified and tend to be mostly east-west with minor north-south extent. <s> The center of a subtropical gyre is a high pressure zone. <s> Circulation around the high pressure is clockwise in the northern hemisphere and counterclockwise in the southern hemisphere, due to the Coriolis effect. <s> The high pressure in the center is due to the westerly winds on the northern side of the gyre and easterly trade winds on the southern side. <s> These cause frictional surface currents towards the latitude at the center of the gyre. <s> Subpolar gyres form at high latitudes (around 60°). <s> Circulation of surface wind and ocean water is counterclockwise in the Northern Hemisphere, around a low-pressure area, such as the persistent Aleutian Low and the Icelandic Low. <s> Surface currents generally move outward from the center of the system. <s> This drives the Ekman transport, which creates an upwelling of nutrient-rich water from the lower depths.
simple: A gyre is a large system of ocean currents moving in a circle. <s> Gyres are caused by the Coriolis effect. <s> The term "gyre" can be used to mean any type of vortex in the air or the sea, but it is most used in oceanography for the major ocean current systems. <s> Tropical gyres tend to be mostly east-west with minor north-south extent. <s> The centre of a subtropical gyre is a high pressure area, which the ocean moves around. <s> The high pressure in the centre is due to the westerly winds on the northern side of the gyre and easterly winds on the southern side of the gyre. <s> These cause frictional surface currents towards the latitude at the centre of the gyre. <s> Subpolar gyres form at high latitudes (around 60°). <s> Surface currents generally move outward from the centre of the system.

title: David H. Hubel
complex: David Hunter Hubel (February 27, 1926 – September 22, 2013) was a Canadian American neurophysiologist noted for his studies of the structure and function of the visual cortex. <s> He was co-recipient with Torsten Wiesel of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (shared with Roger W. Sperry), for their discoveries concerning information processing in the visual system. <s> For much of his career, Hubel was the John Franklin Enders University Professor of Neurobiology at Harvard Medical School. <s> In 1978, Hubel and Wiesel were awarded the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize from Columbia University. <s> The Hubel and Wiesel experiments greatly expanded the scientific knowledge of sensory processing. <s> The partnership lasted over twenty years and became known as one of the most prominent research pairings in science. <s> In one experiment, done in 1959, they inserted a microelectrode into the primary visual cortex of an anesthetized cat. <s> They then projected patterns of light and dark on a screen in front of the cat. <s> They found that some neurons fired rapidly when presented with lines at one angle, while others responded best to another angle. <s> Some of these neurons responded to light patterns and dark patterns differently. <s> Hubel and Wiesel called these neurons simple cells." <s> Still other neurons, which they termed complex cells, detected edges regardless of where they were placed in the receptive field of the neuron and could preferentially detect motion in certain directions. <s> These studies showed how the visual system constructs complex representations of visual information from simple stimulus features. <s> Hubel and Wiesel received the Nobel Prize for two major contributions: firstly, their work on development of the visual system, which involved a description of ocular dominance columns in the 1960s and 1970s; and secondly, their work establishing a foundation for visual neurophysiology, describing how signals from the eye are processed by visual parcels in the neo-cortex to generate edge detectors, motion detectors, stereoscopic depth detectors and color detectors, building blocks of the visual scene. <s> By depriving kittens from using one eye, they showed that columns in the primary visual cortex receiving inputs from the other eye took over the areas that would normally receive input from the deprived eye. <s> This has important implications for the understanding of deprivation amblyopia, a type of visual loss due to unilateral visual deprivation during the so-called critical period. <s> These kittens also did not develop areas receiving input from both eyes, a feature needed for binocular vision. <s> Hubel and Wiesel's experiments showed that the ocular dominance develops irreversibly early in childhood development. <s> These studies opened the door for the understanding and treatment of childhood cataracts and strabismus. <s> They were also important in the study of cortical plasticity. <s> Hubel married Ruth Izzard in 1953; she died February 17, 2013. <s> The couple had three sons and four grandchildren. <s> He died in Lincoln, Massachusetts from kidney failure on September 22, 2013 at the age of 87.
simple: David Hunter Hubel (February 27, 1926 – September 22, 2013) was a Canadian neurophysiologist noted for his studies of the structure and function of the visual cortex. <s> David Hunter Hubel (February 27, 1926 – September 22, 2013) was a Professor of Neurobiology Emeritus at Harvard Medical School. <s> He was co-recipient with Torsten Wiesel of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (shared with Roger W. Sperry), for their discoveries concerning information processing in the visual system. <s> Hubel was co-recipient with Torsten Wiesel of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries about information processing in the visual system. <s> The prize was shared with Roger Sperry for his independent research on the cerebral hemispheres. <s> For much of his career, Hubel was the John Franklin Enders University Professor of Neurobiology at Harvard Medical School. <s> In 1978, Hubel and Wiesel were awarded the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize from Columbia University. <s> In one experiment, done in 1959, they inserted a microelectrode into the primary visual cortex of an anesthetized cat. <s> They then projected patterns of light and dark on a screen in front of the cat. <s> They found that some neurons fired rapidly when presented with lines at one angle, while others responded best to another angle. <s> Some of these neurons responded differently to light patterns than to dark patterns. <s> Hubel and Wiesel called these neurons 'simple cells'. <s> Still other neurons, which they called 'complex cells', detected edges regardless of how they were placed in the visual field, and could detect motion in certain directions. <s> These studies showed how the visual system constructs complex pictures of visual information from simple stimulus features. <s> By depriving kittens from using one eye, they showed that columns in the primary visual cortex receiving inputs from the other eye took over the areas that would normally receive input from the deprived eye. <s> These kittens did not develop areas receiving input from both eyes, a feature needed for binocular vision. <s> Hubel and Wiesel's experiments showed that ocular dominance (dominance of one eye is normal) develops early in childhood development, and cannot be reversed. <s> They did important work in the study of cortical plasticity (flexibility). <s> Hubel died of renal failure.
