title: Kamba people
complex: The Kamba or Akamba people are a Bantu ethnic group - or tribe - who live in the eastern and south eastern areas of Kenya, formerly Eastern Province of Kenya stretching east from Nairobi to Tsavo and north up to Embu, Kenya. <s> This land is called "Ukambani" which constitutes of Makueni County, Kitui County and Machakos County and coastal Counties of Kwale, Mombasa and Kilifi. <s> Kambas are also found in parts of Tana River County. <s> Sources vary on whether Kambas are the third, fourth or fifth largest ethnic group in Kenya. <s> They make up to 11 percent of Kenya's population. <s> They speak the Bantu Kikamba language as a mother tongue. <s> The Kamba are predominantly based in Machakos, Kitui and Makueni Counties of Kenya. <s> The total population of the Kamba stands at approximately 4.1 million. <s> The Kamba are also called Akamba or Wakamba. <s> The Kamba are of Bantu origin. <s> They are closely related in language and culture to the Kikuyu, Embu, Mbeere and Meru, and to some extent relates closely to Digos and Giriama people of the Kenyan coast.
simple: They live in the semi-arid Eastern Province of Kenya, from Nairobi east to Tsavo and north up to Embu, Kenya. <s> This land is called "Ukambani". <s> They are one of the largest ethnic group in Kenya. <s> They speak the Bantu Kikamba language as a mother tongue. <s> The Kamba mostly live in the Machakos District of Kenya. <s> The total population of the Kamba is about 4 million. <s> The Kamba are also called Kikamba, Kekamba, Masaku, Ukamba, Kitui and Mumoni. <s> The Kamba (Akamba in the plural) are a Bantu ethnic group.

title: Sound of...
complex: Sound of... is an annual BBC poll of music critics and industry figures to find the most promising new music talent. <s> It was first conducted by the BBC News website in 2003, and is now widely covered by the corporation's online, radio and TV outlets, as well as other media. <s> A 10-strong longlist is published each December, with a ranked shortlist and annual winner announced the following January.
simple: Sound of... is a yearly BBC poll of music critics and industry figures. <s> The people polled say who they think is the most promising new music talent. <s> It was first done by the BBC News website in 2003. <s> It is now widely covered by the corporation's online, radio and TV outlets, as well as other media. <s> A longlist of 15 artists is published each December. <s> A ranked shortlist and the yearly winner is announced the following January.

title: Acre-foot
complex: The acre-foot is a unit of volume commonly used in the United States in reference to large-scale water resources, such as reservoirs, aqueducts, canals, sewer flow capacity, irrigation water, and river flows. <s> An acre-foot equals approximately a 8 lane, 25 m long swimming pool. <s> Since an acre is defined as a chain by a furlong (i.e. 66 × ), an acre-foot is 43,560 cuft . <s> As a rule of thumb in U.S. water management, one acre-foot is taken to be the planned water usage of a suburban family household, annually. <s> In some areas of the desert Southwest, where water conservation is followed and often enforced, a typical family uses only about 0.25 acre-foot of water per year. <s> One acre-foot/year is approximately 893 gallons (3.38 m ) per day. <s> Water reservoir capacities in the U.S. are commonly given in thousands of acre-feet, abbreviated TAF.
simple: An acre-foot is a unit of volume used in the United States to measure large amounts of water resources. <s> An acre-foot is the amount of water it would take to cover an acre of land with water 1 ft deep. <s> It is about the same amount of water as a 8-lane, 25 m long competition swimming pool. <s> One acre-foot of water is the same as 43,560 cuft of water. <s> In some places in the deserts of the Southwestern United States, water conservation is a rule. <s> In these ares, a normal family only uses 0.25 acre-feet of water per year. <s> Large amounts of water can also be in thousands of acre-feet or TAF.

title: El Lissitzky
complex: Lazar Markovich Lissitzky ( , ; November 23 O.S. November 11 1890 – December 30, 1941), known as El Lissitzky , was a Russian artist, designer, photographer, typographer, polemicist and architect. <s> He was an important figure of the Russian avant-garde, helping develop suprematism with his mentor, Kazimir Malevich, and designing numerous exhibition displays and propaganda works for the Soviet Union. <s> His work greatly influenced the Bauhaus and constructivist movements, and he experimented with production techniques and stylistic devices that would go on to dominate 20th-century graphic design. <s> Lissitzky's entire career was laced with the belief that the artist could be an agent for change, later summarized with his edict, "das zielbewußte Schaffen" (goal-oriented creation). <s> Lissitzky, of Lithuanian Jewish оrigin, began his career illustrating Yiddish children's books in an effort to promote Jewish culture in Russia. <s> When only 15 he started teaching, a duty he would maintain for most of his life. <s> Over the years, he taught in a variety of positions, schools, and artistic media, spreading and exchanging ideas. <s> He took this ethic with him when he worked with Malevich in heading the suprematist art group UNOVIS, when he developed a variant suprematist series of his own, Proun, and further still in 1921, when he took up a job as the Russian cultural ambassador to Weimar Germany, working with and influencing important figures of the Bauhaus and De Stijl movements during his stay. <s> In his remaining years he brought significant innovation and change to typography, exhibition design, photomontage, and book design, producing critically respected works and winning international acclaim for his exhibition design. <s> This continued until his deathbed, where in 1941 he produced one of his last works – a Soviet propaganda poster rallying the people to construct more tanks for the fight against Nazi Germany. <s> In 2014, the heirs of the artist, in collaboration with Van Abbemuseum and leading worldwide scholars on the subject, the Lissitzky Foundation was established in order to preserve the artist's legacy and to prepare a catalogue raisonné of the artist's oeuvre. <s> In 1921, roughly concurrent with the demise of UNOVIS, suprematism was beginning to fracture into two ideologically adverse halves, one favoring Utopian, spiritual art and the other a more utilitarian art that served society. <s> Lissitzky was fully aligned with neither and left Vitebsk in 1921. <s> He took a job as a cultural representative of Russia and moved to Berlin where he was to establish contacts between Russian and German artists. <s> There he also took up work as a writer and designer for international magazines and journals while helping to promote the avant-garde through various gallery shows.
simple: Lazar Markovich Lissitzky (23 November O.S. November 11 1890 – 30 December 1941), better known as El Lissitzky, was a Russian artist, designer, photographer, typographer, and architect. <s> He was an important figure of the Russian avant-garde, helping develop suprematism with his mentor, Kazimir Malevich. <s> He designed exhibition displays and propaganda works for the former Soviet Union. <s> His work greatly influenced the Bauhaus and constructivist movements, and he experimented with techniques and ideas ine 20th-century graphic design. <s> El Lissitzky's entire career was based on his belief that the artist could be an agent for change. <s> Lissitzky, who was Jewish, began his career illustrating Yiddish children's books. <s> This was to promote Jewish culture in Russia, which had just ended its antisemitic laws. <s> He started teaching at 15; and taught throughout his life. <s> Over the years, he taught in a variety of positions, schools and artistic media, spreading and exchanging ideas. <s> He took this ethic with him when he worked with Malevich in the art group UNOVIS and when he worked his own. <s> In his remaining years he brought innovation and change to typography, exhibition design, photomontage, and book design. <s> He produced critically respected works and won international acclaim for his exhibition design. <s> In 1941 he produced one of his last works – a Soviet propaganda poster rallying the people to make more tanks for the fight against Nazi Germany. <s> He took up a job as the Russian cultural ambassador to Weimar Germany.

title: Monty Python's The Meaning of Life
complex: Monty Python's The Meaning of Life, also known simply as The Meaning of Life, is a 1983 British musical sketch comedy film written and performed by the Monty Python troupe, directed by Terry Jones. <s> It was the last film to feature all six Python members before Graham Chapman's death in 1989.
simple: Monty Python's The Meaning of Life is a 1983 British musical sketch comedy movie. <s> It is Monty Python's last movie.

title: Mike E. Clark
complex: Michael Earl Clark (born December 25, 1962) is an American record producer and DJ from Detroit, Michigan best known for working with Insane Clown Posse, Kid Rock, Prozak and Mickey Avalon. <s> Clark has also worked with George Clinton, Patti Smith, Primal Scream, R.L. Burnside and other noteworthy artists.
simple: Mike E. Clark is an American record producer and DJ. <s> He is best known for working with Insane Clown Posse. <s> Mike E. Clark has worked with famous musicians and groups like Insane Clown Posse, Kid Rock and George Clinton.

title: Chalcolithic
complex: The Chalcolithic , a name derived from the Greek: "khalkós", "copper" and from "líthos", "stone" or Copper Age, also known as the Eneolithic or Aeneolithic (from Latin "aeneus" "of copper") is an archaeological period which researchers usually regard as part of the broader Neolithic (although scholars originally defined it as a transition between the Neolithic and the Bronze Age). <s> In the context of Eastern Europe, archaeologists often prefer the term "Eneolithic" to "Chalcolithic" or other alternatives. <s> The Copper Age in the Ancient Near East began in the late 5th millennium BC and lasted for about a millennium before it gave rise to the Early Bronze Age. <s> The transition from the European Copper Age to Bronze Age Europe occurs about the same time, between the late 5th and the late 3rd millennia BC.
simple: It is also named "Chalcolithic" ( "khalkos" "copper" + "lithos" "stone"). <s> The Copper Age was a time period between the Neolithic and the Bronze Age.

title: Töss (river)
complex: The Töss is a river of the canton of Zürich. <s> It starts with the confluence of the Vordertöss and the Hindertöss in the Zürcher Oberland, at "Tössscheidi" on 796 m on the border between the munacipalities of Wald west of the Dägelschberg (1267 m ), east of the Hüttchopf (1231 m ), and north of the Tössstock (1153 m )). <s> The Töss flows to the north before it meets the main valley of its own name, Töss Valley ("Tösstal") just before Steg im Tösstal. <s> Here, the river and its valley turns to the west in order to flow through Bauma then turns to the north again. <s> West of the village Turbenthal it turns west again, and the valley gets even more ragged than before. <s> It traverses Winterthur on its most western part of the city, just northeast of the "Töss", a city mountain. <s> After joining the Eulach on the western exit of the city, the river Töss then continues more or less westnorthwestern and joins the Rhine after about 11 km on Rhine's large southern bend called "Tössegg" west of Teufen and just before Eglisau.
simple: The Töss is a river of the canton of Zurich, Switzerland. <s> The river begins in the Zürcher Oberland. <s> It flows along the Töss Valley ("Tösstal") past Winterthur. <s> It joins the Rhine at Tössegg near Teufen.

title: Tomáš Galásek
complex: Tomáš Galásek (] ; born 15 January 1973) is a Czech former football player and current manager. <s> He was a holding midfielder who was also strong as a centre-back.
simple: Tomáš Galásek (born 15 January 1973) is a Czech football player.

title: Univerzitet u Prištini Faculty of Arts
complex: The Faculty of Arts of Pristina ( or ) is the faculty of arts of the University of Pristina in North Kosovo . <s> The Faculty was founded in Pristina in 1973 as the Academy of Arts and got the present name in 1986. <s> During the Kosovo War of 1999 it was moved, first to Varvarin and later to Zvečan and Kosovska Mitrovica, where it is now. <s> It is part of the University of Pristina, provisionally relocated to Kosovska Mitrovica.
simple: The Faculty of Arts of Priština (Serbian: Факултет уметности у Приштини or Fakultet umetnosti u Prištini) is the faculty of arts of the University of Priština in Kosovo, Serbia. <s> The Faculty of Arts of Pristina was founded in 1973 as the Academy of Arts, and got its present name in 1986. <s> Because of Albanian terrorist attacks it was moved in 1999. <s> It first moved to Varvarin and later to Zvečan, where it is now. <s> It is part of the University of Priština temporarily relocated in Kosovska Mitrovica.

title: Haarlem
complex: Haarlem (] ; predecessor of "Harlem" in the English language) is a city and municipality in the Netherlands. <s> It is the capital of the province of North Holland and is situated at the northern edge of the Randstad, one of the most populated metropolitan areas in Europe.
simple: Haarlem is a city in the Netherlands and the capital of the province North Holland.

title: Bank of Israel
complex: The Bank of Israel (Hebrew: בנק ישראל , ) is the central bank of Israel. <s> The bank's headquarters is located in Kiryat HaMemshala in Jerusalem with a branch office in Tel Aviv. <s> The current governor is Amir Yaron.
simple: The Bank of Israel is the central bank of Israel. <s> It is in Kiryat HaMemshala in Jerusalem, and has a branch office in Tel Aviv. <s> The current governor of the bank is Karnit Flug.

title: Edvard Evers
complex: Edvard Evers (12 May 1853 – 22 October 1919) was a Swedish Lutheran priest and hymnwriter. <s> Edvard Evers is mostly famous for writing the lyrics of the Christmas carole "Jul, jul, strålande jul". <s> The song was composed by Gustaf Nordqvist and was first published in 1921.
simple: Edvard Evers (born May 12, 1853 in Uddevalla, Sweden, died October 22, 1919 in Stockholm) was a Swedish hymn writer and priest. <s> He is best known for writing the lyrics for the Christmas song "Jul, jul, strålande jul".

title: Eino Leino
complex: Eino Leino (birth name Armas Einar Leopold Lönnbohm) (6 July 1878 – 10 January 1926) was a Finnish poet and journalist and is considered one of the pioneers of Finnish poetry. <s> His poems combine modern and Finnish folk elements. <s> The style of much of his work is like the "Kalevala" and folk songs. <s> Nature, love, and despair are frequent themes in Leino's work. <s> He is beloved and widely read in Finland today.
simple: Eino Leino (6 July 1878 – 10 January 1926) was a Finnish poet and journalist. <s> He is considered to be one of the pioneers of Finnish poetry. <s> His poems combine modern and Finnish folk elements. <s> The style of much of his work is like the "Kalevala" and folk songs. <s> He was known for writing about love, sadness, and about nature.

title: List of men's national association football teams
complex: The national football teams included in this section are not members of FIFA, or of any of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> The teams are not eligible to enter the FIFA World Cup or any continental confederation championships. <s> FIFA's statutes do not allow member teams to compete against these sides without FIFA's prior permission. <s> There are seven United Nations member and observer states which are not members of FIFA or any of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> Five of them, however, have fielded national teams in unofficial friendlies, Olympic-level tournaments (such as the Pacific Games or Micronesian Games), or in tournaments held outside the auspices of FIFA. <s> These teams are listed below. <s> Three states with limited international recognition, de facto sovereign states, are full members of FIFA and are listed above: the Republic of China (as Chinese Taipei) and Palestine, which are members of FIFA and the AFC; Kosovo, which is a member of FIFA and UEFA. <s> None of the remaining de facto sovereign or partially recognized states are members of FIFA or any of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> The national associations representing all seven of these teams are members of ConIFA, an organization for teams representing unrecognized states, subnational regions, and stateless minorities. <s> The statutes further define 'country' as "an independent state recognized by the international community". <s> The main condition for joining FIFA is thus general international recognition as a nation state, which is usually associated with membership of the UN. <s> However, this rule is not applied retroactively, and 26 of FIFA's members are not internationally recognised sovereign nations. <s> Non-sovereign associations may still join FIFA or its affiliated confederations in specific circumstances. <s> FIFA have offered exceptions for associations representing a dependency where the application apply for membership is authorised by the association in its parent state. <s> The New Caledonia team was admitted under this regulation in 2004 on the grounds of the distance of New Caledonia from its 'parent' nation, France. <s> The applications for membership by Gibraltar, a territory of the UK and Kosovo, a sovereign state with limited international recognition, were both initially rejected by FIFA in line with the above policy. <s> However, the Court of Arbitration for Sport has rejected this decision and both teams were accepted in May 2016. <s> A variety of other national, separatist, sub-national, pseudo-national, and ethnic teams have formed international football organizations outside FIFA's jurisdiction, and play in international tournaments against each other. <s> The Confederation of Independent Football Associations (ConIFA), was founded with the aim of regularising non-FIFA international football, by having a two-year international tournament cycle, with the ConIFA World Football Cup in even numbered years, and continental tournaments in odd-numbered years. <s> This developed the work of the now-defunct N.F.-Board (Nouvelle Fédération-Board), founded in 2001. <s> ConIFA aims to help unrecognised national teams gain recognition, but also to provide a platform for representative teams of regions or diasporas, which do not have a place in a system of international football based on nation-states. <s> In some cases, participation in non-FIFA football has been a first step for teams who later sought (and in some cases, achieved) the right to participate in matches sanctioned by FIFA or one of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> For example, both Kosovo and Gibraltar played in non-FIFA football tournaments before being recognized by FIFA and UEFA. <s> These national teams no longer exist due to the dissolution of the nation or territory that they represented. <s> Only national teams that were once members of FIFA are listed below.
simple: The national football teams included in this section are not members of FIFA, or of any of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> The teams are not eligible to enter the FIFA World Cup or any continental confederation championships. <s> FIFA's statutes do not allow member teams to compete against these sides without FIFA's prior permission. <s> There are seven United Nations member and observer states which are not members of FIFA or any of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> Six of them, however, have fielded national teams in unofficial friendlies, Olympic-level tournaments (such as the Pacific Games or Micronesian Games), or in tournaments held outside the auspices of FIFA. <s> These teams are listed below. <s> There are eleven states with limited international recognition, de facto sovereign states, and associated states who are not members or observers of the United Nations. <s> Four of these have national teams which are listed above: the Republic of China, which is a member of FIFA and the AFC (as Chinese Taipei); the Cook Islands, which is a member of FIFA and the OFC; Kosovo, which is a member of FIFA and UEFA; and Niue, who has no membership in FIFA but is an associate member of the OFC. <s> None of the remaining seven de facto sovereign or partially recognized states are members of FIFA or any of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> The national associations representing all six of these teams are members of ConIFA, an organization for teams representing unrecognized states, subnational regions, and stateless minorities. <s> The main condition for joining FIFA is thus general international recognition as a nation state and membership of the UN. <s> However, this rule is not applied retroactively, and 26 of FIFA's members are not internationally recognised sovereign nations. <s> Non-sovereign associations may still join FIFA or its affiliated confederations in specific circumstances. <s> FIFA have offered exceptions for associations representing a dependency where the application apply for membership is authorised by the association in its parent state. <s> The New Caledonia team was admitted under this regulation in 2004 on the grounds of the distance of New Caledonia from its 'parent' nation, France. <s> The applications for membership by Gibraltar, a territory of the UK and Kosovo, a sovereign state with limited international recognition, were both initially rejected by FIFA in line with the above policy. <s> However, the Court of Arbitration for Sport has rejected this decision and both teams were accepted in May 2016. <s> A variety of other national, separatist, sub-national, pseudo-national, and ethnic teams have formed international football organizations outside FIFA's jurisdiction, and play in international tournaments against each other. <s> In 2013, a new organisation, the Confederation of Independent Football Associations (ConIFA), was founded to carry on this work, with a number of its members having previously been affiliated to the NF-Board. <s> ConIFA was founded with the aim of regularising non-FIFA international football, by having a two-year international tournament cycle, with the ConIFA World Football Cup in even numbered years, and continental tournaments in odd-numbered years. <s> The older of the two, the N.F.-Board (Nouvelle Fédération-Board), was founded in 2001 to promote international football among sovereign nations, unrecognised nations, regions and stateless peoples that are not members of FIFA, and to assist in their possible future membership of FIFA. <s> In some cases, participation in non-FIFA football has been a first step for teams who later sought (and in some cases, achieved) the right to participate in matches sanctioned by FIFA or one of its affiliated continental confederations. <s> For example, both Kosovo and Gibraltar played in non-FIFA football tournaments before being recognized by FIFA and UEFA. <s> These national teams no longer exist due to the dissolution of the nation or territory that they represented. <s> Only national teams that were once members of FIFA are listed below.

title: Dennison, Minnesota
complex: Dennison is a city in Goodhue and Rice counties in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> The population was 212 at the 2010 census. <s> Most of Dennison is in Goodhue County, with only a small part that extends into Rice County.
simple: Dennison is a city in Goodhue County and Rice County, Minnesota. <s> It has a population of 212 residents in 2010. <s> Most of it is in Goodhue.

title: Omsk
complex: Omsk ( ; Russian: ) is a city and the administrative center of Omsk Oblast, Russia, located in southwestern Siberia 2236 km from Moscow. <s> With a population of 1,154,116, it is Russia's second-largest city east of the Ural Mountains after Novosibirsk, and seventh by size nationally.
simple: Omsk is a city in Russia in the Siberia region.

title: Ian Wachtmeister
complex: Count Ian Melcher Shering Wachtmeister af Johannishus (] ; 24 December 1932 – 11 November 2017) was a Swedish industrialist and politician. <s> He was a member of the Swedish Riksdag from 1991 to 1994. <s> He was the son of Count Ted Wachtmeister and Adrienne, "née" De Geer. <s> Together with record company owner Bert Karlsson he founded the populist political party "New Democracy", and as party leader achieved parliamentary representation in the 1991 general election from Örebro County. <s> The party's criticism of the Swedish immigration politics generated accusations of racism. <s> Wachtmeister left the party in April 1994. <s> He died of cancer on 11 November 2017.
simple: Count Ian Melcher Shering Wachtmeister af Johannishus (]; 24 December 1932 – 11 November 2017) was a Swedish businessman and politician. <s> He was a member of the Swedish Riksdag from 1991 to 1994. <s> Together with record company owner Bert Karlsson he founded the populist political party "New Democracy", and as party leader achieved parliamentary representation in the 1991 general election from Örebro County. <s> Wachtmeister died of lymphoma on 11 November 2017 in Stockholm, Sweden at the age of 84.

title: Lina Wertmüller
complex: Lina Wertmüller (] ; born 14 August 1928) is an Italian screenwriter and film director. <s> She was the first woman nominated for an Academy Award for Best Director for "Seven Beauties" in 1977. <s> She is also known for her films "The Seduction of Mimi", "Love and Anarchy" and "Swept Away". <s> In 2019, Wertmüller was announced as one of the four recipients of the Academy Honorary Award for her career.
simple: Lina Wertmüller (]; born 14 August 1928) is an Italian screenwriter and movie director. <s> She was the first woman nominated for an Academy Award for Best Director for "Seven Beauties" in 1977. <s> She is also known for her movies "The Seduction of Mimi", "Love and Anarchy" and "Swept Away". <s> In 2019, Wertmüller was announced as one of the four recipients of the Academy Honorary Award for her career.

title: Susumu Katsumata (footballer)
complex: Susumu Katsumata (勝俣 進 , Katsumata Susumu , born February 17, 1956) is a former Japanese football player and manager.
simple: Susumu Katsumata (born 17 February 1956) is a former Japanese football player.

title: E-commerce
complex: E-commerce is the activity of buying or selling of products on online services or over the Internet. <s> Electronic commerce draws on technologies such as mobile commerce, electronic funds transfer, supply chain management, Internet marketing, online transaction processing, electronic data interchange (EDI), inventory management systems, and automated data collection systems. <s> E-commerce markets are growing at noticeable rates. <s> The online market is expected to grow by 56% in 2015–2020.
simple: Electronic commerce more well known as e-commerce, consists of the buying or selling of products via electronic means such as the internet or other electronic services. <s> This type of trade has been growing rapidly because of the expansion of the Internet.

title: A
complex: A (named , plural "As", "A's", "a"s, "a's" or "aes" ) is the first letter and the first vowel of the modern English alphabet and the ISO basic Latin alphabet. <s> It is similar to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives. <s> The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar. <s> The lowercase version can be written in two forms: the double-storey a and single-storey ɑ. <s> The latter is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type. <s> The earliest certain ancestor of "A" is aleph (also written 'aleph), the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet, which consisted entirely of consonants (for that reason, it is also called an abjad to distinguish it from a true alphabet). <s> In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended. <s> By 1600 BC, the Phoenician alphabet letter had a linear form that served as the base for some later forms. <s> Its name is thought to have corresponded closely to the Paleo-Hebrew or Arabic aleph. <s> When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter to represent the glottal stop—the consonant sound that the letter denoted in Phoenician and other Semitic languages, and that was the first phoneme of the Phoenician pronunciation of the letter—so they used their version of the sign to represent the vowel /a/ , and called it by the similar name of alpha. <s> In the earliest Greek inscriptions after the Greek Dark Ages, dating to the 8th century BC, the letter rests upon its side, but in the Greek alphabet of later times it generally resembles the modern capital letter, although many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set. <s> The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to their civilization in the Italian Peninsula and left the letter unchanged. <s> The Romans later adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write the Latin language, and the resulting letter was preserved in the Latin alphabet that would come to be used to write many languages, including English. <s> In algebra, the letter "a" along with other letters at the beginning of the alphabet is used to represent known quantities, whereas the letters at the end of the alphabet ("x", "y", "z") are used to denote unknown quantities. <s> In geometry, capital A, B, C etc. are used to denote segments, lines, rays, etc. <s> A capital A is also typically used as one of the letters to represent an angle in a triangle, the lowercase a representing the side opposite angle A.
simple: A is the first letter of the English alphabet. <s> The same letter of the Greek alphabet is named alpha. <s> The earliest letter 'A' has appeared was in the Phoenician alphabet's aleph. <s> The Greeks later modified this letter and used it as their letter alpha. <s> The Greek alphabet was used by the Etruscans in northern Italy, and the Romans later modified the Etruscan alphabet for their own language. <s> In algebra, the letter "A" along with other letters at the beginning of the alphabet is used to represent known quantities. <s> In geometry, capital A, B, C etc. are used to label line segments, lines, etc. <s> Also, A is typically used as one of the letters to label an angle in a triangle.

title: Fontaine-lès-Boulans
complex: Fontaine-lès-Boulans is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Fontaine-lès-Boulans is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Cypress Hill
complex: Cypress Hill is an American hip hop group from South Gate, California. <s> Cypress Hill was the first Latino American hip hop recording group to have a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame and platinum and multi-platinum albums, selling over 20 million albums worldwide. <s> They are considered to be among the main progenitors of West Coast rap and hip hop in the early 1990s, being critically acclaimed for their first four albums. <s> The band has also advocated for medical and recreational use of cannabis in the United States. <s> After recording a demo in 1989, Cypress Hill signed a record deal with Ruffhouse Records. <s> Their self-titled first album was released in August 1991. <s> The lead single was the double A-side "The Phuncky Feel One"/"How I Could Just Kill a Man" which received heavy airplay on urban and college radio. <s> The other two singles released from the album were "Hand on the Pump" and "Latin Lingo", the latter of which combined English and Spanish lyrics. <s> The success of these singles led to the album selling two million copies in the US alone. <s> Cypress Hill contributed the song "Shoot 'Em Up" to the soundtrack of the movie "Juice". <s> The group made their first appearance at Lollapalooza on the side stage in 1992. <s> "Black Sunday", the group's second album, debuted at number one on the "Billboard" 200 in 1993, Also in 1999, the band released a greatest-hits album in Spanish, "Los grandes éxitos en español". <s> In 2000, Cypress Hill then fused genres with their fifth album, "Skull & Bones", which was a Canada. <s> The first single was "Rock Superstar" for rock radio and "Rap Superstar" for urban radio. <s> Following the release of the album, Cypress Hill (along with MxPx) landed a slot opening for experimentation with rock on the "Stoned Raiders" album in 2001.

title: Jarosław Kaczyński
complex: Jarosław Aleksander Kaczyński (; born 18 June 1949) is a Polish politician and lawyer, and the current leader of the Law and Justice party (PiS by its Polish acronym), which he co-founded in 2001 with his identical twin brother, the late Polish President Lech Kaczyński. <s> Running for PiS, he served as Prime Minister of Poland from July 2006 to November 2007, while his brother was President of Poland. <s> After PiS's electoral defeat in 2007, Kaczyński was the main leader of the opposition to Civic Platform's governments. <s> Following the death of his brother in a plane crash, Jarosław Kaczyński ran against acting President Bronisław Komorowski in the Polish presidential election on 20 June 2010, but lost. <s> As children, Jarosław and Lech Kaczyński starred in the 1962 Polish film "The Two Who Stole the Moon" , based on a popular children's story by Kornel Makuszyński.
simple: Jarosław Aleksander Kaczyński (born 18 June 1949 in Warsaw) is a Polish politician. <s> He is also the chairman of Law and Justice ("Prawo i Sprawiedliwość"), a political party which he helped start in 2001. <s> He was Prime Minister of Poland from July 2006 to November 2007. <s> He ran for President in 2010, but was defeated by Civic Platform candidate Bronisław Komorowski. <s> As a child, he and his brother Lech Kaczyński starred in the 1962 Polish movie The Two Who Stole The Moon ("O dwóch takich, co ukradli księżyc"), based on a popular Polish children's story by Kornel Makuszyński.

title: Anthony Daniels
complex: Anthony Daniels (born 21 February 1946) is an English actor and mime artist. <s> He is best known for playing C-3PO in the "Star Wars" film series, beginning with the original 1977 film. <s> He is the only actor to have appeared in all of the episodic films in the series, as well as many of its spin-offs, including television shows, video games, radio serials, etc. <s> Daniels was born in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, the son of a plastics company executive. <s> He was educated at Giggleswick School and studied law for two years at university, then dropped out to participate in amateur dramatics and attend Rose Bruford College.
simple: Anthony Daniels (born 21 February 1946) is an English actor. <s> He played the droid C-3PO in the "Star Wars" series of movies made between 1977, 2005 and 2015. <s> Daniels was born in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England on 21 February 1946.

title: National Treasure (film)
complex: National Treasure is a 2004 American adventure film released by Walt Disney Pictures. <s> It was written by Jim Kouf and the Wibberleys, produced by Jerry Bruckheimer and directed by Jon Turteltaub. <s> It is the first film in the "National Treasure" film series and stars Nicolas Cage, Harvey Keitel, Jon Voight, Diane Kruger, Sean Bean, Justin Bartha and Christopher Plummer. <s> Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment released Blu-ray Disc versions of "National Treasure" and its sequel, "National Treasure 2: Book of Secrets", on May 20, 2008.
simple: National Treasure is a 2004 American action thriller movie starring Nicolas Cage. <s> Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment released Blu-ray Disc versions of "National Treasure" and its sequel, "National Treasure 2: Book of Secrets", on May 20, 2008.

title: Solar power in Spain
complex: Spain is one of the European countries with the most hours of sunshine. <s> The country initially had a leading role in the development of solar power. <s> Generous prices for grid connected solar power were offered to encourage the industry. <s> The boom in solar power installations were faster than anticipated and prices for grid connected solar power were not cut to reflect this, leading to a fast but unsustainable boom in installations. <s> Spain would find itself second only to Germany in the world for solar power installed capacity. <s> In the wake of the 2008 financial crisis, the Spanish government drastically cut its subsidies for solar power and capped future increases in capacity at 500 MW per year, with effects upon the industry worldwide. <s> Between 2012 and 2016, new installations stagnated in Spain while growth accelerated in other leading countries leaving Spain to lose much of its world leading status to countries such as Germany, China and Japan. <s> The controversial "sun tax" and intimidating regulation surrounding solar self consumption introduced in 2015 were only begun to be repealed in late 2018 by the new government. <s> Spain added a record 2.6 GW of solar photovoltaic power in 2008, a figure almost five times that of the next record year, increasing capacity to 3.5 GW. <s> Spain surpassed both Japan and the USA in 2008 as the number two market as measured by cumulative installed PV capacity behind the world leader at the time Germany, accounting for 24% of global PV capacity. <s> PV capacity added during 2008 would still account for more than half of total capacity as of 2016. <s> In 2008 the Spanish government committed to achieving a target of 12% of primary energy from renewable energy by 2010 and by 2020 expected the installed solar generating capacity of 10 GW. <s> Through a ministerial ruling in March 2004, the Spanish government removed economic barriers to the connection of renewable energy technologies to the electricity grid. <s> The Royal Decree 436/2004 equalized conditions for large-scale solar thermal and photovoltaic plants and guaranteed feed-in tariffs. <s> In March 2007, Europe's first commercial concentrating solar power tower plant was opened near the sunny Andalusian city of Seville. <s> The 11 MW plant, known as the PS10 solar power tower, produces electricity with 624 large heliostats. <s> Each of these mirrors has a surface measuring 120 square meters (1,290 square feet) that concentrates the Sun's rays to the top of a 115-meter (377 feet) high tower where a solar receiver and a steam turbine are located. <s> The turbine drives a generator, producing electricity. <s> Solar thermal power plants designed for solar-only generation are well matched to summer noon peak loads in prosperous areas with significant cooling demands, such as Spain. <s> Using thermal energy storage systems, solar thermal operating periods can even be extended to meet base-load needs. <s> BP Solar begun constructing a new solar photovoltaic cell manufacturing plant at its European headquarters in Tres Cantos, Madrid. <s> For phase one of the Madrid expansion, BP Solar aimed to expand its annual cell capacity from 55 MW to around 300 MW. <s> Construction of this facility was underway, with the first manufacturing line expected to be fully operational in 2009. <s> The new cell lines would use innovative screen-printing technology. <s> By fully automating wafer handling, the manufacturing lines would be able to handle the very thinnest of wafers available and ensure the highest quality. <s> Thin wafers are of particular importance since there has been a silicon shortage in recent years. <s> However, after the new national law limiting installed power by year, in April 2009 BP Solar closed its factories. <s> Since the beginning of 2007, Aleo Solar AG has also been manufacturing high-quality solar modules for the Spanish market at its own factory in Santa Maria de Palautordera near Barcelona. <s> In 2014 SITECNO S.A. took over this facility <s> The "Plataforma Solar de Almería" (PSA), part of the Center for Energy, Environment and Technological Research (CIEMAT), is a center for research, development, and testing of concentrating solar power technologies. <s> ISFOC in Puertollano is a development institute for concentrator photovoltaics (CPV) which evaluates CPV technologies at the pilot production scale to optimize operation and determine cost.
simple: Spain is one of the most attractive countries with regard to the development of solar energy, as it has the greatest amount of available sunshine of any country in Europe. <s> The Spanish government wants to produce 12 percent of primary energy from renewable energy by 2010. <s> Through a ministerial ruling in March 2004, the Spanish government removed economic barriers to grid-connection of renewable energy. <s> The widely applauded Royal Decree 436/2004 equalises conditions for large-scale thermal and photovoltaic plants and guarantees feed-in tariffs. <s> In March 2007, Europe's first commercial concentrating solar power tower plant was opened near the sunny southern Spanish city of Seville. <s> The 11 megawatt plant, known as the PS10 solar power tower, produces electricity with 624 large heliostats. <s> Each of these mirrors has a surface measuring 120 square meters (1,290 square feet) that concentrates the Sun's rays to the top of a 115 meter (377 foot) high tower where a solar receiver and a steam turbine are located. <s> The turbine drives a generator, producing electricity. <s> Solar thermal power plants designed for solar-only generation are ideally matched to summer noon peak loads in prosperous areas with significant cooling demands, such as Spain. <s> Using thermal energy storage systems, solar thermal operating periods can even be extended to meet base-load needs. <s> BP Solar has begun constructing a new solar photovoltaic (PV) solar cell manufacturing plant at its European headquarters in Tres Cantos, Madrid. <s> For phase one of the Madrid expansion, BP Solar is aiming to expand its annual cell capacity from 55 megawatts (MW) to around 300 MW. <s> Construction of this facility is underway, with the first manufacturing line expected to be fully operational this year. <s> The new cell lines use innovative screen-printing technology. <s> By fully automating wafer handling, the manufacturing lines will be able to handle the very thinnest of wafers available and ensure the highest quality. <s> Since the beginning of 2007, Aleo Solar AG has also been manufacturing high-quality solar modules for the Spanish market at its own factory in Santa Maria de Palautordera near Barcelona. <s> The Plataforma Solar de Almería (PSA) in Spain, part of the Center for Energy, Environment and Technological Research (CIEMAT), is the largest center for research, development, and testing of concentrating solar technologies in Europe.

title: Lateef Raji
complex: Lateef Oludare Raji (12 October 1962 – 14 August 2017) was a former adviser on information and strategy to former Lagos State Governor, Babatunde Raji Fashola. <s> He was also a commissioner to former Lagos state Governor Bola Tinubu. <s> He was a serving member of the Lagos State Independent Electoral Commission committee (LASIEC) before his death. <s> He contested for the House of Representatives Osodi/Isolo federal Constituency in 2011 under the platform of APC but didn't get the party ticket. <s> He was later sworn in as Special Adviser on Information and Strategy to former Lagos State Governor, Babatunde Raji Fashola between 2011 and 2015. <s> Raji died in the early hours of 14 August 2017 after suffering for a longtime from cancer of the throat. <s> And was later buried on the same day at his hometown in Idoani, Ondo state according to Islamic rite.
simple: Lateef Oludare Raji (12 October 1962 – 14 August 2017) was a Nigerian politician. <s> He was the former special adviser on Information and Strategy to former Lagos State Governor, Babatunde Raji Fashola. <s> He was also a commissioner to former Lagos state Governor Bola Tinubu. <s> Raji was a serving member of the Lagos State Independent Electoral Commission committee (LASIEC) before his death. <s> Raji died of throat cancer at his home in Magodo, Nigeria on 14 August 2017 at the age of 54.

title: Martin Jiránek
complex: Martin Jiránek (] ; born 25 May 1979 in Prague) is a former Czech international footballer. <s> A defender, Jiránek played in the top division of several countries.

title: Cy Young Award
complex: The Cy Young Award is given annually to the best pitchers in Major League Baseball (MLB), one each for the American League (AL) and National League (NL). <s> The award was first introduced in 1956 by Baseball Commissioner Ford Frick in honor of Hall of Fame pitcher Cy Young, who died in 1955. <s> The award was originally given to the single best pitcher in the major leagues, but in 1967, after the retirement of Frick, the award was given to one pitcher in each league. <s> Each league's award is voted on by members of the Baseball Writers' Association of America, with one representative from each team. <s> As of the 2010 season, each voter places a vote for first, second, third, fourth and fifth place among the pitchers of each league. <s> The formula used to calculate the final scores is a weighted sum of the votes. <s> The pitcher with the highest score in each league wins the award. <s> If two pitchers receive the same number of votes, the award is shared. <s> The current formula started in the 2010 season. <s> Before that, dating back to 1970, writers voted for three pitchers, with the formula of 5 points for a first place vote, 3 for a second place vote and 1 for a third place vote. <s> Prior to 1970, writers only voted for the best pitcher and used a formula of one point per vote. <s> The Cy Young Award was first introduced in 1956 by Commissioner of Baseball Ford C. Frick in honor of Hall of Fame pitcher Cy Young, who died in 1955. <s> The award would be given to pitchers only. <s> Originally given to the single best pitcher in the major leagues, the award changed its format over time. <s> From 1956 to 1966, the award was given to one pitcher in Major League Baseball. <s> After Frick retired in 1967, William Eckert became the new Commissioner of Baseball. <s> Due to fan requests, Eckert announced that the Cy Young Award would be given out both in the American League and the National League.
simple: In baseball, the Cy Young Award is an honor given to the best pitcher in the Major League Baseball. <s> Each league's award is voted on by two members of the Baseball Writers Association of America in each league city, meaning 28 ballots are cast for the American League winner, and 32 for the National League. <s> Each places a vote for first, second, and third place among the pitchers of each league. <s> The formula used to calculate the final scores is a weighted sum of the votes: Score = 5F + 3S + T, where "F" is the number of first place votes, "S" is second place votes, and "T" is third place votes. <s> The pitcher with the highest score in each league wins the award. <s> If two pitchers receive the same number of votes, the award is shared between the two. <s> Prior to that, writers only voted for the best pitcher and used a formula of one point per vote. <s> The award was first introduced in 1956 by Commissioner Ford Frick in honor of Hall of Fame pitcher Cy Young, who died in 1955. <s> The award was given to the best pitcher in the major leagues. <s> In 1967, the year after Frick retired as Commissioner, the practice began of honoring one pitcher in each league, the American League, and the National League.

title: Richard Karn
complex: Richard Karn Wilson (born February 17, 1956) is an American actor and former game show host. <s> He is best known for his co-starring role as Al Borland in the 1990s sitcom "Home Improvement" and his tenure as the fourth host of "Family Feud" from 2002 to 2006. <s> Karn was born Richard Karn Wilson in Seattle, Washington. <s> His father Gene was a Seabee who served in World War II. <s> Richard graduated from Roosevelt High School and the University of Washington, where he was a member of Beta Theta Pi. <s> Karn also gained drama experience in Scotland at the Edinburgh Festival. <s> In 2002, Karn replaced Louie Anderson as the fourth host of the game show "Family Feud". <s> Karn left "Family Feud" in 2006 and was replaced by John O'Hurley. <s> On October 6, 2008, Karn replaced Patrick Duffy as host of Game Show Network's "Bingo America". <s> Karn served as a substitute host on GSN Radio.
simple: Richard Karn (born February 17, 1956) is an American actor and game show host. <s> He is best known for acting as Al Borland in the 1990s ABC sitcom "Home Improvement", and for hosting "Family Feud" during the 2000s. <s> He was born in Seattle, Washington. <s> Karn became host of "Family Feud" in September 2002. <s> He left in 2006 and was replaced by John O'Hurley. <s> He also hosted GSN's "Bingo America" in 2008. <s> He replaced Patrick Duffy, who hosted the show for the first season.

title: Antecedent (grammar)
complex: In grammar, an antecedent is an expression (word, phrase, clause, sentence, etc.) that gives its meaning to a proform (pronoun, pro-verb, pro-adverb, etc.). <s> A proform takes its meaning from its antecedent, e.g. "John arrived late because traffic held him up".
simple: In grammar, an antecedent is a segment of text represented by or repeated by another segment of text.

title: Jerauld County, South Dakota
complex: Jerauld County is a county in the U.S. state of South Dakota. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 2,071. <s> Its county seat is Wessington Springs.
simple: Jerauld County is a county located in the U.S. state of South Dakota. <s> As of the 2010 census, 2,071 people lived there. <s> Its county seat is Wessington Springs.

title: Jorge Zavala
complex: Jorge Zavala Baquerizo (13 May 1921 – 9 May 2014) was an Ecuadorian politician. <s> He served as the Vice President of Ecuador from 1968 to 1970 under the José María Velasco Ibarra administration. <s> He served as President of the National Congress 1987–1988. <s> He was a member of the Democratic Left. <s> Zavala died in Guayaquil, Ecuador from natural causes, aged 92.
simple: Jorge Zavala Baquerizo (13 May 1921 – 9 May 2014) was an Ecuadorian politician. <s> He served as the Vice President of Ecuador from 1968 to 1970 under the José María Velasco Ibarra administration. <s> Zavala died in Guayaquil, Ecuador from natural causes, aged 92.

title: Disney Legends
complex: The Disney Legends Awards is a hall of fame program that recognizes individuals who have made an extraordinary and integral contribution to The Walt Disney Company. <s> Established in 1987, the honor was traditionally awarded annually during a special private ceremony; since 2009, it has been awarded biennially during Disney's D23 Expo. <s> Recipients are chosen by a selection committee, formerly appointed and chaired by Disney Legend Roy E. Disney, Walt Disney's nephew, former vice chairman and director emeritus of The Walt Disney Company. <s> The committee consists of long-time Disney executives, historians, and other authorities.
simple: Disney Legends Awards are given to individuals whose work has made significant contributions to The Walt Disney Company. <s> More than 200 people have received the Disney Legends award. <s> The award was created in 1987. <s> A selection committee chooses who will receive the award.

title: Strum, Wisconsin
complex: Strum is a village in Trempealeau County, Wisconsin, along the Buffalo River. <s> The population was 1,114 at the 2010 census. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 1,001 people, 411 households, and 249 families residing in the village. <s> The population density was 920.7 people per square mile (354.6/km2).
simple: Strum is a village in Trempealeau County of the state of Wisconsin in the United States. <s> It can be found along the Buffalo River. <s> 1,001 people were living in Strum as of the 2000 census.

title: Elise Christie
complex: Elise Christie (born 13 August 1990) is a British short track speed skater. <s> She is coached by Nicky Gooch and she specialises in the 1000m event. <s> She is ten times a European gold medalist, including two overall European titles in 2015 and 2016. <s> In the 2017 World Championships in Rotterdam she won world titles in the 1000m and 1500m events, as well as the overall gold, the first British woman and first European woman to do so.
simple: Elise Christie (born August 13th, 1990) is a British short track speed skater. <s> She is trained by Nicky Gooch. <s> She has won gold medals ten times at European championships in the sport. <s> She has won the entire event in 2015 and 2016.

title: Atsushi Natori
complex: Atsushi Natori (名取 篤 , Natori Atsushi , born November 12, 1961) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He played for Japan national team.

title: Protein Data Bank
complex: The Protein Data Bank (PDB) is a database for the three-dimensional structural data of large biological molecules, such as proteins and nucleic acids. <s> The data, typically obtained by X-ray crystallography, NMR spectroscopy, or, increasingly, cryo-electron microscopy, and submitted by biologists and biochemists from around the world, are freely accessible on the Internet via the websites of its member organisations (PDBe, PDBj, RCSB, and BMRB). <s> The PDB is overseen by an organization called the Worldwide Protein Data Bank, wwPDB. <s> The PDB is a key in areas of structural biology, such as structural genomics. <s> Most major scientific journals, and some funding agencies, now require scientists to submit their structure data to the PDB. <s> Many other databases use protein structures deposited in the PDB. <s> For example, SCOP and CATH classify protein structures, while PDBsum provides a graphic overview of PDB entries using information from other sources, such as Gene ontology.
simple: The Protein Data Bank (PDB) is a collection of information about the three dimensional (3-D) structure of large biological molecules, such as proteins and nucleic acids. <s> Biologists and biochemists from around the world send in the data. <s> Most data comes from X-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy. <s> The Worldwide Protein Data Bank, wwPDB, manages the PDB. <s> The PDB is useful for scientists studying structural biology and structural genomics. <s> Major scientific journals and some funding agencies, such as the National Institutes of Health in the United States have rules telling scientists to send the data to the PDB. <s> Hundreds of other databases reuse the data.

title: Eiji Ueda
complex: Eiji Ueda (上田 栄治 , Ueda Eiji , born December 22, 1953) is a former Japanese football player and manager. <s> He managed the Japan women's national team. <s> After retirement, Ueda became coach for Fujita Industries. <s> In 1999, he became manager for Bellmare Hiratsuka.
simple: Eiji Ueda (上田栄治, Ueda Eiji, born 22 December 1953) is a Japanese sportsman. <s> Ueda was the head coach of the Japan women's national football team in 2004-2006. <s> After retirement as a coach, Ueda became Chairman of the Japan Football Association Women’s Football Committee.

title: Tokitenkū Yoshiaki
complex: Tokitenkū Yoshiaki (時天空 慶晃 , Tokitenkū Yoshiaki , born as Altangadasyn Khüchitbaatar, ; September 10, 1979 – January 31, 2017) was a sumo wrestler. <s> He made his professional debut in 2002, reaching the top "makuuchi" division just two years later. <s> The highest rank he reached was "komusubi", which he held on three separate occasions, but never retained for more than one tournament. <s> He earned one special prize, for Technique. <s> He wrestled for the Tokitsukaze stable and acquired Japanese citizenship in 2014. <s> Tokitenkū was diagnosed with malignant lymphoma in 2015 and retired from sumo in 2016 to become a coach; he was the first Mongolian-born wrestler to acquire the right to remain with the Sumo Association as a coach following retirement as an active wrestler. <s> He died in January 2017. <s> Born in Töv Province, Mongolia, Tokitenkū was the son of a Mongolian wrestler, who reached a rank equivalent to "komusubi" in Mongolian wrestling. <s> He first came to Japan in March 2000 to study at Tokyo University of Agriculture, having deferred his studies at Mongolian State University of Agriculture. <s> The Japan Sumo Association announced on August 26, 2016, that Tokitenkū had retired. <s> He had become a Japanese citizen in January 2014 and had purchased the Magaki "kabu" (elder stock) in May 2014 from former "yokozuna" Wakanohana Kanji II, making him the first Mongolian-born wrestler to acquire the right to remain with the sumo association following retirement. <s> He became known as Magaki Oyakata and worked as a coach at Tokitsukaze stable, the second Mongolian-born wrestler to remain as a coach after Kyokutenhō.
simple: Tokitenkū Yoshiaki (born Altangadasyn Khüchitbaatar, ; 10 September 1979 – 31 January 2017) was a Mongolian sumo wrestler. <s> He made his professional debut in 2002. <s> He reached the top "makuuchi" division just two years later. <s> The highest rank he reached was "komusubi". <s> He held this three separate times, but never for more than one tournament. <s> He earned one special prize, for Technique. <s> He wrestled for Tokitsukaze stable. <s> Yoshiaki died from lymphoma on 31 January 2017 in Tokyo. <s> He was born in Altanbulag, Töv Province. <s> He became a Japanese citizen in January 2014.

title: Maleficium (sorcery)
complex: Maleficium (plural: "maleficia") as a Latin term, "An act of witchcraft performed with the intention of causing damage or injury; the resultant harm." <s> In general, the term applies to any magical act intended to cause harm or death to people or property.
simple: Maleficium is a term from Latin.

title: Division of Farrer
complex: The Division of Farrer is an Australian electoral division in the state of New South Wales. <s> The division was created in 1949 and is named for William Farrer, an agricultural scientist. <s> The division is located in the far south-western area of the state and includes Albury, Corowa, Narrandera, Leeton, Griffith, Deniliquin, Hay, Balranald and Wentworth.
simple: The Division of Farrer is an Australian Electoral Division in New South Wales. <s> It was set up in 1949 and is named for William Farrer, an agricultural scientist. <s> It is in the southern rural area of the state and includes Albury, Balranald, Broken Hill, Deniliquin and Jerilderie.

title: Larissa Wilson
complex: Larissa Hope Wilson (born 5 May 1989) is an English actress best known for her role as Jal Fazer in the first two series of the UK television series "Skins".
simple: Larissa Wilson (born 5 May 1989) is an English actress. <s> She is best known for playing the role of Jal Fazer in the first two seasons of "Skins".

title: Lady with an Ermine
complex: Lady with an Ermine ( ] ; ) is a painting by Italian artist Leonardo da Vinci from around 1489–1490 and one of Poland's national treasures. <s> The portrait's subject is Cecilia Gallerani, painted at a time when she was the mistress of Ludovico Sforza, Duke of Milan, and Leonardo was in the Duke's service. <s> It is one of only four portraits of women painted by Leonardo, the others being the "Mona Lisa", the portrait of Ginevra de' Benci, and "La belle ferronnière".
simple: Lady with an Ermine (Portrait of Cecilia Gallerani) ( ]; ) is a painting by Leonardo da Vinci. <s> It was painted between 1489 and 1490. <s> "Lady with an Ermine" is displayed in the Czartoryski Museum, Kraków, Poland. <s> The subject of the portrait is Cecilia Gallerani, the mistress of Ludovico Sforza, Duke of Milan. <s> Leonardo was in the service of the Duke at the time the portrait was painted.

title: Ruslan Salei
complex: Ruslan Albiertavič Saliej (Belarusian: Руслан Альбертавіч Салей; November 2, 1974 – September 7, 2011), better known as Ruslan Salei (Russian: Руслан Альбертович Салей), was a Belarusian professional ice hockey player. <s> Salei played 14 seasons in the National Hockey League (NHL) for the Detroit Red Wings, Colorado Avalanche, Florida Panthers and the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, the latter of which selected him ninth overall in the 1996 NHL Entry Draft. <s> On September 7, 2011, at 4:02 PM local time, the Yakovlev Yak-42 passenger aircraft, carrying nearly the entire Lokomotiv Yaroslavl hockey team crashed near Yaroslavl, Russia, en route to Minsk, Belarus, to begin the 2011–12 season. <s> Salei was 1 of the 44 passengers and crew to die in the crash.
simple: Ruslan "Rusty" Salei (Belarusian: Руслан Салей; November 2, 1974 – September 7, 2011) was a Belarusian professional ice hockey player. <s> During 14 seasons in the National Hockey League (NHL) he played for the Detroit Red Wings, Colorado Avalanche, Florida Panthers and the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim. <s> On September 7, 2011, the Yakovlev Yak-42 passenger aircraft, carrying the entire Lokomotiv team including Salei crashed near Yaroslavl on its way to Minsk, Belarus.

title: Carlo Azeglio Ciampi
complex: Carlo Azeglio Ciampi (] ; 9 December 1920 – 16 September 2016) was an Italian politician and banker. <s> He was the 49th Prime Minister of Italy from 1993 to 1994 and was the tenth President of Italy from 1999 to 2006. <s> In 1960, he was called to work in the central administration of the Bank of Italy, where he became Secretary General in 1973, Vice Director General in 1976, and Director General in 1978. <s> In October 1979, he was nominated Governor of the Bank of Italy and President of the national Bureau de Change, positions he filled until 1993. <s> He died in Rome on 16 September 2016 at the age of 95.
simple: Carlo Azeglio Ciampi (9 December 1920 in Livorno, Italy – 16 September 2016 in Rome, Italy) was the 10th President of the Italian Republic. <s> His work started in 1999 and ended in 2006. <s> Since 1979 he had been President of the Bank of Italy, but his task ended in 1993. <s> Ciampi died at a hospital in Rome from multiple organ failure caused by pneumonia, aged 95.

title: Race track
complex: A race track (or "racetrack", "racing track" or "racing circuit") is a facility built for racing of vehicles, athletes, or animals (e.g. horse racing or greyhound racing). <s> A race track also may feature grandstands or concourses. <s> Racetracks are also used in the study of animal locomotion. <s> Some motorsport tracks are called speedways. <s> Beginning in the early 1900s, motorcycle races were run on high, banked, wooden race tracks called board tracks. <s> During the 1920s, many of the races on the AAA Championship circuit were run on such board tracks. <s> Modern racetracks are designed with spectator safety being paramount, following incidents of spectator and track marshals fatalities. <s> These often involve run off areas, barriers, and high fencing.
simple: A race track is a special place built for racing. <s> The racing may be for people, animals, or vehicles. <s> A race track may have seats for the spectators to watch the race. <s> Some race tracks are called road courses. <s> Modern racetracks are designed with safety as the first priority. <s> Safety for the spectator, track workers, and racers.

title: Deaths in June 2019

title: Scott Cawthon
complex: Scott Cawthon is an American independent video game designer, developer, animator, and writer, best known as the creator of the "Five Nights at Freddy's" game franchise. <s> Cawthon has created other games such as "The Desolate Hope" and "There is No Pause Button!, <s> ," as well as Christian-based animations such as "A Christmas Journey" and "The Pilgrim's Progress". <s> He used Autodesk 3ds Max and Clickteam Fusion 2.5 to develop the "Five Nights at Freddy's" series and most of his other games. <s> In December, 2015, Scott Cawthon released teasers for his first novel, "Five Nights at Freddy's: The Untold Story," soon to be renamed "". <s> The book was released on December 17, 2015, as an e-book for The Amazon; a paperback edition is also available for ordering. <s> According to Cawthon, the book was released earlier than its planned release date due to a mistake on Amazon's part. <s> On June 24, 2016, Cawthon announced that he had made a three-book deal with Scholastic Corporation and that the first book ("The Silver Eyes") would be reprinted on paperback in October that year, with the second and third being released in 2017 and 2018. <s> On June 27, 2017, Scott Cawthon's second novel, "", was released.
simple: Scott Cawthon (born July 26, 1971) is an American video game designer, developer, animator, and writer. <s> He is best known as the creator of the "Five Nights of Freddy's" game franchise. <s> Cawthon has also created other games, such as "Chipper & Son's Lumber Co.", "The Desolate Hope", and "There is No Pause Button!, <s> ," as well as Christian-based animations such as "A Christmas Journey" and "The Pilgrim's Progress". <s> He used Autodesk 3ds Max and Clickteam Fusion 2.5 to develop "Five Nights at Freddy's" and most of his other games. <s> In 2015, Cawthon released his first novel, "". <s> On June 24, 2016, Cawthon announced that he had made a 3-book deal with Scholastic and that the first book ("The Silver Eyes") would be re-printed on paperback in October that year, with the second and third being released in 2017 and 2018.

title: List of foreign-born Medal of Honor recipients
complex: The Medal of Honor was created during the American Civil War and is the highest military decoration presented by the United States government to a member of its armed forces. <s> The recipient must have distinguished themselves at the risk of their own life above and beyond the call of duty in action against an enemy of the United States. <s> Due to the nature of this medal, it is commonly presented posthumously. <s> Although Medals of Honor can be awarded only to members of the U.S. armed forces, being a U.S. citizen is not a prerequisite for eligibility to receive the medal. <s> Since the American Civil War, hundreds of people born outside the United States have received the medal, the most recent of these recipients being Pedro Cano and Jesus S. Duran who received their medals in March 2014 for actions performed during World War II and the Vietnam War respectively. <s> The large number of foreign-born recipients during the 19th and early 20th centuries was mostly due to immigration waves from Europe.
simple: The Medal of Honor was created during the American Civil War. <s> It is the highest military decoration presented by the United States government to a member of its armed forces. <s> The recipient must have distinguished themselves at the risk of their own life above and beyond the call of duty in action against an enemy of the United States. <s> Due to the nature of this medal it is commonly presented after the recipient has been killed (posthumously). <s> Although Medals of Honor can be presented only to members of the U.S. armed forces it is not required to be a U.S. citizen. <s> Since the American Civil War hundreds of people born outside the United States have received the medal. <s> The large number of foreign-born recipients during the 19th and early 20th centuries was likely due to immigration waves from Europe.
