title: Marin Marais
complex: Marin Marais (] ; 31 May 1656, Paris – 15 August 1728, Paris) was a French composer and viol player. <s> He studied composition with Jean-Baptiste Lully, often conducting his operas, and with master of the bass viol Monsieur de Sainte-Colombe for six months. <s> In 1676 he was hired as a musician to the royal court of Versailles and was moderately successful there, being appointed in 1679 as "ordinaire de la chambre du roy pour la viole," a title he kept until 1725. <s> Marin Marais was a master of the viol, and the leading French composer of music for the instrument. <s> He wrote five books of "Pièces de viole" (1686–1725) for the instrument, generally suites with basso continuo. <s> These were quite popular in the court, and for these he was remembered in later years as he who "founded and firmly established the empire of the viol" (Hubert Le Blanc, 1740). <s> His other works include a book of "Pièces en trio" (1692) and four operas (1693–1709), "Alcyone" (1706) being noted for its tempest scene. <s> As with Sainte-Colombe, little of Marin Marais' personal life is known after he reached adulthood. <s> Marin Marais married a Parisian, Catherine d'Amicourt, on 21 September 1676. <s> They had 19 children together. <s> Facsimiles of all five books of Marais' "Pièces de viole" are published by Éditions J.M. Fuzeau. <s> A complete critical edition of his instrumental works in seven volumes, edited by John Hsu, is published by Broude Brothers.
simple: Marin Marais (31 May 1656, Paris – 15 August 1728, Paris) was a French composer and viol player. <s> He then learnt from Monsieur de Sainte-Colombe, a famous bass viol player. <s> Marais often conducted the operas Lully had written. <s> Marais was hired as a musician in 1676 to play at the royal court of Versailles. <s> In 1679 he was appointed "ordinaire de la chambre du roy pour la viole", a title he kept until 1725. <s> He was a master of the basse de viol. <s> He wrote a lot of music for that instrument, he was the most important French composer for it. <s> He wrote five books of "Pièces de viole" (1686-1725). <s> Most of the pieces in the book are suites with basso continuo. <s> These were quite popular in the court, and for these he was remembered in later years as he who "founded and firmly established the empire of the viol" (Hubert Le Blanc, 1740). <s> His other works include a book of "Pièces en trio" (1692) and four operas (1693-1709). <s> "Alcyone" (1706) is well known for its storm scene. <s> He married Catherine d'Amicourt, on 21 September 1676. <s> They had 19 children together. <s> Facsimiles of all five books of Marais' "Pièces de viole" are published by Éditions J.M. Fuzeau. <s> A complete critical edition of his instrumental works in seven volumes, edited by John Hsu, is published by Broude Brothers.

title: Wolfgang Völz
complex: Wolfgang Otto Völz (16 August 1930 – 2 May 2018) was a German actor. <s> He is known for his roles in theatre plays, TV shows, feature films (especially German films based on Edgar Wallace works) and taped radio shows. <s> He was also a very prolific voice actor. <s> As a voice actor he dubbed American stars such as Walter Matthau, Peter Falk and Mel Brooks and people or animals in animated films like "Impy's Island".
simple: Wolfgang Otto Völz (16 August 1930 – 2 May 2018) was a German actor. <s> He was known for his roles in theatre plays, television shows, feature movies (especially German movies based on Edgar Wallace works) and taped radio shows. <s> He was also a very prolific voice actor. <s> He dubbed American stars such as Walter Matthau, Peter Falk and Mel Brooks and people or animals in animated movies like "Impy's Island".

title: Bob McKenzie (broadcaster)
complex: Robert Malcomson McKenzie (born August 16, 1956) is a Canadian hockey commentator who has covered hockey since joining TSN in 1986. <s> As a TSN Hockey Insider and TSN's Draft Expert, McKenzie provides analysis for "NHL on TSN" telecasts, as well as for the IIHF World Junior Championships, NHL Draft, NHL Trade Deadline, Free Agency, and for six Olympic Winter Games. <s> Prior to and continuing for several years after joining TSN, McKenzie was editor-in-chief of "The Hockey News" for nine years and a hockey columnist for "The Toronto Star" for six years. <s> McKenzie also files updates and breaking news for SportsCentre and writes a Hockey Insider feature on TSN.ca. <s> In October 2014, McKenzie began appearing as a full-time contributor on NBCSN. <s> McKenzie is heard weekly on the TSN Radio on the "Canucks Lunch with Rick Ball" on TSN 1040, as well on TSN Radio 690 (CKGM) in Montreal, on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday on the Morning Show at 8:05 am. <s> He is also a frequent contributor to the Ottawa Senators pre-game show on TSN 1200 radio in Ottawa.
simple: Robert Malcomson "Bob" McKenzie (born August 16, 1956) is a Canadian hockey commentator who has covered ice hockey since joining TSN in 1986. <s> McKenzie provides analysis for "NHL on TSN" telecasts, as well as for international hockey events, notably the annual IIHF World U-20 Hockey Championship. <s> Prior to joining TSN, McKenzie was editor-in-chief of "The Hockey News" for nine years and a hockey columnist for "The Toronto Star" for six years. <s> In October 2014, McKenzie began appearing as a full-time contributor on NBCSN. <s> McKenzie is heard weekly on the TSN 1040 in Vancouver on the "Canucks Lunch with Rick Ball", as well on TSN Radio 690 (CKGM) in Montreal, on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday on the Morning Show at 8:05 a.m. <s> He is also a frequent contributor to the Ottawa Senators pre-game show on TSN 1200 radio in Ottawa.

title: Amber (name)
complex: Amber is a feminine given name taken from amber, the fossilized tree resin that is often used in the making of jewelry. <s> The word can also refer to a yellowish-orange color. <s> Amber has been a popular name in most English speaking countries. <s> It was the 20th most popular name in the U.S. in the 1990s. <s> It has ranked among the top 50 names for girls in England and Wales, Scotland, Ireland, Belgium, Australia and Canada in recent years.
simple: The name Amber is a female given name. <s> The name is a very popular name for English-speaking areas. <s> It ranked among the top 100 most used female names in Canada, Western Europe and Australia.

title: Crop (anatomy)
complex: A crop (sometimes also called a croup or a craw, or ingluvies) is a thin-walled expanded portion of the alimentary tract used for the storage of food prior to digestion. <s> This anatomical structure is found in a wide variety of animals. <s> It has been found in birds, and in invertebrate animals including gastropods (snails and slugs), earthworms, leeches, and insects. <s> Cropping is used by bees to temporarily store nectar of flowers. <s> When bees "suck" nectar, it is stored in their crops. <s> In a bird's digestive system, the crop is an expanded, muscular pouch near the gullet or throat. <s> It is a part of the digestive tract, essentially an enlarged part of the esophagus. <s> As with most other organisms that have a crop, the crop is used to temporarily store food. <s> Not all birds have a crop. <s> In adult doves and pigeons, the crop can produce crop milk to feed newly hatched birds. <s> Scavenging birds, such as vultures, will gorge themselves when prey is abundant, causing their crop to bulge. <s> They subsequently sit, sleepy or half torpid, to digest their food. <s> Most raptors, including hawks, eagles and vultures (as stated above), have a crop; however, owls do not. <s> Similarly, all true quail (Old World quail and New World quail) have a crop, but buttonquail do not.
simple: A crop (sometimes called a croup or craw) is a thin-walled expanded portion of the alimentary canal used for storing food before digestion. <s> It is found in many animals. <s> It occurs in birds, some dinosaurs, and invertebrate animals such as gastropods (snails and slugs), earthworms, leeches, and insects. <s> Cropping is used by bees to temporarily store nectar of flowers. <s> When bees "suck" nectar, it is stored in their crops. <s> In a bird's digestive system, the crop is an expanded, muscular pouch near the gullet or throat. <s> It is a part of the digestive tract, essentially an enlarged part of the oesophagus. <s> As with most other organisms that have a crop, the crop is used to temporarily store food. <s> Not all birds have a crop. <s> In adult doves and pigeons, the crop can produce crop milk to feed newly hatched birds. <s> Scavenging birds, such as vultures, will gorge themselves when prey is abundant, causing their crop to bulge. <s> They subsequently sit, sleepy or half torpid, to digest their food. <s> Most raptors, including hawks, eagles and vultures (as stated above), have a crop; however, owls do not.

title: Harry Perkowski
complex: Harry Walter Perkowski (September 6, 1922 – April 20, 2016) was a pitcher in Major League Baseball who played between 1947 and 1955 for the Cincinnati Reds / Redlegs (1947, 1949–54) and Chicago Cubs (1955). <s> Listed at 6 ft , 196 lb , he batted and threw left-handed. <s> Following baseball Perkowski served in local law enforcement, ambulance and school bus driver, and with the West Virginia Department of Highways. <s> He died in Beckley, West Virginia on April 20, 2016, aged 93.
simple: Harry Walter Perkowski (September 6, 1922 – April 20, 2016) was an American pitcher in Major League Baseball. <s> He played between 1947 and 1955 for the Cincinnati Reds & Redlegs (1947, 1949–54) and Chicago Cubs (1955). <s> He was listed at 6 ft, 196 lb, he batted and threw left-handed. <s> Perkowski died in Beckley, West Virginia on April 20, 2016, aged 93.

title: Excitebike
complex: Excitebike is a motocross racing video game franchise made by Nintendo. <s> It debuted as a game for the Famicom in Japan in 1984 and as a launch title for the NES in 1985. <s> It is the first game of the "Excite" series, succeeded by its direct sequel "Excitebike 64", its spiritual successors "Excite Truck" and "", and the WiiWare title "". <s> "3D Classics: Excitebike", a 3D remake of the original game, was free for a limited time to promote the launch of the Nintendo eShop in June 2011.
simple: Excitebike (エキサイトバイク, Ekisaitobaiku) is a motocross racing video game series made by Nintendo. <s> It first appeared as a game for the Famicom in Japan in 1984 for a price of 5000 yen. <s> It is the first game in the Excite series. <s> The second game in the series is "Excitebike 64" and the third is "Excite Truck".

title: Otsego Hall
complex: Otsego Hall was a house in Cooperstown, New York, United States built by William Cooper, founder of the town. <s> Construction started in 1796 and was completed by 1799 in the Federal style. <s> For many years, it was the manor house of Cooper's landed estate, and was the one of the largest private residences in central New York. <s> Cooper had moved his family to the settlement in 1790, and his son James Fenimore Cooper, who became an author, also lived in the house. <s> After the death of the senior Cooper and his widow, the mansion was vacant for many years. <s> In June 1834, James Fenimore Cooper resolved to reopen the house after an absence of nearly sixteen years. <s> The building had been long closed and falling into decay. <s> He had it remodelled in a castellated Gothic style. <s> The ceiling on the first floor was raised from ten feet to thirteen feet. <s> Also Gothic windows and battlements were installed. <s> In this, Cooper was assisted by his friend, Samuel F. B. Morse, a painter and inventor, who designed two towers for the front and east sides of the structure. <s> At first, Cooper spent his winters in New York City and summered in Cooperstown, but eventually he made Otsego Hall his permanent abode. <s> The mansion burned down a few years after his death in 1851, and the surrounding property was sold by the heirs. <s> His daughter, Susan Fenimore Cooper, built a house in Cooperstown, built mainly of bricks and material salvaged from the ruins of Otsego Hall.
simple: Otsego Hall was a house in Cooperstown, New York. <s> It was built by his father William Cooper, who also founded the village of Cooperstown. <s> Building began in 1796. <s> The Hall was completed in 1799. <s> It was the largest private home in central New York for a long time. <s> In June 1834 James Fenimore Cooper decided to reopen the Hall. <s> He had lived in other places for almost sixteen years. <s> The Hall had been closed for a long time. <s> It was falling into decay. <s> At first, James spent his winters in New York City and his summers in Cooperstown. <s> Eventually he made Otsego Hall his forever home. <s> The Hall burned down a few years after he died. <s> The surrounding property was sold. <s> His daughter and secretary, Susan Fenimore Cooper, built her home in Cooperstown with bricks and other materials from the ruins of Otsego Hall.

title: 2003–04 Tampa Bay Lightning season
complex: The 2003–04 Tampa Bay Lightning season was the 12th National Hockey League season in Tampa, Florida. <s> The Lightning won their first Stanley Cup over the Calgary Flames this season, after the Flames were attempting to be the first Canadian team to win a Stanley Cup since the 1993 Montreal Canadiens. <s> The Lightning's first Stanley Cup victory came just a year after their NFL (National Football League) counterparts, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, won Super Bowl XXXVII, also their first championship title. <s> The Lightning did not have a first-round pick. <s> For their first pick, they chose Mike Egener in the second round, 35th over-all. <s> On Saturday, December 27, 2003, the Lightning scored three short-handed goals in a 4-2 win over the Boston Bruins. <s> The Lightning finished the regular season having tied the Detroit Red Wings for the most short-handed goals scored, with 15. <s> Divisions: "AT" – Atlantic, "NE" – Northeast, "SE" – Southeast <s> Z – "Clinched Conference"; Y – "Clinched Division"; X – "Clinched Playoff spot" <s> "Note: GP= Games played; G= Goals; A= Assists; PTS = Points; PIM = Points" "Note: GP= Games played; G= Goals; A= Assists; PTS = Points; PIM = Points" "Note: GP= Games played; W= Wins; L= Losses; T = Ties; SO = Shutouts; GAA = Goals Against"

complex: Going Solo is a book by Roald Dahl, first published by Jonathan Cape in London in 1986. <s> It is a continuation of his autobiography describing his childhood, "Boy" and detailed his travel to Africa and exploits as a World War II pilot.

title: Advanced Placement
complex: Advanced Placement (AP) is a program in the United States and Canada created by the College Board which offers college-level curricula and examinations to high school students. <s> American colleges and universities may grant placement and course credit to students who obtain high scores on the examinations. <s> The AP curriculum for each of the various subjects is created for the College Board by a panel of experts and college-level educators in that field of study. <s> For a high school course to have the designation, the course must be audited by the College Board to ascertain that it satisfies the AP curriculum. <s> If the course is approved, the school may use the AP designation and the course will be publicly listed on the AP Course Ledger. <s> After the end of World War II, the Ford Foundation created a fund that supported committees studying education. <s> The program, which was then referred to as the "Kenyon Plan", was founded and pioneered at Kenyon College in Gambier, Ohio, by the then-college president Gordon Chalmers. <s> The first study was conducted by four prep schools—the Lawrenceville School, Phillips Academy, Phillips Exeter Academy, and St. Paul's School —and three universities—Harvard University, Princeton University and Yale University. <s> In 1952 they issued the report "General Education in School and College: A Committee Report" which recommended allowing high school seniors to study college-level material and to take achievement exams that allowed them to attain college credit for this work. <s> The second committee, the Committee on Admission with Advanced Standing, developed and implemented the plan to choose a curriculum. <s> A pilot program was run in 1952 which covered eleven disciplines. <s> In the 1955-56 school year, it was nationally implemented in ten subjects: Mathematics, Physics, Chemistry, Biology, English, History, French, German, Spanish, and Latin. <s> The College Board, a non-profit organization based in New York City, has run the AP program since 1955. <s> From 1965 to 1989, Harlan Hanson was the director of the Advanced Placement Program. <s> It develops and maintains guidelines for the teaching of higher level courses in various subject areas. <s> In addition, it supports teachers of AP courses and supports universities. <s> These activities are funded through fees required to take the AP exams. <s> In 2006, over one million students took over two million Advanced Placement examinations. <s> Many high schools in the United States offer AP courses, though the College Board allows any student to take any examination regardless of participation in its respective course. <s> Therefore, home-schooled students and students from schools that do not offer AP courses have an equal opportunity to take AP exams. <s> As of the 2015 testing season, exams cost $91 each, though the cost may be subsidized by local or state programs. <s> Financial aid is available for students who qualify for it; the exam reduction is $26 or $28 per exam from College Board plus an additional $8 rebate per fee-reduced exam from the school. <s> There may be further reductions depending on the state. <s> Out of the $91, $8 goes directly to the school to pay for the administration of the test, which some schools will reduce to lower the cost to the student. <s> On April 3, 2008, the College Board announced that four AP courses—French Literature, Latin Literature, Computer Science AB, and Italian Language and Culture—would be discontinued after the 2008–2009 school year due to lack of funding. <s> However, the Italian Language and Culture test was again offered beginning in 2011. <s> The multiple choice component of the exam is scored by computer, while the free response and essay portions are scored by trained Readers at the AP Reading each June. <s> The scores on various components are weighted and combined into a raw Composite Score.
simple: The Advanced Placement Program, or AP, is a program that offers higher level school classes for high school students in Canada and the United States. <s> After World War II, the Ford Foundation gave money to support committees studying education. <s> The program was founded and pioneered at Kenyon College in Gambier, Ohio, by the then college president Gordon Chalmers which was then called the "Kenyon Plan". <s> The first study was conducted by three prep schools—the Lawrenceville School, Phillips Academy, and Phillips Exeter Academy—and three universities—Harvard University, Princeton University, and Yale University. <s> In 1952 they gave the report "General Education in School and College: A Committee Report" which said to allow high school seniors to study college level material and to take achievement exams that allowed them to attain college credit for this work. <s> The second committee, the Committee on Admission with Advanced Standing, developed and put the plan to choose a curriculum. <s> A pilot program was run in 1952 which covered eleven disciplines. <s> The College Board, a non-profit organization based in New York City, has run the AP program since 1955. <s> From 1965 to 1989, Harlan Hanson was the director of the Advanced Placement Program. <s> It makes and keeps guidelines for the teaching of higher level courses in various subject areas. <s> In addition, it supports teachers of AP courses and universities. <s> These activities are funded through fees charged to students taking AP Exams. <s> In 2006, over one million students took over two million Advanced Placement examinations. <s> Many high schools in the United States offer AP courses, though the College Board allows any student to take any examination, regardless of participation in the course. <s> Therefore, home-schooled students and students from schools that do not offer AP courses have an equal opportunity to take the examination. <s> As of the 2011 testing season, exams cost $87 each, though the cost may reduced for poor students who cannot pay for it. <s> The exam reduction is $22 per exam from College Board plus an additional $8 rebate per fee-reduced exam from the school. <s> There may be further discounts depending on the state. <s> Out of the $87, $8 goes directly to the school to pay for the administration of the test, which some schools will reduce to lower the cost to the student. <s> On April 3, 2008, the College Board announced that four AP courses – French Literature, Latin Literature, Computer Science AB, and Italian Language and Culture – will be gone after the 2008–2009 school year due to no money. <s> The multiple choice part is graded by a computer and the essays are scored by a group of teachers that do not teach at the student's school.

title: Picardy
complex: Picardy ( ; Picard and , ] ) is a historical territory and a former administrative region of France. <s> Since 1 January 2016, it has been part of the new region of Hauts-de-France. <s> It is located in the northern part of France.
simple: Picardy used to be an administrative region of France. <s> It is now part of the administrative region of Hauts-de-France.

title: Pat Patterson (wrestler)
complex: Patrick Patterson (born Pierre Clermont on January 19, 1941) is a Canadian–American professional wrestler. <s> He is currently employed by the professional wrestling promotion WWE as a creative consultant and producer. <s> He is the inaugural WWE Intercontinental Champion and creator of the Royal Rumble match, Patterson was inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame class of 1996. <s> In 2019, Patterson became the oldest person to ever win a title in WWE history, after winning the WWE 24/7 Championship at 78 years old. <s> He has been described by journalist Dave Meltzer as "Vince McMahon's right-hand man" and "one of the chief architects of the WWE, playing an integral role in helping it become a global phenomenon.". <s> Patterson is openly gay. <s> He first came out in the early 1970s, and although Jim Ross made several jokes about it on commentary, his sexuality was not acknowledged publicly or in WWE storylines until the season finale of "WWE Legends' House", which aired June 12, 2014.
simple: Pierre Clermont (born March 19, 1941) is a Canadian retired professional wrestler. <s> He is better known by the ring name Pat Patterson. <s> He currently works as a creative consultant for the WWE. <s> Patterson was inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame in 1996. <s> Patterson is openly gay.

title: Kevin McDonald
complex: Kevin Hamilton McDonald (born May 16, 1961) is a Canadian actor, voice actor and comedian. <s> He is known as a member of "The Kids in the Hall", the voice of Agent Wendy Pleakley in the "Lilo & Stitch" franchise, Waffle in "Catscratch", Pastor Dave in "That 70s Show", and the Almighty Tallest Purple in "Invader Zim". <s> Kevin also stars as a co-pilot in the 2011 web comedy series "Papillon". <s> McDonald founded The Kids in the Hall comedy troupe with his friend Dave Foley. <s> They met in Toronto at the Second City Training Center, and the two wrote and performed in sketches together more than any other pair in the group.
simple: Kevin Hamilton McDonald (born May 16, 1961) is a Canadian actor, voice artist, and comedian. <s> He's the voice of Pleakley in the "Lilo & Stitch" series, Waffle in "Catscratch" and the Almighty Tallest Purple in "Invader Zim". <s> McDonald founded "The Kids in the Hall" with his friend Dave Foley.

title: Iron plantation
complex: Iron plantations were rural localities emergent in the late-18th century and predominant in the early-19th century that specialized in the production of pig iron and bar iron from crude iron ore. <s> Such plantations derive their name from two sources: first, because they were nearly self-sufficient communities despite an almost singular focus on the production of iron to be sold on the market, and second, because of the large swaths of forest and land necessary to provide charcoal fuel and ore for their operations.
simple: Iron plantations were areas where everyone worked on making pig iron or wrought iron.

title: Napinka
complex: Napinka is an unincorporated community in southwestern Manitoba, Canada. <s> The village of Napinka incorporated on May 1, 1908. <s> On January 1, 1986 the village dissolved and Napinka became part of the Rural Municipality of Brenda.
simple: Napinka is an unincorporated community in southwestern Manitoba, Canada. <s> The village was founded in 1908. <s> In 1986, it became part of the Rural Municipality of Brenda.

title: Autoimmune disease
complex: In both autoimmune and inflammatory diseases, the condition arises through aberrant reactions of the human adaptive or innate immune systems. <s> In autoimmunity, the patient's immune system is activated against the body's own proteins.
simple: Autoimmune disease: when the body's immune system attacks its own body.

title: Interstate 74
complex: Interstate 74 (I-74) is an Interstate Highway in the midwestern and southeastern United States. <s> Its western end is at an interchange with Interstate 80 in Davenport, Iowa (Quad Cities); the eastern end of its Midwest segment is at an interchange with Interstate 75 in Cincinnati, Ohio. <s> The major cities that I-74 connects to includes Davenport, Iowa; Peoria, Illinois; Champaign, Illinois; Indianapolis, Indiana; and Cincinnati, Ohio. <s> I-74 also exists as several disconnected sections of highways in North Carolina. <s> Two sections of I-74 in North Carolina are currently under construction. <s> These include building the first part of a bypass of Rockingham with Interstate 73 by reconstructing US 220 to interstate standards for 4 miles south of Ellerbe and is scheduled to be completed in 2018 and the first segment of the Eastern Half of the Winston-Salem Northern Beltway which is constructing 4 mi of the future I-74 freeway between Business 40/US 421 and U.S. 158, this project should also be completed by 2018.
simple: Interstate 74 is an Interstate Highway in the United States. <s> The main part of it goes from Davenport, Iowa east to Cincinnati, Ohio. <s> There are three parts of Interstate 74 that are in North Carolina, with no part being connected. <s> All four parts of Interstate 74 will become part of one road.

title: America's Next Top Model (season 4)
complex: The winner was 20-year-old Naima Mora from Detroit, Michigan.
simple: The winner was 20-year-old Naima Mora.

title: 1984 State of the Union Address
complex: The 1984 State of the Union address was given by President Ronald Reagan to a joint session of the 98th United States Congress on January 25, 1984. <s> The speech was the third State of the Union address of President Reagan's first term. <s> The speech lasted 43 minutes and 2 seconds and contained 4931 words. <s> The address was broadcast live on radio and television. <s> The Democratic Party response was delivered by Senator Joe Biden (DE), Sen. David Boren (OK), Senator Carl M. Levin (MI), Senator Max S. Baucus (MT), Senator Robert Byrd (WV), Senator Claiborne Pell (RI), Senator Walter Huddleston (KY), Rep. Dante B. Fascell (FL), Rep. Tom Harkin (IA), Rep. William Gray (PA), House Speaker Thomas O’Neill (MA), and Rep. Barbara Boxer (CA).
simple: The 1984 State of the Union address was given by President Ronald Reagan to a joint session of the 98th United States Congress on January 25, 1984. <s> The speech was the third State of the Union address of President Reagan's first term. <s> The speech lasted 43 minutes and 2 seconds and had 4931 words. <s> The address was broadcast live on radio and television. <s> The Democratic Party response was delivered by Senator Joe Biden (DE), Sen. David Boren (OK), Senator Carl Levin (MI), Senator Max Baucus (MT), Senator Robert Byrd (WV), Senator Claiborne Pell (RI), Senator Walter Huddleston (KY), Rep. Dante B. Fascell (FL), Rep. Tom Harkin (IA), Rep. William Gray (PA), House Speaker Thomas O’Neill (MA), and Rep. Barbara Boxer (CA).

title: Philipp Wachsmann
complex: Philipp John Paul Wachsmann (born 5 August 1944) is an African avant-garde jazz/jazz fusion violinist born in Kampala, Uganda, probably better known for having founded his own group Chamberpot. <s> He has worked with many musicians in the free jazz idiom, including Tony Oxley, Fred van Hove, Barry Guy, Derek Bailey and Paul Rutherford, among many others. <s> Wachsmann is especially known for playing within the electronica idiom.
simple: Phil Wachsmann (born August 5, 1944) is an African "avant-garde" jazz/jazz fusion violinist born in Kampala, Uganda, probably better known for having founded his own group Chamberpot. <s> He has worked with many musicians in the free jazz idiom, including Tony Oxley, Fred van Hove, Barry Guy, Derek Bailey and Paul Rutherford, among many others. <s> Wachsmann is especially known for playing within the electronica idiom.

title: Gleb Yakunin
complex: He died at the age of 78 after a long illness on 25 December 2014.
simple: He died at the age of 80 after a long illness on 25 December 2014 in Moscow, Russia.

title: Casualty (person)
complex: A casualty, as a term in military usage, is a person in military service, combatant or non-combatant, who becomes unavailable for duty due to several circumstances, including death, injury, illness, capture or desertion. <s> In civilian usage, a casualty is a person who is killed, wounded or incapacitated by some event; the term is usually used to describe multiple deaths and injuries due to violent incidents or disasters. <s> It is sometimes misunderstood to mean "fatalities", but non-fatal injuries are also casualties. <s> In military usage, a "casualty" is a person in service killed in action, killed by disease, disabled by injuries, disabled by psychological trauma, captured, deserted, or missing, but not someone who sustains injuries which do not prevent them from fighting.
simple: A casualty in military usage is a person in military service, who becomes unavailable for duty due to death or injury. <s> It also includes illness, capture, desertion, etc.; or a civilian casualty. <s> In civilian usage the word "casualty" is properly used for a person who is killed, wounded or injured by some event. <s> It is usually used to describe multiple deaths and injuries due to violent incidents or disasters. <s> "Casualties" is sometimes loosely used to mean "fatalities", but non-fatal injuries are also casualties.

title: Lollipop (Candyman)
complex: "Lollipop (Candyman)" is a song recorded by Danish dance-pop group Aqua. <s> It was released as the fourth overall single from their debut album "Aquarium" as the follow-up to their most successful song "Barbie Girl" in Australasia, North America and Mainland Europe (it was not released in the United Kingdom.) <s> Although it said to be one of the group's favorite songs, "Lollipop (Candyman)" failed to replicate the success of "Barbie Girl", "Doctor Jones" and "My Oh My" where it was released.
simple: "Lollipop (Candyman)" is a pop song from the group Aqua. <s> It is from their first album, "Aquarium". <s> It was not as successful as their song "Barbie Girl". <s> This song was said to be one of the group's favorite songs.

title: Dalitstan.org
complex: Dalitstan.org was a Dalit advocacy website active until mid-2006, one of 18 websites that were blocked by the Indian government following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website claimed to be run by Dalitstan, a "Human Rights Organization working for the Upliftment of Dalits, the Untouchables of India". <s> Note that -stan is a suffix for "place of" or "country", appearing in many place names throughout Central and South Asia. <s> Dalitstan would mean "place or country of the Dalits". <s> The website claimed that the Dalits were the original people of India who created the Harappan civilization, and described the Brahmins as the descendants of the Aryan invaders who enslaved them. <s> Dibyesh Anand of the University of Westminster described Dalitstan.org as a Dalit nationalist group that also acted as a forum for anti-India Christian and Muslim advocacy. <s> Dalitistan.org was among the 18 websites that were blocked in India by the Ministry of Telecommunications of the Government in July 2006, in a bid to check terror and hate messages on the Internet following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website was launched in 1999, with the domain registered by Helen Heklund, with an address in Granbury, Texas. <s> The website was taken down sometime after May 2006. <s> The domain registration lapsed, and was subsequently purchased by an unrelated party.
simple: Dalitstan.org was a Dalit advocacy website active until mid-2006. <s> It was one of 18 websites that were blocked by the Indian government following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website claimed to be run by Dalitstan, a "Human Rights Organization working for the Upliftment of Dalits, the Untouchables of India". <s> Note that -stan is a suffix for "place of" or "country", and forms part of the name of many places throughout Central and South Asia. <s> Dalitstan would mean "place or country of the Dalits". <s> The website stated that the Dalits were the original people of India who created the Harappan civilization, and described the Brahmins as the descendants of the Aryan invaders who enslaved them. <s> Dibyesh Anand of the University of Westminster described Dalitstan.org as a Dalit nationalist group that also acted as a forum for anti-India Christian and Muslim advocacy. <s> Dalitistan.org was one of 18 websites that were blocked in India by the Ministry of Telecommunications of the Government in July 2006. <s> The purpose of the block was to try to stop terror and hate messages on the Internet following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website was started in 1999. <s> The domain was registered by Helen Heklund, with an address in Granbury, Texas. <s> The original version of the website was last archived on May 10, 2006. <s> The domain registration lapsed (expired), and the rights to the name were then purchased by someone else.

title: Szczecin-Dąbie Airstrip
complex: Szczecin-Dąbie Airstrip (German: Flughafen am Dammschen See) is a small airstrip on the Eastern bank of the Oder river in Dąbie, Szczecin, Poland. <s> The original grass landing strip was built in 1921 as Stettin Airfield (at that time belonging to Germany) and was used for domestic flights of Deutsche Luft Hansa over the following years. <s> After World War II, LOT began serving the airfield, which remained the only one in Szczecin until 23 May 1967, when Szczecin-Goleniów Airport was opened.
simple: Szczecin - Dąbie Airstrip is a small airstrip on right side of the river in Szczecin (Poland) in Dąbie. <s> It was built on grass in 1921. <s> After World War II to 23 May 1967, when the airport was moved to Goleniów, it was the main airport of Szczecin, where LOT Polish Airlines has their flights.

title: Kedah
complex: Kedah ( ; ; Jawi: قدح), also known by its honorific Darul Aman or "Abode of Safety", is a state of Malaysia, located in the northwestern part of Peninsular Malaysia. <s> The state covers a total area of over 9,000 km2, and it consists of the mainland and the Langkawi islands. <s> The mainland has a relatively flat terrain, which is used to grow rice, while Langkawi is an archipelago, most of which are uninhabited islands. <s> The state's capital is Alor Setar and the royal seat is in Anak Bukit. <s> Other major towns include Sungai Petani, and Kulim on the mainland, and Kuah on Langkawi.
simple: Kedah is one of the 14 states that form Malaysia. <s> The state is in the northwestern part of the Peninsular Malaysia. <s> It has an area of 9,425 km2. <s> The capital of Kedah is Alor Setar.

title: USS Bunker Hill (CV-17)
complex: USS "Bunker Hill" (CV/CVA/CVS-17, AVT-9) was one of 24 "Essex"-class aircraft carrier s built during World War II for the United States Navy. <s> The ship was named for the Battle of Bunker Hill in the American Revolutionary War. <s> Commissioned in May 1943 and sent to the Pacific Theater of Operations, the ship participated in battles in the Southwest Pacific, Central Pacific and the drive toward Japan through Iwo Jima, Okinawa, and air raids on the Japanese homeland. <s> While covering the invasion of Okinawa, "Bunker Hill" was struck by two kamikazes in quick succession, setting the vessel on fire. <s> Casualties exceeded 600, including 346 confirmed dead and an additional 43 missing, the second heaviest personnel losses suffered by any carrier to survive the war after . <s> After the attack, "Bunker Hill" returned to the U.S. mainland and was still under repair when hostilities ended.
simple: USS "Bunker Hill" (CV/CVA/CVS-17, AVT-9) was one of 24 Essex Aircraft Carriers built during World War II for the United States Navy. <s> The ship was named for the Battle of Bunker Hill in the American Revolutionary War and was commissioned in May 1943. <s> While covering the invasion of Okinawa, "Bunker Hill" was struck by two kamikazes in quick succession, setting the vessel on fire. <s> Casualties exceeded 600, including 346 confirmed dead and an additional 43 missing,

title: Wabash County, Illinois
complex: Wabash County is a county located in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> According to the 2010 census, it had a population of 11,947. <s> Its county seat is Mount Carmel. <s> It is located in the southern portion of Illinois known locally as "Little Egypt".
simple: Wabash County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> In the 2010 census, 11,947 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Mount Carmel.

title: Meloe
complex: The blister beetle genus Meloe is a large, widespread group commonly referred to as oil beetles. <s> They are known as "oil beetles" because they release oily droplets of hemolymph from their joints when disturbed; this contains cantharidin, a poisonous chemical causing blistering of the skin and painful swelling. <s> Members of this genus are typically flightless, without functional wings, and shortened elytra.
simple: The oil beetle (or Meloe) is a blister beetle genus. <s> They are called "oil beetles" because they release oily droplets of hemolymph when disturbed. <s> The liquid is a poisonous chemical that causes skin blistering and painful swelling. <s> Members of this genus do not have wings. <s> They have shortened elytra.

title: Champs, Aisne
complex: Champs is a commune in the Aisne department in Hauts-de-France in northern France.
simple: Champs is a commune.

title: Le Bô
complex: Le Bô is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Le Bô is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Chapel Hill, North Carolina
complex: Chapel Hill is a town in Orange, Chatham, and Durham counties in the U.S. state of North Carolina. <s> Its population was 57,233 in the 2010 census, making Chapel Hill the 15th-largest city in the state. <s> Chapel Hill, Durham, and the state capital, Raleigh, make up the corners of the Research Triangle (officially the Raleigh–Durham–Chapel Hill combined statistical area), with a total population of 1,998,808. <s> Chapel Hill is located in the southeast corner of Orange County. <s> It is bounded on the west by the town of Carrboro and on the northeast by the city of Durham.
simple: Chapel Hill is a town in the U.S. state of North Carolina. <s> It is in an area called The Triangle, because it is next to Raleigh and Durham. <s> Chapel Hill is in southeastern Orange County.

title: Pak Yong-ho
complex: Pak Yong-ho (born May 29, 1974) is a former South Korean football player.
simple: Pak Yong-Ho (朴永浩, born May 29, 1974) is a Japanese athlete.

title: Mats Rådberg
complex: Mats Rådberg, born 8 June 1948 in Brännkyrka Parish in Stockholm, Sweden is a Swedish country singer, guitarist, composer and architect scoring several chart successes in Sweden during the 1970s and 80s. <s> He is well known for working together with the country band Rankarna under the name "Mats Rådberg & Rankarna". <s> He also participated at Melodifestivalen 1977 with the song "Du och jag och sommaren", written by Tomas Ledin, which ended up 10th. <s> Mats Rådberg also acted as a background singer behind Chips at Melodifestivalen 1980. <s> In 1980, he released the album "I'm the Singer, You're the Song" together with Elisabeth Andreasson, and in 1983 he scored a hit with the song "Peta in en pinne i brasan", a Swedish-language version of "Put Another Log on the Fire".
simple: Mats Rådberg, born 8 June 1948 in Brännkyrka Parish in Stockholm, Sweden is a Swedish country singer, guitarist, composer and architect. <s> He scored several chart successes in Sweden during the 1970s and 80s. <s> He is well known for working together with the country band Rankarna under the name "Mats Rådberg & Rankarna". <s> He also participated at Melodifestivalen 1977 with the song "Du och jag och sommaren". <s> The song was written by Tomas Ledin, and ended up 10th. <s> Mats Rådberg also acted as a background singer behind Chips at Melodifestivalen 1980. <s> In 1980, he released the album "I'm the Singer, You're the Song" together with Elisabeth Andreasson. <s> In 1983 he scored a hit with the song "Peta in en pinne i brasan", a Swedish-language version of "Put Another Log on the Fire".

title: Dancing with the Stars (video game)
complex: Dancing with the Stars is a video game based on the show "Dancing with the Stars". <s> It was released on October 23, 2007 in the United States. <s> The game is also being developed for mobile phones, and for the PC. <s> In the game you have option of playing as selected celebrities and professionals from the show. <s> On the mobile phone version, the only characters listed are the celebrities. <s> There are no mentions of their professional partners. <s> For the PC game, the player can choose any of the following characters and he or she will automatically be partnered with either a professional dancer or a celebrity depending on the character the player chooses. <s> The dances included in the game are taken from the ABC TV show of the same name. <s> A sequel, "", was released October 21, 2008 for Wii and Nintendo DS. <s> The game is much improved on the previous ones, with score multipliers, options for new costumes and switching partners, and new songs such as Push It by Salt n' Pepa, Black Horse and the Cherry Tree by KT Tunstall and Lady Marmalade.
simple: Dancing with the Stars is a rhythm game based on the show "Dancing with the Stars". <s> It was released on October 23, 2007 in the United States. <s> In the game you have option of playing as selected celebrities and professional dancers from the show. <s> On the mobile phone version, the only characters listed are the celebrities. <s> There are no mentions of their professional partners. <s> For the PC game, the player can choose any of the following characters and he or she will automatically be partnered with either a professional dancer or a celebrity depending on the character the player chooses. <s> The dances in the game are all dances from the show. <s> , was released October 21, 2008 for Wii and Nintendo DS.

title: Judd Nelson
complex: Judd Asher Nelson (born November 28, 1959) is an American actor best known for his roles as John Bender in "The Breakfast Club", Alec Newbary in "St. Elmo's Fire", Hot Rod / Rodimus Prime in "" and "", Joe Hunt in "Billionaire Boys Club", Nick Peretti in "New Jack City", Billy Beretti in "Empire", and Jack Richmond in the television series "Suddenly Susan".
simple: Judd Asher Nelson (born November 28, 1959) is an American actor, screenwriter, and producer. <s> He is best known for his roles as John Bender in "The Breakfast Club", Alec Newbary in "St. Elmo's Fire", Hot Rod and Rodimus Prime in "" and Jack Richmond in "Suddenly Susan".

title: Arthur Kornberg
complex: Arthur Kornberg (March 3, 1918 – October 26, 2007) was an American biochemist who won the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1959 for his discovery of "the mechanisms in the biological synthesis of deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA)" together with Dr. Severo Ochoa of New York University. <s> He was also awarded the Paul-Lewis Award in Enzyme Chemistry from the American Chemical Society in 1951, L.H.D. degree from Yeshiva University in 1962, as well as National Medal of Science in 1979. <s> His primary research interests were in biochemistry, especially enzyme chemistry, deoxyribonucleic acid synthesis (DNA replication) and studying the nucleic acids which control heredity in animals, plants, bacteria and viruses. <s> Arthur and Sylvy Kornberg had three sons: Roger David Kornberg (1947), Thomas B. Kornberg (1948), and Kenneth Andrew Kornberg (1950). <s> Roger is Professor of Structural Biology at Stanford University, and the 2006 laureate of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry. <s> Thomas discovered DNA polymerase II and III in 1970 and is now a professor at the University of California, San Francisco. <s> Kenneth is an architect specializing in the design of biomedical and biotechnology laboratories and buildings.
simple: Arthur Kornberg (March 3, 1918 – October 26, 2007) was an American biochemist who won the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1959 for his discovery of "the mechanisms in the biological synthesis of deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA)" with Severo Ochoa of New York University. <s> He was awarded the National Medal of Science in 1979. <s> His primary research interests were in biochemistry, especially enzyme chemistry, deoxyribonucleic acid synthesis (DNA replication) and studying the nucleic acids which control heredity in animals, plants, bacteria and viruses. <s> Arthur and Sylvy Kornberg had three sons: Roger Kornberg (1947), Thomas Kornberg (1948), and Kenneth Kornberg (1950). <s> Roger is Professor of Structural Biology at Stanford University, and was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for 2006. <s> Thomas discovered DNA polymerase II and III in 1970 and is now a professor at the University of California, San Francisco. <s> Kenneth is an architect specializing in the design of biomedical and biotechnology laboratories and buildings.

title: Skins (British TV series)
complex: Skins is a British teen comedy-drama television series that follows the lives of a group of teenagers in Bristol, South West England, through the two years of sixth form. <s> Its controversial story-lines have explored issues like dysfunctional families, mental illness (such as depression, eating disorders, post-traumatic stress disorder and bipolar disorder), adolescent sexuality, gender, substance abuse, Autism spectrum disorder, death, and bullying. <s> Each episode generally focuses on a particular character and the struggles he or she faces in his or her life and the episodes are named after the featured character. <s> The show was created by father-and-son television writers Bryan Elsley and Jamie Brittain for Company Pictures, and premiered on E4 on 25 January 2007. <s> "Skins" went on to be a critical success as well as a ratings winner. <s> Other ventures to expand the brand have included a short-lived American remake, which aired on MTV in 2011, but was cancelled after one season after advertisers abandoned the series in response to low ratings and the significant controversy which arose over its depiction of teen sexuality.
simple: Skins is a controversial and two time BAFTA-winning British teen drama about a group of English teenagers growing up in Bristol. <s> The show was created by television writers Bryan Elsley and Jamie Brittain, and was first shown on E4 on 25 January 2007. <s> The remake made in the USA was shown on MTV in 2011.

title: Great power
complex: A great power is a sovereign state that is recognized as having the ability and expertise to exert its influence on a global scale. <s> Great powers characteristically possess military and economic strength, as well as diplomatic and soft power influence, which may cause middle or small powers to consider the great powers' opinions before taking actions of their own. <s> International relations theorists have posited that great power status can be characterized into power capabilities, spatial aspects, and status dimensions.
simple: A great power is a nation or state that is able to influence other states in most of the world. <s> That is possible because it has great economic, political and military strength.

title: Savonlinna
complex: Savonlinna ( , ] , ; ) is a town and a municipality of inhabitants in the southeast of Finland, in the heart of the Saimaa lake region.
simple: Savonlinna is a town in Finland.

title: Lake Zug
complex: Lake Zug is a lake in Central Switzerland, situated between Lake Lucerne and Lake Zurich. <s> It stretches for 14 km between Arth and the Cham-Zug bay. <s> The Lorze as the main feeder river empties its waters into the lake at its northern extremity, but 1 km (0.6 mi) further west issues from the lake to pursue its course towards the Reuss. <s> Due to this poor feeding, Environmental protection is very important as the lake would suffer long term damage if polluted as the second of the rivers, "Rigiaa", feeds only a marginal amount into the lake at its southern end. <s> Already a great part of the fauna in the deep parts of the lake has been lost. <s> The lake is mostly within the borders of the Canton of Zug, with about 10 km2 at its southern end in the canton Schwyz, while the Canton of Lucerne claims about 2 km2 to the north of Immensee. <s> Toward the south-west extremity of the lake the Rigi descends rather steeply to the water's edge, while part of its east shore forms a narrow level band at the foot of the 1,583 m (5,194 ft) Rossberg, and the Zugerberg. <s> The culminating point of the lake's drainage basin is the summit of the Rigi at 1,798 m. <s> At its northern end, the shores are nearly level, while on the west shore the wooded promontory of Buonas (with its castles, old and new) projects picturesquely into the waters. <s> The principal place on the lake is the town of Zug. <s> Three railways follow the shore of the lake, one from Zurich via Zug and Arth-Goldau to the St Gotthard, one from Lucerne via Arth-Goldau to the St Gotthard, and the third from Zurich via Zug to Lucerne. <s> Many fish (including pike and carp of considerable weights) are taken in the lake, which is especially famous for an endemic kind of trout ("Salmo salvelinus", locally called "Rolheli"). <s> The first steamer was placed on the lake in 1852.
simple: The Lake Zug (German: "Zugersee") is one of the lesser known Swiss lakes, on the outskirts of the Alps and north of Lake Lucerne. <s> The Lorze feeds the lake at the northern shore. <s> For the most part, the lake is in the Canton of Zug, but the southern end is up to 10 km in the canton of Schwyz, while the Canton of Lucerne stretches over a 2 km area by the Immensee. <s> At its northern end the shores are nearly level, while on the west shore the wooded promontory of Buonas (with its castles, old and new) projects picturesquely into the waters. <s> The principal place on the lake is the town of Zug. <s> Three railways follow the shore of the lake, one from Zürich via Zug and Arth-Goldau to the St Gotthard, one from Lucerne via Arth-Goldau to the St Gotthard and one from Zürich via Zug to Lucerne. <s> Many fish (including pike and carp of considerable weights) are taken from the lake, which is especially famous for an endemic kind of trout ("Salmo salvelinus", locally called "Rolheli"). <s> The first steamer was placed on the lake in 1852.

title: Shoreditch
complex: Shoreditch is a district in the East End of London, which is divided between the London boroughs of Hackney and Tower Hamlets. <s> It is part of the traditional county of Middlesex, but for administrative purposes became part of the County of London following the passing of the Local Government Act 1888, and part of Greater London in 1965.
simple: Shoreditch is a district in East London, England. <s> It is in the London Borough of Hackney.

title: Port Authority of New York and New Jersey Police Department
complex: The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey Police Department, or Port Authority Police Department (PAPD), is a law enforcement agency in New York and New Jersey, the duties of which are to protect and to enforce state and city laws at all the facilities, owned or operated by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey (PANYNJ), the bi-state agency running airports, seaports, and many bridges and tunnels within the Port of New York and New Jersey. <s> Additionally, the PAPD is responsible for other PANYNJ properties including three bus terminals (the Port Authority Bus Terminal, the George Washington Bridge Bus Station and Journal Square Transportation Center), the World Trade Center in lower Manhattan, and the PATH train system. <s> The PAPD is the largest transit-related police force in the United States. <s> On February 26, 1993, the Port Authority's World Trade Center complex was the target of a terrorist attack bombing. <s> On September 11, 2001, the complex was the target of terrorist attacks for a second time. <s> The complex housed over 50,000 employees and accommodated 70,000 visitors per day; the efforts of the Port Authority Police, the New York City Police Department (NYPD), the New York City Fire Department (FDNY), New York City Sheriff's Office, New York State Court Officers, and federal law enforcement officers, along with countless others, helped to minimize the loss of life. <s> The Port Authority Police suffered the worst loss of police personnel in a single event in American history: 37 police officers, along with one police K-9 named Sirius, were killed on September 11.
simple: The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey Police Department, or Port Authority Police Department (PAPD), is a police department in New York and New Jersey. <s> It protects all the property owned by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, and it enforces state and city laws. <s> The PAPD is owned by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, a two-state agency that runs the bridges, tunnels, airports, and seaports along the New York - New Jersey border. <s> The PAPD is one of the largest police departments in the United States, with 1,660 members. <s> On February 26, 1993 the Port Authority's World Trade Center was the target of a terrorist attack, and of the more successful September 11 attacks in 2001. <s> The area had over 50,000 employees and 70,000 visitors per day; the work of emergency personnel including the Port Authority Police, the New York City Police Department, the New York City Fire Department, New York City EMS, New York State Court Officers, Federal Agents and many others helped to lower the deaths from the attack. <s> The Port Authority Police had the biggest loss of police personnel at a single time in American history: 37 police officers along with one police dog were killed on September 11th.

title: Iggesund
complex: Iggesund is a locality situated in Hudiksvall Municipality, Gävleborg County, Sweden with 3,362 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Iggesund is a locality in Hudiksvall Municipality in Gävleborg County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 3,362 people lived there.

title: Oséas
complex: Oséas Reis dos Santos (born May 14, 1971 in Salvador, Bahia, Brazil), known as Oséas, is a retired Brazilian football player.
simple: Oséas Reis dos Santos (born 14 May 1971) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Treasure Coast
complex: The Treasure Coast is a region of the U.S. state of Florida. <s> It is located on the state's Atlantic coast, comprising Indian River, St. Lucie, and Martin, and in some definitions, Palm Beach counties. <s> The region, whose name refers to the Spanish Treasure Fleet lost in a 1715 hurricane, evidently emerged from residents' desire to distinguish themselves from Miami and the Gold Coast region to the south. <s> The area has long been inhabited, but like other of Florida's vernacular regions, a popular identity for the area did not emerge until the area saw its initial population boom in the 20th century.
simple: Treasure Coast is a region in the US state of Florida. <s> It is found on the state's Atlantic coast. <s> The name "Treasure Coast" refers to the Spanish Treasure Fleet lost in a 1715 hurricane.

title: Syd Ward (cricketer)
complex: Sydney William "Syd" Ward (5 August 1907 – 31 December 2010) was an Australian-born New Zealand cricketer. <s> Ward was a right-handed batsman who bowled right-arm medium pace. <s> He was born in Sydney, New South Wales, and, from the death of Frank Shipston on 6 July 2005 until his death, was considered the oldest living first-class cricketer and the second oldest ever, behind Jim Hutchinson. <s> Following his death, Cyril Perkins became the oldest living first-class cricketer.
simple: Sydney William Ward (born 5 August 1907 – died 31 December 2010) ) was an Australian-born New Zealand cricketer. <s> Ward was a right-handed batsman who bowled right-arm medium pace. <s> He was born in Sydney, New South Wales. <s> He is the second longest-lived cricketer, behind England's Jim Hutchinson, who at the time of his death was 103 years and 344 days old.

title: Apollo 9
complex: Apollo 9 was a March 1969 human spaceflight, the third crewed mission in the United States Apollo program. <s> Flown in low Earth orbit, it was the second crewed Apollo mission to be launched by a Saturn V rocket, and the first flight of the full Apollo spacecraft: the command and service module (CSM) with the Lunar Module (LM). <s> The mission was flown to qualify the LM for lunar orbit operations by demonstrating its descent and ascent propulsion systems, showing that its crew could fly it independently, then rendezvous and dock with the CSM again, as would be required for the first crewed lunar landing. <s> Other objectives of the flight included firing the LM descent engine to propel the spacecraft stack as a backup mode (as would be required on the Apollo 13 mission), and use of the Portable Life Support System backpack outside of the LM cabin. <s> The three-person crew consisted of Commander James McDivitt, Command Module Pilot David Scott, and Lunar Module Pilot Rusty Schweickart. <s> During the ten-day mission, they tested systems and procedures critical to landing on the Moon, including the LM engines, backpack life support systems, navigation systems and docking maneuvers. <s> After launching on March 3, 1969, the crew performed the first crewed flight of a lunar module, the first docking and extraction of the same, one two-person spacewalk (EVA), and the second docking of two crewed spacecraft—two months after the Soviets performed a spacewalk crew transfer between Soyuz 4 and Soyuz 5. <s> The mission concluded on March 13 and was a complete success.
simple: Apollo 9 was a mission in NASA's Apollo program. <s> It was the third manned mission in the Apollo program and was the first flight of the Command/Service Module (CSM) with the Lunar Module (LM). <s> The crew was Commander James A. McDivitt, Command Module Pilot David R. Scott, and Lunar Module Pilot Russell L. Schweickart. <s> The mission tested several things which were important for landing on the Moon, including the LM engines, backpack life support systems, navigation systems, and docking maneuvers. <s> The mission was launched on March 3, 1969.

title: Kay Bailey Hutchison
complex: Kay Bailey Hutchison (born Kathryn Ann Bailey; July 22, 1943) is an American attorney, television correspondent, politician, and diplomat who is the 22nd United States Permanent Representative to NATO. <s> A member of the Republican Party, she was previously a United States Senator for Texas from 1993 to 2013. <s> On June 29, 2017, Hutchison was nominated by President Donald Trump to be the next United States Permanent Representative to NATO. <s> She was confirmed by the U.S. Senate in a voice vote on August 3, 2017. <s> On June 29, 2017, Hutchison was nominated by President Donald Trump to be the United States Permanent Representative to NATO.
simple: Kay Bailey Hutchison (born July 22, 1943) is an American politician. <s> Hutchison is the 22nd and current United States Permanent Representative to NATO since August 28, 2017. <s> On June 29, 2017, Hutchison was nominated to be the next United States Permanent Representative to NATO by Donald Trump. <s> She was confirmed by the Senate in a voice vote on August 3, 2017.

title: Thyreophora
complex: Thyreophora ("shield bearers", often known simply as "armored dinosaurs") is a group of armored ornithischian dinosaurs that lived from the early Jurassic Period until the end of the Cretaceous.
simple: Thyreophora is a suborder of ornithischian dinosaurs. <s> They were the armoured dinosaurs: the name means 'shield-bearer'.

complex: Year 587 (DLXXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. <s> The denomination 587 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: Year 587 (DLXXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. <s> The denomination 587 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.

title: Sinhala script
complex: Sinhala script is an abugida written from left to right. <s> Sinhala letters are ordered into two sets.
simple: Sinhala script is an Abugida, a script between a syllabic and alphabetic script.

title: Charles Ranhofer
complex: Charles Ranhofer (November 7, 1836 in Saint-Denis, France – October 9, 1899 in New York) was the chef at Delmonico's Restaurant in New York from 1862 to 1876 and 1879 to 1896. <s> Ranhofer was the author of "The Epicurean" (1894), an encyclopedic cookbook of over 1,000 pages, similar in scope to Escoffier's "Le Guide Culinaire". <s> Ranhofer was sent to Paris at the age of 12 to begin his training by studying pastry-making, and at 16 became the private chef for the prince d'Hénin, comte d'Alsace. <s> In 1856 he moved to New York to become the chef for the Russian consul, and later worked in Washington, D.C. and New Orleans. <s> He returned to France in 1860 for a short time, where he arranged balls for the court of Napoleon III at the Tuileries Palace, but then came back to New York to work at what was then a fashionable location, "Maison Dorée". <s> In 1862, Lorenzo Delmonico hired him for Delmonico's, and it was there that Ranhofer made his real fame, though others say that he made the fame of the restaurant as well. <s> At that time, Delmonico's was considered the finest restaurant in the United States. <s> He was the chef at Delmonico's until his retirement in 1896, except for a short hiatus from 1876 to 1879 when he owned the Hotel American at Enghien-les-Bains. <s> Ranhofer is credited (often on slim evidence) with inventing or making famous a number of dishes that Delmonico's was known for, such as Lobster Newberg, and had a talent for naming dishes after famous or prominent people—particularly those who dined at Delmonico's—as well as his friends, and events of the day. <s> Examples include: Others may be found under List of foods named after people. <s> Ranhofer did not invent baked Alaska, nor do the menus he provides in "The Epicurean" mention anything similar, not even his own Alaska-Florida (the term he himself used for his similar dessert). <s> He also experimented with new foods, acquainting New Yorkers with the "alligator pear" (avocado) in 1895, among other things. <s> Ranhofer and his wife Rose had five children: three sons and two daughters. <s> He died at home of Bright's Disease in 1899 and was buried at Woodlawn Cemetery in The Bronx, New York City.
simple: Charles Ranhofer (November 7, 1836, Saint-Denis, France — October 9, 1899, New York) was the chef at the famous Delmonico's Restaurant in New York from 1862 to 1876 and 1879 to 1896. <s> Ranhofer wrote "The Epicurean", (1894), a cookbook of over 1,000 pages, similar in scope to Escoffier's "Le Guide Culinaire". <s> Ranhofer was sent to Paris at the age of 12 to begin his training by studying pastry-making, and at 16 became the private chef for the prince d'Hénin, comte d'Alsace. <s> In 1856 he moved to New York to become the chef for the Russian consul, and later worked in Washington, D.C. and New Orleans. <s> He returned to France in 1860 for a short time, where he arranged balls for the court of Napoleon III at the Tuileries Palace, but then came back to New York to work at what was then a fashionable location, "Maison Dorée". <s> In 1862, Lorenzo Delmonico hired him for Delmonico's Restaurant, and it was there that Ranhofer made his real fame, though others say that he made the fame of the restaurant as well. <s> At that time, Delmonico's was considered the finest restaurant in the United States. <s> He was the chef at Delmonico's until his retirement in 1896, except for a short break from 1876 and 1879 when he owned the "Hotel American" at Enghien-les-Bains. <s> Ranhofer invented or made famous a number of dishes that Delmonico's was known for, such as Lobster Newberg, and had a talent for naming dishes after famous or prominent people—particularly those who dined at Delmonico's--as well as his friends, and events of the day. <s> Examples include: "Many others may be found under "List of foods named after people."" <s> Ranhofer did not invent baked Alaska, but he popularized it in 1876 when he named it in honor of the newly acquired Alaskan territory. <s> Ranhofer and his wife Rose had five children: three sons and two daughters. <s> He died at home of Bright's Disease in 1899. <s> He was buried at Woodlawn Cemetery.

title: Qʼeqchiʼ
complex: Qʼeqchiʼ (/qʼeqt͡ʃiʔ/ ) (Kʼekchiʼ in the former orthography, or simply Kekchi in many English-language contexts, such as in Belize) are a Maya people of Guatemala and Belize. <s> Their indigenous language is the Qʼeqchiʼ language. <s> Before the beginning of the Spanish conquest of Guatemala in the 1520s, Qʼeqchiʼ settlements were concentrated in what are now the departments of Alta Verapaz and Baja Verapaz. <s> Over the course of the succeeding centuries a series of land displacements, resettlements, persecutions and migrations resulted in a wider dispersal of Qʼeqchiʼ communities into other regions of Guatemala (Izabal, Petén, El Quiché), southern Belize (Toledo District), and smaller numbers in southern Mexico (Chiapas, Campeche).
simple: Q'eqchi ' (K'ekchi ' , or simply Kekchi) are one of the Maya peoples in Guatemala and Belize. <s> Before the Spanish came in the 1520s, Q'eqchi' were mostly in what are now the departments of Alta Verapaz and Baja Verapaz in Guatemala.

title: How to Train Your Dragon (film)
complex: How to Train Your Dragon is a 2010 American computer-animated action fantasy film loosely based on the 2003 book of the same name by British author Cressida Cowell, produced by DreamWorks Animation and distributed by Paramount Pictures. <s> The film was directed by Chris Sanders and Dean DeBlois from a screenplay by Will Davies, Sanders, and DeBlois, and stars the voices of Jay Baruchel, Gerard Butler, Craig Ferguson, America Ferrera, Jonah Hill, Christopher Mintz-Plasse, T. J. Miller, and Kristen Wiig. <s> The story takes place in a mythical Viking world where a young Viking teenager named Hiccup aspires to follow his tribe's tradition of becoming a dragon slayer. <s> After finally capturing his first dragon, and with his chance at last of gaining the tribe's acceptance, he finds that he no longer wants to kill the dragon and instead befriends it. <s> The film premiered at the Gibson Amphitheater on March 21, 2010, and was released in the United States five days later on March 26. <s> The film was a critical and commercial success, earning praise from film critics and audiences and earning nearly $500 million worldwide. <s> It was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature and Best Original Score at the 83rd Academy Awards, but lost to "Toy Story 3" and "The Social Network", respectively. <s> "How to Train Your Dragon" also won ten Annie Awards, including Best Animated Feature. <s> Two sequels, "How to Train Your Dragon 2" and "", were released on June 13, 2014, and February 22, 2019, respectively. <s> Much like their predecessor, both sequels were widely praised and became box office successes.
simple: How to Train Your Dragon is a 2010 computer animated fantasy-comedy movie from DreamWorks Animation. <s> It is based on the 2003 book of the same name. <s> It was produced by Bonnie Arnold, Doug Davison, Roy Lee, Michael Connolly and Tim Johnson and was directed by Chris Sanders and Dean DeBlois. <s> The movie was released on March 26, 2010. <s> The movie was nominated for two Academy Awards for Best Animated Feature and Best Original Score. <s> A sequel How To Train Your Dragon 2 released on June 13, 2014. <s> A third film How To Train Your Dragon 3 will be released in 2019.

title: Nickelodeon Movies
complex: Nickelodeon Movies is the theatrical motion picture production arm of the Nickelodeon TV channel. <s> Founded in 1996, the company released its first film "Harriet the Spy" in 1996.
simple: Nickelodeon Movies is the motion picture production arm of children's cable channel Nickelodeon, originally launched in 1996.

title: Write Anywhere File Layout
complex: The Write Anywhere File Layout (WAFL) is a proprietary file system that supports large, high-performance RAID arrays, quick restarts without lengthy consistency checks in the event of a crash or power failure, and growing the filesystems size quickly. <s> It was designed by NetApp for use in its storage appliances like NetApp FAS, AFF, Cloud Volumes ONTAP and ONTAP Select.
simple: Write Anywhere File Layout (WAFL) is a file system.

title: Gayle Gardner
complex: Gayle Gardner (born ca. 1950) is an American sportscaster who worked for ESPN and NBC Sports beginning in 1987 until 1993. <s> Gardner is considered a pioneer in sports broadcasting, having been the first female sports anchor to appear weekly on a major network. <s> After being hired by ESPN in 1983, Gardner served as a "SportsCenter" anchor for three years. <s> Gardner then worked for NBC from 1987-1993.
simple: Gayle Gardner is a former sportscaster who worked with ESPN and NBC. <s> She was an anchor for "SportsCenter" for three years before NBC hired her.

title: Takalik Abaj
complex: Tak'alik Ab'aj ( ; ] ; ] ) is a pre-Columbian archaeological site in Guatemala. <s> It was formerly known as Abaj Takalik; its ancient name may have been Kooja. <s> It is one of several Mesoamerican sites with both Olmec and Maya features. <s> The site flourished in the Preclassic and Classic periods, from the 9th century BC through to at least the 10th century AD, and was an important centre of commerce, trading with Kaminaljuyu and Chocolá. <s> Investigations have revealed that it is one of the largest sites with sculptured monuments on the Pacific coastal plain. <s> Olmec-style sculptures include a possible colossal head, petroglyphs and others. <s> The site has one of the greatest concentrations of Olmec-style sculpture outside of the Gulf of Mexico. <s> Takalik Abaj is representative of the first blossoming of Maya culture that had occurred by about 400 BC. <s> The site includes a Maya royal tomb and examples of Maya hieroglyphic inscriptions that are among the earliest from the Maya region. <s> Excavation is continuing at the site; the monumental architecture and persistent tradition of sculpture in a variety of styles suggest the site was of some importance. <s> Finds from the site indicate contact with the distant metropolis of Teotihuacan in the Valley of Mexico and imply that Takalik Abaj was conquered by it or its allies. <s> Takalik Abaj was linked to long-distance Maya trade routes that shifted over time but allowed the city to participate in a trade network that included the Guatemalan highlands and the Pacific coastal plain from Mexico to El Salvador. <s> Takalik Abaj was a sizeable city with the principal architecture clustered into four main groups spread across nine terraces. <s> While some of these were natural features, others were artificial constructions requiring an enormous investment in labour and materials. <s> The site featured a sophisticated water drainage system and a wealth of sculptured monuments.
simple: It is one of several Mesoamerican sites that have Olmec and Maya features. <s> The site was inhabited the during the Preclassic and Classic periods, from the 9th century BC through to at least the 10th century AD. <s> It traded with Kaminaljuyu and Chocolá. <s> It is one of the largest sites with carved monuments on the Pacific coast. <s> Olmec-style sculptures include a possible colossal head, rock carvings and others. <s> The site has one of the biggest collections of Olmec-style sculpture outside of the Gulf of Mexico. <s> Takalik Abaj shows the first signs of Maya culture that happened by about 400 BC. <s> The site includes a Maya royal tomb and examples of Maya writing that are among the first from the Maya region. <s> Studies continue at the site; the monumental buildings and long tradition of sculpture in a variety of styles suggest the site was important. <s> Finds from the site indicate contact with the distant city of Teotihuacan in the Valley of Mexico. <s> They imply that Takalik Abaj was conquered by it or its allies. <s> Takalik Abaj was linked to long-distance Maya trade routes that let the city take part in a trade network that included the Guatemalan highlands and the Pacific coastal plain from Mexico to El Salvador. <s> Takalik Abaj was a large city with the main buildings in four main groups spread across nine terraces. <s> While some of these were natural, others were man-made, needing a lot of work and materials. <s> The site had a clever water drainage system and many stone sculptures.

title: Loleatta Holloway
complex: Loleatta Holloway ( , ; November 5, 1946 – March 21, 2011) was an American singer, mainly known for disco songs such as "Hit and Run" and "Love Sensation", both of which have been sampled extensively. <s> In December 2016, "Billboard magazine" ranked her as the 95th most successful dance artist of all-time. <s> Holloway died aged 64 on March 21, 2011 from heart failure and is survived by her four children.
simple: Loleatta Holloway (November 5, 1946 – March 21, 2011) was an American singer. <s> She was known mainly for disco songs, such as "Hit and Run" and "Love Sensation". <s> She died there from heart failure.

title: Dhṛtarāṣṭra
complex: Dhṛtarāṣṭra (Sanskrit; Pali: "Dhataraṭṭha") is a major deity in Buddhism and one of the Four Heavenly Kings. <s> His name means "Upholder of the Nation." <s> The name "Dhṛtarāṣṭra" is a Sanskrit compound of the words "dhṛta" (possessing; bearing) and "rāṣṭra" (kingdom; territory). <s> Dhṛtarāṣṭra is the guardian of the eastern direction. <s> He lives on the eastern part of Sumeru. <s> He is leader of the gandharvas and piśācas. <s> Most East Asian depictions of Dhṛtarāṣṭra show him playing a stringed instrument, but the presence of this motif varies. <s> In the Pāli Canon of Theravāda Buddhism, Dhṛtarāṣṭra is called Dhataraṭṭha. <s> Dhataraṭṭha is one of the Cātummahārājāno, or "Four Great Kings." <s> each of whom rules over a specific direction. <s> He has many sons who go by the title "Indra, as well as a daughter named "Sirī". <s> In Japan, Jikokuten (持国天) is commonly depicted with a fierce expression. <s> He is clad in armor, often brandishing a sword or trident spear while trampling a jaki.
simple: Dhritarashtra (Sanskrit: धृतराष्ट्र, "Dhṛtarāṣṭra") or Dhatarattha (Pali: धतरट्ठ "Dhataraṭṭha") is one of the Four Heavenly Kings and an important person in Buddhism. <s> The name Dhṛtarāṣṭra comes from two Sanskrit words: "dhṛta" (possessing; bearing) and "rāṣṭra" (kingdom; territory). <s> Dhṛtarāṣṭra is the guardian god of the East. <s> He lives on the eastern part of Mount Sumeru. <s> He is leader of the gandharvas and the pishacas. <s> He is often shown in art playing a stringed instrument. <s> In the Pāli writings of the Theravada Buddhist tradition, Dhṛtarāṣṭra is called "Dhataraṭṭha". <s> Dhataraṭṭha is one of the Four Great Kings, each one of which rules over a direction. <s> He has many sons called "Indra." <s> He also has a daughter named "Sirī". <s> In Japan, Jikokuten (持国天) is often shown wearing a suit of armor. <s> He usually holds a sword and a trident while standing on top of a demon called a "jaki".

title: Yajurveda
complex: The Yajurveda (Sanskrit: यजुर्वेद, " ", from " " meaning "worship", and "veda" meaning "knowledge") is the Veda primarily of prose mantras for worship rituals. <s> An ancient Vedic Sanskrit text, it is a compilation of ritual offering formulas that were said by a priest while an individual performed ritual actions such as those before the yajna fire.
simple: The Yajurveda (Sanskrit: यजुर्वेद, ', from ' meaning "prose mantra" and "veda" meaning "knowledge") is one of the four Vedas, and one of the scriptures of Hinduism.

title: Pietà (Michelangelo)
complex: The Pietà (] ; ; 1498–1499) is a work of Renaissance sculpture by Michelangelo Buonarroti, housed in St. Peter's Basilica, Vatican City. <s> It is the first of a number of works of the same theme by the artist.
simple: The Pieta is a statue by Michelangelo. <s> It is now in the first temple on the right of Saint Peter's Basilica in the Vatican City.

title: Syringa
complex: Syringa (lilac) is a genus of 12 currently recognized species of flowering woody plants in the olive family (Oleaceae), native to woodland and scrub from southeastern Europe to eastern Asia, and widely and commonly cultivated in temperate areas elsewhere. <s> Lilacs are popular shrubs in parks and gardens throughout the temperate zone, and several hybrids and numerous cultivars have been developed. <s> The term French lilac is often used to refer to modern double-flowered cultivars, thanks to the work of prolific breeder Victor Lemoine.
simple: Lilacs are plants in the genus Syringa, in the family Oleaceae. <s> Syringas are another name for the Lilac, as well as the generic name. <s> Lilacs are popular garden plants in many area.

title: Diprotodontia
complex: Diprotodontia is an order of about 155 species of marsupial mammals including the kangaroos, wallabies, possums, koala, wombats, and many others. <s> Extinct diprotodonts include the rhinoceros-sized "Diprotodon", and "Thylacoleo", the so-called "marsupial lion". <s> † means extinct family, genus or species.
simple: The Diprotodontia is a large order of about 120 Australasian marsupial mammals. <s> It includes the kangaroos, wallabies, possums, koala, wombats, and many others. <s> Extinct members include the giant Diprotodon family, and "Thylacoleo", the so-called "marsupial lion". <s> † means extinct family, genus or species.
