title: Chailley
complex: Chailley is a commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France.
simple: Chailley is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Mo Collins (American football)
complex: Damon Jamal Collins (September 22, 1976 – October 26, 2014), nicknamed Mo Collins, was an American college and professional football player who was an offensive lineman in the National Football League (NFL) for six seasons during the 1990s and early 2000s. <s> Collins played college football for the University of Florida, and was a member of a national championship team. <s> The Oakland Raiders selected him in the first round of the 1998 NFL Draft, and he played his entire professional career for the Raiders. <s> Collins was hired as the head coach of the West Charlotte Lions football team of West Charlotte High School, his alma mater, on February 7, 2014. <s> Collins died Sunday, October 26, 2014; he had been receiving dialysis treatment after suffering kidney failure.
simple: Damon Jamal Collins (September 22, 1976 – October 26, 2014), nicknamed Mo Collins, was an American college and professional football player. <s> He was an offensive lineman in the National Football League (NFL) for six seasons during the 1990s and early 2000s. <s> Collins played college football for the University of Florida, and was a member of a national championship team. <s> The Oakland Raiders selected him in the first round of the 1998 NFL Draft, and he played his entire professional career for the Raiders. <s> Collins died of kidney failure in Charlotte, North Carolina, aged 38.

title: Saiful Muluk National Park
complex: Saiful Muluk National Park is located in the Kaghan Valley in Mansehra District of Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa, in northern Pakistan. <s> The park was created in 2003, and is centred upon the alpine Saif ul Maluk Lake. <s> Some of the park's fauna includes the snow leopard, asiatic black bear, marmot, weasel, eurasian lynx, indian leopard, Himalayan snowcock, and the snow partridge. <s> The park's lakes and wetlands habitats are of significant ecological importance for resident fauna and migratory waterfowl. <s> Lulusar-Dudipatsar National Park, with Lulusar Lake and Dudipatsar Lake, is adjacent to Saiful Muluk National Park in the Kaghan Valley region. <s> Together the parks protect 88000 ha .
simple: Saiful Muluk National Park is located in the Kaghan Valley in Mansehra District of Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa, in northern Pakistan. <s> The park was created in 2003. <s> Some of the park's fauna includes the snow leopard, asiatic black bear, marmot, weasel, eurasian lynx, indian leopard, Himalayan snowcock, and the snow partridge. <s> Lulusar-Dudipatsar National Park is close to Saiful Muluk National Park.

title: Grand Bahama International Airport
complex: Grand Bahama International Airport (GBIA) is a privately owned international airport in Freeport, Bahamas. <s> The airport is a joint venture between Hutchison Port Holdings (HPH) and The Port Group (or the Grand Bahama Port Authority). <s> The facility also includes 741 acre of land that adjoins it to the Freeport Harbour Company Limited as they operate as one entity, known as the Sea Air Business Centre (SABC). <s> The airport has a 3359 x runway which is capable of handling the largest aircraft in service and is relatively close to all major cities of the Eastern Seaboard of the United States. <s> Grand Bahama International Airport is one of two Bahamian airports that has US border preclearance facilities (the other being Lynden Pindling).
simple: Grand Bahama International Airport (GBIA) is a privately owned international airport. <s> It is in Freeport, Bahamas. <s> The airport is a joint venture between Hutchison Port Holdings (HPH) and The Port Group (or the Grand Bahama Port Authority). <s> It also has 741 acre of land. <s> This adjoins it to the Freeport Harbour Company Limited. <s> So, they work as one body, known as the Sea Air Business Centre (SABC). <s> The airport has a 3359 x runway. <s> It can handle the largest aircraft in service. <s> It is quite close to all major cities of the Eastern Seaboard of the United States. <s> Grand Bahama International Airport is one of two Bahamian airports that has US border preclearance facilities.

title: Laxmi Prasad Devkota
complex: Laxmi Prasad Devkota ( ,(12 November 1909 – 14 September 1959) was a Nepali poet, playwright, and novelist. <s> Honored with the title of Mahakavi (literal translation: "The Great Poet" or Poet the Great) in Nepali literature, and is known as the poet with the golden heart. <s> Devkota is by and large regarded as the great poet (महाकवि) of Nepali language. <s> Some of his popular works including the best selling "Muna Madan", along with "Sulochana","Kunjini", and "Sakuntala".
simple: Laxmi Prasad Devkota was a Nepali poet, playwright, scholar, and novelist. <s> He is given the title of Mahakavi in Nepali Literature, which means The Great Poet. <s> He is known as the poet with the golden heart. <s> Some of his famous works are "Muna Madan", "Sulochana", "Kunjini", and "Sakuntala".

title: Cath Kidston Limited
complex: Cath Kidston Limited is a British international chain of home furnishing retail stores based in England, registered with Companies House, number 02808583, on 13 April 1993. <s> The company's profits jumped more than 60 per cent from £2.9million to £4.6million in the year to March 2009. <s> Sales rose to £31.3m during the period, compared with £19.3m the year before, partly due to new store openings. <s> In 2010, Cath Kidston sold a majority stake of the company to private equity investors TA Associates, retaining a minority stake and remaining the company's Creative Director.
simple: Cath Kidston Limited was registered with Companies House, on 3 April 1993. <s> In 2009, the company's profits jumped more than 60 percent from £2.9million to £4.6million. <s> Sales rose to £31.3m, compared with £19.3m the year before. <s> This was partly due to new store openings. <s> She sold most of her shares in the company in 2010. <s> She sold them to private equity investors called TA Associates.

title: Walter Ulbricht
complex: Walter Ernst Paul Ulbricht (] ; 30 June 18931 August 1973) was a German communist politician. <s> Ulbricht played a leading role in the creation of the Weimar-era Communist Party of Germany (KPD) and later (after spending the years of Nazi rule in exile in France and the Soviet Union) in the early development and establishment of the German Democratic Republic in East Germany. <s> As the First Secretary of the Socialist Unity Party from 1950 to 1971, he was the chief decision maker in East Germany. <s> From President Wilhelm Pieck's death in 1960 on, he was also the East German head of state until his own death in 1973. <s> After the end of World War II, Ulbricht re-organized the German Communist Party in the Soviet occupation zone along Stalinist lines.
simple: Walter Ernst Paul Ulbricht (30 June 18931 August 1973) was a German communist politician. <s> Ulbricht played a leading role in the creation of the Weimar-era Communist Party of Germany (KPD). <s> Some time after Hitler's rise to power Ulbricht fled to France and later to the Soviet Union. <s> He was the first secretary of the Socialist Unity Party (SED), and leading East Germany from 1950 to 1971. <s> From President Wilhelm Pieck's death in 1960, he was also the East German head of state until his own death in 1973.

title: Breckin Meyer
complex: Breckin Erin Meyer (born May 7, 1974) is an American actor, voice actor, writer, producer and drummer known for his roles in films such as "Clueless", "Road Trip", "Rat Race" and "".
simple: Breckin Erin Meyer (born May 7, 1974) is an American actor, comedian, writer, television producer, and drummer.

title: Districts of Luxembourg
complex: The three districts of Luxembourg ( , , ) were the top-level administrative divisions of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg. <s> The cantons were created on 24 February 1843. <s> In 1857, Mersch District was created from the cantons of Mersch and Redange. <s> However, this fourth district was abolished in 1867, when the re-arrangements of 1857 were undone. <s> The districts were abolished per 3 October 2015.
simple: The former three districts of Luxembourg (, , ) were the top-level administrative divisions of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg. <s> The districts (and cantons) were created on 24 February 1843. <s> In 1857, the "Mersch" district was created from the cantons of Mersch and Redange. <s> However, this fourth district was abolished in 1867. <s> In October 2015, the districts were abolished.

title: Bonsall, California
complex: Bonsall is a census-designated place (CDP) in San Diego County, California. <s> The population was 3,982 at the 2010 census, up from 3,401 at the 2000 census. <s> Bonsall is located just east of Oceanside and Camp Pendleton, north of Vista and northwest of Hidden Meadows. <s> The 2010 United States Census reported that Bonsall had a population of 3,982. <s> The population density was 293.5 people per square mile (113.3/km2).
simple: Bonsall is a census designated place (CDP) in San Diego County, California, United States. <s> It is east of Oceanside and Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton. <s> In 2010, the city had 3,982 people.

title: Cradle of Filth
complex: Cradle of Filth are an English extreme metal band, formed in Suffolk, England in 1991. <s> The band's musical style evolved originally from black metal to a cleaner and more "produced" amalgam of gothic metal, symphonic metal and other metal genres. <s> Their lyrical themes and imagery are heavily influenced by Gothic literature, poetry, mythology and horror films.
simple: Cradle of Filth is an extreme metal band from England. <s> Some people say the band’s musical style is black metal, others say that it is gothic metal, extreme metal, or many other different styles.

title: Liberal Party (UK)
complex: The Liberal Party was one of the two major parties in the United Kingdom with the opposing Conservative Party in the 19th and early 20th centuries. <s> The party arose from an alliance of Whigs and free trade Peelites and Radicals favourable to the ideals of the American and French Revolutions in the 1850s. <s> By the end of the 19th century, it had formed four governments under William Gladstone. <s> Despite being divided over the issue of Irish Home Rule, the party returned to government in 1905 and then won a landslide victory in the following year's general election. <s> Under Prime Ministers Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman (1905–1908) and H. H. Asquith (1908–1916), the Liberal Party passed the welfare reforms that created a basic British welfare state. <s> Although Asquith was the party's leader, its dominant figure was David Lloyd George. <s> Asquith was overwhelmed by the wartime role of coalition Prime Minister and Lloyd George replaced him as Prime Minister in late 1916, but Asquith remained as Liberal Party leader. <s> The pair fought for years over control of the party, badly weakening it in the process. <s> The government of Lloyd George was dominated by the Conservative Party, which finally deposed him in 1922. <s> By the end of the 1920s, the Labour Party had replaced the Liberals as the Conservatives' main rival. <s> The party went into decline after 1918 and by the 1950s won no more than six seats at general elections. <s> Apart from notable by-election victories, its fortunes did not improve significantly until it formed the SDP–Liberal Alliance with the newly formed Social Democratic Party (SDP) in 1981. <s> At the 1983 general election, the Alliance won over a quarter of the vote, but only 23 of the 650 seats it contested. <s> At the 1987 general election, its share of the vote fell below 23% and the Liberal and Social Democratic parties merged in 1988 to form the Liberal Democrats. <s> A splinter group reconstituted the Liberal Party in 1989.
simple: It was one of the two big political parties in the United Kingdom in the 19th and early 20th century. <s> The party came from an alliance of Whigs and free-trade Peelites and radicals in the 1850s. <s> In the next 50 years it formed four governments under William Gladstone. <s> The party split over the issue of Irish Home Rule. <s> They introduced the welfare reforms that created a basic British welfare state. <s> H. H. Asquith was Liberal Prime Minister between 1908 and 1916. <s> He was followed by David Lloyd George, whose premiership lasted until 1922. <s> By the end of the 1920s, the Labour Party had replaced the Liberals as the Conservatives' main rival. <s> The party went into decline. <s> By the 1950s, it won no more than six seats at general elections. <s> Apart from notable by-election victories, the party's fortunes did not improve significantly until it formed the SDP-Liberal Alliance with the newly formed Social Democratic Party (SDP) in 1981. <s> At the 1983 General Election, the Alliance won over a quarter of the vote, but only 23 of the 650 seats it contested. <s> At the 1987 General Election, it won less than 23% of the vote. <s> The Liberal and Social Democratic parties merged in 1988 to form the Liberal Democrats.

title: Love Gun
complex: Love Gun is the sixth studio album by American hard rock band Kiss, released on June 30, 1977. <s> Casablanca Record and FilmWorks shipped 1,000,000 copies of the album on this date.
simple: Love Gun is the sixth studio album by the American hard rock/heavy metal band Kiss. <s> It was released on June 30, 1977.

title: Dumiso Dabengwa
complex: Dumiso Dabengwa (6 December 1939 – 23 May 2019) was a Zimbabwean politician. <s> He served as the head of Zimbabwe People's Revolutionary Army (ZIPRA) intelligence during the Rhodesian Bush War. <s> From 1992 to 2000 he served in the government as Minister of Home Affairs, and in 1991 he was appointed to the chair of the Matabeleland Zambezi Water Project. <s> He was a candidate of ZAPU for President of Zimbabwe during the 2013 general election. <s> He moved out of ZANU-PF together with Benny Ncube, whom they had trained together during the armed struggle.
simple: Dumiso Dabengwa (December 6, 1939– 23 May 2019) was a Zimbabwean politician. <s> Dabengwa died on 23 May 2019 in Harare from liver disease at the age of 79. <s> He was the head of Zimbabwe People's Revolutionary Army (ZIPRA) intelligence during the Rhodesian Bush War. <s> He was Minister of Home Affairs from 1992 to 2000. <s> He was a candidate of ZAPU for President of Zimbabwe during the 2013 general election.

title: House of Representatives
complex: House of Representatives is the name of legislative bodies in many countries and sub-national entitles. <s> In many countries, the House of Representatives is the lower house of a bicameral legislature, with the corresponding upper house often called a "Senate". <s> In some countries, the House of Representatives is the sole chamber of a unicameral legislature.
simple: A House of Representatives is a part of some legislatures, which are law-making bodies. <s> In a House of Representatives, the members are called representatives. <s> One of these parts is called the House of Representatives and the other one is called the Senate. <s> Many state legislatures in the United States also have Houses of Representatives.

title: Archway tube station
complex: Archway is a London Underground station at the intersection of Holloway Road, Highgate Hill, Junction Road and Archway Road in Archway, north London, directly underneath the Vantage Point building. <s> It is on the High Barnet branch of the Northern line, between Highgate and Tufnell Park stations, in Zones 2 and 3.
simple: Archway tube station is a London Underground station in north London, underneath the Archway Tower, at the intersection of Holloway Road, Highgate Hill and Junction Road in the area known as Archway. <s> It is on the High Barnet branch of the Northern line, between Highgate and Tufnell Park. <s> It is in both Travelcard Zone 2 and Zone 3.

title: Michael Somare
complex: Sir Michael Thomas Somare (born 9 April 1936) is a Papua New Guinean politician. <s> He was a pivotal politician in the coming of independence. <s> His political career spanned from 1968 until his retirement in 2017. <s> He has been the longest serving prime minister (17 years). <s> Besides that he has been minister of foreign affairs, leader of the opposition and governor of East Sepik.
simple: Sir Michael Thomas Somare (born 9 April 1936) is a Papua New Guinean politician. <s> His career lasted from 1968 until his retirement in 2017. <s> He has been the longest serving Prime Minister of Papua New Guinea (17 years). <s> He was the country's first Prime Minister.

complex: Jonás Gómez Gallo (12 July 1923 – 24 June 2019) was a Chilean businessman and politician who served as Deputy and Senator.
simple: Jonás Gómez Gallo (12 July 1923 – 24 June 2019) was a Chilean businessman and politician. <s> He died on 24 June 2019 in Santiago, at the age of 95.

title: South Andaman district
complex: South Andaman district is one of the 3 districts of the Indian Union Territory of Andaman and Nicobar Islands located in the Bay of Bengal. <s> Port Blair town, the capital of the Union Territory is the district headquarters. <s> The area covered by this district is 2980 km2. <s> According to the 2011 census South Andaman district has a population of 237,586, roughly equal to the nation of Vanuatu. <s> This gives it a ranking of 584th in India (out of a total of 640). <s> The district has a population density of 80 PD/sqkm . <s> Its population growth rate over the decade 2001-2011 was 13.97%. <s> South Andaman has a sex ratio of 874 females for every 1000 males, and a literacy rate of 88.49%. <s> Four Andamanese indigenous peoples, namely, Onges, Jarawas, Great Andamanese and Sentinelese live in this district.
simple: South Andaman district is one of the 3 districts of the Indian Union Territory of Andaman and Nicobar Islands in the Bay of Bengal. <s> Port Blair town, the capital of the Union Territory is the district headquarters. <s> The area covered by this district is 2980 km2. <s> According to the 2011 census South Andaman district has a population of 237,586, roughly equal to the nation of Vanuatu. <s> This gives it a ranking of 584th in India (out of a total of 640). <s> The district has a population density of 80 PD/sqkm . <s> Its population growth rate over the decade 2001-2011 was 13.97%. <s> South Andaman has a sex ratio of 874 females for every 1000 males, and a literacy rate of 88.49%. <s> Four Andamanese indigenous peoples, namely, Onges, Jarawas, Great Andamanese and Sentinalese live in this district.

title: Sanctuary lamp
complex: A sanctuary lamp, chancel lamp, altar lamp, everlasting light, or eternal flame is a light that shines before the altar of sanctuaries in many Jewish places of worship. <s> Prescribed in Exodus 27:20-21 of the Torah, this icon has taken on different meanings in each of the religions that have adopted it.
simple: An altar lamp, or sanctuary lamp, is the flame kept near the altar in a church or synagogue.

title: Magnetic levitation
complex: Magnetic levitation (maglev) or magnetic suspension is a method by which an object is suspended with no support other than magnetic fields. <s> Magnetic force is used to counteract the effects of the gravitational acceleration and any other accelerations. <s> The two primary issues involved in magnetic levitation are "lifting forces": providing an upward force sufficient to counteract gravity, and "stability": ensuring that the system does not spontaneously slide or flip into a configuration where the lift is neutralized. <s> Magnetic levitation is used for maglev trains, contactless melting, magnetic bearings and for product display purposes.
simple: Magnetic levitation, maglev, or magnetic suspension is a method by which an object is suspended with no support other than magnetic fields. <s> Magnetic force is used to counteract the effects of the gravitational acceleration and any other accelerations. <s> The two primary issues involved in magnetic levitation are "lifting forces": providing an upward force sufficient to counteract gravity, and "stability": ensuring that the system does not spontaneously slide or flip into a configuration where the lift is neutralized. <s> Magnetic levitation is used for maglev trains, contactless melting, magnetic bearings and for product display purposes.

title: Strueth
complex: Strueth is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France.

title: Frits Thors
complex: Alexander Frederik Paul "Frits" Thors (13 September 1909 – 19 April 2014) was a Dutch journalist and news anchor. <s> Thors was best known as the newscaster of the NTS-Journaal from 1965 until 1972.
simple: Alexander Frederik Paul "Frits" Thors (13 September 1909 – 19 April 2014) was a Dutch journalist and television and news anchor. <s> Thors died from natural causes on 19 April 2014 in Laren, North Holland. <s> He was best known for being the newscaster of the NTS-Journaal from 1965 until 1972.

title: Clarendon Parish, Jamaica
complex: Clarendon is a parish in Jamaica. <s> It is located on the south of the island, roughly halfway between the island's eastern and western ends. <s> Located in the county of Middlesex, it is bordered by Manchester on the west, Saint Catherine in the east, and in the north by Saint Ann. <s> Its capital and largest town is May Pen.
simple: Clarendon is a parish in Jamaica. <s> It is in the county of Middlesex. <s> The parish capital is May Pen.

simple: Hikaru Sulu is a fictional character in the television and movie franchise "Star Trek".

title: Lou Marcon
complex: Louis Angelo Marcon (born May 28, 1935) is a Canadian retired professional ice hockey player who played 60 games in the National Hockey League for the Detroit Red Wings.
simple: Louis Angelo Marcon (born May 28, 1935 in Fort William, Ontario) is a retired Canadian professional ice hockey player. <s> His career included 60 games in the National Hockey League for the Detroit Red Wings.

title: Narbonne
complex: Narbonne ( , , ] ; ] ; ] ; Late Latin:"Narbona") is a commune in southern France in the Occitanie region. <s> It lies 849 km from Paris in the Aude department, of which it is a sub-prefecture. <s> It is located about 15 km from the shores of the Mediterranean Sea and was historically a prosperous port, but declined from the 14th century following a change in the course of the Aude River. <s> It is marginally the largest commune in Aude, although the prefecture is the slightly smaller commune of Carcassonne.
simple: It is in the Occitanie region. <s> It was a wealthy port and major city in Roman times but now is at about 15 km from the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.

title: Palo Alto, California
complex: Palo Alto is a charter city located in the northwest corner of Santa Clara County, California, United States, in the San Francisco Bay Area. <s> Palo Alto means "tall stick" in Spanish; the city is named after a coastal redwood tree called El Palo Alto.
simple: Palo Alto is a city in the American state of California that has a population of about 55,000 people. <s> "Palo Alto" means tall tree in Spanish after a famous redwood that was struck down by lightning in 1955.

title: Archduchess Maria Maddalena of Austria
complex: Maria Maddalena of Austria (Maria Magdalena; 7 October 1589 – 1 November 1631) was Grand Duchess of Tuscany from the accession of her husband, Cosimo II, in 1609 until his death in 1621. <s> With him, she had eight children, including a duchess of Parma, a grand duke of Tuscany, and an archduchess of Further Austria. <s> Born in Graz, she was the youngest daughter of Charles II, Archduke of Inner Austria, and his wife Maria Anna of Bavaria. <s> During the minority of her son, Grand Duke Ferdinando, she and her mother-in-law acted as regents from 1621 to 1628. <s> She died on 1 November 1631 in Passau.
simple: Maria Magdalena of Austria or Maria Maddalena of Austria (7 October 1589 – 1 November 1631) was Grand Duchess of Tuscany from her husband's accession in 1609 until his death in 1621. <s> With him, she had eight children, including a duchess of Parma, a grand duke of Tuscany, and an archduchess of Further Austria. <s> She was the youngest daughter of Charles II, Archduke of Inner Austria, and his wife Maria Anna of Bavaria. <s> During the minority of her son, Grand Duke Ferdinando II, she and her mother-in-law Christina of Lorraine acted as regents.

title: Campbell County, Wyoming
complex: Campbell County is a county in the U.S. state of Wyoming. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 46,133, making it the third-most populous county in Wyoming. <s> Its county seat is Gillette.
simple: Campbell County is a county in the U.S. state of Wyoming. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, 46,133 people lived there that makes it the third-most populous county in Wyoming. <s> Its county seat is Gillette.

complex: Antigua and Barbuda does not have any permanent rivers. <s> Following is a list of streams in Antigua. <s> Barbuda does not have any streams.

title: I Will Survive
complex: "I Will Survive" is a hit song first performed by American singer Gloria Gaynor, released in October 1978. <s> It was written by Freddie Perren and Dino Fekaris. <s> A top-selling song after its initial release, it sold 14 million copies worldwide and has remained a popular disco anthem, as well as being certified platinum by the RIAA. <s> The song's lyrics describe the narrator's discovery of personal strength following an initially devastating breakup. <s> It received heavy airplay in 1979, reaching number one on the "Billboard" Hot 100 and on the UK Singles Chart on consecutive weeks. <s> The song is also frequently recalled as a symbol of female strength. <s> In 2016, the Library of Congress deemed Gaynor's original recording to be "culturally, historically, or artistically significant" and selected it for preservation in the National Recording Registry.
simple: "I Will Survive" is a hit song first performed by American singer Gloria Gaynor. <s> It was released in October 1978. <s> It was written by Freddie Perren and Dino Fekaris. <s> It became a top-selling song after its release as it sold 14 million copies worldwide. <s> It reaches number one on the "Billboard" Hot 100 and on the UK Singles Chart on many weeks in a row. <s> The song is also seen as a symbol of female strength and as a gay anthem. <s> In 2016, the Library of Congress selected it for preservation in the National Recording Registry.

title: Denise DuBarry
complex: Denise DuBarry Hay (March 6, 1956 – March 23, 2019) was an American actress, businesswoman, film producer, and philanthropist. <s> She co-founded Thane International Inc., a direct response industry company along with her husband, Bill Hay, in 1990. <s> She served as its Chief Creative Officer for 15 years, from 1990–2005. <s> As an actress, she is best known for her role as nurse Lieutenant Samantha Green, on the television series "Black Sheep Squadron", and as Johanna Franklin in the film "Being There". <s> DuBarry was born in Killeen, Texas, at Fort Hood Army Base, to Adrian Pierre DuBarry and his wife, Betty Louise (née King). <s> Her parents moved back to Louisiana where they were from so that her father could finish his master's degree at LSU in Baton Rouge. <s> The family later moved to Honduras, Mexico, Guatemala and Costa Rica, where DuBarry grew up from ages 2 to 10, and learned to speak fluent Spanish. <s> The family moved throughout California, eventually settling in Granada Hills, California, where Denise attended middle school and high school. <s> A child of divorce and the eldest of five children, at 14 she watched after her siblings while her mother worked. <s> DuBarry Hay died at UCLA Medical Center on March 23, 2019, seventeen days after her 63rd birthday. <s> Her husband Bill Hay confirmed that DuBarry Hay died after contracting a rare illness Candida Auris.
simple: Denise DuBarry (March 6, 1956 – March 23, 2019) was an American actress, businesswoman, movie producer, and philanthropist. <s> In business, she co-founded Thane International, Inc.. <s> She was its Chief Creative Officer for 15 years, from 1990 to 2005. <s> She was known for her roles as nurse Lieutenant Samantha Green, on the television series "Black Sheep Squadron", and as Johanna Franklin in the movie "Being There". <s> She was born in Killeen, Texas. <s> DuBarry died from a fatal fungal infection on March 23, 2019 in Los Angeles, California, aged 63.

title: DC Talk
complex: DC Talk (stylized as dc Talk) is a Christian rap and rock trio. <s> The group was formed at Liberty University in Lynchburg, Virginia in 1987 by Toby McKeehan, Michael Tait, and Kevin Max Smith.
simple: DC Talk (also written as dc Talk) is a well-known Christian rock/rap band, most famous for its song "Jesus Freak".

title: Cheerios
complex: Cheerios is an American brand of cereal manufactured by General Mills, consisting of pulverized oats in the shape of a solid torus. <s> In some countries, including the United Kingdom, Cheerios is marketed by Cereal Partners under the Nestlé brand; in Australia and New Zealand, Cheerios is sold as an Uncle Toby's product. <s> It was first manufactured in 1941 and was originally called CheeriOats.
simple: Cheerios is a popular brand of cereal. <s> It is manufactured by General Mills. <s> It was founded in 1941 as CheeriOats, the first ready-to-eat oat cereal.

title: Wildest Dreams (Taylor Swift song)
complex: "Wildest Dreams" is a song recorded by American singer-songwriter Taylor Swift for her fifth studio album, "1989". <s> The song was released to radio by Big Machine Records and Republic Records on August 31, 2015, as the album's fifth single. <s> Swift wrote the song with its producers Max Martin and Shellback. <s> Musically, "Wildest Dreams" is a dream pop power ballad, with the lyrics describing Swift's plea for her lover to remember her. <s> Following the release of "1989", it charted in the United States, Canada, and Australia on the strength of digital downloads. <s> After its release as a single, it reached number five on the "Billboard" Hot 100, becoming the fifth consecutive top-10 song from "1989" and Swift's 19th top-10 single on the chart. <s> It also became her sixth chart topper on the Radio Songs chart. <s> On October 11, 2015 a remix by Dutch DJ R3hab was released digitally. <s> The remix received generally positive reviews from music critics.
simple: "Wildest Dreams" is a song by American singer-songwriter Taylor Swift. <s> The song was released on August 31, 2015. <s> Swift co-write the song with its producers Max Martin and Shellback. <s> The song hit #5 on the American "Billboard" Hot 100. <s> It got generally positive reviews from music critics.

title: Kepler conjecture
complex: The Kepler conjecture, named after the 17th-century mathematician and astronomer Johannes Kepler, is a mathematical theorem about sphere packing in three-dimensional Euclidean space. <s> It states that no arrangement of equally sized spheres filling space has a greater average density than that of the cubic close packing (face-centered cubic) and hexagonal close packing arrangements. <s> The density of these arrangements is around 74.05%.
simple: The Kepler conjecture is a mathematical conjecture, about Sphere packing in three-dimensional Euclidean space. <s> It is named after Johannes Kepler (1571-1630) who first had this idea. <s> These packings have a density of slightly over 74 percent, this means that they fill about 74 percent of space available.

title: United States Army Corps of Topographical Engineers
complex: The U.S. Army Corps of Topographical Engineers was a branch of the United States Army authorized on 4 July 1838. <s> It consisted only of officers who were handpicked from West Point and was used for mapping and the design and construction of federal civil works such as lighthouses and other coastal fortifications and navigational routes. <s> Members included such officers as George Meade, John C. Frémont and Stephen Long. <s> It was merged with the United States Army Corps of Engineers on 31 March 1863, at which point the Corps of Engineers also assumed the Lakes Survey for the Great Lakes. <s> In the mid-19th century, Corps of Engineers' officers ran Lighthouse Districts in tandem with U.S. Naval officers.
simple: The U.S. Army Corps of Topographical Engineers was established by the United States Congress in 1838. <s> They formed the Topographical Bureau as a branch of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. <s> It was made up of only officers who were hand-picked graduates of the United States Military Academy at West Point. <s> They designed lighthouses, mapped navigational routes and worked on many other federal projects. <s> Until they were merged with the Corps of Engineers in 1863, they surveyed and built roads bridges and forts for the Union Army during the Civil War.

title: List of Medal of Honor recipients for the Spanish–American War
complex: The Spanish–American War ( , "desastre del 98", "Guerra Hispano-Cubana-Norteamericana" or "Guerra de Cuba ") was a military conflict between Spain and the United States that began in April 1898. <s> Hostilities halted in August of that year, and the Treaty of Paris was signed in December. <s> The war began after the American demand for Spain's peacefully resolving the Cuban fight for independence was rejected, though strong expansionist sentiment in the United States may have motivated the government to target Spain's remaining overseas territories: Cuba, Puerto Rico, the Philippines, Guam and the Caroline Islands. <s> Riots in Havana by pro-Spanish "Voluntarios" gave the United States a reason to send in the warship to indicate high national interest. <s> Tension among the American people was raised because of the explosion of , and "yellow journalism" that accused Spain of extensive atrocities, agitating American public opinion. <s> The war ended after decisive naval victories for the United States in the Philippines and Cuba. <s> The Treaty of Paris ended the conflict 109 days after the outbreak of war giving the United States ownership of the former Spanish colonies of Puerto Rico, the Philippines and Guam. <s> The Medal of Honor was created during the American Civil War and is the highest military decoration presented by the United States government to a member of its armed forces. <s> The recipient must have distinguished themselves at the risk of their own life above and beyond the call of duty in action against an enemy of the United States. <s> Due to the nature of this medal, it is commonly presented posthumously.
simple: The Spanish-American War (, "desastre del 98", "Guerra Hispano-Cubana-Norteamericana" or "Guerra de Cuba ") was a military conflict between Spain and the United States. <s> It began in April 1898. <s> Hostilities halted in August of that year. <s> The Treaty of Paris was signed in December. <s> The war began after America demanded Spain peacefully end the Cuban fight for independence. <s> The demand was rejected. <s> Strong expansionist sentiment in the United States may have motivated the government to target Spain's remaining overseas territories. <s> These territories included Cuba, Puerto Rico, the Philippines, Guam and the Caroline Islands. <s> Riots in Havana by pro-Spanish "Voluntarios" gave the United States a reason to send in the warship . <s> It was sent to indicate high American interest. <s> Tension among the American people was raised because of the explosion of the . <s> "Yellow journalism" added to it accusing Spain of doing a lot of bad things. <s> The war ended after decisive naval victories for the United States in the Philippines and Cuba. <s> The Treaty of Paris ended the conflict 109 days after the outbreak of war. <s> That gave the United States ownership of the former Spanish colonies of Puerto Rico, the Philippines and Guam. <s> The Medal of Honor was created during the American Civil War. <s> It is the highest military decoration presented by the United States government to a member of its armed forces. <s> The recipient must have distinguished themselves at the risk of their own life above and beyond the call of duty in action against an enemy of the United States. <s> Due to the nature of this medal it is commonly presented to the recipient after they are killed (posthumously).

title: S/2003 J 9
complex: S/2003 J 9 is a retrograde irregular satellite of Jupiter. <s> It was discovered by a team of astronomers from the University of Hawaii led by Scott S. Sheppard in 2003. <s> S/2003 J 9 is about 1 kilometre in diameter, and orbits Jupiter at an average distance of 23,858 Mm in 752.839 days, at an inclination of 165° to the ecliptic (165° to Jupiter's equator), in a retrograde direction and with an eccentricity of 0.276. <s> It belongs to the Carme group, made up of irregular retrograde moons orbiting Jupiter at a distance ranging between 23 and 24 Gm and at an inclination of about 165°.
simple: S/2003 J 9 is a non-spherical moon of Jupiter. <s> It was found by a team of astronomers from the University of Hawaii led by Scott S. Sheppard in 2003. <s> S/2003 J 9 is about 1 kilometre in diameter, and orbits Jupiter at an average distance of 23,858,000 km in 752.839 days, at an inclination of 165° to the ecliptic (165° to Jupiter's equator), with an orbital eccentricity of 0.276. <s> It belongs to the Carme group, made up of non-spherical retrograde moons orbiting Jupiter at a distance ranging between 23,000,000 and 24,000,000 km and at an inclination of about 165°.

title: Mineral County, Montana
complex: Mineral County is a county located in the U.S. state of Montana. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 4,223. <s> Its county seat is Superior. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, there were 4,223 people, 1,911 households, and 1,229 families in the county.
simple: Mineral County is a county found in the U.S. state of Montana. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, there were 4,223 people. <s> Its county seat is Superior.

title: Reagan Doctrine
complex: The Reagan Doctrine was stated by United States President Ronald Reagan in his State of the Union address on February 6, 1985: "We must not break faith with those who are risking their lives--on every continent from Afghanistan to Nicaragua--to defy Soviet-supported aggression and secure rights which have been ours from birth." <s> It was a strategy implemented by the Reagan Administration to overwhelm the global influence of the Soviet Union in the late Cold War. <s> The doctrine was a centerpiece of United States foreign policy from the early 1980s until the end of the Cold War in 1991.
simple: It was about being against the global influence of the Soviet Union during the final years of the Cold War. <s> The doctrine lasted for less than a decade, it was the most important document of United States foreign policy from the early 1980s until the end of the Cold War in 1991.

title: Arriva London
complex: Arriva London is a bus company operating services in Greater London. <s> It is a subsidiary of Arriva UK Bus and operates services under contract to Transport for London. <s> It was formed in 1998 from a fusion of previously separate Arriva subsidiaries Grey-Green, Leaside Buses, Kentish Bus, London & Country and South London Transport. <s> Operations are split between two registered companies, Arriva London North Limited and Arriva London South Limited. <s> Arriva London North Limited operates ten bus garages. <s> Arriva London South Limited operate five bus garages.
simple: Arriva London is a bus company. <s> It is a division of Arriva, which operates services in Greater London. <s> It is made up of Grey Green, Leaside Buses and London Country bus operations, that splits into the north and the south. <s> Arriva London North Limited operates nine bus garages. <s> Arriva London South Limited operate four bus garages.

title: Thann, Haut-Rhin
complex: Thann (] ; Alsatian: "Dànn", ] , ) is a commune in the northeastern French department of Haut-Rhin, in Grand Est. <s> It is the "sous-préfecture" of the arrondissement of Thann-Guebwiller and part of the canton of Cernay. <s> Its inhabitants are known as "Thannois". <s> Thann is situated at the foot of the Vosges mountains, at the mouth of the valley of the Thur River. <s> The Thur runs through the middle of the town. <s> Thann is 43 km from Colmar and 21 km from Mulhouse. <s> The town is also well situated for the French autoroute network such as the A35 and A36.
simple: Thann is a commune in Alsace in north-eastern France, in the Haut-Rhin department, of which it is a subprefecture. <s> The inhabitants of Thann are known, in French, as "Thannois" (women: "Thannoises"). <s> Thann is in the southwest of the Haut-Rhin department at the foot of the Vosges mountains, at the mouth of the valley of the Thur river. <s> The Thur runs through the middle of the town. <s> Thann is at 121 km from Strasbourg, the regional capital; at 42 km from Colmar, the departamental capital; and at 21 km from Mulhouse.

title: Windows Server 2003
complex: Windows Server 2003 is a server operating system produced by Microsoft and released on April 24, 2003. <s> It is the successor to Windows 2000 Server and the predecessor to Windows Server 2008.
simple: Windows Server 2003 is a server operating system produced by Microsoft. <s> Introduced on April 24, 2003 as the next version to Windows 2000 Server, it was considered by Microsoft to be the cornerstone of their Windows Server System line of business server products. <s> According to Microsoft, Windows Server 2003 is more scalable and delivers better performance than Windows 2000.

title: Financial regulation
complex: Financial regulation is a form of regulation or supervision, which subjects financial institutions to certain requirements, restrictions and guidelines, aiming to maintain the integrity of the financial system. <s> This may be handled by either a government or non-government organization. <s> Financial regulation has also influenced the structure of banking sectors by increasing the variety of financial products available. <s> Financial regulation forms one of three legal categories which constitutes the content of financial law, the other two being market practices, case law. <s> In the early modern period, the Dutch were the pioneers in financial regulation. <s> The first recorded ban (regulation) on short selling was enacted by the Dutch authorities as early as 1610.
simple: Financial regulation is supervision of financial institutions to certain rules and guidelines. <s> Regulation may be done by either a government or non-government organization. <s> Also, financial regulation has increased the variety of financial products available. <s> In the early modern period, the Dutch were the pioneers in financial regulation. <s> The first recorded regulation was a ban on short selling done by the Dutch authorities in 1610.

title: John Davies (historian)
complex: John Davies (25 April 1938 – 16 February 2015) was a Welsh historian, and a television and radio broadcaster. <s> He attended university at Cardiff and Cambridge and taught Welsh at Aberystwyth. <s> He wrote a number of books on Welsh history. <s> Davies died at the age of 76 in 2015 and, as a tribute to his longstanding friend, Jon Gower republished Davies' autobiography in English.
simple: John Davies (1938 – 16 February 2015) was a Welsh historian, and a television and radio broadcaster. <s> Davies died at the age of 76.

title: Charlene Tilton
complex: Charlene L. Tilton (born December 1, 1958) is an American actress and singer. <s> She is best known for playing Lucy Ewing, the saucy niece of John "J.R." Ewing Jr. (played by Larry Hagman), on the television series "Dallas". <s> Tilton was born on December 1, 1958, in San Diego, California, the daughter of Katherine Thacker, a secretary; she grew up not knowing her father and with few financial resources available to her mother or her.
simple: Charlene Tilton (b. December 1, 1958 in San Diego) is an American actress. <s> She is best known for playing Lucy Ewing on the CBS television series "Dallas".

title: Diefmatten
complex: Diefmatten is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France. <s> It is about 15 km west of Mulhouse.
simple: Diefmatten is a commune. <s> It is found in the Haut-Rhin department of eastern France. <s> It is about 15 km west of Mulhouse.

title: Rheda-Wiedenbrück
complex: Rheda-Wiedenbrück is a town in the district of Gütersloh, in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany.
simple: Rheda-Wiedenbrück is a town in the district of Gütersloh, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany.

title: Protective gear in sports
complex: Personal protective equipment serves an integral role in maintaining the safety of an athlete participating in a sport. <s> The usage and development of protective gear in sports has evolved through time, and continues to advance over time.
simple: Protective equipment helps sport people not get hurt.

title: Winter Park, Florida
complex: Winter Park is a suburban city in Orange County, Florida, United States. <s> The population was 27,852 at the 2010 United States Census.
simple: Winter Park is a city of Florida in the United States.

title: Julio Vallejo Ruiloba
complex: Julio Vallejo Ruiloba (7 May 1945 – 14 January 2019) was a Spanish psychiatrist, medical doctor, Chairman of the Psychiatry Department at the Universitat de Barcelona, ex-President of the Spanish Psychiatry Society, and Academician of the Royal Academy of Medicine of Catalonia. <s> He wrote 56 books about psychiatry and more than 350 scientific papers.
simple: Julio Vallejo-Ruiloba (7 May 1945 – 14 January 2019) was a Spanish psychiatrist. <s> He was Chairman of the Psychiatry Departament at the University of Barcelona. <s> He was President of the Spanish Psychiatry Society, and Academician of the Royal Academy of Medicine of Catalonia. <s> Vallejo Ruiloba died on 14 January 2019 from liver cancer in Barcelona, aged 73. <s> He wrote 56 books about psychiatry and more than 350 scientific papers talking about depression.

title: Saving Abel (album)
complex: Saving Abel is the debut studio album by American rock band Saving Abel. <s> It was released on March 11, 2008 and produced by Skidd Mills, producer of their independently released album of the same name. <s> The first single off the album is "Addicted" which has received airplay across the country. <s> It has reached #20 on the Billboard Hot 100.
simple: On March 11, 2008, the rock band Saving Abel released their hit studio album called Saving Abel (the second self-titled album). <s> The album was produced by producer Skidd Mills. <s> There are two major singles on this album called "Addicted" and "18 Days".

title: Waterbury, Connecticut
complex: Waterbury (nicknamed "The Brass City") is a city in the U.S. state of Connecticut on the Naugatuck River, 33 miles southwest of Hartford and 77 miles northeast of New York City. <s> Waterbury is the second-largest city in New Haven County, Connecticut.
simple: Waterbury is a town in the state of Connecticut.

title: Dear Mr. Gacy
complex: Dear Mr. Gacy is a 2010 Canadian drama thriller film directed by Svetozar Ristovski, and starring William Forsythe and Jesse Moss. <s> The film is based on Jason Moss's memoir, "The Last Victim".
simple: Dear Mr. Gacy is a 2010 Canadian crime drama movie thriller directed by Svetozar Ristovski. <s> It is based on a book by Jason Moss, "The Last Victim".

title: Emblem of the United Arab Emirates
complex: The emblem of the United Arab Emirates was officially adopted in 1973 and later modified in 2008. <s> It is similar to the coats of arms and emblems of other Arab states. <s> It consists of a golden falcon (Hawk of Quraish) with a disk in the middle, which shows the UAE flag and seven stars representing the seven Emirates of the federation. <s> The falcon has 7 feathers also representing the 7 Emirates. <s> The falcon holds with its talons a red parchment bearing the name of the federation in Kufic script. <s> Prior to March 22, 2008, when the emblem was modified, the falcon had a red disk, which showed an Arab sailboat in its interior, surrounded by a chain.
simple: The emblem of the United Arab Emirates was officially adopted in 1973 and later modified in 2008. <s> It is similar to the coats of arms and emblems of other Arab states. <s> It consists of a golden falcon, unlike other Arab countries which use the hawk emblem of the Quraysh branch to which Muhammad belonged. <s> The hawk holds with its claws a red parchment bearing the inscription of the name of the federation. <s> The falcon has a red disk which shows an Arab sailboat in its interior.

title: Jette
