simple: Jette is a municipality in the Belgian Brussels-Capital Region.

title: Luís Miguel Rocha
complex: Luís Miguel Rocha (February 1976 in Porto – 26 March 2015 in Mazaferes) was a Portuguese author, television writer and producer. <s> He became a New York Times bestseller in 2009. <s> Rocha was born in Porto, and raised in Viana do Castelo. <s> Prior to publishing his first novel, Rocha wrote and produced television in London. <s> Rocha's second novel, "The Last Pope", was published in 2006. <s> The novel examines the conspiracy theories about the death of Pope John Paul I.
simple: Luís Miguel Rocha (February 1976 – 26 March 2015) was a Portuguese author, television writer and producer. <s> Rocha wrote and produced television in London. <s> Rocha's second novel, "The Last Pope", was published in 2006. <s> The novel examines the conspiracy theories about the death of Pope John Paul I.

title: Man and Superman
complex: Man and Superman is a four-act drama written by George Bernard Shaw in 1903. <s> The series was written in response to a call for Shaw to write a play based on the Don Juan theme. <s> "Man and Superman" opened at the Royal Court Theatre in London on 23 May 1905, but it omitted the third act. <s> A part of the act, "Don Juan in Hell" (Act 3, Scene 2), was performed when the drama was staged on 4 June 1907 at the Royal Court.
simple: Man and Superman was a drama play written by George Bernard Shaw in 1903. <s> "Man and Superman" opened at The Royal Court Theatre in London on 23 May 1905.

title: Chinese herbology
complex: Color is not only a valuable means of identifying herbs, but in many cases also provides information about the therapeutic attributes of the herb. <s> For example, yellow herbs are referred to as "huang" (yellow) or "jin" (gold). <s> Huang Bai (Cortex Phellodendri) means 'yellow fir," and "Jin Yin Hua" (Flos Lonicerae) has the label 'golden silver flower." <s> Unique flavors define specific names for some substances. <s> "Gan" means 'sweet,' so "Gan Cao" (Radix glycyrrhizae) is 'sweet herb," an adequate description for the licorice root. <s> "Ku" means bitter, thus Ku Shen (Sophorae flavescentis) translates as 'bitter herb.' <s> Some herbs, like Fang Feng (Radix Saposhnikoviae), literally 'prevent wind," prevents or treats wind-related illnesses. <s> Xu Duan (Radix Dipsaci), literally 'restore the broken,' effectively treats torn soft tissues and broken bones. <s> Dang Gui (當歸/当归, "Angelica sinensis" or "female ginseng") is an aromatic herb that grows in China, Korea, and Japan. <s> "Rehmannia" (地黄) is a root where the dark, moist part of the herb is used.
simple: huang bai 黄柏 cortex Phellodendri <s> gan cao 甘草 radix Glycyrrhizae <s> xu duan 续断 radix Dipsaci <s> dang gui 当归 radix Angelicae Sinensis <s> sheng di huang 生地黄 radix Rehmanniae

title: Anne Holton
complex: Anne Bright Holton (born February 1, 1958) is an American lawyer and judge who served as the Secretary of Education for the Commonwealth of Virginia from 2014 to 2016. <s> On August 1, 2019, she assumed the role of interim president of George Mason University. <s> She is the wife of United States Senator and former Virginia Governor Tim Kaine, who was the vice-presidential running mate of Hillary Clinton in the 2016 U.S. presidential election. <s> Holton served as First Lady of Virginia from 2006 to 2010.
simple: Anne Bright Holton (born February 1, 1958) is an American politician and educator. <s> She served as the Virginia Secretary of Education from 2014-2016. <s> She is also the wife of United States Senator and former Governor Tim Kaine. <s> She served as First Lady of Virginia from 2006 to 2010.

title: Defender of the Faith
complex: "Defender of the Faith" has been one of the subsidiary titles of the English and later British monarchs since it was granted on 11 October 1521 by Pope Leo X to King Henry VIII of England and Ireland. <s> His wife Catherine of Aragon was also a Defender of the Faith in her own right. <s> The title was conferred in recognition of Henry's book "Assertio Septem Sacramentorum" ("Defense of the Seven Sacraments"), which defended the sacramental nature of marriage and the supremacy of the Pope. <s> This was also known as the "Henrician Affirmation" and was seen as an important opposition to the early stages of the Protestant Reformation, especially the ideas of Martin Luther. <s> Following Henry's decision to break with Rome in 1530 and establish himself as head of the Church of England, the title was revoked by Pope Paul III (since Henry's act was regarded as an attack on "the Faith") and Henry was excommunicated. <s> However, in 1544, the Parliament of England conferred the title "Defender of the Faith" on King Henry VIII and his successors, now the defenders of the Anglican faith, of which they (except the Catholic Mary I) remain the Supreme Governors (formally above the Archbishop of Canterbury as Primate). <s> King James V of Scotland was granted the title of "Defender of the Faith" by Pope Paul III on 19 January 1537, symbolizing the hopes of the papacy that the King of Scots would resist the path that his uncle, Henry VIII, had followed. <s> James' father, James IV, had been granted the title of "Protector and Defender of the Christian Faith" by Pope Julius II in 1507.
simple: It was originally conferred upon King Henry VIII of England by Pope Leo X on 11 October 1521 as a reward for the king having written a pamphlet in defense of the sacraments against Martin Luther ("Declaration of the Seven Sacraments Against Martin Luther"). <s> When Henry broke with the Roman Catholic Church, Pope Paul III took the title away. <s> It was returned to the king by Parliament in 1544. <s> King James V of Scotland received a similar title from Pope Paul III.

title: Antonio Juliano
complex: Antonio Juliano (] ; born 1 January 1943) is a former Italian footballer who played as a midfielder. <s> A dedicated, hardworking, influential, and creative playmaker, he was renowned in particular for his leadership, technical ability, and ball control, as well as for his outstanding vision, stamina, and passing range.
simple: Antonio Juliano (born 1 January 1943) is a former Italian football player.

title: Cavaillon
complex: Cavaillon (Provençal: "Cavalhon") is a commune in the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region in southeastern France. <s> It is situated in the Durance Valley and the Luberon National Park.
simple: It is in the region Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur in the Vaucluse department in the south of France.

title: Neuvy, Allier
complex: Neuvy is a commune in the Allier department in Auvergne in central France.
simple: Neuvy is a commune. <s> It is found in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: One More Time (Daft Punk song)
complex: "One More Time" is a song by French electronic music duo Daft Punk, first released as a single on 30 November 2000 and later included in the 2001 album "Discovery". <s> It is a French house song featuring a vocal performance by Romanthony that is stylistically autotuned.
simple: One More Time is a popular song by music group Daft Punk.

title: Graph theory
complex: In mathematics, graph theory is the study of "graphs", which are mathematical structures used to model pairwise relations between objects. <s> A graph in this context is made up of "vertices" (also called "nodes" or "points") which are connected by "edges" (also called "links" or "lines").
simple: Graph theory is a field of mathematics about graphs.

title: Strait of Magellan
complex: The Strait of Magellan , also called the "Straits of Magellan", is a navigable sea route in southern Chile separating mainland South America to the north and Tierra del Fuego to the south. <s> The strait is the most important natural passage between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
simple: It is just south of mainland South America and north of Tierra del Fuego. <s> The Strait of Magellan is a passageway from the Atlantic Ocean to the Pacific.

title: Karabük
complex: Karabük is a town and the capital district of Karabük Province in the Black Sea region of Turkey. <s> According to the 2009 census, population of the city is 108 167.
simple: Karabük is a city in northern Turkey.

title: Sandy Silver
complex: Sidney Alexander "Sandy" Silver (born October 15, 1969) is a Canadian politician, the ninth and current premier of Yukon since 2016. <s> He was first elected to the Yukon Legislative Assembly in the 2011 election, and was re-elected in 2016. <s> He represents the electoral district of Klondike and is Leader of the Yukon Liberal Party.
simple: Sidney Alexander "Sandy" Silver (born October 15, 1969) is a Canadian politician. <s> He is the ninth and current Premier of Yukon since 2016. <s> He was first elected to the Yukon Legislative Assembly in the 2011 election. <s> He represents the electoral district of Klondike and is Leader of the Yukon Liberal Party.

title: Koksijde
complex: Koksijde ( , West Flemish: "Koksyde") is a town and a municipality in Belgium. <s> It is located on the North Sea coast in the southwest of the Flemish province of West Flanders.
simple: Koksijde is a municipality in the Belgian province of West Flanders.

title: Landelles-et-Coupigny
complex: Landelles-et-Coupigny is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Landelles-et-Coupigny is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Silent majority
complex: The silent majority is an unspecified large group of people in a country or group who do not express their opinions publicly. <s> The term was popularized by U.S. President Richard Nixon in a November 3, 1969, speech in which he said, "And so tonight—to you, the great silent majority of my fellow Americans—I ask for your support." <s> In this usage it referred to those Americans who did not join in the large demonstrations against the Vietnam War at the time, who did not join in the counterculture, and who did not participate in public discourse.
simple: A silent majority is a large group of people who support something, but choose not to express their opinions publicly. <s> This term was made popular by US President Richard Nixon in a speech he gave on November 3 1969, about the Vietnam War. <s> Nixon said "And so tonight, to you, the great silent majority of my fellow Americans; I ask for your support."

title: ISO basic Latin alphabet
complex: The ISO basic Latin alphabet is a Latin-script alphabet and consists of two sets of 26 letters, codified in various national and international standards and used widely in international communication. <s> They are the same letters that comprise the English alphabet.
simple: The ISO basic Latin alphabet is a version of the Latin alphabet and is made of two sets of 26 letters, the same as the English alphabet, codified in many different national and international standards and used widely in international communication.

title: Amoeboid movement
complex: Amoeboid movement is the most common mode of locomotion in eukaryotic cells. <s> It is a crawling-like type of movement accomplished by protrusion of cytoplasm of the cell involving the formation of pseudopodia ("false-feet") and posterior uropods. <s> One or more pseudopodia may be produced at a time depending on the organism, but all amoeboid movement is characterized by the movement of organisms with an amorphous form that possess no set motility structures. <s> Movement occurs when the cytoplasm slides and forms a pseudopodium in front to pull the cell forward. <s> This type of movement has been linked to changes in action potential, though the exact mechanism is still unknown. <s> Some examples of organisms that exhibit this type of locomotion are the amoeboids, slime molds and some protozoans such as "Naegleria gruberi", as well as some cells in humans such as leukocytes. <s> Sarcomas, or cancers arising from connective tissue cells, are particularly adept at amoeboid movement, thus leading to their high rate of metastasis.
simple: Amoeboid movement is the most common type of movement in eukaryotic cells. <s> It is a crawling type of movement got by pushing out cell cytoplasm in the form of pseudopodia ("false feet"). <s> The cytoplasm slides and forms a pseudopodium in front to move the cell forward. <s> The exact mechanism is still unknown. <s> This type of movement is observed in amoebae, slime molds and some other protozoans such as "Naegleria gruberi", as well as some cells in humans such as white blood cells. <s> Sarcomas, or cancers arising from connective tissue cells, are particularly good at amoeboid movement, thus leading to their high rate of metastasis.

title: Tulare County, California
complex: Tulare County is a county in the U.S. state of California. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 442,179. <s> Its county seat is Visalia. <s> The county is named for Tulare Lake, once the largest freshwater lake west of the Great Lakes.
simple: Tulare County is a county in the U.S. state of California. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 442,179. <s> The county seat is Visalia.

title: Marcelo Gonçalves Costa Lopes
complex: Marcelo Gonçalves Costa Lopes, usually known simply as Gonçalves (born 22 February 1966 in Rio de Janeiro, Rio de Janeiro state) is a Brazilian former footballer who played as a central defender. <s> He was effective on low balls, and was well known because of his long hair, a recognisable hairstyle which he wore for most of his career, and which he only cut during the 1997 FIFA Confederations Cup, when all the Brazilian players entered the field in the semifinal match with shaved heads.
simple: Marcelo Gonçalves Costa Lopes (born 22 February, 1966) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Nevada Test Site
complex: The Nevada National Security Site (N2S2 or NNSS), previously the Nevada Test Site (NTS), is a United States Department of Energy reservation located in southeastern Nye County, Nevada, about 65 miles (105 km) northwest of the city of Las Vegas. <s> Formerly known as the Nevada Proving Grounds, the site was established on January 11, 1951 for the testing of nuclear devices, covering approximately 1,360 square miles (3,500 km) of desert and mountainous terrain. <s> Nuclear weapons testing at the Nevada Test Site began with a 1-kiloton-of-TNT (4.2 TJ) bomb dropped on Frenchman Flat on January 27, 1951. <s> Many of the iconic images of the nuclear era come from the NTS. <s> NNSS is operated by Mission Support and Test Services, LLC. <s> When underground explosions ended in 1992, the Department of Energy estimated that more than 300 MCi of radioactivity remained in the environment at that time, making the site one of the most radioactively contaminated locations in the United States. <s> In the most seriously affected zones, the concentration of radioactivity in groundwater reaches millions of picocuries per liter.
simple: It is in Nye County, Nevada, about 65 miles (105 km) northwest of Las Vegas. <s> The site was begun on January 11, 1951. <s> It covers an area of 1,350 square miles (3,500 km2) of desert and mountain lands. <s> Nuclear testing at the Nevada Test Site began with a one-kiloton (4 terajoule) bomb. <s> This bomb was dropped on Frenchman Flat on January 27, 1951. <s> Many of the famous photos of the nuclear age were taken at the Nevada Test Site. <s> When testing ended in 1992, the Energy Department said that more than 300 million curies of radiation remained, making the site one of the most radioactively contaminated places in the United States.

title: Stainton, South Lakeland
complex: Stainton is a village and a civil parish in the South Lakeland district, in the county of Cumbria, England, situated near the village of Sedgwick and the town of Kendal. <s> It is near the main A590 road.
simple: Stainton is a village and civil parish in South Lakeland, Cumbria, England.

title: Luís Vaz de Torres
complex: Luís Vaz de Torres (Galician and Portuguese), or Luis Váez de Torres in the Spanish spelling (born c. 1565; fl. 1607), was a 16th- and 17th-century maritime explorer of a Spanish expedition noted for the first recorded European navigation of the strait which separates the mainland of Australia from the island of New Guinea, and which now bears his name (Torres Strait). <s> Captain Luis Váez de Torres was recorded as being called a "Breton" by crewmen in reports of the 1606–1608 voyage, which points to an origin in the northwest province of Spain, i. e., Galicia. <s> Most contemporary historians accept this as evidence of his origins. <s> The year and exact place of his birth are unknown; assuming him to have been in his late thirties or forties in 1606, a birth year of around 1565 is considered likely. <s> Torres has been presented by some writers as Portuguese, without any evidence other than his name. <s> Galician spelling at the time being indistinguishable from Portuguese. <s> Records never call Torres Portuguese but note remarks made by crew members of the Portuguese origins of Pedro Fernandes de Queirós. <s> Torres entered the navy of the Spanish Crown at some point and found his way to its South American colonies. <s> By late 160, he first entered the historical record as the nominated commander of the second ship in an expedition to the Pacific proposed by the Portuguese born navigator Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, searching for Terra Australis. <s> There is no known contemporary depiction of his face or person.
simple: Luís Vaz de Torres was a Spanish explorer. <s> Sometimes his name is spelled Luis Váez de Torres. <s> He was born around the year 1565, and died in 1607. <s> Today, he is noted for the first recorded European navigation of the strait which separates the continent of Australia from the island of New Guinea. <s> Captain Luis Váez de Torres undertook a voyage from 1606 to 1607. <s> In this voyage, the crew called him a "Breton" in reports. <s> One of the reports points to an origin in the northwest province of Spain, that is Galicia. <s> Historians accept this as evidence of his origins. <s> The year and exact place of his birth are unknown but he was likely born around 1565. <s> Torres has been presented as Portuguese, without any evidence other than his name. <s> He is never called a Portuguese in the records but they note remarks made by crew members of the Portuguese origins of Pedro Fernandes de Queirós. <s> Torres entered the navy of the Spanish Crown and found his way to its South American colonies. <s> By late 1605 he first entered the historical record as the nominated commander of the second ship in an expedition to the Pacific. <s> The Portuguese born navigator Pedro Fernandes de Queirós proposed him for the positon.

title: Paul Menard
complex: John Paul Menard (born August 21, 1980) is an American professional stock car racing driver. <s> He currently competes full-time in the Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series, driving the No. 21 Ford Mustang for Wood Brothers Racing, and part-time in the NASCAR Xfinity Series, driving the No. 12 Mustang for Team Penske. <s> He is the son of Midwestern home improvement entrepreneur John Menard Jr., founder of the Menards chain. <s> Menard moved to Richard Childress Racing in 2011, driving the No. 27. <s> On July 31, 2011, Menard won his first Sprint Cup race in his 167th start, in the Brickyard 400 at the prestigious Indianapolis Motor Speedway. <s> He did so by making his last pit stop with 36 laps to go.
simple: Paul Menard (born August 21, 1980 in Eau Claire, Wisconsin) is an American racecar driver. <s> Menard drives the No. 21 Ford Mustang for Wood Brothers Racing in the Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series, and runs part-time for Team Penske in the NASCAR Xfinity Series. <s> Menard is the son of home improvement store magnate John Menard. <s> Menard won his first NASCAR Sprint Cup race, the Brickyard 400, on July 31, 2011 at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway.

title: Kaltag, Alaska
complex: Kaltag (KAL-tag) ("Ggaał Doh" in Koyukon) is a city and village in Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska, United States. <s> At the 2010 census the population was 190, down from 230 in 2000. <s> Kaltag was a Koyokon Athabascan area used as a cemetery for surrounding villages. <s> It is located on an old portage trail which led west through the mountains to Unalakleet. <s> The Athabascans had seasonal camps in the area and moved as the wild game migrated. <s> There were 12 summer fish camps located on the Yukon River between the Koyukuk River and the Nowitna River. <s> Kaltag was named by Russians for a Koyokon man named Kaltaga. <s> There was a smallpox epidemic in 1839 that killed a large part of the population of the area. <s> After the Alaska Purchase, a United States military telegraph line was constructed along the north side of the Yukon River. <s> A trading post opened around 1880, just before the gold rush of 1884-85. <s> Steamboats on the Yukon, which supplied gold prospectors ran before and after 1900 with 46 boats in operation on the river in the peak year of 1900. <s> A measles epidemic and food shortages during 1900 reduced the population of the area by one-third. <s> The village Kaltag was established after the epidemic when survivors from three nearby villages moved to the area. <s> There was a minor gold rush in the area in the 1880s. <s> In 1906, gold seekers left for Fairbanks or Nome; however, the galena lead mines began operating in 1919. <s> Kaltag was downriver from the mines and grew as a point on the transportation route for the mines. <s> It declined in the 1940s as mining declined. <s> The old cemetery caved into the river around 1937. <s> An airport and clinic were constructed during the 1960s. <s> Kaltag has a week long Stick Dance (memorial Potlatch) every two years that draws visitors from many neighboring villages. <s> This Potlatch is sponsored by relatives of the recently deceased, in appreciation of those who helped during their time of mourning. <s> Much of the economy around Kaltag is based on subsistence hunting and fishing. <s> Salmon, whitefish, moose, bear, waterfowl and berries are elements of the subsistence economy. <s> Kaltag is located at (64.325145, -158.727030) and is on the west bank of the Yukon River, 120 km west of Galena of 27.4 sqmi , of which, 23.3 sqmi of it is land and 4.1 sqmi of it (14.97%) is water.
simple: Kaltag is a town in Alaska. <s> They used Kaltag as a cemetery for surrounding villages. <s> It is on an old walking track which led west through the mountains to Unalakleet. <s> The Athabascans had many camps in the area. <s> They moved as the animals they hunted for food moved to different areas. <s> There were 12 summer fish camps on the Yukon River between the Koyukuk River and the Nowitna River. <s> The Russians named Kaltag after a Koyokon man named Kaltaga. <s> In 1839 smallpox killed many of the people who lived in the area. <s> When the United States took over Alaska, the army built a telegraph line along the north side of the Yukon River. <s> A trading post opened around 1880. <s> There was a gold rush in 1884-85. <s> Steamboats travelled along the river carrying supplies for the gold miners. <s> In 1900 there were 46 steamboats on the river. <s> Measles and food shortages during 1900 reduced the population of the area by one-third. <s> The village of Kaltag began after this when the people who were left in three nearby villages moved to the area. <s> By 1906, most of the people looking gold had left for Fairbanks or Nome. <s> The Galena lead mines opened 1919. <s> Kaltag was down the river from the mines and grew as a point on the transportation route for the mines. <s> It declined in the 1940s as mining declined. <s> The old cemetery was washed into the river around 1937. <s> An airport and medical clinic were built during the 1960s. <s> Kaltag has a week long Stick Dance Festival every two years that draws visitors from many other villages. <s> This festival is held by relatives of people who have died, to thank those who helped during their time of mourning. <s> Most of the people in Kaltag live by hunting and fishing. <s> Salmon, whitefish, moose, bear, waterfowl and berries are the main foods. <s> Kaltag is on the west bank of the Yukon River, 120 km (75 miles) west of Galena.

title: Benigno Aquino Jr.
complex: Benigno Simeon "Ninoy" Aquino Jr. (November 27, 1932 – August 21, 1983) was a Filipino politician who served as a Senator of the Philippines (1967–1972) and governor of the province of Tarlac. <s> He was the husband of former Philippine President Corazon Aquino and father of former Philippine President Benigno Aquino III. <s> Aquino, together with Gerardo Roxas and Jovito Salonga, formed the leadership of the opposition towards then President Ferdinand Marcos. <s> Shortly after the imposition of martial law, he was arrested in 1972 along with others associated with the Communists' armed insurgency and incarcerated for seven years. <s> He founded his own party, Lakas ng Bayan, and ran in the 1978 Philippine parliamentary election, but all of the party's candidates, including Aquino, lost in the election. <s> In 1980, Aquino was permitted by Marcos to travel to the United States for medical treatment following a heart attack. <s> He was assassinated at the Manila International Airport in 1983 upon returning from his self-imposed exile. <s> His death catapulted his widow, Corazon, into the political limelight, and prompted her to successfully run for a six-year term as President as a member of the UNIDO party in the 1986 snap election.
simple: Benigno Kheng Hon "Ninoy" Aquino, Jr. was a Filipino senator and a former Governor of Tarlac. <s> He was born on November 27, 1932 and died on August 21, 1983 at the age of 50. <s> Aquino, Gerry Roxas and Jovito Salonga formed the leadership of the opposition to the government of President Ferdinand Marcos. <s> Shortly after that, he was arrested in 1973 for seven years. <s> Aquino was allowed to travel to the United States for medical treatment following a heart attack. <s> He was killed at the Manila International Airport in 1983 upon returning from his self-imposed exile. <s> Aquino's death caused his widow, Corazon Aquino, to run for President in 1986.

title: Trackball
complex: A trackball is a pointing device consisting of a ball held by a socket containing sensors to detect a rotation of the ball about two axes—like an upside-down mouse with an exposed protruding ball. <s> Users roll the ball to position the on-screen pointer, using their thumb, fingers, or commonly the palm of the hand while using the fingertips to press the mouse buttons. <s> Large trackballs are sometimes seen on computerized special-purpose workstations, such as the radar consoles in an air-traffic control room or sonar equipment on a ship or submarine. <s> Modern installations of such equipment may use mice instead, since most people now already know how to use one.
simple: In computing, a trackball is a pointing input device. <s> It consists of a ball held by a socket containing sensors to detect a rotation of the ball about two axes. <s> It is like an upside-down mouse with a ball that sticks out. <s> The user rolls the ball with the thumb, fingers or the palm of the hand to move a cursor. <s> Large trackballs are sometimes seen on computerized special-purpose workstations, such as the radar consoles in an air-traffic control room or sonar equipment on a ship or submarine.

title: Salva Kiir Mayardit
complex: Salva Kiir Mayardit (born 13 September 1951) is a South Sudanese politician who has been President of South Sudan since its independence in 2011. <s> He is a Dinka and prior to independence, he was President of the Government of Southern Sudan, as well as First Vice President of Sudan, from 2005 to 2011.
simple: Salva Kiir Mayardit (born 13 September 1951) is a South Sudanese politician who has been President of South Sudan since its independence in 2011. <s> Prior to independence, he was President of the Government of Southern Sudan, as well as First Vice President of Sudan, from 2005 to 2011.

title: The Mississippi Bar
complex: The Mississippi Bar is the integrated (mandatory) bar association of the U.S. state of Mississippi. <s> The Mississippi Bar traces its lineage to a voluntary membership organization formed in 1821; however, this association lapsed after four years. <s> It was revived in 1886, but lapsed six years later. <s> In 1905 it was revived again; its first President was G.D. Shands. <s> During the Great Depression, membership dwindled amid public skepticism about lawyer ethics. <s> In response, the leading Mississippi lawyers successfully urged the passage of the state's Unified Bar Act in 1932, leading to the present-day mandatory Bar.
simple: The Mississippi Bar is the required group that attorneys in the U.S. state of Mississippi must join. <s> The Mississippi Bar was first a voluntary membership organization formed in 1821. <s> However, this association ended four years later. <s> It was restarted in 1886 but ended six years after that. <s> In 1905 it was started again. <s> During the Great Depression, membership declined because the public did not thing that the lawyers were ethical. <s> So, the main lawyers in Mississippi got the state to pass its Unified Bar Act in 1932, which led to the current required Bar assocation.

title: Arcadia, Indiana
complex: Arcadia is a town in Jackson Township, Hamilton County, Indiana, United States. <s> The population was 1,666 at the 2010 census. <s> As of the 2010 census, there were 1,666 people, 612 households, and 427 families residing in the town.
simple: Arcadia is a town in the state of Indiana, in the United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, there were 1,666 people living in Arcadia.

title: Fritz Sdunek
complex: Fritz Sdunek (] ; 18 April 1947 – 22 December 2014) was a German professional boxing trainer and previously an amateur boxer. <s> Regarded as one of the most successful and famous boxing trainers, he trained, among others, such world champions as Wladimir and Vitali Klitschko and Dariusz Michalczewski. <s> He was born in Lüssow, East Germany. <s> Fritz Sdunek's career started in amateur boxing. <s> Its highlight was a victory at a "Students Championship of East Germany" in 1968. <s> He won 99 of his 129 amateur fights, then decided to become a trainer. <s> He died in a hospital in Hamburg on 22 December 2014, at the age of 67 following a heart attack he had suffered earlier on the island of Gran Canaria.
simple: Fritz Sdunek (pronounced "free-ts zdoo-neck", April 18, 1947 – December 22, 2014) was a German professional boxing trainer and former amateur boxer. <s> Sdunek was one of the most successful and famous boxing trainers. <s> He trained, among others, such world champions as Wladimir and Vitali Klitschko and Dariusz Michalczewski. <s> He was born in Lüssow, Germany. <s> Sdunek died in Hamburg on December 22, 2014, at the age of 67.

title: Jemaa el-Fnaa
complex: Jemaa el-Fnaa (Arabic: ساحة جامع الفناء "saaHat jamaaʻ al-fanâʼ", also Jemaa el-Fna, Djema el-Fna or Djemaa el-Fnaa) is a square and market place in Marrakesh's medina quarter (old city). <s> It remains the main square of Marrakesh, used by locals and tourists. <s> Shortly before noon on April 28, 2011, a blast originating in a cafe in the square killed 17 people and injured another 25. <s> Initial reports blamed an accidental gas explosion, but officials later blamed "criminals" and "terrorists".
simple: Jamaa el Fna (Arabic: ساحة جامع الفناء "saaHat jamaaʻ al-fanâʼ", also Jemaa el-Fnaa, Djema el-Fna or Djemaa el-Fnaa) is a famous square in Old city of Marrakesh, Morocco. <s> On April 28, 2011 an explosion originated at the cafe "Aragana" in the square. <s> 17 people were killed while 25 were wounded in the blast.

title: Pebibyte
complex: The pebibyte is closely related to the petabyte (PB), its corresponding unit in the decimal set of multiples defined in the International System of Units (SI), and which represents 10 bytes = . <s> It follows that one pebibyte (1 PiB) is approximately equal to 1.13 PB. <s> One thousand twenty-four pebibytes (1024 PiB) is equal to one exbibyte (1 EiB).
simple: It is related to the petabyte which is 10 bytes. <s> 1024 pebibytes make one exbibyte.

title: Containment building
complex: Containment systems for nuclear power reactors are distinguished by size, shape, materials used, and suppression systems. <s> The kind of containment used is determined by the type of reactor, generation of the reactor, and the specific plant needs.
simple: Containment systems for nuclear power reactors are distinguished by size, shape, materials used, and suppression systems. <s> The kind of containment used is determined by the type of reactor, generation of the reactor, and the specific plant needs.

title: Cairo, Georgia
complex: Cairo is a city in Grady County, Georgia, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 9,607. <s> The city is the county seat of Grady County.
simple: Cairo is a city in Grady County, Georgia, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 9,607. <s> The city is the county seat of Grady County.

title: Gun Hägglund
complex: Karin Gunvor Sjöblom Hägglund (2 March 1932 – 19 August 2011), better known as Gun Hägglund, was a Swedish television host and translator. <s> Hägglund was the first female television news anchor in Sweden, hosting the Swedish national evening news show "Aktuellt" in 1958. <s> She is sometimes credited as the first female television news reader in the world, but that claim is inaccurate as British "ITN" Midday News included female bulletin presenter Barbara Mandell in 1955 and "BBC" Regional news bulletin included Armine Sandford in 1957. <s> Gun Hägglund started her career at Swedish Radio in 1955 where she worked at the foreign news desk as a secretary and program announcer. <s> She moved on to Swedish Television in 1958 to become Sweden's first female news anchor in the national news show "Aktuellt", often accompanied by pioneer news anchor Olle Björklund. <s> In addition, Hägglund was a translator of foreign motion pictures and television series. <s> In an interview from 1966, Hägglund describes the rather complicated process of translating textual versions of the dialog in films and television programs into short subtitles of text at the bottom of the screen. <s> For the general public, Hägglund is probably best known for her participation in Swedish television's entertainment programs and daily shows such as "Halvsju" ("Half Past Six O'Clock"), "Razzel", "Träna med TV" ("Workout with TV"), and "Café Sundsvall". <s> Hägglund was married to news editor Karl-Axel Sjöblom (known as "KAS") with whom she co-hosted "Halvsju", one of the most popular television shows in Swedish history. <s> They were married until his death in 1982. <s> For 30 years, until 1997, Hägglund was closely involved in the "Svenska Cykelfrämjandet" ("National Association for Promotion of Cycling"), first as Secretary-General, and later Executive Chairman. <s> In that capacity, she published a number of books about cycling. <s> In 1986, Hägglund moved from the Swedish capital of Stockholm to the Baltic island of Gotland. <s> She died in Visby after a short illness in 2011.
simple: Karin Gunvor Sjöblom Hägglund (2 March 1932–19 August 2011) was Swedish television star. <s> She is better known as Gun Hägglund. <s> Hägglund presented the national news show Aktuellt. <s> Her career started in 1955 when she started working for the Swedish radio. <s> She was a secretary and program announcer. <s> She was the news presenter of Aktuellt in 1958. <s> In 1958, she moved to television shows and became the first female in Sweden to present the news. <s> She translated movies and TV shows. <s> She was married to the Swedish news editor Karl-Axel Sjöblom. <s> Her husband died in 1982. <s> For 30 years, until 1997, Hägglund was involved in the "Swedish National Association of Promotion of Cycling". <s> First she was Secretary-General and later Executive Chairman. <s> In that position, she published some books about cycling. <s> Hägglund was born in Örnsköldsvik, Sweden and died in Visby. <s> Hägglund died in 2011 after a short illness.

title: Harry Tjutjuna
complex: Harry Tjutjuna is an Aboriginal artist from central Australia. <s> He belongs to the Pitjantjatjara people. <s> Tjutjuna began painting in 2005. <s> He held his first solo exhibition in 2007, in Darwin. <s> His work is now held in several major public galleries in Australia, including the Art Gallery of New South Wales, the National Gallery of Victoria, and the National Gallery of Australia. <s> His painting " " (Bilby Dreaming Story) was a finalist for the Togard Contemporary Art Award in 2009. <s> In 2010 and 2011, another of Tjutjuna's paintings, " ", was chosen as a finalist in both the Western Australian Indigenous Art Awards, and the National Aboriginal & Torres Strait Islander Art Award (NATSIAA). <s> Tjutjuna was born around 1930. <s> He was born in the bushland close to what is now the community of Pipalyatjara in the north-west corner of South Australia. <s> Sources disagree on where exactly he was born. <s> Some say he was born at Walytjatjara, a place to the north-east of Pipalyatjara, just over the border in the Northern Territory. <s> Others say that he was born at Mount Davies, a hill that overlooks Pipalyatjara. <s> When Tjutjuna was still young, his family settled at Ernabella. <s> He went to school on the mission there and later worked as a labourer for the community. <s> He later moved back west to live in the communities of Irrunytju and Pipalyatjara after they were established. <s> He moved there with his wives and children to be closer to his homeland. <s> In his later life, Tjutjuna became known as an important traditional healer (" ") and law man (" ") for the Pitjantjatjara. <s> Tjutjuna began painting in late 2005, when he was aged in his mid-seventies. <s> He was living again at Ernabella, and began to paint for the community's art company Ernabella Arts. <s> His work at Ernabella depicted "Tjukurpa" (traditional law or stories from the Dreamtime). <s> It supported a shift in subject matter for the centre's artists, from quite secular to more spiritual subjects. <s> In 2008, Tjutjuna moved back to Pipalyatjara and began work for Ninuku Arts. <s> Tjutjuna paints concepts and stories from his Dreaming. <s> His main personal totem is a spider (" "), and his Dreaming revolves around the (Spider Man Dreaming). <s> According to his Dreaming, which was passed on to him from previous generations, Tjutjuna's ancestor is a powerful being known as the Spider Man. <s> This creature is said to have created Tjutjuna's country in the Dreamtime, and so Tjutjuna associates his country, his heritage and himself with this set of beliefs. <s> In this way, the paintings are autobiographical in addition to depicting traditional stories. <s> Tjutjuna identifies himself as the Spider Man, and his paintings are often seen to symbolise his work as a " " (healer). <s> Because his totem is a spider, he uses spider webs to treat wounds on people's skin. <s> Tjutjuna also paints figures from several other Dreaming stories associated with his country, such as the "Wati Maḻu" (Red Kangaroo Man) and the "Kungka Mingkiri" (Mice Women). <s> Many of the paintings have sexual themes. <s> One of Tjutjuna's most famous paintings, " ", is a composition of two Dreaming stories. <s> It depicts the story of the Kungkarungkara (Seven Sisters), which is about the constellations of Pleiades (the Sisters) and Orion. <s> Tjutjuna painted it from the male's perspective. <s> , a shape-shifting man, chases the seven sisters and catches the youngest, raping her. <s> The other story depicted is from the Spider Man Dreaming. <s> The painting was chosen as a finalist for the Western Australian Indigenous Art Awards in 2010, and the National Aboriginal & Torres Strait Islander Art Award in 2011. <s> Tjutjuna paints in the typical style of the Western Desert, which can be seen as very abstract. <s> The figures in his paintings, ancestral beings, are obscured and encoded for cultural reasons. <s> He uses fields of dots to represent their interactions, and lines to represent their journeys across the landscape. <s> The landscape is depicted with the earthly colours of the desert (reds, oranges, ochres and white). <s> In his works depicting , he often paints circular patterns across the background. <s> This motif is used to represent both a spider's web and the spider man's many women. <s> Tjutjuna is also known for drip paintings.
