title: Chevrolet Express
complex: The Chevrolet Express and its mechanically identical twin GMC Savana are full-size vans from General Motors. <s> They replaced the Chevrolet Van and GMC Vandura in 1995.
simple: Chevrolet Express and GMC Savana are full sized passenger or cargo vans made via General Motors.

title: Ambergris
complex: Ambergris is formed from a secretion of the bile duct in the intestines of the sperm whale, and can be found floating on the sea or washed up on the coast. <s> It is also sometimes found in the abdomens of dead sperm whales.
simple: Ambergris is lumps of fatty compounds, secreted and expelled by the sperm whale.

title: Macromolecule
complex: A macromolecule is a very large molecule, such as protein, commonly created by the polymerization of smaller subunits (monomers). <s> They are typically composed of thousands of atoms or more.
simple: A macromolecule is a molecule with a large number of atoms. <s> The word is usually used only when describing polymers, molecules which are made up of smaller molecules called monomers.

title: Patricia Gallerneau
complex: Patricia Gallerneau (9 September 1954 – 7 July 2019) was a French politician representing the Democratic Movement. <s> She was elected to the French National Assembly on 18 June 2017, representing the department of Vendée. <s> Patricia Gallerneau was born in the 20th arrondissement of Paris to a Finisterian mother and a Correzian father. <s> The latter was elected by the Rassemblement pour la République in Angers.
simple: Patricia Gallerneau ("née" Sérézat; 9 September 1954 – 7 July 2019) was a French politician. <s> She was a member of the Democratic Movement. <s> Gallerneau died of cancer on 7 July 2019, at the age of 64. <s> She was elected to the National Assembly in June 2017, serving until two days before her death in July 2019. <s> She represented the department of Vendée. <s> She was born in the 20th arrondissement of Paris.

title: Les Landes-Genusson
complex: Les Landes-Genusson is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Les Landes-Genusson is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Vendée department in the west of France.

title: Kevin Cramer
complex: Kevin John Cramer (born January 21, 1961) is an American politician serving as the junior United States Senator for North Dakota since 2019. <s> A member of the Republican Party, he previously served in the United States House of Representatives for North Dakota's at-large Congressional District. <s> He also chaired the North Dakota Republican Party (1991–1993) and served as State Tourism Director (1993–1997) and Economic Development Director (1997–2000).
simple: Kevin John Cramer (born January 21, 1961) is an American politician of the Republican Party. <s> He is the junior United States senator of North Dakota since January 3, 2019. <s> He was a member of the United States House of Representatives for North Dakota from January 3, 2013 to January 3, 2019.

title: Fort William, Ontario
complex: Fort William was a city in Northern Ontario, located on the Kaministiquia River, at its entrance to Lake Superior. <s> It amalgamated with Port Arthur and the townships of Neebing and McIntyre to form the city of Thunder Bay in January 1970. <s> Since then it has been the largest city in Northwestern Ontario. <s> The city's Latin motto was "A posse ad esse" (From a Possibility to an Actuality) featured on its coat of arms designed in 1900 by town officials, "On one side of the shield stands an Indian dressed in the paint and feathers of the early days; on the other side is a French voyageur; the center contains an grain elevator, a steamship and a locomotive, while the beaver surmounts the whole."
simple: Fort William was a city in Northern Ontario. <s> It was on the Kaministiquia River, at its entrance to Lake Superior. <s> It amalgamated with Port Arthur and the townships of Neebing and McIntyre to form the city of Thunder Bay in January 1970. <s> Ever since then it has been the largest city in Northwestern Ontario.

title: Judgment Day (2008)
complex: Judgment Day (2008) was a professional wrestling pay-per-view (PPV) event produced by World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE). <s> It took place on May 18, 2008, at the Qwest Center Omaha in Omaha, Nebraska. <s> It was the tenth annual Judgment Day event and starred wrestlers from the Raw, SmackDown, and ECW brands.
simple: Judgment Day (2008) was a professional wrestling pay-per-view show made by World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE). <s> It was held on May 18, 2008 at the Qwest Center in Omaha, Nebraska. <s> It was the tenth Judgment Day event held by the WWE.

title: Judy Baar Topinka
complex: Judy Baar Topinka (January 16, 1944 – December 10, 2014) was an American politician and member of the Republican Party from the U.S. State of Illinois. <s> Although originally a journalist, Topinka served in the Illinois House of Representatives from 1981 to 1985 and in the Illinois Senate from 1985 to 1995. <s> She was elected to three terms as Illinois State Treasurer, serving from 1995 to 2007. <s> She was the first woman to become state treasurer, the first to be elected to three consecutive terms, and the first Republican to hold the post in more than 32 years. <s> During her last term as treasurer, she was the only Republican to hold statewide elected office in Illinois. <s> In 2002, she was elected chair of the Illinois Republican Party, holding that office until 2005. <s> She declined to run for re-election as treasurer in 2006, instead running for Governor of Illinois. <s> In March 2006, she was nominated as the Republican candidate. <s> She was the second woman (after 1994 Democratic nominee Dawn Clark Netsch) and first Republican woman to be nominated for governor of Illinois. <s> She went on to lose the election to Democratic incumbent Rod Blagojevich. <s> In 2010, she successfully ran for the office of Illinois Comptroller. <s> She was re-elected to a second four-year term in November 2014, however later died of a stroke in December 2014. <s> On November 7, 2005, Topinka announced that she would not seek re-election as state treasurer—instead, she entered the gubernatorial primary, hoping to challenge Democratic Governor Rod Blagojevich. <s> The Republican primary was deeply divisive; her tenure as Party chairman destroyed her support from the conservative wing of her party, and it was feared that her pro-choice and positive gay rights positions would be detrimental to her standing with the same conservatives.
simple: Judy Baar Topinka (January 16, 1944 – December 10, 2014) was an American politician. <s> Topinka was born on January 16, 1944 in Chicago, Illinois. <s> She served as the Illinois Comptroller and Illinois Treasurer, having served as Treasurer from 1995 to 2007, and former chairwoman of the Illinois Republican Party. <s> She was the first woman to become state treasurer, first to be elected to three consecutive terms and the first Republican to hold the post in more than thirty-two years. <s> During her last term, she was the only elected statewide official from the Republican Party, in Illinois. <s> In March 2006, she was nominated as the Republican candidate. <s> She was the second woman (after 1994 Democratic nominee Dawn Clark Netsch) and first Republican woman to be nominated for governor of Illinois. <s> She went on to lose the election to Rod Blagojevich. <s> In 2010, she successfully ran for the office of Illinois State Comptroller and was re-elected in 2014, one month before her death. <s> In November 2005, Topinka announced her decision to run for Governor of Illinois.

title: Redwood City, California
complex: Redwood City is a city on the San Francisco Peninsula in Northern California's Bay Area, approximately 27 mi south of San Francisco, and 24 mi northwest of San Jose. <s> Redwood City's history spans its earliest inhabitation by the Ohlone people to being a port for lumber and other goods.
simple: Redwood City is a community on the San Francisco Peninsula in California, United States. <s> It is located 25 mi south of San Francisco, and about 27 mi north of San Jose, California.

title: Nin'an
complex: Nin'an (仁安 ) , also known as Ninnan, was a Japanese era name (年号, , "nengō", , lit. <s> "year name") after "Eiman" and before "Kaō." <s> This period spanned the years from August 1166 through April 1169. <s> The reigning emperors were Rokujō"-tennō" (六条天皇 ) and Takakura"-tennō" (高倉天皇 ) .
simple: Nin'an (仁安), also known as Ninnan, was a Japanese era name (年号, "nengō", lit. <s> "year name") after "Eiman" and before "Kaō." <s> This period started in August 1166 ended in April 1169. <s> The reigning emperors were Rokujō"-tennō" (六条天皇) and Takakura"-tennō" (高倉天皇).

title: Coosa County, Alabama
complex: Coosa County is a county of the U.S. state of Alabama. <s> As of the 2010 census the population was 11,539. <s> Its county seat is Rockford. <s> Its name derives from a town of the Creek tribe and the Coosa River, which forms one of the county borders. <s> The county was established on December 18, 1832, formed from parts of Montgomery and Shelby counties. <s> It gained a small snippet from Montgomery County in 1837 and lost a portion to the south upon the creation of Elmore County in 1866. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 666 sqmi , of which 651 sqmi is land and 15 sqmi (2.3%) is water. <s> As of the census of 2010, there were 11,539 people, 4,794 households, and 3,293 families residing in the county.
simple: Coosa County is a county of the U.S. state of Alabama. <s> As of 2010, 11,539 people lived there. <s> Its county seat is Rockford. <s> Its name is from a town of the Creek tribe. <s> It was formed on December 18, 1832. <s> According to the 2000 census, the county has a total area of 666.36 sqmi. <s> 652.44 sqmi (or 97.91%) is land and 13.91 sqmi (or 2.09%) is water.

title: Unidentified flying object
complex: Unidentified flying object (UFO) is the popular term for any aerial phenomenon that cannot immediately be identified. <s> Most UFOs are identified on investigation as conventional objects or phenomena. <s> The term is widely used for claimed observations of extraterrestrial spacecraft. <s> Studies show that after careful investigation, the majority of UFOs can be identified as ordinary objects or phenomena.
simple: A UFO (Unidentified Flying Object) is any object flying in the sky which cannot be identified by the person who sees it. <s> Most UFOs are actually natural or man-made objects that looked strange. <s> Studies also show that very few UFO sightings are hoaxes (people trying to trick other people).

title: David Fonseca (politician)
complex: William Henry "David" Fonseca (1 May 1954 – 30 April 2015) was a Belizean politician. <s> A member of the People's United Party, Fonseca served as Mayor of Belize City from 1999 to 2006. <s> On 30 April 2015, Fonesca was found dead of a gunshot wound to the head at a house owned by his mother in Belize City. <s> His death was ruled a suicide.
simple: William Henry "David" Fonseca (1 May 1954 – 30 April 2015) was a Belizean politician and businessman. <s> He served as the Mayor of Belize City from 1 March 1999 until 1 March 2006. <s> He was a member of the People's United Party. <s> Fonseca died on 30 April 2015 in Belize City, aged 60. <s> He committed suicide (killed himself) by shooting himself in the head.

title: Sibylline Books
complex: The Sibylline Books were a collection of oracular utterances, set out in Greek hexameters, that according to tradition were purchased from a sibyl by the last king of Rome, Tarquinius Superbus, and were consulted at momentous crises through the history of the Republic and the Empire. <s> Only fragments have survived, the rest being lost or deliberately destroyed. <s> According to the Roman tradition, the oldest collection of Sibylline books appears to have been made about the time of Solon and Cyrus at Gergis on Mount Ida in the Troad; it was attributed to the Hellespontine Sibyl and was preserved in the temple of Apollo at Gergis. <s> From Gergis the collection passed to Erythrae, where it became famous as the oracles of the Erythraean Sibyl. <s> It would appear to have been this very collection that found its way to Cumae (see the Cumaean Sibyl) and from Cumae to Rome. <s> The story of the acquisition of the Sibylline Books by Tarquinius is one of the famous legendary elements of Roman history. <s> The Cumaean Sibyl offered to Tarquinius nine books of these prophecies; and as the king declined to purchase them, owing to the exorbitant price she demanded, she burned three and offered the remaining six to Tarquinius at the same stiff price, which he again refused, whereupon she burned three more and repeated her offer. <s> Tarquinius then relented and purchased the last three at the full original price and had them preserved in a vault beneath the Capitoline temple of Jupiter. <s> The story is alluded to in Varro's lost books quoted in Lactantius "Institutiones Divinae" (I: 6) and by Origen, and told by Aulus Gellius ("Noctes Atticae" 1, 19). <s> The Roman Senate kept tight control over the Sibylline Books; "Sibylline Books" were entrusted to the care of two patricians; after 367 BC ten custodians were appointed, five patricians and five plebeians, who were called the "decemviri sacris faciundis"; subsequently (probably in the time of Sulla) their number was increased to fifteen, the "quindecimviri sacris faciundis". <s> They were usually ex-consuls or ex-praetors. <s> They held office for life, and were exempt from all other public duties. <s> They had the responsibility of keeping the books in safety and secrecy. <s> These officials, at the command of the Senate, consulted the "Sibylline Books" in order to discover not exact predictions of definite future events in the form of prophecy but the religious observances necessary to avert extraordinary calamities and to expiate ominous prodigies (comets and earthquakes, showers of stones, plague, and the like). <s> It was only the rites of expiation prescribed by the Sibylline Books, according to the interpretation of the oracle that were communicated to the public, and not the oracles themselves, which left ample opportunity for abuses. <s> Since they were written in hexameter verse and in Greek, the college of curators was always assisted by two Greek interpreters. <s> The books were kept in the Temple of Jupiter on the Capitol, and, when the temple burned in 83 BC, they were lost. <s> The Roman Senate sent envoys in 76 BC to replace them with a collection of similar oracular sayings, in particular collected from Ilium, Erythrae, Samos, Sicily, and Africa. <s> This new Sibylline collection was deposited in the restored temple, together with similar sayings of native origin, e.g. those of the Sibyl at Tibur (the 'Tiburtine Sibyl') of the brothers Marcius, and others, which had been circulating in private hands but which were called in, to be delivered to the Urban Praetor, private ownership of such works being declared illicit, and to be evaluated by the Quindecimviri, who then sorted them, retaining only those that appeared true to them. <s> From the Capitol they were transferred by Augustus as "pontifex maximus" in 12 BC, to the temple of "Apollo Patrous" on the Palatine, after they had been examined and copied; there they remained until about AD 405. <s> According to the poet Rutilius Claudius Namatianus, the general Flavius Stilicho (died AD 408) burned them, as they were being used to attack his government. <s> The "Sibylline Oracles" were quoted by the Roman-Jewish historian Josephus (late 1st century) as well as by numerous Christian writers of the second century, including Athenagoras of Athens who, in a letter addressed to Marcus Aurelius in ca. <s> AD 176, quoted "verbatim" a section of the extant "Oracles", in the midst of a lengthy series of other classical and pagan references such as Homer and Hesiod, stating several times that all these works should already be familiar to the Roman Emperor.
simple: The Sibylline Books were a collection of prophecies in rhyme written in Greek. <s> The legendary king of Rome, Tarquinius Superbus bought them from a Sibyl (a kind of prophetess), and the prophecies used to be consulted in times when great danger happened in the history of the Roman Empire. <s> From there, it passed to Erythrae (in eastern Asia Minor) and was called the work of the Erythraean Sibyl. <s> It seems that this collection travelled from there to Cumae, Italy and from there to Rome. <s> The story of how king Tarquinius bought them from the Cumaean Sibyl was a famous legend. <s> She offered to sell Tarquin a collection of nine books of prophecy, but he refused the price, so she burnt three. <s> After that she offered to sell the six remaining books for the same price. <s> He refused again and she burnt another three. <s> Finally he bought these three remaining books for this price so they would not be destroyed, and put them in the temple of Jupiter in Rome. <s> The books were given to the trust of two Roman patricians (nobles). <s> Beginning in 367 BC, ten keepers - five from the patricians and five from the common citizens - were appointed for them. <s> Because the verses were written in Greek, the keepers would always be helped by two Greek translators. <s> The books were destroyed when the Temple of Jupiter burned down in 83 BC. <s> Because of this, the Roman Senate sent messengers in 76 BC to find similar prophecies and replace them. <s> The Roman Emperor Augustus in 12 BC moved them to the Temple of Apollo, when they were studied and a new copy was made. <s> They stayed there until 405 AD. <s> Modern scholars believe these books are not the same as the "Sibylline Oracles" that were often quoted by early Christian writers from the 2nd century through the 5th century AD.

title: Manspach
complex: Manspach (Alsatian: "Mànschbàch") is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France.
simple: Manspach is a commune. <s> It is in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France.

title: Karl-Heinz von Hassel
complex: Karl-Heinz von Hassel (8 February 1939 – 19 April 2016) was a German actor. <s> He appeared in more than 100 films and television shows between 1960 and 2012. <s> Born in Hamburg, he trained for a business career and also took acting lessons. <s> From 1960 he made stage appearances at various theatres and from 1966 he appeared regularly on television and he later had significant roles in films directed by Rainer Werner Fassbinder. <s> Hassel was a tall man who was often cast as police officers, but he also portrayed industrial workers. <s> He died in Hamburg died aged 77 after a short illness.
simple: Karl-Heinz von Hassel (8 February 1939 – 19 April 2016) was a German actor. <s> He acted in more than 100 movies and television shows between 1960 and 2012. <s> He was born in Hamburg, Germany. <s> He trained for a business career and also took acting lessons. <s> From 1960 he acted in plays in several theaters. <s> From 1966 he appeared regularly on television. <s> He later had important roles in movies directed by Rainer Werner Fassbinder. <s> Hassel was a tall man who often acted as a police officer. <s> Hassel died after a short illness on 19 April 2016 in Hamburg, Germany. <s> He was 77 years old.

title: Damocloid
complex: Damocloids are thought to be nuclei of Halley-type comets that have lost all their volatile materials due to outgassing and become dormant. <s> Such comets probably originate from the Oort cloud. <s> This hypothesis is strengthened by the fact that a number of objects thought to be damocloids (and assigned minor-planet provisional designations) subsequently showed a coma and were confirmed to be comets: C/2001 OG (LONEOS), C/2002 CE (LINEAR), C/2002 VQ (LINEAR), C/2004 HV (Spacewatch) and possibly others. <s> Another strong indication of cometary origin is the fact that some damocloids have retrograde orbits, unlike any other minor planets.
simple: They are believed to be comets that have lost their volatile material and are dormant. <s> Scientists think that they come from the Oort cloud. <s> This is because some damocloids, such as C/2001 OG (LONEOS), later developed tails and became comets.

title: Water Lilies (Monet series)
complex: Water Lilies (or Nymphéas, ] ) is a series of approximately 250 oil paintings by French Impressionist Claude Monet (1840–1926). <s> The paintings depict his flower garden at his home in Giverny, and were the main focus of his artistic production during the last thirty years of his life. <s> Many of the works were painted while Monet suffered from cataracts. <s> The paintings are on display at museums all over the world, including the Princeton University Art Museum, Musée Marmottan Monet, the Musée d'Orsay in Paris, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Museum of Modern Art in New York, the Art Institute of Chicago, the Saint Louis Art Museum, the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas City, Missouri, the Carnegie Museum of Art, the National Museum of Wales, the Musée des Beaux-Arts de Nantes, the Cleveland Museum of Art, the Portland Art Museum and the Legion of Honor.
simple: Water Lilies (or Nymphéas, ]) is a series of about 250 oil paintings by French Impressionist Claude Monet. <s> The paintings are of Monet's flower garden at Giverny. <s> They were the main focus of Monet's work during the last thirty years of his life. <s> Many of the works were painted while Monet suffered from cataracts. <s> The paintings are on display in museums all over the world, including the Musée Marmottan Monet and the Musée d'Orsay in Paris, the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York, the Art Institute of Chicago, the Carnegie Museum of Art and the National Museum of Wales, among others.

title: Rambling Rose (film)
complex: Rambling Rose is a 1991 American drama film set in Georgia during the Great Depression starring Laura Dern and Robert Duvall in leading roles with Lukas Haas, John Heard and Diane Ladd in supporting roles. <s> "Rambling Rose" was directed by Martha Coolidge and written by Calder Willingham (adapted from his own 1972 novel of the same name).
simple: Rambling Rose is a 1991 American drama movie. <s> The movie is set in Georgia during the Great Depression. <s> Robert Duvall, Diane Ladd and Lukas Haas play the family she moves in with.

title: Mali at the Olympics
complex: Mali has sent athletes to Summer Olympic Games held in 1964, 1972, and every other Olympics since 1980, although the country has never won an Olympic medal. <s> No athletes from Mali have competed in any Winter Olympic Games. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Mali was formed in 1962 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee in 1963.
simple: Mali has taken part in the Summer Olympic Games held in 1964, 1972, and every Olympics since 1980. <s> The country has never won an Olympic medal. <s> No athletes from Mali have been in any Winter Olympic Games. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Mali was formed in 1962 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee in 1963.

title: Buck Henry
complex: Henry Zuckerman (born December 9, 1930), credited as Buck Henry, is an American actor, writer, film director, and television director. <s> He has been nominated for an Academy Award twice, in 1968 for Best Adapted Screenplay for "The Graduate" and in 1979 for Best Director for "Heaven Can Wait". <s> His long career began on television with work on shows with Steve Allen and Mel Brooks as well as Saturday Night Live.
simple: Henry Zuckerman, credited as Buck Henry (born December 9, 1930), is an American actor, writer, movie director, and television director. <s> He has been nominated for an Academy Award twice, in 1968 for Best Adapted Screenplay for "The Graduate" and in 1979 for Best Director for "Heaven Can Wait".

title: Bara Subdivision
complex: Bara Subdivision is a subdivision located in Khyber District, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan. <s> In the 2000s, Bara achieved some mention in worldwide media with the founding of Lashkar-e-Islam, founded in the area by Mufti Munir Shakir, and later passed to Mangal Bagh, a local driver.
simple: Bara is a tehsil in Khyber Agency, Federally Administered Tribal Areas, Pakistan. <s> In the 2000s, Bara achieved some mention in worldwide media with the founding of Lashkar-e-Islam, founded in the area by Mufti Munir Shakir, and later passed to Mangal Bagh, a local driver.

title: Lytham St Annes
complex: Lytham St Annes is a seaside resort on the Fylde coast of Lancashire, England, south of Blackpool on the Ribble Estuary. <s> The population at the 2011 census was 42,954.
simple: Lytham St Annes is a conurbation in Lancashire, England.

title: Angora goat
complex: The Angora goat is a breed of domesticated goat, historically known as Angora. <s> Angora goats produce the lustrous fibre known as Mohair. <s> The first Angora goats were brought to Europe by Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor, about 1554, but, like later imports, were not very successful. <s> Turkey, Argentina, the United States, and South Africa are the top producers of mohair. <s> Secondary producers include New Zealand and Australia.
simple: The Angora goat is a breed of domestic goat. <s> The Angora produces fine quality white or coloured mohair which is very similar to wool. <s> Angora goats are kept mostly for their output of mohair. <s> Angoras were imported into Europe in 1554 by Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor. <s> Today, the Union of South Africa is one of the world's top mohair producers.

title: Hamois
complex: Hamois (] ; ) is a Walloon municipality and village located in the Belgian province of Namur. <s> The village is around 25 km south-east of the city of Namur.
simple: Hamois is a municipality in the Belgian province of Namur.

title: George Davis Snell
complex: George Davis Snell (December 19, 1903 – June 6, 1996) was an American mouse geneticist and basic transplant immunologist. <s> George Snell shared the 1980 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine with Baruj Benacerraf and Jean Dausset for their discoveries concerning "genetically determined structures on the cell surface that regulate immunological reactions". <s> Snell specifically "discovered the genetic factors that determine the possibilities of transplanting tissue from one individual to another. <s> It was Snell who introduced the concept of H antigens." <s> Snell's work in mice led to the discovery of HLA, the major histocompatibility complex, in humans (and all vertebrates) that is analogous to the H-2 complex in mice. <s> Recognition of these key genes was prerequisite to successful tissue and organ transplantation. <s> George Snell was born in Bradford, Massachusetts, the youngest of three children. <s> His father (who was born in Minnesota), worked as a secretary for the local YMCA; he invented a device for winding induction coils for motorboat engines. <s> Snell was educated in the Brookline, Massachusetts schools and then enrolled at Dartmouth College in Hanover, New Hampshire where he continued his passion for mathematics and science, focusing on genetics. <s> He received his Bachelor's degree from Dartmouth in 1926. <s> On the recommendation of John Gerould, his genetics professor at Dartmouth, Snell did graduate work at Harvard University with William E. Castle, the first American biologist to look for Mendelian inheritance in mammals. <s> Snell earned his PhD from Harvard in 1930. <s> His doctoral thesis was on genetic linkage in mice. <s> Upon receiving the Ph.D from Harvard, George Snell was employed as a teacher at Brown University, from 1930~1931. <s> Snell then spent two years as a postdoctoral fellow at the University of Texas with H.J. Muller, who pioneered radiation genetics (and was also to win a Nobel Prize). <s> Not surprisingly, Snell studied the genetic effects of x-rays on mice with Muller. <s> From 1933~1934, Snell was a teacher at WUSTL. <s> After brief stints as teachers, in 1935 Snell joined the staff of The Jackson Laboratory in Bar Harbor on beautiful Mount Desert Island by the coast of Maine and he remained there for the entire balance of his long career. <s> In Bar Harbor, he met and married Rhoda Carson. <s> Together they had three sons, Thomas, Roy, and Peter. <s> In his leisure time, Snell enjoyed skiing, a passion he developed during his years at Dartmouth, as well as tennis. <s> Snell received the Cancer Research Institute William B. Coley Award in 1978 for distinguished research in immunology. <s> In 1988, he authored a substantial book, "Search for a Rational Ethic", on the nature of ethics and the rules by which we live. <s> It includes an evolution-based ethic founded on biological realities that he believed to be applicable to all human beings. <s> Snell died in Bar Harbor, Maine on June 6, 1996. <s> His wife died in 1994.
simple: George Davis Snell (December 19, 1903 – June 6, 1996) was an American mouse geneticist and basic transplant immunologist. <s> He won the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1980 with Baruj Benacerraf and Jean Dausset. <s> They won it "for their discoveries concerning genetically determined structures on the cell surface that regulate immunological reactions". <s> Snell specifically "discovered the genetic factors that determine the possibilities of transplanting tissue from one individual to another. <s> It was Snell who introduced the concept of H antigens." <s> Snell was born on December 19, 1903 in Bradford, Massachusetts. <s> He was the youngest of three children. <s> In 1926, Snell received a Bachelor's degree from Dartmouth College. <s> After recommendation by John Gerould, his genetics professor at Dartmouth, Snell completed graduate work at Harvard University where he worked with William E. Castle. <s> In 1930, Snell earned his PhD from Harvard. <s> After he earned his PhD, he worked at Brown University from 1930 to 1931. <s> After he left, he spent two years at the University of Texas as a postdoctoral fellow. <s> He worked with H. J. Muller, a pioneer of radiation genetics (and later, a Nobel Prize winner). <s> Snell worked at WUSTL as a teacher from 1933 to 1934. <s> After he had some short stints as a teacher, Snell joined the Jackson Laboratory staff in Bar Harbor, Maine and spent the rest of his life there. <s> Snell won the Wolf Prize in Medicine in 1978. <s> He died on June 6, 1996 in Bar Harbor, Maine.

title: Meslay-du-Maine
complex: Meslay-du-Maine is a commune in the Mayenne department in north-western France.
simple: Meslay-du-Maine is a commune of 2 616 people (1999).

title: Jill Singer
complex: Jill Leonie Singer (1957 – 8 June 2017) was an Australian journalist, writer and television presenter. <s> Singer began her career in journalism as an ABC radio trainee in 1984. <s> She eventually became a senior reporter for "The 7.30 Report" on ABC and later presented the Victorian edition of "Today Tonight" on the Seven Network. <s> She presented for "The 7.30 Report", "The Arts Show", "2-shot" and "People Dimensions" (ABC TV) She was the executive producer of ABC TV's national morning news and current affairs program" First Edition". <s> She wrote a weekly column for Melbourne's "Herald Sun" newspaper between 1997 and 2012, and lectured in television journalism at RMIT University in Melbourne. <s> She made regular appearances on "The Conversation Hour" (ABC 774) and on Sky News Australia's "Melbourne Report". <s> In 2005 she published a book about commercial surrogacy, "Immaculate Conceptions : Thoughts on babies, breeding and boundaries". <s> In February 2017, Singer was diagnosed with terminal AL amyloidosis. <s> On 8 June 2017, a post by her family on Singer's Facebook page announced that she had died at the age of 60 in Melbourne, Victoria. <s> She had married two months earlier on 8 April 2017, and had a daughter from her first marriage.
simple: Jill Singer (1957 – 8 June 2017) was an Australian journalist, columnist and television presenter. <s> Singer began her career in journalism as an ABC radio trainee in 1984. <s> She eventually became a senior reporter for "The 7.30 Report" on ABC and later presented the Victorian edition of "Today Tonight" on the Seven Network. <s> She also presented for "The 7.30 Report", "The Arts Show", "2-shot" and "People Dimensions" (ABC TV). <s> Singer was the executive producer of ABC TV's national morning news and current affairs program" First Edition". <s> She wrote a weekly column for Melbourne's "Herald Sun" newspaper between 1997 and 2012, and lectured in television journalism at RMIT University in Melbourne. <s> She made regular appearances on "The Conversation Hour" (ABC 774) and on Sky News Australia's "Melbourne Report". <s> Singer died of amyloidosis on 8 June 2017 in Melbourne at the age of 60.

title: Alan Rabinowitz
complex: Alan Robert Rabinowitz (December 31, 1953 – August 5, 2018) was an American zoologist who served as the President, CEO, and chief scientist at Panthera Corporation, a nonprofit conservation organization devoted to protecting the world's 40 wild cat species. <s> Called the "Indiana Jones of Wildlife Protection" by "Time", he studied jaguars, clouded leopards, Asiatic leopards, tigers, Sumatran rhinos, bears, leopard cats, raccoons, and civets. <s> Rabinowitz was diagnosed with chronic lymphocytic leukemia in 2001. <s> He died on August 5, 2018 from the progression of his cancer. <s> Conservation magazine "Conjour" said he left behind a "legacy of inspirational big cat conservation".
simple: Alan Robert Rabinowitz (December 31, 1953 – August 5, 2018) was an American zoologist. <s> He was the chief scientist at Panthera Corporation, a nonprofit conservation organization devoted to protecting the world's 40 wild cat species. <s> He was called the "Indiana Jones of Wildlife Protection" by "Time". <s> He studied jaguars, clouded leopards, Asiatic leopards, tigers, Sumatran rhinos, bears, leopard cats, raccoons, and civets. <s> On August 5, 2018, Rabinowitz died from leukemia in Manhattan, aged 64.

title: Enryaku
complex: Enryaku (延暦 ) was a Japanese era name (年号 , "nengō" , "year name") after "Ten'ō" and before "Daidō". <s> This period spanned the years from August 782 through May 806. <s> The reigning emperor was Kanmu"-tennō" (桓武天皇 ) .
simple: Enryaku (延暦) was a Japanese era name (年号, "nengō", lit. <s> "year name") after "Ten'ō" and before "Daidō." <s> This period started in August 782 and ended in May 806. <s> During this time, the emperor was Kammu"-tennō" (桓武天皇).

title: Edwards Barham
complex: Erle Edwards Barham (July 10, 1937 – October 17, 2014) was an American businessman, farmer, and conservationist in Oak Ridge, a village in Morehouse Parish in North Louisiana. <s> He was the first Republican elected — by a 29-vote margin — to the Louisiana State Senate since the era of Reconstruction. <s> Barham represented the agricultural District 33 from 1976 to 1980. <s> Barham was narrowly unseated in the 1979 nonpartisan blanket primary by a Democrat, David 'Bo' Ginn of Bastrop, who held the seat until 1988. <s> Like his father, Edwards Barham died in a plane crash. <s> On October 17, 2014, Barham, a certified flight instructor, was taxiing back to the hangar after a flight at Rayville Municipal Airport in Richland Parish when his Beechcraft Bonanza aircraft struck a perimeter fence. <s> He died airborne en route to Shreveport for medical attention.
simple: Erle Edwards Barham (July 10, 1937 – October 17, 2014) was an American farmer and conservationist. <s> He was the first Republican elected—by a 29-vote margin—to the Louisiana State Senate since the era of Reconstruction. <s> Barham represented the agricultural District 33 from 1976 to 1980. <s> He was narrowly unseated in the 1979 nonpartisan blanket primary by the Democrat David "Bo" Ginn of Bastrop, who held the seat until 1988. <s> Barham died in a plane crash on October 17, 2014. <s> He was attempting to take off at Rayville Municipal Airport when his Beechcraft Bonanza aircraft struck a perimeter fence.

title: Together Again (Sash! song)
complex: "Together Again" is a song by German production group Sash!. <s> The record was released in November 2000 via Edel Records as the fourth and final single from their third studio album "Trilenium". <s> The record features vocal parts by Danish artist Blå Øjne and was released in Denmark and Spain only. <s> The group initially planned to release the song with Danish lyrics.
simple: "Together Again" is a 2000 song by the German DJ group Sash! <s> It is the fourth and final single from Sash's third studio album "Trilenium" which was released on 22 May 2000. <s> and it features Danish singer Blå Øjne.

title: Thorey
complex: Thorey is a commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France.
simple: Thorey is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Shani
complex: Shani refers to the planet Saturn, and is one of the nine heavenly objects known as Navagraha in Hindu astrology. <s> Shani is also a male deity in the Puranas, whose iconography consists of a handsome figure carrying a sword or danda (sceptre), and sitting on a crow.
simple: Shani is one of the Navagraha which are the nine main celestial beings in Hindu astrology, or Jyotiṣa. <s> Shani is embodied in the planet Saturn.

title: Porcupine
complex: Porcupines are large rodents with a coat of sharp spines, or quills, that protect against predators. <s> The term covers two families of animals, the Old World porcupines of family Hystricidae, and the New World porcupines of family Erethizontidae. <s> Both families belong to the infraorder Hystricognathi within the profoundly diverse order Rodentia and display superficially similar coats of quills: despite this, the two groups are distinct from each other and are not closely related to each other within the Hystricognathi. <s> The New World porcupines are indigenous to North America and northern South America. <s> They live in wooded areas and can climb trees, where some species spend their entire lives. <s> They are less strictly nocturnal than their Old World relatives, and generally smaller. <s> In taxonomic terms, they form the family Erethizontidae. <s> Most porcupines are about 25 - long, with an 8 - long tail. <s> Weighing 12 - , they are rounded, large, and slow, and use aposematic strategy of defense. <s> Porcupines occur in various shades of brown, gray, and white. <s> Porcupines' spiny protection resembles that of the unrelated erinaceomorph hedgehogs and Australian monotreme echidnas. <s> The name "porcupine" comes from Latin "porcus" pig + "spina" spine, quill, via Old Italian—Middle French—Middle English. <s> A regional American name for the animal is quill pig. <s> Porcupines' quills, or spines, take on various forms, depending on the species, but all are modified hairs coated with thick plates of keratin, and embedded in the skin musculature. <s> Old World porcupines have quills embedded in clusters, whereas in New World porcupines, single quills are interspersed with bristles, underfur, and hair. <s> Quills are released by contact or may drop out when the porcupine shakes its body. <s> New quills grow to replace lost ones. <s> Porcupines were long believed to have the ability to project their quills to a considerable distance at an enemy, but this has since been proven to be untrue. <s> Porcupines occupy a short range of habitats in tropical and temperate parts of Asia, Southern Europe, Africa, and North and South America. <s> They live in forests and deserts, and on rocky outcrops and hillsides. <s> Some New World porcupines live in trees, but Old World porcupines stay on the rocks. <s> Porcupines can be found on rocky areas up to 3700 m high.
simple: A porcupine is a rodent with a coat of sharp spines, or quills, that defend them from predators. <s> Most porcupines are about 60–90 cm long, with a 20–25 cm long tail. <s> Weighing between 12-35 pounds (5–16 kg), they are rounded, large and slow. <s> Porcupines come in various shades of brown, grey, and the unusual white. <s> The name "porcupine" comes from Middle French "porc d'épine" "thorny pork", hence the nickname "quill pig" for the animal. <s> The animal's quills or spines take on many forms, depending on the type, but all are hairs coated with thick plates of keratin, and they are in the skin musculature. <s> Old World porcupines (Hystricidae) have quills in clusters, whereas in New World porcupines (Erethizontidae) single quills are mixed with bristles, underfur, and hair. <s> The ancient belief that porcupines can throw their quills at an enemy has long been proved to be incorrect. <s> Porcupines can live in a wide range of places in tropical and mild parts of Asia, Italy, Africa, and North and South America. <s> Porcupines live in forests, deserts and grasslands. <s> Some live in trees, others stay on the ground.

title: Pruillé-l'Éguillé
complex: Pruillé-l'Éguillé is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Pruillé-l'Éguillé is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Cyril Bourlon de Rouvre
complex: Cyril Hubert Marie Bourlon de Rouvre is a French businessman and politician, born 19 December 1945 at Boulogne-Billancourt. <s> After studies at the "collège Maspero" in Paris, then at the "collège Saint-Martin de France" in Pontoise, the Oratory School in Reading, the "Collège Saint-Jean" in Fribourg and at the "Lycée Janson-de-Sailly", Cyril Bourlon de Rouvre studied electrical engineering at "Jussieu" before graduating as an aerospace engineer at the "Institut polytechnique des sciences avancées". <s> In 1979, upon the death of his father (who was murdered by his valet), he inherited large real estate holdings, a sugar refinery and 28 companies. <s> He became CEO of "Financière Robur et de Cofragec" (1982–1992), "Coficine" (1984–1992) and many other companies. <s> He modernized the sugar factory and his inheritance prospered, taking, in 1981, control of the holding Fraissinet, owner of the business airline Transair. <s> In 1987, he started a new career in film distribution by acquiring, from the producer Robert Dorfmann, by one of its companies, the "Financière Robur", Cofragec company with its catalog of 650 films including "La Grande Vadrouille" or "La Vache et le Prisonnier". <s> He produced movies including "La Nuit bengali" (1988) of Nicolas Klotz, "Les Deux Fragonard" (1989) of Philippe Le Guay, and "La Peste" (1992) of Luis Puenzo. <s> He also invested in real estate, including a hotel in Tahiti. <s> In 1989, he started a political career in "Haute-Marne", a department where which his grandfather Charles de Rouvre was a deputy during the Third Republic. <s> He was elected mayor of Chaumont, as an independent (classified as miscellaneous right) against the centrist senator and mayor Georges Berchet, and regional councilor for the Champagne-Ardenne region (1992–1998). <s> Owner of the Formula 1 team AGS from March 1989 to 1991, he swallowed $18 million and began selling activities of his group, about 70 companies: First Transair, then the sugar factory, sold to the "Compagnie de Navigation Mixte", and in 1992, the catalog of movies, lent to UGC in the form of a merger. <s> In 1991, he gives AGS the Italians Gabriele Rafanelli and Patrizio Cantu. <s> In 1992, Cyril de Rouvre bought the Formula 1 team Ligier for an estimated price of 200 million of francs. <s> With its new owner, the team started to again be competitive – the 1993 season was a success, with a 5th place in the constructor's championship (the team's best result since 1986). <s> But the involvement of Cyril de Rouvre lasted only one season because of legal troubles. <s> The 14 December 1993, the judge Eva Joly incarcerated him at the Fleury-Mérogis Prison, as part of a complaint for fraud filed by the leaders of UGC, Guy Verrecchia and Alain Sussfeld, following the takeover in June 1992 the company Cofragec. <s> This company has been emptied of its assets, leaving a liability estimated at 172.6 million francs. <s> Cyril de Rouvre had promised to repay this sum at the end of 1992 but at that time, he still had 100 million. <s> On 5 May 1993, leaders of UGC have filed a complaint against him. <s> He spent two months in prison. <s> In early 1994, he sold Ligier to Flavio Briatore. <s> He lost the mayoralty of Chaumont at the French municipal elections of 1995. <s> In 1996, a judicial investigation was opened against him at the "Tribunal de grande instance" of Chaumont. <s> He appeared before the Criminal Court of this city in September 1999 for tax evasion. <s> Knowing that the prosecution had requested a sentence of three years imprisonment and a 20-year ban on company management, he was sentenced on 19 December 1999, his birthday, to a suspended sentence of 18 months imprisonment' a ban from managing a company for 3 years, and a large fine.
