suspended and a ban from managing a company for 3 years and a fine large tax.

title: Bare Mountain (Massachusetts)
complex: Bare Mountain, 1014 ft above sea level, is a prominent peak of the Holyoke Range of traprock mountains located in the Connecticut River Valley of Massachusetts, and part of the greater Metacomet Ridge that stretches from Long Island Sound to nearly the Vermont border. <s> The peak rises steeply from the river valley 1000 ft below; its bald summit offers sweeping views. <s> Bare Mountain is located within the towns of Amherst and South Hadley, Massachusetts. <s> Part of its northeastern flanks are in Hadley and part of its southern flanks are in Granby.
simple: Bare Mountain is a prominent peak of the Holyoke Range in the Connecticut River Valley of Massachusetts. <s> It is 1014 ft above sea level. <s> It is part of the greater Metacomet Ridge that goes from Long Island Sound almost to the Vermont border. <s> Bare Mountain is in the towns of Amherst and South Hadley, Massachusetts.

title: Latvian Wikipedia
complex: The Latvian Wikipedia ( ] ) is the Latvian-language edition of the free online encyclopedia Wikipedia. <s> It was created on 6 June 2003. <s> With about articles, it is currently the -largest Wikipedia as measured by the number of articles and the second-largest Wikipedia in a Baltic language.
simple: Latvian Wikipedia is the Latvian edition of Wikipedia. <s> It was started on 6 June 2003.

title: Miriam Margolyes
complex: Miriam Margolyes, ( ; born 18 May 1941) is a British-Australian actress and voice artist. <s> Her earliest roles were in theatre and after several supporting roles in film and television she won a BAFTA Award for her role in "The Age of Innocence" (1993) and was cast in the role of Professor Sprout in the "Harry Potter" film series. <s> For many years she has divided her time between England and Australia, and she has starred in productions in both countries, including the Australian premiere of the 2013 play "". <s> In 2013, she became an Australian citizen, thereby holding dual British and Australian citizenship. <s> Margolyes was born in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, on 18 May 1941, the only child of Ruth ("née" Walters; 1905–1974), a property investor and developer, and Joseph Margolyes (1899–1995), a physician from Glasgow. <s> She grew up in a Jewish family; her ancestors migrated to the UK from Poland and Belarus. <s> Her great-grandfather, Symeon Sandmann, was born in the town of Margonin in central-western Poland, which Margolyes visited in 2013. <s> She played Professor Sprout in "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets" released in 2002. <s> In her 2011 interview on "The Graham Norton Show", in regard to her fellow cast, Margoyles claimed that she liked Maggie Smith, but rather bluntly admitted that she, "Didn't like the one that died", meaning Richard Harris. <s> Margolyes is a lesbian. <s> On becoming an Australian citizen, on Australia Day 2013, Margolyes referred to herself as a "dyke" live on national television and in front of the then Prime Minister, Julia Gillard.
simple: Miriam Margolyes OBE (born 18 May 1941) is an English-Australian actress. <s> She is best known for her role as Professor Sprout in the "Harry Potter" movie series. <s> She also appeared appeared in the movies "The Age of Innocence" (1993), which won her a BAFTA Award, "Babe" (1995), and "" (1998). <s> Margolyes was born in Oxford, Oxfordshire. <s> She was the daughter of Ruth (née Walters; 1905–1974), a property investor and developer, and Joseph Margolyes (1899–1996), a Scottish physician from Glasgow. <s> She was grew up in a Jewish family and her ancestors are from Poland and Belarus. <s> She is a lesbian and has been with her partner Heather for over forty years. <s> She has also been an Australian citizen since 2013.

title: Konstantyn K. Kuzminsky
complex: Konstantin Konstantinovich Kuzminsky (16 April 1940 – 2 May 2015) was a Russian performance poet. <s> Born in Leningrad, Kuzminsky emigrated from the Soviet Union in 1978. <s> He published "The Blue Lagoon Anthology of Modern Russian Poetry". <s> Other publications include a collection of Russian poetry "The Living Mirror". <s> He appeared in several documentary films, among them two by Andrei Zagdansky: Vasya, a portrait of a close friend and Russian/Soviet nonconformist artist Vasily Sitnikov and Konstantin and Mouse a.k.a. "Kostya and Mouse", a double-portrait of Konstantin Kuzminsky and his wife Emma, nicknamed Mouse. <s> Kuzminsky died in the United States on 2 May 2015.
simple: Konstantin Konstantinovich Kuzminsky (; 16 April 1940 – 2 May 2015) was a Russian-American performance poet. <s> Kuzminsky was born in Leningrad (now called Saint Petersburg). <s> He moved to the United States from the Soviet Union in 1978. <s> He published "The Blue Lagoon Anthology of Modern Russian Poetry" as well as other publications including a collection of Russian poetry "The Living Mirror". <s> He also appeared in many documentary movies, including two by Andrei Zagdansky. <s> Kuzminsky died on 2 May 2015 in New York City, aged 75.

title: Ellen Muth
complex: Ellen Muth (born March 6, 1981) is an American actress, known for her role as Georgia "George" Lass in Showtime's series "Dead Like Me". <s> Muth was born in Milford, Connecticut, the daughter of Rachel and Erich Muth. <s> After a brief stint as a model with Ford Models and Rascal's Agency, Muth pursued a career in acting, studying at the Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute in New York City, and getting her first professional experience doing commercials in 1993.
simple: Ellen Muth (born March 6, 1981) is an American actress. <s> Muth was born in Milford, Connecticut.

title: Patty Mills
complex: Patrick Sammy Mills (born 11 August 1988) is an Australian professional basketball player for the San Antonio Spurs of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> Mills was selected by the Portland Trail Blazers with the 55th overall pick in the 2009 NBA draft after playing two years of college basketball for Saint Mary's. <s> Mills was born and raised in Canberra, Australia, and is of Torres Strait Islander and Aboriginal Australian descent. <s> In 2007, he became only the third indigenous basketball player to play for Australia behind Olympians Michael Ah Matt (1964) and Danny Morseu (1980–84).
simple: Patrick Sammy "Patty" Mills (born 11 August 1988) is an Australian professional basketball player. <s> He plays for the San Antonio Spurs of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> Mills was born in Canberra to a Torres Strait Islander father and an Aboriginal Australian mother.

title: Carmen Stănescu
complex: Carmen Stănescu (29 July 1925 – 11 April 2018) was a Romanian stage and film actress. <s> She was born in Bucharest and died in Snagov.
simple: Carmen Stănescu (29 July 1925 – 11 April 2018) was a Romanian actress. <s> Stănescu died of cardiopulmonary arrest on 11 April 2018 in Snagov, Romania at the age of 92. <s> She was born in Bucharest.

title: Boolean algebra
complex: In mathematics and mathematical logic, Boolean algebra is the branch of algebra in which the values of the variables are the truth values "true" and "false", usually denoted 1 and 0 respectively. <s> Instead of elementary algebra where the values of the variables are numbers, and the prime operations are addition and multiplication, the main operations of Boolean algebra are the conjunction "and" denoted as ∧, the disjunction "or" denoted as ∨, and the negation "not" denoted as ¬.
simple: Boolean algebra is algebra for binary (0 means false and 1 means true).

title: Roland Taylor
complex: Roland Morris "Fatty" Taylor (March 13, 1946 – December 7, 2017) was an American professional basketball player. <s> A 6’0" guard born in Washington, D.C. and an alum of La Salle University, Taylor joined the American Basketball Association in 1969. <s> After one year playing for the Washington Capitals, he moved on to the Virginia Squires, with whom he spent the prime of his career, tallying 3,495 points, 1,737 assists, and 1,715 rebounds in five seasons. <s> Taylor became known as one of the few outstanding defensive players in a league known primarily for a "run-and-gun" style. <s> On the Squires Taylor played with former or later NBA stars including Adrian Smith, "Jumbo" Jim Eakins and Julius "Doctor J" Erving. <s> For one-and-a-half seasons Taylor was a teammate of George Gervin, and Taylor has been credited with coining Gervin's nickname "The Iceman" (he first called Gervin "Iceberg Slim", which gradually developed into the more familiar nickname). <s> Taylor spent one season in the NBA (1976–77) as a member of the Denver Nuggets, and he retired in 1977 with combined ABA/NBA totals of 5,098 points, 2,563 assists, and 2,524 rebounds. <s> Fatty Taylor died from the complications on December 7, 2017 at the age of 71.
simple: Roland Morris "Fatty" Taylor (March 13, 1946 – December 7, 2017) was an American professional basketball player. <s> He was born in Washington, D.C.. <s> He also played for the Denver Nuggets from 1974 through 1975 and again from 1976 through 1977. <s> Taylor died on December 7, 2017 at the age of 71 from male breast cancer in Denver, Colorado.

title: Caussols
complex: Caussols is a commune in the Alpes-Maritimes department in southeastern France. <s> It is known for the CERGA Observatory on the Calern plateau.
simple: Caussols is a commune.

title: Sansha
complex: Sansha is a prefecture-level city of Hainan province of the People's Republic of China (PRC). <s> It is located on Woody Island and administers (actually or nominally) several island groups and undersea atolls in the South China Sea including the Spratly Islands, the Paracel Islands, Macclesfield Bank, Scarborough Shoal, and a number of other ungrouped maritime features. <s> The entire territory is disputed, and the PRC's "de facto" control over the area varies.
simple: Sansha (三沙) is a city of the People's Republic of China (PRC) in Hainan Province. <s> In 2012, the city was established to administer several uninhabited island groups and undersea atolls in the South China Sea, including the Spratly and Paracel Islands as well as the Macclesfield Bank.

title: Pavillon de l'Arsenal
complex: The Pavillon de l'Arsenal is the "Paris Center for architecture and urbanism", a center for urban planning and museum located in the 4th arrondissement at 21, boulevard Morland, Paris, France. <s> It is open daily except Mondays; admission is free. <s> The museum building was built in 1878-1879 for Laurent-Louis Borniche, wood merchant and amateur painter, near the former site of a Celestine monastic community turned arsenal. <s> In 1988 it became a center for documentation and exhibitions related to urban planning and the architecture of Paris.
simple: The Pavillon de l'Arsenal is a museum in Paris, France. <s> The museum is dedicated to architecture and urban planning in Paris and the Parisian metropolis. <s> In 1988, it became the first centre for urban planning and architecture in Paris.

title: Doug Wilson (rugby union)
complex: Douglas Dawson Wilson (30 January 1931 – 18 May 2019) was a New Zealand rugby union player. <s> A first and second five-eighth, Wilson represented Canterbury and Wellington at a provincial level, and was a member of the New Zealand national side, the All Blacks, on their 1953–54 tour of Britain, Ireland, France and North America. <s> On that tour, he played 14 matches, including two internationals, and scored five tries and one drop goal. <s> He died in Kowhanui Hospital, Whanganui. <s> He had been married to Janice for 64 years.
simple: Douglas Dawson Wilson (30 January 1931 – 18 May 2019) was a New Zealand rugby union player. <s> He played 14 matches, including two internationals, and scored five tries and one drop goal. <s> Wilson died at Kowhainui Hospital in Whanganui on 18 May 2019.

title: Playback singer
complex: A playback singer is a singer whose singing is pre-recorded for use in movies. <s> Playback singers record songs for soundtracks, and actors or actresses lip-sync the songs for cameras; the actual singer does not appear on the screen. <s> South Asian movies produced in the Indian subcontinent are particularly known for using this technique. <s> A majority of Indian movies as well as Pakistani movies typically include six or seven songs. <s> After "Alam Ara" (1931), the first Indian talkie film, for many years singers made dual recordings for a film, one during the shoot, and later in the recording studio, until 1952 or 1953. <s> Popular playback singers in India enjoy the same status as popular actors, and music directors, and they also receive wide public admiration. <s> Most of the playback singers are initially trained in classical music, but they later often expand their range. <s> Mohammed Rafi and Ahmed Rushdi are regarded as two of the most influential playback singers in South Asia. <s> The sisters Lata Mangeshkar and Asha Bhosle, who have mainly worked in Hindi films, are often referred to as two of the best-known and prolific playback singers in India.
simple: A playback singer is a singer whose singing is pre-recorded for use in movies. <s> Playback singers record songs for soundtracks. <s> The actors or actresses lip-sync the songs for cameras. <s> The actual singer does not appear on screen. <s> South Asian movies produced in the Indian subcontinent are particularly known for using this technique. <s> A majority of Indian movies as well as Pakistani movies typically include six or seven songs. <s> Popular playback singers in India enjoy the same status as popular actors. <s> Most of the playback singers are initially trained in classical music. <s> Mohammed Rafi and Ahmed Rushdi are regarded as two of the most influential playback singers in South Asia.

title: Jim Whittaker
complex: James W. Whittaker (born February 10, 1929), also known as Jim Whittaker, is an American mountaineer and mountain guide. <s> Born and raised in Seattle, Washington, on May 1, 1963 he became the first American to reach the summit of Mount Everest as a member of the American Mount Everest Expedition led by Norman Dyhrenfurth, alongside the Sherpa Nawang Gombu (a nephew of Tenzing Norgay). <s> They ran out of oxygen but managed to reach the summit. <s> Once there, Whittaker planted a U.S. flag at the top.
simple: James W. Whittaker (born February 10, 1929), also known as Jim Whittaker, is an American mountaineer, autobiographer and mountain guide. <s> On May 1, 1963 he became the first American to reach the summit of Mount Everest as a member of the American Mount Everest Expedition led by Norman Dyhrenfurth. <s> They ran out of oxygen but managed to reach the summit. <s> Once there, Whittaker planted a U.S. flag at the top.

title: Lionello Manfredonia
complex: Lionello Manfredonia (] ; born 27 November 1956 in Rome) is an Italian former footballer who played as a defender or midfielder. <s> He is currently the leader of the youth sector at Brescia.
simple: Lionello Manfredonia (born 27 November, 1956) is a former Italian football player.

title: Obelus
complex: An obelus (symbol: ÷ or †, plural: obeluses or obeli) is a symbol consisting of a short horizontal line with a dot above and another dot below, and in other uses it is a symbol resembling a small dagger. <s> In mathematics it is mainly used to represent the mathematical operation of division. <s> It is therefore commonly called the division sign. <s> In editing texts an obelus takes the form of a dagger mark (†) and is used as a reference mark, or to indicate that a person is dead, and often used to indicate a footnote. <s> The word "obelus" comes from , the Ancient Greek word for a sharpened stick, spit, or pointed pillar. <s> This is the same root as that of the word "obelisk". <s> The obelus was first used as a symbol for division in 1659 in the algebra book " " by Johann Rahn. <s> Some think that John Pell, who edited the book, may have been responsible for this use of the symbol.
simple: An obelus (plural, obeli) is a symbol consisting of a line with dots above and below, formula_1, used to represent the mathematical division operation. <s> This symbol is also known as a division sign. <s> The word "obelus" comes from the Greek word for a sharpened stick, spit, or pointed pillar. <s> This is the same root as that of the word "obelisk". <s> The obelus was first used as a symbol for division in 1659 in the algebra book "Teutsche Algebra" by Johann Rahn.

title: Snares penguin
complex: The Snares penguin ("Eudyptes robustus"), also known as the Snares crested penguin and the Snares Islands penguin, is a penguin from New Zealand. <s> The species breeds on The Snares, a group of islands off the southern coast of the South Island. <s> This is a medium-small, yellow-crested penguin, at a size of 50 – and a weight of 2.5 – . <s> It has dark blue-black upperparts and white underparts.
simple: The Snares penguin ("Eudyptes robustus"), is a crested penguin. <s> It is a penguin from New Zealand. <s> It breeds on The Snares, a small island group south of New Zealand's South Island. <s> It has a size of 50-70 cm and a weight of 2.5-4 kg.

title: Billy Williams (cinematographer)
complex: Billy Williams OBE, BSC (born 3 June 1929, Walthamstow, London) is a British cinematographer. <s> Williams was responsible for shooting a number of films, including "Women in Love" (1969), "Gandhi" (1982), for which he won an Oscar, and "On Golden Pond" (1981). <s> Williams joined his father, also named Billy, as an apprentice cameraman, remaining with him for four years. <s> Later he served in the RAF as a photographer. <s> On leaving the RAF he obtained a job with British Transport Films (BTF), filming all forms of transportation. <s> Williams retired on New Year's Day 1996. <s> Since retirement he has travelled, conducting workshops on film. <s> He was appointed Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2009 Birthday Honours. <s> Williams is featured in a new book on cinematographers called Conversations with Cinematographers by David A Ellis and published by Scarecrow Press, which is part of the Rowman and Littlefield publishing group.
simple: Billy Williams OBE, BSC (born 3 June 1929) is a British cinematographer. <s> He was born in London. <s> Williams is known for his works for "Women in Love" (1969), "Gandhi" (1982), for which he won an Oscar, and "On Golden Pond" (1981). <s> He worked in the RAF as a photographer. <s> On leaving the RAF he got a job with British Transport Films (BTF), filming all forms of transportation. <s> Williams retired on New Year's Day 1996. <s> He was appointed Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2009 Birthday Honours.

title: Ostend
complex: Ostend ( , ] ; ] ; ] ; ) is a coastal city and municipality, located in the province of West Flanders, Belgium. <s> It comprises the boroughs of Mariakerke, Raversijde, Stene and Zandvoorde, and the city of Ostend proper – the largest on the Belgian coast.
simple: Oostende (German / French: Ostende, English Ostend) is a city in the Belgian province of West Flanders.

title: Piroska Oszoli
complex: Piroska Oszoli (21 January 1919 – 22 March 2017) was a Hungarian painter, is known as "The lover of the Danube and the beautiness". <s> She worked especially as applied to plein air landscape painting. <s> Piroska Oszoli (née Névery) was born in Dunaföldvár, Hungary in a Roman Catholic baron family on 21 January 1919. <s> After finishing her studies, she taught literature and history in Budapest. <s> Her master as an amateur artist was the note Transylvanian painter "Ferenc Doór" (1918–2015). <s> From 1947, after having returned in her native village to teach painting for schoolchildren, she completed her art studies as well. <s> Her husband was István Oszoli, a high school biology and chemistry teacher from 1949 until his death in 2003. <s> They have two sons, István (b. 1950) and András (b. 1953). <s> After teaching she became a pensioner, and started her painting as an individual artist. <s> She worked all around her village and neighborhood, after in Hungary, at Lake Balaton for example, and also in some beautiful places of Europe, from Italy to Norway, and from Germany to Croatia. <s> She had numerous expositions in her Country. <s> Her paintings are present around the World from Austria to New Zealand. <s> She died in her home in Dunaföldvár at the age of 98 years on 22 March 2017.
simple: Piroska Oszoli (21 January 1919 – 22 March 2017) was a Hungarian painter, is known as "The lover of the Danube and the beautiness". <s> She made especially as applied to plein-air landscape painting. <s> She was born and also dead in Dunaföldvár, Hungary. <s> Her master as an amateur artist was the famous Transylvanian painter Ferenc Doór (1918–2015). <s> After teaching she became a pensioner, and started her painting as an individual artist. <s> Oszoli worked all around her village and neighborhood, after in Hungary, at Balaton. <s> She painted natural surroundings in Italy, Croatia, Germany and Norway. <s> Her paintings are present from Austria to New Zealand. <s> Oszoli died on 22 March 2017 in Dunaföldvár, aged 98.

title: Ústí nad Labem
complex: Ústí nad Labem (] ), formerly known by its German name Aussig, is the 7th-most populous city of the Czech Republic. <s> It is the capital of its eponymous region and district.
simple: Ústí nad Labem (ˈuːsciː ˈnad labɛm, ) is the seventh-largest city in the Czech Republic.

title: National Museum of Mongolia
complex: The National Museum of Mongolia ; formerly the National Museum of Mongolian History is located in Ulaanbaatar. <s> This museum is a cultural, scientific, and educational organization, which is responsible for the collection, conservation and interpretation of the objects under its curation.
simple: The National Museum of Mongolia has exhibitions about archaeology, history and Mongolian culture.

title: Tentoku
complex: Tentoku (天徳 , te̞nto̞ku͍) was a Japanese era name (年号 , "nengō" , "year name") after "Tenryaku" and before "Ōwa." <s> This period spanned the years from October 957 through February 961. <s> The reigning emperors was Murakami"-tennō" (村上天皇 ) .
simple: Tentoku (天徳) was a Japanese era name (年号, "nengō", lit. <s> "year name") after "Tenryaku" and before "Ōwa." <s> This period started in October 957 and ended in February 961. <s> The reigning emperors was Murakami"-tennō" (村上天皇).

title: Andriy Voronin
complex: Andriy Viktorovych Voronin ( ; born 21 July 1979) is a Ukraine professional football manager and a former player.
simple: Andriy Voronin (born 21 July 1979) is an Ukrainian football player.

title: Mysterious (song)
complex: "Mysterious" is a song by English singer/songwriter Jentina. <s> It was released as the third and final single from her eponymous debut album "Jentina" (2005). <s> It was released only in Italy. <s> Plans were made for a UK release but were cancelled.
simple: "Mysterious" is the third and final single by Jentina from her self titled debut album, "Jentina". <s> It was released only in Italy where it reached number 49 on the Italian charts..

title: Ahmed Chalabi
complex: Ahmed Abdel Hadi Chalabi ( ; 30 October 1944 – 3 November 2015) was an Iraqi politician, a founder of the Iraqi National Congress (INC) and the President of the Governing Council of Iraq (37th Prime Minister of Iraq) <s> He was interim Minister of Oil in Iraq in April–May 2005 and December 2005 – January 2006 and Deputy Prime Minister from May 2005 to May 2006. <s> Chalabi failed to win a seat in parliament in the December 2005 elections, and when the new Iraqi cabinet was announced in May 2006, he was not given a post. <s> Once dubbed the "George Washington of Iraq" by American supporters, he later fell out of favor and came under investigation by several U.S. government sources. <s> Chalabi died on 3 November 2015, four days after his 71st birthday, having apparently suffered a heart attack at his home in Kadhimiya, Baghdad. <s> When he died, he was a current Member of the Iraqi Parliament, serving as the chairman of the Finance Committee.
simple: Ahmed Abdel Hadi Chalabi (‎; 30 October 1944 – 3 November 2015) was an Iraqi politician. <s> He was interim Minister of Oil in Iraq serving from 16 April 2005 to 1 January 2006. <s> He served as Deputy Prime Minister from 1 May 2005 to 20 May 2006. <s> Chalabi failed to win a seat in parliament in the December 2005 elections. <s> Chalabi died on 3 November 2015 from a heart attack at his home in Kadhimiya, Baghdad, aged 71.

title: Sulz, Lucerne
complex: Sulz is a former municipality in the district of Hochdorf in the canton of Lucerne in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2009, Sulz together with Gelfingen, Hämikon, Mosen, Müswangen, and Retschwil joined Hitzkirch.
simple: Sulz is a former municipality of the district of Hochdorf in the canton of Lucerne in Switzerland. <s> Since 1 January 2009, it became part of the municipality of Hitzkirch.

title: List of T.U.F.F. Puppy episodes
complex: This is a list of episodes for Nickelodeon's animated television series, "T.U.F.F. Puppy". <s> The first two seasons consist of 26 episodes and the third season consists of 8 episodes, for a total of 60 episodes. <s> On October 20, 2013, remaining episodes started airing on Nicktoons. <s> This season contained 26 episodes. <s> The season's finale "Lie Like A Dog / Cold Fish" and subsequent seasons were produced in high definition (HD).
simple: This is a list of episodes for Nickelodeon's animated television series, "T.U.F.F. Puppy". <s> The first two seasons consist of 26 episodes and the third season consists of 8 episodes, for a total of 60 episodes. <s> On October 20, 2013, remaining episodes started airing on Nicktoons. <s> This season contained 26 episodes. <s> The season's finale "Lie Like A Dog / Cold Fish" and subsequent seasons were produced in high definition (HD).

title: Jiao Ruoyu
complex: Jiao Ruoyu (; born November 7, 1915) is a retired People's Republic of China politician and diplomat. <s> He was born in Ye County, Henan. <s> He was deputy mayor of Shenyang under Huang Oudong. <s> He was Chinese Ambassador to North Korea (1965–1970), Peru (1972–1977) and Iran (1977–1979). <s> He was mayor of Beijing (1981–1983). <s> On August 14, 2012, Jiao, 97, was confirmed as the oldest member of the Communist Party of China to attend the 18th National Congress of the Communist Party of China. <s> He turned 100 in November 2015.
simple: Jiao Ruoyu (; born 7 November 1915) is a retired Chinese politician and diplomat. <s> Jiao was born in Ye County, Henan. <s> He served as deputy mayor of Shenyang under Huang Oudong. <s> He was Chinese Ambassador to North Korea (1965–1970), Peru (1972–1977) and Iran (1977–1979). <s> Jiao was also mayor of Beijing from 1981 to 1983. <s> He turned 100 in November 2015.

title: Neoteny
complex: Neoteny in humans is the slowing or delaying of body development, compared to non-human primates, resulting in features such as a large head, a flat face, and relatively short arms and legs. <s> These neotenic changes may have been brought about by sexual selection in human evolution.
simple: Neoteny is a type of heterochrony where bodily development is slowed, but sexual development goes on at the same rate. <s> These are some of the neotenous traits in humans: flattened face, broadened face, large brain, hairless body, hairless face, small nose, reduction of brow ridge, small teeth, small upper jaw (maxilla), small lower jaw (mandible), thinness of skull bones, limbs proportionately short compared to torso length, longer leg than arm length, larger eyes, and upright stance.

title: Champlay
complex: Champlay is a commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France.
simple: Champlay is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Matthias Herget
complex: Matthias Herget (born 14 November 1955) is a retired German footballer who played as a sweeper.
simple: Matthias Herget (born 14 November, 1955) is a former German football player.

title: SunTrust Park
complex: SunTrust Park is a baseball park located in the Atlanta metropolitan area 10 miles (16 km) northwest of downtown Atlanta in the unincorporated community of Cumberland, in Cobb County, Georgia. <s> It is the home ballpark of the Atlanta Braves of Major League Baseball (MLB). <s> On November 11, 2013, the Braves announced that the franchise would leave Turner Field for a new park after the 2016 season.
simple: SunTrust Park is a baseball stadium in a section of Cobb County, Georgia that has an Atlanta mailing address. <s> It is the home of the Atlanta Braves of Major League Baseball (MLB).

title: Humberto Tozzi
complex: Humberto Barbosa Tozzi (4 February 1934 – 17 April 1980) was a Brazilian international footballer who played for São Cristóvão, Palmeiras, Lazio and Fluminense. <s> Tozzi represented Brazil at the 1954 FIFA World Cup.
simple: Humberto Tozzi (born 4 February, 1934) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Saint Helier
complex: Saint Helier ( ; ; ) is one of the twelve parishes of Jersey, the largest of the Channel Islands in the English Channel. <s> St Helier has a population of about 33,500, roughly 34.2% of the total population of Jersey, and is the capital of the Island (although Government House is situated in St Saviour). <s> The urban area of the parish of St Helier makes up most of the largest town in Jersey, although some of the town area is situated in adjacent St Saviour, with suburbs sprawling into St Lawrence and St Clement.
simple: Saint Helier or St. Helier (; French language: "Saint-Hélier" ], Jèrriais: "Saint Hélyi") is one of the twelve parts (called parishes) of Jersey, the largest of the Channel Islands in the English Channel. <s> 33,500 people live in Saint Helier. <s> 33,500 is about 34.2% of the number of people of Jersey. <s> It is the capital of the Island (but Government House is in St. Saviour).

title: Interregnum
complex: In some monarchies, such as the United Kingdom, an "interregnum" is usually avoided due to a rule described as "The King is dead. <s> Long live the King", i.e. the heir to the throne becomes a new monarch immediately on his predecessor's death or abdication. <s> This famous phrase signifies the continuity of sovereignty, attached to a personal form of power named "Auctoritas". <s> This is not so in other monarchies where the new monarch's reign begins only with coronation or some other formal or traditional event. <s> In the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth for instance, kings were elected, which often led to relatively long interregna. <s> During that time it was the Polish primate who served as an interrex (ruler between kings). <s> In Belgium the heir only becomes king upon swearing before the parliament. <s> A "Papal interregnum" occurs upon the death or resignation of the Catholic Church's Pope, though this is generally known as a "sede vacante" (literally "when the seat is vacant"). <s> The interregnum ends immediately upon election of a new Pope by the College of Cardinals.
simple: In some monarchies, such as the United Kingdom, an "interregnum" is usually avoided due to a rule described as "the king is dead, long live the King", i.e. the heir to the throne becomes a new monarch immediately on his predecessor's death or abdication. <s> This famous phrase signifies the continuity of sovereignty. <s> This is not so in other monarchies where the new monarch's reign begins only with coronation or some other formal or traditional event. <s> An "interregnum" occurs also upon the death of the Roman Catholic Pope, though this is generally known as a "sede vacante" (vacant seat). <s> The interregnum ends immediately upon election of the new Pope by the College of Cardinals.

title: Eli Thayer
complex: Eli Thayer (June 11, 1819 – April 15, 1899) was a member of the United States House of Representatives from 1857 to 1861. <s> He was born in Mendon, Massachusetts. <s> He graduated from Worcester Academy in 1840, from Brown University in 1845, and in 1848 founded Oread Institute, a school for young women in Worcester, Massachusetts. <s> He is buried at Hope Cemetery, Worcester. <s> Local leagues were established whose members emigrated to Kansas and established towns. <s> The Company provided hotels for temporary accommodation (such as the Free State Hotel in Lawrence) and provided sawmills and other improvements. <s> Settlements were established at Manhattan, Lawrence, Topeka, and Osawatomie. <s> The clash of these settlers and other "Free-Stater" Northerners with pro-slavery settlers spawned the violence of Bleeding Kansas.
simple: Eli Thayer (June 11, 1819 – April 15, 1899) was an educator, reformer, legislator and founder of the New England Emigrant Aid Company. <s> He was a member of the United States House of Representatives from 1857-1861. <s> Thayer died in Worcester, Massachusetts on April 15, 1899. <s> Thayer was elected as a Republican to the U.S. House of Representatives where he served two terms (March 4, 1857-March 3, 1861). <s> Thayer was born in Mendon, Massachusetts on June 11, 1819. <s> He attended the Academy of Amherst and in 1840 graduated from Worcester Academy. <s> In 1845 he graduated from Brown University as salutatorian. <s> The towns of Lawrence, Topeka, Manhattan and Osawatomie, Kansas were all settled by or with help from the Emigrant Aid Company.

title: Coahoma County, Mississippi
complex: Coahoma County is a county located in the U.S. state of Mississippi. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 26,151. <s> Its county seat is Clarksdale. <s> Coahoma County was established February 9, 1836, and is located in the northwestern part of the state in the fertile Yazoo Delta region. <s> The name "Coahoma" is a Choctaw word meaning "red panther." <s> The act creating the county defined its limits as follows: Beginning at the point where the line between townships 24 and 25 of the surveys of the late Choctaw cession intersects the Mississippi River, and running thence up the said river to the point where the dividing line between the Choctaw and Chickasaw tribes of Indians intersects the same; thence with the dividing line to the point where the line between ranges two and three of the survey of the said Choctaw cession intersects the same; thence with said range line, to the line between townships 24 and 25 aforesaid, and thence with the said township line to the beginning. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 30,622 people, 10,553 households, and 7,482 families residing in the county. <s> The population density was 55 people per square mile (21/km2).
simple: Coahoma County is a county in the northwestern part of Mississippi. <s> It was started on February 9, 1836. <s> "Coahoma" is a Choctaw word that means "red panther." <s> There are about 30,622 people living there.

title: Saprobiontic
complex: Saprobiontic organisms feed off dead and or decaying matter, to digest this they excrete digestive enzymes which breaks down the cell tissues allowing the organism to extract the nutrients it needs to survive while leaving the indigestible waste. <s> This is called extracellular digestion.
simple: Saprophytic bacteria are fungal organisms that feed off of decaying organic matter.

title: Tropical Storm Beryl (2006)
complex: Tropical Storm Beryl was the third tropical storm of the 2006 Atlantic hurricane season. <s> Developing from a tropical disturbance on July 18, it tracked generally northward, and strengthened to attain peak winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) under generally favorable conditions. <s> After turning to the northeast, Beryl weakened over cooler waters. <s> On July 21 it struck the island of Nantucket, and shortly thereafter it became extratropical. <s> The extratropical remnants continued northeastward through Nova Scotia, and on July 22 it merged with an approaching cold front. <s> Beryl produced rough seas along the northeast United States coastline. <s> In Massachusetts, its impact was limited to light rainfall and gusty winds, with no reported damage. <s> Beryl later produced moderate rainfall and gusty winds across Atlantic Canada, resulting in some localized power outages though little damage. <s> No deaths were reported. <s> A cold front moved off the East Coast of the United States on July 16 and stalled off the coast of North Carolina. <s> It gradually decayed into a surface low pressure trough, and developed into two disturbances; one was centered 290 miles (490 km) south-southeast of Cape Cod and another was located 200 miles (320 km) south of Cape Hatteras, North Carolina. <s> The first low quickly organized into an unnamed tropical storm, and the other area initially remained broad and ill-defined. <s> However, by July 18, the system became much better organized with improved banding features, and the area developed into Tropical Depression Two while located 220 miles (355 km) south-southeast of Cape Hatteras. <s> The depression moved slowly to the north-northwest through a break in the subtropical ridge, and as convective banding features became more prominent the system intensified into Tropical Storm Beryl. <s> Throughout much of its duration, the storm tracked through an environment with light vertical wind shear and well-established upper-level outflow. <s> Shortly after becoming a tropical storm, the low-level circulation of Beryl became exposed with limited deep convection, though deep convection re-developed the following morning. <s> Outflow continued to improve, and with warm sea surface temperatures Beryl gradually intensified to attain peak winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) early on July 20 while located about 120 miles (190 km) east of Nags Head, North Carolina. <s> Beryl maintained peak winds for about 18 hours as it paralleled the Mid-Atlantic and New Jersey coasts, during which an eye-like feature developed in the center of the convection. <s> Late on July 20, it began a slow weakening trend after passing over cooler waters. <s> Steering winds ahead of an approaching mid-level trough caused Beryl to accelerate northeastward, and early on July 21 the center of the storm crossed the island of Nantucket. <s> The convection diminished as it moved through progressively colder waters, and shortly after 1200 UTC on July 21 Beryl became an extratropical cyclone a short distance east of Cape Cod. <s> Hours later, it made landfall in southwestern Nova Scotia, and on July 22 the extratropical remnants of Beryl merged with an approaching cold front over Newfoundland. <s> Forecasters initially predicted Beryl to brush the Carolinas; as such, a tropical storm watch was issued for the eastern coast of North Carolina from Cape Lookout northward to Currituck Beach Lighthouse. <s> When a more northeastward track became apparent, a tropical storm watch was issued about 33 hours prior to moving ashore from Woods Hole to Plymouth, Massachusetts, including Cape Cod, Nantucket, and Martha's Vineyard. <s> About 22 hours before landfall, the National Hurricane Center replaced the watch with a tropical storm warning for the same area, and also issued a tropical storm watch from Woods Hole, Massachusetts westward to New Haven, Connecticut and for the eastern portion of Long Island from east of Fire Island to Port Jefferson. <s> In anticipation for the storm, the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency was activated as a trial run for the hurricane season. <s> Local Red Cross chapters were opened, as well, with two volunteer teams placed on standby to assist. <s> Across southeastern Massachusetts, police departments maintained extra staff in preparation for any potential problems from the storm. <s> Many fishermen secured their boats, while some business owners boarded up windows to prevent storm damage. <s> Several days prior to the passage of Beryl through Atlantic Canada, the Canadian Hurricane Centre issued gale warnings for the coastal waters off Nova Scotia and Newfoundland. <s> In anticipation of heavy rainfall, the agency also issued heavy rainfall warnings for western Nova Scotia, including Halifax. <s> The storm caused high waves along the East Coast of the United States, with 19-foot seas (5.97 m) in the open ocean. <s> Waves along the southern coast of Nantucket reached 10 feet (3 m) in height as the storm approached the island, resulting in four people being rescued by lifeguards from rip currents. <s> High surf also occurred along the southern coast of Massachusetts, prompting the closing of the ferry between Nantucket and Boston. <s> Beryl produced a storm surge of 0.9 feet (.27 m) on Nantucket. <s> Winds across southeastern Massachusetts were fairly light, with no sustained tropical storm force winds and wind gusts peaking at 44 mph (71 km/h); unofficially gusts reached 51 mph (82 km/h). <s> Beryl dropped moderate precipitation just offshore, though the maximum precipitation total in the United States was only 0.97 inches (24.6 mm) on Nantucket. <s> Rainfall along southeastern Massachusetts reached 0.33 inches (8.38 mm) at Chatham. <s> The only reported damage were some downed telephone poles and fallen tree branches. <s> Overall impact was minor; there were no reported power outages, deaths, injuries, or maritime emergencies in association with the storm. <s> The remnants of Beryl dropped moderate precipitation in Atlantic Canada, officially peaking at 2.8 inches (71 mm) in Scots Bay, Nova Scotia with an unofficially higher total of 3.5 inches (88 mm); in some locations 1 inch of rain fell in an hour. <s> Additionally, a station in Fredericton, New Brunswick reported 1.77 inches (45 mm) in two hours. <s> The rainfall caused some flooding, with some overflown streams flooding some streets. <s> Moderate winds were reported along its path, which peaked at 60 mph (96 km/h) in southern Nova Scotia. <s> The winds downed some tree limbs and led to some power outages. <s> Overall damage was minor.

outflow. <s> Shortly after becoming a tropical storm, the low-level circulation of Beryl became exposed with limited deep convection, though deep convection re-developed the following morning. <s> Outflow continued to improve, and with warm sea surface temperatures Beryl slowly strengthened further to reach peak winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) early on July 20 while located about 120 miles (190 km) east of Nags Head, North Carolina. <s> Beryl maintained peak winds for about 18 hours as it paralleled the Mid-Atlantic and New Jersey coasts, during which an eye-like feature developed in the center of the convection. <s> Late on July 20, it began a slow weakening trend after passing over cooler waters. <s> Steering winds ahead of an approaching mid-level trough caused Beryl to speed up northeastward, and early on July 21 the center of the storm crossed the island of Nantucket. <s> The convection diminished as it moved through progressively colder waters, and shortly after 1200 UTC on July 21 Beryl became an extratropical cyclone a short distance east of Cape Cod. <s> Hours later, it made landfall in southwestern Nova Scotia, and on July 22 the extratropical remnants of Beryl merged with an approaching cold front over Newfoundland. <s> Forecasters originally predicted Beryl to brush the Carolinas; as such, a tropical storm watch was issued for the eastern coast of North Carolina from Cape Lookout northward to Currituck Beach Lighthouse. <s> When a more northeastward track became apparent, a tropical storm watch was issued about 33 hours before moving ashore from Woods Hole to Plymouth, Massachusetts, including Cape Cod, Nantucket, and Martha's Vineyard. <s> About 22 hours before landfall, the National Hurricane Center replaced the watch with a tropical storm warning for the same area, and also issued a tropical storm watch from Woods Hole, Massachusetts westward to New Haven, Connecticut and for the eastern portion of Long Island from east of Fire Island to Port Jefferson. <s> Expecting for the storm, the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency was activated as a trial run for the hurricane season. <s> Local Red Cross chapters were opened, as well, with two volunteer teams placed on standby to assist. <s> Across southeastern Massachusetts, police departments maintained extra staff in preparation for any potential problems from the storm. <s> Many fishermen secured their boats, while some business owners boarded up windows to prevent storm damage. <s> Several days prior to the passage of Beryl through Atlantic Canada, the Canadian Hurricane Centre issued gale warnings for the coastal waters off of Nova Scotia and Newfoundland. <s> In anticipation of heavy rainfall, the agency also issued heavy rainfall warnings for western Nova Scotia, including Halifax. <s> The storm caused high waves along the East Coast of the United States, with 19 foot seas (5.97 m) in the open ocean. <s> Waves along the southern coast of Nantucket reached 10 feet in height as the storm approached the island, resulting in four people being rescued by lifeguards from rip currents. <s> High surf was also reported along the southern coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island. <s> Beryl also produced a storm surge of 0.9 feet on Nantucket. <s> Winds across southeastern Massachusetts were fairly light, with no sustained tropical storm force winds and wind gusts peaking at 44 mph; unofficially gusts reached 51 mph. <s> Beryl dropped moderate precipitation just offshore, though the maximum precipitation total in the United States was only 0.97 inches (24.6 mm) on Nantucket. <s> Rainfall along southeastern Massachusetts reached 0.33 inches at Chatham. <s> The only reported damage were some downed telephone poles and fallen tree branches. <s> Overall impact was minor; there were no reported power outages, deaths, injuries, or maritime emergencies in association with the storm. <s> The remnants of Beryl dropped moderate precipitation in Atlantic Canada, officially peaking at 2.8 inches (71 mm) in Scotts Bay, Nova Scotia with an unofficially higher total of 3.5 inches (88 mm); in some locations 1 inch of rain fell in an hour. <s> Additionally, a station in Fredericton, New Brunswick reported 1.77 inches (45 mm) in 2 hours. <s> The rainfall caused some flooding, with some overflown streams flooding some streets. <s> Moderate winds were reported along its path, which peaked at 60 mph (96 km/h) in southern Nova Scotia. <s> The winds downed some tree limbs and led to some power outages. <s> Overall damage was minor.

title: Vahan Hovhannisyan
complex: Vahan Hovhannisyan ( ; August 16, 1956 – December 28, 2014) was an Armenian politician of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF). <s> He was Vice-President of the National Assembly of Armenia from 2007 to 2008 and was a candidate in the February 2008 presidential election. <s> A 2008 leaked confidential document by the US State Department described him as "clearly the most likeable Dashnak by public persona."
simple: Vahan Hovhannisyan (; August 16, 1956 – December 28, 2014) was an Armenian politician of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF). <s> He was Vice-President of the National Assembly of Armenia from 2007 to 2008 and was a candidate in the February 2008 presidential election.

title: Ankarsrum
complex: Ankarsrum is a locality situated in Västervik Municipality, Kalmar County, Sweden with 1,254 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Ankarsrum is a locality in Västervik Municipality in Kalmar County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 1,254 people lived there.

title: Subaru Telescope
complex: Subaru Telescope (すばる望遠鏡 , Subaru Bōenkyō ) is the 8.2 m flagship telescope of the National Astronomical Observatory of Japan, located at the Mauna Kea Observatory on Hawaii. <s> It is named after the open star cluster known in English as the Pleiades. <s> It had the largest monolithic primary mirror in the world from its commission until 2005. <s> Construction of the Subaru telescope began in April 1991, and later that year, a public contest gave the telescope its official name, "Subaru Telescope." <s> Construction was completed in 1998, and the first scientific images were taken in January 1999. <s> In September 1999, Princess Sayako of Japan dedicated the telescope. <s> Subaru is one of the few state-of-the-art telescopes to have been used with the naked eye. <s> For the dedication, an eyepiece was constructed so that Princess Sayako could look through it directly. <s> It was enjoyed by the staff for a few nights until it was replaced with the much more sensitive working instruments.
simple: Subaru Telescope (すばる望遠鏡, Subaru Bōenkyō) is the large telescope of the National Astronomical Observatory of Japan at the Mauna Kea Observatory on the island of Hawaii. <s> The telescope is named after the Pleiades star cluster. <s> From 1999 to 2005, its main mirror was the largest in the world. <s> In September 1999, former-Princess Sayako of Japan dedicated the telescope. <s> For the dedication, an eyepiece was constructed so that Princess Sayako could look through it directly.

title: Elena Verdugo
complex: Elena Angela Verdugo (April 20, 1925 – May 30, 2017) was an American actress who began in films at the age of five in "Cavalier of the West" (1931). <s> Her career in radio, television, and film spanned six decades. <s> Verdugo had a starring role as a singer in 1957's "Panama Sal", a musical comedy film. <s> Verdugo is perhaps best known today for her role as office assistant/nurse Consuelo Lopez in the ABC series "Marcus Welby, M.D.," starring with Robert Young in the title role and James Brolin as the medical associate. <s> The series aired from 1969 to 1976. <s> In 1971 and 1972, Verdugo was nominated for Emmy Awards in the Outstanding Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role in Drama category. <s> Both nominations were for her performances on "Marcus Welby, M.D." <s> She has a star at 1709 Vine Street in the Television section of the Hollywood Walk of Fame. <s> It was dedicated on February 8, 1960. <s> Verdugo and Marion had one son, Richard Marion (1949–1999), who became an actor/director. <s> Her second husband was Charles "Rosy" Rosewall, M.D., a psychiatrist, who died in 2012. <s> Verdugo died on May 30, 2017 in Los Angeles at the age of 92.
simple: Elena Angela Verdugo (April 20, 1925 – May 30, 2017) was an American actress. <s> She began in movies at the age of five in "Cavalier of the West" (1931). <s> Her career in radio, television, and movie lasted from 1931 through 1985. <s> She had a starring role as a singer in 1957 musical comedy "Panama Sal". <s> Verdugo was known for her role as Nurse Consuelo Lopez in the ABC series "Marcus Welby, M.D.", which ran from 1969 to 1976. <s> In 1971-72, Verdugo was nominated for Emmy Awards in the Outstanding Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role in Drama category. <s> Both nominations were for her performances on "Marcus Welby, M.D." <s> Verdugo has a star at 1709 Vine Street in the Television section of the Hollywood Walk of Fame. <s> It was dedicated on February 8, 1960. <s> Then, she married Charles R. Rosewall from 1972 until his death in 2012. <s> Verdugo died on May 30, 2017 in Los Angeles, California from natural causes at the age of 92.

title: Pentti Lund
complex: Pentti Alexander Lund (December 6, 1925 – April 16, 2013) was a Finnish Canadian professional ice hockey right winger who played for the Boston Bruins and New York Rangers in the National Hockey League. <s> Lund was often credited as being the first Finnish player in the National Hockey League. <s> (Albert Pudas, however, played 4 games with the Toronto Maple Leafs in 1926-1927). <s> Lund moved to Canada from Finland at the age of six. <s> He began his junior career with the local Port Arthur teams in the Thunder Bay Junior A Hockey League from 1942 to 1945.
simple: Pentti Alexander Lund (born December 6, 1925 – April 16, 2013) was a Finnish-Canadian professional ice hockey right winger who played for the Boston Bruins and New York Rangers in the National Hockey League. <s> Lund is often said to have been the first Finnish player in the National Hockey League. <s> (Albert Pudas, however, played 4 games with the Toronto Maple Leafs in 1926-1927). <s> Lund moved to Canada from Finland at the age of six.

title: Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game
complex: Trading Card Game, known as the "Yu-Gi-Oh!" <s> Official Card Game (遊☆戯☆王オフィシャルカードゲーム , Yū-Gi-Ō Ofisharu Kādo Gēmu ) in Asia, is a Japanese collectible card game developed and published by Konami. <s> It is based on the fictional game of Duel Monsters created by manga artist Kazuki Takahashi, which is the main plot device during the majority of the manga franchise, "Yu-Gi-Oh!", <s> , and its various anime adaptations and spinoff series. <s> The trading card game was launched by "Konami" in 1999 in Japan and March 2002 in North America. <s> It was named the top selling trading card game in the world by Guinness World Records on July 7, 2009, having sold over 22 billion cards worldwide. <s> As of March 31, 2011, Konami Digital Entertainment Co., Ltd. <s> Japan sold cards globally since 1999. <s> In the trading card game, players draw cards from their respective decks and take turns playing cards onto "the field." <s> Each player uses a deck containing forty to sixty cards, and an optional "Extra Deck" of up to fifteen cards. <s> There is also an optional fifteen card side deck, which allows players to swap cards from their main deck and/or extra deck between games. <s> Players are restricted to three of each card per deck and must follow the Forbidden/Limited card list, which restricts selected cards by Konami to be limited to two, one, or zero. <s> Each player starts with 8,000 "Life Points", with the main aim of the game to use monster attacks and spells to reduce the opponent's Life Points. <s> Gameplay revolves around three types of cards; Monster, Spell, and Trap. <s> Monster cards are summoned by each player to attack the opposing player's monsters or life points or defend against their attacks.
simple: Trading Card Game is a Japanese card game developed and published by Konami. <s> It is based on the fictional game of "Duel Monsters", which is the main story for the anime series "Yu-Gi-Oh!". <s> In 2009 it broke the world record for most trading cards sold. <s> is a trading card game in which players draw cards from separate decks and take turns playing cards. <s> Each deck contains 40 to 60 cards. <s> Each player also has an optional "extra deck" of up to 15 cards that are used in certain situations. <s> There is also a 15-card "side deck", which allows players to modify their deck between games. <s> Players are only allowed three of the same card per deck and side deck. <s> Each player starts with a certain number of "Life Points". <s> The other two card types are "spells" and "traps".

title: Klaus Fichtel
complex: Klaus Fichtel (born 19 November 1944 in Castrop-Rauxel, Province of Westphalia) is a former German international footballer who played as a defender.
simple: Klaus Fichtel (born 19 November, 1944) is a former German football player.

title: Jeu de paume
complex: Jeu de paume ( , ] ; originally spelled ; ), nowadays known as real tennis, (US) court tennis or (in France) courte paume, is a ball-and-court game that originated in France. <s> It was an indoor precursor of tennis played without racquets, though these were eventually introduced. <s> It is a former Olympic sport, and has the oldest ongoing annual world championship in sport, first established over 250 years ago. <s> In the earliest versions of the game, the players hit the ball with their hands, as in palla, volleyball, or certain varieties of pelota. <s> "Jeu de paume", or "jeu de paulme" as it was formerly spelled, literally means "palm game". <s> In time, gloves replaced bare hands. <s> Even when paddle-like bats, and finally racquets, became standard equipment for the game by the late 17th century, the name did not change. <s> It became known as "tennis" in English "(see History of tennis)", and later "real tennis" after the derived game of lawn tennis became the more widely known sport. <s> The painter Jacques-Louis David's famous sketch, "le Serment du jeu de paume" ('the Tennis Court Oath') now hangs in the court of the Palace of Versailles. <s> It depicts a seminal moment of the French Revolution, when, on 20 June 1789, deputies of the Estates-General met at the court and vowed that they would not disband before the proclamation of a formal Constitution for France.
simple: Jeu de paume was originally a French game similar to lawn tennis, but played without racquets. <s> The players hit the ball with their hands as in volleyball. <s> "Jeu de paume" literally means: game of palm (of the hand). <s> After some time gloves replaced bare hands. <s> But even when bats, and finally racquets, became standard equipment for the game, the name did not change. <s> It became known as "tennis" in English (see History of tennis), and later "real tennis" after lawn tennis became more popular than the parent game. <s> Several works of art also bear this name, including the famous "serment du jeu de paume" ('the Tennis Court Oath') in the Palace of Versailles. <s> It depicts the formal announcement of the French revolution made in the Royal Tennis Court there on 20 June, 1789.

title: And Now for Something Completely Different
complex: And Now for Something Completely Different is a 1971 British sketch comedy film based on the television comedy series "Monty Python's Flying Circus" featuring sketches from the show's first two series. <s> The title was taken from a catchphrase used in the television show. <s> "And Now for Something Completely Different" is the Pythons' first feature film, composed of some well-known sketches from the first two series of the Flying Circus, including the "Dead Parrot" sketch, "The Lumberjack Song", "Upperclass Twits", "Hell's Grannies", the "Nudge Nudge" sketch and others.
simple: And Now for Something Completely Different is a British movie spin-off from the comedy television series "Monty Python's Flying Circus". <s> The title was used as a catchphrase in the series.

title: Stevie Wonder Live
complex: Stevie Wonder Live is a 1970 live album by American musician Stevie Wonder on the Tamla (Motown) label. <s> The second live collection by the singer-songwriter, it also was released during the crossroads of Wonder's career as he was about to make unprecedented moves to free himself of the Motown machine that had, at the time, not allowed him to showcase his singular talents.
simple: Stevie Wonder Live is a 1970 live album by Stevie Wonder on the Tamla label. <s> It is Wonder's second live album.

title: Kashmir Solidarity Day
complex: Kashmir Solidarity Day or Kashmir Day, is a national holiday in Pakistan and also observed by Kashmiri nationalists on 5 February each year. <s> It is in observance of Pakistan's support of and unity with the people of Indian-administered Kashmir, the nationalists' efforts to separate from India, and to pay homage to Kashmiris who have died in the conflict.
simple: Kashmir Solidarity Day has been celebrated on 5 February each year since 1990. <s> It is a national holiday in Pakistan.

title: Valentín Paz-Andrade
complex: Valentín Paz-Andrade (b. Pontevedra, 23 April 1898 – Vigo, 19 May 1987) was a Galician lawyer, writer, politician, journalist, poet, businessman and economist. <s> Galician Literature Day is dedicated to him in 2012.
simple: Valentín Paz-Andrade (b. Pontevedra, 23 April 1898-d. <s> Vigo, 19 May 1987) was a Galician lawyer, writer, politician, journalist, poet, businesspeople and economist. <s> Galician Literature Day is dedicated to him in 2012.

title: Sinethemba Jantjie
complex: Sinethemba Jantjie (15 February 1989 – 1 April 2019) was a South African professional footballer who played for Mbombela United and Free State Stars as a winger. <s> Jantjie came from Whittlesea. <s> Jantjie was described as a "late bloomer who rose to prominence in the 2015/16 season with Mbombela United when he helped take the club close to promotion to the Premier League". <s> During that season he scored 3 goals in 12 league games. <s> He then moved to Free State Stars for the 2016–17 season, scoring 8 goals in 63 league games during his 3 seasons with the club. <s> He was due to sign for Bidvest Wits ahead of the 2019–20 season. <s> Following his death, Bidvest Wits declared his contract "null and void". <s> Jantjie died in a road accident in Bethlehem on 1 April 2019, aged 30. <s> He was buried on 6 April 2019.
simple: Sinethemba Jantjie (15 February 1989 – 1 April 2019) was a South African professional footballer. <s> He played as a winger. <s> Jantjie was from Whittlesea, Eastern Cape. <s> He soon signed for PSL club Free State Stars. <s> In his three seasons with the Free State Stars, he scored eight goals in 63 league appearances. <s> At the time of his death, he was set to play for PSL side Bidvest Wits from the 2019–20 season onward. <s> On 1 April 2019, Jantjie died in a car crash in Bethlehem, Free State.

title: Saint-Martin-du-Var
complex: Saint-Martin-du-Var is a commune in the Alpes-Maritimes department in southeastern France.
simple: Saint-Martin-du-Var is a commune.

title: Metropolitan-Vickers
complex: Metropolitan-Vickers, Metrovick, or Metrovicks, was a British heavy electrical engineering company of the early-to-mid 20th century formerly known as British Westinghouse. <s> Highly diversified, they were particularly well known for their industrial electrical equipment such as generators, steam turbines, switchgear, transformers, electronics and railway traction equipment. <s> Metrovick holds a place in history as the builders of the first commercial transistor computer, the Metrovick 950, and the first British axial-flow jet engine, the Metropolitan-Vickers F.2. <s> Their factory in Trafford Park, Manchester, was for most of the 20th century one of the biggest and most important heavy engineering facilities in Britain and the world.
simple: Metropolitan-Vickers, Metrovick, or Metrovicks, was a British heavy electrical engineering company of the early-to-mid 20th century formerly known as British Westinghouse. <s> Highly diversified, they were particularly well known for their industrial electrical equipment such as generators, steam turbines, switchgear, transformers, electronics and railway traction equipment. <s> Metrovick holds a place in history as the builders of the first commercial transistor computer, the Metrovick 950, and the first British axial-flow jet engine, the Metrovick F.2. <s> Their factory in Trafford Park, Manchester, was for most of the 20th century one of the biggest and most important heavy engineering facilities in Britain and the world.

title: Vibble
complex: Vibble is a locality in Västerhejde on the Swedish island of Gotland. <s> Sweden with 1,300 inhabitants in 2010. <s> Situated 3 km south of Visby, it is sometimes regarded as a suburb to the town of Visby.
simple: Vibble is a locality in Gotland Municipality in Gotland County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 1,286 people lived there.

title: Beverly Byron
complex: Beverly Barton Butcher Byron (born July 27, 1932), is a former American politician and member of the Democratic Party who served as the U.S. Congresswoman representing the 6th congressional district of Maryland from January 3, 1979, to January 3, 1993. <s> Byron was born in Baltimore, Maryland. <s> She attended the National Cathedral School for Girls in Washington, D.C. Byron earned a two-year degree from Hood College in Frederick, Maryland, and after graduation she became involved in several nonprofit groups and in fundraising for the Democratic Party.
simple: Beverly Barton Butcher Byron (born July 27, 1932) is an American politician. <s> Byron is a member of the Democratic Party. <s> She was the U.S. Representative representing the 6th congressional district of Maryland from January 3, 1979, to January 3, 1993. <s> She was born in Baltimore, Maryland. <s> Byron studied at Hood College in Frederick, Maryland.

title: Sadaharu Oh
complex: Sadaharu Oh (Japanese: , "Ō Sadaharu"; born May 20, 1940), also known as Wang Chen-chih , is a retired Chinese baseball player and manager of Chinese-Japanese descent who played 22 seasons for the Yomiuri Giants in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB) from 1959 to 1980. <s> Oh holds the world lifetime home run record, having hit 868 home runs during his professional career. <s> He established many NPB batting records, including runs batted in (RBIs) (2,170), slugging percentage (.634), bases on balls (2,390), and on-base plus slugging percentage (OPS) (1.080). <s> In 1977, Oh became the first recipient of the People's Honour Award. <s> He was inducted into the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame in 1994. <s> Oh played his entire professional career with the Giants and was their manager from 1984 to 1988. <s> He also managed the Fukuoka Daiei/Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks from 1995 to 2008. <s> He was the manager of the Japanese national team in the inaugural World Baseball Classic. <s> The Japanese team defeated the Cuban national team for the championship. <s> He is currently the chairman of the Hawks. <s> Oh was born in Sumida, Tokyo, the son of a Japanese mother and a Chinese father from Zhejiang. <s> Although born in Japan, he had citizenship of Republic of China which he holds today, as his father left China when the ROC governed the mainland and chose to remain a Chinese citizen. <s> Sadaharu Oh retired in 1980 at age 40, having amassed 2,786 hits (third after Isao Harimoto (Jang Hoon) and Katsuya Nomura), 2,170 RBIs, a lifetime batting average of .301, and 868 home runs. <s> Sadaharu Oh was the assistant manager of the Yomiuri Giants between 1981 and 1983.
simple: Sadaharu Oh (王貞治, Oh Sadaharu, born May 20, 1940), also known as Wang Chenchih , is a Japanese-Taiwanese professional athlete. <s> From 1984 to 1988, he was the Giants' manager. <s> He managed the Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks from 1995 to 2008. <s> In 2006, he was the manager of the Japanese national team in the World Baseball Classic. <s> Oh was born in Tokyo. <s> He is the son of a Taiwanese father and a Japanese mother. <s> Although Oh has always lived in Japan, he has always been a citizen of the Republic of China (Taiwan). <s> Oh retired from playing in 1980.

title: Editors (band)
complex: Editors are an English rock band, formed in 2002 in Birmingham. <s> Previously known as Pilot, The Pride and Snowfield, the band currently consists of Tom Smith (lead vocals, guitar, piano), Russell Leetch (bass guitar, synthesiser, backing vocals), Ed Lay (drums, percussion, backing vocals), Justin Lockey (lead guitar), and Elliott Williams (keys, synthesisers, guitars, and backing vocals). <s> Editors have so far released two platinum studio albums, and six in total, with several million combined sales. <s> Their debut album "The Back Room" was released in 2005. <s> It contained the hits "Munich" and "Blood" and the following year received a Mercury Prize nomination. <s> Their follow-up album "An End Has a Start" went to number 1 in the UK Album Chart in June 2007 and earned the band a Brit Awards nomination for best British Band. <s> It also spawned another Top 10 hit single, "Smokers Outside the Hospital Doors". <s> The band's third album, "In This Light and on This Evening", was released in October 2009 and went straight to number 1 in the UK Album Chart. <s> The band released their fourth studio album, "The Weight of Your Love", in July 2013, followed by self-produced "In Dream" in October 2015. <s> In 2018, the band released their sixth album "Violence". <s> Alongside their critical acclaim and strong success in the charts, Editors have consistently enjoyed sold-out tours and numerous headlining festival slots. <s> Their brand of dark indie rock is commonly compared to the sound of bands such as Echo & the Bunnymen, Joy Division, Interpol, The Chameleons and U2. <s> The band was initially known as Pilot and played its first show under this name in 2002.
simple: Editors are an indie rock band from England. <s> They were formed in 2002. <s> They were first called Pilot, then The Pride and also Snowfield. <s> Editors have so far made two platinum albums, selling over two million copies around the world. <s> Their first album, "The Back Room", came out in 2005. <s> It had hit songs such as "Munich" and "Blood" and the following year was nominated for the Mercury Prize. <s> Their next album "An End Has a Start" went to number one in the UK Album Chart in June 2007. <s> It was nominated for a BRIT Award for best British Band. <s> The second album also had a Top 10 hit single, "Smokers Outside the Hospital Doors". <s> After success in the charts, sold out tours and playing as the main act at many festivals, The Mail on Sunday newspaper said the Editors were the second biggest British band of the decade, after Arctic Monkeys. <s> Their style of epic, sweeping, indie rock is often compared to the sound of bands such as Echo and the Bunnymen, Joy Division, Interpol and U2.

title: Frauen-Bundesliga
complex: The Frauen-Bundesliga (English: Women's Federal League), currently known as the FLYERALARM Frauen-Bundesliga due to sponsorship by FLYERALARM, is the top level of league competition for women's association football in Germany. <s> In 1990 the German Football Association (DFB) created the German Women's Bundesliga, based on the model of the men's Bundesliga.
simple: The Frauen-Bundesliga (English: Women Bundesliga) is the main women's association football league competition in Germany.

title: Manvieux
complex: Manvieux is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Manvieux is a commune.

title: Timeline of Christianity
complex: The purpose of this timeline is to give a detailed account of Christianity from the beginning of the current era (AD) to the present. <s> on dates indicate approximate dates. <s> The year one is the first year in the "Christian calendar" (there is no year zero), which is the calendar presently used (in unison with the Gregorian calendar) almost everywhere in the world. <s> Traditionally, this was held to be the year Jesus was born; however, most modern scholars argue for an earlier or later date, the most agreed upon being between 6 BC and 4 BC. <s> Jesus begins his ministry after his baptism by John and during the rule of Pilate, preaching: "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is near" . <s> While the historicity of the gospel accounts is questioned to some extent by some critical scholars and non-Christians, the traditional view states the following chronology for his ministry: Temptation, Sermon on the Mount, Appointment of the Twelve, alleged Miracles, Temple Money Changers, Last Supper, Arrest, Trial, Passion, Crucifixion on Nisan 14th ( , , Gospel of Peter) or Nisan 15th (Synoptic Gospels), entombment by Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus, professed Resurrection by God and claimed Resurrection appearances of Jesus to Mary Magdalene and other women , Simon Peter , and others, , Great Commission, Ascension, Second Coming Prophecy to fulfill the rest of Messianic prophecy such as the Resurrection of the dead, the Last Judgment, and establishment of the Kingdom of God and the Messianic Age. <s> Shortly after the death and resurrection of Jesus (Nisan 14 or 15), the Jerusalem church is founded as the first Christian church with about 120 Jews and Jewish Proselytes , followed by Pentecost (Sivan 6), the Ananias and Sapphira incident, Pharisee Gamaliel's defense of the Apostles , the stoning of Saint Stephen (see also Persecution of Christians) and the subsequent dispersion of the Apostles ( , also ) which leads to the baptism of Simon Magus in Samaria , and also an Ethiopian eunuch . <s> Paul's "Road to Damascus" conversion to "Apostle to the Gentiles" is first recorded in , cf. . <s> Peter baptizes the Roman Centurion Cornelius, who is traditionally considered the first Gentile convert to Christianity . <s> The Antioch church is founded, it was there that the term Christian was first used . <s> Constantine called the First Council of Nicaea in 325 to unify Christology, also called the first great Christian council by Jerome, the first ecumenical, decreed the Original Nicene Creed, but rejected by Nontrinitarians such as Arius, Theonas, Secundus of Ptolemais, Eusebius of Nicomedia, and Theognis of Nicaea who were excommunicated, also addressed Easter controversy and passed 20 Canon laws such as Canon VII which granted special recognition to Jerusalem.
simple: This timeline is to show the history of Christianity from the beginning to the present. <s> Question marks on dates mean that dates are not exact. <s> The Gregorian calendar is now used almost everywhere in the world (except for calculating the holy days of other religions). <s> There is no year zero. <s> The exact date is not certain, but most agree that it was between 6 BC and 4 BC. <s> Jesus began his ministry after his baptism by John and during the rule of Pilate, preaching: "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is near" (Matt 4:12–17). <s> While the historicity of the gospel accounts is questioned to some extent by most critical scholars and non-Christians, the traditional view states the following chronology for his ministry: Temptation, Sermon on the Mount, Appointment of the Twelve, Miracles, Temple Money Changers, Last Supper, Arrest, Trial, Passion, Crucifixion on Good Friday (Mark 15:42, John 19:42), Nisan 14th (John 19:14, Mark 14:2, Gospel of Peter) or Nisan 15th (Synoptic Gospels), (7 Apr 30, 3 Apr 33, 30 Mar 36, possible Fri-14-Nisan dates – Meier), entombment by Pharisees Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus of the Sanhedrin, Resurrection by God on Easter Sunday, appearances to Paul of Tarsus (1Cor 15:3–9), Simon Peter (Luke 24:34), Mary Magdalene (Mark 16:9, John 20:10–18), and others, Great Commission, Ascension, Second Coming Prophecy to fulfill the rest of Messianic prophecy such as the Resurrection of the dead, the Last Judgment, and establishment of the Kingdom of God and the Messianic Age. <s> Shortly after the Crucifixion of Jesus (Nisan 14 or 15), the Jerusalem church was founded as the first Christian church with about 120 Jews and Jewish proselytes (Acts 1:15), followed by Pentecost, the Ananias and Sapphira incident, Pharisee Gamaliel's defense of the Apostles (5:34–39), the stoning of Saint Stephen (see also Persecution of Christians) and the subsequent dispersal of the church (7:54–8:8) which led to the baptism of Simon Magus in Samaria (8:9–24), and also an Ethiopian eunuch (8:26–40). <s> Paul's conversion to "Apostle to the Gentiles" is first recorded in (9:13–16, cf. Gal 1:11–24). <s> Peter baptized the Centurion Cornelius, who is traditionally considered the first Gentile convert to Christianity (10). <s> The Antioch church was founded. <s> It was there that the term Christian was first used (11:26). <s> Constantine called the First Council of Nicaea in 325 to unify Christology, also called the first great Christian council by Jerome, the first ecumenical, decreed the Original Nicene Creed, but rejected by Nontrinitarianism such as Arius, Theonas, Secundus, Eusebius of Nicomedia, and Theognis who were excommunicated, also addressed Easter controversy and passed 20 Canon laws.

title: Balkassar
complex: Balkassar is a village and union council, an administrative subdivision, of Chakwal District in the Punjab Province of Pakistan It is part of Chakwal Tehsil. <s> The village gets its name from the Kassar tribe, who also make up the bulk of the population.
simple: Balkassar is a village and Union Council, an administrative subdivision, of Chakwal District in the Punjab Province of Pakistan, it is part of Choa Saidan Shah Tehsil and is located at 32°55'60N 72°39'0E.

title: North Gyeongsang Province
complex: North Gyeongsang Province ( ; RR: Gyeongsangbuk-do; ] ), also known as Gyeongbuk (] ), is a province in eastern South Korea. <s> The province was formed in 1896 from the northern half of the former Gyeongsang province, and remained a province of Korea until the country's division in 1945, then became part of South Korea. <s> Daegu was the capital of North Gyeongsang Province between 1896 and 1981, but has not been a part of the province since 1981. <s> In 2016, the provincial capital moved from Daegu to Andong. <s> Gyeongsangbuk-do is divided into 10 cities ("si") and 13 counties ("gun"). <s> The names below are given in English, hangul, and hanja.
simple: North Gyeongsang Province is a province in South Korea. <s> Gyeongsang Province divided into North Gyeongsang and South Gyeongsang in 1896. <s> Later, in 1896, the districts were abolished, and today's North Gyeongsang and South Gyeongsang were formed. <s> Daegu was the capital from 1896 to 1981, but Daegu left the province in 1981. <s> The capital changed to Andong in 2016. <s> Currently, North Gyeongsang has 10 cities ("si") and 13 counties ("gun").

title: Rusty Anderson
complex: Rusty Anderson is an American guitarist and singer-songwriter. <s> He is known as the lead guitarist for Sir Paul McCartney, though he has worked with an extensive list of artists in addition to his own solo career. <s> Now officially a band, Rusty Anderson Afternoon released their first single, “Effortless”, on April 30, 2013. <s> "Effortless" made it to #1 at Sirius Radio's “20 on 20".
simple: Rusty Anderson (born January 20, 1959) is an American guitarist, singer and songwriter from La Habra, California. <s> He has played lead guitar for Paul McCartney since 2001. <s> He also has a band called Rusty Anderson Afternoon whose first single "Effortless" hit Number One on American radio and whose first full-length record "RAA" debuted in the Top Ten Alt Chart on iTunes.

title: Minos Kyriakou
complex: Minos Xenophon "Minas" Kyriakou ( , ] ; 31 May 1942 – 2 July 2017) was a Greek media and shipping magnate and businessman. <s> He was the president of the Hellenic Olympic Committee and was the President of the International Olympic Academy (IOA, 2004-2009). <s> He was elected to the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) council in August 2003. <s> Kyriakou died of a heart attack on 2 July 2017, at the Athens Medical Center. <s> He was twice divorced and was survived by his three children from his first marriage.
simple: Minos Xenophon "Minas" Kyriakou (; 31 May 1942 – 2 July 2017) was a Greek media and shipping magnate and businessman. <s> He was the president of the Greek Olympic Committee and was the President of the International Olympic Academy (IOA, 2004-2009). <s> He was elected to the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) council in August 2003. <s> Kyriakou died of a heart attack on 2 July 2017 at a hospital in Athens, aged 75.

title: Châtellerault
complex: Châtellerault (] ) is a commune in the Vienne department in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region in France. <s> It is located in the northeast of the former province Poitou, and the residents are called "Châtelleraudais".
simple: Châtellerault is a "commune" in the Vienne department in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region in western France. <s> Châtellerault is in the centre of the Vienne department.

title: Saint-Trinit
complex: Saint-Trinit is a commune in the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region in southeastern France.
simple: Saint-Trinit is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur in the Vaucluse department in the south of France.

title: Micro black hole
