character of the work is lighter than other multiple-movement works for large ensemble (for example the symphony), with tunefulness being more important than thematic development or dramatic intensity. <s> Most of these works are from Italy, Germany, Austria and Bohemia. <s> Among the most famous examples of the serenade from the 18th century are those by Mozart, whose serenades typically comprise between four and ten movements. <s> His serenades were often purely instrumental pieces, written for special occasions such as those commissioned for wedding ceremonies. <s> Famous serenades by Mozart include the "Haffner" Serenade, the "Serenata notturna", and one of his most famous works, "Eine Kleine Nachtmusik." <s> The last two of these, had they been written earlier in the century, would have been atypical for using only string instruments.
simple: In music, a serenade (or sometimes serenata) is a song or piece of music which is sung or played in someone’s honour. <s> The word comes from the Latin "serenare" meaning: "to make calm". <s> In the Baroque period a serenade was a type of cantata performed outdoors, in the evening, with singers and various musical instrumentas. <s> Composers who wrote this kind of serenade include Alessandro Stradella and Alessandro Scarlatti. <s> They are similar to a symphony but lighter in character. <s> Other Romantic composers often wrote short instrumental works which they called “serenades”. <s> Mozart wrote several serenades of this type, e.g. his famous "Eine kleine Nachtmusik".

title: Salamandastron
complex: Salamandastron is a fantasy novel by Brian Jacques, published in 1992. <s> It is the fifth book published and eighth chronologically in the "Redwall" series. <s> Ferahgo the Assassin, a terrible weasel warlord, and his son Klitch lead their army of Corpsemakers to Salamandastron, to take over from the Badger Lord, Urthstripe the Strong. <s> Meanwhile, at Redwall Abbey, two stoats run off with the Sword of Martin the Warrior after accidentally killing Brother Hal with a bow and arrow left out from a carnival the night before, and young Samkim, a mischievous squirrel, and his partner Arula the molemaid set off to claim back the sword. <s> At the same time, Mara the badgermaid leaves Salamandastron with Pikkle Ffolger, her friend the gluttonous hare, only to be tricked by Feragho's son Klitch and his lackey, Goffa. <s> The book follows the tale of the Badger Lord Urthstripe the Strong and his battle against Ferahgo the Assassin.
simple: Salamandastron is a fantasy book, written by Brian Jacques in 1992. <s> It is the fifth book in the Redwall series, and has been translated into four different languages. <s> Salamandastron, the mountain ruled by Badger Lord Urthstripe the Strong, and guarded by forty hares of the Long Patrol, is under siege by the weasel Ferahgo the Assassin, his son Klitch, and his vermin army of "Corpsemakers". <s> Meanwhile, two stoats at Redwall Abbey accidentally kill a Brother of Redwall and then run away with the sword of Martin the Warrior. <s> Mara (Urthstripe's adopted daughter) and Pikkle Ffolger, her trusted hare friend, are fooled by Klitch and his lackey, and Mara and Pikkle leave Salamandastron.

title: Fontenay-le-Pesnel
complex: Fontenay-le-Pesnel is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Fontenay-le-Pesnel is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Avallon
complex: Avallon (] ) is a town (French: " ") in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in central-eastern France.
simple: The city of Avallon is in the southeastern part of the Yonne department.

title: Obdurodon tharalkooschild
complex: Obdurodon tharalkooschild is an extinct species of monotreme in the genus "Obdurodon". <s> It is known from a single tooth found at the Miocene-aged Two Tree Site fossil beds in Riversleigh in Queensland, Australia. <s> The type material, a single tooth, was discovered in 2012 by a team from the University of New South Wales including Mike Archer, Suzanne Hand, and Rebecca Pian. <s> The description, published in the same year, was the fourth species of the family Ornithorhynchidae to be described, the second from the Riversleigh site, and estimated to have been the largest. <s> The specific name was chosen in honour of an indigenous Australian creation story for the platypus, where a duck named Tharalkoo gives birth to a chimeric creature after being ravished by a rakali. <s> An ornithorhynchid-like monotreme with a bill resembling the modern aquatic forager, the platypus, but a much larger animal that was probably up to one metre long. <s> The species was estimated to have been present in the middle and upper Miocene (5–15 million years ago). <s> The wear patterns on the tooth are suggestive of crushing, perhaps by consuming hard-shelled animals such as turtles, rather than using a shearing action. <s> "Obdurodon tharalkooschild" is believed to have been carnivorous and estimated to be twice the size of the modern platypus at one metre long.
simple: Obdurodon tharalkooschild is an extinct species of platypus in the genus "Obdurodon". <s> Only one single tooth has been found. <s> This was at the Miocene fossil beds in Riversleigh in Queensland, Australia. <s> The tooth was discovered in 2012 by a team from the University of New South Wales including Mike Archer, Suzanne Hand, and Rebecca Pian. <s> Its name was chosen in honour of an indigenous Australian creation story for the platypus, where a duck named Tharalkoo gives birth to a strange and fantastic creature after being ravished by a water-rat. <s> The species lived during in the middle and upper Miocene about 5–15 million years ago. <s> Wear on the tooth shows that it probably crushed hard shells such as those of turtles. <s> Because of this, scientists believe that "O. tharalkooschild" was carnivorous. <s> They also believe that it was twice the size of the modern platypus at one metre long.

title: Fiat Automobiles
complex: Fiat Automobiles S.p.A. ( , ; originally FIAT, ) is an Italian automobile manufacturer, a subsidiary of FCA Italy S.p.A., which is part of Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (previously Fiat S.p.A.). <s> Fiat Automobiles was formed in January 2007 when Fiat reorganized its automobile business, and traces its history back to 1899 when the first Fiat automobile, the Fiat 4 HP, was produced. <s> Fiat Automobiles is the largest automobile manufacturer in Italy.
simple: Fiat is a car company in Italy. <s> It was founded in Turin in 1899.

title: Second Epistle to Timothy
complex: In the New Testament, the Second Epistle of Paul to Timothy, usually referred to simply as Second Timothy and often written 2 Timothy or II Timothy, is one of the three pastoral epistles traditionally attributed to Paul the Apostle. <s> The three epistles are called "pastoral" because they relate to the conduct of church leaders, thought of as pastors (literally shepherds).
simple: This book is believed to a letter from the Apostle Paul to Timothy.

title: Dihya
complex: Dihya or Kahina ( , or ) was a Berber warrior queen and a religious and military leader who led indigenous resistance to the Muslim conquest of the Maghreb, the region then known as Numidia. <s> She was born in the early 7th century and died around the end of the 7th century in modern-day Algeria.
simple: Dihya (Algerian Arabic: ', Berber: ', Dihya, or Damya), was a Berber queen and religious and military leader. <s> She was born in the early 7th century and died around the end of the 7th century in what is now Algeria.

title: Saint-Bois

title: Cashmere wool

title: Oedipina maritima

title: Metropolitan Borough of Wirral
complex: The Metropolitan Borough of Wirral is a metropolitan borough of Merseyside, in North West England. <s> It has a population of 321,238, and encompasses 60 sqmi of the northern part of the Wirral Peninsula. <s> Major settlements include Birkenhead, Wallasey, Bebington, Heswall, Hoylake and West Kirby. <s> The city of Liverpool over the Mersey, faces the northeastern side of Wirral. <s> Bordering is the River Mersey to the east, the Irish Sea to the north and the River Dee to the west; the borough of Cheshire West and Chester occupies the remainder of the Wirral Peninsula and borders the borough of Wirral to the south. <s> The borough of Wirral has greater proportions of rural areas than the Liverpool part of Merseyside. <s> This is a chart of trend of regional gross value added of Wirral at current basic prices published (pp. 240–253) by "Office for National Statistics" with figures in millions of British Pounds Sterling. <s> ^ includes hunting and forestry <s> ^ includes energy and construction <s> ^ includes financial intermediation services indirectly measured <s> ^ Components may not sum to totals due to rounding <s> In September 2006 a large scale development called Wirral Waters was unveiled by the company Peel Holdings, that if constructed as outlined may see the creation of up to 27,000 jobs.

title: Mutabar Tadjibayeva
complex: Mutabar Tadjibayeva ("Uzbek: Mo'tabar Tojiboyeva") is an independent journalist and human rights activist. <s> She is a founder of the International Human Rights Organization ‘’Fiery Hearts Club’’. <s> Tadjibayeva monitored human rights implementation and carried out journalist investigations. <s> She participated in investigative actions and judicial trials as a defense counsel and authorized representative in Uzbekistan. <s> In 2005 the international organization PeaceWomen Across the Globe under the Nobel Committee included Mutabar Tadjibayeva’s name to the list of "1000 women peace activists", thus making her the official nominee for the Nobel Peace Prize. <s> On May 15, 2008, when she was still in prison, Mutabar Tadjibayeva was awarded with the Martin Ennals Award. <s> The same day the bloggers who wrote about human rights announced a top 10 list of the women who had played the most significant role in human rights protection. <s> Mutabar Tadjibayeva was among them. <s> On July 2, 2008, Tadjibayeva was released. <s> The Martin Ennals Award Ceremony was held in Geneva on November 20, 2008. <s> For the 60th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the ‘’Fiery Hearts Club’’ was awarded with the French Republic's “Liberty, Equality, Fraternity” Prize. <s> On December 10, 2008, Mutabar Tadjibayeva was awarded with the same prize during the ceremony in Paris. <s> In March 2009, Tadjibayeva received the International Women of Courage Award established by the State Department of the USA. <s> Later she returned the award because of her own principles. <s> In August she became a member of the International Council of the Human Rights Found. <s> In 2011 Mutabar Tadjibayeva appeared in the list of the ten most influential women in Central Asia. <s> In 2011 she wrote a book ‘’Prisoner of Torture Island’’.
simple: Mutabar Tadjibayeva ("Uzbek: Mo'tabar Tojiboyeva") is a journalist and human rights activist from Uzbekistan. <s> In 2005, the international organization "Peace Women Across the Globe", part of the Nobel Committee, added Tadjibayeva’s name to the list of "1000 women peace activists". <s> In 2008, Tadjibayeva received the Martin Ennals Award. <s> When she received the award, she was still in prison. <s> Mutabar Tadjibayeva was on a top 10 list of women who worked for human rights. <s> Tadjibayeva was in jail from October 2005 to June 2008. <s> For the 60th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the Fiery Hearts Club received the "Liberty, Equality, Fraternity" Prize from France. <s> Mutabar Tadjibayeva accepted the prize in Paris. <s> In 2009 she received the International Women of Courage Award. <s> In March 2009, Tadjibayeva received the International Women of Courage Award from the U.S. State Department. <s> Later she returned the award. <s> In 2011, Mutabar Tadjibayeva was on a list of ten most influential women in Central Asia.

title: Näsijärvi

title: Darryl Drake
complex: Darryl Drake (December 11, 1956 – August 11, 2019) was an American football player and coach. <s> His career spanned four decades, including stints as the wide receivers coach of the Chicago Bears, Arizona Cardinals, and Pittsburgh Steelers of the National Football League (NFL). <s> Drake played wide receiver for Western Kentucky University from 1975 to 1978. <s> Drake played wide receiver for three professional teams, the Washington Redskins in 1979, the Ottawa Rough Riders in 1981, and the Cincinnati Bengals in 1983. <s> Drake and his wife, Sheila, had three daughters. <s> He died on August 11, 2019, at the age of 62. <s> The official cause of death is still to be determined.
simple: Darryl Drake (December 11, 1956 – August 11, 2019) was an American football player and coach. <s> His career lasted four decades, including stints as the wide receivers coach of the Chicago Bears, Arizona Cardinals, and Pittsburgh Steelers of the National Football League (NFL). <s> Drake played wide receiver for Western Kentucky University from 1975 to 1978. <s> Drake played for the Washington Redskins in 1979. <s> He later played for the Ottawa Rough Riders in 1981 and for the Cincinnati Bengals in 1983. <s> Drake was found dead on August 11, 2019 at his home in Latrobe, Pennsylvania at the age of 62.

title: Stellan Bojerud
complex: Stellan Bojerud (5 August 1944 – 19 July 2015) was a Swedish politician, representing the Sweden Democrats (SD). <s> He was a Lieutenant colonel, and had previously been a member of the Moderate Party and the Centre Party. <s> Bojerud was the 22nd candidate on the list of SD in the 2010 parliamentary election. <s> In 2010-2011 he was serving as a MP replacing Julia Kronlid during her absence for having a child. <s> Following the death of William Petzäll in 2012 (who had been elected to parliament on the SD list), Bojerud became a member of parliament. <s> He died at the age of 70 in 2015.

title: Upper Normandy
complex: Upper Normandy ( , ] ; ) is a former administrative region of France. <s> On 1 January 2016, Upper and Lower Normandy merged becoming one region called Normandy. <s> It was created in 1956 from two departments: Seine-Maritime and Eure, when Normandy was divided into Lower Normandy and Upper Normandy. <s> This division continued to provoke controversy, and many people continued to call for the two regions to be reunited.

title: Indigenous peoples of the Americas
complex: Indigenous peoples of the United States are commonly known as Native Americans or American Indians and Alaska Natives. <s> Application of the term "Indian" originated with Christopher Columbus, who, in his search for India, thought that he had arrived in the East Indies. <s> Eventually, those islands came to be known as the "West Indies", a name still used.
simple: Native Americans (also called Aboriginal Americans, American Indians, Amerindians or indigenous peoples of America) are the people and their descendants, who were in the Americas when Europeans arrived. <s> He was in the Caribbean but thought he was in the East Indies, so he called the people Indians.

title: Lady Byng Memorial Trophy
complex: The Lady Byng Memorial Trophy, formerly known as the Lady Byng Trophy, is presented each year to the National Hockey League "player adjudged to have exhibited the best type of sportsmanship and gentlemanly conduct combined with a high standard of playing ability". <s> The Lady Byng Memorial Trophy has been awarded 88 times to 53 different players since it was first awarded in 1925. <s> The original trophy was donated to the league by Lady Byng of Vimy, then–viceregal consort of Canada. <s> The voting is conducted at the end of the regular season by members of the Professional Hockey Writers Association, and each individual voter ranks their top five candidates on a 10-7-5-3-1 points system. <s> Three finalists are named and the trophy is awarded at the NHL Awards ceremony after the Stanley Cup Playoffs.
simple: The Lady Byng Memorial Trophy, originally known as the Lady Byng Trophy, is given each year to the National Hockey League "player adjudged to have exhibited the best type of sportsmanship and gentlemanly conduct combined with a high standard of playing ability". <s> The Lady Byng Memorial Trophy has been awarded 84 times to 50 different players since it was first awarded in 1925. <s> The voting is done at the end of the season by the members of the Professional Hockey Writers' Association.

title: Lake Morat

title: Wally Westlake
complex: Waldon Thomas Westlake (born November 8, 1920) is a former utility player in Major League Baseball who had a ten-year career from 1947 to 1956. <s> At age , Westlake is the oldest living former National League player and, following the death of Bobby Doerr on November 13, 2017, the oldest living former All-Star. <s> He is also the oldest living former player to play in a World Series. <s> Born in Gridley, California, Westlake played for the Pittsburgh Pirates, St. Louis Cardinals, Cincinnati Reds and Philadelphia Phillies of the National League, and the Cleveland Indians and Baltimore Orioles of the American League. <s> He primarily played as an outfielder, with some appearances as a third baseman.
simple: Waldon Thomas Westlake (born November 8, 1920) is an American utility baseball player. <s> He had a ten-year career from 1947 to 1956. <s> Westlake is the oldest living former National League player, and is also the oldest living member of the Cincinnati Reds, Philadelphia Phillies, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St. Louis Cardinals. <s> He was born in Gridley, California. <s> Westlake played for the Pittsburgh Pirates, St. Louis Cardinals, Cincinnati Reds and Philadelphia Phillies of the National League, and the Cleveland Indians and Baltimore Orioles of the American League.

title: Muppet Babies (1984 TV series)
complex: Jim Henson's Muppet Babies, commonly known by the shortened title Muppet Babies, is an American animated television series that aired from September 15, 1984 to November 2, 1991 on CBS. <s> The show portrays childhood versions of the Muppets living together in a nursery under the care of a human woman identified only as Nanny (the whereabouts of their parents are never addressed), who appears in almost every episode, but her face is never visible; only the babies' view of her pink skirt, purple sweater, and distinctive green and white striped socks is shown. <s> The idea of presenting the Muppets as children first appeared in a dream sequence in "The Muppets Take Manhattan" (1984), released two months before "Muppet Babies" debuted, in which Miss Piggy imagined what it would be like if she and Kermit the Frog had grown up together. <s> "Muppet Babies" was produced by Jim Henson Productions and Marvel Productions.
simple: Muppet Babies is an American children's animated series produced by The Jim Henson Company and Nick Jr. <s> The concept of presenting familiar Muppet characters as babies was introduced in a sequence of "The Muppets Take Manhattan".

title: Doğan Babacan
complex: Doğan Babacan (30 November 1929 – 18 May 2018) was a Turkish football referee. <s> He was the first Turkish referee to supervise a match in FIFA World Cup history. <s> Babacan was born in Istanbul. <s> He played football for Beşiktaş JK, Karşıyaka S.K., Kasımpaşa S.K. and Hacettepe. <s> His career as a referee began in 1955 and he was placed on FIFA's Referees List in 1968. <s> He is known for supervising the first round Group 1 match between West Germany and Chile in the 1974 FIFA World Cup. <s> In that match, Babacan sent off Chilean Carlos Caszely. <s> It was the first red card in World Cup history. <s> On 10 April 1974 he sent off three Atlético Madrid players in the first leg of the European Cup semi-final match against Celtic in Glasgow. <s> Later he was referee for the 1975 UEFA Super Cup final between FC Bayern Munich and FC Dynamo Kyiv. <s> He retired from international refereeing in 1978. <s> He died on 18 May 2018, aged 88.
simple: Doğan Babacan (30 November 1929 – 18 May 2018) was a Turkish football referee. <s> He was the first Turkish referee to supervise a match in FIFA World Cup history. <s> He was born in Istanbul. <s> Later he was referee for the 1975 UEFA Super Cup final between FC Bayern Munich and FC Dynamo Kyiv. <s> He retired from international refereeing in 1978. <s> He died on 18 May 2018, aged 88.

title: Years of Refusal
complex: Years of Refusal is the ninth studio album by English alternative rock singer Morrissey. <s> It was released on 16 February 2009 in the UK by record label Decca and on 17 February 2009 in the US by Lost Highway.
simple: Years of Refusal is the ninth solo album by Morrissey, the former lead singer of The Smiths. <s> The album, distributed by Decca, was released on February 16, 2009 in the United Kingdom and on February 17, 2009 in the United States.

title: Ingonish
complex: Ingonish is a Canadian rural community in northeastern Victoria County, Nova Scotia. <s> Located along the northeast coast of Cape Breton Island, Ingonish is situated on the Cabot Trail approximately 60 kilometres from the shire town of Baddeck. <s> Ingonish lies at the eastern entrance to Cape Breton Highlands National Park. <s> The regional economy is tied to the seasonal tourism and fishing industries. <s> The community is in the federal electoral district of Sydney—Victoria. <s> Ingonish was one of the first areas settled on Cape Breton Island, and is home to the "Keltic Lodge" resort, downhill skiing at Cape Smokey, and a public golf course, the Highlands Links.
simple: Ingonish is a Canadian rural community in northeastern Victoria County, Nova Scotia. <s> Ingonish is on the northeast coast of Cape Breton Island along the Cabot Trail. <s> It is about 60 km from the shire town of Baddeck. <s> Ingonish is located at the eastern entrance to Cape Breton Highlands National Park. <s> The regional economy is tied to the seasonal tourism and fishing industries. <s> The community is in the federal electoral district of Sydney—Victoria. <s> Ingonish was one of the first areas settled on Cape Breton Island.

title: Boki Milošević
complex: Božidar "Boki" Milošević ( ; 31 December 1931 – 15 April 2018) was a Serbian clarinetist. <s> Milošević was born in Prokuplje, Kingdom of Yugoslavia, now Serbia. <s> Božidar Milošević was clarinet teacher at the Josip Slavenski School of Music in Belgrade from 1960 to 1968. <s> Milošević died on 15 April 2018 in Belgrade, aged 86.
simple: Božidar "Boki" Milošević (31 December 1931 – 15 April 2018), a renowned Serbian and Yugoslav clarinetist. <s> He was born in Prokuplje to father Krsta, a farmer (1892–1968), and mother Vidosava, a housewife (1896–1971). <s> From 1960 to 1966 he was engaged in teaching, working as a professor of clarinet at the Music School "Slavenski" which was a part of the Music Academy in Belgrade. <s> Milošević died on 15 April 2018 in Belgrade at the age of 86.

title: Victor Găureanu
complex: Victor Dan Găureanu, better known as Dan Găureanu (15 November 1967 – 20 May 2017) was a Romanian fencer. <s> He competed in the sabre events at the 1992 and 2000 Summer Olympics. <s> He won the bronze medal at the 1999 World Fencing Championships after he was defeated by Wiradech Kothny, who eventually won the gold medal. <s> As part of the Romanian team he earned two bronze medals at the World Championships. <s> He died on 20 May 2017.
simple: Victor Dan Găureanu, better known as Dan Găureanu (15 November 1967 – 20 May 2017) was a Romanian fencer. <s> He competed in the sabre events at the 1992 and 2000 Summer Olympics. <s> He won the bronze medal at the 1999 World Fencing Championships after he was defeated by Wiradech Kothny, who eventually won the gold medal. <s> As part of the Romanian team he earned two bronze medals at the World Championships. <s> Găureanu died on 20 May 2017 in Bucharest from a suspected case of cardiac arrest at the age of 49.

title: 2018 FIFA World Cup Group D
complex: Group D of the 2018 FIFA World Cup took place from 16 to 26 June 2018. <s> The group consists of Argentina, Iceland, Croatia, and Nigeria. <s> The top two teams, Croatia and Argentina, advanced to the round of 16. <s> All times listed are local time. <s> The two teams had never met before. <s> The two teams had never met before.

title: Chesterfield, South Carolina
complex: Chesterfield is a town in Chesterfield County, South Carolina, United States. <s> The population was 1,472 at the 2010 census. <s> It is the county seat of Chesterfield County. <s> At the time of the 2010 census, Chesterfield was the least populous of all of South Carolina's county seats.
simple: Chesterfield is a town in Chesterfield County, South Carolina, United States. <s> The population was 1,472 at the 2010 census. <s> It is the county seat of Chesterfield County.

title: Australian Customs and Border Protection Service
complex: The Australian Customs and Border Protection Service was the Australian federal government agency responsible for managing the security and integrity of the Australian border. <s> It facilitated the movement of legitimate international travellers and goods, whilst protecting the safety, security and commercial interests of Australians. <s> Customs controlled the import and export of goods to and from Australia, in particular the control of prohibited or restricted items, and the interception of illegal and potentially harmful goods such as drugs, weapons and computer games. <s> Techniques used to target high-risk aircraft, vessels, cargo, postal items and travellers included using intelligence, computer-based profiling and analysis, detector dogs, Smartgate, container X-ray facilities, closed-circuit television (CCTV) monitoring and other means.
simple: The Australian Customs and Border Protection Service is the Australian Federal Government agency with the duty of protecting the Australian border, helping with the movement of legal international travellers and goods, and collecting border related duties and taxes. <s> This includes using intelligence, and computers, detector dogs, Smartgate, x-rays, Closed Circuit Television (CCTV) and other methods.

title: London, Brighton and South Coast Railway
complex: The London, Brighton and South Coast Railway (LB&SCR; known also as "the Brighton line", "the Brighton Railway" or "the Brighton") was a railway company in the United Kingdom from 1846 to 1922. <s> Its territory formed a rough triangle, with London at its apex, practically the whole coastline of Sussex as its base, and a large part of Surrey. <s> It was bounded on its western side by the London and South Western Railway (L&SWR), which provided an alternative route to Portsmouth. <s> On its eastern side the LB&SCR was bounded by the South Eastern Railway (SER)—later one component of the South Eastern and Chatham Railway (SE&CR)—which provided an alternative route to Bexhill, St Leonards-on-Sea, and Hastings. <s> The LB&SCR had the most direct routes from London to the south coast seaside resorts of Brighton, Eastbourne, Worthing, Littlehampton and Bognor Regis, and to the ports of Newhaven and Shoreham-by-Sea. <s> It served the inland towns/cities of Chichester, Horsham, East Grinstead and Lewes, and jointly served Croydon, Tunbridge Wells, Dorking and Guildford. <s> At the London end was a complicated suburban and outer-suburban network of lines emanating from London Bridge and Victoria, and shared interests in two cross-London lines. <s> The LB&SCR was formed by a merger of five companies in 1846, and merged with the L&SWR, the SE&CR and several minor railway companies in southern England under the Railways Act 1921 to form the Southern Railway from 1 January 1923. <s> The LB&SCR existed for 76 years until 31 December 1922, when it was wound up as a result of the Railways Act 1921 and merged with the London and South Western Railway and the South Eastern and Chatham Railway to form the Southern Railway.
simple: The London, Brighton and South Coast Railway (LBSCR was a railway company in England from 1846 to 1922. <s> Its territory formed a rough triangle, with London at its apex, most of the coastline of Sussex as its base, and a large part of Surrey. <s> The LBSCR had the most direct routes from London to the south coast seaside resorts of Brighton, Eastbourne, Worthing, Littlehampton and Bognor Regis, and to the ports of Newhaven and Shoreham-by-Sea. <s> It served the inland towns/cities of Chichester, Horsham, East Grinstead and Lewes, and jointly served Croydon, Tunbridge Wells, Dorking and Guildford. <s> At the London end was a complicated suburban and outer-suburban network of lines emanating from London Bridge and Victoria, and shared interests in two cross-London lines. <s> The LBSCR was formed by a merger of five companies in 1846. <s> On 1 January 1923, it became part of the Southern Railway under the Railways Act 1921.

title: Maracaibo
complex: Maracaibo ( ; ] ) is a city and the municipal seat of Maracaibo Municipality in northwestern Venezuela, on the western shore of the strait that connects Lake Maracaibo to the Gulf of Venezuela. <s> It is the second-largest city in Venezuela, after the national capital, Caracas, and the capital of the state of Zulia. <s> The population of the city is approximately 2,658,355 with the metropolitan area estimated at 5,278,448 as of 2010 . <s> Maracaibo is nicknamed "The Beloved Land of the Sun" (: "La Tierra del Sol Amada").
simple: Maracaibo is a city in northwestern Venezuela. <s> It is the second-largest city in the country and the capital of Zulia State. <s> The population of the city is approximately 1,495,200 with the metropolitan area at 2,108,404 as of 2010. <s> Maracaibo is nicknamed La Tierra del Sol Amada ("The Beloved Land of the Sun").

title: Colón, Panama
complex: Colón (] ) is a city and seaport in Panama, beside the Caribbean Sea, lying near the Atlantic entrance to the Panama Canal. <s> It is the capital of Panama's Colón Province and has traditionally been known as Panama's second city.
simple: Colón is a port city at the Caribbean Sea in Panama.

complex: Joseba Jon Larrinaga Perea (Aretxabaleta, 1968 – Aramaio, 7 May 2013) was a paralympic athlete from Spain who competed mainly in category T46 distance running events.
simple: Joseba Jon Larrinaga Perea (born June 5, 1968 in Guipúzcoa) is a track and field athlete from Spain.

title: Jizz in My Pants
complex: "Jizz in My Pants" is a SNL Digital Short which aired on "Saturday Night Live" on December 6, 2008 and YouTube on the same day. <s> It serves as the music video for the first single from the Lonely Island's debut album, "Incredibad". <s> The video stars the Lonely Island members Andy Samberg, Jorma Taccone and, briefly, Akiva Schaffer, and also features guest appearances by Justin Timberlake (who had also appeared in "Dick in a Box"), Molly Sims and Jamie-Lynn Sigler. <s> The video was published first on YouTube along with most of Lonely Island's works. <s> s of February 2019 , "Jizz in My Pants" has been watched over 171 million times, making it Lonely Island's third most popular video ever, coming after "I Just Had Sex" and "Jack Sparrow".
simple: "Jizz in My Pants" (also known as "J*** in My Pants") is a comedy sketch that was performed on YouTube and the television show "Saturday Night Live" on 6 December 2008. <s> The sketch was made into the music video for a song by The Lonely Island. <s> The video stars band members Andy Samberg, Jorma Taccone and Akiva Schaffer. <s> It also features Justin Timberlake, Molly Sims and Jamie-Lynn Sigler. <s> "Jizz in My Pants" has been viewed over 117 million times on YouTube, as of 2012.

title: St. Clairsville, Ohio
complex: St. Clairsville is a city in and the county seat of Belmont County, Ohio, United States. <s> Nicknamed "Paradise on the Hilltop", it is part of the Wheeling, WV-OH Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The population was 5,184 at the 2010 census.
simple: St. Clairsville is a city in and the county seat of Belmont County, Ohio, United States. <s> It is part of the Wheeling, WV-OH Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The population was 5,184 at the 2010 census.

title: Gangrel (wrestler)
complex: David William Heath (born February 16, 1969) is an American professional wrestler. <s> He is best known for his appearances in the World Wrestling Federation (WWF) from 1998 to 2001 and intermittently throughout the mid-2000s under the ring name Gangrel.
simple: David William Heath (born February 16, 1969) is an American professional wrestler. <s> He is best known for competing with the World Wrestling Federation/World Wrestling Entertainment under the ring name, Gangrel.

title: Richard F. Heck
complex: Richard Frederick Heck (August 15, 1931 – October 10, 2015) was an American chemist noted for the discovery and development of the Heck reaction, which uses palladium to catalyze organic chemical reactions that couple aryl halides with alkenes. <s> The analgesic naproxen is an example of a compound that is prepared industrially using the Heck reaction. <s> For his work in palladium-catalyzed coupling reactions and organic synthesis, Heck was awarded the 2010 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, shared with the Japanese chemists Ei-ichi Negishi and Akira Suzuki. <s> Heck died on October 9, 2015 in Manila in a public hospital. <s> His wife predeceased him by 2 years.
simple: Richard Fred Heck (August 15, 1931 – October 10, 2015) was an American chemist. <s> He was known for the discovery and development of the Heck reaction, which uses palladium to catalyze organic chemical reactions that couple aryl halides with alkenes. <s> Heck was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry on October 6, 2010, with the Japanese chemists Ei-ichi Negishi and Akira Suzuki, for their work in palladium-catalyzed coupling reactions in organic synthesis. <s> Heck died on October 10, 2015 in Manila in hospital, aged 84.

title: Cunt
complex: Cunt is a vulgar word for the vulva or vagina and is also used as a term of disparagement. <s> Reflecting different national usages, "cunt" is described as a "usually disparaging and obscene" term for a woman or an "offensive way to refer to a woman" in the United States by the Merriam-Webster dictionary, but "an unpleasant or stupid person" in the "Compact Oxford English Dictionary", and "a contemptible person" in the "Macquarie Dictionary" of Australian English.
simple: Cunt is an abusive word that is used against people as an insult. <s> It can also be slang for the vagina or vulva.

title: Electric blues
complex: Electric blues refers to any type of blues music distinguished by the use of electric amplification for musical instruments. <s> The guitar was the first instrument to be popularly amplified and used by early pioneers T-Bone Walker in the late 1930s and John Lee Hooker and Muddy Waters in the 1940s.
simple: The electric blues is a type of blues music made different by the amplification of the guitar, the bass guitar, and/or the harmonica.

title: Diene
complex: In organic chemistry a diene (diolefin or alkadiene) is a covalent compound that contains two double bonds, usually among carbon atoms. <s> They thus contain two alk"ene" units, with the standard prefix "di" of systematic nomenclature. <s> As a subunit of more complex molecules, dienes occur in naturally occurring and synthetic chemicals and are used in organic synthesis. <s> Conjugated dienes are widely used as monomers in the polymer industry. <s> Polyunsaturated fats are of interest to nutrition. <s> Compounds that contain more than two double bonds are called polyenes. <s> Polyenes and dienes share many properties. <s> An important reaction for conjugated dienes is the Diels–Alder reaction. <s> Many specialized dienes have been developed to exploit this reactivity for the synthesis of natural products (e.g., Danishefsky's diene).
simple: In organic chemistry, a diene or diolefin is a hydrocarbon that contains two carbon pi bonds. <s> Dienes occur occasionally in nature but are widely used in the polymer industry. <s> Compounds that contain more than two double bonds are called polyenes. <s> Polyenes and dienes, share many of their properties. <s> An important reaction for conjugated dienes is the Diels–Alder reaction. <s> Many specialized dienes have been developed to exploit this reactivity for the synthesis of natural products, e.g. Danishefsky’s diene.

title: Nipissing University
complex: Nipissing University is a primarily undergraduate public liberal arts university located in North Bay, Ontario, Canada. <s> The university overlooks Lake Nipissing.
simple: Nipissing University is a university in Ontario, Canada. <s> It is located in located in North Bay, Ontario.

title: Bucov
complex: Bucov (] ) is a commune in Prahova County, Romania, just east of Ploieşti, the county seat. <s> It is composed of five villages: Bighilin, Bucov, Chițorani, Pleașa and Valea Orlei.
simple: Bucov is a commune in the Prahova County, Romania.

title: Tony Madigan
complex: Antony Morgan "Tony" Madigan (4 February 1930 – 29 October 2017) was an Australian boxer and rugby player. <s> He competed in boxing at the 1952, 1956 and 1960 Olympics and finished in fifth, fifth and third place, respectively. <s> In 1960 Madigan lost his semi-final to Muhammad Ali. <s> He also won medals at three Commonwealth Games in the light-heavyweight division – a silver in 1954 and gold in 1958 and 1962. <s> Tony was the 2010 Inductee for the Australian National Boxing Hall of Fame Veterans category.
simple: Antony Morgan "Tony" Madigan (4 February 1930 – 29 October 2017) was an Australian boxer and rugby player. <s> He competed in boxing at the 1952, 1956 and 1960 Olympics and finished in fifth, fifth and third place. <s> In 1960 Madigan lost his semifinal to Muhammad Ali. <s> He also won medals at three Commonwealth Games in the light-heavyweight division – a silver in 1954 and gold in 1958 and 1962. <s> Madigan was the 2010 addition for the Australian National Boxing Hall of Fame Veterans category.

title: List of territorial entities where English is an official language
complex: The following is a list of territories where English is an official language, that is, a language used in citizen interactions with government officials. <s> s of 2019 , there are 55 sovereign states and 27 non-sovereign entities where English was an official language. <s> Many country subdivisions have declared English an official language at the local or regional. <s> The majority of states where English is an official language are former territories of the British Empire. <s> Notable exceptions include Rwanda, which was formerly a Belgian territory, Cameroon, where only part of national territory were under British mandate, and Liberia, the Philippines, the Federated States of Micronesia, the Marshall Islands, and Palau, which were American territories. <s> English is the sole official language of the Commonwealth of Nations and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations. <s> English is one of the official languages of the United Nations, the European Union, NAFTA, African Union, Organisation of Islamic Cooperation, Caribbean Community, Union of South American Nations and many other international organisations. <s> Although English is "de jure" not an official language at the national level in the United States, most states and territories within the United States have English as an official language. <s> Only Puerto Rico uses a language other than English as a primary working language. <s> In these country subdivisions, English has "de jure" official status, but English is not official in their respective countries at the national level.
simple: The following is a list of territories where English is an official language. <s> As of 2019, there are 55 sovereign states and 27 non-sovereign states where English was an official language. <s> Most countries where English is a prominent or official language are former colonies of the British Empire. <s> Notable exceptions include Rwanda, which was a former Belgian colony, and Eritrea, which was an Italian colony where the British Empire controlled it only in World War II and shortly after (1941–1952). <s> English is the sole official language of the Commonwealth of Nations and the Commonwealth Games. <s> English is one of the official languages of the United Nations, the European Union and the International Olympic Committee. <s> Although English is not classified as an official language in the United States many states and regions within the U.S. do have English as an official language. <s> In these country subdivisions, English has "de jure" official status, but English is not official in their relevant countries at the national level.

title: Herbert Kretzmer
complex: Herbert Kretzmer, OBE (born 5 October 1925) is an English journalist and lyricist. <s> He is best known as the lyricist for the English-language musical adaptation of "Les Misérables" as well as for his long-time collaboration writing the English-language lyrics to the songs of French songwriter Charles Aznavour.
simple: Herbert Kretzmer, OBE (born 5 October 1925) is a South African-born English journalist and lyricist. <s> He is best known as the lyricist for the English-language musical adaptation of "Les Misérables" as well as for his long-time writing works with the French singer Charles Aznavour.

title: Barbegal aqueduct and mill
complex: The Barbegal aqueduct and mill is a Roman watermill complex located on the territory of the commune of Fontvieille, near the town of Arles, in southern France. <s> The complex has been referred to as "the greatest known concentration of mechanical power in the ancient world" and the sixteen overshot wheels are considered the biggest ancient mill complex.
simple: The Barbegal aqueduct and mill is a Roman watermill complex. <s> It is on the territory of the commune of Fontvieille, near the town of Arles in southern France

title: Antonio Borrero
complex: Antonio María Vicente Narciso Borrero y Cortázar (29 October 1827 – 9 October 1911) was Vice President of Ecuador from 1863 to 1864, and President from 9 December 1875 to 18 December 1876. <s> Antonio Borrero was born in Cuenca, Ecuador and completed much of his education in his home town. <s> He received his law license in Quito.
simple: Antonio María Vicente Narciso Borrero y Cortázar (29 October 1827 – 9 October 1911) was Vice President of Ecuador from 1863 to 1864 and President from 9 December 1875 to 18 December 1876. <s> Borrero was born in Cuenca, Ecuador on 29 October 1827.

title: Cyclone Yasi
complex: Severe Tropical Cyclone Yasi was a powerful and destructive tropical cyclone that made landfall in northern Queensland, Australia in early 2011, causing major damage to the affected areas. <s> Originating as a tropical low near Fiji on 26 January, the system intensified to tropical cyclone status during the evening of 30 January. <s> Yasi deepened rapidly over the next 24 hours, and was classified as a Category 3 cyclone at about 5 PM AEST (07:00 UTC) on 31 January 2011. <s> Late on 1 February, the cyclone strengthened to a Category 4 system; then, early on 2 February, the cyclone intensified into a Category 5 Severe Tropical Cyclone. <s> The system had a well-defined eye and continued to track west-southwestward, maintaining a central pressure of 930 hPa (27 inHg) and a Dvorak intensity of T6.5 into the evening. <s> Tropical Cyclone Yasi was the biggest storm in Queensland's history, with more than 10,000 people moved from their homes. <s> The storm passed between the two big cities of Cairns and Townsville which only suffered minor damage. <s> Early estimates of damage put the cost at about AU$100 million. <s> It did not cause as much damage as government expected, as it missed major cities. <s> It did however destroy 30% of the houses in Tully. <s> At least 75% of the banana crop was destroyed, and damage to the sugar cane farms was expected to cost about AU$500 million. <s> Damage to power lines left 150,000 homes without electricity. <s> One death was due to carbon monoxide poisoning by exhaust of a portable generator being used in a confined space at Bambaroo near Ingham.
simple: Tropical Cyclone Yasi was a tropical cyclone that caused a lot of damage when it reached the Australian coast at about midnight on Wednesday 2 February 2011. <s> It was the biggest storm in Queensland's history, with more than 10,000 people moved from their homes. <s> The storm passed between the two big cities of Cairns and Townsville which only suffered minor damage. <s> Early estimates of damage put the cost at about AU$100 million. <s> Cyclone Yasi did not cause the damage that government expected as it missed major cities. <s> It did however destroy 30% of the houses in Tully. <s> At least 75% of the banana crop was destroyed, and damage to the sugar cane farms is expected to cost about AU$500 million. <s> Damage to power lines left 150,000 homes without electricity. <s> One person died when they were poisoned by fumes from a portable generator.

title: Nature Coast
complex: The Nature Coast is an informal, unofficial region of the U.S. state of Florida. <s> The broadest definition of the Nature Coast includes the eight counties that abut the Gulf of Mexico along the Big Bend Coast defined by geologists: from west to east, Wakulla, Jefferson, Taylor, Dixie, Levy, Citrus, Hernando, and Pasco counties. <s> (Note that the Big Bend Coast differs from the Big Bend region of Florida.) <s> This region of Florida is culturally partially southern, with the Deep South culture extending to Levy County. <s> The lower southern end (Pasco, Hernando, and Citrus County) are often considered part of the Tampa Bay Area. <s> The name "Nature Coast" was devised in 1991 as part of a marketing campaign to attract vacationers to the eight county area. <s> The name eventually began to be used locally, and describes the area formally known as the "Big Bend" of Florida. <s> Activities common in this area include hunting, fishing, boating, bird watching and nature hiking. <s> Snorkeling spots are found in the rivers along the Nature Coast. <s> Diving and manatee tours are available, predominantly in areas such as Crystal River, Homosassa and Homosassa Springs. <s> The Naturecoast is home to wildlife including deer, wild pigs, roseate spoonbills, alligators, raccoons, opossums, snakes, great blue herons, egrets, turtles and at least 19 endangered species. <s> There are also 50 golf courses in the area.
simple: The Nature Coast is a region of the U.S. state of Florida. <s> It is made up of the Big Bend (Florida) area of the western coast and includes Citrus, Dixie, Hernando, Jefferson County, Pasco County, Levy County, Taylor County, and Wakulla County counties. <s> This area of Florida is southern culturally, with the Deep South culture reaching to Levy County with the lower southern end (Pasco, Hernando, and sometimes Citrus county) often considered part of the Tampa Bay Metropolian Area. <s> Pasco County is sometimes considered part of the Sun Coast. <s> The history of the name "The Nature Coast" goes back to 1991 as part of a marketing campaign to attract vacationing people to the nine county area, the name "Nature Coast" caught on quickly and describes the area previously known as the "Big Bend" of Florida. <s> Common activities in this area are: hunting, fishing, boating, bird watching, nature hiking and the like. <s> Snorkeling spots are found in the rivers along the Nature Coast. <s> Also diving and Manatee tours, predominate in areas such as Crystal River, Homosassa and Homosassa Springs. <s> The Naturecoast is also home to wildlife such as: Deer, wild pigs, roseate spoonbills, alligators, raccoons, opossums, snakes, great blue herons, egrets, turtles and countless others, including at least 19 endangered species. <s> There are also 50 Golf Courses located within these counties

title: Latin American Canadians
complex: Latin American Canadians are Canadians who are descendants of people from countries of Latin America. <s> The majority of Latin American Canadians are multilingual, primarily speaking Spanish or Portuguese. <s> Most are fluent in one or both of Canada's two official languages, English and French. <s> Spanish, Portuguese and French are Romance languages and share some similarities in morphology and syntax. <s> The majority of Latin American Canadians are recent immigrants who arrived in the late 20th century from Mexico, Colombia, El Salvador, Peru, and Brazil, with smaller communities from Chile, Venezuela, Argentina, Cuba, Guatemala, and elsewhere, with nearly all Latin American countries represented. <s> Reasons for immigrating include Canada's better economic opportunities and politics or civil war and political repression in their native countries, as in the case of Cubans fleeing from the Fidel Castro revolution, Chileans escaping from Augusto Pinochet's rule, Salvadorans fleeing from the Salvadoran Civil War, Peruvians escaping from the Juan Velasco Alvarado dictatorship, Dominicans opposed to the regimes of Rafael Trujillo and Joaquin Balaguer, Mexicans escaping from the Mexican Drug War, Colombians from the violence in their country and Venezuelans opposed to the rule of the Socialist Unity Party.
simple: Latin American Canadians are Canadians with ancestry from Latin America. <s> Almost all Latino American Canadians are Christian. <s> Most Latin American Canadians speak two or more languages. <s> They usually speak Spanish and/or Portuguese along with English and French. <s> A lot of Latin American Canadians came to Canada in the late 20th century. <s> They came to Canada because it has better economic opportunities than their native country. <s> Some Cubans came to Canada to escape Fidel Castro's regime.

title: Lluís Homar
complex: Lluís Homar i Toboso (born 20 April 1957) is a Spanish actor and theater director from Barcelona. <s> He is best known for his roles in Pedro Almodóvar's "Bad Education" (2004) and "Broken Embraces" (2009), in Emilio Aragón's "Paper Birds" (2010), and for his portrayal of the robot Max in Kike Maíllo's film "Eva" (2011).
simple: Lluís Homar i Toboso (born April 20, 1957) is a Spanish actor and theater director from Barcelona. <s> He is known for his roles in "Bad Education" (2004) and "Broken Embraces" (2009).

title: Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu
complex: The Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu ("Cultural Association of the Leonese Language El Fueyu") was a Leonese language association whose main effort was promoting the knowledge of Leonese language and the defense of the rights of Leonese language speakers. <s> The Leonese language association El Fueyu was created in Llión in 2005, and developed some activity mainly in the province of Llión, and also in Zamora and Salamanca (Spain). <s> The last public activities of the "Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu" took place in 2011. <s> The "Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu" signed some agreements with Leonese public institutions for promoting some municipality courses on Leonese language, as the town councils of León, Mansilla de las Mulas, Valencia de Don Juan, La Bañeza and Zamora and the provincial government of León <s> The "Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu" first celebrated the Leonese Language Day on June 20, 2006. <s> After that year, the town council of León organized for some years that Day with the support of a few Leonese language associations, all of them dependent on the political association Conceyu Xoven. <s> The sixth and last Leonese Language Day was celebrated on June 18, 2011. <s> The "Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu" published, with the collaboration of the Asociación Berciana en Defensa de la Llingua Llïonesa El Toralín, the book Cuentos del Sil ("Tales of the Sil"), where several authors from or related to El Bierciu wrote short stories in Leonese language.
simple: The Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu ("Cultural Leonese Association of the Leonese Language El Fueyu") is a Leonese language who wants to promote the knowledge of Leonese language and the defense of the rights of Leonese language speakers. <s> Leonese language association El Fueyu born in Llión in 2005, an actually develops its activities mainly in the provinces of Llión, Zamora and Salamanca (Spain). <s> The "Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu" have signed many agreements with the most important leonese institutions for teaching Leonese language in official courses. <s> With the agreement signed between the Provincial Government of León and the "Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu" born the Leonese Language Day on June 20th, 2006. <s> After that year, the Leonese City Council organizes that Day with the support of the Leonese language associations. <s> Leonese language book Cuentos del Sil (Tales of the Sil) was published with the agreement between the Provincial Government of León and the Asociación Cultural de la Llingua Llïonesa El Fueyu. <s> In its edition collaborated the Asociación Berciana en Defensa de la Llingua Llïonesa El Toralín. <s> In this book several authors from or with rellations with El Bierzu wrote stories in Leonese language.

title: Johnny Pesky
complex: John Michael Pesky (born John Michael Paveskovich; February 27, 1919 – August 13, 2012), nicknamed "The Needle" and "Mr. Red Sox", was an American professional baseball player, manager and coach. <s> He was a shortstop and third baseman during a ten-year major league playing career, appearing in 1,270 games played in 1942 and from 1946 to 1954 for three teams. <s> He missed the 1943–45 seasons while serving in World War II.
simple: John Michael "Johnny" Pesky (born John Michael Paveskovich; February 27, 1919 – August 13, 2012), nicknamed "The Needle" and "Mr. Red Sox", was an American professional baseball player, manager and coach. <s> He was a shortstop and third baseman during a ten-year major league playing career, appearing in 1,270 games played in 1942 and from 1946 to 1954 for three different teams.

title: Sugarland
complex: Sugarland is an American country music duo consisting of singer-songwriters Jennifer Nettles (lead vocals) and Kristian Bush (vocals, guitar, mandolin). <s> Sugarland was founded in 2002 by Kristen Hall (vocals, guitar) with Bush and became a trio after hiring Jennifer Nettles.
simple: Sugarland is a country music duo from the Southern United States. <s> The lead singer is Jennifer Nettles.

title: Atlanta SC
complex: Atlanta SC is an American soccer team based in Atlanta, Georgia, United States, that plays in the National Independent Soccer Association, a Division III professional league. <s> Founded in 2007 as Atlanta FC, it became the reserve team of the Atlanta Silverbacks in 2011, and took over the name of the first team when it folded in 2016.
simple: Atlanta FC is an American football team based in Sandy Springs, Georgia, United States.

title: Albany, Pepin County, Wisconsin
complex: Albany is a town in Pepin County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> The population was 620 at the 2000 census. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 620 people, 180 households, and 156 families residing in the town.
simple: Albany is a town in Pepin County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> 620 people lived here as of the year 2000.

title: Porophyllum ruderale
complex: Porophyllum ruderale is an herbaceous annual plant whose leaves can be used for seasoning food. <s> The taste has been described as "somewhere between arugula, cilantro and rue." <s> The plant is commonly grown in Mexico and South America for use in salsas. <s> When fully grown, this plant grows to about 5 feet in height and 3 feet in diameter. <s> Having been used by many cultures, Porophyllum ruderale is known by many names, including Bolivian coriander, "quillquiña" (also spelled "quirquiña" or "quilquiña"), "yerba porosa", "killi", "pápalo", "tepegua", "mampuritu" and "pápaloquelite". <s> Despite the name "Bolivian coriander", this plant is not botanically related to Coriandrum sativum.
simple: Its leaves can be used for seasoning food. <s> The taste has been described as "somewhere between arugula, cilantro and rue." <s> The plant is commonly grown in Mexico and South America. <s> There it is used in salsas. <s> When fully grown, this plant grows to about 5 feet in height and 3 feet in diameter. <s> This herb is known by many names, including "quillquiña" (also spelled "quirquiña" or "quilquiña"), "killi", "papalo", "tepegua" and "pápaloquelite". <s> Also, even though the name is "Bolivian coriander", this plant is not botanically related to the coriander.

title: Temple of Athena Nike
complex: The Temple of Athena Nike (Greek: Ναός Αθηνάς Νίκης, "Naós Athinás Níkis") is a temple on the Acropolis of Athens, dedicated to the goddess Athena Nike. <s> Built around 420 BC, the temple is the earliest fully Ionic temple on the Acropolis. <s> It has a prominent position on a steep bastion at the south west corner of the Acropolis to the right of the entrance, the Propylaea.
simple: The Temple of Athena Nike is a temple on the Acropolis of Athens. <s> It was named after the Greek goddess, Athena Nike. <s> Built around 420BC, the temple is the earliest fully Ionic temple on the Acropolis.

title: Jacques Marquette
complex: Father Jacques Marquette S.J. (June 1, 1637 – May 18, 1675), sometimes known as Père Marquette or James Marquette, was a French-American Jesuit missionary who founded Michigan's first European settlement, Sault Ste. Marie, and later founded St. Ignace, Michigan. <s> In 1673, Father Marquette and Louis Jolliet were the first Europeans to explore and map the northern portion of the Mississippi River Valley.

title: Jean Sorel
complex: Jean Sorel (] ; born 25 September 1934) is a French actor. <s> Born Jean Bernard de Chieusses de Combaud de Roquebrune, he worked extensively in European cinema during the 1960s and 1970s with directors such as Luis Buñuel and Luchino Visconti. <s> However, since 1980 he has worked mostly in television. <s> He was married to Italian actress Anna Maria Ferrero from 1962 until her death in 2018.
