title: Barter
complex: In trade, barter (derived from "baretor") is a system of exchange where participants in a transaction directly exchange goods or services for other goods or services without using a medium of exchange, such as money. <s> Economists distinguish barter from gift economies in many ways; barter, for example, features immediate reciprocal exchange, not delayed in time.
simple: Barter is trading one thing for another without using money.

title: Angela Haynes
complex: Angela Haynes (born September 27, 1984 in Bellflower, California) is a former professional tennis player from the United States. <s> Her top WTA singles ranking is world No. 95 which she attained in August 2005. <s> Her brother Dontia Haynes, a former San Diego State University tennis player, ranked among the top 100 ranked collegiate tennis players in the United States, died 23 September 2005. <s> Angela's clothing is provided by Adidas. <s> Her racquets are provided by Babolat. <s> Angela's current racquet is believed to be the Babolat Pure Storm. <s> Angela likes to wear bandanas while playing. <s> Angela appears in Top Spin 2 which is for the Xbox 360, Game Boy Advance and Nintendo DS.
simple: Angela Haynes (born September 27, 1984 in Bellflower, California ) is a professional tennis player from the United States. <s> Haynes's top WTA singles ranking is World No. 95 which she got in August, 2005. <s> Haynes' brother, Dontia Haynes, who used to be a San Diego State University tennis player ranked among the top 100 ranked collegiate tennis players in the United States, died on 23 September 2005. <s> Angela's clothes are made by Adidas. <s> Her racquets are made by Babolat. <s> Angela's current racquet is believed to be the Babolat Pure Storm. <s> Angela likes to wear bandanas while playing. <s> Angela appears in "Top Spin 2" which is for the Xbox 360, Nintendo Game Boy, and Nintendo DS.

title: Jessie Hill
complex: Jessie Hill (December 9, 1932 – September 17, 1996) was an American R&B and Louisiana blues singer and songwriter, best remembered for the classic song "Ooh Poo Pah Doo". <s> Hill was born in New Orleans, Louisiana, United States. <s> By his teens he was playing drums in local bands, and in 1951 he formed his own group, the House Rockers. <s> After periods performing as drummer with Professor Longhair and then Huey "Piano" Smith, Hill formed a new version of the House Rockers in 1958, which enabled him to focus on singing with the band. <s> The origins of "Ooh Poo Pah Doo" were apparently created from a tune played by a local pianist, who was known only as Big Four. <s> Hill wrote the lyrics and melody, later expanding the work with an intro taken from Dave Bartholomew. <s> It was further honed on stage, before Hill recorded a demo that he shopped to local record labels, finally recording a session at Cosimo Matassa's studio produced by Allen Toussaint. <s> Upon its early 1960 release, "Ooh Poo Pah Doo" emerged as a favorite at Mardi Gras, selling 800,000 copies and reaching the Top 5 in the US "Billboard" R&B chart and a Top 30 slot in the "Billboard" Hot 100 pop chart. <s> There have been over 100 cover versions of "Ooh Poo Pah Doo" recorded and performed live over the years by other popular musicians. <s> Further recordings in New Orleans were less successful, and he moved to California to work with fellow New Orleans musicians including Harold Battiste and Mac Rebennack. <s> In this period, he wrote songs recorded by Ike and Tina Turner, Sonny and Cher, and Willie Nelson. <s> A 1972 solo album was unsuccessful, and he began to suffer financial difficulties exacerbated by a drinking problem. <s> These problems continued after his return to New Orleans in 1977, and several benefit gigs did little to revive his personal or professional fortunes. <s> Hill died of heart and renal failure in New Orleans in September 1996, at the age of 63. <s> He is buried in Holt Cemetery in New Orleans, in a pauper's grave for the poorest citizens of the city. <s> Two of his grandsons are James and Troy "Trombone Shorty" Andrews. <s> The pair performed "Ooh Poo Pah Doo" in Episode 7 of the HBO series "Treme". <s> A third grandson, Travis "Trumpet Black" Hill, was a rising New Orleans-based performer. <s> Trumpet Black died from an infection while on tour in Tokyo on May 4, 2015.
simple: Jessie Hill (December 9, 1932 – September 17, 1996) was an American R&B and Louisiana blues singer and songwriter. <s> He was best known for his popular call and response song "Ooh Poo Pah Doo". <s> Hill was born in New Orleans, Louisiana. <s> While still a teenager, he played drums in local bands. <s> In 1951, while still drumming, he started his own group, the House Rockers. <s> At first, Professor Longhair played piano, then later it was Huey "Piano" Smith. <s> Hill got different musicians for the House Rockers in 1958, and started singing. <s> The idea for the song "Ooh Poo Pah Doo" began from some music played by a local pianist, who had the nickname Big Four. <s> Hill wrote the lyrics and melody. <s> Hill also added an opening part written by Dave Bartholomew. <s> Hill recorded a demo that he shopped to local record labels, finally recording a session at Cosimo Matassa's studio. <s> The record was produced by Allen Toussaint. <s> When it was released in early 1960, it became popular, especially during Mardi Gras in New Orleans. <s> That year, the record sold 800,000 copies and reached the Top 5 in the US "Billboard" R&B chart. <s> It was in the Top 30 in the "Billboard" Hot 100 pop chart as well. <s> In addition to his original, there have been over 100 cover versions made by other artists. <s> There have been over 100 cover versions of "Ooh Poo Pah Doo" recorded and performed live over the years by other popular musicians. <s> Other records he made in New Orleans were not as successful. <s> He then moved to California and worked with other musicians from New Orleans, including Harold Battiste and Mac Rebennack. <s> Songs he wrote there were recorded by Ike Turner and Tina Turner, (singing together as "Ike & Tina Turner"), Sonny Bono and Cher (singing together as "Sonny & Cher") and Willie Nelson. <s> Stil living in California, a 1972 solo album was not successful at all. <s> He moved back to New Orleans in 1977. <s> Hill died of heart and renal failure in New Orleans in September 1996. <s> He is buried in Holt Cemetery in New Orleans, in a grave for the poorest citizens of the city. <s> Two of his grandsons are James and Troy "Trombone Shorty" Andrews. <s> The pair performed "Ooh Poo Pah Doo" in Episode 7 of the HBO series "Treme". <s> A third grandson, Travis "Trumpet Black" Hill, also performed as a trumpet player in New Orleans. <s> He died from an infection while on tour in Tokyo on May 4, 2015.

title: Volcanoes of Kamchatka
complex: The volcanoes of Kamchatka are a large group of volcanoes situated on the Kamchatka Peninsula, in eastern Russia. <s> The Kamchatka River and the surrounding central side valley are flanked by large volcanic belts containing around 160 volcanoes, 29 of them still active. <s> The peninsula has a high density of volcanoes and associated volcanic phenomena, with 29 active volcanoes being included in the six UNESCO World Heritage List sites in the Volcanoes of Kamchatka group, most of them on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> The highest volcano is Klyuchevskaya Sopka (4,750 m or 15,584 ft), the largest active volcano in the Northern Hemisphere, while the most striking is Kronotsky, whose perfect cone was said by celebrated volcanologists Robert and Barbara Decker to be a prime candidate for the world's most beautiful volcano. <s> Somewhat more accessible are the three volcanoes visible from Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky: Koryaksky, Avachinsky, and Kozelsky. <s> In the center of Kamchatka is Eurasia's world-famous Geyser Valley which was partly destroyed by a massive mudslide in June 2007. <s> Owing to the Kuril-Kamchatka Trench, deep-focus seismic events and tsunamis are fairly common. <s> A pair of megathrust earthquakes occurred off the coast on October 16, 1737, and on November 4, 1952, in the magnitude of ~9.3 and 8.2 respectively. <s> A chain of more shallow earthquakes were recorded as recently as April 2006.
simple: The volcanoes of Kamchatka are a large group of volcanoes situated on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> The volcanoes of Kamchatka are a large group of volcanoes on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> They are listed as the Volcanoes of Kamchatka group, and most of them are on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> The Kamchatka River and the surrounding central side valley are flanked by large volcanic belts containing around 160 volcanoes, 29 of them still active. <s> The Kamchatka River and the surrounding central side valley are flanked by large volcanic belts containing around 160 volcanoes, including the 29 active ones. <s> The peninsula has a high density of volcanoes and associated volcanic phenomena, with 29 active volcanoes being included in the six UNESCO World Heritage List sites in the Volcanoes of Kamchatka group, most of them on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> 29 active volcanoes are included in six UNESCO World Heritage List sites. <s> The highest volcano is Klyuchevskaya Sopka (4,750 m or 15,584 ft), the largest active volcano in the northern hemisphere. <s> The most striking is Kronotsky, whose perfect cone was said by celebrated volcanologists Robert and Barbara Decker to be a prime candidate for the world's most beautiful volcano. <s> In the center of Kamchatka is Eurasia's world famous Geyser Valley which was partly destroyed by a massive mudslide in June 2007. <s> Deep seismic events and tsunamis are fairly common. <s> A pair of huge earthquakes occurred off the coast on October 16, 1737, and on November 4, 1952, in magnitudes ~9.3 and 8.2 respectively. <s> More shallow earthquakes were recorded as recently as April 2006.

title: Gabriel Popescu
complex: Gabriel Popescu (born 25 December 1973) is a Romanian former footballer.
simple: Gabriel Popescu (born 25 December 1973) is a former Romanian football player.

title: Division of North Sydney
complex: The Division of North Sydney is an Australian electoral division in the state of New South Wales. <s> It was proclaimed in 1900 and was one of the original 65 divisions contested at the first federal election. <s> Second only to the nearby Division of Wentworth, the Division of North Sydney has the nation's second highest proportion (56.4%) of high income families. <s> As with all North Shore seats, the division has usually been a comfortably safe seat for the Liberal Party of Australia and its predecessors. <s> Labor has usually run dead in this seat, though it came within 3.1 percent of winning it at the 1943 election landslide. <s> North Sydney and Wentworth are the only two federation divisions in New South Wales to have never been held by Labor. <s> It has been held by a member of a non-Labor party for all but six years of its existence, when held by "father of the independents" Ted Mack, from the 1990 election before choosing to resign from federal parliament after two terms at the 1996 election, for the same reason he previously chose to resign from state parliament after two terms − to avoid receiving a parliamentary pension. <s> However, during Mack's tenure, North Sydney was always a safe Liberal seat in traditional two-party matchups, and it was a foregone conclusion that it would revert to the Liberals once Mack retired. <s> As expected, when Mack retired in 1996, Joe Hockey reclaimed the seat for the Liberals on a swing large enough to revert the seat to its traditional status as a comfortably safe Liberal seat. <s> Hockey held it easily until 2015, serving as Treasurer from 2013 to 2015 in the Abbott Government. <s> After Abbott was ousted as Liberal leader and Prime Minister by Malcolm Turnbull in the September 2015 Liberal leadership spill Hockey moved to the backbench, however six days later he announced his intention to resign from parliament, taking effect from 23 October. <s> The 2015 North Sydney by-election occurred on 5 December to elect his replacement, Trent Zimmerman, a former Hockey staffer, despite a large swing. <s> Located along Sydney's Lower North Shore, the division is named after the suburb of North Sydney. <s> It also includes the suburbs of Artarmon, Cammeray, Castlecrag, Crows Nest, Greenwich, Henley, Hunters Hill, Huntleys Cove, Huntleys Point, Kirribilli, Lane Cove, Lane Cove North, Lane Cove West, Lavender Bay, Linley Point, Longueville, McMahons Point, Middle Cove, Milsons Point, Naremburn, North Willoughby, Northbridge, Northwood, Riverview, St Leonards, Waverton, Willoughby, Willoughby East, Wollstonecraft, and Woolwich; as well as parts of Chatswood, Chatswood West, Cremorne, Gladesville, Gore Hill, and Neutral Bay.
simple: The Division of North Sydney is an Australian Electoral Division in New South Wales. <s> It was set up in 1900 for the first federal election in 1901. <s> North Sydney is one of only two original divisions in New South Wales, which have never been held by the ALP. <s> It has been held by a member of a non-Labor party for all but six years, when independent Ted Mack held it. <s> Joe Hockey was Treasurer in the Abbott Government, but lost his position when Malcolm Turnbull became Prime Minister. <s> The division is named after the North Sydney area. <s> The electoral division includes the suburbs of Artarmon, Cammeray, Cremorne, Cremorne Point, Crows Nest, Gore Hill, Greenwich, Henley, Hunters Hill, Huntleys Point, Kirribilli, Lane Cove, Lane Cove North, Lane Cove West, Lavender Bay, Linley Point, Longueville, McMahons Point, Milsons Point, Naremburn, Neutral Bay, North Sydney,Northbridge, Northwood, Riverview, St Leonards, Tarban, Waverton, Wollstonecraft, Woolwich and parts of Castlecrag, Gladesville and Willoughby.

title: Clément Mouamba
complex: Clément Mouamba (born 1944?) <s> is a Congolese politician who has been Prime Minister of the Republic of the Congo since 2016. <s> Previously he served as Minister of Finance from 1992 to 1993.
simple: Clément Mouamba (born 1944) is a Congolese politician. <s> He has been the Prime Minister of the Republic of the Congo since 2016. <s> Before he was Minister of Finance from 1992 to 1993.

title: Graph of a function
complex: In science, engineering, technology, finance, and other areas, graphs are tools used for many purposes. <s> In the simplest case one variable is plotted as a function of another, typically using rectangular axes; see "Plot (graphics)" for details.
simple: Scientists and engineers use graphs so that they can get a better understanding of the broad meaning and importance of their data.

title: Goldfield, Iowa
complex: Goldfield is a city in Wright County, Iowa, United States. <s> The population was 635 at the 2010 census.
simple: Goldfield is a city of Iowa in the United States. <s> It is in Wright County.

title: Filippo Raciti
complex: Filippo Raciti (17 January 1967–2 February 2007) was an Italian police officer ("ispettore capo di polizia") who was killed in a violent confrontation between Calcio Catania football supporters and police officers. <s> Raciti's death resulted in all of the Italian football matches, even the national team, to be suspended for a week. <s> It provoked outrage in Italy, with a great and somewhat uncommon amount of solidarity towards the Italian law enforcement forces, and massive coverage worldwide.
simple: Filippo Raciti (17 January 1967–2 February 2007) was an Italian police officer who was killed in a fight between Calcio Catania fans outside a stadium in Catania. <s> Raciti's death was in the news around the world. <s> All of the Italian football matches, even the national team, were suspended for a week.

title: Strahler number
complex: In mathematics, the Strahler number or Horton–Strahler number of a mathematical tree is a numerical measure of its branching complexity.
simple: In mathematics, the Strahler number or Horton–Strahler number of any tree shape measures its complexity.

title: Knuth's up-arrow notation
complex: In mathematics, Knuth's up-arrow notation is a method of notation for very large integers, introduced by Donald Knuth in 1976. <s> It is closely related to the Ackermann function and especially to the hyperoperation sequence. <s> The idea is based on the fact that multiplication can be viewed as iterated addition and exponentiation as iterated multiplication. <s> Continuing in this manner leads to tetration (iterated exponentiation) and to the remainder of the hyperoperation sequence, which is commonly denoted using Knuth arrow notation. <s> This notation allows for a simple description of numbers far larger than can be explicitly written out.
simple: Knuth's up-arrow notation is a way of expressing very big numbers. <s> It was made by Donald Knuth in 1976. <s> It is related to the hyperoperation sequence. <s> This notation is used to describe the incredibly large Graham's Number.

title: Samoa at the Olympics
complex: Samoa first participated at the Olympic Games in 1984, and has sent athletes to compete in every Summer Olympic Games since then. <s> The nation has never participated in the Winter Olympic Games. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Samoa was created in 1983 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee that same year.
simple: Samoa was first at the Olympic Games in 1984. <s> They have been in every Summer Olympic Games since then. <s> The nation has never been in the Winter Olympic Games. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Samoa was formed in 1983 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee the same year.

title: Maple syrup urine disease
complex: Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is an autosomal recessive metabolic disorder affecting branched-chain amino acids. <s> It is one type of organic acidemia. <s> The condition gets its name from the distinctive sweet odor of affected infants' urine, particularly prior to diagnosis, and during times of acute illness. <s> Infants with this disease seem healthy at birth but quickly deteriorate, often with severe brain damage, which may be permanent. <s> Death often occurs within the first five months in severe cases of the disease, when left untreated. <s> Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is a rare, inherited metabolic disorder. <s> Its prevalence in the United States population is approximately 1 newborn out of 180,000 live births. <s> However, in populations where there is a higher frequency of consanguinity, such as the Mennonites in Pennsylvania or the Amish, the frequency of MSUD is significantly higher at 1 newborn out of 176 live births. <s> In Austria, 1 newborn out of 250,000 live births inherits MSUD. <s> It also is believed to have a higher prevalence in certain populations due in part to the founder effect since MSUD has a much higher prevalence in children of Amish, Mennonite, and Jewish descent.
simple: Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is a genetic medical disorder. <s> Maple syrup urine disease affects about 1 in 185,000 infants worldwide. <s> The most noticeable symptom of the disorder is an infant with sweet-smelling urine. <s> Infants with this disease seem healthy at birth. <s> The urine of infants with this disease has a very sweet odor, much like burned caramel or maple syrup. <s> MSUD is much more common in children of Amish and Mennonite descent.

title: Dado Cavalcanti
complex: Luis Eduardo Barros Cavalcanti (born 9 July 1981), known as Dado Cavalcanti, is a Brazilian retired footballer who played as a left back, and is a manager.
simple: Luis Eduardo Barros Cavalcanti, or simply Dado Cavalcanti (born July 9, 1981 in Arcoverde) is a Brazilian football manager.

title: Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company
complex: The Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company (BRC&W) was a railway locomotive and carriage builder, founded in Birmingham, England and, for most of its existence, located at nearby Smethwick, with the factory divided by the boundary between the two places. <s> The company was established in 1854.
simple: The Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company (BRC&W) was a railway locomotive and carriage builder, founded in Birmingham, England. <s> For most of its existence, it was at nearby Smethwick, with the factory divided by the boundary between the two places. <s> The company was established in 1854.

title: B. S. Abdur Rahman
complex: Buhari Syed Abdur Rahman (15 October 1927 – 7 January 2015) was an Indian Tamil serial entrepreneur, philanthropist and educationist. <s> He had a range of business interests in the UAE and India (in Tamil Nadu) including maritime shipping, real estate, insurance etc. <s> He founded numerous schools, colleges, hospitals and university. <s> He was one of the 24 Indians to feature in "The 500 Most Influential Muslims", an annual publication which ranks the most influential Muslims in the world. <s> Abdur Rahman was the Vice-Chairperson of Emirates Trading Agency (commonly known as ETA Star) and Ascon Group, a Dubai-based conglomerate from 1973 to 2015. <s> He is the founder of B. S. Abdur Rahman University (earlier named Crescent Engineering College), one of the first private owned engineering colleges in Chennai. <s> He was the Chairman of East Coast Constructions and Industries, West Asia Exports and Imports, West Asia Maritime, Buhari Group, Amana Investments in Hong Kong and Transcar India. <s> He was also the Vice-Chairman of Coal & Oil and Coastal Energy. <s> He founded India's first stand-alone health insurer Star Health and Allied Insurance with the help of Oman Insurance Company. <s> East Coast Constructions and Industries, founded in 1962, built several landmarks in Chennai including Gemini Flyover, Kodambakkam Flyover, Chepauk Stadium, Chennai Citi Centre, Government General Hospital, Valluvar Kottam, the Marina Lighthouse and the Apollo Hospital complex in Greams Road. <s> He died on 7 January 2015 at the age of 87. <s> B. S. Abdur Rahman was born in Kilakarai, Tamil Nadu, India, in a middle-class Marakkar family, the son of Bhukari Aalim. <s> His father was a prominent Pearl Trader in South Asia.
simple: Buhari Syed Abdur Rahman (15 October 1927 – 7 January 2015) was an Indian serial entrepreneur, philanthropist and educator. <s> He had a range of business interests in the UAE and India. <s> He was one of the 24 Indians to feature in "The 500 Most Influential Muslims". <s> Rahman was the Vice-chairman of Emirates Trading Agency from 1973 to 2015. <s> He was the founder of B. S. Abdur Rahman University. <s> Rahman died in Chennai, India, aged 87. <s> Rahman was born in Kilakarai, Madras State, British India.

title: Kappa (folklore)
complex: The "kappa" is said to be roughly humanoid in form and about the size of a child, inhabiting the ponds and rivers of Japan. <s> It is typically greenish in color (or yellow-blue ), and either scaly or slimy skinned, with webbed hands and feet, and a turtle-like carapace on its back.
simple: The Kappa is said to be the size of a 6 to 10 year old boy.

title: Guîtres
complex: Guîtres is a commune in the Gironde department in southwestern France.
simple: Guîtres is a commune.

title: Your Show of Shows
complex: Your Show of Shows is a live 90-minute variety show that was broadcast weekly in the United States on NBC from February 25, 1950, through June 5, 1954, featuring Sid Caesar and Imogene Coca. <s> Other featured performers were Carl Reiner, Howard Morris, Bill Hayes, baritone Jack Russell (singer), Judy Johnson, The Hamilton Trio and the soprano Marguerite Piazza. <s> José Ferrer made several guest appearances on the series. <s> Writers for the series included Mel Brooks, Neil Simon, Danny Simon, Mel Tolkin, Lucille Kallen, Selma Diamond, Joseph Stein, Michael Stewart, Tony Webster (the only Gentile among the show's writers), and Carl Reiner who, though a cast member, also worked with the writers. <s> (Larry Gelbart and Woody Allen joined the writing staff for later Caesar ventures.) <s> The series is historically significant for the evolution of the variety genre by incorporating situation comedies (sitcoms) such as the running sketch "The Hickenloopers"; this added a narrative element to the traditional multi-act structure. <s> A common misconception is that Larry Gelbart wrote for "Your Show of Shows"; in fact, he wrote for its successor program, "Caesar's Hour", which was broadcast from 1954 to 1957. <s> Likewise, Woody Allen did not write for "Your Show of Shows", as he only worked on several Sid Caesar TV series and specials from 1958 forward.
simple: Your Show of Shows was a 90-minute long comedy television series appearing weekly in the United States on NBC, from 1950 until June 5, 1954. <s> The main people of the show were Sid Caesar and Imogene Coca. <s> Other people who appeared were Carl Reiner, Howard Morris, Nanette Fabray, Bill Hayes, Judy Johnson, The Hamilton Trio and the soprano Marguerite Piazza. <s> José Ferrer also appeared on the show sometimes, as a guest. <s> Writers for the show included Mel Brooks, Neil Simon, Danny Simon, Larry Gelbart, Mel Tolkin, and Carl Reiner who, though a cast member, always sat in with the writers. <s> He did, however, write for "Caesar's Hour", which ran from 1954 to 1957. <s> Although it is not true, some people think that Woody Allen wrote for "Your Show of Shows".

title: Ishq Subhan Allah
complex: Ishq Subhan Allah (English: "This Love, Oh God") is an Indian television series, which airs on Zee TV. <s> The show is produced by Zuby Kochchar and Dheeraj Kumar .I <s> It stars Eisha Singhand Adnan Khan.
simple: Ishq Subhan Allah is an Indian television series that premiered on 14 March 2018 and Telecasts Monday To Friday at 10:00 P.M. And airs on Zee TV. <s> The series stars Eisha Singh and Adnan Khan in lead roles.

title: Minneapolis–Saint Paul International Airport
complex: Minneapolis–Saint Paul International Airport , also less commonly known as Wold–Chamberlain Field, is a joint civil-military public use international airport. <s> It is located in a portion of Hennepin County, Minnesota, United States, within 10 mi of both downtown Minneapolis and Saint Paul. <s> MSP is the largest and busiest airport in the six-state Upper Midwest region of Minnesota, Iowa, Nebraska, North Dakota, South Dakota, and Wisconsin.
simple: The Minneapolis—Saint Paul International Airport represents a joint civil-military public use airport. <s> It is located in Hennepin County, Minnesota within ten miles of both Minneapolis and Saint Paul and serves Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin, the Dakotas and Nebraska.

title: Mathematical analysis
complex: Mathematical analysis is the branch of mathematics dealing with limits and related theories, such as differentiation, integration, measure, infinite series, and analytic functions. <s> The modern foundations of mathematical analysis were established in 17th century Europe. <s> Descartes and Fermat independently developed analytic geometry, and a few decades later Newton and Leibniz independently developed infinitesimal calculus, which grew, with the stimulus of applied work that continued through the 18th century, into analysis topics such as the calculus of variations, ordinary and partial differential equations, Fourier analysis, and generating functions. <s> During this period, calculus techniques were applied to approximate discrete problems by continuous ones.
simple: Mathematical analysis is a part of mathematics. <s> The mathematical analysis is about continuous functions, differential calculus and integration. <s> An example for mathematical analysis is limits. <s> Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz and Isaac Newton developed most of the basis of mathematical analysis.

title: New York State Route 9G
complex: New York State Route 9G (NY 9G) is a state highway in the Hudson Valley of New York in the United States. <s> It runs north from U.S. Route 9 (US 9) at Poughkeepsie, starting out as Violet Avenue, then follows the Hudson River mostly along the eastern side of the US 9 to Rhinebeck, where the two routes cross just north of the village. <s> From this point onward, NY 9G runs on the western side of US 9, closer to the Hudson River, to Hudson.
simple: New York State Route 9G (NY 9G) is a road in Dutchess County, New York, United States. <s> It starts at US 9 in Poughkeepsie and follows the Hudson River as it goes north. <s> It crosses Route 9 just north of Rhinebeck and ends in Hudson.

title: Hund's rules
complex: In atomic physics, Hund's rules refers to a set of rules that German physicist Friedrich Hund formulated around 1927, which are used to determine the term symbol that corresponds to the ground state of a multi-electron atom. <s> The first rule is especially important in chemistry, where it is often referred to simply as Hund's Rule. <s> Hund's rules work best for the determination of the ground state of an atom or molecule.
simple: In atomic physics, Hund's rules are rules that determine how the electrons in an atom work. <s> Often, the first rule of Hund's rules is most often mentioned. <s> The first rule of Hund's rules is so important in chemistry that it is simply just called "Hund's rule".

title: Jōkyō calendar
complex: The Jōkyō calendar (貞享暦 , Jōkyō-reki ) was a Japanese lunisolar calendar, in use from 1684 to 1753. <s> It was officially adopted in 1685. <s> The "Jōkyō-reki" system was developed and explained by Shibukawa Shunkai. <s> He recognized that the length of the solar year is 365.2417 days. <s> Shibukawa discovered errors in the traditional Chinese calendar, the "Senmyō" calendar, which had been in use for 800 years.
simple: Jōkyō calendar (貞享暦, Jōkyō-reki), also called Teikyō-reki, was a Japanese lunisolar calendar ("genka reki"). <s> It was used from 1684-1753. <s> It was made official in 1685. <s> The "Jōkyō-reki" system was the work of Shibukawa Shunkai. <s> He recognized that the length of the solar year is 365.2417 days. <s> Shirakawa discovered errors in the traditional Chinese calendar which had been in use for 800 years.

title: Vienna Bend, Louisiana
complex: Vienna Bend is an unincorporated community and census-designated place (CDP) in Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana, United States. <s> The population was 1,251 at the 2010 census.
simple: Vienna Bend is an unincorporated community and census-designated place in Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana United States. <s> The population was 1,251 at the 2010 census.

title: Hypochlorite
complex: In chemistry, hypochlorite is an ion with the chemical formula ClO. <s> It combines with a number of cations to form hypochlorites, which may also be regarded as the salts of hypochlorous acid. <s> Common examples include sodium hypochlorite (household bleach) and calcium hypochlorite (a component of bleaching powder, swimming pool "chlorine"). <s> Hypochlorites react with ammonia first giving chloramine (NH2Cl ), then dichloramine (NHCl2 ) and finally nitrogen trichloride (NCl3 ). <s> Hypochlorite is the strongest oxidizing agent of the chlorine oxyanions. <s> This can be seen by comparing the standard half cell potentials across the series; the data also shows that the chlorine oxyanions are stronger oxidizers in acidic conditions.
simple: Hypochlorite is an ion. <s> Their chemical formula is ClO. <s> It can be found in household bleach, sodium hypochlorite. <s> Hypochlorites react with acids to produce chlorine. <s> It is a strong oxidizing agent.

title: Brain Stew / Jaded
complex: "Brain Stew" and "Jaded" are two songs released as a joint single by American punk rock band Green Day. <s> They are the tenth and eleventh tracks and third single from the group's fourth studio album, "Insomniac". <s> The song was also included on "".
simple: Brain Stew, A.K.A. Jaded is a song by the punk rock band Green Day. <s> The song was on their fourth studio album "Insomniac" in the year 1995.

title: Oz the Great and Powerful
complex: Oz the Great and Powerful is a 2013 American fantasy adventure film directed by Sam Raimi and written by David Lindsay-Abaire and Mitchell Kapner from a story by Kapner. <s> Based on L. Frank Baum's "Oz" novels and set 20 years before the events of the original novel, the film is a spiritual prequel to the 1939 Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer film "The Wizard of Oz". <s> Starring James Franco in the title role, Mila Kunis, Rachel Weisz, Michelle Williams, Zach Braff, Bill Cobbs, Joey King, and Tony Cox, the film tells the story of Oscar Diggs, a deceptive magician who arrives in the Land of Oz and encounters three witches: Theodora, Evanora, and Glinda. <s> Oscar is then enlisted to restore order in Oz while struggling to resolve conflicts with the witches and himself.
simple: Oz the Great and Powerful is an American fantasy adventure movie from 2013. <s> It is directed by Sam Raimi, produced by Joe Roth, and written by David Lindsay-Abaire and Mitchell Kapner. <s> It stars James Franco as Oscar Diggs, Mila Kunis as Theodora, Rachel Weisz as Evanora, Michelle Williams as Glinda, Zach Braff as Finley, Bill Cobbs as Master Tinker, and Joey King as China Girl.

title: Neufchâtel-en-Saosnois
complex: Neufchâtel-en-Saosnois is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Neufchâtel-en-Saosnois is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Besny-et-Loizy
complex: Besny-et-Loizy is a commune in the department of Aisne in Hauts-de-France in northern France.
simple: Besny-et-Loizy is a commune.

title: La Réole
complex: La Réole is a commune in the Gironde department in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in southwestern France.
simple: La Réole is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Aquitaine in the Gironde department in the southwest of France.

title: Aydıncık, Mersin
complex: Aydıncık is a town and district of Mersin Province on the Mediterranean coast of Turkey, 173 km from Mersin and 325 km from Antalya. <s> Aydıncık has also been called in Armenian Կելենդերիդա, and "Gilindire", from Kelenderis . <s> In 1228, Celenderis castle was captured from the Armenians by the Karamanoğlu Beylik and the coast was settled by Turkish peoples. <s> The town's name mutated to "Gilindere" and it continued to be an important port between Anatolia and Cyprus until the beginning of the twentieth century. <s> It was renamed Aydıncık in 1965. <s> The remains of ancient Celenderis are very few and the ruins today are mostly overlaid by the expanding modern Aydıncık. <s> Fortifications may still be detected around the modern lighthouse on the small promontory which forms and commands the harbor. <s> There is a landlocked bay with its famous spring 1.6 km to the west at Soguksu. <s> Here there are ancient ruins, notably a bath at the head of the bay and archaeological debris on the peninsula at its mouth. <s> There are handsome but much destroyed rock-cut tombs at Duruhan 9.6 km to the North. <s> There is a large Roman Cenotaph with four columns from the 2nd century. <s> It was marked as a CENOTAPH (a monument erected as a memorial to a dead person or dead people buried elsewhere, especially people killed fighting a war) on the map of Chelindreh harbor prepared by Rear Admiral Sir Francis Beaufort. <s> This is a tetrapylon made of well-cut limestones with a rectangular burial room on the lower part, four pylons erected on this and a pyramidal roof carried by the arches of the four pylons. <s> This type is a common one in the Roma period and may be dated to the second half of the second or early third century AD. <s> The cave of Gilindere is about an hour's ride along the coast by small boat, and is 555m of attractive stone and crystal formations.
simple: Aydıncık is a district of Mersin Province on the Mediterranean coast of Turkey. <s> It is 173 km from Mersin and 325 km from Antalya. <s> Aydıncık is near the Mediterranean Sea. <s> Aydıncık has also been called "Celenderis", "Gilindire", Kelenderis (Κελενδερίς in ancient Greek). <s> In 1228 Celenderis castle was captured from the Armenians by the Ottomans. <s> The coast was settled by Turkish peoples. <s> The town's name changed to Gilindere. <s> It continued to be an important port between Anatolia and Cyprus until the beginning of the 20th century. <s> It was renamed Aydıncık in 1965. <s> The remains of ancient Celenderis are very few. <s> The ruins today are mostly covered over by the expanding modern Aydıncık. <s> Fortifications may still be seen around the modern lighthouse near the harbor. <s> There is a landlocked bay with its famous spring 1.6 km to the west at Soguksu. <s> Here there are ancient ruins There is a bath at the head of the bay. <s> There are also traces of archaeological debris on the peninsula at its mouth. <s> There is a large Roman Cenotaph with four columns from the 2nd century. <s> The cave of Gilindere is about an hour's ride along the coast by small boat. <s> It has attractive stone and crystal formations.

title: Jackie Biskupski
complex: Jackie Biskupski (born January 11, 1966) is an American Democratic politician, and the current Mayor of Salt Lake City, Utah. <s> Upon taking office, Biskupski became Salt Lake City's 35th mayor, the city's first openly gay mayor, and the second female mayor (after Deedee Corradini). <s> She is a former member of the Utah House of Representatives, representing the 30th District in Salt Lake County from 1999 to 2011.

title: Ankylosauria
complex: Ankylosauria is a group of mainly herbivorous dinosaurs of the order Ornithischia. <s> It includes the great majority of dinosaurs with armor in the form of bony osteoderms. <s> Ankylosaurs were bulky quadrupeds, with short, powerful limbs. <s> They are known to have first appeared in the early Jurassic Period, and persisted until the end of the Cretaceous Period. <s> They have been found on every continent. <s> The first dinosaur discovered in Antarctica was the ankylosaurian "Antarctopelta", fossils of which were recovered from Ross Island in 1986.
simple: Ankylosaurs were herbivorous armoured dinosaurs of the order Ornithischia. <s> They were quadrupeds with short and strong legs. <s> Fossils of Ankylosaurs have been found on every continent.

title: Samuel J. Jones
complex: Samuel Jefferson Jones (April 16, 1827 – December 10, 1883) was a pro-slavery settler who held the position of Douglas County sheriff in Kansas Territory from late 1855 until early 1857. <s> He helped found the territorial capital of Lecompton and played a prominent role in the "Bleeding Kansas" conflict. <s> In 1858, he moved to La Mesilla, New Mexico Territory. <s> In September of that year, he was appointed the collector of customs at Paso del Norte (now Ciudad Juárez). <s> In New Mexico, he was involved with the promotion of Mowry City. <s> When that settlement's prospects collapsed, he bought a ranch near La Mesilla and died there in 1883. <s> His tombstone was later returned to Lecompton in 2013.
simple: Samuel Jefferson Jones (April 16, 1827 – December 10, 1883) was a pro-slavery man who was the Douglas County sheriff in Kansas Territory from late 1855 until early 1857. <s> He helped create the territorial capital of Lecompton. <s> He was an important person in the "Bleeding Kansas" conflict. <s> In 1858, he moved to La Mesilla, New Mexico Territory. <s> In September 1858, he was chosen to be the collector of customs at Paso del Norte (now Ciudad Juárez). <s> In New Mexico, he was involved with the of Mowry City. <s> When that town's future failed, he bought a ranch near La Mesilla and died there in 1883. <s> His grave was later returned to Lecompton in 2013.

title: Shulem Deen
complex: Shulem Deen (born 1974) is an American author, essayist, former Skver "hasid", and critic of "haredi" and Hasidic Judaism. <s> He is the author of the memoir "All Who Go Do Not Return" (2015), and is a regular columnist at "The Forward". <s> He is also the founding editor of "Unpious", a journal for voices critical of Hasidic lifestyle and beliefs. <s> Deen first became known as the author of the blog "Hasidic Rebel," which he wrote from 2003 until 2012, and which was the subject of a 2003 feature article in the "Village Voice". <s> Deen's blog was the first widely read website by a practicing Hasid casting doubt on his religious faith. <s> In 2010, Deen launched the "Unpious" website along with "Shtreimel," another ex-Hasidic blogger, and has served as its editor throughout. <s> The site was intended as a platform for voices critical of the Hasidic and ultra-Orthodox lifestyle and beliefs. <s> His memoir, "All Who Go Do Not Return", was published in 2015, and chronicles his transition from devout member of the Skver Hasidic sect to secular Jew. <s> Deen's book is part of a subgenre of memoirs by formerly Orthodox writers, and is considered to be one of the best. <s> Deen is a regular columnist at "The Forward", and writes widely on the intersection of Hasidic and secular life, including articles in the "New Republic", "Salon", and "Tablet". <s> His work is also seen to be highly critical of the ultra-Orthodox lifestyle and worldview. <s> He currently serves as a Board member at Footsteps, a New York City organization that assists formerly ultra-Orthodox Jews with transitioning to life outside the Orthodox world. <s> Deen spent his early life among Satmar Hasidim in the Borough Park section of Brooklyn, and joined the Skver sect when he was a teenager, moving to the town of New Square, NY, the sect's headquarters, to settle after marriage. <s> He was married in 1993, and has five children. <s> In 2005, Deen was expelled from New Square by its leaders for holding heretical views, and several years later divorced his wife and left the Hasidic lifestyle entirely. <s> He is mostly estranged from his children, who have remained among the Skverer Hasidim in New Square, N.Y. <s> He currently lives in Brooklyn New York
simple: Shulem Deen (born 1974) is the author of a memoir, "All Who Go Do Not Return" (2015), and the editor of "Unpious.com", an online journal for voices critical of Hasidic lifestyle and beliefs. <s> Deen first became known as the author of the blog, "Hasidic Rebel," which he wrote from 2003 until 2012, and which was the subject of a 2003 feature article in the "Village Voice". <s> Deen's blog was the first widely read website by a practicing Hasid casting doubt on his religious faith. <s> In 2010, Deen launched the Unpious website along with "Shtreimel," another ex-Hasidic blogger, and has served as its editor throughout. <s> His memoir chronicles his often painful change from a devout member of the Skverer Hasidic community in New Square, New York to a secular Jew. <s> He has also written several pieces for other publications on the intersection of Hasidic and secular lives, including articles in the "Jewish Daily Forward", "Tablet Magazine", "Salon", and "Zeek". <s> He currently serves as a Board member at Footsteps, a New York City organization that assists formerly ultra-Orthodox Jews with transitioning to life outside the Orthodox world. <s> Deen spent his early life among Satmar Hasidim in Borough Park, Brooklyn, and joined the Skverer sect when he was a teenager, moving to the town of New Square, to settle after marriage. <s> He was married in 1993, and has five children. <s> In 2005, Deen was expelled from New Square by its leaders for holding heretical views, and several years later divorced his wife and left the Hasidic lifestyle entirely. <s> He currently lives in Brooklyn New York He is mostly estranged from his children, who have remained among the Skverer Hasidim in New Square, N.Y.

title: Kesha Wizzart
complex: Kesha Wizzart ( ; 22 October 1988 – 12 July 2007), born Estella Wizzart, was an English singer and participant on the television show "Stars In Their Eyes" on ITV in 2004. <s> Wizzart was born in 1988 around the area of Fallowfield and Withington, a few miles south of Manchester City Centre. <s> Her parents are of Jamaican heritage. <s> In 2004, Wizzart appeared on the British talent show "Stars in Their Eyes:Kids" performing the song "Un-Break My Heart" by Toni Braxton. <s> On 12 July 2007 Wizzart and her mother Beverley Samuels were murdered in their home in Fallowfield. <s> Her brother Fred was also murdered at the scene.

title: Adactylidium
complex: Adactylidium is a genus of mites known for its unusual life cycle. <s> The pregnant female mite feeds upon a single egg of a thrips, growing five to eight female offspring and one male in her body. <s> The single male mite mates with all the daughters when they are still in the mother. <s> The females, now impregnated, eat their way out of their mother's body so that they can emerge to find new thrips eggs. <s> The male emerges as well, but does not look for food or new mates, and dies after a few hours. <s> The females die at the age of 4 days, when their own offspring eat them alive from the inside.
simple: Adactylidium is a genus of mites. <s> It is known for its short and unusual life cycle. <s> The pregnant female mite attaches herself to a single egg of a thrip. <s> She grows from five to eight female offspring and one male in her body. <s> The single male mite mates with all his sisters when they are still in the mother. <s> The females, now pregnant, cut holes in their mother's body. <s> This is so that they can get out to find new thrips eggs. <s> But having served his biological function he dies after a few hours. <s> The offspring begin to eat their mother from the inside out. <s> The females die at the age of four days, when their own offspring eat them alive from the inside.

title: Håkan Carlqvist
complex: Håkan Carlqvist (15 January 1954 – 6 July 2017) was a Swedish professional motocross racer. <s> Carlqvist was a two-time world champion who was known for his fierce competitiveness. <s> Born in the Järfälla Municipality near Stockholm, Sweden, Carlqvist began competing in the world championships as a privateer riding an Ossa. <s> He won the F.I.M. 250cc Motocross World Championship in 1979 as a member of the Husqvarna factory racing team. <s> In 1980, he switched to Yamaha to contest the 500cc motocross world championship. <s> He finished 3rd in 1981 and 7th in 1982. <s> In 1983, he battled against Honda teammates André Malherbe and Graham Noyce to claim the 500cc world championship, on a Yamaha. <s> In 1984, an injury stopped Carlqvist from contesting the title again. <s> He raced for Yamaha until end of 1986. <s> He continued the 500 GPs in 1987 and 1988 with a privateer Kawasaki KX500. <s> His last Grand Prix victory was the Belgian Grand Prix at Namur in 1988. <s> During this race, he stunned the spectators by stopping before the end of the 2nd moto to drink a beer, while leading the race by somewhat 50 seconds, and going back into the race to win it. <s> Carlqvist died on 6 July 2017 from the effects of a brain hemorrhage he suffered the previous day.

title: Procompsognathus
complex: Procompsognathus is an extinct genus of coelophysid theropod dinosaur that lived approximately 210 million years ago during the later part of the Triassic Period, in what is now Germany. <s> "Procompsognathus" was a small-sized, lightly built, ground-dwelling, bipedal carnivore, that could grow up to 1 m (3.3 ft) long. <s> "Procompsognathus" may have been about 1 m long, though Fraas in 1913 estimated a length of 75 cm . <s> In 2010 Gregory S. Paul gave an estimate of 1 kg for the weight with a length of 1.1 m . <s> A biped, "Procompsognathus" had long hind legs, short arms, large clawed hands, a long slender snout with many small teeth, and a stiff tail. <s> The femur discovered for the type specimen of this genus measures 93mm and the tibia, 112mm. <s> The tibia is approximately 20% longer than the femur in "Procompsognathus", an adaptation which has been strongly correlated with the development of cursorial habits in dinosaurs, suggesting that they were good runners. <s> "Procompsognathus" lived in a relatively dry, inland environment and may have eaten insects, lizards and other small prey. <s> Contemporaries of "Prompsognathus" included the coelophysoids "Halticosaurus" and "Dolichosuchus", as well as the Sauropodomorphs "Plateosaurus gracilis" and "Efraasia minor".

title: Waterloo Wind Farm
complex: Waterloo wind farm is east of Manoora, South Australia. <s> It is the largest wind farm operated by EnergyAustralia. <s> The wind farm is positioned along a rocky north-south ridge on privately owned property at Waterloo. <s> The 111 megawatt wind farm spreads across five acres of land and cost about $350 million, it began construction in November, 2008 and has been operational since October 2010. <s> Each wind turbine produces on average 24 megawatt hours of power each day. <s> On a windy day three wind turbines can power the whole of Clare and the whole wind farm can power up to 163,000 homes or 5 to 10% of South Australia.

title: Richard II, Duke of Normandy
complex: Richard II (died 28 August 1026), called the Good (French: "Le Bon"), was the eldest son and heir of Richard I the Fearless and Gunnor. <s> He was a Norman nobleman of the House of Normandy. <s> He was the paternal grandfather of William the Conqueror. <s> Richard succeeded his father as Duke of Normandy in 996. <s> During his minority, the first five years of his reign (suggesting he was born between 980 and 990), his regent was Count Rodulf of Ivry, his uncle, who wielded the power and put down a peasant insurrection at the beginning of Richard's reign. <s> Richard had deep religious interests and found he had much in common with Robert II of France, who he helped militarily against the duchy of Burgundy. <s> He forged a marriage alliance with Brittany by marrying his sister Hawise to Geoffrey I, Duke of Brittany and by his own marriage to Geoffrey's sister, Judith of Brittany. <s> In 1000–1001, Richard repelled an English attack on the Cotentin Peninsula that was led by Ethelred II of England. <s> Ethelred had given orders that Richard be captured, bound and brought to England. <s> But the English had not been prepared for the rapid response of the Norman cavalry and were defeated at the Battle of Val-de-Saire. <s> Richard attempted to improve relations with England through his sister Emma of Normandy's marriage to King Ethelred. <s> This marriage was significant in that it later gave his grandson, William the Conqueror, the basis of his claim to the throne of England. <s> The improved relations proved to be beneficial to Ethelred when in 1013 Sweyn Forkbeard invaded England. <s> Emma with her two sons Edward and Alfred fled to Normandy followed shortly thereafter by her husband king Ethelred. <s> Soon after the death of Ethelred, Cnut, King of England forced Emma to marry him while Richard was forced to recognize the new regime as his sister was again Queen. <s> Richard had contacts with Scandinavian Vikings throughout his reign. <s> He employed Viking mercenaries and concluded a treaty with Sweyn Forkbeard who was en route to England. <s> Richard II commissioned his clerk and confessor, Dudo of Saint-Quentin, to portray his ducal ancestors as morally upright Christian leaders who built Normandy despite the treachery of their overlords and neighboring principalities. <s> It was clearly a work of propaganda designed to legitimize the Norman settlement, and while it contains numerous historically unreliable legends, as respects the reigns of his father and grandfather, Richard I and William I it is basically reliable. <s> In 1025 and 1026 Richard confirmed gifts of his great-grandfather Rollo to Saint-Ouen at Rouen. <s> His other numerous grants to monastic houses tends to indicate the areas over which Richard had ducal control, namely Caen, the Éverecin, the Cotentin, the Pays de Caux and Rouen. <s> Richard II died 28 Aug 1026. <s> his eldest son, Richard becoming the new duke.

Caen, the Éverecin, the Cotentin, the Pays de Caux and Rouen. <s> Richard II died 28 Aug 1026.

title: Arnold Koller
complex: Arnold Koller (born 29 August 1933) is a Swiss politician and member of the Swiss Federal Council (1986–1999). <s> He was elected to the Federal Council of Switzerland on 10 December 1986 as a member of the Christian Democratic People's Party of Switzerland from the canton of Appenzell Inner Rhodes. <s> He handed over office on 30 April 1999. <s> Arnold Koller was Chairman of the Board of the Forum of Federations from 2006 to 2010. <s> This is an international organization designed to help develop best practices in countries around the world with federal and devolved systems of government. <s> During his time in office he held the following departments: He was President of the Confederation twice in 1990 and 1997.
simple: Arnold Koller (born 29 August 1933) is a Swiss politician. <s> He was a member of the Swiss Federal Council (1986-1999). <s> He was elected to the Federal Council of Switzerland on 10 December 1986. <s> He was member of the Christian Democratic People's Party of Switzerland from the canton of Appenzell Innerrhoden. <s> He handed over office on 30 April 1999. <s> Koller was Chairman of the Board of the Forum of Federations from 2006 to 2010. <s> He was President of the Confederation twice in 1990 and 1997.

title: Joseph Yobo
complex: Joseph Phillip Yobo (born 6 September 1980) is a former Nigerian professional footballer who played as a centre back. <s> He was the captain of the Nigerian national team until his international football retirement in June 2014, and is Nigeria's joint record appearance holder. <s> Yobo left Nigeria to join Standard Liège in 1998. <s> He made his first team debut in 2000, and went on to appear 46 times. <s> In 2001, he was bought by Marseille.
simple: Joseph Yobo (born 6 September 1980) is a Nigerian football player who plays for Everton in the Premier League. <s> Yobo is also captain of the national Nigerian side. <s> He signed from French side Olympique Marseille in 2001 and has become a favourite at Everton ever since.

title: Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg
complex: Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg (19 April 1795 – 27 June 1876), German naturalist, zoologist, comparative anatomist, geologist, and microscopist, was one of the most famous and productive scientists of his time. <s> Ehrenberg was an evangelist. <s> Ehrenberg was appointed professor of medicine at Berlin University in 1827. <s> In 1829 he accompanied Humboldt through eastern Russia to the Chinese frontier. <s> After his return he began to concentrate his studies on microscopic organisms, which until then had not been systematically studied. <s> For nearly 30 years Ehrenberg examined samples of water, soil, sediment, blowing dust and rock and described thousands of new species, among them well-known flagellates such as Euglena, ciliates such as "Paramecium aurelia" and "Paramecium caudatum", and many fossils, in nearly 400 scientific publications. <s> He was particularly interested in a unicellular group of protists called diatoms, but he also studied, and named, many species of radiolaria, foraminifera and dinoflagellates. <s> These researches had an important bearing on some of the infusorial earths used for polishing and other economic purposes; they added, moreover, largely to our knowledge of the microorganisms of certain geological formations, especially of the chalk, and of the marine and freshwater accumulations. <s> Until Ehrenberg took up the study it was not known that considerable masses of rock were composed of minute forms of animals or plants. <s> He also demonstrated that the phosphorescence of the sea was due to organisms. <s> He was a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences from 1836 and a foreign member of the Royal Society of London from 1837. <s> In 1839, he won the Wollaston Medal, the highest award granted by the Geological Society of London. <s> Ehrenberg was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1849. <s> He continued until late in life to investigate the microscopic organisms of the deep sea and of various geological formations. <s> He died in Berlin on 27 June 1876. <s> After his death in 1876, his collections of microscopic organisms were deposited in the Berlin's Natural History Museum (this museum was a part of the University of Berlin until it left the university in 2009). <s> The "Ehrenberg Collection" includes 40,000 microscope preparations, 5,000 raw samples, 3,000 pencil and ink drawings, and nearly 1,000 letters of correspondence. <s> His collection of scorpions, and other arachnids from the Middle East, is also held in the Berlin Museum.
simple: Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg (19 April 1795 – 27 June 1876), German naturalist, zoologist, comparative anatomist, geologist, and microscopist, was one of the most famous and productive scientists of his time. <s> Ehrenberg was appointed professor of medicine at Berlin University in 1827. <s> In 1829 he accompanied Humboldt through eastern Russia to the Chinese frontier. <s> After his return he began to concentrate his studies on microscopic organisms, which then were not much studied. <s> For nearly 30 years Ehrenberg examined samples of water, soil, sediment, blowing dust and rock and described thousands of new species, among them well-known flagellates such as Euglena, ciliates such as "Paramecium aurelia" and "Paramecium caudatum", and many fossils, in nearly 400 scientific publications. <s> He was particularly interested in a unicellular group of protists called diatoms, but he also studied, and named, many species of radiolaria, foraminifera and dinoflagellates. <s> These researches built up our knowledge of the microorganisms of certain geological formations, especially of the chalk, and of the marine and freshwater accumulations. <s> Until Ehrenberg took up the study it was not known that considerable masses of rock were composed of minute forms of animals or plants. <s> He also demonstrated that the phosphorescence of the sea was due to organisms. <s> He was a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences from 1836 and a foreign member of the Royal Society of London from 1837. <s> In 1839, he won the Wollaston Medal, the highest award granted by the Geological Society of London. <s> He continued until late in life to investigate the microscopic organisms of the deep sea and of various geological formations. <s> He died in Berlin on 27 June 1876. <s> After his death in 1876, his collections of microscopic organisms were deposited in the Humboldt Museum at the University of Berlin. <s> The "Ehrenberg Collection" includes is also held in the Berlin Museum.

title: Thomas Blatt
complex: Thomas "Toivi" Blatt (born Tomasz Blatt; April 15, 1927 – October 31, 2015) was a Polish-American Holocaust survivor, writer of mémoires, and public speaker, who at the age of 16 escaped from the Sobibór extermination camp during the uprising staged by the Jewish "Sonderkommando" prisoners in October 1943. <s> The escape was attempted by about 300 inmates, many of whom were recaptured and killed by the German search squads. <s> Following World War II Blatt lived in the Soviet-controlled Poland until the Polish October revolution. <s> In 1957, he emigrated to Israel, and in 1958 settled in the United States. <s> Blatt wrote two books about Sobibór. <s> His first mémoire, "From The Ashes of Sobibor" (1997), is about his life before the war and the German occupation of Izbica leading up to the deportation of his family to the Sobibór death camp. <s> His second mémoire titled "Sobibor: the forgotten revolt" (1998) also based on his own experience and supplementary research, and written with the help of his son Leon Blatt, describes the story of the prisoner revolt of October 14, 1943, as remembered by Alexander Pechersky and others. <s> The book material was used as the source for his personal website by the same name. <s> Blatt lived in Santa Barbara, California. <s> He died at his home on October 31, 2015, at the age of 88.
simple: Thomas "Toivi" Blatt (born Tomasz Blatt; April 15, 1927 – October 31, 2015) was a Polish-American writer and speaker. <s> At the age of 16, Blatt was one of the few Jewish people to survive an uprising and escape from the Sobibor extermination camp in October 1943. <s> Blatt later wrote two books about Sobibor. <s> His memoir, "From The Ashes of Sobibor" (1997), is about his experience in the camp. <s> He also wrote "Sobibor, the Forgotten Revolt" (1997), a history based on his years of research. <s> Blatt died at his home in Santa Barbara, California on October 31, 2015 at the age of 88.

title: Salt mining
complex: A salt mine is a mine from which salt is extracted. <s> The mined salt is usually in the form of halite (commonly known as rock salt), and extracted from evaporite formations.
simple: A salt mine is a mine where salt is taken from the earth.

title: Seven (1995 film)
complex: Seven (stylized as SE7EN) is a 1995 American neo-noir crime thriller film directed by David Fincher and written by Andrew Kevin Walker. <s> It stars Brad Pitt, Morgan Freeman, Gwyneth Paltrow, John C. McGinley, R. Lee Ermey, and Kevin Spacey. <s> It tells the story of David Mills, a detective who partners with the retiring William Somerset to track down a serial killer who uses the seven deadly sins as a motif in his murders. <s> Somerset and Mills investigate a set of murders inspired by the seven deadly sins: a man forced to eat until his stomach ruptured, representing gluttony, and a defense attorney killed after a pound of flesh was taken from him, representing greed. <s> Clues at the murder scenes lead them to a suspect's apartment, where they find a third victim, a drug dealer and child molester, strapped to a bed, emaciated but alive, representing sloth.
simple: Seven is a 1995 American neo-noir crime horror thriller movie. <s> It stars Brad Pitt as David Mills and Morgan Freeman as William Somerset, police detectives who are working together to catch serial killer John Doe, played by Kevin Spacey. <s> Doe murders people he believes are guilty of the seven deadly sins.

title: Wookiee
complex: Wookiees are fictional hirsute humanoids in the "Star Wars" universe. <s> They come from the planet Kashyyyk and are taller and stronger than most humans. <s> The most prominent Wookiee is Chewbacca, co-pilot of the "Millennium Falcon" alongside Han Solo. <s> Adult Wookiees are typically taller than most humans, averaging 2.1 m . <s> They possess enormous strength; Solo states that a Wookiee can pull a man's arms out of his sockets if angered or slighted, and in books and comics no humanoid species is shown to equal a Wookiee in pure strength. <s> Wookiees have a keen sense of smell, are fully covered with a thick coat of hair, have good hand–eye coordination, and are shown to be excellent marksmen. <s> Wookiees have been shown in many diverse environments, such as those of Hoth, Tatooine and Endor, never wearing any protective clothing or showing any signs of discomfort. <s> Wookiees have a lifespan of several hundred years. <s> Wookiees greatly value morality, courage, compassion, and loyalty. <s> A sacred and ancient Wookiee tradition is that of the honor family. <s> An honor family comprises a Wookiee's closest friends and companions. <s> These family members pledge a commitment to lay down their lives for one another, as well as members of any honor families these individuals may have. <s> Like the similarly sacred Wookiee life debt, Wookiees are willing to extend this tradition to members outside their species. <s> Chewbacca considered Han Solo, Leia Organa Solo, their children, and Luke Skywalker part of his honor family. <s> The Wookiee language is Shyriiwook. <s> Wookiees are capable of understanding , but generally none are able to speak it because of the structure of Wookiee vocal cords. <s> In the original "Star Wars" trilogy, it seems that Chewbacca can understand humans. <s> His human partner, Han Solo, also shows knowledge of Shyriiwook, or can at least understand Chewbacca; in "Solo" it is shown that Han does indeed have the ability to speak Shyriiwook at a rudimentary level. <s> In the "Star Wars" expanded universe novels, Chewbacca builds a miniature translator droid ("Em Teedee") for his nephew Lowbacca when he later begins training as a Jedi, to facilitate communications with his fellow students.
simple: A Wookiee is a fictional race of aliens from the Star Wars series of movies. <s> Their home planet is Kashyyyk. <s> The best known Wookiee character is Chewbacca. <s> When angered they can pull a man's arms out of their s. Wookiees have a great sense of smell. <s> They are fully covered with a thick coat of hair. <s> Wookiees prize loyalty and above all else. <s> The Wookiee language is Shyriiwook. <s> Wookiees are capable of understanding English but cannot speak it. <s> In the original Star Wars trilogy Chewbacca showed he could understand humans. <s> His human partner, Han Solo, also shows knowledge of Shyriiwook. <s> In the Star Wars expanded universe books, Chewbacca builds a miniature translator droid ("Em Teedee") for his nephew Lowbacca. <s> When Lowbacca begins training as a Jedi the droid helped him communicate with his fellow students.

title: PZL TS-8 Bies
complex: The PZL TS-8 "Bies" is a Polish trainer aircraft, used from 1957 to the 1970s by the Polish Air Force and civilian aviation.
simple: The PZL TS-8 is a Polish military training aircraft built between 1957 and 1959.

title: Ottmarsheim
complex: Ottmarsheim is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France, on Highway 9 just across the Rhein River from its terminus at the German Autobahn Steinenstadt interchange.
simple: Ottmarsheim is a commune. <s> It is found in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France, on Highway 9 just across the Rhine River from its terminus at the German Autobahn Steinenstadt interchange.

title: Andrew of Cornwall
complex: Andrew of Cornwall (Andreas Cornubiensis, Andreas de Cornubia, André de Cornouailles) (fl. 1290s) was a philosopher at Oxford during the 1290s. <s> He is thought to have introduced Parisian Modism into England, and possibly to have influenced the young Duns Scotus. <s> These conclusions are tentative, since we are almost totally ignorant of the details of Andrew's life, and the dates and location of his activities are not certain.
simple: Andrew of Cornwall (Andreas Cornubiensis, Andreas de Cornubia, André de Cornouailles) (fl. 1290s) was a philosopher at Oxford during the 1290s. <s> It is thought that he brought Parisian Modism to England, and that he helped to shape Duns Scotus with his ideas.

title: Bakerhill, Alabama
complex: Bakerhill or Baker Hill is a town in Barbour County, Alabama, United States, near Eufaula. <s> According to the 2010 U.S. Census, the town had a population of 279. <s> Although it existed as an unincorporated village since before 1860, the town was officially incorporated in 1997. <s> Bakerhill is located at 31.88 degrees north, 85.15 degrees west (31.88495, -85.15390).
simple: Bakerhill or Baker Hill is a city in Barbour County, Alabama, United States, near Eufaula. <s> Although it existed as an unincorporated village since before 1860, the city was officially incorporated in 2000. <s> Bakerhill is located at 31.88 degrees north, 85.15 degrees west (31.88495, -85.15390).

title: Skirwith
complex: Skirwith is a village in the English county of Cumbria.
simple: Skirwith is a village in Cumbria, England.

title: Saint-Fraimbault-de-Prières
complex: Saint-Fraimbault-de-Prières is a commune in the Mayenne department in north-western France.
simple: Saint-Fraimbault-de-Prières is a commune of 904 people (1999).

title: Philip K. Dick Award
complex: The Philip K. Dick Award is an American science fiction award given annually at Norwescon and sponsored by the Philadelphia Science Fiction Society and (since 2005) the Philip K. Dick Trust. <s> Named after science fiction and fantasy writer Philip K. Dick, it has been awarded since 1983, the year after his death. <s> It is awarded to the best original paperback published each year in the US. <s> The award was founded by Thomas Disch with assistance from David G. Hartwell, Paul S. Williams, and Charles N. Brown. <s> As of 2016, it is administered by Gordon Van Gelder. <s> Past administrators include Algis Budrys, David G. Hartwell, and David Alexander Smith. <s> Winners are listed in bold. <s> Authors of special citation entries are listed in "italics". <s> The year in the table below indicates the year the book was published; winners are announced the following year.
simple: The Philip K. Dick Award is a science fiction award. <s> It is given at the Norwescon science fiction convention every year. <s> The Philadelphia Science Fiction Society supports the award. <s> The Philip K. Dick Trust has supported the award since 2005. <s> It is named after science fiction and fantasy writer Philip K. Dick. <s> It has been awarded since 1983. <s> The prize is given to the best original paperback published each year in the US. <s> Thomas Disch started this award with help from David G. Hartwell, Paul S. Williams, and Charles N. Brown. <s> David G. Hartwell and Gordon Van Gelder manage the award now. <s> Some other people who have been in charge of the award include Algis Budrys and David Alexander Smith. <s> Winning authors are listed in bold. <s> Authors of books that were given special notice or citations are listed in "italics". <s> The year in the table below tells the year the book was published.

title: Siret (river)
complex: The Siret or Sireth ( , ] , , ) is a river that rises from the Carpathians in the Northern Bukovina region of Ukraine, and flows southward into Romania before it joins the Danube. <s> It is 647 km long, of which 559 km in Romania, and its basin area is 44811 km2 , of which 42890 km2 in Romania. <s> Its average discharge is 250 m3/s . <s> In ancient times, it was named "Hierasus" (Ancient Greek Ιερασός). <s> The following towns and villages are situated along the river Siret, from source to mouth: Berehomet, Storozhynets, Siret, Grămești, Zvoriștea, Liteni, Dolhasca, Pașcani, Stolniceni-Prăjescu, Roman, Bacău, Adjud, Mărășești, Galați. <s> Left: Bahna (Mihăileni), Molnița, Bahna (Lozna), Gârla Sirețel, Gârla Huțanilor, Vorona, Pleșu, Turbata, Pitrosul (or Pietrosul), Trestioara, Sirețel, Sodomeni, Stolniceni, Hărmănești, Pârâul Țigăncilor, Mihailei, Boca, Albuia, Rediu, Vulpășești, Țiganca, Icușești, Glodeni, Râpaș, Moara, Valea Morii, Răcătău, Soci, Fulgeriș, Polocin, Lupa, Bârlad, Călmățui, Geru, Lozova, Valea lui Odobescu, Rusca, Mălina, Cătușa. <s> Right: Malyi Seret, Găvan, Negostina, Pârâul Mare, Verehia, Baranca, Leahu, Hănțești, Grigorești, Sălăgeni, Suceava, Șomuzul Mic, Șomuzul Mare, Probota, Conțeasca, Ruja, Valea Părului, Podul Turcului (or Draga), Tămășeni, Moldova, Valea Neagră, Turbata, Bistrița, Cleja (or Climăuț, or Moise), Răcăciuni, Orbeni, Valea Seacă, Botohan, Fântânele, Conțești, Trotuș, Valea Boului, Carecna, Zăbrăuț, Șușița, Gârla Morilor, Putna, Leica, Râmnicul Sărat, Buzău.
simple: The Siret River (Ukrainian: "Серет", Russian: "Сирет ", Hungarian: "Szeret") is a river that comes up from the Carpathians in the northern Bukovina region of Ukraine. <s> It flows southward into Romania for about 470 kilometers before it joins the Danube. <s> It was named "Hierasus" in times of old. <s> The following towns and villages can be found along the Siret River, from source to mouth: Berehomet, Storozhynets, Siret, Grămeşti, Zvoriştea, Liteni, Paşcani, Stolniceni-Prăjescu, Roman, Bacău, Adjud, Mărăşeşti, Galaţi. <s> Left: Bahna, Molniţa, Bahna, Gârla Sireţel, Gârla Huţanilor, Vorona, Pleşu, Turbata, Pitrosul, Trestioara, Sireţel, Sodomeni, Stolniceni, Hărmăneşti, Pârâul Ţigăncilor, Mihailei, Boca, Albuia, Vulpăşeşti, Ţiganca, Icuşeşti, Glodeni, Râpaş, Pârâul Morii, Răcătău, Fulgeriş, Polocin, Lupa, Bârlad, Călmăţui, Gerului, Mălina, Fălcoaia, Cătuşa. <s> Right: Găvan, Negostina, Verehia, Baranca, Leahu, Hănţeşti, Grigoreşti, Sălăgeni, Suceava, Şomuzul Mic, Şomuzul Mare, Probota, Conţeasca, Ruja, Valea Părului, Podul Turcului, Tămăşeni, Moldova, Valea Neagră, Turbata, Bistriţa, Cleja, Răcăciuni, Orbeni, Botohan, Fântânele, Conţeşti, Trotuş, Valea Boului, Carecna, Zăbrăuţi, Şuşiţa, Gârla Morilor, Putna, Leica, Râmnicul Sărat, Buzău.

title: Ulmaceae
complex: The Ulmaceae are a family of flowering plant that includes the elms (genus "Ulmus"), and the zelkovas (genus "Zelkova"). <s> Members of the family are widely distributed throughout the north temperate zone, and have a scattered distribution elsewhere except for Australasia.
simple: Ulmaceae is a family of flowering plants that includes the elms (genus "Ulmus"), and the zelkovas (genus "Zelkova"). <s> Members of the family are widely distributed throughout the north temperate zone, and have a scattered distribution elsewhere except for Australasia.

title: Guacamole
complex: Guacamole (] ; informally shortened to "guac" in North America since the 1980s) is an avocado-based dip, spread, or salad first developed by the Aztecs in present-day Mexico. <s> In addition to its use in modern Mexican cuisine, it has become part of international and American cuisine as a dip, condiment and salad ingredient.
simple: Guacamole (called Guacamol in Central America and Cuba) is a Mexican dip made of avocados, salt and sometimes tomatoes.

title: Josimar
complex: Josimar Higino Pereira (born 19 September 1961), more commonly known as Josimar, is a Brazilian former footballer. <s> He played right-back mainly with Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas and the Brazilian national team. <s> In his prime, he was named the best right-back in the world by FIFA.
simple: Josimar (born 19 September, 1961) is a former Brazilian football player. <s> He has played for Brazil national team.

title: Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare
complex: Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare is a 1991 American slasher film and the sixth installment in the "Nightmare on Elm Street" series. <s> It is the sequel to "" and was originally supposed to be the concluding chapter of the series; "Wes Craven's New Nightmare" was released after "The Final Nightmare" but takes place outside the series canon. <s> A canonical sequel, "Freddy vs. Jason", was released later. <s> This was New Line Cinema's first 3D film release. <s> Critical reception to the film was very negative upon release. <s> The release of the film was timed for September 13 in 1991 being a friday the 13th, as is the practice for fellow slasher franchise "Friday the 13th". <s> Robert Englund reprises his role as Freddy Krueger. <s> The film stars Lisa Zane, Yaphet Kotto, Breckin Meyer, Shon Greenblatt, Ricky Dean Logan, Lezlie Deane, and Tobe Sexton. <s> Additionally, several well-known actors make cameo appearances in the film, including Johnny Depp (whose screen debut was in the original "A Nightmare on Elm Street"), Roseanne Barr, Tom Arnold, and Alice Cooper. <s> Iggy Pop sings the title song, which plays during the end credits over a montage of scenes from the previous "Nightmare" films. <s> "Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare" made $12,966,525 in its opening weekend, which was the highest opening weekend for the series until the release of "Freddy vs. Jason". <s> After its initial run, the film grossed a total of $34,872,033 in the United States, making it the fifth-highest-grossing film in the series. <s> The soundtrack for the film was released on September 24, 1991, by Warner Bros. <s> Although not included on the soundtrack, the song "In-a-Gadda-Da-Vida" by Iron Butterfly is featured in the film.
simple: Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare is a 1991 American comedy horror slasher movie and the sixth movie in the "Nightmare on Elm Street" series. <s> It is the sequel to "" and is followed by "Wes Craven's New Nightmare". <s> This was New Line Cinema's first movie released in 3-D. <s> Upon its release, the movie received a poor critical reception. <s> Robert Englund reprises his role as Freddy Krueger; Lisa Zane, Yaphet Kotto, Breckin Meyer, Shon Greenblatt, Ricky Dean Logan, Lezlie Deane and Tobe Sexton also star. <s> The movie made $34.9 million in the box office. <s> It was released on September 13, 1991.

title: Hückel's rule
complex: In organic chemistry, Hückel's rule estimates whether a planar ring molecule will have aromatic properties. <s> The quantum mechanical basis for its formulation was first worked out by physical chemist Erich Hückel in 1931. <s> The succinct expression as the 4"n" + 2 rule has been attributed to W. v. E. Doering (1951), although several authors were using this form at around the same time.
simple: In organic chemistry, Hückel's rule is a rule that help to determine if a molecule has the properties of an aromatic compound. <s> It is named after chemist Erich Hückel, who formulated it in 1931.

title: Acton, London
complex: Acton is an area of west London, England, within the London Borough of Ealing. <s> It is 6.1 mi west of Charing Cross.
simple: Acton is a district of west London. <s> It is in the London Borough of Ealing.

title: Balochistan, Pakistan
complex: Balochistan ( ; ) is one of the four provinces of Pakistan. <s> It is the largest province in terms of land area, forming the southwestern region of the country, but is the least populated. <s> Its provincial capital and largest city is Quetta. <s> The main ethnic groups in the province are the Baloch people and the Pashtuns, who constitute 52% and 36% of the population respectively (according to the preliminary 2011 census). <s> The remaining 12% comprises smaller communities of Brahuis, Hazaras along with other settlers such as Sindhis, Punjabis, Uzbeks and Turkmens. <s> The name "Balochistan" means "the land of the Baloch". <s> Largely underdeveloped, its provincial economy is dominated by natural resources, especially its natural gas fields, estimated to have sufficient capacity to supply Pakistan's demands over the medium to long term. <s> Aside from Quetta, the second-largest city of the province is Turbat in the south, while another area of major economic importance is Gwadar Port on the Arabian Sea. <s> Balochistan is situated in the southwest of Pakistan and covers an area of 347,190 km2 . <s> It is Pakistan's largest province by area, constituting 44% of Pakistan's total land mass. <s> The province is bordered by Afghanistan to the north and north-west, Iran to the south-west, Punjab and Sindh, and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and the Federally Administered Tribal Areas to the north-east. <s> To the south lies the Arabian Sea. <s> Balochistan is located on the south-eastern part of the Iranian plateau. <s> It borders the geopolitical regions of the Middle East and Southwest Asia, Central Asia and South Asia. <s> Balochistan lies at the mouth of the Strait of Hormuz and provides the shortest route from seaports to Central Asia. <s> Its geographical location has placed the otherwise desolate region in the scope of competing global interests for all of recorded history. <s> The capital city Quetta is located in a densely populated portion of the Sulaiman Mountains in the north-east of the province. <s> It is situated in a river valley near the Bolan Pass, which has been used as the route of choice from the coast to Central Asia, entering through Afghanistan's Kandahar region. <s> The British and other historic empires have crossed the region to invade Afghanistan by this route. <s> Balochistan is rich in exhaustible and
