renewable resources; it is the second major supplier of natural gas in Pakistan. <s> The province's renewable and human resource potential has not been systematically measured or exploited due to pressures from within and without Pakistan. <s> Local inhabitants have chosen to live in towns and have relied on sustainable water sources for thousands of years. <s> In common with the other provinces of Pakistan, Balochistan has a parliamentary form of government. <s> The ceremonial head of the province is the Governor, who is appointed by the President of Pakistan on the advice of the provincial Chief Minister. <s> The Chief Minister, the province's chief executive, is normally the leader of the largest political party or alliance of parties in the provincial assembly. <s> The unicameral Provincial Assembly of Balochistan comprises 65 seats of which 11 are reserved for women and 3 reserved for non-Muslims. <s> The judicial branch of government is carried out by the Balochistan High Court, which is based in Quetta and headed by a Chief Justice.
simple: Balochistan is a province in Pakistan. <s> The capital of Balochistan is Quetta. <s> There are also relatively smaller communities of Iranian Baloch, Hazaras, Sindhis and other settlers, including Punjabis, Uzbeks, and Turkmens. <s> The name Balochistan means "the land of the Baloch" in many regional languages. <s> Balochistan has a population of about 10 million people and an area of 134,051 mi or (347,190 km). <s> Balochistan is situated in the south-west of Pakistan and covers an area of 347,190 km2. <s> It covers 45% of Pakistani territory; in terms of area the province of Balochistan is greater in area than Republic of the Congo but smaller than Germany. <s> It is Pakistan's largest province by area constituting 44% of Pakistan's total land mass. <s> The province is bordered by Afghanistan to the north and north-west, Iran to the south-west, Punjab and Sindh, and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and the Federally Administered Tribal Areas to the north-east. <s> To the south lies the Arabian Sea. <s> Balochistan is located on the south-eastern part of the Iranian plateau. <s> It borders the geopolitical regions of the Greater Middle East and Southwest Asia, Central Asia and South-central Asia. <s> Balochistan lies at the mouth of the Strait of Hormuz and provides the shortest route from seaports to Central Asia. <s> Its geographical location has placed the otherwise desolate region in the scopes of competing global interests like Afghanistan for all of recorded history. <s> The capital city Quetta is located in a densely populated portion of the Sulaiman Mountains in the north-east of the province. <s> It is situated in a river valley near the Bolan Pass which has been used as the route of choice from the coast to Central Asia, entering through Afghanistan's Kandahar region. <s> The British and other historic empires have crossed the region to invade Afghanistan by this route. <s> Balochistan is rich in exhaustible and renewable resources; it is the second major supplier of natural gas in Pakistan. <s> The province's renewable and human resource potential has not been systematically measured nor exploited due to pressures from within and without Pakistan. <s> Local inhabitants have chosen to live in towns and have relied on sustainable water sources for thousands of years. <s> In common with the other provinces of Pakistan, Balochistan has a parliamentary form of government. <s> The ceremonial head of the province is the Governor, who is appointed by the President of Pakistan on the advice of the provincial Chief Minister. <s> The chief executive of the province is the Chief Minister who is normally the leader of the largest party or alliance in the provincial assembly. <s> The unicameral Provincial Assembly of Balochistan comprises 65 seats of which 4% are reserved for non-Muslims and 16% for women only. <s> The judicial branch of government is carried out by the Balochistan High Court, based in Quetta, and headed by a Chief Justice.

title: Fatima (given name)
complex: Fatima is a female given name of Arabic origin used throughout the Islamic world. <s> Several relatives of the Islamic prophet Muhammad had the name, including his daughter Fatimah as the most famous one. <s> The colloquial Arabic pronunciation of the name in some dialects (e.g., Syrian and Egyptian) often omits the unstressed second syllable and renders it as "Fatma" when romanized. <s> Fatima is also used by non-Muslims: the town of Fátima, Portugal was named after a Moorish princess. <s> It was the site of a famous Marian apparition in 1917, after which it achieved some popularity as a female personal name among Roman Catholic populations, particularly in the Portuguese-speaking and Spanish-speaking worlds.
simple: Fatima (Arabic: فَاطِمَة‎, "Fāṭimah") is a female given name of Arabic origin used throughout the Islamic world. <s> Several relatives of the Islamic prophet Muhammad had the name, including his daughter Fatimah <s> The colloquial Arabic pronunciation of the name in some dialects (e.g., Syria and Egyptian ) often omits the unstressed second syllable and renders it as "Fatma" when romanized. <s> Fatima is also used by non-Muslims: the town of Fátima, Portugal was named after a Moorish princess. <s> It was the site of a famous Marian apparition in 1917, after which it achieved some popularity as a female personal name among Roman Catholic populations, particularly in the Portuguese-speaking and Spanish-speaking worlds.

title: Talking past each other
complex: Talking past each other is an English phrase describing the situation where two or more people talk about different subjects, while believing that they are talking about the same thing. <s> The idiomatic expression is an allusion to the interaction between Thrasymachus and Socrates over the question of "justice" in Plato's "Republic I." In their dialogue, neither man addressed any of the issues raised by the other and two different concepts which need not have been disputed are somehow confused. <s> In fictional dialogue, when characters "talk past each other ... they are said to expose an unbridgeable gulf between their respective perceptions and intentions. <s> The result is an exchange, but never an interchange, of words in fragmented and cramped utterances ..." <s> The phrase is used in widely varying contexts. <s> For example, in 1917, Albert Einstein and David Hilbert had dawn-to-dusk discussions of physics; and they continued their debate in writing, although Felix Klein records that they "talked past each other, as happens not infrequently between simultaneously producing mathematicians."
simple: Talking past each other is an idiom. <s> The phrase describes a situation in which people communicate at cross purposes. <s> In talking past each other, two different concepts which need not have been disputed are somehow confused or conflated. <s> The idiom applies to disputes in which neither side addressed any of the issues raised by the other. <s> In fictional dialogue, when characters talk past each other, the result is an exchange with flaws or defects. <s> The phrase is used in many contexts.

title: Sisimiut
complex: Sisimiut, formerly known by its colonial name Holsteinsborg, is the capital and largest city of the Qeqqata municipality, and the second-largest city in Greenland, and the largest arctic city in North America. <s> It is located in central-western Greenland, on the coast of Davis Strait, approximately 320 km north of Nuuk.
simple: Sisimiut (also known by its Danish name 'Holsteinsborg') is a town in southwestern Greenland.

title: Ulricehamn Municipality
complex: Ulricehamn Municipality ("Ulricehamns kommun") is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in western Sweden. <s> Its seat is located in the city of Ulricehamn.
simple: Ulricehamn Municipality is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Ulricehamn.

title: Kaufland
complex: Kaufland ] is a German hypermarket chain, part of the Schwarz Gruppe which also owns Lidl and Handelshof. <s> It opened its first store in 1984 in Neckarsulm and quickly expanded to become a leader in what was formerly East Germany. <s> The chain operates over 1,200 stores in Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland, Romania, Bulgaria and Croatia. <s> Kaufland plans to open stores in Australia, and Moldova.
simple: Kaufland ] is a German hypermarket chain, part of the Schwarz Gruppe which also owns Lidl and Handelshof. <s> In 1984, the first store was opened in Neckarsulm and quickly expanded to become a leader in what was formerly East Germany. <s> The chain operates over 1,200 stores in Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland, Romania, Bulgaria and Croatia. <s> Kaufland plans to open stores in Australia, and Moldova.

title: Vera Tembo
complex: Vera Tembo (born July 25, 1953) is a Zambian politician and member of the Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD). <s> She served as the First Lady of Zambia from 1991 until her separation from her former husband, President Frederick Chiluba. <s> Tembo was married to Frederick Chiluba, with whom she had nine children, for thirty-three years, until he announced their separation in 2000. <s> Chiluba became President of Zambia in 1991, making Tembo the country's First Lady from 1991 until their divorce. <s> Tembo left the State House, the presidential residence, shortly after Chiluba's announcement and moved in with family in Ndola. <s> Their divorce became final on September 25, 2001, when an annulment was granted by a local court in Ndola after thirty-three years of marriage. <s> By early 2002, Zambian newspapers reported that Tembo was living in poverty after Chiluba had allegedly frozen her bank account. <s> She filed a $2.5 U.S. dollar lawsuit against Chiluba as part of the divorce settlement. <s> The Zambian government offered Tembo financial assistance in May 2002 after she listed her personal possessions in an auction. <s> In March 2015, Vera Tembo announced that she had become a Christian pastor and had founded a new church called the Healing International Ministry.
simple: Vera Tembo (born July 25, 1953) is a Zambian pastor, politician and member of the Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD). <s> She has served as the First Lady of [Zambia] from 1991 until her separation from her former husband, President Frederick Chiluba. <s> Tembo was married to Chiluba, with whom she had nine children, for thirty-three years, until he announced their separation in 2000. <s> Chiluba became President of Zambia in 1991, making Tembo the country's First Lady from 1991 until their divorce. <s> Tembo left the State House, the presidential residence, shortly after Chiluba's announcement and moved in with family in Ndola. <s> Their divorce became final on September 25, 2001, when an annulment was granted by a local court in Ndola after thirty-three years of marriage. <s> By early 2002, Zambian newspapers reported that Tembo was living in poverty after Chiluba had allegedly frozen her bank account. <s> She filed a $2.5 U.S. dollar lawsuit against Chiluba as part of the divorce settlement. <s> The Zambian government offered Tembo financial assistance in May 2002 after she listed her personal possessions in an auction. <s> In March 2015, Tembo announced that she had become a Christian pastor and had founded a new church called the Healing International Ministry.

title: Béla Magyari
complex: Béla Magyari (8 August 1949 – 23 April 2018) was a colonel in the Hungarian Air Force. <s> He graduated from the György Kilián Air Force Academy in 1969. <s> Born in Kiskunfélegyháza, he was selected as the back-up for Bertalan Farkas, the first Hungarian cosmonaut who flew to space on Soyuz 36, but he himself never flew. <s> He graduated from the Budapest Technical University in 1986. <s> He spent his active career as an aeronautical engineer and pilot. <s> He was also president of the Hungarian Astronautical Society and worked for the Hungarian Space Office.
simple: Béla Magyari (8 August 1949 – 23 April 2018) was a Hungarian military official and engineer. <s> He was Colonel of the Hungarian Air Force. <s> Magyari died on 23 April 2018 in Budapest at the age of 68. <s> He graduated from the Hungarian Airforce Academy "György Kilián" in 1969. <s> He used to be the President of the Hungarian Astronautical Society and worked for the Hungarian Space Office.

title: Riffat Hassan
complex: Riffat Hassan (born 1943) is a Pakistani-American theologian and a leading Islamic feminist scholar of the Qur'an.
simple: Riffat Hassan (born 1943 in Lahore) is a Pakistani-American feminist and Islamic scholar of the Quran.

title: Surfactant
complex: Surfactants are compounds that lower the surface tension (or interfacial tension) between two liquids, between a gas and a liquid, or between a liquid and a solid. <s> Surfactants may act as detergents, wetting agents, emulsifiers, foaming agents, and dispersants.
simple: A surfactant is a chemical that lowers the surface tension of a liquid.

title: Alan Davies
complex: Alan Roger Davies ( ; born 6 March 1966) is an English stand-up comedian, writer and actor. <s> He has played the title role in the BBC mystery drama series "Jonathan Creek" since 1997, and has been the only permanent panellist on the BBC panel show "QI" since 2003, outlasting hosts Stephen Fry (2003–16) and Sandi Toksvig (2016–present) who took over after Fry's exit. <s> Davies was born in Loughton, Essex. <s> His childhood years were spent in Chingford. <s> When Davies was six, his mother died from leukaemia and he was raised by his father. <s> Davies attended Staples Road School in Loughton and was privately educated at the independent Bancroft's School in Woodford Green, where he gained eight O-Levels. <s> He then moved on to Loughton College of Further Education where he gained four more O-Levels and two A-Levels (Communications & Theatre Studies). <s> He graduated in Drama & Theatre Studies from the University of Kent in 1988, and was awarded an Honorary Doctorate by the university in 2003. <s> Davies married writer Katie Maskell on 13 January 2007 after a six-month engagement. <s> The couple first met backstage at "QI" in 2005. <s> Friend and comedy partner Bill Bailey was Davies's best man. <s> Davies and his wife have three children. <s> In late 2007 "The Times" and "The Daily Telegraph" both reported that Davies bit the ear of a homeless man. <s> Davies had just left a wake at the nearby Groucho Club. <s> He told "The Times" in 2009, "He wasn't a tramp. <s> He was a raging, horrendous arsehole. <s> He called me a cunt several times. <s> Or if it wasn't him, it was his mate. <s> And, yes, I went for him and, yes, I did it in what turned out to be an amusing way." <s> Following the incident, Davies was banned from the Groucho Club. <s> Davies is a lifelong fan and season ticket holder of Arsenal F.C.. <s> Davies also used to host the podcast "It's Up For Grabs Now" which took a light-hearted look at goings on at the club. <s> On 18 January 2011, he began hosting the new Arsenal Podcast "The Tuesday Club" with Ian Stone, Keith Dover, Tayo Popoola and Skint Records founder Damian Harris. <s> His support of Arsenal has been used as a recurring source of humour on "QI" in various ways, such as by assigning him a buzzer sound of a chant by fans of rival club Manchester United. <s> Davies's first book, the autobiographical "My Favourite People and Me, 1978–88" was published by Michael Joseph (Penguin Books) in September 2009. <s> Of the memoir, Davies said he wished to "attempt to remember what I liked as a boy/youth/idiot and to work out why".
simple: Alan Davies (born 6 March 1966) is an English comedian, writer and actor. <s> He is best known for starring in Jonathan Creek and for being a panellist on QI. <s> Davies was born in Loughton, Essex. <s> His childhood years were spent in Chingford, London. <s> Davies' mother died when he was six. <s> He graduated in Drama from the University of Kent in 1988. <s> Davies married writer Katie Maskell on 13 January 2007 after a 6-month engagement. <s> The couple met backstage at "QI" in 2005. <s> "The Times" and "Daily Telegraph" reported that Davies was involved in a fight and bit the ear of a homeless man. <s> Davies had just left a wake at the nearby Groucho Club. <s> Davies is no longer allowed at the Groucho Club. <s> Davies is a fan of Arsenal F.C. and a season ticket holder. <s> Davies' first book, the autobiographical "My Favourite People and Me, 1978-88", was published by Penguin Books in late 2009.

title: Stanisław Lem
complex: Stanisław Herman Lem (] ; 12 or 13 September 1921 – 27 March 2006) was a Polish writer of science fiction, philosophy, and satire, and a trained physician. <s> Lem's books have been translated into 41 languages and have sold over 45 million copies. <s> From the 1950s to 2000s, he published many books, both science fiction and philosophical/futurological. <s> He is best known as the author of the 1961 novel "Solaris", which has been made into a feature film three times. <s> In 1976, Theodore Sturgeon wrote that Lem was the most widely read science fiction writer in the world. <s> Lem is one of the most highly acclaimed science fiction writers, hailed by critics as equal to such classic authors as H. G. Wells and Olaf Stapledon. <s> In 1976, Theodore Sturgeon wrote that Lem was the most widely read science fiction writer in the world. <s> His works were widely translated abroad, appearing in over 40 languages, though the bulk of them were in Eastern Bloc countries (Poland, Germany, and the Soviet Union). <s> Franz Rottensteiner, Lem's former agent abroad, had this to say about Lem's reception on international markets: His best-known novels include "Solaris" (1961), "His Master's Voice" ("Głos pana", 1968), and the late "Fiasco" ("Fiasko", 1987). <s> "Solaris" was made into a film in 1968 by Russian director Boris Nirenburg, a film in 1972 by Russian director Andrei Tarkovsky—which won a Special Jury Prize at the Cannes Film Festival in 1972—and an American film in 2002 by Steven Soderbergh.
simple: Stanisław Herman Lem (September 12, 1921 – March 27, 2006) was a Polish science fiction writer. <s> His books have been translated into 41 languages. <s> Over 27 million copies of his books have been sold worldwide. <s> Lem is perhaps best known for his novel "Solaris". <s> This novel was published in 1961. <s> At one point he was among the most widely read science fiction authors in the world. <s> This book has also been made into a film by Andrei Tarkowski in 1972.

title: The Conjuring 2
complex: The Conjuring 2 is a 2016 American supernatural horror film, directed by James Wan. <s> The screenplay is by Chad Hayes, Carey W. Hayes, Wan, and David Leslie Johnson. <s> It is the sequel to 2013's "The Conjuring", the second installment in "The Conjuring" series, and the third installment in the Conjuring Universe franchise. <s> Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga reprise their roles as paranormal investigators and authors Ed and Lorraine Warren from the first film. <s> The film follows the Warrens as they travel to Britain to assist the Hodgson family, who are experiencing poltergeist activity at their Enfield council house in 1977 which later became referred to as the Enfield poltergeist. <s> "The Conjuring 2" had its world premiere at TCL Chinese Theatre on June 7, 2016, and was theatrically released in the United States on June 10, 2016, by Warner Bros. <s> Pictures and New Line Cinema. <s> The film received generally positive reviews from critics—who praised the performances, Wan's direction, screenplay, atmosphere and Joseph Bishara's musical score—and grossed over $320million worldwide. <s> A spin-off prequel, "The Nun", was released on September 7, 2018. <s> A sequel, "The Conjuring 3", is currently in production.
simple: The Conjuring 2 is a 2016 American horror movie directed by James Wan. <s> It is the sequel to 2013's "The Conjuring" and the third movie in "The Conjuring" series. <s> Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga reprise their roles as paranormal investigators and authors Ed and Lorraine Warren from the first movie. <s> The movie is about the Warrens as they travel to England to help the Hodgson family, who are experiencing poltergeist activity in Enfield council house in 1977. <s> This event became referred to as the Enfield Poltergeist. <s> "The Conjuring 2" was released in North America on June 10, 2016. <s> The movie received positive reviews from critics and has made over $320 million worldwide. <s> A spin-off prequel movie, "The Nun", is scheduled to be released in 2018.

title: Ismail Hussain
complex: Ismail Hussain (1 April 1950 – 24 April 2015) was an Indian politician who was a member of the Indian Parliament representing the Barpeta (Lok Sabha constituency) for the Indian National Congress party.
simple: Ismail Hussain (1 April 1950 – 24 April 2015) was an Indian politician. <s> He was a member of the Indian Parliament representing the Barpeta (Lok Sabha constituency) for the Indian National Congress party.

title: Emile Roemer
complex: Emile Gerardus Maria Roemer (born 24 August 1962) is a Dutch politician of the Socialist Party (SP). <s> He was the Parliamentary leader of the Socialist Party in the House of Representatives and the leader of the Socialist Party from 5 March 2010 until 13 December 2017 and a member of the House of Representatives from 30 November 2006 until 18 January 2018.
simple: Emile Gerardus Maria Roemer (born August 24, 1962 in Boxmeer) is a Dutch politician of the Socialist Party (SP). <s> He was political and parliamentary leader from March 5, 2010 to December 13, 2017. <s> He was a member of the Second Chamber from 2006 to 2018.

title: Al Quie
complex: Albert Harold "Al" Quie (born September 18, 1923) is an American politician who served as the 35th governor of Minnesota from January 4, 1979, to January 3, 1983. <s> Quie was born on his family's farm near Dennison, Minnesota, in Rice County. <s> Three of his grandparents were Norwegian immigrants.
simple: Albert Harold "Al" Quie (born September 18, 1923) is an American politician. <s> He was the 35th Governor of Minnesota, from January 4, 1979 to January 3, 1983. <s> Quie was born in Dennison, Minnesota.

title: Nobuo Kawakami
complex: Nobuo Kawakami (川上 信夫 , Kawakami Nobuo , born October 4, 1947) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Nobuo Kawakami (川上 信夫, Kawakami Nobuo, born October 4, 1947) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: Saline County, Nebraska
complex: Saline County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 14,200. <s> Its county seat is Wilber. <s> Saline County was formed in 1855 and organized in 1867. <s> The first permanent settler arrived in 1858.
simple: Saline County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 census, 14,200 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Wilber. <s> It was founded in 1855.

title: San Jacinto County, Texas
complex: San Jacinto County is a county in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> As of the 2010 census, its population was 26,384. <s> Its county seat is Coldspring. <s> The county's name comes from the Battle of San Jacinto which, in 1836, secured Texas' independence from Mexico and established a republic.
simple: San Jacinto County is a county in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> In 2010, 26,384 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Coldspring.

title: Bredbury
complex: Bredbury is a suburban town in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport, Greater Manchester, England, 7.9 mi south-east of Manchester, 1.8 mi east of Stockport and 3.2 mi south-west of Hyde. <s> At the 2011 census, it had a population of 13,593.
simple: Bredbury is a village in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport, in Greater Manchester, England. <s> Bredbury is found 7 mi southeast of the city of Manchester, and 2 mi east-northeast of Stockport.

title: Sprint (running)
complex: In athletics and track and field, sprints (or dashes) are races over short distances. <s> They are among the oldest running competitions, being recorded at the Ancient Olympic Games.
simple: Sprints are short running races in athletics.

title: TV Tokyo
complex: TV Tokyo Corporation (or TX) (株式会社テレビ東京 , Kabushiki-gaisha Terebi Tōkyō ) is a television station headquartered in Roppongi, Minato, Tokyo, Japan. <s> Also known as "Teleto" (テレ東 , Teretō ) , a blend of "terebi" and "Tokyo", it is the flagship station of TX Network. <s> It is one of the major Tokyo television stations, particularly specializing in anime. <s> The station is partly owned by the "Nihon Keizai Shimbun".
simple: TV Tokyo is a television station in Tokyo, Japan. <s> It is also known as "Teleto," a portmanteau of "terebi," the Japanese word for "television," and "Tokyo." <s> Its main owner is Nihon Keizai Shimbun.

title: Tokyo Verdy
complex: Tokyo Verdy (東京ヴェルディ , Tōkyō Verudi ) is a Japanese professional football club, based in Tokyo, Japan, that plays in J2 League.
simple: Tokyo Verdy (東京ヴェルディ, Tōkyō Verudi) is a Japanese professional football club in Tokyo.

title: Statue
complex: A statue is a free-standing sculpture in which the realistic, full-length figures of persons or animals or non-representational forms are carved in a durable material like wood, metal, or stone. <s> Typical statues are life-sized or close to life-size; a sculpture that represents persons or animals in full figure but that is small enough to lift and carry is a statuette or figurine, while one more than twice life-size is a colossal statue.
simple: Statues are often at least life-size (the same size as the real person), but often they are much bigger, especially statues in the open air.

title: Skin Yard
complex: Skin Yard was an American grunge band from Seattle, Washington, who were active from 1985 to 1993. <s> The group never gained a mainstream audience, but were an influence on several of their grunge contemporaries, including Soundgarden, Screaming Trees, and Green River.
simple: Skin Yard was a rock band from Seattle, Washington, who were active from 1985 to 1992. <s> The group never gained any mainstream audience, but were an influence on their contemporaries – most notably Soundgarden, The Melvins, and Green River – alongside whom they are considered the early pioneers of the sound that would later be called grunge.

title: Narita International Airport
complex: Narita International Airport (成田国際空港 , Narita Kokusai Kūkō ) , also known as Tokyo Narita Airport, formerly and originally known as New Tokyo International Airport (新東京国際空港 , Shin Tōkyō Kokusai Kūkō ) , is an international airport serving the Greater Tokyo Area of Japan. <s> It is located approximately 60 km east of central Tokyo in the Chiba Prefecture, straddling the border between the city of Narita and the adjacent town of Shibayama.
simple: Narita International Airport (成田国際空港, Narita Kokusai Kūkō) is a Japanese airport in Chiba, near Tokyo.

title: Kälarne
complex: Kälarne is a locality situated in Bräcke Municipality, Jämtland County, Sweden with 451 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Kälarne is a locality in Bräcke Municipality in Jämtland County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 451 people lived there.

title: Duisans
complex: Duisans is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Duisans is a commune.

title: The Destruction of Sodom And Gomorrah
complex: The destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah is a painting by the English painter John Martin from 1852. <s> John Martin's painting, shows the biblical story of the destruction of the two cities of Sodom and Gomorrah, which was God's punishment for the two cities for people's immoral behavior. <s> Only Lot and his daughters were saved. <s> Lot's wife disobeyed God's instruction not to look back, and was turned into a pillar of salt. <s> The fiery red color is characteristic of John Martin's dramatic scenes of destruction. <s> The swirling storm in heaven was also a frequent feature of his paintings. <s> It is 136.3 x 212.3 cm. <s> It is in the collection of the Laing Art Gallery in Newcastle upon Tyne.
simple: The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah is a painting by John Martin (1789-1854). <s> Martin painted it in 1852. <s> "The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah" was the last painting that Martin finished. <s> The painting shows the destruction of the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah from the Bible. <s> Lot's wife looked back and became a pillar of salt. <s> The painting has a red color and a storm in the sky, typical of Martin's work. <s> "The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah" is in the Laing Art Gallery in Newcastle, England.

title: Totem and Taboo
complex: Totem and Taboo: Resemblances Between the Mental Lives of Savages and Neurotics, or Totem and Taboo: Some Points of Agreement between the Mental Lives of Savages and Neurotics, is a 1913 book by Sigmund Freud, the founder of psychoanalysis, in which the author applies his work to the fields of archaeology, anthropology, and the study of religion. <s> It is a collection of four essays inspired by the work of Wilhelm Wundt and Carl Jung and first published in the journal "Imago" (1912–13): "The Horror of Incest", "Taboo and Emotional Ambivalence", "Animism, Magic and the Omnipotence of Thoughts", and "The Return of Totemism in Childhood".
simple: Totem and Taboo is a book by Sigmund Freud.

title: Red Barber
complex: Walter Lanier "Red" Barber (February 17, 1908 – October 22, 1992) was an American sports commentator. <s> Barber, nicknamed "The Ol' Redhead", was primarily identified with radio broadcasts of Major League Baseball, calling play-by-play across four decades with the Cincinnati Reds (1934–1938), Brooklyn Dodgers (1939–1953), and New York Yankees (1954–1966). <s> Like his fellow sports pioneer Mel Allen, Barber also gained a niche calling college and professional American football in his primary market of New York City.
simple: Walter Lanier "Red" Barber (February 17, 1908October 22, 1992) was an American sports commentator. <s> Barber, nicknamed ""The Ol' Redhead"", by the radio broadcasts of Major League Baseball. <s> He broadcasted for forty years with the Cincinnati Reds (193438), Brooklyn Dodgers (19391953), and New York Yankees (19541966).

title: Opel Signum
complex: The Opel Signum is a large family car that was engineered and manufactured by the German automaker Opel from 2003 to 2008. <s> It was almost exclusively sold in Europe. <s> In the United Kingdom, it was rebadged and sold under the Vauxhall Signum name. <s> The Opel Signum was largely based on the Opel Vectra, and used the long wheelbase version of the GM Epsilon platform, also used by the Opel Vectra Caravan.
simple: The Opel Signum is a automobile produced by Opel. <s> It was sold in the UK as the Vauxhall Signum.

title: The Mall, London
complex: The Mall is a road in the City of Westminster, central London, between Buckingham Palace at its western end and Trafalgar Square via Admiralty Arch to the east. <s> Near the east end at Trafalgar Square/Whitehall it is met by Horse Guards Road and Spring Gardens where the Metropolitan Board of Works and London County Council were once based. <s> It is closed to traffic on Saturdays, Sundays, public holidays and on ceremonial occasions. <s> The Mall was envisioned as a ceremonial route in the early 20th century, matching the creation of similar ceremonial routes in other cities such as Berlin, Mexico City, Oslo, Paris, Saint Petersburg, Vienna and Washington, D.C. <s> These routes were intended to be used for major national ceremonies. <s> As part of the development – designed by Aston Webb – a new façade was constructed for Buckingham Palace, and the Victoria Memorial was erected. <s> The Victoria Memorial is immediately before the gates of the Palace, whilst Admiralty Arch at the far end leads into Trafalgar Square. <s> The length of The Mall from where it joins Constitution Hill at the Victoria Memorial end to Admiralty Arch is exactly 0.5 nmi . <s> St. James's Park is on the south side of The Mall, opposite Green Park and St James's Palace, on the north side. <s> Running off The Mall at its eastern end is Horse Guards Parade, where the Trooping the Colour ceremony is held. <s> The surface of The Mall is coloured red to give the effect of a giant red carpet leading up to Buckingham Palace. <s> This colour was obtained using synthetic iron oxide pigment from Deanshanger Oxide Works (Deanox), which was created using the Deanox Process devised by chemist Ernest Lovell. <s> It was David Eccles' decision, as Minister of Works from 1951 to 1954, to make The Mall red. <s> On VE Day (8 May 1945), the Palace was the centre of British celebrations, with the King, Queen and Princess Elizabeth (the future queen) and Princess Margaret appearing on the balcony, with the Palace's blacked-out windows behind them, to the cheers from a vast crowd on The Mall. <s> During state visits, the monarch and the visiting head of state are escorted in a state carriage up The Mall and the street is decorated with Union Flags and the flags of the visiting head of state's country. <s> During the Golden Jubilee celebrations of Queen Elizabeth II in 2002, over one million people packed The Mall to watch the public displays and the appearance of the Royal Family on the palace balcony. <s> These scenes were repeated in 2011 for the wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton, and again in 2012 for the Queen's Diamond Jubilee, and the Jubilee concert.
simple: The Mall is a short but important road in London. <s> It runs from Buckingham Palace at its western end to Whitehall, right near Trafalgar Square. <s> It is closed to traffic on Sundays and public holidays, and on ceremonial occasions. <s> The Mall was built as a ceremonial route in the early 20th century. <s> There are similar ceremonial routes in cities such as Berlin, Mexico City, Oslo, Paris, Saint Petersburg, Vienna and Washington, D.C.. <s> These routes are often used for major national ceremonies. <s> When the Mall was built, a new façade (front face) was constructed for Buckingham Palace, and the Victoria Memorial was erected. <s> The Queen Victoria Memorial is in front of the gates of the Palace, whilst Admiralty Arch at the far end leads into Trafalgar Square. <s> The length of The Mall from where it joins Constitution Hill at the Victoria Memorial end to Admiralty Arch is exactly 0.5 nmi. <s> St. James's Park is on the south side of The Mall, opposite Green Park and St James's Palace, on the north side. <s> Running off The Mall at its eastern end is Horse Guards Parade, where the Trooping the Colour ceremony is held. <s> The surface of The Mall is coloured red to give the effect of a giant red carpet leading up to Buckingham Palace. <s> This colour was obtained using synthetic iron oxide pigment from Deanshanger Oxide Works (Deanox), which was created using the Deanox Process devised by chemist Ernest Lovell. <s> On VE Day – 8 May 1945 – the Palace was the centre of British celebrations. <s> The King, Queen and Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret were on the balcony behind them, to the cheers from a vast crowd on The Mall. <s> During state visits, the monarch and the visiting head of state are escorted in a state carriage up The Mall, and the street is decorated with Union Flags and the flags of the visiting head of state's country. <s> During the Golden Jubilee celebrations of Queen Elizabeth II in 2002, over one million people packed The Mall to watch the public displays and the appearance of the Royal Family on the palace balcony. <s> These scenes were repeated in 2011 for the wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton, and again in 2012 for the Queen's Diamond Jubilee, and the Diamond Jubilee concert.

title: Bucklesham
complex: Bucklesham is a village and civil parish in the East Suffolk district of Suffolk, England, a few miles east of Ipswich.
simple: Bucklesham is a village and civil parish in Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England.

title: Hearse
complex: A hearse is a vehicle used to carry the dead in a coffin/casket. <s> They range from deliberately anonymous vehicles to very formal heavily decorated vehicles.
simple: A hearse is a car used to transport a coffin.

title: Maravar
complex: Maravar (also known as Maravan and Marava) are a Tamil community in the state of Tamil Nadu. <s> These people are one of the three branches of the Mukkulathor confederacy. <s> Members of the Maravar community often use the honorific title "Thevar". <s> The term "Maravar" has diverse proposed etymologies; it may come simply from a Tamil word "maravar" (warrior), or a term meaning "bravery".
simple: Maravar is a Tamil community of the state of Tamil Nadu, southern India, and are one of the three branches of the Mukkulathor confederacy or league of caste.Members of the Maravar community often use the honorific title "Thevar".T <s> The term "Maravar" has diverse proposed etymologies; it may come simply from a Tamil word "maravar" (warrior), or a term meaning "bravery".

title: The Big Parade
complex: The Big Parade is a 1925 American silent war drama film directed by King Vidor, starring John Gilbert, Renée Adorée, Hobart Bosworth, Tom O'Brien, and Karl Dane. <s> Adapted by Harry Behn from the autobiographical novel "Plumes" by Laurence Stallings, with titles by Joseph W. Farnham, the film is about an idle rich boy who joins the US Army's Rainbow Division and is sent to France to fight in World War I, becomes a friend of two working class men, experiences the horrors of trench warfare, and finds love with a French girl. <s> Although other anti-war films preceded it, "The Big Parade" is an early film which neither glorified the war nor ignored its human costs. <s> It heavily influenced a great many subsequent war films, especially "All Quiet on the Western Front" (1930). <s> In 1992, "The Big Parade" was selected for preservation in the United States National Film Registry by the Library of Congress as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant". <s> "The Big Parade" was one of the greatest hits of the 1920s earning gross rentals of $4,990,000 in the United States and $1,141,000 overseas on a budget of $382,000 during its initial release, with MGM recording a profit of $3.4 million, its biggest of the silent era. <s> The domestic earnings were MGM's biggest until the release of Gone With the Wind.
simple: The Big Parade is a 1925 silent movie. <s> It was directed by King Vidor. <s> It was adapted by Harry Behn and King Vidor from the play by Joseph Farnham and the autobiographical novel "Plumes" by Laurence Stallings. <s> It tells the story of an idle rich boy who joins the US Army's Rainbow Division and is sent to France to fight in World War I. <s> He becomes friends with two working class men, experiences the horrors of trench warfare, and finds love with a French girl. <s> In 1992 "The Big Parade" was selected for preservation in the United States National Film Registry by the Library of Congress as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant". <s> "The Big Parade" was one of the greatest hits of the 1920s earning gross rentals of $4,990,000 in North America and $1,141,000 overseas on a budget of $382,000 during its initial release, The film ultimately grossed $18–$22 million in worldwide rentals and is sometimes proclaimed as the most successful film of the silent era.

title: Into Eternity (band)
complex: Into Eternity is a Canadian progressive metal band from Regina, Saskatchewan, Canada. <s> It was formed in 1997 by Tim Roth, Scott Krall and Jim Austin. <s> Into Eternity was formed in 1997 by founding members Tim Roth, Scott Krall and Jim Austin and later released an eponymous, independent album in 1999, with the addition of Chris Eisler and Chris McDougall. <s> The band signed to Century Media Records a year later and then re-released their debut album. <s> In 2001, the band returned with their second album "Dead or Dreaming", an album which saw a more pronounced integration of progressive and death metal. <s> The trend continued on 2004's "Buried in Oblivion" and even further on 2006's "The Scattering of Ashes". <s> Into Eternity performed on Gigantour 2006, which kicked off in Boise, Idaho on September 6, 2006. <s> According to Soundscan, "The Scattering of Ashes" sold a little over 2,000 copies in the US during its first week of release. <s> During the summer of 2007, Into Eternity (along with progressive metal band Redemption) toured in support of Dream Theater during their North American leg of the Chaos in Motion tour. <s> Their new album entitled, "The Incurable Tragedy", which is a concept album, was released on August 25, 2008 in Europe and on September 2, 2008 in North America. <s> On March 9, 2011, Into Eternity announced the addition of drummer Bryan Newbury. <s> Also in 2011, Stu Block also joined the bandIced Earth. <s> In February 2012, Amanda Kiernan joined the band as their new vocalist. <s> In late 2012, Into Eternity began demoing new material with both Block and Kiernan.
simple: Into Eternity are a Canadian progressive metal band from Regina, Saskatchewan. <s> Into Eternity was formed in 1997 by band members Tim Roth, Scott Krall and Jim Austin. <s> They released their eponymous debut studio album "Into Eternity" in 1999. <s> They re-released their debut album when they signed to Century Media Records a year later. <s> Their second album "Dead or Dreaming" was released in 2001. <s> The album saw the band move more into a progressive and death metal style. <s> Their third studio album "Buried in Oblivion" was released on February 10, 2004 and their fourth studio album "The Scattering of Ashes" was released on October 3, 2006. <s> The band then went on tour from 2006 to 2008 and released their fifth studio album "The Incurable Tragedy" on August 25, 2008. <s> Drummer Bryan Newbury joined the band on March 9, 2011 and Stu Block joined Iced Earth in 2011. <s> Amanda Kiernan joined the band in February 2012.

title: Clay County, Georgia
complex: Clay County is a county located in the U.S. state of Georgia. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 3,183, making it the fifth-least populous county in Georgia. <s> The county seat is Fort Gaines.
simple: Clay County is a county Georgia. <s> Its county seat is Fort Gaines.

title: Promaucae
complex: Promaucae, also spelled as "Promaucas" or "Purumaucas" (from Quechua "purum awqa": wild enemy), were an indigenous pre-Columbian Mapuche tribal group that lived in the present territory of Chile, south of the Maipo River basin of Santiago, Chile and the Itata River. <s> Those to the north were called "Quillotanes" and "Mapochoes" by the Spanish colonists). <s> They spoke Mapudungun, like the Moluche to the south, and were part of the Picunche tribe that lived north of the Itata River.
simple: Promoucaes, Promaucaes, Promaucas or Purumaucas (: wild people); were a pre-Columbian Mapuche tribe that lived in Chile, from the south of the River of Maipo in Santiago, Chile and the River of Itata, (tribes at the north were called "Quillotanes" and "Mapochoes" by the Spanish). <s> They were speakers of Mapudungun like the Moluche and Picunche tribes.

title: Oklahoma City Blue
complex: The Oklahoma City Blue are an NBA G League team based in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, and the minor league affiliate of the Oklahoma City Thunder. <s> The franchise began as the Asheville Altitude in 2001, before moving to Tulsa, Oklahoma, in 2005 and becoming the Tulsa 66ers. <s> After nine seasons in Tulsa, the franchise moved to Oklahoma City in 2014 and were subsequently renamed the Oklahoma City Blue.
simple: The Oklahoma City Blue are an NBA Development League team based in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, United States. <s> They were also known as the Asheville Altitude when they played in Asheville, North Carolina from 2001 until 2005 and as the Tulsa 66ers when the team played in Tulsa, Oklahoma from 2005 until 2014.

title: Allen Crabbe
complex: Allen Lester Crabbe III (born April 9, 1992) is an American professional basketball player for the Atlanta Hawks of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> He played college basketball for the California Golden Bears. <s> He earned third-team All-American honors as a junior, when he was also named the conference player of the year in the Pac-12.
simple: Allen Lester Crabbe III (born April 9, 1992) is an American professional basketball player. <s> He plays for the Portland Trail Blazers of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> He played college basketball for the California Golden Bears.

title: Division of Martin
complex: The Division of Martin was an Australian Electoral Division in the state of New South Wales. <s> It was located in the inner western suburbs of Sydney, and initially included the suburbs of Concord and Mortlake, although by the time it was abolished in 1955, it had moved to cover Abbotsford, Balmain and Drummoyne. <s> The Division was named after Hon Sir James Martin, a former Premier of New South Wales. <s> It was proclaimed at the redistribution of 13 September 1922, and was first contested at the 1922 Federal election. <s> It was abolished at the redistribution of 30 August 1955. <s> The seat was at one stage held by William Holman, a former Premier of New South Wales.
simple: The Division of Martin was a Australian Electoral Division for the Australian House of Representatives in the state of New South Wales. <s> It was located in inner western Sydney. <s> It was also located in Concord and Mortlake. <s> By the time it was abolished, the division of Martin had spread to Abbotsford, Balmain and Drummoyne. <s> It was named after Sir James Martin, former Premier of New South Wales. <s> It was abolished in 1955.

title: Easton, Minnesota
complex: Easton is a city in Faribault County, Minnesota, United States. <s> The population was 199 at the 2010 census.
simple: Easton is a city in Faribault County, Minnesota, United States. <s> The population was 199 at the 2010 census.

title: Kohei Morita
complex: Kohei Morita (盛田 剛平 , Morita Kohei , born July 13, 1976) is a former Japanese football player.
simple: Kohei Morita (born 13 July 1976) is a Japanese football player.

title: Common year
complex: A common year is a calendar year with 365 days, as distinguished from a leap year, which has 366. <s> More generally, a common year is one without intercalation. <s> The Gregorian calendar, (like the earlier Julian calendar), employs both common years and leap years to keep the calendar aligned with the tropical year, which does not contain an exact number of days. <s> The common year of 365 days has 52 weeks and one day, hence a common year always begins and ends on the same day of the week (for example, January 1 and December 31 fell on a Sunday in 2017) and the year following a common year will start on the subsequent day of the week. <s> In common years, February has four weeks, so March will begin on the same day of the week. <s> November will also begin on this day. <s> In the Gregorian calendar, 303 of every 400 years are common years. <s> By comparison, in the Julian calendar, 300 out of every 400 years are common years, and in the Revised Julian calendar (used by Greece) 682 out of every 900 years are common years.
simple: A common year is a year that is not a leap year. <s> In the Gregorian Calendar a common year has 365 days. <s> This means a common year has 52 weeks and one day. <s> Stated differently, a common year always begins and ends on the same day of the week. <s> In the Gregorian calendar, 303 out of every 400 years are common years. <s> In the Julian calendar, 300 out of every 400 years were common years.

title: The Great Quest
complex: The Great Quest by Charles Boardman Hawes is a children's adventure novel which was a Newbery Honor recipient in 1922. <s> Illustrated by George Varian, it was published by The Atlantic Monthly Press in 1921. <s> The story opens in fictional Topham, Massachusetts, in 1826. <s> After the man Cornelius "Neal" Gleazen unexpectedly returns to town, he involves childhood friend Seth Woods and Seth's nephew, twenty-year-old protagonist Josiah "Joe" Woods, in a dangerous sea journey to retrieve a hidden treasure. <s> Accompanying them are Seth's two store-clerks, Arnold Lamont and Sim Muzzy, and farmer Abraham Guptil, on whose mortgage Neal forced Seth to foreclose in order to raise money to outfit the expedition. <s> When the travelers reach Cuba it is revealed that there is no hidden treasure, and that Neal's actual intent is to kidnap native Africans from Guinea to sell as slaves. <s> However, it is not until they reach Africa that Joe, Seth, and the others find an opportunity to take control of the expedition from Neal. <s> While in Africa, they rescue from danger a white missionary's daughter, who is accompanied by a native African slave or servant (his status is unclear) belonging to the Fantee nation. <s> Both of these accompany them back to Massachusetts via South America.
simple: The Great Quest by Charles Hawes is an adventure story for children. <s> It was a Newbery Honor book in 1922. <s> The Atlantic Monthly Press was its publisher. <s> The story happens in 1826. <s> It starts in Topham, Massachusetts. <s> Seth Woods has a friend named Cornelius Gleazen. <s> In Guinea, they rescue a white girl.

title: Greenland, Minnesota
complex: Greenland is an unincorporated community in Elysian Township, Le Sueur County, Minnesota, United States. <s> The community is located along 231st Avenue near its junction with Greenland Road. <s> Highway 60 (MN 60) is nearby. <s> Greenland had a post office from 1883 to 1914, and a station on the former Chicago Great Western Railroad. <s> Nearby places include Elysian and Madison Lake.
simple: Greenland is an unincorporated community in Elysian Township, Le Sueur County, Minnesota, United States. <s> Greenland is found along 231st Avenue near its crossing with Greenland Road. <s> Highway 60 (MN 60) is not far from Greenland. <s> Greenland had a post office from 1883 to 1914, and was on the old Chicago Great Western Railroad. <s> Some places not far from Greenland are Elysian and Madison Lake.

title: Nick Buoniconti
complex: Nicholas Anthony Buoniconti (December 15, 1940 – July 30, 2019) was an American professional football player who was a middle linebacker in the American Football League (AFL) and National Football League (NFL). <s> He played for the Boston Patriots and Miami Dolphins, winning two Super Bowls with the Dolphins. <s> Buoniconti was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Buoniconti died on July 30, 2019, in Bridgehampton, New York, at the age of 78.
simple: Nicholas Anthony Buoniconti (December 15, 1940 – July 30, 2019) was an American professional football player. <s> He was a middle linebacker in the American Football League (AFL) and National Football League (NFL). <s> He played for the Boston Patriots and Miami Dolphins. <s> He won two Super Bowls with the Dolphins. <s> Buoniconti was added into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Buoniconti died on July 30, 2019, in Bridgehampton, New York, at the age of 78.

title: Bucket-wheel excavator
complex: A bucket-wheel excavator (BWE) is a heavy equipment machine used in surface mining. <s> The primary function of BWEs is to act as a continuous digging machine in large-scale open-pit mining operations, removing thousands of tons of overburden a day. <s> What sets BWEs apart from other large-scale mining equipment, such as bucket chain excavators, is their use of a large wheel consisting of a continuous pattern of buckets used to scoop material as the wheel turns. <s> They rank among the largest vehicles (land or sea) ever produced, and the largest of the bucket-wheel excavators (the 14,200 ton Bagger 293) still holds the Guinness World Record for the heaviest land-based vehicle ever constructed. <s> Bucket-wheel excavators have been used in mining for the past century, with some of the first being manufactured in the 1920s. <s> They are used in conjunction with many other pieces of mining machinery (conveyor belts, spreaders, crushing stations, heap-leach systems, etc.) to move and mine massive amounts of overburden (waste). <s> While the overall concepts that go into a BWE have not changed much, their size has grown drastically since the end of World War II. <s> BWEs built since the 1990s, such as the Bagger 293, have reached sizes as large as tall, long, and as heavy as . <s> The bucket-wheel itself can be over in diameter with as many as 20 buckets, each of which can hold over of material. <s> BWEs have also advanced with respect to the extreme conditions in which they are now capable of operating. <s> Many BWEs have been designed to operate in climates with temperatures as low as -45 C . <s> Developers are now moving their focus toward automation and the use of electrical power.
simple: Bucket-wheel excavators (BWEs) are huge machines used for surface mining. <s> They are continuous digging machines in large-scale open cast mining operations. <s> What sets BWEs apart from other large-scale mining equipment is their large wheel with a continuous pattern of buckets to scoop material as the wheel turns. <s> They are among the largest vehicles ever constructed. <s> BWEs built since the 1990s, such as the Bagger 293, have reached sizes as large as 96 metres (314.9 feet) tall, 225 metres (738.2 feet) long, and as heavy as 14,200 metric tons (31.3 million lb). <s> The bucket-wheel itself can be over 70 feet in diameter with as many as 20 buckets, each of which can hold over 15 cubic metres of material. <s> BWEs are now capable of operating in extreme climates. <s> Many BWEs have been designed to operate in climates with temperatures as low as -45°C (-49°F).

title: Arrondissement of Bourg-en-Bresse
complex: The arrondissement of Bourg-en-Bresse is an arrondissement of France in the Ain department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> Since the January 2017 reorganization of the arrondissements of Ain, it has 199 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Bourg-en-Bresse is an arrondissement of France in the Ain department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> When the Ain department was created on 1800, the "arrondissement" of Bourg-en-Bresse was part of that original department. <s> The "arrondissement" of Bourg-en-Bresse is bordered to the northwest by the Saône-et-Loire department, to the northeast by the Jura department, to the west by the "arrondissements" of Nantua and Belley, and to the southwest by the Rhône department.

title: Talca
complex: According to the 2002 census of the National Statistics Institute, Talca spans an area of 231.5 sqkm and had, in that year, 201,797 inhabitants. <s> Of these, in 2002, 193,755 (96%) lived in urban areas and 8,042 (4%) in rural areas.
simple: Talca is a Chilean city with 201.797 inhabitants (2002 census).

title: Corps of Guides (India)
complex: The Corps of Guides was a regiment of the British Army (India) made up of white British officers and Indian lower ranks to serve on the North West Frontier. <s> As originally raised in 1846, The Guides consisted of infantry and cavalry. <s> It evolved through the 20th century to become the Guides Cavalry and Guides Infantry. <s> Once independence was granted to India and after the partition, The Guides were given over to Pakistan and became part of the Pakistan Army with all ranks including officers being recruited solely from Pakistan. <s> The brainchild of Sir Henry Lawrence, the Corps had Lt. Harry Lumsden as its commandant and W.S.R. Hodson (the Hodson of "Hodson's Horse") as second-in-command. <s> On 6 February 1847 Lumsden wrote to his father " I have just been nominated to raise the corps of Guides. <s> It will be the finest appointment in the country".
simple: The Corps of Guides was a regiment of the British Indian Army which was formed and served mostly in the North-West Frontier Province of British India. <s> Its infantry section was incorporated into the Frontier Force Regiment while its cavalry side became the Guides Cavalry. <s> After 1947 and the independence of Pakistan, the Guides regiment became part of the Pakistan Army. <s> The idea for raising such a body of troops was Sir Henry Lawrence's. <s> He appointed a young officer, Lt. Harry Lumsden as its commandant and on 6 February 1847 Lumsden took over his famous command.

title: Eric Hill
complex: Eric Gordon Hill (7 September 1927 – 6 June 2014) was an English author and illustrator of children's picture books, best known for his puppy character named Spot. <s> His works have been widely praised for their contributions to child literacy. <s> He was born in Holloway, London, but was evacuated to the countryside during World War II. <s> He left school at 14 and first worked as an errand boy in an illustration studio where he was encouraged to draw cartoons and comic strips in his spare time. <s> Following National Service, he produced sketches for magazines, and later worked as a freelance designer and illustrator in advertising. <s> He was appointed Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2008 New Year Honours. <s> He died aged 86 on 6 June 2014, at his home in California. <s> He was married to second wife Gillian, and has a son named Christopher, and a daughter, Jane.
simple: Eric Gordon Hill OBE (7 September 1927 – 6 June 2014) was a British author and illustrator of children's picture books. <s> He was best known for his character Spot the Dog. <s> Hill was born in Holloway, London. <s> He was made an Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2008 New Year Honours. <s> Hill died after a short illness on 6 June 2014 in California, United States, aged 86. <s> He was married to Gillian and had two children, Christopher and Jane.

title: Valery Asapov
complex: Valery Grigorievich Asapov ( ; 1 January 1966 – 23 September 2017) was Lieutenant General in the Russian Army. <s> According to the Russian Defence Ministry, he was killed on 23 September 2017 by mortar fire from ISIL militants near the city of Deir ez-Zor during the Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War in the course of the Syrian Civil War. <s> Asapov's position in Syria was described by the Ministry of Defence as the chief of the group of Russian military advisers in Syria. <s> On 23 February 2013, Col Valery Asapov, then commander of the Motor Rifle brigade, was awarded the 4th Class of the Order "For Merit to the Fatherland" by Russian president Vladimir Putin.
simple: Valery Grigorievich Asapov (; 1 January 1966 – 23 September 2017) was a Russian lieutenant general in the Russian military. <s> Asapov was killed by mortar fire from ISIL militants near the city of Deir ez-Zor during the Syrian Civil War, according to the Russian Defence Ministry. <s> Asapov has been described as one of the senior Russian military advisers in Syria. <s> Asapov, then commander of an army motorised rifle brigade, was awarded the 4th Class of the Order "For Merit to the Fatherland" by President Vladimir Putin on 23 February 2013.

title: Nagaland
complex: Nagaland is a state in northeastern India. <s> It borders the state of Assam to the west, Arunachal Pradesh and Assam to the north, Myanmar to the east, and Manipur to the south.
simple: Nagaland is a northeastern state in the Republic of India.

title: Internet Watch Foundation
complex: The Internet Watch Foundation (IWF) is a registered charity based in Cambridgeshire, England. <s> It states that its remit is "to minimise the availability of online sexual abuse content, specifically child sexual abuse images and videos hosted anywhere in the world and non-photographic child sexual abuse images hosted in the UK.
simple: The Internet Watch Foundation (IWF) is an organisation in the United Kingdom that gets reports from people and acts on those reports.

title: Manfred Porsch
complex: Manfred Maria Porsch (born 14 April 1950 in Vienna) is a composer of Austrian contemporary worship music and a teacher. <s> Manfred Porsch comes from the Focolare Movement. <s> In 1971 and 1972 he toured with Gen Rosso. <s> In 1983 he won the first prize at the "World Festival of the Religious Song", the "Rassegna Mondiale della Canzone Religiosa Populare" in Rom. <s> In 1987 Porsch founded "Musica e Vita Österreich" and initiated the festival series "Fest der Lieder". <s> He published about 200 songs on more than 20 albums. <s> After a long musical break, in 2012 Porsch published new songs together with the producer Thomas Raber.
simple: Manfred Maria Porsch (born 14 April 1950 in Vienna) is an Austrian composer and teacher. <s> He composes Austrian contemporary worship music. <s> Manfred Porsch comes from the Focolare Movement. <s> In 1971 and 1972, he toured with Gen Rosso. <s> In 1983, he won first prize at the "Worldfestival of religious Song", the "" in Rome. <s> In 1987, Porsch founded "" and started the festival series "Fest der Lieder". <s> He has published about 200 songs. <s> In 2012, after a long break from writing music, Porsch published new songs with the producer Thomas Raber.

title: Sandon, British Columbia
complex: Sandon is a ghost town in the Kootenay region of British Columbia, Canada. <s> Once the unofficial capital of the mining region known as the "Silvery Slocan", only some of it remains standing.
simple: Sandon, British Columbia is a mining town in British Columbia, Canada.

title: LaTeX
complex: LaTeX was originally written in the early 1980s by Leslie Lamport at SRI International. <s> The current version is LaTeX2e (stylised as LaTeX2ε). <s> LaTeX is free software and is distributed under the LaTeX Project Public License (LPPL).
simple: LaTeX was first made in the early 1980s by Leslie Lamport at SRI International. <s> The current version is LaTeX2e (styled ).

title: Chris Wilson (Australian musician)
complex: Christopher John Wilson (1956 – January 16, 2019) was an Australian blues musician who sang and played harmonica, saxophone and guitar. <s> He performed as part of the Sole Twisters, Harem Scarem and Paul Kelly and the Coloured Girls, and fronted his band Crown of Thorns. <s> Wilson's solo albums are "Landlocked" (June 1992), "The Long Weekend" (March 1998), "Spiderman" (2000), "King for a Day" (July 2002), "Flying Fish" (2012) and the self titled "Chris Wilson" (2018). <s> Wilson and his wife Sarah had two sons. <s> He died January 16, 2019, having been diagnosed with pancreatic cancer in 2018.
simple: Christopher John Wilson (1956 – January 2019) was an Australian blues musician and singer-songwriter. <s> He played harmonica, saxophone, and guitar. <s> He performed as part of the Sole Twisters, Harem Scarem and Paul Kelly and the Coloured Girls, and fronted his band Crown of Thorns. <s> Wilson's solo albums are "Landlocked" (June 1992), "The Long Weekend" (March 1998), "Spiderman" (2000) "King for a Day" (July 2002), "Flying Fish" (2012) and the self titled "Chris Wilson" (2018). <s> Wilson's death was announced on 16 January 2019 from pancreatic cancer at the age of 62.

title: D. J. King
complex: Dwayne "D. J." King (born June 27, 1984) is a Canadian former professional ice hockey left winger who played in the National Hockey League (NHL) with the St. Louis Blues and the Washington Capitals. <s> He was drafted in the 6th round of the 2002 NHL Entry Draft, 191st overall, by the St. Louis Blues. <s> As a junior from the Western Hockey League's, Lethbridge Hurricanes and Kelowna Rockets, King, known as an enforcer, spent his first two professional seasons within the Blues organization with affiliates in the American Hockey League and ECHL. <s> A free agent during the 2012–13 season, King was signed to a contract with the minor league team, the Ontario Reign of the ECHL on February 20, 2013. <s> King is of Métis heritage. <s> His younger brother Dwight also plays professional hockey, currently playing for Avtomobilist Yekaterinburg of the Kontinental Hockey League (KHL).
simple: Dwayne "D.J." King (born June 27, 1984) is a Canadian professional ice hockey left winger. <s> He previously played 118 games in the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> He played for the St. Louis Blues and the Washington Capitals. <s> He was drafted by the St. Louis Blues with the 190th overall pick in the 2002 NHL Entry Draft. <s> Before playing in the NHL, King played 4 seasons in the Western Hockey League; 3 seasons with the Lethbridge Hurricanes and 1 season with the Kelowna Rockets. <s> He currently plays for the Ontario Reign of the ECHL. <s> King is of Métis heritage.

title: Mickey (song)
complex: "Mickey" is a 1981 song recorded by American singer and choreographer Toni Basil on her debut album "Word of Mouth". <s> Written by Mike Chapman and Nicky Chinn as "Kitty", it was first recorded by UK music group Racey during 1979, appearing on their debut album "Smash and Grab".
simple: "Mickey" is a song by US singer Toni Basil.

title: New College, Oxford
complex: New College is one of the constituent colleges of the University of Oxford in the United Kingdom. <s> Founded in 1379 by William of Wykeham, the full name of the college is St Mary's College of Winchester in Oxford. <s> The name "New College", however, soon came to be used following its completion in 1386 to distinguish it from the older existing college of St. Mary, now known as Oriel College.
simple: New College is one of the colleges of the University of Oxford. <s> New College is one of the oldest colleges at Oxford. <s> It was founded in 1379.

title: Tomonobu Hayakawa
complex: Tomonobu Hayakawa (早川 知伸 , Hayakawa Tomonobu , born July 11, 1977) is a former Japanese football player.
simple: Tomonobu Hayakawa ( born 11 July 1977) is a Japanese professional athlete.

title: 2006–07 UCI Oceania Tour
complex: The 2006–07 UCI Oceania Tour was the third season of the UCI Oceania Tour. <s> The season began on 8 October 2006 with the Herald Sun Tour and ended on 5 May 2007 with the Oceania Cycling Championships. <s> The points leader, based on the cumulative results of previous races, wears the UCI Oceania Tour cycling jersey. <s> Gordon McCauley of New Zealand was the defending champion of the 2005–06 UCI Oceania Tour. <s> Robert McLachlan of Australia was crowned as the 2006–07 UCI Oceania Tour champion.
simple: The 2006-2007 UCI Oceania Tour is the third season of the UCI Oceania Tour of professional road bicycle racing held in various countries throughout the Oceania region. <s> The season begins with the Jayco Herald Sun Tour stage race in October 2006 and runs until September 2007. <s> The points leader, based on the cumulative results of previous races, wears the UCI Oceania Tour cycling jersey. <s> Gordon McCauley is the 2005-2006 champion of the UCI Oceania Tour. <s> The final points leader is crowned the 2006-2007 UCI Oceania Tour champion.

title: Mission California
complex: Mission California is Cross Canadian Ragweed's fourth studio album. <s> It was released on October 2, 2007. <s> The band spent 25 days in the studio; the first 5 cutting 15 tracks, the next 20 polishing each. <s> It was recorded in San Diego, California. <s> Lee Ann Womack laid down background vocals on 4 of the tracks to include the Chris Knight cover "Cry Lonely." <s> Hidden Track: "On The Right Path" begins at 6:15 on "NYCG"
simple: Mission California is Cross Canadian Ragweed's fourth studio album. <s> It was released on October 2, 2007. <s> The band spent 25 days in the studio. <s> It was recorded in San Diego, California. <s> Lee Ann Womack did background vocals on 4 of the songs to include the Chris Knight cover "Cry Lonely." <s> Hidden Track: "On The Right Path" begins at 6:15 on "NYCG"

title: PAX AM Days
complex: PAX AM Days (stylized as PAX•AM Days) is an EP by American rock band Fall Out Boy, released on October 15, 2013 by Island Records and PAX AM. <s> It consists of 1980s and 90s hardcore punk and punk rock influenced tracks recorded during a two-day "marathon" session with producer Ryan Adams and the band in July 2013 at PAX AM Studios.
simple: PAX AM Days is an EP released by American rock band Fall Out Boy. <s> They released it on October 15, 2013.

title: List of England Test cricketers
complex: This is a list of England Test cricketers. <s> A Test match is an international two-innings per side cricket match between two of the leading cricketing nations.
simple: This is a list of cricketers that play Test cricket for England. <s> A number of cricketers have played Test match cricket for England and another Test match team.

title: Jan Wahl
complex: Jan Boyer Wahl (April 1, 1931 - January 29, 2019) was an American children's author. <s> He was a prolific author of over 120 works, and was known primarily for his award-winning children's books, including "Pleasant Fieldmouse", "The Furious Flycycle", and "Humphrey's Bear". <s> Wahl sometimes jokingly referred to himself as "Dr. Mouse," a nickname given him by a young fan. <s> Jan (pronounced "Yahn") Wahl was born in Columbus, Ohio. <s> His father was physician Russell Rothenburger, and his mother was Nina Marie Boyer Wahl.
simple: Jan Boyer Wahl (April 1, 1931 – January 29, 2019) was an American children's author. <s> Wahl died on January 29, 2019 in Toledo, Ohio from prostate cancer, aged 87. <s> He was an author of over 120 works, and was known primarily for his award-winning children's books, including "Pleasant Fieldmouse", "The Furious Flycycle", and "Humphrey's Bear". <s> He was born in Columbus, Ohio.

title: La Marseillaise
complex: "La Marseillaise" ( , ] ) is the national anthem of France. <s> The song was written in 1792 by Claude Joseph Rouget de Lisle in Strasbourg after the declaration of war by France against Austria, and was originally titled "Chant de guerre pour l'Armée du Rhin" ("War Song for the Rhine Army"). <s> As the French Revolution continued, the monarchies of Europe became concerned that revolutionary fervor would spread to their countries.
simple: La Marseillaise is the national anthem of France. <s> It was written by Rouget de Lisle in Strasbourg on April 26, 1792. <s> It was first called ""Chant de guerre pour l'armée du Rhin"" ("Marching Song of the Rhine Army").

title: Sunny Murray
complex: James Marcellus Arthur "Sunny" Murray (September 21, 1936 – December 7, 2017) was one of the pioneers of the free jazz style of drumming. <s> Murray was born in Idabel, Oklahoma and spent his youth in Philadelphia before moving to New York City where he began playing with Cecil Taylor: "We played for about a year, just practicing, studying — we went to workshops with Varèse, did a lot of creative things, just experimenting, without a job" He was featured on the influential 1962 concerts in Denmark released as "Nefertiti the Beautiful One Has Come". <s> He later recorded under his own name for ESP-Disk and then when he moved to Europe for BYG Actuel. <s> Murray died on December 7, 2017 from unspecified causes at the age of 81.
simple: James Marcellus Arthur "Sunny" Murray (September 21, 1936 – December 8, 2017) was an American jazz drummer. <s> He was one of the pioneers of the free jazz style of drumming. <s> He was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. <s> He later recorded under his own name for ESP-Disk and then when he moved to Europe for BYG Actuel. <s> Murray died on December 8, 2017 from unspecified causes at the age of 81.

title: Red Lake County, Minnesota
complex: Red Lake County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 4,089, making it the third-least populous county in Minnesota. <s> Its county seat is Red Lake Falls.
simple: Red Lake County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> As of 2010, 4,089 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Red Lake Falls.

title: Mandi Bahauddin
complex: Mandi Bahauddin (Punjabi and ) is a city in central Punjab, Pakistan. <s> It is also the capital of Mandi Bahauddin District.
simple: Mandi Bahauddin is the capital of Mandi Bahauddin District in Punjab, Pakistan.

title: Ramat Gan
complex: Ramat Gan (Hebrew: or ) is a city in the Tel Aviv District of Israel, located east of the municipality of Tel Aviv and part of the Tel Aviv metropolitan area. <s> It is home to one of the world's major diamond exchanges, and many high-tech industries. <s> Ramat Gan was established in 1921 as a moshav, a communal farming settlement. <s> In 2018 it had a population of 159,159 . <s> The mayor of Ramat Gan is Carmel Shama. <s> The mayor of Ramat Gan is Carmel Shama.
simple: Ramat Gan (Hebrew: ; ) is a city in the Tel Aviv District of Israel, located east of Tel Aviv. <s> It is home to one of the world's major diamond exchanges, and many high-tech industries. <s> Ramat Gan was established in 1921 as a moshava, a communal farming settlement, and in 2015 it had a population of 152,596. <s> The current mayor is Carmel Shama.

title: James Taylor
complex: James Vernon Taylor (born March 12, 1948) is an American singer-songwriter and guitarist. <s> A five-time Grammy Award winner, he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2000. <s> He is one of the best-selling music artists of all time, having sold more than 100 million records worldwide. <s> He is known for his covers, such as "How Sweet It Is (To Be Loved by You)" and "Handy Man", as well as originals such as "Sweet Baby James". <s> He was active in support of Barack Obama's 2012 reelection campaign, and opened the 2012 Democratic National Convention. <s> He performed "America the Beautiful" at the President's second inauguration.
simple: James Taylor (born March 12, 1948) is an American singer and songwriter. <s> He is popular for his songs "Fire and Rain", "You've Got a Friend", and "How Sweet It Is (To Be Loved By You)". <s> Taylor is a Democrat and attended the 2012 Democratic National Convention in support of President Obama's re-election. <s> Taylor even performed during Obama's second inauguration.

title: Wegberg
complex: Wegberg is the northernmost town in the district of Heinsberg in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany. <s> Wegberg is situated between Mönchengladbach in the northeast and Erkelenz in the southeast; the town of Rheindahlen is to the east. <s> The city lies in the "Naturpark Maas-Schwalm-Nette", a nature and wildlife park hugging the border to the Netherlands. <s> Its name derives from the three rivers that define its boundaries.
simple: Wegberg is a town in the very west of Germany, in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia. <s> Wegberg is located between Mönchengladbach and Erkelenz. <s> Wegberg is in the Naturpark Maas-Schwalm-Nette, a nature and wildlife park.

title: Western European Summer Time
complex: Western European Summer Time (WEST) is a summer daylight saving time scheme, 1 hour ahead of Greenwich Mean Time and Coordinated Universal Time. <s> The scheme runs from the last Sunday in March to the last Sunday in October each year. <s> At both the start and end of the schemes, clock changes take place at 01:00 . <s> During the winter, Western European Time (WET, GMT+0 or ) is used.
simple: Western European Summer Time (WEST) is a summer daylight saving time scheme, 1 hour ahead of Coordinated Universal Time. <s> Western European Summer Time is also known by other names: The scheme runs from the last Sunday in March to the last Sunday in October each year. <s> At both the start and end of the schemes, clock changes take place at 01:00 UTC.

title: Gautier, Mississippi
complex: Gautier ( ; ] ) is a city in Jackson County, Mississippi, United States, along the Gulf of Mexico west of Pascagoula. <s> It is part of the Pascagoula Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The population was 18,572 at the 2010 census, up from 11,681 at the 2000 census. <s> In 2002, Gautier had annexed land more than doubling its area.
simple: Gautier is a city along the Gulf of Mexico, west of Pascagoula, in Jackson County, Mississippi, United States. <s> It is part of the Pascagoula, Mississippi Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The population was 11,681 at the 2000 census.

title: Hillsborough County, Florida
complex: Hillsborough County is a county in the U.S. state of Florida. <s> In the 2010 census, the population was 1,229,226, making it the fourth-most populous county in Florida and the most populous county outside the Miami Metropolitan Area. <s> A 2018 estimate has the population of Hillsborough County at 1,436,888 people, which itself is greater than the populations of 12 states according to their 2018 population estimates. <s> Its county seat and largest city is Tampa. <s> As of the census of 2000, 998,948 people, 391,357 households, and 255,164 families resided in the county. <s> The population density was 951 people per square mile (367/km2).
simple: Hillsborough County is a county in the U.S. state of Florida, and was formed on June 13, 1915. <s> Hillsborough County's seat is Tampa. <s> As of 2000, 11,057 people lived there.

title: Network File System
complex: Network File System (NFS) is a distributed file system protocol originally developed by Sun Microsystems in 1984, allowing a user on a client computer to access files over a computer network much like local storage is accessed. <s> NFS, like many other protocols, builds on the Open Network Computing Remote Procedure Call (ONC RPC) system. <s> The NFS is an open standard defined in a Request for Comments (RFC), allowing anyone to implement the protocol.
simple: Network File System (NFS) is a file system protocol. <s> It was originally developed by Sun Microsystems in 1984. <s> Using NFS, a user on a client computer can access files over a network in the same way as if they were attached to its local disks. <s> NFS uses the Open Network Computing Remote Procedure Call (ONC RPC) system. <s> The Network File System is an open standard defined in RFCs. <s> That way, anyone can implement the protocol.

title: Puttad
complex: Puttad is a small village in KoyilandyTaluk near Perambra in Kozhikode district, Kerala, India. <s> People here are mainly engaged in agriculture such as paddy, banana and tapioca. <s> Coconut farming also is a main source of income. <s> Lots of people from Puttad work abroad and that is an alternate mode of income.
simple: Puttad is a small village near Perambra in Kozhikode district, Kerala, south-west India. <s> People here grow banana and tapioca for money. <s> Coconut farming also is a main source of income. <s> Animal produce is also another source of income.

title: Tsuyoshi Kunieda
complex: Tsuyoshi Kunieda (国枝 強 , Kunieda Tsuyoshi , born September 18, 1944) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Tsuyoshi Kunieda (国枝 強, Kunieda Tsuyoshi, born September 18, 1944) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: Province of Siena
complex: The Province of Siena is a province in the Tuscany region of Italy. <s> Its capital is the city of Siena. <s> There are 35 "comuni" (singular: "comune") in the province .
simple: The Province of Siena (Italian: "Provincia di Siena")is a province in the Tuscany region of Italy. <s> The capital of the province is the city of Siena. <s> There are 36 "comuni" (singular: "comune") in the province.

title: The Exorcism of Emily Rose
