complex: The Exorcism of Emily Rose is a 2005 American supernatural horror crime film directed by Scott Derrickson and starring Laura Linney and Tom Wilkinson. <s> The film is loosely based on the story of Anneliese Michel and follows a self-proclaimed agnostic (Linney) who acts as defense counsel representing a parish priest (Wilkinson), accused by the state of negligent homicide after he performed an exorcism.
simple: The Exorcism of Emily Rose is a horror-drama movie of 2005.

title: James von Brunn
complex: James Wenneker von Brunn (July 11, 1920 – January 6, 2010) was an American man who perpetrated the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum shooting in Washington, D.C. on June 10, 2009. <s> Security guard Stephen Tyrone Johns was killed in the shooting, and von Brunn was wounded by two security guards who returned fire. <s> Von Brunn was named the prime suspect in the shooting, and was charged with first-degree murder and firearms violations. <s> While awaiting trial, von Brunn died on January 6, 2010. <s> Von Brunn was a white supremacist, neo-Nazi and Holocaust denier who had written numerous antisemitic essays, created an antisemitic website called "The Holy Western Empire", and is the author of a 1999 self-published book, "Kill the Best Gentiles", which praises Adolf Hitler and denies the Holocaust including propagating the belief of a supposed white genocide. <s> After the shooting, traces of his personal writings and works online were deleted from many websites, including AskArt.com, FreeRepublic and his personal user page on Wikipedia where he was indefinitely blocked, the latter said to constitute "a violation of policy of hate speech". <s> He also made posts expressing his opposition to the Iraq War, and felt that the September 11 attacks were an "inside job". <s> Von Brunn was born in St. Louis, Missouri, the first of two children. <s> His father was a native of Houston, Texas, and a superintendent at the Scullin Steel Mill in Houston during World War II.
simple: James Wenneker von Brunn (July 11, 1920 – January 6, 2010) was an American man who was responsible for the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum shooting in Washington, D.C. on June 10, 2009. <s> Security guard Stephen Tyrone Johns was killed in the shooting, and von Brunn was wounded by two security guards who returned fire. <s> Von Brunn was named the prime suspect in the shooting, and was charged with first-degree murder and firearms violations. <s> While awaiting trial, von Brunn died on January 6, 2010 in Butner, North Carolina from congestive heart failure caused by sepsis, aged 89. <s> Von Brunn was a white supremacist. <s> and Holocaust denier He was born in St. Louis, Missouri.

title: Estréelles
complex: Estréelles is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Estréelles is a commune. <s> It is found in the Nord-Pas-de-Calais region in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Mesenteric ischemia
complex: Mesenteric ischemia is a medical condition in which injury to the small intestine occurs due to not enough blood supply. <s> It can come on suddenly, known as acute mesenteric ischemia, or gradually, known as chronic mesenteric ischemia.
simple: Mesenteric ischemia is a medical condition. <s> It happens when not enough blood gets to the small intestine. <s> Mesenteric ischemia happens mostly to the elderly (older people).

title: Loudness (band)
complex: Loudness (ラウドネス , Raudonesu ) is a Japanese heavy metal band formed in 1981 by guitarist Akira Takasaki and drummer Munetaka Higuchi. <s> They were the first Japanese metal act signed to a major label in the United States, releasing twenty-six studio albums (five in America) and nine live albums by 2014 and reaching the "Billboard" Top 100 in their moment of maximum international popularity, as well as charting on Oricon dozens of times.
simple: Loudness is a heavy metal band from Japan. <s> The band was founded in 1981 by singer Akira Takasaki and drummer Munetaka Higuchi. <s> Loudness was the first Japanese heavy metal band to be signed to a recording contract in the United States.

title: Livery company
complex: The livery companies of the City of London, currently 110 in number, comprise London's ancient and modern trade associations and guilds, almost all of which are styled the 'Worshipful Company of...' their respective craft, trade or profession. <s> London's livery companies play a significant part in City life, not least by providing charitable-giving and networking opportunities. <s> Liverymen retain voting rights for the senior civic offices, such as the Lord Mayor, Sheriffs and City of London Corporation, its ancient municipal authority with extensive local government powers. <s> Most livery companies still maintain contacts with their original trade, craft or professional roles. <s> Some still exercise powers of regulation, inspection and enforcement, while others are awarding bodies for professional qualifications. <s> The Scriveners' Company admits senior members of legal and associated professions, the Apothecaries' Company awards post-graduate qualifications in some medical specialties, and the Hackney Carriage Drivers' Company comprises licensed taxi drivers who have passed the "Knowledge of London" test. <s> Several companies restrict membership only to those holding relevant professional qualifications, "eg." <s> the City of London Solicitors' Company and the Worshipful Company of Engineers. <s> Other companies, whose trade died out long ago, such as the Longbow Makers' Company, have evolved into being primarily charitable foundations. <s> In 1515, the Court of Aldermen of the City of London settled an order of precedence for the 48 livery companies then in existence, based on those companies' contemporary economic or political power. <s> The 12 highest-ranked companies remain known as the Great Twelve City Livery Companies. <s> Today there are 110 City livery companies, all post-1515 companies being ranked by seniority of creation. <s> The Merchant Taylors and the Skinners have long disputed their precedence, so once a year (at Easter) they swap between sixth and seventh places. <s> This mix-up is a favourite theory for the origin of the phrase "at sixes and sevens", as has been pointed out by at least one Master Merchant Taylor; however, it is possible that the phrase may have been coined before these two companies (Taylors and Skinners) resolved their dispute, which arose from their both receiving Charters in 1327 with no proof surviving as to which was granted first. <s> Neither the "Company of Parish Clerks" nor the "Company of Watermen" have applied or intend to apply for livery status, which remains a long-standing City tradition. <s> This is granted by the City Corporation in effect to control a company.
simple: The City of London Livery Companies began as trade associations or trade guilds, which controlled who could carry out certain jobs in the City of London. <s> Some still have a statutory role. <s> The order of precedence was first set down in 1515 by the Aldermen of the City of London. <s> The list was based on the companies' economic or political power. <s> The first twelve livery companies are known as the "Great Twelve City Livery Companies". <s> There are now 108 livery companies, some very new, so the Order of Precedence is sometimes reviewed. <s> The Merchant Taylors and the Skinners have always disputed their precedence, so once a year (at Easter) they exchange sixth and seventh place. <s> This is one of the theories for the origin of the phrase "at sixes and sevens", as the master of the Merchant Taylors has said a number of times, although the first use of the phrase may have been before the Taylors and the Skinners decided to alternate their position. <s> Two old companies do not intend applying for a grant of the right to wear the special costume or uniform known as a livery. <s> Three groups intend applying for livery.

title: Ball and chain
complex: A ball and chain was a physical restraint device historically applied to prisoners, primarily in the British Empire and its former colonies, from the 17th century until as late as the mid-20th century. <s> A type of shackle, the ball and chain is designed so that the weight of the iron ball at the end of the short chain restricts and limits the pace at which its wearer is able to move, making any attempt at escape much more difficult.
simple: A ball and chain is a device historically worn by prisoners. <s> The ball and chain was mainly used in the British Empire and its penal colonies. <s> It was used from the 17th century until as late as the mid 20th century.

title: Corneille Heymans
complex: Corneille Jean François Heymans (28 March 1892 – 18 July 1968) was a Belgian physiologist. <s> He studied at the Jesuit College of Saint Barbara and then at Ghent University, where he obtained a doctor's degree in 1920. <s> Heymans won the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine in 1938 for showing how blood pressure and the oxygen content of the blood are measured by the body and transmitted to the brain.
simple: Corneille Jean François Heymans (March 28, 1892 - July 18, 1968) was an Belgian doctor. <s> He won the 1938 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine, for his discoveries about how breathing is regulated.

title: Grave
complex: A grave is a location where a dead body (typically that of a human, although sometimes that of an animal) is buried. <s> Graves are usually located in special areas set aside for the purpose of burial, such as graveyards or cemeteries.
simple: A grave is where somebody or something is buried after they have died. <s> Graves are usually placed in a graveyard, with a headstone used to identify the dead person.

title: Sarah Thyre
complex: Sarah Christine Thyre (born July 7, 1968) is an American actress and writer.
simple: Sarah Christine Thyre (born July 7, 1968) is an American actress and writer.

title: Probyn Inniss
complex: Sir Probyn Ellsworth Inniss MBE (18 November 1936 – 12 March 2017) was the Governor of Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla from 1975 to 1980, and then, following the separation of Anguilla, the Governor of Saint Christopher and Nevis from 1980 to 1981.
simple: Sir Probyn Ellsworth Inniss MBE (18 November 1936 – 12 March 2017) was the Governor of Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla from 1975 to 1980. <s> Following the separation of Anguilla, he served as the Governor of Saint Christopher and Nevis from 1980 to 1981.

title: Concert of Europe
complex: The Concert of Europe represented the European balance of power from 1815 to 1848 and from 1871 to 1914. <s> With the Revolutions of 1848 the Vienna system collapsed and, although the republican rebellions were checked, an age of nationalism began and culminated in the unifications of Italy (by Sardinia) and Germany (by Prussia) in 1871. <s> The German Chancellor Otto von Bismarck re-created the Concert of Europe to avoid future conflicts escalating into new wars. <s> The revitalized concert included France, Britain, Austria, Russia, and Italy with Germany as the main continental power economically and militarily.
simple: The Concert of Europe was a group of countries in Europe who worked together and agreed on policies to maintain a steady balance of power which included alliances between the great powers in 1814 and 1914. <s> The member countries were the United Kingdom, Austria, Russia, France (from 1815), Prussia (Germany from 1871) and Italy (from 1871). <s> After Napoleon, ruler of France, was no longer in power, France joined the Concert of Europe. <s> Its importance diminished with the revolutions of 1848 and subsequent wars between the big powers. <s> Otto von Bismarck re-established the Concert of Europe after the unifications of Germany and Italy.

title: The Butler
complex: The Butler (full title Lee Daniels' The Butler) is a 2013 American historical drama film directed and co-produced by Lee Daniels and with a screenplay by Danny Strong. <s> It is inspired by Wil Haygood's "Washington Post" article "A Butler Well Served by This Election". <s> Loosely based on the real life of Eugene Allen, who worked in the White House for decades, the film stars Forest Whitaker as Cecil Gaines, an African-American who is a witness of notable political and social events of the 20th century during his 34-year tenure serving as a White House butler. <s> In addition to Whitaker, the film's all-star cast also features Oprah Winfrey, John Cusack, Jane Fonda, Alex Pettyfer, Cuba Gooding Jr., Terrence Howard, Lenny Kravitz, James Marsden, David Oyelowo, Vanessa Redgrave, Alan Rickman, Liev Schreiber, Robin Williams, Minka Kelly, Mariah Carey, and Clarence Williams III. <s> It was the last film produced by Laura Ziskin, who died in 2011.
simple: Lee Daniels' The Butler is a 2013 American historical drama movie directed by Lee Daniels. <s> The fictional Cecil Gaines is based on Eugene Allen who worked at the White House during eight presidential terms from 1952 to 1986. <s> It was the last movie produced by Laura Ziskin.

title: Interstate 8
complex: Interstate 8 (I-8) is an Interstate Highway in the southwestern United States. <s> It runs from the southern edge of Mission Bay at Sunset Cliffs Boulevard in San Diego, California, almost at the Pacific Ocean, to the junction with I-10, just southeast of Casa Grande, Arizona.
simple: Interstate 8 or I-8 is an Interstate Highway that runs from Interstate 10 near Casa Grande, Arizona to San Diego, California.

title: Plum (color)
complex: Plum is a purple color with a brownish-gray tinge, like that shown on the right, which is a close representation of the average color of the plum fruit. <s> The first recorded use of "plum" as a color name in English was in 1805.
simple: Plum is a color similar to purple. <s> The first written use of "plum" as a color name in English was in 1805.

title: Elmdon
complex: Elmdon is a village in the Uttlesford district of Essex, England, near the boundary with Cambridgeshire and Hertfordshire. <s> The hilly topography of the area differentiates it from countryside to the north, which is predominantly fenland and flat.
simple: Elmdon is a village and civil parish in Uttlesford, Essex, England.

title: Viscosity
complex: The viscosity of a fluid is a measure of its resistance to deformation at a given rate. <s> For liquids, it corresponds to the informal concept of "thickness": for example, syrup has a higher viscosity than water. <s> The word "viscosity" is derived from the Latin "" "", meaning mistletoe and also a viscous glue made from mistletoe berries. <s> Viscosity is the material property which relates the viscous stresses in a material to the rate of change of a deformation (the strain rate). <s> Although it applies to general flows, it is easy to visualize and define in a simple shearing flow, such as a planar Couette flow.
simple: In a simple example, water has a low viscosity, as it is "thin". <s> Syrup and tar, on the other hand, have a high viscosity, as they are "thick". <s> The word "viscous" comes from the Latin "viscum", meaning sticky. <s> Viscosity is a physical property of fluids.

title: Alfons Schuhbeck
complex: Alfons Schuhbeck (born on May 2, 1949) is one of Germany's top chefs, as well as being a restaurateur, celebrity chef, author and businessman. <s> Born "Alfons Karg", he trained as a telecommunications technician, but soon became disenchanted with this profession. <s> While playing with his band in the Bavarian holiday resort of Waging am See, he ran into the restaurateur Sebastian Schuhbeck. <s> This man committed Alfons in a career in the hospitality business and became his mentor. <s> Sebastian Schubeck later adopted Alfons and made him his heir. <s> He studied at the "College of Hotel Management Bad Reichenhall" in Bavaria. <s> After that he went through practical training in Salzburg, Geneva, Paris, London and Munich (in Eckart Witzigmanns three stars awarded "Aubergine"). <s> He finally took the "Kurhausstüberl" from his mentor in 1980. <s> Alfons was the driving force in Sebastian Schuhbeck's business. <s> His chef skills impressed the guests of the "Kurhausstüberl" in a way, that this former village inn became a favourite restaurant for the upper society of Munich and Salzburg. <s> In 1983 he was awarded with one star in the French Michelin Guide, as the third chef outside France at this time. <s> The also French Gault Millau restaurant guide gave him 17 points and 3 hoods and elected him "Cook of the year" in 1989. <s> Since 1990 Schubeck has operated a catering service and supplied many first-class events like the Federal Chancellor’s celebration, the "Ball des Sports" and the German music industry's "ECHO" award ceremony. <s> In 2003 he established a new restaurant, the "Südtiroler Stuben" in Munich. <s> There he won his second Michelin star in December 2003. <s> In November 2005 he was awarded with the "Five Star Diamond Award" by the American Academy of Hospitality Sciences. <s> German TV-Station Bayerischer Rundfunk has broadcast his show "Schuhbecks" since 1993. <s> His popularity in Germany results in this as well as publishing more than 20 books about cooking. <s> He is also a regular guest in other German TV shows. <s> During the 1990s Schuhbeck amassed up to DM 60 million from business partners for capital investments. <s> Dubious practices such as being solely responsible for several millions of DM invested in an account with the Citibank Monte Carlo resulted in court proceedings, Schuhbeck being indicted for fraud. <s> The court found the business practices unusual but not illegal, and he was exonerated. <s> At the end of the 1990s he set up "Schuhbecks GmbH". <s> This company now includes the restaurant "Südtiroler Stuben", a wine bistro, the catering service, a cookery school, a spice shop and an ice-cream parlour, all based in Munich. <s> "Schuhbeck Check Inn GmbH" was formed in 2001 to manage the "Check Inn restaurant and bar" in Egelsbach (south Hesse).

title: Plummer, Idaho
complex: Plummer is a city in Benewah County, Idaho, United States. <s> The population was 1,044 at the 2010 census, up from 990 in 2000. <s> It is the largest city within the Coeur d'Alene Reservation, and is accessed by U.S. Route 95, the state's primary north-south highway. <s> Plummer is located at (47.333423, -116.884393), at an elevation of 2743 ft above sea level. <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 1.25 sqmi , all of it land. <s> The median age in the city was 31.4 years. <s> 32.8% of residents were under the age of 18; 9.6% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 22.3% were from 25 to 44; 24.8% were from 45 to 64; and 10.3% were 65 years of age or older. <s> The gender makeup of the city was 51.1% male and 48.9% female. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 990 people, 336 households, and 257 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 875.2 people per square mile (338.3/km2). <s> There were 380 housing units at an average density of 335.9 per square mile (129.8/km2). <s> The racial makeup of the city was 55.86% White, 0.71% African American, 39.29% Native American, 0.10% Asian, 0.10% Pacific Islander, 0.81% from other races, and 3.13% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.93% of the population. <s> There were 336 households out of which 38.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.4% were married couples living together, 17.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 23.5% were non-families. <s> 19.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. <s> The average household size was 2.95 and the average family size was 3.33. <s> In the city, the population was spread out with 33.3% under the age of 18, 12.2% from 18 to 24, 26.6% from 25 to 44, 17.6% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older. <s> The median age was 29 years. <s> For every 100 females, there were 96.8 males. <s> For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.6 males. <s> The median income for a household in the city was $28,438, and the median income for a family was $31,806. <s> Males had a median income of $26,583 versus $20,357 for females. <s> The per capita income for the city was $10,564. <s> About 17.3% of families and 22.0% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.8% of those under age 18 and 18.8% of those age 65 or over.

title: Jastrzębie-Zdrój
complex: Jastrzębie-Zdrój ( ; , originally "Jastrzemb", ) is a city in south Poland with 89,128 inhabitants (31.12.2018). <s> Its name comes from the Polish words "jastrząb" ("hawk") and "zdrój" ("spa" or "spring").
simple: Jastrzębie-Zdrój is a city in Poland in Silesian Voivodeship.

title: Hindu calendar
complex: Hindu calendar is a collective term for the various lunisolar calendars traditionally used in the Indian subcontinent. <s> They adopt a similar underlying concept for timekeeping, but differ in their relative emphasis to moon cycle or the sun cycle and the names of months and when they consider the New Year to start.
simple: The Hindu calendar is a lunisolar calendar used in ancient times.

title: AD 15
complex: AD 15 (XV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Caesar and Flaccus (or, less frequently, year 768 "Ab urbe condita"). <s> The denomination AD 15 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: It was a common year starting on Tuesday of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Caesar and Flaccus.

title: Albert Viaplana
complex: Albert Viaplana (c. 1933 – 16 May 2014) was a Spanish architect and author. <s> He is known for creating the Center of Contemporary Culture of Barcelona (CCCB), the Plaza de Sants and dock Xoan XXIII Avenue of Santiago de Compostela. <s> He won many awards during his career. <s> His career spanned nearly 50 years. <s> Viaplana died in Barcelona, Spain, aged 81.

title: Toni Ucci
complex: Antonio "Toni" Ucci (13 January 1922 – 16 or 19 February 2014) was an Italian actor and comedian. <s> He appeared in 86 films between 1948 and 2000.

title: Kent County, Rhode Island
complex: Kent County is a county located in the U.S. state of Rhode Island. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 166,158 making it the second-most populous county in Rhode Island. <s> The county was formed in 1750 from the southern third of Providence County. <s> It was named after the county of Kent, England. <s> Kent County, like other counties in Rhode Island, no longer has governmental functions (other than as court administrative and sheriff corrections boundaries).
simple: Kent County is a county located in the U.S. state of Rhode Island. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 166,158 making it the second-most populous county in Rhode Island. <s> It was named after the county of Kent, England.

title: Zion Gate
complex: Zion Gate ( , "Sha'ar Zion", , "Bab Sahyun") also known in Arabic as Bab Harat al-Yahud ("Jewish Quarter Gate"), or Bab an-Nabi Dawud ("Prophet David Gate"), is one of eight gates in the walls of the Old City of Jerusalem.

title: Florent Malouda
complex: Florent Johan Malouda (] ; born 13 June 1980) is a French football coach and former professional player.
simple: Florent Malouda (born 13 June 1980) is a French football player.

title: Armenian National Committee of America
complex: The Armenian National Committee of America (ANCA) is the largest and most influential Armenian American grassroots organization. <s> Working in coordination with a network of offices, chapters and supporters throughout the United States and affiliated organizations around the world, the ANCA actively advances the concerns of the Armenian American community on a broad range of issues. <s> Beyond the national headquarters of the ANCA located in Washington, there are two regional offices in New York City and Los Angeles, and more than fifty local chapters and thousands of activists, it is cooperating with a large web of regional Armenian National Committees (or "Armenian Cause/Hay Tad" Offices) in Armenia, Russia, France, the Middle East, Canada, South America, and Australia. <s> The Chairman of ANCA is Raffi Hamparian. <s> The staff is composed of Executive Director Aram Hamparian, Communications Director Elizabeth S. Chouldjian, Government Affairs Director Raffi N. Karakashian, Esq., and Chief Financial Officer Christopher Hekimian.
simple: The Armenian National Committee of America (ANCA) is the largest and most influential Armenian American advocacy organization in the United States. <s> Working in coordination with a network of offices, chapters, and supporters throughout the country and affiliated organizations around the world, the ANCA advances the concerns of the Armenian American community on a broad range of issues. <s> Beyond the Central offices of ANCA are in Washington DC, Boston and Los Angeles, ANCA has more than fifty local chapters and thousands of activists, it is cooperating with a large web of regional Armenian National Committees (or "Armenian Cause/Hay Tad" Offices) in Armenia, Russia, France, the Middle East, Canada and Australia. <s> The Executive Director of ANCA is Aram Hamparian.

title: David McAllister
complex: David James "Mac" McAllister (born 12 January 1971) is a German politician and member of the European Parliament from Germany. <s> He is a member of the Christian Democratic Union, part of the European People's Party. <s> He is the current Vice President of the European People's Party and he is also Vice Chairman of the International Democrat Union. <s> He was appointed Chair of the European Parliament Foreign Affairs Committee in February 2017. <s> On 1 July 2010 McAllister was elected Minister-President of the state of Lower Saxony, succeeding Christian Wulff, who resigned following his election as President of Germany. <s> Until his election defeat on 19 February 2013, he headed a coalition government with the liberal FDP, the Cabinet McAllister. <s> In the 2014 European elections, McAllister was elected a Member of the European Parliament as the CDU's top candidate in Lower Saxony. <s> A lawyer by profession, he served as chairman of the CDU parliamentary group in the Lower Saxon Parliament from 2003 to 2010 and was elected chairman of the state party in 2008. <s> In November 2016 he left the chairman post, and announced that he sees his political future in Europe. <s> McAllister holds both German and British citizenship. <s> McAllister was born in West Berlin on 12 January 1971 to a Scottish father and a German mother. <s> His father, James Buchanan McAllister, was a British civil servant, originally from Glasgow (where the family still has relatives), stationed in West Berlin since 1969, where he was attached to the Royal Corps of Signals. <s> His mother, Mechthild McAllister, is a music teacher. <s> David McAllister was raised bilingually and attended a British primary school in Berlin. <s> In a 2010 interview he linked his family's name to Clan MacAlister. <s> After his parents moved to the small town of Bad Bederkesa in Lower Saxony in 1982, he went to the Lower Saxon "Internatsgymnasium" (boarding school) in Bederkesa, where he took his Abitur in 1989. <s> From 1989 till 1991, McAllister served his compulsory military service in the Bundeswehr, in Panzerbataillon 74 in Cuxhaven. <s> From 1991–96 he studied law with a scholarship from the Konrad Adenauer Foundation at the University of Hanover. <s> In 1994, McAllister became local chairman of the CDU youth organisation, Junge Union, in the Cuxhaven district. <s> McAllister holds both German and British citizenship and speaks both German and English as native languages, although he has stated that he's "more or less completely German. <s> I've lived in Germany all my life. <s> I did all my school in Germany and my military service in Germany." <s> His upbringing in West Berlin, however, he describes as "very British" with "British network, British schools". <s> Holding dual citizenship, he could have relinquished his German citizenship to avoid compulsory military service in Germany (the UK does not have compulsory military service), but opted to serve instead. <s> McAllister has said that "my upbringing in West Berlin may have had an impact on my resentment towards communists. <s> I became a member of the CDU when I was 17 – it was a birthday present. <s> My parents said, ‘What do you want for your birthday?’ <s> I said I wanted to become a member of the CDU", explaining that his father was a Conservative, although neither of his parents were involved in party politics. <s> From 1996 till 2010, McAllister was a member of the Cuxhaven district council (Kreistag). <s> He served as mayor of his hometown of Bad Bederkesa from 2001 to 2002. <s> From 2002 to 2003, he also was secretary general of the CDU in Lower Saxony. <s> Since 2003, McAllister has served as the leader of the CDU parliamentary party group in the Parliament of Lower Saxony, of which he has been a member since 1998. <s> McAllister succeeded Christian Wulff as party chairman of the CDU in Lower Saxony from June 2008 until November 2016. <s> He was succeeded by Bernd Althusmann. <s> In the United Kingdom, McAllister is a supporter of the Conservative Party. <s> In 2005, Chancellor Angela Merkel offered him the position of Secretary General of the CDU, but McAllister declined, arguing he did not want to rise too far too fast. <s> He was a CDU delegate to the Federal Convention for the purpose of electing the President of Germany in 2004, 2009, 2010 and 2012. <s> On 4 June 2010, McAllister was designated by his party to succeed Christian Wulff as Minister-President of Lower Saxony, if the latter were to be elected President of Germany on 30 June. <s> After the election of Wulff as President, David McAllister was elected the new Minister-President of Lower Saxony the following day. <s> He was subsequently also appointed to the supervisory board of Volkswagen, the largest company in Lower Saxony and of which the state of Lower Saxony is a major stockholder. <s> From 2010, he also served as a member of the supervisory board of Volkswagen. <s> Following the 2013 Lower Saxony state election, McAllister's CDU-FDP Coalition lost control of the Landtag, which meant that the Christian Democrats and the Free Democrats eventually lost the government role. <s> On 19 February 2013, Stephan Weil of the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) was elected Minister-President of Lower Saxony with the votes of SPD and Alliance '90/The Greens. <s> McAllister is married to Dunja McAllister, née Kolleck, who is also a lawyer. <s> They have two daughters named Jamie Elizabeth and Mia Louise. <s> He lives in Bad Bederkesa in the district of Cuxhaven. <s> McAllister proposed to his wife on the shore of Loch Ness, and married in August 2003, wearing a kilt. <s> He later explained it was a family tradition. <s> He supports Rangers FC and Hannover 96.

title: Luxembourg (canton)
complex: Luxembourg is a canton in the south of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg. <s> Its name, like the name of the Grand Duchy itself, derives from the name of its principal city, Luxembourg (more commonly known as Luxembourg City). <s> It is not to be confused with the former district of Luxembourg, one of three administrative units in Luxembourg abolished in October 2015. <s> It is the only canton, other than Mersch, to be entirely surrounded by other cantons and therefore to have no international boundary. <s> The capital is Luxembourg City.
simple: Luxembourg is a canton in Luxembourg. <s> It is the only canton, other than Mersch, to be entirely surrounded by other cantons, and therefore not to have an international boundary. <s> Its capital is Luxembourg.

title: Epik High
complex: Epik High (Hangul: 에픽하이) is a South Korean alternative hip hop group from Seoul, composed of Tablo, Mithra Jin, and DJ Tukutz. <s> They are known for having combined genres and different styles of hip hop throughout their career, which has seen the release of eleven studio albums since their debut in 2003, as well as for their coverage of diverse lyrical themes.
simple: Epik High is a South Korean hip hop music group. <s> Group members are Tablo, DJ Tukutz and Mithra Jin.

title: Thalassomedon
complex: Thalassomedon (from Greek, "thalassa", "sea" and Greek, "medon", "lord" or "ruler", meaning "sea lord") is a genus of plesiosaur, named by Welles in 1943. <s> "Thalassomedon" is among the largest elasmosaurids, with a total length of 10.86 m for the holotype. <s> There is a larger skull however suggesting a much larger animal, potentially up to 11.7 m . <s> The neck is also very long; it comprises 62 vertebrae and is about 5.9 m - over half of the total length. <s> The skull is 47 cm long, with 5 cm long teeth. <s> The flippers were about 1.5 – long.
simple: Thalassomedon (meaning "lord of the seas") was a plesiosaur (not a dinosaur, but an extinct marine reptile from the Mesozoic Era that lived in the open oceans and breathed air). <s> The type species, "Thalassomedon haningtoni" (named by Welles in 1943). <s> It had a long neck (with 63 vertebrae), a long snout, long, sharp teeth (up to 5 cm long), a short, pointed tail and four flippers. <s> This reptile was about 40 feet (12 m) long; its skull was about 18.7 inches (47 cm) long.

title: Richard N. Gardner
complex: Richard Newton Gardner (July 9, 1927 – February 16, 2019) served as the United States Ambassador to Spain and the United States Ambassador to Italy. <s> He was a professor emeritus of law at Columbia Law School. <s> Gardner was born in New York City, New York, the son of Ethel (Alias) and Samuel Gardner (former family name was Goldberg). <s> He served in the United States Armed Forces during World War II.
simple: Richard Newton Gardner (July 9, 1927 – February 16, 2019) was an American politician. <s> He was a professor emeritus of law at Columbia Law School. <s> He was born in New York City.

title: CraveOnline
complex: CraveOnline Media, LLC is a male lifestyle website based in Los Angeles with sales offices in New York City, Chicago and San Francisco. <s> The site is owned by media company Evolve Media, LLC. <s> CraveOnline focuses its contents into the male-lifestyle audience.
simple: CraveOnline is an entertainment website. <s> It is based in Los Angeles and has sales offices in New York, Chicago, and San Francisco. <s> The site is owned by media company AtomicOnline.

title: Zombie
complex: Zombies are featured widely in Haitian rural folklore as dead persons physically revived by the act of necromancy of a "bokor", a sorcerer or witch. <s> The "bokor" is opposed by the "houngan" or priest and the "mambo" or priestess of the formal voodoo religion. <s> A zombie remains under the control of the "bokor" as a personal slave, having no will of its own. <s> The Haitian tradition also includes an incorporeal type of zombie, the "zombie astral", which is a part of the human soul. <s> A "bokor" can capture a zombie astral to enhance his spiritual power. <s> A zombie astral can also be sealed inside a specially decorated bottle by a "bokor" and sold to a client to bring luck, healing, or business success. <s> It is believed that God eventually will reclaim the zombie's soul, so the zombie is a temporary spiritual entity. <s> Several decades after Hurston's work, Wade Davis, a Harvard ethnobotanist, presented a pharmacological case for zombies in a 1983 paper in the "Journal of Ethnopharmacology", and later in two popular books, "The Serpent and the Rainbow" (1985) and "Passage of Darkness: The Ethnobiology of the Haitian Zombie "(1988). <s> Davis traveled to Haiti in 1982 and, as a result of his investigations, claimed that a living person can be turned into a zombie by two special powders being introduced into the blood stream (usually via a wound). <s> The first, "coup de poudre" (French: "powder strike"), includes tetrodotoxin (TTX), a powerful and frequently fatal neurotoxin found in the flesh of the pufferfish (order Tetraodontidae).
simple: In Haiti people believe that Voodoo sorcerers or 'bokor' can bring dead people back to life, making a zombie. <s> The zombie is under the control of the sorcerer because zombies have no free will. <s> It's believed a zombie is a trapped human soul. <s> Wade Davis, a Canadian ethnobotanist (someone who studies what effect plants have on people), wrote about zombies in two books, The Serpent and the Rainbow (1985) and (1988). <s> Davis went to Haiti in 1982 and wrote about how a living person can be turned into a zombie by two special powders being rubbed into a wound.

title: Liopleurodon
complex: Liopleurodon ( ; meaning 'smooth-sided teeth') is a genus of large, carnivorous marine reptile belonging to the Pliosauroidea, a clade of short-necked plesiosaurs. <s> The two species of "Liopleurodon" lived during the Callovian stage of the Middle Jurassic Period (c. 164 to 155 mya). <s> It was the apex predator of the Middle to Late Jurassic seas that covered Europe. <s> The largest species, "L. ferox", is estimated to have grown up to 6.4 m in length.
simple: Liopleurodon was a large species of Pliosaur. <s> It was an apex predator in the Upper Jurassic seas, around 160–155 million years ago.

title: Carson Cistulli
complex: Carson Cistulli (born December 23, 1979) is an American poet, Wikipedia editor, essayist and sabermetrician. <s> His works of poetry include "Some Common Weaknesses Illustrated", "Assorted Fictions," and "A Century of Enthusiasm." <s> Carson Cistulli was born December 23, 1979, in Concord, New Hampshire, to Philip Cistulli Jr. and Holly Young. <s> Carson passed his early childhood in a middle class Italian-American household until his parents' divorce in 1994. <s> Cistulli attended boarding school at Milton Academy in Massachusetts.
simple: Carson Cistulli is a poet and a journalist. <s> He was born on December 23, 1979 in New Hampshire. <s> He read a lot of poetry when he was away from home at a boarding school called Milton Academy.

title: Skinnskatteberg Municipality
complex: Skinnskatteberg Municipality ("Skinnskattebergs kommun") is a municipality in Västmanland County in central Sweden. <s> Its seat is located in the town of Skinnskatteberg.
simple: Skinnskatteberg Municipality is a municipality in Västmanland County in central Sweden. <s> The seat is in Skinnskatteberg.

title: California State University
complex: The California State University (Cal State or CSU) is a public university system in California. <s> With 23 campuses and eight off-campus centers enrolling 484,300 students with 26,858 faculty and 25,305 staff, CSU is the largest four-year public university system in the United States. <s> It is one of three public higher education systems in the state, with the other two being the University of California system and the California Community Colleges System. <s> The CSU System is incorporated as The Trustees of the California State University. <s> The California State University system headquarters are at 401 Golden Shore in Long Beach, California. <s> In the 2011–12 academic year, CSU awarded 52 percent of newly issued California teaching credentials, 47 percent of the state's engineering degrees, 28 percent of the state's information technology bachelor's degrees, and it had more graduates in business (50 percent), agriculture (72 percent), communication studies, health (53 percent), education, and public administration (52 percent) than all other universities and colleges in California combined. <s> Altogether, about half of the bachelor's degrees, one-third of the master's degrees, and nearly two percent of the doctoral degrees awarded annually in California are from the CSU. <s> Furthermore, the CSU system is one of the top U.S. producers of graduates who move on to earn their Ph.D. degrees in a related field. <s> The CSU has a total of 17 AACSB accredited graduate business schools which is over twice as many as any other collegiate system. <s> Since 1961, nearly three million alumni have received their bachelor's, master's, or doctoral degrees from the CSU system. <s> CSU offers more than 1,800 degree programs in some 240 subject areas.
simple: The California State University (CSU) is a public university system established in 1857 in California. <s> It is one of three public higher education systems in the state, the other two being the "University of California" system and the "California Community College" system. <s> The California State University system headquarters are in Long Beach, California. <s> CSU prepares about 60 percent of the teachers in the state, 40 percent of the engineering graduates, and more graduates in business, agriculture, communication studies, health, education and public administration than all other California universities and colleges combined. <s> Altogether, about half the bachelor's degrees and a third of the master's degrees awarded annually in California are from the CSU. <s> Since 1961, nearly 2.5 million alumni have received a bachelor's, master's or doctoral degree from the CSU system which offers more than 1,800 degree programs in 240 subject areas.

title: Jimmy Roy
complex: Jimmy Roy (born September 22, 1975 in Sioux Lookout, Ontario) was a Canadian ice hockey player for the Manitoba Moose of the International Hockey League and American Hockey League from 1997 to 2006. <s> Later in his career he played for Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga from 2006-2011. <s> He is currently Director of Player Development for the Winnipeg Jets of the National Hockey League. <s> Roy was drafted 254th overall by the Dallas Stars in the 1994 NHL Entry Draft but never played in the National Hockey League. <s> After spending two years at Michigan Technological University he signed with the Manitoba Moose in 1997. <s> Roy spent nine seasons with the Manitoba Moose, the first four in the International Hockey League and the rest in the American Hockey League after the Moose became members of the league when the IHL folded. <s> He holds different team records like games played and most goals. <s> For the 2006–07 season Roy signed with the Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga. <s> In Iserlohn he developed to a key player, known for his leading quality on and off the ice. <s> He also helped the club to sign some former Moose players like Ryan Ready and Pat Kavanagh. <s> Roy extended his contract after his first season in Germany for two years. <s> On Christmas Day 2008 the Roosters announced again that Roy has signed for two more years. <s> As a Rooster he usually plays on a line with Ryan Ready. <s> In the 2007–08 season their center was Pat Kavanagh, the next season Bob Wren was their line mate. <s> In 2011, he retired as a player to take the position of Director of Player Development in the Winnipeg Jets organization.
simple: Jimmy Roy (born September 22, 1975 in Sioux Lookout, Ontario) is a Canadian ice hockey player currently playing for the Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga. <s> Roy was drafted 254th overall by the Dallas Stars in the 1994 NHL Entry Draft but never played in the National Hockey League. <s> After spending two years at Michigan Technological University he signed with the Manitoba Moose in 1997. <s> Roy spent nine seasons with the Manitoba Moose, the first four in the International Hockey League and the rest in the American Hockey League after the Moose became members of the league when the IHL folded. <s> He holds different team records like games played and most goals. <s> For the 2006–07 season Roy signed with the Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga. <s> In Iserlohn he developed to a key player, known for his leading quality on and off the ice. <s> He also helped the club to sign some former Moose players like Ryan Ready and Pat Kavanagh. <s> Roy extended his contract after his first season in Germany for two years. <s> On Christmas Day 2008 the Roosters announced again that Roy has signed for two more years. <s> As a Rooster he usually plays on a line with Ryan Ready. <s> In the 2007–08 season their center was Pat Kavanagh, the next season Bob Wren was their linemate.

title: Ronald Paulson
complex: Ronald Howard Paulson (born May 27, 1930 in Bottineau, North Dakota) is an American professor of English, a specialist in English 18th-century art and culture, and English artist William Hogarth. <s> Paulson has taught and held various administrative positions at several universities in the United States, including the University of Illinois from 1959 to 1963 and Rice University from 1963 to 1967. <s> He was the Chairman of the Johns Hopkins University English Department from 1967 to 1975. <s> From 1975 to 1984 he was a professor at Yale University and served as the Director of Graduate Studies in the English Department from 1976 to 1983 and the Director of the British Studies Program from 1976 to 1984. <s> He has been a member of the editorial board of the academic journal "ELH: English Literary History" and was senior editor from 1985 to 2004; he served on the editorial boards of the journals "Studies in English Literature"; PMLA; "Eighteenth-Century Studies"; and the Johns Hopkins University Press.
simple: Ronald Paulson (born May 27, 1930) is an American professor of English, a specialist in English 18th-century art and culture, and English artist William Hogarth. <s> Paulson was born in Bottineau, North Dakota. <s> Paulson has taught and held many administrative positions at several universities in the United States, including the University of Illinois from 1959 to 1963 and Rice University from 1963 to 1967. <s> He was the Chairman of the Johns Hopkins University English Department from 1967 to 1975. <s> From 1975 to 1984 he was a professor at Yale University and served as the Director of Graduate Studies in the English Department from 1976 to 1983 and the Director of the British Studies Program from 1976 to 1984. <s> He has been a member of the editorial board of the academic journal "ELH: English Literary History" and was senior editor from 1985 to 2004; he served on the editorial boards of the journals "Studies in English Literature"; PMLA; "Eighteenth-Century Studies"; and the Johns Hopkins University Press.

title: Barn-owl
complex: Barn owls (family Tytonidae) are one of the two families of owls, the other being the true owls or typical owls, Strigidae. <s> They are medium to large owls with large heads and characteristic heart-shaped faces. <s> They have long, strong legs with powerful talons. <s> They also differ from the Strigidae in structural details relating in particular to the sternum and feet. <s> The barn owls are a wide-ranging family, although they are absent from northern North America, Saharan Africa, and large areas of Asia. <s> They live in a wide range of habitats from deserts to forests, and from temperate latitudes to the tropics. <s> The majority of the twenty living species of barn-owls are poorly known. <s> Some, like the red owl, have barely been seen or studied since their discovery, in contrast to the common barn-owl, which is one of the best known owl species in the world. <s> However, some subspecies of the common barn-owl possibly deserve to be separate species, but are very poorly known. <s> The fossil record of the barn owls goes back to the Eocene, with the family eventually losing ground to the true owls after the radiation of rodents and owls during the Neogene epoch. <s> Two subfamilies are only known from the fossil record, the Necrobyinae and the Selenornithinae. <s> The barn owls' main characteristic is the heart-shaped facial disc, formed by stiff feathers which serve to amplify and locate the source of sounds when hunting. <s> Further adaptations in the wing feathers eliminate sound caused by flying, aiding both the hearing of the owl listening for hidden prey and keeping the prey unaware of the owl. <s> Barn-owls overall are darker on the back than the front, usually an orange-brown colour, the front being a paler version of the back or mottled, although considerable variation is seen even amongst species.
simple: Barn-owls (family Tytonidae) are one of the two families of owls. <s> The other is the true owls, Strigidae. <s> They are medium to large sized owls with large heads and heart-shaped faces. <s> They have long, strong legs with powerful talons. <s> The barn owls are a wide ranging family. <s> They are not found in northern North America, Saharan Africa and large areas of Asia. <s> They live in a wide range of habitats from deserts to forests, and from temperate latitudes to the tropics. <s> The fossil record of the barn-owls goes back to the Eocene. <s> The barn-owls' main characteristic is the heart-shaped facial disc, formed by stiff feathers. <s> The feathers help to amplify and locate the source of sounds when the bird hunts. <s> Adaptations to the wing feathers eliminate sound caused by flying. <s> This helps both the owl's hearing, and keeps the prey unaware of the owl.

title: Wildwood, New Jersey
complex: Wildwood is a city in Cape May County, New Jersey, United States. <s> It is part of the Ocean City Metropolitan Statistical Area and is a popular summer resort destination along the Jersey Shore. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the city's year-round population was 5,325, reflecting a decline of 111 (-2.0%) from the 5,436 counted in the 2000 Census, which had in turn increased by 952 (+21.2%) from the 4,484 counted in the 1990 Census. <s> With visitors, the population can swell to 250,000 during the summer months.
simple: Wildwood is a city in Cape May County, New Jersey, United States. <s> It is part of the Ocean City Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the city's year-round population was 5,325.

title: Redlands, California
complex: Redlands is a city in San Bernardino County, California, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 68,747, up from 63,591 at the 2000 census. <s> The population was estimated at 69,999 in 2013. <s> The city is located approximately 10 mi east of downtown San Bernardino.
simple: Redlands (Serrano: "Tukut") is a city in San Bernardino County, California, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 68,747. <s> The city is located about 10 mi east of San Bernardino.

title: Kazimierz Ryczan
complex: Kazimierz Ryczan (10 February 1939 – 13 September 2017) was a Polish Roman Catholic bishop. <s> Ordained to the priesthood on 16 June 1963, Ryczan was named bishop of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Kielce, Poland on 17 July 1993.
simple: Kazimierz Ryczan (10 February 1939 – 13 September 2017) was a Polish Roman Catholic bishop. <s> He was ordained to the priesthood on 16 June 1963, Ryczan was named bishop of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Kielce, Poland on 17 July 1993.

title: Powerbomb
complex: This move involves a wrestler standing over a bent over opponent, locking their arms around the opponent's waist and lifting them up, flipping them over, and slamming them down to the mat back first. <s> The difference compared to a regular powerbomb is that the opponent's head does not go between the wrestler's thighs, instead they remain slightly in front or to the side of the wrestler.
simple: This maneuver has a wrestler tuck an opponent's head in-between their legs, hook their arms lift them up, turning them in mid-air, and slam them down to the mat (ring).

title: Florence Bjelke-Petersen
complex: Florence Isabel Bjelke-Petersen (née Gilmour; 11 August 1920 – 20 December 2017) was an Australian politician and writer. <s> She was a member of the Australian Senate from 1981 to 1993, and was the wife of the longest-serving Premier of Queensland, Sir Joh Bjelke-Petersen. <s> She was styled as Lady Bjelke-Petersen upon her husband's knighthood, and was also known informally as Lady Flo. <s> She was re-elected at the 1983 and 1987 elections (both double dissolutions), and her term expired on 30 June 1993. <s> Bjelke-Petersen died in Kingaroy, Queensland, at Orana Aged Care, where she had resided since August 2014, at the age of 97, after suffering a short illness. <s> Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull and Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk offered to hold a state funeral which was accepted by their son John Bjelke-Petersen.
simple: Florence Isabel Bjelke-Petersen (née Gilmour; 11 August 1920 – 20 December 2017) was an Australian politician and writer. <s> She was a member of the Australian Senate from 1981 to 1993. <s> Bjelke-Petersen was the wife of the longest-serving Premier of Queensland, Sir Joh Bjelke-Petersen. <s> She was styled as Lady Bjelke-Petersen upon her husband's knighthood, and was also known informally as Lady Flo. <s> She was re-elected at the 1983 and 1987 elections (both double dissolutions), and her term expired on 30 June 1993. <s> Lady Bjelke-Petersen died in Kingaroy, Queensland on 20 December 2017 of cardiopulmonary arrest at the age of 97, after suffering a short illness.

title: Viktor Onopko
complex: Viktor Savelyevich Onopko (born 14 October 1969) is a football coach and a former defender. <s> He held the record for most international appearances for the Russian national team until 8 September 2015, when he was overtaken by Sergei Ignashevich.
simple: Viktor Onopko (born 14 October 1969) is a former Russian football player.

title: Kalayaan, Palawan
complex: President Ferdinand E. Marcos created the Municipality of Kalayaan by signing "Presidential Decree 1596" into law on June 11, 1978. <s> This established what the document described as "a distinct and separate municipality of the Province of Palawan".
simple: In 1978, the Presidential Decree No. 1596 established the municipality as part of Palawan.

title: Vijaya Mulay
complex: Vijaya Mulay (16 May 1921 – 19 May 2019) was a documentary filmmaker, film historian, writer, educationist and researcher. <s> Her close friendships with Satyajit Ray, Louis Malle, Mrinal Sen and other film personalities gave her a unique perspective into Indian cinema and influenced her work. <s> Her body of work has shaped how India is viewed by Indian and non-Indian filmmakers. <s> She is the mother of National Award winning actor Suhasini Mulay and Atul Gurtu the high energy physicist is her son-in-law. <s> Vijaya Mulay is remembered for her animation film "Ek Anek Aur Ekta" which won the National Film Award for Best Educational Film. <s> Vijaya Mulay was born in Bombay, India.
simple: Vijaya Mulay (16 May 1921 – 19 May 2019) was an Indian filmmaker, historian, writer, educationist and researcher. <s> Mulay died on 19 May 2019 at her south Delhi home. <s> For the movie, she won the National Film Award for Best Educational Film. <s> She was born in Bombay.

title: László Sólyom
complex: László Sólyom ( , ] ; born 3 January 1942) is a Hungarian political figure, lawyer, and librarian who was President of Hungary from 2005 until 2010. <s> Previously he was president of the Constitutional Court of Hungary from 1990 to 1998.
simple: László Sólyom (, ]; born 3 January 1942) is a Hungarian politician, lawyer, and librarian. <s> He was the President of Hungary from 2005 until 2010.

title: Zdeněk Grygera
complex: Zdeněk Grygera (] ; born 14 May 1980) is a retired Czech footballer. <s> A former defender, he was known for his work-rate, competitiveness, and versatility, and usually played as a full-back, wing-back, or winger along right flank, although he was also capable of playing on the left, or as a centre-back; while being solid defensively, he was also known for his ability to get forward and for his all-round good quality of play.
simple: Zdeněk Grygera (born 14 May 1980) is a Czech football player.

title: Anthony Mamo
complex: Sir Anthony Joseph Mamo, KUOM OBE QC (9 January 1909 – 1 May 2008) was the first President of Malta and previously served as the last Governor-General of the State of Malta before the country became a republic. <s> He was also the first Maltese citizen to be appointed Governor-General, and before independence, briefly served as acting Governor. <s> Mamo died on 1 May 2008 at the age of 99, at Casa Arkati Home for Elderly.
simple: Sir Anthony Joseph Mamo, KUOM OBE QC (9 January 1909 – 1 May 2008) was a Maltese politician. <s> He was the first President of Malta. <s> He was the last Governor-General of the State of Malta before the country became a republic. <s> Mamo died on 1 May 2008 at the age of 99, at Casa Arkati Home for Elderly.

title: Howard David
complex: Howard David is an American sportscaster. <s> Over the years, David has been the radio play-by-play man for several pro sports teams including the NBA's New Jersey Nets, Milwaukee Bucks, and Boston Celtics, and the NFL's New York Jets and Miami Dolphins. <s> He also had stints with the New York Cosmos soccer team and as the voice of Princeton University basketball and football. <s> David was one of Westwood One's NFL voices, having replaced Bill Rosinski in the booth for the Sunday doubleheader coverage the network carries. <s> He also served as a substitute for Dave Sims on Sunday nights when his other broadcasting endeavors leave him unavailable. <s> David was joined in the booth by Tony Boselli until 2012. <s> Tom McCarthy replaced David in the booth. <s> As of 2012, Dial Global's other NFL play-by-play announcers include Kevin Kugler, Kevin Harlan, Dave Sims, and Ian Eagle. <s> In 2012, David became the play-by-play voice for the United Football League broadcasts on the CBS Sports Network. <s> In 2013, he served as a fill-in play-by-play commentator for "Major League Baseball on Fox".
simple: Howard David is a longtime sportscaster. <s> He called NBA games for the New Jersey Nets, Milwaukee Bucks, and the Boston Celtics. <s> David called NFL games for the New York Jets and the Miami Dolphins. <s> David also called NBA games for ESPN Radio. <s> He called football and basketball for the New York Cosmos and the Princeton Tigers. <s> David returned to Westwood One until 2012. <s> David calls play-by-play for the United Football League on the CBS Sports Network. <s> He also called two games for MLB on Fox during the 2013 MLB season.

title: Second Party System
complex: Historians and political scientists consider the Second Party System to be a term of periodization to designate the political party system operating in the United States from about 1828 to 1854, after the First Party System ended. <s> The system was characterized by rapidly rising levels of voter interest, beginning in 1828, as demonstrated by Election Day turnouts, rallies, partisan newspapers, and high degrees of personal loyalty to parties. <s> Two major parties dominated the political landscape: the Democratic Party, led by Andrew Jackson, and the Whig Party, assembled by Henry Clay from the National Republicans and from other opponents of Jackson. <s> Minor parties included the Anti-Masonic Party, an important innovator from 1827 to 1834; the abolitionist Liberty Party in 1840; and the anti-slavery expansion Free Soil Party in 1848 and 1852. <s> The Second Party System reflected and shaped the political, social, economic and cultural currents of the Jacksonian Era, until succeeded by the Third Party System. <s> Historian Richard P. McCormick is most responsible for defining the term. <s> Among the best-known figures on the Democratic side were: Andrew Jackson, Martin Van Buren, John C. Calhoun, James K. Polk, Lewis Cass, and Stephen Douglas. <s> On the Whig side were John Quincy Adams, Henry Clay, Daniel Webster, William H. Seward, and Thurlow Weed. <s> The 1824 presidential election operated without political parties and came down to a four-man race. <s> Each candidate (Henry Clay, William Crawford, Andrew Jackson, and John Quincy Adams), all of whom were nominally Democratic Republicans, had a regional base of support involving factions in the various states. <s> With no electoral college majority, the choice devolved on the United States House of Representatives. <s> Clay was not among the three finalists, but as Speaker of the House he negotiated the settlement. <s> Jackson, despite having won the most popular votes and the most electoral votes, was not elected. <s> John Quincy Adams, son of former President John Adams, was elected, and he immediately chose Clay as Secretary of State. <s> Jackson loudly denounced this "corrupt bargain." <s> Campaigning vigorously he launched a crusade against the corruption he saw in Washington. <s> Appealing both to local militia companies (as the most famous of the nation's Indian fighters, and a hero of the War of 1812) and to state political factions, Jackson assembled a coalition, the embryonic Democratic Party, that ousted Adams in 1828. <s> Martin Van Buren, brilliant leader of New York politics, was Jackson's key aide, bringing along the large electoral votes of Virginia and Pennsylvania. <s> His reward was appointment as Secretary of State and later nomination and election to the vice presidency as heir to the Jacksonian tradition. <s> The Adams-Clay wing of the Democratic-Republican Party became known as the National Republicans, although Adams never considered himself a loyal member of the party. <s> Jackson considered himself a reformer, but he was committed to the old ideals of Republicanism, and bitterly opposed anything that smacked of special favors for special interests. <s> While Jackson never engaged in a duel as president, he had shot political opponents before and was just as determined to destroy his enemies on the battlefields of politics. <s> The Second Party System came about primarily because of Jackson's determination to destroy the Second Bank of the United States. <s> Headquartered in Philadelphia, with offices in major cities around the country, the federally chartered Bank operated somewhat like a central bank (like the Federal Reserve System a century later). <s> Local bankers and politicians annoyed by the controls exerted by Nicholas Biddle grumbled loudly. <s> Jackson did not like any banks (paper money was anathema to Jackson; he believed only gold and silver "specie" should circulate.) <s> After Herculean battles with Henry Clay, his chief antagonist, Jackson finally broke Biddle's bank. <s> Jackson continued to attack the banking system. <s> His "Specie Circular" of July 1836 rejected paper money issued by banks (it could no longer be used to buy federal land), insisting on gold and silver coins. <s> Most businessmen and bankers (but not all) went over to the Whig party, and the commercial and industrial cities became Whig strongholds. <s> Jackson meanwhile became even more popular with the subsistence farmers and day laborers who distrusted bankers and finance. <s> Jackson systematically used the federal patronage system, what was called the "Spoils System". <s> Jackson not only rewarded past supporters; he promised future jobs if local and state politicians joined his team. <s> As Syrett explains: When Jackson became President, he implemented the theory of rotation in office, declaring it "a leading principle in the republican creed." <s> He believed that rotation in office would prevent the development of a corrupt civil service. <s> On the other hand, Jackson's supporters wanted to use the civil service to reward party loyalists to make the party stronger. <s> In practice, this meant replacing civil servants with friends or party loyalists into those offices. <s> The spoils system did not originate with Jackson. <s> It originated under Thomas Jefferson when he removed Federalist office-holders after becoming president. <s> Also, Jackson did not out the entire civil service. <s> At the end of his term, Jackson had only dismissed less than twenty percent of the original civil service. <s> While Jackson did not start the spoils system, he did encourage its growth and it became a central feature of the Second Party System, as well as the Third Party System, until it ended in the 1890s. <s> As one historian explains: "Although Jackson dismissed far fewer government employees than most of his contemporaries imagined and although he did not originate the spoils system, he made more sweeping changes in the Federal bureaucracy than had any of his predecessors.
simple: It is a phrase used by historians and political scientists to describe the time period between 1828 and 1854. <s> People quickly became more interested in voting starting in 1828. <s> One was the Democratic Party, led by Andrew Jackson. <s> The other was the Whig Party, started by Henry Clay. <s> The Whig party was made up of members of the National Republican Party and other people who opposed Jackson. <s> The Anti-Masonic Party (1827-34) was important in developing political ideas and laws. <s> The United States Free Soil Party in 1848 and 1852 was another anti-slavery party. <s> The Second Party System was an important part of the politics, society, economics, and culture of the Jacksonian Era. <s> The phrase "second party system" was defined by the historian Richard P. McCormick. <s> Some famous democrats were: Andrew Jackson, Martin Van Buren, John C. Calhoun, James K. Polk, Lewis Cass, and Stephen Douglas. <s> Some famous Whigs were: Henry Clay, Daniel Webster, William H. Seward, and Thurlow Weed. <s> The United States presidential election in 1824 did not have any political parties. <s> There were four main candidates for president: Henry Clay, William Crawford, Andrew Jackson, and John Quincy Adams. <s> The three final candidates were Adams, Crawford, and Jackson. <s> At the end of the race, none of the candidates had enough votes in the electoral college to win, and the United States House of Representatives had to choose the winner. <s> Even though Clay was not one of these finalists, he was the Speaker of the House, and it was his job to negotiate who would become president. <s> Jackson had the most popular votes (votes cast by citizens) and the most electoral votes (votes cast by the electoral college), but was not elected. <s> Instead, John Quincy Adams was elected president. <s> He immediately chose Clay to be his Secretary of State. <s> Jackson loudly declared this to be a "corrupt bargain." <s> Jackson was a very popular politician, the most famous fighter of the American Indian Wars, and a hero of the War of 1812. <s> Martin Van Buren, a brilliant leader in New York politics, was Jackson's most important supporter. <s> Van Buren was popular in Virginia and Pennsylvania, and he had the support of their electoral college votes. <s> Van Buren became the Secretary of State, and later Vice President. <s> Adams, Clay, and their supporters in the Democratic-Republican Party became known as the National Republicans. <s> Andrew Jackson opposed (was against) the idea of giving special favors to special interest groups. <s> He strongly opposed the Second Bank of the United States. <s> The Bank was a federal institution that worked somewhat like a central bank. <s> Jackson did not like any banks, and he did not believe in paper money. <s> (He believed that money should only be gold and silver.) <s> Jackson continued to attack the banking system. <s> He issued his "Specie Circular" in July 1836. <s> The Circular said that only gold and siver coins, and not paper money, could be used to buy federal land. <s> This made most businessmen and bankers join the Whig party. <s> Also, cities that depended on commerce (trade) and industry became supporters of the Whig party. <s> Jackson became more popular with subsistence farmers (farmers who grow crops to eat, but not to sell) and day laborers. <s> Jackson used the spoils system a lot when he was president. <s> He rewarded his supporters and promised future jobs if local and state politicians joined his team. <s> He believed in the theory of rotation in office, where people would only remain in a position for a short time. <s> He believed that this would keep the civil service from becoming corrupt. <s> In total, Jackson dismissed less than twenty percent (20%) of the original civil service. <s> As president, Jackson encouraged the use of the spoils system. <s> It became an important part of the Second Party System and the Third Party System. <s> The spoils system was ended in the 1890s.

title: Hiroaki Hiraoka
complex: Hiroaki Hiraoka (平岡 拓晃 , Hiraoka Hiroaki , born February 6, 1985 in Hiroshima City) is a Japanese judoka. <s> He won a silver medal at the 2009 World Judo Championships and the 2011 World Championships and a bronze medal at the 2010 World Judo Championships. <s> Hiroka also won a silver medal at the 2012 Summer Olympics at London, in the men's under 60 kg extra-lightweight category.
simple: Hiroaki Hiraoka (平岡 拓晃, Hiraoka Hiroaki, born February 6, 1985) is a Japanese athlete. <s> He is best known as a judoka. <s> He won a silver medal at the 2009 World Judo Championships and bronze medal at the 2010 World Judo Championships. <s> Hiroka won the silver medal in 2012 Summer Olympics at London, in the men's under 60 kg extra-lightweight judo.

title: Amparo Rivelles
complex: María Amparo Rivelles Ladrón de Guevara (11 February 1925 – 7 November 2013), better known as Amparo Rivelles, was a Spanish actress. <s> She worked in Mexican films and telenovelas. <s> She was the daughter of actor Rafael Rivelles and actress María Fernanda Ladrón de Guevara, and the half-sister of actor Carlos Larrañaga.
simple: Amparo Rivelles, (real name: María Amparo Rivelles Ladrón de Guevara) (11 February 1925 – 7 November 2013) was a Spanish actress. <s> Rivelles was born on 11 February 1925 in Madrid, Spain. <s> In the beginning of her career, she was known as Amparito Rivelles. <s> Rivelles died on 7 November 2013 in Madrid, Spain from unknown causes, aged 88. <s> She worked in Cinema of Mexico and in telenovelas.

title: Rodrigo Valdéz
complex: Rodrigo Valdéz (December 22, 1946 – March 14, 2017) was a Colombian boxer who was the undisputed world middleweight champion, whose rivalry with Carlos Monzón has long been considered among the most legendary boxing rivalries. <s> Valdez was trained by International Boxing Hall of Fame coach Gil Clancy. <s> Many people consider him, Antonio Cervantes and Miguel "Happy" Lora to be the three greatest boxers ever to come from that country. <s> He is 29th on Ring Magazine's list of 100 greatest punchers of all time. <s> According to Colombian sources, Valdez died of a massive heart attack on March 14, 2017. <s> Cartagena mayor Manuel Duque confirmed the two time former world champion's death, calling him "one of the greatest Colombian sportsmen of all time".
simple: Rodrigo Valdez (December 22, 1946 – March 14, 2017) was a boxer from Colombia who was a World Middleweight Champion and Undisputed World Middleweight Champion whose rivalry with Carlos Monzón has long been considered among the most legendary boxing rivalries. <s> Valdez was trained by International Boxing Hall of Fame coach Gil Clancy. <s> Many people consider him, Antonio Cervantes and Miguel "Happy" Lora to be the three greatest boxers ever to come from that country. <s> He is 29th on Ring Magazine's list of 100 greatest punchers of all time. <s> Valdéz died on March 14, 2017 in Cartagena, Colombia from a heart attack, aged 70.

title: Linden, Alabama
complex: Linden is a city in and the county seat of Marengo County, Alabama, United States. <s> The population was 2,123 at the 2010 census. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 2,424 people, 938 households, and 662 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 675.6 people per square mile (260.7/km2).
simple: Linden is a city in and the county seat of Marengo County, Alabama, United States. <s> The population was 2,424 at the 2000 census.

title: Evgeny Tomashevsky
complex: Evgeny Yuryevich Tomashevsky ( ; born 1 July 1987) is a Russian chess grandmaster. <s> He was European champion in 2009. <s> Tomashevsky was Russian champion in 2015 and 2019. <s> Tomashevsky won the Russian under-10 championship in 1997 and the Russian U18 championship in 2001, at the age of 13 years, in Rybinsk with a score of 9.5 points from 11 games. <s> In 2004 he finished runner-up in the U18 division of the World Youth Chess Championships. <s> In 2007, he came second in the Aeroflot Open. <s> In 2009, Tomashevsky won the 10th European Individual Chess Championship after tie-breaks. <s> The decisive match against Vladimir Malakhov went into armageddon stadium, where Malakhov blundered a rook in a winning position. <s> In January 2010, he played for the gold medal-winning Russian team at the World Team Chess Championship 2009 in Bursa. <s> In 2011, he tied for first place with Nikita Vitiugov and Lê Quang Liêm in the Aeroflot Open, placing third on tiebreak. <s> He was one of the seconds to Boris Gelfand for the World Chess Championship 2012. <s> Partly for being a mostly positional player, partly for wearing glasses and being well-educated, Tomashevsky earned himself the nickname "Professor" among the chessplayers.
simple: Evgeny Tomashevsky, born 1 July 1987 in Saratov, is a Russian chess grandmaster. <s> In 2001 he won the U18 Russian championship in Rybinsk with 9/10 and in 2004 he became second in the U18 World Youth Chess Championship. <s> In 2007 he became second in the Aeroflot Open. <s> In 2009 Tomashevsky won the 10th European Individual Chess Championship after tie-breaks. <s> The decisive match against Vladimir Malakhov went into armageddon, where Malakhov blundered a rook in a winning position. <s> He was a member of the gold-medal-winning Russian team at the World Team Chess Championship 2009 in Bursa. <s> In 2011, he tied for 1st-3rd with Nikita Vitiugov and Le Quang Liem in the Aeroflot Open. <s> Tomashevsky's style of play is described as being mostly positional.

title: Patrice Talon
complex: Patrice Guillaume Athanase Talon (born 1 May 1958) is a Beninese businessman and politician who has been President of Benin since 6 April 2016.
simple: Patrice Guillaume Athanase Talon (born 1 May 1958) is a Beninese businessman and politician. <s> He has been President of Benin since 6 April 2016.

title: Sangatte
