simple: Sangatte is a commune.

title: Lyceum (Classical)
complex: It was best known for the Peripatetic school of philosophy founded there by Aristotle in 334 / 335 BCE . <s> Aristotle fled Athens in 323 BCE , but the school continued to function under a series of leaders until the Roman general Sulla destroyed it during his assault on Athens in 86 BCE. <s> In 335 BCE, Athens fell under Macedonian rule and Aristotle, aged 50, returned from Asia. <s> Upon his return, Aristotle began teaching regularly in the morning in the Lyceum and founded an official school called "The Lyceum". <s> After morning lessons, Aristotle would frequently lecture on the grounds for the public, and manuscripts of his compiled lectures were eventually circulated. <s> The group of scholars who followed the Aristotelian doctrine came to be known as the Peripatetics due to Aristotle's tendency to walk as he taught. <s> Aristotle's main focus as a teacher was cooperative research, an idea which he founded through his natural history work and systematic collection of philosophical works to contribute to his library. <s> His students were assigned historical or scientific research projects as part of their studies. <s> The school was also student run. <s> The students elected a new student administrator to work with the school leadership every ten days, allowing all the students to become involved in turn. <s> Before returning to Athens, Aristotle had been the tutor of Alexander of Macedonia, who became the great conqueror Alexander the Great. <s> Throughout his conquests of various regions, Alexander collected plant and animal specimens for Aristotle's research, allowing Aristotle to develop the first zoo and botanical garden in existence. <s> It is also suspected that Alexander donated what would be the equivalent of more than 4 million dollars to the Lyceum. <s> In 322 BCE , Aristotle was forced to flee Athens with his family when the political leadership reacted against the Macedonians again and his previously published works supporting Macedonian rule left him a target. <s> He passed on his Lyceum to Theophrastus and died later that year in Chalcis, near his hometown.
simple: He founded the Peripatetic school there in 334/335 BC. <s> The school started when Athens fell under Macedonian rule, and the 50-year old Aristotle returned from Asia. <s> In Athens, he began teaching regularly in the morning in the Lyceum. <s> The group of scholars who took part came to be known as the Peripatetics. <s> Aristotle encouraged cooperative research. <s> His students were given projects as part of their studies. <s> The school was also student run. <s> They elected a new student administrator every ten days, which allowed the students to become involved in turn. <s> During his conquests of Asian regions, Alexander collected plant and animal specimens for Aristotle’s research. <s> Aristotle developed the first zoo and botanical garden in existence. <s> Alexander may also have given money to the Lyceum. <s> In 322 BC, Aristotle was forced to flee Athens with his family when the political leaders reacted against the Macedonians. <s> Aristotle's published works supporting Macedonian rule left him a target. <s> He passed on his Lyceum to Theophrastus and died later that year near his hometown.

title: Session key
complex: A session key is a single-use symmetric key used for encrypting all messages in one communication session. <s> A closely related term is content encryption key (CEK), traffic encryption key (TEK), or multicast key which refers to any key used to encrypt messages, as opposed to other uses, like encrypting other keys (key encryption key (KEK) or key wrapping key). <s> Session keys can introduce complication into a system. <s> However, they solve some real problems. <s> Like all cryptographic keys, session keys must be chosen so that they cannot be predicted by an attacker, usually requiring them to be chosen randomly. <s> Failure to choose session keys (or any key) properly is a major (and too common in actual practice) design flaw in any crypto system.
simple: A session key is a single-use symmetric key used for encrypting all messages in one communication session. <s> A closely related term is traffic encryption key or TEK, which refers to any symmetric key that is used to encrypt traffic messages. <s> Session keys introduce complexities in a cryptosystem. <s> However, they also help with some real problems, which is why they are used. <s> Like all cryptographic keys, session keys must be chosen so that they are unpredictable by an attacker. <s> Failure to choose session keys (or any key) properly is a major drawback in any cryptosystem.

title: Txillardegi
complex: José Luis Álvarez Enparantza (27 September 1929 – 14 January 2012), better known by his pseudonym Txillardegi, was a Basque linguist, politician and writer from Spain. <s> Born in San Sebastián (Basque Country, Spain), he did not learn the Basque language until the age of 17, but came to be considered one of the most influential figures in Basque nationalism and culture in the second half of the 20th century. <s> After becoming disillusioned with the PNV, Txillardegi was one of the founders of ETA in 1959, together with a group of young nationalists and was the visible leader of the cultural branch of the movement. <s> In 1961 he fled into exile, in Paris and Brussels, returning in 1967.
simple: José Luis Álvarez Enparantza (27 September 1929 – 14 January 2012) was a Basque linguist, politician and writer. <s> When writing he used the pseudonym Txillardegi. <s> He was born in Donostia, which is called "San Sebastian" in Spanish. <s> Even though he did not learn the Basque language until he was 17, he came to be seen as one of the most influential figures in Basque nationalism and culture in the second half of the 20th century. <s> Together with some friends he started ETA in 1959, and became responsible for their social and cultural activities.

title: Vesanto
complex: Vesanto is a municipality of Finland. <s> Neighbour municipalities are Keitele, Konnevesi, Rautalampi, Tervo, Viitasaari and Äänekoski.

title: Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home
complex: The Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home is the house located at 816 South Hennepin Avenue, Dixon, Illinois, in which the 40th President of the United States Ronald Reagan lived as a youth beginning in 1920. <s> The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.
simple: The Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home is the house located at 816 South Hennepin Street, Dixon, Illinois, in which the late former President of the United States Ronald Reagan lived as a youth beginning in 1920. <s> The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.

title: Hult, Sweden
complex: Hult is a locality situated in Eksjö Municipality, Jönköping County, Sweden. <s> It had 455 inhabitants in 2010. <s> The artist and writer Albert Engström grew up at Hult. <s> He was born on May 12, 1869 in Bäckfall, Lönneberga.
simple: Hult is a locality in Eksjö Municipality in Jönköping County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 455 people lived there. <s> Swedish writer Albert Engström grew up in Hult.

title: Observation deck
complex: An observation deck, observation platform or viewing platform is an elevated sightseeing platform usually situated upon a tall architectural structure such as a skyscraper or observation tower. <s> Observation decks are sometimes enclosed from weather, and a few may include coin-operated telescopes for viewing distant features.
simple: An observation deck is a place up high where people can see things.

title: Dana Bash
complex: Dana Bash ( ; born Dana Ruth Schwartz; June 15, 1971) is an American journalist, anchorwoman, and political correspondent for CNN. <s> Bash was born to a Reform Jewish family in Manhattan. <s> Her father was an ABC News producer who served as the senior broadcast producer for "Good Morning America" and her mother was an author and educator in Jewish studies. <s> Bash was one of the women honored at "Elle" magazine's 2014 "Women in Washington Power List" event.
simple: Dana Bash ( ; born Dana Ruth Schwartz; June 15, 1971) is an American journalist, anchorwoman and political correspondent. <s> She is known for being a correspondent for "CNN". <s> Born in New York City to a Jewish family and raised in Montvale, New Jersey. <s> Bash was one of the women honored at "Elle" magazine's 2014 "Women in Washington Power List" event.

title: List of colleges and universities in Vermont
complex: There are 18 currently operating colleges and universities based in the U.S. state of Vermont. <s> This figure includes one research university, six master's universities, an art school, a culinary school, a law school, and a number of undergraduate associates and baccalaureate colleges. <s> Four institutions chartered in other states offer degree programs at locations in Vermont. <s> The state's largest school is its flagship public university, the University of Vermont. <s> The other four public institutions are organized as the Vermont State Colleges system.
simple: In the state of Vermont, United States, there are 23 colleges and universities. <s> This includes one research university, six master's universities, an art school, a culinary school, a law school. <s> The state's largest school is its public university, the University of Vermont.

simple: Lillehammer is a city in Oppland county, Norway.

title: Superland
complex: Superland is an amusement park in Rishon LeZion, Israel. <s> Superland covers an area of 94 acres and has three roller coasters, three wet and dry facilities, a cablecar, and a bungee jumping "Skycoastr." <s> Superland opened to the public in 1991 and is one of the main amusement parks in Israel, along with Luna Park in Tel Aviv, My Baby in Yarka Zapari Birds park in Tel Aviv.
simple: Superland is an amusement park in Rishon LeZion, Israel. <s> It was opened in 1991.

title: Pennsylvania Route 82
complex: Pennsylvania Route 82 (PA 82) is a 32 mi north–south state highway located in Chester County in southeast Pennsylvania, USA. <s> The southern terminus is at the Delaware state line southeast of Kennett Square, where PA 82 continues south as Delaware Route 82 (DE 82).
simple: Pennsylvania Route 82 is a state highway in Pennsylvania.

title: Cryptosporidium parvum
complex: Cryptosporidium parvum is one of several species that cause cryptosporidiosis, a parasitic disease of the mammalian intestinal tract.
simple: Cryptosporidium is a protozoan parasite which causes outbreaks of diarrhea. <s> The most common species to infect man is "Cryptosporidium parvum".

title: Kevum
complex: Kevum or Kavum is a deep-fried Sri Lankan sweet made from rice flour and kithul (sugar-palm) treacle, with a number of variants adding additional ingredients. <s> It is also known as "oil cake". <s> Kevum is traditionally given and consumed during celebrations of Sinhala New Year.
simple: Kavum (Konda Kavum) is a sweet food often eaten in Sri Lanka. <s> The main ingredients are rice flour and treacle, which are fried together. <s> It may also be known as 'oil cakes'.

title: Salt evaporation pond
complex: A salt evaporation pond is a shallow artificial salt pan designed to extract salts from sea water or other brines. <s> Natural salt pans are geological formations that are also created by water evaporating and leaving behind salts. <s> Some salt evaporation ponds are only slightly modified from their natural version, such as the ponds on Great Inagua in the Bahamas, or the ponds in Jasiira, a few kilometres south of Mogadishu, where seawater is trapped and left to evaporate in the sun. <s> The seawater or brine is fed into large ponds and water is drawn out through natural evaporation which allows the salt to be subsequently harvested. <s> The ponds also provide a productive resting and feeding ground for many species of waterbirds, which may include endangered species. <s> The ponds are commonly separated by levees. <s> Salt evaporation ponds may also be called salterns, salt works or salt pans. <s> Due to variable algal concentrations, vivid colors (from pale green to bright red) are created in the evaporation ponds. <s> The color indicates the salinity of the ponds. <s> Microorganisms change their hues as the salinity of the pond increases. <s> In low- to mid-salinity ponds, green algae such as Dunaliella salina are predominant, although these algae can also take on an orange hue. <s> In middle- to high-salinity ponds, Halobacteria, which is actually a group of halophilic Archaea (sometimes called Haloarchaea), shift the colour to pink, red and orange. <s> Other bacteria such as "Stichococcus" also contribute tints.
simple: A Salt evaporation pond (or saltern pond) is a man-made shallow pond. <s> The water is then left to evaporate. <s> The salt is left behind, and can be harvested. <s> Such ponds also provide a habitat for several kinds of animals. <s> The color tells how much salt there is left in the water. <s> These algae are there in low to mid salinity ponds (ponds with little salt in the water). <s> In middle to high salinity ponds, an alga called Dunaliella salina shifts the color to red. <s> Other bacteria such as Stichococcus also contribute tints.

title: Northern Mariana Islands
complex: The Northern Mariana Islands, officially the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands (CNMI; ; Refaluwasch or Carolinian: "Commonwealth Téél Falúw kka Efáng llól Marianas"), is an insular area and commonwealth of the United States consisting of 14 islands in the northwestern Pacific Ocean. <s> The CNMI includes the 14 northernmost islands in the Mariana Archipelago except the southernmost island of the chain, Guam, which is a separate U.S. territory. <s> The CNMI and Guam are the westernmost point (in terms of jurisdiction) and territory of the United States. <s> The Northern Mariana Islands, together with Guam to the south, compose the Mariana Islands archipelago. <s> The southern islands are limestone, with level terraces and fringing coral reefs. <s> The northern islands are volcanic, with active volcanoes on several islands, including Anatahan, Pagan, and Agrihan. <s> The volcano on Agrihan has the highest elevation at 3166 ft . <s> An expedition organized by John D. Mitchler and Reid Larson made the first complete ascent to the summit of this peak on June 1, 2018. <s> Anatahan Volcano is a small volcanic island 80 mi north of Saipan. <s> It is about 6 mi long and 2 mi wide. <s> Anatahan began erupting from its east crater on May 10, 2003. <s> It has since alternated between eruptive and calm periods. <s> On April 6, 2005, an estimated 50000000 cuft of ash and rock were ejected, causing a large, black cloud to drift south over Saipan and Tinian.
simple: The Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands is a group of islands in the Pacific Ocean that are a political division controlled by the United States. <s> The Northern Mariana Islands, together with Guam to the south, compose the Mariana Islands. <s> The southern islands are limestone, with level terraces and fringing coral reefs. <s> The northern islands are volcanic, with active volcanos on Anatahan, Pagan and Agrihan. <s> The volcano on Agrihan has the highest elevation at 3166 ft. Anatahan Volcano is a small volcanic island 80 mi north of Saipan. <s> It is about 6 mi long and 2 mi wide. <s> Anatahan began erupting suddenly from its east crater on May 10, 2003, at about 6 p.m. (0800 UTC). <s> It has since alternated between eruptive and calm periods. <s> On April 6, 2005, approximately 1800000 cuft of ash and rock were ejected, causing a large, black cloud to drift south over Saipan and Tinian.

title: Cry of Dolores
complex: The Cry of Dolores is a historical event that occurred in Dolores (now Dolores Hidalgo), Mexico, in the early morning of 16 September 1810. <s> Roman Catholic priest Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla rang the bell of his church and gave the "pronunciamiento" (call to arms) that triggered the Mexican War of Independence. <s> Gutiérrez de Lara went to Washington, D.C. for military support (being the first Mexican to do so). <s> Hidalgo remained in Dolores, waiting for Gutiérrez de Lara to return with military support. <s> However, fearing arrest, Hidalgo told his brother Mauricio to make the sheriff free the pro-independence inmates there. <s> Mauricio and armed men set 80 inmates free in the early morning of 16 September 1810. <s> Around 2:30 a.m., Hidalgo ordered the church bells to be rung and gathered his congregation. <s> Flanked by Ignacio Allende and Juan Aldama, he addressed the people in front of his church, urging them to revolt. <s> His speech became known as the "Cry of Dolores". <s> The liberated country adopted Mexico as its official name. <s> Mexico's independence from Spain took a decade of war. <s> Gutiérrez de Lara commanded and led Mexico to victory. <s> Independence was achieved by the Declaration of Independence of the Mexican Empire on 28 September 1821. <s> However, Hidalgo is credited as being the "father of his country." <s> There is no scholarly consensus on the exact words Miguel Hidalgo said at the time. <s> The book "The Course of Mexican History" says "the exact words of this most famous of all Mexican speeches are not known, or, rather, they are reproduced in almost as many variations as there are historians to reproduce them". <s> The Cry of Dolores has assumed an almost mythical status. <s> Since the late 20th century, the event has come to symbolize Mexican independence and to initiate Independence Day ceremonies the following day (16 September). <s> Independence Day in Mexico is a patriotic holiday, marked by parades, concerts, patriotic programs, drum and bugle and marching band competitions, and special programs on the national and local media outlets. <s> Every 15 September at around 11 p.m., the President of Mexico stands on the balcony of the National Palace in Mexico City and rings the same bell that Hidalgo rang in 1810, which was moved to the National Palace. <s> The President then recites a shout of patriotism (a Grito Mexicano) based upon the "Grito de Dolores", with the names of the important heroes of the Mexican War of Independence who were there on that historic day. <s> The Grito ends with the threefold shout of "¡Viva México!" <s> After the recitation, the President rings the bell one last time, and waves the Flag of Mexico to the applause of the crowd. <s> This is followed by the playing of the Mexican national anthem by a military band from the Mexican Armed Forces. <s> The crowd sings along. <s> The ceremonies conclude with a spectacular fireworks display at the Zocalo grounds. <s> On the morning of 16 September, or Independence Day, the national military parade in honor of the holiday starts in the Zócalo and its outskirts, passes the Hidalgo Memorial and ends on the Paseo de la Reforma, Mexico City’s main boulevard, passing "El Ángel de la Independencia" memorial column and other places along the way. <s> President Felipe Calderón made an exception by re-enacting the Grito in Dolores Hidalgo as part of the bicentennial celebrations on 16 September 2010, even though he had already done so the night before from the National Palace balcony to launch the celebrations. <s> As a result, in 2012, Calderón's final year as President, he did not go to Dolores Hidalgo but gave the Grito from the National Palace balcony instead. <s> President Enrique Peña Nieto did not give the Grito in Dolores Hidalgo in any of his six years as President, becoming the fourth president to break the tradition. <s> Similar celebrations to the Presidential one occur in cities and towns throughout Mexico, and in Mexican embassies and consulates worldwide on 15 or 16 September. <s> The chief executive, ambassador, or consul rings a bell and recites the traditional words, including the names of independence heroes and local patriots, and ending with the threefold shout of "Viva Mexico!" <s> The bell rings a second time, the Mexican flag is waved, and everyone sings the National Anthem, followed by fireworks.
simple: The Grito de Dolores ("Cry of Dolores") was the call issued by Father Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla, a Catholic priest, on 16 September, 1810 in the small town of Dolores (Therefore the Grito "de Dolores"). <s> Because he was afraid to get arrested, Hidalgo made his brother Mauricio and a number of other men with guns go to the sheriff. <s> They set eighty free. <s> The next morning, at around 6:00 am, Hidalgo ordered the church bells to be rung. <s> With Ignacio Allende and Juan Aldama by his side, he spoke to the people in front of his church. <s> Mexico's independence from Spain wouldn't be declared until September 27, 1821, after ten years of war. <s> This happened with the declaration of the first Mexican Empire. <s> Researchers do not agree as to what exactly Hidalgo said at the time. <s> September 16 is Independence Day in Mexico and is considered a patriotic holiday, or fiesta patria (literally, "holiday of the Fatherland"). <s> This day is celebrated with parades, patriotic programs, drum and bugle and marching band competitions, and other special events. <s> Every year on the night of September 15 the President of Mexico rings the bell of the National Palace in Mexico City at around eleven in the evening. <s> After the ringing of the bell, he repeats a cry of patriotism (a Grito Mexicano) based upon the "Grito de Dolores". <s> He calls out the names of the important heroes of the Mexican War of Independence and ends with the shout of "Viva Mexico!" <s> After the shouting, he rings the bell again and waves the Flag of Mexico to the applause of the crowd in the Plaza de la Constitución. <s> This is followed by the playing and mass singing of the Himno Nacional Mexicano, the national anthem. <s> On the morning of September 16, or Independence Day, the national military parade starts in the Zócalo (another name for the Plaza de la Constitución). <s> It goes past the Hidalgo Memorial and ends on the Paseo de la Reforma, Mexico City’s main boulevard. <s> President Calderón went to Dolores Hidalgo as part of the bicentennial celebrations in 2010 on the 16th of September. <s> A similar celebration happens in cities and towns all over Mexico, and in Mexican embassies and consulates worldwide, on the 15th or the 16th. <s> The mayor or governor, ambassadors or consuls will take on the role of the president, and ring the bells, give a speech and so on.

title: Thalía
complex: Ariadna Thalía Sodi Miranda (] ; born 26 August 1971) is a Mexican singer, songwriter, producer, actress and entrepreneur. <s> She is considered one of the most successful and influential Mexican artists worldwide. <s> Apart from her native Spanish, Thalía has also sung in English, French, Portuguese and Tagalog. <s> She is sometimes referred to as the "Queen of Latin Pop" by international media because of her renown within the Latin pop music scene for the last three decades. <s> She has sold over 25 million records worldwide. <s> She has received numerous accolades, including five "Billboard" Latin Music Awards (from 17 nominations), several Premios Juventud and Lo Nuestro Awards, as well as seven Latin Grammy Award nominations. <s> She has collaborated with renowned artists, such as Tony Bennett, Michael Bublé, Robbie Williams, Marc Anthony, Laura Pausini, Romeo Santos and Carlos Vives as well as with younger popular artists like Maluma, Prince Royce, Becky G, Natti Natasha, Gente de Zona and Lali.
simple: Ariadna Thalía Sodi Miranda (born August 26, 1971), known as Thalía, is a Mexican singer, songwriter and actress. <s> She has sung in Spanish, English, French, Portuguese and Tagalog. <s> She has sold over 25 million albums worldwide. <s> Thalia has been nominated for various Latin Grammy, Latin Billboard and many other awards.

title: 1995 Chicago heat wave
complex: The 1995 Chicago heat wave was a heat wave which led to 739 heat-related deaths in Chicago over a period of five days. <s> Most of the victims of the heat wave were elderly poor residents of the city, who could not afford air conditioning and did not open windows or sleep outside for fear of crime. <s> The heat wave also heavily impacted the wider Midwestern region, with additional deaths in both St. Louis, Missouri and Milwaukee, Wisconsin. <s> The temperatures soared to record highs in July with the hottest weather occurring from July 12 to July 16. <s> The high of 106 °F on July 13 was the second warmest July temperature (warmest being 110 °F set on July 23, 1934) since records began at Chicago Midway International Airport in 1928. <s> Nighttime low temperatures were unusually high — in the upper 70s and lower 80s °F (about 26 °C).
simple: The 1995 Chicago heat wave was a major heat wave. <s> It led to over 600 heat-related deaths in Chicago. <s> Most of the heat wave victims were old or poor people. <s> They did not have enough money for air conditioning and would not open their windows. <s> The people also didn't sleep outside for fear of crime. <s> The heat also affected Milwaukee and St. Louis. <s> There were near-record highs as well. <s> The hottest weather was between Wednesday, July 12 and Sunday, July 16. <s> The highest temperature was 106 F at Chicago's Midway International Airport.

title: Fernando Gómez Doblas
complex: Fernando Gómez Doblas (born October 16, 1965 in Málaga) is a track and field athlete from Spain with cerebral palsy. <s> He competes as a T36 type athlete. <s> He competed at the 1996 Summer Paralympics in Atlanta, Georgia, winning a silver in the 400 meter T34-T35 race, the 200 meter T34-T35 race and the 100 meter T35 race. <s> He competed at the 2000 Summer Paralympics in Sydney, Australia, where he did not meal in any of his races.
simple: Fernando Gómez Doblas (born October 16, 1965 in Málaga) is a track and field athlete from Spain. <s> He has a disability: He has cerebral palsy and a T36 type athlete. <s> He raced at the 1996 Summer Paralympics in Atlanta, Georgia. <s> He finished second in the 400 meter T34-T35 race, the 200 meter T34-T35 race and the 100 meter T35 race. <s> He raced at the 2000 Summer Paralympics in Sydney, Australia. <s> He did not finish 1, 2 or 3 in any race he raced in at the 2000 Games.

title: Mohamed Sissoko
complex: Mohamed Lamine Sissoko Gillan (born 22 January 1985) is a Malian professional footballer who plays as a defensive midfielder.
simple: Mohamed Sissoko (born 22 January 1985) is a Malian football player.

title: Moros
complex: Moros is the offspring of Nyx, the primordial goddess of the night. <s> It is suggested by Gaius Julius Hyginus that Moros was sired by Erebus, primordial god of darkness.
simple: He was the child of Nyx and brother to Thanatos.

title: SMS Posen
complex: SMS "Posen" was one of four battleships in the "Nassau" class , the first dreadnoughts built for the German Imperial Navy ("Kaiserliche Marine"). <s> The ship was laid down at the Germaniawerft shipyard in Kiel on 11 June 1907, launched on 12 December 1908, and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet on 31 May 1910. <s> She was equipped with a main battery of twelve 28 cm guns in six twin turrets in an unusual hexagonal arrangement. <s> The ship served with her three sister ships for the majority of World War I. <s> She saw extensive service in the North Sea, where she took part in several fleet sorties. <s> These culminated in the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, where "Posen" was heavily engaged in night-fighting against British light forces. <s> In the confusion, the ship accidentally rammed the light cruiser , which suffered serious damage and was scuttled later in the night. <s> The ship also conducted several deployments to the Baltic Sea against the Russian Navy. <s> In the first of these, "Posen" supported a German naval assault in the Battle of the Gulf of Riga. <s> The ship was sent back to the Baltic in 1918 to support the White Finns in the Finnish Civil War. <s> At the end of the war, "Posen" remained in Germany while the majority of the fleet was interned in Scapa Flow. <s> In 1919, following the scuttling of the German fleet in Scapa Flow, she was ceded to the British as a replacement for the ships that had been sunk. <s> She was then sent to ship-breakers in the Netherlands and scrapped in 1922. <s> "Posen" was 146.1 m long, 26.9 m wide, and had a draft of 8.9 m . <s> She displaced 18,873 t with a standard load, and 20,535 t fully laden. <s> The ship had a crew of 40 officers and 968 enlisted men. <s> "Posen" retained three-shafted triple expansion engines with twelve coal-fired water-tube boilers instead of more advanced turbine engines. <s> Her propulsion system was rated at 28000 PS and provided a top speed of 20 kn . <s> She had a cruising radius of 8300 nmi at a speed of 12 kn . <s> This type of machinery was chosen at the request of both Admiral Alfred von Tirpitz and the Navy's construction department; the latter stated in 1905 that the "use of turbines in heavy warships does not recommend itself." <s> This decision was based solely on cost: at the time, Parsons held a monopoly on steam turbines and required a 1 million gold mark royalty fee for every turbine engine. <s> German firms were not ready to begin production of turbines on a large scale until 1910. <s> "Posen" was ordered under the provisional name "Ersatz Baden", as a replacement for the , one of the elderly "Sachsen"-class ironclad s. <s> She was laid down on 11 June 1907 at the Germaniawerft shipyard in Kiel. <s> As with her sister , construction proceeded under absolute secrecy; detachments of soldiers guarded the shipyard and also guarded contractors that supplied building materials, such as Krupp. <s> The ship was launched a year and a half later, on 12 December 1908. <s> Wilhelm August Hans von Waldow-Reitzenstein gave a speech at her launching, and "Posen" was christened by Johanna von Radolin, the wife of Hugo Fürst von Radolin, a German diplomat who hailed from the ship's namesake province. <s> Initial trials were conducted through April 1910, followed by final fitting-out in May. <s> The ship was commissioned into the fleet on 31 May. <s> Sea trials were conducted afterward and completed by 27 August. <s> In total, her construction cost the German government 36,920,000 marks.
simple: SMS Posen was a German battleship built in 1907 and launched in 1910. <s> She had twelve 11 inch guns in six turrets. <s> Her guns were 28 cm wide and were in six twin turrets in a hexagon shape around the ship. <s> The ship served with her three sister ships for the majority of World War I. <s> She saw extensive service in the North Sea, where she took part in several fleet sorties. <s> These culminated in the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, where "Posen" was heavily engaged in night-fighting against British light forces. <s> In the confusion, the ship accidentally rammed the light cruiser SMS "Elbing", which suffered serious damage and was scuttled later in the night. <s> The ship also conducted several deployments to the Baltic Sea against the Russian Navy. <s> In the first of these, "Posen" supported a German naval assault in the Battle of the Gulf of Riga. <s> The ship was sent back to the Baltic in 1918 to support the White Finns in the Finnish Civil War. <s> At the end of the war, "Posen" remained in Germany while the majority of the fleet was interned in Scapa Flow. <s> In 1919, following the scuttling of the German fleet in Scapa Flow, she was ceded to the British as a replacement for the ships that had been sunk. <s> She was then sent to ship-breakers in the Netherlands and scrapped in 1922. <s> Posen was 146 m long and 27 m wide. <s> She weighed 18,873 tonnes. <s> Her crew was 40 officers and 968 sailors, 1008 total. <s> Posen was first ordered in 1906 as the Ersatz Baden. <s> She started being built on 11 June 1907 in secret. <s> She sailed for the first time in December 1908. <s> She cost the German government 36,920,000 Marks.

title: Pak Hon-yong
complex: Pak Hon-yong (Hangul: 박헌영, Hanja:朴憲永, 28 May 1900 – 18 December 1955 ) was a Korean independence activist, politician, philosopher and Communist activist. <s> One of the main leaders of the Korean communist movement during Japan's colonial rule (1910–45). <s> His nickname was Ijong (이정) and Ichun (이춘), his courtesy name being Togyong (덕영). <s> In September 1948, while keeping his role as secretary of the Workers' Party of South Korea, he became Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister of North Korea.
simple: Pak Hon-Yong (: ; : , May 28, 1900 - December 5, 1956) was a Korean independence activist, politician, thinker, Communist, and leader of the Korean Chosen Communist Party. <s> He served in North Korea as the Foreign Minister and Vice Prime Minister, August 1948 to 1953.

title: Abbeville County, South Carolina
complex: Abbeville County is a county located in the U.S. state of South Carolina. <s> As of the 2010 census, its population was 25,417. <s> Its county seat is Abbeville. <s> It is the first county in the United States alphabetically.
simple: Abbeville County is a county in the state of South Carolina, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, 25,417 people lived there. <s> Its county seat is Abbeville.

title: Covasna County
complex: Covasna County (] , , ] ) is a county (județ) of Romania, in Transylvania, with the capital city at Sfântu Gheorghe. <s> Covasna county has a total area of 3,710 km2. <s> Covasna County has two municipalities, three towns and 40 communes.
simple: Covasna is a county (judeţ) of Romania, in Transylvania. <s> The capital of Covasna County is Sfântu Gheorghe. <s> Covasna County has an area of 3,710 km2. <s> Covasna County has 2 municipalities, 3 towns and 40 communes.

title: Mercury sulfide
complex: Mercury sulfide, mercuric sulfide, mercury sulphide, or mercury(II) sulfide is a chemical compound composed of the chemical elements mercury and sulfur. <s> It is represented by the chemical formula HgS. <s> It is virtually insoluble in water.
simple: Mercury(II) sulfide, also known as cinnabar, mercuric sulfide, and mercury sulfide, is a chemical compound. <s> It has mercury and sulfide ions in it. <s> Mercury(II) sulfide is a red or black solid. <s> Mercury(II) sulfide is found as the mineral cinnabar. <s> Mercury(II) sulfide is what makes the pigment vermilion. <s> Its chemical formula is HgS.

title: Area code 710
complex: Area code 710 is a special area code, reserved to the federal government of the United States in 1983. <s> As of December 2006, it had only one working number, 710-NCS-GETS (710-627-4387), which requires a special access code to use.
simple: Area code 710 is the area code used by the United States Government.

title: Tommy Page
complex: Thomas Alden Page (May 24, 1970 – March 3, 2017) was an American singer-songwriter, best known for his 1990 hit single "I'll Be Your Everything" and was later a music industry executive. <s> Born in Glen Ridge, New Jersey, to parents Fred and Miriam Page, he grew up in nearby West Caldwell. <s> He graduated from James Caldwell High School with the class of 1985 at the age of 15. <s> Page was found dead on March 3, 2017 at the age of 46 of an apparent suicide. <s> He had three children (Owen, Alden, and Ruby) with his husband Charlie.
simple: Thomas Alden "Tommy" Page (May 24, 1970 – March 3, 2017) was an American singer-songwriter and pianist. <s> He was best known for his 1990 hit single, "I'll Be Your Everything". <s> He later became a music industry executive for "Billboard magazine". <s> Page was born in Glen Ridge, New Jersey and raised in West Caldwell, New Jersey. <s> He studied at James Caldwell High School. <s> Page died on March 3, 2017 in New York City in an apparent suicide, aged 46. <s> Page had three children with his partner, Charlie.

title: Mumu (Turgenev)
complex: Mumu is a short story by Ivan Turgenev, a Russian novelist and story writer, written in 1854. <s> The story of Gerasim, a deaf and mute serf whose life of poverty is brought into sharp relief by his connection with Mumu, a dog he rescued, brought greater national attention to the cruelties of serfdom, and received praise for its brutal portrayal of this institution in Russian society. <s> Originally published in 1854, "Mumu" was written by Turgenev while he was in custody for writing an obituary for fellow writer Nikolai Gogol.
simple: Mumu is a Russian tale. <s> The story is about the relationship between Gerasim - a deaf mute servant - and his dog. <s> It was published in 1852 by Ivan Turgenev in the political magazine: "Sovremennik".

title: Saint-Rémy-de-Sillé
complex: Saint-Rémy-de-Sillé is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Saint-Rémy-de-Sillé is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Fürsteneck Castle
complex: Fürsteneck Castle is a castle, situated in central Germany between Fulda and Bad Hersfeld. <s> It belongs to the commune of Eiterfeld. <s> The castle is at an elevation of 406 metres on a small plateau. <s> Fürsteneck Castle belonged to the monastery of Fulda. <s> The first written mention of it dates to 1309, but it might have been built one or two hundred years before. <s> After secularization in 1802, it became the property of the German state of Hesse. <s> Since 1952 the castle has been used as an academy for vocational and cultural continuing education. <s> It was rebuilt by the architect Otto Bartning. <s> Each year about 4,000 participants take part in one of nearly 200 courses, with 15,000 overnight stays.
simple: Burg Fürsteneck is a castle, situated in the middle of Germany between the towns of Fulda and Bad Hersfeld. <s> It belongs to the commune of Eiterfeld. <s> The castle lies at an altitude of 406 meters on a small plateau. <s> Burg Fürsteneck belonged to the monastery of Fulda. <s> It was first mentioned in 1309, but it might have been built one or two hundred years before. <s> Since 1802 it became the property of the German state of Hesse. <s> Since 1952 Burg Fürsteneck became an academy for vocational and cultural education. <s> It was rebuilded by the architect Otto Bartning. <s> Each year about 4000 participants take part in one of more than 175 courses, with 15.000 overnight stays.

title: Walter Bernstein
complex: Walter Bernstein (born August 20, 1919) is an American screenwriter and film producer who was blacklisted by the Hollywood movie studios in the 1950s. <s> Bernstein was born to a Jewish family in Brooklyn, New York, the son of Hannah (née Bistrong) and Louis Bernstein, a teacher. <s> He attended Dartmouth College, where he got his first writing job, as a film reviewer for the campus newspaper, and where he also joined the Young Communist League.
simple: Walter Bernstein (born August 20, 1919) is an American screenwriter and movie producer. <s> He was blacklisted by the Hollywood movie studios in the 1950s. <s> He was born in New York City.

title: Carcassonne and Trèbes attack
complex: On 23 March 2018, there was a series of Islamist terrorist attacks in the towns of Carcassonne and Trèbes in southern France. <s> Redouane Lakdim, a 25-year-old French-Moroccan (born 11 April 1992 in Taza, Morocco), shot the two occupants of a car in Carcassonne, killing the passenger and hijacking it. <s> He then opened fire on four police officers, seriously wounding one. <s> Lakdim drove to nearby Trèbes, where he stormed a Super U supermarket, killing two civilians, wounding others, and taking at least one hostage. <s> He swore allegiance to the Islamic State and demanded the release of Salah Abdeslam, the only surviving suspect of the November 2015 Paris attacks. <s> A senior gendarmerie officer, Lieutenant Colonel Arnaud Beltrame, voluntarily swapped places with a hostage. <s> After a three-hour stand-off, Lakdim shot and fatally stabbed Beltrame. <s> A police tactical unit immediately stormed the building and killed Lakdim. <s> He was named a "soldier of the Islamic State" by the Amaq News Agency, and the President of France called the attacks an act of Islamist terrorism. <s> Five people were killed in the attacks, including the perpetrator, and fifteen were wounded.
simple: On 23 March 2018, there was a series of Islamist terrorist attacks in the towns of Carcassonne and Trèbes in southern France. <s> Redouane Lakdim, a 25-year-old French-Moroccan, shot the two occupants of a car in Carcassonne, killing the passenger and hijacking it. <s> He then opened fire on four police officers, seriously wounding one. <s> Lakdim drove to nearby Trèbes, where he stormed a Super U supermarket, killing two civilians, wounding others, and taking at least one hostage. <s> Lakdim swore allegiance to the Islamic State and demanded the release of Salah Abdeslam, the only surviving suspect of the November 2015 Paris attacks. <s> A senior gendarme, Lt. Col. Arnaud Beltrame, voluntarily swapped places with a hostage. <s> After a three-hour stand-off, Lakdim fatally shot and stabbed Beltrame. <s> A police tactical unit immediately stormed the building and killed Lakdim. <s> He was named a "soldier of the Islamic State" by the Amaq News Agency, and the President of France called the attacks an act of Islamist terrorism. <s> Five people were killed in the attacks, including the perpetrator, and fifteen were wounded.

title: Mad Hatter (comics)
complex: The Mad Hatter (Jervis Tetch) is a fictional supervillain appearing in comic books published by DC Comics, commonly as an adversary of the superhero Batman. <s> He is modeled after the Hatter from Lewis Carroll's novel "Alice's Adventures in Wonderland", a character often called the "Mad Hatter" in adaptations of Carroll. <s> The Mad Hatter has been substantially adapted from the comics into various forms of media, including feature films, television series, and video games. <s> He has been voiced by Roddy McDowall in the DC animated universe, and Peter MacNicol in the "" video game series. <s> He has also been portrayed in live-action by David Wayne in the 1960s "Batman" series, and Benedict Samuel in the Fox show "Gotham".
simple: The Mad Hatter (Jervis Tetch) is a fictional Batman character who appears in comic books by DC Comics. <s> He dresses-up as the Mad Hatter from "Alice in Wonderland". <s> He was voiced by Roddy McDowall in "".

title: Neoclassicism (music)
complex: Neoclassicism in music was a twentieth-century trend, particularly current in the interwar period, in which composers sought to return to aesthetic precepts associated with the broadly defined concept of "classicism", namely order, balance, clarity, economy, and emotional restraint. <s> As such, neoclassicism was a reaction against the unrestrained emotionalism and perceived formlessness of late Romanticism, as well as a "call to order" after the experimental ferment of the first two decades of the twentieth century. <s> The neoclassical impulse found its expression in such features as the use of pared-down performing forces, an emphasis on rhythm and on contrapuntal texture, an updated or expanded tonal harmony, and a concentration on absolute music as opposed to Romantic program music. <s> In form and thematic technique, neoclassical music often drew inspiration from music of the 18th century, though the inspiring canon belonged as frequently to the Baroque and even earlier periods as to the Classical period—for this reason, music which draws inspiration specifically from the Baroque is sometimes termed "neo-Baroque" music. <s> Neoclassicism had two distinct national lines of development, French (proceeding partly from the influence of Erik Satie and represented by Igor Stravinsky, who was in fact Russian-born) and German (proceeding from the "New Objectivity" of Ferruccio Busoni, who was actually Italian, and represented by Paul Hindemith). <s> Neoclassicism was an aesthetic trend rather than an organized movement; even many composers not usually thought of as "neoclassicists" absorbed elements of the style.
simple: Neoclassicism in music was popular in the twentieth-century. <s> This kind of music is when composers try to come back to beautiful ways with the broadly defined way of "classicism", namely order, balance, clarity, economy, and emotions. <s> Neoclassicism had two distinct national lines of development. <s> Neoclassicsim was a beautiful trend rather than a movement. <s> Many composers normally do not think of themselves as "neoclassicists."

title: Prank call
complex: A prank call (also known as a crank call, phony call or hoax call) is a telephone call intended by the caller as a practical joke played on the person answering. <s> It is often a type of nuisance call.
simple: A prank phone call is when someone calls a phone number to play a practical joke on them.

title: Jhando Mari
complex: Jhando Mari is a town and union council of Tando Allahyar District in the Sindh Province of Pakistan. <s> It is part of Jhando Mari Taluka and is located in the north of the district at , the Union Council has a population of 30,384.
simple: Jhando Mari is a town and Union Council of Tando Allah Yaar District in the Sindh Province of Pakistan. <s> It is part of Jhando Mari Taluka and is in the north of the district at 25°38'60N 68°54'0E. <s> The Union Council has 30,384 people.

title: Halifax Explosion
complex: The Halifax Explosion was a maritime disaster in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada, which happened on the morning of 6 December 1917. <s> The Norwegian vessel collided with , a French cargo ship laden with high explosives, in the Narrows, a strait connecting the upper Halifax Harbour to Bedford Basin, causing a large explosion on the French freighter, devastating the Richmond district of Halifax. <s> Approximately 2,000 people were killed by the blast, debris, fires or collapsed buildings, and an estimated 9,000 others were injured. <s> The blast was the largest man-made explosion at the time, releasing the equivalent energy of roughly 2.9 ktonTNT .
simple: The Halifax explosion took place on December 6, 1917 when the SS "Mont-Blanc", a French cargo ship loaded with explosives collided with the SS "Imo", a Norwegian ship in the harbour in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada. <s> 2,000 people were killed and over 9,000 people were injured.

title: Khayu
complex: Khayu is mentioned in the Palermo Stone as a Predynastic Egyptian king who ruled in Lower Egypt. <s> As there is no other evidence of such ruler, he may be a mythical king preserved through oral tradition, or may even be completely fictitious.
simple: Khayu is a king from the Early Dynastic Period who ruled in Lower Egypt. <s> The only mention of his name is on the Palermo Stone. <s> He could be a mythical king preserved through ancient stories, or may even be completely fictitious.

title: Alfredo Biondi
complex: Alfredo Biondi (born June 29, 1928) is an Italian politician and lawyer. <s> In 1994 he served as Minister of Justice of the Italian Republic during the first cabinet chaired by Silvio Berlusconi.
simple: Alfredo Biondi (born June 29, 1928) is an Italian politician and lawyer. <s> In 1994 he served as Minister of Justice of the Italian Republic during the first cabinet chaired by Silvio Berlusconi.

title: Kutch district
complex: Kutch district (Kutchi and Gujarati: કચ્છ જિલ્લો; also spelled as Kachchh) is a district of Gujarat state in western India. <s> Covering an area of 45,674 km2, it is the largest district of India. <s> The population of Kutch is about 2,092,000.
simple: Kutch district (also spelled Kutch or Kachchh, ) is a formerly-independent district of Gujarat state in western Republic of India. <s> Covering an area of 45,612 km2, it is the largest district in the state of Gujarat and also the largest district of within India.

title: Nick Clooney
complex: Nicholas Joseph Clooney (born January 13, 1934) is an American journalist, anchorman, and television host. <s> He is the brother of singer Rosemary Clooney and the father of actor George Clooney. <s> Clooney was born in Maysville, Kentucky, the son of Marie Frances (née Guilfoyle; 1904–1972) and Andrew Joseph Clooney (1902–1974). <s> He was one of five children. <s> His father was of Irish and German descent and his mother was of Irish and English ancestry. <s> While serving as a Corporal in the U.S. Army, he was a disc jockey in the American Forces Network in Germany, hosting the shows "Music in the Air" and "Melody-Go-Round". <s> He then moved to California for a try at show business. <s> When that did not work out, Clooney moved to Ohio, where he met Nina Warren when she was a contestant in a beauty pageant he was judging; they married in August 1959. <s> In addition to his son, George, Nick Clooney has a daughter named Adelia (known as Ada). <s> Clooney ran as a Democrat in the 2004 election for a seat in the House of Representatives representing Kentucky's 4th Congressional District. <s> His opponent for the open seat was Republican Geoff Davis. <s> Clooney was recruited to run by Ken Lucas, the outgoing Democratic congressman who had held onto the conservative district with his moderate views. <s> With his name recognition and well-publicized endorsement from Lucas, Clooney was a big favorite to keep the seat in Democratic hands. <s> Clooney lost 44% to 54%. <s> During his concession speech, he said his short career in politics was over.
simple: Nicholas Joseph "Nick" Clooney (born January 13, 1934) is an American journalist, anchorman, and television host. <s> He is the brother of Rosemary Clooney and the father of George Clooney. <s> He is also the father of Adelia Clooney. <s> Clooney was born on January 13, 1934 in Maysville, Kentucky. <s> His parents had German, Irish, and English ancestry. <s> His career would begin in California during the 1960s. <s> Clooney was married to Nina Bruce Warren since 1959. <s> Clooney ran to be part of the United States House of Representatives for Kentucky for the Democrat Party in 2004. <s> He ran against Ken Lucas. <s> Clooney lost 44% to 54%.

complex: Year 1008 (MVIII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.
simple: 1008 (MVIII) was a common year when the Julian calendar was used.

title: Rugby World Cup
complex: The Rugby World Cup, through the upcoming 2019 edition, is a men's rugby union tournament contested every four years between the top international teams. <s> The tournament was first held in 1987, when the tournament was co-hosted by New Zealand and Australia. <s> The winners are awarded the Webb Ellis Cup, named after William Webb Ellis, the Rugby School pupil who, according to a popular legend, invented rugby by picking up the ball during a football game. <s> Four countries have won the trophy; New Zealand three times, Australia and South Africa each twice, and England once. <s> New Zealand are the current champions, having defeated Australia in the final of the 2015 tournament in England. <s> The tournament is administered by World Rugby, the sport's international governing body. <s> Sixteen teams were invited to participate in the inaugural tournament in 1987, however since 1999 twenty teams have taken part. <s> Japan will host the 2019 Rugby World Cup and France will host in 2023.
simple: The Rugby World Cup is the most important tournament in the sport of rugby union. <s> The cup happens every four years. <s> The first one was in 1987. <s> The current champions are New Zealand. <s> The 2019 competition will be held in Japan.

title: North Laurel, Maryland
complex: North Laurel is a census-designated place (CDP) in Howard County, Maryland, United States. <s> The published population was 4,474 at the 2010 census. <s> This population was substantially less than the CDP's population in 2000, and was the result of an error in defining the boundary prior to tabulation and publication of 2010 Census results. <s> The corrected 2010 Census population is 20,259. <s> North Laurel is adjacent to the City of Laurel, which is located across the Patuxent River in Prince George's County. <s> North Laurel is located in the southern corner of Howard County at (39.134343, −76.862690).
simple: North Laurel is a census-designated place (CDP) in Howard County, Maryland, United States. <s> The published population was 4,474 at the 2010 census. <s> North Laurel is near the City of Laurel.

title: Congolese rainforests
complex: The Congolese forests cover southeastern Cameroon, eastern Gabon, the northern and central Republic of the Congo, the northern and central Democratic Republic of the Congo and portions of southern and southwestern Central African Republic. <s> To the north and south, the forests transition to drier forest-savanna mosaic, a mosaic of drier forests, savannas, and grasslands. <s> To the west, the Congolese forests transition to the coastal Lower Guinean forests, which extend from western Gabon and Cameroon into southern Nigeria and Benin; these forests zones share many similarities, and are sometimes known as the Lower Guinean-Congolese forests. <s> To the east, the lowland Congolese forests transition to the highland Albertine Rift montane forests, which cover the Mountains lining the Albertine Rift, a branch of the East African Rift system. <s> The Congolese Forests are a global 200 ecoregion. <s> The Congo Rainforest is the world’s second largest tropical forest, spans six countries, and contains a quarter of the world’s remaining tropical forest. <s> With annual forest loss of 0.3% during the 2000s, the region has the lowest deforestation rate of any major tropical forest zone.
simple: The Congolese forests cover southeastern Cameroon, eastern Gabon, the northern and central Republic of the Congo, the northern and central Democratic Republic of the Congo and portions of southern and southwestern Central African Republic. <s> To the north and south, the forests transition to drier forest-savanna mosaic, a mosaic of drier forests, savannas, and grasslands. <s> To the west, the Congolese forests transition to the coastal Lower Guinean forests, which extend from western Gabon and Cameroon into southern Nigeria and Benin; these forests zones share many similarities, and are sometimes known as the Lower Guinean-Congolese forests. <s> To the east, the lowland Congolese forests transition to the highland Albertine Rift montane forests, which cover the Mountains lining the Albertine Rift, a branch of the East African Rift system. <s> The Congolese Forests are a global 200 ecoregion. <s> The tropical rainforest covers most of the eastern part of the Congo. <s> The Congo Rainforest is the world’s second largest tropical forest, spans six countries, and contains a quarter of the world’s remaining tropical forest. <s> With annual forest loss of 0.3% during the 2000s, the region has the lowest deforestation rate of any major tropical forest zone.

title: Bulk cargo
complex: Bulk cargo is commodity cargo that is transported unpackaged in large quantities.
simple: Bulk cargo is a type of cargo that is carried in big amounts.

title: Fornication
complex: Fornication is generally consensual sexual intercourse between two people not married to each other. <s> When one of the partners having consensual sexual intercourse is a married person, it is described as adultery. <s> Mennonites believe that sex outside marriage is sinful. <s> The Mennonite "Confession of Faith" states "According to Scripture, right sexual union takes place only within the marriage relationship.
simple: Fornication is a word that means having sex with someone who is not your spouse. <s> Many Christians and Muslims believe it is sinful.

title: Paul Petersen
complex: Paul William Petersen (born September 23, 1945) is an American actor, singer, novelist, and activist. <s> Petersen began his show business career at the age of ten as a Mouseketeer on the "Mickey Mouse Club". <s> He appeared in the 1958 movie "Houseboat" with Sophia Loren and Cary Grant, but achieved stardom playing teenager Jeff Stone from 1958 to 1966 on the ABC family television sitcom "The Donna Reed Show".
simple: William Paul Petersen (born September 23, 1945) is an American actor and comedian, best known for portraying Jeff Stone on "The Donna Reed Show". <s> He began his show business career at the age of 10 as a Mouseketeer on the "Mickey Mouse Club".

title: Salmonella enterica
complex: Salmonella enterica (formerly Salmonella choleraesuis) is a rod-shaped, flagellate, facultative aerobic, Gram-negative bacterium and a species of the genus "Salmonella". <s> A number of its serovars are serious human pathogens.
simple: Salmonella enterica is a rod-shaped bacterium. <s> It is a member of the genus "Salmonella".

title: Battlefield 1
complex: Battlefield 1 is a first-person shooter video game developed by EA DICE and published by Electronic Arts. <s> "Battlefield 1" is the fifteenth installment in the "Battlefield" series, and the first main entry in the series since "Battlefield 4". <s> It was released worldwide for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, and Xbox One on October 21, 2016. <s> Similar to its predecessors, "Battlefield 1" is a first-person shooter game that emphasizes teamwork. <s> It is set in the period of World War I, and is inspired by historical events. <s> Players can make use of World War I weapons, including bolt-action rifles, submachine guns, automatic and semi-automatic rifles, artillery, flamethrowers, and to combat opponents. <s> Melee combat was reworked, with DICE introducing new melee weapons such as sabres, trench clubs, and shovels into the game. <s> These melee weapons were divided into three groups: heavy, medium and light. <s> Players can also take control of various armored vehicles, including light and heavy tanks, armored trucks, cars, torpedo boats, bi- and tri-plane aircraft, an armored train, reconnaissance vehicles, a dreadnought and an M-class zeppelin, as well as ride horses into battle. <s> Destructible environments and weapon customization, features present in the previous games, returned in "Battlefield 1" and are more dynamic. <s> The game's world designer, Daniel Berlin, said the campaign mode has larger and more open environments than those in previous installments in the franchise, with more options and choices in terms of paths to completing levels and how to approach combat. <s> Players can control several characters in the campaign. <s> If the player dies in the prologue, they will then take control of another soldier and role instead of reloading from a checkpoint. <s> These roles can range from tank gunner to rifleman. <s> When the player dies, a name appears on the screen of a real soldier, along with their birth year. <s> Unlike its predecessors, the game features a collection of war stories, similar to an anthology. <s> The game's multiplayer mode supports up to 64 players. <s> The new squad system allows a group of players to enter and leave game servers together. <s> According to Berlin, playing without joining a squad would make gameplay significantly more difficult. <s> Multiplayer maps are based on locations around the world, including Arabia, the Western Front, and the Alps. <s> The game launched with nine maps and six modes, which include Conquest, Domination, Operations, Rush, Team Deathmatch, and War Pigeons, a mode in which players must secure war pigeons and use them to call for an artillery strike.
simple: Battlefield 1 is a first-person shooter video game made by EA DICE and published by EA. <s> This is the fourteenth battlefield game. <s> The game was released on Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, on October 21, 2016. <s> This game is a first-person shooter which is built around teamwork. <s> This game is set in World War I and is based on historic events. <s> The player can also use many vehicles used in World War I. <s> The campaign, according to Daniel Berlin the game's designer, is larger with more open environments, with more option in the levels. <s> The game's multiplayer is planned to allow 64 players. <s> The new squad system will allow a group of players to join and leave games together. <s> Multiplayer maps are based on World War I location. <s> The game will launch with nine maps and six game modes.

title: Lesse
complex: The Lesse is a river in the Ardennes, in the Walloon region of Belgium. <s> It is a right tributary to the river Meuse. <s> The source of the Lesse is near Libramont-Chevigny, in the Belgian province of Luxembourg. <s> The Lesse flows roughly in north-western direction. <s> Near Han-sur-Lesse (municipality of Rochefort) the entire river goes underground, flowing through limestone caves. <s> Many of the caves along the banks of the Lesse are important archaeological sites; these include the Trou de Chaleux (by the Cirque de Chaleux), and the Trou des Nutons and Trou du Frontal at Furfooz. <s> The Lesse flows into the river Meuse in the village of Anseremme, municipality of Dinant. <s> Towns along the Lesse are Daverdisse, Han-sur-Lesse, Houyet and Anseremme.
simple: The Lesse (Walloon: Aiwe di Lesse) is a river in the Ardennes, in the Walloon region of Belgium. <s> It is a right tributary to the river Meuse. <s> Its source is near Libramont-Chevigny, in the Belgian province of Luxembourg. <s> It flows roughly in a northwestern direction. <s> Near Han-sur-Lesse (commune of Rochefort), by the "Gouffre de Belvaux", the entire river goes underground, flowing through limestone caves. <s> Many of the caves along the banks of the Lesse are important archaeological sites - these include the Trou de Chaleux (by the Cirque de Chaleux), and the Trou des Nutons and Trou du Frontal at Furfooz. <s> The Lesse flows into the river Meuse in the town of Anseremme, commune of Dinant, Namur province.

title: Jorge Mendonça (footballer, born 1954)
complex: Jorge Pinto Mendonça (June 6, 1954 – February 17, 2006) was a famous Brazilian footballer during the 1970s and 1980s, playing in a striker role.
simple: Jorge Mendonça (born 6 June 1954) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Punching bag
complex: A punching bag (or, British English, punchbag) is a sturdy bag designed to be repeatedly punched. <s> A punching bag is usually cylindrical, and filled with various materials of corresponding hardness. <s> Punching bags have been used in martial arts and swordplay for the entire written history of military training. <s> Similar apparatus in Asian martial arts include the Okinawan makiwara and the Chinese mook jong, which may have padded striking surfaces attached to them.
simple: A punching bag is a tough bag which is supposed to be punched a lot. <s> Punching bags have been used in martial arts for as long as there has been a written history of military training. <s> Similar apparatus in Asian martial arts include the Okinawan "makiwara" and the Chinese "mook jong", which may have padded striking surfaces attached to them.

title: Cashville Records
complex: Cashville Records (formerly G-Unit South) was an American independent record label based in Nashville, Tennessee founded by rapper Young Buck. <s> Initially founded as a southern branch of 50 Cent's G-Unit Records, the label became "Cashville Records" in late 2007 after a dispute between 50 Cent and Young Buck led to Buck being banned from using the G-Unit logo or name to distribute his music. <s> The label has signed such acts as The Outlawz, C-Bo, Lil Scrappy, D4L and more.
simple: Casville Records (often stylized as Ca$hville Records) is an independent record label based in Nashville, Tennessee. <s> It was originally called G-Unit South. <s> It has so far signed acts such as Outlaws and Lil Scrappie and is currently being distributed by RED distrubution.

title: Coat of arms of Peru
complex: The Coat of arms of Peru is the national symbolic emblem of Peru. <s> Four variants are used: the Coat of arms "per se" (" "); the National Coat of arms, or National Shield (" "); the Great Seal of the State (" "); and the Naval Coat of arms (" ").
simple: The Coat of arms of Peru is the national symbolic emblem of Peru. <s> Four types are used: the Coat of Arms ('); the National Coat of Arms, or National Shield ('); the Great Seal of the State ('); and the Naval Coat of Arms (').

title: ZTE
complex: ZTE Corporation is a Chinese multinational telecommunications equipment and systems company headquartered in Shenzhen, Guangdong, China. <s> It is one of China's leading telecom equipment manufacturers. <s> It also offers products that provide value-added services, such as video on demand and streaming media. <s> ZTE primarily sold products under its own name, but it is also an OEM.
simple: ZTE (Chinese: 中兴通讯) (Zhong Xing Telecommunication Equipment Company Limited) is a publicly-owned, Chinese business that designs and builds telecommunications equipment and systems. <s> The company is located in Shenzhen, and was started in 1985 ZTE offers a many telecommunications products that provide services, such as video on demand and streaming media to its customers, which are mainly people that provide telecommunications services.

title: Saint-Georges, Pas-de-Calais
complex: Saint-Georges is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France. <s> Communes of the Pas-de-Calais department
simple: Saint-Georges, Pas-de-Calais is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Coptic calendar
complex: The Coptic calendar, also called the Alexandrian calendar, is a liturgical calendar used by the Coptic Orthodox Church and also used by the farming populace in Egypt. <s> This calendar is based on the ancient Egyptian calendar. <s> To avoid the calendar creep of the latter, a reform of the ancient Egyptian calendar was introduced at the time of Ptolemy III (Decree of Canopus, in 238 BC) which consisted of the intercalation of a sixth epagomenal day every fourth year.
simple: Coptic calendar (also known as Alexandrian calendar) is a calendar used by the Coptic Church in Egypt. <s> It is based on the Egyptian calendar which was first introduced in 238 BC.

title: Chernivtsi Oblast
complex: Chernivtsi Oblast ( , "Černivećka oblasť," ) is an oblast (province) in western Ukraine, consisting of the northern parts of the regions of Bukovina and Bessarabia. <s> It has an international border with Romania and Moldova.
simple: Chernivtsi Oblast is an oblast (province) of western Ukraine.

title: Nebling
complex: Nebling is a small village in the municipality of Untergriesbach in the District of Passau in Lower Bavaria, Germany.
simple: Nebling is a small village in Passau, Lower Bavaria, Germany.

title: Bill Foulkes
complex: William Anthony Foulkes ( or ; 5 January 1932 – 25 November 2013) was an English footballer who played for Manchester United in the Busby Babes teams of the 1950s, and also in the 1960s. <s> His favoured position was centre-half.
simple: Bill Foulkes (5 January 1932 – 25 November 2013) was an English footballer-turned-manager.

title: Stupid (art movement)
complex: Stupid was a short-lived grouping of constructivist artists, formed in Cologne in 1919. <s> The founding members were Willy Fick, Heinrich Hoerle, Angelika Hoerle, Anton Räderscheidt, Marta Hegemann, and Franz Wilhelm Seiwert. <s> The Stupid group aimed to address sociopolitical issues through an art of proletarian character. <s> Seiwert and Räderscheidt had previously been active in the Cologne Dada scene, along with Max Ernst. <s> Ernst later described Stupid as "a secession from Cologne Dada. <s> As far as Hoerle and especially Seiwert were concerned, Dada's activities were aesthetically too radical and socially not concrete enough". <s> Seiwert described the group's esthetic: "We are attempting to be so clear that everyone will be able to understand us." <s> Räderscheidt's studio was their base of operations, but by 1920 he had abandoned the constructivist style. <s> The group exhibited together and issued a publication, "Stupid 1", before disbanding.
simple: Stupid was a short-lived grouping of constructivist artists, formed in Cologne in 1919. <s> The founding members were Willy Fick, Heinrich Hoerle and his wife Angelika Hoerle (1899–1923), Anton Räderscheidt and his wife Marta Hegemann, and Franz Wilhelm Seiwert. <s> The Stupid group aimed to address sociopolitical issues through an art of proletarian character. <s> Seiwert and Räderscheidt were at the time active in the local Dada scene. <s> Räderscheidt's studio was their base of operations, but by 1920 he had abandoned the constructivist style. <s> The group exhibited together and issued a publication, "Stupid 1", before disbanding.

title: Walter Pidgeon
complex: Walter Davis Pidgeon (September 23, 1897 – September 25, 1984) was a Canadian-American actor. <s> He earned two Academy Award for Best Actor nominations for his roles in "Mrs. Miniver" (1942) and "Madame Curie" (1943). <s> Pidgeon also starred in many films such as "How Green Was My Valley" (1941), "The Bad and the Beautiful" (1952), "Forbidden Planet" (1956), "Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea" (1961), "Advise & Consent" (1962), "Funny Girl" (1968), and "Harry in Your Pocket" (1973). <s> Born in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada, Pidgeon was the son of Hannah (née Sanborn), a housewife, and Caleb Burpee Pidgeon, a haberdasher. <s> His brother, Larry, was an editorial writer for the "Santa Barbara News-Press". <s> Pidgeon died on September 25, 1984 in Santa Monica, California, two days after his 87th birthday following a series of strokes. <s> He bequeathed his body to the University of California, Los Angeles School of Medicine for the furtherance of medical science.
simple: Walter Pidgeon (September 23, 1897 – September 25, 1984) was a Canadian actor. <s> He starred in many movies, including "Forbidden Planet". <s> He was born in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada. <s> He died in Santa Monica, California.

title: A Carnival Christmas
complex: A Carnival Christmas is the third EP by American hip hop group Insane Clown Posse, released on December 6, 1994, by Psychopathic Records. <s> It was reissued in 1997 by Island Records with alternate artwork.
simple: A Carnival Christmas is the third EP by the American Horrorcore band, Insane Clown Posse. <s> It was released on December 6, 1994. <s> The EP was a Christmas EP.

title: Spiere-Helkijn
complex: Spiere-Helkijn ("Espierres-Helchin" in French) is a municipality located in the Belgian province of West Flanders. <s> The municipality comprises the towns of Helkijn and Spiere.
simple: Spiere-Helkijn is a municipality in the Belgian province of West Flanders.

title: Texas Lutheran University
complex: Texas Lutheran University (TLU) is a private Evangelical Lutheran university in Seguin, Texas.
simple: Texas Lutheran University is a private Lutheran university in Seguin, Texas, United States.

title: Joel Daly
complex: Joel Daly (born August 21, 1934) is an American former news anchor. <s> Daly is most known for serving as an anchor for WLS-TV (an ABC-affiliate) in Chicago, Illinois for 38 years from 1967–2005. <s> Daly served as co-anchor on the 4PM news broadcast alongside Linda Yu from January 1985 until his retirement in May 2005. <s> Daly was inducted into the Silver Circle, a group of elite Chicago broadcasters, in 2003. <s> Since his retirement from news broadcasting in 2005, From March 2007 until October 2013, Daly served as spokesperson for Chicago's Cook County Federal courthouse.
simple: Joel Daly (born August 21, 1934) is an American former news anchor. <s> Daly is most known for serving as an anchor for WLS-TV (an ABC-affiliate) in Chicago, Illinois for 38 years from 1967–2005. <s> Daly served as co-anchor alongside Linda Yu from January 1985 until his retirement in May 2005. <s> From March 2007 until October 2013, Daly served as spokesperson for Chicago's Cook County Federal courthouse.

title: Caroline Bittencourt
complex: Caroline Bittencourt (December 13, 1981 – April 28, 2019) was a Brazilian model and television presenter. <s> In 1997, at the age of fifteen, Bittencourt began her career as a model. <s> She had lived in Italy and modelled for designers including Valentino Garavani and Roberto Cavalli. <s> On television, she worked for RedeTV! <s> She was a reporter for the "Top Report" and on RecordTV in the "Hoje em Dia" program. <s> Caroline Bittencourt disappeared on the afternoon of 28 April 2019, around 4.30pm, when she was taking a boat trip in Ilhabela, on the coast of state of São Paulo. <s> During a strong storm in the area, the boat capsized, throwing those onboard into the sea.
simple: Caroline Bittencourt (13 December 1981 – 28 April 2019) was a Brazilian model and television presenter. <s> In 1997, she started her modelling career at the age of 15. <s> She lived in Italy for a time and worked for fashion houses such as Valentino and Roberto Cavalli. <s> She later worked on television for RedeTV!, <s> , as a reporter for the "Top Report" program, and on RecordTV's "Hoje em Dia". <s> On 28 April 2019, Bittencourt died by drowning during a boat trip off the coast of Ilhabela, São Paulo state.

title: Joni Sledge
complex: Joan Elise Sledge (September 13, 1956 – March 10, 2017) was an American singer–songwriter, actress and producer. <s> Sledge was best known as a founding member of the American family vocal group Sister Sledge, who were best known for their hits during the mid–1970s through the mid–1990s; most notably 1979's "We Are Family" and "He's the Greatest Dancer". <s> Sledge died from natural causes on March 10, 2017 at age 60. <s> Sledge was born the third of five daughters in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania to Edwin Sledge (1923–1996), a tap dancer, and his actress wife, Florez (née Williams; 1928–2007). <s> Described as a warm extrovert, Sledge attended Olney High School; graduating in 1974. <s> Sledge majored in communications while in college and began acting in school productions at Temple University. <s> During her sophomore year at Temple, Sledge produced and directed her first stageplay "WildFlower". <s> Sometime during her career, Sledge briefly lived in Paris, France and studied at Sorbonne University. <s> In addition to singing, Sledge was also a songwriter and producer; writing and producing the song "Brother, Brother Stop" for a Sister Sledge greatest hits album in 1996. <s> Sledge's production of their album "African Eyes" which was released in 1997 was nominated for a best–production Grammy. <s> Sledge had one child, a son named Thaddeus Everett Whyte IV from her marriage to Thaddeus E. Whyte, III which was from 1992 until 2000. <s> Sledge was found dead by a friend at her home on March 11, 2017 in Phoenix, Arizona. <s> She was 60 years old. <s> Her death was originally attributed to unknown circumstances as she had no known illnesses, according to close family sources. <s> On March 14, 2017, Sledge's cause of death was ruled "natural causes".
simple: Joan Elise Sledge (September 13, 1956 – March 10, 2017), better known as Joni Sledge, was an American singer–songwriter and producer. <s> Sledge was best known as a founding member of the American family vocal group Sister Sledge. <s> Sledge was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. <s> She studied at Temple University. <s> In addition to singing, Sledge was also a songwriter and producer. <s> She wrote and produced the song "Brother, Brother Stop" for a Sister Sledge greatest hits album in 1996. <s> Sledge's production of their album "African Eyes" which was released in 1997 was nominated for a best–production Grammy. <s> She had one son Thaddeus Sledge. <s> Sledge was found dead by a friend at her home on March 11, 2017 in Phoenix, Arizona at the age of 60. <s> Her death was originally considered due to unknown circumstances as she didn't have any known illnesses, according to close family sources. <s> On March 14, 2017, Sledge's cause of death was ruled "natural causes".

title: Homeless shelter
complex: Homeless shelters are a type of homeless service agency which provide temporary residence for homeless individuals and families. <s> Shelters exist to provide residents with safety and protection from exposure to the weather while simultaneously reducing the environmental impact on the community. <s> They are similar to, but distinguishable from, various types of emergency shelters, which are typically operated for specific circumstances and populations—fleeing natural disasters or abusive social circumstances.
simple: A homeless shelter is a place for homeless people to take refuge. <s> Shelters provide safety and protection from exposure to the weather.

title: Euzebiusz Smolarek
complex: Euzebiusz "Ebi" Smolarek (; born 9 January 1981) is a former Polish footballer who is currently youth manager at Dutch club Feyenoord.
simple: Euzebiusz Smolarek (born 9 January 1981) is a Polish football player.

title: Winged Creatures (film)
complex: Winged Creatures (released as "Fragments" on DVD) is a 2008 crime film directed by Rowan Woods and starring Kate Beckinsale, Dakota Fanning, Josh Hutcherson, Guy Pearce, Forest Whitaker, Jennifer Hudson, Jackie Earle Haley, Jeanne Tripplehorn and Embeth Davidtz. <s> It is an adaptation of Roy Freirich's novel "Winged Creatures".
simple: Fragments or Winged Creatures is a 2008 crime-drama movie. <s> "Fragments" stars Dakota Fanning and Kate Beckinsale along with Forest Whittaker.

title: Lyriel
complex: Lyriel are a German heavy metal band who formed in autumn of 2003 in Gummersbach. <s> Originally playing folk metal, they turned more towards symphonic and gothic metal.
simple: Lyriel is a German band.

title: Patricia Heaton
complex: Patricia Helen Heaton (born March 4, 1958) is an American actress and comedian. <s> She is known for her starring role as Debra Barone in the CBS sitcom "Everybody Loves Raymond" (1996–2005) and as Frances "Frankie" Heck on the ABC sitcom "The Middle" (2009–2018). <s> Patricia Heaton was born in Bay Village, Ohio, the daughter of Patricia (née Hurd) and Chuck Heaton, who was a sportswriter for "The Plain Dealer". <s> Heaton's mother died of an aneurysm when the actress was 12. <s> The fourth of five children, Heaton was raised as a devout Catholic. <s> Heaton has three sisters, Sharon, Alice, and Frances, and one brother, Michael, who is the "Minister of Culture" columnist for "The Plain Dealer" and a writer for the paper's Friday Magazine. <s> From September 2009 to May 2018, she starred in the ABC comedy "The Middle" as Frankie Heck. <s> She received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame on May 22, 2012. <s> Heaton has been married to British actor David Hunt since 1990. <s> They have four sons and as of 2002, they divide their time between Los Angeles and Cambridge, England. <s> Her memoir, "Motherhood and Hollywood: How to Get a Job Like Mine", was published by Villard Books in 2002. <s> Hunt is Heaton's second husband. <s> After her divorce from her first husband, she went through a self-described "Protestant wilderness". <s> Since June 2017, Heaton's first marriage has been annulled by the Catholic Church and she had returned as an observant of Catholicism. <s> Heaton has been open about having plastic surgery; citing having a tummy-tuck and a breast reduction after undergoing four Caesarean sections.
