simple: Patricia Helen Heaton (born March 4, 1958 in Bay Village, Ohio) is an Emmy Award-winning American Actress best known for playing lead character and Ray Barone's wife Debra Barone on the CBS television sitcom "Everybody Loves Raymond". <s> She currently stars as Frankie Heck on the ABC sitcom "The Middle". <s> Patricia Heaton was born in Bay Village, Ohio, the daughter of Patricia (née Hurd) and Chuck Heaton, who was a sportswriter for "The Plain Dealer." <s> Heaton's mother died of an aneurysm when the actress was 12. <s> The fourth of five children, Heaton was raised as a devout Catholic. <s> Heaton has three sisters, Sharon, Alice, and Frances, and one brother, Michael, who is the "Minister of Culture" columnist for "The Plain Dealer" and a writer for the paper's Friday Magazine. <s> She received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame on May 22, 2012. <s> Heaton has been married to British actor David Hunt since 1990. <s> They have four sons and they divide their time between Los Angeles and Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England. <s> Her memoir, "Motherhood and Hollywood: How to Get a Job Like Mine", was published by Villard Books in 2002. <s> Hunt is Heaton's second husband. <s> After her divorce from her first husband, she went through a self-described "Protestant wilderness". <s> Since June 2017, Heaton's first marriage has been annulled by the Catholic Church and has since returned as an observant of Catholicism. <s> Heaton has been open about having plastic surgery; citing having a tummy-tuck and a breast reduction after undergoing four Caesarean sections.

title: First All-Union Philatelic Exhibition
complex: The First All-Union Philatelic Exhibition was held in Moscow in 1924–1925. <s> Its full name was the First All-Union Philatelic, Scripophilic and Numismatic Exhibition. <s> This was because it combined the objects of philately, scripophily (collecting stock and bond certificates), and numismatics. <s> The exhibition was organised from 15 December 1924 to 15 February 1925. <s> This was done by the Presidium of the All-Union Philatelic Association and Board of the All-Russian Society of Philatelists. <s> The combined exhibition was meant to prepare formation of the "All-Union Society of Collectors". <s> The society was to be under the direction of , the Commissioner for Philately and Scripophily.
simple: The First All-Union Philatelic Exhibition was held in Moscow in 1924–1925. <s> Its full name was the First All-Union Philatelic, Scripophilic and Numismatic Exhibition. <s> This was because it combined the objects of philately, scripophily (collecting stock and bond certificates), and numismatics (of coins, money). <s> The exhibition was organised from 15 December 1924 to 15 February 1925. <s> This was done by the Presidium of the All-Union Philatelic Association and Board of the All-Russian Society of Philatelists. <s> The combined exhibition was meant to prepare formation of the "All-Union Society of Collectors". <s> The society was to be under the direction of Feodor Chuchin, the Commissioner for Philately and Scripophily.

title: Broadheath, Worcestershire
complex: Broadheath with Lower Broadheath is a civil parish officially known as "Lower Broadheath", in the Malvern Hills district of Worcestershire, England. <s> According to the 2011 census it had a population of 1,728. <s> The parish also includes Upper Broadheath. <s> The village is about 3 miles north-west of Worcester. <s> There are many housing estates in the village, including the Jacomb estate (Jacomb Road, Jacomb Drive, Jacomb Close and Rectory Close). <s> The village has a village hall, church, post office and shop, a village green (containing a football pitch, running track and many children's play areas) and a large village common. <s> There is also a primary school (Broadheath C.E. Primary School). <s> The school contains around 150 children, from the age of four up to eleven. <s> There are also three pubs in the village. <s> Broadheath is the birthplace of the English composer Edward Elgar. <s> The cottage in which he was born is now a museum.
simple: Broadheath with Lower Broadheath is a civil parish officially known as "Lower Broadheath", in the Malvern Hills district of Worcestershire, England. <s> According to the 2001 census it had a population of 1,713. <s> The parish also includes Upper Broadheath, which is about 3 miles north-west of Worcester. <s> There are many housing estates in the village. <s> The village has a village hall, church, post office and shop, a village green with a football pitch, running track and many children's play areas. <s> There is a large village common. <s> There is also a primary school (Broadheath C.E. Primary School). <s> The school has about 150 children, from the age of four up to eleven. <s> There are also three pubs in the village. <s> Broadheath is the birthplace of the English composer Edward Elgar.

title: Saalfeld-Rudolstadt
complex: Saalfeld-Rudolstadt is a "Kreis" (district) in the south of Thuringia, Germany. <s> Neighboring districts are (from the north clockwise) the districts Weimarer Land, Saale-Holzland, Saale-Orla, the district Kronach in Bavaria, and the districts Sonneberg, Hildburghausen and Ilm-Kreis. <s> The district dates back to the "Landratsamt" Saalfeld, which was created in 1868, and in 1922 it was converted into the "Landkreis". <s> Also in 1922 the district Rudolstadt was created, the second historical root of the district as of today. <s> Both districts were merged in the communal reform of 1994. <s> The main rivers in the district is the Saale.
simple: Saalfeld-Rudolstadt is a "Landkreis" (district) in the south of Thuringia, Germany. <s> The district dates back to the "Landratsamt" Saalfeld, which was created in 1868, and in 1922 it was converted into the "Landkreis". <s> Also in 1922 the district Rudolstadt was created. <s> Both districts were merged in the local government changes of 1994.

title: AD 19
complex: AD 19 (XIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Silanus and Balbus (or, less frequently, year 772 "Ab urbe condita"). <s> The denomination AD 19 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: It was a common year starting on Sunday of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Silanus and Balbus.

title: Xu Xin (table tennis)
complex: Xu Xin (; born 8 January 1990) is a Chinese professional table tennis player who is currently ranked world No. 1 for men's singles by the International Table Tennis Federation (ITTF). <s> He first reached his career-high singles ranking of World No.1 in January 2013. <s> The next month, Xu Xin was a part of the winning team China at the 2018 World Team Table Tennis Championships in his tenth appearance at the World Championships. <s> Xu earned the final point for team China during the final, beating Patrick Franziska 3–1 for China to claim the title with a 3–0 win over Germany.
simple: Xu Xin (; born 8 January 1990) is a Chinese table tennis player. <s> In January 2013 he finished for the first time world number one. <s> In 2018 Xu Xin won with the team gold at the World Championships.

title: Gavin Watson
complex: Gavin Joseph Watson (12 July 1948 – 26 August 2019) was a South African businessman who served as Chief Executive Officer of African Global Operations, previously known as Bosasa, from 2000 until his death in 2019. <s> His company was implicated in state capture during judicial hearings in January 2019. <s> Watson died in a car accident early on 26 August 2019 when the company Toyota Corolla he was driving struck a pillar on an approach road leading to O. R. Tambo International Airport in Johannesburg. <s> His BMW X5 was in for mechanical repairs at the time.
simple: Gavin Joseph Watson (12 July 1948 – 26 August 2019) was a South African businessman. <s> He was Chief Executive Officer of State Capture-implicated company, African Global Operations, previously known as Bosasa, from 2000 until his death in 2019. <s> Watson died in a car accident on 26 August 2019, near O. R. Tambo International Airport in Johannesburg at the age of 71.

title: Dictation machine
complex: A dictation machine is a sound recording device most commonly used to record speech for later playback or to be typed into print. <s> It includes digital voice recorders and tape recorders.
simple: A voice recorder or a dictation machine is a device to record speech or other sounds, and then play it back.

title: Flobots
complex: Flobots are a experimental rap rock band from Denver, Colorado, formed in 2005 by Jamie Laurie. <s> The band's origins date back 5 years earlier to a similar project by Laurie. <s> Flobots found mainstream success with their major label debut "Fight with Tools" (2007), featuring the single "Handlebars", which became a popular hit on Modern Rock radio in April 2008. <s> The band has released four studio albums and one EP, with their latest "Noenemies" being released in May 2017.
simple: Flobots are an alternative rock/alternative hip hop band from Denver, Colorado. <s> They have released three albums.

title: Rivière, Pas-de-Calais
complex: Rivière is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Rivière, Pas-de-Calais is a commune.

title: Parole
complex: Parole is the early release of a prisoner who agrees to abide by certain conditions, originating from the French "parole" ("voice, spoken words" but also "promise"). <s> The term became associated during the Middle Ages with the release of prisoners who gave their word.
simple: Parole is the release of a prisoner before the end of his or her original sentence. <s> This is based on the prisoner accepting certain conditions.

title: County Durham
complex: County Durham ( , locally /ˈdɜrəm/ ) is a county in North East England. <s> The county town is Durham, a cathedral city. <s> The largest settlement is Darlington, closely followed by Hartlepool and Stockton-on-Tees. <s> It borders Tyne and Wear to the north east, Northumberland to the north, Cumbria to the west and North Yorkshire to the south. <s> The county's historic boundaries stretch between the rivers Tyne and Tees, thus including places such as Gateshead, Jarrow, South Shields and Sunderland. <s> Many counties are named after their principal town, and the expected form here would be Durhamshire, but this form has never been in common use. <s> The ceremonial county is officially named "Durham", but the county has long been commonly known as "County" Durham and is the only English county name prefixed with "County" in common usage (the practice is common in Ireland). <s> Its unusual naming (for an English shire) is explained to some extent by the relationship with the Bishops of Durham, who for centuries governed Durham as a county palatine (the County Palatine of Durham), outside the usual structure of county administration in England. <s> The ceremonial county of Durham is administered by four unitary authorities. <s> The ceremonial county has no administrative function, but remains the area to which the Lord Lieutenant of Durham and the High Sheriff of Durham are appointed. <s> The historic boundaries of County Durham included a main body covering the catchment of the Pennines in the west, the River Tees in the south, the North Sea in the east and the Rivers Tyne and Derwent in the north. <s> The county palatinate also had a number of liberties: the Bedlingtonshire, Islandshire and Norhamshire exclaves within Northumberland, and the Craikshire exclave within the North Riding of Yorkshire. <s> In 1831 the county covered an area of 679530 acre and had a population of 253,910. <s> These exclaves were included as part of the county for parliamentary electoral purposes until 1832, and for judicial and local-government purposes until the coming into force of the Counties (Detached Parts) Act 1844, which merged most remaining exclaves with their surrounding county. <s> The boundaries of the county proper remained in use for administrative and ceremonial purposes until the 1972 Local Government Act. <s> The Municipal Corporations Act 1835 reformed the municipal boroughs of Durham, Stockton on Tees and Sunderland. <s> In 1875, Jarrow was incorporated as a municipal borough, as was West Hartlepool in 1887. <s> At a county level, the Local Government Act 1888 reorganised local government throughout England and Wales. <s> Most of the county came under control of the newly-formed Durham County Council in an area known as an administrative county. <s> Not included were the county boroughs of Gateshead, South Shields and Sunderland. <s> However, for purposes other than local government, the administrative county of Durham and the county boroughs continued to form a single county to which the Crown appointed a Lord Lieutenant of Durham. <s> Over its existence, the administrative county lost territory, both to the existing county boroughs, and because two municipal boroughs became county boroughs: West Hartlepool in 1902 and Darlington in 1915. <s> The county boundary with the North Riding of Yorkshire was adjusted in 1967: that part of the town of Barnard Castle historically in Yorkshire was added to County Durham, while the administrative county ceded the portion of the Borough of Stockton-on-Tees in Durham to the North Riding. <s> In 1968, following the recommendation of the Local Government Commission, Billingham was transferred to the county borough of Teesside, in the North Riding. <s> In 1971, the population of the county—including all associated county boroughs (an area of 2570 km2 )—was 1,409,633, with a population outside the county boroughs of 814,396. <s> In 1974, the Local Government Act 1972 abolished the administrative county and the county boroughs, reconstituting County Durham as a non-metropolitan county. <s> The reconstituted County Durham lost territory to the north-east (around Gateshead, South Shields and Sunderland) to Tyne and Wear and to the south-east (around Hartlepool) to Cleveland. <s> At the same time it gained the former area of Startforth Rural District from the North Riding of Yorkshire. <s> The area of the Lord Lieutenancy of Durham was also adjusted by the Act to coincide with the non-metropolitan county (which occupied 3019 km2 in 1981). <s> In 1997 Darlington became a unitary authority and was separated from the shire county. <s> As part of the 2009 structural changes to local government in England initiated by the Department for Communities and Local Government, the seven district councils within the County Council area were abolished. <s> The County Council assumed their functions and became a unitary authority. <s> The changes came into effect on 1 April 2009.
simple: County Durham is a county in north-east England. <s> Its county town is Durham. <s> Many counties are named after their principal town, and the expected form here would be "Durhamshire". <s> Lord-lieutenants and high sheriffs are appointed to the ceremonial county of Durham. <s> The historic county covered from the Pennines in the west, the River Tees in the south, the North Sea in the east and the Rivers Tyne and Derwent in the north. <s> The county several had a number of exclaves: Bedlingtonshire, Islandshire and Norhamshire within Northumberland, and Craikshire within the North Riding of Yorkshire. <s> The historic boundaries were used for parliamentary purposes until 1832, and for law courts and local government until the Counties (Detached Parts) Act 1844, which merged most remaining exclaves with their surrounding county. <s> In 1889, under the Local Government Act 1888 England and Wales was divided into administrative counties and county boroughs. <s> In 1889 the administrative county of Durham consisted of the historic county less the county boroughs of Gateshead, South Shields and Sunderland. <s> Over its existence, the administrative county lost territory, both to the existing county boroughs, and also due to the creation of county boroughs at West Hartlepool in 1902 and Darlington in 1915. <s> The boundary with the North Riding of Yorkshire was adjusted: the part of the town of Barnard Castle that was in Yorkshire was added to County Durham, but the part of the Borough of Stockton-on-Tees in Durham was given to the North Riding. <s> In 1967 the borough of Hartlepool was removed from the administrative county when it merged with West Hartlepool to form a new county borough of Hartlepool, and in 1968 Billingham was included within the boundaries of the county borough of Teesside, associated with the North Riding. <s> The administrative county was abolished in 1974. <s> The metropolitan county of Tyne and Wear became responsible for Gateshead, Sunderland and South Tyneside. <s> The new non-metropolitan county of Durham also covered the former area of Startforth Rural District, a part of the historic North Riding of Yorkshire, and south of the historical boundary of the River Tees. <s> In 1997 the non-metropolitan county (including unitary Darlington), together with that part of the former county of Cleveland north of the River Tees became a ceremonial county. <s> The Department for Communities and Local Government has said that the seven district councils and the County Council will be abolished and a new unitary authority for the whole of the existing County Council area will be created. <s> The change will be on 1 April 2009 at the latest.

title: Cashew
complex: The cashew tree ("Anacardium occidentale") is a tropical evergreen tree that produces the cashew seed and the cashew apple. <s> It can grow as high as 14 m , but the dwarf cashew, growing up to 6 m , has proved more profitable, with earlier maturity and higher yields. <s> While the cashew plant is native to northeast Brazil, the Portuguese took it to Goa, India, between 1560 and 1565. <s> From there, it spread throughout Southeast Asia and eventually Africa.
simple: The cashew is a tropical tree in the flowering plant. <s> The plant is native to northeastern Brazil.

title: CIS Tower
complex: The CIS Tower is an office skyscraper on Miller Street in Manchester, England. <s> It was completed in 1962 and rises to 387 feet (118 m) in height. <s> The Grade II listed building, which houses the Co-operative Banking Group, is Manchester's fifth-tallest building and the tallest office building in the United Kingdom outside London. <s> The tower remained as built for over 40 years until maintenance issues on the service tower required an extensive renovation which included covering its facade in photovoltaic panels. <s> The office tower building rises above a five-storey podium block. <s> It has a steel frame and glass curtain walls with metal window frames.

title: Hana Orgoníková
complex: Hana Orgoníková (8 December 1946 – 5 June 2014) was a Czech politician. <s> She was an MP for the Czech Social Democratic Party (CSDP) from 1989 until her death. <s> Orgoníková was born in Přibyslav, Czechoslovakia. <s> She was divorced and had two children, Vladimír and Lucie. <s> Orgoníková died following a long illness on 5 June 2014 in Hradec Králové, Czech Republic, aged 67.

title: Gump Worsley
complex: Lorne John "Gump" Worsley (May 14, 1929 – January 26, 2007) was a professional ice hockey goaltender. <s> Born and raised in Montreal, Quebec, 'Gump' was given his nickname because friends thought he looked like comic-strip character Andy Gump. <s> Worsley suffered a heart attack on January 22, 2007, and died at his home in Beloeil, Quebec on January 26, 2007.

title: Andy Bathgate
complex: Andrew James "Andy" Bathgate (August 28, 1932 – February 26, 2016) was a Canadian professional ice hockey right wing who played 17 seasons in the National Hockey League (NHL) for the New York Rangers, Toronto Maple Leafs, Detroit Red Wings and Pittsburgh Penguins. <s> In 2017 Bathgate was named one of the "100 Greatest NHL Players" in history. <s> Bathgate died at the age of 83 on February 26, 2016, in Brampton, Ontario. <s> At the time of his death, he had Alzheimer's disease and Parkinson's disease.

title: Miss USA
complex: Miss USA is an American beauty pageant that has been held annually since 1952 to select the entrant from United States in the Miss Universe pageant. <s> The Miss Universe Organization operates both pageants, as well as Miss Teen USA.

title: Bebop
complex: Bebop or bop is a style of jazz developed in the early to mid-1940s in the United States, which features songs characterized by a fast tempo, complex chord progressions with rapid chord changes and numerous changes of key, instrumental virtuosity, and improvisation based on a combination of harmonic structure, the use of scales and occasional references to the melody. <s> The term "bebop" is derived from nonsense syllables (vocables) used in scat singing; the first known example of "bebop" being used was in McKinney's Cotton Pickers' "Four or Five Times", recorded in 1928. <s> It appears again in a 1936 recording of "I'se a Muggin'" by Jack Teagarden.
simple: Bebop or bop is a kind of jazz that became popular near the beginning of the Second World War, in the mid-1940s. <s> Bebop is often fast. <s> The term "bebop" originates from a group of syllables used in scat singing, where random strings of sound were used in place of words.

title: Anne Cuneo
complex: Anne Cuneo (6 September 1936 – 11 February 2015) was a Swiss journalist, novelist, theatre and film director and screenwriter. <s> She was born in Paris of Italian parents, but studied in Lausanne. <s> Her first novel came in 1967 and was called "Gravé au diamant." <s> In 1979 she received the lesser prize of the Schweizerische Schillerstiftung and by 1987 she worked for Télévision Suisse Romande.

title: Space Shuttle Columbia disaster
complex: On February 1, 2003, the "Columbia" disintegrated during atmospheric entry, killing all seven crew members. <s> The disaster was the second fatal accident in the Space Shuttle program, after "Challenger" , which broke apart 73 seconds after liftoff and killed the seven-member crew in 1986.
simple: The Space Shuttle Columbia disaster occurred when "Columbia" broke up when it was reentering the atmosphere on February 1, 2003.

title: René Pétillon
complex: René Pétillon (] ; 12 December 1945 – 30 September 2018) was a French satirical and political cartoonist and comics artist. <s> As a cartoonist he was most famous for his work in "Canard Enchaîné". <s> As a comics artist his best known and longest-running series was the humoristic comic strip Jack Palmer, about a goofy private detective. <s> He died in 2018 after a long illness.

title: Joseph Joffo
complex: Joseph Joffo (2 April 1931 – 6 December 2018) was a French author. <s> A noted autobiographer, Joffo was perhaps best known for his memoir "Un sac de billes" ("A Bag of Marbles"), which has been translated into eighteen languages. <s> Joffo was born in Paris in the 18th arrondissement. <s> He left school at 14 with a certificat d'études (a former school leaving certificate, taken at the end of primary education) in his pocket and joined his brothers in the family's barber shop. <s> His novel "Baby-foot", published in 1977, follows on from "Un sac de billes" and describes his life in Paris following World War II and his discovery of American values. <s> Joffo died on 6 December 2018 at a hospital in Saint-Laurent-du-Var, Alpes-Maritimes from a short-illness at the age of 87.

title: Union Army
complex: During the American Civil War, the Union Army referred to the United States Army, the land force that fought to preserve the Union of the collective states. <s> Also known as the Federal Army, it proved essential to the preservation of the United States as a working, viable republic.

title: Olympic Hockey Nagano '98
complex: Olympic Hockey 98, known in Japan as Olympic Hockey Nagano '98 (オリンピック ホッキー NAGANO98 ( ナガノ98 ) , Orinpikku Hakkī Nagano 98 ) is an ice hockey game for the Nintendo 64 that was released in 1998. <s> It is a re-release of "Wayne Gretzky's 3D Hockey", but this time not endorsed by Wayne Gretzky and featuring the license for the 1998 Winter Olympics that were celebrated in Nagano, Japan. <s> It is also a video game developer debut of Treyarch Besides the box art, in-game titles, and some minor graphic changes (such as team logos and colors), every single aspect of the game is practically identical to "Wayne Gretzky's 3D Hockey". <s> IGN rated "Olympic Hockey Nagano '98" a zero, the lowest rated IGN game of all time, due to this fact. <s> Olympic Hockey Nagano 98 features 14 national teams from the 1998 Winter Olympics. <s> While the gameplay is very similar to Wayne Gretzky's 3D Hockey, there are minor differences. <s> The first difference is that the rink is bigger than the rink in the previous game (since its Olympic size).

title: Franklin Cleckley
complex: Franklin Dorrah Cleckley (August 1, 1940 – August 14, 2017) was an American law professor and judge. <s> He was Arthur B. Hodges Professor of Law at West Virginia University College of Law. <s> He taught at the law school from 1969 to 2013. <s> He held the endowed professorship emeritus. <s> Cleckley was the first African-American to serve as a Justice of the West Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals. <s> Governor Gaston Caperton appointed Cleckley to the bench in 1994. <s> He served on the Court until 1996. <s> Cleckley was born in Huntington, West Virginia, on August 1, 1940, but was raised in McDowell County, West Virginia. <s> He received an A.B. degree from Anderson College in 1962, a J.D. degree from Indiana University School of Law in 1965, and a LL.M. <s> degree from Harvard Law School in 1969. <s> He also did post-graduate studies at the University of Exeter in England. <s> Cleckley died at his home in Morgantown, West Virginia, on August 14, 2017 at the age of 77.

title: Diabetic retinopathy
complex: Diabetic retinopathy, also known as diabetic eye disease, is a medical condition in which damage occurs to the retina due to diabetes mellitus. <s> It is a leading cause of blindness. <s> Diabetic retinopathy affects up to 80 percent of those who have had diabetes for 20 years or more. <s> At least 90% of new cases could be reduced with proper treatment and monitoring of the eyes. <s> The longer a person has diabetes, the higher his or her chances of developing diabetic retinopathy. <s> Each year in the United States, diabetic retinopathy accounts for 12% of all new cases of blindness. <s> It is also the leading cause of blindness in people aged 20 to 64. <s> Diabetic retinopathy often has no early warning signs. <s> Even macular edema, which can cause rapid vision loss, may not have any warning signs for some time. <s> In general, however, a person with macular edema is likely to have blurred vision, making it hard to do things like read or drive. <s> In some cases, the vision will get better or worse during the day. <s> In the second stage, abnormal new blood vessels (neovascularisation) form at the back of the eye as part of "proliferative diabetic retinopathy" (PDR); these can burst and bleed (vitreous hemorrhage) and blur the vision, because these new blood vessels are fragile. <s> The first time this bleeding occurs, it may not be very severe. <s> In most cases, it will leave just a few specks of blood, or spots floating in a person's visual field, though the spots often go away after a few hours. <s> These spots are often followed within a few days or weeks by a much greater leakage of blood, which blurs the vision. <s> In extreme cases, a person may only be able to tell light from dark in that eye. <s> It may take the blood anywhere from a few days to months or even years to clear from the inside of the eye, and in some cases the blood will not clear. <s> These types of large hemorrhages tend to happen more than once, often during sleep. <s> On funduscopic exam, a doctor will see cotton wool spots, flame hemorrhages (similar lesions are also caused by the alpha-toxin of "Clostridium novyi"), and dot-blot hemorrhages. <s> Panretinal photocoagulation, or PRP (also called scatter laser treatment), is used to treat proliferative diabetic retinopathy (PDR). <s> The goal is to create 1,600 – 2,000 burns in the retina with the hope of reducing the retina's oxygen demand, and hence the possibility of ischemia. <s> It is done in multiple sittings. <s> In treating advanced diabetic retinopathy, the burns are used to destroy the abnormal blood vessels that form in the retina. <s> This has been shown to reduce the risk of severe vision loss for eyes at risk by 50%.
simple: Diabetic retinopathy, is the most common eye disease caused by diabetes, it damages the retinas in both eyes, causing vision problems which may lead to blindness. <s> It affects up to 80 percent of all patients who have had diabetes for 10 years or more. <s> However it is possible that at least 90% of these new cases could be kept from becoming severe with early diagnosis and proper treatment. <s> Diabetic retinopathy often has no early warning signs. <s> As new blood vessels form at the back of the eye as a part of "proliferative diabetic retinopathy" (PDR), they can bleed (ocular hemorrhage) and blur vision. <s> The first time this happens, it may not be very severe. <s> In most cases, it will leave just a few specks of blood, or spots, floating in a person's visual field, though the spots often go away after a few hours. <s> These spots are often followed within a few days or weeks by a much greater leakage of blood, which blurs vision. <s> In extreme cases, a person will only be able to tell light from dark in that eye. <s> It may take the blood anywhere from a few days to months or even years to clear from the inside of the eye, and in some cases the blood will not clear. <s> These types of large hemorrhages tend to happen more than once, often during sleep. <s> On funduscopic exam, a doctor will see spots, flame hemorrhages, and dot-blot hemorrhages. <s> Proliferative retinopathy is treated with scatter laser surgery, which helps to shrink the abnormal blood vessels. <s> During the surgery 1,000 to 2,000 laser burns are placed in the areas of the retina away from the macula, causing the abnormal blood vessels to shrink. <s> Focal laser treatment stabilizes vision and reduces the risk of vision loss by 50 percent.

complex: Wing Commander George Hedley Stainforth AFC RAF (1899 - 27 September 1942) was a British Royal Air Force pilot and the first man to exceed 400 miles per hour. <s> On 29 September 1931, the record attempt was made.

title: Be Good to Me
complex: "Be Good to Me" is a song recorded by American recording artist Ashley Tisdale from her debut album, "Headstrong" (2007). <s> It was written by Kara DioGuardi, Joacim Persson and Niclas Molinder, and produced by Twin. <s> The song was released in the US as the album's lead single on December 26, 2006 and in South America in January 2007. <s> The album version features uncredited rap vocals by Swedish musician David Jassy.

title: Paper Mario: Sticker Star
complex: Paper Mario: Sticker Star is a 2012 role-playing video game developed by Intelligent Systems and published by Nintendo for the Nintendo 3DS console. <s> It is the fourth installment of the "Paper Mario" series and is the first game in the series playable on a handheld console. <s> The game was released in North America on November 11, 2012 and in December 2012 in Japan, Europe, and Australia. <s> Unlike the previous "Paper Mario" games, "Sticker Star" uses a papercraft visual style, which is heavily incorporated into its gameplay mechanics. <s> "Sticker Star" introduces the use of stickers, which are littered throughout the game world and are used as items or power-ups, aiding the player in turn-based battles against enemies or in solving puzzles. <s> The plot follows Mario's quest to gather the six Royal Stickers that were scattered by Bowser.
simple: Paper Mario: Sticker Star is a role-playing video game for the Nintendo 3DS. <s> It is the first "Paper Mario" game for a handheld video game console. <s> It was released on November 11, 2012 in North America, on December 6, 2012 in Japan, and on December 7, 2012 in Europe. <s> His attack breaks the Sticker Comet into six pieces called the Royal Stickers. <s> Mario has to find the six Royal Stickers to restore the Sticker Comet and bring peace to the Mushroom Kingdom.

title: Howards End
complex: Howards End is a novel by E. M. Forster, first published in 1910, about social conventions, codes of conduct and relationships in turn-of-the-century England. <s> "Howards End" is considered by some to be Forster's masterpiece. <s> The book was conceived in June 1908 and worked on throughout the following year; it was completed in July 1910. <s> In 1998, the Modern Library ranked "Howards End" 38th on its list of the 100 best English-language novels of the 20th century. <s> A film version made in 1992 stars Emma Thompson, Vanessa Redgrave, Helena Bonham Carter, Anthony Hopkins, and Samuel West. <s> Thompson won an Academy Award for her performance.
simple: Howards End is a novel by E. M. Forster, first published in 1910. <s> it is about social conventions, personal relationships and conflicting values in Edwardian England. <s> Some people think "Howards End" was Forster's best piece of work. <s> In 1998, the Modern Library ranked "Howards End" 38th on its list of the 100 best English-language novels of the 20th century. <s> It was adapted into a film in 1992 starring Anthony Hopkins, Vanessa Redgrave, Emma Thompson, and Helena Bonham Carter.

title: Alexander Ramsey
complex: Alexander Ramsey (September 8, 1815 April 22, 1903) was an American politician. <s> He served as a Whig and Republican over a variety of offices between the 1840s and the 1880s. <s> He was the first Minnesota and Wisconsin Territorial Governor. <s> Alexander Ramsey was elected from Pennsylvania as a Whig to the U.S. House of Representatives and served in the 28th and 29th congresses from March 4, 1843, to March 3, 1847. <s> He served as the first Territorial Governor of Minnesota from June 1, 1849, to May 15, 1853, as a member of the Whig Party. <s> Ramsey was of Scottish and German ancestry. <s> In 1855, he became the mayor of St. Paul, Minnesota. <s> Ramsey was elected the second Governor of Minnesota after statehood and served from January 2, 1860, to July 10, 1863. <s> Ramsey is credited with being the first Union governor to commit troops during the American Civil War. <s> He happened to be in Washington, D.C., when fighting broke out. <s> When he heard about the firing on Ft. Sumter he went straight to the White House and offered Minnesota's services to Abraham Lincoln. <s> He resigned the governorship to become a U.S. Senator, having been elected to that post in 1863 as a Republican. <s> He was re-elected in 1869 and held the office until March 3, 1875, serving in the 38th, 39th, 40th, 41st, 42nd, and 43rd congresses. <s> Ramsey served as Secretary of War from 1879 to 1881, under President Rutherford B. Hayes. <s> The Minnesota Historical Society preserves his home, the Alexander Ramsey House as a museum. <s> It was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1969. <s> Alexander Ramsey Park, located in Redwood Falls, Minnesota, is the largest municipal park in Minnesota. <s> Ramsey County, Minnesota, Ramsey County, North Dakota, the city of Ramsey, Minnesota, the city of Ramsey, Illinois, Ramsey Park in Stillwater, Minnesota, Ramsey Junior High School in Saint Paul, Minnesota, and Alexander Ramsey Elementary School in Montevideo, Minnesota, are also named for him. <s> Justice Page Middle School in Minneapolis, Minnesota (formerly Ramsey International Fine Arts Center and formerly Alexander Ramsey Junior High School) was named after him when it was first founded in 1932.
simple: Alexander Ramsey (September 8, 1815– April 22, 1903) was an American politician. <s> Ramsey was elected from Pennsylvania as a Whig to the U.S. House of Representatives and served in the 28th and 29th congresses from March 4, 1843 to March 3, 1847. <s> He served as the first Territorial Governor of Minnesota June 1, 1849 to May 15, 1853 as a member of the Whig Party. <s> In 1855, he became the mayor of St. Paul, Minnesota. <s> Ramsey was elected the second Governor of Minnesota after statehood and served from January 2, 1860 to July 10, 1863. <s> Ramsey is credited with being the first Union governor to commit troops during the American Civil War (he happened to be in Washington, D.C. when fighting broke out). <s> He resigned the governorship to become a U.S. Senator, having been elected to that post in 1863 as a Republican. <s> He was re-elected in 1869 and held the office until March 3, 1875, serving in the 38th, 39th, 40th, 41st, 42nd, and 43rd congresses. <s> Ramsey served as Secretary of War from 1879 to 1881, under President Rutherford B. Hayes. <s> The Minnesota Historical Society preserves his home as a museum. <s> It was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1969. <s> Alexander Ramsey Park, located in Redwood Falls, Minnesota, is the largest municipal park in Minnesota. <s> Ramsey County, Minnesota, Ramsey County, North Dakota, the city of Ramsey, Minnesota, the city of Ramsey, Illinois, Ramsey Park in Stillwater, Minnesota, and Alexander Ramsey Elementary School in Montevideo, Minnesota are also named for him.

title: Kow Swamp Archaeological Site
complex: The Kow Swamp archaeological site comprises a series of late Pleistocene burials within the lunette of the eastern rim of a former lake known as Kow Swamp. <s> The site is located 10 km south-east of Cohuna in the central Murray River valley, in northern Victoria, at . <s> The site is significant for archaeological excavations by Alan Thorne between 1968 and 1972 which recovered the partial skeletal remains of more than 22 individuals. <s> The name of Kow Swamp is derived from an Aboriginal word in the Yorta Yorta language, "(Ghow)", which refers to the white gypsum soil found in the area. <s> Kow Swamp is now a permanent water body, due to its use for irrigation storage, 15 kilometres in circumference, with an average depth of 3 metres. <s> Originally a low lying swamp, it was filled when the Murray River is in flood or running at high levels, while Bendigo creek provides a smaller amount of water. <s> There is evidence of recent Aboriginal occupation of the area from canoe trees and middens, while early settlers' records describe an Aboriginal ceremonial site on the north side of the swamp. <s> The most notable evidence was the discovery in 1925, on the west side of the swamp, of the Cohuna Cranium by a local earthmoving contractor. <s> The editor of the local newspaper "Cohuna Farmers Weekly" notified authorities and the significance of the discovery was realised. <s> In the 1960s, Alan Thorne also identified archaic bone from the collection at the Museum of Victoria, and traced the find spot to Kow Swamp. <s> Archaeological excavations were undertaken between 1968 and 1972 by Thorne for the Australian National University in Canberra. <s> Further remains were found around the swamp by an interested local resident, Gordon Spark. <s> By 1972 the remains of at least forty individuals had been excavated and studied. <s> These discoveries helped establish the diversity of Aboriginal genetic history and have been interpreted as representing different waves of immigrants to Australia before European discovery. <s> Radiocarbon dates returned a wide range of ages for the burials, with 13,000 ± 280 (ANU1236) from shell in the grave of KS5 and 10,070 ± 250 (ANU-403b), from bone apatite from KS10 respectively. <s> The youngest date was approximately 6500 BP for KS1. <s> Optically stimulated luminescence (OSL) dating was undertaken of the Kow Swamp burial site in 2003 (close to KS 9, the only burial excavated in situ), which suggested that the cemetery was in use between 22 and 19 ka, rather than 15 – 9 ka. <s> Some question the OSL dates due to the difficulty of ensuring that the dated sand is contemporary with the actual burials. <s> However, the OSL dates from the burial units directly contradict the C14 dates, which were only ever minimum ages because of contamination by younger carbon. <s> The initial descriptions of the crania from Kow Swamp identified "receding frontal squama, massive supraorbital regions and a supraglabella fossae..." which were considered to be "preserving an almost unmodified eastern erectus form" displaying a ".. <s> complex of archaic characteristics not seen in recent Aboriginal crania...". <s> The features were considered to indicate "the survival of "Homo erectus" features in Australia until as recently as 10,000 years ago". <s> However, Donald Brothwell disputed this interpretation suggesting the vault size and shape at Kow Swamp had been influenced by artificial cranial deformation, particularly in Kow Swamp 5. <s> The varying morphological and metrical comparisons of the burials have distinguished them from modern Aboriginal crania and also a more gracile group of Pleistocene remains found at Lake Mungo and Keilor. <s> These differences have been used to postulate separate arrivals of distinct groups of people. <s> However, more recent comparison does not support Thorne's dual Pleistocene population model. <s> Following a campaign by Aboriginal community groups to have human remains repatriated from Australian and overseas museum collections, the Kow Swamp skeletons were returned to the area and re-interred. <s> Casts of some of the Kow Swamp crania and mandibles are held by the Archaeology and Human Sciences department at the Australian National University, with some casts (including casts of KS1 and 5) being sent to the London Natural History Museum and other institutions. <s> Despite extensive reconstruction, the Kow Swamp material was extremely fragmentary, with only two of the crania, KS1 and 5, being relatively complete.
simple: The Kow Swamp archaeological site is on the eastern side of Kow Swamp in northern Victoria. <s> A number of Pleistocene burials have been found in a sand dune, known as a lunette. <s> Archaeologist Alan Thorne dug up the skeletons of more than 22 people between 1968 and 1972. <s> Kow Swamp is named for an Aboriginal word, "Ghow", from the Yorta Yorta language. <s> It means white gypsum soil which is found in the area. <s> Kow Swamp is now a lake used to store irrigation water. <s> It is 15 kilometres in circumference and about 3 metres deep. <s> It was once a low lying swamp which only filled when the Murray River was in flood or running at high levels. <s> Early European settlers described an Aboriginal ceremonial site on the north side of the swamp. <s> In 1925 part of a skull was found on the west side of the swamp during digging works. <s> The editor of the local newspaper "Cohuna Farmers Weekly" notified authorities and the importance of the discovery was realised. <s> In the 1960s, Alan Thorne also found an ancient bone in the collection at the Museum of Victoria, and traced the find spot to Kow Swamp. <s> Archaeological excavations took place between 1968 and 1972 by Thorne for the Australian National University in Canberra. <s> Further remains were found around the swamp by a local person, Gordon Spark. <s> By 1972 the remains of at least forty individuals had been excavated and studied. <s> These discoveries helped prove the wide range of Aboriginal genetic history. <s> They have been used to show that there were different waves of immigrants to Australia before European discovery. <s> Radiocarbon dating has shown that most of the burials took place between 13,000 and 10,000 years ago. <s> The youngest burial 6500 was about 6,500 years old. <s> Optically stimulated luminesence (OSL) dating in 2003 showed the burials were between 22,000 and 19,000 years old. <s> However, these dates have been questioned due to the difficulty of making sure the dated sand is the same age as the actual burials. <s> Thorne believed that it showed "the survival of "Homo erectus" features in Australia until as recently as 10,000 years ago". <s> However, Donald Brothwell disagreed and said size and shape of the skulls at Kow Swamp had been caused by artificial cranial deformation. <s> They are also different to Pleistocene remains found at Lake Mungo and Keilor. <s> These differences have been used to suggest that different people came to Australia at different times in the past. <s> However, more recent studies do not support this theory. <s> Aboriginal community groups have asked for the human remains from Kow Swamp be returned from Australian and overseas museum collections. <s> The Kow Swamp skeletons were returned to the area and reburied. <s> Casts of some of the Kow Swamp skulls are held by the Archaeology and Human Sciences department at the Australian National University. <s> Some casts are also at London Natural History Museum and other institutions.

title: Alban, Wisconsin
complex: Alban is a town in Portage County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> The population was 897 at the 2000 census. <s> The unincorporated community of Alban is located within the town.
simple: Alban is a town in Portage County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> 897 people lived there as of the year 2000.

title: Ninigi-no-Mikoto
complex: Ninigi-no-Mikoto (Japanese: 瓊瓊杵尊 ) , also known as Ame-nigishi-kuni-nigishi-amatsuhiko-hiko-ho-no-ninigi-no-Mikoto (天邇岐志国邇岐志天津日高日子番能邇邇芸命 ) , is in Japanese mythology, the son of Ame no Oshihomimi no Mikoto (天忍穗耳尊 ) and Takuhadachiji-hime no Mikoto (栲幡千千姫命 ) , and grandson of Amaterasu, who sent him down to earth ("Tenson kōrin") to plant rice there. <s> He was the great-grandfather of Emperor Jimmu. <s> His wife was Konohanasakuya-hime. <s> Amaterasu sent him to pacify Japan by bringing the three celestial gifts used by the Emperor: the sword Kusanagi, the mirror Yata no Kagami, and the jewel Yasakani no Magatama. <s> These three gifts signify that the Emperor is the descendant of Amaterasu herself. <s> The account of Ninigi being sent to earth appears in the "Nihon Shoki".
simple: He was the great-grandfather of Emperor Jimmu. <s> Amaterasu sent him to bring peace to Japan by bringing the three gifts from Heaven used by the emperor. <s> The sword, Kusanagi, the mirror, Yata no kagami, and the jewel, Yasakani no magatama. <s> These three gifts mean to the world that the emperor is the descendant of Amaterasu herself. <s> The tale of Ninigi no Mikoto being sent to earth is told in the Nihon Shoki.

title: Roger Joseph Boscovich
complex: Roger Joseph Boscovich, S.J. (; ] ; ; ; 18 May 1711 – 13 February 1787) was a physicist, astronomer, mathematician, philosopher, diplomat, poet, theologian, Jesuit priest, and a polymath from the Republic of Ragusa (modern-day Dubrovnik, Croatia). <s> He studied and lived in Italy and France where he also published many of his works. <s> Boscovich produced a precursor of atomic theory and made many contributions to astronomy, including the first geometric procedure for determining the equator of a rotating planet from three observations of a surface feature and for computing the orbit of a planet from three observations of its position. <s> In 1753 he also discovered the absence of atmosphere on the Moon. <s> Boscovich was born on 18 May 1711 in Ragusa (Dubrovnik), Republic of Ragusa, to Nikola Bošković, a Ragusan merchant, and Paola Bettera (1674–1777), daughter of a local nobleman of Italian origin. <s> He was baptised on 26 May 1711 by Marinus Carolis, "curatus et sacristia". <s> The name Ruđer/Ruggiero may have been given to him because both his great-grandfather Agostino Bettera and his mother's brother were called Ruggiero, the godparent was his uncle Ruggiero Bettera. <s> He was the seventh child of the family and the second youngest. <s> His father was born in 1642, at Orahov Do near Ravno, at the time part of the Ottoman Empire (now Bosnia and Herzegovina). <s> His father was rich in trading experience and knowledge of that part of the Ottoman Empire, but Ruđer knew him only as a bedridden invalid with paralysed legs and he died when Ruđer was 10 years old. <s> Boscovich's mother Paola, nicknamed "Pavica", was a member of a cultivated Italian merchant family established in Dubrovnik since the early 17th century, when her ancestor Pietro Bettera settled from Bergamo in northern Italy. <s> She was a robust and active woman with a happy temperament who lived to 103. <s> On 16 September 1725, Ruđer Bošković left Dubrovnik for Rome. <s> He was in the care of two Jesuit priests who took him to the Society of Jesus, famous for its education of youth and at that time having some 800 establishments and 200,000 pupils under its care throughout the world. <s> We learn nothing from Bošković himself until the time he entered the novitiate in 1731, but it was the usual practice for novices to spend the first two years not in the Collegium Romanum but in Sant'Andrea delle Fratte. <s> There, he studied mathematics and physics; and so brilliant was his progress in these sciences that in 1740 he was appointed professor of mathematics in the college. <s> Notwithstanding the arduous duties of his professorship, he found time for investigation in various fields of physical science, and he published a very large number of dissertations, some of them of considerable length. <s> Among the subjects were the transit of Mercury, the Aurora Borealis, the figure of the Earth, the observation of the fixed stars, the inequalities in terrestrial gravitation, the application of mathematics to the theory of the telescope, the limits of certainty in astronomical observations, the solid of greatest attraction, the cycloid, the logistic curve, the theory of comets, the tides, the law of continuity, the double refraction micrometre, and various problems of spherical trigonometry. <s> In 1742 he was consulted, with other men of science, by Pope Benedict XIV, as to the best means of securing the stability of the dome of St. Peter's, Rome, in which a crack had been discovered. <s> His suggestion of placing five concentric iron bands was adopted. <s> In 1745 Bošković published "De Viribus Vivis" in which he tried to find a middle way between Isaac Newton's gravitational theory and Gottfried Leibniz's metaphysical theory of monad-points. <s> He developed a concept of "impenetrability" as a property of hard bodies which explained their behaviour in terms of force rather than matter. <s> Stripping atoms of their matter, impenetrability is disassociated from hardness and then put in an arbitrary relationship to elasticity. <s> Impenetrability has a Cartesian sense that more than one point cannot occupy the same location at once. <s> A dispute arose between Francis the Grand Duke of Tuscany and the Republic of Lucca with respect to the drainage of a lake. <s> As agent of Lucca, Bošković was sent, in 1757, to Vienna and succeeded in bringing about a satisfactory arrangement in the matter. <s> In Vienna in 1758, he published the first edition of his famous work, "Philosophiæ naturalis theoria redacta ad unicam legem virium in natura existentium" ("Theory of Natural philosophy derived to the single Law of forces which exist in Nature"), containing his atomic theory and his theory of forces. <s> A second edition was published in 1763 in Venice and a third again in Vienna in 1764. <s> In 1922 it was published in London, and in 1966 in the United States. <s> Another edition was published in Zagreb in 1974.
simple: Roger Joseph Boscovich (18 May 1711 - 13 February 1787) was a Croatian polymath and Jesuit from the city of Dubrovnik in the Republic of Ragusa (modern-day Croatia). <s> He studied and lived in Italy and France, where he published many of his works. <s> He produced a precursor of atomic theory and made many contributions to astronomy. <s> In 1753 he discovered the absence of atmosphere on the Moon. <s> Boscovich was born in Dubrovnik as the youngest of seven children. <s> He joined the Jesuit school in Dubrovnik, leaving for Rome in 1725. <s> In Rome he was under the care of 2 Jesuit priests whom introduced him to the Society of Jesus. <s> There, he studied mathematics and physics and in 1740 he was appointed professor of mathematics in the college. <s> Boscovich studied the transit of Mercury, the Aurora borealis, the figure of the Earth, the observation of the fixed stars, the inequalities in terrestrial gravitation, the application of mathematics to the theory of the telescope, the limits of certainty in astronomical observations, and various problems in solid geometry and spherical trigonometry. <s> In 1742 he and other scientists were consulted by Pope Benedict XIV, as to the best way of securing the structure of the dome of St. Peter's, Rome, in which a crack had been discovered. <s> His suggested placing five iron bands and it was accepted. <s> He explained the resistance of hard bodies as due to force rather than "hardness". <s> In Vienna in 1758, he published the first edition of his famous work, "Philosophiæ naturalis theoria redacta ad unicam legem virium in natura existentium" ("Theory of natural philosophy derived to the single law of forces which exist in nature"). <s> A second edition was published in 1763 in Venice and a third again in Vienna in 1764. <s> In 1922 it was published in London, and in 1966 in the United States. <s> Another edition was published in Zagreb in 1974.

title: Keizō Obuchi
complex: Keizō Obuchi (小渕 恵三 , Obuchi Keizō , 25 June 1937 – 14 May 2000) was a Japanese politician who served as Prime Minister of Japan from 1998 to 2000, and was elected to the House of Representatives twelve times. <s> His political career ended prematurely when, in early 2000, he suffered a serious, and ultimately fatal, stroke. <s> Obuchi suffered a stroke on 1 April 2000 and slipped into a coma at Tokyo's Juntendo University Hospital. <s> When it became apparent he would never regain consciousness, he was replaced by Yoshirō Mori on 5 April. <s> Obuchi died on 14 May at the age of 62; a state funeral was held in his honour at the Nippon Budokan on 8 June and was attended by foreign dignitaries from 156 countries and 22 organizations, includes about 25 heads of state. <s> Notable presence at Obuchi’s funeral includes UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, United States President Bill Clinton and South Korea President Kim Dae-jung.
simple: Keizō Obuchi (小渕 恵三, Obuchi Keizō, 25 June 1937 – 14 May 2000) was a Japanese politician. <s> He served in the House of Representatives for twelve terms. <s> He became the 84th Prime Minister of Japan from 30 July 1998 to 5 April 2000. <s> His political career ended when he suffered a serious stroke and slipped into a coma. <s> Obuchi died on 14 May 2000 at the age of 62 in Tokyo from complications of a stroke.

title: GMA Network

simple: GMA Network is the leading television network in the Philippines in Quezon City.

title: DuPage County, Illinois
complex: DuPage County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois, and one of the collar counties of the Chicago metropolitan area. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 916,924, making it Illinois' second-most populous county. <s> Its county seat is Wheaton. <s> DuPage County has become mostly developed and suburbanized, although some pockets of farmland remain in the county's western and northern parts. <s> The county has a high socioeconomic profile and residents of Hinsdale, Naperville and Oak Brook include some of the wealthiest people in the Midwest. <s> On the whole, the county enjoys above average median household income levels and low overall poverty levels when compared to the national average.
simple: DuPage County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 916,924, making it Illinois' second-most populous county. <s> Its county seat is Wheaton. <s> DuPage County has become mostly developed and suburbanized. <s> Residents of Hinsdale, Naperville, and Oak Brook include some of the wealthiest people in the Midwest, and in 2010, "Midwest Living" voted Hinsdale the Midwest's second-wealthiest town.

complex: Year 1445 (MCDXLV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.
simple: Year 1445 was a common year. <s> It started on a Friday.

title: Candidatus
complex: In prokaryote nomenclature, Candidatus (Latin for candidate of Roman office, named after the white gown worn by Roman senators) is a component of the taxonomic name for a bacterium or other prokaryote, that cannot be maintained in a microbiological culture collection. <s> It is an interim taxonomic status for yet-to-be-cultured microorganisms. <s> An example would be ""Candidatus" Phytoplasma allocasuarinae". <s> This can be abbreviated to ""Ca." <s> Candidatus status may be used when a species or genus is well characterized but yet-uncultured. <s> With today's technology much information is obtained by 16S ribosomal RNA or even near-complete genomes with modern metagenomics techniques. <s> For valid publication of a species, bacteria must be isolated, cultured, described, and deposited in a bacteriology culture collection. <s> However, some bacteria require special culture conditions and cannot be maintained in such collections. <s> These include obligately intracellular pathogens and endosymbionts, insect symbionts, and populations from oceans or sludge. <s> In 1994, Murray and Schleifer published a taxonomic note in which they recommended that the new category of indefinite rank ("Candidatus") be established for certain putative taxa that could not be described in sufficient detail to warrant establishment of a new taxon. <s> It was also recommended that a "Candidatus" list should be established in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology - IJSB (now International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology).
simple: Candidatus is a term in the taxonomy (scientific classification) of bacteria. <s> An example would be ""Candidatus" Phytoplasma allocasuarinae". <s> Candidatus status may be used when a species or genus is well studied but cannot be cultured. <s> Nowadays much information is got by 16S ribosomal RNA sequence analysis. <s> For correct publication of a species, bacteria must be isolated, cultured, described, and deposited in a bacteriology culture collection. <s> However, some bacteria require special tissue culture conditions and cannot be maintained in Bacteriology Culture Collections. <s> These include obligately intracellular pathogens and endosymbionts, insect symbionts, and populations from oceans or sludge. <s> In 1994, Murray and Schleifer published a taxonomic note. <s> They recommended that the new category of indefinite rank (Candidatus) be established for certain putative taxa that could not be described in sufficient detail to warrant establishment of a new taxon. <s> It was also recommended that a Candidatus list should be established in the "International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology".

title: Adile Naşit
complex: Adile Naşit (17 June 1930 – 11 December 1987) was a Turkish actress, who is best known for being the partner of Münir Özkul in movies like "Happy Days" and in "Hababam Sınıfı" (Hababam Class). <s> She also starred in many plays, movies, and a children's programme called "Uykudan Önce" (Before Sleep) as a storyteller.

title: Bézier curve
complex: A Bézier curve is a parametric curve used in computer graphics and related fields. <s> The curve, which is related to the Bernstein polynomial, is named after Pierre Bézier, who used it in the 1960s for designing curves for the bodywork of Renault cars.
simple: A Bézier curve is a type of parametric curve (a curve defined by a set of equations changing in respect to another variable) that is used in computer graphics and related fields.

title: Wolfgang Bötsch
complex: Wolfgang Bötsch (8 September 1938 in Bad Kreuznach – 14 October 2017 in Würzburg) was a German politician, representative of the Christian Social Union of Bavaria. <s> Between 1974 and 1976 he represented the Landtag of Bavaria. <s> From 1976 to 2005 he was a member of the Bundestag, and between 1993 and 1997 he was the last Minister of Post and Telecommunications. <s> Bötsch died on 14 October 2017 at the age of 79.
simple: Wolfgang Bötsch (8 September 1938 – 14 October 2017) was a German politician. <s> He was a representative of the Christian Social Union of Bavaria. <s> Between 1974 and 1976 he represented the Landtag of Bavaria. <s> From 1976 to 2005 he was a member of the Bundestag, and between 1993 and 1997 he was the last Minister of Post and Telecommunications. <s> Bötsch died on 14 October 2017 in Würzburg, Germany at the age of 79.

title: LaMarcus Aldridge
complex: LaMarcus Nurae Aldridge (born July 19, 1985) is an American professional basketball player for the San Antonio Spurs of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> The power forward played college basketball for two seasons with the Texas Longhorns. <s> Aldridge was selected second overall in the 2006 NBA draft. <s> After spending nine seasons with the Portland Trail Blazers, he signed with the Spurs in 2015. <s> He has been selected to five All-NBA teams and is a seven-time NBA All-Star. <s> He is widely known for his signature fadeaway jump shot.
simple: LaMarcus Aldridge (born July 19, 1985 ) is an American basketball player for the Portland Trail Blazers of the NBA. <s> He played college basketball at the University of Texas at Austin. <s> He has been chosen as an all-star for the past three years.

title: Cabrières-d'Avignon

title: Erika Remberg
complex: Erika Remberg (15 February 1932 – 10 November 2017) was an Austrian film actress. <s> She appeared in 31 films between 1950 and 1970. <s> She was born in Medan, Indonesia.

title: Sphere Fluidics
complex: Sphere Fluidics is a Cambridge, UK-based Life Sciences R&D company that specializes in biopharmaceutical discovery and development, cell therapy engineering, bioproduction and synthetic biology, and analysis and isolation. <s> The company is reported to own 25 patented products that include instruments, biochips, and specialist chemicals. <s> Sphere Fluidics was originally established in 2010, with two chemistry professors of Cambridge University, namely, Professor Chris Abell and Professor Wilhelm Huck, Dr. Frank F. Craig, an entrepreneur, and Dr. Maher Khaled, a Cambridge University Enterprise, as founders. <s> The total funds raised by Sphere Fluidics as of 2017, is reported to be, $13 million through various funding rounds and grants. <s> Cyto-Mine is a patented single cell analysis and characterisation system by Sphere Fluidics. <s> This technology is said to aid the development of biotherapeutics for treatment of cancer and inflammatory diseases and vaccine generation. <s> Cyto-Mine is said to be an integrated device which can automatically perform single cell analysis, sorting, imaging and dispensing into individual wells of microtiter plates in a single compact system. <s> 2015: UK's top 50 disruptive SMEs by Real Business
simple: Sphere Fluidics is an England-based Life Sciences Research and Development company specializing in developing novel tools for biopharmaceutical discovery and development, cell therapy engineering, analysis and isolation. <s> Sphere Fluidics operates in various markets including biopharmaceutical discovery and development, anti-microbial screening, synthetic biology and genome editing of single cells. <s> Sphere Fluidics Limited was originally established in 2010, by two chemistry professors of Cambridge University, namely, Professor Chris Abell and Professor Wilhelm Huck along with Dr. Frank F. Craig, an entrepreneur, and Dr. Maher Khaled, a Cambridge University Enterprise. <s> Sphere Fluidics has raised £11 million as of 2017, from investors namely, 24 Haymarket, Amadeus Capital Partners, Greenwood Way Capital, University of Cambridge Enterprise, University of Cambridge, Parkwalk Advisors, Providence Investment Company, London Business Angels, Envestors, Angels5K, Cambridge Angels, Q-Ventures and a Japanese corporate investor. <s> Cyto-Mine Technology is one of the patented products of Sphere Fluidics. <s> Cyto-Mine technology is the integrated device that is able to automatically perform single cell analysis, sorting, imaging and dispensing into individual wells of microtitre plates in a single compact system. <s> Sphere Fluidics has been named one of the UK's top 50 disruptive SMEs by Real Business in 2015.

title: Veiled Christ
complex: The Veiled Christ (Italian: "Cristo velato") is a 1753 marble sculpture by Giuseppe Sanmartino exhibited in the Cappella Sansevero, Naples. <s> "Veiled Christ" is considered one of the world's most remarkable sculptures, and legendary thought to have been created by alchemy. <s> Sculptor Antonio Canova, who tried to acquire the work, declared that he would willingly give up ten years of his life to produce a similar masterpiece. <s> "Veiled Christ"' s production was originally assigned to the sculptor Antonio Corradini, who specialized in veiled statues. <s> However, Corradini died a short time later, having produced only a terracotta bozzetto (today displayed at the Museo nazionale di San Martino). <s> The job thus passed to Giuseppe Sanmartino, who was charged with producing "a marble statue sculpted with the greatest realism, representing Our Lord Jesus Christ in death, covered by a transparent shroud carved from the same block of stone as the statue." <s> Sanmartino produced a work with the dead Christ laid on a couch, covered by a veil which adheres perfectly to his form. <s> The mastery of the Neapolitan sculptor lies in his successful depiction, looking through the veil, of the suffering that Christ had undergone during the crucifixion. <s> Signs of Jesus's pain can be seen on his face and body. <s> Shaping further detail into the marble block, at Jesus's feet Sanmartino has carved depictions of the instruments of Christ's torture: the crown of thorns, pliers, and shackles. <s> In reality, a close analysis leaves no doubt that the work was entirely produced in marble. <s> This is also confirmed by some letters written at the time of its production. <s> A receipt of payment to Sanmartino, dated 16 December 1752 and signed by the prince, is preserved in the Historical archive of the Bank of Naples, states: In other letters, di Sangro also states that the veil was produced from the same block of stone as the statue.
simple: The Veiled Christ (Italian: "Cristo velato") is a statue made of marble. <s> It was made by Giuseppe Sanmartino. <s> It is in Cappella Sansevero, Naples. <s> Antonio Canova who once tried to acquire the work declared that he would willingly give up ten years of his own life to produce a similar masterpiece. <s> The order for the Veiled Christ was given to Antonio Corradini. <s> However, he died a short time later. <s> Sanmartino took over the work. <s> He decided to place the Christ figure on a couch, covered by a veil. <s> It was to show the suffering that Christ has undergone. <s> At the sculpture's feet, finally, the artist also carves the instruments of his torture: the crown of thorns, pliers, and some shackles. <s> An analysis shows that the work is completely made in marble. <s> A receipt of payment to Sanmartino dated 16 December 1752, signed by the prince, is preserved in the historical archive of the Bank of Naples.

title: Codification (law)
complex: In law, codification is the process of collecting and restating the law of a jurisdiction in certain areas, usually by subject, forming a legal code, i.e. a codex (book) of law. <s> Codification is one of the defining features of civil law jurisdictions. <s> In common law systems, such as that of English law, codification is the process of converting and consolidating judge-made law into statute law. <s> Ancient Sumer's Code of Ur-Nammu was compiled "circa" 2050–1230 BC, and is the earliest known surviving civil code. <s> Three centuries later, the Babylonian king Hammurabi enacted the set of laws named after him. <s> Besides religious laws such as the Torah, important codifications were developed in the ancient Roman Empire, with the compilations of the Lex Duodecim Tabularum and much later the Corpus Juris Civilis. <s> These codified laws were the exceptions rather than the rule, however, as during much of ancient times Roman laws were left mostly uncodified. <s> The first "permanent" system of codified laws could be found in imperial China , with the compilation of the "Tang Code" in AD 624. <s> This formed the basis of the Chinese criminal code, which was eventually replaced by the "Great Qing Legal Code", which was in turn abolished in 1912 following the Xinhai Revolution and the establishment of the Republic of China. <s> The new laws of the Republic of China were inspired by the German codified work, the Bürgerliches Gesetzbuch. <s> A very influential example in Europe was the French Napoleonic code of 1804. <s> Another early system of laws is Hindu law framed by Manu and called as Manu Smriti, dating back to the 2nd century BC. <s> The use of civil codes in Islamic Sharia law began with the Ottoman Empire in the 16th century AD. <s> Because each Congressional act may contain laws on a variety of topics, many acts, or portions thereof are also rearranged and published in a topical, subject matter codification by the Office of the Law Revision Counsel.
simple: In law, codification is the process of collecting and restating the law of a jurisdiction. <s> They are listed, usually by subject, forming a legal code (a codex or book of law). <s> Codification is the defining feature of civil law jurisdictions. <s> Ancient Sumer's Code of Ur-Nammu was compiled 2100-2050 BC. <s> It is the earliest known surviving civil code. <s> Three centuries later, the Babylonian king Hammurabi enacted the set of laws named after him. <s> Religious laws such as the Torah were codified. <s> Important codifications were developed in the ancient Roman Empire, with the compilations of the Lex Duodecim Tabularum. <s> These codified laws were the exceptions rather than the rule. <s> During much of ancient history the Roman laws were left mostly uncodified. <s> The first "permanent" system of codified laws could be found in China. <s> This was with the compilation of the "Tang Code" in AD 624. <s> This formed the basis of the Chinese criminal code. <s> This was then replaced by the "Great Qing Legal Code". <s> This code was in turn abolished in 1912 following the Xinhai Revolution and the establishment of the Republic of China. <s> The new laws of the Republic of China were inspired by the German codified work, the "Bürgerliches Gesetzbuch". <s> A very influential example in Europe was the French Napoleonic code of 1804. <s> Another early system of laws is Hindu law framed by Manu and called as Manu Smriti. <s> They date back to the 2nd century BC. <s> The use of civil codes in Islamic Sharia law began with the Ottoman Empire in the 16th century AD.

title: Scandinavian Canadians
complex: Scandinavian Canadians are Canadian citizens with ancestral roots in Scandinavia.
simple: Scandinavian Canadians are Canadian citizens with ancestral roots in Scandinavia.

title: Stone of Scone
complex: The Stone of Scone ( ; , )—also known as the Stone of Destiny, and often referred to in England as The Coronation Stone—is an oblong block of red sandstone that has been used for centuries in the coronation of the monarchs of Scotland, and later the monarchs of England and those of the United Kingdom. <s> Historically, the artefact was kept at the now-ruined Scone Abbey in Scone, near Perth, Scotland. <s> It is also known as Jacob's Pillow Stone and the Tanist Stone, and in Scottish Gaelic, "clach-na-cinneamhain". <s> Its size is approximately 660 mm by 425 mm by 267 mm and its weight is approximately 152 kg . <s> A roughly incised cross is on one surface, and an iron ring at each end aids with transport. <s> The Stone of Scone was last used in 1953 for the coronation of Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.
simple: The Stone of Scone, also known as the Stone of Destiny, and the Coronation Stone, is a stone used in the coronation ceremonies of England and Scotland. <s> It is an oblong shaped block of red sandstone. <s> It was kept at the now-ruined Scone Abbey in Scone, near Perth, Scotland. <s> Its size is about 26 in by 16.75 in by 10.5 in and weighs about 336 lb. <s> The Stone of Scone was last used in 1953 for the coronation of Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.

title: Probable prime
complex: In number theory, a probable prime (PRP) is an integer that satisfies a specific condition that is satisfied by all prime numbers, but which is not satisfied by most composite numbers. <s> Different types of probable primes have different specific conditions. <s> While there may be probable primes that are composite (called pseudoprimes), the condition is generally chosen in order to make such exceptions rare.
simple: In mathematics, particularly number theory, a probable prime is a whole number that is likely to be prime by having passed a probabilistic test such as Fermat's primality test. <s> Probable primes may be composite, but the tests are designed so they are really unlikely to be composite.

title: Samuel P. Huntington
complex: Samuel Phillips Huntington (April 18, 1927 – December 24, 2008) was an American political scientist, adviser and academic. <s> He spent more than half a century at Harvard University, where he was director of Harvard's Center for International Affairs and the Albert J. Weatherhead III University Professor. <s> During the presidency of Jimmy Carter, Huntington was the White House Coordinator of Security Planning for the National Security Council. <s> During the 1980's Apartheid era in South Africa, he served as an adviser to P.W. Botha's Security Services. <s> He is best known for his 1993 theory, the "Clash of Civilizations", of a post–Cold War new world order. <s> He argued that future wars would be fought not between countries, but between cultures, and that Islamic extremism would become the biggest threat to world peace. <s> Huntington is credited with helping to shape U.S. views on civilian–military relations, political development, and comparative government even into the current Trump administration. <s> After several years of declining health, Huntington died on December 24, 2008, at age 81 on Martha's Vineyard, Massachusetts.
simple: Samuel Phillips Huntington (April 18, 1927 – December 24, 2008) was an American political scientist, adviser and academic. <s> He spent most of his career working at Harvard University, where he was director of Harvard's Center for International Affairs and the Albert J. Weatherhead III University Professor. <s> During the Presidency of Jimmy Carter, Huntington was the White House Coordinator of Security Planning for the National Security Council. <s> Huntington was best known for his 1993 theory, the "Clash of Civilizations", of a post-Cold War new world order. <s> He argued that future wars would be fought not between countries, but between cultures. <s> Many believed Hunting was responsible for helping to shape U.S. views on civilian-military relations, political development, and comparative government. <s> Huntington died on December 24, 2008 in Martha's Vineyard, Massachusetts from congestive heart failure complicated by diabetes, aged 81.

title: Museum for Architectural Drawing
complex: The Museum for Architectural Drawing is a private museum in Berlin, Germany run by the Tchoban Foundation. <s> It was opened in June 2013. <s> Three to four exhibitions are shown each year, made up of drawings from the Tchoban Foundation’s collection and from works on loan in cooperation with other museums and institutions.
simple: Museum for Architectural Drawing (in German: Museum für Architekturzeichnung) is a private museum in Berlin, Germany dedicated to Architectural Drawing around the world. <s> the museum was open in 2013.

title: Wild Frontier
complex: Wild Frontier is the sixth solo studio album by Irish guitarist Gary Moore, released in 1987. <s> His first studio effort after a trip back to his native Belfast, Northern Ireland in 1985, the album contains several songs about Ireland and even the music itself is steeped in Celtic roots. <s> The album is dedicated to the memory of Moore's close friend and former Thin Lizzy bandmate Phil Lynott, who died on 4 January 1986, with the words "For Philip" on the rear cover. <s> "Wild Frontier" contains the hit single "Over the Hills and Far Away", which reached No. 20 in the UK, as well as a cover of the Easybeats' song "Friday on My Mind". <s> The Max Middleton-penned "The Loner" was originally recorded by Cozy Powell for his "Over the Top" album in 1979 (on which Moore performed, albeit not on Powell's recording of "The Loner"). <s> The track was substantially altered by Moore for his own recording, thus he is credited as a co-writer. <s> All drums on "Wild Frontier" are sequenced with a drum machine, although the programming is uncredited in the liner notes of the album, electronic drummer Roland Kerridge, of the band Re-Flex did a lot of the drum tracks, and would appear in the music video for "Over the Hills and Far Away," as well as early TV promotions for the album. <s> Future Alice Cooper, Kiss (band) and former Black Sabbath drummer Eric Singer played drums for the tour, before going on to form Badlands. <s> "Over the Hills and Far Away" was covered by the Finnish symphonic power metal band Nightwish on their 2001 EP of the same title, and by Swedish viking metal band Thyrfing on their album "Urkraft". <s> The Spanish band Saurom also recorded a cover of this song with alternative lyrics, titled "La Disolución de la Comunidad".
