simple: Wild Frontier is the sixth solo studio album by Irish guitarist Gary Moore, released in 1987. <s> His first studio effort after a trip back to his native Belfast, Northern Ireland in 1985. <s> The album contains several songs about Ireland and even the music itself is steeped in Celtic roots. <s> The album is dedicated to the memory of Moore's close friend and former Thin Lizzy bandmate Phil Lynott, who died on 4 January 1986, with the words "For Philip" on the rear cover. <s> "Wild Frontier" contains the hit single "Over the Hills and Far Away", which reached No. 20 in the UK, as well as a cover of the Easybeats' song "Friday on My Mind". <s> The Max Middleton-penned "The Loner" which was originally recorded by Cozy Powell for his "Over the Top" album in 1979 (on which Moore performed, but not on Powell's recording of "The Loner"). <s> The track was substantially altered by Moore for his own recording, that is why he is credited as a co-writer. <s> All drums on "Wild Frontier" are sequenced with a drum machine, although the programming is uncredited in the liner notes of the album. <s> Future Toto drummer Simon Phillips would appear on the music video for "Over the Hills and Far Away," as well in early promotions for the album. <s> He would be replaced by former Black Sabbath drummer Eric Singer for the tour, before leaving shortly afterwards to form Badlands. <s> "Over the Hills and Far Away" was covered by the Finnish symphonic power metal band Nightwish on their 2001 EP of the same title, and by Swedish viking metal band Thyrfing on their album "Urkraft". <s> The Spanish band Saurom also recorded a cover of this song with alternative lyrics, titled "La Disolución de la Comunidad".

title: Microsoft FrontPage
complex: Microsoft FrontPage (full name Microsoft Office FrontPage) is a discontinued WYSIWYG HTML editor and website administration tool from Microsoft for the Microsoft Windows line of operating systems. <s> It was branded as part of the Microsoft Office suite from 1997 to 2003. <s> Microsoft FrontPage has since been replaced by Microsoft Expression Web and SharePoint Designer, which were first released in December 2006 alongside Microsoft Office 2007, but these two products were also discontinued in favor of a web-based version of SharePoint Designer, as those three HTML editors were desktop applications. <s> As a "WYSIWYG" (What You See Is What You Get) editor, FrontPage is designed to hide the details of pages' HTML code from the user, making it possible for novices to create web pages and web sites easily.
simple: Microsoft FrontPage (Full name: Microsoft Office FrontPage) is a program made by Microsoft to help people make webpages and full websites. <s> It was one of Microsoft Office programs until 2003. <s> It was discontinued in 2006, being replaced by Microsoft Expression Web and Microsoft Office SharePoint Designer. <s> FrontPage is a WYSIWYG, "What You See Is What You Get", Web Editor.

title: The Waitresses
complex: The Waitresses were a post-punk band from Akron, Ohio, known for their singles "I Know What Boys Like" and "Christmas Wrapping". <s> They released two albums, "Wasn't Tomorrow Wonderful" and "Bruiseology", and two EPs, "I Could Rule the World If I Could Only Get the Parts" and "Make the Weather". <s> The Waitresses recorded the theme song to the television program "Square Pegs", starring Sarah Jessica Parker, which aired during the 1982–1983 season, and the band appeared as themselves in the pilot episode. <s> The song was issued by Polydor as a single in 1982, and was included (along with "Christmas Wrapping") on the EP "I Could Rule the World If I Could Only Get the Parts" that same year. <s> Donahue left the band in summer 1984 and was briefly replaced by Holly Beth Vincent (formerly of Holly and the Italians). <s> Vincent departed two weeks later and Donahue returned. <s> The band finally split up in late 1984. <s> Donahue died of lung cancer at the age of 40 on December 9, 1996.
simple: The Waitresses were an American experimental new wave music group. <s> They were from Akron, Ohio. <s> Their song "I Know What Boys Like" was released in 1980 but did not chart until 1982. <s> They also represented the theme song for the television series "Square Pegs" in 1982-1983. <s> The group broke up in 1984. <s> Their lead singer died due to lung cancer in 1996.

title: The Late Show with Stephen Colbert
complex: The Late Show with Stephen Colbert is an American late-night talk show hosted by Stephen Colbert, which premiered on September 8, 2015. <s> Produced by Spartina Productions and CBS Television Studios, "The Late Show" "with Stephen Colbert" is the second iteration of CBS's "Late Show" franchise.
simple: The Late Show with Stephen Colbert is an American late-night talk show hosted by Stephen Colbert on CBS. <s> The show premiered on September 8, 2015.

title: Lagnicourt-Marcel
complex: Lagnicourt-Marcel is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Lagnicourt-Marcel is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Dengie
complex: Dengie is a village and civil parish in the Maldon district of Essex, England, with a population of 119 at the 2011 census.
simple: Dengie is a village and civil parish in Maldon District, Essex, England.

title: Perlin noise
complex: Perlin noise is a type of gradient noise developed by Ken Perlin in 1983 as a result of his frustration with the "machine-like" look of computer graphics at the time. <s> He formally described his findings in a SIGGRAPH paper in 1985 called "An image Synthesizer".
simple: Perlin noise was made by Ken Perlin in 1983.

title: Saurophaganax
complex: Saurophaganax ("lord of lizard-eaters") is a genus of allosaurid dinosaur from the Morrison Formation of Late Jurassic (latest Kimmeridgian age, about 151 million years ago) Oklahoma, United States. <s> Some paleontologists consider it to be a species of "Allosaurus" ("A. maximus"). <s> "Saurophaganax" represents a very large Morrison allosaurid characterized by horizontal laminae at the bases of the dorsal neural spines above the transverse processes, and "meat-chopper" chevrons. <s> The maximum size of "S. maximus" has been estimated at anywhere from 10.5 m to 13 m in length, and about 3 MT to 4.5 MT in weight. <s> The identification of "Saurophaganax" is a matter of dispute. <s> It has been described as its own genus, or as a species of "Allosaurus": "Allosaurus maximus". <s> The most recent review of basal tetanurans accepted "Saurophaganax" as a distinct genus. <s> New possible "Saurophaganax" material from New Mexico may clear up the status of the genus. <s> "Saurophaganax" was one of the largest carnivores of Late Jurassic North America.
simple: Saurophaganax ("lizard-eating master") is a genus of allosaurid dinosaur from the Morrison Formation of Upper Jurassic in Oklahoma. <s> It lived about 151 million years ago). <s> Some paleontologists think it is a species of "Allosaurus" ("Allosaurus maximus"). <s> "Saurophaganax" was a very large Morrison allosaurid. <s> The maximum size of "S. maximus" has been estimated at anywhere from 10.5 m to 13 m in length, and around 3 t in weight. <s> It has also been described as a separate genus. <s> The most recent review of basal tetanurans accepted "Saurophaganax" as a distinct genus. <s> New possible "Saurophaganax" material from New Mexico may clear up the status of the genus.

title: Widzew Łódź
complex: RTS Widzew Łódź is a Polish football club based in Łódź. <s> The club was founded in 1910. <s> Its official colours are red and white, hence their nicknames "Czerwona Armia" (Red Army) and "Czerwono-biało-czerwoni" (Red-white-reds). <s> Widzew has won four Polish league championships (in 1981, 1982, 1996 and 1997) and the 1985 Polish Cup.
simple: Widzew Łódź is a Polish football (soccer) club from Łódź, Poland. <s> The club was started in 1910 and currently plays in the Polish First League. <s> Their official colours are red-white-red. <s> They have won the Polish league four times (1981, 1982, 1996 and 1997).

title: Criss Angel Mindfreak
complex: Criss Angel: Mindfreak is an American reality TV show that aired on A&E from 2005 to 2010. <s> It centers on stunts and street magic acts by magician Criss Angel.
simple: Criss Angel Mindfreak is an American television program.

title: Jeet Gayi Toh Piya Morey (TV series)
complex: Jeet Gayi Toh Piya Morey (English: If I win then, O Beloved, you're mine) is an Indian Hindi romantic drama television series, which premiered on 21 August 2017 and is broadcast on Zee TV. <s> The series is produced by Jay Production of Jay Mehta. <s> The series ended on 23 July 2018.
simple: Jeet Gayi Toh Piya Morey is an Indian Hindi romantic drama television series that premiered on 21 August 2017 and airs on Zee TV. <s> The series is produced by Jay Production .

title: Alva, Oklahoma
complex: Alva is a city in and the county seat of Woods County, Oklahoma, United States, along the Salt Fork Arkansas River. <s> The population was 4,945 at the 2010 census.
simple: Alva is a city of Oklahoma in the United States. <s> It is the county seat of Woods County.

title: Defoliant
complex: A defoliant is any herbicidal chemical sprayed or dusted on plants to cause their leaves to fall off. <s> Defoliants are widely used for the selective removal of weeds in managing croplands and lawns.
simple: Defoliants are a type of chemical that destroys plants like trees, bushes and grass .

title: Busch Stadium
complex: Busch Stadium, also referred to informally as "New Busch Stadium" or "Busch Stadium III", is a baseball park located in St. Louis, Missouri, the home of the St. Louis Cardinals, the city's Major League Baseball (MLB) franchise. <s> The stadium has a seating capacity of 44,494, and contains 3,706 club seats and 61 luxury suites.
simple: Busch Stadium is a baseball park in Saint Louis, Missouri. <s> It is the home field of the Major League Baseball team called the St. Louis Cardinals.

title: Balliol College, Oxford
complex: Balliol College is one of the constituent colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> One of Oxford's oldest colleges, it was founded around 1263 by John I de Balliol, a rich landowner from Barnard Castle in County Durham, who provided the foundation and endowment for the college. <s> When de Balliol died in 1269 his widow, Dervorguilla, a woman whose wealth far exceeded that of her husband, continued his work in setting up the college, providing a further endowment, and writing the statutes. <s> She is considered a cofounder of the college. <s> The college's alumni include the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, Boris Johnson MP, as well as three former prime ministers (H. H. Asquith, who once described Balliol men as possessing "the tranquil consciousness of an effortless superiority", Harold Macmillan, and Edward Heath), Harald V of Norway, Empress Masako of Japan, five Nobel laureates, and numerous literary and philosophical figures, including Adam Smith, Gerard Manley Hopkins, and Aldous Huxley. <s> John Wycliffe, who translated the Bible into English, was Master of the college in the 1360s.
simple: Balliol College is one of the colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> Balliol is Oxford's most popular college. <s> It was founded in 1263 by John Balliol, father of King John Balliol of Scotland. <s> The college's alumni include several former prime ministers.

title: Eshtaol Forest
complex: Eshtaol Forest is a forest in Israel, located north of Beit Shemesh and near Ta'oz and Neve Shalom, south of the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem Highway. <s> The Forest of the Martyrs lies to the east. <s> The forest is a popular recreation area, featuring an 8 kilometer hiking trail and numerous scenic views. <s> The forest (like most other forests in Israel) was planted in by the Jewish National Fund, which continues to expand it.
simple: Eshtaol Forest is a forest in Israel, located north of Beit Shemesh and near Ta'oz and Neve Shalom. <s> The Forest of the Martyrs lies to the east. <s> The forest is a popular recreation area and is one of the largest forests in Israel. <s> The forest (like most other forests in Israel) was planted in by the Jewish National Fund, which continues to expand it.

title: Animal coloration
complex: Animal coloration is the general appearance of an animal resulting from the reflection or emission of light from its surfaces. <s> Some animals are brightly colored, while others are hard to see. <s> In some species, such as the peafowl, the male has strong patterns, conspicuous colors and is iridescent, while the female is far less visible. <s> Animal coloration has been a topic of interest and research in biology for centuries. <s> In the classical era, Aristotle recorded that the octopus was able to change its coloration to match its background, and when it was alarmed. <s> According to Charles Darwin's 1859 theory of natural selection, features such as coloration evolved by providing individual animals with a reproductive advantage. <s> For example, individuals with slightly better camouflage than others of the same species would, on average, leave more offspring. <s> Animal coloration may be the result of any combination of pigments, chromatophores, structural coloration and bioluminescence.
simple: Animal colour (or coloration) is produced by light reflecting from an animal's surface. <s> Animal colour has been a topic of interest and research in biology for a long time. <s> According to Charles Darwin's 1859 theory of natural selection, features such as colouration evolved by providing individual animals with a reproductive advantage. <s> For example, individuals with slightly better camouflage than others of the same species would, on average, leave more offspring. <s> The ways animals produce colours include pigments, chromatophores and other structures, and bioluminescence.

title: 5 Tracks
complex: 5 Tracks is the second extended play by Welsh musician John Cale, released in May 2003 and comprising five previously unreleased songs. <s> It was Cale's first release for EMI. <s> The EP was followed by the album "HoboSapiens", which was released in October 2003 and does not contain any songs from this EP. <s> The song "Wilderness Approaching" features in the 2003 Ramin Niami film "Paris". <s> All songs written by John Cale.
simple: 5 Tracks is second EP by multi-instrumentalist John Cale. <s> It was released in May 2003. <s> It was his first album on EMI Records label. <s> Song called "Wilderness Approaching" features in the Ramin Niami movie "Paris" (2003). <s> All songs written by John Cale.

title: Phyllis Vance
complex: Phyllis Vance (née Lapin) is a fictional character on the U.S. comedy television series, "The Office". <s> She is portrayed by Phyllis Smith, and has no specific counterpart in the British version of the series, instead being an amalgamation of several different office workers. <s> Phyllis Lapin is a sales representative at fictitious paper distributor Dunder Mifflin. <s> She is a quiet but friendly type who loves "girl talk" and gossip. <s> Though she has a sweet, motherly exterior, she can sometimes be very vindictive, often to Angela Martin.
simple: Phyllis Margaret Vance (née Lapin) is a fictional character on the U.S. comedy television series, "The Office". <s> She is played by Phyllis Smith. <s> The character is not based from anyone in the British version of the series. <s> Lapin is a sales representative at fictitious paper distributor Dunder Mifflin. <s> She is a quiet but friendly type who loves "girl talk" and gossip.

title: British Rail Class 418
complex: British Rail Class 418 (or 2-SAP) was a class of electrical multiple unit commissioned by British Railways Southern Region in England. <s> The units were formed by declassifying the first class accommodation in selected 2-HAP units. <s> They were employed mainly on semi-fast suburban routes such as the South Western Main Line as far as Weybridge, Waterloo to Reading Line, Staines to Windsor Line and Hounslow Loop Line.
simple: British Rail Class 418 (or 2Sap) was a class of electrical multiple unit commissioned by British Railways Southern Region. <s> The units were formed in the 1970s by simply declassifying the first class accommodation in selected 2Hap units. <s> They were employed on inner suburban routes such as the Hounslow Loop.

title: Wayne Flynt
complex: James Wayne Flynt (born October 4, 1940) is University Professor Emeritus in the Department of History at Auburn University. <s> He has won numerous teaching awards and been a Distinguished University Professor for many years. <s> His research focuses on Southern culture, Alabama politics, Southern religion, education reform, and poverty. <s> He is Editor-in-Chief of the Online "Encyclopedia of Alabama". <s> Flynt received his Bachelor of Arts degree from Howard College (shortly before its reorganization as Samford University) in 1961 before taking his Master of Science (1962) and Ph.D. (1965) from Florida State University. <s> After teaching at Samford for 12 years, he joined the faculty at Auburn University in 1977, where he remained until his retirement in 2005. <s> In 2002, the University of Alabama journalism department named Flynt as the winner of the Clarence Cason Writing Award, given to an author writing about or closely identified with the state of Alabama. <s> He was a longtime friend of Harper Lee, the author of To Kill a Mockingbird and gave the eulogy at her funeral. <s> He was inducted into the Alabama Academy of Honor in 2006.
simple: James Wayne Flynt (born October 4, 1940) is an American educator, editor and historian. <s> He is Professor Emeritus in the Department of History at Auburn University. <s> He has won many teaching awards and been a Distinguished University Professor for many years. <s> His research focuses on Southern culture, Alabama politics, Southern religion, education reform, and poverty. <s> He is Editor-in-Chief of the Online "Encyclopedia of Alabama". <s> He was a longtime friend of Harper Lee, the author of "To Kill a Mockingbird" and gave the eulogy at her funeral.

title: Askham, Cumbria
complex: Askham is a village and civil parish in the Eden District of Cumbria, England. <s> It is in the historic county of Westmorland. <s> According to the 2001 census the parish had a population of 360, decreasing slightly to 356 at the 2011 Census. <s> It is situated in the eastern edge of the Lake District National Park, about 5 mi south of Penrith.
simple: Askham is a village and civil parish in Eden, Cumbria, England. <s> In 2001 there were 360 people living in Askham.

title: Mega Man (video game)
complex: Mega Man, known as Rockman (ロックマン , Rokkuman ) in Japan, is a 1987 action-platform video game developed and published by Capcom for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES). <s> It was directed by Akira Kitamura, with Nobuyuki Matsushima as lead programmer, and is the first game of the "Mega Man" franchise and the original video game series. <s> "Mega Man" was produced by a small team specifically for the home console market, a first for Capcom, who previously focused on arcade titles. <s> The initial Western release of the game, while keeping the basic plot the same, significantly changed some details from the original Japanese manual. <s> In this version, Dr. Light and Dr. Wily (here Light's assistant turned disloyal) co-create the humanoid robot Mega Man alongside the six advanced robots, each of whom were designed for the benefit of Monsteropolis's citizens (no such place existed in the original plot). <s> Dr. Wily grows disloyal of his partner and reprograms these six robots to aid himself in taking control of the world, creating the seven empires of Monsteropolis. <s> Dr. Light sends Mega Man to destroy his fellow creations and stop Dr. Wily.
simple: Mega Man is also known as Rockman (ロックマン, Rokkuman) in Japan. <s> It is a video game developed and published by Capcom for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES). <s> It is the first game in the original "Mega Man" series. <s> Two scientists, Dr. Light and Dr. Wily, create humanoid robots; Wily goes rogue and reprograms most of the robots for world domination. <s> It's up to Mega Man, a robot created by Dr. Light, to stop Dr. Wily and his army of "Robot Masters".

title: Potassium bromate
complex: Potassium bromate (KBrO), is a bromate of potassium and takes the form of white crystals or powder. <s> It is a strong oxidizing agent. <s> Potassium bromate is produced when bromine is passed through a hot solution of potassium hydroxide. <s> This first forms unstable potassium hypobromite, which quickly disproportionates into bromide and bromate: Electrolysis of potassium bromide solutions will also give bromate. <s> Both processes are analogous to those used in the production of chlorates. <s> Potassium bromate is typically used in the United States as a flour improver (E number E924). <s> It acts to strengthen the dough and to allow higher rising.
simple: Potassium bromate is a chemical compound. <s> Its chemical formula is KBrO. <s> It contains potassium and bromate ions. <s> Potassium bromate is a white solid. <s> It is a strong oxidizing agent. <s> It can be made by dissolving bromine in hot potassium hydroxide. <s> Normally when the bread is baked the potassium bromate is broken down. <s> It can also be made by electrolysis of potassium bromide solution. <s> Potassium bromate is used to make wheat flour better.

title: German order of precedence
complex: The German order of precedence is a symbolic hierarchy of the five highest federal offices in Germany used to direct protocol. <s> It has no official status, but has been established in practical use.
simple: The German order of precedence is a hierarchy of the government officials in the Government of Germany. <s> It is not official, but it is used.

title: SR Class 2Wim
complex: 2-WIM was the designation given, by Southern Railway (SR), to a small fleet of electric multiple units, dedicated for use on the West Croydon to Wimbledon Line. <s> None of these units survived long enough in British Rail ownership to be allocated a TOPS class.
simple: 2Wim was the designation given, by Southern Railway (SR), to a small fleet of electric multiple units, dedicated for use on the West Croydon to Wimbledon Line. <s> None of these units survived long enough in British Rail ownership to be allocated a TOPS class.

title: Telephone numbers in the United Kingdom
complex: Additionally, numbers in the range 0808 80x xxxx are reserved for not-for-profit helplines and as such are usually free to call from most mobile telephones. <s> A number of other numbers can also called for free from mobiles, but this varies by network. <s> The UK has two free emergency numbers—the traditional 999, which is still widely used, and the EU standard 112, which can be used in all member states of the European Union. <s> Both 999 and 112 are used to contact all emergency services: Police, Fire Service, Ambulance Service, and Coastguard. <s> (Standard advice for Mountain Rescue or Cave Rescue is to ask the emergency operator for the police, who oversee the communication with these two services.) <s> The National Health Service (NHS) can be reached on 111 for non-emergency calls (from landlines and mobiles only). <s> In other European countries the number 116 117 is used for a similar purpose. <s> Telephone numbers in British Overseas Territories do not come under the UK telephone numbering plan. <s> These calls are treated as international calls.
simple: The caller also pays an Access Charge to their own phone network and this varies from network to network. <s> Emergency services: 999 or 112 <s> National Health Service (non-emergency): 111 <s> Telephone numbers in British Overseas Territories do not come under the UK telephone numbering plan. <s> These calls are treated as international calls.

title: Great Yeldham
complex: Great Yeldham is a village in north Essex, England, about 6 mi from the Suffolk border. <s> Surrounding villages and towns include Little Yeldham, Tilbury Juxta Clare, Toppesfield, Stambourne, Ridgewell, Sible Hedingham, Castle Hedingham, Halstead and Sudbury (Suffolk).
simple: Great Yeldham is a village and civil parish in Braintree district, Essex, England.

title: Louis, Dauphin of France (son of Louis XV)
complex: Louis, Dauphin of France (4 September 1729 – 20 December 1765) was the elder and only son of King Louis XV of France and his wife, Queen Marie Leszczyńska to survive to adulthood. <s> He had a younger brother, Philippe, who died as a toddler. <s> As a son of the king, Louis was a "fils de France". <s> As heir apparent, he became Dauphin of France. <s> However, he died before ascending to the throne. <s> Three of his sons became kings of France: Louis XVI (reign: 1774–1792), Louis XVIII (reign: 1814–1815; 1815–1824) and Charles X (reign: 1824–1830). <s> Louis' governess was Madame de Ventadour who had previously served as his father's governess. <s> When he was seven years old, the Duke of Châtillon was named his governor, the Count of Muy was named under-governor, and Jean-François Boyer, formerly bishop of Mirepoix, was named preceptor. <s> From an early age Louis took a great interest in the military arts. <s> He was bitterly disappointed when his father would not permit him to join the 1744 campaign in the War of the Austrian Succession. <s> When his father became deathly ill with fever at Metz, Louis disobeyed orders and went to his bedside. <s> This rash action, which could have resulted in the deaths of both Louis and his father, resulted in a permanent change in the relations between father and son. <s> Until then, Louis XV had doted on his son, but now the relationship was more distant. <s> He was very close to his three older sisters. <s> In 1744 Louis XV negotiated a marriage between his fifteen-year-old son and the nineteen-year-old Infanta Maria Teresa Rafaela of Spain, daughter of King Philip V and his Italian wife, Elisabeth Farnese, and first cousin of Louis XV. <s> The marriage contract was signed 13 December 1744; the marriage was celebrated by proxy at Madrid 18 December 1744 and in person at Versailles 23 February 1745. <s> Louis and Maria Teresa Rafaela were well-matched and had a real affection for each other. <s> They had one daughter, Princess Marie Thérèse of France (19 July 1746 – 27 April 1748). <s> Three days after the birth of their daughter, Louis's wife, Maria Teresa Rafaela, died on 22 July 1746. <s> Louis was only 16 years old. <s> He grieved intensely at the loss of his wife, but his responsibility to provide for the succession to the French crown required he marry again quickly. <s> On 10 January 1747, Louis was married by proxy at Dresden to Maria Josepha of Saxony, the 15-year-old younger daughter of Frederick Augustus II, Prince-Elector of Saxony and King of Poland, and his wife Archduchess Maria Josepha of Austria. <s> A second marriage ceremony took place in person at Versailles on 9 February 1747. <s> Louis died of tuberculosis at Fontainebleau in 1765 at the age of 36, while his father was still alive, so he never became king of France. <s> His mother, Queen Marie Leszczyńska, and his maternal grandfather, the former king of Poland, Stanisław I Leszczyński, Duke of Lorraine, also survived him. <s> His eldest surviving son, Louis-Auguste, duc de Berry, became the new dauphin, ascending the throne as Louis XVI at the death of Louis XV, in May 1774. <s> Louis was buried in the Cathedral of Saint-Étienne in Sens. His heart was buried at Saint Denis Basilica.
simple: Louis of France (Louis Ferdinand; 4 September 1729 – 20 December 1765) was the only surviving son of King Louis XV of France and his wife, Marie Leszczyńska. <s> He was the Dauphin of France all his life. <s> As the heir apparent to the throne of France, he was given the traditional title of Dauphin of France. <s> He was the father of three kings of France, Louis XVI, Louis XVIII and Charles X. <s> Louis' governess was Madame de Ventadour. <s> From an early age Louis took a great interest in the military arts. <s> He was very close to his three oldest sisters. <s> In 1744 Louis XV negotiated a marriage between his fifteen year old son and the nineteen year old Infanta Maria Teresa Rafaela of Spain, daughter of King Philip V of Spain and Elisabeth Farnese. <s> The marriage contract was signed 13 December 1744 and the marriage was celebrated by proxy at Madrid 18 December 1744 and in person at Versailles 23 February 1745. <s> Louis and Maria Teresa Rafaela were well matched and had a real affection for each other. <s> They had one daughter Princess Marie Thérèse who died before reaching adulthood and killed her mother. <s> On 10 January 1747 Louis was married by proxy at Dresden to Maria Josepha of Saxony, the fifteen year old younger daughter of Frederick Augustus II, Prince-Elector of Saxony and King of Poland and his wife, Archduchess Maria Josepha of Austria. <s> A second marriage ceremony took place in person at Versailles on 9 February 1747. <s> Louis died of consumption at Fontainebleau in 1765 at the age of thirty-six. <s> Louis was buried in the Cathedral of Saint-Étienne in Sens his heart being buried at the Royal Basilica of Saint Denis.

title: Tábor
complex: Tábor (] ; ) is a town in the South Bohemian Region of the Czech Republic, 100 km south of the capital Prague. <s> It lies on the river Lužnice.
simple: Tábor is a city in the Czech Republic. <s> It is in the South Bohemian Region.

title: Mariano Rajoy
complex: Mariano Rajoy Brey (] ; born 27 March 1955) is a Spanish politician who served as Prime Minister of Spain from 2011 to 2018, when a vote of no confidence ousted his government. <s> On 5 June 2018, he announced his resignation as People's Party leader. <s> On 5 June 2018, Rajoy announced his resignation as President of the People's Party. <s> On 15 June, he resigned his seat as Deputy after thirty years.
simple: Mariano Rajoy Brey (born 27 March 1955) is the former Prime Minister of Spain. <s> On 5 June 2018, Rajoy resigned as President of the People's Party.

title: Jacques Santer
complex: Jacques Santer (born 18 May 1937) is a Luxembourg politician who served as the 9th President of the European Commission from 1995 to 1999. <s> He served as Finance Minister of Luxembourg from 1979 until 1989, and the 20th Prime Minister of Luxembourg from 1984 to 1995, as a member of the Christian Social People's Party, which has been the leading party in the Luxembourg government since 1979. <s> As Prime Minister of Luxembourg he also led the negotiations on the Single European Act, which effectively set aside the 20-year-old Luxembourg Compromise.
simple: Jacques Santer (born 18 May 1937 in Wasserbillig) is a Luxembourgian politician. <s> He was the President of the European Commission from 1995 to 1999. <s> He was finance minister of Luxembourg from 1979 until 1989. <s> He was the 22nd Prime Minister of Luxembourg serving from 1984 to 1995. <s> He was a member of the Christian Social People's Party, which has been the leading party in the Luxembourg government since 1979. <s> As Prime Minister of Luxembourg he also led the negotiations on the Single European Act, which effectively set aside the 20-year-old Luxembourg Compromise.

title: Communist Party of Pakistan
complex: The Communist Party of Pakistan (abbreviated CPP; ) is a communist party in Pakistan. <s> The CPP was founded in Calcutta, Union of India on March 6, 1948. <s> A decision was taken at the Second All-India Conference of the Communist Party of India, which was held in Calcutta at that time, that a separate communist party ought to be created in the new state of Pakistan. <s> It was thought that Pakistan, being a relatively small country (in comparison to India) and suffering from instability, was ripe for revolution. <s> The delegates from Pakistan separated themselves and held a separate session where they constituted the CPP. <s> Sajjad Zaheer (founder of the All-India Progressive Writers Association), from West Pakistan, was elected General-Secretary.
simple: The Communist Party of Pakistan is a communist party in Pakistan. <s> The CPP was founded in Calcutta, Union of India on March 6, 1948. <s> A decision was taken at the Second All India Conference of the Communist Party of India, which was held in Calcutta at that time, that a separate communist party ought to be created in the new State of Pakistan. <s> It was thought that Pakistan, being a relatively small country (in comparison to India) and suffering from instability, was ripe for revolution. <s> The delegates from Pakistan separated themselves and held a separate session were they constituted the CPP.

title: Edwin Meese
complex: Edwin Meese III (born December 2, 1931) is an American attorney, law professor, author and member of the Republican Party who served in official capacities within the Ronald Reagan Gubernatorial Administration (1967–1974), the Reagan Presidential Transition Team (1980) and the Reagan White House (1981–1985), eventually rising to hold the position of the 75th Attorney General of the United States (1985–1988). <s> Meese was born in Oakland, California, the eldest of four sons born to Leone (née Feldman) and Edwin Meese, Jr. <s> He was raised in a practicing Lutheran family, of German descent.
simple: Edwin "Ed" Meese, III (born December 2, 1931) is an American attorney, law professor, and author. <s> He served under Ronald Reagan's administration back when Reagan was Governor (1967–1974), the Reagan Presidential Transition Team (1980), and under Reagan's presidential administration (1981–1985). <s> Meese was the 75th Attorney General of the United States (1985–1988), a position from which he resigned while serving in office under investigation from a special prosecutor. <s> Meese was born on December 2, 1931 in Oakland, California.

title: Choapa Province
complex: Choapa Province is one of the provinces making up the Coquimbo Region of Chile. <s> It has an area of 10,079.8 km2 and a population of 81,681. <s> The capital of the province is the town of Illapel. <s> The current governor is Gisella Mateluna Gambo. <s> According to the 2002 census by the National Statistics Institute ("INE"), the province spans an area of 10131.6 sqkm and had a population of 81,681 inhabitants (41,578 men and 40,103 women), giving it a population density of 8.1 PD/sqkm . <s> Between the 1992 and 2002 censuses, the population grew by 4.6% (3,603 persons).
simple: Choapa Province is one of three provinces of the Chilean region of Coquimbo Region (IV). <s> Its capital is the city of Illapel <s> s of 2002 (last national census), there were 81,681 people living in the province, giving it a population density of 8.062004027004619 /km2 inhabitants/km2.

title: Journans
complex: Journans is a commune in the Ain department in eastern France.
simple: Journans is a commune.

title: Alanganallur
complex: Alanganallur is a panchayat town in Madurai district in the state of Tamil Nadu, India. <s> It is headquarters for the Alanganallur taluka and revenue block. <s> Agriculture is carried out in about large area around this place. <s> Paddy, Sugar cane, Coconut and Plantain are the major crops. <s> There is a sugar factory located within 1 km from Alanganallur. <s> The Jallikattu (A way to find best Bull for Breed) ceremony is conducted here during the Pongal (harvest festival) season, to choose the best breed, which occurs during the middle of January (usually 14 January) and on the first day of Tamil month Thai. <s> Tourists all over from India, even from abroad visit here during this festival to watch Jallikattu. <s> Madurai is accessible within 16 km. <s> Alagar kovil is also close by, within 18 km. <s> The Thadakai Amman falls(Kutladampatti) are located near T. Mettupatti village. <s> Kodaikanal, Vaigai dam, Kumbakarai falls
simple: Alanganallur is a panchayat town in the district of Madurai in the state of Tamil Nadu, India. <s> This town is the headquarters of Alanganallur taluk and Alanganallur revenue block. <s> Agriculture is the main occupation in the town. <s> Alanganallur town is famous for the Jallikattu ceremony conducted throughout the four days of Pongal festival. <s> The district headquarters Madurai city is 16 km away from this town. <s> Alagar kovil is also near by, within 18 km. <s> Nearby places which attracts tourist are : The Thadakai Amman falls, Kodaikanal, Vaigai dam, Kumbakarai falls and Kutladampatti.

title: AK-47
complex: In 1974, the Soviets began replacing their AK-47 and AKM rifles with a newer design, the AK-74, which uses 5.45×39mm ammunition. <s> This new rifle and cartridge had only started to be manufactured in Eastern European nations when the Soviet Union collapsed, drastically slowing production of the AK-74 and other weapons of the former Soviet bloc. <s> The AK-47 was designed to be a simple, reliable fully automatic rifle that could be manufactured quickly and cheaply, using mass production methods that were state of the art in the Soviet Union during the late 1940s. <s> The AK-47 uses a long stroke gas system that is generally associated with great reliability in adverse conditions. <s> The large gas piston, generous clearances between moving parts, and tapered cartridge case design allow the gun to endure large amounts of foreign matter and fouling without failing to cycle. <s> The AK-47 and its variants have been and are made in dozens of countries, with "quality ranging from finely engineered weapons to pieces of questionable workmanship." <s> As a result, the AK-47 has a service/system life of approximately 6,000, to 10,000, to 15,000 rounds. <s> The AK-47 was designed to be a cheap, simple, easy to manufacture assault rifle, perfectly matching Soviet military doctrine that treats equipment and weapons as disposable items. <s> As units are often deployed without adequate logistical support and dependent on "battlefield cannibalization" for resupply, it is actually more cost-effective to replace rather than repair weapons. <s> In the pro-communist states, the AK-47 became a symbol of the Third World revolution. <s> They were utilized in the Cambodian Civil War and the Cambodian–Vietnamese War. <s> During the 1980s, the Soviet Union became the principal arms dealer to countries embargoed by Western nations, including Middle Eastern nations such as Iran, Libya, and Syria, which welcomed Soviet Union backing against Israel. <s> After the fall of the Soviet Union, AK-47s were sold both openly and on the black market to any group with cash, including drug cartels and dictatorial states, and more recently they have been seen in the hands of Islamic groups such as Al-Qaeda, ISIL, and the Taliban in Afghanistan and Iraq, and FARC, Ejército de Liberación Nacional guerrillas in Colombia. <s> The proliferation of this weapon is reflected by more than just numbers. <s> The AK-47 is included in the flag of Mozambique and its emblem, an acknowledgment that the country gained its independence in large part through the effective use of their AK-47s. <s> It is also found in the coats of arms of East Timor and the revolution era Burkina Faso, as well as in the flags of Hezbollah, Syrian Resistance, FARC-EP, the New People's Army, TKP/TIKKO and the International Revolutionary People's Guerrilla Forces.
simple: It was later replaced by the AK-74. <s> The AK-47 uses gas-operated reloading. <s> The AK-47 and its successors continue to be used by many of the world's armies. <s> It is a cheap, reliable, and easy-to-use weapon. <s> In the pro-communist states, the AK-47 became a symbol of the Third World revolution. <s> They were used in the Cambodian Civil War and the Cambodian–Vietnamese War. <s> During the 1980s, the Soviet Union became the principal arms dealer to countries embargoed by Western nations. <s> This included Middle Eastern nations such as Iran, Libya, and Syria, which welcomed Soviet Union backing against Israel. <s> After the end of the Soviet Union (1989/90), AK-47s were sold openly and on the black market to any group with cash, including drug cartels and dictatorial states. <s> More recently they have been seen in the hands of Islamic groups such as Al-Qaeda, ISIL, and the Taliban in Afghanistan and Iraq, and FARC, Ejército de Liberación Nacional guerrillas in Colombia. <s> The proliferation of this weapon is shown by more than just numbers. <s> The AK-47 is included in the flag of Mozambique, an acknowledgment that the country gained its independence in large part through the effective use of their AK-47s. <s> It is also found in the coats of arms of East Timor and the revolution era Burkina Faso, as well as in the flags of Hezbollah, FARC-EP, the New People's Army in the Phillipines, TKP/TIKKO and other "Revolutionary Peoples" groups.

title: Ray Mathews
complex: Raymond Dyral Mathews (February 26, 1929 – December 20, 2015) was an American football halfback and end in the National Football League (NFL) for the Pittsburgh Steelers and the Dallas Cowboys. <s> He played college football for Clemson University.
simple: Raymond Dyral Mathews (February 26, 1929 – December 20, 2015) was an American football running back and wide receiver in the National Football League for the Pittsburgh Steelers (1951-59) and the Dallas Cowboys (1960). <s> He played college football for Clemson University.

title: Kelly Ripa
complex: Kelly Maria Ripa ( ; born October 2, 1970) is an American actress, dancer, talk show host, and television producer. <s> Ripa portrayed Hayley Vaughan on the ABC daytime soap opera, "All My Children", between 1990 and 2002. <s> She is the co-host of the syndicated morning talk show, "Live! <s> with Kelly and Ryan", in various formats since 2001. <s> She also played Faith Fairfield on the ABC sitcom, "Hope & Faith", from 2003 to 2006. <s> Ripa and her husband, Mark Consuelos, own a New York-based production company, Milojo. <s> In 2014, "The Hollywood Reporter" named her one of the Most Powerful People in Media. <s> Kelly Maria Ripa was born and raised in Berlin, New Jersey, the daughter of Esther, a homemaker, and Joseph Ripa, a labor union president and bus driver. <s> She has a sister, Linda, who is a children's book author. <s> She is three-quarters Italian and one-quarter Irish ancestry. <s> Ripa was raised Roman Catholic. <s> Her father has been the Democratic County Clerk for Camden County, New Jersey, since June 2009. <s> She is the first in her family to enter the acting profession. <s> She has studied ballet since age three, plays the piano, and in her words is "no Barbra Streisand" but can carry a tune. <s> Ripa graduated from Eastern Regional High School in Voorhees Township, New Jersey. <s> During her high school years she was a cheerleader and was encouraged by her drama teacher to pursue acting. <s> "I owe so much of my career to Jim Boeckle," she said. <s> "He thought I was a natural performer and so he gave me the lead in the next show." <s> She starred in local theatre productions and was discovered while performing in "The Ugly Duckling" during her senior year. <s> She attended Camden County College studying psychology, but dropped out and moved to New York City to pursue an acting career. <s> Ripa replaced Philbin as the head of the show and returned the following Monday, November 21, 2011, to continue the show, which was re-titled "Live!
simple: Kelly Maria Ripa (born October 2, 1970) is an American actress, talk show host, and television producer. <s> Ripa, who played Hayley Vaughan on the television soap opera "All My Children" from 1990–2002, is best known as co-host of the popular syndicated morning talk show "Live! <s> with Kelly and Ryan". <s> She is also known for her role as Faith Fairfield on "Hope & Faith". <s> Additionally, Ripa and her husband Mark Consuelos own a New York based production company, Milojo. <s> In 2012, "The Hollywood Reporter" named her one of the Most Powerful People in Media. <s> Ripa was born in Stratford, New Jersey. <s> She is the daughter of Esther, a homemaker, and Joseph Ripa, a labor-union president and bus driver. <s> She has a younger sister, Linda, who is a children's book author. <s> She is of Italian and Irish ancestry. <s> Her father has been the Democratic County Clerk for Camden County, New Jersey since June 2009. <s> She is the first in her family to enter the acting profession. <s> She has studied ballet since age three, plays the piano, and, in her words, is "no Barbra Streisand," but can carry a tune. <s> Ripa graduated from Eastern High School in Voorhees Township, New Jersey, where she became a cheerleader and was later encouraged by her drama teacher to pursue acting. <s> "I owe so much of my career to Jim Beckley," she said. <s> "He thought I was a natural performer and so he gave me the lead in the next show." <s> She starred in local theatre productions and was discovered while performing in the comedy play "The Ugly Duckling" (c. 1941), by A.A. Milne, during her senior year. <s> She attended Camden County College studying psychology, but dropped out and moved to New York City to be an actress.

title: Orbiting Carbon Observatory
complex: The Orbiting Carbon Observatory (OCO) is a NASA satellite mission intended to provide global space-based observations of atmospheric carbon dioxide . <s> The original spacecraft was lost in a launch failure on 24 February 2009, when the payload fairing of the Taurus rocket which was carrying it failed to separate during ascent. <s> The added mass of the fairing prevented the satellite from reaching orbit. <s> It subsequently re-entered the atmosphere and crashed into the Indian Ocean near Antarctica. <s> The replacement satellite, Orbiting Carbon Observatory 2, was launched 2 July 2014 aboard a Delta II rocket.
simple: The Orbiting Carbon Observatory (OCO) was a NASA satellite mission that was supposed to provide world-wide observations of atmospheric carbon dioxide from space. <s> It was lost in a launch failure on February 24, 2009, when the box of the Taurus rocket which was carrying it failed to come off during launch. <s> The added weight of the box it was in prevented the satellite from reaching its intended speed and height. <s> After that it fell back into the atmosphere and crashed into the Indian Ocean near Antarctica.

title: Eugène Gigout
complex: Eugène Gigout (] ; 23 March 1844 – 9 December 1925) was a French organist and a composer, mostly of music for his own instrument. <s> Gigout was born in Nancy, and died in Paris. <s> A pupil of Camille Saint-Saëns, he served as the organist of the French capital's Saint-Augustin Church for 62 years. <s> He became widely known as a teacher and his output as a composer was considerable. <s> Renowned as an expert improviser, he also founded his own music school. <s> His nephew by marriage was Léon Boëllmann, another distinguished French composer and organist. <s> The "10 pièces pour orgue" (composed 1890) include the "Toccata in B minor", Gigout's best-known creation, which turns up as a frequent encore at organ recitals. <s> Also fairly often played, and to be found in the same collection, is a "Scherzo in E major". <s> Other notable pieces by Gigout are "Grand chœur dialogué", which dates from 1881, and "Marche religieuse". <s> Gigout's works are now available on several commercial recordings.
simple: Eugène Gigout (23 March 1844 – 9 December 1925) was a French organist and composer of European late-romantic music for organ. <s> Gigout was born in Nancy, and died in Paris. <s> A student of Camille Saint-Saëns, he served as the organist of Saint-Augustin Church in Paris for 62 years. <s> He became known as a teacher. <s> Also, his output as a composer was large and of high quality. <s> Renowned as an expert improviser, he also founded his own music school. <s> His nephew-by-marriage, Leon Boëllmann, became another fine organist and composer for the organ (but died at the very young age of 35). <s> The "10 pièces pour orgue", composed in 1890, are Gigout's most famous compositions. <s> They are the "Toccata in B minor", his best-known composition, which turns up as a common encore at organ concerts. <s> Also fairly often performed, and to be found in the same collection, is a "Scherzo in E major". <s> Other compositions by Gigout sometimes played nowadays are "Grand Choeur Dialogué" and "Marche Religieuse". <s> Gigout's works are now available on many commercial recordings.

title: Chain letter
complex: A chain letter is a message that attempts to convince the recipient to make a number of copies and pass them on to a certain number of recipients. <s> The "chain" is an exponentially growing pyramid (a tree graph) that cannot be sustained indefinitely. <s> Common methods used in chain letters include emotionally manipulative stories, get-rich-quick pyramid schemes, and the exploitation of superstition to threaten the recipient. <s> Originally, chain letters were letters sent by mail; today, chain letters are often sent electronically via email, social network sites, and text messages.
simple: A chain letter is a message that tries to cause the person who gets it to make copies of the letter and then pass them on to as many people as possible. <s> Common ways used in chain letters include stories that make the recipient feel sorry for the person, get-rich-quick pyramid schemes, and the use of superstition to threaten the recipient with bad luck, physical violence or death if he or she "breaks the chain" and does not follow the instructions given in the letter.

title: Ställdalen
complex: Ställdalen is a locality situated in Ljusnarsberg Municipality, Örebro County, Sweden with 539 inhabitants in 2010. <s> In January 1956 there was a rail accident there.
simple: Ställdalen is a locality in Ljusnarsberg Municipality in Örebro County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 539 people lived there.

title: Spontaneous process
complex: As an example, the conversion of a diamond into graphite is a spontaneous process at room temperature and pressure. <s> Despite being spontaneous, this process does not occur since the energy to break the strong carbon-carbon bonds is larger than the release in free energy.
simple: An example of a spontaneous process is the conversion of diamond into graphite, because graphite has a more thermodynamically stable structure.

title: Wang Xiaobo
complex: Wang Xiaobo (May 13, 1952 – April 11, 1997) was a renowned contemporary Chinese novelist and essayist from Beijing. <s> He was a sent-down youth in Yunnan during Cultural Revolution. <s> From 1978 to 1982, he studied at Renmin University of China. <s> He went to the United States to continue his education in 1984 and received a master's degree from the University of Pittsburgh in 1988.
simple: Wang Xiaobo (; pinyin: Wáng Xiǎobō; May 13, 1952–April 11, 1997) is a famous writer in mainland China. <s> In 1978, he started studying at the Renmin University of China.

title: Humidex
complex: The humidex (short for humidity index) is an index number used by Canadian meteorologists to describe how hot the weather feels to the average person, by combining the effect of heat and humidity. <s> The term humidex was first coined in 1965. <s> The humidex is a nominally dimensionless quantity (though generally recognized by the public as equivalent to the degree Celsius) based on the dew point. <s> The current formula for determining the humidex was developed by J. M. Masterton and F. A. Richardson of Canada's Atmospheric Environment Service in 1979. <s> Humidex differs from the heat index used in the United States in being derived from the dew point rather than the relative humidity, though both dew point and relative humidity (when used in conjunction with air temperature) are both directly related to atmospheric moisture. <s> For a long time, the record humidex in Canada was set by Windsor, Ontario, which hit 52.1 on 20 June 1953, as reported by Environment Canada. <s> This value was beaten on 25 July 2007 when Carman, Manitoba, hit 53. <s> When the temperature is 30 °C and the dew point is 15 °C , the humidex is 34. <s> If the temperature remains 30 °C and the dew point rises to 25 °C , the humidex rises to 42. <s> The humidex is higher than the U.S. heat index at equal temperature and relative humidity.
simple: The humidex ("Hyu-mah-deks") is a temperature index used by Canadian meteorologists to describe how hot the weather feels to a person, by adding the effect of heat and humidity. <s> The current formula for getting the humidex (see below: Humidex formula) was developed by J.M. Masterton and F.A. Richardson of Canada's Atmospheric Environment Service in 1979. <s> The humidex differs from the heat index used in the United States, in being derived from the dew point rather than the relative humidity. <s> That number broke the previous record of 52.1 set during 1953 in Windsor, Ontario (The residents of Windsor would not have known it at the time, since the humidex had yet to be invented). <s> The record highest humidex in Canada occurred on July 25, 2007, when Carman, Manitoba hit 53.0. <s> When the temperature is 30 °C (86 °F) and the dew point is 15 °C (59 °F), the humidex is 34. <s> For example, if the temperature is 30 °C and the calculated humidex is 40, then that means the humid heat feels like a dry temperature of 40 °C. <s> If the temperature remains 30 °C and the dew point rises to 25 °C (77 °F), the humidex rises to 42. <s> The humidex tends to be higher than the U.S. heat index at equal temperature and relative humidity.

title: Volcanology of Iceland
complex: The volcanoes of Iceland include a high concentration of active ones due to Iceland's location on the mid-Atlantic Ridge, a divergent tectonic plate boundary, and its location over a hot spot. <s> The island has 30 active volcanic systems, of which 13 have erupted since the settlement of Iceland in AD 874. <s> The eruption under Eyjafjallajökull ("glacier of Eyjafjöll") in 2010 was notable because the volcanic ash plume disrupted air travel in northern Europe for several weeks; however this volcano is minor in Icelandic terms. <s> In the past, eruptions of Eyjafjallajökull have been followed by eruption of the larger volcano Katla, but after the 2010 eruption no signs of an imminent eruption of Katla were seen.
simple: This is due to its location on the mid-Atlantic Ridge which is a tectonic plate boundary. <s> Iceland has 30 active volcanic systems. <s> Of these, 13 have erupted since the settlement of Iceland in 874 AD. <s> The eruption under Eyjafjallajökull ("glacier of Eyjafjöll") in 2010 was notable because the volcanic ash plume disrupted air travel in northern Europe for several weeks.

title: Keith Allen (ice hockey)
complex: Courtney Keith "Bingo" Allen (August 21, 1923 – February 4, 2014) was a Canadian professional ice hockey defenceman and National Hockey League (NHL) head coach and general manager. <s> He was born in Saskatoon, Saskatchewan. <s> He was the executive vice-president of the Philadelphia Flyers, a position he held from 1980 for the rest of his life. <s> Allen was elected to the Hockey Hall of Fame as a Builder in 1992. <s> He was the executive vice-president of the Flyers. <s> Due to developing dementia in his later years, Allen lived in the care of an assisted living community, along with wife Joyce, in Newtown Square, Pennsylvania. <s> He died on Tuesday, February 4, 2014. <s> He was 90 years old.
simple: Courtney Keith Allen (August 21, 1923 – February 4, 2014) was a Canadian former professional ice hockey defenceman and former National Hockey League (NHL) head coach and general manager. <s> He was born in Saskatoon, Saskatchewan. <s> He was the executive vice president of the Philadelphia Flyers. <s> He had suffered from dementia in his later years. <s> Allen died at an assisted living facility on February 4, 2014. <s> He was 90 years old.

title: Greyfriars Bobby
complex: Greyfriars Bobby (May 4, 1855 – January 14, 1872) was a Skye Terrier who became known in 19th-century Edinburgh for spending 14 years guarding the grave of his owner until he died himself on 14 January 1872. <s> The story continues to be well known in Scotland, through several books and films. <s> A prominent commemorative statue and nearby graves are a tourist attraction. <s> The best-known version of the story is that Bobby belonged to John Gray, who worked for the Edinburgh City Police as a nightwatchman. <s> When John Gray died he was buried in Greyfriars Kirkyard, the kirkyard surrounding Greyfriars Kirk in the Old Town of Edinburgh. <s> Bobby then became known locally, spending the rest of his life sitting on his master's grave. <s> Bobby is said to have sat by the grave for 14 years. <s> He died in 1872 and was buried just inside the gate of Greyfriars Kirkyard, not far from John Gray's grave. <s> Several books and films have since been based on Bobby's life, including the novel "" (1912) by Eleanor Atkinson and the films "Greyfriars Bobby" (1961) and "The Adventures of Greyfriars Bobby" (2006). <s> The Greyfriars Bobby Fountain in Edinburgh includes a life-size statue of Greyfriars Bobby created by William Brodie in 1872. <s> It was paid for by a local aristocrat, Baroness Burdett-Coutts, and unveiled on 15 November 1873.
simple: Greyfriars Bobby (4 May 1855 - 14 January 1872) was a Skye terrier. <s> The little dog came to be called Greyfriars Bobby. <s> He belonged to a policeman in Edinburgh named John Gray. <s> When Mr. Gray died in 1858, he was buried in Greyfriars Kirkyard. <s> He stayed at the grave for the rest of his life. <s> Bobby died in 1872. <s> He was buried just inside the gates of the kirkyard. <s> Eleanor Atkinson wrote a book about Bobby in 1912. <s> A movie based on the book was made in 1961. <s> The bronze statue of Bobby on top of the fountain was made by William Brodie.

title: Grâce-Hollogne
complex: Grâce-Hollogne is a municipality of Belgium. <s> It lies in the country's Walloon Region and Province of Liege.
simple: Grâce-Hollogne is a municipality in the Belgian province of Liège.

title: Immanuel Church, Norrköping
complex: The Immanuel Church is a church building in Norrköping, Sweden. <s> Belonging to the Uniting Church in Sweden, it earlier belonged to the Mission Covenant Church of Sweden. <s> It was opened on 28 December 1884.
simple: The Immanuel Church is a church building in Norrköping, Sweden. <s> It belongs to the Uniting Church in Sweden. <s> It earlier belonged to the Mission Covenant Church of Sweden. <s> It was opened on 28 December 1884.

title: Igor Luchenok
complex: Igor Mikhailovich Luchenok (Belarusian: Iгар Міхайлавіч Лучанок, Ihar Mikhaylavich Luchanok, Russian: Игорь Михайлович Лученок; 6 August 1938 in Maryina Horka — 12 November 2018 in Minsk) was a Belarusian composer, People's Artist of Belarus (and People's Artist of the USSR), and chairman of the Belarusian Union of Composers. <s> Luchenok worked in various genres — vocal-symphonic, chamber-instrumental, chamber-vocal, but most fruitfully — in song. <s> From his works formed the repertoire of Pesniary, Syabry, Verasy, Joseph Kobzon, Sofia Rotaru, Valentina Tolkunova, Maria Pakhomenko, Lev Leshchenko, Victor Vuyachich, Eduard Khil and many others.
simple: Igor Mikhailovich Luchenok (Belarusian: Iгар Міхайлавіч Лучанок, Ihar Mikhaylavich Luchanok, Russian: Игорь Михайлович Лученок; 6 August 1938 — 12 November 2018) was a Belarusian composer. <s> He was chairman of the Belarusian Union of Composers. <s> Luchenok died on 12 November 2018 from a stroke in Minsk at the age of 80. <s> Luchenok worked in many genres ranging from vocal-symphonic, chamber-instrumental, and chamber-voca. <s> From his works formed the repertoire of Pesniary, Syabry, Verasy, Joseph Kobzon, Sofia Rotaru, Valentina Tolkunova, Maria Pakhomenko, Lev Leshchenko, Victor Vuyachich, Eduard Khil and many others.

title: Phi
complex: Phi ( ; uppercase Φ, lowercase φ or φ; "pheî" ] ; Modern Greek "fi" ] ) is the 21st letter of the Greek alphabet. <s> It may be that phi originated as the letter qoppa and initially represented the sound /kwh/ before shifting to Classical Greek ] . <s> In traditional Greek numerals, phi has a value of 500 or 500,000 . <s> The Cyrillic letter Ef (Ф, ф) descends from phi.
simple: Phi (uppercase/lowercase Φ φ), is the 21st letter of the Greek alphabet, used to represent the "ph" sound in Ancient Greek. <s> In the system of Greek numerals, it has a value of 500. <s> The Cyrillic letter Ф came from Phi.

title: Keita Goto (footballer)
complex: Keita Goto (後藤 圭太, born 8 September 1986) is a Japanese football player. <s> He plays for Fagiano Okayama.
simple: Keita Goto (born 8 September 1986) is a Japanese football player. <s> He plays for Fagiano Okayama.

title: Lill-Babs
complex: Barbro Margareta Svensson (9 March 1938 – 3 April 2018), better known as Lill-Babs, was a Swedish singer, actress and television presenter. <s> From the early 1950s until her death in 2018, she was one of Sweden's best known and popular singers. <s> She represented Sweden in the 1961 Eurovision Song Contest in Cannes with the song "April, april". <s> She was also well-known for the song "Är du kär i mej ännu Klas-Göran?" <s> ("Are You Still In Love With Me, Klas-Göran?"). <s> Lill-Babs died on 3 April 2018 after suffering from cancer and heart failure.
simple: Barbro Margareta Svensson, known as Lill-Babs (9 March 1938 – 3 April 2018), was a Swedish singer, actress and television presenter. <s> She represented Sweden in the Eurovision Song Contest in 1961 in Cannes with the song "April, april". <s> She was also well-known for the song "Är du kär i mej ännu Klas-Göran?". <s> Lill-Babs died of heart failure complicated by cancer in Stockholm on 3 April 2018 at the age of 80.

title: Pöcking
complex: Pöcking is a municipality in the district of Starnberg in Bavaria in Germany. <s> Duchess Elisabeth in Bavaria, consort of Emperor Franz Josef I of Austria-Hungary, grew up here in the Possenhofen Castle as daughter of Duke Max in Bavaria and Princess Ludovika of Bavaria.
simple: Pöcking is a city in Germany. <s> It is in the district of Starnberg in Bavaria.

title: Prajñā (Buddhism)
complex: Prajñā (Sanskrit) or paññā (Pāli) "wisdom" is insight in the true nature of reality, namely primarily anicca (impermanence), dukkha (dissatisfaction or suffering), and anattā (non-self). <s> In addition, Abhidharma and later Mahāyāna text may include suññatā (Skt; Eng: emptiness).
simple: Prajna is a Buddhist word meaning wisdom.

title: Chicago Public Schools
complex: Chicago Public Schools (CPS), officially classified as City of Chicago School District #299 for funding and districting reasons, in Chicago, Illinois, is the third largest school district in the United States. <s> For the 2014–2015 school year, CPS reported overseeing 660 schools, including 484 elementary schools and 176 high schools; of which 517 were district-run, 130 were charter schools, 11 were contract schools and 2 were SAFE schools. <s> The district serves over 396,000 students.
simple: Chicago Public Schools (CPS) is a system of public schools in the city of Chicago. <s> It is the third largest school district in the United States. <s> CPS reported having 681 schools including 472 elementary schools, 106 high schools, 96 charter schools, and 7 contract schools.

title: Acute toxicity
complex: Acute toxicity describes the adverse effects of a substance that result either from a single exposure or from multiple exposures in a short period of time (usually less than 24 hours). <s> To be described as "acute" toxicity, the adverse effects should occur within 14 days of the administration of the substance. <s> Acute toxicity is distinguished from chronic toxicity, which describes the adverse health effects from repeated exposures, often at lower levels, to a substance over a longer time period (months or years). <s> It is widely considered unethical to use humans as test subjects for acute (or chronic) toxicity research. <s> However, some information can be gained from investigating accidental human exposures (e.g., factory accidents). <s> Otherwise, most acute toxicity data comes from animal testing or, more recently, "in vitro" testing methods and inference from data on similar substances.
simple: Acute toxicity describes the bad effects of a substance that come either from a single exposure, or from many exposures in a short amount of time (usually less than 24 hours). <s> To be known as "acute" toxicity, the bad effects should happen within 14 days of the substance thouching something. <s> Acute toxicity is different from chronic toxicity. <s> Chronic toxicity talks about the bad health effects from many exposures, often at lower levels, to a substance over a longer amount of time (months or years). <s> It is widely thought to be wrong to use humans as tests for acute (or chronic) toxicity research. <s> However, some information can be picked up from investigating cases when humans accidentally make contact with the substance (e.g., factory accidents). <s> Otherwise, most acute toxicity data comes from animal testing or, more recently, "in vitro" testing methods and inference from data on similar substances.

title: Housekeeping
complex: Housecleaning is done to make the home look and smell better and to make it safer and easier to live in. <s> Without housecleaning, lime scale can build up on taps, mold grows in wet areas, smudges appear on glass surfaces, dust forms on surfaces, bacterial action makes the garbage disposal and toilet smell and cobwebs accumulate.
simple: Housecleaning is getting rid of mess, trash, dirt, and unclean actions so a household is better-looking.

title: Channel 5 (Singapore)
complex: Channel 5 is a 24-hour Singapore English free-to-air nationwide terrestrial television channel. <s> Its programming mainly consists of English language dramas, movies, sports, reality show, variety show, news, current affairs and game shows. <s> Local editions of imported programmes such as "Singapore Idol", "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?" <s> and "Deal or No Deal" have also been aired on the channel.
simple: MediaCorp Channel 5 or Channel 5 (Chinese: 五频道, Before 1 January 2005: 第五波道) is a 24-hour free-to-air English television channel based in Singapore. <s> Programmes on Channel 5 normally include English language drama (both foreign imports and locally-made), movies, sports, reality show, variety show, news, current affairs and game show programmes. <s> Local editions of overseas programmes like Singapore Idol, Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?, <s> , and Deal or No Deal have also been produced.

title: Belchior (singer)
complex: Belchior (] , born Antonio Carlos Belchior, October 26, 1946 – April 30, 2017) was a Brazilian singer and composer. <s> He was one of the first MPB singers from the Brazilian northeast to reach mainstream success, in the early 1970s. <s> He died on April 30, 2017, at the age of 70.
simple: Belchior (], born Antônio Carlos Gomes Belchior, October 26, 1946 – April 30, 2017), was a Brazilian singer and composer. <s> He was one of the first MPB singers from the Brazilian northeast to reach mainstream success, in the early 1970s. <s> Belchior died on April 30, 2017 at a hospital in Santa Cruz do Sul, Brazil from multiple organ failure, aged 70.

title: Fontenai-sur-Orne
complex: Fontenai-sur-Orne is a former commune in the Orne department in north-western France. <s> On 1 January 2018, it was merged into the commune of Écouché-les-Vallées.
simple: Fontenai-sur-Orne is a commune in the Orne department of Lower Normandy, France.

title: Snail kite
complex: The snail kite ("Rostrhamus sociabilis") is a bird of prey within the family Accipitridae, which also includes the eagles, hawks, and Old World vultures. <s> Its relative, the slender-billed kite, is now again placed in "Helicolestes", making the genus Rostrhamus monotypic. <s> Usually, it is placed in the milvine kites, but the validity of that group is under investigation. <s> Snail kites are 36 to long with a 99 - wingspan. <s> They weigh from 300 to . <s> There is very limited sexual dimorphism, with the female averaging only 3% larger than the male. <s> They have long, broad, and rounded wings, which measure 29 - each. <s> Its tail is long, at 16 - , with a white rump and undertail coverts. <s> The dark, deeply hooked beak, measuring 2.9 - is an adaptation to its diet. <s> The tarsus is relatively long as well, measuring 3.6 - . <s> It flies slowly with its head facing downwards, looking for its main food, the large apple snails. <s> For this reason, it is considered a molluscivore. <s> The snail kite breeds in tropical South America, the Caribbean, and central and southern Florida in the United States. <s> It is resident all-year in most of its range, but the southernmost population migrates north in winter and the Caribbean birds disperse widely outside the breeding season. <s> It nests in a bush or on the ground, laying 3–4 eggs. <s> This is a gregarious bird of freshwater wetlands, forming large winter roosts. <s> Its diet consists almost exclusively of apple snails.
simple: The snail kite ("Rostrhamus sociabilis") is a bird of prey. <s> It is in the family Accipitridae, which also includes the eagles, hawks, and Old World vultures. <s> Snail kites are 36 to long with a 99 - wingspan. <s> They weigh from 300 to. <s> They have long, broad, and rounded wings. <s> Its tail is long with a white rump. <s> The dark, deeply hooked beak measures 2.9 -. <s> It flies slowly with its head facing downwards to see its prey. <s> The snail kite lives in tropical South America, the Caribbean, and central and southern Florida in the United States. <s> It nests in a bush or on the ground and lays 3–4 eggs. <s> It mostly eats large apple snails.

title: ATP synthase
complex: ATP synthase is an enzyme that creates the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP). <s> ATP is the most commonly used "energy currency" of cells for all organisms.
simple: ATP synthase is an enzyme found in cells that make ATP from ADP and inorganic phosphate.

title: Carrie (2013 film)
complex: Carrie is a 2013 American supernatural horror film directed by Kimberly Peirce, and is the third film adaptation (the others were in 1976 and 2002) of Stephen King's 1974 novel of the same name. <s> The film was produced by Kevin Misher, with a screenplay by Lawrence D. Cohen and Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa. <s> The film stars Chloë Grace Moretz as the titular character Carrie White, alongside Julianne Moore as Margaret White. <s> The cast also features Judy Greer, Portia Doubleday, Gabriella Wilde, Ansel Elgort and Alex Russell.
simple: Carrie is an American teen horror movie. <s> Moore plays Carrie's mother Margaret White in this 2013 adaptation. <s> Starring in this are Chloë Grace Moretz, Julianne Moore and Judy Greer; Moretz plays Carrie White.

title: The Story of Doctor Dolittle
complex: The Story of Doctor Dolittle, Being the History of His Peculiar Life at Home and Astonishing Adventures in Foreign Parts (1920), written and illustrated by the British author Hugh Lofting, is the first of his Doctor Dolittle books, a series of children's novels about a man who learns to talk to animals and becomes their champion around the world. <s> It was one of the novels in the series which was adapted into the film "Doctor Dolittle". <s> John Dolittle, MD, is a respected physician and quiet bachelor living with his spinster sister in the small English village of Puddleby-on-the-Marsh. <s> His love of animals grows over the years and his household menagerie eventually scares off his human clientele, leading to loss of wealth.
simple: The Story of Doctor Dolittle is a 1920 book about Doctor John Dolittle and his animals. <s> This book is the first in a series of children's books by Hugh Lofting. <s> Dolittle lives in the English village of Puddleby-on-the-Marsh in the West Country.

title: List of Bangla Academy Literary Award recipients (2010–19)
complex: This is a list of the recipients of the Bangla Academy Literary Award from 2010 to 2019.
simple: In the list below, the winner of the award for each year from 2010 to 2019 is given.

title: John Law (economist)
complex: John Law ("baptised" 21 April 1671 – 21 March 1729) was a Scottish economist who believed that money was only a means of exchange that did not constitute wealth in itself and that national wealth depended on trade. <s> He was appointed Controller General of Finances of France under the Duke of Orleans, who served as regent for the youthful king, Louis XV.
simple: John Law ("baptized" 21 April 1671 - 21 March 1729) was a Scottish economist who believed that money was only a means of exchange that did not have wealth in itself, and that national wealth depended on trade.

title: Super Bowl LII
complex: Super Bowl LII was an American football game played to determine the champion of the National Football League (NFL) for the 2017 season. <s> The National Football Conference (NFC) champion Philadelphia Eagles defeated the American Football Conference (AFC) and defending Super Bowl LI champion New England Patriots, 41–33, to win their first Super Bowl and their first NFL title since 1960. <s> The game was played on February 4, 2018, at U.S. Bank Stadium in Minneapolis, Minnesota. <s> This was the second time that a Super Bowl was played in Minneapolis, the northernmost city to ever host the event, after Super Bowl XXVI at the Metrodome during the 1991 season.
simple: Super Bowl LII (meaning Super Bowl 52 in Roman numerals) was an American football game in which the Philadelphia Eagles, who were winners of the National Football Conference (NFC) in the 2017 season, beat the New England Patriots, who were winners of the American Football Conference (AFC) in the 2017 season, 41-33 to become winners of the National Football League (NFL) for the 2017 season. <s> It was the first time the Philadelphia Eagles won a Super Bowl and was their second NFL title. <s> It was played at the U.S. Bank Stadium in Minneapolis, Minnesota on February 4, 2018.

title: Sodium fluoride
complex: Sodium fluoride (NaF) is an inorganic compound with the formula Na F . <s> It is a colorless or white solid that is readily soluble in water.
simple: Sodium fluoride is a chemical compound. <s> It is made of sodium and fluoride ions. <s> Its chemical formula is NaF.

title: University of Tübingen
complex: The University of Tübingen, officially the Eberhard Karls University of Tübingen ( ; ), is a public research university located in the city of Tübingen, Baden-Württemberg, Germany. <s> The University of Tübingen was founded in 1477 by Count Eberhard V (Eberhard im Bart, 1445–1496), later the first Duke of Württemberg, a civic and ecclesiastic reformer who established the school after becoming absorbed in the Renaissance revival of learning during his travels to Italy. <s> Its first rector was Johannes Nauclerus. <s> In May 2010, Tübingen joined the Matariki Network of Universities (MNU) together with Dartmouth College (USA), Durham University (UK), Queen’s University (Canada), University of Otago (New Zealand), University of Western Australia (Australia) and Uppsala University (Sweden). <s> The University of Tübingen is not a campus university, but is spread throughout the town: Tübingen is one of five classical "university towns" in Germany. <s> The other four are Marburg, Göttingen, Freiburg and Heidelberg.
simple: Eberhard Karls University, Tübingen is a public university in the city of Tübingen, Baden-Württemberg, Germany. <s> The University of Tübingen was founded in 1477. <s> In 2010, Tübingen joined the Matariki Network of Universities (MNU) together with Dartmouth College (USA), Durham University (UK), Queen’s University (Canada), University of Otago (New Zealand), University of Western Australia (Australia) and Uppsala University (Sweden). <s> In Germany, Tübingen became known as one of the "five classical university towns".

title: New Castle County, Delaware
complex: New Castle County is the northernmost of the three counties of the U.S. state of Delaware. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 538,479, making it the most populous county in Delaware, with just under 60% of the state's population of 897,936 in the same census. <s> The county seat is Wilmington. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 500,265 people, 188,935 households, and 127,153 families residing in the county. <s> The population density is 1,174 people per square mile (453/km2).
simple: New Castle County is a county in the state of Delaware in the United States. <s> The county seat is Wilmington. <s> New Castle County had 500,265 people in 2000.

title: Douglas A-1 Skyraider
complex: The Douglas A-1 Skyraider (formerly AD Skyraider) is an American single-seat attack aircraft that saw service between the late 1940s and early 1980s. <s> The Skyraider had a remarkably long and successful career; it became a piston-powered, propeller-driven anachronism in the jet age, and was nicknamed "Spad", after the French World War I fighter. <s> Skyraider production ended in 1957 with a total of 3,180 having been built. <s> In 1962, the existing Skyraiders were redesignated A-1D through A-1J and later used by both the USAF and the Navy in the Vietnam War.
simple: The Douglas A-1 Skyraider is an attack aircraft designed and built in the United States. <s> Before 1962, the US Navy's A-1 were called AD.

title: The Balcony (painting)
complex: The Balcony ("French: Le balcon") is an 1868-69 oil painting by the French painter Édouard Manet. <s> It depicts four figures on a balcony, one of whom is sitting; the painter Berthe Morisot, who married Manet's brother Eugène in 1874. <s> In the centre is the painter Jean Baptiste Antoine Guillemet. <s> On the right is Fanny Claus, a violinist. <s> The fourth figure, partially obscured in the interior's background, is possibly Léon Leenhoff, Manet's son. <s> It was exhibited at the Paris Salon of 1869, and then kept by Manet until his death in 1883. <s> It was sold to the painter Gustave Caillebotte in 1884, who left it to the French state in 1894. <s> It is currently held at the Musée d'Orsay, in Paris. <s> The painting, inspired by "Majas on the Balcony" by Francisco Goya, was created at the same time and with the same purpose as "Luncheon in the Studio". <s> The three characters, who were all friends of Manet, seem to be disconnected from each other: while Berthe Morisot, on the left, looks like a romantic and inaccessible heroine, the young violinist Fanny Claus and the painter Antoine Guillemet seem to display indifference. <s> The boy in the background is probably Manet's son, Léon. <s> Just behind the railings, there are a hydrangea in a ceramic pot, and a dog with a ball below Morisot's chair. <s> This was the first portrait of Morisot by Manet. <s> Manet adopts a retrained colour palette, dominated by white, green and black, with a accents of blue (Guillemet's tie) and red (Morisot's fan). <s> Manet made many preparatory studies, painting the four subjects individually many times: Guillemet as many as fifteen times. <s> A preparatory study for "The Balcony" was painted at Boulogne in 1868. <s> This unfinished portrait of Fanny Claus, the closest friend of Manet’s wife Suzanne Leenhoff;
