Claus married Manet's friend Pierre Prins in 1869. <s> The work was bought after Manet's death in a studio sale by John Singer Sargent. <s> The portrait had only been seen once in public since it was first painted in 1868, but in 2012 the Ashmolean Museum in Oxford succeeded in raising the funds to acquire it and keep it permanently in a public collection in the United Kingdom. <s> The painting was not well received when it was exhibited at the Paris Salon in 1869. <s> The aggressive and bold green of the balcony rails drew much attention, as evidenced by the article devoted to the work by the in 1878 which stated: "This painting was exhibited at the Salon of 1869 and is one of those who contributed to form this reputation for eccentricity realistic, this reputation of bad taste that was attached to Mr. Manet." <s> The press considered the painting as "discordant". <s> The contrast of colours (the background completely black, the white faces and clothes, the blue tie of the man, and the green railings) contributes to create an atmosphere of "mystery".
simple: The Balcony is an 1868 oil painting by the French painter Édouard Manet. <s> The painting depicts four figures. <s> On the left is Berthe Morisot, who became in 1874 the wife of Manet's brother, Eugène. <s> In the centre is the painter Jean Baptiste Antoine Guillemet. <s> On the right is Fanny Claus, a violist. <s> The fourth figure in the background is possibly Leon Leenhoff, Manet's stepson. <s> It was exhibited at the Paris Salon of 1869. <s> It was sold by Gustave Caillebotte in 1884. <s> It hangs at this time in Paris at the Musée d'Orsay. <s> The painting was inspired by "The Majas at the Balcony" by Francisco Goya. <s> It was created at the same time and with the same purpose as "Luncheon in the studio". <s> The three characters were all friends of Manet. <s> They seem to be disconnected from each other. <s> Berthe Morisot, on the left, looks like a romantic and inaccessible heroine, the young violinist Fanny Claus and the painter Antoine Guillemet seem to display indifference. <s> The boy in the background is Manet's stepson, Léon. <s> Just behind the railings, there are a hydrangea and a dog with a ball. <s> This was the first time Berthe Morisot posed for Manet. <s> The portrait’s subject is Fanny Claus, the closest friend of Manet’s wife Suzanne Leenhoff. <s> This unfinished portrait was painted as a study for the finished picture. <s> Following Manet’s premature death in 1883, the portrait was bought in a studio sale by the artist John Singer Sargent. <s> The portrait had only been seen once in public since it was first painted in 1868. <s> In 2012 the Ashmolean Museum succeeded in raising the funds to acquire it and keep it permanently in a public collection in the United Kingdom. <s> The press considered the painting "discordant". <s> The contrast of colors (the background completely black, the white faces and clothes, the blue tie of the man, and the green railings) contributes to create an atmosphere of "mystery".

title: Moyar River
complex: The Mayar River is one of the tributaries of the Bhavani in Tamil Nadu, South India. <s> The Mayar river originates from a small town called Mayar off the Masinagudi–Ooty road. <s> This is a natural line of separation between the state of Karnataka and Tamil Nadu and a separation between the forest of Bandipur National Park and the Mudumalai sanctuary to the south. <s> The Mayar River Gorge is 20 km long and is also called the Mayar Canyon. <s> The river flows into the gorge below Theppakadu in a roaring waterfall called Mayar Falls. <s> This river is checked by Bhavanisagar Dam on the plains near Satyamangalam, along with the Bhavani River.
simple: The Moyar River is one of the tributaries of the Bhavani in Tamil Nadu, India. <s> The Moyar river starts from a small town called Moyar. <s> This is a natural line of separation between Bandipur and the Mudumalai sanctuary to the south. <s> This river is checked (stopped) by Bhavanisagar Dam on the plains near Satyamangalam.

title: Rodrigo Mendes
complex: Rodrigo Fabiano Mendes (born August 9, 1975 in Uberaba), or simply Rodrigo Mendes or Rodrigo, is a Brazilian former left winger, he last played for Novo Hamburgo, formerly played for Fortaleza who was released on 5 June 2009 due to successive muscular problems on both tights.
simple: Rodrigo Mendes (born 9 August 1975) is a Brazilian football player. <s> He plays for Novo Hamburgo.

title: Coefficient
complex: In mathematics, a coefficient is a multiplicative factor in some term of a polynomial, a series, or any expression; it is usually a number, but may be any expression. <s> In the latter case, the variables appearing in the coefficients are often called parameters, and must be clearly distinguished from the other variables.
simple: In mathematics, a coefficient is a constant multiplicative factor of a certain object.

title: Duck Commander
complex: Duck Commander is both the brand of a duck call and the name of the company in West Monroe, Louisiana, United States. <s> The company manufactures these calls and other duck-hunting merchandise, as well as deer-hunting merchandise under the Buck Commander brand. <s> Phil Robertson, a football quarterback at Louisiana Tech University, founded the company. <s> He began his business in a dilapidated boat, where he spent 25 years making duck calls from Louisiana cedar trees. <s> Robertson's third son, Willie Robertson, currently serves as the company's chief executive officer and has expanded it into a multimillion-dollar enterprise. <s> The Robertson family and business are the subjects of "Duck Dynasty", a reality television series on A&E. <s> Before that, they were featured in the "Duck Commander" television show on the Outdoor Channel.
simple: Duck Commander is a company that makes duck calls. <s> They also make duck and deer hunting equipment Their main office is in West Monroe, Louisiana, United States. <s> Phil Robertson, an American football quarterback at Louisiana Tech University, was originally going to play professional football in the NFL. <s> He began his business in a dilapidated shed. <s> He spent 25 years there making duck calls from Louisiana cedar trees. <s> Phil's third son, Willie Robertson, is the company's chief executive officer. <s> Willie expanded it into a multi-million dollar enterprise. <s> The Robertson family and business are the subjects of "Duck Dynasty", a reality television series on A&E. <s> Before that, they were featured in the "Duck Commander" television show on the Outdoor Channel.

title: Ofra Haza
complex: Bat-Sheva Ofra Haza-Ashkenazi ( ; 19 November 1957 23 February 2000) was an Israeli singer, actress and Grammy Award-nominee recording artist, commonly known as "The Israeli Madonna", or "Madonna of the East". <s> Her voice has been described as a "tender" mezzo-soprano. <s> Haza is buried in the Artists section of Yarkon Cemetery in Petah Tikva near Tel Aviv.
simple: Ofra Haza, Hebrew: עפרה חזה , full name: "Bat-Sheva Ofra Haza-Ashkenazi ", (19 November 1957 in Tel Aviv – 23 February 2000 in Ramat Gan) was an Israeli (pop) singer. <s> She died of AIDS and was buried in the Yarkon Cemetery in Petah Tikva.

title: Lumbrein
complex: Lumbrein is a former municipality in the district of Surselva in the Swiss canton of Graubünden. <s> The municipalities of Cumbel, Degen, Lumbrein, Morissen, Suraua, Vignogn, Vella, and Vrin merged on 1 January 2013 into the new municipality of Lumnezia.
simple: Lumbrein is a former municipality of the district Surselva in the canton of Lucerne in Switzerland. <s> The municipalities of Cumbel, Degen, Lumbrein, Morissen, Suraua, Vignogn, Vella, and Vrin merged on 1 January 2013 into the new municipality of Lumnezia.

title: Carla Anderson Hills
complex: Carla Anderson Hills (born January 3, 1934) is an American lawyer and a public figure. <s> She served as United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development in the Gerald Ford administration, and as U.S. Trade Representative. <s> She was the first woman to serve as Secretary of Housing and Urban Development and the third woman to serve as a cabinet officer.
simple: Carla Anderson Hills (born January 3, 1934) is an American lawyer and a public figure. <s> She served as United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development in the Gerald Ford administration and as U.S. Trade Representative. <s> She was the first woman to serve as Secretary of Housing and Urban Development and the third woman to serve as a cabinet officer.

title: The Ice Storm (film)
complex: The Ice Storm is a 1997 American drama film directed by Ang Lee, based on Rick Moody’s 1994 novel of the same name. <s> The film features an ensemble cast of Kevin Kline, Joan Allen, Tobey Maguire, Christina Ricci, Elijah Wood, Katie Holmes, Glenn Fitzgerald, Jamey Sheridan, and Sigourney Weaver. <s> Set during Thanksgiving 1973, "The Ice Storm" is about two dysfunctional New Canaan, Connecticut upper-class families who are trying to deal with tumultuous social changes of the early 1970s, and their escapism through alcohol, adultery, and sexual experimentation. <s> The film opened in the United States on September 26, 1997. <s> Its release was limited and it ultimately grossed US$8 million on a budget of US$18 million. <s> A special two-disc DVD set was released as part of the Criterion Collection on March 18, 2008.
simple: The Ice Storm is a 1997 American drama movie. <s> Christina Ricci, Elijah Wood and Kevin Kline are in the cast. <s> The movie is about two families in New Canaan, Connecticut who are dealing with politics and serious social matters in November 1973. <s> These two families do that using adultery, alcohol and sexual experimenting. <s> This movie was released in the United States in autumn 1997. <s> Its performance at the box office, however was terrible: the movie only got back close to half its $18 million budget.

title: Rohit
complex: Rohit (Devanagri: रोहित), ] ) is a given name, typically male, used among Indian people. <s> It is also used in some parts of Nepal. <s> It is mostly used by Jains, Hindus, and Sikhs. <s> The word "rohit" signifies the color red. <s> It is derived from Sanskrit, meaning "the first rays of the sun". <s> The early morning sunlight usually has a reddish tint. <s> It is also said to be derived from the Sanskrit word Rohitah (रोहित:) which signifies a red coloured deer – a form which Brahma once took. ]
simple: Rohit is a given name, usually for males. <s> It is mostly used in India. <s> The word "rohit" refers to the color red. <s> It is derived from Sanskrit, meaning "the first rays of the sun". <s> The early morning sunlight usually has a reddish tint.

title: Radio drama
complex: Radio drama (or audio drama, audio play, radio play, radio theatre, or audio theatre) is a dramatised, purely acoustic performance. <s> With no visual component, radio drama depends on dialogue, music and sound effects to help the listener imagine the characters and story: "It is auditory in the physical dimension but equally powerful as a visual force in the psychological dimension."
simple: A radio drama ("audio" or "radio play", "dramatized audiobook") is a live or recorded performance of actors without visual elements.

title: Deneuille-lès-Chantelle
complex: Deneuille-lès-Chantelle is a commune in the Allier department in central France.
simple: Deneuille-lès-Chantelle is a French commune. <s> It is in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: Shaukat Tarin
complex: Shaukat Tarin ( ; born 1953) is a Pakistani banker and former Finance Minister of Pakistan from 2009 to 2010 in the Gillani cabinet. <s> Shaukat Tarin was appointed adviser to the finance ministry of Pakistan with a status of federal minister, on 7 October 2008.
simple: Shaukat Tarin or Shaukat Tareen (born 1953) is a senior Pakistani banker. <s> He was Pakistan's finance minister from 2009 to 2010.

title: Nebula Award for Best Novel
complex: The Nebula Award for Best Novel is given each year by the Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America (SFWA) for science fiction or fantasy novels. <s> A work of fiction is defined by the organization as a novel if it is 40,000 words or longer; awards are also given out for pieces of shorter lengths in the categories of short story, novelette, and novella.
simple: The Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers of America gives awards for good Science Fiction writing. <s> Each year they give the Nebula Award for Best Novel.

title: Dnieper
complex: The Dnieper is one of the major rivers of Europe, rising in the Valdai Hills near Smolensk, Russia, before flowing through Belarus and Ukraine to the Black Sea. <s> It is the longest river of Ukraine and Belarus and the fourth-longest river in Europe. <s> The total length is approximately 2200 km with a drainage basin of 504000 km2 . <s> Historically, the river was an important barrier, dividing Ukraine into right and left banks. <s> Nowadays, the river is noted for its dams and hydroelectric stations. <s> The Dnieper is an important navigable waterway for the economy of Ukraine and is connected via the Dnieper–Bug Canal to other waterways in Europe. <s> In antiquity, the river was known to the Greeks as the Borysthenes and was part of the Amber Road. <s> The total length of the river is variously given as 2145 km or 2201 km , of which 485 km are within Russia, 700 km are within Belarus, and 1095 km are within Ukraine. <s> Its basin covers 504000 km2 , of which 289000 km2 are within Ukraine, 118360 km2 are within Belarus. <s> The river is part of the quagga mussel's native range. <s> The mussel has been accidentally introduced around the world where it has become an invasive species.
simple: The Dnieper River is one of the major rivers in Europe. <s> It flows from Russia, through Belarus and Ukraine, to the Black Sea. <s> It is fourth largest by length in Europe. <s> In antiquity, it was known to the Greeks as the Borysthenes. <s> 485 km is in Russia, 595 km is in Belarus, and 1095 km is in Ukraine. <s> Its basin covers 504000 km2. <s> 289000 km2 is in Ukraine. <s> The river is part of the Quagga mussel's native range.

title: Mira Zakai
complex: Mira Zakai ( ‎; 21 September 1942 – 20 May 2019) was an Israeli operatic contralto. <s> Zakai was born in Jerusalem as Mira Koigen, the daughter of George Koigen and his wife Eva (née Patai). <s> She studied at the University of Tel Aviv, initially in the Faculty of Humanities, and later at the Rubin Academy of Music, graduating in 1976. <s> She married Jacob Zakai and they had two daughters. <s> She appeared with Yehudi Menuhin in a concert at Castel Gandolfo for Pope John Paul II, having previously appeared at Menuhin's festival as a soloist in Bach's "Mass in B minor". <s> Her 1982 recording of Mahler's Symphony No. 2 with Georg Solti won the Grammy for Best Overall Classical Recording at the 1982 awards. <s> Zakai later moved into teaching, becoming a professor at the Buchmann-Mehta School of Music, University of Tel Aviv.
simple: Mira Zakai (‎; 21 September 1942 – 20 May 2019) was an Israeli opera singer. <s> She was a contralto. <s> On 20 May 2019, Zakai died of problems caused by a stroke she had a year before. <s> She was born in Jerusalem. <s> She studied at the University of Tel Aviv, where she later served as a professor. <s> She appeared with Menuhin at a concert in Castel Gandolfo for Pope John Paul II. <s> Before this, she appeared in Menuhin's festival as a soloist in Bach's "Mass in B minor". <s> Her recording of Mahler's Symphony No. 2 with Georg Solti won the Grammy Award for Best Overall Classical Recording in 1982.

title: Ferdinand Lemaire
complex: Ferdinand Lemaire (1832–1879) was a French librettist and poet, best known for writing the libretto of Camille Saint-Saëns's opera "Samson et Dalila". <s> Lemaire was a creole, originally from Martinique, and had married a cousin of Saint-Saëns's wife. <s> Saint-Saëns had previously set two of his poems, “Souvenance” and “Tristesse”, for voice and piano. <s> Approached by the composer to write an oratorio on the story of Samson and Delilah, Lemaire agreed, but only if the work was to be an opera.
simple: Ferdinand Lemaire was a librettist and writer. <s> He was a creole. <s> He married into Saint-Saëns's family. <s> He agreed to write "Samson" but only as opera, rather than as an oratorio as the composer first intended.

title: Setanta Sports
complex: Setanta Sports is a sports television company based in Dublin, Ireland broadcasting throughout Ukraine Russia and CIS territories. <s> The company was formed in 1990 to facilitate the broadcasting of Irish sporting events to international audiences. <s> The company previously operated channels in Ireland, the UK, Asia, Australia, the United States and Canada.
simple: Setanta Sports (pronounced sɛˈtantə) is an Irish sports broadcaster, operating 12 channels in 24 countries. <s> Setanta Sports was formed in 1990.

title: 1940 Summer Olympics
complex: The 1940 Summer Olympics, officially known as the Games of the XII Olympiad, were originally scheduled to be held from September 21 to October 6, 1940, in Tokyo, Japan. <s> They were rescheduled for Helsinki, Finland, to be held from July 20 to August 4, 1940, but were ultimately canceled due to the outbreak of World War II.
simple: The 1940 Summer Olympics, officially known as Games of the XII Olympiad, were not held.

title: James H. Burnley IV
complex: James Horace Burnley IV (born July 30, 1948) is an American politician and lawyer. <s> He served as the United States Secretary of Transportation from 1987 until 1989, during the administration of President Ronald Reagan. <s> In 1987, President Ronald Reagan chose Burnley, Dole's Deputy Secretary and the Department's former General Counsel, to be the nation's ninth Secretary of Transportation.
simple: James Horace Burnley IV (born July 30, 1948) is an American politician and lawyer. <s> He served as the United States Secretary of Transportation from 1987 until 1989. <s> He served during the administration of President Ronald Reagan.

title: Ashurbanipal
complex: Ashurbanipal ( ; 'Ashur is the creator of an heir'), also spelled Assurbanipal or Ashshurbanipal, was King of the Neo-Assyrian Empire from 668 BC to c. 627 BC, the son of Esarhaddon and the last strong ruler of the empire, which is usually dated between 934 and 609 BC. <s> He is famed for amassing a significant collection of cuneiform documents for his royal palace at Nineveh. <s> This collection, known as the Library of Ashurbanipal, is now in the British Museum, which also holds the famous "Lion Hunt of Ashurbanipal" set of Assyrian palace reliefs. <s> In the Hebrew Bible he is called Asenappar ( - ). <s> Roman historian Justinus identified him as Sardanapalus, although the fictional Sardanapalus is depicted as the last king of Assyria and an ineffectual, effete and debauched character, whereas four further kings succeeded Ashurbanipal, who was in fact an educated, efficient, highly capable and ambitious warrior king.
simple: Ashurbanipal (685 BC – 627 BC), the son of Esarhaddon, was the last great king of the Neo-Assyrian Empire. <s> In the Bible he is called Asenappar. <s> Roman historian Justinus identified him as Sardanapalus, and describes him as effeminate.

title: Gamlingay
complex: Gamlingay is a village and civil parish in South Cambridgeshire, England, near the border with Bedfordshire, and the traditional county of Huntingdonshire. <s> It is 14 miles (22 km) from Cambridge and the population in 2011 was 4,900 people. <s> At the time of the 2001 census, Gamlingay parish had 3,535 inhabitants living in 1,410 households. <s> The ethnic group of 99% was white, with 0.4% Asian or Asian British, 0.1% black or Black British, 0.3% mixed and 0.2% other.
simple: Gamlingay is a village and civil parish in South Cambridgeshire, Cambridgeshire, England. <s> In 2001 there were 3,535 people living in Gamlingay.

title: Stuart Duncan
complex: Stuart Duncan (born April 14, 1964) is an American bluegrass musician who plays the fiddle, mandolin, guitar and banjo. <s> Duncan has been a member of the Nashville Bluegrass Band since 1985. <s> He also works as a session musician and has played with numerous well known performers including George Strait, Dolly Parton, Guy Clark, Reba McEntire and Barbra Streisand. <s> In 2006, he toured with the Mark Knopfler–Emmylou Harris "Roadrunning" tour, and he appears on their "All the Roadrunning" and "Real Live Roadrunning" albums.
simple: Stuart Duncan (born April 14, 1964) is an American fiddle, banjo, mandolin, and guitar player. <s> In his career, Duncan has recorded with artists such as Dolly Parton, Barbra Streisand, George Strait, Reba McEntire, Bela Fleck, Jerry Douglas, and Chris Thile.

title: Lowesville, Virginia
complex: Lowesville is an unincorporated community in Nelson County, Virginia, United States. <s> It lies along the path of the now-defunct Virginia Blue Ridge Railway.
simple: Lowesville is an unincorporated community in Nelson County, Virginia, United States. <s> It lies along the path of the now-defunct Virginia Blue Ridge Railway.

title: Goshen, Connecticut
complex: Goshen is a town in Litchfield County, Connecticut, United States. <s> The population was 2,976 at the 2010 census.
simple: Goshen is a town in Litchfield County, Connecticut, United States. <s> The population was 2,976 at the 2010 census.

title: Anton Raphael Mengs
complex: Anton Raphael Mengs (March 22, 1728 – June 29, 1779) was a German (Saxon) painter, active in Dresden, Rome and Madrid, who while painting in the Rococo period of the mid-18th century became one of the precursors to Neoclassical painting, which replaced Rococo as the dominant painting style.
simple: Anton Raphael Mengs (March 12, 1728 – June 29, 1779) was a German painter. <s> He worked in Rome, Madrid, and Saxony.

title: Rod (unit)
complex: The rod or perch or pole is a surveyor’s tool and unit of length exactly equal to 5 ⁄ yards, 16 feet, of a statute mile, or one-fourth of a surveyor's chain (approximately 5.0292 meters). <s> The rod is useful as a unit of length because whole number multiples of it can form one acre of square measure. <s> The 'perfect acre' is a rectangular area of 43,560 square feet, bounded by sides of length 660 feet and 66 feet (220 yards and 22 yards) or, equivalently, 40 rods and 4 rods. <s> An acre is therefore 160 square rods. <s> Despite no longer being in widespread use, the rod is still employed in certain specialized fields. <s> In recreational canoeing, maps measure portages (overland paths where canoes must be carried) in rods; typical canoes are approximately one rod long. <s> The term is also in widespread use in the acquisition of pipeline easements, as the offers for an easement are often expressed on a "price per rod". <s> In the United Kingdom, the sizes of allotment gardens continue to be measured in square poles in some areas, sometimes being referred to simply as "poles" rather than "square poles".
simple: A rod, a perch or a pole is a unit of length in the imperial and US systems. <s> The rod is still in use as a unit of measure in certain specialised fields. <s> In recreational canoeing, overland paths where canoes must be carried are measured in rods. <s> This is probably because the length of a typical canoe is about one rod. <s> In the United Kingdom, some gardens are measured in rods.

title: MIMO
complex: In radio, multiple-input and multiple-output, or MIMO , is a method for multiplying the capacity of a radio link using multiple transmission and receiving antennas to exploit multipath propagation. <s> MIMO has become an essential element of wireless communication standards including IEEE 802.11n (Wi-Fi), IEEE 802.11ac (Wi-Fi), HSPA+ (3G), WiMAX (4G), and Long Term Evolution (4G LTE).
simple: MIMO (Multiple Input, Multiple Output) is a technology which allows an antenna or multiple antennas to communicate with multiple devices, which minimizes errors and maximize efficiency.

title: Lidingöloppet
complex: Lidingöloppet is an annual cross country running competition held in Lidingö, Sweden. <s> The 30 km run has about 15,000 participants per year and the shorter races several thousands, making it the largest cross-country event in the world.
simple: Lidingöloppet is an annual cross-country running competition held in Lidingö in Sweden.

title: Kungälv Municipality
complex: Kungälv Municipality ("Kungälvs kommun") is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in western Sweden. <s> Its seat is located in the city of Kungälv.
simple: Kungälv Municipality is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Kungälv.

title: Wonder (Palacio novel)
complex: "Wonder" was on "The New York Times" Best Seller list and was also on the Texas Bluebonnet Award master list. <s> The book was the winner of the 2014 Maine Student Book Award, Vermont's Dorothy Canfield Fisher Children's Book Award, the 2015 Mark Twain Award, Hawaii's 2015 Nene Award, and the Junior Young Reader's Choice Award for 2015.
simple: "Wonder" was ranked #1 on The New York Times Best Seller list. <s> It was also on the Texas Bluebonnet Award master list.

title: Alan Aldridge
complex: Alan Aldridge (8 July 1938 – 17 February 2017) was a British artist, graphic designer and illustrator. <s> He is best known for his psychedelic artwork made for books and record covers by The Beatles and The Who. <s> Aldridge was born in North London and lived in Los Angeles, California. <s> Aldridge was twice divorced. <s> He was survived by eight children: Miles, Saffron, Pim, Marc, Toby, James, Lily and Ruby. <s> Four of his children are fashion photographer Miles Aldridge and models Saffron Aldridge, Lily Aldridge and Ruby Aldridge. <s> On 17 February 2017, his daughter Lily announced his death via Instagram.
simple: Alan Aldridge (1 June 1943 – 17 February 2017) was a British artist, graphic designer and illustrator. <s> He was well known for his art works for musicians and bands such as The Who, The Beatles and Elton John. <s> Aldridge was born in London. <s> Aldridge lived in Los Angeles, California, United States. <s> He had eight children, including Lily Aldridge. <s> He died on 17 February 2017, at the age of 73.

title: Pleujouse
complex: Pleujouse is a village and a former municipality in the district of Porrentruy in the canton of Jura in Switzerland. <s> Since January 1, 2009, it has been part of the new municipality La Baroche.
simple: Pleujouse is a former municipality in the district of Porrentruy in the canton of Jura in Switzerland. <s> Since 1 January 2009, it is part of the new municipality of La Baroche

title: Dole, Jura
complex: Dole was the capital of Franche-Comté until Louis XIV conquered the region; he shifted the "parlement" from Dole to Besançon. <s> The university, founded by Duke Philippe le Bon of Burgundy in 1422, was also transferred to Besançon at that time.
simple: It was the capital of the Free County until Louis XIV conquered the region, which from then on became Besançon.

title: Putney
complex: Putney is a district in south-west London, England in the London Borough of Wandsworth. <s> It is centred 6.1 mi south-west of Charing Cross.
simple: Putney is a rich area of the London Borough of Wandsworth in south-west London.

title: Fork (software development)
complex: In software engineering, a project fork happens when developers take a copy of source code from one software package and start independent development on it, creating a distinct and separate piece of software. <s> The term often implies not merely a development branch, but also a split in the developer community, a form of schism. <s> Free and open-source software is that which, by definition, may be forked from the original development team without prior permission, without violating copyright law. <s> However, licensed forks of proprietary software ("e.g." Unix) also happen.
simple: In software engineering, a project fork happens when a copy of source code from one software package is made into a different piece of software. <s> Free and open-source software is code that may be forked from the original development team without prior permission. <s> This does not violate copyright law. <s> However, licensed forks of proprietary software ("e.g." Unix) also happen.

title: Dr. Oetker
complex: Dr. Oetker is a German multinational company that produces baking powder, cake mixes, frozen pizza, pudding, cake decoration, cornflakes, and various other products. <s> The company is a wholly owned branch of the Oetker Group, headquartered in Bielefeld. <s> The company was founded by Doctor August Oetker in 1891; the first product developed was Backin, a measured amount of baking powder that, when mixed with 500 g of flour and other ingredients, produced a cake.
simple: Dr. Oetker is a German food company that produces baking powder, cake mixes, yogurts, frozen pizza, pudding, cake decoration, cornflakes and various other products. <s> The company is a wholly-owned branch of the Oetker Group. <s> The company was founded by Doctor August Oetker in 1891.

title: Liqueur
complex: A liqueur is an alcoholic drink composed of distilled spirits and additional flavorings such as sugar, fruits, herbs, and spices. <s> Often served with or after dessert, they are typically heavily sweetened and un-aged beyond a resting period during production, when necessary, for their flavors to mingle. <s> Liqueurs are historical descendants of herbal medicines. <s> They were made in Italy as early as the 13th century, often prepared by monks (for example, Chartreuse). <s> Today they are produced the world over, commonly served straight, over ice, with coffee, in cocktails, and used in cooking. <s> The French word "liqueur" is derived from the Latin "liquifacere", which means "to dissolve". <s> In some parts of the United States and Canada, liqueurs may be referred to as cordials, or schnapps. <s> This can cause confusion as in the United Kingdom a cordial would refer to a non-alcoholic concentrated fruit syrup, typically diluted to taste and consumed as a non-carbonated soft drink. <s> Schnapps, on the other hand, can refer to any distilled beverage in Germany and aquavit in Scandinavian countries. <s> In the United States and Canada, where spirits are often called "liquor" , there is often confusion discerning between liqueurs and liquors, due to the many different types of flavored spirits that are available today (e.g., flavored vodka). <s> Liqueurs generally contain a lower alcohol content (15–30% ABV) than spirits and it has sweetener mixed, while some can have an ABV as high as 55%.
simple: A liqueur is a sweet-tasting alcoholic drink. <s> It is often flavored with fruits, herbs, spices, flowers, seeds, roots, plants, barks, and sometimes cream. <s> They are often served with dessert or as a dessert. <s> Liqueurs were made in Italy as early as the 13th century, and were used during signings of treaties during the Middle Ages. <s> They are commonly drank by themselves, poured over ice, with coffee, or mixed with cream or other mixers to create cocktails. <s> The word "liqueur" comes from the Latin word "liquifacere" which means "to dissolve." <s> In some parts of the world, liqueurs are sometimes called cordials. <s> Most liqueurs have 15 to 30% alcohol content but may have an alcohol content as high as 55%.

title: Salim Ahmed Salim
complex: Salim Ahmed Salim ( , Urdu: , , born 23 January 1942) is a Tanzanian politician and diplomat who has worked in the international diplomatic arena since the early 1960s.
simple: Salim Ahmed Salim (, Urdu: , , born 23 January 1942) is a Tanzanian diplomat.

title: Wikimania
complex: , the fifteenth Wikimedia conference, was held in Stockholm, Sweden from 14 to 18 August 2019, with an attendance of over 800. <s> Emna Mizouni was minted the Wikimedian of the year.
simple: , the fifteenth Wikimedia conference, will be held in Stockholm, Sweden.

title: Ethiopian Airlines Flight 961
complex: Ethiopian Airlines Flight 961 was a scheduled flight serving the route Addis Ababa–Nairobi–Brazzaville–Lagos–Abidjan. <s> On 23 November 1996, the aircraft serving the flight, a Boeing 767-200ER, was hijacked en route from Addis Ababa to Nairobi by three Ethiopians seeking asylum in Australia. <s> The plane crash-landed in the Indian Ocean near Grande Comore, Comoros Islands, due to fuel exhaustion; 125 of the 175 passengers and crew on board, including the three hijackers, died. <s> The crash was captured on video. <s> Of the 175 passengers and crew members, 125 were killed, including the three hijackers. <s> According to the accident report, all six surviving crew members and 38 passengers received serious injuries, two passengers received minor injuries, and four passengers received no injuries.
simple: Ethiopian Airlines Flight 961 was a domestic passenger flight from Addis Ababa to Nairobi, with stopovers at Brazzaville, Lagos, and Abidjan. <s> On November 23, 1996 the Boeing 767 was hijacked by three Ethiopians that were seeking asylum in Australia. <s> However the plane ran out of fuel, and crash-landed in the Indian Ocean near the Comoros Islands. <s> Of the 175 occupants on-board 125 people including the hijackers were killed, and 50 people survived.

title: Rosel
complex: Rosel is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Rosel is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Eddie Vedder
complex: Eddie Jerome Vedder (born Edward Louis Severson III; December 23, 1964) is an American musician, multi-instrumentalist and singer-songwriter best known as the lead vocalist and one of three guitarists of the American rock band Pearl Jam. <s> He is known for his powerful baritone vocals.
simple: Eddie Vedder (born Edward Louis Severson III; December 23, 1964) is an American musician, singer and songwriter. <s> He is best known for being the lead singer and one of three guitarists of the alternative rock band Pearl Jam.

title: Vengeance (2004)
complex: Vengeance (2004) was a professional wrestling pay-per-view (PPV) event produced by American promotion, World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE). <s> It took place on July 11, 2004, from the Hartford Civic Center in Hartford, Connecticut. <s> It was the fourth annual Vengeance chronology featured talent from the Raw brand.

title: Humphrey Mijnals

simple: Humphrey Mijnals (21 December 1930 – 27 July 2019) was a Surinamese-Dutch footballer. <s> He played international football for both the Netherlands and Suriname. <s> Mijnals died on 27 July 2019 in Utrecht at the age of 88. <s> Then he played 45 times in the Suriname national football team. <s> In 1999, he was elected Surinamese footballer of the century. <s> On 24 August 2008, Mijnals also received Sports Medal of the city of Utrecht.

title: Pat Verbeek
complex: Patrick Martin Verbeek (born May 24, 1964) is a Canadian former professional ice hockey player and current assistant general manager for the Detroit Red Wings of the National Hockey League. <s> Verbeek played for five teams over a 20 year playing career, earning a Stanley Cup ring with the Dallas Stars in 1999. <s> His nickname, "The Little Ball of Hate", was given to him in 1995 by Glenn Healy after fellow New York Rangers teammate Ray Ferraro was tagged as the "Big Ball of Hate".
simple: Patrick "The Little Ball of Hate" Verbeek (born May 24, 1964 in Sarnia, Ontario) is a former Canadian NHL ice hockey right winger who played 21 seasons in the NHL. <s> He was given the nickname "The Little Ball of Hate" by Glenn Healy because teammate Ray Ferraro was nicknamed "Big Ball of Hate".

title: Escape from Alcatraz (film)
complex: Escape from Alcatraz is a 1979 American prison thriller film directed by Don Siegel. <s> It is an adaptation of the 1963 non-fiction book of the same name by J. Campbell Bruce and dramatizes the 1962 prisoner escape from the maximum security prison on Alcatraz Island. <s> The film stars Clint Eastwood, and features Patrick McGoohan, Fred Ward, Jack Thibeau and Larry Hankin. <s> Danny Glover appears in his film debut.
simple: Escape from Alcatraz is a 1979 American prison/thriller/action movie. <s> It was directed by Don Siegel. <s> It stars Clint Eastwood, Larry Hankin, Patrick McGoohan, Fred Ward, Roberts Blossom, and Danny Glover.

title: Reino Paasilinna
complex: Reino Paasilinna (born 5 December 1939 in Arctic Ocean) is a Finnish politician and former Member of the European Parliament (MEP). <s> He is a member of the Social Democratic Party of Finland, which is part of the Party of European Socialdemocrats. <s> He was in the European Parliament from 1996 to 2009, and has sat on the Parliament's Committee on Industry, Research and Energy. <s> Reino Paasilinna was born on "Aunus", a ship on the Arctic Ocean, on the coast of Norway, where the Paasilinna family fled the Winter War. <s> His family is from Petsamo but they moved to Kittilä because the Soviet Union invaded Petsamo during the Winter War. <s> The writers Erno, Mauri and Arto Paasilinna are his brothers.
simple: Reino Paasilinna (born 5 December 1939) is a Finnish politician and former Member of the European Parliament (MEP). <s> He is a member of the Social Democratic Party of Finland. <s> He is a member of the Party of European Socialdemocrats. <s> He was on the European Parliament's Committee on Industry, Research and Energy. <s> He was an MEP from 1996 to 2009. <s> Reino Paasilinna was born on "Aunus", a ship on the Arctic Ocean, on the coast of Norway. <s> His brother was novelist Arto Paasilinna.

title: Giovanni Corrieri
complex: Giovanni Corrieri (7 February 1920 – 22 January 2017) was an Italian professional road bicycle racer. <s> Corrieri won 7 stages in the Giro d'Italia between 1947 and 1955. <s> Corrieri died on 22 January 2017 at the age of 96.
simple: Giovanni Corrieri (7 February 1920 – 22 January 2017) was an Italian road bicycle racer. <s> Corrieri died on 22 January 2017 in Prato, Tuscany at the age of 96.

title: Vitreous enamel
complex: Vitreous enamel, also called porcelain enamel, is a material made by fusing powdered glass to a substrate by firing, usually between 750 and . <s> The powder melts, flows, and then hardens to a smooth, durable vitreous coating. <s> The word comes from the Latin , meaning "glass". <s> Vitreous enamel has many useful properties: it is smooth, hard, chemically resistant, durable, scratch resistant (5–6 on the Mohs scale), has long-lasting colour fastness, is easy to clean, and cannot burn. <s> Enamel is glass, not paint, so it does not fade under ultraviolet light.
simple: Sometimes called vitreous or porcelain enamel, it is made by fusing powdered glass to a base by firing, usually between 750 and 850°C (1,380 and 1,560°F). <s> The powder melts, flows, and then hardens to a smooth, durable coating on metal, or on glass or ceramics. <s> The glass is hard-wearing, scratch resistant and easy to clean.

title: River Adur
complex: The Adur ( or ) is a river in Sussex, England; it gives its name to the Adur district of West Sussex. <s> The river, which is 20 miles long, was once navigable for large vessels up as far as Steyning, where there was a large Saxon port, but by the 11th century the lower river became silted up and the port moved down to the deeper waters at the mouth of the river in Shoreham-by-Sea.
simple: The River Adur is a river in the county of Sussex, in England.

title: AD 18
complex: AD 18 (XVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Augustus and Caesar (or, less frequently, year 771 "Ab urbe condita"). <s> The denomination AD 18 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: It was a common year starting on Saturday of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Augustus and Caesar.

title: Elsie Quarterman
complex: Elsie Quarterman (November 28, 1910 – June 9, 2014) was a prominent plant ecologist. <s> She was a Professor Emerita at Vanderbilt University. <s> Quarterman was born on November 28, 1910 in Valdosta, Georgia. <s> She earned a B.A. from Georgia State Women's College (now Valdosta State University) in 1932 and earned an M.A. in botany from Duke University in 1943. <s> She completed her PhD at Duke University in 1949 with Henry J. Oosting. <s> During her graduate work and afterward, she also collaborated extensively with Catherine Keever. <s> Quarterman is best known for her work on the ecology of Tennessee cedar glades. <s> These herb-dominated plant communities on the shallow soils of limestone outcrops are globally rare habitats and contain many endemic plant species. <s> She is also credited with rediscovering the native Tennessee coneflower, "Echinacea tennesseensis", which was thought to be extinct, in 1969. <s> Conservation efforts for the coneflower were successful, and it was delisted as an endangered species in 2011. <s> She died on June 9, 2014, aged 103.
simple: Elsie Quarterman (November 28, 1910 – June 9, 2014) was an American plant ecologist. <s> She was a Professor Emerita at Vanderbilt University. <s> Quarterman was born on November 28, 1910 in Valdosta, Georgia. <s> She earned a B.A. from Georgia State Women's College (now Valdosta State University) in 1932 and earned an M.A. in botany from Duke University in 1943. <s> She is known for her work on the ecology of Tennessee cedar glades. <s> She died on June 9, 2014, at the age of 103.

title: Freeport, Illinois
complex: Freeport is the county seat and largest city of Stephenson County, Illinois. <s> The population was 25,638 at the 2010 census, and the mayor of Freeport is Jodi Miller, elected in 2017. <s> Freeport is known for hosting the second Lincoln-Douglas debate of 1858, and as "Pretzel City, USA", due to a popular local German bakery known for its pretzels in the 1850s.
simple: Freeport is a city of Illinois in the United States, it is also the county seat of Stephenson County, Illinois. <s> The population was 25,638 at the 2010 census.

title: Gary Weiss
complex: Gary Weiss is an American investigative journalist, columnist and author of two books that critically examine the ethics and morality of Wall Street. <s> He was also a contributing editor for "Condé Nast Portfolio". <s> His "Businessweek" articles exposed organized crime on Wall Street and the Salomon Brothers bond trading scandal in the 1990s, and more recently he has covered the 2008 financial crisis and its aftermath. <s> Weiss is co-founder of The Mideast Reporter.
simple: Gary Weiss is an American investigative journalist, columnist and author. <s> He wrote two books about the ethics and morality of Wall Street. <s> The articles he wrote for Business Week exposed organized crime on Wall Street and the Salomon Brothers bond trading scandal in the 1990s. <s> He also has covered the financial crisis of 2007–2010 and the events caused by it."

title: Pattazhy
complex: Pattazhy, also Pattazhiis a village located in Pathanapuram taluk in the eastern part of the Kollam District, Kerala state, India. <s> It is best known as the site of an ancient Bhagavathy temple, Pattazhy Devi Temple. <s> The name Pattazhy has an uncertain etymology. <s> Pattazhy may stem from an imperfect Malayalam portmanteau fusing Patt ("Soft") and Aazhy ("Ocean"). <s> Thus the word Pattazhy represents the compassion and affection of Pattazhy Devi to her beloved devotees and depth of her grace. <s> The name Pattazhy may have also derived from the word "Bhattarika" which means a virtuous and pious woman. <s> Pattazhy is a temple village situated in Pathanapuram Taluk of Kollam District in Kerala. <s> The land of Pattazhy comprising two panchayat areas (Pattazhy and Pattazhy vadakekara) was given as a gift to Pattazhy Devi by the King of Travancore for the help and shelter given in the fierce fight against the king of Kayamkulam. <s> When the king was extending his kingdom by winning war with the neighboring kingdoms with the help of Ramayyan Dalawa, Kambithan, a hardcore worshipper of Pattazhy Devi helped the king to take over Kayamkulam Kingdom. <s> As a symbol of his gratitude the king ordered to let Pattazhy be named and dedicated to Devi by issuing a royal order. <s> The annual festival at Pattazhy Devi Temple is one of the famous temple festivals in central Travancore.The Kumbhathiruvathira and Meenathiruvathira were the famous festivals of Pattazhy. <s> The festival is known for Kambam (fire works), Aalpindi Vilakku Ezhunnallathu (Procession of small structure made out of plantain kernel and germinating leaves of coconut tree with numerous lamps on it), Ponnin Thirumudi (Devi's idol carved out of pure gold and rare precious stones) Ezhunnallathu. <s> Pattazhy also got a place in the Guinness Book of world records for the 'Longest bamboo'.
simple: Pattazhy, also Pattazhi is a village in Pathanapuram taluk, Kollam district, Kerala, India. <s> The name Pattazhy has an uncertain etymology. <s> Pattazhy may stem from an imperfect Malayalam portmanteau fusing Patt ("Soft") and Aazhy ("Ocean"). <s> Thus the word Pattazhy represents the compassion and affection of Pattazhy Devi to her beloved devotees and depth of her grace. <s> The name Pattazhy may have also derived from the word "Bhattarika" which means a virtuous and pious woman. <s> The annual festival at Pattazhy Devi Temple is one of the famous temple festivals in central Travancore.The Kumbhathiruvathira and Meenathiruvathira were the famous festivals of Pattazhy. <s> The festival is known for Kambam (fire works), Aalpindi Vilakku Ezhunnallathu (Procession of small structure made out of plantain kernel and germinating leaves of coconut tree with numerous lamps on it), Ponnin Thirumudi (Devi's idol carved out of pure gold and rare precious stones) Ezhunnallathu. <s> Pattazhy also got a place in the Guinness Book of world records for the 'Longest bamboo'.

title: Lapiș Forest
complex: Lapiș Forest nature reserve IUCN category IV, is located in northwestern Romania, in the west of Sălaj County, near the village of Nușfalău, which is about 9 km from Șimleu Silvaniei. <s> The Forest Lapiș with an area of 430,40 ha was declared natural protected area by the Government Decision No.2151 in 2004 (published in "Romanian Official Paper" Number 152 on April 12, 2005) and is a relict of a much bigger cluster of ancient forests "Codrii Silvaniei".
simple: Lapiș Forest is a forest in northwestern Romania. <s> It is near the village of Nușfalău, which is about 9 km from Șimleu Silvaniei. <s> It was declared a natural protected area by the Government Decision No. 2151 in 2004 (publishied in "Romanian Official Paper" Number 152 on April 12, 2005)

title: Semione
complex: Semione is a former municipality in the district of Blenio in the canton of Ticino in Switzerland. <s> Since 15 March 2011, it is part of the municipality Serravalle. <s> The municipalities of Ludiano, Malvaglia and Semione merged on 15 March 2011 into the new municipality Serravalle.
simple: Semione is a former municipality of the district Blenio in the canton of Ticino in Switzerland. <s> On 1 April 2012 the former municipalities of Ludiano, Malvaglia and Semione merged to form the new municipality of Serravalle.

title: Pietro Anastasi
complex: Pietro Anastasi (] ; born 7 April 1948), nicknamed Petruzzu 'u turcu by fans, is a former Italian footballer who played mainly in the role of a striker. <s> Anastasi is regarded as one of the best Italian strikers of his generation, and he was a fast, reliable, and agile striker, with good reactions.
simple: Pietro Anastasi (born 7 April, 1948) is a former Italian football player.

title: Geoffrey (name)
complex: Geoffrey is a French and English masculine given name. <s> It is the Anglo-Norman form of the Germanic compound 'god' and 'peace'.
