title: Robert M. Pirsig
complex: Robert Maynard Pirsig ( ; September 6, 1928 – April 24, 2017) was an American writer and philosopher. <s> He was the author of the philosophical novels "Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance: An Inquiry into Values" (1974) and "" (1991). <s> Pirsig was born on September 6, 1928, in Minneapolis, Minnesota, the son of Harriet Marie Sjobeck and Maynard Pirsig. <s> He was of German and Swedish descent. <s> His father was a University of Minnesota Law School (UMLS) graduate who started teaching at the school in 1934. <s> The elder Pirsig served as the law school dean from 1948 to 1955, and retired from teaching at UMLS in 1970. <s> He resumed his career as a professor at the William Mitchell College of Law, where he remained until his final retirement in 1993. <s> Pirsig died aged 88, at his home in South Berwick, Maine, on April 24, 2017, after a period of failing health.
simple: Robert Maynard Pirsig (September 6, 1928 – April 24, 2017) was an American writer and philosopher. <s> They include: "" (1974) and "" (1991). <s> Pirsig was born in Minneapolis, Minnesota. <s> He died on April 24, 2017 at his home in South Berwick, Maine from a long-illness, aged 88.

title: Charlemagne Péralte
complex: Charlemagne Masséna Péralte (1886 - 1 November 1919) was a Haitian nationalist leader who opposed the US Invasion of his country in 1915. <s> Leading guerrilla fighters called the Cacos, he posed such a challenge to the US forces in Haiti that the occupying forces had to upgrade their presence in the country. <s> Péralte remains a highly praised hero in Haiti. <s> Born in 1886 in the central city of Hinche, Péralte was born into , (Péralte is a French version of the Spanish name Peralta). <s> Péralte is revered in Haiti as a national hero. <s> Name on birth certificate: François Borgia Charlemagne Peralte <s> Date of birth on birth certificate: 10 October 1885 <s> His father was General Remi Massena Peralte. <s> Source for correction: "1885–1985, Un Centenaire; Charlemagne Peralte,", Georges Michel. <s> Privately published in Port-au-Prince, 1989. <s> Cites research of Roger Gaillard concerning birth and baptismal certificates in "Premiere Ecrasement du Cacoism", Port-au-Prince:Le Natal, 1981. <s> Also appears in Douglas Henry Daniels's English translation of Michel's book,"Charlemagne Peralte and the First American Occupation." <s> Dubuque, Iowa: Kendall/Hunt Publishing CO., 1996. <s> An officer by career, Charlemagne Péralte was the military chief of the city of Léogane when the US Marines invaded Haiti in July 1915. <s> (See United States occupation of Haiti (1915–1934)) <s> Refusing to surrender to foreign troops without fighting, Péralte resigned from his position and returned to his native town of Hinche to take care of his family's land. <s> In 1917, he was arrested for a botched raid on the Hinche gendarmerie payroll, and was sentenced to five years of forced labor. <s> Escaping his captivity, Charlemagne Péralte gathered a group of nationalist rebels and started guerrilla warfare against the US troops. <s> The troops led by Péralte were called "Cacos", a name that harked back to rural troops that historically took part in the political turmoil of late 19th century Haiti. <s> The guerrilla warriors of the Cacos were such strong adversaries that the United States upgraded the US Marine contingent in Haiti and even employed airplanes for counter-guerrilla warfare. <s> His forces attacked Port-au-Prince in 1919, but were driven off. <s> After two years of guerrilla warfare, leading Péralte to declare a provisional government in the north of Haiti, Charlemagne Péralte was betrayed by one of his officers, Jean-Baptiste Conzé, who led disguised US Marines Sergeant Herman H. Hanneken (later meritoriously promoted to Second Lieutenant for his exploits) and Corporal William Button into the rebels camp, near Grand-Rivière Du Nord. <s> Péralte was shot in the heart at close range. <s> Hanneken and his men then fled with Peralte's body strapped onto a mule. <s> In order to discourage rebel support from the Haitian population, the US troops took a picture of Charlemagne Péralte's body tied to a door, and distributed it in the country. <s> However, it had the opposite effect, with the image's resemblance to a crucifixion making it an icon of the resistance and establishing Péralte as a martyr. <s> Charlemagne Péralte remains were unearthed after the end of the US occupation in 1935. <s> A national funeral, attended by the then-President of Haiti, Sténio Vincent, was held in Cap-Haïtien, where his grave can still be seen today. <s> A portrait of Charlemagne Péralte can now be seen on the Haitian coins issued by the government of Jean-Bertrand Aristide after his 1994 return under the protection of US troops.
simple: Charlemagne Masséna Péralte (1886 - 1 November 1919) was a leader in Haiti. <s> He stood against the US Invasion of his country in 1915. <s> He led fighters called the Cacos against the US forces in Haiti. <s> Péralte is a hero in Haiti today. <s> He was born in 1886 in the Hinche, His family had come from the Dominican Republic. <s> Name on birth certificate: François Borgia Charlemagne Peralte, Date of birth on birth certificate: 10 October 1885. <s> His father was General Remi Massena Peralte. <s> Source for correction: "1885–1985, Un Centenaire; Charlemagne Peralte,", Georges Michel. <s> Privately published in Port-au-Prince, 1989. <s> Cites research of Roger Gaillard concerning birth and baptismal certificates in "Premiere Ecrasement du Cacoism", Port-au-Prince:Le Natal, 1981. <s> Also appears in Douglas Henry Daniels's English translation of Michel's book,"Charlemagne Peralte and the First American Occupation." <s> Dubuque, Iowa: Kendall/Hunt Publishing CO., 1996. <s> An officer by career, Charlemagne Péralte was a military officer and chief of the city of Léogane when the US Marines invaded Haiti in July 1915. <s> (See United States occupation of Haiti (1915–1934)) He did not surrender to US troops without fighting, He quit his job and went home to Hinche to take care of his family's land. <s> In 1917, he was arrested. <s> Péralte's fighters were called "Cacos", a historic name of previous heroes. <s> The Cacos were strong fighters. <s> The "Cacos" attacked Port-au-Prince in 1919, but did not win. <s> He began a new a provisional government in the north of Haiti, He was betrayed by one of his officers, Jean-Baptiste Conzé. <s> The US soldier was Herman H. Hanneken and was promoted afterwards.Péralte was shot in the heart at close range. <s> The US troops took a picture of Charlemagne Péralte's body tied to a door. <s> The picture looked like the crucifixion and made Peralte a hero and a martyr. <s> The the then-President of Haiti, Sténio Vincent attended. <s> The funeral was held in Cap-Haïtien. <s> His grave can still be seen today. <s> A portrait of Charlemagne Péralte can now be seen on Haitian coins. <s> These coins were stamped by the government of Jean-Bertrand Aristide after his 1994 return.

title: Second-class citizen
complex: A second-class citizen is a person who is systematically discriminated against within a state or other political jurisdiction, despite their nominal status as a citizen or legal resident there. <s> While not necessarily slaves, outlaws or criminals, second-class citizens have limited legal rights, civil rights and socioeconomic opportunities, and are often subject to mistreatment or neglect at the hands of their putative superiors. <s> However, they are different from "less-than-whole citizens", as second-class citizens are often disregarded by the law or have it used to harass them (see police misconduct and racial profiling). <s> Systems with "de facto" second-class citizenry are generally regarded as violating human rights.
simple: A second-class citizen is a person who is discriminated by their nations system, even though they are classified as a citizen or legal resident to said nation. <s> Second-class citizenry is usually seen as a violation of human rights.

title: Pete Geren
complex: Preston Murdoch Geren, III, known as Pete Geren (born January 29, 1952) served as the 20th United States Secretary of the Army from July 16, 2007 to September 16, 2009. <s> He is a Democratic former member of the United States House of Representatives from Texas's 12th congressional district. <s> He is currently president of the Sid W. Richardson Foundation in Fort Worth, Texas and chair of the Institute for Defense Analyses in Alexandria, Virginia. <s> On July 29, 2005, Bush appointed Geren the acting United States Secretary of the Air Force, a position he served in until the confirmation of his successor Michael Wynne in November 2005.
simple: Preston M. Geren, III (born January 29, 1952 in Fort Worth, Texas) was the 20th United States Secretary of the Army from 16 July 2007 to 16 September 2009. <s> Geren was also a member of the United States House of Representatives from Texas. <s> He had already been acting United States Secretary of the Air Force, between 29 July 2005 and position he served in until the confirmation of his successor Michael Wynne on 4 November 2005.

title: Hose
complex: A hose is a flexible hollow tube designed to carry fluids from one location to another. <s> Hoses are also sometimes called "pipes" (the word "pipe" usually refers to a rigid tube, whereas a hose is usually a flexible one), or more generally "tubing". <s> The shape of a hose is usually cylindrical (having a circular cross section).
simple: A hose is a tube made to take fluids or gasses from one place to another. <s> Hoses are also called tube or pipes. <s> The shape of a hose is usually cylindrical.

title: Gladys Horton
complex: Gladys Catherine Horton (May 30, 1945 – January 26, 2011) (various sources cite her year of birth as 1944) was an American R&B and pop singer, famous for being the founder and lead singer of the popular Motown all-female vocal group The Marvelettes. <s> Born in Gainesville, Florida, she was raised in the western Detroit suburb of Inkster by foster parents. <s> By the time of her high school years at Inkster High School on Middlebelt Road, Gladys had taken a strong interest in singing, joining the high school glee club. <s> In 1960 Horton formed a group with her former highschool glee club members Georgeanna Tillman, Katherine Anderson and Juanita Cowart. <s> She also invited Georgia Dobbins to join her new group. <s> Gladys Horton died on January 26, 2011, in a nursing home in Sherman Oaks, California, following several strokes and years of declining health.
simple: Gladys Catherine Horton (May 30 – January 26, 2011) was an American R&B and pop musician. <s> She was the lead singer and founder of the all female group The Marvelettes. <s> Different sources say that she was born in 1943, 1944 or 1945. <s> She was raised in the Detroit area. <s> On 26 January 2011 she died in a Sherman Oaks nursing home. <s> Her death was from complications following a stroke.

title: T. V. R. Shenoy
complex: T. V. R Shenoy (10 June 1941 – 17 April 2018) was a journalist and columnist of India. <s> Shenoy had served as the Editor of the weekly news magazine "The Week" and "Sunday Mail" and held various posts in "Indian Express" and "Malayala Manorama". <s> He was a member of the Board of Trustees of India First Foundation. <s> He was awarded the Padma Bhushan award in 2003. <s> He died on 17 April 2018 at Manipal hospital, Mangalore
simple: T. V. R Shenoy (1941 – April 17, 2018) was an Indian journalist and columnist. <s> Shenoy had served as the editor of the weekly news magazine "The Week" and "Sunday Mail" and held many posts in "The Indian Express" and "Malayala Manorama". <s> He was a member of the Board of Trustees of India First Foundation. <s> He was awarded the Padma Bhushan award in 2003. <s> Shenoy died on April 17, 2018 at a hospital in Mangalore, India at the age of 77.

title: Green Lake County, Wisconsin
complex: Green Lake County is a county located in the U.S. state of Wisconsin. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 19,051. <s> Its county seat is Green Lake. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 380 sqmi , of which 349 sqmi are land and 31 sqmi (8.1%) are covered by water. <s> It is the third-smallest county in Wisconsin by total area. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 19,105 people, 7,703 households, and 5,322 families residing in the county. <s> The population density was 54 people per square mile (21/km2).
simple: Green Lake County is a county in the U.S. state of Wisconsin. <s> Its county seat is Green Lake. <s> The county has a total area of 380 sqmi. <s> Of this, 354 sqmi is land and 26 sqmi (6.87%) is water. <s> As of 2000, 19,105 people lived there.

title: Fishing trawler
complex: A fishing trawler is a commercial fishing vessel designed to operate fishing trawls. <s> Trawling is a method of fishing that involves actively dragging or pulling a trawl through the water behind one or more trawlers. <s> Trawls are fishing nets that are pulled along the bottom of the sea or in midwater at a specified depth.
simple: A fishing trawler is a commercial fishing vessel which controls fishing trawls. <s> Trawling is a way of fishing that involves pulling a trawl through the water behind one or more trawlers.

title: Prince of Orange
complex: Prince of Orange (or Princess of Orange if the holder is female) is a title originally associated with the sovereign Principality of Orange, in what is now southern France. <s> Under the Treaty of Utrecht of 1713, Frederick William I of Prussia ceded the Principality of Orange to King Louis XIV of France (while retaining the title as part of his dynastic titulature). <s> After William III of England died without children, a dispute arose between Johan Willem Friso and Frederick I of Prussia, which was settled in the Treaty of Partition (1732); consequently, Friso's son, William IV had to share use of the title "Prince of Orange" (which had accumulated prestige in the Netherlands and throughout the Protestant world) with Frederick William I of Prussia. <s> With the emergence of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, the title is traditionally borne by the heir apparent of the Dutch monarch. <s> Originally only worn by men, since 1983 the title descends via absolute primogeniture, which means that the holder can be either Prince or Princess of Orange. <s> The Dutch royal dynasty, the House of Orange-Nassau, is not the only family to claim the dynastical title. <s> Rival claims to the title have been made by German emperors and kings of the House of Hohenzollern and by the head of the French noble family of Mailly. <s> The current users of the title are Princess Catharina-Amalia of the Netherlands (Orange-Nassau), Georg Friedrich, Prince of Prussia (Hohenzollern), and Guy, Marquis de Mailly-Nesle (Mailly). <s> The title originally referred to Orange in the Vaucluse department in the Rhone valley of southern France, which was a property of the House of Orange, then of the House of Baux and the House of Châlon-Arlay before passing in 1544 to the House of Orange-Nassau. <s> The last descendant of the original princes, René of Châlon, left the principality to his cousin William the Silent, who was not a descendant of the original Orange family but the heir to the principality of Orange by testament, however in violation against the inheritance pattern enacted by the last will of Marie des Baux, the Princess of Orange through kinship to whom Prince René derived his own right thereto. <s> In 1673, Louis XIV of France annexed all territory of the principality to France and to the royal domain, as part of the war actions against the stadtholder William III of Orange — who later became King William III of Great Britain. <s> Orange ceased to exist as a sovereign realm, de facto. <s> After the marquis (who died in 1713), the next holder was , marquis de Nesle (1689–1764). <s> Although no longer descended from Louis-Charles, a branch of the Mailly family still claim the title today. <s> In 1714 Louis XIV bestowed the usufruct of the principality on his kinsman, Louis Armand of Bourbon, Prince de Conti. <s> After his death in 1727 the principality was deemed merged in the Crown by 1731. <s> Because William III died without legitimate children, the principality was regarded as having been inherited by his closest cognate relative on the basis of the testament of Frederic-Henry, Frederick I of Prussia, who ceded the principality — at least the lands, but not the formal title — to France in 1713. <s> France supported his claim. <s> In this way, the territory of the principality lost its feudal and secular privileges and became a part of France. <s> The Treaty of Utrecht allowed the King of Prussia to erect part of the duchy of Gelderland (the cities of Geldern, Straelen and Wachtendonk with their bailiwicks, Krickenbeck, Viersen, the land of Kessel, the lordships of Afferden, Arcen-Velden-Lomm, Walbeck-Twisteden, Raay and Klein-Kevelaer, Well, Bergen and Middelaar) into a new "Principality of Orange". <s> The kings of Prussia and the German emperors styled themselves Princes of Orange till 1918. <s> An agnatic relative of William III, John William Friso of Nassau, who was also cognatically descended from William the Silent, was designated the heir to the princes of Orange in the Netherlands by the last will of William III. <s> Several of his descendants became stadtholders. <s> They claim the principality of Orange on the basis of agnatic inheritance, similar to that of William the Silent, who had inherited Orange from his cousin René of Châlon. <s> They did however have a claim, albeit distant, to the principality itself due to John William Friso's descent from Louise de Coligny, who was a descendant of the original Princes of Orange. <s> (Louise's great grandmother, Anne Pot, Countess of St. Pol, was a descendant of Tiburge d'Orange, who married into the des Baux family) <s> They also claimed on the basis of the testament of Philip William, Maurice and William III. <s> Finally, they claimed on the basis that Orange was an independent state whose sovereign had the right to assign his succession according to his will. <s> France never recognized any of this, nor allowed the Orange-Nassaus or the Hohenzollerns to obtain anything of the principality itself. <s> The Oranje-Nassaus nevertheless assumed the title and also erected several of their lordships into a new principality of Orange. <s> From that derivation of the title comes the tradition of the house of Nassau-Dietz, the later stadtholders of the Netherlands, and the present-day royal family of the Netherlands, of holding this title. <s> They maintain the tradition of William the Silent and the house of Orange-Nassau. <s> Until 1340, it was customary for all sons of the prince of Orange to inherit the title. <s> Only the direct line of descent to Raimond V is shown here. <s> William of Nassau inherited the principality of Orange from his cousin René.
simple: Prince of Orange is a title of nobility. <s> The title was at first related to a self-ruling state called the Principality of Orange. <s> At the moment, the title is used by Prince Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands (Orange-Nassau), Georg Friedrich, Prince of Prussia (Hohenzollern) and Guy, Marquis de Mailly-Neslé, Prince d'Orange. <s> The land was the property of the house of Orange and from 1544 of the house of Orange-Nassau. <s> The last of the original princes, René of Nassau, left the principality to his cousin William the Silent after he died. <s> William the Silent was not related to the original house of Orange, but was the legal heir. <s> In a war in 1673, Louis XIV of France took over the lands of the principality and added them to his own royal domain. <s> This was part of the war against the stadtholder William III of Orange. <s> His descendant still claims the title today. <s> In 1714, Louis XIV allowed Prince Louis Armand of Bourbon-Conti to use the land of the Principality to make money. <s> Prince Louis Armand died in 1727 and the principality was merged in the Crown in 1731. <s> William III died without legitimate children. <s> This meant that the principality was seen as inherited by his closest cognate relative on the basis of the testament of Frederic-Henry, Frederick I of Prussia . <s> He handed over the principality's lands but not the title to France in 1713. <s> France supported his claim. <s> In this way, the territory of the principality was no longer a separate state, but became a part of France. <s> Through the Treaty of Utrecht. <s> The kings of Prussia and the German emperors styled themselves Princes of Orange till 1918. <s> John William Friso of Nassau was chosen as the heir to the princes of Orange in the Netherlands by the last will of William III. <s> Several of his descendants became stadtholders. <s> They claim the principality of Orange on the basis of agnatic inheritance (inheritance of lands to the brother rather than the sons of the king) . <s> This way of inheriting is similar to the way William the Silent inherited from his cousin René. <s> The claim to the title is also on basis of the testament of Philips William, Maurice and William III. <s> Although they claimed the title "Prince of Orange", France never allowed them to obtain anything of the lands of the principality itself. <s> It is from this tradition that later stadtholders of the Netherlands, and the present-day royal family of the Netherlands, also hold the title. <s> Until 1340, it was customary for all sons of the prince of Orange to inherit the title. <s> Only the direct line of descent to Raimond V is shown here.

title: Dexter (TV series)
complex: Dexter is an American television crime drama mystery series that aired on Showtime from October 1, 2006, to September 22, 2013. <s> Set in Miami, the series centers on Dexter Morgan (Michael C. Hall), a forensic technician specializing in blood spatter pattern analysis for the fictional Miami Metro Police Department, who leads a secret parallel life as a vigilante serial killer, hunting down murderers who have slipped through the cracks of the justice system. <s> The show's first season was derived from the novel "Darkly Dreaming Dexter" (2004), the first in a series of novels by Jeff Lindsay. <s> It was adapted for television by screenwriter James Manos Jr., who wrote the first episode.
simple: Dexter is an American television series that was shown on Showtime network. <s> The show tells a story about a serial killer, Dexter Morgan, who works as a forensics analyst for the police in Miami. <s> It is based on the book "Darkly Dreaming Dexter" written by Jeff Lindsay.

title: Defenceman
complex: Defence (defense in the USA) in ice hockey is a player position whose primary responsibility is to prevent the opposing team from scoring. <s> They are often referred to as defencemen, D, D-men or blueliners (the latter a reference to the blue line in ice hockey which represents the boundary of the offensive zone; defencemen generally position themselves along the line to keep the puck in the zone). <s> They were once called cover-point. <s> A good defenceman is both strong in defensive and offensive play and for defenceman pairing also need to be good at defending and attacking. <s> In regular play, two defencemen complement three forwards and a goaltender on the ice. <s> Exceptions include overtime during the regular season and when a team is shorthanded (i.e. has been assessed a penalty), in which two defencemen are typically joined by only two forwards and a goaltender; in National Hockey League play in overtime effective with the 2015-16 season the teams have only three position players and a goaltender on the ice and may use either two forwards and one defenceman (typically), or conversely, two defencemen and one forward.
simple: Defence (defense in the U.S.) in ice hockey is a player position whose main job is to stop the other team from scoring. <s> They are often called defencemen, defensemen, D, or "blueliners" (a reference to the blue line in ice hockey which is boundary of the offensive zone; defencemen generally stay along the line to keep the puck in the zone). <s> In regular play, two defencemen play with three forwards and a goaltender on the ice. <s> Exceptions include overtime and when a team is shorthanded (i.e. has been assessed a penalty), in which two defencemen are typically joined by only two forwards and a goaltender.

title: Toucan
complex: Toucans are primarily frugivorous (fruit eating), but are opportunistically omnivorous and will take prey such as insects, smaller birds, and small lizards. <s> Captive toucans have been reported to hunt insects actively in their cages, and it is possible to keep toucans on an insect-only diet.
simple: They mostly eat fruit, but sometimes they also eat insects and small lizards.

title: Xiluodu Dam
complex: The Xiluodu Dam is an arch dam on the Jinsha River, i.e. the upper course of the Yangtze in China. <s> It is located near the town of Xiluodu in Yongshan County of Yunnan Province but the dam straddles into Leibo County of Sichuan Province on the opposite side of the river. <s> The primary purpose of the dam is hydroelectric power generation and its power station has an installed capacity of 13,860 MW. <s> Additionally, the dam provides for flood control, silt control and its regulated water releases are intended to improve navigation downstream. <s> Construction on the dam and power station began in 2005 and the first generator was commissioned in 2013, the last in 2014. <s> It is operated by China Yangtze Power and is currently the third-largest power station with the fourth-tallest dam in the world.
simple: The Xiluodu Dam is a hydroelectric dam on the Yangtze River in China. <s> It is near the town of Xiluohu in Yunnan Province. <s> One of the largest of its kind in the world, construction began in 2005 and the dam was put into use in 2013.

title: Margaret Court
complex: Margaret Court (née Smith; born 16 July 1942), also known as Margaret Smith Court, is a retired Australian tennis player and former world No. 1. <s> She amassed more major titles than any other player in history and is considered as one of the greatest tennis players of all time. <s> She is currently a Christian minister in Perth, Western Australia. <s> In 1970, Court became the first woman during the Open era (and the second woman in history after Maureen Connolly) to win the singles Grand Slam (all four major tournaments in the same calendar year). <s> She won 24 of those titles (11 in the Open era), a record that still stands. <s> She also won 19 women's doubles and 21 mixed doubles titles, giving her a record 64 major titles overall.
simple: Margaret Court (née Smith; born 16 July 1942), also known as Margaret Smith Court, is a retired Australian tennis player and former world #1. <s> That is more than any other player in history. <s> She is currently a Christian minister in Perth, Western Australia. <s> In tennis, she won 24 major titles (11 in the open era).

title: Saintes, Charente-Maritime
complex: Saintes (] ) is a commune and historic town in southwestern France, in the Charente-Maritime department of which it is a sub-prefecture, in Nouvelle-Aquitaine. <s> Its inhabitants are called "Saintaises" and "Saintais". <s> Saintes is the second-largest city in Charente-Maritime, with inhabitants in 2008. <s> Its immediate surrounds form the second-most populous metropolitan area in the department, with inhabitants, the majority of which is fertile, productive fields; a significant minority of the region remains forest, its natural state. <s> Saintes is on the banks of the Charente River, in the center-eastern part of the department. <s> The city is centred 60 km southeast of La Rochelle, 33 kilometers northeast of Royan and about 100 km north of Bordeaux (to which it is linked by the A10 autoroute).
simple: Saintes is a French commune and historic town, a subprefecture in the Charente-Maritime department in southwestern France. <s> It is in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region. <s> The inhabitants of this city are known, in French, as "Saintais" (women: "Saintaises"). <s> Saintes is in the central eastern part of the Charente-Maritime department, in the old province of Saintonge, along the Charente river that flows through the "commune" from south to north.

title: Peer, Belgium
complex: Peer is a municipality located in the province of Limburg, Flemish Region, Belgium. <s> On January 1, 2006, Peer had a total population of 15,810.
simple: Peer is a municipality in the Belgian province of Limburg.

title: Meulles
complex: Meulles is a former commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France. <s> On 1 January 2016, it was merged into the new commune of Livarot-Pays-d'Auge.
simple: Meulles is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Golden eagle
complex: The golden eagle ("Aquila chrysaetos") is one of the best-known birds of prey in the Northern Hemisphere. <s> It is the most widely distributed species of eagle. <s> Like all eagles, it belongs to the family Accipitridae. <s> These birds are dark brown, with lighter golden-brown plumage on their napes. <s> Immature eagles of this species typically have white on the tail and often have white markings on the wings. <s> Golden eagles use their agility and speed combined with powerful feet and massive, sharp talons to snatch up a variety of prey, mainly hares, rabbits, and marmots and other ground squirrels. <s> Once widespread across the Holarctic, it has disappeared from many areas which are now more heavily populated by humans. <s> Despite being extirpated from or uncommon in some of its former range, the species is still widespread, being present in sizeable stretches of Eurasia, North America, and parts of North Africa. <s> It is the largest and least populous of the five species of true accipitrid to occur as a breeding species in both the Palearctic and the Nearctic.
simple: The golden eagle ("Aquila chrysaetos") is one of the best-known birds of prey in the northern hemisphere. <s> It is the most widely distributed species of eagle. <s> Like all eagles, it belongs to the family Accipitridae. <s> Golden eagles use their agility and speed combined with powerful feet and massive, sharp talons to snatch up prey. <s> They eat hares, rabbits, marmots and other ground squirrels. <s> Once common across the Holarctic, it has gone from many areas heavily populated by humans. <s> The species is still widespread. <s> It lives in Eurasia, North America, and parts of North Africa.

title: Blue-green
complex: Blue-green is a color that is a representation of the color that is between green and blue on a typical traditional old-fashioned RYB color wheel. <s> "Blue-green" belongs to the cyan family of colors.
simple: Blue-green is a color that is a deep tone of cyan.

title: Domingos da Guia
complex: Domingos Antônio da Guia (born in Rio de Janeiro, November 19, 1912 – died in Rio, May 18, 2000) was a Brazilian footballer.
simple: Domingos da Guia (born 19 November, 1912) is a former Brazilian football player.

title: Saint-Gilles-Croix-de-Vie
complex: Saint-Gilles-Croix-de-Vie is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Saint-Gilles-Croix-de-Vie is a commune. <s> It is found in the Pays de la Loire region in the Vendée department in the west of France.

title: Arrondissement of Villeneuve-sur-Lot
complex: The arrondissement of Villeneuve-sur-Lot is an arrondissement of France in the Lot-et-Garonne department in the Nouvelle Aquitaine région. <s> It has 92 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Villeneuve-sur-Lot is an arrondissement of France. <s> It is part of the Lot-et-Garonne "département" in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region. <s> When the Lot-et-Garonne department was created on 17 February 1800, the "arrondissement" of Villeneuve-sur-Lot was part of that original department. <s> The "arrondissement" of Villeneuve-sur-Lot is in the northeast of Lot-et-Garonne, with an area of 1559.7 km2, the largest "arrondissement" of the department.

title: Anne Marie d'Orléans
complex: Anne Marie d'Orléans (27 August 1669 – 26 August 1728) was the first Queen consort of Sardinia by marriage to Victor Amadeus II of Savoy. <s> She served as regent of Savoy during the absence of her spouse in 1686 and during the War of the Spanish Succession. <s> She is also an important figure in British history (see Jacobite Succession below). <s> She was the daughter of Philippe I, Duke of Orléans, younger brother of Louis XIV, and Henrietta of England, the youngest daughter of Charles I of England. <s> Her mother died at the "Château de Saint-Cloud" ten months after Anne Marie's birth. <s> A year later, her father married 19-year-old Elizabeth Charlotte of the Palatinate, who became very close to her stepdaughters. <s> Her half-brother Philippe II, Duke of Orléans, the future regent of France, was born of her father's second marriage. <s> Her stepmother later described her as "one of the most amiable and virtuous of women". <s> The proxy marriage of Anne Marie and Víctor Amadeus took place at Versailles on 10 April 1684, the day after the signature of the marriage contract. <s> Her husband-to-be was represented by her cousin, Louis Auguste, Duke of Maine. <s> Louis XIV gave her a dowry of 900,000 "livres". <s> The Duke of Orléans accompanied his daughter as far as Juvisy-sur-Orge (18 kilometers south of Paris), and the comtesse de Lillebonne accompanied her all the way to Savoy. <s> She met her husband Victor at Chambéry on 6 May, the nuptials being performed at the castle by the Archbishop of Grenoble. <s> Two days later, the newlyweds made their "Joyous Entry" into Turin. <s> This marriage was arranged with the assistance of the maréchal de Tessé and of Jeanne Baptiste d'Albert de Luynes, comtesse de Verrué, who was Victor's mistress from 1689 till 1700. <s> Her husband had two children with Jeanne. <s> Nonetheless, when he fell ill with smallpox, Anne Marie nursed him until his recovery. <s> Despite his marriage ties to France, Victor Amadeus joined the anti-French side in the War of the Spanish Succession. <s> Anne Marie was appointed by him to serve as regent of Savoy during his absence in the war, a task she handled with maturity and judgement. <s> In 1706, Turin was besieged by French forces under the command of Anne Marie's half-brother Philippe d'Orléans, and Spanish forces of her cousin and son-in-law Philip V. <s> She and her sons Victor Amadeus and Carlo Emanuele were forced to flee to Genoa. <s> When the war was ended in 1713 by the Treaty of Utrecht, Victor Amadeus received the Kingdom of Sicily, formerly a Spanish possession. <s> Anne Marie's stepmother wrote: "I shall neither gain nor lose by the peace, but one thing I shall enjoy is to see our Duchess of Savoy become a queen, because I love her as though she were my own child ..." When Victor Amadeus left for his coronation in Sicily, he had originally planned to leave Anne Marie behind to function as regent in his absence, but as he feared that she would let herself be directed by his mother because of her loyalty to her, he changed his mind and took her along with him instead. <s> Anne Marie was crowned with him in Sicily. <s> At the death of her eldest son in 1715, both she and Victor Amadeus fell into severe depression and left the capital to mourn, leaving Marie Jeanne to handle their official duties. <s> Victor Amadeus was forced to exchange Sicily for the less important domain of Sardinia in 1720, but retained the title of King. <s> As the Savoyard consort, Anne-Marie had the use of the Royal Palace of Turin, the vast Palazzina di caccia di Stupinigi outside the capital, and the Vigna di Madama Reale. <s> Queen Anne Marie died of heart failure at her villa on 26 August 1728, the day before her 59th birthday. <s> She is buried at the Basilica of Superga in Turin, where all her children, except Marie-Adélaïde and Maria Luisa, are also buried. <s> From 1714 to 1720, Anne Marie d'Orléans was the heiress presumptive to the Jacobite claim to the thrones of England, Scotland, and Ireland. <s> These claims were held at the time by James Francis Edward Stuart ("the Old Pretender", son of James II). <s> Anne Marie became heiress presumptive with the death of James' daughter Queen Anne in 1714. <s> She was displaced as heir by the birth of the Old Pretender's son, Charles Edward Stuart ("Bonnie Prince Charlie"), on 31 December 1720. <s> Charles Edward and his brother Henry, Cardinal Stuart, both died without legitimate issue, so the descendants of Anne Marie d'Orléans inherited the Jacobite claim, i.e. they would have inherited the British crown had it not been for the Act of Settlement, which excluded the claims of the Catholic Stuarts and d'Orléans' and settled the throne on the nearest Protestant relatives, the Hanoverians.
simple: Anne Marie d'Orléans (27 August 1669 - 26 August 1728) was a niece of Louis XIV and was the wife of Victor Amadeus II of Sardinia. <s> She was born at the Château de Saint-Cloud. <s> Her mother died when she was ten months old. <s> A year later, her father remarried Elizabeth Charlotte of the Palatinate. <s> Her half-brother Philippe d'Orléans, the future Regent of France. <s> Her stepmother described her as "one of the most amiable and virtuous of women". <s> Anne Marie d'Orléans' proxy marriage to Víctor Amadeus II took place at Versailles on 10 April 1684. <s> Louis XIV gave her a dowry of 900,000 "livres". <s> She met her husband at Chambéry the following 6 May which were followed by another wedding ceremony. <s> Her husband had two further children with Jeanne Baptiste d'Albert de Luynes, his mistress from 1689 till 1700. <s> Nonetheless, when he fell ill with smallpox, she nursed him until his recovery. <s> In 1706, during the siege of Turin by French forces under the command of her half-brother Philippe d'Orléans, and Spanish forces from her cousin Philip V of Spain, she and her sons, Victor Amadeus and Carlo Emanuele, were forced to flee the city. <s> As a result of his aid in the War of the Spanish Succession Victor Amadeus II was made King of Sicily in 1713 under the Treaty of Utrecht which ended the war. <s> However Victor Amadeus II was forced to exchange Sicily for the less important kingdom of Sardinia in 1720. <s> As queen, Anne Marie used the Royal Palace of Turin as well as the Villa della Regina which was her own property. <s> Queen Anne Marie died of heart failure at her villa on 26 August 1728, the day before her 59th birthday. <s> She is today buried at the Basilica of Superga in Turin being moved there in 1786 by her son Victor Amadeus III. <s> From 1714 to 1720, Anne Marie d'Orléans was the heiress presumptive to the Jacobite claim to the thrones of England, Scotland, and Ireland. <s> These claims were held at the time by James Francis Edward Stuart (son of James II) upon the death of his half-sister, Queen Anne. <s> Anne Marie was displaced as his heir by the birth of the Old Pretender's son, Charles Edward Stuart ("Bonnie Prince Charlie") in December 1720.

title: John Finnegan (actor)
complex: John P. "J.P." Finnegan (August 18, 1926 – July 29, 2012) was an American film and television actor, mostly known for his recurrent role on the American crime fiction series "Columbo". <s> He voiced the villainous character Warren T. Rat in the 1986 Don Bluth film "An American Tail". <s> Finnegan died on July 29, 2012 at his home in Palm Desert, California from complications of pneumonia, aged 85.
simple: John P. Finnegan (August 18, 1926 – July 29, 2012) was an American television, voice, stage, and movie actor. <s> He died on July 29, 2012 from pneumonia and old age in his home in Palm Desert, California, aged 85.

title: British Rail Class 46
complex: The British Rail Class 46 is a class of diesel locomotive. <s> They were built from 1961–1963 at British Railways' Derby Works and were initially numbered D138–D193. <s> With the arrival of TOPS they were renumbered to Class 46. <s> Fifty-six locomotives were built. <s> The first was withdrawn in 1977 and all of them were withdrawn by the end of 1984. <s> The Class 46 design was structurally the same as the preceding Class 45 build, and had the same Sulzer engine, but differed in the fitment of a Brush generator and traction motors, in place of the Crompton Parkinson equipment fitted to the Class 45. <s> Along with the other Sulzer class 44 and 45 designs they are often referred to as "Peaks", so named because the earliest of the Class 44 were named after mountains.
simple: The British Rail Class 46 is a class of diesel locomotive. <s> They were built from 1961-1963 at British Railways' Derby Works and were initially numbered D138-D193. <s> With the arrival of TOPS computer system they were renumbered to Class 46. <s> Fifty-six locomotives were built. <s> The first was withdrawn in 1977 and all of them were withdrawn by 1984. <s> The Class 46 design was structurally the same as the earlier Class 45 build, and had the same Sulzer engine. <s> It differed in the fitment of a Brush generator and traction motors, in place of the Crompton Parkinson equipment fitted to the Class 45.

title: Tooting
complex: Tooting is a district of South London, England, forming part of the London Borough of Wandsworth and partly in the London Borough of Merton. <s> It is located 5 mi south south-west of Charing Cross.
simple: Tooting is a suburb in the London Borough of Wandsworth in south London. <s> It is 5 mi south south-west of Charing Cross.

title: Fran Mérida
complex: Francisco Mérida Pérez (] ; born 4 March 1990) is a Spanish professional footballer who plays as a central midfielder for CA Osasuna.
simple: Fran Mérida (born 4 March 1990) is a Spanish football player.

title: Chromium(III) chloride
complex: The hydrated chlorides are prepared by treatment of chromate with hydrochloric acid and methanol. <s> In laboratory the hydrates are usually prepared by dissolving the chromium metal or chromium(III) oxide in hydrochloric acid.
simple: It can be formed by dissolving chromium in hydrochloric acid or by dissolving chromium(III) oxide in hydrochloric acid.

title: MV Rachel Corrie
complex: MV "Rachel Corrie" is a 499 GT coaster owned and operated by the Free Gaza Movement. <s> The ship is named in honour of Rachel Corrie, a deceased member of the International Solidarity Movement. <s> Built by J.J. Sietas in Hamburg in 1967, she was originally named "Carsten"; she has also carried the names "Norasia Attika", "Manya" and more recently "Linda". <s> In June 2010 the vessel was intercepted by Israeli Defence Forces while attempting to break the Israeli blockade of the Gaza Strip and to deliver humanitarian aid.
simple: MV "Rachel Corrie" is a ship that is owned and operated by the Free Gaza Movement. <s> The ship is named in honour of Rachel Corrie, a former member of the International Solidarity Movement. <s> It was built by J.J. Sietas in Hamburg in 1967, and was originally named "Carsten". <s> it has also carried the names "Norasia Attika", "Manya" and more recently "Linda". <s> In June 2010, the ship was boarded by Israeli Defence Forces while it was trying to deliver humanitarian aid to the Gaza Strip.

title: Arthur Blythe
complex: Arthur Murray Blythe (July 5, 1940 – March 27, 2017) was an American jazz alto saxophonist and composer. <s> He was described by critic Chris Kelsey as displaying "one of the most easily recognizable alto sax sounds in jazz, big and round, with a fast, wide vibrato and an aggressive, precise manner of phrasing" and furthermore as straddling the avant garde and traditionalist jazz, often with bands featuring unusual instrumentation. <s> Born in Los Angeles, Blythe lived in San Diego, returning to Los Angeles when he was 19 years old. <s> He took up the alto saxophone at the age of nine, playing R&B until his mid-teens when he discovered jazz. <s> In the mid-1960s, Blythe was part of The Underground Musicians and Artists Association (UGMAA), founded by Horace Tapscott, on whose 1969 "The Giant Is Awakened" he made his recording debut. <s> Blythe died from complications of Parkinson's disease in Lancaster, California, at the age of 76.
simple: Arthur Blythe (July 5, 1940 – March 27, 2017) was an American jazz alto saxophonist and composer. <s> He was born in Los Angeles, California. <s> Blythe died of Parkinson's disease at his home in Los Angeles on March 27, 2017, aged 76.

title: Mara Wilson
complex: Mara Elizabeth Wilson (born July 24, 1987) is an American actress, voice actress, stage actress, and writer. <s> As a child, she rose to prominence after landing the role as Natalie Hillard in "Mrs. Doubtfire" (1993), having only acted in commercials previously. <s> Wilson also portrayed the role of Susan Walker in "Miracle on 34th Street" (1994), Matilda Wormwood in "Matilda" (1996), and Lily Stone in "Thomas and the Magic Railroad" (2000). <s> Since retiring from acting in 2000, Wilson has focused on writing and appeared in numerous podcasts. <s> Wilson was born in Burbank, California. <s> She is the oldest daughter of Mike Wilson, a television broadcast engineer at KTLA-TV News and the late Suzie Shapiro Wilson, a homemaker and Burbank PTA school volunteer.
simple: Mara Elizabeth Wilson (born July 24, 1987 in Los Angeles, California) is an American actress and playwright. <s> Her best known movies include "Mrs. Doubtfire" (1993), "Matilda" (1996) and Lily Stone in "Thomas and the Magic Railroad" (2000). <s> She was born in Los Angeles.

title: Kings Island
complex: Kings Island is a 364 acre amusement park located 24 mi northeast of Cincinnati in Mason, Ohio. <s> Owned and operated by Cedar Fair, the park first opened in 1972 by the Taft Broadcasting Company. <s> It was part of a larger effort to move and expand Coney Island, a popular resort destination along the banks of the Ohio River that was prone to frequent flooding. <s> After more than $300 million in capital investments, the park features over 100 attractions including fourteen roller coasters and a 33 acre water park. <s> Less than two years after breaking ground, Kings Island opened its gates to the public on April 29, 1972. <s> It was the first of several preview events.
simple: Kings Island is the name of an amusememt park in Mason, Ohio. <s> The park is owned and operated by the Cedar Fair company. <s> The park opened to the public on April 29, 1972.

simple: Skatval is a small village in the municipality called Stjørdal in the province Nord-Trøndelag, Norway.

title: Yami Lester
complex: James Yami Lester (1941 – 21 July 2017) was a Yankunytjatjara man, an Indigenous person of northern South Australia. <s> Lester, who survived nuclear testing in outback Australia, is best known as an anti-nuclear and indigenous rights advocate. <s> In the 1950s, while still a young boy, he was blinded by a "black mist" from the south. <s> His actions helped lead to the McClelland Royal Commission in 1985, which found significant radiation hazards still existed at the Maralinga test sites. <s> Recommendations included group compensation for the Maralinga Tjarutja people and an extensive, long-term cleanup operation to restore the land. <s> He retired to his traditional home at Walatina Station near Marla in the far north of South Australia. <s> He died on 21 July 2017 in Alice Springs at the age of 75.T <s> The passing of Yami Lester was a sad event for the aboriginal community but his legacy and impact still lives on in through the lives of his relatives, this includes Kate Lester.
simple: Yami Lester ( 1942 – 21 July 2017) is an Australian Yankunytjatjara man, an Indigenous person of northern South Australia. <s> He was born in Lester, who survived nuclear testing in outback Australia is best known as an anti-nuclear and Indigenous rights advocate. <s> In the 1950s, while still a young boy, he was blinded by a "black mist" from the south. <s> His actions helped lead to the McClelland Royal Commission in 1985, which found significant radiation hazards still existed at the Maralinga test sites. <s> Lester died in Alice Springs, Australia from complications of a stroke on 21 July 2017 at the age of 75.

title: Hiep Thi Le
complex: Hiep Thi Le ( ; February 18, 1971 – December 19, 2017) was a Vietnamese-American actress and restaurateur. <s> She is perhaps best known for her role in the film "Heaven & Earth" (1993). <s> Le subsequently appeared in "Bugis Street" (1995, released in the United States in 1997) and co-starred in the little-seen "Dead Man Can't Dance" (1997). <s> Le made an appearance in the 1999 film "Bastards". <s> On February 23, 2014, Le appeared on the Food Network game show "Chopped", competing in the eighteenth-season episode "Beer Here!" <s> While she advanced past the appetizer round over private chef Larry Monaco, she was eliminated in the entrée round after serving undercooked beef to judges Scott Conant, Chris Santos, and guest judge Greg Koch, as well as not using enough beer cheese in her dish. <s> Le died on December 19, 2017 in Los Angeles from stomach cancer at the age of 46. <s> Despite having a fairly short resume, she was acknowledged in the "In Memoriam" segment at the 90th Academy Awards.
simple: Hiep Thi Le (; November 30, 1971 – December 19, 2017) was a Vietnamese-American actress. <s> She was known for her role in "Heaven & Earth" (1993). <s> She appeared in "Bugis Street" (1995, released in the United States in 1997) and co-starred in the little-scene "Dead Man Can't Dance" (1997). <s> On February 23, 2014, Le appeared on the Food Network game show "Chopped", appearing and competing in the eighteenth-season episode "Beer Here!". <s> Le died on December 19, 2017 in Los Angeles, California from stomach cancer at the age of 46.

title: Phil Crane
complex: Philip Miller Crane (November 3, 1930 – November 8, 2014) was an American politician. <s> He was a Republican member of the United States House of Representatives from 1969 to 2005, representing the 8th District of Illinois in the northwestern suburbs of Chicago. <s> At the time of his defeat in the 2004 election, Crane was the longest-serving Republican member of the House. <s> Crane was born in Chicago, Illinois, the son of Cora Ellen (née Miller) and George Washington Crane III, a physician and college professor. <s> Crane died of lung cancer at the home of his daughter, Rebekah, in Jefferson, Maryland on November 8, 2014, five days after his 84th birthday.
simple: Philip Miller "Phil" Crane (November 3, 1930 – November 8, 2014) was a former American politician. <s> He was a Republican member of the United States House of Representatives from 1969 to 2005. <s> He was representing the 8th District of Illinois in the northwestern suburbs of Chicago. <s> At the time of his defeat in the 2004 election, Crane was the longest-serving Republican member of the House. <s> Crane was born in Chicago, Illinois on November 3, 1930. <s> Crane died of lung cancer at the home of his daughter, Rebekah, in Jefferson, Maryland on November 8, 2014, aged 84.

title: 2016 Nice truck attack
complex: On the evening of 14 July 2016, a 19-tonne cargo truck was deliberately driven into crowds of people celebrating Bastille Day on the Promenade des Anglais in Nice, France, resulting in the deaths of 86 people and the injury of 458 others. <s> The driver was Mohamed Lahouaiej-Bouhlel, a Tunisian resident of France. <s> The attack ended following an exchange of gunfire, during which Lahouaiej-Bouhlel was shot and killed by police.
simple: The 2016 Nice attack happened on 14 July 2016 in Nice, France. <s> A truck drove into people celebrating Bastille Day, the national day of France. <s> The driver, Tunisian truck driver Mohamed Lahouaiej-Bouhlel, was killed by police.

title: Paul Eisler
complex: Paul Eisler (1907 – 26 October 1992, London) was an Austrian inventor born in Vienna. <s> Among his innovations were the printed circuit board. <s> In 2012, "Printed Circuit Design & Fab" magazine named its Hall of Fame after Eisler. <s> He graduated in engineering from Vienna University of Technology in 1930. <s> Being Jewish, antisemitic German-Nationalist organizations prevented him from getting an engineering job in Vienna, so he obtained employment with the English recording technology firm (Gramaphone Company, EMI from March 1931) operating under its His Master's Voice brand in Belgrade. <s> His task there was to eliminate radio interference on the music broadcast system on trains running from Belgrade to Niś. <s> The project was a technical success but a financial failure because the Serbian railroad could only pay HMV by barter in grain, not pounds sterling, due a foreign exchange crisis.
simple: Paul Eisler (1907 - 26 October 1992) was an Austrian inventor. <s> Eisler was born in Vienna, Austria. <s> He invented the modern circuit board. <s> He invented the modern circuit board. <s> He was a student at Vienna University of Technology. <s> German nationalists would not let Eisler get a job in Vienna, because he was Jewish. <s> He got a job with an English company (Gramaphone Company, EMI from March 1931). <s> He removed interference from music broadcast on trains.

title: Child abuse
complex: Child abuse or child maltreatment is physical, sexual, and/or psychological maltreatment or neglect of a child or children, especially by a parent or a caregiver. <s> Child abuse may include any act or failure to act by a parent or a caregiver that results in actual or potential harm to a child, and can occur in a child's home, or in the organizations, schools or communities the child interacts with. <s> The World Health Organization (WHO) defines "child abuse" and "child maltreatment" as "all forms of physical and/or emotional ill-treatment, sexual abuse, neglect or negligent treatment or commercial or other exploitation, resulting in actual or potential harm to the child's health, survival, development or dignity in the context of a relationship of responsibility, trust or power." <s> In the United States, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) uses the term "child maltreatment" to refer to both acts of commission (abuse), which include "words or overt actions that cause harm, potential harm, or threat of harm to a child", and acts of omission (neglect), meaning "the failure to provide for a child's basic physical, emotional, or educational needs or to protect a child from harm or potential harm". <s> The United States federal Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act defines "child abuse and neglect" as, at minimum, "any recent act or failure to act on the part of a parent or caretaker which results in death, serious physical or emotional harm, sexual abuse or exploitation" or "an act or failure to act which presents an imminent risk of serious harm". <s> Many children who have been abused in any form develop some sort of psychological problem. <s> These problems may include: anxiety, depression, eating disorders, OCD, co-dependency, or even a lack of human connections. <s> There is also a slight tendency for children who have been abused to become child abusers themselves. <s> In the U.S. in 2013, of the 294,000 reported child abuse cases only 81,124 received any sort of counseling or therapy. <s> Treatment is greatly important for abused children.
simple: Child abuse is the abuse, mistreatment or hurt done by adults to children. <s> It often means abuse done by a child's parents or another caregiver. <s> The World Health Organization (WHO) defines "child abuse" and "child maltreatment" as "all forms of physical and/or emotional ill-treatment ... or other exploitation, resulting in actual or potential harm to the child's health, survival, development or dignity in the context of a relationship of responsibility, trust or power." <s> In the United States, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) uses the term "child maltreatment" to refer to both acts of absue and neglect. <s> According to the WHO, the term abuse includes "words or overt actions that cause harm, potential harm, or threat of harm to a child"; neglect means "the failure to provide for a child's basic physical, emotional, or educational needs or to protect a child from harm or potential harm". <s> The United States federal Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act defines "child abuse and neglect" as, at minimum, "any recent act or failure to act on the part of a parent or caretaker which results in death, serious physical or emotional harm, sexual abuse or exploitation" or "an act or failure to act which presents an imminent risk of serious harm". <s> Talking about these things and helping children who suffer from child abuse is very important, but some people do not believe it could happen in their country, neighbourhood or family.

title: Beatrice Mintz
complex: Beatrice Mintz (born January 24, 1921 in New York City) is an American embryologist who has contributed to the understanding of genetic modification, cellular differentiation and cancer, particularly melanoma.Mintz was a pioneer of genetic engineering techniques, and was among the first scientists to generate both chimeric and transgenic mammals. <s> In 1996 she shared the inaugural March of Dimes Prize in Developmental Biology with Ralph L. Brinster for their work in developing transgenic mice. <s> Much of her career has been spent at the Fox Chase Cancer Center in Philadelphia where, in 2002, she was named to the Jack Schultz Chair in Basic Science. <s> Mintz is a member of both the United States National Academy of Sciences and the Pontifical Academy of Sciences.
simple: Beatrice Mintz (born January 24, 1921) is an American embryologist who has helped to the understanding of genetic modification, cellular differentiation and cancer, particularly melanoma. <s> Mintz was a pioneer of genetic engineering techniques, and was among the first scientists to generate both chimeric and transgenic mammals. <s> Mintz was born on January 24, 1921 in New York City. <s> In 1996 she shared the inaugural March of Dimes Prize in Developmental Biology with Ralph L. Brinster for their work in developing transgenic mice. <s> Much of her career has been spent at the Fox Chase Cancer Center in Philadelphia where, in 2002, she was named to the Jack Schultz Chair in Basic Science. <s> Mintz is a member of both the United States National Academy of Sciences and the Pontifical Academy of Sciences.

title: Jair da Rosa Pinto
complex: Jair da Rosa Pinto (21 March 1921 – 28 July 2005), or simply Jair, was an association footballer who played offensive midfielder – one of the leading Brazilian footballers of the 1940s and 1950s, who is best remembered for his performance in Brazil's 1950 FIFA World Cup campaign. <s> Usually playing as an inside-forward, Jair da Rosa was noted for his free-role style of play and was most known for his pace and technical ability. <s> Jair died of a lung infection on July 21, 2005 at the age of 84, in Rio de Janeiro. <s> He made 49 appearances for the Brazilian national football team, scoring 24 goals.
simple: Jair da Rosa Pinto (21 March 1921 – 28 July 2005) is a former Brazilian football player. <s> He has played for Brazil national team.

title: Ward Ruyslinck
complex: Raymond De Belser (17 June 1929 – 3 October 2014), pseudonym Ward Ruyslinck, was a Belgian writer. <s> He is the son of Leo De Belser and Germaine Nauwelaers. <s> His father was a librarian at an oil company, and Ward Ruyslinck grew up in a Roman Catholic family. <s> During the Second World War, the family moved to Mortsel. <s> Ruyslinck was born in Berchem. <s> At age 12, he had written a novel, "Vaargeulen" (in English, "Channels"). <s> His father, who himself wrote the novel "Gepantserde Beschaving" (Armoured Civilization), sent his son's novel to Stijn Streuvels, who returned the novel unread but with an accompanying letter full of recommendations. <s> The manuscript was lost during an air raid in 1943, which devastated their house. <s> He wrote a number of poems and stories, some of which were published in the daily "Het Vlaamsche land". <s> His most widely read book "" (""Incense and Tears"") was published in 1958. <s> In 1961, with the novel "Het dal van Hinnom", he broke with church and society. <s> In 1964, he moved to Pulle and wrote the novel "Het reservaat" about the illusion of individual freedom. <s> He won the "Prijs voor Letterkunde van de Vlaamse provincies" for this work. <s> In 1966, he wrote the bittersweet fairy tale "Golden Ophelia". <s> Ward Ruyslinck retired in 1984. <s> After the suicide of his wife in 1990, he moved to Meise to live with his mistress Monika Lo Cascio. <s> Ward Ruyslinck and Monika Lo Cascio jointly wrote the autobiographical novel "De speeltuin" ("The Playground") in 1992. <s> Ruyslinck, who had from Alzheimer's disease, died on 3 October 2014 in a retirement home in Meise.
simple: Raymond De Belser (17 June 1929 – 3 October 2014), pseudonym Ward Ruyslinck, was a Belgian writer. <s> He was born in Berchem, Belgium. <s> He was known for his book "Wierook en tranen" (""Incense and Tears""). <s> He won the "Prijs voor Letterkunde van de Vlaamse provincies" for this work. <s> In 1966, he wrote the bittersweet fairy tale "Golden Ophelia". <s> Ward Ruyslinck retired in 1984. <s> Afterwards, he moved to Meise to live with his mistress Monika Lo Cascio. <s> Ruyslinck and Cascio wrote the autobiographical novel "De speeltuin" ("The Playground") in 1992. <s> Ruyslinck, who had from Alzheimer's disease, died on 3 October 2014 in a retirement home in Meise.

title: Zalman King
complex: Zalman King (born Zalman King Lefkowitz; May 23, 1941 – February 3, 2012) was an American film director, writer, actor and producer. <s> His films are known for incorporating sexuality, and are often categorized as erotica. <s> King directed several films, including "Two Moon Junction" (1988), "Wild Orchid" (1990), "" (1991) and "Red Shoe Diaries" (1992), which became a long-running television series for Showtime network. <s> It spawned many sequels. <s> He directed and co-wrote the movie "In God's Hands" (1998). <s> He died on February 3, 2012, aged 70, from cancer.
simple: Zalman King (May 23, 1942 – February 3, 2012) was an American movie writer, producer, movie director and actor. <s> He directed several erotic movies, including "Wild Orchid" (1990) and "Two Moon Junction" (1988). <s> He died from cancer in Santa Monica, California.

title: Mastung, Pakistan
complex: Mastung , the capital of Mastung District, is a town in the Balochistan province of Pakistan. <s> It is located at 29°48'0N 66°50'60E and has an altitude of 1701 metres (5583 feet). <s> The town is also the administrative centre of Mastung Tehsil, an administrative subdivision of the district – the town itself is administratively subdivided into two Union Councils.

title: Rodolfo Severino Jr.
complex: Rodolfo Certeza Severino Jr. (27 April 1936 – 19 April 2019) was a Filipino diplomat best known for his term as the Secretary General of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) from 1998 to 2002. <s> Severino died of complications from Parkinson's disease on 19 April 2019, eight days before his 83rd birthday.

title: James Cameron
complex: James Francis Cameron (born August 16, 1954) is a Canadian filmmaker and environmentalist who currently lives in New Zealand and the United States. <s> After working in special effects, he found major success since directing and writing the science fiction action film "The Terminator" (1984).
simple: James Cameron (born August 16, 1954) is an Academy and Golden Globe Award winning Canadian movie director.

title: Shimon Peres
complex: Shimon Peres ( ; ] ; born Szymon Perski; 2 August 1923 – 28 September 2016) was an Israeli politician who served as the ninth President of Israel (2007–2014), the Prime Minister of Israel (twice), and the Interim Prime Minister, in the 1970s to the 1990s. <s> He was a member of twelve cabinets and represented five political parties in a political career spanning 70 years. <s> Peres was elected to the Knesset in November 1959 and except for a three-month-long hiatus in early 2006, was in office continuously until he was elected President in 2007. <s> At the time of his retirement in 2014, he was the world's oldest head of state and was considered the last link to Israel's founding generation. <s> On 13 June 2007, Peres was elected President of the State of Israel by the Knesset. <s> 58 of 120 members of the Knesset voted for him in the first round (whereas 38 voted for Reuven Rivlin, and 21 for Colette Avital). <s> His opponents then backed Peres in the second round and 86 members of the Knesset voted in his favor, while 23 objected. <s> He resigned from his role as a Member of the Knesset the same day, having been a member since November 1959 (except for a three-month period in early 2006), the longest serving in Israeli political history. <s> Peres was sworn in as President on 15 July 2007. <s> On 13 September 2016, Peres suffered a severe stroke and was hospitalized at Sheba Medical Center. <s> His condition was reported to be very serious, as he had suffered a massive brain hemorrhage and significant bleeding. <s> Two days later, he was reported as being in a serious but stable condition. <s> However, on 26 September, an examination found irreversible damage to his brainstem, indicating that it was not possible for him to recover, and the following day, his medical condition deteriorated significantly. <s> He died on 28 September at the age of 93.
simple: Shimon Peres (; born Szymon Perski; 2 August 1923 – 28 September 2016) was a Polish-born Israeli statesman. <s> He was the President of the State of Israel. <s> Peres served twice as the Prime Minister of Israel. <s> He also served as Interim Prime Minister twice. <s> Peres has been a member of 12 cabinets. <s> His political career spanned over 66 years. <s> On September 13, 2016, Peres, aged 93, suffered a severe stroke and was hospitalized in Ramat Gan, Israel. <s> He had suffered a massive brain hemorrhage. <s> Two days later, he was reported as being in a serious but stable condition. <s> However, on September 26, an examination found damage to his brainstem. <s> He died on September 28 of complications from the stroke.

title: Caitlin McHugh
complex: Caitlin Maureen McHugh (born May 13, 1986) is an American actress, writer, and model. <s> McHugh is signed with Wilhelmina Models. <s> In 2016, she appeared in television commercials for Colgate toothpaste and the following year, for the Buick "Encore". <s> On October 23, 2017, McHugh announced her engagement to actor John Stamos after a year of dating. <s> In December 2017, the couple announced they were expecting their first child, due in the spring of 2018. <s> Stamos and McHugh married in February 2018. <s> On April 15, 2018, Stamos announced the birth of their first son, Billy, named after John's father.

title: Brighton College
complex: Brighton College is an independent, co-educational boarding and day school for boys and girls aged 3 to 18 in Brighton, England. <s> The school has three sites: Brighton College (the senior school, ages 11 to 18); Brighton College Preparatory School (children aged 8 to 13, located next to the senior school); and the Pre-Prep School (children aged 3 to 8). <s> Founded in 1845 by William Aldwin Soames, Brighton College was the first Victorian public school to be founded in Sussex. <s> Soames originally planned for use of the Brighton Pavilion, but after refusal by Queen Victoria, built the school in the suburb of Kemptown, Brighton.
simple: Brighton College is a boarding school in Brighton, England. <s> It is for boys and girls aged between 3 and 18. <s> It was started by William Aldwin Soames in 1845.

title: A Philosopher Lecturing on the Orrery
complex: A Philosopher Lecturing on the Orrery, or the full title, A Philosopher giving a Lecture on the Orrery in which a lamp is put in place of the Sun, is a 1766 painting by Joseph Wright of Derby depicting a lecturer giving a demonstration of an orrery to a small audience. <s> It is now in the Derby Museum and Art Gallery The painting preceded his similar "An Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump" (National Gallery, London). <s> In both of these works, the candlelit setting had a realist justification. <s> Viewing sculpture by candlelight, when the contours showed well, and there might even be an impression of movement from the flickering light, was a fashionable practice described by Goethe. <s> In the orrery demonstration the shadows cast by the lamp representing the Sun were an essential part of the display. <s> But there seems no reason other than heightened drama to stage the air pump experiment in a room lit by a single candle, and in two later paintings of the subject by Charles-Amédée-Philippe van Loo the lighting is normal. <s> An anonymous review from the time called Wright "a very great and uncommon genius in a peculiar way". <s> "The Orrery" was painted without a commission, probably in the expectation that it would be bought by Washington Shirley, 5th Earl Ferrers, an amateur astronomer who had an orrery of his own, and with whom Wright's friend Peter Perez Burdett was staying while in Derbyshire. <s> Figures thought to be portraits of Burdett and Ferrers feature in the painting, Burdett taking notes and Ferrers seated with a youth next to the orrery. <s> Ferrers purchased the painting, which was exhibited in 1766, for £210, but the 6th Earl auctioned it off, and it is now in the Derby Museum and Art Gallery, where it is on permanent display, close to a working replica of a full-sized mechanical Grand Orrery. <s> A biographer of Wright, Benedict Nicolson, argued in 1968 that John Whitehurst was the model for the lecturer, while another commentator points out the figure's resemblance to "a painting of Isaac Newton by Godfrey Kneller". <s> Close observation of the adult faces in the picture reveals that each one demonstrates one or other of the main phases of the Moon – new moon, half moon, gibbous moon and full moon.
simple: A Philosopher Lecturing on the Orrery is an 18th-century oil painting by Joseph Wright of Derby. <s> Wright later created his similar "An Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump" (National Gallery, London) in 1768. <s> In the orrery demonstration, the shadows created by the lamp mimic the sun, and it is a part of the display of heliocentrism. <s> In two later paintings, the lighting is normal. <s> One person called Wright "a very great and uncommon genius in a peculiar way". <s> "The Orrery" was painted without payment. <s> Wright expected that Washington Shirley, 5th Earl Ferrers, an amateur astronomer, will buy the painting, because Shirley had his own orrery, and Wright's friend Peter Perez Burdett was staying with him. <s> Figures are considered to be portraits of Burdett and Ferrers. <s> In the picture, Burdett is taking notes and Ferrers is seated with his son next to the orrery. <s> Ferrers purchased the painting for £210, but the 6th Earl sold it at an auction. <s> It is now held by Derby Museum and Art Gallery as its permanent display. <s> However, other people say the figure is similar to "a painting of Isaac Newton by Godfrey Kneller".

title: David Lean
complex: Sir David Lean (25 March 190816 April 1991) was an English film director, producer, screenwriter and editor. <s> Widely considered as one of the most influential directors of all time, Lean was mostly famous for his large-scale epics such as "The Bridge on the River Kwai" (1957), "Lawrence of Arabia" (1962), "Doctor Zhivago" (1965) and "A Passage to India" (1984). <s> He also directed adaptations of Charles Dickens novels "Great Expectations" (1946) and "Oliver Twist" (1948), and the romantic drama "Brief Encounter" (1945). <s> Lean was born at 38 Blenheim Crescent, South Croydon, Surrey (now part of Greater London), to Francis William le Blount Lean and the former Helena Tangye (niece of Sir Richard Trevithick Tangye). <s> His parents were Quakers and he was a pupil at the Quaker-founded Leighton Park School in Reading.

title: Bikont
complex: A bikont ("two flagella") is any of the eukaryotic organisms classified in the group Bikonta. <s> Many single-celled members of the group, and the presumed ancestor, have two flagella. <s> Another shared trait of bikonts is the fusion of two genes into a single unit: the genes for thymidylate synthase (TS) and dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR) encode a single protein with two functions. <s> The genes are separately translated in unikonts.

title: 916 America
complex: 916 America is a minor planet orbiting the Sun in the main belt between Mars and Jupiter. <s> It was discovered on 7 August 1915 by the Russian astronomer Grigory Nikolaevich Neujmin at Simeis, Russian Empire. <s> Originally designated 916I, it was renamed '916 America' on 24 February 1923 after the Council of Astronomers at Pulkovo Observatory decided to commemorate "the friendly relations of the astronomical observatories and astronomers". <s> Another possible reason for the name was as a mark of appreciation for the help given during the 1921 Russian famine by the American Relief Administration under the later President Herbert Hoover. <s> In 1986, assuming that the asteroid was of S-type and that it had a diameter of 15 km, the rotational period was measured to be 38 hours. <s> Observations by the Infrared Astronomical Satellite have since shown that it has a diameter of 33.2±1.3 km, with an absolute magnitude of 11.20 and an albedo of 0.053±0.004.
simple: 916 America is a minor planet that is orbiting the Sun in the main belt between Mars and Jupiter. <s> It was discovered on 7 August 1915 by the Soviet astronomer Grigory Nikolaevich Neujmin at Simeis, Ukraine. <s> It was originally called 916I, but was renamed "916 America" on 24 February 1923 after the Council of Astronomers at Pulkovo Observatory decided to pay tribute to "the friendly relations of the astronomical observatories and astronomers". <s> Another possible reason for the name was as a mark of thankfulness for the help given during the famine in Crimea by the American Relief Administration under President Herbert Hoover. <s> In 1986, believing that the asteroid was of S-type and that it had a diameter of 15 km, the length of 916 America's day was thought to be 38 hours. <s> Observations by the Infrared Astronomical Satellite have since shown that it has a diameter of 33.2±1.3 km, with an absolute magnitude of 11.20 and an albedo (the extent to which it reflects light) of 0.053±0.004.

title: James Hylton
complex: James Harvey Hylton (August 26, 1934 – April 28, 2018) was an American stock car racing driver. <s> He was a two-time winner in NASCAR Winston Cup Series (now Monster Energy Cup Series) competition and was a long-time competitor in the ARCA Racing Series. <s> Hylton finished second in points in NASCAR's top series three times. <s> Hylton was born on August 26, 1934 to a Roanoke, Virginia family farm; he was one of thirteen children. <s> Hylton's early years centered primarily around farming but he soon found himself immersed in the world of stock car auto racing. <s> On April 28, 2018, Hylton, his son James "Tweet" Hylton Jr., and the team's crew chief Terry Strange were driving home from the ARCA race at Talladega, and the team's hauler was in a traffic accident going northbound on Interstate 85 near Carnesville, Georgia. <s> Both Hyltons died in the accident, while Strange survived with severe injuries.
simple: James Harvey Hylton (August 26, 1934 – April 28, 2018) was an American stock car racing driver. <s> He was a two-time winner in NASCAR Winston Cup Series (now Monster Energy Cup Series) competition. <s> He was a long-time competitor in the ARCA Racing Series. <s> Hylton finished second in points in NASCAR's top series three times. <s> He was born in Roanoke, Virginia. <s> Hylton was killed in a car crash near Carnesville, Georgia on April 28, 2018 at the age of 83.

title: Bass Highway, Tasmania
complex: The Bass Highway is a highway in Tasmania, Australia. <s> It is a part of the National Highway, designated as National Highway 1 and connects the major cities across the north of the state - Burnie, Devonport and Launceston. <s> The road was named due to its proximity to the Bass Strait. <s> Other bypasses have included Carrick and Hadspen in the late 1980s and the longest stretch of highway, the Hagley-Westbury bypass, which was completed in 2001. <s> The 'old' highway alignment between Deloraine and Hadspen is now known as Meander Valley Road, and is promoted as a tourist route. <s> The Bass Highway is, like Bass Strait, named for explorer George Bass.

title: Cisgender
complex: Cisgender (sometimes cissexual, often abbreviated to simply cis) is a term for people whose gender identity matches the sex that they were assigned at birth. <s> For example, someone who identifies as a woman and was assigned female at birth is a cisgender woman. <s> The term "cisgender" is the opposite of the word "transgender".

title: Impeachment of Dilma Rousseff
complex: The impeachment of Dilma Rousseff, the 36th president of Brazil, began on 2 December 2015 with a petition for her impeachment being accepted by Eduardo Cunha, then president of the Chamber of Deputies, and continued into late 2016. <s> Rousseff, then more than 12 months into her second four-year term, was charged with criminal administrative misconduct and disregard for the federal budget in violation of article 85, items V and VI of the Constitution of Brazil and the , article 36. <s> Rousseff was formally impeached on 17 April 2016. <s> On 12 May, the Senate voted to suspend Rousseff's powers for the duration of the trial, and Vice President Michel Temer became acting president. <s> On 31 August 2016, the Senate removed President Rousseff from office by a 61–20 vote, finding her guilty of breaking Brazil's budget laws. <s> Accordingly, Temer was sworn in as the 37th president of Brazil. <s> Temer was accused by an Odebrecht executive of soliciting campaign donations in 2014 for his party.

title: Begum Jan
complex: Begum Jan is a doctor and the founder of the Tribal Women Welfare Association, which educates tribal women in Northwest Pakistan about their rights, and gives them medical training. <s> She grew up in South Waziristan, a conservative area of Pakistan, but her father encouraged her to become a doctor. <s> She attended a school for boys as a child because there was no school for girls, and when her tribal elders forbid her to attend high school she studied with a tutor instead. <s> She received a 2008 International Women of Courage Award, making her the first Pakistani woman to receive that award.
